अंकुशा
Aṃkuśā --a Śakti on the Drāviṇikā mudrā. Br. IV. 36. 76.

अंकुशेश्वरम्
Aṃkuśeśvaram --in the Narmadā. M. 194. 1.

अंकोल
Aṃkola --a tīrtha, and its merits. M. 191. 118-25.

अंचोलद्विचराः
Aṃcoladvicarāḥ(c) --a kingdom watered by the R. Sītā. Br. II. 18, 45.

अकपि
Akapi --a sage of the Tāmasa epoch. M. 9. 15.

अकम्पन
Akampana --a son of Khaśā and a Rākṣasa: 1) Br. III. 7, 136; Vā. 69, 167. an Asura in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. 2) M. 161. 81.

अकर्ण
Akarṇa --a kādraveya nāga. Br. III. 7. 33.

अकर्मक
Akarmaka(i) --a class of Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 379.

अकल्मष
Akalmaṣa --a son of Tāmasa Manu. M. 9. 17.

अकार
Akāra --its significance in Oṃ; 1) Vā. 20. 8ff. the source of 63 varṇas; 2) Vā. 26. 28. the primordial svara and its place in creation. 3) Vā. 26. 29ff. 

अकारादिक्षकारान्तवर्णमूर्ति
Akārādikṣakārāntavarṇamūrti --the house of, to the north of Mātṛkā. Br. IV. 36. 20.

अकृतचूड
Akṛtacūḍa --one who has not had tonsure: his death leaves pollution for one night; pollution after cūḍa is for three nights. M. 18. 3.

अकृतव्रण
Akṛtavraṇa  (I)--a Brāhman invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira to officiate as a priest. Bhā., X. 74. 9.

अकृतव्रण
Akṛtavraṇa  (II)--a Paurāṇika. Learnt one of the four Mūlasamhitas from the disciple of Vyāsa; 1) Bhā., XII. 7. 5, 7. a pupil of Romaharṣaṇa; otherwise known as Kāśyapa. 2) Vi. III. 6. 17.

अकृतव्रण
Akṛtavraṇa  (III)--a sage. Br. II. 35. 63.

अकृतव्रण
Akṛtavraṇa  (IV)--the Brahman boy rescued by Paraśurāma, his guru, from the jaws of a tiger. 1) Br. III. 26. 3; 30. 21; 34, 8, 29; 35. 37. Advised to take courage and console his mother; condoled with him on the loss of his parents. 2) Br. III. 37. 10; 38, 2, 35; 39. 13; 41. 15, 17; 43, 31; 44. 1, 30. Accompanied Paraśurāma, to Mandira for a twelve years' penance and to Mahendra for another course of austerities. Helped Paraśurāma in his Aśvamedha and the penance after. 3) Br. III. 46. 3, 28; 47. 34, 59.

अकृताश्व
Akṛtāśva --a son of Samhatāśva. Br. III. 63. 65; M. 12, 34. 

अक्रिय
Akriya --the son of Gambhīra. Of his wife was born Brahman. Bhā. IX. 17. 10.

अक्रूर
Akrūra  (I)--a Yadu prince; welcomed Kṛṣṇa to Dvāraka. 1) Bhā. I. 11. 16; 14, 28. The foremost of the sons of Śvaphalka and Gāndinī; married a daughter of Ugrasena and had two sons, Devavān and Upadeva (Deva and Anupadeva-Vi). 2) Bhā. IX. 24. 15, 17, 18; Br. III. 71. 113; Vi. IV. 13. 126; 14. 7, 10; Vā. 96. 112. Stayed in Madhurā (Mathurā) when the Yadus migrated. 3) Bhā. X. 2. 4 []. Once visited Brahmaḥrada. 4) Bhā. X. 28. 16. Kaṃsa sent for him and asked him to take in his chariot Kṛṣṇa and Rāma to the capital for the Dhanuryāga (‘festival of arms’) at which they were to be killed. Returned home with this message. 5) Bhā. X. 36. 27-40; Vi. V. 15, 9, 12. When the night passed by, Akrūra started for the vraja of Nanda thinking all the way of the meeting and embraces of Kṛṣṇa and Rāma who had made friends with people of Brindāvan. Reached Gokula by evening. 6) Bhā. X. 38, 1-24 Vi. V. 15. 24. Saw Rāma and Kṛṣṇa in fine deportment and form, milking cows: prostrated before them in divine ecstasy. Welcomed in the proper way by the brothers and Nanda, Akrūra was lost in wonder, and did not feel the fatigue of the journey. 7) Bhā. X. 38. 25-43; Vi. V. 17. 2-25. Gopis who came to know of Akrūra's mission called him Krūra for taking away Kṛṣṇa from their midst. 8) Bhā. X. 39. 21-26. It was early morning when Akrūra and the two brothers started after morning prayers. Reaching the Yamunā, Akrūra went to the river for a bath, asking the brothers to stay in the chariot. But he was surprised to see the brothers in the waters, and at the same time in the chariot also. He also saw Hari reclining on Śeṣa. 9) Bhā. X. 39. 32-57; Vi. V. 18. 11 and 19. Akrūra's praise of Hari. 10) Bhā. X. 40. (whole). Congratulating himself on his luck to have had a darśan of Hari, he drove Kṛṣṇa and Rāma to Mathurā before sunset. 11) Bhā. X. 41. 4-6. Invited Kṛṣṇa to his home, and the latter agreed to go to his place only after Kaṃsavadha. Informed Kaṃsa of  Kṛṣṇa's arrival in the camp, and went back to his house. 12) Bhā. X. 41. 11-18. Attended the wrestling match. 12(a) Vi. V. 20. 28. Gopis took Uddhava to Akrūra. 13) Bhā. X. 46. 48. Was visited by Kṛṣṇa with Rāma and Uddhava to whom Akrūra gave a royal welcome. 14) Ib. X. 48. 12-28. Kṛṣṇa told Akrūra that they looked to him for guidance, and that he was their guru. Was requested by Kṛṣṇa to go to Hastināpura to find out the exact position of the Pāṇḍavas. 15) Ib. X. 48. 29-35. Visited Hastināpura and returned to Mathurā after meeting Kunti and ascertaining the evil intentions of Dhṛtarāṣṭṛa against the Pāṇḍavas. 16) Ib. X. ch. 49 (whole). One of those stationed by Kṛṣṇa to defend the western gate of Mathurā, 17) Ib. X. 50. 20[4]. was consulted by Kṛṣṇa on the eve of his attack on Jarāsandha. 18) Ib. X. [50. (V). 8]. A member of the Yādava sabhā. 19) Ib. X. [52. (V). 15]. Satyabhāmā refusing to part with the jewel Syamantaka (s.v.), Akrūra suggested with Kṛtavarman to Śatadhanvan Bhoja its seizure from Satrājita as he had failed to keep his promise to marry his daughter to them. 20) Ib. X. 57. 3; Vā. 96. 57, 97; Vi. IV. 13. 115-26. Asked by Śatadhanvan for help against Kṛṣṇa, Akrūra refused; Bhoja Śatadhanvan killed Satrājita, the father of Satyabhāmā, and secured the jewel but placed it in Akrūra's custody. 21) Bhā. X. 57. 14-18. Became afraid, after Śatadhanva's death at the hands of Kṛṣṇa and Balarāma, and left Dvārakā. Evil portents in the city and cessation of rains. It was said that rain fell where Akrūra lived. Was sent for by Kṛṣṇa to return to Dvārakā; gave his sister in marriage to Kṛṣṇa who after duly honouring him, requested him to show the jewel in public, so that Rāma might not misunderstand him. He did so in the sabhā of the Sātvatas but Kṛṣṇa placed Syamantaka back in his hand. 22) Ib. X. 57. 29-41 [1-4]; Br. III. 71. 59 and 83; Vi. IV. 13. 67-90. Was sent back to Dvārakā after the Rājasūya for its defence. 23) Bhā. X. 76. 7 [5]
14. Visited Syamantapañcaka on the occasion of the solar eclipse. 24) Ib. X. 82. 5. Fought with Bhoja, deluded by Kṛṣṇa. 25) Ib. XI. 12. 10. Got killed in the Yādava contest at Prabhāsa. 26) Ib. XI. 30. 16. 

अक्रूर
Akrūra  (II)--a kādraveya nāga. Br., III. 7. 36.

अक्रूर
Akrūra  (III)--Mahāsena: a varamūrti. Br. IV. 44. 50.

अक्रूर
Akrūra  (IV)--a son of Jayanta, married Ratnā, Śaibya's daughter; father of eleven powerful sons. M. 45. 27-8.

अक्रोधन
Akrodhana  (I)--a son of Tvaritāyu or simply Āyu. M. 50. 37.

अक्रोधन
Akrodhana  (II)--a son of Ayutāyu and father of Devātithi. Vā. 99. 232.

अक्ष
Akṣa  (I) 1) Bhā. IX. 9. 17; M. 220. 8; Vā. 88. 174; Vi. IV. 4. 37; Br. III. 63. 173. --the game of dice. Ṛtuparṇa, an expert in it. Taught the game to Nala; to be avoided by a king. 2) M. 154. 520; 220. 8.

अक्ष
Akṣa  (II)--a dānava. Br. III. 6. 11.

अक्ष
Akṣa  (III)--a son of Satyabhāmā and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 247; Vā. 96. 238.

अक्षपाद
Akṣapāda --a son of Somaśarman, the avatār of the Lord at Prabhāsa, contemporary with the 27th Vyāsa. Vā. 23. 216.

अक्षमाला
Akṣamālā --of Śeṣa; see Akṣasūtra. Vā. 50. 50. 

अक्षर
Akṣara  (I)--Father of Suyajña. Br. III. 70. 23.

अक्षर
Akṣara  (II)--an epithet of Hari--(ety.) 1) M. 248. 39. is Brahma. 2) Vā. 32. 1.

अक्षर
Akṣara  (III)--rises out of the neck of Brahmā in the contemplation of creation. 1) Vā. 26. 14. A system of letters formed by Brahmā. 2) Bhā. XII. 6. 43-44.

अक्षर
Akṣara  (IV)--a term for mahān. Vā. 102. 21.

अक्षरी
Akṣarī --the highest yogi. Vā. 19. 43; 20, 4.

अक्षसूत्र
Akṣasūtra --given to Vāmana by Pulaha: adorns Agastya, (also Akṣamālā) (s.v.). M. 61. 36; 245. 87.

अक्षयवट
Akṣayavaṭa --in Gayā; 1) Vā. 105. 45; 109. 16. the fruits of anna śrāddha at. 2) Vā. 111. 79 & 83.

अक्षया
Akṣayā --a Brahmarākṣasī. Vā. 69. 134.

अक्षयाश्व
Akṣayāśva --one of the two sons of Saṃhatāśva. Vā. 88. 63.

अक्षयतृतीया
Akṣayatṛtīyā (vratam) --the third day of Śuklapakṣa of the month Vaiśākha. It is all the more important if Kṛttikā happens to be the nakṣatra of that day. A prayer to Janārdana on that day accompanied by fasting is equal to performing the Rājasūya. M. 65. 1-7. 

अक्षि
Akṣi --a daughter of Rohiṇī and Ānakadundubhi. M. 46. 12.

अगज
Agaja --a son of the elephant Mṛga. Br. III. 7. 332.

अगम्यागमनम्
Agamyāgamanam  (Anyāṅganārati s.v.)--Bṛhaspati tells Indra that intercourse with mother, sister, wife of preceptor and uncle's wife is illegal. The last two could be atoned for by a kṛcchra of 12 and 6 years respectively. Similar cases of forbidden intercourse and their respective prāyaścittas given. Repetition of Pañcadaśākṣarī 1008 times after worshipping Parāśakti could remove all sins. Br. IV. 8. 1-37.

अगम्यगामि
Agamyagāmi --goes to the naraka Śabala. Vā. 101. 157.

अगरु
Agaru --the forest in the Kuru country between the two mountains Candrakānta and Sūryakānta. Vā. 45. 31.

अगस्त्य
Agastya  (I)--a son of Pulastya and Havirbhū: he was Dahra-agni in his previous birth. Bhā., IV, 1. 36.

अगस्त्य
Agastya  (II)--a contemporary of Kṛṣṇa and Rāma; and a resident of Mount Malaya. Visited by Balarāma. 1) Bhā., X. 79. 17. Came to Syamantapañcaka to see Kṛṣṇa. 2) Ib. X. 84. 5. Called on Parīkṣit practising prāyopaveśa. 3) Ib. I. 19. 10. 

अगस्त्य
Agastya (Kumbhayoni)  (III)--born from a pitcher into which Mitra and Varuṇa dropped their vīrya at the sight of the charms of Urvaśī: a brother of Vasiṣṭha. 1) Bhā. VI. 18. 5; Br. IV. 5. 38 M. 61. 21-31; 201. 29; 202. 1. Dwarfed the Vindhyas, made a home in Laṅkā: seeing the universe troubled by Tāraka and other Asuras caused the ocean to dry up by drinking the waters and brought relief to the Devas: performed tapas seated on Mount Malaya with his wife Lopāmudrā: white in colour, with four hands, Akṣa mālā and Kamaṇḍalu, narrated the story of Ajāmila: 2) Bhā., VI. 3. 35; M. 61. 17; 36-41; Br. III. 56. 53. present at Rāma's abhiṣeka. 2(a) Vi. IV 4. 99. Visited by Paraśurāma, initiated him to the Kṛṣṇapremāmṛtam mantra which he heard from Śeṣa, the Nāga king. Spoke to him of the threefold bhakti and its characteristics. 3) Br. II, 32. 119; III. 34. 50; 35. 34, 41, 48; 36, 1-59; 37, 2; 56. 23. A Brahmiṣṭha, versed in Vaikhānasa; a Devaṛṣi, versed in Vedic literature. 4) M. 145. 93, 114. The guest of Ilvala who cooked Vātāpi for him. 5) Bhā. VI. 18, 15. Roaming about, he found all creatures engrossed in ignorance. Reaching Kāñcī, he prayed to Kāmākṣi and Ekāmraśiva. Here Hayagrīva Viṣṇu appeared before him and pointed out ways to redeem the ignorant millions. Was entertained with the story of Śakti by Hayagrīva. 6) Br. IV. 5. 3-29; 6. 1; 39. 7. Praised Śiva out to ruin Tripuram. 7) M. 133. 67. He who worships Agastya becomes lord of the seven worlds. 8) M. 61. 44-55.

अगस्त्य
Agastya  (IV)--married the first born daughter of King Malayadhvaja Pāṇḍya, and had a son Dṛḍhācyuta. 1) Bhā. IV. 28. 32. Cursed the Pāṇḍyan king Indradyumna to become an elephant. 2) Ib. VIII. 4. 9-10.

अगस्त्य
Agastya  (V)--the constellation (Canopus) that moves fast above Dhruvamaṇḍala. Br. II. 21. 101; Vā. 50, 155. 

अगस्त्य
Agastya  (VI)--a hill of that name. M. 124. 97.

अगस्त्य
Agastya  (VII)--born of garbha; born later as Dattāli; 1) Vā. 28. 22; Vi. I, 10. 9. (Dattoli-Vi.). residence (bhavana) at Mahāmalaya; 2) Vā. 48. 23. relation of, to Potṛyaṇa; 3) Vā. 59. 93, 208. Udayantaka Mt. brought by; and his wife. 4) Vā. 108. 44, 53.

अगस्त्यकुण्डम्
Agastyakuṇḍam --in the Udayantaka Mt.; here eight sages performed austerities and attained salvation. Vā. 108. 45.

अगस्त्यपदम्
Agastyapadam --in Gayā. Vā. 109. 19; 111. 53; Vi. II. 8. 85.

अगस्त्यभवनम्
Agastyabhavanam --see Agastya. M. 163. 74.

अगस्त्य
Agastyas --a group of Rākṣasas. Br. III. 7. 162.

अगस्त्येश्वरम्
Agastyeśvaram --a tīrtha in the Narmadā. M. 191. 15-18.

अगारदाहिन्
Agāradāhin --unfit for inter-dining. Vā. 83. 62.

अगावह
Agāvaha --Father of four sons and a daughter. Br. III. 71. 257.

अग्नजिती
Agnajitī --a queen of Kṛṣṇa. Vi. V. 28. 3. 

अग्नि
Agni  (I)--the God of Fire also known as Hutāśana, Havyavāhana and Vahni. 1) Bhā., I. 15. 8; Br., III. 10. 24-35. A place sacred to Agni in the Sarasvatī which Vidura visited. 2) Bhā., III. 1. 22. Svāhā and her three sons are deities presiding over Agni. 3) Ib. IV. 1. 60. One of the gods with power to confer boons or pronounce curse on the world, curse on elephants. 4) Ib. IV. 14. 26-27; Br. III. 7, 352. On the tail of Śiśumāra. 5) Bhā., V. 23. 5; Br. II. 23. 104. Invested by the Māyā of Bhagavān, Agni does not sometimes understand his will and work. 6) Bhā., VI. 3. 14. 15. A guardian of the world. 7) Ib., VIII. 10. 26. The mouth of Hari as embodying all Vedas. 8) Ib. VIII. 16. 9. Is pleased with a devotee of Hari. 9) Ib. X. 41. 13. Even the powerful Agni could not digest Brāhman's property when misappropriated. 10) Ib. X. 64. 32. Identified with Hari. 11) Ib. XI. 16. 13. Swallowed the seed of Śiva borne by Gaṅgā as a punishment for disturbing Umā's union with the Lord, and unable to digest it, he discharged it into a bush of reeds (śarakānana) where it became Kumāra. 12) Ib. IV. 7. 64[]; VI. 6. 14; Br. IV. 15. 21; 20. 46; 26. 53. Goes round Dhruva. 13) Bhā., IV. 9. 21. Presented Ājagava bow to Pṛthu. 14) Ib. IV. 15. 18. Married a daughter of Dakṣa. 15) Ib. IV. 1. 48. Worshipped in Kuśadvīpa. 16) Ib. V. 20. 2. His son was Manu Svārociṣa. 17) Ib. VIII. 1. 19. Fought with Puloma in a Devāsura war, 18) Ib. VIII. 10. 31; followed Indra's army against Kṛṣṇa who took away Pārijāta from heaven. Beaten by Kṛṣṇa, he escaped alive from the field. 19) Ib. X. [65 (V) 40]; [66 (V) 27-31]. His town visited by Arjuna in search of a dead child of a Brāhman of Dvārakā. 20) Ib. X. 89. 44.

अग्नि
Agni  (II)--a lokapāla: Gold pleasing to Agni; worship of; 1) M. 225. 13; 266. 20, 63. burning women and children in Tripura, he pleaded that he was not a free agent, but only carrying out orders. 2) M. 188. 29-57. The vamśa of Agni. The succession of fires and their descendants detailed in Ch. 51 of the Matsya Purāṇa. 3) Cf. Mhb. Vana: 220. 4. The Bhāgavata Purāṇa mentions 49 Agnis. Pāvaka, Pavamāna  and Śuci and their 45 sons together with Svāhā. All invoked in sacrifices. 4) Bhā. IV. 1. 60-62; 7, 16. Another classification of fires: divyam, bhautikam or abyoni, and pārthivam. 5) Br. II. 24. 6; 21. 53. 56; Vā. 53. 5.

अग्नि
Agni  (III)--one of the eight Vasus, and a son of Vasu. Wife Vasorddhāra. Draviṇaka and others are sons. 1) Bhā., VI. 6. 11, 13. Identified with Hari. 2) Ib. XI. 16. 13; M. 8. 4.

अग्नि
Agni  (IV)--married Vikeśi. Father of Ūrjja clan of apsaras and also of Nala and Aṅgāraka, who afterwards became a planet. Br. II. 24. 91; III. 7. 21, 229.

अग्नि
Agni  (V)--an Ātreya, and one of the seven sages of Tāmasa epoch. Br. II. 36. 47; M. 9. 15; Vā. 62. 41.

अग्नि
Agni  (VI)--a son of Āgneyī and Ūru: His daughter Succhāyā married Śiṣṭa, son of Dhruva: Ārṣeya pravara. M. 4. 38, 43; 196. 9.

अग्नि
Agni  (VII)--alias Ṛta; son of Samvatsara; 1) Br. II. 13. 23. married Svāhā, a daughter of Dakṣa. 2) Vā. 1. 76; Br. II. 9. 56; 12. 1.

अग्नि
Agni  (VIII)--a Marut gana of that name. M. 171. 52. 

अग्नि
Agni  (IX)--The eldest son and mindborn son of Brahmā in Svāyambhuva antara; 1) Vā. 29. 1; Vi. I. 10. 14. of Brahmā's tapas; 2) Vā. 21. 63-4. one of the eight tanus of Mahādeva, 3) Vā. 27. 35. hymns to; 4) Vā. 21. 71ff. gave rise to a family of 49 fires. 5) Vi. I. 10. 15-7.

अग्नि
Agni  (X)--(Bhūtapati) one Agni made into three by Aila to attain the Gandharva loka in the Tretāyuga. The Gandharvas presented him with a pot of Agni which he took to his city to perform sacrifices. He placed it on the Araṇi when an Aśvattha appeared to his surprise. When Aila informed Gandharvas the latter asked him to turn the Aśvattha thrice and get three fires with which to sacrifice. Vā. 91. 48: 101. 21.

अग्नि
Agni  (XI)--see Anila. Vi. I. 15. 114.

अग्नि
Agni  (XII)--a Mahāpurāṇa (also Āgneya). Vi. III. 6. 22.

अग्नि
Agni Abhimānī --see Agni. Vi. I. 10. 14.

अग्निका
Agnikā --one of the three daughters of Vikrāntā; originator of the Āgneya gaṇa of the Gandharvas. Vā. 69. 21-23.

अग्निकुण्ड
Agnikuṇḍa --the fire pot from which Śiva appeared to Dakṣa. 1) Vā. 30. 172. Rise of Tilottamā from Brahmā's agnikuṇḍa. 2) Vā. 69. 59.

अग्निक्षेत्र
Agnikṣetra --from which Sītā came. Vā. 89. 17. 

अग्निजिह्व
Agnijihva  (I)--a daitya in the fifth talam (MahātalamVā.). Br. II. 20. 36; Vā. 50. 35.

अग्निजिःव
Agnijiḥva  (II)--A Trayārṣeya. M. 196. 43.

अग्निज्वाल
Agnijvāla --the name of a hell to which disturbers of hermitages go; 1) Br. IV. 2. 149, 174. those fallen from their āśrama duties undergo torments in. 2) Vā. 101. 148, 171.

अग्नितीर्थम्
Agnitīrtham --on the southern bank of the Yamunā. M. 108. 27.

अग्नितेजस्
Agnitejas --a sage of the XI epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 31.

अग्निध्र
Agnidhra --a son of Bhautya Manu. Vā. 100. 116.

अग्निपुराण
Agnipurāṇa --one among the Mahāpurāṇas comprises 15400 ślokas. See Agni. Bhā., XII. 7. 23; 13. 5.

अग्निप्रवेशम्
Agnipraveśam --the custom of wife entering her husband's funeral pyre. Br. III. 47. 82.

अग्निप्रस्कन्दनम्
Agnipraskandanam --diarrhoea--Yayāti caused his son Anu to be afflicted by it. M. 33. 24. 

अग्निबाहु
Agnibāhu  (I)--one of the ten sons of Svāyambhuva Manu. Br. II. 13. 104; M. 9. 4.

अग्निबाहु
Agnibāhu  (II)--one of the ten sons of Kardama. Br. II. 14. 9.

अग्निबाहु
Agnibāhu  (III) (Bhārgava)--a sage of the epoch of Bhautya Manu; 1) Br. IV. 1. 113. a son of Bhautya (fourteenth) Manu. 2) Vā. 100. 116.

अग्निबाहु
Agnibāhu  (IV)--a son of Priyavrata; 1) Vi. II. 1. 7. had no inclination for rule and was given to yoga; 2) Vi. II. 1. 9. a sage of the XIV epoch of Manu. 3) Vi. III. 2. 44.

अग्निभाव
Agnibhāva --an Amitābha deva. Br. II. 36, 53.

अग्निभास
Agnibhāsa --one of the fourteen sons of Vasiṣṭha Prajāpati in the Cāriṣṇava antara. Vā. 62. 46.

अग्निमाढक
Agnimāḍhaka  (also Agnimāṭhara)--a pupil of Bāṣkala was instructed the second śākhā of the Ṛgveda. Vā. 60. 26; Vi. III. 4. 18.

अग्निमत्
Agnimat --one who keeps up the sacred fire. M. 16. 21.

अग्निमन्त्र
Agnimantras --in homas to ward off calamities to the state. M. 231. 11. 

अग्निमाता
Agnimātā --a second disciple of Bāṣkala, in charge of a śākhā of the Ṛgveda. Br. II. 34, 27.

अग्निमित्र
Agnimitra  (I)--the son of Puṣyamitra Śuṅga and father of Sujyeṣṭha; 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 16; Vi. IV. 24. 34-5. reigned for eight years. 2) Br. III. 74. 151.

अग्निमित्र
Agnimitra  (II)--a pupil of Bāṣkala. Bhā., XII. 6. 54.

अग्निमुख
Agnimukha --the name of an Asura who has his city in the third talam. Br. II. 20. 26.

अग्निर्बाहु
Agnirbāhu --a sage of the epoch of the 14th Manu (Agni bāhu) (Burnouf). Bhā. VIII. 13. 34.

अग्निलिङ्गम्
Agniliṅgam --from its middle Maheśvara spoke out the Liṅga Purāṇa. M. 53. 37-8.

अग्निवचस्
Agniva(r)cas --a sage: 1) Br. II. 35. 64. a pupil of Romaharṣaṇa. 2) Vi. III. 6. 17.

अग्निवर्ण
Agnivarṇa --of the (Kuśa dynasty); the son of Sudarśana, and father of Śīghra(ga). Bhā. IX. 12. 5; Br. III. 63. 209-10; Vā. 88. 209; Vi. IV. 4. 108. 

अग्निवेश्य
Agniveśya  (I)--the son of Devadatta, was an incarnation of Agni. Was known also by other names--Kānīna and Jātūkarṇa. He was a great sage, and the originator of the Brāhman group of Agniveśyāyana. 1) Bhā., IX. 2. 21-22; Br. III. 47. 49. (Pravara-Aṅgiras). 2) M. 196. 12.

अग्निवेश्य
Agniveśya  (II)--a son of Śūli in the 24th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 207.

अग्निशर्म
Agniśarma --a mānasa ṛtvik at Brahmā's yāga, created five Agnis from his face. Vā. 106. 34, 41.

अग्निशमायण
Agniśamāyaṇas --the originators of Kaśyapa gotra. M. 199. 7.

अग्निष्टुत्
Agniṣṭut  (I)--produced by Brahmā. Bhā., III. 12. 40.

अग्निष्टुत्
Agniṣṭut  (II)--a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu. Br. II. 36. 79, 106; M. 4. 42.

अग्निष्टोम
Agniṣṭoma --a son of Manu Cākṣuṣa and Naḍvalā. Bhā. IV. 13. 16: Vi. I. 13. 5.

अग्निष्टोमम्
Agniṣṭomam --origin of, from the first face of Brahmā; 1) Br. II. 8. 50; Vā. 9. 49; Vi. I. 5. 53. performing Agniṣṭomam is equal to honouring pitṛs; done by Vāli. 2) Br. III. 7. 268; 11, 43; 15. 11. Here the sacrifice of paśu is involved. 3) M. 53. 33; 58. 53; 239. 30.

अग्निष्णुत्
Agniṣṇ(ṣṭ)ut --a son of Nāḍvaleya Manu. Vā. 62. 67, 91. 

अग्निष्वात्ताः
Agniṣvāttāḥ --a pitṛgaṇa dwelling in the Somapāda region in the direction of Vaivasvata. 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 63; V. 26. 5; Vi. I. 10. 18; II. 12. 13; Br. II. 13. 6; Vā. 73. 2; 110. 10. Pitṛs representing ārttavas, the name given to householders who do not perform yajñas. 2) Br. II. 13. 6-7; 23. 75-77; 28. 4, 16, 19, 20 and 73; Vā. 30. 6, 27f; 52. 67-8; 56. 13-15, 68; 73. 2-4. Pitṛs in Viraja's kingdom. Their mind-born daughter Pīvarī was married by Śuka, son of Vyāsa. 3) Br. III. 10. 75-80. Gave Menā their mind-born daughter to Himavān; 4) Vā. 30. 27-9, 31; 56. 13 and 68; Vi. I. 10. 19; Br. II. 13. 31. overlord of other pitṛs. 5) M. 14. 2; 18. 21; 19. 5; 102. 20; 126. 69; 141. 4, 13 and 16.

अग्निसम्भव
Agnisambhavas --a Kanyā gaṇa born of Manu from Ūrjā. Vā. 69. 54.

अग्निहोत्रम्
Agnihotram --personified as the son of Pṛśni and Savitā; 1) Bhā. VI. 18, 1. a vedic sacrifice; 2) Ib. III, 13, 36. performed by Bharata. 3) Ib. V. 7, 5. Its nature and effects. 4) Ib. VII. 15, 48. Performers of Agnihotra live in Pitṛyāna; 5) Br. II. 21. 160; 30, 13; III. 14, 2; 26, 14; 35, 44; 44, 5; 66, 2; M. 124. 98. performed by Śukra, Dhūminī, the sonless wife of Ajamīḍha; 6) M. 11, 58; 25, 34; 50, 18; 107, 16; 183, 81. performed by Purūravas; 7) Vā. 91, 2; 107, 18; 77, 9. the face of the personified Vedas. 8) Ib. 104, 83. As efficacious as hearing the Viṣṇupurāṇa once. 9) Vi. VI. 8, 30.

अग्नीध्र
Agnīdhra  (I)--a Nadīputra and Dhiṣṇi agni. Br. II. 12, 20. Vā. 29. 18, 26.

अग्नीध्र
Agnīdhra  (II)--(Kāśyapa)--a sage of the epoch of Bhautya Manu (XIVth Manu). Br. IV. 1. 112; Vi. III. 2, 44.

अग्नीध्र
Agnīdhra  (III)--a son of Svāyambhuva Manu. 1) Vā. 31. 17. Lord of Jambūdvīpa. 2) Vā. 33. 9, 11. 

अग्नीषोमयम
Agnīṣomayama--Āpyāyanam  offered to Agni, Soma and Yama in the śrāddha; the pitṛsthānam of places prescribed. M. 15. 32; 16. 33.

अग्नीषोमविधिज्ञ
Agnīṣomavidhijña --an attribute of Śiva, Agnīṣoman representing Brahman. Br. III. 72. 188; IV. 43. 76.

अग्न्याधानक्रिया
Agnyādhānakriyā --Vedic rituals which are to begin on Parvasandhis. M. 141. 32.

अग्र्यम्
Agryam --a region of the Pātāla; the soil with the gold colour. Vi. II. 5. 2 and 3.

अघ
Agha --an asura; friend of Kaṃsa. Appeared in the guise of a boa-constrictor in order to devour Kṛṣṇa, his playmates and cattle in Bṛndāvana. Thinking it to be a part of the landscape of the Bṛndāvana, Kṛṣṇa's playmates and cattle entered his wide-open mouth. Kṛṣṇa understood the situation, and after a little hesitation, he also went in and killed him by choking his throat. Agha, however, attained salvation. Bhā. X. 12. 13-38; 13. 4; 14. 60.

अघमर्षण
Aghamarṣaṇa  (I)--a tīrtha at the foot of the Vindhyas. Here Dakṣa performed tapas and praised Hari with the Hamsaguḥya. Bhā. VI. 4. 21 & 35.

अघमर्षण
Aghamarṣaṇa  (II)--a Kauśika and a sage. 1) Br. II. 32. 117; M. 145. 112. Not to have matrimonial alliance with Viśvāmitra and others. 2) M. 198. 12. 

अघविनाशिनी
Aghavināśinī --a mother goddess. M. 179. 28.

अघोर
Aghora --the form of Maheśvara in the 32nd kalpa, all black. Vā. 23. 29, 76.

अघोरकल्प
Aghorakalpa --an account of, in the Bhaviṣya. M. 53. 31.

अङ्गार
Aṅgāra--(c)  a southern country. Br. II. 16. 59.

अङ्गारक
Aṅgāraka  (I) (Mars)--an inauspicious planet; traverses each of the signs of the zodiac once in three fortnights. 1) Bhā. V. 22. 14. The planet with Skanda as presiding deity; fed by Sampadvasu ray of the sun, attains Lauhitam sthānam or the Lohita region. Consists of nine rays and looks in size equal to Bṛhaspati: Placed above Śukra at a distance of 200,000 yojanas. Also known as Lohita and Vakra. 2) Br. II. 24. 48, 70, 82, 95 & 105; Vi. II. 7. 8-9. The first of Planets, originally Vīrabhadra who destroyed Dakṣa's sacrifice; son of mother Earth; fought with Soma. 3) M. 23. 40; 72. 16 & 23; 93. 13; 133. 20. Day sacred to. 4) M. 193. 8-9. Vratam in honour of, conduces to health and prosperity; the Śūdras observe it; described by Śukra in detail. 5) M. 72. 5-36. The tanu of Śarva (Agni) by Vikeśi. 6) Br. II. 10. 78; Vā. 27. 51. Born in Āṣāḍha. 7) Br. II. 24. 82, 133.

अङ्गारक
Aṅgāraka  (II)--a Rudra. Br. III. 3. 70; Vā. 66. 69.

अङ्गारक
Aṅgāraka  (III)--a name of Skanda. Vā. 53. 31; 112. 52.

अङ्ग
Aṅga  (I)--the father of Vena; knew the power of Kṛṣṇa's yoga. 1) Bhā. II. 7. 43; Vi. I. 13. 6. A son of Ulmuka (Kuru and Āgneyī- Vi. P.). His wife was Sunīthā, the cruel-faced daughter of Mṛtyu. Finding the son's conduct cruel and unbecoming, he departed from the city. 2) Bhā. IV. 13, 17-18. Once he performed the Aśvamedha but the gods did not partake of the offerings. When he consulted the learned assembly, was advised by it that he could get a son by worshipping Hari. But the son born, Vena, was so mischievous that the king abandoned the kingdom in distress. Though messengers were deputed in search of him, his whereabouts remained untraced. 3) Ib. IV. 13. 24-49. Devoted to Hari, sought refuge with Him. 4) Ib. IV. 21. 28; X. 60. 41. According to the Brahmāṇḍa, Matsya and Vāyu Purāṇas he was the son of Ūru and Āgneyī. 5) Br. II. 36. 108 & 126; Vā. 62. 92-3; M. 4. 44. A Prajāpati of the family of Svāyambhuva Manu (of the Atri line. Vā.) 6) M. 10. 3-4; Vā. 62. 107.

अङ्ग
Aṅga  (II)--A kṣetraja son of Bali: born of Dīrghatamas. Father of Khanapāna (Anapāna-Vā.). 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 5 & 6; M. 48. 25 & 9; Vā. 99. 28, 85; Br. III. 74. 27, 87. After him was the Aṅgadeśa. 2) Vi. IV. 18. 13-14. Father of Dadhivāhana, born without apāna (anus). 3) Br. III. 74. 102; Vā. 99. 100. The last king of his line was Vṛṣasena. 4) Vi. IV. 18. 29.

अङ्ग
Aṅga  (III) (c)--An eastern kingdom. Its king got war elephants from Devas. Br. II. 16. 51; 18. 51; III. 7. 349; 74. 213; M. 114. 44; 121. 50; Vā. 47. 48; 99. 402.

अङ्ग
Aṅga  (IV)--a son of Havirdhāna. M. 4. 45.

अङ्ग
Aṅga  (V)--the son of Viśvajit Janamejaya and father of Karṇa. M. 48. 102; Vā. 99. 112. 

अङ्गजा
Aṅgajā --a daughter of Brahmā. M. 3. 12.

अङ्गद
Aṅgada  (I)--a son of Lakṣmaṇa. 1) Bhā. IX. 11. 12; Vi. IV. 4. 104. Capital Kārayana in the Aṅgada kingdom. 2) Br. III. 63. 188; Vā. 88. 187-8. (Kārapatha-Vā.).

अङ्गद
Aṅgada  (II)--a son of Vāli: married the eldest daughter of Mainda; father of Dhruva. 1) Br. III. 7. 219-20. Present at Rāma's abhiṣeka. 2) Vi. IV. 4. 100. Helped Rāma in his expedition to Laṅkā. 3) Bhā. IX. 10. 19-20. Bore the sword when Bharata carried the pādukā of Rāma. 4) Ib. IX. 10. 44.

अङ्गद
Aṅgada  (III)--a kingdom with its capital Kārayana. Br. III. 63. 189.

अङ्गद
Aṅgada  (IV)--a son of Bṛhatī. Br. III. 71. 256; Vā. 96. 247.

अङ्गदीया
Aṅgadīyā --the capital of Kārapatha deśa(?) Vā. 88. 188.

अङ्गदेव्यन्तरम्
Aṅgadevyantaram --the residence of Hṛddevī and others. Br. IV. 37. 40.

अङ्गद्वीपम्
Aṅgadvīpam --a part of Jambūdvīpa inhabited by Mlecchas. Vā. 48. 14-18.

अङ्गना
Aṅganā --wife of Vāmana, the elephant. Br. III. 7. 339.

अङ्गभूतम्
Aṅgabhūtam --a tīrtham sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 51. 

अङ्गराजा
Aṅgarājā --killed by Arjuna. Vi. V. 38. 47.

अङ्गलोकवर
Aṅgalokavaras --a tribe. Vā. 47. 43.

अङ्गलोक्य
Aṅgalokyas --kingdom of. M. 121. 43.

अङ्गलौहिक
Aṅgalauhika --A northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 49.

अङ्गारपातन
Aṅgārapātana --name of a hell. Br. IV. 33. 61.

अङ्गारवाहिका
Aṅgāravāhikā --sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 35.

अङ्गारवाहिनी
Aṅgāravāhinī --a R. in the Bhadrāśva continent. Vā. 43. 26.

अङ्गारेश्वरम्
Aṅgāreśvaram --a place sacred to Aṅgāraka on the R. Narmadā. M. 190. 9; 191. 59-60.

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras  (I)--a mānasa son of Brahmā, born of his mouth. 1) Bhā. III. 12. 22, 24; Br. II. 32. 96; M. 3. 6; 5. 14; 15. 16. Married Śraddhā, (Pitrī-Vi. P.) a daughter of Kardama. 2) Bhā. III. 24. 22; Vi. I. 7. 5, 7; 15. 136. Father of four daughters. His two sons were Utathya and Bṛhaspati. 3) Bhā. IV. 1. 34-5; M. 102. 19; 106. 17. Had not yet realised the Supreme Being. 4) Bhā. IV. 29. 43. With his pupils visited Bhīṣma lying on his bed of arrows. 5) Bhā. I. 9. 8. Came to see Parīkṣit practising prāyopaveśa. 6) Ib. I. 19. 9. Married two of the daughters of Dakṣa. These were Svadhā and Satī. His sons were Pitṛ and Atharvāngiras. A Prajāpati. 7) Ib. VI. 6. 2, 19; Br. II. 37. 45; M. 167. 43; 171. 27; Vā. 1. 137; 3. 3; 25. 82; 30. 48; 65. 97-101. Once  called on Citraketu, the king of Śūrasenas, who was childless and blessed his first queen with a son. The jealous co-wives of the king administered poison to the baby and it died. Finding the king and queen weeping bitterly, Aṅgiras accompanied by Nārada came to the palace. These two sages appeared there in avadhūta form. Aṅgiras consoled the king and cited the story of King Bhoja. 8) Bhā. VI. 14. 14-30, 37-61; 15. 10; 12, 17-26 [1-4]. Went back to Brahmaloka with Nārada. 9) Ib. VI. 16. 26. Was appointed by King Rathikara to produce sons on his wife. 10) Ib. IX. 6. 2. The sage presiding over the month of Nabha. 11) Ib. XII. 11. 37; M. 126. 10. Was present at the anointing of Vāmana. 12) Bhā. VIII. 23. 20. Came to see Kṛṣṇa at Syamantapañcaka. 13) Ib. X. 84. 5. Went to Dvārakā to ask Kṛṣṇa to go back to Vaikuṇṭha. 14) Ib. XI. 6. 2. Had another son named Samvarta (s.v.). 15) Ib. IX. 2. 26. Cursed Vidyādhara Sudarśana (s.v.) to become a reptile for mocking at him. 16) Ib. X. 34. 13-15. Performed a sacrifice when Śarayāti explained on the rituals of the second day. 17) Ib. IX. 3. 1. Stood near the wheel of the chariot Tripurāri in defence; served Prayāga and lived in Benares; a mahaṛṣi and mantrakṛt. 18) M. 133. 20, 61, 67; 145. 90, 101; 146. 17; 184. 15; 192. 10; Vā. 59. 98.

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras  (II)--a son of Ulmuka. Bhā. IV. 13. 17.

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras  (III)--author of Aṅgiras Kalpa; a master of Atharva Samhitā. Bhā. XII. 7. 4.

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras  (IV)--one of the sages who left for Piṇḍāraka. Bhā. XI. 1. 12. 

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras  (V)--born in Vāruṇi yajña by an oblation in the aṅgāra (fuel) from it, and hence the name. Agni therefore claimed him to be his son, and so Aṅgirasas became Āgneyas. Bhāradvājas and Gautamas belong to this line; performed penance at Amarakaṇṭaka, praised Soma and spoke on the Śrāddha Kalpa to his son Śaṃyu at Dāruvana. 1) Br. II. 9. 18, 23; III. 1. 21, 39-40, 101; 13. 5; 20. 19; IV. 2. 33 and 47; Vā. 64. 2; 73, 63; 75. 56; 77. 5; 88. 7; Br. II. 27. 103. Married Surūpā, daughter of Marīci and had ten sons. 2) Vā. 65. 105-8; M. 195. 9; 196. 1; 245. 86.

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras  (VI)--A son of Kaśyapa; married Smṛti and had two sons and four daughters; 1) Br. II. 11. 17; 9. 55; Vā. 28. 14. flourished in Svāyambhuva antara; a Devaṛṣi. 2) Ib. 31. 16; 30. 86; Br. II. 11. 17; 13. 53.

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras  (VII)--with the sun for the months Nabhonabha (Nabha-Vi. P.). Br. II. 23. 9; Vi. II. 10. 9.

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras  (VIII)--the name of Vyāsa in the fourth dvāpara; avatār of the lord Suhotri. Vā. 23. 126.

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras  (IX)--one of the Ātreyas of the Raivata antara. 1) Br. II. 36. 62. Sprung out of charcoal in which Brahmā offered a second oblation: adopted by Agni as his son and hence Aṅgiras called Āgneyas. 2) Ib. III. 1. 40-42. See Aṅgiras. V.

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras  (X)--a son of Ṛṣabha, the ninth avatār of Maheśvara. Vā. 23. 144.

अङ्गिरस्
Aṅgiras  (XI)--A son of Atharva: 1) Vā. 29. 9. known as Atharvan. 2) Ib. 65. 97; Br. I. 5. 70. 

अङ्गिरस
Aṅgirasa  (I)--a son of Āgneyi and Ūru (Kuru-Vi. P.). M. 4. 43; Vi. I. 13. 6.

अङ्गिरस
Aṅgirasa  (II)--the fourth part of Atharva Veda. Vi. III. 6. 14.

अङ्गिरस
Aṅgirasas  (I)--the name of a devagaṇa. Br. III. 1. 50.

अङ्गिरस
Aṅgirasas  (II)--the thirty-three sages, all mantrakṛts. Vā. 59. 102.

अङ्गिरसकल्प
Aṅgirasa-Kalpa --name given to a portion of Atharva Veda. Br. II. 35. 62 and 82; Vā. 61. 54.

अङ्गिरसाः
Aṅgirasāḥ --born of Rathītara's wife and Aṅgiras. Hence Kṣatriya-cum-Brāhmaṇa. Bhā. IX. 6. 3.

अङ्गिरसी
Aṅgirasī --a R. of Plakṣadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 4.

अङ्गुलम्
Aṅgulam --is eight times a yava. For other details see Matsya P. 12 aṅgulas: 1 vitasti. 21 aṅgulas: 1 ratni 24 aṅgulas: 1 hasta Br. II. 7. 96; IV. 2. 121; M. 258. 18-21; Vā. 8. 102; 101. 121 and 122.

अङ्गुलीय
Aṅgulīya --a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 53; Vā. 61. 46. 

अङ्गुलीयम्
Aṅgulīyam --rings to be presented in connection with Vṛkṣotsava. M. 59. 14.

अङ्गुष्ठ
Aṅguṣṭha --gifts, receiving of gifts, homa, feeding, bali offering, all to be done. Vā. 79. 88.

अचल
Acala  (I) ety.--immovable, hence a mountain. Br. II. 7. 11.

अचल
Acala  (II)--the name of Bhairava in the Kiricakra. Br. IV. 20. 82.

अचल
Acala  (III)--the son of Mahīnetra; ruled for 32 years. M. 271. 28.

अचल
Acala  (IV)--a devaṛṣi. Vā. 61. 84.

अचेतना
Acetanā --the wife of Manu. Br. III. 1. 82.

अच्युत
Acyuta  (I)--a god of the Lekha group. Br. II. 36. 75.

अच्युत
Acyuta  (II)--an epithet for Viṣṇu, 1) Br. II. 36. 178; IV. 29. 71; 43. 70; VI. I. 11. 43. et. seq. M. 47. 5; 245. 49. 246. 33, 60. ety. One who does not fall from his place (na cyavate). 2) M. 248. 35.

अच्युत
Acyuta  (III)--the Lord of the western region and son of Prajāpati; also known as Ketumān. Vā. 70. 17.

अच्छावाक
Acchāvāka --the Agni at Bhuvasthānam. Vā. 29. 28. 

अच्छोदम्
Acchoda(ka)m --the name of a lake at the foot of Candraprabha. 1) Vā. 47. 5-7; M. 121, 6-7. Here Acchodā, the Pitṛ-kanyā, sprang up and was again born in Matsya-yoni; 2) Vā. 77. 76-7. residence of the Apsaras Adrikā. 3) Ib. 73. 3.

अच्छोदा
Acchodā  (I)--the mind-born daughter of Barhiṣada pitṛs. After her name was the Acchoda lake. Without finding her own Pitṛs, she took as her Pitṛ, another (Amāvasu) and consequently lost her yogic powers. Then seeing her Pitṛs in the form of Trasareṇu, she prayed to them for succour. They said that she would be born on the earth on the 28th Dvāpara as the daughter of Matsya and marry Śantanu and be mother of two seers--Vicitravīrya as well as of king Citrāṅgada. Afterwards she would attain the aṣṭaka place in the Pitṛ world. As the daughter of the fisherman, she was known as Satyavatī and Matsyagandhi. 1) Br. III. 10. 54-74; Vā. 73. 2-21; M. ch. 14 (whole). In the form of a river rising from lake Acchodam. 2) M. 121. 7.

अच्छोदा
Acchodā  (II)--the R. from lake Acchoda. Vā. 47. 5-6, 7.

अज
Aja  (I)--a name of Brahmā. Bhā. II. 4. 19; Vā. 73. 62; 98. 54.

अज
Aja  (II)--a son of Pratihartā and Stuti. Bhā. V. 15. 5.

अज
Aja  (III)--a Rudra, and a son of Bhūta and Sarūpā. Bhā. VI. 6. 17.

अज
Aja  (IV)--the son of Raghu, and father of Daśaratha. (Burnouf makes Aja, son of Pṛthuśravas. But Pṛthuśravas here is an adjective of Raghu meaning--highly renowned). Bhā. IX. 10. 1; Br. III. 63. 184; Vā. 88. 183: Vi. IV. 4. 85-6. 

अज
Aja  (V)--the son of Ūrdhvaketu and father of Purujit. Bhā. IX. 13. 22.

अज
Aja  (VI)--a Tuṣita god. Br. II. 36. 10.

अज
Aja  (VII)--a son of Uttama Manu. Br. II. 36. 39; Vā. 61. 185; 62. 9. 34; Vi. III. 1. 15.

अज
Aja  (VIII)--a Kūṣmāṇḍa Piśāca, one of the two sons of Kapī. Had a daughter Jantudhanā. Br. III. 7. 74-85.

अज
Aja  (IX)--an attribute of Kumāra. Br. III. 10. 48.

अज
Aja  (X)--a Sudhamāna god. Br. IV. 1. 60.

अज
Aja  (XI)--a horse of the chariot of the moon. M. 126. 52.

अज
Aja and Ajā  (XII)--the one god and goddess; mystery of; Ajā, eight letters, sixteen hands, and feet, four faces, three knots of hair, one horned goddess--Māyā. Vā. 20. 28-29.

अज
Aja  (XIII)--a son of Bhṛgu. Vā. 65. 87.

अज
Aja  (XIV)--a division of the night. Vā. 66. 43.

अज
Aja  (XV)--the name of a Dānava. Vā. 68. 11. 

अज
Aja  (XVI)--the name given to Dhanvantari when he first appeared out of the churning of the ocean for nectar. Vā. 92. 10.

अजक
Ajaka  (I)--a son of Balāka and father of Kuśa. Bhā. IX. 15. 3-4.

अजक
Ajaka  (II)--the son of Sunaha (Suhotra-Vā. P., and Sumantu-Vi. P.) and father of Balākāśva; 1) Br. III. 66. 30; 74-126; Vā. 91. 60-61; Vi. IV. 7. 8. ruled for 21 years (31 ? Vā.). 2) Vā. 99. 313.

अजक
Ajaka  (III)--the son of Dilīpa. M. 12. 48.

अजकर्ण
Ajakarṇa --a son of Maya. Br. III. 6. 29.

अजगन्धा
Ajagandhā --an Apsaras. Br. III. 7. 8.

अजगवम्
Ajagavam --the name of Siva's bow (also Ājagavam). M. 23. 37; Vā. 90. 31.

अजतुङ्ग
Ajatuṅga --a place fit for performing śrāddham, noted for the tree Virajā; 1) Br. III. 13. 48. the shadow of gods seen at the place in parvas; the Pāṇḍavas performed śrāddham at. 2) Vā. 77. 48.

अजन
Ajana  (I)--the parent of Buddha. (Añjana-Burnouf). Bhā. I. 3. 24.

अजन
Ajana  (II)--a name of Kṛṣṇa-Hari. Bhā. X. 3. 1 & 5; 6. 23. 

अजनाभ
Ajanābha (c) --the kingdom of Ṛṣabha, later known as Bhārata. Bhā. V. 4. 3; 7. 3; XI. 2. 24.

अजबस्त
Ajabasta --a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 52.

अजभूः
Ajabhūḥ --one of the nine sons of Ugrasena. M. 44. 75.

अजमीढ
Ajamīḍha  (I)--a son of Hastin. Had three queens of Kuru line; Priyamedhā and other Brāhmans belonged to his family. Father of Kaṇva and Bṛhadiṣu. 1) Bhā. IX. 21. 21-22; Vā. 99. 166; Vi. IV. 19. 29-30, 33; M. 49. 43-5. By Nalinī he had a son Nīla. 2) Bhā. IX. 21-30; Vā. 99. 194; Vi. IV. 19. 56. Ṛkṣa was another son of his. 3) Bhā. IX. 22. 3; M. 50. 19. Vi. IV. 19. 74. Sons born through the grace of Bharadvāja. 4) Vā. 99. 169.

अजमीढ
Ajamīḍha  (II)--an Aṅgirasa and mantrakṛt. A Kṣatriya-dvija. Br. II. 32. 109; III. 66. 87; M. 145. 103; Vā. 91. 116; 59. 100.

अजमुखिका
Ajamukhikā --a mindborn mother. M. 179. 24.

अजय
Ajaya --the son of Darbhaka and father of Nandivardhana. Bhā. XII. 1. 6, 7.

अजवीथि
Ajavīthi --on the back of the Śiśumāra (s.v.) 1) Bhā. V. 23. 5. the southern course. Here are three kinds of sunrise, one in mūla and the other two in two āṣāḍhas; on its south was Pitṛyāna: consists of three constellations--mūla and āṣāḍhas--pūrva and uttara. 2) Br. II. 21. 76 & 159; III. 3. 51; M. 124. 53-8; Vā. 1. 93; 66. 51; Vi. II. 8. 85. 

अजस्य
Ajasya --a son of Aṅgiras and Surūpā: a gotrakara. M. 196. 4.

अजा
Ajā --born of Yaśodā--Māyā (s.v); 1) Bhā. X. 3. 47; 13. 52. the energy of the Creator--through her, Hari is spoken of in nine forms. 2) Ib., XI. 9. 28; XII. 11. 31.

अजाकर्ण
Ajākarṇa --a place fit for śrāddha offering. M. 15. 33.

अजात
Ajāta --one of the ten sons of Hṛdīka: Father of three powerful sons: Sudamṣṭra, Sunābha and Kṛṣṇa. M. 44. 82-4.

अजातशत्रु
Ajātaśatru  (I)--the son of Vidhisāra and father of Darbhaka (Arbhaka-Vi. P.). Bhā. XII. 1. 6; Vi. IV. 24. 14-15.

अजातशत्रु
Ajātaśatru  (II)--the son of Bhūmimitra. 1) Vā. 99. 317. His reign lasted for 25 (27?) years. 2) Br. III. 74. 131; M. 272. 10.

अजामुख
Ajāmukha --one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 5.

अजामुख
Ajāmukhas  (also Adhomukhas)--a group of piśācas. Br. III. 7. 381; Vā. 69. 263, 267.

अजामिल
Ajāmila --an old itihāsa of. A Brāhmaṇa of Kanyākubja, versed in śāstras and celebrated in ācāra. Once when out to get kuśa grass, he saw a dāsī and fell in love. Then he abandoned all his duties and discarded his wedded wife. The dāsī became his wife. She bore him ten sons. The last was named Nārāyaṇa best loved of his parents. At  the time of his death, when the messengers of Yama were waiting to remove him to hell, he called out his last son by his name Nārāyaṇa. On this, the messengers of Vīṣṇu were on the scene and prevented Yama's men from taking the Brāhman to hell. It was argued that pronouncing the name of Hari at his death redeemed him of all his sins, and that alone was the secret of Dharma. Yama heard this and approved it. Ajāmila, thus rescued from Death, felt penitent, and while making tapas at Gaṅgādvāra, he cast off his body and reached Viṣṇuloka. Bhā. VI. 1. 20. to the end; Ib. VI. ch. 2 & 3.

अजित
Ajita  (I)--a manifestation of Hari during the epoch of Manu Cākṣuṣa. In this period the Kṣīroda was churned and nectar was secured. 1) Bhā. II. 2. 5; VIII. 5. 9-10. Praised by Brahmā. 2) Ib. VIII. 5. 25-50. Advised gods to befriend Asuras and then get amṛta by churning the ocean, with their co-operation, to be able ultimately to prevail against them; 3) Ib. VIII. 6. 18-25. began to take part in Amṛtamathana when the efforts of others produced no results. 4) Ib. VIII. 7. 16; X. 2. 20; X. 51. 48.

अजित
Ajita  (II)--a Pṛthuka god. Br. II. 36. 74.

अजित
Ajita  (III)--the name of Hari born in Svārociṣa epoch from Tuṣitā. Br. III. 3. 114.

अजिता
Ajitā  (I)--the goddess following Bhavamālinī. M. 179. 71.

अजिता
Ajitā  (II)--the mother of devas known as Ajitas. Vā. 67. 33. 

अजित
Ajitas  (I)--a group of gods with Āyuṣmanta formed 14 gaṇas whose residence was Maharloka. From there they go to Janaloka. Br. III. 4. 27; IV. 1. 122.

अजित
Ajitas  (II)--a devagaṇa; 1) Vā. 10. 21. they are Asama, Ugradṛṣṭi, Sunaya, Śuciśravas, Kevala, Viśvarūpa, Sudakṣa, Madhupa, Turiya, Indrayuk. 2) Br. II. 9. 46; 13. 90. Remembered by Brahmā. 3) Vā. 31. 4.

अजित
Ajitas  (III)--sons of Ajita and Ruci in the Svāyambhuva Manvantara. Vā. 67. 33.

अजिन
Ajina --a son of Havirdhāna. Br. II. 37. 24; Vā. 63. 23; Vi. I. 14. 2.

अजिम्ह
Ajimha --a Pārāvata god. Br. II. 36. 13; Vā. 62. 12.

अजिर
Ajira --a Śukra deva. Vā. 31. 9.

अजीगर्त
Ajīgarta --a sage who sold his second son Śunaḥśepha to Rohita to be sacrificed in his place. Bhā. IX. 7. 20-21; IX. 16. 30.

अजेय
Ajeya --a Pārāvata god; also a Vaikuṇṭha god. Br. II. 36. 14 and 57.

अजेश
Ajeśa --one of the eleven Rudras. M. 153. 19.

अजैकपात्
Ajaikapāt  (I)--a Rudra, and a son of Bhūta and Sarūpā; the Bhūta chieftain 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 18; Br. III. 3. 71; Vā. 66. 69. one of the eleven Rudras. 2) M. 5. 29. 

अजैकपात्
Ajaikapāt  (II)--the agni at Śālāmukhi; see Upastheya. Br. II. 12. 25. Vā. 29. 24.

अजैकपात्
Ajaikapāt  (III)--a muhūrta of the night. Br. III. 3. 42.

अजैडकम्
Ajaiḍakam (c) --a kingdom. Br. III. 74. 218; Vā. 99. 406.

अञ्जन
Añjana  (I)--the son of Irāvati, the elephant of golden colour; belonging to the fold of Vāmadeva Sāma. Br. III. 7. 292, 327 & 339.

अञ्जन
Añjana  (II)--a Sāman. Br. III. 7. 343.

अञ्जन
Añjana  (III)--Mt. a hill west of the Sitoda; 1) Vā. 36. 28. residence of the Uragas; 2) Vā. 39. 59. famous for elephant forests. 3) Ib. 69. 238.

अञ्जन
Añjana  (IV)--a son of Kṛti. Father of Kurujit. Vi. IV. 5. 31.

अञ्जना
Añjanā --a daughter of Kuñjara and queen of Kesari. Loved by Vāyu, gave birth to Hanumān. Br. III. 7. 224-5.

अञ्जनावती
Añjanāvatī --born of Añjana (elephant); two sons-Prathitāyu and Ajaḥ; pleasant looking and well-formed animals. Vā. 69. 227-28; Br. III. 7. 343-4.

अञ्जनसिद्धि
Añjanasiddhi --a yoga siddhi. Br. IV. 36. 52. 

अञ्जन
Añjanas --sons of Kallolaha. Br. III. 7. 442.

अञ्जनी
Añjanī --the mother of Hanumān. Vā. 60. 73.

अञ्जलि
Añjali --a mode of worship with both hands. He who worships a god by raising only one hand is liable to have that hand cut off. Bhā. X. 22. 19[1-3].

अञ्जिष्ठ
Añjiṣṭha --a god of the Sutāra group. Br. IV. 1. 89.

अज्ञानम्
Ajñānam --of tamas quality and the source of all dfficulties; the enemy to knowledge; creates a thirst for desire (rāga). If not got rid of, one attains Tiryak-yoni. Br. IV. 3. 41 and 49; 4. 23. Vā. 102. 62, 69.

अटमान
Aṭamāna --the son of Meghasvāti and father of Aniṣṭakarman. Bhā. XII. 1. 24-25.

अट्टहास
Aṭṭahāsa^1 --the avatār of the Lord in the 20th dvāpara when people are fond of aṭṭhāsa in the Aṭṭahāsa hill of the Himālayas attended by Siddhas and Cāraṇas and yogins. Vā. 23. 190-1.

अट्टहास
Aṭṭahāsa  (II)--a Mt. in the Himalayas where was the avatār of Aṭṭahāsa. Vā. 23. 191.

अट्टहास
Aṭṭahāsa(m) --a tīrtham sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 68; Vā. 23. 191. 

अट्टहसी
Aṭṭahasī --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 88.

अट्टालक
Aṭṭālakas --generally frequented by evil spirits. Br. III. 7. 405; IV. 21. 14.

अणिमा
Aṇimā  (I)--an aiśvarya, one of the eight kinds; 1) Br. I. 2. 39; II. 29. 82; III. 3. 65; 36. 17; 67. 16; Vā. 2. 39. the first to be attained by the yogin; 2) Vā. 13. 3 and 10. leading to siddhi. 3) Vā. 57. 76; 92. 15.

अणिमा
Aṇimā  (II)--Siddhi devī on the 9th parvan of Cakrarājaratha; one of Uttama siddhis. Br. IV. 19. 4; 25. 59; 35. 104; 36. 5; 44. 108.

अणु
Aṇu --a measurement of time. Two aṇus make one Paramāṇu. Bhā. III. 11. 5.

अणुह
Aṇuha  (I)--the son of Vibhrāja; wife Kīrtī, daughter of Śuka; father of Brahmadatta. Vi. IV. 19. 43-5.

अणुह
Aṇuha  (II)--Satyaka? The eldest of Nīpa's sons; married Kṛtvī, the daughter of Śuka; father of Brahmadatta. Bhā. IX. 21. 24-25.

अणुह
Aṇuha  (III)--Married Kīrtimati, daughter of Śuka. Father of Brahmadatta. Br. III. 8. 94; 10. 82; Vā. 73. 31.

अणुह
Aṇuha  (IV)--son of Vibhrāja; married Kṛtvī, daughter of Śuka. Husband of Ṛcī. M. 49. 56-7; Vā. 99. 179. 

अण्ड
Aṇḍa --the egg shaped universe; the vyakta-rūpa of Viṣṇu described. See also Puruṣa. Vi. I. 2. 54-60.

अण्डम्
Aṇḍam --beyond Āloka. Here are the seven continents and earth surrounded by a sea of clouds. 1) Br. I. 1. 43f; II. 19. 154-5, 160; 21. 24; III. 59. 27; IV. 2. 230-1. The golden egglike aṇḍa emerges from Īśvara's seed and attains yoni (prakṛti), the latter being the embodiment of Nārāyaṇa, in a period of a thousand years. It became heaven and earth, ākāśa being in the middle. 2) M. 2. 29-32; 247. 43; 248. 1. The outside is covered with waters ten times the aṇḍa-covered by tejas,--successively covered by vāyu, by ākāśa, this by Bhūtādi; that by mahat and that in turn by avyakta each ten times the mass of its predecessor. These are the seven Prakṛtis. Avyakta is kṣetra and Brahmā ksetrajña. 3) Vā. 1. 50-52; 4. 82-9; 101. 227; Br. I. 3. 26. Brahmā born of. 4) Vā. 9. 122. Like the moon in Kumbha rāśi at the commencement of the Śukla pakṣa; there are several aṇḍams, each covered by seven characteristics of Prakṛti. 5) Vā. 49. 147-51.

अण्डकटाह
Aṇḍakaṭāha --consisting of Bhūrloka, Bhuvaḥ, Suvar, Mahar, Jana, Tapa and Satya; all in the shape of an umbrella, each covered by ten Prakṛtis more than the preceding. 1) Vā. 50. 78-81. A shell of egg encircling the dark regions beyond the Lokāloka; encircled by water ten times the earth in space; waters encompassed on the outer surface by fire, fire by air; air by sky; sky by Anger of elements; and that by intellect; the last girt by chief principle, Ananta. 2) Vi. II. 4. 95: 7. 22-5.

अतल
Atala  1) Bhā. II. 1. 27. --a thigh of the cosmic Puruṣa; is dependent on the loins of the Puruṣa. 2) Ib. II. 5. 40. An underworld, ruled by Bala, son of Maya. 3) Ib. V. 24. 7 & 16. The fourth world of pink (pīta) soil and residence of daityas like Kālanemi. 4) Br. II. 20. 12, 14, 32-34. 

अतलम्
Atalam --an underworld of dark earth; here is the house of Namuci, the Indra of the Asuras besides those of Śaṅkukarṇa, Nāgas, Rākṣasas, etc. White soil. Vā. 50. 11, 13 and 15-19. Vi. II. 5. 2, 3.

अतिकपिल
Atikapila --a son of Jyotiṣmat, after whom the kingdom got its name. Vi. II. 4. 36.

अतिकाय
Atikāya --a Rākṣasa who was killed in the war at Laṅkā. Bhā. IX. 10. 18.

अतिगुल्म
Atigulma --a son of Balarāma. Br. III. 71. 167.

अतिच्छन्दस्
Aticchandas --a poetic metre. Bhā. XI. 21. 41.

अतिजगती
Atijagatī --poetic metre. Bhā. XI. 21. 41.

अतितानम्
Atitānam --the name of divine Gāndharvam sung by Hāhā and Hūhū in Brahmaloka. Vi. IV. 1. 68.

अतिथि
Atithi  (I)--the son of Kuśa, Ramā's son and father of Niṣadha: a good looking monarch. Bhā. IX. 12. 1; Br. III. 63. 201; M. 12. 52; Vā. 88. 201; Vi. IV. 4. 105.

अतिथि
Atithi  (II)--a god of Ādya group. Br. II. 36. 69.

अतिथि
Atithi  (III)--honouring the guest is a kind of yāga. 1) Br. III. 15. 8-20; 21. 46. An imperative duty of a householder; 2) Vi. III. 9. 15; 11. 58-70; 78, 106-110; 15. 25. to be entertained in śrāddhas. 3) Vā. 79. 7-19. 

अतिथीश
Atithīśa --a varamūrti. Br. IV. 44. 49.

अतिथ्य
Atithya --a great Brāhman. Br. I. 1. 134.

अतितेजस्
Atitejas (Paulaha) --a sage of the epoch of the 3rd Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 80.

अतिनामा
Atināmā --a Paulastya, and sage of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Br. II. 36. 78; M. 9. 23; Vi. III. 1. 28.

अतिबल
Atibala  (I)--a medicinal plant used in the first bathing of a deity. M. 267. 14.

अतिबल
Atibala  (II)--a king of the Gandharvas. Vā. 62. 188.

अतिबला
Atibalā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 12.

अतिभानु
Atibhānu --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā. Bhā. X. 61. 10.

अतिबाहु
Atibāhu --a son of Svāyambhuva Manu. Vā. 31. 17.

अतिमान
Atimāna --a Paulastya. Vā. 62. 66.

अतिमाय
Atimāya --a son of Bhaṇḍa, and a commander. Br. IV. 21. 84; 26. 49. 

अतिरथ
Atiratha (Karṇa) --the son of Satyakarman, found a son discarded by Pṛthā in a basket on the banks of the Ganges. Vi. IV. 18. 27-8.

अतिरात्र
Atirātra  (I)--a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu and Naḍvalā. Bhā. IV. 13. 16; Br. II. 36. 79 & 106; M. 4. 42.

अतिरात्र
Atirātra  (II)--a son of Manu and Naḍvalā. Vi. I. 13. 5.

अतिरात्रम्
Atirātram --a sacred rite (yajña) produced by the Creator. 1) Bhā. III. 12. 40; Vā. 9. 51; 62. 67 and 91; 67. 50. Done by Kaśyapa. 2) Br. III. 5, 4; M. 44. 65; 58, 53. Punarvasu born in the middle of the ritual of Aśvamedha; 3) Vā. 96. 119; Br. III. 71, 120. fruit of, by honey gift in ceremonies; 4) Vā. 79. 11; Br. III. 15. 11. from the face of Brahmā. 5) Br. II. 8. 52; Vi. I. 5. 55.

अतिविभूति
Ativibhūti:  the son of Khaninetra and father of Karamdhama. Vi. IV. 1. 28-9.

अतिविराट्
Ativirāṭ --a poetic metre. Bhā. XI. 21. 41.

अतुनान्तक्य
Atunāntakya --a madhyamādhvaryu. Br. II. 33. 15.

अत्यष्टि
Atyaṣṭi --a poetic metre. Bhā. XI. 21. 41.

अत्याकरालगोज्वाल
Atyākarālagojvālas (c) --a Janapada of the Ketumāla. Vā. 44. 12.

अत्रय
Atraya --a tribe (Atris). M. 114. 43. 

अत्रायनि
Atrāyani --ārṣeyapravara (Aṅgiras). M. 196. 9.

अत्रि
Atri  (I)--a son of Brahmā, born of his eyes. 1) Bhā. III. 12. 22 & 24; M. 3. 6; 9. 27. Father of Soma, born of his eyes. 2) Bhā. IX. 14. 2-3; Br. III. 65. 1 & 47; Vā. 1. 138; 3. 3; 30. 48. Married Anasūyā, a daughter of Kardama (Dakṣa-Vā.). Their son was Dattātreya (s.v.). Taught Ānvīkṣikī to Alarka, Praḥlāda and others. 3) Bhā. I. 3. 11; III. 24. 22. Br. II. 9. 56. Paid a visit to Bhīṣma who was in his death-bed. 4) Bhā. I. 9. 7. Came to see Parīkṣit practising prāyopaveśa. 5) Bhā. I. 19. 9. A sage. 6) Ib. II. 7. 4. Vā. 90. 1-8. Was engaged with his wife in meditation at Mount Ṛkṣa by prāṇāyāma for the birth of a son. His praise of Trimūrtis who appeared before him, and blessed him with three glorious sons, being their own amśas. Accordingly Datta (Viṣṇu), Durvāsas (Śiva), and Soma (Brahmā) were born. 7) Bhā. IV. 1. 15-33; Vi. IV. 6. 5-6. Pointed out to Pṛthu's son, Indra running away with the consecrated horse twice and urged him to slay him. 8) Bhā. IV. 19. 12-15 and 21. Had not yet seen the Supreme Being. 9) Ib. IV. 29. 43. A sage of the Vaivasvata epoch. 10) Ib. VIII. 13. 5; Br. II. 38. 25. Went with Kṛṣṇa to Mithilā. 11) Bhā. X. 86. 18. The sage who presides over the month of Śukra 12) Ib. XII. 11. 35. and Śuci. 13) Br. II. 23. 5. Vā. 52. 6. Vi. II. 10. 7; III. 1. 32. A mantrakāra: took Uttānapāda as his son. 14) Br. II. 27. 104; 32. 96 & 113. Had a daughter, a Brahmavādinī. Visited Paraśurāma engaged in austerities. 15) Br. III. 23. 4. Worshipped Pitṛs by śrāddha and relieved Soma of the disease Rājayakṣma. 16) Br. III. 10. 111; Vā. 73. 63; Appointed by Brahmā for creation of the world he performed the tapas called anuttama when Śiva saw him: acted as hotā for Soma's Rājasūya: 16(a) M. 23. 2-20. Hermitage in the Himalayas, visited by Purūravas: 17) M. 102. 19; 118. 62 & 77; 120. 45; 126. 7. Praised Śiva out to destroy Tripuram. 18) M. 133. 67.

अत्रि
Atri  (II)--one of the sages who left for Piṇḍāraka. Bhā. XI. 1. 12. 

अत्रि
Atri  (III)--the third Prajāpati Of Svāyambhuva epoch, created by Brahmā from ahaṃ tṛtīya. Br. I. 1. 117; 5. 70; II. 9. 18, 23; Vā. 31. 16; 34. 62; 65. 45; Vi. V. 1. 17.

अत्रि
Atri  (IV) (c)--a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 50.

अत्रि
Atri  (V)--born in Vāruṇī yajña from Agni's flames; 1) Br. III. 1. 21 & 44; 8. 73; M. 171. 27; 192. 10; 195. 9; Vā. 62. 17; 64. 27; Vi. I. 7. 5, 7. Had ten beautiful and chaste wives, all daughters of Bhadrāśva and Ghṛtācī. His ten sons were all known as Ātreyas, 2) Vā. 70. 67-76. also Svastyātreyas; a mahaṛṣi and a mantrakṛt. Tra yārṣeya with Vasiṣṭha and Jātūkarṇa: a contemporary of Vṛddha Garga. 3) M. 145. 90, 107-9; 197. 1 & 4; 200. 19; 229. 2 & 3; Vā. 59. 104. One of the 18 writers on architecture. Has a place in the Viśvacakra. 4) M. 252. 2; 285-6.

अत्रि
Atri  (VI)--the avatār of the Lord in the 12th dvāpara in the Haimaka forest with sons with bath and ashes. Vā. 23. 155.

अत्रि
Atri  (VII)--a son of Gautama, an avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 164.

अत्रिघन
Atrighana --a special rite in the yajñas after the celebrated sage Atri. Vā. 70. 73.

अथर्वन्
Atharvan  (I)--married Śānti, a daughter of Kardama. It was he who spread yajña in the world. 1) Bhā. III. 24. 24. His son was Dadhyañca who had a horse's head. 2) Ib. IV. 1. 42. 

अथर्वन्
Atharvan  (II)--a Brāhman priest invited by Yudhiṣṭhira to officiate in his Rājasūya sacrifice. Bhā. X. 74. 9.

अथर्व
Atharva Veda --one of the four Vedas useful for kings. 1) Bhā., X. 53. 12; Vā. 9. 51; 60. 15, 20. Rearranged by Sumantu (s.v.) under the guidance of Vyāsa; in five parts. 2) Bhā. I. 4. 22; XII. 7. 1; Br. II. 34. 15; Vi. III. 4. 9 & 14; 6. 8, 13-14. Part of Viṣṇu. 3) Vi. V. 1. 37. Mantras connected with war. 4) Br. IV. 20. 104. Twenty-one Atharvas from the face of Brahmā. 5) Br. II. 8. 53.

अथर्वाङ्गिरस्
Atharvāṅgiras --name of the Veda personified, as the son of Prajāpati Aṅgiras and Sati: 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 19; Vā. 65. 98. Praise of Soma. 2) Br. III. 65. 12. To be uttered in founding a temple. 3) M. 265. 28.

अथर्वाङ्गीरसी
Atharvāṅgīrasī --taught by Vyāsa to Sumantu. Bhā. XII. 6. 53.

अथर्वा
Atharvā --a Laukikāgni; is Bhṛgu; father of Darpahā. Belongs to Dadhyaṅgātharvaṇa category. Vā. 29. 8, 9; Br. II. 12, 9.

अथार्विका
Athārvikā --5000+980 according to Ṛṣis like Aṅgīrasa. Vā. 61. 72.

अदर्शना
Adarśanā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 27. 

अदिति
Aditi  (I)--a daughter of Dakṣa and a wife of Kaśyapa. 1) Bhā. IX. 1. 10; VI. 6. 25; Br. II. 33. 17; III. 3. 56, 117; 71. 200; Vi. I. 15. 124; III. 1. 42. Mother of Vāmana-Hari and other gods. 2) Bhā. VIII. 13. 6; VI. 6. 38-39; VI. 18. 9; X. 3. 42; M. 172. 5; 178. 20; Vā., 96. 196; 97, 23. Was much concerned at the evacuation of Amarāvati by gods, and informed her husband of her grief. Kaśyapa consoled her saying that it was all Hari's māyā and everything would be rectified by His aid. Asked to the means of approaching Hari, Kaśyapa taught her the Payovrata. Observed the vrata for twelve days as directed. Hari heard her prayers, promised to be born in her womb to protect her sons, and desired that she should keep it a secret. She soon waited on Kaśyapa and became pregnant with Hari. Then Hari was praised by Brahmā. 3) Bhā. VIII. ch. 16 & 17. Birth of the Lord described. 4) Bhā. VIII. 18. 1-11; Br. III. 72. 22; 73. 75. Changed before her into a boy-brahmacārin. 5) Bhā. VIII. 18. 12. Worshipped for food and other things, while her sons the Ādityas are prayed to for attainment of heaven. 6) Ib. VIII. 18. 13-19; II. 3. 4; M. 171. 55-8. Her desire was fulfilled by Vāmana. Pleased with his anointing, gods sent their praises to Aditi on the exploits of Vāmana. 7) Ib. VIII. 23. 4, 21, 27; M. 244. 9-48; 245. 63; 246. 58. Kṛṣna took back the Kuṇḍalas which had been taken away by Naraka, and Satyabhāmā in her Lord's company bowed to Aditi and handed over the Kuṇḍalas. At this Aditi embraced her daughter-in-law. 8) Bhā. X. 59. 38; Ib. [65 (v) 6-10]; Vi. V. 29. 11, 35; 30 (whole). Prajāpati caused the tejas of the aṇḍam in her garbha, and removing it at the request of gods, made it into two pieces, and finding it weak, placed it on the lap of the Sungod (Mārtāṇḍa): given to dharma. 9) Br. III. 7. 277-94, 465. A part of Mother Earth. 10) Br. III. 71. 238; M. 6. 1. 5; 11. 2; 47. 9; 146. 18; 154. 351; 171. 29. A mother goddess. 11) M. 179. 15. Worshipped in housebuilding. 12) M. 253. 27. Mother of the 12 Ādityas the former Jayadevas. 13) Br. III. 4. 34; Vā. 66. 55; 60. 65. Known for strength. 14) Vā. 69. 92. Br. II. 13. 79. 

अदिति
Aditi  (II)--born of Dakṣa and son was Vivasvān. Vi. IV. 1. 6.

अदीन
Adīna --a son of Sahadeva and father of Jayatsena; a righteous soul. Vā. 93. 10; Vi. IV. 9. 27.

अदृश्यन्ती
Adṛśyantī --the wife of Śakti, and mother of Parāśara. Br. I. 2. 12; III. 8. 91; Vā. 2. 12; 70. 83.

अद्भुत
Adbhuta  (I)--the name of Indra of the 9th manvantara of the Rohita epoch. Bhā. VIII. 13. 19-20; Br. IV. 1. 61; Vi. III. 2. 22.

अद्भुत
Adbhuta  (II)--the son of Savanāgni (Sahasa-Br.) and father of Vividha. Vā. 29. 38; Br. II. 12. 41.

अद्भुत
Adbhutas --see Utpātas. M. 228. 2.

अद्म
Adma --a dānava. Br. III. 6. 10.

अद्रिका
Adrikā --an apsaras with whom Amāvasu sported. 1) Br. III. 7. 7; 10. 57 & 68. Living in the Acchoda lake. 2) Vā. 69. 6; 73. 3.

अद्विषेण
Adviṣeṇa --a mantrakṛt. Vā. 59. 97.

अधर्म
Adharma  (I)--a son of Brahmā, born of his back. 1) Bhā. III. 12. 25. Had for his wife Mrṣā. 2) Ib. IV. 8. 2. Three chief characteristics--pride, luxury and intoxication. 3) Ib. I. 17. 24. His son was Dambha and daughter Māyā, both of whom were adopted later on by the  childless Nirṛti. 4) Ib. IV. 8. 2. Five branches of: vidharma, paradharma, ābhāsa, upamā, and chala. 5) Ib. VII. 15. 12-14.

अधर्म
Adharma  (II)--wife, Himsā; sons Nikṛti, Anṛta. (daughter Nikṛtī-Vi. P.). Br. II. 9. 63; Vā. 10. 39; Vi. I. 7. 32.

अदश्छायाभय
Adaśchāyābhayas --Kaśyapa gotra-kāras. M. 199. 4.

अधश्शिरस्
Adhaśśiras --the name of a hell: also Adhomukham. He who receives bad gifts and from forbidden persons, who lives by astrology and those who do not request for sacrifice go to it. Br. IV. 2. 148 & 163; Vā. 101. 147, 161; Vi. II. 6, 4 & 18.

अधिदान्त
Adhidānta --a son of Hṛdīka. Br. III. 71. 141.

अधिपति
Adhipati --a son of Bhṛgu, and a deva. Br. III. 1. 90; Vā. 65. 87.

अधिपूरुष
Adhipūruṣa --the title earned by Svāyambhuva Manu for his great character. M. 3. 45.

अधिमास
Adhimāsa --the intercalary month; 1) Vā. 50. 201. fit for piṇḍa at Gayā. 2) Vā. 83. 42; 105. 18.

अधिरथ
Adhiratha --the son of Satkarman (Satyakarman-M.). Once playing on the banks of the Ganges, he found a male child in a box. It was born of Kunti and abandoned by her. Childless, he brought him up as his son; 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 12-13. also known as Sūta. 2) M. 48. 108. 

अधिराज
Adhirāja --in Rājasūya, Pṛthu was anointed as. Br. III. 8. 25.

अधिवासनम्
Adhivāsanam  (also Adhivāsam) [See Pratimā]--preliminary purification in connection with founding a new temple. M. 265. 49 & 52; 266. 1; 274. 57; 275. 3; 289. 11.

अधिसामकृष्ण
Adhisā(ī)makṛṣṇa --the son of Aśvamedhādatta. A great warrior ruling now--(sāmprataḥ)--Performed a long yajña extending over three years at Kurukṣetra on the Dṛṣadvatī; a Paurava; father of Nicaknu. Vā. 99. 258, 270; Vi. IV. 21. 6-7.

अधिसोमकृष्ण
Adhisomakṛṣṇa --the son of Śatānīka--‘the king now ruling’: performed three great sacrifices--one for three years at Puṣkara, the other two of two years' duration at Kurukṣetra and Dṛṣadvatī respectively-Father of Vivikṣu. M. 50. 66, 78.

अधीति
Adhīti --a son of Brahmā with Mantraśarīra. Vā. 67. 6.

अधीष्ट
Adhīṣṭa --a son of Brahmā with Mantraśarīra. Vā. 67. 6.

अधृति
Adhṛti --a god of Ābhūtarayas group. Br. II. 36. 55.

अधोमुख
Adhomukha --see Adhaśśiras. Br. IV. 2. 163.

अध्यवसाय
Adhyavasāya --one of the two vṛttis of Mahat. Vā. 4. 46. 

अध्वनि
Adhvani --a son of Āpa. Vi. I. 15. 111.

अध्वर
Adhvara --an yajña; fires in, described. Vā. 29. 41.

अध्वर्यु
Adhvaryu --one of the 16 Ṛtviks for an yajña, issued from the arms of Nārāyaṇa of Paraśurāma's sacrifice, was presented with the whole of the west: 1) Bhā. IX. 11. 2; 16. 21; M. 167. 7; 265. 26. Bhṛgu was Adhvaryu at Soma's Rājasūya. 2) M. 23. 20.

अनघ
Anagha  (I)--the son of Upadānavī: The Vaibhrāja king of Pāñcāla: Father of Brahmadatta. M. 21. 11.

अनघ
Anagha  (II)--a Mauneya. Vā. 69. 1.

अनघ
Anagha  (III)--a son of Trasu. Vā. 99. 133.

अनघ
Anagha  (IV)--a son of Ūrja and Vasiṣṭha; a sage of XIth epoch of Manu. Vi. I. 10. 13: III. 2. 31.

अनघा
Anaghā --a R. of Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 26.

अनङ्ग
Anaṅga  (I)--a madhyamādhvaryu. Br. II. 33. 17.

अनङ्ग
Anaṅga  (II)--another name of God of Love, after he was burnt to ashes by Śiva. M. 7. 23; 23. 30; 154. 272; 291. 32; Vā. 104. 48. 

अनङ्गदानव्रतम्
Anaṅgadānavratam --sacred to Hari: to be begun on Sunday when the star Hasta, Puṣya or Punarvasu was in the ascendant: duration being 13 months: originally communicated by Indra. M. 70. 33-62.

अनङ्गमदना
Anaṅgamadanā --a śakti devī on the 7th parvan of the Cakrarājaratha. Br. IV. 19. 25; 44, 124.

अनङ्गमदनातुरा
Anaṅgamadanāturā --a śakti on the 7th parvan of the Cakrarājaratha. Br. IV. 19. 25; 44, 124.

अनङ्गमालिनी
Anaṅgamālinī --a śakti devī on the 7th parvan of the Cakrarājaratha. Br. IV. 19. 26.

अनङ्गमेखला
Anaṅgamekhalā --a śakti devī. Br. IV. 44. 124.

अनङ्गरेखा
Anaṅgarekhā --a śakti devī. Br. IV. 44. 125.

अनङ्गलेखा
Anaṅgalekhā --a śakti devī on the 7th parva of Cakrarājaratha. Br. IV. 19. 25.

अनङ्गवती
Anaṅgavatī --the courtesan who observed the Vibhūtidvādaśī-vratam and became Prītī, the co-wife with Rati, to the Lord of Love in her next birth. M. 100. 18 & 32.

अनङ्गवेगि
Anaṅgavegi --a śakti devī on the 7th parva of Cakrarājaratha. Br. IV. 19. 25. 

अनङ्गा
Anaṅgā --was the Apsaras sent by Indra to ruin Hari's tapas. M. 61. 22.

अनङ्गाकुशा
Anaṅgākuśā --a śakti devī on the 7th parva of Cakrarājaratha. Br. IV. 19. 25; 44. 125.

अनङ्गाधारमालिनी
Anaṅgādhāramālinī --a śakti devī. Br. IV. 44. 125.

अनन्त
Ananta  (I)--the Tāmasī Kalā of Hari. Followers of Sātvata Tantra designate him Saṅkarṣaṇa. He bears the Earth on one of his 1000 hoods. From between his agitated brows came out Rudra exhibiting in eleven forms. The Nāga princes make obeisance to him for his blessings. He wears the Vaijayantī garland. His glory is sung by Nārada and Tumburu in the court of the Creator. Also known as Śeṣa. 1) Bhā III. 26. 25; IV. 9. 14; V. 25. 1-11; VII. 7. 10-11; Vi. II. 5. 13-27; V. 18. 54. Identified with Balarāma, the seventh son of Devakī. 2) Bhā. X. 1. 24; 2. 5. At the time of the deluge, withdraws the universe unto himself. 3) Ib. X. 68. 46. Identified with Hari; 4) Ib. XI. 16. 19. a Nāga; 5) Br. IV. 20. 53. ety. of; 6) M. 248. 38. Balarāma, an incarnation of. 7) Vi. V. 25. 3; 35. 3; Bhā. I. 14. 35.

अनन्त
Ananta  (II)--the sacred hill. Br. III. 13. 58.

अनन्त
Ananta  (III)--a king and the son of Vītihotra (Vīrahotra-Vā. P.). Father of Durjaya. Br. III. 69. 53; Vā. 94. 53.

अनन्ततृतीयाव्रतम्
Anantatṛtīyāvratam --see Giritanayāvratam. M. ch. 62. 

अनन्तभागिन्
Anantabhāgin --A Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 20.

अनन्तशयनम्
Anantaśayanam --a manifestation of Hari, as reposing on Śeṣa. M. 276. 8.

अनन्ता
Anantā --the wife of Svāyambhuva Manu. M. 4. 33.

अनपान
Anapāna  (I)--see Dadhivāhana. Br. III. 74. 102.

अनपान
Anapāna  (II)--the son of Aṅga and father of Diviratha. Vi. IV. 18. 15; Br. III. 74. 103.

अनपाया
Anapāyā --an apsaras. Br. III. 7. 5.

अनमित्र
Anamitra  (I)--a son of Yudhājit. Father of Nimna, and Śini. A third son was Vṛṣṇi. Bhā. IX. 24. 12-14; Br. III. 71. 20.

अनमित्र
Anamitra  (II)--a son of Nighna: went to the forest for penance. M. 12. 47-8.

अनमित्र
Anamitra  (III)--the youngest son of Mādrī and Vṛṣṇi (Sumitra-Vi. P.). Father of Nighna, Śini, (Chini-Vā. P.) Yudhājit, Vṛṣabha and Kṣetra. M. 45. 2-3, 22 & 25; Vā. 96. 99; Vi. IV. 13. 9; 14. 1.

अनमित्र
Anamitra  (IV)--a son of Mādrī. Vā. 96. 19; Br. I. 1. 123. 

अनरकम्
Anarakam --a Kṣetram in the Narmaḍā. After a bath here, there is no need to fear a hell. M. 193. 1-3; 194. 17.

अनरण्य
Anaraṇya  (I)--the son of Trasaddasyu and father of Haryaśva (Pṛṣadaśva-Vi. P.); killed by Rāvaṇa in his digvijaya. Bhā. IX. 7. 4; Vi. IV. 3. 17-18.

अनरण्य
Anaraṇya  (II)--the son of Sambhūta, killed by Rāvaṇa. Br. III. 63. 74; Vā. 88. 75-6.

अनरण्य
Anaraṇya  (III)--the son of Sarvakarman. M. 12. 47.

अनर्क
Anarkas --a piśāca clan. Vā. 69. 264.

अनर्वन्
Anarvan --a follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra. Bhā., VI. 10. 19, 31.

अनल
Anala  (I)--a Vasava, (Tejas) has a son Kumāra through Svāhā. Śākha, Viśākha, and Naigameya were other sons (see Agni). Married Śivā, daughter of Hari and had two sons born with qualities of fire. Father of Skanda and Sanatkumāra. Br. III. 3. 21; M. 5. 21-5; 203. 3; Vi. I. 15. 110, 115; Vā. 66. 20, 24.

अनल
Anala  (II)--a chief monkey. Br. III. 7. 235.

अनल
Anala  (III)--a hill of the Rākṣasas. Vā. 39. 53. 

अनल
Anala  (IV) (Agni)--one became threefold at the instance of Purūravas; 1) Vi. IV. 6. 94. the presiding deity of svarṇa or gold; 2) Vi. V. 1. 14. different kinds of; 3) Vā 53. 5. five kinds of, overcome by Kṛṣṇa in Bāṇa's war. 4) Vi. V. 33. 20.

अनल
Anala  (V)--the son of Niṣadha and father of Nabhas. Vi. IV. 4. 106.

अनवद्या
Anavadyā --an Apsaras. Vā. 69. 48.

अनवम
Anavama  (Bahava--s.v)--son of Cakora and father of Śivasvāti. Bhā. XII. 1. 26.

अनवशा
Anavaśā --an Apsaras. Vā. 69. 48.

अनसूय
Anasūya --a Kaśyapa and a Trayārṣeya. M. 199. 12.

अनसूया
Anasūyā --the wife of the sage Atri (s.v.) and a daughter of Kardama (Dakṣa-Vā. P. and Vi. P.). Mother of Datta, Durvāsas, and Soma; 1) Bhā. I. 3. 11; III. 24: 22; IV. 1. 15; Vi. I. 7, 7, 25. mother of five Ātreyas and a daughter Śruti. 2) Vā. 10. 28, 31; 28. 18-9; Br. II. 9. 52 and 56; 11. 22.

अनादृष्ट
Anādṛṣṭa --a rājaṛṣi; a brother of Vasudeva. Vā: 96. 148; Vā. 99. 127.

अनादृष्टि
Anādṛṣṭi --son of Asmaki. Vā. 96. 186. 

अनाधृष्टि
Anādhṛṣṭi --a son of Śūra and Bhojā. Br. III. 71. 149 and 189; M. 46. 3.

अनायु
Anāyu --a daughter of Dakṣa: a consort of Kaśyapa, and a mother goddess. Fond of eating. Br. III. 3. 56; 7. 468; M. 171. 29.

अनायुषा
Anāyuṣā --Had Araru and other four sons; 1) Br. III. 6. 30. mother of diseases. 2) M. 171. 59.

अनाशकफलम्
Anāśakaphalam --a bath in the prescribed manner for a month in the Pryāga; attained by (oneness with godhead). M. 108. 2 & 14.

अनाहिताग्नि
Anāhitāgni --those who do not perform yajñas, as opposed to agnihotrins. Vā. 30. 6.

अनिरुद्ध
Aniruddha  (I)--One of the four forms of Hari. 1) Bhā. 1. 5. 37; Vi. 16. 18; X. 16. 45; 40. 21; XII. 11. 21. M. 276. 9. Invoked as a principal divinity. Source of all sounds (śabdayoni); presiding over the mind as fourth in order. 2) Bhā. III. 1. 34. The supreme ruler of all senses. 3) Ib. III. 26. 28; IV. 24. 36. Created specially in the battle of Lalitā with Bhaṇḍa. 4) Br. IV. 29. 128.

अनिरुद्ध
Aniruddha  (II)--the son of Pradyumna and Rukmavati; carried away by air by Citralekhā, to the harem of the daughter of Baṇā at her instance. For him Bāṇa had his arms reduced from thousand to two. Married Rocanā, grand-daughter of Rukmin at Bhojakaṭa to which Kṛṣṇa, Balarāma and others went. Came back to Dvārakā with his newly wedded wife. 1) Bhā. X. 61. 18. 23[9], 25-26 & 40. Seen in a dream by Uṣā. Picture of him drawn by Citralekhā, who made him enjoy Uṣā's  company at Śoṇitapura. Bāṇa came to know of this and imprisoned him to the great regret of his daughter. 2) Ib. X. 62. 12. 20-27, and 35. Nārada communicated the news of Aniruddha's imprisonment to Kṛṣṇa and Vṛṣṇis. These departed to Śoṇitapura, beseiged it, and humbled the pride of Bāṇa. The latter agreed to set Aniruddha free and allow him to marry his daughter. Left for Dvārakā with Uṣa. 3) Ib. X. ch. 63 (whole). Famous for his speed in battle. 4) Ib. I. 14. 30. Unable to recover the dead child of the Dvārakā Brāḥmaṇa. 5) Ib. X. 89. 31 and 41. Father of Vajra. 6) Ib. X. 90. 33, 36-7. Went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse. 7) Ib. X. 82. 7. Fought with Sātyaki at Prabhāsā. 8) Ib. XI. 30, 16. One of the five vamśavīras. 9) Br. III. 72. 2. Mṛgaketana was a son of his: an authority on architecture. 10) M. 47. 23; 93. 51; 248. 49; 252. 3.

अनिरुद्ध
Aniruddha  (III)--a vamśavīra. Vā. 97. 2; 111. 21.

अनिल
Anila  (I)--The God of Wind invoked. 1) Bhā. III. 6. 16. A surname of Vāyu; 2) Br. II. 25. 12. father of Bhīmasena. 3) Vi. IV. 14. 35; Bhā. IX. 22. 27.

अनिल
Anila  (II)--a Vāsava: married Śivā and had two sons --Manojava and Avijñatagati. See Iśāna. Br. II. 10. 80; III. 3. 21; M. 5. 21; 203. 3; Vā. 66. 20, 25; Vi. I. 15. 110, 114.

अनिल
Anila  (III)--The Vāyu Purāṇa narrated by Wind-god with samāsa bandhas and rhythm; 1) Vā. 3. 8. 23,000 stanzas. 2) Vā. 104. 7.

अनिल
Anila  (IV)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Mitravindā. Bhā. X. 61. 16.

अनिष्टकर्मन्
Aniṣṭakarman --son of Aṭamāna and father of Hāleya. Bhā. XII. 1. 25. 

अनीक
Anīka --a son of first Sāvarṇa Manu Br. IV. 1. 65.

अनीकवान्
Anīkavān --a son of Arka Agni. Vā. 29. 40; Br. II. 12. 43.

अनीचकम्
Anīcakam --the continent lying round Śyāma hill. M. 122. 23.

अनीह
Anīha --a son of Devānīka and father of Pāriyātra. Bhā. IX. 12. 2.

अनु
Anu  (I)--a son of Svāyambhuva Manu. Knows the power of the yoga of Hari. Bhā. II. 7. 44.

अनु
Anu  (II)--a son of Yayāti and Śarmiṣṭhā. Refused to part with his youth to his father. 1) Bhā. IX. 18. 33 & 41; Br. I. 1. 133; III. 68. 16-17, 51-79; IV. M. 24. 54; 32. 10; Vi. IV. 10. 10-15. Became overlord of the north part of the kingdom. 2) Bhā. IX. 19. 22. Br. III. 68. 90; 73. 126; Vā. I. 156: 93. 17; Vi. IV. 10. 32. Had three sons Sabhānara, Cakṣu and Parākṣa. 3) Bhā. IX. 23. 1; Br. III. 74. 12; M. 48-10: Cursed to die in youth suffering from diarrhoea. Originator of several mleccha groups. 4) M. 33. 21-24; 34. 30.

अनु
Anu  (III)--the son of Kuruvaśa (Kuravaśa-Burnouf) and father of Puruhotra. Bhā. IX. 24. 5-6.

अनु
Anu  (IV)--the son of Kapotaroman and father of Andhaka. His friend was Tumburu. Bhā. IX. 24. 20.

अनु
Anu  (V)--(alias Vaina) a pupil of Laugākṣi. Br. II. 35. 41. 

अनु
Anu  (VI)--the son of Kumāravamśa and father of Purumitra. Vi. IV. 12. 42.

अनु
Anu  (VII)--a son of Viloma and friend of Tumburu and father of Ānakadundubhi. Vi. IV. 14. 13-14.

अनु
Anu  (VIII)--the son of Yadu and father of three sons. Vi. IV. 18. 1.

अनुकृष्ण
Anukṛṣṇa --a Carakādhvaryu. Br. II. 33. 13.

अनुगङ्गाप्रयाग
Anugaṅgāprayāga(c) --lie of territory under the Nāgas 1) Br. III. 74. 194. and the Guptas. 2) Vā. 99. 383.

अनुग्रह
Anugraha Sarga --divided into four, viparyaya, śakti, tuṣṭi, and siddhi; accounts for vivṛtta, and the varttamāna (present) in cycle; this is the fifth sarga or creation. Vā. 6. 57, 67-9; 9. 117.

अनुग्रहेश्वर
Anugraheśvara--(Sadyojāta)  a varamūrti. Br. IV. 44. 50.

अनुचर
Anucara --a god of the Haritagaṇa. Br. IV. 1. 84.

अनुजीविन्
Anujīvins --officials (lit. dependents on the king)--rules for the personal conduct of. M. 216. 1-38.

अनुतप्ता
Anutaptā  (I)--another name for R. Sukumārī of Śākadvīpa. Vā. 49. 91. 

अनुतप्ता
Anutaptā  (II)--a R. in the Plakṣadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 19; Vā. 49. 17; Vi. II. 4. 11.

अनुतापन
Anutāpana --one of the 61 sons of Danu. Bhā. VI. 6. 31.

अनुत्तमम्
Anuttamam --the name of the tapas performed by Atri (s.v.) for creation. M. 23. 2.

अनुदृक्साम
Anudṛksāma --one of the Marutgaṇas. Vā. 67. 129.

अनुपदेव
Anupadeva --a son of Akrūra and Ugrasenī. Vā. 96. 112.

अनुपर्वतम्
Anuparvatam --the forest noted for padma class of elephants between the Lauhitya and Sindhu; the name of Yamavanam (s.v.). Br. III. 7. 359; Vā. 69. 241.

अनुपालिका
Anupālikā --a daughter of Vākā. Br. III. 8. 56.

अनुभानु
Anubhānu --a Dānava. Vā. 68. 14.

अनुभूमि
Anubhūmi --a Carakādhvaryu. Br. II. 33. 13.

अनुमति
Anumati  (I)--a daughter of Śraddhā and Aṅgīras. 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 34. Wife of Dhātā and mother of Pūrṇimā. 2) Ib. VI. 18. 3.

अनुमति
Anumati  (II)--a R. in Śālmalidvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 10. 

अनुमति
Anumati  (III)--a śakti devī on the Ṣoḍaśapatrābja. Br. IV. 32. 12.

अनुमति
Anumati  (IV)--a time in the evening of Pratipada comprising two lavas. 1) M. 133. 36; 141. 33, 40 and 51; Vā. 56. 35, 55. The day when one digit of the moon is deficient, fit for making gifts. 2) Vi. II. 8. 80.

अनुमति
Anumati  (V)--one of the Bhārgava-gotrakāras. M. 195. 28.

अनुमति
Anumati  (VI)--a daughter of Smṛti and Aṅgiras; 1) Vā. 28. 15; Vi. I. 10. 7. the name of the first pūrṇimā. 2) Vā. 50. 201; Br. II. 11. 18.

अनुमन्ता
Anumantā --a god of Ādya group: 1) Br. II. 36. 69; III. 3. 16. a śādhya. 2) Vā. 66. 15.

अनुम्लोचन्ती
Anumlocantī --an Apsaras. Vā. 69. 50.

अनुम्लोचा
Anumlocā  (I)--resides in the sun's chariot during the month of Bhādrapada. Vi. II. 10. 10.

अनुम्लोचा
Anumlocā  (II)--The apsaras presiding over the month Nabhasya. (nabho-nabha). Bhā. XII. 11. 38; Br. II. 23. 10; III. 7. 15.

अनुराधा
Anurādhā --a nakṣatra. Vā. 66. 50; 82. 9.

अनुरूपमाय
Anurūpamāya --a Vasu, and a son of Dharma and Sudevī. M. 171. 47. 

अनुर्देश्य
Anurdeśya --see Ahirbudhnya. Br. II. 12. 26.

अनुलोम
Anuloma --a Saimhikeya. Vā. 68. 19.

अनुवत्सर
Anuvatsara --the fourth year in a five year yuga; 1) Bhā. III. 11. 14; V. 22. 7; Vi. II. 8. 72. is Vāyu. 2) Br. II. 13. 115, 119, 134; 21. 134; 28. 22; M. 141. 18; Vā. 31. 31. (Yajur samhitā) ahorātrakara. 3) Vā. 31. 27; 56. 20; 50. 183; Br. II. 13. 134.

अनुवंश
Anuvaṃśa --Devāvṛdha and his son Babhru belonged to this line. M. 44. 57.

अनुवह
Anuvaha --the chief of the 6th vātaskandha, situated between the planets and the Saptaṛṣimaṇḍala. Br. III. 5. 87.

अनुविन्द
Anuvinda --a prince of Avanti. Brother of Vinda and and Mitravindā: Shared Vinda's (s.v) views and did not wish his sister to be married to Kṛṣṇa as against Duryodhana. 1) Bhā. X. 58. 30; Br. III. 71. 158. Stationed at the south gate of Mathurā by Jarāsandhā, 2) Bhā. X. 50. 11[3]. and also on the south during the seige of Gomanta. 3) Ib. X. 52. 11[9]. Son of Rājadhidevī according to the Bhāgavata. 4) Ib. X. 58. 31; Vā. 96. 157; Vi. IV. 14. 43.

अनुवृत्ता
Anuvṛttā --a daughter of Rṣā (Rṣi-Vā. P.); gave birth to the class of maṇdūkas, aineya and śambaka varieties. Br. III. 7. 414 and 418; Vā. 69. 291, 295.

अनुव्रत
Anuvrata  (I)--a son of Śrutakīrti. M. 46. 5. 

अनुव्रत
Anuvrata  (II)--the son of Kṣema, ruled for 64 years. M. 271. 25.

अनुव्रत
Anuvratas --a class of people in Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 27.

अनुषङ्ग
Anuṣaṅga --the one after sṛṣṭisarga; the second pāda of the purāṇa; 1) Br. I. 1. 39; II. 31. 127; III. 1. 1; IV. 4. 43; Vā. 4. 13; 65. 1-2. equal to Tretā; of 3000; 2) Vā. 32. 61; Vā. 58. 126; 103. 44. ends with the 99th chapter of the Vāyu. 3) Vā. 100. 2.

अनुष्टुब्
Anuṣṭub --a poetic metre; 1) Bhā. XI. 21. 41; Vā. 9. 52. a horse yoked to the sun's chariot; 2) Vā. 51. 64; Br. II. 22. 72; M. 125. 47; Vi. II. 8. 5. from the fourth face of Brahmā. 3) Br. II. 8. 53. Vi. I. 5. 56.

अनुह्लाद
Anuhl(r)āda --a son of Kayādhu and Hiraṇyakaśipu; wife Sūrmyā. Father of Bāṣkala and Mahīṣa; 1) Bhā. VI. 18. 13, 16: Br. III. 5. 33. also of Vāyu and Sinīvāli from whom the hālāhala gaṇa came; 2) M. 6. 9; Vā. 67. 70, 75; Vi. I. 15. 142. as asura of the Vitalam. His daughter was married by Rajatanābha, the yakṣa. 3) Br. II. 20. 26; III. 7. 119; Vā. 50. 25.

अनूप
Anūpa(c) --the kingdom got by Sūta from Pṛthu. The people were Anūpas, a Vindhya tribe. Br. II. 36. 172; 16. 65; Vā. 62. 147.

अनूरु
Anūru --(Aruṇa) a son of Tārkṣya and Kadrū. Charioteer of the sun. Bhā. VI. 6. 22. 

अनृतम्
Anṛtam  (as opposite to satyam) when falsehood is tolerated. 1) Bhā. VIII. 19. 38-43. Bali shrinks from it. 2) Ib. VIII. 20. 2-5. No pātaka on five occasions: Jest or fun, speaking to women, for a marriage, when life is in danger, and when deprived of his wealth. 3) M. 31. 16.

अनृतम्
Anṛtam --son of Himsā and Adharma; father of Bhaya and Naraka. Br. II. 9. 63; Vā. 10. 39.

अनेक
Aneka --a son of Raucya Manu. Br. IV. 1. 104.

अनेकक्षत्रबद्ध
Anekakṣatrabaddha --a son of Raucya Manu. Vā. 100. 109.

अनेकजन्मजनन
Anekajanmajanana --a son of Anala. M. 203. 6.

अनेनस्
Anenas  (I)--the son of Kakustha (Paurañjaya-Bhā.) of Pṛthu. Bhā. IX. 6. 20; Br. III. 63. 26; Vā. 88. 25; Vi. IV. 2. 33.

अनेनस्
Anenas  (II)--a son of Āyu and father of Śuddha. Bhā. IX. 17. 2 and 11; Br. III. 67. 2; Vi. IV. 8. 3.

अनेह
Aneha --a Pravara. M. 196. 31.

अनौपम्या
Anaupamyā --the wife of Bāṇāsura. Illtreated by mother-in-law and sister-in-law she was initiated into a mantra by Nārada to control them and to be ever pleasing to her husband. By this she left the strict path of chastity; offered gifts to the sage who refused them on the plea of his plenty. M. 187. 25-52. 

अन्त
Anta --1000 crores×niyuta (1 lakh). Vā. 101. 98.

अन्तक
Antaka  (I)--surname of Yama: milkman of Pitṛs on the earth: ety. Bhā. VI. 10. 15; Br. II. 36. 209; M. 10. 19; 213. 6.

अन्तक
Antaka  (II)--a surname of Śiva. Br. III. 3. 81.

अन्तक
Antaka  (III)--a son of Vasumitra, ruled for 2 years. M. 272. 29.

अन्तकारि
Antakāri --the tāmasic aspect of Svayambhū. Vā. 66. 103.

अन्तकाल
Antakāla --prescriptions for; 1) Bhā. II. 1. 15-21; yogic methods laid down. 2) Ib. H. 2. 14-23.

अन्तर
Antara --the son of Pṛthuśravas; in previous births the son of Yājña; also called Uśanas, performed 100 horse sacrifices as king. Vā. 95. 22, 23.

अन्तरक्षय
Antarakṣaya --reference to the deluge in the Cākṣusa antara. M. 2. 1 and 14.

अन्तरनर्मदा
Antaranarmadā (c) --a western country; Narmada tribes. Br. II. 16. 61; M. 140. 50.

अन्तरा
Antarā --one of 44 apsarases. Vā. 69. 4. 

अन्तरिक्ष
Antarikṣa  (I)--a son of Ṛṣabha and Jayanti. Brother of Bharata. A bhāgavata and sage; 1) Bhā. V. 4. 11; XI. 2. 21. expounded to Nimi the nature of Māyā and mentions how the pure jñāna shines as threefold by the work of illusion. 2) Ib. XI. 3. 2[1-4]-16.

अन्तरिक्ष
Antarikṣa  (II)--a son of Mura (s.v.) who went to the field to attack Kṛṣṇa who caused the death of his father. Bhā. X. 59. 12.

अन्तरिक्ष
Antarikṣa  (III)--the son of Puṣkara and father of Sutapas. Bhā. IX. 12. 12.

अन्तरिक्ष
Antarikṣa  (IV)--the 13th Veda Vyāsa: 1) Br. II. 35. 120. Vi. III. 3. 14. Heard the Purāṇa from Triviṣṭa, and narrated it to Trayyāruṇi 2) Br. IV. 4. 62; Vā. 103. 61. (CarṣiVā. P.)

अन्तरिक्ष
Antari(ī)kṣa  (V)--an Ādya god; a devagaṇa. Br. II. 36. 69; Vā. 62. 59.

अन्तरिक्ष
Antarikṣa  (VI)--the son of Kinnarāśva (Kinnara-Vā. P.); and father of Suparṇa (Suṣeṇa--M. P.). M. 271. 9; Vā. 99. 285; Vi. IV. 22. 5.

अन्तरिक्षम्
Antarikṣam --the Bhuvarloka or the region between earth and heaven. 1) Vā. 23. 107; 24. 18; 30. 98; 47. 29; 64. 10; 101. 19; 110. 49. One account is that Yayāti made this his abode when he was sent away from heaven; 2) M. 35. 4; 38. 20; 39. 11; 41. 8 & 10. to be propitiated as a deity in palace building. 3) Ib. 268. 12.

अन्तर्गिरि
Antargiri --a tribe. M. 114. 44.

अन्तर्गिरिबहिर्गिर
Antargiribahirgiras --Peoples of an eastern country. Br. II. 16. 53; Vā. 45. 122. 

अन्तर्धान
Antardhāna  (I)--a surname of Vijitāśva (s.v.); got from Indra the power of moving about, unseen by others. Bhā. IV. 24. 5.

अन्तर्धान
Antardhāna  (II) (Antarddhi)--A son of Pṛthu; wife Śikhaṇḍinī: father of Havirdhāna, and Mārīca. Br. II. 37. 23; M. 4. 45; Vā. 63. 22; Vi. I. 14. 1.

अन्तशिला
Antaśilā --R. originating from the Vindhyas. Vā. 45. 103.

अन्तःपुराणि
Antaḥpurāṇi --harems, origin of. Vā. 8. 100.

अन्तःपुराध्यक्ष
Antaḥpurādhyakṣa --Superintendent of the harem and his qualification. M. 215. 42; 216. 9.

अन्तावसायिन्
Antāvasāyin --an untouchable. Br. III. 14. 88; Vā. 79. 24.

अन्तिक
Antika --a son of Yadu. M. 43. 7.

अन्तिनार
Antināra  (I)--the son of Jvalanā and Auceya; wife Manasvinī. Father of two sons and a daughter Gaurī, mother of Māndhatṛ. M. 49. 7-8.

अन्तिनार
Antināra  (II)--the son of Ṛteṣu and father of three sons, Sumati and others. Vi. IV. 19. 3-4.

अन्त्य
Antya --a son of Bhṛgu, and a deva. Br. III. 1. 89. 

अन्त्य
Antya(Janmanā) --members of the fourth caste: home of. M. 207. 19; 227. 54; 255. 14.

अन्त्यज
Antyajas --to follow the vṛtti of their ancestors. Also known Antevasāyins: 1) Bhā. VII. 11. 30; 14. 11. a low caste to be abandoned: 2) Br. IV. 7. 3, 8, 19 and 67; 8. 10. also Antyayoni. 3) Ib. II. 31. 40.

अन्त्यावसायि
Antyāvasāyi --an untouchable. Vā. 79. 24.

अन्ध
Andha --R. of Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 18.

अन्धक
Andhaka  (I)--a son of Sātvata [Sātvatī (Kausalya)]: suspected Kṛṣṇa of having taken away Syamantaka. 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 6; Br. III. 71. 1. 36, 53; Vā. 96. 2; Vi. IV. 13. 1. A mahābhoja who married the daughter of Kaṅka and was father of four sons, Kukura and others. 2) M. 44. 48-61; Vi. IV. 14. 12.

अन्धक
Andhaka  (II)--son of Anu and father of Dundubhi. Bhā. IX. 24. 20.

अन्धक
Andhaka  (III)--a son of Viloma, and a friend of Tumburu: also known as Danodakadundubhi. Br. III. 71. 118.

अन्धक
Andhaka  (IV)--a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 82.

अन्धक
Andhaka  (V)--the 8th among twelve incarnations, after the battle of that name. Here Trayambaka slew thousands of Asuras: 1) M. 47. 44-50. in the Varāha Kalpa. 2) Vā. 97. 75. 

अन्धक
Andhaka  (VI)--the asura killed by Śiva: Āḍi and Baka were his sons; attempted to abduct the Devī in the presence of Śiva in the Mahākālavana of Avanti. Smitten by Pāśupata, blood came out of his body, out of which were born numberless Andhakas (s.v.) who overpowered Rudra. The latter created a number of Mātṛs who were not enough to meet them. Vāsudeva was thought of, and he created one Śuṣkarevati who drank off the blood of Andhakas. On his submission he was admitted to the group of Gaṇeśas. M. 55. 16; 156. 11-12; 179. 2-40; 252. 5-19.

अन्धक
Andhaka  (VII)--an elder Yādava advised in the council to secure the return of Akrūra; it was adopted. Vi. IV. 13. 114-137.

अन्धक
Andhakas  (I)--a community of the Yādava tribe 1) Bhā. I. 11. 11; 14. 25; II. 4. 20; Vā. 86. 28. defending Dvārakā; at Dvāravatī their overlord was Ugrasena. 2) Bhā. X. 1. 69; 39. 25; 45, 15. Praise the heroic deeds of Hari. 3) Bhā. IX. 24. 63. Relieved by Kamsa's death. 4) Ib. X. 45. 15. Ended their lives by fighting their kinsmen. 5) Ib. XI. 29. 39; 30. 18. Kṛṣṇa, an Andhaka. 6) Br. III. 61. 23; 71. 85 & 143-144. Kingdom of. 7) M. 114. 36. Their line; 8) M. 44. 61. 85; 47. 33. fetch Balarāma and Kṛṣṇa to Dvāraka. 9) Vā. 96. 84.

अन्धक
Andhakas  (II)--the Asuras born of the blood of Andhaka Asura, hit by the pāśupata of Rudra. To counteract their evil propensities Rudra created a number of Mātṛs who could not bring about the desired effect. Hence Vāsudeva created a Śuṣkarevatī who brought about their destruction by drinking off their blood. M. 179. 7-37.

अन्धकार
Andhakāra  (I)--a son of Dyutimat after whom the kingdom Andhakāra came to be known. Br. II. 14. 22, 25. 

अन्धकार
Andhakāra  (II)--the eighth battle of Devas and Asuras. Br. III. 72. 75 & 82; Vā. 97. 75.

अन्धकारक
Andhakāraka  (I) (c)--a kingdom of Krauñcadvīpa: also a name of the hill in that region. Br. II. 14. 25; 19. 67 & 72; M. 122. 81, 85; Vā. 49. 61, 67.

अन्धकारक
Andhakāraka  (II)--a Mt. in Krauñcadvīpa. M. 122. 81; Vi. II. 4. 50.

अन्धकारक
Andhakāraka  (III)--a son of Dyutimān; after his name a Janapada. Vā. 33. 21, 23; Vi. II. 4. 48.

अन्धकासुरमर्दिन्
Andhakāsuramardin --a surname of Śiva. Br. III. 25. 12.

अन्धकूप
Andhakūpa --one of the 28 hells. Those who do not follow the prescribed course of life and who have no sympathy for the sufferings they inflict on others are subject to affliction in this hell. Bhā. V. 26. 7 and 17.

अन्धतामिस्र
Andhatāmisra --one of 28 hells. Here the person who deceives the husband and robs him of his wife and property is made to suffer. Bhā. III. 30. 28 & 33; V. 26. 7 & 9.

अन्धतामिस्रम्
Andhatāmisram --a hell. Vi. I. 6. 41.

अन्धिनी
Andhinī --one of the five devīs on the third parva of the Kiricakra of Lalitā. Br. IV. 20. 9 & 38. 

अन्ध्र
Andhra  (I)--born of Dīrghatamas and Bali's wife. (Burnouf's reading--Oḍra). Bhā., IX. 23. 5.

अन्ध्र
Andhra  (II)--the son of Dṛṣadaśva (Vṛṣadaśva-Vā. P.). Br. III. 63. 27; Vā. 88. 26.

अन्ध्र
Andhra  (III) (c)--a Janapada under the Devarakṣitas. Vā. 99. 385; Vi. IV. 24. 64.

अन्ध्र
Andhras --a people of the southern country ruled for 300 years; 1) Bhā., XII. 1. 22; Vā. 45. 127; 47. 44; 78. 69; 99. 268, 361. a sinful tribe got purified by praying to Hari; 2) Bhā. II. 4. 18. defeated by Bharata. 3) Ib. IX. 20. 30. See Āṇdhras. 4) M. 50. 76.

अन्ध्रक
Andhraka --the Śuṅga, ruled for 2 years. Vā. 99. 339.

अन्ध्रक
Andhrakas --succeeded the Kaṇva dynasty of kings. Thirty of them ruled for 456 years. Kingdom of: Br. III. 73. 109; 74. 160, 170, 178, 197, 229-30; Vā. 98. 108; Bhā. XII. 1. 22-28.

अन्ध्रवाक
Andhravākas --people of an eastern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 53; Vā. 45. 11.

अन्न
Anna --gift of, the best of all; especially in a śrāddha: 1) Br. III. 16. 3, 52-5; 68, 66; Vā. 80. 55-7 (cf. Rāmā. II. ch. 103). Annavikrayam condemned. 2) Br. IV. 8. 44-58.

अन्नपूर्णा
Annapūrṇā --a devī in the Cintāmaṇigṛha. Br. IV. 36. 23.

अन्नाद
Annāda  (I)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Mitravindā. Bhā. X. 61. 16. 

अन्नाद
Annāda  (II)--a son of Agni Arka. Br. II. 12. 43.

अन्य
Anya  (I)--a son of Bhṛgu. Vā. 65. 87.

अन्य
Anya  (II)--a rājaṛṣi, becoming a Brāhmaṇa. Vā. 91. 116.

अन्यादृक्
Anyādṛk --one of the seven Maruts in the fourth marutgaṇa. Br. III. 5. 96-7; Vā. 67. 127.

अन्यादृक्ष
Anyādṛkṣas --one of the names in the fifth marutgaṇa. Vā. 67. 128.

अन्यायतः
Anyāyataḥ --a son of Bhṛgu. Vā. 65. 87.

अन्वता
Anvatā --an Apsaras. Vā. 69. 48.

अन्वष्टका
Anvaṣṭakā --the ninth day in the latter half of the three (or four) months following the full moon in Agrahāyana, Pauṣa, Māgha, (Phālguna). The fourth month is mentioned in the Purāṇa. Vā. 81. 4, 5.

अन्वाहार्य
Anvāhārya --the Dakṣiṇāgni. Vā. 97. 25.

अन्वाहार्यपचन
Anvāhāryapacana --the particular Agni from which Vṛtra was born. Bhā. VI. 9. 12. 

अन्वाधानक्रिया
Anvādhānakriyā --a fire rite on the conjunction of the parvas. Br. II. 28. 37.

अपः
Apaḥ  (I)--one of the ten branches of the Harita group of Devas. Vā. 100. 89.

अपः
Apaḥ  (II)--water: variations in temperature explained in relation to the solar rays. Br. II. 21. 59-62.

अपग
Apagas --a tribe. Vā. 45. 120.

अपचिति
Apaciti --a daughter of Marīci and Sambhūti. Vā. 28. 9.

अपत्तन
Apattanas --Gandharvas in the Hemakakṣa hill; their ruler is Rājarāja Kapiñjala. Vā. 39. 52.

अपथ
Apathas --the people of a mountain kingdom. M. 114. 55.

अपप्रावरण
Apaprāvaraṇas --a hill tribe. Br. II. 16. 67.

अपरा
Aparā --one of the thirteen wives of Vāsudeva. Vā. 96. 160.

अपराजित
Aparājita  (I)--fought with Namuci in Devāsura war. Bhā. VIII. 10. 30.

अपराजित
Aparājita  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Mādrī. Bhā., X. 61. 15. 

अपराजित
Aparājita  (III)--the horse on which Lalitā rode to fight Kuraṇḍa. Br. IV. 22. 94.

अपराजित
Aparājita  (IV)--a Rudra. M. 171. 38; Vi. I. 15. 122.

अपराजिता
Aparājitā  (I)--an elephant at one of the four cardinal points to maintain the balance of the worlds. Bhā. V. 20. 39.

अपराजिता
Aparājitā  (II)--(R.) of Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 26.

अपराजिता
Aparājitā  (III)--a mindborn mother; following Māyā. M. 179. 13, 69.

अपराःण
Aparāḥṇa --when the sun passes three muhūrtas from the madhyāḥna. Vā. 50. 96, 173.

अपराण्हा
Aparāṇhā --a Śakti of Kāla in the Pañcakoṇa. Br. IV. 32. 10.

अपरान्त
Aparānta(kam) --a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 46; III. 62. 39; M. 114. 51; Vā. 58. 81.

अपरान्त
Aparāntas --the people of the western country. Vi. II. 3. 16.

अपर्णा
Aparṇā  (I)--one of the three daughters of Menā and Himavat. Seeing her severe penance houseless and foodless her mother said ‘soma’, (Umā-Vā. P.) whence she became Umā and married Śiva. Br. III. 10. 8-13; Vā. 72. 7, 11-2. 

अपर्णा
Aparṇā  (II)--a daughter of Menā: married Jaigīṣavya. M. 13. 8-9.

अपवर्ग
Apavarga --the final beatitude from sūkṣma, the latter to be realised by Jñāna; cf. Sankhya k. 44. Jñānena cāpavargaḥ. From this results vyāpaka; from this comes Puruṣa and from it the highest bliss. Vā. 13. 22.

अपसव्य
Apasavya --a son of Śamśya Agni. Br. II. 12. 13.

अपस्फूर्ज
Apasphūrja (Vivasvat) --Agni known as Āstha. Br. II. 12. 31.

अपस्मार
Apasmāras --a group of evil spirits. Bhā. X. 6. 28.

अपस्यति
Apasyati --a son of Ūttānapāda and Sūnṛtā. M. 4. 35.

अपस्यन्त
Apasyanta --a son of Uttānapāda and Sūnṛtā. M. 4. 35.

अपस्यौष
Apasyauṣa --a mantrakṛt. M. 145. 104.

अपस्वान्त
Apasvānta --a son of Śakrajit and a loveable man. Vā. 96. 53.

अपहारिणी
Apahāriṇī --a Brahmarākṣasī. Br. III. 7. 99.

अपाग्नेय
Apāgneya --a Trayārṣeya. M. 196. 43. 

अपाङ्क्तेय
Apāṅkteyas --a list of those unfit for interdining. Vā. 83. 60-70.

अपाण्डु
Apāṇḍu --a sage. M. 196. 45.

अपान
Apāna  (I)--a Sādhya god. Br. III. 3. 16.

अपान
Apāna  (II)--a Tuṣita god. Br. III. 3. 19; Vā. 66. 18.

अपान
Apāna  (III)--an Ajita deva. Vā. 67. 34.

अपान्तरतम
Apāntaratama --a Siddha chief, who could not comprehend the māyā of Hari. Bhā. VI. 15. 12; IX. 4. 57.

अपांगर्भ
Apāṃgarbha --attribute of Agni. Br. II. 23. 53.

अपांपति
Apāṃpati --an attribute of Varuṇa, the lord of a dik. Br. III. 7. 331; Vā. 69. 215.

अपांरस
Apāṃrasa --a son of Bharatāgni. Vā. 29. 8.

अपांशु
Apāṃśu --a god of the Harita gaṇa. Br. IV. 1. 84.

अपार्य
Apārya --the name of Rudra. Br. IV. 34. 42. 

अपास्य
Apāsya --a sage by tapas. Br. II. 32. 99.

अप्तोर्यामम्
Aptoryāmam --a yāga; 1) Vā. 9. 51. from the fourth face of Brahmā. 2) Br. II. 8. 53.

अप्रकाश
Aprakāśas --a deva gaṇa with Yama as their lord. Br. III. 1. 52.

अप्रतीपी
Apratīpī --son of Śrutaśravas, ruled for 36 years. M. 271. 21.

अप्रतिम
Apratima --a son of Uttama Manu. Br. II. 36. 39; Vā. 62. 34.

अप्रतिमन्
Apratiman --the son of Diti; also known as Ariṣṭanemi. Vā. 65. 112.

अप्रतिमौज
Apratimauja --a sage of the Xth epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 27.

अप्रतिरथ
Apratiratha --the son of Rantibhāra (Antimāra-Vi. P.) and father of Kaṇva and Ailīna. Bhā. IX. 20. 6; Vi. IV. 19. 4, 5, 8.

अप्रमाद
Apramāda --a son of Buddhi. Br. II. 9. 60; Vā. 10. 36.

अप्रतिष्ठ
Apratiṣṭha --a hell under the earth; the fourth one below the earth; ever in motion. Br. IV. 2. 150 & 182-4; Vā. 101. 149, 179 and 181.

अप्सर
Apsaras --Divine dancers born of Muni and Kaśyapa. Joined Gandharvas in milking the cow Earth; worship Barhiṣad pitṛs. Love sports with Gandharvas over the Hima layas. 1) M. 6. 45; 10. 24; 15. 3; 22. 59; 120. 1. A group of celestial women who often go to Mount Kailāsa. 2) Bhā. II. 1. 36; IV. 6. 9. Thirty-four 3) Vā. 69. 4; 101. 28. wait on Indra. 4) Bhā. VI. 7. 4. Joined the gods in offering prayers to Hari. 5) Ib. VII. 8. 38. Take their origin from the sportful motion of Hari. 6) Ib. VIII. 5. 40. Danced at the avatār of Kṛṣṇa. 7) Ib. X. 3. 6; 4. 11. Went to Dvāraka with gods and prayed for the return of Hari to Vaikuṇṭha. 8) Ib. XI. 6. 3. Their association with the wise and the righteous. 9) Ib. XI. 12. 3. Welcome Kṛṣṇa back to his own region. 10) Ib. XI. 31. 2. Were asked by Indra to obstruct the completion of Mārkaṇḍeya's tapas. 11) Ib. XII. 8. 16. Dance in front of the Sun god and move with him by turns. 12) Ib. XII. 11. 47; Br. II. 23. 27 and 50. Live in Meru: Kāmadeva was their overlord; 13) Br. II. 15. 49; III. 8. 15; 7. 25-26. born on earth as 16000 gopis during Kṛṣṇa's avatāra; 14) Ib. III. 71. 243-4; IV. 2. 26. sprung from the churning of the ocean; 15) Bhā. VIII. 8. 7. strew fired grain at the conquering tour of Lalitā. 16) Br. IV. 18. 9. Fourteen birth spots for them distinguished. 17) Ib. IV. 33. 18-25. Once when the Apsaras ladies, all daughters of Agni, were engaged in water sports in Mānasa, there came Nārada. Without saluting him they asked him how to attain the Lord as husband. He gave them a vratam but cursed that they would be separated from the Lord and become slaves of robbers; became the rekhas on the body of Vāmana. 18) M. 70. 21-5; 246. 54.

अप्सरस
Apsarasa gaṇas --fourteen in number, the mindborn daughters of Brahmā, daughters of Manu, etc. most of them were wives and mothers of gods and sages. Vā. 9. 55; 30. 87; 69. 53, 62; 96. 235.

अप्सरेशम्
Apsareśam --a tīrtham in the Narmadā. M. 194. 16-17.

अबला
Abalā --a sister of Dattātreya and Durvāsās; a Brahmavādinī. Vā. 70. 76. 

अबाला
Abālā --a mindborn mother. M. 179. 27.

अब्ज
Abja --an attribute of Brahmā. Br. IV. 5. 31.

अब्जम्
Abjam (abdam) --100 crores. Br. IV. 2. 94; Vā. 101. 95.

अब्जयोनि
Abjayoni --is Brahmā also known as Pitāmaha; originally narrated the Viṣṇu Purāṇa to Dakṣa and other sages. Vi. I. 2. 8; IV. 1. 67; 6. 5.

अब्धिप
Abdhipa --an attribute of Agastya. Br. IV. 31. 36.

अभय
Abhaya  (I)--son of Dharma and Dayā: a sage. Bhā. IV. 1. 50; M. 198. 3.

अभय
Abhaya  (II)--one of the seven continents of Plakṣadvīpa. (Jambūdvīpa--Burnouf). Bhā. V. 20. 3.

अभयद
Abhayada --the son of Manasyu and father of Sudyu. Vi. IV. 19. 1.

अभय
Abhaya  (I)--a R. of Krauñcadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 21.

अभया
Abhayā  (II)--the goddess enshrined in Uṣṇatīrtha. M. 13. 42.

अभारिष्ट
Abhāriṣṭa --a dānava. Br. III. 6. 15. 

अभिज
Abhija --the name of a hell. Br. IV. 2. 150.

अभिजातकोविदः
Abhijātakovidaḥ --experts in astrology predicted Parīkṣit's future glory at the time of his birth. Bhā. I. 16. 1; cf. I. 12. 15-29.

अभिजित्
Abhijit  (I)--an auspicious hour between 1--2 p.m. midday time: 1) Bhā. III. 18. 27; VII. 10. 67. best for gifts. 2) M. 22. 2.

अभिजित्
Abhijit  (II)--the 28th nakṣatra on the right nostril of Śiśumāra; 1) Bhā. V. 22. 11; 23. 6; Vā. 50. 130; 82. 12; 96. 201. the nakṣatra of Kṛṣṇa. 2) Bhā. VIII. 18. 5; Br. III. 71. 205. Identified with Hari. 3) Bhā. XI. 16. 27.

अभिजित्
Abhijit  (III)--A son of Andhaka, (ĀnakadundhubhiVi. P.), and father of Punarvasu. Br. III. 71. 119; Vi. IV. 14. 14.

अभिजित
Abhijita  (I)--ārṣeyapravara (Aṅgiras). M. 196. 6.

अभिजित
Abhijita  (II)--(Punarvasu) the son of Candanodakadundubhi; performed Aśvamedha. Father of twins, Āhuka and Āhuki. Vā. 96. 118, 120; Br. III, 71. 119-122.

अभिनयम्
Abhinayam --technique of dancing started by Bharata. M. 24. 30.

अभिभूत
Abhibhūta --the son of Durdama or Durmada: 1) Br. III. 71. 171. of the Rohiṇi family. 2) Vā. 96. 169. 

अभिमन्यु
Abhimanyu  (I)--a son of Arjuna and Subhadrā. Wife Uttarā. Conqueror of atirathas. 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 33. Br. III. 71. 178; M. 50. 56; Vi. IV. 20. 51; Famous for valour even as a boy. Father of Parīkṣit. 2) Bhā. I. 4. 9. Vi. IV. 20. 52. Drauṇi wanted to destroy his seed in embryo. Kṛṣṇa frustrated this attempt. Taken by Kṛṣṇa to Dvāraka. 4) Ib. X. 64 [11]. Slew Bṛhadbala in the Bhārata war. 4(a) Vi. IV. 4, 112. Went with Kṛṣṇa to Upaplāvya to see the Pāṇḍavas. 5) Bhā. X. 78. [16 (V) 4]. Killed by Saindhava. 6) Ib. X. 78. [30]. A rathī; 7) Vā. 96. 176; 99. 249. considered as god. 8) Vā. 31. 7. ^3) Bhā. III. 3. 17.

अभिमन्यु
Abhimanyu  (II)--a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu. Br. II. 36. 80, 107; M. 4. 42; Vā. 62. 68, 91.

अभिमन्यु
Abhimanyu  (III)--a sage of the second Sāvarṇa epoch. Br. IV. 1. 71.

अभिमन्यु
Abhimanyu  (IV)--a son of Manu and Naḍvalā. Vi. I. 13. 5.

अभिमान
Abhimāna --(Rudra) entered Ātman (ahaṅkāra) of Virāṭ Puruṣa. Bhā. III. 6. 25.

अभिमित्र
Abhimitra --one of the names in the second marut gaṇa. Vā. 67. 125.

अभियुः
Abhiyuḥ --one of the names in the third marut gaṇa. Vā. 67. 126.

अभियुक्ताक्षिक
Abhiyuktākṣika --a marut of the third gaṇa. Br. III. 5. 95. 

अभियुक्त
Abhiyuktas --a class of people in Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 16.

अभिषाह
Abhiṣāha --a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 48.

अभिषेक
Abhiṣeka --The anointing ceremony: when Puru, the last son was recommended by Yayāti, the people said that it was dharma to anoint the eldest; defined the law that the faithful son alone was fit for the throne; Puru having fulfilled his father's wishes was to be regarded the faithful and dutiful; this was agreed to; further it was endorsed by Śukra. Vā. 93. 76-87; 99. 451.

अभिषेकमङ्गलम्
Abhiṣekamaṅgalam --of Rāma, described. Vi. IV. 4. 98-99.

अभिषेचनम्
Abhiṣecanam --of Pṛthu. M. 8. 2; 10. 10; Vā. 32. 48.

अभूमि
Abhūmi  (I)--a son of Citraka. Br. III. 71. 115; Vā. 96. 114.

अभूमि
Abhūmi  (II)--a son of Aśvini and Akrūra. M. 45. 33.

अभ्युक्षणम्
Abhyukṣaṇam --slightly different from Prokṣaṇam; the former is for articles of diet, etc. and the latter for flowers, grass, etc.; details of the śrāddha. Vā. 79. 33.

अभ्रम
Abhrama --the king of the elephants. Br. III. 7. 355. 

अभ्रमु
Abhramu --an elephant and a daughter of Bhauvana-mother of dig-gajas. Br. III. 7. 329.

अभ्रयन्ती
Abhrayantī --a queen of Varṣa-ṛtu. Br. IV. 32. 29.

अभ्राणि
Abhrāṇi --formation of clouds described: kinds of. Br. II. 22. 23-48.

अमर
Amara  (I)--a mountain kingdom. M. 114. 56.

अमर
Amara  (II)--a marut gaṇa. M. 171. 52.

अमरम्
Amaram --a place sacred to Śiva. M. 181. 26.

अमरकण्टक
Amarakaṇṭaka --(Mt.) the sacred hill at the top of Mālyavat. Here Aṅgiras performed penance for fifteen crores of years; here is the R. Viśalyakaraṇī, forming a part of Kalinga; Siddhikṣetram, noted for śrāddha offering, 1) Br. III. 13. 4-16. and pitṛ piṇḍa; a kṣetra of the Narmadā by name Jaleśvarā; surrounded by the hill Rudrakoṭi; superior to Kurukṣetra; 2) M. 22. 28; 186. 12-34; 188. 79 and 82; 191. 25; 193. 54; 194. 44. its crest lustrous as the Pralayāgni; there were golden kuśas touching the bank of the south Narmadā; here Aṅgiras, once after Agnihotra saw the step to svarga or heaven; on the west is a tank, bordering on Kalinga another holy place. Sung even by Śukra. 3) Vā. 77. 4-16; 112. 32.

अमरगण्डिक
Amaragaṇḍika --on the western side of Gandhamādana. M. 113. 48. 

अमरपुर
Amarapura --another term for Heaven whose lord was Indra. Br. IV. 6. 11 and 32.

अमरप्रख्य
Amaraprakhya --a Dānava. M. 177. 8.

अमरावती
Amarāvatī --Heaven noted for the pleasure-park Nandana. A description of the city, occupied for some time by Bali. 1) Bhā. VIII. 15. 11-22 and 33; Vā. 77. 26. Though it was really the capital of Indra, the latter says that it belonged to Kṛṣṇa. 2) Bhā. X. [67 (V) 26]; Vi. I. 9. 25. When it is midday here, the sun rises at Samyamana. 3) Br. II. 21. 37; III. 13. 26 and 30; M. 124. 27.

अमर्ष
Amarṣa --the son of Susandhi and father of Sahasvān. Vi. IV. 4. 111.

अमर्क
Amarka --a son of Śukrācārya. Bhā. VII. 5. 1, 48.

अमर्षण
Amarṣaṇa --the son of Sandhi and father of Mahasvat. Bhā. IX. 12. 7.

अमर्त्तस्
Amarttas --a deva gaṇa with Yama as their lord. Br. III. 1. 52.

अमा
Amā --a ray of the sun. Vi. II. 12. 8.

अमात्य
Amātyas --their irritation against king, a cause of internal dissensions; to be banished after being deprived of possession, for doing wrongs: Residence of. M. 223. 9; 227. 160; 254. 21-22. 

अमावसु
Amāvasu  (I)--a son of Aila. Him Acchodā adopted as her pitṛ and lost her yogic powers; son of Purūravas and Urvaśī. Father of Bhīma. Br. III. 10. 56 and 68; 66. 22; M. 14. 5, 7. Vā. 91. 51. 2; Vi. IV. 7. 1 and 2.

अमावसु
Amāvasu  (II)--the son of Āyu; a Vasu passing through the sky loved by Acchodā. Vā. 73. 5.

अमावास्या
Amāvāsyā --the time when Pitṛs worship moon and when the sun, moon and constellations meet together in the same maṇḍala; Pitṛs drink the nectar of the moon (1/15) part of it remaining; there is no moon, middle sun--half night half day. 1) Br. II. 10. 62. 65; 21. 153; 23. 70; 28. 6; 17. 19; M. 17. 2; 126. 66. 72; 141. 42-49; Vā. 52. 64; 53. 92; 56. 1, 6, 42 and 49 Yajñas with 21 samjñas. 2) Br. III. 11. 14. Vā. 74. 13. Only when two of its kalas remain, the moon enters the orbit of the sun and stays in the ray called Amā and hence the period is Amāvāsyā, 3) Vi. I. 20. 38; II. 8. 80; 12. 8; III. 14. 7-10. fit for śrāddha. 4) Vi. III. 14. 7-10.

अमावस्यका
Amāvasyakā --a śakti devī on the Soḍaśapatrābja. Br. IV. 32. 12.

अमावीर्या
Amāvīryā --called kuhū because it casts the length of time a cuckoo takes to say kuhū. M. 141. 42, 49.

अमित
Amita  (I)--a son of Jaya. Bhā. IX. 15. 2.

अमित
Amita  (II)--a Sudharmāṇa god. Br. IV. 1. 60. 

अमित
Amita  (III)--a mantrakṛt of the Aṅgirasa branch. Vā. 59. 98.

अमितध्वज
Amitadhvaja --a son of Dharmarāja--Janaka and father of Kāṇḍikya. Vi. VI. 6. 7-8.

अमिताभा
Amitābhās  (I)--one of the three deva gaṇas of the first epoch of Sāvarṇi Manu; 1) Br. IV. 1. 12, 16 and 18; Vi. III. 2. 15. twenty branches mentioned. 2) Vā. 100. 13-17.

अमिताभा
Amitābhās  (II)--a group of gods of the Raivata epoch, fourteen in number. Br. II. 36. 51 and 54; Vi. III. 1. 21.

अमिताश्व
Amitāśva --the son of Nikumbha and father of Kṛśāśva. Vi. IV. 2. 45-6.

अमित्र
Amitra --a Marut of the second gaṇa. Br. III. 5. 93.

अमित्रघ्न
Amitraghna --one of Bhaṇḍa's eight councillors. Br. IV. 12. 12.

अमित्रजित्
Amitrajit  (I)--A son of Sutapas and father of Bṛhadrāja. Bhā. IX. 12. 12-13.

अमित्रजित्
Amitrajit  (II)--the son of Suparṇa and father of Bṛhadbhāja. (Bharadvāja-Vā. P.). Vi. IV. 22. 5-6; Vā. 99. 286.

अमित्रह
Amitraha --a son of the fourth Savarṇa Manu (Ṛtu Sāvarṇa Manu). Br. IV. 1. 94; Vā. 100. 99. 

अमीना
Amīnā --a daughter of Ṛṣā: gave birth to four kinds of crocodiles. Br. III. 7. 414 and 416.

अमूर्तरय
Amūrtaraya --a sage who had transcended the force of Māyā. (Burnouf makes this into two names Amūrti and Aya). Bhā. II. 7. 44.

अमूर्तरयस
Amūrtarayasa  (I)--one of the four sons of Kuśa. Br. III. 66. 32; Vā. 91. 62.

अमूर्तरयस
Amūrtarayasa  (II)--a son of Antināra. M. 49. 8.

अमृत
Amṛta  (I)--an Amitābha god. Br. II. 36. 53; Vā. 62. 46.

अमृत
Amṛta  (II)--a son of Bharatāgni. Vā. 29. 8.

अमृत
Amṛta  (III)--one of the seven divisions of Plakṣadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 3.

अमृतम्
Amṛtam  (I)--the juice from medicinal herbs of the Candra hill of Plakṣadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 8; 24. 27 and 31.

अमृतम्
Amṛtam  (II)--nectar arising out of the churning of milk ocean by gods and Asuras. Others that came out of it were curds, liquor, Soma, Lakṣmī, horse, Kaustubha, Pārijāta, and lastly Kālakūṭa. Then appeared Dhanvantari. Distribution of amṛtam by Mohinī, the form assumed by Hari to delude the Asuras. When Rāhu was seen, partaking of it,  had his head cut off. Finding themselves deceived, the Asuras began war. M. 1. 9; 249. 14 to the end; cha. 250 and 251 (whole); Vā. 23. 90; 52. 37; 92. 9; Vi. I. 9. 80-111.

अमृतप्रभ
Amṛtaprabhas --gods of Sāvarṇi epoch. Bhā. VIII. 13. 12.

अमृतमन्थन
Amṛtamanthana --the fourth devāsura battle, in which Indra defeated Praḥlāda. 1) Br. III. 72. 73 and 79; IV. 6. 7. Also the fourth of twelve incarnations of Hari by name Indra; with details of the battle. 2) M. 47. 43 and 48; 249. 51; Vā. 97. 74. 79.

अमृतवान्
Amṛtavān --a Śukradeva. Vā. 31. 8.

अमृता
Amṛtā  (I)--a Śakti devī; the goddess enshrined in a Vindhyan cave. Br. IV. 44. 84; M. 13. 42.

अमृता
Amṛtā  (II)--the goddess enshrined at Veṇa. M. 13. 49; 122. 33.

अमृता
Amṛtā --R. of the Plakṣadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 19; Vā. 49. 17; Vi. II. 4. 11.

