Aruṇa  (V)--a son of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 90. 33. 

अरुण
Aruṇa  (VI)--a hill near (on the other side of-Vā. P.) Kailāsa, the residence of Girīśa and full of medicinal herbs. At its foot is the Śailodā lake from which rises the R. Śilodā on whose bank is the forest Surabhī. Br. II. 18. 18-23; Vā. 47. 17-22.

अरुण
Aruṇa  (VII)--A son of Viṅatā and brother of Garuḍa. 1) Br. III. 7. 29; M. 6. 34; 150. 151-2; Vi. I. 21. 18. The charioteer of the Sun. He is said to yoke the seven horses bearing the names of metres (Chandas). 2) Bhā. V. 21. 15-16; Vā. 28. 32; Br. II. 11. 37. Came to see Parīkṣit practising prāyopaveśa. 3) Bhā. I. 19. 11. Vā. 69. 66. Married Gṛdhrī (Śyenī-Vā. P.) who gave birth to Sampāti and Jaṭāyu; 4) Br. III. 7. 446; Vā. 69. 326. A personification of Dawn: Image of. 5) M. 261. 7.

अरुण
Aruṇa  (VIII)--a son of Raivata. M. 9. 21.

अरुण
Aruṇa  (IX)--a sādhya. M. 171. 43.

अरुण
Aruṇas  (I)--the sons of Dullola. Br. III. 7. 443.

अरुण
Aruṇas  (II)--of the Kṣatriyas of Śālmali dvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 30.

अरुणा
Aruṇā  (I)--R. of Plakṣa dvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 4.

अरुणा
Aruṇā  (II)--an apsaras. Br. III. 7. 5. 

अरुणा
Aruṇā  (III)--a Devī. Br. IV. 19. 48; 44. 41.

अरुणि
Aruṇi  (I)--a son of Brahmā, who remained celibate: 1) Bhā. IV. 8. 1; VI. 15. 13. a sage. 2) Br. III. 36. 6.

अरुणि
Aruṇi  (II)--went with Kṛṣṇa to Mithilā. Bhā. X. 86. 18.

अरुणोदा
Aruṇodā --R. of celestial mango juice flowing from the top of Mandara and irrigating the eastern part of Ilāvṛta. In this river bathe Yakṣa damsels, who are attendants of Pārvatī. Bhā. V. 16. 17 and 18.

अरुणोदम्
Aruṇodam --a sacred lake in Meru (in the east-Vā. P.) (in Ilāvṛta-Vi. P.). M. 113. 46; Vā. 36. 16; Vi. II. 2. 26.

अरुध
Aru(d)dha --the son of Setu and father of Gāndhāra. Br. III. 74. 7-9; Vā. 99. 7-9.

अरुन्तिजा
Aruntijā --a deva of Harita gaṇa. Vā. 100. 88.

अरुन्धती
Arundhatī  (I)--a daughter of Kardama, sister of Parvata and Nārada, (Kāśyapa) and wife of Vasiṣṭha; 1) Bhā. III. 24. 23; Vā. 2. 10; 19. 2; 30. 73; 69. 65; 70. 79. a surname of hers was Ūrjā. Mother of seven sons, Citraketu and others, all sages of renown. 2) Bhā. IV. 1. 40. Did not feed Kumāra while the wives of other six sages fed him. 3) Br. III. 10. 40. Mother of Śakti. Goddess among Satis; meditated on the 108 names of Devī as narrated to attain fruits of yoga. 4) M. 13. 53, 61; 187. 45; 201. 30. 

अरुन्धती
Arundhatī  (II)--a daughter of Dakṣa, and one of Dharma's wives: gave birth to Pṛthivī and all Viṣayas; (gave birth to all earthly objects, Vi. P.). Br. III. 3. 2 and 34; 7. 28; 8. 86; M. 5. 15 and 19; 203. 2; Vā. 66. 2 and 35; Vi. I. 15. 105, 108.

अरूप
Arūpa --a mantrakṛt. Vā. 59. 97.

अरूप
Arūpas --the people of a Janapada on the other side of the Vindhyas. (Anūpas--Vā. P.). M. 114. 54; Vā. 45. 134.

अरूपा
Arūpā --a daughter of Riṣṭa. Br. III. 7. 13; Vā. 69. 48.

अरूरू
Arūrū --a son of Danāyuṣa, had a son Dhundhu, killed by Kubalāśva. Vā. 68. 30-31.

अरोगा
Arogā --the goddess enshrined at Vaidyanātha. M. 13. 41.

अर्क
Arka  (I)--a son of Vasu, and a Vasu. Wife Vāsanā. Sons Tarṣa and others. Bhā. III. 21. 51; VI. 3. 14; 6. 11 and 13.

अर्क
Arka  (II)--the son of Puruja, and father of Bharmyāśva. Bhā. IX. 21. 31. 

अर्क
Arka  (III)--the son of Vivici Agni; see Vividha; he had a number of sons like Anīkavān, etc. Vā. 1. 145; 29. 40; Br. II. 12. 42.

अर्कज
Arkaja --a name of Śanaiścara. M. 93. 10.

अर्कपर्ण
Arkaparṇa --a Mauneya Gandharva. Br. III. 7. 2.

अर्कमर्क
Arkamarkas --a gaṇa of the Piśācas, resembling monkeys, with residences in trees; short and pushing nature. Br. III. 7. 382 and 390; Vā. 69. 271.

अर्कवंश
Arkavaṃśa --see Sūryavamśa. Ila was common ancestor. M. 12. 14.

अर्कव्रतम्
Arkavratam --of kings: to collect taxes in proper seasons, as the sun's rays draw water for 8 months. M. 226. 11.

अर्कसंक्रम
Arkasaṃkrama --a yugādi for sādhāraṇa śrāddha. M. 17. 2, 5.

अर्चला
Arcalā --(see Suvarcalā--Burnouf)

अर्चा
Arcā --of Hari. Worship of Hari's image is said to promote one's welfare. Some special places devoted to. This form is prevalent even in Tretā yuga; 1) Bhā. VII. 14. 28-40. to be worshipped in the payovrata. 2) Ib. VIII. 16. 28. Arcā is Rājasa. Mere idol worship condemned. When proper; 3) Ib. III. 29. 9, 21-25 Arcā may be of gold, silver,  of earth or water or other substance. 4) Ib. IV. 8. 56. Upāsanā of, a means to concentration on the Absolute. 5) Ib. XI. 20. 24. Worship may be offered on the ground, fire, sun, waters, Brāhmaṇa or any other thing. Image of eight kinds including stone, wood and metal; may be moveable or immoveable. The mode in worship. Subsidiary worship to the ornaments, implements and attendants on Hari. Founding a shrine, flowergarden and instituting festivals form part of the worship. 6) Ib. XI. 27. 9-43, Only people of little tapas are engaged in arcā, this being regarded inferior to worshipping Brahman. 7) Ib. X. 84. 10; 86. 55.

अर्चास्थापन
Arcāsthāpana --founding of shrines is a form of bhakti to Hari. Bhā. XI. 11. 38.

अर्चिस्
Arcis  (I)--the female child born from the arms of Vena, churned by the sages. An aṃśa of Lakṣmī, and a queen of Pṛthu. 1) Bhā. IV. 15. 5-6. Follows Pṛthu to the forest and at his death performs sati, evoking praise from goddesses. 2) Ib. IV. 23. 19-28.

अर्चिस्
Arcis  (II)--Wife of Krśāśva and mother of Dhūmrakeśa. Bhā. VI. 6. 20.

अर्चिष्मती
Arciṣmatī --a daughter of Sāraṇa. Br. III. 71. 168; Vā. 96. 166.

अर्चिष्मान्
Arciṣmān --a sutapa god. Br. IV. 1. 15; Vā. 100. 15.

अर्चिसण
Arcisaṇa --a mantrakāra and Ātreya. Vā. 59. 104. 

अर्जुन
Arjuna  (I) (Kārtavīrya)--son of Kṛtavīrya. Lord of seven islands and of Haihayaṣ, Samrāṭ and Cakravartin. By the grace of Hari he got 1000 arms and enjoyed aṣṭaaiśvaryas. Learnt the merit of yoga from Dattātreya. Ruled in peace for 85,000 years 1) Bhā. IX. 15. 17-19; 23. 24-27; Br. III. 30. 4. 75; 69. 9, 49, 56; Vi. IV. 11. 11-21; M. 43. 15; Vā. 94. 10. and was ambitious to have more territorial possessions. 2) Bhā. XII. 3. 9; I. 12. 21. Was engaged in water-sports with women wearing the garland of Vaijayanti. 3) Bhā. IX. 15. 20. Imprisoned Rāvaṇa in his capital Māhiṣmatī and released him on an appeal from Pulasya. 4) Bhā. IX. 15. 21-22; Br. III. 33. 50; M. 43. 37-40; In the course of a hunting expedition, he came to the hermitage of Jamadagni who entertained him with the help of his Kāmadhenu. The king, envious of the sage's prosperity, desired its possession, and on being refused by the sage, he took the cow by force. 5) Bhā. IX. 15. 23-26; Br. III. 26. 7 whole chapter, chaps. 27 and 28; 30. 4. Parasurāma who was away, heard the story on his return, went to Arjuna's capital, cut off his head with his axe after a terrible battle in which Matsyarāja took part and recovered the cow and the calf. 6) Bhā. IX. 15. 27-36; Br. III. 30. 5-15; 32. 61; 38 8, 27; 40. 19; 41, 37, 38; 44. 14; 47. 63, 88. Jamadagni regretted his son's action as the king was a Naradeva, and killing him was an offence greater than brāhmanicide. 7) Bhā. IX. 15. 37-41; Br. III. 38. 8. Had 1000 (?) sons, (100 sons) all of whom except five died in battles. These sons killed Jamadagni when Rāma and his brothers were gone out. 8) M. 43. 46-51; These five were great warriors. 9) Bhā. IX. 16. 9-12. His minister was the evil Candragupta and the Purohita, Garga. 10) Br. III. 28. 31-63. Incarnation of Viṣṇu Cakra; 11) Br. III. 37. 27-28; 40. 66. to his family belonged Tālajaṅgha; 12) Vā. 94. 50. performed thousands of yajñas with golden yūpas and vedis, which were attended by gods. A Rājaṛṣi, paśupāla, kṣetrapāla. 13) M. 43. 13-25. Defeated Karkoṭaka's son at Māhiṣmatī and established his city on the banks of the Narmadā. Could control the waters of the Narmadā and the fury of the ocean: a terror to Asuras in Pātāla as also to Rākṣasas and Uragas. Defeated Rāvaṇa and released  him at the intervention of Pulastya: burnt down the Hematālavanam, residence of Āpava and was cursed that a Bhārgava and a Brāhmaṇa would chop off his 1000 hands. 14) M. 43. 25-43; Vā. 94. 9-24. A gātha in his honour by Nārada. 14(a) Vi. IV. 11. 16. Once Āditya in the guise of a Brāhmaṇa asked to be fed at the expense of all immobile things (sthāvara) in the world and it was granted. This included Āpava's hermitage also. 15) Br. III. 70. 3-10; M. 44. 3-13. Performed the Saubhāgyaśayana-vratam and made the 16 gifts. 16) M. 60. 49.

अर्जुन
Arjuna  (II)--a son of Raivata Manu. Bhā. VIII. 5. 2.

अर्जुन
Arjuna  (III)--a Pāṇḍava, son of Indra and Kuntī and father of Śrutakīrti. Had a son Irāvān by Ulūpi and another son Babruvāhana by the daughter of Maṇipurapati. Father of Abhimanyu by Subhadrā. 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 29-33; Br. III. 71. 154 and 178; Vi. IV. 14. 35; 20. 40; V. 12. 17-24; 35. 28. Promised Draupadī to cut off Aśvathāma's head and place it before her for his killing her sons when asleep. Aśvathāma heard this and ran for escape. Arjuna pursued him. Unwilling to slay the son of his preceptor, he bound him with ropes and took him to his queen's presence. She requested Arjuna to release him on the ground that he was a Brāhmaṇa, a son of the guru, and for the sake of his old mother Gautamī. Bhīma was not for the release. But Arjuna took the hint from Kṛṣṇa, and after depriving him of his crest-jewel, banished him. 2) Bhā. I. 7. 15-57. Accompanied Yudhiṣṭhira to see Bhīṣma on the eve of his death. 3) Ib. I. 9. 3. A playmate of Kṛṣṇa. 4) Ib. X. 22. 31. Had a chariot with monkey standard. When he was once in the forest with Kṛṣṇa, they met Kālindī, daughter of the Sun god anxious to marry Kṛṣṇa. When Arjuna burnt Khāṇḍava, Kṛṣṇa was his charioteer. Drove away the princes who attacked  Kṛṣṇa returning with Satyā of Kośala. 5) Ib. X. 58. 4, 13-25, 54. Commended by Indra to Kṛṣṇa's protection. 6) Ib. X. [67 (V) 36]; Vi. V. 13. 17-18. Consoled by Kṛṣṇa when banished to the forest. 7) Bhā. X. 64. 9. A great name among the Kurus. 8) Ib. X. 68. 28. Joy at Kṛṣṇa's visit to Indraprastha. By burning the forest he released Maya and enjoyed Kṛṣṇa's company. Went to the eastern countries. Went again with Kṛṣṇa and Bhīma disguised as a Brāhmaṇa to Girivraja. Revealed himself before Jarāsandha who thought that he was not his equal. Returned after Jarāsandha's fall. 9) Ib. X. 71. 22-30, 45-46; 72. 13-16, 29 and 32; 73. 31 and 34. Entertained elders at the Rājasūya of Yudhisthira. On seeing the enemy's army in the battle-field, his teachers, kith and kin among them, he expressed to Kṛṣṇa his reluctance to fight them. Kṛṣṇa taught him the truth (Gītā), showed him his Viśvarūpa and roused him to action. He fought, Kṛṣṇa serving as charioteer. 10) Ib. X. 75. 5; [78. (V), 21-25]; XI. 16. 6-8. Victory due to Kṛṣṇa. 11) Ib. IX. 24. 67. Heard of Abhimanyu's death and vowed to kill Jayadratha the following day, which he did. 12) Ib. X. 78. [31-35]. Was taken by Kṛṣṇa to Kailāsa where Śiva blessed him. Took part in the svayamvaram of Lakṣmaṇā. His arrow touched the fish target but did not hit it. 13) Ib. X. 83. 24. In the course of his pilgrimage he heard at Prabhāsa that his uncle's daughter Subhadrā was being proposed by Balarāma to Duryodhana. He wished to marry her, and with this object spent four months in Dvāraka as Tridaṇḍī ascetic. At this time Rāma invited him one day for bhikṣā. When he and Subhadrā met, both exchanged their love by their eyes. On a day of festive occasion Subhadrā came out, when Arjuna carried her off in a chariot with the approval of Kṛṣṇa. Rāma protested but Kṛṣṇa pacified him. Finally Rāma sent presents to his sister. 14) Ib. X. 86. 1-12. On a visit to Syamantapañcaka. 15) Ib. X. 84. 57. Once a Brāhmaṇa of Dvāraka preferred a complaint during Kṛṣṇa's aśvamedha that his children died immediately after their birth. Arjuna offered to recover them  for him, though Kṛṣṇa had his own doubt. Accompanying the Brāhmaṇa, Arjuna guarded the delivery room. The child was born and soon died. At this Arjuna went to Indra's place, and Yama's, and to the abodes of all gods, with the resolution to fall in a fire in case he did not rescue the child. Unable to recover it, Arjuna was about to plunge into the flames when Kṛṣṇa prevented him. He was taken to the abode of Nārāyaṇa and all the children were recovered. Returned to Dvārakā to attend Kṛṣṇa's aśvamedha, after bringing joy to the Brāhmaṇa. 16) Ib. X. 89. 22-64. Other exploits of Arjuna were defeating Indra at Khāṇḍava, pleasing Śiva in Kirāta's disguise, and vanquishing Nivātakavacas. 17) Ib. X. 89. 34 [4-5]; M. 6. 29. Went once to Heaven to please Indra, when he slew singlehanded 60,000 dānavas who obstructed yajñas. 18) Bhā. VI. 6. 36. Went to Dvārakā to see his relations. Was advised to take Yādavas to Indraprastha as Dvārakā was about to be swallowed by the sea. Performed the last rites to the dead in Dvārakā, and took the remainder to his place. Was defeated by robbers and Ābhiras after the departure of Kṛṣṇa to Heaven. Informed Yudhiṣṭhira of Kṛṣṇa's departure to Heaven and of his great sorrow, and also of the almost end of the Yādava stock. Crowned Vajra king. 19) Ib. I. 12. 36; 14, 1 and 22; 15. 5-27 and 32; XI. 30. 47-48; 31. 21-25; M. 70. 12. Vi. V. 38. 5-6, 12-24, 34-36. Arjuna knew and realised the māyā of Hari. 20) Bhā. II. 7. 45. Observed the Ādityaśayanam vow. Visited the Vāmana temple at Kurukṣetra during his tīrthayātrā and asked Śaunaka to narrate the circumstances of that Avatār after Vārāha. 21) M. 55. 32: 244. 4. Was asked by Vyāsa to perform penance expelling death. 22) Vi. V. 38. 37-92. Put down the prowess of Kārtavīrya by the curse of Āpava. 23) Vā. 94. 45; 99. 280; Br. III. 69. 46. Known as Pārtha, Dhanamjaya, Jiṣṇu.

अर्जुन
Arjunas --The reference is to both Pāṇḍava Arjuna and Kārtavīrya Arjuna, both noted for military prowess. Parīkṣit is compared to them. Bhā. I. 12. 21. 

अर्जुनम्
Arjunam --a tīrtha sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 43.

अर्जुनपाल
Arjunapāla --a son of Śamīkā and Sudāminī. Bhā. IX. 24. 44.

अर्णव
Arṇava --(Arbuda, Wilson); a sacred place. (?) Vi. VI. 8. 29.

अर्णवक
Arṇavaka --four in number, Pṛthvī, antarikṣa, divya and maha. Vā. 101. 13.

अर्थ
Artha --born of dharma and buddhi: 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 51; I. 2. 9. Its ills; 2) Bhā. XI. 23. 17-21. not to be earned by a king by illegitimate means and not to abuse it by giving it to undesirables. 3) M. 220. 11; Vā. 23. 81; 61. 130.

अर्थप
Arthapas --a Janapada. Vā. 45. 111.

अर्थशास्त्र
Arthaśāstra --one of the 18 vidyas: 1) Br. II. 31. 23; 35. 89; Vā. 58. 23; 61. 79. Science of Polity pleaded by Indra in extenuation of his destruction of Diti's garbha: 2) M. 7. 63; 10. 32; Vi. III. 6. 28. No regard for the śāstra during Pṛthu's reign: Budha learned in; 3) M. 24. 2. to be learnt by a prince. 4) M. 144. 23; 220. 2.

अर्थसिद्धि
Arthasiddhi --the son of Sādhya gaṇa. Bhā. VI. 6. 7.

अर्थाकर्षिणिका
Arthākarṣiṇikā --a Devī. Br. IV. 36. 71. 

अर्धनारीनरवपुः
Ardhanārīnaravapuḥ --from Hiraṇyagarbha: two parts, male and female; the male half divided into eleven parts called Rudras by crying and running (oozing); each became a gaṇeśvara; the female half came to be divided into two, Śukla (right) and Kṛṣṇa (left); from her came Prajñā and Śrī and these in turn spread over the whole world in thousand ways. Vā. 9. 75-98; 41. 36.

अर्धनारीश्वर
Ardhanārīśvara --Śiva became this by worshipping Śakti: 1) Br. II. 27. 98; IV. 5. 30; 44. 48. Image of; with details of dress and ornaments. 2) M. 60. 25; 192. 28; 260. 1-10.

अर्धपण्य
Ardhapaṇyas --Ātreya gotrakaras. M. 197. 3.

अर्धबाहु
Ardhabāhu --one of the seven sons of Vasiṣṭha. Vā. 28. 36.

अर्धमुण्ड
Ardhamuṇḍa --one of the four sons of the 33rd Kalpa. Vā. 23. 59.

अर्धशशी
Ardhaśaśī (Ardhacandra) --one of the ten pīṭhas for images. This yields one a number of sons. M. 262. 7 and 11, 18.

अर्धस्वन
Ardhasvana --a mantrakṛt. M. 145. 107.

अर्बुद
Arbuda --the dvijas of: became Vrātyas after Puramjaya's days: 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 38. a western kingdom sacred to Lalitā. 2) Br. II. 16. 62; IV. 44. 94.

अर्बुद
Arbudas --a tribe, of the south, fought with their kinsmen and ended themselves. 1) Bhā. XI. 30. 18; M. 114. 51; Vā. 45. 131. Country of. 2) Vi. II. 3. 16. 

अर्बुदम्
Arbudam --10,00,00,000 (10 crores). Vā. 101. 95.

अर्बुदसरस्वती
Arbudasarasvatī --the R. sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 38.

अर्भक
Arbhaka --the son of Ajātaśatru and the father of Udayana. Vi. IV. 24. 15-16.

अर्यमन्
Aryaman  (I)--an Āditya, and a son of Aditi: named Mātṛkā: sons were Caṣaṇis. 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 39-42; Br. III. 3. 67; II. 24. 33 and 40; M. 126. 3; 127. 23; 171. 56; 225. 12; Vā. 62. 186; 66. 66; 110. 10; Vi. I. 15. 130. Acted for one hundred years as the Lord of Death when Yama was cursed to be a Śūdra for that period. 2) Bhā. I. 13. 15. Identified with Hari; 3) Bhā. XI. 16. 15. to be worshipped in houses and palace buildings; 4) M. 253. 30: 268. 24. one of the hinder legs of Śiśumāra. 5) Vi. II. 12. 32.

अर्यमन्
Aryaman  (II)--The name of the sun in the month of Mādhava (Vaiśākha). Bhā. XII. 11. 34; Vā. 52. 2, 94; Vi. II. 10. 5; V. 18. 56.

अर्यमन्
Aryaman  (III)--a chief Pitṛ who worships KūrmaHari in Hiraṇmaya. 1) Bhā. V. 18. 29. Served as calf for Pitṛs to milk Kavya from the earth. 2) Ib. IV. 18. 18.

अर्यमन्
Aryaman  (IV)--represents the thigh of the Śisumāra planet; south of, is pitṛyānam. Br. II. 23. 103: 25. 111.

अर्यमी
Aryamī vīthī --represented by the two Phālgunis and Maghā. Vā. 66. 49. 

अर्यम्न
Aryamna --the name of a muhūrta of a day. Br. III. 3. 40; M. 79. 6; Vā. 66. 41.

अर्वरीवान्
Arvarīvān --the son of Pulaha and Kṣamā and one of the seven sages of the Svarocisa epoch. Br. II. 36. 18; Vi. I. 10. 10.

अर्वसन
Arvasana --An Ātreya and a sage. Br. II. 32. 113.

अर्वाक्
Arvāk --the 25th Vedavyāsa. Br. II. 35. 123.

अर्वाक्तलम्
Arvāktalam --the fifth world of Śarkara earth: residence of Virocana and other daityas. Br. II. 20. 12 and 14. 35 and 38.

अर्वाक्सुत
Arvāksuta --Dhanvantri called such by Viṣṇu. Vā. 92. 14.

अर्वाक्स्रोत
Arvāksrota --the lower current, full of three qualities, eight stars, siddhis and men; this is known as Taijasa sarga. Vā. 6. 53-6.

अर्वावसु
Arvā(g)vasu --one of the seven important rays of the sun; yoni of Bṛhaspati. Br. II. 24. 67; Vā. 53. 45. 49.

अर्ह
Arha --a name of Śiva. Vā. 97. 172.

अर्ह
Arhas --a group of people defending Dvārakā, and related to Pāṇḍavas. Bhā. I. 11. 11; 14. 25. 

अर्हण
Arhaṇa --An attendant on Hari. Bhā. II. 9. 14.

अर्हत्
Arhat  (I)--a king of Konka, Venka, and Kuṭaka led astray by the teachings of Ṛṣabha. Gave up his svadharma and adopted the path of heretics. Bhā. V. 6. 9.

अर्हत्
Arhat  (II)--a name of Śiva. Br. III. 72. 173.

अर्हत
Arhatas --the Asuras who performed penance on the Narmadā, were deluded by Viṣṇu Māyāmoha to give up Vedic path and take to other non-Vedic doctrines. Vi. III. 18. 13.

अलक
Alaka --a Śrutaṛṣi. Br. II. 33. 4.

अलकनन्दा
Alakanandā --The R. in Kailāsa: a branch of Gaṅgā issuing out of the city of Brahmā descends the southern slopes of Meru. Her course can be traced from the Gandhamādana. Traversing the Hemakūṭa and Himalayas as also the continent of Bharata and dividing itself into seven branches it enters the sea on the south. A bath in this stream is equal to performing Aśvamedhas and other sacrifices. A mahānadī: borne by Śiva on his head for more than a hundred years: Elevated Sagara's sons to heaven. Bhā. IV. 6. 24; V. 17. 5 and 9; IX. 29. 42; Br. III. 41. 21; 56. 12; Vi. II. 2. 34, 36; 8. 113-20; Vā. 41. 18. 42. 25-35; 108. 80.

अलका
Alakā --the city of Yakṣas in Kailāsa. Capital of Kubera. 1) Br. II. 18. 2; III. 7. 163; Vā. 47. 1; Bhā. IV. 6. 23. Purūravas and Urvaśī sported here for a time; 2) Vā. 91. 6; Br. III. 66. 6; Vi. IV. 6. 48. as seen by Bhārgava Rāma. 3) Br. III. 41. 18-23. 

अलकाधिप
Alakādhipa --is Kubera. Vā. 47. 1; 69. 196.

अलता
Alatā --a daughter of Irā, and mother of trees. Br. III. 7. 460-1.

अलब्ध
Alabdhas --Ekārṣeyas. M. 200. 3.

अलंकारस्
Alaṃkāras --depend on varṇa, sthānayoga and nāṭya: Three places of origin--neck, head and mind: 4 varṇas, eight vikalpas, and sixteen deities: Different kinds of, described: 1) Br. III. 62. 2-23. 300 varieties distinguished. 2) Vā. 87. 1-3, 10-21.

अलम्बाक्षि
Alambākṣi --a mindborn mother. M. 179. 22.

अलम्बुषा
Alambuṣā --an Apsaras. Br. III. 7. 6; IV. 33. 18; Vā. 69. 5.

लम्बुषा
(A)lambuṣā --the queen of Tṛṇabindu; 1) Br. III. 8. 37; Bhā. IX. 2. 31. an apsaras and mother of Viśāla. 2) Vi. IV. 1. 48-9.

अलर्क
Alarka  (I)--a pupil of Dattātreya: a sage who realised the force of Harimāyā. Bhā. I. 3. 11; II. 7. 44.

अलर्क
Alarka  (II)--a son of Dyumat, and father of Sannati. He retained his youth and ruled for 66,000 years. The Br. Purāṇa and the Viṣṇu Purāṇa make him the son respectively  of Vatsa and Pratardana, and father of Sannati. 1) Br. III. 67. 69, 72; Vi. IV. 8. 16-18; Bhā. IX. 17. 6-8. A Rājaṛṣi of Kāśī; attained longevity through the grace of Lopāmudrā. Killed the Rākṣasa Kṣemaka and recovered his capital. Two ancient verses in his praise. 2) M. 180. 68-9; Vā. 92. 66-8.

अलसा
Alasā --a deity. Br. IV. 27. 38.

अलाबु
Alābu --gourds unfit for śrāddha. Vi. III. 16. 8.

अलाबूपात्रम्
Alābūpātram --the gourd-vessel of the Nāgas to milk the earth cow. Br. II. 36. 213; M. 10. 19.

अलिपिण्डक
Alipiṇḍaka --a Kādraveya nāga. Br. III. 7. 35.

अलिमद्र
Alimadras --a tribe. Vā. 45. 120.

अलिमान्
Alimān --the son of Gomatīputra and the father of Śāntakarṇa. Vi. IV. 24. 47-8.

अलोक
Aloka --attained by Vṛtra. Bhā. VI. 12. 35; Br. II. 19. 153.

अल्पमेधस्
Alpamedhas --a god of Sumedhas group. Br. II. 36. 59.

अवगाह
Avagāha  (I)--a son of Vṛkadevī and Vasudeva. M. 46. 18.

अवगाह
Avagāha  (II)--a son of Citrasena. Vā. 96. 248. 

अवटनिरोधन
Avaṭanirodhana --one of 28 hells, intended for those who confine beings in dark holes, granaries, etc. Bhā. V. 26. 7 and 34.

अवटोदा
Avaṭodā --R. in Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 18.

अवतार
Avatāras --of Hari, innumerable. Kṛṣṇa is the Lord himself. Metaphysics of. Bhā. I. 3. 26 and 28, 30-39.

अवधूत
Avadhūta --the friend who accompanied Purañjana to the Saurabha kingdom, through the entrances Nalini and Nālini. 1) Bhā. IV. 25. 48. Allegorically sense of smell. 2) Ib. IV. 29. 11. Taught spiritual wisdom to Yadu. 3) Ib. XI. 7. 24-9.

अवध्य
Avadhya --a Pratardana god. Br. II. 36. 30.

अवनेजनम्
Avanejanam --a ceremonial in a śrāddhā. M. 17. 47.

अवन्तय
Avantaya --on the other side of the Vindhyas. Vā. 45. 134.

अवन्तिपुर
Avantipura --Here lived Sāndīpani of Kāśī; 1) Bhā. X. 45. 31; 58. 30; Vi. V. 21. 19. also Avantikā; 2) Br. IV. 40. 91. one of the seven great cities. One of its kings married Rājādhidevī and became father of Vinda and Anuvinda. 3) Vi. IV. 14. 43; Bhā. X. 58. 31; Vā. 96. 157. Capital of the sons of Kārtavīrya Arjuna. 4) Vā. 94. 50. The navel of the Veda Puruṣa. 5) Vā. 104. 76. 

अवन्ति
Avanti  (I) (c)--a kingdom: Here there was a Brāhmaṇa miser who lost all his wealth and the love of his kith and kin, and who became ultimately an ascetic. Though illtreated by the public as a thief, he never took notice of it, and ever meditating on Hari, attained release. 1) Bhā. XI. 23. 6-62. The dvijas of, became Vrātyas after Puramjaya's days. 2) Ib. XII. 1. 38. The people of, were enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus. 3) Ib. X. [50 (V) 3]; XI. 23. 6. Here is Mahākālavana where Rudra vanquished Andhaka who sought to abduct Pārvatī; 4) M. 179. 5. ruled by Śūdras and Ābhīras. 5) Vi. IV. 24. 68; Bhā. XII. 1. 38.

अवन्ति
Avanti  (II)--a R. from the Pāriyātra, of the Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 29; Vā. 45. 98; M. 114. 24.

अवन्तिका
Avantikā --a tīrtha sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 33.

अवन्ति
Avantis --a Vindhya tribe: attacked Paraśurāma and were defeated; Jayadhvaja established at; one of the five gaṇas of Haihayas; 1) Br. II. 16. 65; III. 39. 11; 69. 50 and 52; M. 43. 46; 114. 54. a king of, married Āhukī, sister of Āhuka. 2) Br. III. 71. 128; M. 44. 70.

अवन्ती
Avantī --a son of Arjuna (Kārtavīrya). M. 43. 46.

अवन्ध्य
Avandhya --the son of Aṅgirasa. Vā. 65. 100.

अवभृत
Avabhṛta (Pāvaka) --Agni; his son Hṛcchaya. Vā. 29. 31; Br. II. 12. 33. 

अवभृतम्
Avabhṛtam --the concluding bath of a sacrifice; 1) Br. I. 2. 24; Vā. 103. 40-42. of of Soma. 2) M. 23. 23; Vā. 90. 26.

अवभृति
Avabhṛti --the city of Ābhīras. Bhā. XII. 1. 29.

अवरगात्र
Avaragātra --a chief monkey. Br. III. 7. 237.

अवरति
Avarati --a Pratardana god. Br. II. 36. 30.

अवरीयान्
Avarīyān --one of the nine sons of Sāvarṇi. Vā. 100. 21.

अवरोधन
Avarodhana --a son of Gaya and Gayantī. Bhā. V. 15. 14.

अवरोहम्
Avaroham --a variety of Rohaṇa Varṇa in music. Vā. 87. 7.

अवशावध
Avaśāvadha --A Śrutarṣi. Br. II. 33. 5.

अवस्यु
Avasyu --the Agni-Acchāvāka at Bhuvasthānam. Vā. 29. 28.

अविकारा
Avikārā --a mindborn mother. M. 179. 26.

अविक्षित्
Avikṣit --the son of Karamdhama and father of Marutta. Bhā. IX. 2. 26; Vi. IV. 1. 30-31. 

अविक्षित
Avikṣita --Marutta, different from Marutta of Turvasu's line. Vā. 99. 2.

अविजाति
Avijāti --goats and sheep born of Bhadrā. Br. III. 3. 75.

अविज्ञानगति
Avijñānagati --a son of Anila. Br. III. 3. 26.

अविज्ञातगति
Avijñātagati --a Vasava, and a son of Ana(i)la-Īśāna and Śiva. M. 5. 25; Vā. 66. 25; Br. II. 10. 80; Vi. I. 15. 114.

अविज्ञातम्
Avijñātam --a territorial division of Śālmali-dvīpa. (Abhijñātam--Burnouf) Bhā. V. 20. 9.

अविद्ध
Aviddha --the son of Janamejaya; conquered the eastern region. Vā. 99. 120.

अविद्या
Avidyā --of five degrees--Tāmisra, Andhatāmisra, Tama, Moha, and Mahātama. Bhā. III. 20. 18.

अविद्या
Avidyā --Pañcaparva; precedes creation. Vā. 6. 37.

अविधेय
Avidheya  (I)--the seventh hell under the earth. Vā. 101. 179.

अविधेय
Avidheya  (II)--a hell under the earth. Br. IV. 2. 182 and 186. 

अविपाल
Avipāla --Hiraṇyakaśipu as. Br. III. 5. 21.

अविमुक्तम्
Avimuktam  (I)--the name which Benares got after Śiva and Umā made it their residence. In Kaliyuga his original form disappears. Br. III. 67. 60 and 63.

अविमुक्त
Avimukta(m)  (II)--ety. Benares which is not left by Śiva at any time. M. 180. 54 and 94; 181. 13, 15, 31; 182. 4-5, 19-20, 23, 26; 183. 19, 36 and 39; 184, 1-2, 21-2, 48-9, 74; 185. 1-2, 17-18, 46-7, 54, 71; Vā. 106. 69; Vi. V. 34. 30.

अविशेषाः
Aviśeṣāḥ --Bhūtādi covered by śabda; both by sparśa; the three by rūpa, these four by rasa and all the five by gandha. Vā. 4. 58.

अवीचि
Avīci --one of the 28 hells--a structure with no support to stand on. Here are punished false witnesses and wrong givers of gifts. Bhā. V. 26. 7 and 28.

अवीचिकम्
Avīcikam --a hell. Vi. I. 6. 41.

अवीचिमत्
Avīcimat --a hell. Bhā. V. 26. 28; Br. IV. 2. 182 and 185.

अवीची
Avīcī --the fifth hell under the earth; torture by machinery. Vā. 101. 179, 182; 112. 11. 

अव्यक्तम्
Avyaktam --another term for Prakṛti; shines like firefly; overlordship consisting of Brahma, Viṣṇu, Sūrya and Śiva. These are to be worshipped with no difference, by means of fire and Brāhmaṇas. 2) Br. III. 10. 37; M. 52. 22. One form of Brahman; also Pradhānam, Kāraṇam. 3) Vi. I. 2. 15, 18-22. ^1 M. 3. 15; 145. 73; Vā. 34. 37; 101. 115; 102. 31, 34, 95; 103. 11-12, 28, 36.

अव्यय
Avyaya  (I)--a son of Bhṛgu, and a deva. Br. III. 1. 90; M. 195. 13.

अव्यय
Avyaya  (II) (Paulastya)--a sage of the Raucya epoch. Br. IV. 1. 102.

अव्यय
Avyaya  (III)--An Ajitadeva. Vā. 67. 34.

अव्यय
Avyaya  (IV)--a sage of the XIIIth epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 40.

अशना
Aśanā --the queen of Bali, and mother of Bāṇa and other sons. Bhā. VI. 18. 17.

अशनिमेघ
Aśanimeghas --creation of, by Brahmā. Vā. 9. 52; Br. II. 8. 54.

अशनी
Aśanī --a mother goddess. M. 179. 29.

अशिज
Aśija --the son of Vāmadeva. Vā. 65. 102; 99. 141.

अशिरस्
Aśiras --a dānava. Br. III. 6. 5. 

अशीतिमण्डलशतम्
Aśītimaṇḍalaśatam --8000 maṇḍalas traversed by the sun in a year. Its own maṇḍala in one day. Vā. 52. 46.

अशून्यशयनव्रतम्
Aśūnyaśayanavratam --offering worship to Hari sleeping with His consort in the milk ocean, on the black half of the Śrāvaṇa month, second day, with ritual, dancing and music. Gifts of bed, food, lights, etc., conduce to happiness in married life and the attainment of Viṣṇuloka. M. 71. 5-20.

अशोक
Aśoka --a kulaparvata of the Ketumāla. Vā. 44. 4.

अशोकवनम्
Aśokavanam --In Tripuram. Here Yayāti built a house for Śarmiṣṭhā, servant maid of his queen Devayānī. M. 31. 2 & 10; 130. 16; Vā. 38. 68.

अशोक
Aśoka(vardhana) --son of Bindusāra (Vārisāra-Bhā.). 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 13-14; Vi. IV. 24. 30. The Maurya king who ruled for 36 years; 26 years (Vā. P.). Father of Suyaśas. 2) Br. III. 74, 145; Vā. 99. 332; Vi. IV. 24. 30.

अश्मक
Aśmaka --a Kṣetraja son of Kalmāṣapāda (MitrasahaVi.) born of Madayantī, queen of Saudāsa, to Vasiṣṭha, with the king's assent. The period of pregnancy lasted for seven years when Vasiṣṭha bit the queen's stomach with a stone. Father of Mūlaka. Bhā. IX. 9. 39-40; Br. III. 63. 177; Vā. 88. 177; Vi. IV. 4. 72-3.

अश्मक
Aśmakas --the people of a southern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 58; M. 272. 16.

अश्मकी
Aśmakī --the mother of Śūra. Br. III. 71. 145 & 189. 

अश्मदंशना
Aśmadaṃśanā --the goddess following Bhavamālinī. M. 179. 71.

अश्मरथ्य
Aśmarathya --a Trayārṣeya; not to have marital relations with Viśvāmitra and Vañjuli. M. 198. 13.

अश्मराविन्
Aśmarāvin --the chief minister of Śantanu; made certain ascetics teach Devāpi heretical doctrines (Aśmasārio --Cal. edn.). Vi. IV. 20. 21.

अश्व
Aśva  (I)--an avatār of Hari. Bhā. X. 2. 40.

अश्व
Aśva  (II)--a Satya god, and a progenitor. Br. II. 36. 35; III. 11. 76.

अश्व
Aśva  (III)--a son of Khaśā and a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 136.

अश्व
Aśva  (IV)--a horse of the moon's chariot. Vā. 52. 53.

अश्व
Aśva  (V)--a son of Citraka. Vā. 96. 114.

अश्व
Aśvas  (I)--a class of people similar to Caṇḍālas. Bhā. X. 24. 28.

अश्व
Aśvas  (II)--created from the feet of the Lord; 1) Vi. I. 5. 49. horses of Tāmrā line. 2) Vi. I. 21. 17. 

अश्वकर्ण
Aśvakarṇa --a place fit for śrāddha offering. M. 15. 33.

अश्वक्रान्त
Aśvakrānta --music, with Aśvini as deity. Vā. 86. 64.

अश्वग्रीव
Aśvagrīva  (I)--a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 10.

अश्वग्रीव
Aśvagrīva  (II)--a son of Citraka. Br. III. 71. 114; Vā. 96. 113.

अश्वजित्
Aśvajit --son of Jayadratha. M. 49. 49.

अश्वतर
Aśvatara  (I)--a chief Nāga of Pātāla; a thousand hooded snake in the Prajāpatikṣetra in Prayāga on the banks of the Yamunā; 1) Bhā. V. 24. 31; M. 6. 29; 104. 5; 106. 27; 110. 8. used in the chariot of Tripurāri; 2) M. 133. 20. presides over the month of Ūrja; 3) Bhā. XII. 11. 44. A Kādraveya Nāga. 4) Br. II. 20. 23; 23. 21; III. 7. 33; Vi. I. 21. 21. A Nāga of the Sutalam; 5) Vā. 50. 23. resides in the sun's chariot during Phalguna. 6) Vi. II. 10. 18.

अश्वतर
Aśvatara  (II)--heard the Viṣṇu Purāṇa from Vatsa and narrated it to Kambala. Vi. VI. 8. 46.

अश्वतर
Aśvatara  (III)--a nāga. Vā. 69. 70.

अश्वतर
Aśvataras --created by Brahmā from his feet. Vi. I. 5. 49.

अश्वतीर्थम्
Aśvatīrtham --sacred to Pitṛs on the Narmadā. M. 22. 71; 194. 3. 

अश्वत्थ
Aśvattha  (I)--the sacred tree under which Kṛṣṇa is said to have sat in contemplation on the eve of his departure to Heaven. 1) Bhā. III. 4. 3 & 8; Br. III. 11. 35 & 109; 13. 29; IV. 43. 17; Vā. 35. 33; 91. 44. Growing out of Śami tree; by attrition Purūravas created fire and made it threefold for sacrificial purposes. 2) Vi. IV. 6. 85-94.

अश्वत्थ
Aśvattha  (II)--the tīrtha sacred to Vandanīya. M. 13. 51.

अश्वत्थ
Aśvattha  (III)--a follower of Māyā. M. 179. 69.

अश्वत्थराज
Aśvattharāja --the Bodhi tree. Vā. 111. 27.

अश्वत्थामन्
Aśvatthāman  (I)--son of Droṇa and Gautamī. (KṛpiVi. P.). Killed the sons of Draupadī while asleep thinking that it would please his master. Fought with Arjuna, was defeated and taken prisoner. Roused Draupadī's pity in that state and was released after being deprived of his crown and hair. 1) Bhā. I. 7. 14-52; Vi. IV. 19. 68. Hit the infant in the womb of Uttara with brahmaśiras. Kṛṣṇa's protection of Parīkṣit in the womb from Aśvathāman's arrow, and of Arjuna from Aśvathāman's arrows. 2) Bhā. I. 8. 12; 12. 1; 15. 16; 16. 15. Destroyed the Kurus by his brahmāstra. 3) Bhā. IX. 22. 34. In Duryodhana's army. Survived Kurukṣetra war. 4) Bhā. X. 78. [95. (V) 16]; 80[2]. A sage of the first epoch of Śāvarṇa Manu 5) Vā. 100. 12; M. 9. 32. hurled brahmāstra when Parīkṣit was in his mother's womb. 6) Vi. IV. 20. 52.

अश्वत्थामन्
Aśvatthāman  (II)--(Droṇaputra) becomes a sage of the 8th manvantara. Bhā. VIII. 13. 15. 

अश्वत्थामन्
Aśvatthāman  (III)--a son of Aśvinī and Akrūra. M. 45. 32.

अश्वपति
Aśvapati --the king of Madras; issueless sacrificed to goddess Sāvitrī and was blessed with a daughter of that name. M. 208. 5-11.

अश्वप्र
Aśvapra --a dānava. Br. III. 6. 15.

अश्वबाहु
Aśvabāhu --a son of Citraka. Vā. 96. 113.

अश्वमित्र
Aśvamitra --a Marut gaṇa. M. 171. 53.

अश्वमुख
Aśvamukha --a horse-faced image on the figure of God of Love. M. 261. 53.

अश्वमुख
Aśvamukh(y)as --a group of people, perhaps Gandharvas; 1) Br. III. 22. 56; M. 4. 53; Vā. 47. 57; 69. 31. kingdom of. 2) M. 121. 58.

अश्वमेध
Aśvamedha --Thrice performed by Yudhiṣṭhira. 1) Bhā. I. 8. 6; 10. 2. [1]; 12. 34. One hundred performed by Bali; 2) Ib. VIII. 15. 34. of Ambarīṣa where Vasiṣṭha and Gautama were present. 3) Ib. IX. 4. 22. Thrice performed by Parīkṣit. 4) Ib. I. 16. 3. Performed by Aṅga when gods did not respond to his call. 5) Ib. IV. 13. 25. A hundred were performed by Pṛthu. But in the last Indra stole away the horse. 6) Ib. IV. 16. 24; 19, 1. Performed by Indra. 7) Ib. VI. 13. 18-20; Br. II. 30. 10; M. 143. 6-26. Performed by Kṛṣṇa at Dvārakā. The sacrificial horse was sent out with a number of warriors to watch its course. All  kings including the Pāṇḍavas attended the sacrifice. In the course of the sacrifice a Brāhmaṇa complained of the death of his children immediately after birth. At this Arjuna (s.v.) offered to give succour and recovered them with Kṛṣṇa's aid, from Nārāyaṇa's abode. Nārāyaṇa said that he took the children as a means to see Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna in their human form. The Avabhṛta of the sacrifice was celebrated in the Yamunā. 8) Bhā. X. 89. 22-64. A remedy for brahmicide. 9) Ib. VI. 13. 6-9. Performed by Śūdra kings in Kali age; 10) Br. II. 31. 67; M. 144. 43. of other kings; 11) Br. II. 34. 24; III. 5. 7; 7. 268; 11. 13-16; 64. 17; 68. 26; 70. 24 and 27; 71. 119; 72. 28; IV. 12. 31. of Ikṣvāku, of Dakṣa, of Suyajña, of Nala, of Śatānīka of Purūravas; 12) M. 12. 10; 12. 15; 44, 23 and 64; 24. 10; Vā. 105. 10. 32; 111. 17, 51; 112. 31-2. equal to going to Gayā, bath in the Prayāga and Ganges, koṭihoma, grahabali, etc. 13) M. 22. 6; 28. 6; 53. 15; 58. 54; 106. 29; 183. 71 and 80. 100 of them performed by Somadatta; 14) Vi. IV. 1. 56. as efficacious as reading the Viṣṇu Purāṇa; 15) Vi. VI. 8. 28 & 34. performed by other sages. 16) Vā. 20. 16; 32. 52; 30. 291; 50. 221; 57. 52; 60. 23; 67. 50, 53-8; 71. 77; 75. 60, 75; 99. 456; 104. 84; Bhā. IX. 22. 39.

अश्वमेधज
Aśvamedhaja --the son of Sahasrānīka and father of Asīmakṛṣṇa. Bhā. IX. 22. 39.

अश्वमेधदत्त
Aśvamedhadatta --the son of Śatānīka and father of Adhisīmakṛṣṇa. Vi. IV. 21. 5-6; Vā. 99. 257.

अश्वमेढ्र
Aśvameḍhra --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 89.

अश्वयुक्
Aśvayuk--(śukla-navami),  a manvantarādi for śrāddha. M. 17. 6. 

अश्ववाह
Aśvavāha --a son of Citraka. Br. III. 71. 114.

अश्वविद्या
Aśvavidyā --was taught to Ṛtuparṇa by Nala; also Aśvaśikṣā. Bhā. IX. 9. 17.

अश्वव्रतम्
Aśvavratam --the performer of it, becomes Rājarāja. M. 101. 71.

अश्वशिक्षा
Aśvaśikṣā --the science of horses. M. 215. 8.

अश्वशिरस्
Aśvaśiras  (I)--the mantra taught by the sage Dadhyaṅga to Aśvins. Bhā. VI. 9. 52.

अश्वशिरस्
Aśvaśiras  (II)--a follower of Bali. M. 245. 31.

अश्वसुत
Aśvasuta --married Sutanu; father of Vajra. Vā. 96. 251.

अश्वसेन
Aśvasena --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyā (Nāgnicit). Bhā. X. 61. 13.

अश्वाध्यक्ष
Aśvādhyakṣa --Superintendent of horses and his qualifications. M. 215. 38.

अश्वानन
Aśvānana --also Vājivaktra--see Hayagrīva. Br. IV. 17. 17; 29. 1; 30. 1; 39. 1. 

अश्वायु
Aśvāyu  (I)--a son of Purūravas and Urvaśī. M. 24. 33.

अश्वायु
Aśvāyu  (II)--a Trayārṣeya. M. 196. 43.

अश्वारूढा
Aśvārūḍhā --a devī who killed Ulūkajit. Br. IV. 28. 38 & 99.

अश्वास्य
Aśvāsya --a son of Citraka. Br. III. 71. 115.

अश्विनी
Aśvinī  (I)--the wife of Akrūra, and mother of thirteen sons. M. 45. 32-3.

अश्विनी
Aśvinī  (II)--a nakṣatra; as part of Nāgavithī; 1) Vā. 66. 48. effect of Śrāddha, performed in; 2) Ib. 82. 14. as the presiding deity of musical melody Aśvakrantā. 3) Ib. 86. 64.

अश्विन्
Aśvins --the gods of Vaivasvata epoch; sons of Badavā (Samjñā) and Vivasvat born through the nose and hence Nāsatyas; 1) Bhā. VIII. 13. 4, 10; Br. III. 59. 74-76; M. 9. 29; 11. 35-7; 25. 43; Vi. I. 9. 64; III. 2. 7; Vā. 84. 23-24, fought with Vṛṣaparva in Devāsura war. 2) Bhā. VIII. 10. 30. Were taught the Aśvasiras mantra by the sage Dadhyaṅga. 3) Ib. VI. 9. 52; 10. 17. Called on Cyavana. Being physicians they could not participate in Soma. Cyavana offered a share in Soma to them if they could give him a youthful form. He was made to look exactly like themselves so much so that Sukanyā was not able to distinguish her husband. On a prayer the  Aśvins showed Sukanyā her lord and departed. 4) Bhā. IX. 3. 11-17. Vā. 10. 71; 30. 84; 39. 49. In the yajña of Śaryāti, were allowed to partake of Soma juice. 5) Bhā. IX. 3. 24-26. Parents of Nakula and Sahadeva through Pāṇḍu's queen Mādrī. 6) Ib. IX. 22. 28; M. 46. 10; 50. 50; Vi. IV. 20. 40. Came to Dvārakā to ask Kṛṣṇa to go to Vaikuṇṭha; 7) Bhā. XI. 6. 2; Vā. 96. 154; 99. 245. worshipped for long life; 8) Bhā. II. 3. 5. form the nose of Puruṣa; 9) Bhā. II. 1. 29. guard medicinal herbs in Candra hill of Plakṣa for nectar; 10) Br. II. 19. 8; Vā. 49. 9. born from the nostrils of Prajāpati; vanquished by Rāvaṇa; 11) Br. III. 1. 57; 7. 254. present in the Candraśāla of Devī. 12) Ib. III. 35. 57. Fought with Devas against Kālanemi, being experts in Citrayuddham. 13) M. 148. 86, 97. Also Aśvikumārakau; worship of, in the grahabali. 14) M. 93. 16; 247. 10. Born of Brahmā; 15) Vā. 65. 57. the two forefeet of the Śiśumāra (porpoise); 16) Vā. II. 12. 32; Vā. 52. 93; Br. II. 23. 103; M. 127. 23. inhabit the Bhuvarloka; 17) Vā. 101. 29; Br. IV. 2. 27. stood on Gayāsura, along with other gods; 18) Vā. 106. 59. presented their weapons on the occasion of the marriage of Śiva with Lalitā to the divine couple; 19) Br. IV. 15. 24. came with other gods to pray to goddess Lalitā for her victory against Bhaṇḍa; 20) Ib. IV. 20. 52. the ears of Vāmana avatāra 21) M. 246. 56.

अश्विषेण
Aśviṣeṇa --a Bhārgava-gotrakāra. Vā. 65. 96.

अष्टक
Aṣṭaka  (I)--a śrāddha performed by Ikṣvāku, which led to the banishment of his son Vikukṣi (s.v.); 1) Bhā. IX. 6. 6; Br. III. 17. 2-7; 63. 11; Vā. 88. 11-19. a yugāḍi for sādharaṇa śrāddha; 2) M. 17. 2, 5. the eighth day after full moon on which Manes are worshipped; three are distinguished, in the month of Caitra, of Pauṣa and Māgha; 3) Vā. 81. 2; sacred to Kāvya pitṛs. 4) Vā. 56. 19.

अष्टक
Aṣṭaka  (II)--a son of Viśvāmitra by Dṛṣadvatī and a sage; 1) Bhā. IX. 16. 36; Br. II. 32. 118; III. 66. 68-74; Vi. IV. 7. 38; Vā. 91. 96, 103. father of Lauhi; 2) Br. III. 66. 75. originator of the Jaḥnugaṇa. 3) Vā. 91. 103. 

अष्टक
Aṣṭaka  (III)--a Rājaṛṣi who met Yayāti falling from Heaven and discoursed with him on several points: A grandson of Yayāti by his daughter; a Brahmiṣṭha, and Trayārṣeya with Viśvāmitra and Lohita; goes to Heaven with all his relations including Yayāti. M. 35. 5; Ib. Chapters 37-41; 42. 14 & 28.

अष्टक
Aṣṭaka  (IV)--a brother of Vasudeva. Vi. IV. 14. 30.

अष्टका
Aṣṭakā --the name of Acchodā in Pitṛloka after she went from the earth. In her honour a river is named. M. 14. 19-20; 141. 17.

अष्टकापति
Aṣṭakāpatis --are Kāvyas. Br. II. 28. 21; M. 141. 17.

अष्टताल
Aṣṭatāla --the normal height of man, 84 inches. Navatāla is superior man. Br. II. 32. 9; Vā. 59. 8.

अष्टवान्
Aṣṭavān --an Amśa of Skanda. Vā. 101. 280.

अष्टाङ्ग
Aṣṭāṅga --the name of a book on medical science. M. 215. 34.

अष्टाङ्गप्राणवृत्ति
Aṣṭāṅgaprāṇavṛtti --action of vital airs in life. Vā. 102. 90, 91.

अष्टाङ्गयोग
Aṣṭāṅgayoga --consists of āsana, prāṇarodha, pratyāhāra, dhāraṇā, dhyāna, samādhi, together with yamas and niyamas. Vi. 104. 24-25. 

अष्टावाहुतीः
Aṣṭāvāhutīḥ --the Vaiśvadeva homa where eight oblations are offered to Vaiśvānara; the five following to be done with svāhā; afterwards touch the heart with mantra specified; then touch all over the body--cf. Yajurveda: the oblation of rice offered in Agni is the food for devas and dānavas. Vā. 15. 5-16.

अष्टादशविद्य
Aṣṭādaśavidyas --the 14 vidyas besides Āyurveda, Dhanurveda, Gandharva and Arthaśāstra The fourteen vidyas are the six Vedāṅgas, four Vedas, mīmāmsā, nyāya, dharmaśāstras and Purāṇas. Vā. 61. 78-79.

अष्टापदम्
Aṣṭāpadam --gaming board (dyūtaphalaka) with which Baladeva beat Rukmi to death. Vi. V. 28. 23.

अष्टावक्र
Aṣṭāvakra --a sage crooked in eight parts of the body; was performing penances with his body below the neck under waters. The nymphs who went to Merupṛṣṭa to see a festival beheld him and hymned him; pleased he asked them their wish. “Puruṣottama for husband” they said. He agreed and when he came out of waters, seeing his form they laughed at him. Insulted, he imprecated that they would be the wives first of Puruṣottama and then fall into the hands of robbers. They prayed fervently and he said that they would attain heaven afterwards. Vi. V. 38. 71-84.

अष्टाविंशतितममनु
Aṣṭāviṃśatitamamanu --the period when Baladeva flourished. Vi. IV. 1. 76.

असकृत्
Asakṛt --a Bhārgavagotrakara. M. 195. 28. 

असक्नि
Asakni --the daughter of Vīraṇa Prajāpati and wife of Dakṣa; 1000 sons, lost by Nārada's tricks; another 1000 sons were brought forth, but they met with similar result (mother of 5000 Haryaśvas and 1000 Śabalāśvas-Vi. P.). Vā. 65. 128, 134, 146-51 and 154; Vi. I. 15. 89-100.

असङ्ग
Asaṅga --the son of Yuyudhāna. M. 45. 23.

असम
Asama --an Ajita deva. Br. II. 13. 93.

असमञ्जस्
Asamañjas --a Kākutstha; the son of Sagara by Keśinī. Father of Amśumān: In previous birth as a Vaiśya he discovered a treasure. A spirit guarding it asked him to quench his hunger with cow's flesh and carry away the treasure. But he took it without providing food. So when born to Keśinī, the spirit entered him as wind and hence demented; used to throw his playmates into the Sarayū; was banished by his father. He left the capital after bringing them back to life by his wonderful yogic powers. Bhā. IX. 8. 15-19; M. 12. 42-43; Br. III. 51. 38-69; 63. 160 & 165; Vā. 88. 160, 165-66; Vi. IV. 4. 5-10.

असमौजस्
Asamaujas --the son of Kambalabarhis and father of Susamaujas. 1) Br. III. 71. 142; Vā. 96. 141. [Asāmañjas (Matsya P.)]
Tamojāta was his son. 2) M. 44. 83.

असंख्येय
Asaṃkhyeya --calculated by rāśi and not by enumeration. Vā. 101. 108-9. 

असंसृष्ट
Asaṃsṛṣṭa --a name for Havyasūda. Vā. 29. 22.

असलिका
Asalikā --a daughter of Vākā and Viśravas. Vā. 70. 50.

असि
Asi --the sword; particularly that of Śiva. Vā. 30. 124; 101. 272.

असिक्नी
Asiknī  (I)--R. in Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 18.

असिक्नी
Asiknī  (II)--the daughter of Pañcajana (Viraṇa-Vi. P.) the wife of Dakṣa 1) Bhā. VI. 4. 51; Vi. I. 15. 89. and the mother of Haryaśvas who were ten thousand in number (five thousand-Vi. P.) of Śabalāśvas who were also a thousand in number 2) Bhā. VI. 5. 1, 24; Br. III. 2. 5, 21-30; Vi. I. 15. 90, 97. and of sixty daughters. 3) Bhā. VI. 6. 1; Vi. I. 15. 102.

असिज
Asija  (I)--An Aṅgiras and mantrakṛt. Br. I. 32. 111.

अशिज
Aśija  (II)--a sage; the brother of Bṛhaspati; wife, Mamatā. Vā. 99. 36.

असिज
Asija  (III)--a kind of hell. Vā. 101. 149. 

असित
Asita  (I)--a siddha--called on dying Bhīṣma. 1) Bhā. VI. 15. 12; I. 9. 7. Invited for Yudhṣṭhira's sacrifice. 2) Ib. X. 74. 7. Came to Syamanta-pañcaka to see Kṛṣṇa. 3) Ib. X. 84. 3. One of the sages who left Dvārakā for Piṇḍāraka. 4) Ib. XI. 1. 12. Went with Kṛṣṇa to Mithilā. 5) Ib. X. 86. 18. Acted as Purohita at Kṛṣṇa's sacrifice in Kurukṣetra. 6) Ib. X. 90. 46 [2]. Identified with Hari. 7) Ib. XI. 16. 28. A place in the Sarasvatī sacred to Asita. 8) Ib. III. 1. 22.

असित
Asita  (II)--a gotrakara son of Kaśyapa, married Ekaparṇā, daughter of Himavān: Father of Devala, the best among Śāṇḍilyas and Brahmiṣṭha (Vā. P.). A Brahmavādin. Not to marry with members of Kaśyapa and Devala. 2) M. 199. 19. A yogācarya; Ekaparṇā, his wife, gave birth to Devala by her mind. 3) Vā. 72. 17. ^1 Br. II. 32. 112; III. 8. 29; 10. 18. M. 145. 107; Vā. 59. 103; 70. 25.

असित
Asita  (III)--the sacred hill fit for Śrāddha; 1) Br. III. 13. 39. the residence of the sage Asita. 2) Vā. 77. 39.

असित
Asita  (IV)--the sage to whom the earth revealed the ignorance of worldly kings; this he reported to Janaka. Vi. IV. 24. 127.

असितम्
Asitam --same as Kusumotkaram. M. 122. 24.

असिता
Asitā --an apsaras. Br. III. 7. 7.

असिताङ्ग
Asitāṅga --a Bhairava on the sixth parva of Geyacakra. Br. IV. 19. 77-8.

असितोदम्
Asitodam --a lake in Ilāvṛta. Vi. II. 2. 26. 

असिप
Asipa --a dānava. Br. III. 6. 5.

असिपत्रवन
Asipatravana --one of 28 hells. Intended for those who leave the Vedic path to that of the Pākhaṇḍas; here their bodies are torn to pieces by the sharp edges of asipatra leaves (lit. forest where leaves are swords); 1) Bhā. V. 26. 7 & 15; Br. II. 28. 84; IV. 2. 149 and 173; 33. 61; M. 141. 71; Vā. 101. 170; Vi. I. 6. 41; II. 6. 3. in it fall those who cut and deal in camels and hunters who cut off animals, besides those fallen from karma. 2) Vā. 56. 79; 110. 43. Those that cut trees for no reason also fall into this. 3) Vi. II. 6. 3 and 26.

असिपर्णिनी
Asiparṇinī --an apsaras. Br. III. 7. 6.

असिलोमन्
Asiloman  (I)--a dānava, a son of Danu. Br. III. 6. 9; M. 6. 20; Vā. 68. 9.

असिलोमन्
Asiloman  (II)--a son of Śambhu. Vā. 67. 81.

असीमकृष्ण
Asīmakṛṣṇa --the son of Aśvamedhaja, and the father of Nemicakra; 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 39. was king when the Vāyu Purāṇa was uttered. 2) Vā. 1. 12.

असिसाहारीतायन
Asisāhārītāyanas --Kaśyapagotrakaras. M. 199. 9.

असुर
Asura --a deity personified; to be worshipped in housebuildings. M. 253. 26; 268. 16. 

असुर
Asuras  1) Bhā. I. 13. 6; VII. 3. 37; XII. 9. 28; Br. II. 32. 1, 2. 6; M. 47. 12; 131. 10, 39-41. --The foes and cognates of Devas; 2) Bhā. VI. 7. 18; Vā. 31. 11; Br. II. 8. 5; IV. 9. 67-8. born out of the jaghana of Prajāpati; etymology of; 3) Vā. 9. 4-5; Br. II. 8. 4; Vi. I. 5. 31. could secure Hari's blessing by adorning him; 4) Bhā. VII. 7. 50. opposed to Yajña; 5) Ib. VIII. 1. 17. the Āsura hour; 6) Ib. X. 28. 2. praise Śeṣa; 7) Ib. X. 39. 44-45. abode down the earth. 8) Ib. XI. 24. 13. Ruled the earth for ten yugas when it went back to the Devas on a curse by Śukra after 12 wars; 9) Br. III. 72. 69-93; Vā. 97. 68-93. worship Barhiṣad Pitrs. 10) M. 15. 3. Had three Indras--Hiraṇyakaśipu, Bali and Praḥlāda; 11) M. 47. 59. lost their refulgence on the eve of Vāmana avatāra. 12) M. 245. 1. represent night and darkness and full of tamas. 13) Br. II. 8. 4; Vi. I. 5. 31-4. Asura's killed in the wars with Devas are born as men in earth and create trouble in this world. 14) Br. III. 71. 263.

असुरथ
Asuratha --fought with Sumitra, deluded by Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. XI. 30. 16.

असुरान्तक
Asurāntaka --a chief monkey. Br. III. 7. 238.

असुत्वान
Asutvāna --the name by which Danu's sons were known. Br. III. 6. 14.

असूया
Asūyā --a son of Mṛtyu. Vā. 10. 41.

असोम
Asoma --an yakṣa; a son of Puṇyajanī and Maṇibhadra. Br. III. 7. 124.

अस्तगिरि
Asta-giri --A hill of Śākadvīpa. It was here that Bali who fell unconscious in the Devāsura war was treated with sañjīvinī vidyā. Bhā. VIII. 11. 46; Br. II. 19. 89; Vā. 49. 83; Vi. II. 4. 62. 

अस्ति
Asti --Daughter of Jarāsandha and a queen of Kamsa. After her husband's death she went to her father's place and reported the circumstances in which her husband was killed. Bhā. X. 50. 1-2; Vi. V. 22. 1.

अस्त्र
Astras --arranged alphabetically: Asiratnam, Āgneyam, Aindram, Aiṣīkāmam, Kampanam, Kāpalam, Kālamudgaram, Kainkaram, Krauñcam, Gāndharvam, Tāpanam, Tvāṣtram, Nandakam, Nārasimham, Nārāyaṇāstram, Pāśupatam, Paiśācam, Pramathanam, Prasthāpanam, Prasvāpanam, Brahmaśiras, Brāhmam, Bhāvanam, Bhairavam, Mathanam, Mahābalam, Māyādharam, Mohanam, Mausalam, Raudram, Vāruṇam, Vikampanam, Vāyavyam, Śātanam, Śāmanam, Śailam, Ṣośadam, Samvartanam, Sārpam, Sāvitram, Somāstram, Hayaśiras; 1) M. 150. 113, 164, 205; 151. 24, 31; 153. 83, 87, 90, 97; 162. 22-7; 179. 6. used by Hiraṇyakaśipu against Narasimha; arms used in Bhaṇḍāsura war. 2) Br. IV. 29. 62-74.

अस्त्रग्रामम्
Astragrāmam --That relating to the use of astras. Parasurāma learnt the four aspects from Śiva; 1) Br. III. 21. 79; 25. 39; 32. 59; 34. 34. learnt by Kṛṣṇa and Rāma. 2) Vi. V. 21. 23.

अस्त्राचार्य
Astrācārya --the teacher of weapons of warfare: 4 kinds are mentioned; throwing by machines, by hands, thrown simply, and taking back after throwing away. M. 215. 41.

अस्मक
Asmakas --of the Dākṣiṇātya country. Vā. 45. 127.

अस्मकी
Asmakī  (I)--the wife of Śūra. Vā. 96. 143. 

अस्मकी
Asmakī  (II)--the son Anādṛṣṭi. Vā. 96. 186.

अस्वस्थलय
Asvasthalaya --a Trayārṣeya. M. 200. 14.

अस्वहार्य
Asvahārya --a mantrakṛt. M. 145. 103.

अहतम्
Ahatam --unwashed cloths, to be given in Śrāddha. Vā. 80. 4, 37.

अहंकार
Ahaṃkāra --one of the tatvas; description of. Vā. 103. 38; Vi. I. 2, 36-46.

अहंकारकर्षिणी
Ahaṃkārakarṣiṇī --a Gupta Śakti. Br. IV. 19. 17; 44. 117.

अहंयाति
Ahaṃyāti --the son of Samyāti and the father of Raudrāśva. Bhā. IX. 20. 3; Vi. IV. 19. 1.

अहल्या
Ahalyā  (I)--the daughter of Mudgala, the wife of Gautama and the mother of Śatānanda. 1) Bhā. IX. 21. 34. A tīrtham in her honour, as she performed tapas and attained release there. 2) M. 191. 90-1.

अहल्या
Ahalyā  (II)--a daughter of Vindhyāśva (Badhyāśva, Vā. P.) (Haryaśva. Vi. P.) and Menakā; sister of Divodāsa, and wife of Śaradvat; mother of Śadānanda; 1) M. 50. 7-8; Vā. 99. 201; Vi. IV. 19. 62, 200-2. redeemed of her sins by Rāma. 2) Vi. IV. 4. 91.

अहल्यातीर्थम्
Ahalyātīrtham --on the Narmadā. Here she performed tapas and got salvation. By worshipping here, one becomes beloved of ladies. M. 191. 90-3. 

अहस्
Ahas (sitā, rātri) --of Brahmā) one cycle of a thousand caturyugas; at the end, when dāhakāla sets in Vaimānika devas come into existence, as also stars, asterisms, sun and moon, etc.; 1) Vā. 3. 14; 7. 14-16; 24. 2; 61. 42; 100. 224-6; M. 231. 2; duration of in ordinary years; 2) Vā. 100. 131; Br. II. 6. 57f. enters the waters in the evening; 3) Vā. 53. 14-15. created with the Devas; 4) Br. II. 7. 19; 8. 11; 13. 14. of the Pitṛs is Kṛṣṇapakṣa. 5) Vā. 57. 9.

अहस्परमेश्वर
Ahas-Parameśvara --is sṛṣṭi or creation; at the end of this day occurs pralaya. Vā. 5. 1-6.

अहित
Ahita --an Yakṣa--a son of Devajanī and Maṇvara. Br. III. 7. 129.

अहिमुख्य
Ahimukhya --to be worshipped in housebuilding. M. 253. 26.

अहिमूर्छ
Ahimūrcha --Varuṇa as presiding deity. Vā. 86. 61.

अहीनक
Ahīnak(g)a --the son of Devānīka 1) Vā. 88. 202. and the father of Ruru. 2) Vi. IV. 4. 106. (Pāripātra-Va.)

अहिंसा
Ahiṃsā --one aspect of Sanātana dharma, largely observed in Tretāyuga; 1) Br. II. 29. 69; 30, 35; III. 23. 51, 68 and 72. non-injury in thought, speech and action towards all beings prescribed for ascetics. 2) Vā. 18. 15-16; M. 61. 15; 106. 48; 143. 12-13 and 30.

अहिंसाव्रतम्
Ahiṃsāvratam --the performer becomes a king; consists in abstention from meat for a year and the gift of a cow at the end. M. 101. 35. 

अहिर्बुध्न
Ahirbudhna  (I)--a division of the night. Vā. 66. 43.

अहिर्बुध्न
Ahirbudhna  (II)--(see also Anurdeśya)--a name for Grahapati Agni. Vā. 29. 26; Br. II. 12. 26.

अहिर्बुध्न्य
Ahirbudhnya --a Rudra, and son of Bhūta and Sarūpā. Bhā. VI. 6. 18; Br. III. 3. 71; M. 5. 29, 32; 171. 39; Vā. 66. 69.

अहीन
Ahīna --the son of Sahadeva. Father of Jayatsena. Br. III. 68. 10.

अहीनगु
Ahīnagu --the son of Devānīka, and father of Pāriyātra. Br. III. 63. 203-4; M. 12. 54.

अहोरात्रकल
Ahorātrakalas --more than 600; thirty muhūrtas or 602 kalas make one day and one night; 605 kalas according to the measurement of the sun. Vā. 66. 38; 100. 216, 223.

अहोरात्रम्
Ahorātram --a day and a night; 30 muhūrtas: For pitṛs --Kṛṣṇapakṣa and Śuklapakṣa (one month); for Devas one full year is one day. Br. II. 13. 112; M. 1. 19; 142. 5-6, 9; Vā. 65. 59; 66. 37.  Ā

आकर्णनी
Ākarṇanī --the goddess following Revatī. M. 179. 72.

आकर्षिणी
Ākarṣiṇī --a mudrā Devī. Br. IV. 42. 6.

आकार
Ākāra --the second face of the fourteen faced Deva, Manu Svārociṣa born in white colour. Vā. 26. 33.

आकाश
Ākāśa  (I)--a god to be worshipped in housebuilding. M. 253. 24; 265. 39.

आकाश
Ākāśa  (II)--with Dik; a sthāna of Rudra; son, Sarga. Vi. I. 8. 7-11.

आकाशम्
Ākāśam --the ether, stands uncovered, formless, devoid of rasa, sparśa and gandha; its characteristic is śabda. Vā. 102. 15, 17; M. 3. 23.

आकाशगङ्गा
Ākāśagaṅgā --R. that encircles Amarāvatī; 1) Bhā. VIII. 15. 14. that water which comes down without the cloud; bath in this is called celestial ablution. 2) Vi. II. 9. 12 and 17.

आकाशगङ्गा
Ākāśagaṅgā tīrtham --in Gayā. Vā. 112. 25.

आकूति
Ākūti  (I)--A daughter of Svāyambhuva Manu (Vairāja-Vā. P.) and Śatarūpā. Wife of Ruci. From her Hari manifested himself for imparting dharma and jñāna. Gave birth to twins--a son and a daughter by putrikādharma. These were Yajña and Dakṣiṇā. Bhā. I. 3. 12; III. 12. 55-56; IV. 1. 1-4; VIII. 1. 5; II. 7. 2; Br. III. 3. 113; Vā. 10. 17-9; Br. I. 1. 58; II. 9. 42-43; Vi. I. 7. 18-19. 

आकूति
Ākūti  (II)--the queen of Sarvatejas and mother of Manu Cākṣuṣa. Bhā. IV. 13. 15.

अकूति
Akūti  (III)--the wife of Pṛthusena and mother of Nakta. Bhā. V. 15. 6.

आकूति
Ākūti  (IV)--a Jayādeva. Br. III. 3. 6; 4. 2; Vā. 66. 6.

आकूति
Ākūti  (V)--the twenty-fourth kalpa. Vā. 21. 55.

आकूति
Ākūti  (VI)--became twins in the Ākūti kalpa. Vā. 21. 55-56.

आकूति
Ākūti  (VII)--a son of Brahman with a mantraśarīra Vā. 67. 4-5.

आकूति
Ākūti  (VIII)--the mother of Yajña, the mindborn son in the first epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 1. 36.

आकृति
Ākṛti  (I)--a progenitor, responsible for form and shape. Br. II. 9. 1 and 7.

आकृति
Ākṛti  (II)--a son of Babhru. Br. III. 70. 38.

आखण्डल
Ākhaṇḍala --name of Indra. Bhā. III. 33. 20. 

आखुवाहन
Ākhuvāhana --Gaṇeśa. Br. IV. 27. 101.

आख्यानम्
Ākhyānam --a feature of the Purāṇa the fifth Veda; 1) Br. II. 34. 21; III. 1. 6; 5. 8 and 11; 13. 54; 59. 4; Vā. 54. 1; 60. 21; 67. 54, 58. Purāṇic stories. 2) M. 53. 65; 214. 23; Vi. I. 22. 84; III. 6. 15.

आख्यानकुशल
Ākhyānakuśala --Sūta. Vā. 84. 4.

आगम
Āgama  1) Vi. I. 17. 58.--the rules of; 2) Br. II. 30. 19 and 27; III. 21. 46. for digging wells, constructing tanks and gardens; 3) M. 58. 55; 143. 13. cited for yajñas where paśu was not involved and where bīja (seeds) served the purpose of the animal. 4) Vā. 53. 122; 57. 100.

आगस्त्य
Āgastyas --the Brahmarākṣasas--a clan moving about in the night; 1) Br. III. 8. 59 and 62; Vā. 69. 195-6. of Surabhi forest; 2) M. 121. 62. summoned Kauberaka to live at Hariśṛṅga. 3) Vā. 47. 60-1.

आगावह
Āgāvaha --a son of Vasudeva and Vṛkadevī a mahātmā. Br. III. 71. 180.

आगाही
Āgāhī --a daughter of Vṛkadevī. Vā. 96. 180.

आग्न
Āgnas --Kaśyapagotrakaras. M. 199. 8.

आग्नायि
Āgnāyi --a goddess, wife of Dikpāla Agni. M. 286. 7. 

आग्नीध्र
Āgnīdhra  (I)--a son of Priyavrata and Barhiṣmatī. Father of Nābhi. Appointed lord of Jambūdvīpa. 1) Bhā. XI. 2. 15; V. 1. 25 and 33. Protected the people like his children. Issueless, he performed tapas when Brahmā sent the divine damsel Pūrvacitti with whom Āgnīdhra enjoyed life for 100,000 years. After giving birth to nine sons, she went back to the court of Brahmā. He divided his kingdom among his sons, and rejoined his wife in another world. On his death, his nine sons married the nine daughters of Meru. 2) Ib. V. 2. 1-23; Br. II. 14. 44-53; Vi. II. 1. 7, 12, 16-24.

आग्नीध्र
Ā(A)gnīdhra  (II)--one of the ten sons of Svāyambhuva Manu; 1) Br. II. 13. 104; M. 9. 4. milked the Cow-Earth with Svāyambhuva as calf. 2) Vā. 63. 13.

आग्नीध्र
Āgnīdhra  (III)--one of the ten sons of the daughter of Kardama, and Priyavrata. Br. II. 14. 9.

आग्निध्र
Āgnidhra  (IV)--one of the 16 Ṛtviks for an Yajña; created from the hands of Nārāyaṇa. M. 167. 10.

आग्नीध्रक
Āgnīdhraka --a sage of the epoch of the XIIth Manu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 28.

आग्निवेश्यायन
Āgniveśyāyanas --a Brahma-kula originating from Jātūkarṇa. Bhā. IX. 2. 22.

आग्निष्टोमिक
Āgniṣṭomika --the first Gāndhāra-grāma. Vā. 86. 41.

आग्नेय
Āgneya  (I)--the 18th kalpa. M. 290. 7. 

आग्नेय
Āgneya  (II)--a division of the night. Vā. 66. 43.

आग्नेय
Āgneyas  (I)--the Gandharva followers of Kubera; 1) Vā. 40. 8. their residences on the southern peaks of Maryādā Parvata. 2) Vā. 40. 5.

आग्नेय
Āgneyas  (II)--the Aṅgiras adopted by Agni when they sprung out of the sacrificial fire of Vāruṇī-yajña. Vā. 65. 42.

आग्नेयपुराण
Āgneya-Purāṇa --one among the eighteen Purāṇas; 1) Bhā. XII. 7. 23. deals with Īśāna Kalpa; narrated by Agni to Vasiṣṭha: of 16,000 verses; its gift and fruits thereof. 2) M. 53. 28-30.

आग्नेयव्रतम्
Āgneya-vratam --of kings; ruin rebellious sāmantas by his valour. M. 226. 7.

आग्नेयास्त्रम्
Āgneyāstram --given to Sagara by Bhārgava (Aurva). Vā. 88. 124 and 135; Vi. IV. 3. 37.

आग्नेयि
Āgneyi  (I)--the city of Agni. Bhā. X. 89. 44.

आग्नेयी
Āgneyī  (II)--the wife of Havirdhāna, and mother of six children: also known as Dhiṣaṇā. Br. II. 37. 23; Vā. 63. 23; Vi. I. 14. 2; M. 4. 45.

आग्नेयी
Āgneyī  (III)--the wife of Ūru. M. 4. 43.

आग्नेयी
Āgneyī  (IV)--the wife of Kuru and mother of six sons. Vi. I. 13. 6. 

आग्रयणम्
Āgrayaṇam --a Pitṛ ritual; offering of śyāmāka and sugar; 1) Br. III. 14. 9; Vā. 78. 8. the first Soma libation at the Agniṣṭoma sacrifice. 2) Vā. 75. 6.

आङ्गिरस
Āṅgirasa --a teacher of Atharva Veda. (Āṅgirasa kalpa Burnouf). Bhā. XII. 7. 4.

आङ्गिरसम्
Āṅgirasam --a sacrifice performed by Brāhmaṇas near Brindāvana. Bhā. X. 23. 3.

आङ्गिरसी
Āṅgirasī --the wife of Vasu and mother of Viśvakarman. Bhā. VI. 6. 15.

आचमनम्
Ācamanam --the mode and significance of; 1) Vā. 79. 42-47. occasions for performing Ācamanam. 2) Ib. 79. 37-42.

आचार
Ācāra --a Gandharva. Br. III. 7. 11.

आचार्य
Ācāryas --qualifications of; old, selfless, highly learned, humble, well disciplined, truthful, etc.; he who by himself follows the rules of good conduct and thus establishes the ācāra and thinks of the truth of the Śāstra by yamas and niyamas. Br. II. 32. 30-32; IV. 8. 5; M. 145. 28-29; Vā. 59. 28-30.

आजगर
Ājagara --a vrata followed by Ṛṣabha when he became a mendicant. Bhā. V. 5. 32.

आजगर
Ājagara --a sage. Praḥlāda saw him one day lying on the bare ground on a cliff of the Sahya hills, and bowed to  him. Praḥlāda asked the sage how he who had no comforts was able to maintain a sound body. The sage replied that he had renounced all desires, learning renunciation from the bee and contentment from the serpent, while his mind was ever absorbed in Hari. Bhā. VII. 13. 11-18, 20-45.

आजगव
Ājagava --the bow of Pṛthu; 1) Br. II. 36. 148; Vā. 62. 127; Vi. I. 13. 40 and 69. of Śiva. 2) Br. III. 65. 32.

आजन
Ājana --a nephew of Hiraṇyakaśipu. M. 6. 27.

आजपाल
Ājapāla --a son of Aja and father of Daśaratha. M. 12. 49.

आजानेय
Ājāneya --the country noted for horses. Br. IV. 16. 17.

आजिगर्त
Ājigarta --Śunaḥśepa, the son of Ajigarta--(see Ajigarta, s.v.). Bhā. IX. 16. 30; IX. 7. 20-21.

आजिहायनहास्तिक
Ājihāyanahāstikas --Kaśypagotrakāras. M. 199. 9.

आजीवक
Ājīvaka --a heretic sect. Br. III. 14. 39.

आज्ञा
Ājñā --a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 19. 

आज्य
Ājya  (I)--good to be seen first after rising from one's bed; 1) Bhā. X. 70. 12; Vā. 29. 30. as a sacrificial offering. 2) Br. IV. 1. 98; Vā. 100. 103.

आज्य
Ājya  (II)--one of the nine sons of Sāvarṇi. Vā. 100. 22.

आज्य
Ājyas --four kinds of. Br. IV. 1. 98-100.

आज्यप
Ājyapas --a class of Manes who reside in regions belonging to Kardama Prajāpati, descendants of Pulaha; Virajā, wife of Nahuṣa was their mindborn daughter; largely worshipped by Vaiśyas. Br. II. 28. 19; III. 10. 93-5; Bhā. IV. 1. 63; M. 102. 21; Vā. 30. 100; 56. 17; 73. 43; 101. 43.

आटवी
Āṭavī --a Vāyu. Vā. 61. 25.

आटव्य
Āṭavyas --the people of a southern country. Br. II. 16. 57; M. 114. 48; Vā. 45. 126.

आडम्बर
Āḍambara --Instrument of war music. M. 137. 29; 138. 3.

आडि
Āḍi --a son of Asura Andhaka; to wreak vengeance on Śiva for having slain his father, he entered the harem of Śiva in the guise of a snake, and assumed the guise of Umā before him. He could change his form twice as he liked owing to a boon from Brahmā; but the second change would be followed by death. On close examination, Śiva discovered the figure to be the Asura in disguise, threw the Vajra and slew him. M. 156. 12-37. 

आडिबक
Āḍib(v)aka --the sixth war of gods and Asuras. 1) Br. III. 72. 74. In this Kakustha helped Indra; 2) Vā. 88. 25. the sixth of the twelve incarnations of Hari. 3) M. 47. 34-35 and 44; Vā. 97. 81.

आण्डकोश
Āṇḍakośa --comprised of sixteen vikāras and eight prakṛtis. 50 crores of yojanas in breadth in the interior. Outside encircled by seven sheaths of the earth and other elements. Bhā. III. 11. 39-41; 20. 15; II. 1. 25.

आण्डीर
Āṇḍīra  (I)--the son of Sarūpya. Father of Pāṇḍya, Kerala, Chola and Kulya. Br. III. 74. 5-6.

आण्डीर
Āṇḍīra  (II)--the son of Varūtha. M. 48. 4.

आततायिन्
Ātatāyins --Those who set fire to buildings, administer poison, lift their weapons to strike, or practise ābhicāra or become talebearers or seditionists. M. 227. 116-9.

आत्तखण्डिक
Āttakhaṇḍikas --a tribe. M. 114. 40.

आतप
Ātapa --a son of Uṣā and Vibhāvasu. A Vasu. Father of Pañcayāma. Bhā. VI. 6. 16.

आत्म
Ātma --has no guṇas. Twelve characteristics of. Bhā. I. 18. 50; VII. 1. 7-9; 7. 19-20.

आत्मज
Ātmaja --a son of Svarbhānu and Prabhā. Vā. 92. 2. 

आत्मभू
Ātmabhū --name of Brahmā. Bhā. III. 12. 20.

आत्मवत्
Ātmavat --a mantrakṛt; 1) Br. II. 32. 104; M. 145. 98; Vā. 59. 96. the son of Cyavana Bhārgava; married Ruci; Father of Nahuṣa. 2) Vā. 65. 90-91.

आत्मविद्या
Ātmavidyā --the Vedānta; 1) M. 215. 54. symbolical of Devī. 2) Vi. I. 9. 120.

आत्मसम्भव
Ātmasambhava --Nārāyaṇa, ety. M. 2. 30.

आत्मा
Ātmā --that which is attained, which is taken away and that which is, and hence the ever present bhāva. Vā. 5. 34-5.

आत्माकर्षणिका
Ātmākarṣaṇikā --a Gupta Śakti. Br. IV. 19. 20.

आत्मायु
Ātmāyu --a son of Aṅgirasa. M. 196. 2.

आत्यन्तिक
Ātyantika --one of the three movements of creatures. Vā. 1. 161; 100. 132.

आत्यन्तिक
Ātyantika kalpa --one division of Brahma kalpa. Vā. 100. 134.

आत्रेय
Ātreya --a pupil of Sūta; 1) Va. 61. 56. the last reference is to the sage in the Raivatamanvantara. 2) Vā. 62. 17, 54. Sage of the Tāmasa manvantara. 3) Vā. 62. 41. Ātreya Śaradvata one of the seven sages; 4) Vā. 100. 11. Ātreyavāruni, 5) Vā. 100. 82. Niṣprakampa, 6) Vā. 100. 107. Sūtapūḥ. 7) Vā. 100. 96; 106. 39. 

आत्रेय
Ātreyas  (I)--a deva gaṇa of the Pitṛs, like Svastyātreya, Br. III. 1. 51; 8. 81.

आत्रेय
Ātreyas  (II)--the five sons of Atri and Anasūyā; Satynetra, Havya, Āpomūrṭi, Śanīśvara and Soma. Vā. 28. 18-20; Br. II. 11. 23-24.

आत्रेय
Ātreyas  (III)--a tribe. Vā. 45. 119.

आत्रेयायणि
Ātreyāyaṇi --pravara (Aṅgiras). M. 196. 12.

आथर्वणीश्रुति
Ātharvaṇī(a)śruti --is Atharva Veda. Vi. VI. 5. 65; Vā. 76. 1.

आदर्श
Ādarśa  (I)--its use for dressing. Devahūtī used it to dress herself; 1) Bhā. III. 23. 30. auspicious to look at in the morning. 2) Br. III. 28. 10; Vi. III. 11. 22; Bhā. X. 70. 11.

आदर्श
Ādarśa  (II)--a son of the Third Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 81; Vā. 100. 84.

आदिगदाधर
Ādigadādhara --Viṣṇu; bore for the first time the gadā out of the bone of Gadā-asura. He is Vyakta, the whole universe appearing in him in the gayā śilā; in praise of, by Brahmā and Śiva. Vā. 109. 13-17, 25, 27-31, 41-42 and 43-50; 111. 16.

आदिकर्ता
Ādikartā --Viṣṇu. Br. IV. 5. 18.

आदिकूर्म
Ādikūrma --created by Lalitā to consume waters due to Bhaṇḍa's arṇavāstram. Br. IV. 29. 92. 

आदिकेशव
Ādikeśava --a name of Viṣṇu. Br. IV. 15. 18.

आदित्य
Āditya  (I)--patronymic of Vidhātṛ. Bhā. VI. 18. 3.

आदित्य
Āditya  (II)--a name of Sūrya (s.v.); 1) Br. II. 21. 3; M. 2. 31-4. presented the jewel Syamantaka to Satrājit. 2) Vi. IV. 13. 11.

आदित्य
Āditya  (III)--from ādāna receiving waters and letting them off; kālāgni, pitāmaha and soma, all prapitāmahas; 1) Vā. 12. 37; 31. 29-35. same as Rudra; see Rudra. 2) Br. II. 10. 22.

आदित्य
Āditya  (IV)--a division of the night. Vā. 66. 44.

आदित्य
Ādityas --sons of Aditi and Kaśyapa, originally Vaikuṇṭhas and Sādhyas; 1) Br. II. 38. 3; III. 1. 61; 3. 57-61, 67-8; 4. 34; M. 171. 55; Vā. 30. 83, 99, 163; 39. 49; 64. 2; 66. 60, 66-7; Vi. I. 15. 129. Gods of the Vaivasvata epoch at the commencement of the first Tretāyuga, known as Jayadevas; 2) Bhā. VIII. 13. 4; VI. 7. 2; 10. 17; M. 9. 29. twelve in number; were known as Tuṣitas in the Cākṣuṣa epoch. 3) Vā. 67. 44; M. 6. 3; Vi. I. 15. 132. Names were Indra, Dhātṛ, Bhaga, Tvaṣṭṛ, Mitra, Varuṇa, Yama, Vivasvat, Savitṛ, Pūṣan, Amśumat, and Viṣṇu. 4) Bhā. XII. 11. 30-45; Br. II. 24. 33-4, 75; 26-42; M. 132. 3; 247. 10; Vi. I. 15. 130-1. Born of Viṣṇu as their overlord. 5) Vi. V. 1. 17-8; 4. 5; Bhā. XII. 11. 30f; XI. 16. 13. Br. III. 8. 5. Escorted Indra; vanquished Diti's sons, and vanquished by Rāvaṇa; 6) Br. III. 5. 48; 7. 254. came with gods to Dvārakā to request Kṛṣṇa to leave for Vaikuṇṭha. 7) Bhā. XI. 6. 2. One of the names of the first Marut Gaṇa. 8) Vā. 67. 123. Born with Rudras. 9) Ib. 65. 61. Residents of Bhuvarloka. 10) Ib. 101. 30; Br. IV. 2. 28-9. Offered presents (upāyana) at the time of the marriage of Kāmeśvara with Lalitā. 11) Br. IV. 15. 24. Praised Lalitā when Bhaṇḍa was killed. 12) Ib. IV. 30. 8. 

आदित्यत्वम्
Ādityatvam --the right of being born as sons of Aditi. Vā. 66. 59.

आदित्य
Āditya Purāṇa --an upapurāṇa. M. 53. 63-4.

आदित्यमण्डल
Ādityamaṇḍala --the Yajus returned to possession of Sūrya when Yājñavalkya surrounded them. Vā. 61. 21.

आदित्य
Āditya Vamśa --the solar race. M. 11. 1.

आदित्यवर्त्मा
Ādityavartmā --by this the divine weapons of Kṛṣṇa went to heaven. Vi. V. 37. 52.

आदित्यवारम्
Ādityavāram --Sunday, fit for Anaṅgadeva vratam; inauspicious for housebuilding; 1) M. 70. 46; 253. 7. devoted to worship of Sūrya, Candra and Agni. 2) M. 97. 3-20.

आदित्यशयनम्
Ādityaśayanam --a vow in honour of Śaṅkara in the name of Sūrya; auspicious day is Sunday preferably with constellation Hasta; accompanied by gifts to Brāhmaṇas: Relieves one from bondage of birth; practised by Vasiṣṭha, Arjuna, Kubera, Indra in olden days. M. 55. 3-33.

आदित्य
Āditya samjñam --an upapurāṇa. M. 53. 63.

आदित्येशम्
Ādityeśam --a tīrtha on the Narmadā. M. 191. 5. 

आदिदेव
Ādidevas --seven gaṇas of which three are without form and four are with form; above them are three Bhāvamūrtis and below them four sūkṣmamūrtis. Vā. 71. 54-6.

आदिपाल
Ādipāla --a name of Viṣṇu. Vā. 109. 15.

आदिपुराणम्
Ādipurāṇam --Ten thousand and six hundred ślokas. Vā. 104. 7.

आदिपुराणानि
Ādipurāṇāni --earlier Purāṇa literature. M. 164. 16.

आदिलक्ष्मी
Ādilakṣmī --is Kāmakṣī. Br. IV. 40. 46.

आदिसर्ग
Ādisarga --origin of, 1) Br. II. 10. 2. described; 2) Ib. II. Ch. 9. the primary creation. 3) M. 8. 1; 52. 2.

आद्य
Ādya --a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 11.

आद्य
Ādyas --a group of gods of Cākṣuṣa epoch, eight in number. Br. II. 36. 66 and 69.

आद्य
Ādya Pratīhāri --the first servant maid of Śiva with four arms and six white clothes; behind are other ladies to honour Śaṅkara. Vā. 101. 274-7.

आधन
Ādhana --one of the seven sons of Vasiṣṭha. Vā. 28. 36. 

आधार
Ādhāra cakra --Into this Hari enters. Bhā. XI. 12. 17.

आधाराधेयभाव
Ādhārādheyabhāva --By this avikāras became vikāras. Earth, etc., are vikāras. Br. II. 19. 181-2.

आद्ध
Āddha --a pupil of Yājñavalkya. Br. II. 35. 28.

आध्यात्मकी
Ādhyātmakī Vidyā --the knowledge of Ātman taught by Kapila to his mother Devahūti; also Ānvīkṣikī. Bhā. III. 24. 40; 25. 4, 13-15.

आध्वर्यवम्
Ādhvaryavam --12000 chandas; from Yajus; uttered by the Adhvaryu in an yajña. Vā. 58. 15; 60. 15-16; 61. 64; Vi. III. 4. 12.

आनक
Ānaka  (I)--a son of Śūra and Māriṣā. Married Kankā and had two sons--Satyajit and Purujit. Bhā. IX. 24. 28 and 41.

आनक
Ānaka  (II)--a kind of divine musical instrument. Bhā. X. 83. 30; M. 135. 83. 140-43; Vā. 96. 145; Br. III. 71. 147.

आनकदुन्दुभी
Ānakadundubhī --a previous name of Vasudeva. (s.v.) 1) Br. III. 71. 146, 164. 217; M. 46. 2 and 11; Vi. V. 2. 8 and 16. When he was born Dundubhi and the Ānakas were sounded as in a festival in the house of Śūra by the gods; 2) Vā. 96. 144-5; Vi. IV. 14. 29. at Nandagopagṛha. 3) Vā. 96. 211. Son of Anu. 4) Vi. IV. 14. 14. Entered fire after the departure of Rāma and Kṛṣṇa to Heaven. 5) Vi. V. 38. 4. 

आनकदुन्दुभि
Ānakadundubhis --divine musicians, played at the birth of Vesudeva. Vi. IV. 14. 28.

आनका
Ānakā --a son of Ugrasena. Vi. IV. 14. 20.

आनन्द
Ānanda  (I) (c)--a kingdom adjoining the Dundubhi hill in Plakṣadvīpa. Br. II. 14. 39; 17. 16.

आनन्द
Ānanda  (II)--a Satya god. Br. II. 36. 35.

आनन्द
Ānanda  (III)--The Lord of first kalpa consisting 100 lakhs of years by name Bhāva; this is the place of Brahmā. Vā. 21. 28.

आनन्द
Ānanda  (IV)--a son of Medhātithi; a varṣa after his name, in Plakṣadvīpa. Vā. 33. 32; Vi. II. 4. 4 and 5.

आनन्दम्
Ānandam --a varṣa centering round the Dundubhi hill of Plakṣa. Vā. 49. 14.

आनन्दकम्
Ānandakam --same as Anicakam varṣam. M. 122. 23.

आनन्दजलम्
Ānandajalam --a lake in the Jātudha hill of pure and crystal waters; here lives Caṇḍa, the lord of the Nāgas. Vā. 41. 68-73. 

आनन्दपीठम्
Ānandapīṭham --is Bindupīṭham. Br. IV. 37. 47.

आनन्दव्रतम्
Ānandavratam --in honour of Brahmā. M. 101. 32.

आनर्त
Ānarta  (I) (c)--a western country; that of Kṛṣṇa; 1) Bhā. I. 11. 1. on the way from Dvāraka to Indraprastha. 2) Ib. X. 71. 21. Its king went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse. 3) Ib. X. 82. 13; Br. II. 16. 62; M. 12. 22. Destroyed by Dvivida; 4) Ib. X. 67. 4. named after Śaryāti; its capital Kuśasthalī. 5) Vā. 86. 24; Vi. IV. 1. 64.

आनर्त
Ānarta  (II)--a son of Śaryāti and father of Reva(ta). 1) Bhā. IX. 3. 27; Br. III. 61. 18; Vā. 86. 23-24; Vi. IV. 1. 63-4. Rocamāna was his son; ruled over the kingdom of Ānarta from Kuśasthalī. 2) M. 12. 21-2.

आनर्त
Ānarta  (III)--a son of Vītihotra. M. 43. 49.

आनर्त
Ānartas --people of Ānarta over whom Revata ruled. 1) Bhā. I. 10, 35; 14. 25; IX. 3. 28; X. 52. 15; M. 114. 51. Heard of Kṛṣṇa going to Mithilā and met him on the way with presents; 2) Bhā. X. 86. 20. of the south. 3) Vā. 45. 131.

आनर्तपुरी
Ānartapurī --the capital of Ānarta--Dvāraka; from here Kṛṣṇa went to Vidarbha in one night. Bhā. I. 14. 25; X. 53. 6.

आन्त्यायन
Āntyāyana --a son of Bhṛgu, and a deva. Br. III. 1. 89. 

आन्दोलिकनियुद्धम्
Āndolika-niyuddham --swinging on the hands of friends and boxing; by Kṛṣṇa and Rāma. Vi. V. 9. 8.

आन्धक
Āndhaka --a son of Vipracitti and Simhikā. Vi. I. 21. 12.

आन्धकार
Āndhakāra (c) --a kingdom after the name of Andhakāra, 1) Br. II. 14. 25. near Pīvara hill. 2) Ib. II. 19. 72.

आन्ध्र
Āndhras  (I)--the kings of Andhra dynasty, thirty in number, ruled the earth for 456 years. Seven of them were contemporaries of seven Kauśalas, chiefs of Vidūra and Niṣadhas; 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 22-28 and 35. According to Matsya Purāṇa, 19 members of the dynasty ruled for 460 years. Kingdoms of Ārya and Mleccha existed side by side--Ābhīras, Gardabhilas, Śakas, Yavanas, Tuṣāras, Guruṇḍas, and Hūṇas. 2) M. 272. 37; 273. 16-19, 25.

आन्ध्र
Āndhras  (II)--a tribe purified by the worship of Hari. 1) Bhā. II. 4. 18. Enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus; 2) Bhā. X. [50 (V) 3]. a southern country unfit for performing Śrāddha. 3) Br. II. 16. 59; III. 14. 80; IV. 29. 131.

आन्ध्रभृत्य
Āndhrabhṛtyas --seven in number. Vi. IV. 24. 51.

आनृहवान्
Ānṛhavān --a rājaṛṣi becoming a Brāhmaṇa. Vā. 91. 116.

आन्वीक्षिकि
Ānvīkṣiki  (Adhyātmakī vidyā, s.v.)--Taught by Dattātreya to Alarka and others. 1) Bhā. I. 3. 11; M. 215. 54; Vi. V. 10. 27. Produced by Brahmā. 2) Bhā. III. 12. 44; 25. 4. Helps concentration on the Absolute. 3) Ib. XI. 20. 24. Learnt by Rāma and Kṛṣṇa. 4) Ib. X. 45. 34. Symbolical of Devī. 5) Vi. I. 9. 121. 

आन्हिकक्रम
Ānhikakrama --the daily routine of duties. Vā. 53. 39; Vi. V. 18. 34.

आप
Āpa  (I)--a vyāpaka. ety. of; came out of Agni, when the latter was lost in the earth. Br. I. 5. 131-5; II. 6. 56-7; 20. 1 and 5; Vā. 6. 1.

आप
Āpa  (II)--a Rākṣasa with the Śarat sun. Br. II. 23. 15; Vā. 52. 15.

आप
Āpa  (III)--a son of Vasiṣṭha, and a Prajāpati of the Svārociṣa epoch. M. 9. 9.

आप
Āpa  (IV)--is Bhava; hence do not commit nuisance in waters; nor bathe naked, nor have sexual intercourse in water; forsake colourless, tasteless and small waters; their source is the ocean and hence they must not be stopped in their progress to it. Vā. 27. 21-7.

आपक
Āpakas --certain grahas which cause fear to children. Vā. 69. 191.

आपन
Āpana (c) --a kingdom to which Puramjana went by the entrance Mukhyā; allegorically Vyavahāra. Bhā. IV. 25. 49; 29. 12.

आपनाप
Āpanāpa --a pupil of Bāṣkali. Br. II. 35. 6.

आपव
Āpava (Vasiṣṭha)  (I)--a sage of the time of second Sāvarṇa Manu. 1) Br. IV. 1. 70. Finding his hermit destroyed by Kārtavīrya's fire, cursed that he would be slain by Paraśurāma. 2) Ib. III. 69. 44-5; M. 44. 1. 12-14. Resident of Hematālavanam. 3) M. 43. 41. 

आपव
Āpava  (II)--the son of Varuṇa; cursed Kārtavīryārjuna who allowed his tapovana to be consumed by Citrabhānu; for ages past he was performing penance at the place, living on water. Vā. 94. 43; 95. 11-13.

आपवत्स
Āpavatsa --to be worshipped in housebuildings. M. 253. 31; 268. 20.

आपस्तम्ब
Āpastamba --acted as priest in the Putreṣṭi of Diti. M. 7. 33-4; 192. 60.

आपस्तम्बि
Āpastambi --a Bhārgava, of Āṅgirasapravara. M. 195. 33; 196. 18.

आपस्थूण
Āpasthūṇas --Ekārṣeyas. M. 200. 4.

आपादबद्ध
Āpādabaddha --the son of Śātakarṇi, ruled for 30 years. Vā. 99. 351.

आपानगोष्ठि
Āpānagoṣṭhi --Revelry and mirth in the assembly of Kṛṣṇa with 16000 ladies; of Apsaras with Gandharvas. M. 70. 4; 120. 31.

आपिकायनि
Āpikāyani --ārṣeyapravara (Bhārgavas). M. 195. 41.

आपीतक
Āpītaka --son of Lambodara Āndhra, ruled for 12 years. M. 273. 5.

आपीशि
Āpīśi --ārṣeyapravara (Bhārgavas). M. 195. 41. 

आपूरण
Āpūraṇa  (I)--the Yakṣa who resides in the sun's chariot during the month of Bhādrapada. Vi. II. 10. 10.

आपूरण
Āpūraṇa  (II)--a Nāga (Dhṛtarāṣṭra). Vā. 69. 72; Vi. IV. 8. 45.

आपोमयदेव
Āpomayadeva --worshipped in Krauñcadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 22-3.

आपोमूर्ति
Āpomūrti --an Ātreya; a sage of the epoch of the second Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. II. 11. 23; IV. 1. 70; Vā. 28. 20.

आपोलव
Āpolava --the son of Śāntakarṇi; ruled for 12 years. Br. III. 74. 163.

आप्तोर्याम
Āptoryāma --a sacrifice 1) Bhā. III. 12. 40. created from the west face of Brahmā. 2) Vi. I. 5. 56. (north face-Vi. P.).

आप्नुवान
Āpnuvāna --a son of Bhṛgu and a gotrakara; a pravara of Bhārgava gotra; Father of Aurva. M. 195. 15 and 29.

आप्य
Āpya  (I)--a Vājin. Vā. 61. 25.

आप्य
Āpya  (II)--a particular period of the day. Vā. 66. 40.

आप्य
Āpyas --one of the gaṇas of the eight gods of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Bhā. VIII. 5. 8; Vi. III. 1. 27. 

आप्यायन
Āpyāyana --a territorial division of Śālmalidvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 9.

आप्यायनम्
Āpyāyanam --a particular offering to Agni, Soma and Yama in the Śrāddha ritual. First to Pitṛs and then to Devas, as Pitṛs are Pūrvadevatas. M. 15. 32-41; 16. 33; 17. 58.

आप्रवान
Āpravāna --a son of Cyavana; married Ṛci, daughter of Nahuṣa: Father of Aurva, born from her thigh. Br. III. 1. 93-5.

आबाधविस्तर
Ābādhavistara --of the earth; one crore in every direction from Meru as centre; also calculated in another way. Vā. 50. 69-70.

आब्रह्मस्तम्बपर्यन्तम्
Ābrahmastambaparyantam --from Brahmā to grass. Vā. 110. 21, 64.

आभिचार
Ābhicāra --Incantations done by Purohita and ministers for defeating the enemy--according to Bhaṇḍa; 1) Br. IV. 21. 97. Brhaspati did this on behalf of Indra to vanquish Rāji's sons. 2) Vi. IV. 9. 19.

आभिल
Ābhila --a mahāratha, and a commander of Bhaṇḍa's army. His riding vehicle was Simha. Br. IV. 29. 21-2.

आभीर
Ābhīra --country of Ābhīras. 1) Bhā. I. 10. 35; Br. II. 16. 46 and 57; 18. 48. Dvijas of, became vrātyas after Puramjaya's days. 2) Bhā. XII 1. 38. Purified of sin by devotion to Hari. 3) Ib. II. 4. 18. Seven of this tribe ruled from Avabhṛti. 4) Bhā. XII. 1. 29; Vā. 99. 359; Vi. IV. 24. 51, 68. The Braḥmāṇḍa and Vāyu say ten of them ruled after the Āndhras; 5) Br. III. 74. 174; M. 50. 76; 114. 40; 163. 72; 273. 18. for 67 years. 

आभीर
Ābhīras --a tribe of Dakṣiṇāpatha saw Arjuna singly carrying much wealth and women and attacked him; he took up his Gāṇḍiva and found he had lost its secret and power; 1) Vā. 45. 115, 126; 47. 46; 99. 269; Vi. II. 3. 16. freebooters and shepherds of the Pañcanada country who lived in villages; mlecchas; chief weapons of, staves and cudgels. 2) Vi. V. 38. 14-28, 50-52.

आभीरकन्या
Ābhīrakanyā --observed the Kalyāṇinī vratam and became Urvaśī of the Heaven. M. 69. 59.

आभूतरजस
Ābhūtarajasa --gods of the Raivata epoch. M. 9. 20.

आभूतसम्प्लव
Ābhūtasamplava --or the Deluge; the duration of destruction of all except the five bhūtas, earth, water, vāyu, ākāśa and tejas; eternal and not dying. Vā. 6. 74; 7, 22; 10. 33; 28. 16 and 32; 30. 318; 50. 206, 212; 52. 47; 53. 76; 54. 109; 59. 57; 100. 11, 33, 37, 203, 240: 101. 73, 334, 354; Vi. II. 8. 92-97: Br. II. 6. 22; IV. 1. 200 and 208, 230-31, 242; M. 2. 16 and 20; 4. 20; 80. 11: 89. 10; 106. 10; 124. 94 and 102; 128. 44; 181. 4; 188. 96; 192. 32; 204. 10; 206. 40.

आभ्रहमु
Ābhrahamu --a son of Bhadra. Vā. 69. 213.

आम
Āma  (I)--a son of Ghṛtapṛṣṭha. Bhā. V. 20. 21.

आम
Āma  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and (Satyā) daughter of Nagnacit. Bhā. X. 61. 13. 

आमगर्भ
Āmagarbhas --Pitṛs dead as small children. Vā. 110. 53.

आमपात्रम्
Āmapātram --the milking vessel of the Yakṣas. Br. II. 36. 215; Vā. 62. 182.

आमश्राद्धम्
Āmaśrāddham --see Āmānnam. M. 18. 27; Vā. 18. 20.

आमान्नम्
Āmānnam --gift of uncooked food in a śrāddha, generally by Śūdras; also Āmaśrāddham; forbidden for yatis. M. 17. 70; Vā. 18. 20.

आमोद
Āmoda --a vighna nāyaka. Br. IV. 27. 81; 44. 68.

आम्नायनाथा
Āmnāyanāthā --a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 18. 17.

आम्ब
Āmba --a son of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. I. 10. 29.

आम्बिकेय
Āmbikeya  (I)--a place where Hiraṇyākṣa was slain by Vārāha Hari. M. 122. 16.

आम्बिकेय
Āmbikeya  (II)--a hill of the Śākadvīpam. Vā. 49. 84; Vi. II. 4. 62.

आम्र
Āmra --the mango tree in Brahmasaras, in the shape of Brahmā; he who waters the tree will lead the Pitṛs to salvation. Vā. 43. 6; 111. 35-36. 

आम्रवनम्
Āmravanam --between Viśākha and Pataṅga hills. Vā. 38. 18-22.

आम्रातकेश्वरम्
Āmrātakeśvaram --a tīrtham on the Narmadā sacred to Pitṛs, and to Śiva. M. 22. 51; 181. 28; 190. 5.

आय
Āya --a Tuṣita god. Br. II. 36. 11.

आयतनम्
Āyatanam of Deva --called divyam by the Veda, at the end of Nirāloka and of ākāśa or ether: Inaccessible to gods. 1) Br. II. 19. 168-9; III. 11. 34. Temples as places for śrāddha; construction of: description shows the Vaiṣṇava and Śaiva shrines in the same compound. 2) M. 17. 11; 58. 2; 83. 3; 105. 15; 268. 35; 270. 34. Shrines where Purāṇas were read. 3) Vā. 4. 7; 30. 150; 38. 31, 48, 58; 54. 3; 77. 63; 92. 52.

आयतायन
Āyatāyana --A Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 3.

आयति
Āyati  (I)--a daughter of Meru and Dharaṇi, wife of Dhātṛ (Vidhātṛ-Vā. P.) and mother of Mṛkaṇḍa; 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 43-44; Vā. 28. 4; 30. 34; Vi. I. 10. 3. mother of Prāṇa also. 2) Br. II. 11. 5-6; 13. 37.

आयति
Āyati  (II)--a son of Nahuṣa. Bhā. IX. 18. 1; Br. III. 68. 12; Vā. 93. 13; Vi. IV. 10. 1.

आयसम्पात्रम्
Āyasampātram --the iron vessel sacred to Asuras. Br. II. 36. 210; M. 10. 20.

आयाप्य
Āyāpya --a mantrakṛt and of Aṅgirasa branch. Vā. 59. 101. 

आयु
Āyu  (I)--a son of Prāṇa and Ūrjasvatī: a Vasu; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 12. Father of Vaitaṇḍya and others. 2) Br. III. 3. 21, 24.

आयु
Āyu  (II)--the son of Puruhotra, and father of Sātvata. Bhā. IX. 24. 6.

आयु
Āyu  (III)--one of the six sons of Purūravas and Urvaśī; wife Prabhā, Rāhu's daughter; father of five sons, Nahuṣa, Vṛddhaśarman, Rāju, Dambha, and Vipāpman, all of them expert warriors. Bhā. IX. 15. 1; 17. 1; Br. III. 66. 22, 90; 67. 1; M. 24. 33-5; Vā. 91. 51; Vi. IV. 6. 73; 7. 1; 8. 1-3.

आयु
Āyu  (IV)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Bhadrā. Bhā. X. 61. 17.

आयु
Āyu  (V)--The sage presiding over the month of Puṣya. Bhā. XII. 11. 42.

आयु
Āyu  (VI)--(Śuci Agni). Father of Mahiṣa. Br. II. 12. 38-40.

आयु
Āyu  (VII)--a Carakādhvaryu. Br. II. 33. 13.

आयु
Āyu  (VIII)--the Agni that lives in Paśu. Vā. 29. 37.

आयु
Āyu  (IX)--a son of Aṅgirasa; father of Amāvasu. Vā. 65. 105; 73. 5.

आयुतायु
Āyutāyu --the son of Sindhudvīpa. M. 12. 46; Vā. 88. 173. 

आयुध
Āyudhas --weapons of war, enumerated and described. Br. IV. 22. 10-14; M. 129. 35; 149. 7-8; 173. 5, 12, 29, etc.

आयुधागार
Āyudhāgāra --arsenal: meddling with it was punished with death. M. 163. 51; 215. 44; 217. 16; 227. 174.

आयुर्दा
Āyurdā --R. in Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 26.

आयुर्दान
Āyurdāna --a Pārāvata god. Br. II. 36. 14.

आयुर्वेद
Āyurveda --originated from Dhanvantari; 1) Bhā. II. 7. 21; VIII. 8. 35; IX. 17. 4; Br. III. 67. 18; Vā. 92. 16; Vi. IV. 8. 10. from the east face of Brahmā; 2) Bhā. III. 12. 38. one of the eighteen vidyas; 3) Br. II. 35. 88; Vi. III. 6. 28; Vā. 61. 79. begins in Dvāpara; 4) M. 144. 22; Vā. 58. 23; Br. II. 31. 23. Bharadvāja was the compiler of the Āyurveda and other sciences connected with medicine; it was divided into eight parts each of which was given to one of his disciples. 5) Vā. 92. 22; Br. III. 67. 24.

आयुर्व्रतम्
Āyurvratam --in honour of Śiva. M. 101. 22.

आयुष
Āyuṣa --the son of Aiḍa. Vā. 1. 192.

आयुष्मत्
Āyuṣmat  (I)--the father of Ṛṣabha-Hari by Ambudhārā. Bhā. VIII. 13. 20.

आयुष्मत्
Āyuṣmat  (II)--a son of Uttānapāda. Br. II. 36. 89. 

आयुष्मत्
Āyuṣmat  (III)--a son of Praḥlāda. M. 6. 9; Vi. I. 21. 1.

आयुष्मत्य
Āyuṣmatya --an apsarasa gaṇa from Sūrya. Vā. 69. 55.

आयुष्मन्त
Āyuṣmanta --a gaṇa of gods. Br. IV. 1. 122.

आरट्टदेश
Āraṭṭadeśa --noted for horses. M. 48. 7.

आरण्य
Āraṇya --a madhyamādhvaryu; a Prajāpati and father of five deva gaṇas of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. 1) Br. II. 33. 15; 36. 68. Son of Atri. 2) Vā. 62. 58.

आरण्यवाक्य
Āraṇyavākyas --passages of the Āraṇyaka portion of the Vedas. Br. III. 21. 55.

आरब्ध
Ārabdha --the son of Setu and father of Gāndhāra. Bhā. IX. 23. 15; Vi. IV. 17. 3-4.

आरम्भयज्ञ
Ārambhayajñas --for Kṣatriyas. Br. II. 29. 55; Vā. 57. 50.

आराधि
Ārādhi --a son of Jayatsena. Vā. 99. 231.

आराधित
Ārādhita --a son of Jayatsena and father of Ayutāyu. Vi. IV. 20. 4.

आराम
Ārāma --Laying out parks at the auspicious hour--also Udyāna; 1) M. 58. 1 and 52. in Tripuram; 2) Ib. 130. 5. punishment for misuse of. 3) Ib. 227. 30; Vā. 101. 160. 

आरुणायनि
Āruṇāyani--ārṣeya pravara  (Aṅgiras). M. 196. 8.

आरुणि
Āruṇi  (I)--a siddha. Bhā. VI. 15. 13.

आरुणि
Āruṇi  (II)--(Ātreya) a sage of the epoch of the third Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 79.

आरुणि
Āruṇi  (III)--a sādhya. M. 171. 43.

आरुणि
Āruṇi  (IV)--the fifteenth Vyāsa, Vedaśiras, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 166.

आरुणि
Āruṇi  (V)--a sage of the XIth epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 31.

आरुणि
Āruṇi  (VI)--the first of the madhyadeśas. Vā. 61. 9.

आर्चनानश
Ārcanānaśa --an Ātreya gotrakāra. M. 197. 5.

आर्जव
Ārjava --a pupil of Bāṣkali. Br. II. 35. 6.

आर्तव
Ārtavas  (I)--five sons of Brahmā: represented by Agniṣvāttas. Br. II. 21. 152; 23. 75-77; 28. 16 ff. 

आर्तव
Ārtavas  (II)--five sons of Ṛtus: These are half months: Represent Pitṛs; 1) M. 141. 14 and 57; Vā. 30. 18, 22. sections of the year; depend on the seasons. 2) Vā. 70. 14; Br. II. 13. 19-25, 149.

आर्द्रक
Ārdraka --the father of Dhṛti. Br. III. 71. 124.

आर्द्रा
Ārdrā --the name of a constellation. Vā. 82. 3.

आर्द्रानन्दकरि
Ārdrānandakari--Tṛtīyāvratam:  sacred to Bhavānī sitting with Mahādeva: to be done for four months, once in every pakṣa: the performer enjoys the world of Rudrāṇī. M. 64 (whole).

आर्य
Ārya  (I)--opposite of Mleccha. Vā. 45. 93; 47. 49; 99. 404.

आर्य
Ārya  (II)--collective name of Aṅgiras' sons 1) Bhā. IX. 4. 2; Br. II. 16. 24. as opposed to Mleccha. 2) M. 227. 198; 114. 20. Their country was Bhāratavarṣa; side by side with Mleccha in Kaliyuga. 3) M. 121. 46-51; 273. 25; 274. 37.

आर्यक
Āryaka  (I)--the father of Dharmasetu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 26.

आर्यक
Āryaka  (II)--a Kādraveya nāga. Br. III. 7. 33.

आर्यक
Āryakas --caste equal to Brāhmaṇa in Plakṣadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 17. 

आर्यका
Āryakā --a R. in Krauñca-dvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 21.

आर्यसमय
Āryasamaya --does not accept the duties of Pākhaṇḍas. Bhā. V. 14. 29.

आर्यव
Āryava --one of the three disciples of Rathītara. Vā. 61. 3.

आर्या
Āryā --Dvaipāyanī--a R. visited by Balarāma. Bhā. X. 79. 20.

आर्यावर्त
Āryāvarta --twenty-five of Ikṣvāku's sons were rulers over this territory; given to Upadraṣṭa by Paraśurāma. Bhā. IX. 6. 5; 16. 22.

आर्वत
Ārvata --a sage by tapas. Br. II. 32. 99.

आर्ष
Ārṣa  (I)--a form of marriage; girls to be given in the Ganges-Yamuna doab. M. 106. 8; Vi. III. 10. 24.

आर्ष
Ārṣa  (II)--origin of; when the whole world was in a state of cetana-acetana knowledge like the fish in the water, the truth influenced by cetana arises with guṇa; kāryam is the result of kāraṇa or reason; so also viṣaya is the result of viṣayitva and artha of arthitva; by this Mahat and others function by degrees. Vā. 59. 63-8.

आर्षकम्
Ārṣakam --Ṛṣis, past and future. M. 145. 65. 

आर्षणि
Ārṣaṇi --a pravara. M. 196. 31.

आर्षभ
Ārṣabhas --a branch of Aṅgirasa. Vā. 65. 107.

आर्षभि
Ārṣabhi --the street with the constellations of Pūrva and Uttara Phalguni and Magha; in madhyama mārga. Br. III. 3. 49; M. 124. 56.

आर्ष्टिषेण
Ārṣṭiṣeṇa  (I)--a chief Gandharva who sings Rāma's glory in Kimpuruṣa; came to see Parīkṣit practising prāyopaveśa. Knew the yoga-power of Hari. Bhā. V. 19. 2; I. 19. 10; II. 7. 45.

आर्ष्टिषेण
Ārṣṭiṣeṇa  (II)--the son of Śala. Br. III. 67. 6; Vā. 92. 5.

आर्ष्टिषेण
Ārṣṭiṣeṇa  (III)--a rajaṛṣi becoming a Brāhmaṇa. Vā. 91. 116.

आर्ष्टिषेण
Ārṣṭiṣeṇa  (IV)--a mantrakṛt--a Pañcārṣeya Bhārgava. Br. II. 32. 105; M. 145. 99; 195. 34.

आर्ष्टिषेण
Ārṣṭiṣeṇas --a Bhārgava branch--Kṣatradvijas. Br. III. 1. 100; 66. 87; 67. 6; Vā. 92. 6.

आर्हतम्
Ārhatam --one of the six darśanas. Vā. 104. 16.

आर्हण
Ārhaṇa  (Arhaṇa--Bur.) a chief attendant on Hari. Bhā. II. 9. 14.

आलम्ब
Ālambas --a class of sages. M. 200. 17. 

आलम्बनम्
Ālambanam --see Yoga. Vi. VI. 7. 42.

आलम्बा
Ālambā --a daughter of Khaśā, and a Rākṣasī, after whom came the Ālambeya gaṇa. Br. III. 7. 138; Vā. 69. 170.

आलम्बि
Ālambi --a Śrutaṛṣi: the chief author of the Yajurveda of the Eastern recension. Br. II. 33. 6.

आलम्बिरादि
Ālambirādi --of the Prācyas; also trayodaśyādayaḥ. Vā. 61. 9.

आलम्बेयगण
Ālambeyagaṇa --a Rākṣasa clan after Ālambā. Br. III. 7. 140.

आलम्बेय
Ālambeyas --a cruel Rākṣasa gaṇa from Ālambā. Vā. 69. 172.

आलयम्
Ālayam --temple for Iśvara.--(see Āyatanam); 1) Vā. 30. 279; 91. 29; 101. 214. or a place of residence. 2) Ib. 50. 15, 17, 22 and 35.

आलुकि
Āluki --a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 25.

आलोक
Āloka --the lokas which spring from Aloka. 1) Br. II. 19. 151-3, 187; 21. 155; M. 123. 47; 124. 93. Ākāśa that seems to exist to our eyes. 2) Vā. 49. 145 and 176.

आवटी
Āvaṭī --a pupil of Yājñavalkya. Br. II. 35. 29.

आवन्ति
Āvantis --a tribe. M. 114. 36. 

आवन्त्य
Āvantya --a Brāhmaṇa pupil of Sukarman. Imparted in his turn the samhitas to his pupils. Bhā. XII. 6. 77-80.

आवन्त्यौ
Āvantyau --the two sons of Jayasena so called. Bhā. IX. 24. 39.

आवरण
Āvaraṇa --a son of Bharata and Pāñcajanī. Bhā. V. 7. 3.

आवर्तक
Āvartakas --clouds of the Pakṣaja class that rain copiously. Br. II. 22. 40; IV. 28. 63.

आवर्तन
Āvartana --An upadvīpa to Jambūdvīpa. Bhā. V. 19. 30.

आवर्तय
Āvartaya --a Haihaya clan. Vā. 94. 52.

आवसथ्य
Āvasathya --a son of Śamsya Agni. Vā. 29. 12.

आवसथ्यम्
Āvasathyam --the lower lip of the personified Veda. Vā. 104. 84.

आवह
Āvaha  (I)--a wind that helps Āgneya clouds to rain: 1) Br. II. 22. 34; III. 5. 82; 71. 112. one of the seven Maruts; 2) M. 163. 32. controls the mūka clouds. 3) Vā. 51. 32, 49; 67. 114.

आवह
Āvaha  (II)--a son of Gāndini. Vā. 96. 111.

आवाहनी
Āvāhanī --a mudrā Devī. Br. IV. 42. 2. 

आविक्षिः
Āvikṣiḥ --a true son of his father in virtuous qualities. Vā. 86. 8.

आविर्मुखि
Āvirmukhi --one of the eastern entrances of the city of Puramjana: allegorically the right eye. Bhā. IV. 25. 47; 29. 10.

आविहोत्र
Āvihotra --an Ātreya and sage. Br. II. 32. 114.

आविर्होत्र
Āvirhotra --a son of Ṛṣabha; a sage and a bhāgavata; asked as to the truth of karmayoga by Nimi, the sage instructed the king that karma, akarma and vikarma are Vedavāda and not laukika which thesis he expanded. Bhā. V. 4. 11; XI. 2. 21; 3. 41-55.

आवीचि
Āvīci --a hell. Vi. II. 6. 4.

आवेद
Āveda --a Bhārgava gotra-kara. M. 195. 18.

आवेशक
Āveśaka --an Yakṣa gaṇa. Vā. 69. 40.

आशय
Āśaya --the cause of karmas which in turn lead to birth. Vā. 8. 30.

आशी
Āśī --an apsaras. Vā. 69. 5.

आशी
Āśīs --the daughter of Bhaga and Siddhi. Bhā. VI. 18. 2.

आशौचम्
Āśaucam --for father's death 10 days for Brāhmaṇas, 12 days for Kṣatriyas, 15 days for Vaiśyas, and a month for the Śūdras. M. 18. 1-3. 

आश्रम
Āśramas (āśramadharma) --four, Brahmacarya, gṛhasta, vānaprastha and bhikṣuka; duties:--Brahmacarya: study by service to guru and begging food; gṛhasta: the source and strength of all āśramas; those celibate do penance, sacrifice, give birth to sons, perform śrāddha, learn the Vedas and give gifts of food; dārāgni, guests, sacrifice and śrāddha; become devapitṛs; vānaprastha: bathe in morning and evening and on ceremonials; eating of fruits and roots, non-theft, purity, sympathy and non-injury--ten kinds of dharma; Bhikṣu: daṇḍi, mekhali, and lying in ground floor. 1) Bhā. VII. 12. 1-31; 13. 1-10; 14. to the end; M. 141. 61-2; 248. 16; Vā. 8. 177-88; 23. 82; 33. 27; 56. 68; 61. 167; Vi. III. 8. 20; ch. 9 (whole). A reference to the fifth āśrama; 2) Br. II. 16. 15; III. 15. 37-8. will be lost at the end of Kaliyuga when anarchy prevails. 3) M. 47. 257.

आश्रायणि
Āśrāyaṇis --a group of sages of Kaśyapa gotra. M. 199. 2.

आश्लेषा
Āśleṣā --on the left hind foot of the Śiśumāra. 1) Bhā. V. 23. 6; Br. II. 24. 135. Its importance for śrāddha; 2) Br. III. 18. 5. the seventh nakṣatra. 3) Vā. 82. 5.

आश्वलायन
Āśvalāyana --a son of Sahiṣṇu avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 213.

आश्वलायनि
Āśvalāyani --a pravara of Aṅgiras. M. 196. 13.

आश्वलायनिन्
Āśvalāyanins --Kaśyapagotrakaras. M. 199. 6.

आश्वायनि
Āśvāyani --a Pañcārṣeya (Bhārgavas). M. 195. 34.

आषाढ
Āṣāḍha(daśami) --a manvantara for śrāddha. M. 17. 7-8. 

आषाढम्
Āṣāḍham --sacred to Aṅgāraka, and for performing śrāddha. Br. II. 21. 76; 24. 133; III. 18. 10; Vā. 53. 108; 66. 51; 82. 10.

आषाढितीर्थम्
Āṣāḍhitīrtham --on the Narmadā. M. 194. 30.

आसनम्
Āsanam--Svastikam, Padmam  and Ardhāsanam--the sitting posture of the Pāśupata yoga; 1) Vā. 11. 12-14. a kind of dharaṇā. 2) Vā. 104. 24.

आसङ्ग
Āsaṅga --the son of Śvaphalka and Gāndini. Bhā. IX. 24. 16.

आसव
Āsava --also Pānam; different kinds of; forbidden to Brāhmaṇas, widows and girls. Br. IV. 7. 63.

आसारण
Āsāraṇa --the Yakṣa presiding over the month Nabhasya. Bhā. XII. 11. 38.

आसुर
Āsura --a form of marriage. Vi. III. 10. 24.

आसुरह
Āsuraha --a sādhya. M. 171. 43.

आसुरायण
Āsurāyaṇa --a pupil of Pārāśarya Kauthuma. 1) Br. II. 35. 46. His descendants were Kaśyapagotrakaras. 2) M. 199. 3.

आसुरी
Āsurī  (I)--the name of the entrance of the west of the city of Puramjana; allegorically the organ of procreation. Bhā. IV. 25. 52; 29. 14. 

आसुरी
Āsurī  (II)--a pupil of Kapila from whom he learnt Sāṅkhya; a siddha; 1) Bhā. I. 3. 10; III. 24. 17; VI. 15. 14. did not comprehend Hari's māyā; 2) Bhā. IX. 4. 57. was invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira. 3) Bhā. X. 74. 9.

आसुरी
Āsurī  (III)--the queen Devatājit and mother of Devadyumna. (Asuri-Burnouf). Bhā. V. 15. 3.

आसुरी
Āsurī  (IV)--the chief author of the recension of the Yajur Veda of the middle country; 1) Br. II. 35. 12. a Brahmaṛṣi. 2) M. 102. 18.

आसुरी
Āsurī  (V)--a son of Brahmā. Vā. 101. 338.

आसुरीवेल
Āsurīvela --part of night when Nanda entered the Yamunā and was carried to Varuṇa by an Asura. Bhā. X. 28. 2.

आहवनीय
Āhavanīya (Havyavāhana) --a sacred fire. Br. III. 72. 25; Vā. 29. 11; 30. 107; 97. 25; 106. 41.

आहवणीय
Āhavaṇīya Padam --in Gayā. Vā. 111. 51.

आहार्य
Āhārya --an Aṅgirasa and a mantrakṛt: 1) Br. II. 32. 109: Vā. 59. 100. Father of Urukṣava. 2) M. 49. 38.

आहुक
Āhuka --A son of Punarvasu and father of Devaka and Ugrasena and Dhṛti (Vā.); 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 20-21; Vā. 96. 120-123; Vi. IV. 14. 15-16; Br. III. 71. 120-121. a prince who had thousands of sons. 2) Bhā. I. 14. 28; X. 90. 42. Hated by Kaṃsa. 3) Ib. X. 36. 24 [28]; X[50 (V) 8]. Consulted by Kṛṣṇa on the eve of attack on Jarāsandha. His defence in the third campaign  of Jarāsandha. 4) Ib. X [51 (V) 26]. Met Kṛṣṇa at the council hall, and welcomed him after the Kurukṣetra war. 5) Ib. X. [67 (V) 42]; 80. [13]. Went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse. 6) Ib. X. 82. 5. An ideal ruler; married Kāśi king's daughter. 7) Br. III. 71. 128; M. 44. 70. Specialist in chariot war; 8) Vā. 96. 121-2; Br. III. 71. 122-3. Āhukī was his sister, married to Āhukāndha; 9) Vā. 96. 127; M. 44. 66-70. had 800 lakhs of horses, 21,000 elephants with silver and gold chains in east and west directions; equal to great Bhoja; 10) Br. III. 71. 123-127; Vā. 96. 121-126; M. 44. 67-68. informed of happenings in Prabhāsa. 11) Vi. V. 37. 59.

आहुका
Āhukās --the people of an eastern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 52; Vā. 45. 121.

आहुकान्ध
Āhukāndha --married sister of Āhuka; father of two sons and a daughter. Vā. 96. 127; Br. III. 71. 127.

आहुकी
Āhukī --the daughter of Punarvasu and sister of Āhuka (s.v.) the queen of the king of Avanti (Āhukāndha). Bhā. IX. 24. 21; Br. III. 71. 121 and 127; M. 44. 66; Vā. 96. 120, 127; Vi. IV. 14. 15.

आहृति
Āhṛti --a son of Vastu. Vā. 95. 37.

आहृत्य
Āhṛtya --an Apsaras gaṇa from Brahmā. Br. III. 7. 18.

आह्वय
Āhvaya --one of the names in the third marutgaṇa. Vā. 67. 126.  I

इकार
Ikāra --from the third face of the fourteen faced deva came Āditya, Yajurmaya and Yajurveda. Vā. 26. 34.

इक्षलक
Ikṣalaka --a pupil of Rathītara. Br. II. 35. 4.

इक्षु
Ikṣu  (I)--a tree peculiar to Harivarṣa. Br. II. 17. 7.

इक्षु
Ikṣu  (II) (Kratu)--a R. of Śākadvīpa, from the side of the Himalayas. Br. II. 19. 96; M. 122. 32; Vā. 49. 93; Vi. II. 4. 65.

इक्षु
Ikṣu  (III)--one of the seven oceans; see Ikṣurasodā. Br. IV. 31. 18; M. 2. 34.

इक्षु
Ikṣu  (IV)--a R. from the side of the Himālayas, in the Bhāratavarṣa. M. 114. 22; Vā. 45. 96.

इक्षु
Ikṣu  (V)--a R. joining the Narmadā; very holy. A bath here makes one lord of a Devagaṇa. M. 191. 49-50.

इक्षुचाप
Ikṣucāpa --given by Brahmā to Kāmeśvara as a wedding present; also Ikṣudhanus. Br. IV. 15. 19; 19. 26; 18. 1.

इक्षुदण्डम्
Ikṣudaṇḍam --sugarcane juice for śrāddha; one of the eight saubhāgyams. M. 7. 11 and 26; 15. 35; 60. 8; 85. 6. 

इक्षुदा
Ikṣudā --a R. from Mahendra hills. M. 114. 31.

इक्षुमती
Ikṣumatī  (I)--a R. On its banks was the hermitage of Kapila. Bhā. V. 10. 1; Vi. II. 13. 53.

इक्षुमती
Ikṣumatī  (II)--a tīrtham sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 17.

इक्षुरसोद
Ikṣurasoda --one of the seven seas surrounding Plakṣadvīpa. Bhā. V. 1. 33; 20. 7; Vi. II. 4, 20.

इक्षुला
Ikṣulā --a R. of the Mahendra hill. Vā. 45. 106.

इक्ष्वाकु
Ikṣvāku --one of the ten (nine-Br. P.) sons of Vaivasvata Manu. Born of his sneezing. 1) Bhā. VIII. 13. 2; IX. 1. 3 and 12; 2. 2; Vā. 64. 29; 85. 4; 88. 9; Vi. IV. 1. 7; Br. II. 38. 30; III. 60. 2 and 20; 63. 8; M. 9. 30; 11. 41. Father of a hundred sons--Vikukṣi, Nimi, Daṇḍa and others. 25 of these sons ruled Āryāvarta, 25, the western territory, three, the middle country and the rest all other provinces. Once in connection with an Aṣṭaka ritual, Vikukṣi was asked to secure some flesh. Accordingly he did. But feeling hungry he partook a part of hare's flesh. When the remainder was presented, the Purohita refused to take it on the ground that it was remainder of that already tasted. Vikukṣi was therefore punished with banishment. It is said that he became a yogin and attained salvation. 2) Bhā. IX. 6. 4-10; Vi. IV. 2. 15-18. A king known for his exemplary protection of his subjects. Parīkṣit compared to him. 3) Bhā. I. 12. 19. Prominent kings of his line. 4) M. 12. 15-56; Vā. 99. 280-290. Knew the power of Hari's yoga, and in his line Hari incarnated. 5) Bhā. II. 7. 23 and 44; XII. 2. 37; Sumitra was the last Kṣatriya king of this line. 6) Br. III. 74. 244; M. 273. 53; Vā. 99. 266 and 431. Originator of the solar race; the genealogy given down to Śantāyu of the Bhārata war. 7) M. 12. 15-56. Heard from Vasiṣṭha of Ila's conversion to the other sex in the Śaravaṇa forest and performed Aśvamedha by which Ila was  turned into a Kimpuruṣa. 8) M. 12. 1-15. Was addressed by the Pitṛs in Kalāpa forest on the effect of offering śrāddha at Gayā. 10) Vi. III. 1. 33; 16. 17-18. The line of. 11) Vā. 1. 142; 88. 175-184; Vi. IV. 22. 1-13. Had 100 branches. 12) Vā. 99. 451.

इच्छाप्राप्ति
Icchāprāpti --one of the Uttama siddhis. Br. IV. 36. 51.

इज्यावेदात्मक
Ijyāvedātmaka --is Śrauta Ijyā or sacrifice being one of the eight practices of śiṣṭas. Br. II. 32. 40 and 44.

इडविड
Iḍaviḍa --son of Śataratha; married the daughter of Viśvasahasra. Br. III. 63. 180.

इडविडा
Iḍaviḍā --the daughter of Tṛṇabindu: a queen of Viśravas, and mother of Kubera. Bhā. IV. 1. 37; 12. 9.

इडस्पति
Iḍaspati  (I)--a son of Dakṣiṇā and a Tuṣita god. Bhā. IV. 1. 7-8.

इडस्पति
Iḍaspati  (II)--a name of Hari; Puruṣa. Bhā. IX. 2. 35.

इडा
Iḍā  (I)--see Ilā. Br. III. 60. 11; Vā. 85. 7.

इडा
Iḍā  (II)--a śakti of Māruta. Br. IV. 33. 70. 

इडावत्सर
Iḍāvatsara --the third year of a five year yuga. Also Idvatsara; 1) Bhā. III. 11. 14; V. 22. 7; Vi. II. 8. 72; 13. 115; Vā. 50. 183. is Soma or moon. 2) Br. II. 13. 118; 129; 21. 132; 28. 22. M. 141. 18. Vā. 31. 30; 56. 20.

इडिविला
Iḍivilā --a daughter of Tṛṇabindu and wife of Pulastya, father of the sage Vaiśravas. Vā. 70. 31.

इति
Iti naḥ Śrutam (Iti śruti) --recording of tradition by the Purāṇas 1) Br. II. 13. 27, 82; M. 3. 45; 6. 7; 24. 64; 35. 5; 36. 2; 44. 2; 47. 186; 50. 4 and 7; 247. 1 and 39; Vā. 30. 25, 175 and 302; 88. 153; 90. 3, 10, and 24; 95. 2; 99. 175; Vi. I. 15. 140.--also Ityevam anuśuśruma. 2) M. 43. 19. Iti naḥ śrutiḥ; 3) Vā. 99. 200. Iti śrutam; 4) Vā. 94. 51. Iti śrutaḥ; 5) Ib. 88. 118, 206. Iti śruti; 6) Vā. 21. 73; 30. 96, 303; 53. 108; 59. 70; 88. 28, 182; 89. 8; 92. 70; 94. 4; 99. 231. Iti hi naḥ śrutam. 7) Br. I. 2. 15; Vā. 2. 15.

इतिहास
Itihāsa (Purāṇa) --Historical literature known to Sūta; 1) Bhā. I. 1. 6; M. 57. 15; 58. 4; 69. 33; 72. 6; 247. 17. the fifth Veda; their origin; to be read or heard on days of fasting; 2) Bhā. I. 4. 20, 22; III. 12. 39; M. 99. 11; Vā. 54. 115; 55. 2; 60. 16; 79. 53; 104. 2; Vi. I. 22. 83; III. 4. 10; V. 1. 38. came in a personified form, to see Trivikrama Hari. 3) Bhā. VIII. 21. 2; Br. I. 1. 171; II. 34. 16; III. 15. 25; IV. 4. 47, 56; 7. 9; Vā. I. 25, 32.

इद्वत्सर
Idvatsara  (I)--see Iḍāvatsara. Vi. II. 8. 72.

इद्वत्सर
Idvatsara  (II)--a name of the moon. Vā. 50. 183; 56. 20.

इद्वत्सर
Idvatsara  (III)--the third year in a five year cycle; 1) Vā. 31. 27. Soma according to Purāṇic tradition; he is Prapitāmaha ensuring prosperity. 2) Br. II. 13. 115, 118, 129; Vā. 31. 55. 

इध्मवाह
Idhmavāha  (I)--the son of Dṛḍhacyuta and grandson of Agastya; a sage who came to see Parīkṣit practising prāyopaveśa. Bhā. IV. 28. 32; I. 19. 9.

इध्मवाह
Idhmavāha  (II)--a son of Agastya; and the adopted son of Kratu; hence Āgastyas are Kratus. M. 202. 8-9.

इध्मजिह्व
Idhmajihva --a son of Priyavrata and Barhiṣmatī. Appointed lord of Plakṣadvīpa, which he divided into seven parts among his seven sons, and retired to practise austerities. Bhā. V. 1. 25 and 33; 20. 2.

इन
Ina --a divinity invoked by cowherdesses to protect the neck of the baby Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 6. 22.

इन्दिरा
Indirā  (I)--a surname of Lakṣmī; a śakti bearer of fly whisk to Lalitā. Bhā. X. 31. 1; Br. IV. 35. 98.

इन्दिरा
Indirā  (II)--R. a mahānadi. Vā. 108. 79.

इन्दु
Indu  (I)--a name of Soma (s.v.). Br. II. 19. 134; 37. 44; III. 65. 21; Vā. 63. 41; Vi. I. 15. 77.

इन्दु
Indu  (II)--the son of Viśvaga. M. 12. 29.

इन्दु
Indu  (III)--Moon--married the 27 Mānasa daughters of Dakṣa. Vā. 63. 41. 

इन्दुमती
Indumatī --the mother of Daśaratha. Br. IV. 40. 100 and 137.

इन्दुमौलि
Indumauli --also Candramauli. Br. IV. 30. 38 and 67.

इन्दुवत्सरा
Induvatsarā --a śakti. Br. IV. 32. 16.

इन्द्र
Indra  (I)--(Sahasrākṣa, Devendra, etc.). A Lokapāla. He and three other Lokapālas have their cities on the Mānasottara mountain in Puṣkaradvīpa; 1) Bhā. V. 20. 30; M. 266. 19. worshipped for vigour of organs. 2) Bhā. II. 3. 2. Served as calf for gods to milk from the Earth. 3) Ib. IV. 18. 15; M. 10. 18. Presented Pṛthu with a crown. 4) Bhā. IV. 14. 26; 15. 15. Deprived Pṛthu of his sacrificial horse during the hundredth Aśvamedha. Urged by Atri, Pṛthu's son pursued Indra, when the latter abandoned the house and disappeared. A second time Indra deprived Pṛthu of his horse; when the king's men pursued him, he left the horse and went away in disguise. This enraged Pṛthu, who aimed his arrow at Indra but was pacified by Brahmā in the name of dharma. A reconciliation was effected when Pṛthu embraced him. 5) Ib. IV. 16. 24; 19. 10-17, 19-22, 26-39; 20. 18. Invested Vijitāśva with power of moving about unseen by others. 6) Ib. IV. 24. 3. Jealous of Ṛṣabha, refused rains for his kingdom Ajanābha. Bestowed Jayantī on him. 7) Ib. V. 4. 3 and 8. During Hiraṇyakaśipu's absence at Mandara hill, Indra captured his queen and took her to his heavenly abode. Nārada intervened and set her at liberty. 8) Ib. VII. 7. 6-11. Took up his vajra against Cyavana for allowing Aśvins to partake of soma juice. But Cyavana's tapas tied down his arms, when Indra yielded. 9) Ib. IX. 3. 25, 26. Assumed the form of a bull over which Kakustha rode and defeated Asuras in a battle. Made the crying Māndhāta suckle his finger. 10) Ib. IX. 6. 12-15, 31; Vi. IV. 2. 29-32. Prevented Rohita from entering  his city for six years: Awarded Hariścandra a golden chariot after his Puruṣamedha. 11) Bhā. VII. 7. 17-20, 23. Robbed Sagara's sacrificial horse and left it near Kapila's hermitage. 12) Ib. IX. 8. 8 and 10. Performed a sacrifice which was attended by Vasiṣṭha. 13) Ib. IX. 13. 1 and 2. Joined the gods in Tārakāmaya war. 14) Ib. IX. 14. 7. Asked Gandharvas to take back Urvaśī living with Purūravas. 15) Ib. IX. 14. 26. Helped by Rāji, gave back his kingdom. After his death, his sons refused to give back the kingdom, and Indra slew all of them. 16) Ib. IX. 17. 13-16; Br. III. 67. 87-105. Cursed by Durvāsa, he lost all fortune. The three worlds became empty. Varuṇa and other gods conferred with Brahmā. Finding no means to restore their fortunes, they repaired to Hari Ajita when Brahmā belauded Hari as mahāvibhūti. Hari advised them to secure Bali's alliance. 17) Bhā. VIII. 5. 16-50; 6. 30-31. When the Devāsura war broke out, the gods fought with Bali who defeated them. At that time Indra prayed to Hari for help. Encouraged by the latter, the war was renewed and Bali was defeated. At this Jambha offered to fight Indra and disabled his elephant. Mātali supplied a chariot and Jambha's head was cut off. Namuci, Bala and Pāka attacked Indra. The latter two were slain. Namuci proved too much for Indra's vajra. A voice from the sky told Indra that Namuci could not be crushed by a wet or dry thing. Then Indra used phena (foam) and vanquished him. Bali in the meantime gathered strength and beseiged Indra. Indra sought counsel of Bṛhaspati who cared for his welfare, and as advised by the latter, he abandoned the city. 18) Ib. VIII. 10. 24 and 28, 41-53; 11. 1-40; 15. 24-33; M. 22. 60-61; 29. 11; 31. 12. Got back Heaven from Vāmana-Hari. He took him to his abode. 19) Bhā. VIII. 23. 19 and 24. Defeated by Arjuna who got the sabhā made by Maya. Arjuna for a short time shared his throne. Defeated by Arjuna at Khāṇḍava. His city visited by Arjuna in the course of a search for the dead children of the Dvārakā Brāhmaṇa. 20) Ib. X. 89. 34[4], 44. Was not able to defeat Nivāta  Kavacas. 21) Ib. X. 89. 34[5]. Afraid of Nara's superior powers, sent Kāma to spoil his tapas; was struck with fear with the sage's greatness; 22) Ib. XI. 4. 7 and 16. sent nymphs to disturb Mārkaṇḍeya's vrata but in vain. 23) Ib. XII. 8. 15-31. Sheltered Takṣaka and was about to be sacrificed when Bṛhaspati luckily intervened. 24) Ib. XII. 6. 17-23. Said to be afraid of the Kurus. 25) Ib. X. 68. 28 and 34. Attended Varuṇa's sacrifice and Yudhiṣṭhira's. 26) Ib. X. 74. 13. For his sake Hari went to Bali in the disguise of a Brāhmaṇa. 27) Ib. X. 72. 25. Once he sat with Indrāṇī in his sabhā surrounded by all gods. In his pride he did not welcome his preceptor Bṛhaspati in the proper way. The latter went away home at once and concealed himself from the gods. On this the Asuras attacked the gods. Indra repented and on Brahmā's advice appointed Viśvarūpa as his preceptor. Having been initiated into the Vidyā Varma Nārāyaṇātmakam, he was enjoying his original prosperity. One day Indra discovered that a part of Viśvarūpa's offerings went to the Asuras and therefore cut off his head in anger. Thus he incurred the sin of brahmahatyā. After a year, in order to rid himself of it he divided his sin into four parts among (1) the earth with the boon that dug portion should get filled up, (2) the waters with the boon of increasing volume when mixed up, (3) trees with the boon that branches cut off grow again, and (4) women with the boon of ever cherishing the passion of love. The saline soil, bubbles and foam, gum and monthly discharges respectively represent the brahmahatyā sin. 28) Ib. VI. 7. 2-40; 8. 42; 9. 4-11. With Vajra made of Dadhīci's bones (made by Tvaṣṭr from sun's tejas--Matsya P.), Indra attacked Vṛtra as Rudra attacked Yama. The encounter took place on the banks of the Narmadā in the first Tretāyuga. Battle described. Seeing his friends escaping in fright, Vṛtra encouraged them to stand and fight. He also disabled Indra's Airāvata, and addressed him at length. Indra cut off one of his arms. With the remaining arm Vṛtra hit Indra while the Vajra slipped from his hands causing concern to the gods.  Encouraged by the straight speech of Vṛtra, Indra took up his Vajra and cut off his other arm. Vṛtra swallowed him; but Indra, the vanquisher of Bala, got out of his stomach and cut off his head. Indra's regret at the murder of another Brāhmaṇa. The sin of brahmicide, says the legend, took the disguise of a Caṇḍāla woman and ran towards him in a terrific form when he entered the lake Mānasa and lived in the lotus stalks for a thousand years. Invited by Brāhmaṇas, he performed an Aśvamedha and got rid of his sins. 29) Ib. VIII. 10. 13-33; 11. 10-27; 12. 3-33; 13. 4-21. Father of three sons Jayanta and others through Paulomī. Getting to know that his mother Diti was observing a vow to get a child to slay him he offered to do service to her. Once he found her slack in her duty. He entered the womb and cut the child into seven pieces and each of these again into seven. At her request he offered to her to give them the rank of gods, by name Maruts, 30) Ib. VI. 18. 7, 37, 54, 56-77; M. 7. 50-65; 69. 60; 146. 20, 28-44, 45-55; Br. III. 5. 55-79; IV. 20. 44. who were allowed to share in the yajñas. Diti thought of another son Vajrānga who bound Indra and placed him before her. Was released on mediation from Brahmā and Kaśyapa. 30a) M. 146. 45-55. Reported to Kṛṣṇa the wicked deeds of Naraka. Got a gift of Maṇiparvata of Naraka from Kṛṣṇa. 31) Bhā. X. 59. 1 [1]
and 2, 22[3]; Vi. V. 29. 1-15. Visited by Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā. At the latter's wish, Pārijāta was removed without any intimation. Indra, induced by Indrāṇi attacked him with all gods. Kubera, Varuṇa and others were defeated. Indra himself offered resistance. Garuḍa disabled his elephant and Indra retreated. Satyabhāmā made fun of him ‘Do not run, Lord of Indrāṇī.’ Indra apologised. Kṛṣṇa answered that Indra was not in the wrong as he (Kṛṣṇa) took the offensive. Indra asked pardon and begged that his son Bībhatsu be protected. Kṛṣṇa told him that Pārijāta would go back to him when he left the mortal world. Returned to his city with all gods. 32) Ib. V. 37. 16; Bhā. X. 59. 38-39; [65 (V) 5], [37-51]; [66. (V)]
whole; [67 (V) 1-37]; Vi. V. 30. 51-70; 31. 1-10. The God of rain: Sent torrents of showers on Gokula when Kṛṣṇa protected his friends by holding up the hill  Govardhana. At this Indra and Surabhi came to visit him. Indra asked for pardon. Told by Kṛṣṇa that he was humiliated for his own good. In the company of Surabhi, Indra got Kṛṣṇa bathed with the waters of the Gaṅgā and called him Govinda. Returned to his region. 33) Bhā. X. 3. 50; 26. 25; 27. 1-17. 22-28; Vi. V. chap. 11 & 12 whole. Presented Sudharma and Pārijāta to Kṛṣṇa for his new city. 34) Bhā. X. 50-55; Vi. V. 21. 13-17. Requested Mucukunda for aid against the Asuras. 35) Bhā. X. 51. 15. Went to Dvārakā with gods to invite Kṛṣṇa to go back to Vaikuṇṭḥa. 36) Ib. XI. 6. 2; 31. 1. Place on the Śiśumāra. 37) Ib. V. 23. 5. Prayer to Narasimha. 38) Ib. VII. 8. 42. Devoid of energy. 39) Ib. VIII. 5. 19. Pleased with the yajña of Marutta. 40) Ib. IV. 2. 28; Father of Arjuṅa. 41) Br. III. 71. 154; M. 46. 9; 50. 50; IX. 22. 27; Vi. IV. 14. 35; Vā. 92. 82; 96. 153; 103. 60; 106. 20, 59; 108. 4, 31. See Indrayāga. With the sun for the months Nabhonabhasi: An Āditya; represents a face of Śiva; 42) Bhā. XII. 11. 37; Br. II. 23. 9; 24. 33, 38; 26. 40; 27. 23; III. 3. 68, 102; M. 6. 4; 171. 56; Vā. 52. 7; Vi. II. 10. 9. also Viśvabhuk; introduced yajña at the commencement of Tretāyuga; 43) Br. II. 30. 9, 16, 21; M. 143. 5. the seventh Vedavyāsa. Realm of. 44) Br. II. 35. 98 and 118; IV. 33. 55; M. 82. 31; Vi. III. 3. 13. Vanquished the sons of Varatri when they disturbed Manu's sacrifice. 45) Br. III. 1. 80. Sent Agni to disturb Mahādeva's enjoying Umā when the latter cursed him to bear the garbha. 46) Ib. III. 7. 72, 326; 10. 23-28; 24. 2, 4. Was born as Gādhi, son of Kuśika. 47) Ib. III. 63. 25; 66. 34-5. As an avatār of Viṣṇu, defeated Prahlada who offered battle for a period of 300 years and killed his son Virocana in Tārakāmaya battle; obtained sovereignty over the three worlds. 48) Br. III. 5. 55-79; IV. 20. 44; M. 8. 4; 22. 61; 24. 38-49; 27. 37; 47. 48-61. Slew Jambha who had won the grace of Śiva. 49) M. 47, 72. Knowing Nārada on a mission to bring about the wedding of Umā  and Śiva, sent the God of Love and the seven sages in its accomplishment. 50) M. 154. 111-131. Praised Śiva on his conquest of Tripura: Cursed Yayāti to fall from heaven; 51) M. 34. 6; 35. 3-6; 36. 3-4; 64. 27. disturbed Varāngi's penance by disguises of monkey, reptile, etc. 52) M. 146. 23, 63-70. A friend of Purūravas, offered half his seat when he visited him daily. 53) M. 24. 14, 26. Addressed Bṛhaspati on the nature and meaning of the bad omens he saw. 54) Br. IV. 4. 60; 6. 31-5. Sacrifice on the banks of the Ganges and in the Gaura hill. Helped Lalitā in her conquest of Bhaṇḍa; the place of his penance became Indraprastha. 55) Br. II. 18. 28; I. 1. 130; IV. 6. 24; 8. 61; 12. 35. 9, 43; 19. 83; 26. 53; 30. 8. Clipped the wings of mountains which flew into the sea. 56) Br. II. 22. 41; M. 121. 78; Gave boons to Sukarman, a manvantara Lord; 57) Br. II. 35. 34; 36. 1. Sent Apsaras as gopis to aid Kṛṣṇa. Festival of, by cowherds; disapproved by Kṛṣṇa, was discontinued; 58) Br. III. 68. 17; 71. 201, 244; Vi. V. 10. 16-26; Bhā. X. 24 (whole). gifts of elephants and gems pleasing to. 59) M. 47. 114-122, 171-9; 266. 62. Sent his daughter Jayantī to earn the good will of Śukra and then disturb his penance. 60) M. 172. 5; 245. 82. Fight of, with Gajāsura and Nemi; 61) M. 153. 59; 177. 47; 223. 4. 11; 244. 8. 266. 43. made the six children into one Kārtikeya. 62) M. 159. 5. Cursed Agni and Marut to be born in the world for failure to obey his orders in drying up the ocean and vanquishing the Asuras. 63) M. 61. 3-17; Indra of Vaivasvata antara equal to other Indras. Lord of devagaṇas; 64) Br. II. 13. 97; Vā. 66. 14. Lord of the past, present and future; the thousand eyed; performer of 100 sacrifices; 65) Vā. 64. 5-8. slew Varūtri's sons who rioted by eating the offerings intended for gods. 66) Vā. 65. 79-81. 

इन्द्र
Indra  (II)--the temple of, in Vidarbhā (see Indrāṇī). Bhā. X. 53. 49[1].

इन्द्र
Indra  (III)--a son of Vasiṣṭha, and Prajāpati of the Svārociṣa epoch. M. 9. 9.

इन्द्र
Indra  (IV)--a division of the day. Vā. 66. 41.

इन्द्र
Indra  (V)--one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 8.

इन्द्रकील
Indrakīla --a mountain in Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā., V. 19. 16.

इन्द्रकीलम्
Indrakīlam --a tīrtham sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 53.

इन्द्रकेतु
Indraketu --flags flying in the streets of Dvārakā during Kṛṣṇa's marriage with Rukmiṇi. Bhā. X. 54. 56.

इन्द्रजालम्
Indrajālam --one of the upayās of a king. M. 222. 2.

इन्द्रजित्
Indrajit  (I)--a son of Rāvaṇa, killed in the Lanka war. Bhā. IX. 10. 18; Br. III. 6. 6.

इन्द्रजित्
Indrajit  (II)--a son of Danu. M. 6. 19; Vā. 68. 6.

इन्द्रजित्
Indrajit  (III)--a tīrtham near Garjanam on the Narmadā. M. 190. 3. 

इन्द्रतापन
Indratāpana --a dānava, in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. Br. III. 6. 8; M. 161. 81.

इन्द्रत्वम्
Indratvam --Indrahood, attained by Heti. Vā. 109. 9.

इन्द्रदत्त
Indradatta --a Kinnara with human face. Vā. 69. 35.

इन्द्रद्युम्न
Indradyumna --the son of Tejasa (Taijasa-Vā. P.). A Drāviḍa and a Pāṇḍyan king. Devoted to Hari. While engaged in tapas Agastya came to his hermitage. Finding him not extending a welcome, the angry sage cursed him to become an elephant. Indradyumna considered that to be the will of the Lord. He was born as the Lord of the elephants, and had reminiscences of his past life; 1) Bhā. VIII. 4. 7-12; Br. II. 14. 64; Vā. 33. 54; Vi. II. 1. 36. an account of, in the Kūrma Pūrāṇa. 2) M. 53. 47-8.

इन्द्रद्युम्न
Indradyumna saras --a lake through which Pāvani flows (Nalinī--Matsya P.). Br. II. 18. 56; M. 121. 55; Vā. 47. 54.

इन्द्रद्वीप
Indradvīpa --one of the nine divisions of Bhāratavarṣa: 1) Br. II. 16. 9; Vā. 45. 79; Vi. II. 3. 6; M. 114. 8. Here the R. Nalinī enters the sea. 2) M. 121. 57.

इन्द्रद्वीपसमुद्र
Indradvīpasamudra --a place where Pāvanī enters the sea. Br. II. 18. 58; Vā. 47. 55.

इन्द्रधनुस्
Indradhanus --the rainbow created by Vāmadeva. M. 4. 29; Vā. 9. 52; 19. 8; Br. II. 8. 54. 

इन्द्रधन्व
Indradhanva --a son of Bāṇa. Br. III. 5. 45.

इन्द्रध्वज
Indradhvaja --the fall of Cāṇūra, compared to the falling of. Bhā. X. 44. 23.

इन्द्रनदी
Indranadī --a R. of the Bhadra country. Vā. 43. 26.

इन्द्रपद
Indrapada --a kingdom on the west, watered by the Sindhu; 1) Br. II. 18. 48. in Gayā. 2) Vā. 109. 19.

इन्द्रपालित
Indrapālita (Maurya) --the son of Bandhupālita, ruled for 10 years. Br. III. 74. 147; Vā. 99. 334.

इन्द्रप्रतिम
Indrapratima --a Vāsiṣtha and a Brahmavādin; 1) M. 145. 110. a name of Kuśi, son of Vasiṣṭha. 2) Vā. 70. 88.

इन्द्रप्रमति
Indrapramat(d)i --the sage and a Vāsiṣṭha who came to see Parīkṣit practising prāyopaveśa. Learnt Ṛk Samhita from Paila and taught it to the sage Māṇḍukeya; (Markaṇḍeya-Vā.) 1) Bhā. I. 19. 9; XII. 6. 54-56; Br. II. 32. 115; 33. 3; 34. 25; Vā. 60. 25, 27; Vi. III. 4. 16, 19. Also known as Kuṇi; 2) Br. III. 8. 96-7. not to have marriage alliances with Vāsiṣṭhas and Bhagīvasu, a resident of Brahmakṣetra. 3) Vā. 59. 105.

इन्द्रप्रमद
Indrapramada --a sage; called on dying Bhīṣma. Bhā. I. 9. 7; 19. 9. 

इन्द्रप्रस्थ
Indraprastha (t) --Yādavas of Dvāraka taken to, by Arjuna, fearing erosion of the sea. See also Hastināpuram; 1) Bhā. X. 58. 1; XI. 30. 48; 31. 25. after Indra who performed penance here in honour of Parāśakti to vanquish Bhaṇḍa. 2) Br. IV. 12. 44. Arjuna had Vajra crowned here. 3) Vi. V. 38. 34.

इन्द्रबाधनकेशि
Indrabādhanakeśi --a dānava with manuṣyadharma. Br. III. 6. 16; Vā. 68. 15.

इन्द्रबाहु
Indrabāhu --An Āgastya and Brahmiṣṭha. M. 145. 114.

इन्द्रमानसा
Indramānasā --the wife of Bāṇa and mother of Lauhitya. Vā. 67. 85.

इन्द्रमरु
Indramaru --the kingdom of. M. 121. 47.

इन्द्रयाग
Indrayāga --performed every year by Nanda and other gopas to please Indra, the Lord of rains and hence conducive to Trivarga. Kṛṣṇa explained that rain was the work of nature, and that no credit went to Indra. So he persuaded them to worship cows, Brāhmaṇas and hills. So it happened. Indra who was thus deprived of his bali grew wrathful and sent down a continuous heavy downpour of rain creating panic in the minds of gopas. Kṛṣṇa took hold of the hill Govardhana and held it aloft as an umbrella steadily for seven days. Astonished at this, Indra withdrew his rains and Govardhana was planted in its place. Bhā. X. 24 (whole); ch. 25. 1-28.

इन्द्रलोकम्
Indralokam --the world of Indra. See also ‘Realm of’ under Indra (footnote 44). M. 277. 22; 278. 29; Vā. 34. 76-7; 61. 88; 111. 52. 

इन्द्रवाह
Indravāha --see Puramjaya. Bhā. IX. 6. 12.

इन्द्रव्रतम्
Indravratam --of a king; to create prosperity in the country, as Indra gives rains; 1) M. 226. 10. leads to the world of Indra. 2) Ib. 101. 69.

इन्द्रशत्रु
Indraśatru --one of Bhaṇḍa's councillors. Br. IV. 12. 12.

इन्द्रशैल
Indraśaila --(Mt.) a hill north of Mahābhadra lake. Vā. 36. 31.

इन्द्रसद
Indrasadas --the assembly of Indra. Vā. 2. 29.

इन्द्रसावर्णि
Indrasāvarṇi --Manu the fourteenth. Uru and others were his sons. During his period Śuci was Indra, while Agnibāhu and others were sages. Bṛhadbhānu was a manifestation of Hari. Bhā. VIII. 13. 33-35.

इन्द्रसूक्तम्
Indrasūktam --to be uttered in founding a temple. M. 265. 25.

इन्द्रसेन
Indrasena  (I)--a boundary hill in Plakṣadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 4.

इन्द्रसेन
Indrasena  (II)--a son of Devaṛṣabha. Bhā. VI. 6. 5.

इन्द्रसेन
Indrasena  (III)--a son of Kūrca (Pūrva-Burnouf) and father of Vītihotra. Bhā. IX. 2. 19-20. 

इन्द्रसेन
Indrasena  (IV)--previously Bali. Received Kṛṣṇa and Rāma with due honours to his region Sutala, and praised their glory; gave them back their brothers killed by Kaṃsa. Bhā. X. 85. 35-46, 52.

इन्द्रसेन
Indrasena  (V)--a son of Brahmiṣṭha and father of Vindhyāśva. M. 50. 6.

इन्द्रसेना
Indrasenā --the wife of Mudgola and mother of Badhyaśva. Vā. 99. 200.

इन्द्रस्पृग्
Indraspṛg --a son of Ṛṣabha and Jayantī. Bhā. V. 4. 10.

इन्द्राणी
Indrāṇī  (I)--sat with Indra in his sabhā. 1) Bhā. VI. 7. 6. Punished Nahuṣa for his overweening pride. 2) Ib. IX. 18. 3; VI. 13. 16. Was the mother of Jayanta and two other sons. 3) Ib. VI. 18. 7. Welcomed Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā to Amarāvati. Satyabhāmā aggrieved against her and thought her proud of her riches and of her Lord's prowess. 4) Ib. X. 59. 38; [65 (V) 5], [28]; [67 (V) 19]. A śakti. 5) Br. IV. 44. 84, 111.

इन्द्राणी
Indrāṇī  (II)--The temple of--in Vidarbha. This was visited by Rukmiṇī on the day prior to her marriage for worship. Indrāṇī and Indra were kuladevatas of Vidarbhas. 1) Bhā. X. 53. 49 [1 & 2], and 50. Image of. 2) M. 13. 52; 260. 70; 261. 31.

इन्द्रायुध
Indrāyudha --the rainbow appearing in cloudless sky or at night, a bad sign for a state. M. 233. 7. 

इन्द्रियाणि
Indriyāṇi  (I)--(Indriyagrāmam) Senses: Five, under the control of Buddhi (Jñānam) and five under Karma. M. 3. 18-20; 184. 56; Vā. 31. 43.

इन्द्रियाणि
Indriyāṇi  (II)--the devas of Tāmasamanvantara, so called. Vā. 62. 39.

इन्द्रोत
Indrota --a Śaunaka sage who gave succour to Janamejaya in his Aśvamedha yajña. Br. III. 68. 25; Vā. 93. 25.

इरा
Irā  (I)--a name of Sarasvatī. Bhā. X. 13. 57.

इरा
Irā  (II)--a daughter of Dakṣa (Garuḍa (?)-Vā. P.) and one of the wives of Kaśyapa; mother of three daughters: Latā (creeper), Vallī (creeping plant) and Vīrudhā (a plant which grows again after being cut); they became in turn mothers of trees, plants and shrubs; Latā created flowerless wild plants standing in sandy regions and also trees with fruits and flowers; Vallī, bushes and grass of all kinds and Vīrudhā created Vīrudha group as her issues. Br. III. 7. 459-63, 468; M. 6. 2 and 46; 146. 18; Vā. 69. 339-42; Vi. I. 15. 125; 21. 24.

इरागर्भशिर
Irāgarbhaśiras --a son of Danu. M. 6. 18.

इरावत्
Irāvat --a son of Arjuna by Ulūpi. Bhā. IX. 22. 32; Vi. IV. 20. 49.

इरावती
Irāvatī  (I)--a daughter of Uttara and wife of Parīkṣit. Bhā. I. 16. 2. 

इरावती
Irāvatī  (II)--one of the wives of Rudra. Bhā. III. 12. 13.

इरावती
Irāvatī  (III)--a R. from the Himālayas; 1) Br. II. 16. 25; Vā. 45. 95. sacred to Pitṛs; a river-consort of fire Havyavāha; in the chariot of Tripurāri. 2) M. 22. 19; 51. 13; 133. 23; Br. II. 12. 15; Vā. 29. 13.

इरावती
Irāvatī  (IV)--a daughter of Krodhavaśa and wife of Pulaha: In her womb was placed the aṅḍakapāla by the progenitor and she gave birth to 4 kingly sons (elephants), Airāvaṇa, Kumuda, Añjana and Vāmana. Br. III. 7. 172, 289-292.

इरावती
Irāvatī  (V)--a daughter of Krodhā and mother of Airāvata. Vā. 69. 205, 211.

इल
Ila --the eldest son of Vaivasvata Manu; born of Putreṣṭi; anointed by Manu going to Mahendra hill for tapas; set out for digvijaya, when he reached Śaravaṇa gardens where Umā was sporting with Śiva. There was a curse by which a male who entered the garden was turned into a female. So Ila became Ilā. Bewildered Ilā was wandering and was met by Budha, Soma's son. She agreed to be his partner and followed him. Ikṣvāku and his brothers were concerned at their missing Ila and were told by Vasiṣṭha of his whereabouts. On Vasiṣṭha's advice, Ikṣvāku performed an Aśvamedha, as the result of which Ila would be a Kimpuruṣa for a month and Ilā for the next alternately. As Ilā, she gave birth to Purūravas, the first of the lunar race. In a way Ila was responsible for the two dynasties--solar and lunar. M. 11. 40-66; 12. 1-14. 

इलक
Ilaka --a madhyamādhvaryu. Br. II. 33. 15.

