Ṛṣabha  (VI)--a playmate of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 22. 31.

ऋषभ
Ṛṣabha  (VII)--identified with the sun. Bhā. XII. 6. 68.

ऋषभ
Ṛṣabha  (VIII)--the son of Nābhi and Sudevī (Merudevī according to Vi., Vā. & Br. P.) An avatār of Viṣṇu, eldest of all Kṣatra. A Paramahamsa. Had a hundred sons of whom Bharata was the eldest. 1) Br. II. 14. 60-62; Bhā. II. 7. 10; XI. 4. 17; Vi. II. 1. 27; Vā. 33. 50-51. Nine of these became rulers of the nine dvīpas of the world. Eightyone  of them became addicted to Karma tantra, and the remainder nine became sages. 2) Bhā. XI. 2. 15-20. Indra grew jealous of him and stopped rains in his kingdom Ajanābha. But Ṛṣabha, invoked rains by yogic powers. 3) Ib. V. 3 (whole); 4. 1-3. As king, married Jayantī, bestowed on him by Indra, who gave birth to 100 sons. Under Ṛṣabha, his kingdom flowed with milk and honey. Once he went to control Brahmāvarta and proclaimed the importance of self-control and discipline to his sons and to the world at large. Installed Bharata on the throne, renounced life and became a wandering mendicant. Finding the world opposed to his yoga practice he adopted the vow of a python (ājagaram) by which he ate, chewed, drank and passed water all lying down. By his yogic powers he wandered through Koṅka, Veṅka, Kuṭaka, S. Karnāṭa, and was consumed by forestfire. By listening to his story, devotion to Hari was increased. His path was followed by Sumati; 4) Ib. V. 4. 8-19; chap. 5 (whole); 6. 6-19; 15. 1; Vā. 33. 51. took to the third āśrama at Pulaha's hermitage and lived there until his death. 5) Vi. II. 1. 28-31.

ऋषभ
Ṛṣabha  (IX)--a son of Aṅgiras, and a sage of the Svārociṣa epoch; a mantrakṛt. Br. III. 36. 17; Vā. 59. 100.

ऋषभ
Ṛṣabha  (X)--a son of Sudhanvan. Vā. 65. 102.

ऋषभ
Ṛṣabha  (XI)--a dānava with manuṣya dharma. Vā. 68. 15.

ऋषभ
Ṛṣabha  (XII)--a ṛtvik at Brahmā's yājña. Vā. 106. 37. 

ऋषभ
Ṛṣabha  (XIII)--a mountain on the north base of Meru but in Bhāratavarṣa; sacred to Hari and visited by Balarāma; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 26; 19. 16; X. 79. 15; M. 163. 78; Vi. II. 2. 30. entered the sea. 2) M. 121. 72; Br. II. 18. 75.

