Aurva  (I)--a son born of Apravāṇa (Apruvat-Matsya P.) and Ṛcī, being born from her thigh. Father of Ṛcīka. Jamadagni was his grandson; a mantrakṛt and sage. 1) Br. III. 1. 95; II. 32. 105; 38. 27; M. 195. 15-16; Vā. 59. 96; 65. 92. Sagara who had no son visited his hermitage with his two wives and was blessed for sons. Present at Sagara's Aśvamedha and other sacrifices and taught him the path to salvation; 2) Bhā. IX. 8. 8 & 31; Br. III. 34. 2; 50. 29-58; 51. 1-41; 52. 37; 55. 3; 63. 122, 133-4; Vā. 88. 123, 132-4; Vi. IV. 3. 29, 37. spoke to Sagara on the mode of worshipping Viṣṇu; 3) M. 12. 40; Vi. III. 8. 6-19. on Varṇadharma; 4) Vi. III. 8. 20-40. on Āśramadharma; 5) Ib. ch. 9 (whole). on rituals; 6) Ib. ch. 10 (whole). on the duties of the householder; 7) Ib. chapters 11-12. on funeral rites; 8) Ib. chapter 13 (whole). on the Śrāddha; 9) Ib. chapters 14-16; 17. 1. pre vented the pregnant queen of Bāhu(ka) from committing satī, 10) Bhā. IX. 8. 3; Vi. IV. 3. 29-37. and the posthumous son Sagara brought up in his hermitage to whom he did all samskaras. Was visited and revisited by Paraśurāma. 11) Br. III. 21. 35; 25. 81; Vi. IV. 3. 36. Phalgutanta took refuge near his hermitage; 12) Br. III. 47. 79-87. extinguished the Tālajaṅgha line. 13) Bhā. IX. 23. 28. Came to see Parīkṣit practising prāyopaveśa. 14) Bhā. I. 19. 10. A description of his hermitage. 15) Br. III. 50. 34-45. A sage of the Svārociṣa epoch, and one of the five Pravaras of Bhārgava gotra. 16) M. 9. 8; 195. 29.

