Kaṃsāvatī --a daughter of Ugrasena. Married Devaśravas. Bhā. IX. 24. 25 & 41; Br. III. 71. 134; M. 44. 75; Vi. IV. 14. 21. 

ककुत्स्थ
Kakutstha  (I)--the son of Śaśāda; rode on Indra in the form of a bull in the Āḍīvaka Yuddha. Father of Anenas. Vā. 88. 24-25; Br. III. 63. 25; Vi. IV. 2. 32-3.

ककुत्स्थ
Kakutstha  (II)--a surname of Puramjaya (s.v.); a son of Vikukṣi; lust of, after more territory; eldest of 114 ruling south of Meru. Bhā. IX. 6. 12; XII. 3. 10; M. 12. 20.

ककुद्
Kakud --a Marīci god. Br. IV. 1. 58.

ककुदः
Kakudaḥ --a son of Satyaka and Kāśī king's daughter; his son, Vṛṣṭi. Vā. 96. 115-16.

ककुदचक्र
Kakudacakra --a brother of Vasudeva. Vi. IV. 14. 30.

ककुद्मान्
Kakudmān  (I)--a Mt. of Śālmalidvīpa noted for precious gems rained by Vāsava; a hill containing medicinal herbs, on the N. W. of the Kailāsa. Br. II. 19. 41-2; M. 121. 14; Vā. 49. 38; Vi. II. 4. 27.

ककुद्मान्
Kakudmān  (II)--Mt. in Kuśadvīpa. M. 122. 60.

ककुद्मिन्
Kakudmin --The eldest of Reva(ta)'s hundred sons. Father of Revatī (Surata-Vā.) whom he took to Brahmā for a suitable bridegroom. As Brahmā was engaged in attending to music, the king waited, and afterwards the Creator laughingly said that it was past 27 × 4 yugas since he came there. At that time was flourishing Balarāma whose name was suggested for his daughter's husband. On return he found his country overrun by Yakṣas, and getting his daughter married to Balarāma, he retired to Badari to  perform penance. 1) Bhā. IX. 3. 29-36; M. 12. 23; Vā. 86. 26-30; 88. 1. Ruled from Kuśasthali. During his sojourn at Brahmā's residence, the Rākṣasas captured the capital and put to flight his younger brothers who established smaller states then and there. 2) Br. III. 61. 20-27; Vi. IV. 1. 65-96.

ककुपाद
Kakupāda --a Rākṣasa in Sutalam. Br. II. 20. 23.

ककुभ
Kakubha --a hill in Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 16.

ककुभि
Kakubhi --a daughter of Dakṣa and a wife of Dharma. Mother of Saṃkaṭa. Bhā. VI. 6. 4 & 6.

कक्लस
Kaklasa --a commander who aided Viṣaṅga; killed by Vanhivāsā. Br. IV. 25. 28 & 95.

कक्लिवाहन
Kaklivāhana --a commander of Viṣaṅga--also Kekivāhana. Was killed by Mahāvajreśvarī. Br. IV. 25. 28 & 96.

कक्षीवट्
Kakṣīvaṭ  (I)--a rājaṛṣi becoming a Brāhmaṇa. Vā. 91. 117.

कक्षीवत्
Kakṣīvat  (II)--a sage who called on Bhīṣma on his death bed. 1) Bhā. 1. 9. 7. An Aṅgiras and a mantrakṛt; a Kṣatropetadvija. 2) Br. II. 32. 111; III. 66. 88.

कक्षीवट्
Kakṣīvaṭ  (III)--the son born of Dīrghatamas to Bali's slave girl: Followed his father Gautama afterwards to Girivraja (Giripraja-Vā. P.) and got engaged in tapas. Attained  Brahmahood at the place with his brother Cakṣus. Father of 1000 sons known as Kūṣmāṇḍa Gautamas and Kṛṣṇāṅgas. 1) Br. III. 74. 71, 95 & 99; Vā. 99. 70, 93-7. A mantrakṛt and of the Aṅgirasa branch. 2) M. 145. 105; Vā. 59. 102.

कक्षीवत्
Kakṣīvat  (IV)--a pupil of Pauṣpiñji. Vi. III. 6. 6.

कक्षेयु
Kakṣeyu  (I)--a son of Bhadrāśva. M. 49. 5.

कक्षेयु
Kakṣeyu  (II)--one of the ten sons of Raudrāśva. Vā. 99. 124; Vi. IV. 19. 2.

कङ्क
Kaṅka(u)  (I)--a son of Ugrasena, and brother of Kaṃsa; killed by Balarāma. 1) Bhā. IV. 24. 24; X. 44. 40-41. His daughter was the queen of Andhaka. 2) M. 44. 61 & 74.

कङ्क
Kaṅka  (II)--a son of Devamīḍha alias Śūra, and Māriṣā. His queen was Karṇikā and sons were Ṛtadhāman and Jaya. Bhā. IX. 24. 27-9. & 44.

कङ्क
Kaṅka  (III)--the avatār of the Lord in the fifth dvāpara with four sons, all yogins. Vā. 23. 129.

कङ्क
Kaṅka  (IV)--a ṛtvik at Brahmā's yajña. Vā. 106. 36.

कङ्क
Kaṅka  (V)--(Mt.) a chief hill of the Śālmalidvīpa. Vā. 42. 50; 49. 36; Vi. II. 4. 27. 

कङ्क
Kaṅka  (VI)--a Mt. in Kuśadvīpa. M. 122. 57.

कङ्क
Kaṅkas  (I)--a royal dynasty of sixteen princes noted for their greed. See Maunas. Bhā. XII. 1. 29.

कङ्क
Kaṅkas  (II)--a tribe defeated by Bharatas. Purified of sin by devotion to Hari. 1) Bhā. IX. 20. 30; II. 4. 18. Heard of Kṛṣṇa going to Mithilā, and met him there with presents. 2) Bhā. X. 86. 20.

कङ्का
Kaṅkā --a daughter of Ugrasena; wife of Ānaka and mother of Satyajit and Purujit. Bhā. IX. 24. 25 and 41; M. 44. 76.

कच
Kaca --the son of Bṛhaspati; deputed by gods to learn Samjīvinī vidyā from Śukrācārya; offered himself as a disciple and admitted as a pupil by Śukra; conducted himself to the satisfaction of his teacher and his daughter Devayānī for a period of 500 years. Once while out in the woods tending Śukra's cows, the Asuras killed him and left his body to be devoured by dogs and jackals. The cows returned home but not Kaca. Devayānī suspected of foul play and reported his death. Śukra brought him back to life. 1) M. 25. 14-37. On another occasion he went to the woods to gather flowers for Devayānī and this time the Asuras ground him to pieces and mixing them with surā offered it to Śukra who drank it. Again Devayānī persisted wanting him back to life. This meant Śukra's death for he had to come out by tearing open his belly. So he taught Kaca the Samjīvinī vidyā so that he might restore him after his revival. Thus he did and so he learnt the vidyā. After a sojourn of ten hundred years he returned with due leave from his teacher. Now Devayānī offered to marry him but he pointed out that it was not proper to marry his preceptor's daughter. So  she cursed that he would not get the fruits of his vidyā and he retorted that she would not find a Brāhmaṇa husband but only a Kṣatriya. Returned to the gods who gave him a share in their oblations; put to death by Vṛṣaparvan's men. 2) M. 25. 38-69; chap. 26 whole; Bhā. IX. 18. 22.

कच्छ
Kaccha (c) --a western country. Br. II. 16. 62.

कच्छनीर
Kacchanīra --the Nāga presiding over the month of Mādhava. Bhā. XII. 11. 34.

कच्छप
Kacchapa  (I)--a son of Viśvāmitra. Br. III. 66. 69; Vā. 91. 97; Vi. IV. 7. 38.

कच्छप
Kacchapa  (II)--a Nāga. Vā. 69. 73.

कच्छप
Kacchapa  (III)--one of the eight nidhis of Kubera. Vā. 41. 10.

कच्छवीर
Kacchavīra --the sarpa who resides in the sun's chariot during the month of Mādhava. Vi. II. 10. 5.

कच्छिप
Kacchipa (c) --a western country. Br. II. 16. 62.

कच्छियस्
Kacchiyas --of the south. Vā. 45. 131. 

कञ्ची
Kañcī --in the liṅga deśa of the personified Veda. Vā. 104. 76.

कञ्चीपीठम्
Kañcīpīṭham --in the waist of the personified Veda. Vā. 104. 80.

कञ्ची
Kañcī --a R. of the Ketumāla country. Vā. 44. 18.

कञ्चुकि
Kañcukis  1) Bhā. X. 53. 41[]. --followed Rukmiṇī going to Devī temple; also Kañcukadhāri. 2) Br. IV. 32. 3; M. 254. 23.

कटक
Kaṭaka --Viṣṇu. Vi. IV. 15. 13.

कटकर्म
Kaṭakarma --a part of death rituals. Vi. III. 13. 10.

कटकृत्
Kaṭakṛt --a maker of mats of reeds. Bhā. I. 3. 18.

कटायनी
Kaṭāyanī --a Bhārgava. M. 195. 33.

कटुक
Kaṭuka gaṇa --articles of, detailed. M. 217. 62-7.

कटुमुखी
Kaṭumukhī --a mother goddess. M. 179. 29.

कट्य
Kaṭya --a sage. M. 196. 47. 

कठ
Kaṭhas --Ekārṣeyas. M. 200. 3.

कठेश्वरम्
Kaṭheśvaram --a tīrtham on the Narmadā. M. 191. 63-4.

कड
Kaḍa --a brother of Vasudeva. Vā. 96. 148.

कणाद
Kaṇāda --a son of Somaśarman, an avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 216.

कण्टकारा
Kaṇṭakārās --a northern tribe. M. 114. 42.

कण्ठ
Kaṇṭha  (I)--a son of Ajamīḍha and Keśinī; father of Medhātithi. Vā. 99. 169-170.

कण्ठ
Kaṇṭha  (II)--a son of Dhurya. Vā. 99. 130.

कण्ठकाल
Kaṇṭhakāla --a Śrutaṛṣi. Br. II. 33. 5.

कण्ठमुद्गल
Kaṇṭhamudgalas --the Mudgalas belonging to the branch of Aṅgiras. Vā. 99. 199.

कण्ठायन
Kaṇṭhāyanas --(the text is confused). Apparently the four kings beginning with Navakaṇṭhāyāna are Śuṅgabhṛtyas and were known as Kaṇṭāyanadvijas. Vā. 99. 346-7. 

कण्डरीक
Kaṇḍarīka --the minister of Pañcāla Brahmadatta; remembered his previous birth as a son of Kauśika, left for the forest to practise yoga with his brother minister. M. 20. 24; 21. 31.

कण्डिन
Kaṇḍina --a Vāśiṣṭha and a sage. Br. II. 32. 116.

कण्डु
Kaṇḍu  (I)--a sage engaged in austerities on the banks of the Gomatī; had a daughter through Pramlocā who abandoned the child in the midst of trees and departed. Soma nourished it with nectar, and trees looked after her as their baby. To get rid of the sin Kaṇḍu entered the temple of Puruṣottama and meditated on Keśava. Bhā. IV. 30. 13-14; Vi. I. 15. 11-54.

कण्डु
Kaṇḍu  (II)--a pupil of Lāṅgali. Br. II. 35. 48.

कण्डु
Kaṇḍu  (III)--a Lāṅgala. Vā. 61. 43.

कण्डू
Kaṇḍū --father of thousand snakes, moveable and immoveable having a number of heads, and flying in the air and having different names. Vā. 69. 68.

कण्व
Kaṇva  (I)--a son of Apratiratha and father of Medhātithi; Śakuntalā was brought up in his āśrama; performed birth and other samskāras to the son born to her. Bhā. IX. 20. 6-12 and 18; Vi. IV. 19. 5-6.

कण्व
Kaṇva  (II)--a sage and contemporary of Kṛṣṇa with whom he went to Mithilā. Left Dvārakā for Piṇḍāraka. Invited for Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya. Bhā. X. 86. 18; XI. 1. 12; X. 74. 7; Vi. V. 37. 6 

कण्व
Kaṇva  (III)--the minister of Devabhūti Śuṅga, whom he assassinated and usurped the throne. Bhā. XII. 1. 19.

कण्व
Kaṇva  (IV)--An Aṅgirasa and mantrakṛt. A pupil of Yājñavalkya. Br. II. 32. 109; 35. 28; Vā. 59. 100; 61. 24.

कण्व
Kaṇva  (V)--a son of Ajāmīḍha and Keśinī and father of Medhātithi. M. 49. 46; Vi. IV. 19. 30-31.

कण्व
Kaṇva  (V)--a ṛtvik at the yāga of Brahmā. Vā. 106. 35; 108. 42.

कण्व
Kaṇvas --a royal dynasty after Śuṅgas; four kings in all, ruled for 45 years. Bhā. XII. 1. 19; M. 272. 36; Vi. IV. 24. 38, 42.

कण्वायनद्विज
Kaṇvāyanadvijas --the family of Brāhmaṇas originally from Kaṇva and his son Medhātithi. (See Wilson, Note at p. 32). Vi. IV. 19. 7.

कण्वायन
Kaṇvāyanas --the predecessors of the Āndhra rulers; their reign of 4 kings lasted for 45 years. Br. III. 74. 158 & 159.

कत
Kata --a Kauśika and a sage. Br. II. 32. 118.

कतक
Katakas --a tribe conquered by Kalki. Br. II. 31. 84.

कत्तृण
Kattṛṇa --a Trayārṣeya. M. 196. 39. 

कथन
Kathana --a Rākṣasa living in Sutalam. Br. II. 20. 22.

कथा
Kathā --of Kāma and Keśava to be narrated in Madanadvādaśīvrata. M. 7. 14.

कथाजप
Kathājapa --a pupil of Bāṣkala. Vi. III. 4. 25.

कदम्बवनवासिनी
Kadambavana-vāsinī --a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 34; 28. 67.

कदम्बेशी
Kadambeśī --a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 34.

कदली
Kadalī --a R. sacred to Pitṛs. Once Rāma resided on her banks. M. 22. 52.

कद्रुक
Kadrukas --sons of Dullola. Br. III. 7. 443.

कद्रू
Kadrū --a daughter of Dakṣa, wife of Tārkṣyā, and mother of Nāgas, including Kāliya: 1) Bhā. V. 24. 8; VI. 6. 21-2; X. 17. 4, 73. according to Bṛahmāṇḍa Vi., Vā., and Mastya P. Consort of Kāśyapa; 2) Br. III. 3. 57; 7. 31, 467; M. 6. 2 & 38; 146. 19 & 22; 171. 29 & 63; Vā. 66. 55; Vi. I. 15. 125. known for anger. 3) Vā. 69. 94.

कद्रूपुत्र
Kadrūputra --Reference to Takṣaka in Sutalam. Br. II. 20. 24.

कद्वशंकु
Kadvaśaṃku --a son of Ugrasena. Vā. 96. 132. 

कनक
Kanaka  (I)--a Saṃhikeya Asura. Br. III. 6. 20.

कनक
Kanaka  (II)--a son of Durmada (Durdama-Matsya P.); father of Kṛtavīrya and three other sons, Kārtavīrya, Kṛtavarma and Kṛta. Br. III. 69. 8; M. 43. 12; Vā. 94. 7-9.

कनक
Kanaka  (III)--a son of Hṛdika. Br. III. 71. 141.

कनक
Kanaka  (IV)--a son of Bṛhati. Br. III. 71. 256.

कनक
Kanaka  (V)--a king who ruled over Strīrāṣṭra, Bhojaka and other kingdoms. Br. III. 74. 199.

कनक
Kanakas  (I)--enjoy kingdoms of Trairājya and Mūṣika. Vi. IV. 24. 67.

कनक
Kanakas  (II)--two sons of Kṛṣṇa. Vā. 96. 189.

कनकनन्दि
Kanakanandi --a sacred place (tīrtha); a bather here goes to heaven, relieved of all three Ṛṇas; east of the Muṇḍapṛṣṭa hill. Br. III. 13. 113-5; Vā. 77. 105.

कनकपर्वत
Kanakaparvata--(Mt.)  from the aṇḍa; 1) Vā. 24. 75. ten thousand yojanas in length, containing caves of red arsenic. 2) Vā. 35. 10. 

कनकपीठ
Kanakapīṭha --a son of Pulaha and Kṣamā; wife Yaśodharā and son Sahiṣṇu. Br. II. 11. 31.

कनकबिन्दु
Kanakabindu --His wife was met by Agni, and Nala was their son. Br. III. 7. 229-230.

कनकम्
Kanakam --Raudram metal, dear to Pitṛs. Br. III. 1. 60; 11. 5.

कनका
Kanakā --R. a Mahānadī, remembered by Lomaśa performing penance at the Muṇdapṛṣṭa hill; fit for performance of Śrāddha. Vā. 108. 80.

कनकाह्वय
Kanakāhvaya --ruled over Strirāṣṭra and Bhakṣyakas. Vā. 99. 387.

कनकेश्वर
Kanakeśvara --one of the forms of Brahmā in the Gaya stone. Vā. 106. 56; 111. 72.

कनकोद्भव
Kanakodbhava --a son of Hṛdika. Br. III. 71. 141; Vā. 96. 140.

कनखल
Kanakhala --a sacred place on the Ganges, where Garuḍa performed tapas. Here Śiva danced with a yoginī. Bath here leads to Rudralokam. M. 186. 10; 192. 11; 193. 69-71; Vā. 83. 21.

कनखलम्
Kanakhalam --a tīrtha in Gaya; on its right side is Dakṣiṇamānasa. Vā. 111. 7. 

कनिष्ठ
Kaniṣṭhas --one of the five deva-gaṇas of the 14th epoch of Bhautya Manu. These are the seven sāmas commencing with Bṛhat. Br. IV. 1. 106 & 108; Vā. 100. 111-2; Vi. III. 2. 43.

कनीयक
Kanīyaka --one of the ten sons of Hṛdīka. M. 44. 82.

कन्दरसेन
Kandarasena --a chief Vānara. Br. III. 7. 234.

कन्दर्प
Kandarpa --the name of the 8th kalpa M. 290. 4.

कन्दर्प
Kandarpa(vīra) --an attribute of Manmatha. Br. IV. 19. 67; 30. 54 and 85; M. 154. 250.

कन्दुकलीला
Kandukalīlā --a game with balls indulged in by girls. Mohinī played it. Bhā. VIII. 12. 18 & 23; M. 160. 4.

कन्यक
Kanyaka --a son of Maṇibhadra. Vā. 69. 154.

कन्यक
Kanyakas --Kāśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 3.

कन्यका
Kanyakā --a name of Yogamāyā. Bhā. X. 2. 12.

कन्या
Kanyā  (I)--rāśi and month Puraṭṭāśi. Vā. 105. 47. 

कन्या
Kanyā  (II)--daughter of Kardama and wife of Priyavrata; mother of two daughters and ten sons. Vi. II. 1. 5.

कन्या
Kanyā  (III)--shrine of, south of Malaya {??}ills, visited by Balarāma. Bhā. X. 79. 17.

कन्यातीर्थम्
Kanyātīrtham --on the Narmadā. M. 193. 76-7.

कन्यापुरम्
Kanyāpuram --the harem of a palace. Vi. V. 29. 31.

कपटसंग्राम
Kapaṭasaṃgrāma --the deceitful battle waged during night by Asuras; also Kūṭayuddha. Br. IV. 26. 2-10.

कपर्दवान्
Kapardavān --an attribute of Vighneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 66.

कपर्दिन्
Kapardin --a name of Śiva; 1) Br. II. 25. 68; III. 25. 12; IV. 34. 27. a Rudra. 2) M. 171. 39; Vi. I. 15. 122.

कपर्दिनी
Kapardinī  (I)--a śakti. Br. IV. 44. 60.

कपर्दिनी
Kapardinī  (II)--a mindborn mother. M. 179. 20.

कपर्दीश
Kapardīśa --a name of Śiva. Vā. 109. 23.

कपर्देय
Kapardeya --a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 10. 

कपाल
Kapāla --one of the eleven Rudras. Vā. 66. 70.

कपालम्
Kapālam --Śiva's begging bowl; shattered into 1000 pieces at Benares by Hari's grace. M. 183. 91-100.

कपालमोचन
Kapālamocana --a tīrtham sacred to śuddhi 1) M. 13. 48. of Śiva at Banaras. 2) Ib. 183. 101.

कपालि
Kapāli --a name of Śiva: a Rudra. 1) Br. II. 25. 68; III. 3. 71; 25. 8. A Bhairava god; 2) Ib. IV. 19. 79; Vi. I. 15. 123. killed Gajāsura; 3) M. 153. 19-68; 171. 39. Śiva had to become Kapāli for having destroyed the fifth face of Brahmā, but released through Hari's grace. 4) M. 183. 87-100.

कपालित्वम्
Kapālitvam --a theophany of Śiva. M. 1. 8.

कपाली
Kapālī --a mother goddess. M. 179. 16.

कपि
Kapi  (I)--Asura (?) vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. II. 7. 34.

कपि
Kapi  (II)--An Aṅgirasa and mantrakṛt; a Kṣatropetadvija; 1) Br. II. 32. 109; III. 66. 86. a Bhārgava. 2) M. 195. 33.

कपि
Kapi  (III)--had two sons Pisācas Aja and Śaṇḍa, who were Kūṣmāṇḍas in the previous birth; their line described. Br. III. 7. 74-88.

कपि
Kapi  (IV)--a god of Sukarmaṇa group. Br. IV. 1. 88. 

कपि
Kapi  (V)--a sage of the Tāmasa epoch. M. 9. 15.

कपि
Kapi  (VI)--a son of Raivata Manu. M. 9. 21.

कपि
Kapi  (VII)--a rājaṛṣi becoming a Brāhmaṇa. Vā. 91. 115.

कपि
Kapi  (VIII)--a son of Viśālā. Vā. 99. 163.

कपि
Kapi  (IX)--a son of Durukṣaya, became a Brāhmaṇa (Matsya P. speaks of three branches of Kavi Brāhmaṇas). Vi. IV. 19. 25, 26.

कपिञ्जल
Kapiñjala  (I)--a sage. M. 200. 8.

कपिञ्जल
Kapiñjala  (II)--the king of kings to the Gandharvas in the Hemakūṭa hill. Vā. 39. 52.

कपिञ्जल
Kapiñjala  (III)--a Mt.; between this hill and Nāga Śaila are many fine orchards. Vā. 38. 66-70; 42. 67.

कपिञ्जली
Kapiñjalī (Ghṛtācī) --wife of Vasisṭha, and mother of Indrapramati (Indrapratima--Vā. P.) Br. III. 8. 97; Vā. 70. 88.

कपित्थ
Kapittha --illustrative of the world which is compared to the shape of an egg. Vi. II. 7. 22. 

कपिथक
Kapithaka --a Kādraveya Nāga Br. III. 7. 36.

कपिभू
Kapibhū --a Trayārṣeya; Aṅgiras and Gārgya are Pravaras. M. 196. 48-49.

कपिमुख
Kapimukhas --Kṛṣṇa Parāśāras. M. 201. 35.

कपिल
Kapila  (I)--the fifth avatār of Hari. Born of Kardama and Devahūti. Had nine sisters. Taught the knowledge of Brahman to his mother. 1) Bhā. I. 3. 10; II. 7. 3; VIII. 1. 6; Br. III. 63. 145 and 148. A siddha. 2) Bhā. VI. 15. 13; III. 24. 16-17. Propounder of tattvas. Imparted to Āsuri the Sāṅkhya obscured by time. After Kardama left the family, Kapila lived with his mother at Bindusaras and instructed her on Sāṅkhya tattvas, tattvalakṣaṇa, the distinction of Prakṛti and Puruṣa, Aṣṭāṅga yoga, Bhakti yoga, Kāla, attachment and consequent hell, garbha and attachment to women and evils attending thereon, kāmya karma and Jñāna yoga; left his mother for north. Being worshipped by Samudra (sea) with arghya and residence, he devoted his mind to yoga. 3) Ib. III. chapters 24-33; Br. IV. 40. 66; M. 3. 29; 102. 18; 171. 4 and 19. Knew Vāsudeva's glory but could not comprehend His māyā. 4) Bhā. I. 9. 19; IX. 4. 57. Served as calf for Vidyadharas to milk siddhi and vidyā. 5) Ib. IV. 18. 19. Attended Pṛthu's sacrifice. 6) Ib. IV. 19. 6. Prācīnabarhis who retired from kingly duties came to his hermitage to perform tapas. 7) Ib. IV. 29. 81. One of the twelve who knew the dharma ordained by Hari. 8) Ib. VI. 3. 20; 8. 16. A sage who went about the world imparting knowledge; 9) Ib. VI. 15. 13. would find no fault with Hara's violation of dharma. 10) Ib. VI. 17. 12. King Rahūgaṇa went to visit him. 11) Ib. V. 10. 1 and 16. Near by his āśrama was the consecrated horse of Sagara. The 60,000 Sāgaras who searched for it imputed the theft to the sage and attacked him, who in wrath burnt them down. Met by Amśumān, he gave back the horse and said that the Sāgaras would get redemption by the Ganges waters. 12) Ib. IX. 8. 10-29; XI. 16. 15; Br. III. 15. 15-43; 53. 17-52; chap. 54; Vi. IV. 4. 12-28. The  four who were not victims to the sage's curse were Barhiketu, Saketu, Dharmarata, and Pañcavana. 13) Vā. 88. 147-53.

