continued their yoga practice. These yogins would start the course of Varṇāśrama dharma again at the end of Kali; 3) IX. 12. 6; 22. 17; XII. 2. 37-38; Br. I. 1. 164; III. 63. 210; 66. 7; M. 121. 49; 273. 56. watered by the Ganges. 4) Br. II. 18. 50. Devāpi and Manu originate Kṣatriya clans in Kṛta yuga at; the race of Manu responsible for rulers throughout the three ages, Kṛta, Tretā and Dvāpara. 5) Vā. 88. 210: 91. 7: 99. 437; Vi. IV. 24. 118-121. Manu stands rooted to yoga at. 6) Vi. IV. 4. 109. 

कलि
Kali  (I)--born of Krodha and Hīmsā. Married Durukti who gave birth to Bhaya and Mṛtyu. 1) Bhā. IV. 8. 3. Personified as king but Śūdra by birth, kicking a cow and bull. Vanquished by Parīkṣit. Kali fell at his feet when Parīkṣit asked him to leave Brahmāvarta. Asked for a place to reside, Parīkṣit appointed him to five unrighteous spheres--wine, dice, gold, women and slaughter. Father of adharma, heroic in the midst of children and cowardly before the valiant. 2) Ib. I. 16. 4; 17. 29-40; 18. 6-8. His rule in yugāntara described. 3) Ib. II. 7. 38.

कलि
Kali  (II)--a Mauneya Gandharva; a son of Brahmadhana. Br. III. 7. 4; Vā. 69. 3, 133.

कलि
Kali  (III)--a son of Varuṇa and Śunādevī (SāmudriVā. P.); father of Jaya and Vijaya; one wife of Kali, Surā, mother of Mada; other wives, Tvāṣṭri, Himsā and Nikṛti; other sons of Kali, all cannibals, Nāka, Vighna, Śadrama and Vidhama. Br. III. 59. 6; Vā. 84. 6-10.

कलि
Kali  (IV)--a door-keeper of Mahākāla. Br. IV. 32. 18.

