Kaliṅga  (I)--a Kṣetraja son of Bali; after him came Kaliṅgas (s.v.); 1) Br. III. 74. 28 & 87; M. 48. 25; Vā. 99. 28; Vi. IV. 18. 13-14. a Rākṣasa in the Atalam. (TatvalamBr. P.). 2) Vā. 50. 17; Br. II. 19. 18.

कलिङ्ग
Kaliṅga  (II)--(Mt.) a hill on the south of the Mānasa. Vā. 36. 22; 42. 28.

कलिङ्ग
Kaliṅga  (III)--a southern kingdom of madhyadeśa unfit for śrāddha; a Janapada of the Dakṣiṇāpatha. Its king was stationed by Jarāsandha on the east gate of Mathurā, and on the same direction during the siege of Gomanta; 1) Br. II. 16. 42 & 57; III. 13. 13; 14. 33 & 80; 74. 198 & 213; M. 163. 72; Vā. 77. 13; 78. 23; 99. 324, 386, 402. present at  Pradyumna's marriage. Advised Rukmin to vanquish Balarāma in dice, and laughed at the latter when he was defeated. His teeth were broken by Rāma. 2) Bhā. X. 50. 11[2]; 52. 11[5]; 61. 27-29; 32[1]
& 37; IV. 5. 21; Vi. V. 28. 10, 15, 24. Its 32 kings. 3) M. 272. 16. On its south flows the Narmadā where the hill Amarakaṇṭaka is. 4) M. 186. 12. In the Kṛtayuga, the first man appeared in this country 5) Vā. 58. 110. under Guhas. 6) Vi. III. 7. 36.

कलिङ्ग
Kaliṅgas --a tribe born of Dīrghatamas and Bali's wife; enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus; 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 5; X. [50 (V) 3]; M. 114. 36 and 47; Vā. 45. 125. people of the Dakṣiṇāpatha. 2) Vā. 45. 125; Vi. II. 3. 16.

कालिन्दी
Kālindī --the daughter of Samjñā. Vā. 84. 36.

कलियुग
Kaliyuga --the features of the yuga, and its discontents. Removed by hearing the story of Kṛṣṇa, as the Ṛṣis did in the Naimiṣa forest. The source of unrighteousness. 1) Bhā. I. 1. 10, 16 & 21; 12. 26; 15. 36-7; XI. 5. 20, 31-42; Vā. 58. 30-73. Form of Hari worshipped in. 2) M. 142. 17-27; 273. 49; Vā. 99. 429. Reflections on the conduct of castes and observance of dharma by persons. Kali becomes Kṛta after the avatār of Kalki. When the Saptaṛṣis traverse Maghas, and on the day when Kṛṣṇa left the earth for Heaven then began Kali of 1200 divine years. Grows in strength commencing with Nanda. The actual beginning was when Kṛṣṇa left for Vaikuṇṭha; a description of the yuga. Worship of Hari by Kīrtana. 3) Bhā. XII. chap. 2 & 3. Its advent was recognised by Mucukunda from the smallness of the men, plants, trees, etc., which he saw after he woke up from his long sleep. 4) Ib. X. 52. 2. Deterioration of Vedic dharma and rise of Pākhaṇḍas. Incarnation of Pramati in the form of a horse who puts down all heretics and the unrighteous. 5) Br. II. 29. 23-34; 31. 5-102; III. 14. 46. 74. 207-241; M. 144. 30-88. Predominance of here tics and Śūdras in; 6) Vā. 78. 36. 106,000 or 360,000-duration of; its sandhyāmśa 1,000 years. 7) Vā. 32. 63; 99. 264; 102. 4. M. 273. 27-33, 45. 50. Noted for theft; see Tṛṣyam; 8) Br. II. 7. 59. dānam the chief act and tamas the chief quality. 9) Vā. 8. 66. description of the evils of: bad rule and decay of civilization and morality; age of man 23 years; began with Parīkṣit when the two first stars of seven Ṛṣis were in Magha; its duration according to the calculation of men 360,800. Then comes Kṛta. 10) Vi. IV. 24. 71-96, 97, 109. 114-15.

कलिल
Kalila --son of Soma. Br. III. 3. 23; Vā. 66. 23.

कलिवन
Kalivana --a western kingdom. Br. II. 16. 60.

कलिस्पर्श
Kalisparśas --a degraded Kṣatriya community. Br. III. 63. 140.

कलोपनत
Kalopanata --Music; Māruta, the presiding deity. Vā. 86. 52.

कल्कि
Kalki --the 21st (10th Vā.) avatār of Hari, in Kaliyuga and emperor of the world by name Pārāśraya with Yājñavalkya as Purohita. Born of a Brāhmaṇa Viṣṇuyaśas in Śambalagrāma. His horse would be known as Devadatta. Riding on it, Kalki would rid the earth of the unrighteous and implant dharma again. 1) Bhā. I. 3. 25; XII. 2. 18-23; M. 273. 27; 285. 7; Vi. IV. 24. 98-101. Invoked; 2) Bhā. VI. 8. 19. destroyer of Kṣatriyas who became mlecchas by character. 3) Ib. X. 40. 22. State of the world then. 4) Vā. 99. 390-411; 424-29. According to the Br. Purāṇa, his name is Viṣnuyāśas, and son of Parāśara: the tenth incarnation of Hari, with Purohita Yājñavalkya. After rooting out  adharma with Brāhmaṇa warriors he gives up his ghost at the confluence of the Gaṅgā and the Yamunā; in the previous birth was Pramiti; would bring round all tribes and wander the world unseen; except vegetation; his life of 25 years' duration and of Parāśara gotra; then again adharma, disease, etc., at the end of Kali and commencement of the Kṛta yuga. 5) Br. III. 73. 104-24; 74. 206; IV. 29. 133; M. 47. 248-62; Vā. 98. 104-17. Purify the Śūdras, cross the ocean and destroy sinners. Then will follow civil strife and the disorder of the world. 6) M. 54. 19.

कल्किवाहन
Kalkivāhana --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 79.

कल्प
Kalpa  (I)--a son of Dhruva and Bhramī. Bhā. IV. 10. 1.

कल्प
Kalpa  (II)--a nephew of Hiraṇyakaśipu. M. 6. 26.

कल्प
Kalpa  (III)--the period of fourteen Manus or 1000 yugas followed by pralaya; 1) Bhā. II. 8. 12; IV. 9. 14; XII. 4. 2-3; Br. IV. 1. 116, 173 and 210; Vi. III. 2. 50-2; VI. 3. 12. in the day Brahmā; in the night Nārāyaṇa sleeping over his couch Śeṣa the thirty kalpas and the thirty days of Brahmā. These are mixed, Tāmasa, rājasa and sātvika 2) M. 290. 1-16. from klipu, to introduce with intelligence; the fourteen samsthas Brahmā introduced and hence kalpa; 3) Vā. 7. 77; 21. 28ff. twenty-eight in number, each of two kalpārdhas; 4) Vā. 21. 17-18; 22. 7; 30. 231: 59. 138; 61. 54 and 102. the 14 kalpas made by Brahmā and hence the name. 5) Br. II. 6. 74.

