कारुकर्म
Kārukarma --the svadarma of Śūdras. Vi. VI. 1. 36.

कारुकायण
Kārukāyaṇas --Trayārṣeyas. M. 198. 7. 

कारूष
Kārūṣa --a surname of Vṛddhaśarman, son of Karūṣa, (who married Śrutadevā). Bhā. IX. 24. 36.

कारूषा
Kārūṣās --descendants of Karūṣa, the son of Vaivasvata Manu 1) Bhā. IX. 2. 16; Br. III. 61. 2; M. 12. 24; 114. 48; Vi. IV. 1. 18. and, kings of Uttarāpatha; a Kṣatriya clan, the country of. 2) Vi. II. 3. 17; IV. 14. 39.

कारोटक
Kāroṭaka --Ārṣeya Pravara of Aṅgiras. M. 196. 8.

कार्कोटक
Kārkoṭaka --with the sun during the month of Pauṣa. Vi. II. 10. 14.

कार्तवीर्यार्जुण
Kārtavīryārjuṇa --a prominent king of the lunar line. See Arjuna. Vi. IV. 6. 4.

कार्ता
Kārtā --a Sāmaga. Vā. 99. 191.

कार्त्तिक
Kārttika --Navami and Dvādaśī, as yugādis for śrāddha. M. 17. 4.

कार्त्तिकेय
Kārttikeya (Guha)  (I)--a god with his vāhana as peacock; conqueror of Krauñca of Asuras; also Kumāra; 1) Br. II. 25. 16; III. 10. 44; 32. 23; 41. 32; 42. 6; 43. 31. brought up by the Kṛttikas; 2) Vā. 41. 38; 72. 43; Vi. I. 15. 116. delight to the mind of Umā; 3) Vā. 54. 19. overheard the report given by his father to Pārvati on the subject of the colour of his throat, the Nīlakaṇṭha legend, when he was lying down on the lap of Umā on the top of the Kai lāsa hills. 4) Vā. 54. 28f. Took part in Bāṇa's war with Kṛṣṇa and disabled by Garuḍa and Pradyumna. 5) Vi. V. 33. 21 and 26.

कार्त्तिकेय
Kārttikeya  (II)--Kumāra, being the son of Kṛttikas; narrates the mahātmyam of Nandi in Nandīpurāṇa, 1) M. 5. 27; 53. 61. born in the full moon day of the citra month and Indra made sin into one on the fifth day and on the sixth anointed Devasenāpati. All important gods gave him some present or other and praised him. 2) Ib. 159. 4. 18. Promised to slay Tāraka and slew him. 3) Ib. 160. 10-26. Image of; 12 hands in a city, four in a Kharvaṭa and two in a village; one of the hands has a cock; others detailed. 4) Ib. 260. 19, 45-51.

कार्त्तिकेय
Kārttikeya  (III)--(Pāvaki) a sage of the Rohita epoch. Br. IV. 1. 62.

कार्त्तिकेय
Kārttikeya  (IV)--a tīrtham sacred to Yāśaskari. M. 13. 45.

कार्त्तिकेयपदम्
Kārttikeyapadam --in Gayā. Vā. 109. 19; 111. 54.

कार्त्तिवय
Kārttivaya --a Kaśyapa gotrakara. M. 199. 5.

कार्त्तिवीर्य
Kārttivīrya  (I)--a son of Kanaka. Vā. 94. 8.

कार्त्तिवीर्य
Kārttivīrya  (II)--see Arjuna. Br. III. 28. 25; 31. 3 & 5; 32. 61; 34. 3 & 30: M. 43. 15; Vi. IV. 11. 16. 

कार्दमायनि
Kārdamāyani --ārṣeya Pravara of Bhārgavas. M. 195. 34 & 43.

कार्पट
Kārpaṭas --a heretical sect. Br. III. 14. 39.

कार्पासपर्वत
Kārpāsaparvata --20 bhārams of cotton as the best gift. M. 83. 5; 88. 1-5.

कार्बूरम्
Kārbūram --the colour of the 14th Manu Sāvarṇi. Vā. 26. 46.

कार्यकारण
Kāryakāraṇa rūpiṇi --Lalitā. Br. IV. 15. 8.

कार्मुकालय
Kārmukālaya --see Dhanuśśāla. Vi. V. 20. 17.

कार्षणि
Kārṣaṇi --a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 18.

कार्षापणम्
Kārṣāpaṇam --a coin in common use; fines in terms of. M. 227. 79 & 93, 197.

कार्ष्णायन
Kārṣṇāyanas --Kṛṣṇa Parāsara. M. 201. 35.

कार्ष्णेय
Kārṣṇeyas --a Rākṣasa gaṇa. Vā. 69. 172.

काल
Kāla  (I)--time as the phase of the Universal Spirit. 1) Bhā. I. 6. 4; 11. 6; 13. 45; II. 10. 43; VIII. 17. 27. Is Īśvara, and only rūpabheda. 2) Ib. III. 12. 12; 29. 4, 37 & 45; X. 51. 19. Lord of creation and destruction; fearful to look at. 3) Ib. IV. 12. 3; Vā. 32. 11, 22. Vanquished by Kṛṣṇa; 4) Bhā. III. 3. 10; Br. III. 3. 82; Vā. 32. 29. makes and unmakes things by keeping all things under control. 5) Vi. V. 38. 55-64. 

काल
Kāla  (II)--a name for Mṛtyu: ety. as Lord of Death; adhidevata for Rāhu the planet; 1) Br. II. 36. 128; M. 93. 14; 213. 5 & 18. described as having four faces each comprising a yuga. 2) Vā. 32. 8-67. One origin of. 3) Ib. 21. 52, 73.

काल
Kāla  (III)--a son of Dhanva; a Vasava; a Viśvedeva. Br. III. 3. 23, 30; M. 5. 23; 203. 4; Vā. 66. 21, 31; Vi. I. 15. 111.

काल
Kāla  (IV)--a Bhairva god. Br. IV. 20. 82.

काल
Kāla  (V)--one from Brahman; see also Avyakta. Vi. I. 2. 14, 15 and 27.

काल
Kāla  (VI)--a Mt. west of the Sitoda lake. Vā. 36. 27.

काल
Kāla  (VII)--division of time--Paramāṇu defined: 2 Paramāṇus make 1 Aṇu 3 Aṇus make 1 Traṣareṇu 3 Trasareṇus make 1 Truti 100 Truṭis make 1 Vedhas 3 Vedhas make 1 lava 3 lavas make 1 Nimeṣa 3 Nimeṣas make 1 Kṣaṇa 5 Kṣanas make 1 Kāṣṭha 15 Kāṣṭhas make 1 laghu 15 laghus make 1 Nāḍika 2 Nāḍikas make 1 Muhūrta 6 or 7 Nāḍikas make 1 Prahara or Yāma 4 Yāmas make 1 day or night 15 days and nights make 1 Pakṣa 2 Pakṣas make 1 māsa or a day and night for Pitṛs 2 Māsas make 1 Ṛtu  6 months make 1 Ayanam 2 Ayanams make 1 year 1 day of Brahmā make 1 period of 14 Manus 1 night of Brahmā make 1 period of Pralaya 1 Yuga make 5 years. 1) Bhā. III. ch. 11 (whole); Br. II. 24. 58; 13. 109; Vā. 50. 179-82; 97. 30-31. based on Sūrya. 2) Vā. 31. 24; 53. 39.

कालक
Kālaka  (I)--s son of Vijvara. Br. III. 6. 33.

कालक
Kālaka  (II)--a son of Virakṣa. Vā. 68. 33.

कालकन्या
Kālakanyā --see Durbhagā. Bhā. IV. 27. 27.

कालका
Kālakā --a daughter of Vaiśvānara, and a wife of Kaśyapa; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 33-34; M. 6. 22. sons were Kālakeyas. 2) Vi. I. 21. 8-9.

कालक
Kālakas --kings (24) contemporaneous with Śisunāgas (10). Br. III. 74. 136; Vā. 99. 323.

कालकाम
Kālakāma --one of the ten Viśvedevas. M. 203. 13.

कालकूटम्
Kālakūṭam --poison from the churning of ocean of milk by gods and asuras; swallowed by Śiva. Br. II 25. 60; III. 25-9; IV. 23. 30; M. 250. 20-60; Vā. 54. 57-9, 63 and 95. 

कालकेय
Kālakeyas --sons of Marīci, a dānava; vanquished by Rāvaṇa and by Durgā; 1) Br. III. 7. 255; IV. 29. 76; M. 6. 23; Vi. I. 21. 9. their mother is Kālā. 2) M. 171. 59. Asuras in the Devakūṭa hill. 3) Vā. 40. 15.

कालकोशक
Kālakośakas --country of, under Maṇidhānya kings. (Cal. Edn. Kālatoya). Vi. IV. 24. 66.

कालक्रित
Kālakrita --a Veśya form of marriage. Br. IV. 15. 4.

कालख्य
Kālakhya --(antakāri) Tāmasi. Vā. 66. 90, 104.

कालचक्र
Kālacakra  (I)--a chief Vānara. Br. III. 7. 235.

कालचक्र
Kālacakra  (II)--is the solar system: relativity of its movement is illustrated by the Potter's wheel. The sun stands in relation to Kālacakra, midway between the Earth and Heaven. Placed on the right side of Meru, the twentyeight nakṣatras including Abhijit are fixed on this cakra. 1) Bhā. V. 22. 2-11; 23. 3; M. 162, 1, 19; Vi. II. 8. 4. The seat of Mahākāla. 2) Br. IV. 32. 7. 18-20.

कालजंघिका
Kā(ka)lajaṃghikā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 23.

कालजिह्वा
Kālajihvā --a śakti. Br. IV. 44. 76.

कालञ्जर
Kālañjara --Mt. on the north base of Meru. Here was born Bharata as deer; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 26; 8-30; Br. III. 13. 100; Vi. II. 2. 30. sacred to Kālī. 2) M. 13. 32. Here were reborn the seven sons of Kauśika as deer; remembering their past birth,  they practised yoga; 3) Ib. 20. 15; 21. 9 and 28. sacred to Pitṛs; 4) Ib. 22. 24; Vā. 77. 93. the best of hills where Śveta took his avatār (kālam jarayiṣyāmī). 5) Vā. 23. 204.

कालंजरस्
Kālaṃjaras --the kingdom of. M. 121. 54.

कालतोयक
Kālatoyaka --a northern kingdom; a tribe; 1) Br. II. 16. 46; III. 74. 196; M. 114. 40. a Janapada of Maṇidhānya. 2) Vā. 99. 384.

कालत्वम्
Kālatvam --Yama aspect; rajas and tamas predominate; terminates the worlds; as dark as the sky (añjana). Vā. 5. 28, 31.

कालदंष्ट्र
Kāladaṃṣṭra --an Asura who entered the ocean. M. 61. 4.

कालनर
Kālanar(l)a --(Kālānala-Vā. P.) the son of Sabhānara, and father of Sṛñjaya. Bhā. IX. 23. 1; Vā. 99. 13.

कालनाथ
Kālanātha --Śiva assuming the form of Death. Br. IV. 16. 12.

कालनाभ
Kālanābha  (I)--a son of Hiraṇyākṣa and Bhānū. A nephew of Hiraṇyakaśipu. Took an active part in the Devāsura battle between Bali and Indra. Fought with Yama. A follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra. 1) Bhā. VII. 2. 18; Vā. 67. 67; M. 6. 27; Br. III. 5. 30; Bhā. VIII. 10. 20 and 29; VI. 10. [20]. Vi. I. 21. 3. A Saṃhikeya asura. 2) Br. III. 6. 20; Vā. 68. 19.

कालनाभ
Kālanābha  (II)--a son of Vipracitti. Vi. I. 21. 12. 

कालनेमी
Kālanemī --a son of Virocana and father of four sons. Kaṃsā's previous birth as Kālanemī sent his śūla towards Hari who vanquished him with the same implement; 2) Bhā. X. 1. 68; VIII. 10. 56; X. 51. 42; Vi. V. 1. 22, 23, 65. residing in Atalam (IV tala or abhastalam). 3) Br. II. 20. 32; Vā. 50. 31. Killed by Hari in Tārakāmaya, where he was a commander; rode on a chariot of elephants, used illusory powers and brahmāstram in the war; devas as prisoners of war but released by Tāraka; attacked Hari and fell dead slain by his cakra. 4) Br. III. 72. 21; M. 148. 42-51; 150. 140-189; 154. 3; 160. 3 & 18; 176. 49; chaps. 177-78; Vā. 97. 22. ^1 Vā. 67. 76; 80; Br. III. 5. 39.

कालपर्णी
Kālaparṇī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 22.

कालभवन
Kālabhavana --an Yakṣa gaṇa. Vā. 69. 40.

कालमही
Kālamahī --R. M. 163. 64.

कालमूर्ति
Kālamūrti --a chief Vānara. Br. III. 7. 233.

कालमृत्यु
Kālamṛtyu --a servant of Mahākāla. Br. IV. 32. 5.

कालयवन
Kālayavana --the son of Yavaneśvara, black in colour and hard-hearted; after crowning him king, his father retired to the woods; full of prowess he asked Nārada of some powerful heroes and being told about Yādavas he directed himself towards them with a big army of Mlecchas; Kṛṣṇa met him unarmed and was pursued; seeing him entering a cave where Mucukunda was sleeping, Kāla entered and thinking Mucukunda to be Kṛṣṇa kicked him; on Mucukunda waking up and looking at Kālanemi he was  burnt to ashes as there was a vow that he who would awake Mucukunda would meet with such an end. Bhā. X. 50. 44-9; 51. 1-12; Vi. V. 23. 5-8 and 17-23.

कालचक्षु
Kālacakṣu --a son of Anu. Br. III. 74. 13.

कालरात्री
Kālarātrī --a Varṇa Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 60.

कालवन्दि
Kālavandi (c) --a kingdom noted for horses. Br. IV. 16. 17.

कालवाषित
Kālavāṣita --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 77.

कालवीर्य
Kālavīrya --a nephew of Hiraṇyakaśipu. M. 6. 28.

कालशम्बर
Kālaśambara --Killed by Pradyumna (see also Sambara). Vi. V. 27. 3 and 20.

कालशीख
Kālaśīkha --a sage. M. 200. 8.

कालसंकर्षणी
Kālasaṃkarṣaṇī --a goddess from the back part of Nṛsimha: a follower of Vāgīśī. M. 179. 68.

कालसर्पि
Kālasarpi (Kaśyapatīrtha) --a sacred tīrtham dear to Kaśyapa, fit for śrāddha and noted for devadāruvanam. Br. III. 13. 98-9; Vā. 77. 87. 

कालसूत्र
Kālasūtra --one of the twenty-eight hells. Those who treacherously behave towards Pitṛs, Brāhmaṇas, etc., are sent to this; 1) Bhā. V. 26. 7 & 14; Vā. 110. 42; Vi. I. 6. 41; II. 6. 4. a hell under the earth: also mahāhī 2) Br. IV. 2. 181, 184; 33. 60. the third hell under the earth: also known as mahāhavividhi; haunted by a fierce serpent. 3) Vā. 101. 178.

काला
Kālā  (I)--a goddess enshrined at Candrabhāgā. M. 13. 49.

काला
Kālā  (II)--a daughter of Dakṣa, and wife of Kaśyapa. 1) M. 171. 29; Vā. 66. 54. Mother of Kālakeyas. 2) M. 171. 59.

कालात्मा
Kālātmā--Yugābhimāni;  Rudra. Vā. 31. 55; 66. 125.

कालानल
Kālānala  (I)--a son of Sabhānara and a Paṇḍita; and father of Sṛñjaya. Br. III. 74. 13; Vi. IV. 18. 2-3.

कालानल
Kālānala  (II)--see Samvartāgni. Br. II. 25. 45 & 56.

कालाम्र
Kālāmra --a tree of Bhadrāśva, the juice of its fruit protects the youthfulness of women; 1) Br. II. 15. 58 & 61. in the Sālavanam; the juice of which makes the drinker young. 2) Vā. 43. 6.

कालायनि
Kālāyani --a pupil of Bāṣkala. Vi. III. 4. 25.

कालायसशाला
Kālāyasaśālā --the first prākāra of Śripuram. Br. IV. 31. 34. 50. 

कालावस्थ
Kālāvasthas --six according to months, aho-rātra, ṛtus, ayanas, and years; also nimeṣa, kalā, kāṣṭhā, muhūrta and dinakṣapa; 1) Vā. 30. 10-14. fivefold, day, half-month, month, ṛṭu and ayanam. 2) Ib. 31. 26.

कालि
Kāli --a manneya. Vā. 69. 2.

कालिक
Kālika  (I)--a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 51; Vā. 61. 44.

कालिक
Kālika  (II)--a son of Maya. Br. III. 6. 29.

कालिका
Kālikā  (I)--a śakti. Br. IV. 44. 86.

कालिका
Kālikā  (II)--R. sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22-36.

कलिका
Kali(a)kā  (III)--a daughter of Vaiśvānara; after her came the Kālakeya asuras. Br. III. 6. 23-5; Vā. 68. 23.

कालीक
Kālīkas --the kingdom of. M. 121. 45.

कालिंग
Kāliṃga --the king of, present at the marriage of Anīruddha and advised Rukmin to invite Rāma for dice. Laughed aloud when Rāma failed, and supported Rukmin playing falsely. His teeth pulled out by Rāma. Bhā. X. 61. 27-37.

कालिंगक
Kāliṃgaka --a Brāhmaṇa friend of Bhīṣma hailing from Kalinga; narrated to Bhīṣma ways by which to be free from Yama's subjection. Vi. III. 7-38. 

कालिञ्जरवनम्
Kāliñjaravanam --sacred to Śiva. M. 181. 27.

कालितक
Kālitakas --of the S. country. Vā. 45. 128.

कालिन्
Kālin --a son of Caidyoparicara. M. 50. 28.

कालिन्द
Kālinda --a kinnara gaṇa; horse-faced. Vā. 69. 32.

कालिन्दी
Kālindī  (I)--the daughter of the sun god; wandering in the forest in quest of Kṛṣṇa, she expressed herself to Arjuna who was there with Kṛṣṇa; the latter married her; welcomed by Draupadī to Hāstinapura, she narrated to her how she married Kṛṣṇa. 1) Bhā. X. 58. 17-23, 29; 71. 43; 83. 11; M. 47. 14. Devī and wife of Kṛṣṇa; mother of Śruta and other sons. 2) Vā. 96. 234; Vi. V. 28. 3; 32. 4.

कालिन्दी
Kālindī  (II)--a R. of the Ketumāla country. Vā. 44. 21.

कालिन्दी
Kālindī  (III)--a name for Yamunā. Vi. V. 7. 2; 18. 34; VI. 8. 36.

कालिय
Kāliya  (I)--a chief of the Krodhavaśa group of serpents. Got into a pool of the Yamunā, causing the death of people who drank of the waters. Kṛṣṇa subjugated it and ordered it to go to the sea, thus making the waters drinkable. He assured Kālīya of freedom from Garuḍa's hostility. Son of Kadru, Kāliya originally lived in Ramaṇaka, and refused to give Bali to Garuḍa according to an agreement with him. In the fight that ensued, Kāliya was vanquished, and he resorted to the Kālindi pool where Garuḍa could not come. But he was expelled by Kṛṣṇa. 1) Bhā. V. 24. 29; X. ch. 16 (whole); 17. 1-12; X. 43. 26. In the Atalam region; 2) Vā. 50. 18; 69. 72. in Talvalam ? 3) Br. II. 20. 19; M. 163. 56. 

कालिय
Kāliya  (II)--a dānava king. Br. IV. 29. 124.

कालिय
Kāliyas --the serpents of Mahātalam. Bhā. V. 24. 29.

काली
Kālī  (I)--one of the wives of Bhīmasena, and mother of Sarvagata. Bhā. IX. 22. 31.

काली
Kālī  (II)--a mother goddess, and a varṇa śakti; 1) Br. IV. 7. 72; 44. 59 & 76. a goddess enshrined at Kālanjara; took part in the Tārakāmaya and enveloped the whole in darkness. 2) M. 13. 32; 172. 19.

काली
Kālī  (III)--a doorkeeper of Mahākāla. Br. IV. 32. 18.

काली
Kālī  (IV)--the Dāśeyī brought forth Vicitravīrya by Śantanu. M. 50. 45.

काली
Kālī  (V)--a mind-born mother; 1) M. 179. 14. from the bones of Nṛsimha. 2) Ib. 179. 26, 64.

काली
Kālī  (VI)--the wife of Parāśara and mother of Kṛṣṇadvaipāyana. Vā. 70. 84.

कालि
Kāli  (VII)--R. a sacred river. M. 22. 20.

कालीयनाग
Kālīyanāga --the venomous serpent in a pool of Yamunā; Kṛṣṇa dived into it and was about to kill him when on an appeal from the wives of Nāga and the Nāga  himself to do as he bade he set them free and sent them to the sea to live there for ever. See Kāliya. Vi. V. 7. 3 to the end; 13. 4.

कालेय
Kāleya --an Asura who was exhausted in Amṛtamanthana. Bhā. VIII. 7. 14.

कालेय
Kāleya --an Ātreya, Putrikā putra. M. 197. 9.

कालेय
Kāleyas --Dānavas and Nāgas in Rasātala. These took part in Devāsura war between Bali and Indra. They fought with Vasus. Bhā. V. 24. 30; VIII. 10. 22 and 34.

कालेश्वर
Kāleśvara --famous for Lalitā piṭha: a tīrtham on the Narmadā. Br. IV. 44. 97; M. 191. 85.

कालोदर
Kālodara (c) --an eastern kingdom watered by Hlādinī; 1) Br. II. 18. 55. peoples of. 2) Vā. 47. 52.

काल्या
Kālyā --a wife of Parāśara, and mother of Kṛsṇa dvaipāyana. Br. III. 8. 92.

कावेरी
Kāverī  (I)--R. personified as one of the wives of Havyavāhana (Śamsya) fire; Sangamam in the Narmadā, where Kubera attained siddhi by penance to Śiva. Its greatness described. Br. II. 12. 14; M. 51. 13; 163. 61; 189. 2-20; Vā. 29. 130. 

कावेरी
Kāverī  (II)--the grand-daughter of Yuvanāśva and wife of Janhu; mother of Suhotra. (Sunaha-Br. P.); made of one half of Gangā. Br. III. 66. 28-30; Vā. 91. 58.

कावेरी
Kāverī  (III)--a R. of the Bhadra country. Vā. 43. 26.

कावेरी
Kāverī  (IV)--R. a mahānadi (Vā. P.) in Bhāratavarṣa; 1) Vā. 108. 79. takes its source in the Sahya (Ṛṣyavat) hills noted for Vainana elephants in Drāviḍa deśa (Dakṣiṇa deśa); 2) Bhā. V. 19. 18; VII. 13. 12; XI. 5. 40; Br. II. 16. 35; III. 7. 357; Vā. 45. 104; 77. 28. visited by Balarāma; 3) Bhā. X. 79. 14; M. 114. 23. fit for śrāddha offerings, and sacred to Pitṛs. 4) Br. III. 13. 28; M. 22. 27.

काव्य
Kāvya  (I)--a son of Bhṛgu and Divyā; also Śukra, Uśana, the Ācārya for devas and asuras; Kavisuta and the name of a planet; wife Gonāma, had four sons, Tvaṣṭa, Varūtrī, Śaṇḍa, and Marka; 1) Br. III. 1. 76; 68. 86; 72. 95; 73. 1, 37. Vā. 59. 90; 62. 41; 65. 74-7. the lord of Bhṛgus; 2) Vi. 70. 4. cursed Yayāti. 3) Vi. IV. 10. 7. Asuras defeated by Indra appealed to Kāvya and resolved to go to Rasātala; Kāvya encouraged them and said that rains, vegetation, etc., would stand completely with them and only (1/4) with the devas; at that time the devas appealed to him for help; but Kāvya went to Mahādeva and learnt the mantra for their success; in the meantime he asked them to keep quiet and perform austerities after laying their weapons down. Mahādeva insisted on Kuṇḍadhūma observance for a thousand years with their heads down; while so engaged the asuras got afraid of the devas and appealed to his mother and the wife of Bhṛgu; she offered them shelter but finding them being killed by the devas she resolved to deprive Indra of his place; then Indra appealed to Viṣṇu whose body he entered; but she set on  fire the whole world of devas, when out of rage Viṣṇu killed her; Bhṛgu cursed him to be born seven times among men; then by power of tapas he restored his wife to life; Śukra's religious observance so as to please him; penance over, Maheśvara granted him three things: non-defeat by others, lordship over wealth, and eternal life; on this he praised Nīlalohita by many names; pleased, Śiva disappeared; then Śukra was attracted towards Jayantī the daughter of Indra and promised to be with her for ten years unknown to the asuras by means of māyā; when Kāvya returned the asuras were pleased; but during the ten years Bṛhaspati appeared before the asuras in the guise of Kāvya and pretended to speak to them the mantra he had heard; the asuras accepted him; ten years were over and a daughter Devayāni was born to Śukra who appeared before the asuras; finding two Kāvyas the asuras became mystified and Kāvya said that he was Bṛhaspati in disguise; the asuras did not believe in the real Śukra who left them in anger; soon they found out the mistake and approached Śukra through Prahlāda and he became pleased; then he approached Brahmā who said that after ten yugas and in the Svārociṣa Yuga the asuras would get back their kingdom; saying this he pointed out to two disciples Saṇḍa and Marka equal to Bṛhaspati, and at last the devas were defeated. Seeing the success of the asuras Viṣnu took different avatars to put them down. 4) Vā. 97. 94 to end and ch. 98; Br. III, 72. 96 to the end; 73. 1-64.

काव्य
Kāvya  (II)--an Aṅgirasa, and one of the seven sages of Tāmasa Manu; 1) Br. II. 32. 98 and 104; 33. 7; 36. 47. a mantrakṛt. 2) Vā. 59. 96.

काव्य
Kāvya  (III)--a son of Senājit. M. 49. 50; Vā. 99. 173.

काव्य
Kāvya  (IV)--a son of Bharatāgni. Vā. 29. 8. 

काव्य
Kāvyas --a group of Pitṛs who drink Soma's Svadhā. Their mind-born daughter is Yogotpatti; other names are Samvatsaras, Pañcābdas, Ājyapas, being presiding deities of Aṣtakas and others. They drink ghee. Br. II. 23. 39 and 73-5; 28. 4, 23 and 70; III. 10. 85; M. 141. 4-16; Vā. 56. 13, 16.

काश
Kāśa --a son of Śunahotra (Sutahotra-Vā. P.) (Suhotra-Vi. P.). Br. III. 67. 4; Vā. 92. 3; Vi. IV. 8. 5.

काशय
Kāśaya --the kingdom of Kāśa. Vā. 92. 6.

काश
Kāśas --a kind of grass (saccarum spontanerum) best for śrāddha purposes; significance of. Vā. 75. 41.

काशि
Kāśi --son of Kāśya and father of Rāṣṭra. Bhā. IX. 17. 4.

काशिका
Kāśikā --R. from Śuktimanta. M. 114. 32.

काशिप
Kāśipa --a son of Kāśya. Br. III. 67. 7.

काशिराज
Kāśirāja --the kingdom of, got rain by the presence of Śvaphalka; daughter of (Gāndinī) married to Śvaphalka; 1) Vā. 96. 103-5; Vi. IV. 13. 116. a daughter Jayanti married to Vṛṣabha. 2) M. 45. 26.

काशी
Kāśī  (I) (c)--a kingdom of Madhyadeśa; 1) Br. II. 16. 41; 18. 51; III. 74. 213 and 268. a tribe; 2) M. 114. 35; 163. 67; 273. 73. a Janapada 3) Vā. 45. 110; 47. 48. enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus. 4) Bhā. X. [50 (V) 3]. 

कासी
Kāsī  (II)--capital of Pauṇḍraka invaded by Kṛṣṇa; Pauṇḍraka on the S. of the Gomanta hill during the siege by Jarāsandha. 1) Bhā. X. 66. [12], 10; 52. 11 [9]. The abhicāra Agni sent by Sudakṣiṇa returned and killed Sudakṣiṇa himself, while Viṣṇu's Cakra burnt down the whole city. 2) Ib. X. 66. 30-42; 37. 19. Its king went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse having heard that Kṛṣṇa was there. 3) Ib. X. 82. 25. When the kingdom had no rains, its king gave his daughter Gāndinī to Śvaphalka, and this resulted in plenty of showers. 4) Ib. X. 57. 32. Br. III. 71. 104. Likened to Bhāgavata Purāṇa in its importance. 5) Bhā. XII. 13. 17. Sages of, visited Dvārakā. 6) Ib. X. 90. 28 [3]. Residence of Kāmākṣī 7) Br. IV. 37. 15; 40. 15 and 80, 91. the capital of Kuśadhvaja; 8) Vā. 81. 18; 99. 402. in the brows of the Veda. 9) Ib. 104. 75.

काशी
Kāśī  (III)--the mother of Sarvaga (Sarvavṛka-Vā. P.) by Bhīmasena. M. 50. 54; Vā. 99. 247; Vi. IV. 20. 46.

काशीपति
Kāśīpati --a Dānava king. Br. IV. 29. 122.

कासीपति
Kāsīpati --see (Kāśirāja): king of Kāsi who went to aid Pauṇḍraka against Kṛṣṇa and who was so struck that his head shot into the city; his son together with the priest prayed to Śiva to avenge his father's murder; Śiva granted the boon and sent a female created from fire to destroy Kṛṣṇa whose discus was more than a metal; the dead ran to Kāśi followed by the discus which burnt the whole city. Vi. V. 34. 14-43.

काशेय
Kāśeya --the son of Kāśa; king of Kāsī; father of Rāṣṭra. Vi. IV. 8. 7.

काशेय
Kāśeyas --a ruling dynasty of 24 rulers. M. 272. 15. 

काश्मा
Kāśmā --father of Supārśva. Vā. 96. 252.

काश्मीर
Kāśmīra (maṇḍala) --became the possession of Vrātyas and Mlecchas; 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 39; Vi. IV. 24. 69. a kingdom of the West watered by the Sindhu. 2) Br. II. 16. 51. 18. 47; III. 74. 213. A tīrtham sacred to Medhā. 3) M. 13. 47.

काश्मीर
Kāśmīras --a tribe. Vā. 45. 120.

काश्य
Kāśya  (I)--a son of Suhotra, and father of Kāśī. Bhā. IX. 17. 3-4.

काश्य
Kāśya  (II)--a son of Senājit. Bhā. IX. 21. 23; Vi. IV. 19. 36.

काश्य
Kāśya  (III)--a Kṣatriya who became a dvija. Br. III. 66. 87.

काश्यदुहिता
Kāśyaduhitā --a daughter of Kāśya, and wife of Āhuka; mother of Devaka and Ugrasena. M. 44. 70-1.

काश्यप
Kāśyapa  (I)--a Samhitā-kartā: officiated as adhvaryu at Paraśurāma's sacrifice and got the whole earth as fee; 1) Br. II. 35. 63 and 66; III. 8. 86; 47. 47 and 60; IV. 9. 3. a mantrakṛt and a Brahmavādin. 2) M. 145. 98 and 106; Vā. 59. 102.

काश्यप
Kāśyapa  (II)--a sage of Sāvarṇi epoch; a pravara. M. 9. 32: 199. 16.

काश्यप
Kāśyapa  (III)--a son of Vāli, the avatar of the lord. Vā. 23. 160. 

काश्यप
Kāśyapa  (IV)--a son of Gokarṇa, the avatār of the 16th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 173.

काश्यप
Kāśyapa  (V)--(Kāśyapa Haviṣmān); a son of Bhautya Manu; 1) Vā. 100. 107, 116; 106. 34. of Vatsa gotra; 2) Ib. 62. 16; 64. 28. a pupil of Sūta; 3) Ib. 61. 55. had three Ādityas as wives, and out of kāma for Devakī took human birth as Kṛṣṇa; 4) Ib. 96. 230. one of the seven sages; a tapasvī. 5) Ib. 100. 82. 100. 96.

काश्यप
Kāśyapa  (VI)--(see Kaśyapa) married thirteen daughters of Dakṣa; 1) Vi. I. 15. 77 and 103. blessed Ditī with a son capable of vanquishing Indra; 2) Ib. I. 21. 30-2. a householder to perform rites in honour of him; 3) Ib. III. 1. 32; 11. 43. resides in the sun's chariot in the month of Mārgaśīrṣa. 4) Ib. II. 10. 13.

काश्यप
Kāśyapa  (VII)--a son of Suhotra. Vi. IV. 8. 5.

काश्यप
Kāśyapa  (VIII)--a son of Parvasa. Vā. 28. 13.

काश्यप
Kāśyapas (Kāśapas) --the lines of kings commencing with Sannuhotra Kāśa, ruled at Kāśī. Six of them were Brahmavādins. Among them were Brāhmaṇas and Kṣatriyas whose sons were righteous, powerful and strong. Br. II. 32. 112; III. 67. 79; Vā. 92. 74.

काश्यपतीर्थम्
Kāśyapatīrtham --(Kālasarpi): fit for śrāddha. Vā. 77. 87. 

काश्यपि
Kāśyapi --Ārṣeya pravara of the Bhārgavas. M. 195. 37.

काश्यपेय
Kāśyapeya --one of the sages who heard the first part (sarga) of the Purāṇa asked Sūta to speak on Pratisandhi; 1) Vā. 7. 1. a gotrakara. 2) M. 199. 9.

काश्या
Kāśyā --a daughter of Supārśva and wife of Sāmba; had five sons. M. 47. 24.

काषाय
Kāṣāyas --pseudo-ascetics. Br. III. 15. 62; Vā. 79. 90.

काष्ठ
Kāṣṭha --a measurement of length and capacity; Yayāti versed in; 1) M. 34. 9; 142. 4. the intervening distance between two kāṣṭhas and the distance between kāṣṭha and lekha, north to south; both the outer and inner circumference in Dakṣiṇāyana and Uttarāyaṇa 2) Vā. 1. 93; 50. 127, 132 and 133. thirty form a kala. 3) Vā. 30. 13; Vi. I. 3. 8; II. 8. 59; VI. 3. 6. Time equal to 15 nimeṣas. 4) Br. II. 7. 19; 13. 16; Vā. 50. 169; 57. 6; 70. 15; 93. 72; 100. 214; Vi. I. 3. 8.

काष्ठा
Kāṣṭhā --one of the Kaśyapa's wives, and mother of quadrupeds with cloven hoofs; a mother goddess. Bhā. VI. 6. 25 and 29; Br. III. 3. 56; IV. 32. 14.

काष्ठाहारिण
Kāṣṭhāhāriṇa --Kaśyapa gotrakaras. M. 199. 9.

कासार
Kāsāra --a pupil of Bāṣkali. Bhā. XII. 6. 59. 

काहल
Kāhala --in Rama's abhiṣeka. Vi. IV. 4. 100.

किंकण
Kiṃkaṇa --a son of Bāhyaka. Br. III. 71. 4.

किङ्किण
Kiṅkiṇa --a son of Bhajamāna. Bhā. IX. 24. 7.

किन्देव
Kindevas --a class of divinities. Bhā. XI. 14. 6.

किन्नर
Kinnara --the son of Sunakṣatra, and father of Antarikṣa. Vā. 99. 285; IV. 22. 4-5.

किन्नर
Kinnaras  (I)--a group of divine singers. 1) Bhā. II. 10. 38. Born of Brahmā's shadow; these frequent Kailāsa; 2) Ib. III. 20. 45; IV. 6. 9; Br. II. 25. 28; III. 7. 176; 8. 71. celebrate Puruṣa, Indra and Hari. 3) Bhā. IV. 30. 6; VI. 7. 4; VII. 8. 38; X. 3. 6; 4. 11. Went to Dvārakā to see Kṛṣṇa, 4) Ib. XI. 6. 3. and learnt the dharma from the seven sages; 5) Ib. XI. 14. 6; 31-2. worship Pitṛs. 6) Br. III. 10. 38 and 111; 22. 59; 37. 19; IV. 20. 49; 33. 27; 39. 56.

किन्नर
Kinnaras  (II)--Born of Ariṣṭā and Kaśyapa: Citraratha is their overlord. Live in Himālayas; help Indra; kingdom of. M. 6. 45; 8. 6; 13. 16; 23. 39; 117. 8; 121. 48; 148. 92.

किन्नर
Kinnaras  (III)--sons of Aśvamukhas; had a number of gaṇas, horse-faced and human-faced; famous for dancing and music; 1) Vā. 69. 31. 36-7. servants in Śivapura; 2) Ib. 101. 252. live in the Mahānīla hill; 3) Ib. 9. 56; 38. 5; 39. 32; 47. 47. hundred cities of, in Kailāsa. 4) Ib. 46. 41. 

किन्नराश्व
Kinnarāśva --a son of Sunakṣatra. M. 271. 8.

किम्पुरुष
Kimpuruṣa  (I)--a son of Āgnihotra and Pūrvacitti, and Lord of Hemakūṭa. Bhā. V. 2. 19; Br. II. 14. 45 and 48; Vā. 33. 38, 41; Vi. II. 1. 16 and 19.

किम्पुरुष
Kimpuruṣa  (II)--a son of Svārociṣa Manu. Br. II. 36. 19; Vi. III. 1. 12.

किम्पुरुष
Kimpuruṣa(m)  (III)--a continent of Jambūdvīpa and bounded by Hemakūṭa on one side. 1) Bhā. V. 16. 9; M. 113. 29; 114. 59, 63-5; 121. 49; Vā. 34. 28; Vi. II. 2. 13. Here Hanumān worships Rāma as a friend of all including wild creatures, and as one who led all Kośala people to Heaven. 2) Bhā. V. 19. 1-8. Its king Dumna was an ally of Jarāsandha and placed on the west of the Gomanta hill during its siege; 3) Ib. X. 52. 11 [11]. conquered by Parīkṣit. 4) Ib. I. 16. 13. There is Plakṣakhaṇḍa like Nandana: People drink of plakṣa and live for 10,000 years and are of golden colour; note for madhuvaha trees. 5) Br. II. 17. 1-5; 18. 74; Vā. 46. 2-6; 47. 71.

किम्पुरुष
Kimpuruṣa  (IV)--a kind of elf, an attendant on Kubera. Ila's conversion from womanhood into. M. 12. 10.

किम्पुरुष
Kimpuruṣas --a class of divinities, born out of Brahma's shadow just like Kinnaras. 1) Bhā. III. 20. 45. Frequent Kailāsa hill. 2) Ib. IV. 6. 31. Joined gods in singing Nṛsimha's praise. 3) Ib. VII. 8. 38. Learnt dharma from the seven sages. 4) Ib. XI. 14. 6. Belong to the line of Krodhavaśā. 5) Br. III. 7. 176; 8. 71; 41. 30; IV. 30. 9; 33. 27. 

किम्भय
Kimbhayas --a branch of Aṅgirasa. Vā. 65. 107.

किंशुकवनम्
Kiṃśukavanam --between hills Vasudhāra and Ratnadhāra; here is the temple of the sun god where every month the sun descends. Vā. 38. 27-32.

किरात
Kirāta --the story of. Br. IV. 7. 13; 8. 9.

किरात
Kirātas --People of an eastern kingdom; a mountain kingdom; defeated by Bharata and purified of sin by the worship of Hari; 1) Bhā. IX. 20. 30; II. 4. 18; Br. II. 16. 12 and 51, 60. 68; M. 114. 56; 121. 49; Vā. 45. 82; 120. 136; 47-48; 58. 83. vanquished by Kalki; 2) Br. II. 18. 50; III. 73. 109; IV. 29. 131 and 135; Vā. 98. 108. a hill tribe. 3) Br. II. 16. 68; III. 48-49; IV. 7. 19; M. 114. 11 and 35. Defeated by Sagara, took caves and hills as residences; 4) Br. III. 48. 23-49. reside on the east of Bhāratavarṣa; 5) Vi. II. 3. 8. co-habitation with Kirāta women by a Brāhmaṇa; purification at the end of the twelfth day--rites cited. 6) Br. IV. 8. 9.

किरिचक्ररथ
Kiricakraratha --of Lalitā, described. Br. IV. 20 (whole); 28. 15; 29. 39; 36. 13.

किरीट
Kirīṭa --of Viṣnu; 1) Vi. IV. 15. 13. of Kamsā. 2) Ib. V. 20. 86.

किर्मिर
Kirmira --a Nāga with his city in the 5th Talam. Br. II. 20. 37. 

किलकील
Kilakīlas --the important kings after the Guṇḍas, Vṛṣalas and Maunas; succeeded Ābhīras. Br. III. 74. 178; M. 273. 24.

किलिकिला
Kilikilā --The capital of Maunas and Bhūtananda. He and his successors reigned for 106 years. These kings had thirteen sons, known by the common name Bāhlikas. Bhā. XII. 1. 32-34.

किशोर
Kiśora --A Dānava who took part in the Tārakāmaya. M. 173. 21; 177. 7.

किष्किण्डीपाण्डुभूमिक
Kiṣkiṇḍīpāṇḍubhūmikas --a Janapada of the Ketumāla. Vā. 44. 13.

किष्किन्ध
Kiṣkindha(ka)s --a Vindhyan tribe. Br. II. 16. 64; M. 114. 52; Vā. 45. 132.

किष्किन्धगुहा
Kiṣkindhaguhā --on the Kailasa. Vā. 54. 116.

किष्किन्धा
Kiṣkindhā --the capital of Vāli. 1) Br. III. 7. 247. A mountain capital; a tīrtham sacred to Tārā. 2) M. 13. 46.

किष्कु
Kiṣku --a measure of length; two ratnis or 42 aṅgulas. Br. II. 7. 96, 99. M. 173. 16. Vā. 8. 102; 101. 123.

किसष्ण
Kisaṣṇa (c) --a Janapada. Vā. 45. 110.

कीकट
Kīkaṭa  (I)--a son of Ṛṣabha. Bhā. V. 4. 10. 

कीकट
Kīkaṭa  (II)--a son of Saṃkaṭa. His sons were godlings, being the presiding deities of fortresses. Bhā. VI. 6. 6.

कीकट
Kīkaṭa  (III) (c)--the land in which the Buddha was born; its people became purified by their devotion to Hari; 1) Bhā. I. 3. 24; VII. 10. 19. noted for the sacred Gayā and the garden park Rājagṛha, also for the āśrama of Cyavana. Other sacred spots fit for śrāddha offerings were Vaikuṇṭha, Lohadaṇḍa, Gṛdhrakūṭā and Śoṇaka. 2) Vā. 108. 73-4.

कीकस
Kīkasa --the mother of Balāhaka and seven other sons, all commanders of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 24. 6.

कीरकत्म
Kīrakatma --a sacred place fit for śrāddha offerings. Vā. 77. 56.

कीर्ति
Kīrti  (I)--the son of Dharmatantra. Vā. 94. 5.

कीर्ति
Kīrti  (II)--a daughter of Dakṣa and wife of Dharma; son Yaśas. Br. II. 9. 50, 62; 13. 80. Vi. I. 7. 23 and 31.

कीर्ति
Kīrti  (III)--a daughter of Śuka and wife of Aṇuha. Vi. IV. 19. 44.

कीर्ति
Kīrti  (IV)--the wife of Vāmana Hari (Viṣṇu). Bhā. VI. 18. 8; Vā. 30. 73; 55. 43; Br. II. 26. 45. 

कीर्ति
Kīrti  (V)--a Devī attending on Soma; 1) Br. III. 65. 26. Vā. 90. 25. wife of Jayanta; left him for Soma; 2) M. 23. 25. in the geyacakra of Lalitā Devī. 3) Br. IV. 19. 71.

कीर्तिमत्
Kīrtimat  (I)--the first son of Vasudeva and Devakī. He was not killed by Kamsā when Vasudeva brought the child to him; of the Rohiṇi family. (Killed by Kamsā-Vi. P.). Bhā. X. 1. 57-60; IX. 24. 54; Br. III. 71. 174; M. 46. 13; Vā. 96. 168; Vi. IV. 15. 26, 27.

कीर्तिमत्
Kīrtimat  (II)--a son of Uttānapāda. Br. II. 36. 89; M. 4. 35; Vā. 62. 76.

कीर्तिमत्
Kīrtimat  (III)--a son of Śaṭha. Br. III. 71. 170.

कीर्तिमत्
Kīrtimat  (IV)--a son of Aṅgiras; wife Dhenukā; sons, Cariṣṇu and Dhṛtimān. Vā. 28. 15, 17; Br. II. 11. 18.

कीर्तिमती
Kīrtimatī  (I)--a daughter of Śuka; husband Aṇuha (Satvaṇuha-Vā. P.) and son Brahmadatta. Br. III. 8. 94; 10. 82; Vā. 70. 86.

कीर्तिमती
Kīrtimatī  (II)--a goddess enshrined at Ekāmbheka. M. 13. 29.

कीर्तिरथ
Kīrtiratha --the son of Pratimbaka, (Pratitvaka-Vā. P.) father of Devamīḍha. Br. III. 64. 11-12; Vā. 89. 11.

कीर्तिराज
Kīrtirāja --a son of Dhṛti. Vā. 89. 13. 

कीर्तिरात
Kīrtirāta --the valorous son of Mahādhṛti. Father of Mahāroman. Br. III. 64. 13.

कीर्तिव्रतम्
Kīrtivratam --in honour of Aśvattha, Sūrya and Gaṅga. M. 101. 24.

कुकुपाद
Kukupāda --a Rākṣasa living in Sutalam. Br. II. 20. 23; Vā. 50. 22.

कुकुर
Kukura  (I)--the father of Vanhi. Bhā. IX. 24. 19.

कुकुर
Kukura  (II)--a son of Satyaka (Andhaka-M. P.) and father of Vṛṣṇi. (Ugrasena-Vā. P.). Br. III. 71. 116; M. 44. 61-2, 76; Vā. 96. 134.

कुकुर
Kukura  (III)--an Asura follower of Bali. M. 245. 32.

कुकुर
Kukura  (IV)--a son of Andhaka and father of Dhṛṣṭa; 1) Vi. IV. 14. 12, 13. descendants of. 2) Ib. V. 35, 16, 37, 39.

कुकुर
Kukuras --a tribe which defended Dvārakā. Relieved by Kamsā's death; fought with their kinsmen and ended their lives; 1) Bhā. I. 11. 11; X. 45. 15; XI. 30. 18. kingdom of. 2) M. 121. 43.

कुकुरान्धक
Kukurāndhakas --see Andhakas. Br. III. 71. 90: Vā. 96. 89. 

कुक्कुट
Kukkuṭa --the banner of Skanda, presented to him by Vāyu: the standard of Kumāra; a cock not to be fed with śrāddha piṇḍa; 2) Br. III. 7. 455; 10. 47; 12. 34; 14. 48; 19. 44; M. 260. 50. killer of, goes to hell. 3) Br. IV. 2. 165; 24. 50; Vā. 101. 163. Cock crying in pradoṣa time is bad to the place. 4) M. 237. 5. ^1 Vā. 72. 45.

कुक्कुती
Kukkutī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 17.

कुक्कुर
Kukkura --a commander of Bhaṇḍa; killed by Kulasundarikā in battle. Br. IV. 21. 79; 25. 28 and 97.

कुक्षि
Kukṣi --a disciple of Pauṣyañti. Learnt a hundred Sāmasamhītas. Bhā. XII. 6. 79.

कुक्षिभूम
Kukṣibhūma --a son of Bali. M. 6. 11.

कुक्षिमित्र
Kukṣimitra --a son of Vasudeva and Madirā. Br. III. 71. 171; Vā. 96. 169.

कुक्षी
Kukṣī  (I)--a daughter of the Progenitor Kardama. Br. II. 14. 8.

कुक्षी
Kukṣī  (II)--a daughter of Priyavrata. Vā. 33. 8; Vi. II. 1. 5.

कुक्षेयु
Kukṣeyu --a son of Raudrāśva. Bhā. IX. 20. 4.

कुखण्डिक
Kukhaṇḍikas --a piśāca clan. Vā. 69. 264. 

कुच
Kucas (c) --a Janapada of the Ketumāla. Vā. 44. 11.

कुचेल
Kucela --a son of Vasu. Vi. IV. 19. 81.

कुचैल
Kucaila --a poor Brāhmaṇa and class-mate of Kṛṣṇa. Having many children and distressed by poverty, his wife advised him to meet Kṛṣṇa. She begged some Pṛthukataṇḍula, and sent it as present to Kṛṣṇa. When he came to Dvārakā, Kṛṣṇa recognised him and entertained him. Rukmiṇī also honoured him. Kṛṣṇa recalled their school days, and their loyalty to Guru Sāndīpani, and how he reciprocated it. Once when they went out and were caught in storm and rains, the Guru came in search of them with great anxiety. Kucaila gave Kṛṣṇa the Pṛthukataṇḍula which Kṛṣṇa shared with Rukminī and heartily ate of it. After spending a jolly night, the Brāhmaṇa took leave of his friend and went home, ruminating on the way why Kṛṣṇa did not offer any riches to him. When he neared his place, he found tall mansions lavishly built and furnished. His wife extended him welcome with servants. He knew it was all the work of his friend Kṛṣṇa. Spent a righteous life ever meditating on Hari's lotus feet. Bhā. X. 80. 6-45; 81 (whole).

कुज
Kuja  (I)--vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. II. 7. 34.

कुज
Kuja  (II)--(3/4) of Bṛhaspati in size. Vā. 53. 67.

कुजम्भ
Kujambha --a prominent Asura, present in Tāraka's coronation; a commander of Tāraka's army: Had a chariot of mules with demon faces: Fought with Kubera. M. 147. 28; 148. 42-50; 150. 76-121; 245. 12. 

कुजिलाश्व
Kujilāśva --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 85.

कुञ्जरी
Kuñjarī --a svara śakti. Br. IV. 44. 56.

कुञ्चि
Kuñci --a son of Bali. Br. III. 5. 43.

कुञ्जतीर्थम्
Kuñjatīrtham --on the Narmadā. M. 194. 9-10.

कुञ्जर
Kuñjara  (I)--an Asura in Atalam (fourth tala or gabhastalam-Vā. P.) 1) Br. II. 20. 32; Vā. 50. 31. A commander of Tāraka with a chariot of horses; killed by Kapāli and other Rudras after a terrific fight. 2) M. 148. 42-50; 153. 29-30, 51-68.

कुञ्जर
Kuñjara  (II)--Father of Añjanā, and father-in-law of Kesari; a Nāga. Br. III. 7. 223 and 233, 350.

कुञ्जर
Kuñjara  (III)--(Mt.) abode of Agastya. M. 163. 79.

कुञ्जरचाया
Kuñjaracāyā --is Hastinaḥ chāyā (s.v.). 1) Br. III. 19. 8. a nakṣatra. 2) Vā. 83. 11.

कुञ्जरपति
Kuñjarapati --was placed on the East of the Gomanta hill during the siege of Mathurā by Jarāsandha. Bhā. X. 52. 11 [5].

कुटक
Kuṭaka--(c)  a kingdom through which Ṛṣabha passed. Arhat was king. Bhā. V. 6. 7 and 9. 

कुटकाचल
Kuṭakācala --Mt. adjoining the Kuṭaka country. Bhā. V. 6. 7.

कुटभी
Kuṭabhī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 16.

कुटीचक
Kuṭīcaka --a class of ascetics. Bhā. III. 12. 43.

कुटिलाक्ष
Kuṭilākṣa --the commander-in-chief of Bhaṇḍa; stationed troops on all sides of the city and got the army ready for action. Sent Durmada, Kuraṇḍa, Karaṅka and others to the field, all being slain; attacked Cakraratha from the front and fled back in fear. Sent again 30 sons of Bhaṇḍa, and lastly went with Bhaṇḍa for the war. Br. IV. 21. 77-100; 22-26 (all chapters); 27-10; 29. 8.

कुटुम्बि
Kuṭumbi --a householder, fit for receiving dānas. M. 53. 19 and 41; 72. 35; 76. 3; 96. 13; Vā. 61. 96.

कुटुम्बिका
Kuṭumbikā --a mother goddess. M. 179. 30.

कुड्मला
Kuḍmalā --a R. sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 46.

कुणि
Kuṇi  (I)--the son of Jaya (Sañjaya-Vi. P.). and father of Yugandhara. Bhā. IX. 24. 14; Vi. IV. 14. 3.

कुणि
Kuṇi  (II)--is Indupramati. Br. III. 8. 97. 

कुनि
Kuni  (III)--a son of Vedaśiras; an avatār of the 15th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 169.

कुणिन्द
Kuṇinda --a powerful ally of Jarāsandha; placed at the north gate of Mathurā during its siege, and of Gomanta during its siege: see Kulinda. Bha. X. 50. 11 (7); 52. 11 (14).

कुणिबाहु
Kuṇibāhu --a son of Vedaśiras; an avatār of the 15th dvāpara. (See also Kunī). Vā. 23. 169.

कुण्ड
Kuṇḍa --a chief Vānara. Br. III. 7. 241.

कुण्ड
Kuṇḍas --Five in Prayāga, in the midst of which flows the Gaṅgā; 1) M. 104. 13. three fire kuṇḍas outside Prayāga through which the Ganges flows. 2) M. 110. 4.

कुण्डक
Kuṇḍaka  (I)--a Śrutaṛṣi. Br. II. 33. 10.

कुण्डक
Kuṇḍaka  (II)--the son of Kṣudraka and father of Suratha. Vi. IV. 22. 9.

कुन्दपर्वत
Kundaparvata --a mountain. Vā. 108. 32. 

कुण्डपायिन्
Kuṇḍapāyins --sons of Nidhruva and Sumedhā. Br. III. 8. 31; Vā. 70. 27.

कुण्डिकेर
Kuṇḍikera --(Tuṇḍikaras-Pargiter) a Haihaya clan. M. 43. 49.

कुण्डिन
Kuṇḍina  (I)--a Vāsiṣṭha Brahmavādin. M. 145. 110; 200. 15.

कुण्डिन
Kuṇḍina  (II)--a resident of Brahmakṣetra. Vā. 59. 106.

कुण्डिन
Kuṇḍina  (III)--one of the eleven Vasiṣṭha branches. Vā. 70. 90.

कुण्डिन
Kuṇḍina  (IV)--the capital of Vidarbhas; Damaghoṣa arrived at; Balarāma's arrival; Rukmi's resolve not to enter the capital without vanquishing Kṛṣṇa. 1) Bhā. X. 53. 7. 15 and 21; 54. 19-20, 52; Vi. V. 26. 1. Here Śālva had a conference of princes to get rid of Kṛṣṇa. 2) Bhā. X. 76. 2 [8-9].

कुण्डिन
Kuṇḍinas --a class of Vāsiṣṭha group. Br. III. 8. 99.

कुतप
Kutapas --eight in relation to a śrāddha--middle noon, khaḍgapātram, Nepal shawl, silver, kuśa grass, seasamum, cow, son of a daughter: ety. kutsitam pāpam tapanti; Of 5 and 6 are born of Viṣṇu's body and are by themselves enough to protect a Śrāddha. M. 22. 84-9.

कुत्स
Kutsa  (I)--a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu. Bhā. IV. 13. 16. 

कुत्स
Kutsa  (II)--a Bhārgava gotrakara. Tripravara. M. 195. 22; 196. 37.

कुथन
Kuthana --a Rākṣasa. Vā. 69. 165.

कुथप्रावर्ण
Kuthaprāvarṇa (c) --a locality through which Pāvanī flows; 1) Br. II. 18. 57. a mountain kingdom; 2) M. 114. 56. people of. 3) Vā. 47. 55.

कुथुमि
Kuthumi  (I)--a son of Jaṭāmāla, an avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 187.

कुथुमि
Kuthumi  (II)--one of the four chief disciples of Pauṣyañji; had three sons. Vā. 61. 36, 38.

कुनाल
Kunāla --a son of Aśoka; ruled for eight years. Vā. 99. 333.

कुनिन्द
Kunindas --a tribe. Vā. 47. 43.

कुनेत्रक
Kunetraka --a son of Vedaśiras, an avatār of the 15th dvāpara. Cf. Kuni. Vā. 23. 169.

कुन्तल
Kuntala  (I)--(Svātikarṇa) Āndhra king ruled for eight years. M. 273. 8.

कुन्तल
Kuntala  (II) (c)--a kingdom of Madhya deśa; a southern country. ^1 Br. II. 16. 41 and 59-60; 18. 44. 

कुन्तल
Kuntalas --a people of southern country; 1) M. 114. 35; Vā. 45. 110, 127; 47. 42. were enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus. 2) Bhā. X. [50 (V) 3].

कुन्ति
Kunti  (I)--the son of Dharmanetra and father of Samjaya (Sohañji-Bhā. P.), (Sahajit-Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 23. 22. Br. III. 69. 5; M. 43. 9; Vi. IV. 11. 8.

कुन्ति
Kunti  (II)--the son of Kratha and father of Dhṛṣṭi(a) (Vṛṣṇi-Burnouf). Bhā. IX. 24. 3; M. 44. 38-9; Vā. 95. 38; Vi. IV. 12. 40-41.

कुन्ति
Kunti  (III)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyā. Bhā. X. 61. 13.

कुन्तिभोज
Kuntibhoja --(Kunti-Vā. P.), went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse; 1) Bhā. X. 82. 25. Vi. IV. 14. 32. 3. adopted Pṛthā, daughter of Śūra, as his daughter. (See Sorenson's Index to Proper Names in Mahābhārata, p. 436). Pāṇḍu married Kuntī, daughter of Kuntibhoja. 2) Br. III. 71. 151-2; M. 46. 7; Vā. 96. 150.

कुन्तिषेण
Kuntiṣeṇa --a commander of Bhaṇḍa, attacked by Mahāmāyā. Br. IV. 21. 84; 28. 39.

कुन्ती
Kuntī --daughter of Śūra and adopted by Kuntibhoja as he was childless. Durvāsas taught her a mantra by which she invoked the sun who returned after blessing her with a child. Being an unmarried girl, she abandoned her son in a box, and this was discovered by Adhiratha who  brought him up. This child was Karṇa; 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 13-14; 24. 31-36; Br. III. 71. 152-5; M. 46. 7. queen of Pāṇḍu: gave birth to Yudhiṣṭhira and four other sons by the favour of gods--Dharma, Vāyu and Indra and the Aśvins; outlived her husband for the sake of their welfare. 2) Bhā. IX. 22. 27; M. 50. 48-50. Br. III. 1. 40. Vi. V. 12. 24. Seen by Akrūra: Narrated to Vidura her troubles after Pāṇḍu's death. Her affection and love for Kṛṣṇa; addressed him on the difficulties encountered by the Pāṇḍavas. Kṛṣṇa comforted her and explained how it was not possible for him to go to Hāstināpura earlier. 3) Bhā. X. 58. 7. 10; X. 49. 1-15; I. 8. 3: 9. 13. Her stotra of Kṛṣṇa; 4) Ib. I. 8. 17-43. grieved at his departure from Hāstināpura. Her thoughts on the other world. 5) Ib. I. 10. 9; 13. 3; 15. 33; X. 82 24. Heard of Drupada's defeat by her sons. Was met by Kṛtavarman at Hāstināpura. At the news of the alleged burning of (Pāṇḍavas, etc.), Kuntī went to the Kurus accompanied by Rāma and Kṛṣṇa, though the latter was aware of the fact of their living. 6) Ib. X. 52. [56 (V) 2], [5], 10; 57. 1. Heard the story of the marriage of Kṛṣṇa from his wives and was lost in wonder. 7) Ib. X. 84. 1. Left for Syamantapañcaka, and complained to Vasudeva of his neglect of her sons. Vasudeva consoled her saying that oppression from Kamsā had scattered them in different directions. 8) Ib. X. 82. 18-22; 84. 57 and 69 [3]. Joy at Kṛṣṇa's visit to Hāstināpura. Taking leave of her Kṛṣṇa went to Dvārakā. 9) Ib. X. 7 1. 39; 77. 7; 10. M. 103. 12. (See Pṛthā) Regretted with her sons the loss of Duryodhana and others.^10

कुन्ती
Kuntī --a R. from the Pāriyatra hill. M. 114. 24.

कुन्ति
Kuntis --a Yadu tribe who took part in the marriage festivities of Kṛṣṇa and Rukminī. 1) Bhā. X. 54. 58. They went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse. 2) Ib. X. 82. 13. Heard of Kṛṣṇa going to Mithilā and met him with presents. 3) Ib. 86. 20. Fought with their kinsmen and ended their lives. 4) Ib. XI. 30. 18. 

कुन्द
Kunda --a Mt. of Śālmalidvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 10.

कुपथ
Kupatha --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 10; Vā. 68. 10.

कुपथ
Kupathas --a hill tribe; a mountain kingdom of the south. Br. II. 16. 67; M. 114. 47. 55; 121. 35.

कुपथप्रावरण
Kupathaprāvaraṇas --the kingdom of. M. 121. 56.

कुबलाश्व
Kubalāśva --Killed Dundhu, the son of Arūru, on the advice of Uttanka. Vā. 68. 31.

कुबेर
Kubera  (I)--the son of Viśravas (Vaiśrāvaṇa) and Iḍaviḍā. His father initiated him into a great vidyā. Father of three sons--Viśāla and others. Lord of Yakṣas, and brother of Śiva; 1) Bhā. IX. 2. 32-33; IV. 1. 37; 11. 33. Vā. 40. 8; 47. 1; 70. 38. 97. 2. was pleased with Dhruva and blessed him though he killed his followers. 2) Bhā. IV. 12. 1-9. Presented a golden throne to Pṛthu. 3) Ib. 15. 14. With his naravāhana attacked Kṛṣṇa taking Pārijāta, but defeated by Satyabhāmā, retreated in fear. Presented to Kṛṣṇa eight treasures and his new city. 4) Ib. X. [65 (V) 45], [66 (V) 4-21]; 50. 56. Attended by Guhyakas, he is compared to Yudhiṣṭhira attended by Pāṇḍavas, Kṛṣṇa and sages. 5) Ib. I. 9. 3. Lord of Alaka and son of Pulastya and resident of Kailāsa; 6) Br. II. 18. 1-2; 35. 94; 36. 218; M. 121. 2-3; 137. 32; Vā. 69. 196. vanquished by Rāvaṇa; wife Ṛddhi and son Nalakūbera. 7) Br. III. 7. 254 and 331; 8. 44; 72. 2; IV. 15. 22; Vā. 70. 41. Man as his riding animal: followed by Yakṣas and Rākṣasas with respective standards--Ulūka and Gṛdhra;  fought with Jambha and Kujambha and was overwhelmed; fled to Indra helpless; beaten by Tāraka. 8) M. 148. 84; 150. 50-108; 153. 179. By residing in Benares, attained the status of a Gaṇeśa; 9) M. 180. 62. observed the Ādityaśayanavṛatam; 10) Ib. 47. 30; 55. 32. penance at the confluence of the Narmadā and the Kāverī and was blessed by Śiva to be the Lord of Yakṣas; 11) Ib. 189. 4-11; 191. 85. icon of; 12) Ib. 261. 20-2. defended the chariot of Tripurāri. 13) Ib. 133. 63; 138. 25; 140. 41.

कुबेर
Kubera  (II)--(Dhanada): the guardian of the north; 1) M. 67. 15; Vi. V. 36. 12. presents of, at Umā's marriage; 2) M. 154. 489. in the army of deva's at Tārakāmaya; riding animal of, man; 3) M. 174. 17-18. Harikeśa got this status at Benares; became annada and kṣetrapāla; Udbhrama and Sambhrama, two Gaṇas in his service. 4) M. 180. 94-99.

कुबेरणि
Kuberaṇi --Tripravara. M. 196. 33.

कुबेरतुङ्ग
Kuberatuṅga --a sacred place fit for śrāddha; near Nandā in the N. E. direction; a siddhakṣetra; a temple of Mahādeva; the lord performed austerities standing on one leg in the Devī's temple for a Yuga (divya). Br. III. 13. 80; Vā. 77. 78-81.

कुबेर
Kubera bhavanam --in the Piśācaka hill. Vā. 39. 57.

कुबेर
Kuberas (c) --a Janapada of the Ketumāla. Vā. 44. 14. 

कुब्ज
Kubja --got final release by satsaṅga. Bhā. XI. 12. 6.

कुब्जाभ्रम्
Kubjābhram --a tīrtham sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 66.

कुमनस्
Kumanas --a people of the Dakṣināpatha. Vā. 45. 125.

कुमार
Kumāra  (I) (Subrahmaṇya)--born in Śarakānana or Śaravana and was nursed by the six Kṛttikas, hence Kārttikeya: Sucking milk with six mouths, the child came to be known as Ṣaṇmukha. Appointed commander of the celestial army in the Tārakāsura war and killed Tāraka. 1) Bhā. IV. 7. 64-5; Vi. I. 15. 115. M. 5. 26-7; 160 (whole): 225. 18; Vā. 66. 24. Śākha, Viśākha and Naigameya were brothers. 2) Ib. 66. 24; M. 5. 2617. An avatār of Hari. 3) Bhā. XI. 4. 17. A son of Agni through Svāhā, and the son of Gangā by taking Agni's garbha due to Uma's curse. Hence son of Śiva. 4) M. 135. 79. His birth was heralded by divine musicians, siddhas, cāraṇas, yakṣas, kinnaras and others. Fed with milk by the wives of the seven sages except Arundhatī. Hari presented him two birds--fowl and peacock, Sarasvatī the lute, Brāhmī a goat, and Śiva a ram. 5) Br. III. 3. 24; 10. 35. -48; M. 203. 6; Vā. 72. 35-46. Married Devasenā, the daughter of Indra: also known as Skanda, Guha, and Devasenāpati. 6) Br. IV. 30. 39, 99 to the end; Vā. 72. 48-50; Br. III. 10. 48-51. Mayūra as the riding animal of. 7) M. 135. 76. Wounded by Maya in the battle of Tripuram. 8) M. 192. 33.

कुमार
Kumāra (Sanat)  (II)--a siddha who could not comprehend the supreme Being and who would not find fault with Hara for violating dharma. 1) Bhā. VI. 3. 20; 15. 12; 17. 12 and 32; VIII. 23. 20. Learnt the Bhāgavata from Sankarṣaṇa and imparted it to Sānkhyāyana. 2) Bhā. III. 8. 3 and 7. 

कुमार
Kumāra  (III)--a son of Havya, after whom Kumāravarṣa was called. Br. II. 14. 17-18; Vā. 33. 16.

कुमार
Kumāra  (IV)--see Bhauma. Br. II. 23. 85; 28. 92.

कुमार
Kumāra  (V)--a prajāpati. Br. III. 1. 54; Vā. 65. 53.

कुमार
Kumāra  (VI)--an author of Architecture. M. 252. 3.

कुमार
Kumāra  (VII)--rose out of the contemplation of Brahmā in the 29th kalpa; with white complexion and a resplendant fearful countenance and mouth; Brahmā worshipped him as the Gods of Gods, Purāṇapuruṣa, the best of yogins and laughed a hearty laugh in wonder; also of red colour. Vā. 22. 10-23.

कुमार
Kumāra  (VIII)--at the commencement of the eighth kalpa Brahmā got a son (Nīlalohita) who was weeping; he asked Brahmā to give him a name for which Brahmā said Rudra; again he cried for a second name and Brahmā said, Bhava; the other names given in order were Śiva, Paśupati, Īśa, Bhīma, Ugra and Mahādeva. Vā. 27. 4-16.

कुमार
Kumāra  (IX)--a Nāga. Vā. 69. 71. 

कुमार
Kumāra  (X)--a son of Bhavya of Śākadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 60.

कुमार
Kumāra (c) --a kingdom watered by Hlādinī; 1) Br. II. 18. 55. a tribe. 2) Vā. 47. 52.

कुमार
Kumāras --a celestial group. Vā. 47. 52.

कुमारक
Kumāraka --the first offspring of Brahmā when he was engaged in thinking of creation devoid of śabda, sparśa, rūpa, rasa and gandha. Brahmā pondered over a form which would be neither male nor female but with colours. Then Akṣara came out of ‘his neck; it was Omkāra with one mātra, then two mātrākṣara, three akṣaras, then fourteenfaced deva and 14 Manus. Vā. 26. 8-28.

कुमारकोशल
Kumārakośala --a tīrtha in the Pālapañjara hill; sacred for śrāddha. Vā. 77. 37.

कुमारनिलय
Kumāranilaya --sages of, visited Dvāraka. Bhā. X. 90. 28[4].

कुमारवनम्
Kumāravanam --Here Purūravas got separated from Urvaśī. M. 24. 19.

कुमारवंश
Kumāravaṃśa --the son of Madhu, and father of Anu. Vi. IV. 12. 42. 

कुमारसम्भव
Kumārasambhava --see Tārakāmaya.

कुमारा
Kumārā --a R. from the Śuktimat hill. Vi. II. 3. 14.

कुमारी
Kumārī  (I)--a daughter of Lalitā aged nine, and trained in military art. Attacked and slew all the sons of Bhaṇḍa to the joy of the Śakti troops; 1) Br. IV. 26. 73-117. goddess enshrined at Māyāpurī. 2) M. 13. 34.

कुमारि
Kumāri  (II)--Cape Comorin, fit for śrāddha offerings. Br. II. 16. 11; III. 13. 28.

कुमारी
Kumārī  (III)--a R. from the Śuktimat hill. Br. II. 16. 38; M. 163. 86.

कुमारी
Kumārī  (IV) (Siddhā)--a R. of Śākadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 96; Vā. 45. 81; 49. 92; Vi. II. 4. 65.

कुमारी
Kumārī  (V)--noted for Candratīrtha. Vā. 77. 28.

कुमारीपुरम्
Kumārīpuram --a part of an artificial fortress (Kṛtrima). Br. II. 7. 103-4.

कुमुञ्ज
Kumuñja --Mt. king of hills, to the east of Aruṇoda; 1) Vā. 36. 18; 37. 1. eight cities of the Dānavas located in. 2) Ib. 39. 28-9.

कुमुथि
Kumuthi --a ṛtvik at Brahmā's sacrifice. Vā. 106. 34. 

कुमुद
Kumuda  (I)--an attendant on Hari. 1) Bhā. VII. 8. 38-39; XI. 27. 28. Attacked Asura followers of Bali. 2) Ib. VIII. 21. 16.

कुमुद
Kumuda  (II)--a disciple of Pathya. Bhā. XII. 7. 2.

कुमुद
Kumuda  (III)--a chief Vānara. Br. III. 7. 242.

कुमुद
Kumuda  (IV)--a son of Irāvatī. Br. III. 7. 292.

कुमुद
Kumuda  (V)--a Nāga from Cāndramasa Sāma. Br. III. 7. 345.

कुमुद
Kumuda  (VI)--a son of Maṇivara. Vā. 69. 160.

कुमुद
Kumuda  (VII)--a son of Bṛhatī. Vā. 96. 247.

कुमुद
Kumuda  (VIII)--a Mt. on one side of Meru west of Śitoda. Here is the celestial Banian Tree Śatabalū's from which flow rivers to Nilāvṛta. The tree would yield whatever was desired of it. 1) Bhā. V. 16. 11 and 24; Vā. 36. 28; 38. 45; 42. 51. One of the seven hills of Śālmaladvīpa. 2) Br. II. 19. 35; Vā. 49. 32-3; Vi. II. 4. 26. Residence of the Kinnaras. 3) Vi. 39. 59.

कुमुद
Kumuda  (IX)--a Mt. in Kuśadvīpa. M. 122. 52.

कुमुद
Kumuda  (X)--a Mt. in Gomedaka. M. 123. 3. 

कुमुद
Kumuda  (XI)--a Cakravāka in Mānasa; a son of Kauśika in previous birth. M. 20. 18.

कुमुद
Kumuda  (XII)--one of the eight nidhis of Kubera. Vā. 41. 10.

कुमुद
Kumudas --a Janapada of the Bhadra continent. Vā. 43. 21.

कुमुदद्युति
Kumudadyuti --a Nāga from Cāndramasa Sāma. Br. III. 7. 345.

कुमुदद्वीप
Kumudadvīpa --a region of Bhāratavarṣa; (kuśa) described. Vā. 48. 14. 34-5.

कुमुदा
Kumudā  (I)--a name of Yogamāya; the goddess enshrined in Mānasa. Bhā. X. 2. 12; M. 13. 27.

कुमुदा
Kumudā  (II)--the wily sister of Mahādeva in the isle of Kumuda. Vā. 48. 35.

कुमुदाक्ष
Kumudākṣa  (I)--an attendant on Hari. Attacked Asura followers of Bali. See Kumudākṣaṇa. Bhā. VIII. 21. 16; XI. 27. 28.

कुमुदाक्ष
Kumudākṣa  (II)--an Yakṣa and a son of Devayāni. Br. III. 7. 129.

कुमुदादि
Kumudādi --a pupil of Pathya. Br. II. 35. 59; Vā. 61. 52; Vi. III. 6. 11. 

कुमुदाभ
Kumudābhas --a Janapada of the Ketumāla country. Vā. 44. 12.

कुमुदिनी
Kumudinī --one of the four queens of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 12. 13.

कुमुदेक्षन
Kumudekṣana --see Kumdākṣa.

कुमुद्वती
Kumudvatī  (I)--a R. in Krauñcadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 75; M. 122. 88; Vā. 49. 69; Vi. II. 4. 55.

कुमुद्वती
Kumudvatī  (II)--a R. from the Vindhyas. Br. II. 16. 33; M. 114. 27; Vā. 45. 102; 47. 2.

कुमुन्द
Kumunda --(Mt.) a hill range on the east of Meru. Vi. II. 2. 27.

कुम्भ
Kumbha  (I)--a Daitya king, originator of the Kāpileyas, Daityarākṣasas; by his wife Kapilā; 1) Br. III. 7. 144-6; Vā. 69. 176-7. killed in the Laṅkā war. 2) Bhā. IX. 10. 18.

कुम्भ
Kumbha  (II)--a son of Muṇḍīśvara, an avatār of the lord of the 25th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 211.

कुम्भ
Kumbha  (III)--helped Soma in the Tārakāmaya war. Vi. IV. 6. 14.

कुम्भ
Kumbha  (IV)--a palace in the shape of a pot, with 9 bhūmikas and a toraṇa of 16 hastas. M. 269. 37-49.

कुम्भ
Kumbha  (V)--fit for śrāddha. Vā. 77. 47. 

कुम्भकर्ण
Kumbhakarṇa --a son of Viśravas and Kaikarī, killed by Rāma in the Lankā war; 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 37; VII. 1. 43; 10. 36; IX. 10. 18; Vā. 70. 41. a brother of Rāvaṇa. 2) Br. III. 8. 47; IV. 29. 113 and 116.

कुम्भकर्णी
Kumbhakarṇī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 22.

कुम्भकर्षाश्य
Kumbhakarṣāśya --a son of the Muṇḍīśvara avatār of the lord. Vā. 23. 211.

कुम्भकारि
Kumbhakāri --a R. of the Ketumāla country. Vā. 44. 22.

कुम्भगर्त्तोदय
Kumbhagarttodaya --a son of Bali. Br. III. 5. 43.

कुम्भग्रीव
Kumbhagrīva --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 88.

कुम्भज
Kumbhaja --a name of Agastya. Br. III. 35. 42; IV. 17. 35; 30. 4.

कुम्भनाभ
Kumbhanābha  (I)--a son of Bali. Vā. 67. 83.

कुम्भनाभ
Kumbhanābha  (II)--one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 10.

कुम्भनास
Kumbhanāsa --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 88.

कुम्भपात्र
Kumbhapātras --a group of Piśācas, little in size, hairy, brownish in hue; 1) Br. III. 7. 378 and 382, 395. are invisible and live on the heads of elephants and camels. 2) Vā. 69. 263, 274-5. 

कुम्भम्
Kumbham --a water vessel, being an adjunct of vratams: to be given as gift. M. 7. 10 and 18.

कुम्भमान
Kumbhamāna --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 10.

कुम्भयोनि
Kumbhayoni --a name of Agastya. Bhā. I. 19. 10.

कुम्भसम्भव
Kumbhasambhava --a name of Agastya. Br. IV. 17, 32; 29. 58.

कुम्भाण्ड
Kumbhāṇḍa  (I)--a minister of Bāṇa. His daughter Citralekhā, was a companion of Ūṣā, Bāṇa's daughter; 1) Bhā. X. 62. 14; Vi. V. 32. 17. was attacked by Balarāma in the siege of Śoṇitapura; defeated, ran away. 2) Bhā. X. 63, 8 and 16. Sent to Mathurā for Jarāsandha's help. Kṛṣṇa overcame his illusory warfare by Vijñānāstra. Defeated by Sātyaki, he fell unconscious; was taken from the field in a chariot back to his city. 3) Ib. X. [51 (V) 18], [28-30, 59-63, 65].

कुम्भाण्ड
Kumbhāṇḍa  (II)--a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 89.

कुम्भिल
Kumbhila --a Rākṣasa with his city in the third Talam; 1) Br. II. 20. 28. a son of Bali. 2) Vā. 50. 27. 68. 32.

कुम्भीक
Kumbhīka --a hell, for those fallen from Karma. Vā. 83. 89.

कुम्भीनसी
Kumbhīnasī  (I)--a daughter of Puṣpotkaṭa and Viśravas. Br. III. 8. 55; Vā. 70. 49. 

कुम्भीनसी
Kumbhīnasī  (II)--a daughter of Bali, and sister of Bāṇa; ill-treated Bāṇa's wife. M. 187. 40-42.

कुम्भीपाक
Kumbhīpāka --one of the 28 hells intended for those who deprive a Brāhmaṇa of his property, and for flesh and meat-eaters. Bhā. V. 26. 7 and 13; X. 64. 38; Br. II. 28. 83; III. 19. 61; M. 141. 70.

कुम्भोत्कच
Kumbhotkaca --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 88.

कुरङ्ग
Kuraṅga --a Mt. on the base of Meru. Bhā. V. 16. 26.

कुरण्ड
Kuraṇḍa --a commander of Bhaṇḍa expert in māyā and skilled in citrayuddha or kūṭayuddha; an elder brother of Durmada; killed by Devī. Br. IV. 21. 77; 22. 71-108.

कुरज
Kuraja --a Viśvedeva. M. 203. 13.

कुरर
Kurara --a Mt. on the base of Meru. Bhā. V. 16. 26.

कुररी
Kurarī --Mt. on hill range on the east of Meru. Vi. II. 2. 27.

कुरव
Kurava  (I)--one of the fourteen gaṇas of Apsaras, born of Soma's rays. Br. III. 7. 19; Vā. 69. 55. 

कुरव
Kurava  (II) (c)--the land of Kurus, part of Haritāśva kingdom; also Kuruvamśa. 1) M. 12. 18; 35. 8; 69. 11; 121. 49. Situated between oceans and served by Siddhas; there is a madhuphala tree from which clothes and ornaments are taken; besides there is another tree kṣīriṇa of six rasas, all the earth set with presious gems; people are born mithunas and soon grow into lofty youthful men and women, loyal like cakravāka birds; they live 13,150 years. There are two kulaparvatas and a river Bhadraśīma besides others flowing with honey, milk and ghee; there are gardens in it of tamāla, agaru, sandal, etc., besides sporting grounds and creeper houses of different kinds and musical instruments of different varieties; men adorn themselves with beautiful jewels of all sorts. They are not troubled by disease or old age. 2) Vā. 45. 11-50.

कुरव
Kuravas  (I)--a caste equal to Kṣatriya in Plakṣadvīpā. Vi. II. 4. 17.

कुरव
Kuravas  (II)--Thirty-six kings who were contemporaries of ten Śisunāgas. Br. III. 74. 137; M. 272. 16; 273. 72.

कुरु
Kuru  (I)--a son of Āgnīdhra and Pūrvacitti; 1) Bhā. V. 2. 19; Vā. 33. 40; Vi. II. 1. 17 and 22. Lord of Śṛngavaṭam. 2) Br. II. 14. 47. Kingdom north-east of Śṛṅgavatvarṣa. 3) Vā. 33. 44; Br. II. 14. 51.

कुरु
Kuru  (II)--a son of Samvarna and Tapaṭī; occupied Prayāga and established Kurukṣetra; Lord of Kurukṣetra. Had four (several-Vi. P.) sons--Parīkṣit and others. 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 4; Vā. 99. 214-7;; Vi. 19. 76-8. Parīkṣit's son Janamejaya was his grandson? At Kurukṣetra he performed tapas and 2) Br. III. 68. 21. pleased Indra. Family members were known as Kauravas. 3) M. 50. 20-2. 

कुरु
Kuru  (III)--a son of Manu and Naḍvalā; wife Āgneyī; gave birth to six sons, Aṅga and others. Vi. I. 13. 5, 6.

कुरु
Kuru  (IV)--(Uttara) country of the; famous for a forest śaḍvala. Vā. 84. 23, 48.

कुरु
Kuru  (V)--a continent bounded by Śṛngavan on one side. Here Hari is worshipped in his Boar incarnation by Pṛthvi (Earth) with the Kurus. Bhā. V. 16. 8; 18. 34-9.

कुरु
Kuru  (VI)--an eastern kingdom watered by the Ganges. Its king was enlisted by Jarāsandha, against Yadus, but was vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. 1) Bhā. I. 10. 34. X. [50 (V) 2]; II. 7. 35. Br. II. 18. 50; III. 59. 3 and 46. He took part in the festivities connected with the marriage of Rukminī and Kṛṣṇa. 2) Bhā. X. 54. 58. He praised Kṛṣṇa's heroism and welcomed him. 3) Ib. X. 71. 29; 72. 5; IX. 24. 63. Took part in the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira. 4) Ib. X. 75. 12. He went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse; 5) Ib. X. 82. 13; 84. 55. migration of Yadus to. 6) Ib. X. 2.

कुरुक्षेत्र
Kurukṣetra --founded by Kuru and sacred to Harī. 1) Bhā III. 3. 12; VII. 14. 30; Vi. VI. 8. 29. Watered by the river Sarasvatī. 2) Bhā. IX. 14. 33. Capital city of the Kurus. 3) Ib. IX. 22. 4. Sages of Kurukṣetra visited Dvāraka. At Kurukṣetra Kṛṣṇa performed sacrifices for twelve years. 4) Ib. X. 90. 28[3], 46[1]. The battlefield where the Pāṇḍavas fought with the Kurus led by Duryodhana. 5) Ib. X. 78. [95 (V) 9], [18]. Here Paraśurāma dug a lake called Syamantapañcaka. 6) Br. III. 47. 2. On the occasion of a sacrifice Sūta narrated the Br. Purāṇa here. 7) Bhā. I. 1. 17. Purūravas met Urvaśī after their separation at; the residence of Sanatkumāra and Dharmarāja fit for śrāddha offerings, and sacred to Pitṛs. Founded by Kuru, son of Samvaraṇa; 8) III. 13. 65 and 68; 66. 18; M. 22. 18; Vā. 77. 64; 91. 31; 99. 215, 259. residence of sage Kauśika, and sacrifice of Adhisīmakṛṣṇa for 2 years at; sacred in Dvāpara; 9) M. 20. 2; 50. 20 and 67; 106. 49 and 57; 109. 3; 180. 55; 184. 16. Dharmakṣetra where a great sacrifice was per formed. 10) Vā. 1. 14; 59. 107. Residence at, leads to mukti; no shaving or upavāsa required here. 11) Ib. 105. 16 and 25. Noted for ambhojasaras or lotus tank. 12) Vi. IV-19. 77. R. Sarasvatī flows here: noted for a temple of Vāmana. 13) M. 186. 10; 192. 12; 244. 3.

कुरुजाङ्गल
Kurujāṅgala(c) --the kingdom of Parīkṣit. Visited by Śuka and Vidura; 1) Bhā. I. 46; 10. 34; 16. 11; III. 1. 24; Br. III. 13. 100; Vā. 77. 93. a Pāñcāla kingdom. 2) M. 21. 9 and 28.

कुरुजाङ्गल
Kurujāṅgalas --heard of Kṛṣṇa going to Mithilā and met him with presents. Bhā. X. 86. 20.

कुरुजिब्
Kurujib --the son of Añjana and father of Ariṣṭanemi. Vi. IV. 5. 31.

कुरुपाञ्चाल
Kurupāñcāla(c) --a kingdom of Madhyadeśa; 1) Br. II. 16. 40; Vi. II. 3. 15. a tribe; a Janapada. 2) M. 114. 34; Vā. 45. 109.

कुरुवश
Kuruvaśa (Kuravaśa-Burnouf) --the son of Madhu and father of Anu. Bhā. IX. 24. 5.

कुरुवान्
Kuruvān --a Viśvedeva. Vā. 66. 32.

कुरुवीर
Kuruvīras --kings of Rasātala, vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 73. 103. 

कुलक
Kulaka  (I)--a class of people in Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 16.

कुलक
Kulaka  (II)--a son of Kṣudraka and father of Suratha. M. 271. 13.

कुलकर्मा
Kulakarmā --a part of Purāṇa samhitā. Vā. 60. 21.

कुलथ
Kulathas --the kingdom of. M. 121. 44.

कुलदेवीयात्रा
Kuladevīyātrā --on the day prior to the marriage it was then a custom for the bride to visit the temple of Pārvatī and offer worship. Rukmini suggested that Kṛṣṇa might carry her off at that time. Bhā. X. 52. 42[1].

कुलधर्म
Kuladharmas --Transgressors of Kuladharma are unfit for Śrāddha purposes. Br. III. 14. 41.

कुलपर्वत
Kulaparvatas --seven in number. M. 114. 17.

कुलसुन्दरी
Kulasundarī(ca) --a Nityā devī. Br. IV. 19. 58; 25. 97; 37. 34.

कुलह
Kulaha --a Pravara Ṛṣi. M. 199. 17.

कुलाचल
Kulācala --the lofty hill to which the Pāṇḍyan Malayadhvaja retired for tapas. Traversed by rivers Candravasā, Tamraparṇī, and Vaṭodaka. Hermitages in. Bhā. III. 13. 41: 23. 39: IV. 28. 33 and 35: VIII. 4. 8. 

कुलालचक्र
Kulālacakra --the potters’ wheel, likened to the wheel of samsāra; the lump of clay becomes a full pot by the constant revolving of the wheel; 1) Vā. 14. 19, 38; 50. 141. the movements of the sun and moon compared to. 2) M. 124. 69; 125. 52; Vi. II. 8. 27.

कुलिक
Kulika --a chief Nāga of Pātāla. Bhā. V. 24. 31.

कुलिन्द
Kulinda --see Kuninda. Bhā. X. 52. 11 [14].

कुलिन्द
Kulindas --people of a southern? kingdom; enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus. Br. II. 16. 59. 48; 18. 45; Vā. 45. 116; Bhā. X. [50 (V) 3].

कुलिय
Kuliyas --a southern tribe. M. 114. 49.

कुलिशाङ्ग
Kuliśāṅga --see Vajrāṅga. M. 154. 31.

कुलिशायुध
Kuliśāyudha --Vajra as the arm of India; to be worshipped in house-building. M. 253. 24.

कुलोत्तीर्ण
Kulottīrṇas --a class of śaktis. Br. IV. 19. 35.

कुल्य
Kulya  (I)--a disciple of Pauṣyañji; learnt a hundred Sāma samhitas. Bhā. XII. 6. 79. 

कुल्य
Kulya  (II)--a son of Āṇḍira, after whom the Kulya deśa was called. Br. III. 74. 6.

कुल्य
Kulya  (III)--one of the four sons of Janāpīḍa; his country, Kulayāḥ. Vā. 99. 6.

कुल्य
Kulyas --the people of a southern kingdom, 1) Br. II. 16. 56; M. 114. 35 and 46. a Janapada. 2) Vā. 45. 110, 124.

कुवलय
Kuvalaya --the name of the horses of Pratardana. Vi. IV. 8. 15.

कुवलयापीड
Kuvalayāpīḍa --the state elephant of Kaṃsā. When Kṛṣṇa came to the Mallaraṅga or the wrestlers’ arena, it was ordered that this elephant should be stationed at the gate of the arena to attack him. When Kṛṣṇa entered the araṅga, the mahout Ambaṣṭha led the animal against him, when Kṛṣṇa took hold of its tail, and whirling it round and round, hit its front when it died with the keeper. He seized its tusks and entered the enclosure in glee. At this Kamsā was perturbed; its keeper was killed by Rāma. Bhā. X. 36. 24 [1], 25; 37. 15; 43. 1-18; Br. II. 73. 100; Vā. 98. 101; Vi. V. 12. 21; 15. 11, 17; 20. 23, 32-42; 29. 5.

कुवलयाश्व
Kuvalayāśva  (I)--the son of Bṛhadaśva (Śrāvasta-M. P.). At the desire of sage Ut(t)anka, he slew an Asura by name Dhundhu and earned the title Dhundhumāra. In this encounter he was helped by his 21,000 (1021-Vi. P.) sons, (brothers) all of whom excepting three (Dhṛḍhāśva, Bhadrāśva and Kapilāśva) were consumed by the fire issuing out of the Asura's mouth. 1) Bhā. IX. 6. 21-23; M. 12. 31; Vā. 88. 28, 48-61; Vi. IV. 2. 39-42. Lust after more territory. 2) Bhā. XII. 3. 10. See Dyumat. Kuvalāśva (s.v.) 3) Ib. IX. 17. 6. 

कुवलयाश्व
Kuvalayāśva  (II)--a name for Pratardana. Vi. IV. 8. 15.

कुवलाश्व
Kuvalāśva --see Kuvalayāśva. Br. III. 6. 32; 63. 29.

कुश
Kuśa  (I)--a son of Rāma, born in Vālmikī's āśrama and brought up by the sage. Father of Atithi. 1) Bhā. IX. 11. 11; 12. 1; M. 12-51; Vi. 4. 104-5. Ruled over Kosala kingdom from its capital Kuśasthalī. 2) Br. III. 63. 198; Vi. 88. 198-9.

कुश
Kuśa  (II)--a son of Ajaka; father of four sons, Kuśāmbu and others. Bhā. IX. 15. 4.

कुश
Kuśa  (III)--a son of Suhotra and father of Prati. Bhā. IX. 17. 3, 16.

कुश
Kuśa  (IV)--a son of Vidarbha. Bhā. 24. 1.

कुश
Kuśa  (V)--the son of Balākāśva. Father of Kauśāmba and three other sons. Br. III. 66. 31-2; Vi. IV. 7. 8.

कुश
Kuśa  (VI)--a son of Caidyoparicara (VidyoparicaraVā P.). M. 50. 27; Vā. 99. 202.

कुश
Kuśa  (VII)--a son of Gaya and father of four sons, all versed in the Vedas. Vā. 91. 61-2. 

कुश
Kuśa  (VIII)--(Kuśadvīpa, Kumudadvīpam?)--thrice the Suroda in size surrounded by Ghṛtoḍa (sea of Ghee) (milk ocean-M.P.). Its name comes from a shining divine cluster of grass in it. Its king was a son of Priyavrata, Hīraṇyaretas, who divided it among his seven sons. Here Agni is worshipped. 1) Bhā. V. 1. 32; 20. 13-17; M. 122. 49; Vā. 33. 12; 49. 47-58. Jyotiṣmat, its first king divided it among his seven sons. Their names, and the names of hills and rivers described. 2) Br. II. 14. 12-30; 19. 52-64. A tīrtham sacred to Kuśodakā 3) M. 13. 50. in the neighbourhood of Jambūdvīpa; 4) Vā. 48. 14. 34. of different villages and the residence of Kumuda the wily sister of Mahādeva. 5) Ib. 48. 34-35.

कुशा
Kuśās --a tribe. Br. III. 74. 268; M. 273. 73.

कुशध्वज
Kuśadhvaja  (I)--the son of Sīradhvaja and father of Dharmadhvaja; 1) Bhā. IX. 13. 19. overlord of Sānkāśya; 2) Br. III. 64. 19. brother of Bhānumān, lord of Kāśi. 3) Vā. 89. 1. 8.

कुशध्वज
Kuśadhvaja  (II)--the lord of Sāṅkāśya and brother of Sīradhvaja Janaka. Vi. IV. 5. 29.

कुशनाभ
Kuśanābha  (I)--one of the four sons of Kuśa. Bhā. IX. 15. 4; Br. III. 66. 32; Vā. 91. 62; Vi. IV. 7. 8.

कुशनाभ
Kuśanābha  (II)--a son of Vaivasvata Manu. M. 11. 41.

कुशप्रावरण
Kuśaprāvaraṇas(c) --the peoples of a hilly country. Vā. 45. 136. 

कुशप्लवनम्
Kuśaplavanam --On this Diti performed her penance. Br. III. 5. 55-6.

कुशरीर
Kuśarīra --a son of Vedaśiras, an avatār of the 15th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 169.

कुशल
Kuśala --a son of Dyutimat after whom Kauśala deśa came to be called. Br. II. 14. 22-24; Vā. 33. 21; Vi. II. 4. 48

कुशलम्
Kuśalam --the name of the forest where Diti performed penance to get a son to slay Indra. Vā. 67. 94.

कुशल
Kuśalas --a class of people in Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 16.

कुशलीमुख
Kuśalīmukha --a son of Bāṣkala. Vā. 67. 79.

कुशवती
Kuśavatī  (I)--the Apsara clan. Br. III. 7. 22.

कुशवती
Kuśavatī  (II)--a R. of the Ketumāla continent. Vā. 44. 18.

कुशस्तम्ब
Kuśastamba  (I)--a Mt. in Kuśadvīpa, after which the island is named. Br. II. 19. 139; M. 123. 37. 

कुशस्तम्ब
Kuśastamba  (II)--(Kuśanābha): performed austerities for 1000 years for a son; Indra the 1000 eyed offered himself to be born his son. Vā. 91. 63-5.

कुशस्थली
Kuśasthalī --see Dvārakā 1) Bhā. I. 10. 27; Br. III. 61. 20, ff; Vā. 88. 199. --capital of Ānarta (KośalaVā. P.) kingdom. Comparable once to Amarāvatī, disappeared; and in its place came Dvārakā; finding Kakudmi, its king not returning from Brahmaloka, Rākṣasas like Puṇyajanas entered it and his 99 brothers fled to different directions in fear, and established small kingdoms there. 2) M. 12. 22; 69. 9; Vā. 86, 24. 88. 1-2.

कुशा
Kuśā(a) --a son of Aśoka: ruled for eight years. Br. III. 74. 146.

कुशाग्र
Kuśāgra --the son of Bṛhadratha and father of Ṛṣabha. (Vṛṣabha-M.P.). Bhā. IX. 22. 6; M. 50. 28; Vā. 99. 223; Vi. IV. 19. 82.

कुशाम्ब
Kuśāmba  (I)--a son of Uparicara and a king of the Cedis. Bhā. IX. 22. 6.

कुशाम्ब
Kuśāmba  (II)--a son of Vasu. Vi. IV. 19. 81.

कुशाम्ब
Kuśāmba(u) --a son of Kuśa and father of Gādhi or Kauśīka, who was Indra himself who offered to be his son when Kuśāmba performed austerities to have a child equal to Indra. (Kuśāśva-Vā. P.). Bhā. IX. 15. 4; Br. III. 66. 32; Vi. IV. 7. 8, 9-11; Vā. 91. 62.

कुशावर्तम्
Kuśāvartam --a tīrtham sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 69. 

कुशावर्त
Kuśāvarta --a son of Ṛṣabha. Bhā. V. 4. 10.

कुशाश्व
Kuśāśva --one of the four sons of Kuśa. Vā. 91. 62.

कुशि
Kuśi --a son of Bali. Vā. 67. 83.

कुसिक
Kusika  (I)--the king who engaged himself in austerities for a son for one thousand years when Indra himself was born his son Gādhi by name. See Kusastamba. Br. III. 66. 33. 5.

कुशिक
Kuśika  (II)--a great sage (Vipraṛṣi). Vā. 1. 157.

कुशिक
Kuśika  (III)--a son of the Nakuli avatār of the lord. Vā. 23. 223.

कुशिक
Kuśika  (IV)--the thirteenth kalpa so-called. Vā. 21. 32.

कुशिकन्धर
Kuśikandhara --a son of the Aṭṭahāsa avaār of the lord. Vā. 23. 193.

कुशिकवर
Kuśikavaras --the 13 sages being descendants of Kuśika, father of Viśvāmitra mentioned. Br. II. 33. 118-19.

कुशिक
Kuśikas --descendants of Kuśika; 1) Bhā. IX. 16. 36-37. kingdom of: sages of. 2) M. 121. 54; 198. 8. 

कुशीतक
Kuśītaka --a son of Vasudeva and Rohiṇī. Br. III. 71. 165; Vā. 96. 163.

कुशीती
Kuśītī --one of the four chief disciples of Pauṣyañji. Vā. 61. 36.

कुसीद
Kusīda --(Kuśīdi-Br. P.) a pupil of Pauṣyañji; learnt a hundred Sāma samhitās. Bhā. XII. 6. 79; Br. II. 35. 40.

कुसीदकि
Kusīdaki --a sage. M. 196. 26.

कुशीदी
Kuśīdī --see Kuśīda. Br. II. 35. 40.

कुशुर
Kuśura --an asura who was attacked by Laghuśyāmā. Br. IV. 28. 40.

कुशेशय
Kuśeśaya  (I)--(Mt.) a hill of Kuśadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 55; Vā. 49. 50; Vi. II. 4. 41.

कुशेशय
Kuśeśaya  (II)--same as Kaṅka. M. 122. 58.

कुशेशयम्
Kuśeśayam --a tīrtham sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 76.

कुशोच्चय
Kuśoccayas --a group of sages. Br. III. 1. 55. 

कुसोदका
Kusodakā --a goddess enshrined at Kuśadvīpa. M. 13. 50.

कुषण्ड
Kuṣaṇḍas --a group of Piśācas with no ears, hair or cloth; all skin; fond of flesh. Br. III. 7. 379 and 387.

कुषण्डिक
Kuṣaṇḍikas --a group of Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 379 and 382.

कुष्टि
Kuṣṭi --a daughter of Sambhūti and Marici. Vā. 20. 9.

कुसु
Kusu --an Yakṣa, and a son of Devayāni. Br. III. 7. 128.

कुसुम
Kusuma --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 231.

कुसुमपुरम्
Kusumapuram --the city on the south bank of the Ganges founded by Udāyi in his fourth year. Vā. 99. 319.

कुसुमा
Kusumā  (I)--a Śaktī. Br. IV. 36. 76.

कुसुमा
Kusumā  (II)--the city founded by Udāyī on the south bank of the Ganges. Br. III. 74. 132.

कुसुमाकरम्
Kusumākaram --the Vimāna or flying machine. Br. IV. 15. 26. 

कुसुमामोदिनी
Kusumāmodinī --the presiding deity of the Himalayas who kept watch and ward over the harem of Umā until her return from tapas. M. 156. 1-7.

कुसुमायुध
Kusumāyudha --a name of Manmatha. Br. IV. 35. 62; M. 3. 10; 4. 11-2, 21; 14. 5-6.

कुसुमि
Kusumi --a Śrutaṛṣi: a pupil of Pauṣyañji. Br. II. 33. 8; 35. 40.

कुसुमोत्करम्
Kusumotkaram --a continent round Somaka hill. M. 122-24.

कुसुमोत्तर
Kusumottara --a son of Havya, after whom Kusumottara Varṣa was named. Br. II. 14. 17-20.

कुसुमोत्तरम्
Kusumottaram --a region of Śākadvīpa, adjoining the Asta hill. B. II. 14. 20; 19. 92; Vā. 49. 87.

कुसुमोद
Kusumoda --a son of Bhavya of Śākadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 60.

कुसुम्ब
Kusumba (kunkumam) --one of eight saubhāgyams. M. 60-9, 27.

कुस्तुम्बुरु
Kustumburu --a son of Maṇivasa. Vā. 69. 159.

कुह
Kuhas --people of the kingdom watered by the Sindhu. Br. II. 18. 47. 

कुहक
Kuhaka --a chief of the Krodhavaśa group of serpents (Nāgas). Bhā. V. 24. 29.

कुहरिणी
Kuhariṇī --a sacred place in Meru where Vyāsa performed austerities. Vā. 104. 61.

कुहू
Kuhū  (I)--a daughter of Aṅgiras and Śraddhā. (SmṛtiVi. P.). Wife of Dhātrī and mother of Sāya. Bhā. IV. 1. 34; VI. 18. 3; Br. II. 11. 18; Vā. 28. 15; 50. 201; 55. 42; 56. 9, 45 and 53; Vi. I. 10. 7.

कुहू
Kuhū  (II)--one of the nine devis serving Soma. Br. III. 65. 26; Vā. 90. 25.

कुहू
Kuhū  (III)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 32. 13.

कुहू
Kuhū  (IV)--a daughter of Maya; wife of Haviṣmanta, left him for Soma. M. 6. 21; 23. 25.

कुहू
Kuhū  (V)--the last phase of the new moon. It is the digit that disappears, and not the moon in Kuhū, as seen from Rāma's words to Rukmiṇī fit for giving gifts; 1) Bhā. X. 54. 47; Br. II. 26. 44; 28. 11 and 59; M. 133. 36; 141. 49, 51; Vi. II. 8. 80. served by Aila. ety. 2) M. 141. 9 and 43, 49, 51; Vā. 56. 53.

कुहू
Kuhū  (VI)--a R. from the Himalayas; of the Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 25; M. 114. 21; Vā. 45. 95. 

कुहू
Kuhū  (VII)--a R. of Śālmalidvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 10.

कुहु
Kuhu  (VIII)--the kingdom of. M. 121. 46.

कुह्व
Kuhva --the hour in which the moon is not visible. In the same way infancy and boyhood, the eleven forms of the notion of ‘I’ are not distinctly seen. Bhā. IV. 29. 72.

कूट
Kūṭa --a Malla friend of Kamsā. Killed by Balarāma. Bhā. X. 42. 37; 44. 26.

कूटक
Kūṭaka --a Mt. in Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 16.

कूटकम्बलमन्षीय
Kūṭakambalamanṣīyas  (c)--a Janapada of the Ketumāla. Vā. 44. 10.

कूटनाकूतन
Kūṭanākūtanas --a group of nāḍis of sun (fire) emitting rain. Br. II. 24. 27.

कूटयुद्ध
Kūṭayuddha --crafty warfare; Kuraṇḍa was an expert in. Br. IV. 22. 74; 25. 46, 55.

कूटशैल
Kūṭaśaila --(Mt.) a hill of Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 23; Vā. 45. 92.

कूटि
Kūṭi  (I)--one of the twenty Sutapa gaṇas. Vā. 100. 15. 

कूति
Kūti  (II)--a Jayādeva Br. III. 3. 6; 4. 2; Vā. 66. 6.

कूपक
Kūpaka --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 82.

कूपकर्ण
Kūpakarṇa --a minister of Bāṇa. Went with Jarāsandha to assault Mathurā. Fought with māyā as weapon which Kṛṣṇa removed by use of Vijñānāstra. Defeated by Kṛtavarman. Seeing Kumbhāṇḍa unconscious, fled towards the city. Was attacked by Balarāma in besieging Śonitapura, and was defeated. Bhā. X. [51 (V) 18], [28-30, 64-65]; 63. 8 and 16.

कूपलोचन
Kūpalocana --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 82.

कूपा
Kūpā --a R. of the Śuktimat. Vā. 45. 107.

कूर्च
Kūrca --the son of Mīḍhvān and father of Indrasena. Bhā. IX. 2. 19.

कूर्दिनि
Kūrdini --a Varṇa Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 60.

कूर्म
Kūrma --an avatār of Hari in the Pātālam. 1) Bhā. II. 7. 13; M. 249. 16, 20; Vi. I. 4. 8. In this form He is worshipped in Hiraṇmaya. By His help the churning of the ocean was possible. Also Kūrma-Kacchapa. 2) Bhā. V. 18. 29; XI. 4. 18: X. 2. 40. Icon of. 3) M. 259. 2; 260. 39; 285. 6. 

कूर्मकल्प
Kūrmakalpa --the age when Vāmana Purāṇa was composed. M. 53. 46.

कूर्मज
Kūrmaja --the flesh of tortoise for a śrāddha. M. 17. 33; 58. 19.

कूर्म
Kūrma (Purāṇa) --a Mahā purāṇa of 18000 ślokas (17000 ślokas, Bhā., Vā. P.); 1) Bhā. XII. 7. 24; 13. 8; Vi. III. 6. 23. said in the presence of Indra containing anecdotes of Indradyumna and of Lakṣmīkalpa. Gift of, with a golden tortoise on the ayanas equals a gift of 1000 cows. 2) M. 53. 47, 49; Vā. 104. 9.

कूर्मशिल
Kūrmaśila --the stone forming the lowest part of the base of an image. M. 266. 5.

कूष्माण्ड
Kūṣmāṇḍa --a Vināyaka. M. 183. 63.

कूष्माण्डगौतम
Kūṣmāṇḍa-Gautamas --the collective name for 1000 sons of Kakṣīvat. Br. III. 74. 99.

कूष्माण्ड
Kūṣmāṇḍa --a sūkta of the Yajur Vedins to be recited in tank rituals. M. 58. 35; 239. 10.

कूष्माण्ड
Kūṣmāṇḍas --a kind of evil spirits. To this group Kapi's sons belonged; said to harass children; 1) Bhā. VI. 8. 24; X. 6. 27; Br. III. 7. 384 and 41. 29. disturbed Dhruva's samādhi. 2) Vi. I. 12. 13. 

कूष्माण्डि
Kūṣmāṇḍi --the son of Kapiśa; gave birth to two Piśacās of brown colour; they have no head, no hair; they are eaters of flesh and tila. Vā. 69. 257, 268.

कृकण
Kṛkaṇa --a son of Bhajamāna. Vi. IV. 13. 2.

कृकवाकु
Kṛkavāku --a cock given by Vivasvat to his son Yama who was cursed by Chāyā, that his leg be full of sores; 1) M. 11. 11-17. cries out in presence of poisoned food; 2) Ib. 219. 19. an emblem of Kaumārī. 3) Ib. 261. 28.

कृच्छ्र
Kṛcchra --a mode of atonement for sins and crimes; Prājāpatya, a form of it. M. 227. 41-3, 52. Vā. 18. 21.

कृच्छ्रातिकृच्छ्रम्
Kṛcchrātikṛcchram --an expiation for yatis causing himsā even inadvertently. Vā. 18. 16.

कृत
Kṛta  (I)--the son of Jaya and father of Haryavana. Bhā. IX. 17. 17.

कृत
Kṛta  (II)--a son of Vasudeva and Rohiṇī. Bhā. IX. 24. 46.

कृत
Kṛta  (III)--a son of Sannati (M.P.); a pupil of Hiraṇyanābha; in yoga imparted twenty-four samhitas to his disciples; 1) Bhā. XII. 6. 80; Br. II. 35. 49 and 55; Vā. 99. 189-90; Vi. III. 16. 7. chief among the Sāmayas by arranging Sāma Veda in 24 parts. 2) M. 49. 75-6. Father of Ugrāyudha. 3) Vi. IV. 19. 50-3. 

कृत
Kṛta  (IV)--an Yakṣa and a son of Devayāni. Br. III. 7. 130.

कृत
Kṛta  (V)--married Śrutadevī; father of Sugrīva. M. 46. 5.

कृत
Kṛta  (VI)--a son of Viśvāmitra. Vā. 91. 96.

कृत
Kṛta  (VII)--a son of Kanaka. Vā. 94. 8.

कृत
Kṛta  (VIII)--a son of Hṛdika. Vā. 96. 139.

कृत
Kṛta  (IX)--a son of Cyavana. Vā. 99. 219.

कृत
Kṛta  (X)--a son of Vijaya; father of Haryadhana. Vi. IV. 9. 26-7.

कृतक
Kṛtaka  (I)--a son of Madirā and Vasudeva. Bhā. IX. 24. 48; Br. III. 71. 172; Vi. IV. 15. 23.

कृतक
Kṛtaka  (II)--a son of Cyavana and father of UparicaraVasu. Vi. IV. 19. 79-80.

कृतकृत्य
Kṛtakṛtya --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 241. 

कृतञ्जय
Kṛtañjaya  (I)--son of Barhi, and father of Raṇamjaya. Bhā. IX. 12. 13.

कृतञ्जय
Kṛtañjaya  (II)--the eighteenth Vedavyāsa. Heard the Br. Purāṇa from Dhanamjaya and narrated it to Tṛṇamjaya; 1) Br. II. 35. 121; IV. 4. 63. heard the Vāyu Purāṇa from Dhanamjaya. 2) Vā. 103. 62.

कृतञ्जय
Kṛtañjaya  (III)--the son of Dharmi, 1) Vā. 99. 287. and father of Raṇamjaya. 2) Vi. IV. 22. 6-7.

कृतदेव
Kṛtadeva --a son (?) of Viśvāmitra. Br. III. 66. 68; Vi. IV. 7. 38.

कृतद्युति
Kṛtadyuti --the senior queen of Citraketu who got a son through the blessings of Aṅgiras. When the child died of poison, she lamented deeply. Bhā. VI. 14. 28-48.

कृतधर्मन्
Kṛtadharman  (I)--a son of Samkṛti and a righteous man. Br. III. 68-11; Vā. 93. 11.

कृतधर्मन्
Kṛtadharman  (II)--a son of Dhanaka. Vi. IV. 11. 10.

कृतध्वज
Kṛtadhvaja --a son of Dharmadhvaja (Janaka-Vi. P.) and father of Keśidhvaja. Bhā. IX. 13. 19-20; Vi. 6. 7-8. 

कृतप्राप्ति
Kṛtaprāpti --a god of Sutāra group. Br. IV. 1. 90.

कृतबन्धु
Kṛtabandhu --a son of Tāmasa Manu. Br. II. 36. 50.

कृतम्
Kṛtam --sets in when the sun, moon, Tiṣya and Bṛhaspati (Planet Jupiter) are in the same mansion. Vi. IV. 24. 102.

कृतमाला
Kṛtamālā --a R. of Drāviḍa from Malaya hills in Bhāratavarṣa. In this Satyavrata offered water-rites to his Pitṛs. Visited by Balarāma. Bhā. V. 19. 18; VIII. 24. 12; XI 5. 39; X. 79. 16; Br. II. 16. 36; III. 35. 17; M. 114. 30; Vā. 45. 105; Vi. II. 3. 13

कृतयुग
Kṛtayuga  (also Kṛta)--commences when the sun, moon and Bṛhaspati are in one, and the same rāśī. Its characteristic features. 1) Bhā. XII. 2. 24; 3. 18-19, 27. Form of Hari as worshipped in this yuga, and worship by contemplation. 2) Ib. XI. 5. 21-23; IX. 10. 52; XII. 3. 52. Etymologically people in this age are kṛtakṛtyas. Hari took the form of a vṛṣa (bull) for the manifestation of dharma. Hamsa was the caste name of men. 3) Ib. XI. 17. 10-11. Its duration; repeats at the end of Kaliyuga. Pitṛs are worshipped. 4) Br. II. 16. 69; 29. 24-31; 31. 103. 11; III. 14. 46-7; 74. 225; M. 1. 34; 142. 19 and 24; 144. 90; 145. 6-7; 165. 1. Physical and moral state of world in; duration 4000 divine years; sandhya, and sandhyāmśa 108 years; dhyāna important in; sandhyāmśa 400 = Prakrīyāpāda; 5) Vā. 8. 32-67. after Kali with seven sages; at the beginning man in Kalinga; 6) Ib. 58. 103, 110. pertaining to the Brahmanas; Vedas honoured. 7) Ib. 78. 36-7. People with no restrictions lived on roots and fruits enjoying sexual bliss; jñānam. 8) Ib. 99. 413. Br. II. 7. 21, 45-59. 

कृतरथ
Kṛtaratha --the son of Pratika and father of Devamīḍha. Vi. IV. 5. 27.

कृतरात
Kṛtarāta --the son of Mahādhṛti and father of Mahāroma. Vi. IV. 5. 27.

कृतलक्षण
Kṛtalakṣaṇa --a son of Mādrī and Vṛṣṇi. M. 45. 2.

कृतवर्मन्
Kṛtavarman  (I)--the eldest son of Hṛdīka. Bhā. I. 14. 28; IX. 24. 27; Br. III. 71. 140; M. 44. 81; Vā. 96. 139; Vi. 14. 24.

कृतवर्मन्
Kṛtavarman  (II)--a son of Dhanaka. Bhā. IX. 23. 23.

कृतवर्मन्
Kṛtavarman  (III)--was stationed to defend the East gate of Mathurā by Kṛṣṇa. Defeated Kūpakarṇa, a minister of Bāṇa; was sent to Hāstinapura by Kṛṣṇa to find out whether Pānḍavas had captured Drupada. He went and met Droṇa, Vidura and others, when Yudhiṣṭhīra made enquiries of Kṛṣṇa. He returned to Dvārakā after taking leave of them and narrated to Kṛṣṇa as he saw and heard; joined with Akrūra to set up Śatadhanvan to kill Satrājit and take the jewel Syamantaka (s.v.) as he did not give his daughter in marriage as promised. Refused to help Śatadhanvan who solicited for it. 1) Bhā. X. 50. 20[2]; [51 (V) 25], [30-31 and 64]; [56 (V) 2-15]; 57. 3-18; Vi. IV. 13. 67-83. Was sent with the sacrificial horse of Kṛṣṇa. 2) Bhā. X. 8-9. 22 [2]. After the Rājasūya, he was sent to Dvārakā for its defence. 3) Ib. X. 76. 7[5]. Went to Upalāvya to see the Pāṇḍavas, and to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse. 4) Ib. X. 78 [95 (V) 3]; 82. 7. His son was married to Cārumatī, a daughter of Rukminī. 5) Ib. X. 61. 24. Survived Kurukṣetra war; 6) Ib. X. 80. [2]. Heard of Śatadhanva's death at Kṛṣṇa's hands, and left Dvārakā in fear. 7) Ib. X. 57, 29. Got killed in the general Yādava contest. 8) Vi. V. 37. 46. 

कृतवर्मन्
Kṛtavarman  (IV)--a son of Kanaka. Br. III. 69. 8; M. 43. 13; Vā. 94. 8.

कृतवाच
Kṛtavāca --a mantrakṛt. M. 145. 101.

कृतवीर्य
Kṛtavīrya  (I)--a son of Dhanaka (Kanaka-Br. P., M.P. and Vā. P.) of Arjuna (Kārtavīrya): 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 23-4; Br. III. 69. 8; M. 43. 13; Vā. 94. 8; Vi. IV. 11. 10-11. A king of the Haihaya clan born in the Kṛtayuga of Vaivasvata epoch, Varāha kalpa. His hundred sons died on account of a curse by Cyavana. He prayed to Sun god who taught him a vratam, by observing which he got a long lived child. 2) M. 68. 6-12.

कृतवीर्य
Kṛtavīrya  (II)--a Deva-gandharva. Vā. 68. 38.

कृतशर्म
Kṛtaśarma --a son of Iḍiviḍa. Vā. 88. 181.

कृतशौच
Kṛtaśauca --the sacred spot where Nṛsimha blessed the Mother Goddess: Here Rudra established his Raudri body in the midst of ‘seven mothers’. Here is Ardhanārīśvara praying to Nṛsimha; 1) M. 179. 87-90. a tīrtham sacred to Suṅhikā. 2) Ib. 13. 45.

कृतस्थलि
Kṛtasthali(a) --the Apsaras who presides over the month of Madhu; 1) Bhā. XII. 11-33. coupled with Ghṛtācī. 2) Br. III. 7. 15; IV. 33. 19.

कृताग्नि
Kṛtāgni --a son of Dhanaka (Kanaka-Br. P., M. P.). Bhā. IX. 23. 23; Br. III. 69. 8; M. 43. 13; Vi. IV. 11. 10-11. 

कृतान्त
Kṛtānta  (I)--a son of Svārociṣa Manu. Br. II. 36. 19; Vā. 62. 18.

कृतान्त
Kṛtānta  (II)--a name of Yama. M. 148. 30.

कृताहार
Kṛtāhāra --a Vānara chieftain, and son of Śveta. Br. III. 7. 180.

कृति
Kṛti  (I)--a son of Bahulāśva, and father of the great Vaśin--the last of the Maithilas (of the Janaka line). Bhā. IX. 13. 26; Br. III. 64. 23; Vā. 89. 23; Vi. IV. 5. 31-2.

कृति
Kṛti  (II)--a son of Nahuṣa. Bhā. IX. 18. 1; Br. III. 68. 12; Vi. IV. 10. 1.

कृति
Kṛti  (III)--a son of Babhru and father of Uśika. Bhā. IX. 24. 2.

कृति
Kṛti  (IV)--a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu. Br. II. 36. 79 and 106.

कृति
Kṛti  (V)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 241.

कृति
Kṛti  (VI)--a Sutapa god. Br. IV. 1. 14.

कृति
Kṛti  (VII)--a son of Bhautya Manu. Br. IV. 1. 114.

कृति
Kṛti  (VIII)--one of the two best Sāmagas. Vā. 61. 48; 62. 67. 

कृति
Kṛti  (IX)--a son of Maṇivara. Vā. 69. 161.

कृति
Kṛti  (X)--a son of Vasiṣṭha, one of the seven sages of Ṛtu sāvarṇa. Vā. 100. 96.

कृति
Kṛti  (XI)--a son of Śatadhvaja and father of Añjana. Vi. IV. 5. 31.

कृतिन्
Kṛtin  (I)--a son of Sannatīmat. Learnt yoga from Hiraṇyanābha, and sang the six early sāma samhitas. Father of Nīpa. Bhā. IX. 21. 28-29.

कृतिन्
Kṛtin  (II)--a son of Cyavana and father of Vasu Uparicara. Bhā. IX. 22. 5.

कृतिमत्
Kṛtimat --a son of Yavīnara and father of Satyadhṛti. Bhā. IX. 21. 27.

कृतिरथ
Kṛtiratha --(Kṛtaratha-Br. P.) the son of Pratīpaka and father of Devamīḍha. Bhā. IX. 13. 16.

कृतिरात
Kṛtirāta --a son of Mahādhṛti and father of Mahāroman. Bhā. IX. 13. 17.

कृती
Kṛtī  (I)--(Ākūti-Br. P.) the wife of Viśvakarman. Bhā. VI. 6. 15. 

कृती
Kṛtī  (II)--the queen of Samhrāda and mother of Pañcajana. Bhā. VI. 18. 14.

कृतेयु
Kṛteyu --one of the ten sons of Raudrāśva. Vā. 99. 124.

कृतौजस्
Kṛtaujas --a son of Dhanaka (Kanaka-Br. P., M. P.). Bhā. IX. 23. 23; Br. III. 69. 8; M. 43. 13; Vi. IV. 11. 10.

कृत्तिकस्
Kṛttikas --The Pleidas; a lunar mansion; personified. Six in number, nursed Kumāra: wives of Soma, childless due to Dakṣa's curse. 1) Bhā. IV. 7. 64; VI. 6. 14 and 23; Br. IV. 30. 100; M. 5. 27; 54. 11; 55. 12; 158. 41; Vā. 72. 43; Vi. I. 15. 115; II. 8. 76. An important day for the śrāḍdha offerings, sacred to moon. 2) Br. II. 21. 77 and 145; 24. 130; III. 10. 44; 18. 2. A constellation containing six stars. 3) Vā. 66. 48. 82. 2.

कृत्तिकस्
Kṛttikas --a parva; when the sun goes to the first amśa, the moon is in the fourth amśa of Viśākha. Vā. 23. 107; 50. 96; 53. 105.

कृत्तिकाचारिणी
Kṛttikācāriṇī --see Dhiṣṇi. Br. II. 12. 17.

कृत्तिवास
Kṛttivāsa --a name of Śiva. Satī who was created by Brahmā was given to him and a number of sons were born who were of all shapes and crude forms and called generally Rudras; they were partakers of the offerings in Śatarudra. On Brahmā's request he did not procreate but became Sthāṇu and Mahādeva. Br. II. 9. 69; III. 25. 14: 72. 184; M. 181. 14 ch. Vā. 21. 51. 

कृत्वी
Kṛtvī --a daughter of Śuka and Pīvarī, and mother of Brahmadatta; married the Pāñcāla king Aṇuha; known also as Gau. Bhā. IX. 21. 25; M. 15. 8-9; 49. 57.

कृप
Kṛpa  (I)--(Kṛpaśāradvata) the son of Satyadhṛti (Śaradvat-Br. P.), found in a forest by Śantanu with the twin Kṛpī. 1) Bhā. IX. 21. 36; X. 82. 24; Vā. 99. 204; 100. 11; 106. 34; Vi. IV. 19. 68. Met by Kṛtavarman, Rāma and Kṛṣṇa; 2) Bhā. X. 52. [56 (V) 4, 12]; 57. 2. invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira. 3) Ib. X. 74. 10. Joined Duryodhana's camp and survived the Kurukṣetra war. 4) Ib. X. 78. [95 (V) 16]; 80. [2]. Went to Syamantapāñcaka for solar eclipse. 5) Ib. 82. 24. Supplied arms to Śatānīka. 6) Vi. IV. 21. 4.

कृप
Kṛpa  (II)--a son of Śiṣṭa and Succāyā. M. 4. 39.

कृप
Kṛpa  (III)--a sage of the eighth epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 17.

कृपणा
Kṛpaṇā --a deity. Br. IV. 27. 38.

कृपा
Kṛpā --a R. from the Śuktimat (Śuktimanta-M. P.). Br. II. 16. 38; M. 114. 32.

कृपि
Kṛpi --one of the ten branches of the Sukarma clan of devas. Vā. 100. 92.

कृपी
Kṛpī --(Gautamī) the wife of Droṇa, and daughter of Satyadhṛti, found by Śantanu in the forest. Mother of Aśvatthāma. Bhā. I. 7. 45; 13. 4; IX. 21. 36; Vā. 99. 204; Vi. IV. 19. 68. 

कृमि
Kṛmi  (I)--the son of Kṛmi and Uśīnara. His capital was Kṛmilā (Krimilā-Vā. P.). Br. III. 74. 20-21; Vā. 99. 20, 22; Vi. IV. 18. 9

कृमि
Kṛmi  (II)--a son of Cyavana. M. 50. 25.

कृमिचण्डेश्वरम्
Kṛmicaṇḍeśvaram --a place sacred to Śiva. M. 181. 29.

कृमिभक्ष
Kṛmibhakṣa --a hell into which fall those who misuse gems (ratna); see also kṛmī. Br. IV. 2. 147 and 160; Vā. 101. 147, 158.

कृमिभोजन
Kṛmibhojana --one of 28 hells. He who eats without doing Pañcayajña, and does not share his food with others, suffers in this, a pit of worms. Bhā. V. 26. 7 and 18.

कृमिल
Kṛmila --a son of Bhajamāna. M. 44. 50.

कृमीला
Kṛmīlā --capital city of Kṛmi. Br. III. 74. 22; Vā. 99. 22.

कृमी
Kṛmī  (I)--one of the five queens of Uśinara; mother of Kṛmi. Br. III. 74. 18-21; Vā. 99. 19.

कृमी
Kṛmī  (II)--a hell; also kīṭaloham, and krmibhakṣa; 1) Br. IV. 2. 147 and 159; 33. 61. here fall those who do wicked deeds, hate gods and Brāhmanas and do not revere elders. 2) Vā. 101. 147, 158.

कृश
Kṛśa  (I)--a Vaikuṇṭha god. Br. II. 36. 57. 

कृश
Kṛśa  (II)--a son of Kṛśā and Uśīnara; capital was Vṛṣalā. M. 48. 18 and 21.

कृश
Kṛśa sarman --the son of Iḍviḍa, and father of Dilīpa Khatvāṅga. Br. III. 63. 181.

कृशा
Kṛśā --one of the five queens of Uśīnara. Mother of Kṛśa. M. 48. 16, 18.

कृशाङ्गी
Kṛśāṅgī --a daughter of Suyaśā. Vā. 69. 14.

कृशानु
Kṛśānu --an indefinite Agni in the second Vedi of the north. See Samrāḍagni. Br. II. 12. 21; Vā. 29. 19.

कृशाश्व
Kṛśāśva  (I)--a son of Saṃyama; married two daughters of Dakṣa, Arcis and Dhiṣanā; and father of Somadatta and the Devapraharaṇas are created and destroyed in every kalpa and manvantara. 3) M. 6. 6-7. ^1 Bhā. VI. 6. 2 and 20; IX. 2. 34-35; M. 5. 14; 146. 17; Vā. 63. 42; 86. 20; Vi. I. 15. 104; IV. 1. 55-6. ^2 Vā. 66. 79.

कृशाश्व
Kṛśāśva  (II)--the son of Barhaṇāśva, and father of Senājit. Bhā. IX. 6. 25.

कृशाश्व
Kṛśāśva  (III)--a Carakādhvaryu; married a daughter of Dakṣa. Br. II. 33. 13; 37. 46.

कृशाश्व
Kṛśāśva  (IV)--a son of Tāmara Manu. Br. II. 36. 50.

कृशाश्व
Kṛśāśva  (V)--a son of Sahadeva and highly righteous. Br. III. 61. 15. 

कृशाश्व
Kṛśāśva  (VI)--a son of Samhatāśva. Br. III. 63. 65; Vā. 88. 63.

कृशाश्व
Kṛśāśva  (VII)--father of Devapraharaṇa. Vi. I. 15. 137.

कृशाश्व
Kṛśāśva  (VIII)--a son of Amitāśva and father of Prasenajit. Vi. IV. 2. 46-7.

कृषि
Kṛṣi --the pursuit of agriculture, a duty of the Vaiśya; introduced by Pṛthu. Br. II. 7. 162; Vā. 79. 71; Vi. I. 13. 84.

कृष्टि
Kṛṣṭi --a daughter of Marīcī. Br. II. 11. 12.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (I)--twenty-three avatār of Hari; according to one version, the twentieth avatār. Went to Dvārakā, bowed to his parents and entered the palace. 1) Bhā. I. 2. 17; 3. 23; Chaps. 10 and 11; M. 7. 60. His boyhood sports--sucked Ulūkika's life, kicked Śakaṭa to pieces and uprooted two Arjuna trees; brought solace to the Gopas of Vraja by expelling the serpent Kāliya from the pool near by and protected their cattle from forest fire. In his mouth Yaśodā saw the fourteen worlds. Rescued Nanda from fear of Varuṇa's noose and recovered the Gopas imprisoned by Vyoma Asura. Shielded the Gokulam from rains by holding up Govardhana Mt. as an umbrella; cut off the head of Kubera's attendant who tried to seize the Gopis engaged in Rāsakṝḍā with Kṛṣṇa. Vanquished several daityas and their wicked kings; manifested Himself through Satyavatī and divided the Vedas into many branches; 2) Bhā. II. 7. 26-36. Lord and goal of Andhakas, Vṛṣṇis, Sātvatas, etc. Supreme Brahman. 3) Bhā. II. 4. 20; VII. 15. 76-79.  Just on the eve of the avatār, Brahmā and other gods pray to him in the womb of Devakī. 4) Ib. X. Chaps. 1-3; M. 46. 14; Vā. 96. 174. Birth at the time of constellation Rohiṇi, first new moon in winter, Abhijit Nakṣatra, Jayanti night, Vijaya-muhūrta and festivities connected with it; enjoyed by Vasudeva and Devakī. Their prayer, and Kṛṣṇa recalled their previous births. Taken to Yaśodā's delivery room at Nandavraja, stupifying the guardsmen of the jail and crossing Yamunā in floods at dead of night; Yogamāyā born to Yaśodā taken back to the jail ward. 5) Bhā. X. Chaps. (whole); Br. III. 71. 196-263; 72. 7-13; Vi. V. 1. 98; 3. 1-29. Yogamāyā announced her birth to Kaṃsā, 6) Bhā. X. Chap. 4, Vā. 96. 199. 215. His jātakarmā. 7) Bhā. X. 5. 1-16. Killed Pūtanā, when at Kamsā's instance, she attempted to poison him by nursing him; Yaśodā warded off evil, (Rakṣā) to Kṛṣṇa by waving cow's tail round him, by placing cow's dung on the twelve points of his body and by purifying him with cow's urine, with prayers to Hari to protect him from evil spirits. 8) Ib. X. 6; Vi. V. 5. 12-31. The first turning in bed was celebrated with festivity. Kṛṣṇa slept under cradle beneath the cart when he kicked the cart which capsized. This roused suspicion of gṛhapīḍa in Yaśodā's mind. Śānti done when cows, food, etc., were given to Brahmanas. Once the demon Tṛṇāvarta created a whirlwind which swept away all Vraja and took up baby Kṛṣṇa high up in the sky to the embarassment of Yaśodā and others. At that time Kṛṣṇa took hold of his neck and strangled him. He fell dead. The child Kṛṣṇa opened his mouth and showed his mother the whole universe. 9) Bhā. X. 7; Vi. V. 6. 1-7.

नामकरणम्
Nāmakaraṇam  as Vāsudeva. Boyish sports in Vraja, charged with eating mud; lived with Nanda and his wife who were the same Droṇa and Dharā born as Nanda and Yaśodā by the command of Brahmā. When once Yaśodā left the churning pot to mind the boiling milk overflowing in the oven, Kṛṣṇa broke the curd pot and ran away with butter to feed a monkey. So he was bound with a rope to an ulūkhala (mortar) but the rope always fell two inches  short in spite of bits being added. At last Kṛṣṇa pitied her and allowed himself to be tied; with the mortar he passed between two tall Arjuna trees, when down fell the trees, out of which emerged two men Nalakubera and Maṇigrīva (sons of Kubera) who had been cursed by Nārada. Kṛṣṇa blessed them and sent them back to their abode. 10) Bhā. X. Chaps. 8, 9 and 10; Vi. V. 6, 8-19. Enjoyed the company of Gopis singing and dancing. Gifts on his janmanakṣatra day. Noticed a Daitya in the guise of a calf and taking him by the tail, he whirled him to death and flung the body on the top of a kapitha tree. On another occasion Asura Baka met him in the guise of a crane, when Kṛṣṇa tore its jaws asunder. Once when in the forest with his playmates, Agha, an asura friend of Kaṃsā took the form of a boa-constrictor with a view to devour the cattle and all boys together. All of them entered his open mouth with Kṛṣṇa who took his life out of his body and came out to the wonderment of gods. The ajāgara skin when dried was a cave for Vraja people. Agha, however, attained salvation. 11) Bhā. X. Chap. II. One day the boys sat and ate merrily when the cattle had gone far into the hill and dale and Kṛṣṇa promised to bring them back. In the meantime Brahmā had them hidden. So Kṛṣṇa created duplicates of the cattle and the children that had been lost. These went home as usual and this continued for a year, when Brahmā released the hidden cows which suckled their calves, and came to see the child, the one Brahman without a second, and belauded the baby Hari, and returned to his region. More boyhood sports. 12) Ib. X. Chaps. 13 and 14; Vi. V. 6. 30 to the end of Chap. 9. In regularly tending cows, imitated voice of beasts and birds in Brindāvana just like a rustic. Once the cattle drank of the poisonous waters of the Yamunā and became unconscious. After reviving them he found the reptile Kālīya in the waters. He immediately jumped into the pool and was enclosed in its coils. At this Nanda and the whole Vraja moved to the banks of the river with great concern.  Rāma advised them to be cool. Slowly Kṛṣṇa brought the reptile under his control, and getting on its hood, began to dance, when the Kālīya acknowledged defeat. Finding his end near, Kālīya's wives prayed to Kṛṣṇa to spare him. The generous Lord allowed him to make his abode in the sea, thus purifying the Yamunā once for all. 13) Bhā. X. Chaps. 15 and 16. Vi. V. 7 (whole). After this incident the whole Vraja was encamped for the night in that vicinity. A forest fire attacked the camp, when Kṛṣṇa swallowed it and protected its inmates. His dances and songs; other past-times. Among the games was one in which the victor rode on the back of the vanquished. Kṛṣṇa carried Śrīdāma on his back. 14) Bhā. X. Chaps. 17 and 18. Once again the cattle went astray in the thick forest, and surrounded by fire they bellowed in thirst and hunger. Kṛṣṇa and his playmates found it impossible to reach the spot. So Kṛṣṇa got upon a tree and called the cattle by names, and they responded. Asking his followers to shut their eyes, he swallowed the forest fire. When they opened their eyes, they found themselves in their homes. 15) Ib. X. 19. 1-13. Kṛṣṇa filled Brindāvana with Gāndharvan music and played at times on flute. Hid the clothes of Gopis who observed Kātyāyani vrata to get him as their husband, and returned them only when they saluted with their two hands over their heads as a penance for bathing naked during the period of a vrata. It was a severe day in summer when some Gopas approached him for food. Kṛṣṇa advised them to go to the neighbouring yajñaśāla and ask for food, singing the praises of Balarāma and himself. The sacrificers were silent at their request. Kṛṣṇa asked them to repeat their request to ladies in his name. The ladies took four kinds of food and in spite of protest by their male relations, they came to have darsan of the Lord and placed before Him all the eatables. On Kṛṣṇa's advice they went back to complete the sacrifice, and assured them of their being accepted by their relations and the world. Their male relations  regretted having missed a chance of meeting the Lord. Then food was distributed among his friends. 16) Bhā. X. Chaps. 21-23. Kṛṣṇa saw the Gopas worshipping Indra and as residents of hills and forests, he suggested worship of mountains and cows. When this was accepted, Indra sent a heavy downpour which was warded off by Kṛṣṇa, a boy of seven, 17) Ib. X. Chaps. 24-26; Vi. V. 10. 25-41; 11. 16-25; 13. 3-62. holding up the Govardhana for a week. A visit from Indra and Surabhi who anointed him, Indra, of Goloka and gave him a new name Govinda. Rescued his father Nanda from Varuṇa region and took him with other Gopas to Brahmaḥrada where the Vedas were praising Hari. Once when playing on a flute, the Gopīs who were in the midst of household duties stopped them and came to where he was in spite of protest from their male relations. Kṛṣṇa advised them to go back to Vraja and be loyal to their husbands. They refused to return as their minds were fixed upon him and longed for mokṣa, and insisted they were his dāsis and should be accepted. After some time he disappeared for their peace and redemption. They indulged in gītam, when the Lord appeared in their midst and shone like Puruṣa among śaktis. After consoling them he engaged them in a rāsakrīḍa, and finding them wearied, he engaged them in watersports and sports in the upavana on the river-bank. There was no carnal act of sin. The Lord who had no bandha, did all this in sport. 18) Bhā. X. Chaps. 27-33; Vi. IV. 12. 12. Released Nanda from a reptile who turned out to be vidyādhara Sudarśana. One day Śankhacūda a follower of Kaṃsā seized some ladies of Kṛṣṇa's party and ran away. They cried for succour. Kṛṣṇa and Rāma followed. He left the women behind and ran. Rāma took charge of the ladies while Kṛṣṇa pursued him, cut off his head and took the cūḍāmaṇi which he presented to Rāma. Killed Arīṣṭa in the form of a bull who entered the Vraja and terrified the inmates. 19) Bhā. X. Chaps. 34-36; Vi. V. Chap. 14.  Killed Keśin who came to the Vraja in the guise of a horse and became Keśava; killed one Vyoma in the guise of a gopāla; seen milking cows with Rāma by Akrūra who came to Dvārakā at the instance of Kaṃsā; agreed readily to start for Mathurā at Akrūra's message. With Akrūra, the two brothers arrived at Mathurā. and asked their friend to go home. He requested them to visit his house to which they agreed only after vanquishing Kaṃsā. Next day afternoon, the two brothers and their Gopa followers went round the city and the women from terraces enjoyed the sight of Kṛṣṇa and Rāma. On the way he met a washerman and asked for good clothes. On his refusal, he was killed, and all his clothes taken and distributed to his Gopas. Then they met a garland-maker Sudāma who voluntarily offered flowergarlands. Him he blessed and went. Next he saw a hunchback woman carrying unguents to Kaṃsā. For the mere asking she offered the whole of it to them. So Kṛṣṇa converted her to a handsome lady who invited him to her house. This was agreed after finishing his work. Then they went through the bazaar and were rewarded with betels, sandal, etc., by merchants. Lastly they entered the place where the bow festival was held. Kṛṣṇa broke it easily. The guards who attacked them were put to death. It was evening when they returned to the camp outside the city. 20) Bhā. X. Chaps. 37. 42; Vi. V. 16. 7-16, 23; Chaps. 18, 19. On his way to the wrestlers' arena, Kṛṣṇa vanquished Kuvalayāpīḍa with some effort. Taking its tusks, entered the enclosure with Balarāma. Accepted challenge from the wrestler Cānūra. The latter fell dead after fighting. The same fate met Śala and Tośalaka. Finding Kaṃsā ready to attack his relations, Kṛṣṇa overpowered him and killed him in a minute: condoled with the women of the dead and set his parents free; consoled his parents for their troubles and was embraced by them in love. Enthroned Ugrasena, as Yadus could not sit on the throne owing to a curse of Yayāti. A regin of peace ushered in Mathurā. 21) Bhā. X. Chaps. 43-44 and 46. 1-19; Vi. V. 9. 8-33; Chap. 20.  Nanda and Gopas were sent back to Vraja with honours. Upanayanam of Kṛṣṇa. With Balarāma Kṛṣṇa went to Sāndīpani and learnt all arts in 64 days. Hearing that Sāndīpani's son was washed away by the sea at Prabhāsā, Kṛṣṇa went to the spot and was told by the seagod that an Asura Pañcajana carried him off. Then he went to Yama's abode, and recovering his son, handed him over to the guru as gurudakṣiṇa and came home. Requested Uddhava to go to Vraja with a message from him to Nanda and Gopis that he would be visiting them shortly. As promised he went to Sairandhri's house with Uddhava. It was decorated according to rules of Kāmaśāstra, and after a brief stay, left it for Akrūra's with Uddhava and Rāma. Akrūra extended a royal welcome. Kṛṣṇa praised him as their guru and requested him to go to Hāstinapur and find out the position of the Pāṇḍavas. Returned to their residence. 22) Bhā. X. 45. 20-49; Chaps. 46-48; Vi. V. 25. 19-31. Kṛṣṇa heard of the siege of Mathurā by Jarāsandha and was devising a plan of attack when two chariots descended from heaven fully armoured. Also Sudarśana, his cakra and other weapons came down to him and to Rāma. Rāma took a chariot and the hala (plough), but was considered by Jarāsandha as a boy and not his equal. Kṛṣṇa made defence arrangements at the four gates, and went out in his chariot of Garuda ensign by the northern gate to where Caidya and Māgadha were. Caidya's challenge and death; prevented Rāma from fettering Jarāsandha, and entered the city in victory and gave the spoils of war to Ugrasena, their king. Second and third defence of Mathurā. Prevented Kumbhāṇḍa and Kūpakarṇa from using māyā in war by the application of vijñānāstra. Honoured after victory by the Sabhā of the Yadus. 23) Bhā. X. Chaps. 50-52 (v). He next desired to see Gomanta and the hill fortress. Left with Rāma towards the south crossing the Yamunā, and many towns and villages. Saw on the way Paraśurāma engaged in austere tapas and bowed to him. Paraśurāma  suggested killing Śrgālavāsudeva, a wicked chieftain of Karavīrapura at the foot of the Gomanta. When they reached the place, Śṛgālavāsudeva offered fight, and his head was cut off by Kṛṣṇa. Welcomed by the citizens of Karavīrapura, they spent there four months after sending the spoils of war to Mathurā. Got up the hill Gomanta where Garuḍa met Kṛṣṇa and placing his crown on his head, left. Reached Mathurā with a large army. Finding Yavana besieging the city and Jarāsandha leading the eighteenth expedition,, Kṛṣṇa in consultation with Rāma resolved to build a fortress of 12 yojanas in the sea to place their kith and kin in security. So a city was built according to Vāstu śāstra to which Indra sent Sudharmā and Pārijāta. Varuṇa supplied horses and Kubera the eight Nidhis. It became a Yādava settlement. Attacked by (Kāla) Yavana, Kṛṣṇa unarmed fled to the cave where Mucukunda was asleep. Here Yavana was burnt to ashes by Mucukunda's energy. Mucukunda's surprise to see Kṛṣṇa and his prayer for salvation. Kṛṣṇa spoke of his future birth as Brāhmaṇa and final salvation. 24) Ib. X. Chap. 53 (v) and 50-51; Vi. V. Chaps. 22-3. Kṛṣṇa returned to Ugrasena at Mathurā, raised the siege of Yavana troops and went to Dvārakā with his plunder. On the way Jarāsandha's army in makara vyūha attacked him but was broken by throwing a huge tree. Returned to Dvārakā with spoils of war left by Yavanas. Jarāsandha's attack again when Rāma and Kṛṣṇa fled to the Gomanta whose topcrest was burnt, while Jarāsandha thought they were dead they reached Dvārakā safe. 25) Bhā. X. Chap. 52; Vi. V. 24. 1-7. Sent Kṛtavarṇa to ascertain from Hāstināpura whether Pāṇḍavas had defeated Drupada. Married Rukmiṇi by the Rākṣasa form of marriage, defeating Jarāsandha and others of the Caidya party in battle. Received with due honours the Brāhmaṇa messenger from Rukmiṇi and promised to do the needful. With the Brāhmaṇa and Rāma, Kṛṣṇa drove from Ānartas to Vidarbhas in a night. Was honoured by Bhīṣmaka and allotted separate residence outside his capital. Ladies of  Kuṇḍina said that Kṛṣṇa was suitable to Rukmiṇi. Seeing Rukmiṇi returning from the Devi temple, he took her in his chariot in the midst of other kings and drove fast. Jarāsandha and others pursued but soon returned with disappointment. Rukmi's resolve to kill Kṛṣṇa and then enter Kuṇḍina. When he offered battle and was about to be killed, Rukmini appealed to the Lord to save her brother. At this he was tied to the chariot with his hair and moustache shaved. Advised by Rāma that punishment of Rukmī was not in order. Married Rukmiṇi according to Śāśtras amidst festivities in Dvārakā. Owing to Śiva's grace, got sacred sons of whom one was Pradyumna by Rukmiṇī, being Kāma in a previous birth. Killed Sambara who stole the baby. Saw the lost Pradyumna and his wife Ratī in his residence, and hearing their account from Nārada, embraced the couple. Present at Pradyumna's marriage. 26) Bhā. X. Chaps. 53-55; Vi. V. 26. 2-11; Chap. 27; 28. 2-8. Requested Satrājita to give the Syamantaka gem for their king but he refused. Suspected by Satrājita to be responsible for his brother Prasena's disappearance in the forest; recovered the jewel from Jāmbavan after fighting for 28 days, and got also his daughter Jāmbavatī in marriage. The jewel was returned to Satrājita in the public assembly. Married Satrājita's daughter Satyabhāmā, and when the jewel was offered, it was returned. Went with Rāma to the Kurus after the rumoured death of the Pāṇḍavas and Kunti; met the Pāṇḍavas at Pāñcāla city in the guise of Brāhmaṇas; killed Śatadhanvan, the murderer of his father-in-law Satrājita. Sent for Akrūra and asked him to exhibit Syamantaka in his possession, and returned it to him afterwards. 27) Bhā. X. Chaps. 56-57; Br. III. 7. 301; 36. 15 and 21; 68-28; 71. 46-96; M. 45. 34; Vi. IV. 13. 64-98. 142-157. Kṛṣṇa once went to Hāstināpura to see the Pāṇḍavas and was heartily welcomed. Paid respects to Yudhiṣṭhira and Bhīma, embraced Arjuna and received respects from Nakula and Sahadeva. Kuntī welcomed him also. When he was spending that winter there, he went to the forest  with Arjuna for hunting and there met an accomplished lady when Arjuna addressed. Hearing that she was the daughter of the Sun waiting to marry Kṛṣṇa, the latter took her home. In the meantime Kṛṣṇa asked Viśvakarmā to build a city for the Pāṇḍavas. Acting as Arjuna's charioteer, he caused the Khāṇḍava forest to be given over to fire. Returned to Dvārakā and married Kālindī, Sun's daughter. Then he married Mitravindā of Avanti, an aunt's daughter. Received Satyā, daughter of Nagnajit of Ayodhyā by curbing the ferocity of seven bulls, with a large dowry of chariots, elephants and treasure. Jealous kings were driven away by Arjuna. Married another aunt's daughter Bhadrā. Took Lakṣmaṇā, daughter of the Madra king and thousands of maidens from Naraka's harem. 28) Bhā. X. Chap. 58. Indra came one day to Dvārakā and reported to Kṛṣṇa the mischief done to him by Naraka. Entering Prāgjyotiṣa, Kṛṣṇa pulled down ramparts and walls and cut off Mura's five heads. His seven sons attacked him led by Pāṭha in vain. Naraka also attacked and had his head cut off. Kṛṣṇa entered the city welcomed by its people, saw Maṇiparvata of Indra and the umbrella of Varuṇa and gave them back to them. Earth, mother of Naraka came before Kṛṣṇa and handed over the kuṇḍalas of Aditi, informing him that Naraka was her son by the touch of Hari in Vārāha form. Then he entered the harem of the Asura and sent away 16000 (some 16100) maidens to Dvārakā and them he married, after distributing the spoils of war among his fellow companions. 29) Bhā. X. Chap. 59; Vi. V. 29. 13-35; 31. 14-20 Had by his wives 18000 sons. With Satyabhāmā he visited Indra's abode and after giving the kuṇḍalas to Aditi, he came back with Pārijāta against Indra's will, because his queen wanted it. He enjoyed the company of all his wives, taking a separate form for each wife. Indra's attack on Kṛṣṇa with gods like Varuṇa, Vāyu, etc., for taking away Pārijāta. Their defeat and Indra's apology. Kṛṣṇa consoled him. Welcomed back in Dvārakā. 30) Bhā. X. 59. 22-45; Chap. 65 (v) to 67 (v); Vi. V. Chap. 30; 31. 1-10.  Love quarrel with his consort Rukmiṇī described. Once when Kṛṣṇa was sitting at leisure, Rukmiṇi who was nearby fanned him. Kṛṣṇa indulged in fun and asked her how she chose a poor fellow like him leaving princes of equal status with her, and added that he was willing to let her go and marry a powerful Kṣatriya prince. This put out poor Rukmiṇi who wept bitterly, speaking words showing her unflinching loyalty to him. Noticing her sincerity Kṛṣṇa consoled her that he simply cut a joke. He said that she knew him to be Hari to whom Rājaṛṣis like Aṅga, Nahuṣa and Gaya had dedicated their lives leaving their kingdoms, and that Brahmā and Śiva sang his praises. Kṛṣṇa assured her of his loyalty to her. In this way he led a household life just like an ordinary mortal. Each one of his eight chief queens gave birth to ten sons, and each thought that Kṛṣṇa was only living with her, as there was a Kṛṣṇa by the side of each lady including the 16000 of Naraka's harem. He played with them blindman's buff, exchanging betels, scents, etc. The chief queens were Rukmini, Satyabhāmā, Jāmbavatī, Satyā, Kālindī, Mādri, Mitravindā, and Bhadrā. Attended Aniruddha's marriage with Rocanā at Bhojakaṭa. Heard from Nārada of Aniruddha's imprisonment by Bāṇa of 1000 arms and besieged Śonitapura. Defeated Śiva who came on Bāṇā's behalf and at Śiva's request, let Bāṇa go with his four arms remaining. Returned to Dvārakā with Aniruddha and Uṣā. 31) Bhā. X. Chaps. 60-63; Vi. IV. 15. 30-4; V. 33. 12-53. Heard from a Brāhmaṇa of the externment of Pāṇḍavas to the forest, and riding on a chariot with Satyabhāmā, met them and consoled them; came back with Subhadrā and Abhimanyu. Heard a report of a huge lizard in a well, and lifting it up, he found it to be a divinity who revealed himself as king Nṛga and who went to heaven. Taught the citizens of Dvāraka on the invisilability of Brāhmaṇas’ property. 32)Bhā. X. Chap. 64.  Kṛṣṇa heard of Pauṇḍraka's invasion of Dvārakā in his absence. Had a message from him either to give up the title of Vāsudeva or offer battle. Ugrasena and others laughed at this. Kṛṣṇa went to Kāśī and had the heads of Pauṇḍraka and his ally cut off and their army destroyed. Kṛṣṇa's return to Dvāraka. An ābhicāra Agni was sent by Pauṇḍraka's son through the grace of Śiva but was vanquished by Hari's cakra. By his yoga power Kṛṣṇa appeared at the mansions of each of his 16000 wives, engaged in a normal domestic life. When Nārada entered every house, he saw the same Kṛṣṇa in each; got up early in the morning and meditated on Brahman; gave cows, etc., to the Brāhmaṇas, saw first ghee, then mirror, cows, gods, etc. Heard from a messenger of the difficulties of kings imprisoned by Jarāsandha. Advised by Uddhava to vanquish Jarāsandha with the aid of Bhīma at Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya. Kṛṣṇa's route to Hāstināpura where he was received by the Pāṇḍavas. Draupadī welcomed his wives and, these were put up comfortably. Hearing Jarāsandha still unconquered, Kṛṣṇa with Bhīma and Arjuna went to Girivraja in Brāhmaṇas’ disguise and asked for meals. They then threw off their disguise and called him to battle in which Bhīma won. After releasing prisoners, Kṛṣṇa enthroned Sahadeva, son of Jarāsandha. 33) Ib. X. Chaps. 67-73; M. 47, 14; Vi. V. 31. 4-28. The kings thus released after the fall of Jarāsandha were 20800, praised the Lord and requested that they might ever remember Him. Kṛṣṇa asked them to go back to their places and assume charge of governments by ruling righteously. Sahadeva arranged their bath, dress and meals, after which they left for where Yudhiṣṭhira and his family were. Received the first honour in the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira when Śiśupāla protested in a vilifying speech. His head was cut off. Lived in Hāstināpura for some months at the request of Yudhiṣṭhīra and others. Attended to arghya and pādya for Brāhmaṇas in the Rājasūya. Welcomed Nārada who informed him of the necessity of vanquishing Śālva. Left for Dvārakā hearing of its blockade by Śālva  who applied illusory powers. Kṛṣṇa broke his car and killed him. Kṛṣṇa went as an ambassador of the Pāṇḍavas to Duryodhana. He was sought to be made prisoner in vain; came back determined to declare war. In the war served as Arjuna's charioteer, and after the war Kṛṣṇa condoled with Dhṛtarāṣṭra and after anointing Yudhiṣṭhīra, returned to Dvārakā. One day there came Kucaila, a Brāhmaṇa classmate of Kṛṣṇa, a poor man with many children. Induced by his wife he visited Kṛṣṇa who welcomed him with Rukmiṇi, indulged in talks of old school days, partook of the pṛthuka rice which Kucaila's wife had sent, and sent him away after keeping him for a night. 34)Bhā. X. Chaps. 76-78; 81. 1-13. Left for Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse, met Gopis there and taught them the nature of the Absolute. Sages waited on him and praised his glory. His joy at Vasudeva's sacrifice. Honoured Nanda. Praised by his father, Kṛṣṇa replied that Ātma is only one. At the request of Devakī to get back all her sons killed by Kamsā, Kṛṣṇa entered Sutalam and with leave of Bali, took them to his mother who embraced them in affection. These children who were degraded gods gained their old form and went to heaven. 35)Ib. X. Chaps. 82-85. Subhadrā was his sister, and Arjuna carried her off with his knowledge and against the wish of Balarāma. He went with sages to Mithilā where was his Brāhmaṇa devotee Śrutadeva. The latter and the king Maithilā welcomed him and requested him to stay. Kṛṣṇa did not like to disoblige them and so stayed in both houses taking two different forms, thus purifying Nimi line, and pleasing Śrutadeva. 36)Ib. X. Chap. 86. Performed Aśvamedha sacrifice in the course of which he had to go to Vaikuṇṭha with Arjuna to recover the lost children of a Dvārakā Brāhmaṇa who preferred a complaint. After return with the lost boy, he had his avabhṛta cele brated in the Yamunā. Then he continued his righteous rule and spent a good time in Dvārakā enjoying pleasures with his chosen wives. 37)Ib. X. Chaps. 88-90. His service to the world was to kill Daityas and relieve the burden of the Earth. Resolved to destroy the Yadu race and reach his eternal abode; approved of the curse of the sages against the Yadu race. Brahmā and other gods visited him, appealing to him to go back to Vaikuṇṭha. He agreed. Uddhava expressed a wish to follow him but was advised by Kṛṣṇa to lead a righteous life. Incidentally Kṛṣṇa narrated to him the conversation of a certain Avadhūta and Yadu. Insisting on yama and niyama, and duties incumbent on varṇa and āśrama. Then he described who was said to be in bondage, who was a free man and a righteous person, and he also explained the need and importance of Satsanga. He proceeded to instruct Uddhava on the nature of the guṇas, and their causes, laying emphasis on satva guṇa. Then he explained Bhakti, Dhyāna, siddhis and their nature. He afterwards narrated the Vibhūtis of Hari, described the dharmas of varṇa and āśrama, explained what was jñāna and vijñāna, giving a list of duties to be observed by all. He further instructed on the three yogas--jñāna, karma and bhakti, on the Vedas, and on the principles of Sāṅkhya and Sāṅkhyavidhi. He then narrated the story of an Avanti Brāhmaṇa who turned out ascetic after being a miser. He enumerated the different characteristics of the three guṇas and the evil effects of bad association, recapitulating kriyāyoga, jñāna yoga and bhakti yoga. Lastly Uddhava was advised to go to Badari. 38)Ib. XI. XI. Chaps. 1-28. Advised his relations to go to Prabhāsa, and there deluded by him, they fought among themselves and died. Balarāma also met his death. Kṛṣṇa heard this while sitting under a pippala tree. A hunter Jarā by name aimed his shaft at his foot little thinking that it was the Lord. Coming to know that it was Kṛṣṇa he regretted much. Kṛṣṇa consoled him and permitted him to go to Heaven.  Kṛṣṇa addressed his charioteer Dāmaka to go to Dvārakā, and advise the people there to leave for Hastinapura with Arjuna. Invited by gods Kṛṣṇa entered his dhāma, while his wives entered fire. 39)Ib. XI. Chaps. 30-31; Vi. V. 37. 1-4; 47-75. It was the first day of Kali yuga. 39a)Ib. XI. Chaps. 30-31; Vi. V. 37. 1-4; 47-75. Resides in Sutalam; the mantra sacred to; 40)Br. II. 20. 21; III. 34. 9 and 34; 36. 114 and 48; 41. 8; 71. 196-7. as Puruṣa with Lakṣmī as prakṛti; the sacred Hari. 41)Ib. IV. 6. 30; 8. 28; 9. 48-55; 29. 126; 39. 59; 40. 8. One of the five Vamśavīras. 42)Ib. III. 72. 1. After his great Decease Arjuna felt himself powerless even against Ābhiras; 43)Vi. V. 38. 47-51; VI. 8. 3, 9. helped Arjuna to overcome the arrow Brahmaśiras of Aśvathāma; advised him to accept Draupadi's plea to release him and to treat him as a brahmabandhu. Went with Draupadī and party to attend the funeral rites of her sons, on the Ganges; anointed Yudhiṣṭhira on the throne. When he was about to leave for Dvārakā, Uttarā ran to him for help to the child in her womb against a burning missile. This was granted. Kuntī's praise of. Followed Yudhiṣṭhira to see the dying Bhīṣma who welcomed and praised him. Painful leave-takings. Praise by women of Hastināpura. Escorted by Yudhiṣṭhira's army and passing through many lands reached Dvārakā. Blew his conch as a sign of his arrival. Welcome in the city. Paid his respects to the wives of his father and enjoyed the company of his 16108 wives. 44)Bhā. I. Chaps. 7-12. His feet marked with Padma, Vajra, Aṅkuśa and Dhvaja. 45)Ib. I. 16. 17 and 34. An able charioteer, councillor, friend, ambassador, soldier and protector of devotees. Remembered by Śiva; called with Rādhā on the Lord and Pārvatī, and spoke to the latter on the greatness of Vināyaka with whom he renewed his friendship. Praised Parasurāma's heroism; no difference between Kṛṣṇa and Śiva. 46)Br. III. 42. 18-55; 43. 12-24; 44. 29; 71. 36 and 85. Married three daughters of Bhangakāra and Vrata vatī; also Mahādeva; a contemporary of Hiraṇyakaśipu; 47)M. 45. 20-21; 47. 1 and 35. Mahātmya of, in the Brahmavaivarta; prayed to by Aditi. 48)M. 53. 34-5; 60. 4; 245. 33-6; 250. 46. on the very day he left this earth, Kaliyuga began. 49)M. 273. 49; Vi. IV. 24. 111-3. a Vṛṣṇi; 50)M. 45. 10. worship of, before gifts. 51)M. 181. 17; 245. 62; 246. 20. 36, 44; 248. 44; 274. 15. When Kṛṣṇa was born 16000 goddesses and 14 gaṇas of Apsaras were reborn in the world to serve the Lord in his quest. 52)Vā. 96. 232 ff.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (II) (davaipāyana)--Vyāsa (s.v.) of the current dvāpara, the son of Parāśara and Satyavatī (Kāli, Vā. P.): a munī; 1) Bhā. I. 4. 3 and 32; IX. 22. 21; XII. 4. 40; 6. 35; Vā. 1. 10; 23. 226; 70. 54; Vi. III. 3. 19. wife Araṇi and son Śuka; author of the Purāṇa Śāstra; 2) Br. III. 8. 92; IV. 4. 50. father of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Vīdura and Pāṇḍu by the widows of Vicitravīrya and their female servant. Another wife Pīvari, by whom he got five sons and one daughter. 3) M. 50. 46; 185. 30; Vā. 99. 241; Vi. IV. 20. 38; VI. 2. 32. Divided the Vedas into four parts: an avatār of Nārāyaṇa; 4) Vi. III. 4. 3-10. the compiler of the Mahābhārata.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (III)--a son of Havirdhāna and Havirdhānī. Bhā. IV. 24. 8; Br. II. 37. 24; Vā. 63. 23; Vi. I. 14. 2.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (IV)--a brother of the Andhra servant Balin (Balipuccaka-Vi. P.) who killed his master Kāṇva Suśarman and usurped the throne. After him, his brother Kṛṣṇa became king. His son was Śrī Śāntakarṇa, 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 23; Br. III. 74. 162; Vi. IV. 24. 44-5. who ruled for 18 years. 2) M. 273. 3. 

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (V)--a name of Arjuna. Bhā. XII, 11. 25.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (VI)--a name of Brahmā. Br. II. 34. 7.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (VII)--a pupil of Sumantu of Atharva Veda fame. Br. II. 35. 56.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (VIII)--a son of Dullola. Br. III. 7. 443.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (IX)--a son of Śuka and Pīvarī. Br. III. 8. 93; 10. 81; M. 15. 10. Vā. 70. 85; 73, 30, 62.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (X)--an Andhaka. Br. III. 71. 143; M. 44. 84.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (XI)--the asura of second tala, the Sutala. Vā. 50. 21.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (XII)--an adopted son of Asamaujasa. Vā. 96. 141.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (XIII)--a name of Vyāsa. Vi. V. 38. 52.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (XIV)--(Mt.) a kulaparvata of the Ketumāla; residence of Gandharvas. Vā. 38. 49; 39. 59; 42. 52; 44. 4.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (XV)--a Mt. to the west of the Śitoda lake. Vā. 36. 28; 38. 49. 

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇa  (XVI)--a hell; illegal intercourse, trespass on others’ lands and living on magic are offences leading to this hell. Vi. II. 6. 3 and 25.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇas  (I)--a class of gods; a Parāśara clan. Br. III. 8. 95; 10. 109; Vā. 70. 87.

कृष्ण
Kṛṣṇas  (II)--the Śūdra caste of Śālmalidvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 30.

कृष्णकल्प
Kṛṣṇakalpa --of Kṛṣṇa colour; Śiva, Kālarūpa and Aghora. Vā. 23. 74-76.

कृष्णगिरि
Kṛṣṇagiri --a Mt. in Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 22; Vā. 45. 91.

कृष्णतीर्थम्
Kṛṣṇatīrtham --sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 38.

कृष्णतोया
Kṛṣṇatoyā --a R. of the Bhadra country. Vā. 43. 28.

कृष्णपक्ष
Kṛṣṇapakṣa  (I)--the day for the Pitṛs. Vā. 52. 37; 57. 9; 83. 80.

कृष्णपक्ष
Kṛṣṇapakṣa  (II)--a śakti. Br. IV. 32. 15.

