Kṛṣṇā  (II)--a name of Yogamāyā. Bhā. X. 2. 12. 

कृष्णा
Kṛṣṇā  (III)--a name of Yamunā. Bhā. X. 32. 12.

कृष्णा
Kṛṣṇā  (IV)--a daughter of Khaśa. Vā. 69. 170.

कृष्णा
Kṛṣṇā  (V)--a R. of the Sahya hills of the Dakṣiṇāpatha. Vā. 45. 104.

कृष्णाङ्गना
Kṛṣṇāṅganā--sabhā  of Virūpākṣa on the 4th inner slope of Meru; the lord of the s. w. direction. Vā. 34. 87.

कृष्णाङ्गमणिपुरीजक
Kṛṣṇāṅgamaṇipurījakas --a Janapada of the Ketumāla. Vā. 44. 10.

कृष्णाजिनम्
Kṛṣṇājinam --as clothing of tapasvins; used for ritual purposes; a good article for gift. 1) M. 47. 89; 82. 3; 204. 11; 206. 1-41; 245. 85; 279. 5; Vā. 25. 34 and 81; 30. 221; 74. 4; 99. 410; Vi. I. 11. 31. Also used by religious students as when Keśidhvaja had it when he visited Khāṇḍikya for instruction. 2) Vi. VI. 6. 20. and 22.

कृष्णापाद
Kṛṣṇāpādas(c) --a Janapada of the Ketumāla. Vā. 44. 11.

कृष्णावेण्या
Kṛṣṇā-veṇyā --a R. in Bhāratavarṣa (Kṛṣṇaveṇī-Br. P.). Bhā. V. 19. 18.

कृष्णाष्टमी
Kṛṣṇāṣṭamī --a vrata; a special prayer to Śankara on the 8th dy of the dark half of every month; other details follow. 1) M. 56. 1-11. the aṣṭami day on which Kṛṣṇa was born. 2) Vi. V. 1. 78. 

केकय
Kekaya  (I)--a son of Śibi after whom the kingdom came to be called. Br. III. 74. 23; M. 48. 19-20; Vā. 99. 23-4; Vi. IV. 18. 10.

केकय
Kekaya  (II)--Its king married Śrutakīrti, sister of Vasudeva; 1) Vi. IV. 14. 41. went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse. 2) Bhā. X. 82. 13.

केकय
Kekayas(c) --people of Kekaya, a northern kingdom enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus. Their princes were stationed on the North during the siege of Gomanta. 1) Bhā. X. [50 (V) 3]; 52. 11 [14]
Br. II. 16. 48. But they became allies of Kṛṣṇa and took part in the marriage festivities of Rukmiṇī. 2) Bhā. X. 54. 58. Heard of Kṛṣṇa going to Mithilā, welcomed him and met him with presents. 3) Ib. X. 86. 20; 71. 29. Followed Bhīmasena in his digvijaya; 4) Ib. X. 72. 13. rose against Śiśupāla. 5) Ib. X. 74. 41. Took part in Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya. 6) Ib. X. 75. 12. In the Mahābhārata war, five princes of Kekaya joined the Pāṇḍavas against the Kurus. 7) Ib. X. 78 [95 (V) 12]; 84. 55. A Janapada. 8) Vā. 45. 117. Migration of Yadus to. 9) Bhā. XI. 2. 3.

केकर
Kekaras --the kingdom of. M. 121. 53.

केतन
Ketana --a charioteer of Viśukra, killed by Śyāmalā. Br. IV. 28. 104.

केतरी
Ketarī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 18.

केतव
Ketava --a disciple of Rathītara (s.v.). Vā. 60. 66.

केतु
Ketu  (I)--a son of Ṛṣabha. Bhā. V. 4. 10. 

केतु
Ketu  (II)--one of the 100 sons of Vipracitta and Simhikā besides Rāhu (s.v.). Bhā. V. 23. 7; VI. 6. 37.

केतु
Ketu  (III)--a son of Tāmasa Manu. Bhā. VIII. 1. 27.

केतु
Ketu  (IV)--a planet with a chariot of 8 horses, all green; 1) Br. II. 23. 90; 24. 136 and 39; M. 93. 10; 127. 11; Vā. 52. 82; 111. 5; Vi. II. 12. 23. in size one-fourth less than Bṛhaspati. 2) M. 128. 64. Dhūmaketu, the first among the Ketus. 3) Vā. 53. 111.

केतु
Ketu  (V)--a son of Danu. M. 6. 18.

केतु
Ketu  (VI)--the second son of Druhyu. M. 48. 6.

केतु
Ketu  (VII)--one of the Prāṇahinas of the king. Vā. 57. 69.

केतुमत्
Ketumat  (I)--a son of Ambarīṣa. Bhā. IX. 6. 1.

केतुमत्
Ketumat  (II)--the son of Dhanvantari and father of Bhīmaratha. Bhā. IX. 17. 5; Br. III. 67. 25; Vā. 92. 23; Vi. IV. 8. 11.

केतुमत्
Ketumat  (III)--(Rajasa-Vā. P.) a Lokapāla of lokāloka; 1) Br. II. 11. 43; 21. 157; 36. 31; III. 8. 19; Vā. 50. 206; Vi. II. 8. 83. son of Rājasa (Br. P.) and Mārkaṇḍeyī and overlord of the west. 2) M. 8. 10; 124. 95; Vā. 28. 37. 

केतुमत्
Ketumat  (IV)--any yakṣa; a son of Puṇyajanī and Maṇibhadra. Br. II. 7. 125; Vā. 62. 28; 69. 156.

केतुमत्
Ketumat  (V)--the son of Kṣema, and father of Suketu. Br. III. 67. 74.

केतुमत्
Ketumat  (VI)--a son of Sutāra, the lord of second dvāpara. Vā. 23. 121.

केतुमत्
Ketumat  (VII)--king of the western region. Vā. 70. 17; Vi. I. 22. 13.

केतुमाल
Ketumāla  (I)--a son of Āgnidhra, and Pūrvacitti; 1) Bhā. V. 2. 19; Vā. 33. 40; Vi. II. 1. 17. Lord of Gandhamādana varṣa. 2) Br. II. 14. 47 and 52; Vā. 33. 45. Vi. II. 1. 23.

केतुमाल
Ketumāla  (II)--a continent bounded on one side by Mālyavat, and traversed by the stream Cakṣus. Viṣṇu reveals himself here as Kāmadeva when Lakṣmī praises his glory. 1) Bhā. V. 16. 10; 17. 7; 18. 15-23; M. 83. 33; 113. 44, 49-50; Vi. II. 2. 24. Conquered by Parīkṣit. 2) Bhā. I. 16. 13. Adjacent to Meru and noted for panasa tree; 3) Br. II. 15. 50-4; Vā. 34. 57. of Mlecchas; 4) Vā. 42. 47. māla, thrown by Indra during the churning of the ocean, struck on a tree there and hence the name; description of; 5) Vā. 35. 36-40; 41. 85; 43. 1-4; 44. 1-25. Viṣṇu in the form of Varāha. 6) Vi. II. 2. 50.

केतुमाली
Ketumālī --a son of Dāruka and an avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 196. 

केतुराट्
Keturāṭ --a Mahāvṛkṣa of the Mandara hill with scented leaves and flowers. Vā. 35. 20-2, 44.

केतुरूप
Keturūpa --a son of Tāmasa Manu. Vi. III. 1. 19.

केतुवीर्य
Ketuvīrya --a Dānava: a son of Danu. Br. III. 6. 6; M. 6. 18.

केतुवृक्ष
Ketuvṛkṣa --a tree. Vā. 35. 44.

केतुशृङ्ग
Ketuśṛṅga --a son of Bhṛgu, an avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 149.

केदार
Kedāra  (I)--a kṣetram in which Vṛka performed tapas to Śiva; a tīrtham sacred to Pitṛs and the goddess Mārgadāyīnī. Bhā. X. 88. 17; M. 13. 30; 22. 11; 181. 29.

केदार
Kedāra  (II)--one of the forms of Brahmā in the Gayā stone. Vā. 106. 56; 111. 72.

केरल
Kerala  (I)--a son of Āṇḍira, after whom came the Keraladeśa. Br. III. 74. 6; M. 48. 5.

केरल
Kerala  (II)--one of the four sons of Janāpiḍa; with him kingdom of Kerala came into being. Vā. 99. 6. 

केरल
Keralas(c)  (I)--of the Dakṣiṇāpatha; 1) Br. II. 16. 56; M. 114. 46; Vā. 45. 124; 47. 52. visited by Balarāma; king of, went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse; 2) Bhā. X. 79. 19; 82. 13. people of, enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus. 3) Ib. X. [50 (v) 2].

केरल
Keralas  (II)--Pravara sages. M. 199. 17.

केलि
Keli --a son of Brahmadhāna. Br. III. 7. 98.

केवल
Kevala  (I)--the son of Nara (Candra-Vi. P.) and father of Bandhumat. Bhā. IX. 2. 30; Br. III. 8. 36; 61. 9; Vā. 86. 14; Vi. IV. 1. 42-3.

केवल
Kevala  (II) a deva (Ajita). Br. II. 13. 94; Vā. 31. 7.

केवल
Kevala  (III)--a pupil of Yājñavalkya. Br. II. 35. 29.

केवल
Kevala  (IV)--the son of Suvṛddhi and father of Sudhṛti. Vi. IV. 1. 38-9.

केशरी
Keśarī --(Ramya) (s.v.) a Mt. in Śākadvīpam. Vā. 49. 84.

केशव
Keśava --is Kṛṣṇa; 1) Br. III. 42. 19; 71. 221; IV. 34. 76; M. 16. 1; 17. 30; 22. 9; 69. 8; 150. 221; 178. 14 and 36; 187. 26; 245. 38. a resident of Prayāga; to be prayed, when there is bad omen. 2) M. 243. 13.

केशव
Keśava  (II)--same as Vibhrāja hill. M. 122. 17-18. 

केशव
Keśava  (III)--a tīrtham in Benares. M. 185. 68.

केशि
Keśi --an Asura. Vi. V. 29. 4.

केशिध्वज
Keśidhvaja --son of Kṛtadhvaja and skilled in devotion; banished in hostility Khāṇdikya from his kingdom; once a tiger slew his milch cow; to find out the prāyaścitta he went to consult Kaśeru who sent him to Sunaka and he commended the name of Khāṇḍikya. So he went to the forest clad in deer-skin like a religious student and demanded the form of penance. Khāṇḍikya thought at first that he had come there to kill him, took up his bow, but laid it aside; instruction was received and the penance was over. Keśi felt that some fee was due to Khāṇḍikya and once more called on him; though his councillors advised him to take back the kingdom, his mind hankering after the other world; he requested for his fee for his instruction on the doctrine of soul; after imparting instruction on yoga to Khāṇḍikya retired to a life of peace and attained liberation; father of Bhānumat. Bhā. IX. 13. 20-21. Vi. VI. 6. 5-50; 7. 101-06.

केशिन्
Keśin  (I)--a son of Vasudeva and Kauśalya; the family of. Bhā. IX. 24. 48.

केशिन्
Keśin  (II)--an asura friend of Kamsā. Set up by him, Keśin appeared in Vraja as a huge horse and attacked Kṛṣṇa with his feet. Being thrown off by Kṛṣṇa, he fell at a distance. Recovering his consciousness, he once again attacked Kṛṣṇa when the latter thrust his arm into his mouth until he was suffocated to death. Bhā. X. 2. 1; 36. 20; 37. 1-8, 25; 43. 25; II. 7. 34; Vā. 98. 100; Vi. V. 1. 24; 4. 1-2; 12. 21. 

केशिन्
Keśin  (III)--a Dānava king; 1) Br. IV. 29. 124. defeated and slain by Purūravas when he was forcibly taking away Citralekhā and Urvaśī. The latter was handed over to Indra. 2) M. 24. 12, 23-5.

केशिनी
Keśinī  (I)--the mother of Rāvaṇa. Bhā. VII. 1. 43.

केशिनी
Keśinī  (II)--a queen of Sagara and mother of Asamañjasa; a vamśakarta by Aurva's grace; the daughter of Vidarbha king. Bhā. IX. 8. 15; Br. III. 49. 2 and 59; 51. 37; 63. 154; Vā. 88. 155-160; Vi. IV. 4. 1-5.

केशिनी
Keśinī  (III)--a daughter of Khaśā, and Rākṣasī. Vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 7. 139; 73. 100: Vā. 69. 170.

केशिनी
Keśinī  (IV)--the wife of Suhotra, and mother of Janhu. Br. III. 66. 25.

केशिनी
Keśinī  (V)--one of the queens of Ajamīḍha. M. 49. 44: Vā. 99. 167.

केशिनी
Keśinī  (VI)--a mind-born mother. M. 179. 23.

केशिन्य
Keśinyas --Yakṣa-rākṣasas from Yakṣa Kampana. Vā. 69. 177.

केषणादि
Keṣaṇādi --a class of Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 380. 

केसर
Kesara --the Mt. from whose summits the Sītā descends. Bhā. V. 17. 6.

केसरद्रोणि
Kesaradroṇi --between hills Kumuda and Añjana; Viṣṇu's temple located at. Vā. 38. 45-8.

केसरी
Kesarī  (I)--an Asura in a city in in Rasātalam (VI tala or Śūtala-Vā. P.). Br. II. 20. 39; Vā. 50. 38.

केसरी
Kesarī  (II)--wife Añjana, whom Vāyu loved and gave birth to Hanumān. Br. III. 7. 223.

केसरी
Kesarī  (III)--a Mt. of Śākadvīpa, having all medicinal herbs. Br. II. 19. 90; Vi. II. 4. 62.

कैकय
Kaikaya --the husband of Śrutakīrti. Br. III. 71. 157.

कैकय
Kaikayas --Five in number born of Dhṛṣṭaketu and and Śrutakīrti. Its king was vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. See Kekayas. Bhā. IX. 24. 38; II. 7. 35.

कैकरसप
Kaikarasapas --Kaśyapa gotrakaras. M. 199. 7.

कैकसी
Kaikasī --Daughter of Mālin. Mother of Rāvaṇa and others. 1) Br. III. 8. 40 and 47. Kekasī (Rāmāyaṇa) one of the four wives of Viśravas, and mother of three sons, Rāvaṇa, Kumbhakarṇa and Vibhīṣaṇa and a daughter Śūrpaṇakhā. 2) Vā. 70. 34, 41. 

कैकेय
Kaikeya --a son of Śibi. His ten daughters were queens of Satrājit. Bhā. IX. 23. 3; M. 45. 19.

कैकेय
Kaikeyas --a tribe. M. 114. 42.

कैकेयी
Kaikeyī --surname of Bhadrā, a wife of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 57. 56.

कैंकिल
Kaiṃkila --the Yavanas; not duly crowned kings, rule after the Mauryas; chief among them was Vindhyaśakti; nine kings rule for 106 years. Vi. IV. 24. 55-56.

कैटभ
Kaiṭabha  (I)--an Asura (Daitya-Vā. P.) slain by Hari, 1) Bhā. III. 24. 18; VI. 12. 1; X. 40. 17; Vā. 25. 30, 54. born with Madhu, representing the qualities of Tamas and Rajas. 2) M. 170. 1; 178. 6-18.

कैटभ
Kaiṭabha  (II)--an Asura slain by Durgā. Br. II. 37. 2; IV. 29. 75.

कैरात
Kairāta  (I)--a pravara sage. M. 199. 16.

कैरात
Kairāta  (II)--a kingdom noted for horses. Here Mūka was vanquished by Arjuna. Br. III. 5. 36; IV. 16. 18.

कैराति
Kairāti --ārṣeya-pravara (Aṅgiras). M. 196. 7. 

कैलापुर
Kailāpura --sacred to Lilitā. Br. IV. 44. 97.

कैलास
Kailāsa(śikhara) --the abode of Śiva seated on a baniyan tree and of Yakṣas, full of different plants, trees and flowers, birds and beasts. Here are the city of Alakā, and the forest Saugandhika. 1) Bhā. IV. 5. 26; VI. 8. 33; IX. 4. 55; X. 10. 2; 55 [1]; M. 54. 3; 62. 2; Vā. 30. 85; 35. 9; 36. 24; 38. 33; 41. 1; 42. 32; 47. 1; 50. 48; 54. 35-6; 101. 303. It is located on the south of Meru, 2) Bhā. V. 16. 27; Vi. II. 2. 42. on the Himalayan slopes; the residence of Kubera. Described. 3) Br. II. 18. 1-4; 20. 50, 25. 24-40; III. 13. 36; 22. 56; 25. 9; 41. 18; IV. 9. 30; 10. 27. North of Atri's hermitage. 4) M. 121. 2-5; 163. 85; 183. 1.

कैलास
Kailāsa --a form of temple with 9 storeys and a toraṇa with 40 hastas. M. 269. 28-31, 47.

कैवर्त्तस्
Kaivarttas --a royal line (tribe?) established by Viśvasphāṇi, kings of. Br. III. 74. 191; M. 50. 76; Vā. 99. 268, 378; Vi. IV. 24. 62.

कैवल्यम्
Kaivalyam --the state of becoming one with the Brahman; one gets this at Benares; 1) M. 143. 34; 180. 59. arises from jñānam. 2) Vā. 102. 79. Ib. 59. 118.

कैशिक
Kaiśika  (I)--a son of Vidarbha; father of Cidi, after whom caidyas came to be known. Br. III. 70. 37; M. 44. 36-38; Vi. IV. 12. 37.

कैशिक
Kaiśika  (II)--a son of Dhṛti. Vi. IV. 12. 39. 

कैशिकम्
Kaiśikam --of seven rūpas. Vā. 87. 35 and 36.

कोकिल
Kokila --said ‘kuha’, and the time came to be known Kuhū. Br. II. 25. 29; 28. 58.

कोङ्क
Koṅka(ṇa) --a kingdom through which Ṛṣabha passed; Arhat was king. 1) Bhā. V. 6. 7 and 9. A southern country; 2) Br. II. 16. 59. unfit for śrāddha. 3) M. 16. 16.

कोटरा
Koṭarā --an evil spirit and mother of Bāṇa. Appeared naked and with dishevelled hair before Kṛṣṇa who had deprived Bāṇa of his chariot. A varṇa śakti. 2) Br. IV. 44. 59. ^1 Bhā. X. 6. 28; 63. 20.

कोटवी
Koṭavī --the goddess enshrined at Koṭitīrtham. M. 13. 37.

कोटितीर्थम्
Koṭitīrtham  (I)--a kṣetram in Prayāga; sacred to Koṭavī. M. 13. 37; 106. 44; Vā. 112. 32.

कोटितीर्थम्
Koṭitīrtham  (II)--on the Narmadā; the Lord enshrined here is Koṭīśvara. Here asuras were slain by Śiva; a man who bathes there becomes king and a woman equal to Gaurī. M. 191. 7-13.

कोटिहोम
Koṭihoma --one of the three kinds of grahabali-detailed. M. 93. 6; 119-139; 239. 1, 17-40.

कोणा
Koṇā --a mother goddess. M. 179. 28. 

कोदण्डराम
Kodaṇḍarāma --is Śrī Rāma created by Lalīta in her battle with Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 29. 114.

कोधनु
Kodhanu --the adopted son of Vastāvana. Vā. 96. 190.

कोपचय
Kopacaya --a pravara of Angiras. M. 196. 21.

कोमला
Komalā (Kosalā?) --Nine kings of the name Megha ruled here. Then came Naiṣadhas. Br. III. 74. 188; Vā. 99. 375. 76.

कोरकृष्ण
Korakṛṣṇa --a sage. M. 200. 8.

कोरञ्ज
Korañja --a kulaparvata of the Bhadrāśva. Vā. 43. 14.

कोल
Kola --a Kauśika and a sage. Br. II. 32. 118.

कोलाट
Kolāṭa --an asura who was slain by Caṇḍa Kāli. Br. IV. 28. 42.

कोलावन
Kolāvanas --of the S. country. Vā. 45. 128.

कोलापुर
Kolāpura --city sacred to Lalitā (perhaps Kolhapur). Br. IV. 44. 97. 

कोलाहल
Kolāhala  (I)--(Mt.) a hill of Bhāratavarṣa; 1) Br. II. 16. 21; Vā. 45. 90; Vi. III. 18. 73. the place where Gayāsura performed austerities. 2) Vā. 106. 5.

कोलाहल
Kolāhala  (II)--the 12th battle between Asuras and Devas. Here Rāji vanquished the Asuras; also the 12th and last incarnation of Hari. Br. III. 72. 76 and 86; M. 47. 45 and 53.

कोलाहल
Kolāhala  (III)--a son of Sabhānara and father of Sañjaya. M. 48. 11.

कोलीकिल
Kolīkilas --a tribe to which Vindhyaśakti belonged. Vā. 99. 365.

कोल्लक
Kollaka --Mt. in Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 16.

कोल्लाट
Kollāṭa --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 85.

कोविद
Kovida --a class of people in Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 16.

कोविदारी
Kovidārī --a mother goddess. M. 179. 30.

कोश
Kośa Karaṇa --a city. M. 163. 66.

कोशा
Kośā --of Kāśi king. Vi. V. 34. 42. 

कोशीतिका
Kośītikā --a Brahmavādinī. Br. II. 33. 19.

कोष्टु
Koṣṭu --one of the five sons of Yadu. Vā. 94. 2.

कोशला
Kośalā(uttara) --the kingdom of Rāma and his son Kuśa. Its people celebrated Rāma's arrival by instituting a festival. They were taken to heaven by the grace of Rāma. 1) Bhā. IX. 10. 4 and 42; V. 19. 8; Vā. 77. 36; 88. 199; 99. 402; Vi. II. 3. 17. Its people took part in the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhīra. 2) Bhā. X. 75. 12. Their king went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse. 3) Ib. X. 2. 13. Migration of Yadus to. 4) Ib. X. 2. 3. Its people met Kṛṣṇa on the way to Mithilā with presents. 5) Ib. X. 86. 20. A kingdom of Madhyadeśa in the Vindhyas. Kuśa ruled it with his capital at Kuśasthalī. 6) Br. II. 16. 41 and 64; III. 63. 199; 74. 197. Its king was defeated by Paraśurāma; 7) Ib. III. 41. 39; 48. 15. ruled by nine kings at a time. 8) Vi. IV. 24. 59.

कोशल
Kośalas --a tribe; a kingdom of the Janapada on the other side of the Vindhyas. M. 114. 35, 53; 163. 67; Vā. 45. 110, 133; 99. 385.

कोसलनगर
Kosalanagara --is Ayodhyā. Vi. IV. 4. 103.

कोसलेन्द्र
Kosalendra --a name of Rāma. Vi. IV. 4. 100.

कोहल
Kohala --a pupil of Lāngala. Br. II. 35. 48.

कौकुरुण्डि
Kaukuruṇḍi --a sage of the Auttama epoch. M. 9. 14. 

कौचकि
Kaucaki --a pravara of Angiras. M. 196. 14.

कौचहस्तिक
Kaucahastika --a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 26.

कौटिलि
Kauṭili --a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 26.

कौटिल्य
Kauṭilya --the Brāhmaṇa who was responsible for vanquishing the Nandas and anointing Chandragupta Maurya. Br. III. 74. 143; M. 272. 22; Vā. 99. 330; Vi. IV. 24. 26-7.

कौतुजातय
Kautujātaya --Nīla-prāśara. M. 201. 34.

कौत्स
Kautsa  (I)--a Tripravara sage. M. 196. 33-34.

कौत्स
Kautsa  (II)--a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 25.

कौथुम
Kauthuma --a son of Parāśara, in charge of a Saṃhitā. Br. II. 35. 45-6.

कौन्ती
Kauntī --the city of, got into the hands of Mlecchas. Bhā. XII. 1. 39.

कौबेरक
Kauberaka --a sage living in Hariśṛṅga summoned by Āgastyas. Vā. 47. 60-61.

कौबेरक
Kauberakas --Kaśyapa gotrakaras. M. 199. 7. 

