Gajakarṇam --a tīrtham sacred to Pitṛs in Gayā; ritual at. M. 22. 38: Vā. 111. 55.

गजचर्मनिवासिन्
Gajacarmanivāsin --a name of Śiva. Br. II. 27. 99. 

गजच्छाया
Gajacchāyā --a yugādi for Śrāddha. M. 17. 3.

गजतुण्ड
Gajatuṇḍa --a Vināyaka. M. 183. 63.

गजमुख
Gajamukhas --a people, perhaps Gandharvas. Br. III. 22. 56.

गजवक्त्र
Gajavaktra --see Gaṇeśa. Br. IV. 44. 66.

गजवीथि
Gajavīthi --residences of constellations in the N. path. Br. 3. 48.

गजशैल
Gajaśaila --a Mt. south of the Mānasa; 1) Vā. 36. 24. residence of the Rudras. 2) Ib. 39. 47.

गजसात्वयम्
Gajasātvayam --see Hastināpura city built by Hasti. Bhā. I. 4. 6. M. 49. 52.

गजाध्यक्ष
Gajādhyakṣa --the superintendent of elephants and his qualifications. M. 215. 36.

गजानान
Gajānāna --is Gaṇeśa. Br. III. 41. 54: 42. 35: 44. 51: IV. 27. 72. M. 154. 505.

गजारोही
Gajārohī --the mahout of the state elephant; qualifications of. M. 215. 37.

गजासुर
Gajāsura --killed by Gaṇeśa (Śiva-M.P.). Br. IV. 27. 98 and 101. M. 55. 16. 

गजेन्द्र
Gajendra  (I)--the legend of Viṣṇu freeing the elephant in trouble. While wandering in the hills, this lord of elephants felt thirsty and entered a lake in the Trikūṭa hill. While drinking water, a crocodile caught hold of its feet. Finding himself on the brink of death, Gajendra bestowed his thought on Hari on account of the vāsana of the previous birth. Pleased with his prayer, Hari flew on Garuḍa with his cakra and released the animal from the crocodile. The elephant attained a form like that of Hari. This elephant was in his previous birth a Pāṇḍyan king by name Indradyumna devoted to Hari but cursed by Agastya to be born as elephant. 1) Bhā. III. 19. 35: VIII. 1. 30: 2. 20-33: 3 (whole): 4. 6-25. Hari blessed Gajendra who got mokṣa by satsanga. 2) Ibid. X. 71. 9: XI. 12. 6. Hence Gajendramokṣa. 3) Ibid. II. 7. 15-16.

गजेन्द्र
Gajendra  (II)--the Airāvata which came out of the churning of the ocean of milk. It was taken up by Indra. M. 251. 3.

गजेन्द्रास्य
Gajendrāsya --is Ganeśa. Br. IV. 44. 67.

गणतीर्थम्
Gaṇatīrtham --sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 73.

गणनाथ
Gaṇanātha --see Gaṇeśa. Br. IV. 27. 72: Vā. 109. 22.

गणनाविधि
Gaṇanāvidhi --18 sthānas, mentioned for enumeration of numbers. Br. IV. 2. 102: Vā. 101. 102.

गणप
Gaṇapa --a deity. Br. IV. 19. 81. 

गणपति
Gaṇapati --also Gaṇeśa. Br. III. 41. 41.

गण
Gaṇas  (I)--of bhūtas; followers of Śiva, of gods, of Pramathas; attacked Kṛṣṇa at Śoṇitapura; 1) Bhā. II. 6. 13: X. [65 (V) 46], [49]: [66. (V) 49]: 63. 6 and 10: XII. 10. 14. eleven celestial gaṇas reckoned. 2) M. 6. 44-5: 52. 21. Twelve groups of seven living with the sun in different parts of the year; their functions. 3) Vā. 52. 24-35. Three clans of sages with twenty branches each. In the first epoch of Sāvarṇī; all of them sons of Mārīca Kaśyapa, with Bali as their Indra. 4) Ib. 100. 13f.

गण
Gaṇas  (II)--five groups of; Yavanas, Pāradas, Kāmbojas, Pahlavas and Śakas; defeated by Sagara, these appealed to Vaisiṣṭha who persuaded the king from further slaughter. Sagara changed their dharma and physical features; were degraded Kṣatriyas and debarred from learning Vedas. Br. III. 63. 127.

गणाधिप
Gaṇādhipa --is Gaṇeśa. Br. III. 41. 41.

गणिक
Gaṇikas --courtesans. Br. III. 27. 14 and 41: 49. 23.

गणित
Gaṇita --the science of computation (Algebra, Geometry and Arithmetic). Vā. 70. 15.

गणेश
Gaṇeśa --is Vināyaka (s.v.); sprung out of Kāmeśvara, thought of by Lalītā; destroyed Bhaṇḍa's 1) Bhā. III. 41. 37-41: 42. 2 and 33: 43. 18 and 31: 44. 70. Br. IV. 27. 72-104: 44. 67. followers and filled the Śakti host with enthusiasm. Killed Gajāsura (s.v.). His riding animal was rat. Lalitā honoured him as the first  to be worshipped among gods; 1) Bhā. III. 41. 37-41: 42. 2 and 33: 43. 18 and 31: 44. 70. Br. IV. 27. 72-104: 44. 67. was Nikumbha in whose honour Divodāsa built a temple. 2) Br. III. 67. 55. The head of a Śiva gaṇa who sports in sidda-kṣetras, Rathyas, desolate gardens and places where there are children, the mad and others. Icons of; 3) M. 23. 38 and 84: 154. 524, 533-41: 250. 25, 259. 23. origin in an elephant-faced doll made by Pārvatī from the oil and dirt scraped off her body in the course of an oil bath; cast into Ganges where he grew in size and became Gāngeya. 4) M. 154. 502-5.

गणेश
Gaṇeśas --formerly men who by brahmacarya and pilgrimages pleased Śankara and attained this status; very dear to Śiva; Pārvatī's first view of them; their habits and food; Vīraka, (s.v.) one of them attracted Pārvatī's attention. M. 154. 522. to 41.

गणेशपदम्
Gaṇeśapadam --in Gayā. Vā. 111. 55.

गणेश्वर
Gaṇeśvara --is Gaṇeśa. Br. III. 32. 23 and 59: IV. 27. 99: 44. 70.

गण्डकी
Gaṇḍakī --R. from the Himalayas visited by Balarāma; 1) Bhā. X. 79. 11: Br. II. 16. 26: M. 114. 22. in the chariot of Tripurārī; 2) M. 133. 23. a mahānadī. 3) Vā. 45. 96: 108. 79.

गण्डगल्ल
Gaṇḍagalla --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 82.

गण्डीका
Gaṇḍīkā --apparently a town; to the East of Mālyavat; on the slopes of the Gandhamādhana and the Mālyavata; in the first line Ketumālas; and there is a mahāvṛkṣa Janasa. M. 113. 51: Vā. 43. 1-4. 

गण्डूष
Gaṇḍūṣa --a son of Śūra and a brother of Vasudeva; Issueless adopted Cārūdeṣṇa and Sāmbha, sons of Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 150 and 191: Vā. 96. 148, 188. Vi. IV. 14. 30.

गतभयम्
Gatabhayam --same as Jaladhāravarṣam. M. 122. 20-1.

गतायु
Gatāyu --one of the six sons of Purūravas. Vā. 91. 52.

गति
Gati --a daughter of Kardama, married to Pulaha. Had three sons--Karmaśreṣṭa, Varīyas and Sahisṇu. Bhā. III. 24. 23: IV. 1. 38.

गतिन
Gatina --not to marry with Viśvāmitras, etc. M. 198. 19.

गद
Gada  (I)--a son of Kṛṣṇa 1) Bhā. I. 14. 28: II. 3. 19: III. 1. 35: IV. 23. 12: X. 41. 32: 47. 40: 52. 40: 59. 10: XI. 30. 16. who was stationed at the western gate of Mathurā for defence. 2) Ib. X. 50. 20 [4]. Had a place on the left detachment of Kṛṣṇa's army. When Jarāsandha attacked Mathurā for a third time, Gada played a heroic part. 3) Ib. [50 (V) 11]: [51 (V) 25]. Attacked Caidya party which pursued Kṛṣṇa taking away Rukmiṇī. 4) Ib. 54. 6. Went with Vṛṣṇis to the city of Bāṇa. 5) Ib. 63. 3. Accompanied Sāmba and others to play and came across a huge lizard in a well and reported it to Kṛṣṇa. 6) Ib. 64. 12 [1-4]. Took part in defending Dvārakā against Śālva and in expelling his forces. 7) Ib. X. 76. 14: 77. 4. Went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse. 8) Ib. 82. 6. At Prabhāsa. 9) Ib. XI. 30. 16.

गद
Gada  (II)--a son of Vasudeva and Rohiṇī. Bhā. IX. 24. 46. 

गद
Gada  (III)--a son of Vasudeva and Devarakṣitā. Bhā. IX. 24. 52.

गद
Gada  (IV)--Art and science of, learnt by Duryodhana from Balarāma; 1) Bhā. X. 57. 26: Br. III. 71. 84. a war weapon. 2) M. 140. 14.

गद
Gada  (V)--an Asura, stronger than Vajrāyudha, gave his bone to Brahmā on the latter's request; Viśvakarman made it a gada. Vā. 109. 3-4.

गद
Gada  (VI)--a son of Bhadrā and Vasudeva. Vi. IV. 15. 24.

गदवर्मन्
Gadavarman --a son of Śūra. Br. III. 71. 138. Vā. 96. 137.

गदा
Gadā  (I)--a votary of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. III. 1. 35: Vā. 55. 12. 109. 4 and 11.

गदा
Gadā  (II)--Mace of Viṣṇu. Vi. IV. 15. 13: V. 34. 23.

गदाधर
Gadādhara --Viṣṇu as; the first narrator of the Matsya Purāṇa; in the Tārakāmaya war; 1) M. 1. 10: 176. 30: 178. 23 and 46 Vā. 106. 55. boon to Dharmavrata after she became a stone. 2) Vā. 60. 77: 107. 47: 108. 52: 109. 12, 20.

गदालोलम्
Gadālolam --a mahātīrtha where Hari got the Gadā cleaned after breaking Heti's head with it. Vā. 111. 75-6. 

गदाशिक्षा
Gadāśikṣā  (I)--taught to Duryodhana by Baladeva. 2) Vi. IV. 13. 106. ^1 Vā. 96. 83.

गदिनी
Gadinī --the wife of Yama. M. 286. 8.

गन्ध
Gandha --a son of Upamadga (see gandhamodavaha). (Cal. Edn.). Vi. IV. 14. 9.

गन्धकाली
Gandhakālī --the daughter of Pitṛs, born in the Parāśara line and mother of Vyāsa; again born as Matsyayoni. After her came Acchoda lake. Br. III. 13. 76-9: Vā. 77. 74-5.

गन्धम्
Gandham --said to be essence milked from cow-earth by the Gandharvas. M. 7. 14: 10. 24: 16. 26.

गन्धमाद
Gandhamāda  (I)--followed Rāma in his expedition to Lankā. Bhā. IX. 10. 19: Br. III. 71. 112.

गन्धमाद
Gandhamāda  (II)--a son of Śvaphalka and Gāndinī. Bhā. IX. 24. 17.

गन्धमादन
Gandhamādana  (I)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 231.

गन्धमादन
Gandhamādana  (II)--a forest on the south of Ilāvṛta. Vi. II. 2. 25. 

गन्धमादन
Gandhamādana  (III)--a mountain range to the East of Ilāvṛta and to the W. of Meru and a boundary limit of Bhadrāśva. On its top falls the Sītā. 1) Bhā. V. 16. 10: 17. 6. Vi. II. 2. 18, 29 and 39: The abode of Nara and Nārāyaṇa, visited by Brahmā. 2) Bhā. IV. 1. 58: V. 1. 8. Vi. V. 24. 5. To this Mucukunda (s.v.) repaired after leaving the cave in which he slept. 3) Bhā. X. 52. 3. Location and length mentioned. Residence of Vānaras. Here Urvaśi stayed for some time with Aila. Here Viṣṇu performed tapas as Dharmasuta and created Urvaśī. 4) Br. II. 15. 40: 17. 16: III. 7. 194: 25. 67: 66. 7: IV. 31. 16: M. 61. 21: 24. 19. One of the Viṣkambagiris round Meru. Here are Ketumālavarṣa and Vaibhāja forest; the crown of Jambūdvīpa; full of celestial groups. 5) M. 83. 22, 32-3: 113. 45: 154. 434: 183. 1. A place of pilgrimage sacred to Kāmākṣī. 6) M. 13. 26. On its south Ānīla and Niṣādhas, and on its East Mālyavan. 7) Vā. 34. 35: 35. 16: 42. 25: 43. 1: 46. 17: 91. 7. The place where the Bhadari āśrama was situated and to which came Uddhava for penance. 8) Vi. V. 37. 34 and 37.

गन्धमादन
Gandhamādana Vaṛṣa --the kingdom of Ketumāla. Br. II. 14. 52: Vā 23. 159: 33. 45.

गन्धमाधन
Gandhamādhana --a division of Jambūdvīpa. Vi. II. 1. 23.

गन्धमोज
Gandhamoja --a son of Upamadga. Vi. IV. 14. 9.

गन्धर्व
Gandharva  (I)--a Kādraveya Nāga, 1) Br. III. 7. 36: Vā. 61. 79: 62. 100: 69. 73: 100. 159: 101. 3 and 28: 106. 59. lives in trees. 2) Br. I. 7. 84: 8. 40.

गन्धर्व
Gandharva  (II)--a kingdom noted for horses; 1) Br. IV. 16. 17: M. 114. 8: 121. 48. a division of the Bhāratavarṣa. 2) Vā. 45. 79: Vi. II. 3. 7.

गन्धर्व
Gandharva  (III)--a god to be worshipped in housebuilding. M. 253. 25. 

गन्धर्व
Gandharva  (IV)--the fourteenth kalpa; here Gāndhārasvara and Nāda came into being. Vā. 21. 32.

गन्धर्व
Gandharvas  (I)--born of Ariṣṭā and Kaśyapa; 1) M. 5. 1: 6. 29 and 45: Vi. I. 5. 46: 21. 25. worshipped for personal beauty; 2) Bhā. II. 3. 6. sent by Indra to disturb Mārkaṇḍeya's tapaṣ; 3) Ib. XII. 8. 16. killed in crores by Bharata; 4) Ib. IX. 11. 13. other references to. 5) Ib. IV. 6. 9: V. 1. 8; VI. 7. 3; VII. 7. 50; 8. 38; X. 3. 6: 4. 11: 25. 31: 55. 23: 62. 19; 85. 41; XI. 6. 3: 12. 3: 14. 5: 16. 33: 31. 2: XII. 11. 47: Br. IV. 1. 155: 2. 26: 4. 2: 9. 77: 15. 24: 20. 48 and 101: 33. 15: 39. 56. A gaṇa moving with the sun by turns praising him; 6) Br. II. 23. 27 and 50: 32. 1-2: 35. 191. sang Sāma in Vāruṇī yajña. 7) Br. III. 1. 25. Three steps inferior to gods; semidivine like Yakṣas, Rākṣasas and Piśācas; frequent Kailāsa; vanquished by Rāvaṇa; Citraratha was their overlord. 8) Br. III. 7. 167-70, 255: 8. 10: 10. 37: 24. 59. IV. 36. 16: M. 8. 6. milked the earth and preserved its essence Gandha (s.v.); worship Barhiṣad manes; attended with Apsaras at the yajña of Arjuna Kārtavīrya; 9) M. 10. 24: 13. 17; 15. 3; 37. 2 and 4: 43. 22. world of; 10) M. 78. 11: 246. 61: 247. 11. live in trees, 11) Br. II. 7. 84: Vā. 9. 55: 21. 33: 30. 86: 33. 64: 34. 55. ety. from singing; 12) Br. II. 8. 40. according to Vā. P. sons of Bhadra. 13) Vā. 66. 73.

गन्धर्व
Gandharvas  (II)--(Mauneya) in number 60 crores, overcame the Nāgas of Rasātala and deprived them of their jewels, etc.; ultimately defeated by Purukutsa, son of Māndhāta. Vi. IV. 3. 4-9.

गन्धर्वनगर
Gandharvanagara (Gandharvapura) --an imaginary city compared to this māyā-ridden universe; seen by the company of merchants (jīvas) wandering in samsāra. Bhā. IV. 12. 15. V. 13. 3 and 7.

गन्धर्ववदन
Gandharvavadana --is Hayagrīva. Br. IV. 32. 40. 

गन्धर्व
Gandharva viṣaya --Bharata in charge of; killed three crores of them. Vi. IV. 4. 100.

गन्धर्वि
Gandharvi --the name om rising from Gāndhāra. Vā. 20. 3.

गन्धवती
Gandhavatī --the sabhā of Vāyu on the sixth slope of Meru. Vā. 34. 89.

गन्धाकर्षणीका
Gandhākarṣaṇīkā --a śakti. Br. IV. 19. 18: 36. 69: 44. 118.

गन्धात्मकंगुणम्
Gandhātmakaṃguṇam --the quality of the earth eaten up by waters in Pratyāhāra. Vā. 102. 7.

गभस्तलम्
Gabhastalam --of pink red; here are cities of Kālanemī, Gajakarṇa and other Asuras and Nāgas. Vā. 50. 12, 14, 31-33.

गभस्ति
Gabhasti --a R. in Śākadvīpa; same as Sukṛta. Br. II. 19. 96: M. 122. 33. Vi. II. 4. 65.

गभस्तिमत्
Gabhastimat  (I)--one of the nine divisions of Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā II. 16. 9 M. 114. 8: Vā. 45. 79. Vi. II. 3. 6.

गभस्तिमत्
Gabhastimat  (II)--a region of the Pātāla, and with brown soil. Vi. II. 5. 2-3. 

गभीर
Gabhīra --a son of Pravīra; ruled for 30 years. Br. III. 74. 186.

गम्भीर
Gambhīra  (I)--(Gabhīra-Br. P.) a son of Rabhasa and father of Akriya. Bhā. IX. 17. 10.

गम्भीर
Gambhīra  (II)--a son of Bhautya Manu. Br. IV. 1. 114.

गम्भीर
Gambhīra buddhi  (I)--a son of Indrasāvarṇi. Bhā. VIII. 13. 33.

गम्भीर
Gambhīra buddhi  (II)--a son of Manu Bhauma. Vi. III. 2. 45.

गय
Gaya  (I)--a sage who knew the power of Viṣṇu's yoga. Bhā. II. 7. 44.

गय
Gaya  (II)--a son of Ulmuka and Puṣkariṇī. Bhā. IV. 13. 17.

गय
Gaya  (III)--a son of Havirdhāna (Ūsu?) and Āgneyī. Bhā. IV. 24. 8: Br. II. 36. 108: 37. 24: Vā. 63. 23. Vi. I. 14. 2.

गय
Gaya  (IV)--a son of Nakta and Druti: A rājaṛṣi and an amśa of Hari; a mahāpuruṣa who ruled his kingdom righteously and with devotion to Hari. His name is sung in an ancient gāthā, as the upholder of dharma, Vedas, Brahmaṇas and yajñas. His queen was Gāyantī who was mother of three sons Citraratha and others. At the end of  his rule, he renounced the throne and sought refuge with Hari. Bhā. V. 15. 6-14: X. 60. 41: Br. II. 14. 68: Vā. 33. 57. Vi. II. 1. 38.

गय
Gaya  (V)--though lord of seven dvīpas, he was not content. He wanted more territory. Bhā. VIII. 19. 23; XII. 3. 10.

गय
Gaya  (VI)--a son of (Ilā) Sudyumna and Lord of Dakṣiṇāpatha; 1) Bhā. IX. 1. 41. M. 12. 17. king of the eastern kingdom with its capital Gaya; 2) Br. III. 60. 18. a Rājaṛṣi. 3) Vā. 85. 19. Performed a big sacrifice and gave lavish gifts to all Brahmaṇas; even gods were pleased and granted a boon perpetuating his name by a city Gayāpuri; attained Viṣṇuloka. 4) Vā. 112. 1-6.

गय
Gaya  (VII)--a son of Angirasa and Ūru. M. 4. 43.

गय
Gaya  (VIII)--a son of Balakāśva. Vā. 91. 61.

गयन्ती
Gayantī --(Gāyantī-Br. P.), wife of Gaya (s.v.) and mother of three sons. Bhā. V. 15. 14.

गयशिरस्
Gayaśiras --sacred to Hari. Bhā. VII. 14. 30.

गया
Gayā  (I)--a R. visited by Balarāma. Bhā. X. 79. 11. 

गया
Gayā  (II)--(c) the kingdom of; sacred for śrāddha offering. Dharmapṛṣṭa, Brahmasaras, and Gṛdhravaṭa are chief places here; capital of Gaya; Paraśurāna performed śrāddha here. 1) M. 12. 17. Br. III. 13. 104: 19-11: 47. 17: 60. 19: Vā. 85. 19. A pitṛtīrtham being the residence of Pitāmaha; a gāthā says that any one son may visit Gayā and satisfy all Pitṛs. 2) M. 22. 4-6 and 26: 110. 2; 192. 11: 204. 8: 207. 40. Fit for śrāddha; a man devoted to Gayāśrāddha must dress himself in beggar's garments, circumambulate the grāma, and the next one with shaving and begging money; śrāddha in Brahmakuṇḍa and other places; going to Dharmaranya after worshipping Gadādhara; feed the Brahmans there without enquiring into their family, conduct or learning; offer piṇḍas in Gayārūpa, even for unknown cognates and names; piṇḍa for one's own self with tila; by this even heinous crimes are mitigated; a superior tīrtha; best in Makara, eclipses of the sun and moon, and Caitra and Pretapakṣa (Mahālaya); others are adhīmāsa, birthday, the evening of Guru and Śukra, the stay of Bṛhaspati in Simha which is once in twelve years. 3) Vā. 77. 97: 80. 45: 83. 12-44. The face of the Veda; 4) Ib. 104. 77. Śambhu, Viṣṇu and Ravi; sacred to Gaya. 5) Ib. 112. 20.

गया
Gayā  (III)--six in number, Gāyāgaya, Gayāditya, Gāyatrī, Gadādhara, Gayā, Gayāsura, all tending to salvation. Vā. 112. 60.

गयाकूट
Gayākūṭa --in Gayā. Vā. 112. 52.

गयाख्यानम्
Gayākhyānam --the legend about Gayā. Vā. 112. 62, 67. 

गयातीर्थम्
Gayātīrtham --origin of; the austerities of Gayāsūra here bearing a stone on his head. Here Gadādhara stood steadfast lest he should move; on this Brahmā performed a sacrifice; shaving and fasting are prescribed in tīrthas but not for this place; measurement 2(1/2) krośa; Gayākṣetram 5 krośas and Gayāśira 1 krośa, the best of all tīrthas. Vā. 105. 4-46.

गयादित्य
Gayāditya --the north sun. Vā. 109. 21.

गयापुरि
Gayāpuri --after the name of king Gaya. Vā. 112. 5.

गयायात्रा
Gayāyātrā --pilgrimage to Gayā; preliminaries; performance of Śrāddha, going round the village, travel to another village and so on, every day without begging food, etc.: purity and selflessness to be maintained; reaching Gayā, bathing and performance of Śrāddha according to his Veda śākha; the next day visit to Pretaparvata, bath in Brahmakuṇḍa and the offer of piṇḍas in other places. See Gaya. Vā. 110. 1-9.

गयाशिर
Gayāśira --one krośa in extent; 1) Vā. 105. 29. Śrāddha there lifts 100 generations. 2) Ib. 105. 31.

गयाश्राद्धम्
Gayāśrāddham --one of the four means to mukti; 1) Vā. 105. 16. special varṇa to mother; 2) Ib. 108. 35: 110. 17. for piṇḍa; 3) Ib. 23. 59. suitable occasions for. 4) Ib. 105. 47-8.

गयासुर
Gayāsura --had a stone over his head on which Brahmā performed sacrifices; Gaya perforhmed yāga in Śvetakalpavārāha; after him the name for the place; the son who goes to Gayā, he who resides at Gayā for three pakṣas  purifies seven descendants; or residence at least for 15, 7 or 3 days; one offers piṇḍa with tila to forefathers and to oneself; the four heinous offences are expiated with the ritual at Gayā. Out of the navel of Viṣṇu came Brahmā who created Asuras one of whom was Gaya, 125 yojanas in length and 60 in breadth; a Vaiṣnava; performed tapas at Kolāhala hill for 1000 of years; 1)  all gods went to Viṣṇu. Gayāsura with whom Viṣṇu was pleased was granted his request, to be the best of all; Yamapuri became vacant; all went to Brahmā and he went to Viṣṇu; on the latter's advice Brahmā went to Gayā and wanted to perform yāga on his body; a true devotee, Gaya agreed readily. But finding him unstable Brahmā ordered Dharma to place a stone on his head and the devas to stand to maintain balance; Viṣnu was again approached who gave his mūrti and finding Gaya still unstable Gadādhara himself took his stand and made the stone motionless. Pleased, Viṣṇu gave him what he desired. It was that they should all live there and that the people who did rites there must reach Brahmaloka. See Gayā tīrtham. Vā. 105. 5-13. ch. 106. (whole): 108. 8: 109. 13.

गरिमा
Garimā --a siddhidevī. Br. IV. 19. 4: 36. 51.

गरिष्ट
Gariṣṭa --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 16.

गरुड
Garuḍa (Garutmat)  (I)--a son of Tārkṣya (Kāśyapa) and Vinatā (Suparṇā), and vehicle of Hari. 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 22: III. 19. 11. Br. III. 7. 29: 8. 11. M. 6. 34: 146. 22. Vā. 49. 10; 69. 66: 70. 11: 72. 45. Vi. I. 21. 18. Has abode in Śālmalidvīpa. 2) Bhā. V. 20. 8. Took Kṛṣṇa to Madhuvana; 3) Ib. IV. 9. 1. Identified with Hari, and regarded as the embodiment of the Vedas. 4) Ib. VI 8. 29. VIII. 3. 31. Attacked Asura followers of Bali, and knowing Hari's mind, he bound Bali with cords of Varuṇa. 5) Ib. VIII. 21. 16 and 26. Serves as a watch for Kṣīroda. When he saw Bali carrying away Hari's crown-jewel, he pursued him and recovered it after a fight. When he saw on his return from Gomanta, he placed it on His  head and belauded him, requesting him for opportunities of service to Him, who ordered him to go back and come whenever He thought of him. 6) Ib. X. 53 (V) 10-19. His winning nectar is compared to Kṛṣṇa winning Vaidarbhī in svayamvara. 7) Ib. X. 52. 17. Kālīya, the enemy of snakes, freed from fear of; entered into an agreement with snakes of Ramaṇaka to give him bali every fortnight. Kālīya failed to do this, and after a fight escaped to the river Kālindī where Garuḍa could not go, as he was under a curse. It happened once that Garuḍa took a kingfish from the river against the wish of the sage Saubhari who cursed that Garuḍa's coming again there would mean the end of his life. 8) Ib. 16. 63; 17. 1-11. Vi. V. 7. 78. Attacked by Mura, 9) Bhā. X. 59. 7-8. killed all elephants of Naraka, 10) Ib. 59. 19. Vi. V. 29. 14. carried Kṛṣṇa to Indra's city. Defeated Varuṇa attacking Kṛṣṇa, flung Śiva and his bull to a distance of a hundred dhanus. Discomfited Airāvata of Indra, and took Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā safely to Dvārakā. 11) Bhā. 65 (V) 1: 66 (V) 22-25, 48; 67 (V) 11-14, 38-39, M. 150. 219 Vi. V. 30. 64-70. XI. 30. 44. Garuḍa standard of Hari. 12) Br. III. 71. 248. Praise of Hari. 13) Bhā. IV. 30. 6. XI. 27. 28. Took nectar for mother's sake to Somaka hill of Plakṣa; married five daughters of Tāmra and became father of birds in all the world. 14) Br. II. 19. 11-12: III. 7. 448-51: M. 122. 15. Younger brother of Aruṇa. 15) M. 150-53. Worship of, on the Bhīmadvādaśi, and in the Lakṣa homa of Grahabali. Icon of. 16) M. 53. 41; 69. 26; 93. 99: 258. 11 and 12. In the Tārakāmaya: in the war with Kālanemī: performed tapas at Kanakhala. 17) M. 152. 6-7, 36: 153. 181: 171. 50: 178. 32 and 50: 193. 70: 249. 35 had a number of wives, sons and grandsons; the eater of all cruel snakes--his descendants spread over largely the whole of Śālmalidvīpa, and the mountains Devakūṭa, Maṇimanta, Sahasraśikhara, Parnamala, Sukeśa, and Sataśruga, the five-peaked Kauraja, Hemakūṭa etc. 18) Vā. 69. 328-335. 

गरुड
Garuḍa  (II)--a son of Viśveśā. M. 171. 50.

गरुडध्वज
Garuḍadhvaja --Viṣṇu (Kṛṣṇa). M. 150. 211: 152. 21: 163. 106-7. Vā. 24. 90: 96. 239.

गरुड
Garuḍa Purāṇa --a mahāpurāṇa comprising 19000 ślokas. Bhā. XII. 7. 23: 13. 8: Vi. IV. 6. 23.

गरुत्मत्
Garutmat --see Garuḍa. Bhā. III. 21. 11. Br. II. 19. 11. Vā. 69. 328, 335: Vi. V. 30. 64: 34, 13 and 23.

गरुत्मत्हृदया
Garutmat-hṛdayā --a goddess following Bhavamālinī. M. 179. 71.

गर्ग
Garga  (I)--a son of (Bhuva) Manyu and father of Śini, (Chini). M. 49. 36: Vi. IV. 19. 21-23.

गर्ग
Garga  (II)--the Purohita of Yādavas. Urged by Vasudeva, he went to the Vraja of Nanda who welcomed him as befitted a Guru, praising him as the great author of Jyotiṣa śāstra. Requested by Nanda to do nāma samskāra to Kṛṣṇa and Rāma without Kaṃśa's knowledge, he did so and returned to his place. 1) Bhā. X. 8. 1-20. Vi. II. 5. 26: V. 6. 8. 9. He held Kṛṣṇa and Rāma to be divine incarnations. 2) Bhā. X. 46. 23. He informed Nanda that Kṛṣṇa was the son of Vasudeva and an amśa of Nārāyaṇa. 3) Ib. 26. 15-23. He officiated at Upanayana samskāras of the two brothers. 4) Ib. 45. 26-29. He had also informed Mucukunda that Nārāyaṇa was to be born on  the earth as Kṛṣṇa. 5) Ib. 51. 45. He was invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira. 6) Ib. 74. 8.

गर्ग
Garga  (III)--an Angirasa and a mantrakṛt. Br. II. 32. 107: M. 145. 101.

गर्ग
Garga  (IV)--the Purohita of Haiha. Br. III. 28. 39.

गर्ग
Garga  (V)--a son of Pratardana. Br. III. 67. 69: Vā. 92. 65.

गर्ग
Garga  (VI)--the preceptor of the seven sons of Kauśika who tended his cow, killed and made a meal of it in a famine. For this sin they were cursed to have five rebirths; no marriage alliance with Bṛhaspati. M. 20. 3: 196. 24.

गर्ग
Garga  (VII)--an author of architecture. M. 252. 3.

गर्ग
Garga  (VIII)--a ṛtvik at Brahmā's sacrifice. Vā. 106. 35.

गर्गभूमि
Gargabhūmi --the son of Gārgya; of Vatsa line. Br. III. 67. 78.

गर्गेश्वरम्
Gargeśvaram --a tīrtham on the Narmadā. M. 191. 82. 3.

गर्जनम्
Garjanam --a tīrtham near Yantreśvara on the Narmadā. M. 190. 3. 

गर्जिनी
Garjinī --a Varṇa śakti. Br. IV. 44. 60.

गर्त
Garta --a son of Vasiṣṭha and Ūrjā. Br. II. 11. 41.

गर्दभ
Gardabhas --the asses of the Tāmasa line. Vi. I. 21. 17.

गर्दभाक्ष
Gardabhākṣa --a son of Bali. Vā. 67. 83.

गर्दभिन
Gardabhinas(la) --ten rulers of this line are distinguished; see Maunas. 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 29. Vi. IV. 24. 51. Seven of them ruled for 72 years (94, M. P.) after Ābhiras. 2) Br. III. 74. 172 and 4: M. 273. 18-20: Vā. 99. 359.

गर्दभी
Gardabhī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 18.

गर्दभीमुख
Gardabhīmukha --a Pravara sage. M. 199. 16.

गर्भ
Garbha  (I)--a son of Turvasu. M. 48. 1.

गर्भ
Garbha  (II)--the child in embryo; 1) Bhā. III. 31. 1-10. Vā. 97. 46-57. a union of Śukra-springing from majja which is from bone which is due to medas, which again results from flesh, that is due to śoṇitam, emerging from Rasa or waters, Śukra constitutes of Soma and soṇitam of Agnī. The former resides in Kaphavarga and the latter in Pittavarga. The place of kapha is heart, and that of pitta is the navel region. Stages in the garbha and formation described. 2) Br. III. 72. 45-57. Vā. 14. 18-26. 

गर्भ
Garbha  (III)--the four central parts out of 16, into which a site (of a temple to be built) is divided; measurements of its foundations, walls, doorways, etc.; likewise other parts of temple bear specific relation to the garbha. M. 269. 1-8.

गर्भभूमि
Garbhabhūmi --a son of Gārgya. Vā. 92. 73.

गर्भाधानम्
Garbhādhānam --a ceremonial connected with pregnancy; a samskāra. Br. III. 42. 43: M. 275. 16.

गर्भिणी
Garbhiṇī --restrictions to be observed by, laid down by Kāśyapa for Diti: Her failure to observe them gave Indra the loophole he was seeking to destroy her foetus; see Diti, Indra. M. 7. 37, 47: 52. 4.

गर्वि
Garvi --a sudharmāna god. Br. IV. 1. 60.

गवय
Gavaya --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 232.

गवय
Gavayas --created by Brahmā from his feet. Vi. I. 5. 49.

गवल्गण
Gavalgaṇa --the father of Samjaya. Bhā. I. 13. 30.

गवाक्ष
Gavākṣa  (I)--a Dānava with manuṣya dharma. Br. III. 6. 16: Vā. 68. 16.

गवाक्ष
Gavākṣa  (II)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 243. 

गवाक्ष
Gavākṣa  (III)--a son of Śambhu. Vā. 67. 81.

गवाम्
Gavām vratam --a sūktam of the Sāma Veda recited in tank ritual. M. 58. 37.

गविष्ठ
Gaviṣṭha  (I)--a Dānava; in the sabhā of Hiranyakaśipu. Br. III. 6. 4: M. 161. 79.

गविष्ठ
Gaviṣṭha  (II)--a son of Angirasa. M. 196. 2.

गविष्ठिर
Gaviṣṭhira --an Ātreya and a sage; a mantrakṛt and gotrakara. Br. II. 32. 113: M. 145. 107: 197. 7-8.

गविस्थिर
Gavisthiras --an Ātreya clan. Br. III. 8. 85; Vā. 70. 77.

गविष्णु
Gaviṣṇu --one of the ten horses of the moon's chariot. Br. II. 23. 57.

गवेषण
Gaveṣaṇa  (I)--a son of Citraka and father of two sons. Br. III. 71. 114, 259: Vā. 96. 113.

गवेषण
Gaveṣaṇa  (II)--a son of Vasudeva and Śrāddhadevi(M. P.) adept in citra warfare. Father of Bhūri and Bhūrīndrasena; 1) Br. III. 71. 184: M. 46. 19: 47. 22: Vā. 96. 250. in a previous birth was Yama and created forests. 2) Vā 96. 181-2.

गवेषण
Gaveṣaṇa  (III)--a son of Aśvinī and Akrūra. M. 45. 32. 

गवेष्ठि
Gaveṣṭhi  (I)--a son of Virocana, and father of three sons. Vā. 67. 76-77.

गवेष्ठि
Gaveṣṭhi  (II)--one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 4.

गवेष्ठि
Gaveṣṭhi  (III)--a mānava with manuṣya dharma. Vā. 68. 16.

गव्यूति
Gavyūti --2000 dhanus. Bhā. V. 29. 19: Br. I. 7. 100: Vā. 8. 106: 101. 126.

गहन
Gahana --a chief Vānara. Br. III. 7. 235.

गा
Gā  (I)--a daughter of Kākustha, and wife of Yati. Br. III. 68. 13: Vā. 93. 14.

गा
Gā  (II)--a name of Sarasvatī. Vā. 23. 5, 55.

गांग
Gāṃga --a Gandharva. Vā. 69. 26.

गांगोदधि
Gāṃgodadhi --a pravara of Angiras M. 196. 17.

गाणपता
Gāṇapatā mantras --sacred to Gaṇapati. Br. IV. 38. 5.

गाणपत्यम्
Gāṇapatyam --the abode of Gaṇapati; 1) Br. II. 27. 123: IV. 7. 59. attained by the Sūdra who is not addicted to drink. 2) Vā. 101. 354. 

गाण्डीव
Gāṇḍīva --the arrow of Arjuna; 1) Bhā. I. 7. 16: 9. 15; X. 58. 13. the bow of Arjuna lost its power after Kṛṣṇa's departure to heaven. 2) Vi. V. 38. 21, 23 and 45.

गात्रवत्
Gātravat --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Mādrī (Lakṣmaṇā-Vi. P.) Bhā. X. 61. 15; Vi. V. 32. 4.

गाथ
Gāthas --ancient popular songs; a feature of the Purāṇas; Nāraḍa on Vāli's sacrifices; on Pitṛs, on Yayāti, on Kārtavīrya, on Rāma; 1) Br. II. 34. 21: III. 7. 272: 19. 9: 63. 192: 68. 96: 69. 19. IV. 15. 32: M. 43. 23: 204. 2 and 19: Vi. III. 6. 15. about Gayā and the Narmadā; 2) M. 22. 5: 186. 5: 207. 39-40. sung by divine ṛṣis in Khaṭvānga's Yajña; 3) Vā. 60. 21: 73. 41: 83. 10: 88. 191: 93. 94: 94. 19: 96. 13. by Prahlāda on Hari. 4) Vi. I. 17. 29.

गाथी
Gāthī --an Ārṣeya pravara of Angiras. M. 196. 22.

गाधि
Gādhi --(Kauśika) a royal sage who knew the yoga powers of Hari; 1) Bhā. I. 19. 9: II. 7. 44. Vā. 91. 65-6. the son of Kuśāmbu(a) (KuśanābhaVā. P.) Indra incarnate. His daughter was Satyavatī whom the Brāhmaṇa Ṛcīka wanted to marry. Gādhi thought him unsuitable and asked for a bride-fee of a thousand horses white like the moon and with one ear black. This condition was satisfied with the help of Varuṇa, and Ṛcīka got her married. Gādhi's wife took the consecrated caru intended for her daughter and became the mother of a Brahmavit, by name Viśvāmītra. 2) Bhā. IX. 15. 4-10: 16. 28 and 32. Vi. IV. 7. 11-16. He was desirous of more territory on the earth. 3) Bhā. XII. 3. 9. Son of Kuśika, wife Paurukutsi. 4) Br. III. 66. 35. 58.

गाधिपुत्र
Gādhiputra --a name of Akrūra. Vā. 96. 80. 

गाधेय
Gādheya --see Viśvāmitra. M. 145. 111.

गान्दिनी
Gāndinī --a daughter of Kāśirāja, married Śvaphalka, mother of Akrūra and other sons, used to present a cow every day to a Brāhmaṇa (born after 12 years in the womb when her parents gave a gift of a cow everyday to a Brahman-Vi. P. for three years). Bhā. IX. 24. 15: X. 41. 6: 49. 3: 57. 32: Br. III. 71. 82-110. Vā. 96. 97, 105, 109: Vi. IV. 13. 124-6; 14. 7.

गान्धर्व
Gāndharva --one of the nine divisions of Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 9. M. 48. 7.

गान्धर्वम्
Gāndharvam  (I)--a form of marriage by which Kṛṣṇa married Rukmiṇī, and Duṣyanta married Śakuntalā. Princesses usually chose their husbands. Bhā. III. 3. 3; IX. 20. 15-16; Br. IV. 15. 5; Vi. III. 10. 24.

गान्धर्वम्
Gāndharvam  (II)--the science of music; a vidyā; mūrchanas and their lakṣaṇas in; 1) Vā. 86. 26, 36-69. Vi. III. 6. 28. the music displayed at the court of Brahmā; also the music played upon by Kṛṣṇa. 2) Bhā. IX. 3. 30; X. 21. 5[1]; Br. III. 61. 21, 26-8.

गान्धर्व
Gāndharva loka --attained by Purūravas. Vi. IV. 6. 93.

गान्धर्व
Gāndharva veda --music. Bhā. III. 12. 38.

गान्धर्वी
Gāndharvī  (I)--a daughter of Surabhi and Kaśyapa, and a sister of Rudras; mother of horses like Uccaiśśravas. Br. III. 3. 73-7.

गान्धर्वी
Gāndharvī  (II)--a daughter of Gandharvas. Vā. 69. 10. 

गान्धर्वी
Gāndharvī  (III)--a R. from the lake Viṣṇupadam. Br. II. 18. 68; Vā. 47. 65.

गान्धार
Gāndhāra  (I)--the son of Aru(d)dha (Ārabdha-Bhā. P., Vi. P.). After him came the Gāndhāra country famous for horses. Father of Dharma. Bhā. IX. 23. 15; Br. III. 74. 9-10; Vā. 99. 9; Vi. IV. 17. 4.

गान्धार
Gāndhāra  (II) (svara)--an auspicious one; 1) M. 243. 21. the third of the seven notes of music. 2) Vā. 21-32; 86. 37.

गान्धार
Gāndhāra  (III) (c)--a northern kingdom and tribe whose king contemporary of Kṛṣṇa was Śakuni who was an ally of Jarāsandha. Hence his subjects were enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus. Śakuni himself was placed on the east of Gomanta hill during its siege. Here Bharata's sons Takṣa and Puṣkara ruled; 1) Bhā. X. 52. 11 [6]; [50 (v) 3]. M. 114. 41; 121. 46; 144. 57. Br. II. 16. 47; 18. 47; 31. 83; III. 63. 190; 73. 108; 74. 9-10. Vā. 88. 189. noted for horses; 2) Vā. 99. 10. also gandhara.

गान्धार
Gāndhāra --a son of Śaradvat and a grandson of Druhyu, after whom was named the country Gāndhāra; had choice horses of the Āraṭṭa country. M. 48. 6-7.

गान्धार
Gāndhāras --people of. Vā. 45. 116; 47. 45; 58. 82; 98. 107.

गन्धारक
Gandhāraka --a kind of sweet rice; unfit for śrāddha. Vi. III. 16. 8.

गान्धारकायण
Gāndhārakāyaṇas --of Agastya family. M. 202. 2.

गान्धारग्राम
Gāndhāragrāma --musical term. Vā. 86. 41, 50. 

गान्धारि
Gāndhāri  (I)--the wife of Dhṛtarāṣṭra and mother of hundred sons--Duryodhana and others. 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 26. M. 50. 47-8. Vā. 99. 242. Vi. IV. 20. 39. Daughter of Subala. 2) Bhā. X. 84. 1. Met by Kṛṣṇa and Rāma after the burning of lac house. 3) Ib. 57. 2. Heard of Kṛṣṇa's marriage from his wives and was lost in wonder. 4) Ib. X. 84. 1. Her grief at Bhīṣma's death; was consoled by Yudhiṣṭhira. 5) Ib. I. 9. 48. Felt keenly Kṛṣṇa's separation. Welcomed Vidura to Hastināpura. 6) Ib. 10. 9; 13. 4. Approved of the anointing of Yudhiṣṭhira. 7) Ib. X. 80[5]. Went with her daughter to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse, and there met Kṛṣṇa and Vṛṣṇis. 8) Ib. 82. 24. Settled on the banks of the Ganges with Dhṛtarāṣṭra, following him to the Himalayas. As a chaste queen she ascended his funeral pyre. 9) Ib. I. 8. 3; 13. 29 and 57.

गान्धारि
Gāndhāri  (II)--one of the wives of Dhṛṣṭi. Father of Sumitra. Br. III. 71. 18-19.

गान्धारी
Gāndhārī  (III)--the wife of Vṛṣṇi; gave birth to Sumitra. M. 45. 1: Vā. 96. 17.

गान्धारी
Gāndhārī  (IV)--a queen of Kṛṣṇa. M. 47. 13.

गान्धारि
Gāndhāri  (V)--a daughter of Surabhi and Kaśyapa. Vā. 66. 71.

गायत्रम्
Gāyatram --a sūktam of the Sāma Veda to be recited in tank ritual; 1) M. 58. 36; Vā. 9. 48. from the first face of Brahmā. 2) Vi. I. 5. 53.

गायत्री
Gāyatrī  (I)--a poetic metre; 1) Bhā. III. 12. 45; XI. 21. 41; M. 125. 47; Br. II. 8. 50; 13. 145; Vā. 23. 65, 69; 31. 47; 50. 165; 51. 64; 55. 42; 69. 67; 106. 58; 109. 21. a sister of Aruṇa and Garuḍa; recitation; 2) Bhā. XI. 17. 25; Br. III. 7. 30; M. 239. 9. wife of Prajāpati. 3) Vā. 21. 42. 

गायत्रि
Gāyatri  (II)--one of the seven horses yoked to sun's chariot; expiation for sin; in Sandhya worship. Br. II. 21. 113; 22. 72; 26. 44; IV. 7. 69. Vi. II. 8. 5; IV. 6. 89.

गायत्रि
Gāyatri  (III)--a śakti; 1) Br. IV. 44. 86. mind-born daughter of Brahmā, inseparable from him; a goddess enshrined in the Vedas; as the basis of dharma in the Bhāgavata P. 2) M. 3. 32; 4. 7, 9 and 24; 53. 20; 171. 23.

गायत्री
Gāyatrī  (IV)--Raudrī, contemplated by Brahmā in the 21st kalpa; gauḥ in Lohita kalpa. 2) Ib. 23. 69.

गायत्रीतीर्थम्
Gāyatrītīrtham --in Gayā; bathing at and offering of Prātassandhyā or morning prayers. Vā. 112. 21.

गायन
Gāyana --a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 23; Vā. 83. 61.

गायन
Gāyanas --Unfit for śrāddha. Vā. 79. 69.

गारुडकल्प
Gāruḍakalpa --the 14th kalpa; an account of, in the Garuḍa Purāṇa. M. 53. 53; 290. 6.

गारुडम्
Gāruḍam --the Purāṇa of 19000 verses narrated by Kṛṣṇa in the Gāruḍa kalpa; the origin of Garuḍa from the mundane egg; a gift of, takes one to Śiva loka, see Gāruḍa Purāṇa. M. 53. 53-4.

गारुडि
Gāruḍi --Sugrīva, the enemy of snakes in the Vaikārika hill. Vā. 39. 40. 

गार्ग
Gārga --a son of Bhuvamanyu. Vā. 99. 159.

गार्गपत्यपदम्
Gārgapatyapadam --in Gayā. Vā. 111. 50.

गार्गि
Gārgi  (I)--a contemporary of Vāsudeva-Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 73. 94.

गार्गि
Gārgi  (II)--a Vīthī comprising Sravaṇa, Dhaniṣṭha and Śatabhiṣak. Vā. 66. 51.

गार्ग्य
Gārgya  (I)--a son of Śini. From Kṣatriyas, Brāhmaṇa lines came into being. Bhā. IX. 21. 19.

गार्ग्य
Gārgya  (II)--a son of Veṇuhotra and father of Gargabhūmi, Vaṃśa and Vatsa--cursed Janamejaya; 1) Br. III. 67. 77-8; 68. 21. Vā. 92. 73-4. the curse led to the destruction of the chariot presented to Rudra by Yayāti; his son Lokagandha was put to trouble by the wicked king Janamejaya; 2) Vā. 93. 21. a sage. 3) Ib. 34. 63.

गार्ग्य
Gārgya  (III)--an ārṣeya pravara of Bhārgavas. M. 195. 38.

गार्ग्य
Gārgya  (IV)--a mantrakṛt. M. 196. 23 and 48. Vā. 59. 98; 65. 106.

गार्ग्य
Gārgya  (V)--a son of Ṛṣabha, the avatar of the lord. Vā. 23. 144. 

गार्ग्य
Gārgya  (VI)--a son of the avatar of the 28th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 223.

गार्ग्य
Gārgya  (VII)--a pupil of Bhāṣkala; was childless and hence was ridiculed as impotent by Syāla; was engaged in penance for Mahādeva for a son by living on iron ore; was appointed to produce a child on the Yavana queen and the son was Kālayavana. Vi. III. 4. 25; V. 23. 1-5.

गार्ग्य
Gārgyas --Kṣatriya-Brahmans. Vā. 99. 161. Vi. IV. 19. 23.

गार्ग्यहरि
Gārgyahari --a pravara. M. 196. 31.

गार्ग्यायन
Gārgyāyana --a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 23.

गार्दभि
Gārdabhi --one of the Pañcārṣeyas and a Bhārgava. M. 195. 34.

गार्हपत्य
Gārhapatya --the sacrificial fire; Dharmavrata performed austerities standing in this fire; 1) Vā. 97. 25, 111. the face of the Veda. 2) Ib. 104. 85; 106. 41. Nirmathya agni; father of two sons, Śamsya and Śukra. 3) Br. I. 12. 11; Vā. 29. 11.

गार्हायन
Gārhāyana --a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 23.

गालव
Gālava  (I)--a sage of the VIIIth manvantara, a sage of Sāvarṇi epoch; a Bhārgava gotrakara and a pravara sage. Bhā. VIII. 13. 15. Br. III. 66-72; IV. 1. 10. M. 9. 32; 195. 22; 196. 31. Vi. III. 2. 17. 

गालव
Gālava  (II)--a sage who came to see Kṛṣṇa at Syamantapañcaka. Bhā. X. 84. 4.

गालव
Gālava  (III)--a Vājin. Vā. 61. 25.

गालव
Gālava  (IV)--a Kauśika; 1) Vā. 100. 10. a son of Viśvāmitra, whose wife took him on her neck (gale baddha) to sell him for 100 cows. Satyavrata (Satyavrata Triśanku-Br. P.) released him and undertook to feed both of them so as to earn the gratitude and grace of Viśvāmitra. 2) Br. III. 63. 89; Vā. 88. 90.

गालव
Gālavas --of Kauśika gotra. Vā. 91. 100.

गालवित्
Gālavit --an Ārṣeya pravara of Angiras. M. 196. 22.

गाव
Gāva --a group of nāḍis of the sun pouring out heat. Br. II. 24. 29. Vā. 53. 22.

गिर
Gira --a son of Sāraṇa. Vā. 96. 165.

गिरि
Giri  (I)--a son of Śvaphalka. Bhā. IX. 24. 16.

गिरि
Giri  (II)--a son of Balarāma. Br. III. 71. 167. 

गिरि
Giri --worship of: Instituted by Kṛṣṇa as a substitute for Indra worship among the Gopas. 1) Bhā. X. 24. 25-32. Ety. of; precious stones and herbs in. 2) Br. II. 7. 11; 19. 137; M. 10. 25-6.

गिरिक
Girika  (I)--a son of Balarāma. Br. III. 71. 167.

गिरिक
Girika  (II)--a son of Sāraṇa. Vā. 96. 165.

गिरिकमिका
Girikamikā --a R. sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 39.

गिरिका
Girikā --the wife of Caidyoparicara (VidyoparicaraVā. P.). M. 50. 26; Vā. 99. 221.

गिरिक्षत्र
Girikṣatra --see Giri and Kṣatropakṣatra. Vi. IV. 14. 9.

गिरिगह्वर
Girigahvara --a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 47.

गिरिजा
Girijā(mantras) --sacred to Umā. Bhā. I. 15. 12. Br. IV. 38. 7.

गिरिजाशिव
Girijāśiva --represent Brahman. Br. IV. 43. 75 and 86.

गिरितनयाव्रतम्
Giritanayāvratam --sacred to Umā--performed for twelve months with different flowers for each month--also Amantaṝyavratam. M. 62. 39. 

गिरित्र
Giritra --a name of Śiva. Bhā. II. 1. 35.

गिरिदुर्ग
Giridurga --the best of six hill fortresses. M. 217. 7.

गिरिप्रजा
Giriprajā --the place where Kakṣivān attained Brahmanhood. Vā. 99. 93.

गिरियज्ञ
Giriyajña --the cult of mountains; appropriate to the environment of cow-herds. Vi. V. 10. 36; 37-8, 43-5.

गिरिरक्ष
Girirakṣa --a son of Gāndinī. Vā. 96. 110.

गिरिराजपुत्री
Girirājaputrī --surname of Umā, Pārvatī. Br. II. 25. 40; Vā. 54. 44, 95 and 115.

गिरिवर
Girivara --sacred to Lalitā. Br. IV. 44. 99.

गिरिव्रज
Girivraja --the capital of Jarāsandha, entered by Kṛṣṇa, Arjuna and Bhīma disguised as Brahmaṇas. 1) Bhā. X. 70. 24; 72. 16. Here Gautama retired and Kakṣivat attained Brahmanhood. Here too the Bṛhadrathas ruled. 2) Br. III. 74. 95, 110 and 128. Capital of Somādhi, son of Sahadeva killed in Bhārata war; capital of Śiśunāka after Nandivardhana while his son ruled from Benares. 3) M. 271. 19; 272. 6. Capital of the Māgadheyas. ^4 Vā. 99. 296, 315.

गिरिश
Giriśa --the name of Śiva, the lord of Bhūtas and Piśācas, having the trident in his hand. Bhā. II. 3. 7. Br. II. 27. 63. M. 47. 190. Vā. 69, 289; 70. 8. 

गीतनादित
Gītanādita --Mt. in the Gayāśilā where Rudra sports with Pārvatī. Vā. 108. 51.

गीतम्
Gītam --of apsaras and Gandharvas; 1) M. 7. 14; 61. 23; 82. 29; 105. 6; 120. 31. in connection with worship of trees and in founding new shrines. 2) Ib. 232. 15; 265. 7 and 51. Kinnaras famous for; 3) Vā. 54. 6; 69. 37. five deities of. 4) Ib. 87. 30.

गीतायोगिनी
Gītāyoginī --a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 48.

गीतालङ्कार
Gītālaṅkāras --description of. Vā. Ch. 87.

गीतिरथेन्द्र
Gītirathendra --also Gīticakranātha, Cakraratha. Br. IV. 19. 77; 34. 56; 36. 12.

गीर्वाण
Gīrvāṇa samiti --assemblage of gods. Br. III. 24. 62.

गुड
Guḍa --with ghee for piṇḍa at Gaya. Vā. 105. 34.

गुड
Guḍa dhenu --a sugar-cow gift connected with Viśokadvādaśivratam. Nine other dhenus are mentioned for this. Jaggery as one of the gifts, ety. guḍācala. M. 81. 27; 82. 2-31; 83. 5; 85. 1.

गुडाकेश
Guḍākeśa --a name of Arjuna. Bhā. I. 17. 31.

गुण
Guṇas --three kinds of persons according to their nature; hence Guṇatrayam; satva prakṛti, rājasa prakṛti and tāmasa prakrti. Their different characteristics. A muni  serves satva and conquers rajas and tamas. 1) Bhā. XI. 25. 9-35. If the three states are normal it is prakṛti, pradhāna or avyakta. If in a condition of agitation, three deities Brahma, Viṣṇu and Śiva are the result. 2) M. 3. 14-6. Twelve qualities; 3) Vā. 62. 24. twenty-six in number; yoga, sāmkhya, tapas, vidyā, vidhi, kriyā, ṛtam, satyam, ahimsā, dhyānam, sānti, avidyā, mati, dhṛti, kānti, smṛti, medha, lajjā, śuddhi, sarasvati, tuṣti, puṣti etc., all in Brahmā. 4) Ib. 23. 54.

गुण
Guṇa śarīra --the five senses and the five prāṇas and the mind of the mukta leave him; a jñānin does not take another body like the seeds burnt. Vā. 102. 105-06.

गुणाकर
Guṇākara --a Vānara chief; son of Śveta. Br. III. 7. 181 and 241.

गुप्त
Gupta --appellation for Vaiśya. Vi. III. 10. 9.

गुप्त
Guptas  (I)--a group of sixteen śaktis. Br. IV. 19. 16 and 23.

गुप्त
Guptas  (II)--rulers of the territory from Gayā to Prayāga. Vi. IV. 24. 63.

गुप्तवंशज
Guptavaṃśajas --ruled over states like Prayāga, Sāketu, Magadha, etc. Vā. 99. 383.

गुरु
Guru  (I)--a son of Samkṛti. Bhā. XI. 21. 2.

गुरु
Guru  (II)--a son of Bhautya Manu. Br. IV. 1. 114. Vā. 110. 51. 

गुरु
Guru  (III)--devotion to, praised by Kaca; his daughter cannot be married by a pupil, as she stands in relation of a sister. 1) M. 25. 69; 26. 6-8, 12-16. Guru (śuśrūṣa) service of the teacher pleases Hari. Kṛṣṇa's discourse on service to guru, and his tribute to his teacher Sāndīpāni. It is said that guru's blessings make a man rise to his full stature. 2) Bhā. X. 80. 28-43. Different kinds of guru--mahāguru, ācārya, deśīka and others. 3) Br. IV. 8. 3-6. Implicit obedience to. Transgressing his orders leads one to be born an aerial spirit: fit to be honoured like a king and a god. 4) Ib. 43. 37-59.

गुरु
Guru  (IV)--the planet Bṛhaspati. M. 93. 14.

गुरु
Guru  (V)--a sage. M. 196. 45.

गुरुण्ड
Guruṇḍas --ten of them were kings; 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 30. rule after Tuṣāras, along with Vṛṣalas. These were mlecchas for 311 years. 2) Br. III. 74. 173 and 7; M. 273. 19, 22-3.

गुरुतल्पक
Gurutalpaka --defiler of the preceptor's bed; a heinous sin. Vā. 60. 75; 78. 34; 101. 153; 105. 13.

गुरुदक्षिणा
Gurudakṣiṇā --the Preceptor's fee, offered by Kṛṣṇa and Rāma; 1) Vi. V. 21. 24. by Keśidhvaja to Khāṇḍikya. 2) Ib. VI. 6. 39, 43 and 48.

गुरुधी
Gurudhī --a son of Mahāyaśas. M. 49. 37. 

गुरुप्रीति
Guruprīti --a son of Samkṛti. Vi. IV. 19. 22.

गुरुवीत
Guruvīta --a mantrakṛt. M. 145. 102.

गुरुवीर्य
Guruvīrya --a son of Sāmkṛti. Vā. 99. 160.

गुरुसेवि
Gurusevi --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 236.

गुर्वक्ष
Gurvakṣa --a son of Bali. M. 6. 11.

गुलिक
Gulika --a Nāga. Br. IV. 20. 54.

गुल्म
Gulma --a son of Sārāṇa. Vā. 96. 165.

गुह
Guha  (I)--(God Subrahmaṇya, Senāpati) a son of Ambikā (Pārvati) was born as Sāmba, son of Kṛṣṇa. Tīrtha sacred to, in the Sarasvatī visited by Vidura. 1) Bhā. III. 1. 22. and 30. Br. III. 24. 4; IV. 30. 104; Vā. 30. 315; 39. 55, 41. 40; Vi. V. 33. 26. Guha is said to hve shot arrows at Krauñca hill. 2) Bhā. V. 20. 19. Fought with Tāraka in the Devāsura war and with Pradyumna at Śonitapura. 3) Ib. VIII. 10. 28; X. 63. 7. Relieved Mucukunda defending Heaven. 4) Ib. 51. 16. With peacock as riding animal, defended Tripurāri's chariot; birth of, in a Śaravana, as a baby of seven days killed Asura Tāraka. 5) M. 133. 64; 140. 40; 146. 10-11; 266. 42. Weapon Śakti. 6) Vi. III. 2. 12. 

गुह
Guha  (II)--the ruler of kingdoms Kalinga, Mahiṣa, Mahendranilaya, etc. Br. III. 74. 198; Vā. 99. 386.

गुह
Guhas --rule over Kalinga, Māhiṣa, and Mahendra hill regions. Vi. IV. 24. 65.

गुहप्रिया
Guhapriyā --a śakti. Br. IV. 44. 76.

गुहा
Guhā --cave (golden) in Kuhariṇi in Meru where Vyāsa composed the four Vedas having conquered hunger, mind and āsana; after one hundred years of contemplation the Vedas came to him in their full form. Vā. 104. 67-9.

गुहाक्ष
Guhākṣa --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 82.

गुहाप्रवेशम्
Guhāpraveśam nagaram --on the northern side of the Niṣadha hill. Vā. 41. 55.

गुहावास
Guhāvāsa --a ṛtvik at the sacrifice of Brahmā. Vā. 106. 39.

गुहावासी
Guhāvāsī --the avatār of the Lord in the seventeenth dvāpara in the siddhakṣetra of the Himalayas; with four sons all Brahmajñas; each of the latter had a number of disciples, all engaged in Maheśvara yoga. Vā. 23. 175-7. 

गुह्यक
Guhyakas --demons and followers of Kubera, 1) Bhā. I. 9. 3; X. 34. 28; II. 10. 37; IV. 4. 34. who reside in Himalayan valley. 2) Ib. IV. 5. 26; 10. 5. Magic relating to; 3) Ib. X. 55. 23. followers of Śiva; 4) Ib. 63. 10. attain heaven by association with the righteous; 5) Ib. XI. 12. 3; 14. 5. are yakṣa-rākṣas; 6) Br. III. 7. 167; IV. 2. 26. M. 13. 17; 121. 2. their habits and duties; 7) M. 180. 9; 246. 53. born out of Devajanani and Maṇivara and their issue. 8) Vā. 69. 162; 101. 28. Rākṣasas. 9) Br. II. 8. 33; Vā. 9. 32; 30. 84.

गुह्य
Guhya vidyā --symbolical of Devī. Vi. I. 9. 20.

गृंजन
Gṛṃjana --garlic unfit for śrāddha. Vi. III. 16. 8.

गृत्स
Gṛtsa --a mantrakṛt. Br. II. 32. 106; M. 145. 100.

गृत्समद
Gṛtsamada  (I)--a sage who called on the dying Bhiṣma. Ārṣeya pravara of Bhārgavas. Bhā. I. 9. 7; M. 155. 44-5.

गृत्समद
Gṛtsamada  (II)--a son of Suhotra (Sutahotra) and father of Śunaka (Saunaka), 1) Bhā. IX. 17. 3; Vā. 92. 3-4; Vi. IV. 8. 5. a kṣatropetadvija. 2) Br. III. 66. 87; 67. 4.

गृत्सामान्
Gṛtsāmān --a mantrakṛt. Vā. 59. 97.

गृध्र
Gṛdhra --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Mitravindā. Bhā. X. 61. 16.

गृद्ध्रका
Gṛddhrakā --a daughter of Tāmṛā, gave birth to vultures. Vi. I. 21. 15, 16. 

गृध्रकुट
Gṛdhrakuṭa --in the left hand of the śilā when sages performed tapas in the form of an eagle; visit to it leads to Śivaloka; 1) Vā. 108. 61-2. in Gayā; 2) Ib. 109. 15; 111. 22, 42. fit for śrāddha. 3) Ib. 77. 38, 97.

गृध्रि
Gṛdhri(kā) --a daughter of Tāmrā, wife of Aruṇa, and mother of Sampāti and Jatāyu. Br. III. 7. 446-8; M. 6. 30-32.

गृध्रेश्वर
Gṛdhreśvara --the deity presiding over the Gṛdhreśvara hill. Vā. 108. 62.

गृहक्षेत
Gṛhakṣeta(ā) --a deity to be worshipped in housebuilding. M. 253. 25; 268. 13.

गृहपति
Gṛhapati  (I)--the Agni where Ahirbudhnya is located. M. 12. 26; Vā. 29. 24.

गृहपति
Gṛhapati  (II)--the yajamāna of the sacrifice. Vā. 1. 23.

गृहपति
Gṛhapati  (III)--his duties; 1) Bhā. VII. 14. (whole); M. 18. 16; 40. 1 and 3. to do five yajñas and 30 samskāras; by adopting a Pāṣaṇḍa as guru, that family will be ruined. 2) M. 52. 16; 267. 33. duties of; good conduct; observance of daily duties and rituals; fasts, feasts, agnihotra, śrāddha, etc.; by observing them he goes to the world of Prajāpati.

