Go  (II)--created from the belly and sides of the Lord; considered a part of Hari's body. As they supplied milk for havis, Kaṃsā resolved to kill them. Nanda gave them as gifts to Brāhmaṇas during Kṛṣṇa's jātakarmā. 1) Bhā. X. 4. 39-41; 5. 3; M. 13. 58; Vi. I. 5. 48. In their stalls and in places cleaned by their dung śrāddha can be performed. Objects of worship. 2) Br. III. 13. 128-130; 28. 11, 57 and 60; IV. 6. 38 and 46; 40. 116. Gorakṣa introduced by Pṛthu; 3) Br. II. 36. 198. their guru was the sun. 4) Vi. V. 1. 14; 10. 26. born of Surabhi, Vṛṣabha their lord; dharmas pertaining to; 5) M. 6. 44; 8. 8; 48. 52; 52. 18. their stall (goṣṭha) as fit for śrāddha offering; 6) Ib. 15. 33; 16. 22; 17. 11; 83. 10. their horn used for washing images, esp. of Śiva. 7) Ib. 56. 6; 60. 33.

गो
Go  (III)--Sūrya; see Gā. Vi. V. 1. 14.

गोकरीषम्
Gokarīṣam --dried cow dung placed on the head of afflicted children to remove evils; an ancient Yādava practice. Vi. V. 5. 13. 

गोकर्ण
Gokarṇa  (I)--a place sacred to Śiva, in extent half a yojana on the western sea; visited by Balarāma. Sages of this place came to Dvārakā; 1) Bhā. X. 79. 19; 90. 28 [4]; Vā. 23. 172. a tapovanaṃ, called Dhūtapāpasthalam; sacred to Rudra. 2) Br. III. 13. 19; IV. 44. 96. Swallowed by sea, the sages left to the Sahya hill and reported of the erosion to Rāma on the Mahendra hill. Addressed by them, Rāma appealed to Varuṇa who at first did not turn up. When he grew wroth, Varuṇa promised to give back the land. 3) Ib. III. 56. 7-56; 57. 12 to the end and ch. 58. whole. Here Yama performed penance and became a Lokapāla and lord of Pitṛs; sacred to Pitṛs. 4) M. 11. 18-20; 22. 38. Sacred to Bhadrakarṇikā; 5) M. 13. 30; 181. 25. a sacred place for the performance of śrāddha; nearby is the R. Tāmraparṇī; sacred to Śankara. 6) Vā. 48. 30; 77. 19-21.

गोकर्ण
Gokarṇa  (II)--the avatar of the 16th dvāpara in the holy Gokarṇa vana with four sons. Vā. 23. 172.

गोकर्ण
Gokarṇa  (III)--a ṛtvik at the sacrifice of Brahmā. Vā. 106. 39.

गोकर्ण
Gokarṇa  (IV)--a measurement by the ring finger. Br. I. 7. 97; Vā. 8. 103.

गोकर्णिका
Gokarṇikā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 24.

गोकामुख
Gokāmukha --a Mt. in Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 16.

गोकुल
Gokula --see Vraja. Bhā. II. 7. 31; Vi. V. 1. 74; 5. 7; 11. 13. 

गोकुलाकीर्णा
Gokulākīrṇā --R. in Bhāratavarṣa; trembled at Hiraṇyakaśipu's reign. M. 163. 63.

गोखल
Gokhala --a pupil of Śākalya. Bhā. XII. 6. 57; Br. II. 35. 2.

गोगृह
Gogṛha --‘raid for taking cows’; death in, leads to heaven. Vā. 105. 16.

गोघ्न
Goghna --the slayer of cows; the other three heinous crimes are ingratitude, wine drinking and defiling of teacher's bed. Vā. 60 74; 101. 152.

गोचपला
Gocapalā  (I)--one of Atri's ten wives. Br. III. 8. 75.

गोचपला
Gocapalā  (II)--a daughter of Ghṛtācī and Bhadrāśva. Vā. 70. 69.

गोचर्मन्
Gocarman --a measurement equal to (1/4) nivartanam. M. 283. 15.

गोणीपति
Goṇīpati --an Ātreya gotrakara M. 197. 4.

गोतीर्थम्
Gotīrtham  (I)--in Prayāga. M. 110. 1.

गोतीर्थम्
Gotīrtham  (II)--in the Narmadā. M. 193. 3. 

गोत्र
Gotra --a son of Ūrjā and Vasiṣṭha. Vi. I. 10. 13.

गोत्रप्रवर्तक
Gotrapravartakas --the seven ṛṣis. Vā. 61. 94.

गोद
Goda --a Gandharva. Vā. 69. 26.

गोदावरि
Godāvari --R. from the Sahya hill, the northern part of the Sahya where the Godāvari is a charming spot. Here was founded the town Govardhana, and was planted flower trees by Bharadvāja. 1) Bhā. V. 19. 18; Br. I. 12. 15; II. 16. 34-45; Vā. 45. 104, 112. Vi. II. 3. 12. R. sacred to Pitṛs, filled with Lingas; also Jāmadagnītīrtham; personified as a wife of Havyavāhana fire. 2) M. 22. 46 and 57-8; 51. 13; 114. 29; 163. 61. Vā. 29. 13.

गोदावरीतट
Godāvarītaṭa --banks of Godāvarī, whence sages visited Dvāraka. Bhā. X. 90. 28 [5].

गोदाव
Godāvas --a Janapada of the Ketumāla continent. Vā. 44. 15.

गोदाश्रम
Godāśrama --sacred to Trisandhyā. M. 13. 37.

गोध
Godha(c) --a kingdom of Madhyadeśa. Br. II. 16. 42.

गोधन
Godhana --a Mt. of the Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 22; Vā. 45. 91. 

गोधर्म
Godharma --(see Dīrghatamas) law of the beasts, learnt by Dīrghatamas from Saurabheya Vṛṣa and practised by him on his younger brother Gautama's wife-Surabhi was pleased as a result and restored health, beauty and vision to Dīrghatams who becme Gautama thereafter. M. 47. 43-55; 80-84; Br. III. 74. 47-55, 91; Vā. 48-9; 99. 47-50.

गोधामन्
Godhāman --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 244.

गोधूम
Godhūma --fit for śrāddha. Vi. I. 6. 21, 24; II. 15. 30; VI. 1. 38; III. 16. 6.

