Cakrī  (I)--an Ārṣeya pravara of Angīras. M. 196. 23.

चक्री
Cakrī  (II)--a name of Kṛṣṇa. Vi. IV. 13. 85.

चक्रेश्वरि
Cakreśvari --a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 19; 18. 15.

चक्रोड
Cakroḍa --a sage. M. 200. 17.

चक्षु
Cakṣu (Manu)  (I)--a son of Vyuṣṭa and Puṣkariṇī; wife Ākūti (Vīriṇi-M. P.) and son Manu. Bhā. IV. 13. 15; VIII. 5. 7; M. 4. 40.

चक्षु
Cakṣu  (II)--a son of Anu. Bhā. IX. 23. 1; Vi. IV. 18. 1.

चक्षु
Cakṣu  (III)--a Tuṣita. Br. III. 3. 19; Vā. 66. 18.

चक्षु
Cakṣu  (IV)--a son of Śiṣṭa. M. 4. 39. 

चक्षु
Cakṣu  (V)--a Marut gaṇa. M. 171. 52.

चक्षु
Cakṣu  (VI)--a R. from the Himālayas. Br. II. 16. 27; 18. 22.

चक्षु
Cakṣu  (VII)--a branch of the Gangā, descending Malayavatī and traversing the continent of Ketumāla, enters the western sea; flows through the countries of Cīnamaru, Tālā, Masamūlika, Bhadra, Tuṣāras, Lāmyaka, Bāhlava, Pāraṭa and Khaśa. Bhā. V. 17. 5 and 7; Br. II. 18. 41, 46-7; M. 121. 40; Vā. 47. 39, 44; Vi. II. 2. 34, 37; 8. 113.

चक्षुष
Cakṣuṣa  (I)--a son of Ripu and Bṛhati; his son was the great Manu born to his wife Vāruṇī. Br. II. 36. 102.

चक्षुष
Cakṣuṣa  (II)--a son of Bali's slave girl through Dīrghatamas; 1) Br. III. 74. 71; Vā. 99. 70. attained Brahmanhood with his brother Kakṣivat. 2) Vā. 99. 94.

चक्षुष
Cakṣuṣa  (III)--a son of Khanitra, and father of Vīmśa. V. IV. 1. 25.

चक्षुष्मती
Cakṣuṣmatī --a consort of Mārtāṇḍa Bhairava. Br. IV. 35. 47; 36. 15.

चञ्चला
Cañcalā --a R. from Ṛṣyavat. M. 114. 26.

चन्चु
Cancu (Hārīta) --a son of Harita and father of Vijaya and Sudeva (Vasudeva-Vi. P.). Br. III. 63. 117; Vā. 88. 119, 120; Vi. IV. 3. 25. 

चण्ड
Caṇḍa  (I)--a son of Bāṣkala. Br. III. 5. 38; IV. 29. 75.

चण्ड
Caṇḍa  (II)--a head of a Śivagaṇa. Br. III. 41. 28.

चण्ड
Caṇḍa  (III)--a Bhairava on the sixth parva of Geyacakra; followed the army of Lalitā. Br. IV. 19. 78; 17. 4.

चण्ड
Caṇḍa  (IV)--a Rudra. M. 153. 19.

चण्ड
Caṇḍa  (V)--a Nāgapati. Vā. 41. 73.

चण्ड
Caṇḍa  (VI)--one of the seven pralaya clouds. M. 2. 8.

चण्ड
Caṇḍa  (VII)--one of the two piśācas who met yakṣa, the son of Khaśā. Vā. 69. 113.

चण्डकालि
Caṇḍakāli --killed Kolāṭa. Br. IV. 28. 42.

चण्डघण्ट
Caṇḍaghaṇṭa --a Gaṇeśvara. M. 183. 64.

चण्डधर्म
Caṇḍadharma --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 82. 

चण्डबाहु
Caṇḍabāhu --a commander of Bhaṇḍa to aid Viṣaṅga; was killed by Kulasundarīkā. Br. IV. 21. 79; 25. 28, 79.

चण्डमना
Caṇḍamanā --one of the ten horses of the moon's chariot. Br. II. 23. 56.

चण्डवेग
Caṇḍavega --the Lord of the Gandharvas, who had 360 followers. These entered Puramjana's city and harassed the people. The superintendent of the city defended it. Allegorically 360 stands for the year, while the Gandharvas represent the day time and their women the night. Bhā. IV. 27. 13-16.

चण्डवेगा
Caṇḍavegā --R. sacred to Pitṛs, to be remembered on the occasion of a śāddha. M. 22. 28.

चण्ड
Caṇḍa Śrī--śāntikarṇa;  Andhra king, the son of Vijaya, ruled for ten years. M. 273. 15.

चण्डा
Caṇḍā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 16.

चण्डाल
Caṇḍālas --redeemed of their sins at Benares; 1) M. 184. 67; 227. 54. prohibited from seeing food offered at the Śrāddha. 2) Vi. III. 16. 12. Satyavrata became a Caṇḍāla. 3) Ib. IV. 3. 23.

चण्डि
Caṇḍi --prayers to. Vā. 112. 58. 

चण्डिका
Caṇḍikā  (I)--a name of Yogamāyā. 1) Bhā. X. 2. 12. Diti during the course of pregnancy was forbidden to take the remainder of offerings to the goddess. 2) Ib. VI. 18. 49. Her shrine was known Caṇḍikāgṛha; 3) Ib. V. 9. 14. a mother-goddess; 4) Br. IV. 7. 72; 19. 70. enshrined at Makarandaka; an epithet of Umā. 5) M. 13. 43; 158. 16.

चण्डिका
Caṇḍikā  (II)--a servant-maid of Pārvatī. Br. IV. 40. 25.

चण्डिन्
Caṇḍins --a Parāśara clan. Br. III. 8. 95.

चण्डीश
Caṇḍīśa  (I)--an attendant on Rudra. Laid his hands on Pūṣan at the destruction of Dakṣa's sacrifice. Bhā. IV. 5. 17.

चण्डीश
Caṇḍīśa  (II)--a Bhautika, a Varamūrti. Br. IV. 44. 50.

चतुरङ्ग
Caturaṅga --the son of R(L)omapāda--Daśaratha (Citra-ratha-Vi. P.), and father of Pṛthulākṣa (PṛthālaśvaVā. P.) through the grace of Ṛṣyaśṛnga. Bhā. IX. 23. 10; M. 48. 95; Vā. 99. 104-5. Vi. IV. 18. 18-19.

चतुरङ्गबल
Caturaṅgabala --the fourfold forces, of Śūra; see Caturangini. Br. III. 26. 7; 45. 1; 46. 18; M. 240. 19-21.

चतुरंगिणी
Caturaṃgiṇī --fourfold forces sent by Yudhiṣṭhīra to escort Kṛṣṇa en route to Dvārakā. Bhā. I. 10. 32.

चतुर्गुप्त
Caturgupta --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 80. 

चतुर्दशमन्वन्तर
Caturdaśamanvantaras --Vaimānika devas, etc., in. Vā. 7. 17, 19.

चतुर्दशमहारत्नेश
Caturdaśamahāratneśa --was Śaśabindu. Vi. IV. 12. 3.

चतुर्दशविद्य
Caturdaśavidyas --four Vedas, six Angas, Mīmāmsa, Nyāya, Dharmaśāstra and Purāṇas. Vā. 61. 78.

चतुर्दशी
Caturdaśī tithi mayī --a name of Jvālāmālinikā. Br. IV. 26. 33.

चतुर्बाहु
Caturbāhu --a son and commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 80; 26. 47, 72.

चतुर्मुख
Caturmukha --Brahmā (s.v.) as Vedarāśī with Gāyatri and Sāvitri; acted as Udgāta for Soma's Rājasūya and officiated as priest for Umā's marriage; 1) M. 4. 7-12; 6. 25; 23. 20; 53. 7; 154. 483. three avastas of: as Brahmā, Kāla and Puruṣa, creating, destroying and as being indifferent; hence three guṇas, three agnis, three Vedas and three worlds. 2) Vā. 5. 15-17.

चतुर्मूर्ति
Caturmūrti --a name of Vighneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 67.

चतुर्युगम्
Caturyugam --Kṛtam, Treta, Dvāparam and Kali. The section deals with the differences between them under the heads yugadharma, yugasandhi, amśaka and yugasandhāna. These are in Bhāratavarṣa; 1) Br. II. 29. 1 ff. M. 142. 2 and 17, 23. According to the yugams the height of men, birds, beasts and plants decreases  or increases; 2) Br. 32. 8 ff. Manu's height is aṣṭatāla and one whose height is navatāla is praised even by Gods. 3) Ib. 35. 172. Kṛta 4000 years sandhya 400 sandhyāmśa 400 Treta 3000 years sandhya 300 sandhyāmśa 300 Dvāpara 2000 years sandhya 200 sandhyāmśa 200 Kali (Tiṣyam) 1000 years sandhya 100 sandhyāmśa 100 Thus on the whole the yugas comprise 12000 divine years; 4) Vā. 23. 105; 24. 1; 32. 65, 67; 45. 137; 57. 5 and 21-8. described. 5) Vi. VI. 1. 5-7; 3. 11-40.

चतुर्वक्त्र
Caturvaktra --a name of Brahmā. Br. IV. 9. 23.

चतुर्वासन
Caturvāsanas --the four stages of all creatures in the world; svedajam, aṇḍajam, udbijjam and jarāyujam. Br. IV. 9. 23.

चतुर्व्यूह
Caturvyūha --the Puruṣa divided into four. Vā. 5. 34.

चतुश्शालम्
Catuśśālam --also Sarvatobhadram; description of. M. 253. 51; 254. 1-4.

चतुश्शृंग
Catuśśṛṃga --Mt. a hill of Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 15. 

चतुःशिर
Catuḥśiras --a son and commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 80; 26. 47.

चतुःसन
Catuḥsana --an avatār of Hari who imparted the lost knowledge of Ātman to Brahmā. Bhā. II. 7. 5.

चन्दन
Candanas --a group of nāḍis of fire (with sun) emitting rain. Br. II. 24. 27.

चन्दना
Candanā --a R. of the Bhāratavarṣa; a mahānadi. Vā. 45. 97; 108. 79.

चन्दनोदकदुन्दुभि
Candanodakadundubhi --son of Revata and a friend of Tumburu. Vā. 96. 117.

चन्द्र
Candra  (I) (personified)--pointed out, in the Amṛtamathana, to Hari, Rāhu drinking nectar in the guise of a deva. Hence Rāhu is said to chase the moon in parvas. Fought with Rāhu in a Devāsura war. Bhā. VIII. 9. 24-26; 10. 31.

चन्द्र
Candra  (II)--the son of Viśvasandhi and father of Yuvanāśva. Bhā. IX. 6. 20.

चन्द्र
Candra  (III)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyā. Bhā. X. 61. 13.

चन्द्र
Candra  (IV)--a son of Bali. M. 6. 11. 

चन्द्र
Candra  (V)--one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 8.

चन्द्र
Candra  (VI)--the son of Nara and father of Kevala. Vi. IV. 1. 41-2.

चन्द्र
Candra  (VII)--the son of Hemacandra, and father of Dhūmrākṣa. Vi. IV. 1. 51-2.

चन्द्र
Candra  (VIII)--the moon who completes in two fortnights the circuit which the sun makes in a year. He is the life of all living beings and occupies each of the twenty-eight constellations for thirty muhūrtas (a day). 1) Bhā. II. 10. 30; V. 22. 8-10. Lord of plants, yajñas, vratas and tapas; not going near Rohini, a bad omen; 2) M. 8. 2; 163. 41; 246. 57. the whitish dark spot in it appears like a śara; 3) Vā. 47. 77. its maṇḍalam made of clouds and waters as of Sūrya; here is the sthāna of all deities, planets, etc., the size of the moon is twice that of the sun; is reckoned as Vasu in the Vaivasvata epoch; 4) Ib. 53. 55-62, 80. grows through the effulgence of the sun and is known as Idvatsara; has 15 kalas and not 16. 5) Ib. 56. 30-31.

चन्द्र
Candra  (IX)--a Mt. one of the seven mountains of Plakṣadvīpa touching the sea and medicinal plants gathered by the Aśvins for nectar. Br. II. 18. 76; 19. 8; Vā. 49. 7; Vi. II. 4. 7.

चन्द्र
Candras --a group of nāḍis of sun (fire) with enough light. Br. II. 24. 29.

चन्द्रकान्त
Candrakānta --Mt. a kulaparvata of the Uttarakuru country; 1) Vā. 45. 25. entered the sea from fear of Indra. 2) M. 121. 73. 

चन्द्रकान्ता
Candrakāntā  (I)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 75.

चन्द्रकान्ता
Candrakāntā  (II)--a Janapada of the Bhadra country. Vā. 43. 19.

चन्द्रकेतु
Candraketu  (I)--a son of Lakṣmaṇa; capital, Candracakra (Candravaktra-Vā. P.). Br. III. 63. 188; Vā. 88. 187-8; Vi. IV. 4. 104.

चन्द्रकेतु
Candraketu  (II)--a Gandharva. Vā. 69. 26.

चन्द्रगति
Candragati --the month reckoned from the new moon day to the new moon day; in some parts the month reckoned from the full moon day to the full moon day. Vā. 100. 217.

चन्द्रगिरी
Candragirī --a son of Tārāpīḍa. M. 12. 55.

चन्द्रगुप्त
Candragupta  (I)--anointed first king of the Mauryas by the Brāhmaṇa Kauṭalya who brought about the fall of Nandas; ruled for 24 years. Bhā. XII. 1. 13; Br. III. 74. 144; Vā. 99. 331; Vi. IV. 24. 28.

चन्द्रगुप्त
Candragupta  (II)--the unrighteous minister of Haihaya who advised the king to get by peace or force the cow of Jamadagni so that he could ever have plenty. The king agreed and sent him to fetch the cow. Jamadagni argued that it was intended for religious purposes. The minister, without listening to those words had the animal bound. Jamadagni tied himself to the cow, and being beaten fell down dead. The cow kicked off her fetters and flew into  heaven. The minister reported the matter to the king who returned to his city greatly dejected. Br. III. 28. 31-7; 29. 8 ff.

चन्द्रगुप्त
Candragupta  (III)--a commander to aid Viṣaṅga; was killed by Duhśilā. Br. IV. 24. 29.

चन्द्रचक्रा
Candracakrā --the capital of Candraketu, son of Lakṣmaṇa. Br. III. 63. 189.

चन्द्रतीर्थ
Candratīrtha --sages of this locality near Cape Comorin visited Dvārakā; fit for śrāddha offerings. 1) Bhā. X. 90. 28 [4]; Br. III. 13. 28; Vā. 77. 28; Bath here on the full moon day takes one to Candraloka. 2) M. 193. 75-6.

चन्द्रद्रुम
Candradruma --a Kinnara with human face. Vā. 69. 35.

चन्द्रद्वीप
Candradvīpa --south of Uttarakuru where Gods live; 1000 yojanas in circumference; in the midst is a hill containing precious mines from which Candrāvartā takes its rise; it is the place of the moon God; people in it are righteous and live to an age of 10,000 years. Vā. 45. 52-60.

चन्द्रपादम्
Candrapādam --a sacred spot at Gayā. Br. III. 47. 18.

चन्द्रपुष्करम्
Candrapuṣkaram --sacred to Lalita. Br. IV. 44. 95.

चन्द्रप्रभ
Candraprabha  (I)--a son of Maṇibhadra. Vā. 69. 155. 

चन्द्रप्रभ
Candraprabha  (II)--Mt. north-west of Kailāsa; here are lake Svacchoda, river Svacchoda, forest Caitraratham, residence of Maṇibhadra, commander-in-chief of the Yakṣas. Br. II. 18. 5-8; M. 121. 6; Vā. 47. 5.

चन्द्रप्रभ
Candraprabha  (III)--a lake on the slopes of Meru Mt. Br. II. 18. 68; Vā. 47. 65.

चन्द्रप्रभ
Candraprabha  (IV)--the name of Ila's horse which became a mare in the Śaravana forest. M. 12. 3.

चन्द्रप्रस्थ
Candraprastha --a Mt. M. 163. 87.

चन्द्रबिम्बशाला
Candrabimbaśālā --adjoining the Sūryabimbaśāla. Here the moon born of Atri's eyes got his lustre. The presiding deity is called Śrī Somanātha surrounded by 27 stars, all śaktis. Other śaktis like Tāra live there besides the Aśvins. Br. IV. 35. 51-58.

चन्द्रभ
Candrabha --an Yakṣa; a son of Puṇyajani. Br. III. 7. 124.

चन्द्रभा
Candrabhā --same as Hlādinī. M. 112. 72.

चन्द्रभागा
Candrabhāgā  (I)--R. a mahānadī near Mānasasaras in Bhāratavarṣa, from the Himalayas; falls into western ocean; 1) Bhā. V. 19. 18; Br. V. 12. 15; II. 16. 25; III. 13. 121; Vā. 45. 95; 77. 113; 108. 78. sacred to Kāla; one of the 16 wives of Havyavāhana fire; in the chariot of Tripurāri. 2) M. 13. 49; 51. 13; 114. 21; 133. 23; 191. 64. Vā. 29. 13; Vi. II. 3. 10. 

छन्द्रभागा
Chandrabhāgā  (II)--the regions of, fell into the hands of Vrātyas and Mlecchas. Bhā. XII. 1. 39; Vi. IV. 24. 69.

चन्द्रभानु
Candrabhānu --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā. Bhā. X. 61. 60.

चन्द्रमण्डलम्
Candramaṇḍalam --contains the essence of the dhāma of Vedas; progresses and degresses with Śukla and Kṛṣṇa pakṣas. M. 23. 14.

चन्द्रमद्वारम्
Candramadvāram --the path of the Pitṛs. Vā. 8. 198.

चन्द्रमा
Candramā  (I)--see Soma; the eighth tanu of Mahādeva; wife Rohiṇi and son Budha. Br. II. 10. 83.

चन्द्रमा
Candramā  (II)--a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 8.

चन्द्रमौलि
Candramauli --see Śiva. Br. III. 48. 9.

चन्द्रलोक
Candraloka --attained by those who observe RohiṇīCandraśayana vratam. M. 57. 26; 193. 76.

चन्द्रवक्ता
Candravaktā --the capital of Candraketu, son of Lakṣmaṇa. Vā. 88. 188.

चन्द्रवती
Candravatī --a R. born of Mārīṣā. M. 4. 50. 

चन्द्रवंश
Candravaṃśa --a Kinnara with human face. Vā. 69. 36.

चन्द्रवासा
Candravāsā  (also Candravaśā)--R. in Bhāratavarṣa, belonging to Kulācala hill. Bhā. IV. 28. 35; V. 19. 18.

चन्द्रविज्ञ
Candravijña --the son of Vijaya and father of Salomadhi. Bhā. XII. 1. 27.

चन्द्रव्रतम्
Candravratam --leads to Candraloka. M. 101. 75.

चन्द्रशुक्ल
Candraśukla --an upadvīpa to Jambūdvīpa. Bhā. V. 19. 30.

चन्द्रशेखर
Candraśekhara --see Śiva. Br. III. 24. 60; 25. 2, 44; 32. 18; IV. 30. 71; 34. 91.

चन्द्रश्री
Candraśrī --the son of Dviyajña and father of Puloma. Vi. IV. 24. 48-9.

चन्द्रसूर्यग्रह
Candrasūryagraha --the eclipse of the sun and moon fit for śrāddha. Vā. 105. 19, 48.

चन्द्रसेन
Candrasena --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 26.

चन्द्रा
Candrā  (I)--a R. in Śālmalidvīpa. Br. II. 19. 46; Vā. 49. 42; Vi. II. 4. 28.

चन्द्रा
Candrā  (II)--a daughter of Vṛṣaparvan. M. 6. 22. 

चन्द्रांशु
Candrāṃśu --the king after Sadācandra. Br. III. 74. 181.

चन्द्रांशुतापन
Candrāṃśutāpana --a son of Bali. M. 6. 11.

चन्द्रार्क
Candrārka --a Rākṣasa. Vā. 69. 166.

चन्द्रार्कभूकर
Candrārkabhūkara --a son of Khaśa and a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 134.

चन्द्रावती
Candrāvatī --a R. of the Ketumāla. Vā. 44. 19.

चन्द्रावर्ता
Candrāvartā --a R. of the Candradvīpa, the sthāna of the moon God. Vā. 45. 56.

चन्द्रावलोक
Candrāvaloka --a son of Sahasrāśva. M. 12. 54.

चन्द्राश्व
Candrāśva --a son of Dundumāra. Vi. IV. 2. 42.

चन्द्रिका
Candrikā  (I)--a kala of the moon. Br. IV. 35. 32.

चन्द्रीका
Candrīkā  (II)--a mother goddess; enshrined at Hariścandra. M. 13. 40; 179. 28.

चन्द्रीका
Candrīkā  (III)--a R. sacred to Pitrs. M. 22. 63. 

चपल
Capala --a son of mṛga elephant. Br. III. 7. 333.

चपला
Capalā --a śakti. Br. IV. 44. 75.

चमस
Camasa --a son of Ṛṣabha, and a bhāgavata; a sage who described to Nimi the nature of those who are not devoted to Hari. Bhā. V. 4. 11; XI. 2. 21; 5. 2-18.

चमसाध्वर्यु
Camasādhvaryus --were ten Viśvedevas in Soma's Rājasūya. M. 23. 22.

चम्प
Campa  (I)--a son of Harita; he built Campāpurā. Bhā. IX. 8. 1.

चम्प
Campa  (II)--the son of Pṛthulākṣa (Pṛthulāśva-Vā. P.) Under him the ancient city Mālini became Campā; father of Haryanga through the grace of Pūrṇabhadra; lived for 60,000 years with the four varṇas. M. 48-97; Vā. 99. 105-7; Vi. IV. 18. 20-21.

चम्पकवनम्
Campakavanam --between Vikaṅka and Maṇiśaila hills; consists of fruit and flower trees; the āśrama of Kaśyapa Prajāpati. Vā. 37. 16-22.

चम्पा
Campā(purī)  (I)--built by Campa; a beautiful city; 1) Bhā. IX. 8. 1; Br. III. 74. 197; Vi. IV. 18. 20. the new name of the ancient Mālinī. 2) M. 48. 97.

चम्पा
Campā  (II)--R. sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 41. 

चम्पा
Campā  (III)--a name of Campāvatī; 1) Vā. 99. 106. a Janapada. 2) Ib. 99. 385.

चम्पावती
Campāvatī  (I)--the capital of the Nāgas, 1) Br. III. 74. 194. of Campā. 2) Vā. 99. 106, 382.

चम्पावती
Campāvatī  (II)--a R. of the Ketumāla country. Vā. 44. 20.

चर
Cara --a son of Devajani, a Yakṣa. Br. III. 7. 128.

चरक
Caraka --a Paulaha and one of the seven sages of the period of Tāmasa Manu. Br. II. 36. 48.

