Tapasya  (I)--Phālguna, the month sacred to Kratu. Bhā. XII. 11. 40; Br. II. 13. 11. Vā. 30. 9.

तपस्य
Tapasya  (II)--a son of Tāmasa Manu. M. 9. 17. 

तपस्विनी
Tapasvinī --the third daughter of Bhangakāra, married to Kṛṣṇa. Vā. 96. 55.

तपस्वी
Tapasvī  (I)--a sage of the epoch of the twelfth Manu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 28.

तपस्वी
Tapasvī  (II)--a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu. Br. II. 36. 79, 106; M. 4. 41.

तपस्वी
Tapasvī  (III)--is Kaśyapa; a sage of the epoch of the fourth Sāvarṇa. Br. IV. 1. 92.

तपस्वी
Tapasvī  (IV)--a son of Manu and Naḍvalā. Vi. I. 13. 5.

तपस्वी
Tapasvī  (V)--a sage of the XII epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 35.

तपा
Tapā --an adopted son of Vastāvana. Vā. 96. 190.

तपोजनि
Tapojani --a Deva of the Rohita group. Vā. 100. 90.

तपोत्सुक
Tapotsuka --a son of Sudarīdra (s.v). M. 21. 3.

तपोद्युति
Tapodyuti --a son of Tāmasa Manu. M. 9. 17.

तपोधन
Tapodhana  (I)--(Paulastya): a sage of the epoch of the 4th Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 92.

तपोधन
Tapodhana  (II)--a son of Tāmasa Manu. M. 9. 17. 

तपोधन
Tapodhana  (III)--a sage of the XII epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 35.

तपोधन
Tapodhana  (IV)--a son of Bhṛgu, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 149.

तपोधृति
Tapodhṛti  (I)--(Bhārgava) a sage of the epoch of the 4th Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 93.

तपोधृति
Tapodhṛti  (II)--a sage of the XII epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 35.

तपोभोगि
Tapobhogi --a son of Tāmasa Manu. M. 9. 18.

तपोमूर्ती
Tapomūrtī  (I)--a sage of the epoch of the twelfth Manu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 28; Vi. III. 2. 35.

तपोमूर्ति
Tapomūrti  (II)--(Angiras): a sage of the epoch of the 4th Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 92.

तपोमूर्ति
Tapomūrti  (III)--a sage of the X epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 27.

तपोमूल
Tapomūla --a son of Tāmasa Manu. M. 9. 17.

तपोयोगि
Tapoyogi --a son of Tāmasa Manu. M. 9. 18. 

तपोराति
Taporāti  (I)--(Paulaha): a sage of the epoch of the 4th Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 92.

तपोराति
Taporāti  (II)--a son of Tāmasa Manu. M. 9. 17.

तपोराति
Taporāti  (III)--a sage of the XII epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 35.

तपोलोक
Tapoloka --see also Tapa. Bhā. II. 5. 39; Vā. 7. 30; 24. 3; 49. 149; 61. 132 and 177.

तप्तकुम्भ
Taptakumbha --(Taptakuṇḍa-Vi. P.); a hell, into which fall disloyal government servants, dealers in horses, gaolers, and women, those who have sexual intercourse with sisters, preceptor's wife, incestuous offenders, murderers of Kṣatriyas and Vaiśyas and slayers of royal emissary. Br. IV. 2. 147, 156; Vā. 101. 146, 154; Vi. II. 6. 2 and 9-10.

तप्तलोक
Taptaloka --a hell into which fall those who deal in horses, guardians of prisoners, sellers of chaste ladies and those who abandon bhaktas and companions. Vā. 101. 154; Vi. II. 6. 11.

तम
Tama  (I)--(lokapṛṣṭha): a kind of hell: persons fallen from Varṇa and Āśramadharma find this hell. Br. IV. 2. 150, 177-78; Vā. 101. 149, 179; Vi. II. 6. 4.

तम
Tama  (II)--equated with ajñāna or ignorance, bound by three fetters; to think that which is not eternal as eternal, to regard happiness in one's difficulties, to regard one's own  self which is not his own, and to regard that as pure which is impure; 1) Br. IV. 3. 33-38. fourfold, with Tāmasi vṛtti, the lowest. 2) Ib. 3. 53.

तम
Tama  (III)--the eleventh kalpa. M. 290. 5.

तमसा
Tamasā --a R. from the Rkṣavat in Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 30; M. 114. 25; 163. 64; Vā. 45. 100, 136.

तमिस्रा
Tamisrā --a Śakti on the Ṣoḍasapatrābjā. Br. IV. 32. 11.

तमोजात
Tamojāta --a son of Asamañja. M. 44. 83.

तमोलिप्तम्
Tamoliptam --the vimāna with faces on all sides on which rode Tiraskarṇikā. Br. IV. 24. 75.

तंकारिणी
Taṃkāriṇī --a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 89.

तम्गणा
Tamgaṇās --an eastern country; 1) Br. II. 16. 51. a hill tribe. 2) Ib. II. 16. 67.

तम्पोट्ट
Tampoṭṭa --a war-musical instrument; others are Bheri, Missāṇa, and Paṇavānaka. Br. IV. 24. 14.

तम्बु
Tambu --a son of Śārngadevā and Vasudeva. Vā. 96. 177, 249.

तम्बुर
Tamburas --a forest tribe of the Vindhyas. Br. II. 36. 145. 

तरङ्गिणी
Taraṅgiṇī --a R. flows through the Uttarakuru country and falls into the north ocean. Vā. 42. 76-7.

तरण्य
Taraṇya --a Devagandharva. Vā. 68. 39.

तरस्वी
Tarasvī --a Yādava; a son of Sāmbā. Vā. 96. 252.

तरुवल्कल
Taruvalkala --barks of trees to cover nakedness; applied to harassed subjects living in the mountain valleys in degenerate times. Vi. IV. 24. 96.

तर्क
Tarka  (I)--came to see the Trivikrama form of Hari. Bhā. VIII. 21. 2.

तर्क
Tarka  (II)--Logic. Vā. 101. 211.

तर्ज
Tarja --a son of Auttama Manu. M. 9. 12.

तर्ष
Tarṣa --a son of Vāsanā and Arka; a Vasu. Bhā. VI. 6. 13.

तलक
Talaka  (I)--a son of Āndhra Hāleya, and father of Purīṣabhīru. Bhā. XII. 1. 25.

तलक
Talaka  (II)--a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 51. 

तलगान
Talagānas --a tribe. M. 114. 43.

तलशब्दम्
Talaśabdam --slapping of arms in defiance by Kṛṣṇa on seeing the asura Ariṣṭa as a bull. Vi. V. 14. 8.

तला
Talā --one of the ten daughters of Raudrāśva. Vā. 99. 126.

तलातल
Talātala --an underworld, being the residence of Asura Maya who won the grace of Śiva and moved about without fear of the Sudarśana; 1) Bhā. II. 1. 26; V. 24. 7 and 28. residence of Prahlāda. 2) Br. II. 20. 12-14, 25-31.

तवर्ग
Tavarga --the two sides of the navel of the Veda. Vā. 104. 72.

ताडका
Tāḍ(ṭ)akā --wife of Sundā (Mārica-Vā. P.) and mother of Mārīca; 1) Br. III. 5. 36; Vā. 67. 72. was killed by Rāma 2) Vi. IV. 4. 88.

ताण्डि
Tāṇḍi --exclusion of marriage alliances among Angiras and Maudgalyas. M. 196. 44.

तान्त्रिक
Tāntrika --a mode of worship but different from the Vaidika or Vedic path; 1) Bhā. VIII. 6. 9. the Tāntrika concept of Hari. 2) Ib. XII. 11 (whole); Br. IV. 2. 108.

तान्त्रिकी
Tāntrikī Dīkṣā --as different from the Vaidika, in the mode of prayer to Hari. Bhā. XI. 11. 37; 27. 7. 

तापका
Tāpakā (c) --a western country. Br. II. 16. 60.

तापत्रयम्
Tāpatrayam --three pains; ādhyātmika (bodily and mental pain), ādhibhautika (natural but incidental pain) and ādhidaivika (superhuman); each is multiplied in thousands. Vi. VI. 5. 1-9.

तापनीय
Tāpanīya --a pupil of Yājñavalkya. Br. II. 35. 29.

तापस
Tāpasas --a southern tribe. M. 114. 49; Vā. 45. 129.

तापसेश्वरम्
Tāpaseśvaram --Here to the wonderment of a hunter, a deer which fell in water due to dread was taken to the world above. M. 191. 102-4.

तापिन
Tāpina --one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 8.

तापी
Tāpī  (I)--a R. in Bhāratavarṣa rising in the Vindhyas; 1) Bhā. V. 19. 18; Br. II. 16. 32; M. 114. 27. visited by Balarāma. 2) Vā. 45. 102; Bhā. X. 79. 20.

तापी
Tāpī  (II)--a R. rises from the Ṛkṣa hill. Vi. II. 3. 11.

तामरसा
Tāmarasā --one of Atri's wives. Br. III. 8. 76. 

तामस
Tāmasa  (I)--a son of Priyavrata, and a Manvantara adhipati. 1) Bhā. V. 1. 28; Vi. III. 1. 24. The fourth Manu and brother of Uttama. He had Pṛthu and nine other sons. During this epoch the gods went by the name of Satyakas, Haris, etc. Triśikha was Indra. Jyotirdhāmā and others were the seven sages. 2) Bhā. VIII. 1. 27-28. Brother of Raivata. 3) Ib. VIII. 5. 2. For different names of Gods, sages and Indra in this epoch; 4) Br. II. 36. 3, 42-50; M. 9. 15. represents ukāra; 5) Vā. 26. 36; 62. 3. twenty-seven gaṇas of Gods mentioned in this epoch--Supāra, Haraya, etc. Śibi was Indra; Nara and Khyāti, his sons. 6) Vi. III. 1. 6, 16-19.

तामस
Tāmasa  (II)--the quality of Bhūtādi swallowed by Mahat of which Buddhi is the guṇa. Vā. 102. 19-20.

तामसमन्वन्तर
Tāmasamanvantara --four gaṇas; each of 25 devas; sages; sons. Vā. 62. 37-43.

तामस
Tāmasa sarga --in this epoch were created sons of Himsa and of Adharma. Vā. 10. 38-45.

तामसी
Tāmasī  (I)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 88.

तामसी
Tāmasī  (II)--one of the three mātras of Om, the Praṇava. Vā. 20. 2.

तामसी
Tāmasī  (III)--a R. of the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 17. 

तामसी
Tāmasī  (IV)--(Kālā, Prajākṣayakari); 1) Vā. 66. 85, 89. 100. possessed by Bhava. 2) Ib. 66. 101-5.

तामसी
Tāmasī  (V)--also known as Pūtanā; wife of Sadrama. Vā. 84. 12.

तामसी
Tāmasī vṛtti --that which is at the bottom; four-fold; no belief in the Veda, Śiṣtācāra, non-observance of Varṇāśrama and of Dharma śāstras. Vā. 102. 54, 70-73.

तामिस्र
Tāmisra --a hell among the twenty-eight in number. Here are put to torments, those who lay hands on another's property, children and women. Bhā. III. 30. 28; IV. 6. 45; V. 26. 7-8; Vi. I. 6. 41; III. 11. 104.

ताम्बूल
Tāmbūla --offered to Hari in Payovrata. 1) Bhā. VIII. 16. 41. Offered by the merchants of Mathurā to Kṛṣṇa and his brother; 2) Ib. X. 42. 13. used by Trivakrā before she met Kṛṣṇa; 3) Ib. X. 48. 5. offered to Brahmana ladies, who were not widows, in the Devi temple just before the marriage of Rukmiṇī; 4) Ib. X. 53. 48; 61. 6. given by Kṛṣṇa to Brahmanas; 5) Ib. X. 70. 13: 73. 26. offered to Kucela by Kṛṣṇa; 6)Ib. X. 80. 22. offered to Hari by Indrasena; 7) Ib. X. 85. 37; XI. 27. 43. to be offered to Tripurasundari during worship. 8) Br. IV. 43. 13.

ताम्बूलधारि
Tāmbūladhāri --an attendant on the king. M. 215. 15.

ताम्र
Tāmra  (I)--a son of Mura (s.v.). Bhā. X. 59. 12.

ताम्र
Tāmra  (II)--a monkey chief. Br. III. 7. 234. 

ताम्र
Tāmra  (III)--a son of Satyabhāmā and Kṛṣṇa. M. 47. 17; Br. III. 71. 247.

ताम्रतप्त
Tāmratapta --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Rohiṇī. Bhā. X. 61. 18.

ताम्रपक्ष
Tāmrapakṣa --a son of Rohiṇi and Kṛṣṇa. Vi. V. 32. 2.

ताम्रपर्ण
Tāmraparṇa  (I)--the elephant of the sāma fold. Br. III. 7. 337.

ताम्रपर्ण
Tāmraparṇa  (II)--one of the nine divisions of Bhāratavarṣa. M. 114. 8; Vi. II. 3. 6.

ताम्रपर्णी
Tāmraparṇī  (I)--a R. of the Kulācala hill in Bhāratavarṣa, 1) Bhā. IV. 28. 35; V. 19. 18. and in Drāviḍa. 2) Ib. XI. 5. 39. Visited by Balarāma; 3) Ib. X. 79. 16. from the Malaya Hills flowing through sandal wood regions; famous for pearls and conch; fit for śrāddha offerings; 4) Br. II. 16. 36; III. 13. 24-7; IV. 33. 52; Vi. II. 3. 13. sacred to Pitṛs; 5) M. 22. 49; 114. 30. flows towards the southern ocean; at its confluence with the ocean are produced conches, shells and pearls. 6) Vā. 77. 24-5.

ताम्रपर्णी
Tāmraparṇī  (II)--a daughter of Satyabhāmā. Br. III. 71. 248; Vā. 96. 240.

ताम्रपात्रम्
Tāmrapātram --(Tāmram) copper vessel for ceremonial purposes; fit for gifts. M. 7. 12; 58. 13; 59. 8; 61. 45; 206. 15; 279. 7; 288. 11; Vā. 74. 1. 

ताम्ररसा
Tāmrarasā --a daughter of Raudrāśva. Vā. 99. 126.

ताम्रलिप्त
Tāmralipta(ka) --the territory under King Devarakṣita; 1) Vi. IV. 24. 64. an eastern country and tribe; a Janapada of the east. 2) Br. II. 18. 51; III. 74. 197; M. 114. 45; 121. 50; 163. 72; Vā. 45. 123; 99. 385.

ताम्रवक्ष
Tāmravakṣa --a son of Satyabhāmā. Vā. 96. 239.

ताम्रवर्ण
Tāmravarṇa --a Mt. near Patanga in the southern direction. Vā. 38. 8.

ताम्रवर्ण
Tāmravarṇa(ṇi)  (I)--a division of the Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 9; Vā. 45. 79.

ताम्रवर्णी
Tāmravarṇī  (II)--a R. of the Malaya hills. Vā. 45. 105.

ताम्रवर्णि
Tāmravarṇi  (III)--name of an elephant; son of Puṣpadanta. Vā. 69. 221.

ताम्रशाल
Tāmraśāla --copper hall; of Lalita's Śrīpura--square in shape spreading to seven yojanas. There was Kalpakavāṭika between this and Kāmśyaśāla full of beautiful and fragrant trees. Br. IV. 31. 66.

ताम्रा
Tāmrā  (I)--one of Kaśyapa's wives. Her progeny were hawks, vultures, eagles, curlews, geese, śukīs and others; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 26-27; M. 6. 2 and 30; Vā. 69. 325-26. Vi. I. 15. 125; 21. 14-17. daughter of Pulaha; 2) Br. III. 3. 56; 7. 445 to 448; 69. 325. mother of Apsarasas. 3) M. 146. 18; 171. 29 and 60. 

ताम्रा
Tāmrā  (II)--Wife of Vasudeva; her son was Sahadeva. M. 46. 16.

ताम्रा
Tāmrā  (III)--a daughter of Dakṣa and wife of Kaśyapa. Vā. 66. 54.

ताम्राभ
Tāmrābha --Mt. south of the Mānasa; 1) Vā. 36. 23. the residence of Kādraveya Takṣaka. 2) Vā. 39. 54.

तार
Tāra  (I)--a monkey chief. Br. III. 7. 231.

तार
Tāra  (II)--a God of the Harita gaṇa. Br. IV. 1. 85.

तारक
Tāraka  (I)--an Asura; took part in a Devāsura battle between Bali and Indra. 1) Bhā. VIII. 10. 21. Fought with Guha in a Devāsura war. 2) Ib. VIII. 10. 28; M. 61. 38. Lust after more territory. 3) Bhā. XII. 3. 11. Escaped to the ocean and gave trouble by coming out often. 4) M. 61. 4; 129. 5; 131. 22; 136. 34 and 67. Slain by Nandin. 5) M. 138. 43-4. City in the third tala named after him. 6) Br. II. 20. 26.

तारक
Tāraka  (II)--a son of Danu, 1) Br. III. 6. 7; M. 6. 19; Vā. 50. 26; 68. 7; Vi. I. 21. 5. and a friend of Bhaṇḍa. 2) Br. IV. 30. 39.

तारक
Tāraka  (III)--from Tāraṇa or that which takes good men across to next world. M. 128. 34 and 56. 

तारक
Tāraka  (IV)--a son of Vajrānga and Varāngī who troubled the Devas and destined to be killed by a baby of seven days; relieved his mother (Tāraka) from sorrows and hence the name; ety. was crowned king of the Asura world; did penance at the Pāriyātra cave when Brahmā granted his wish to be killed by a lad of seven days. All Lokapālas served him. He wanted to vanquish Hari and set out with Grasana as commander. The flag of makara was hoisted. Indra's report to Bṛhaspati. 1) M. Chh. 146-149; 160. 25-6; Br. IV. 11. 7. The war in which he was killed by Kumāra. 2) Br. III. 10. 49; IV. 30. 103; Vā. 72. 47.

तारक
Tāraka  (V)--of Kauśika gotra. Vā. 91. 98.

तारकमण्डल
Tārakamaṇḍala --extent of, west to east five thousand yojanas; above it are the slow moving Saura, Angira and Vakra; under it are the Sun, Moon, Budha and Bhārgava which revolve swiftly. Vā. 53. 70-4.

तारकविधि
Tārakavidhi --by worship of Mukti and Vāmana, the two boats to cross the ocean of Samsāra. Vā. 108. 37.

तारका
Tārakā --Sunītī, the mother of Dhruva, known as. Vi. I. 12. 94.

तारकामय
Tārakāmaya  (I)--A Devāsura battle in Kṛta yuga; Tārā's (Tārakā, Bṛhaspati's wife) abduction by Soma, was the ground for war between the Asuras and the Suras. Śukra joined Soma while Śiva and Indra took up Bṛhaspati's cause. 1) Bhā. IX. 14. 4-7; Br. III. 5. 32; M. 129. 16; 172. 10; Vā. 67. 69; 70. 81; 90. 33. Here Viṣṇu killed Kālanemi, and Indra, Virocana, son of Prahlāda; (Virocana was killed by Viṣṇu in the  guise of Indra-Vā. P.). After the war there was a famine when Vasiṣṭha helped the people with fruits and roots; 2) Br. III. 8. 88; 65. 34; 72. 20-21, 74; M. Chh. 173178. the fifth battle in which Virocana was blessed with eternal life by Śiva; 3) Vā. 97. 21, 74 and 80. ended with the intervention of Brahmā who gave Tārā back to Bṛhaspati. 4) Vi. IV. 6. 16-19.

तारकामय
Tārakāmaya  (II)--the fifth of the twelve Kolāhalas. Indra killed Virocana, son of Prahlāda. M. 47. 43-9.

तारग्रह
Tāragraha --above Nakṣatramaṇḍala; below this Budha moves. Vā. 101. 31, 132.

तारमन्द्रम्
Tāramandram --the high and low strains of a song; sung by Kṛṣṇa. Vi. V. 13. 16, 56.

तारा
Tārā  (I)--the wife of Bṛhaspati, and abducted by Soma. Of this union was born Budha. Through Brahmā's influence she was restored to her husband; (came back to Bṛhaspati after a battle between the Devas and the Dānavas). Bhā. IX. 14. 4-8, 13-14; Br. III. 65. 29; M. 23. 30-47; 24. 3; Vā. 90. 28-35, 43. Vi. IV. 6. 10-33.

तारा
Tārā  (II)--a Brahmavādinī. Br. II. 33. 18.

तारा
Tārā  (III)--a daughter of Suṣeṇa and queen of Vāli; her son was Aṅgada. Br. III. 7. 219. 

तारा
Tārā  (IV)--also Toraṇeśvari and Tārāmbikā; a Śakti living in the midst of waters that could be crossed only by boats of different sizes. Br. IV. 35. 12-24, 58; 36. 16; 44. 80.

तारा
Tārā  (V)--the goddess enshrined at Kiṣkindhaparvata. M. 13. 46.

तारा
Tārā  (VI)--one of the ten branches of the Harita group of Devas. Vā. 100. 89.

तारापति
Tārāpati --Lord of the stars; the moon. Vā. 41. 58.

तारापीड
Tārāpīḍa --a son of Candrāvaloka of the Sūryavamśa. M. 12. 54.

तार्क्ष
Tārkṣa --(Tārkṣya-Vā. P. and Vi. P.): Senāni with the Sun in Hemanta. Br. II. 23. 18; Vā. 52. 18.

तार्क्ष्य
Tārkṣya  (I)--(also Tārkṣa)--see Garuḍa. 1) Bhā. III. 2. 24; 17. 22. Married four daughters of Dakṣa. These were Vinatā, Kadrū, Patangī, and Yāminī, who were mothers of birds, snakes, etc. 2) Ib. VI. 6. 2, 21-22. Tārkṣyasuta inimical to serpents. 3) Ib. VII. 8. 26. X. 17. 7; 37. 4; 59. 7. Invoked for protection on the ground. 4) Ib. X. 6. 23; 17. 7; M. 126. 19; 167. 53.

तार्क्ष्य
Tārkṣya  (II)--the Yakṣa presiding over the month of Satra. (Tārkṣi Br. P.); 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 41. resides in the chariot of the sun during the month of Mārgaśīrṣa. 2) Vi. II. 10. 13. 

ताल
Tāla  (I)--span, employed in describing measurement in iconography; nine tālas generally for deities, dānavas and kinnaras; measurement made usually by the middle finger. Br. I. 7. 97; M. 258. 16 and 75; 259. 1-2; Vā. 8. 103.

ताल
Tāla  (II) (c)--kingdom watered by the R. Cakṣa. Br. II. 18. 46.

ताल
Tāla  (III)--a hell into which falls one, who murders a Kṣatriya or Vaiśya or Brahmana, or one who defiles a preceptor's bed. Br. IV. 2. 146; Vā. 101. 146, 153; Vi. II. 6. 2.

तालक
Tālaka --is Sāmaga. Vā. 61. 44.

तालकायना
Tālakāyanā --a Kauśika gotra. Br. III. 66. 70.

तालकृत्
Tālakṛt --an Ārṣeya-pravara of Angiras. M. 196. 22.

तालकेतु
Tālaketu  (I)--a Dānava with Manuṣya dharma; 1) Br. III. 6. 16; Vā. 68. 16. stationed at the northern gate of the Śūnyaka city with ten Akṣauhiṇis. 2) Br. IV. 22. 25.

तालकेतु
Tālaketu  (II)--the palm tree as the banner of Baladeva. Vi. IV. 1. 95.

तालग्रीव
Tālagrīva --the Asura who was stationed at the western gate of the Śūnyaka city with ten Akṣauhiṇi soldiers. Br. IV. 22. 24. 

तालजंघ
Tālajaṃgha  (I)--the son of Jayadhvaja and father of one hundred sons (Tālajanghas--Vītihotra being the elder). The Tālajangha line came to an end by Aurva's power. 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 28; M. 43. 47; Vā. 88. 122; 94. 50. Afraid of Paraśurāma he escaped to the Himalayas and returned after peace was restored. Led an expedition to Ayodhyā whose king Phalgutantra fled with his wife and child; 2) Br. III. 69. 51; 47. 67, 78. defeated Bāhu, but was defeated by his own son, Sagara. 3) Vi. IV. 3. 26, 40-1.

तालजंघ
Tālajaṃgha  (II)--a commander of Kuṭilākṣa. Br. IV. 29. 16-18.

तालजंघस्
Tālajaṃghas --a class of Kṣatriyas defeated by Sagara; 1) Bhā. IX. 8. 5; 23. 28. the collective name of the 100 sons of Tālajangha and a Haihaya clan; of them five gaṇas could be distinguished; Vītihotra, Bhoja, Avantya, Tuṇḍikera and Tālajangha. 2) Br. III. 48. 23-5; 63. 120 and 134; 69. 51-3; M. 43. 48; Vā. 94. 51-2.

तालजंघक
Tālajaṃghaka --the Asura stationed at the eastern gate of the Śūnyaka city with ten Akṣauhiṇi soldiers. Br. IV. 22. 22.

तालभुज
Tālabhuja --the Asura stationed at the southern gate of the Śūnyaka city with ten Akṣauhiṇi soldiers. Br. IV. 22. 23.

तालवनम्
Tālavanam --a grove of palms near Brindāvana where lived the demon Dhenuka who was killed by Rāma and Kṛṣṇa. Vi. V. 8. 1-3; 9. 1.

तालशाल
Tālaśāla (c) --a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 50. 

तिक्तगण
Tikta-gaṇa --articles of, detailed. M. 217. 68-74.

तिग्म
Tigma --the son of Urva and father of Bṛhadratha. Vi. IV. 21. 13.

तिग्मकेतु
Tigmaketu --a son of Vatsara and Svarvīthī. Bhā. IV. 13. 12.

तिग्मात्म
Tigmātma --a son of Urva. M. 50. 85.

तिति
Titi --a Śakti on the Nāga patra. Br. IV. 32. 17.

तितिक्षा
Titikṣā --a daughter of Dakṣa and a wife of Dharma; gave birth to Kṣema. Bhā. IV. 1. 50 and 52.

तितिक्षु
Titikṣu --the righteous; a son of Mahāmana and father of Ruśadratha. 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 2 and 4; Vā. 99. 18; Vi. IV. 18. 8, 11; Br. III. 74. 17 and 24. (Uśadratha: Br. P; Bṛhatratha: M. P.); a king of the East. 2) M. 48. 15, 22.

तितिख्य
Titikhya --the Śūdra caste of Krauñcadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 53.

तित्तिरि
Tittiri --a Trayārṣeya. M. 196. 48-9.

तिथि
Tithi --an Ārṣeya pravara of Bhārgavas. M. 195. 38. 

तिमि
Timi  (I)--one of the wives of Kaśyapa; gave birth to aquatic animals. Bhā. VI. 6. 26.

तिमि
Timi  (II)--the son of Dūrva, and father of Bṛhadratha. Bhā. IX. 22. 43.

तिमिर
Timira --the God of night. Vā. 108. 32.

तिरस्करणिका
Tiraskaraṇikā(mbā) --a Daṇḍanāthā, attacked Balāhaka and his brothers; rode on Tamolipta vimāna. Aimed at them the Mohana arrow which created darkness all round; wore on her neck a garland of the severed heads; 1) Br. IV. 24. 74, 98. (this Daṇḍanī) all Śaktis praised. 2) Ib. IV. 24. 103; 36. 25.

तिर्यक्
Tiryak --the origin of the different creatures described. Vā. 69. 298-303.

तिर्यक्ज्योति
Tiryakjyoti --one of the names in the first Marut gaṇa. Vā. 67. 123.

तिर्यक्योनि
Tiryakyoni --sixfold; to take birth and undergo all difficulties. Vā. 102. 72.

तिर्यक्स्रोत
Tiryaksrota --at the beginning of creation and when the whole was enveloped in darkness a cross current passed in and resulted in a second universe: 28 parts, 11 senses, 9 udayas, 8 stars; light in as also out; this resulted in sātvika. Vā. 6. 41-7, 56.

तिर्या
Tiryā --a daughter of Krodhā, the wife of Pulaha. Br. III. 7. 172. 

तिलंगा
Tilaṃgā --a Janapada. Vā. 45. 111.

तिलम्
Tilam --seasamum 1) Br. II. 7. 144; Vā. 74. 5; 101. 162; 105. 12. much liked by Piśācās; 2) Br. III. 7. 389, 409. dear to the Pitṛs; 3) Ib. III. 11. 5. Havis of, in a śrāddha; 4) Ib. III. 14. 11; 16. 17; 19. 3. dealer in, goes to hell; 5) Ib. IV. 2. 164. fit for gifts in vratas. 6) M. 7. 15; 15. 34; 82. 18; 83. 5; 87. 1; 187. 27-34; 217. 38; 239. 22.

तिलाचल
Tilācala --one of the Viṣkambha hills round Meru; continent of Uttara Kurus and Sāvītra vanam. M. 83. 23 and 34.

तिलोत्तमा
Tilottamā --the Apsaras 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 43; Br. II. 23. 22; III. 7. 6; IV. 33. 20; M. 13. 53; Vā. 52. 22; 69. 5. presiding over the month of Iṣa (Māgha and Phālguna-Vā. P.); born out of the fire altar of Brahmā; 2) Vā. 69. 59. resides in the Sun's chariot in the month of Māgha; cursed by Aṣtāvakra. 3) Vi. II. 10. 16; V. 38. 73 and 77.

तिष्ठ
Tiṣṭha --the eleventh Vyāsa, the avatar of the Lord. Vā. 23. 151.

तिष्य
Tiṣya  (I)--a constellation. Important for śrāddha. Bhā. XII. 2. 24; Br. III. 18. 4; Vā. 82. 5.

तिष्य
Tiṣya  (II)--(a yuga of Bhāratavarṣa); see also Kaliyuga. Br. II. 16. 69; 31. 30; M. 273. 61; Vā. 24. 1; 32. 40; 58. 30-73.

तीक्ष्णशृङ्ग
Tīkṣṇaśṛṅga --a commander of Bhaṇḍa to aid Viṣaṅga; 1) Br. IV. 21. 80; 25. 29. was killed by Sarvamangalikānityā. 2) Ib. IV. 25. 98. 

तीर्थ
Tīrtha --a righteous person fit to receive a dāna. Vā. 91. 111.

तीर्थयात्रा
Tīrthayātrā --a custom of going on pilgrimage. Vidura undertook one. 1) Bhā. I. 13. 1. Not fruitful to the unfaithful, 2) Br. III. 13. 135-6; 66. 43; IV. 9. 7. of Gādhi; rules that one should not ride in a vehicle but walk; 3) M. 106. 3; 112. 20. of Arjuna. 4) Ib. 244. 3.

तीर्थराज
Tīrtharāja --the Lord of the holy waters; Prayāga, to honour which is to honour the Lord of the waters. M. 109. 15.

तीर्थवती
Tīrthavatī --a R. of Krauñcadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 21.

तीर्थश्राद्ध
Tīrthaśrāddha --prescriptions for; 1) Vā. 110. 28-66. merits of; rituals at different sacred places of Gayā; could be done at any time in the presence of any with no āvāhana; the performer must observe celibacy, live on one meal a day, take bed on the earth and be truthful and pure to get full merits. 2) Ib. 105. 37-41.

तीर्थस्नानम्
Tīrthasnānam --going on pilgrimage for sacred baths. Vi. III. 9. 12.

तीर्थादि
Tīrthādi --sacred places of pilgrimage; as frequented by Piśācas; 1) Br. III. 7. 405; 9. 42; M. 17. 11. śrāddhas at; enumeration of a number of them for śrāddha offerings. 2) Br. III. 13 (whole); M. 15. 17. First Gurutīrtham, then Dhyānatīrtham, and lastly Brahmatīrtham, 3) Br. III. 22. 6; 24. 39. Paraśurāma went about to purify himself; 4) Ib. IV. 5. 4. names of about 100 Tīrthas given. 5) M. Ch. 22; 83. 10. 

तीव्रा
Tīvrā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 72.

तुक्षय
Tukṣaya --an Angīrasa and Mantrakṛt. Br. II. 32. 109.

तुंगप्रस्थ
Tuṃgaprastha --Mt. a hill. Br. II. 16. 22.

तुंगभद्रा
Tuṃgabhadrā --a R. in Bhāratavarṣa from the Sahya hill; sacred to Pitṛs. Bhā. V. 19. 18; Br. II. 16. 35; Vā. 45. 104; M. 22. 45; 114. 29.

तुण्डकोश
Tuṇḍakośa --(Tuṇḍakeśa-Vā. P.); a Rākṣasa; son of Khaśa. Br. III. 7. 135; Vā. 69. 167.

तुण्डिकेर
Tuṇḍikera --a Vindhya tribe; one of the five classes (gaṇas) of the Haihayas; 1) Br. II. 16. 65; III. 69. 53; Vā. 94. 52. on the other side of the Vindhyas. 2) Vā. 45. 134.

तुबुरा
Tuburā --a forest tribe of the Vindhyas; 1) Br. II. 36. 145. to be conquered by Kalki. 2) Ib. III. 73. 108.

तुमुर
Tumura --a tribe, on the other side of the Vindhyas. M. 114. 53; Vā. 45. 133.

तुम्ब
Tumba --a son of Tumba; had two sons. Br. III. 71. 258.

तुम्बबाण
Tumbabāṇa --a son of Tumba. Vā. 96. 249. 

तुम्बर
Tumbaras --a Vindhyan tribe. M. 114. 53.

तुम्बावर्चा
Tumbāvarcā --a son of Tumba. Br. III. 71. 258.

तुम्बुरा
Tumburā --a Niṣāda tribe; on the other side of the Vindhyas. Vā. 62. 124; 45. 133.

तुम्बुरु
Tumburu  (I)--an expert in divine music; had two daughters Manovatī and Sukeśā; 1) Vā. 69. 47, 49. a friend of Candrodaka dundubhī. 2) Ib. 96. 117. A Gandharva disciple of Nārada, came with the sage to see Yudhiṣṭhira, and returned to heaven with him; 3) Bhā. I. 13. 37 and 59. sang with Nārada the glories of Ananta; 4) Ib. V. 25. 8. praised Hiraṇyakaśipu when he became the overlord of all worlds. 5) Ib. VII. 4. 14. Sang the praise of Kṛṣṇa when he held the Govardhana; 6) Ib. X. 25. 32; 27. 24. presiding over the months of Madhu and Mādhava. 7) Ib. XII. 11. 33; Br. II. 23. 4. His two daughters were celebrated as Pañcacūḍas; 8) Ib. III. 7. 9; IV. 20. 50 and 101. residing in the Sun's chariot in the months of Caitra and Madhu. 9) Vā. 52. 3; 36. 47; Vi. II. 10. 3.

तुम्बुरु
Tumburu  (II)--a friend of Anu, son of Kapotaroma. Bhā. IX. 24. 20.

तुम्बुरु
Tumburu  (III)--a friend of Andhaka. Br. III. 71. 118.

तुर
Tura --the son of Kāvaṣa, and Purohita of Janamejaya. Bhā. IX. 22. 37.

तुरग
Turaga --a white horse came out of the churning of the ocean; claimed by the Sun god. M. 250. 3; 251. 3. 

तुरन्य
Turanya --a horse of the Moon's chariot. Vā. 52. 53.

तुरसित
Turasitas --a people of the Narmadā region. Vā. 45. 129.

तुरासङ्गम्
Turāsaṅgam --a Tīrtham on the Narmadā. M. 191. 29.

तुरीय
Turīya  (I)--a name of Brahmā (s.v.). Bhā. XI. 15. 16.

तुरीय
Turīya  (II)--(Turiya Indrayuk?-Br. P.); a Deva (ajita). Br. II. 13. 94; Vā. 31. 8.

तुरुष्क
Turuṣka --frank incense of white colour for dhūpa of the Pitṛs. Br. III. 11. 69.

तुरुष्कक
Turuṣkaka --(Tuṣkaras-Br. P.; Turuṣkāra-Vā. P.)-Fourteen kings among them, see Maunas. Bhā. XII. 1. 30; Vi. IV. 24. 53.

तुर्वसु
Turvasu  (I)--a son of Yayāti and Devayānī; refused to part with his youth to his father; he was therefore cursed to have no issue and to live a king among the wicked and low tribes and Mlecchas; became overlord of the Mlecchas in the western part of the kingdom. His son was Vahni. 1) Bhā. IX. 18. 33 and 41; 19. 22; 23. 16; M. 24. 53; Vā. 93. 16. His line became merged with the Paurava line, during the time of Marutta. 2) Br. III. 68. 16, 40, 50; 73. 126; 74. 1 and 4; M. 33. 9-11; Vā. 99. 1-4. Equal to Viṣṇu; father of Garbha; Yavanas take their origin from him, 3) M. 32. 9; 34. 30; 48. 1. got the south-east of the kingdom, when his father retired to the forest. 4) Vā. 93. 39-44, 89. 

तुर्वसु
Turvasu  (II)--a son of Devayānī and Yadu? Br. I. 1. 132; Vā. 1. 141.

तुलसी
Tulasī --sacred to Hari; 1) Bhā. I. 19. 6; V. 3. 6; X. 30. 7; XI. 30. 41. on the chest of Viṣṇu. 2) Br. IV. 9. 80-2; 17. 74.

तुलसीदामभूषण
Tulasīdāmabhūṣaṇa --Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 32.

तुलान्त
Tulānta --equinox. Vā. 50. 195.

तुलापुरुष
Tulāpuruṣa --Weighing in balance; one of the 16 mahādānas; rules detailed. The gift takes one to the world of Viṣṇu or Indra. M. 274. (whole); 275. 2.

तुल्यार्चि
Tulyārci --a son of Lāngalī of the 22nd Dvāpara. Vā. 23. 200.

तुवर
Tuvara --a tribe belonging to the Vindhya region. Vā. 62. 124.

तुषार
Tuṣāra  (I)--a dynasty of 14 rulers, ruled for 105 years [500 years (Vā. P.)]
after the Yavanas; reigned for 7000 years? Br. III. 74. 172-6; M. 273. 19, 21; Vā. 45. 118; 47. 44; 58. 83; 98. 108; 99. 360. 362.

तुषार
Tuṣāra  (II) (c)--a northern kingdom; 1) Br. II. 16. 47; 18. 46; 31. 83. 14 kings of it ruled for 105 years after the Yavanas. 2) M. 121. 45; 144. 57.

तुषित
Tuṣitas --a class of Devas, sons of Kratu and Tuṣitā, twelve in number, being sons of Dakṣiṇā. Flourished in the  Svāyambhuva epoch. 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 8. They were also Jayadeva gods of the Svārociṣa epoch. 2) Ib. VIII. 1. 20; Br. II. 36. 7-12; M. 9. 9. Vā. 66. 8; 67. 35; 90. 34. They were the same as Jayadevas of the Svāyambhuva. 3) Br. III. 3. 8 and 19; 4. 28; 65. 35. Thirty-three in number, belong to the Sumanasa group of the 4th Sāvarṇa Manu; 4) Ib. IV. 1. 87. Gods also of the Cākṣusa epoch known as Ādityas. 5) M. 6. 3-12. These are the twelve Ādityas of the Vaivasvata epoch; 6) Vi. I. 15. 127. 131-32; Ib. III. 1. 10. known as Prāṇakhyas in the Yajñas.

तुषिता
Tuṣitā  (I)--the wife of Vedaśiras and mother of Vibhu. Bhā. VIII. 1. 21.

तुषिता
Tuṣitā  (II)--the wife of Kratu and mother of the Tuṣita gods in the Svārociṣa epoch; 1) Br. II. 36. 8; Vā. 62. 8; 67. 35. gave birth to Viṣṇu by name Ajita in that epoch. 2) Br. III. 3. 11-15.

तुषिता
Tuṣitā  (III)--the mother of Yajiṣa in the Svārociṣa epoch. Vi. III. 1. 37.

तुष्ट
Tuṣṭa --a son of Ugrasena. Vā. 96. 132.

तुष्टा
Tuṣṭā --a R. in Śālmalidvīpa. Br. II. 19. 46.

तुष्टि
Tuṣṭi  (I)--a daughter of Dakṣa, and a wife of Dharma, gave birth to muda. (Santoṣa-Vā. P. and Vi. P.). Bhā. IV. 1. 49 and 51; Br. I. 9. 49, 59; Vā. 10. 25. 34: 55. 43; Vi. I. 7. 23 and 28.

तुष्टि
Tuṣṭi  (II)--a son of Vasudeva and Madirā. Br. III. 71. 172. 

तुष्टि
Tuṣṭi  (III)--a Śakti on the fourth Parvan of the Geyacakra. Br. IV. 19. 71; 44. 71.

तुष्टि
Tuṣṭi  (IV)--a Kalā of the moon. Br. IV. 35. 92; M. 23. 24.

तुष्टिमन्
Tuṣṭiman --a son of Ugrasena. Bhā. IX. 24. 24; Br. III. 71. 133.

तुहुण्ड
Tuhuṇḍas --a Vindhya tribe. Br. II. 16. 65.

तूर्य
Tūrya --generally a war-musical instrument; employed on auspicious occasions, and in temples; 1) Bhā. I. 11. 18; M. 149. 2; 163. 105; 192. 28. sounding of bugles in a wrestling match; 2) Vi. V. 20. 30. finding Cāṇūra declining, Kamsa stopped the sounding of the drum when the Devas sounded divine music. 3) Vi. V. 20. 71-3.

तूलिक
Tūlikas --a Mleccha tribe. Vā. 99. 268.

तृणकर्णि
Tṛṇakarṇi --A pravara of Angiras. M. 196. 13.

तृणपत्कालि
Tṛṇapatkāli --a Mauneya. Vā. 69. 2.

तृणबिन्दु
Tṛṇabindu  (I)--a king and the son of Bandhu. (BudhaVi. P.). His queen was Alambuṣā. Father of a number of sons and a daughter Ceḍavīḍā. 1) Bhā. IX. 2. 30-31; Br. III. 8. 36-7; 61. 10; Vi. IV. 1. 46-7. (Ilavilā-Vi. P.). Lust after more territory. 2) Bhā. XII. 3. 10. Lived at the commencement of the third  Tretāyuga. His daughter was Draviḍā. Many kings of Viśāla ruled by his grace. 3) Vā 86. 15-16, 22. Begot an Apsaras, Ālambuṣā, a son Viśāla who began the Vaiśāla line of kings which ended with Sumati. 4) Vi. IV. 1. 48-9, 59.

तृणबिन्दु
Tṛṇabindu  (II)--the 27th Veda Vyāsa, learnt the Br. Purāṇa and the Vāyu Purāṇa from Somaśuṣma and narrated the former to Dakṣa. Br. II. 35. 123; IV. 4. 64-65; Vā. 103. 64.

तृणबिन्दु
Tṛṇabindu  (III)--a sage who got freed from a curse at Ṛsitīrtham on the Narmadā. M. 193. 13.

तृणबिन्दु
Tṛṇabindu  (IV)--the Veda-Vyāsa of the 23rd (24thVi. P.) Dvāpara; Śveta, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 203; Vi. III. 3. 17.

तृणबिन्दु
Tṛṇabindu  (V)--the son of Dama and a king at the beginning of the third Tretāyuga in the 11th Manvantara; had a daughter Iḍivilā, who was married to Paulaśtya. Vā. 70. 30-1.

तृणंजय
Tṛṇaṃjaya --heard the Br. and Vāyu Purāṇas from Kṛtamjaya and narrated the former to Bharadvāja. Br. IV. 4. 63; Vā. 103. 63.

तृणावर्त
Tṛṇāvarta --an Asura friend of Kamsa; created a whirlwind which covered all Gokulam with dust and took the baby Kṛṣṇa high in the sky. Kṛṣṇa caught hold of his neck and the demon, unable to bear his weight, fell down dead to the wonder of all Gopas and Gopīs. Bhā. X. 2. 1; 7. 20-32; 26. 6; 46. 26; Br. IV. 29. 124. 

तृष्णा
Tṛṣṇā,  also Tṛṣā--implications of, with regard to life and death; 1) Br. III. 68. 101; IV. 3. 42, 59. annihilation of, leads to mokṣa; 2) Ib. IV. 3. 71. no end of. 3) Vi. IV. 10. 24.

तेज
Teja  (I)--a son of Bala and grandson of Nārāyaṇa. Br. II. 11. 4.

तेज
Teja  (II)--comes out of the subtle element, sparśa (touch) of Vāyu or wind; its qualities are sound, touch and form. M. 3. 24.

तेज
Teja  (III)--one of the twenty Sutapa Gaṇas. Vā. 100. 15.

तेज
Teja  (IV)--of the burning universe in Pralaya; similes used for colour. Vā. 100. 161.

तेज
Teja  (V)--swallows the waters--all mouthed; its quality is prakāśaka or light which Vāyu eats up; vanishes like the flame in the wind. Vā. 102. 10-12.

तेजस
Tejasa --the son of Sumati and father of Indradyumna. Br. II. 14. 64; Vi. II. 1. 36.

तेजस्वी
Tejasvī --a son of Kuthuma. Vā. 61. 38.

तेजोरश्मि
Tejoraśmi --a Sutapa God. Br. IV. 1. 14.

तेजोवती
Tejovatī  (I)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 73. 

तेजोवती
Tejovatī  (II)--the name of the Agni sabhā on the second inner slope of Meru, throwing effulgence on all sides; there live sages and seers bowing down to Agni. Vā. 34. 78-85.

तेजोव्रतम्
Tejovratam --a vow incumbent on kings; to behave like the different Lokapālas. M. 226. 9.

तैजस
Taijasa --a son of Sumati. Vā. 33. 54.

तैजसम्
Taijasam --Brahmā's Arvāktejas. Vā. 65. 33.

तैजससर्ग
Taijasasarga --the fourth creation of the Arvaksrota. Vā. 6. 56.

तैत्तिरि
Taittiri --a son of Kapotaromā and father of Nala, known as Nandanodara dundubhi. M. 44. 62.

तैत्तिरीक
Taittirīka --a southern tribe. M. 114. 49.

तैत्तिरीय
Taittirīya --Yajus-śākha; when Yājñavalkya vomitted the Yajus due to a misunderstanding with his Guru, the other sages who were pupils of Vaiśampāyana became transformed into Tittirā birds and received those portions of the Yajurveda. Hence the name Taittirīya. Bhā. XII. 6. 64-5; Br. II. 35. 75; Vi. III. 5. 13; Vā. 61. 66.

तैलक
Tailaka --a Pravara. M. 196. 30. 

तैलप
Tailapa --an Ātreya gotrakara. M. 197. 4.

तैलेय
Taileya --Dhūmra Parāśara. M. 201. 38.

तोटकम्
Toṭakam --a Chandas in which Bāṇāsura prayed to Śiva who blessed him with immortality. M. 188. 66 and 72.

तोमर
Tomara --an eastern hill tribe; 1) Br. II. 16. 51; M. 121. 58; Vā. 45. 120; 47. 56. an eastern kingdom; 2) Br. II. 16. 68. country of the, watered by the Nalinī. 3) Ib. II. 18. 59.

तोया
Toyā  (I)--a R. from the Vindhyas. Br. II. 16. 33; M. 114. 28; Vā. 45. 103.

तोया
Toyā  (II)--a R. of the Śālmalam. Vā. 49. 42.

तोरणेश्वरी
Toraṇeśvarī --see Tārā. Br. IV. 35. 12.

तोशत
Tośata --a people on the other side of the Vindhyas. Vā. 45. 133.

तोशल
Tośala(ka) --a Malla friend consulted by Kamsa. He had his seat allocated in the arena; was killed by Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 36. 21; 42. 37; 44. 27; Vi. V. 20. 79-80.

तोशल
Tośalas --a Vindhyan tribe. Br. II. 16. 64. 

तोष
Toṣa --a son of Dakṣiṇā and a Tuṣita God. Bhā. IV. 1. 7-8.

तौलेय
Tauleya --an Ārṣeya pravara of Angiras. M. 196. 6.

त्याग
Tyāga --is to look on the useful and the useless equally; renunciation from affection, desire and difficulty; giving up of all Karmas and having an equal eye on good and evil; 1) Vā. 59. 53. result of Jñāna or knowledge; gives the result of Karma, but difficult to achieve; 2) Br. IV. 3. 45. leads to Vairāgya. 3) Vā. 102. 66.

त्याज्य
Tyājya --a son of Bhṛgu. M. 195. 13.

त्रय
Traya --group of three: varṇa loka, etc. Vā. 97. 33.

त्रयम्बक
Trayambaka  (I)--Śiva; 1) Br. II. 27. 69; Vi. I. 15. 122. his riding animal Vṛṣabha, 2) Br. III. 72. 82; 74. 51. followed by the Naiṛṛta clan of Rākṣasas; 3) Ib. III. 7. 141. one of the eleven Rudras; the eighth of twelve incarnations who slew Asuras in the battle of Andhaka; 4) M. 5. 29; 47. 50; 191. 120. sacrifice to, by Puroḍāśa made in Kapālas; Gāyatrī, Triṣṭub and Jagati are present as three means of the Puroḍāśa; 5) Vā. 31. 46-8; 40. 20. with ten arms in Śivapura; his weapons are Paṭṭiśa, bow, trident, and sword; Gandharva leaders entertain him with music; the bull is there, and Skanda and others form the sabhā; sculptures of Dig Devas in the columns of the palace. 6) Ib. 101. 255. 292, 323. Ambakas are the yonis of Vanaspati, king of trees; 7) Br. II. 9. 4. curse of Dakṣa to be born as Prācetas in the Cākṣuṣa Manu epoch. 8) Ib. II. 13. 41, 144. 

त्रयम्बक
Trayambaka  (II)--Kubera whose followers were of the Rākṣasa gaṇa Naiṛṛta, many branches of which gaṇa were worshippers of Śankara; 1) Vā. 69. 173. killed all in Tripura. 2) Vā. 97. 82; 99. 51.

त्रयम्बक
Trayambaka vratam --the vow that leads to the world of Śiva. M. 101. 67.

त्रयंश
Trayaṃśa --a son of Vipracitti. Vi. I. 21. 11.

त्रयी
Trayī  (I)--a daughter of Savitā. Bhā. VI. 18. 1.

त्रयी
Trayī  (II)--A Vidyā; 1) Vā. 49. 118; 59. 36; 61. 167; 67. 27; Vi. V. 10. 27. symbolical of Devī; 2) Vi. I. 9. 121. said to be the body of Hari; 3) Ib. II. 11. 11; III. 18. 15. forbidden to women, śūdras and fallen Brahmanas; 4) Bhā. I. 4. 25. issued from Brahmā; 5) Ib. III. 12. 44. one Veda became three for Purūravas at the commencement of the Tretāyuga; 6) Ib. IX. 14. 48-49. unknown to Puṣkaradvīpa. 7) Br. II. 19. 122; 32. 40; 35. 195; III. 4. 24; Vi. II. 4. 83.

त्रयीसानु
Trayīsānu --the son of Bhānu, and father of Karandama. Vi. IV. 16. 3.

त्रयुषण
Trayuṣaṇa --a son of Uruksava and Vīśālā; became a Brahmana. M. 49. 39.

त्रयोदशि
Trayodaśi --as a Śakti resident in Śodasapatrābja. Br. IV. 32. 15. 

त्रयोदेव
Trayodeva --by the agitation of the guṇas or qualities three gods with body came into being; the Rajas is Brahmā, Tamas Agni and Satva, Viṣṇu; the first had the duty of creation, the second Kāla and the third Udāsīna; these are three worlds, three Vedas and three fires, one dependent on the other; by their joint action the world progresses; (Advaita): three functions of Prajāpati as creator, destroyer and protector. Vā. 5. 14-16 and 30-31.

त्रय्यारुणि
Trayyāruṇi  (I)--a son of Duritakṣaya (DuritakṣayaVi. P.) and a Paurāṇika. Bhā. IX. 21. 19; XII. 7. 5; Vi. IV. 19. 25.

त्रय्यारुणि
Trayyāruṇi(a)  (II)--the Veda Vyāsa of the fifteenth Dvāpara. 1) Br. II. 35. 120; Vi. III. 3. 15. Heard the Purāṇa from Antarikṣa and narrated it to Dhanamjaya. 2) Br. IV. 4. 62.

त्रय्यारुनि
Trayyāruni (a)  (III)--the son of Tridhanvā and father of Satyavrata. Br. III. 63. 76; M. 12. 37; Vi. IV. 3. 20-1.

त्रय्यारुणि
Trayyāruṇi  (IV)--a son of Viśālā. Vā. 99. 163.

त्रसदश्व
Trasadaśva --the son of Anaraṇya. Vā. 88. 76.

त्रसद्दस्य
Trasaddasya --the son of Purukutsa. Vā. 88. 74.

त्रसद्दस्यु
Trasaddasyu  (I)--see Māndhāta. Bhā. IX. 6. 33. 

त्रसदस्यु
Trasad(d)asyu  (II)--(Trasadas-Vā. P., Br. P.) son of Narmadā and Purukutsa, and father of Anaraṇya. Bhā. IX. 7. 4; Br. III. 10. 98; Vā. 73. 49; 88. 74; Vi. IV. 3. 16-17.

त्रसद्दस्यु
Trasaddasyu  (III)--a Mantrakṛt and of the Angirasa branch. Br. II. 32. 108; Vā. 59. 99.

त्रसरेणु
Trasareṇu  (I)--an atom; 1) Bhā. III. 11. 5. the visible speck floating in the sun, seen as the sun shines through a window: a measurement. 2) M. 258. 17. Padmarajas; 3) Vā. 101. 119. eight times the Paramāṇu. 4) Br. III. 10. 59; IV. 2. 119.

त्रसु
Trasu --a son of Ranti and a great charioteer. Vā. 99. 129.

त्राक्षायणि
Trākṣāyaṇi --a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 20

त्रासक
Trāsakas --Rākṣasas fearful to children. Vā. 69. 191.

त्रिककुत्
Trikakut --the son of Śuci; also known as Dharmasārathi. Father of Śāntaraya. Bhā. IX. 17. 11-12.

त्रिककुद
Trikakuda --a Mt. near Kakudman the collyrium of which is fit for Pitṛs and Śrāddha; in it are a burning pit Jāta vedasśilā as also a Tīrtha, where the seven seers had bathed and a temple with a Nandi invisible to the unrighteous; besides golden Yūpas. Br. III. 11. 67; 13. 58; M. 121. 15; Vā. 47. 13; 77. 57-64. 

त्रिकण्टक
Trikaṇṭaka --(Trikarṇaka ?) a commander of Bhaṇḍa to aid Viṣaṅga; 1) Br. IV. 25. 29. was killed by Jvālā mālinikā. 2) Ib. IV. 25. 98.

त्रिकर्मनिरत
Trikarmanirata --a name of Śiva. Vā. 30. 217.

त्रिकुमारिकम्
Trikumārikam Jagat --the whole universe is said to be pervaded by the three daughters of Himavān, Aparṇā, Ekaparṇā and Ekapāṭalā, all eternal youths and Brahmavādinīs. Br. III. 10. 14; Vā. 72. 13-5.

त्रिकूट
Trikūṭa  (I)--a mountain on the base of the Meru, in Bhāratavarṣa; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 26; 19. 16. surrounded by Kṣīroda, and 10000 yojanas high with three shining crests of silver, iron and gold; served by Siddhas, Cāraṇas and others. In its valley was Ṛtumat, the pleasure garden of goddesses, full of varied trees. 2) Ib. VIII. 2. 1-19.

त्रिकूट
Trikūṭa  (II)--Here is Lankā in Malayadvīpa. Vā. 48. 26.

त्रिकोण
Trikoṇa --one of the ten Pīṭhas for images, in the shape of a trident. M. 262. 7, 12, 18.

त्रिखण्ड
Trikhaṇḍa(ikā) --a Prakaṭaśakti. Br. IV. 19. 15; 42. 2; 44. 115.

त्रिगर्त
Trigarta --see Trigartas (s.v.) 

त्रिगर्त
Trigartas --their king was Suśarma (s.v.). He was not able to vanquish Arjuna, supported by Kṛṣṇa. He was stationed by Jarāsandha at the Northern gate of Mathurā, as also during the siege of Gomanta. 1) Bhā. I. 15. 16; X. 50. 11 [7]; 52. 11. [14]; [50 (V) 3]. A hill tribe; 2) Br. II. 16. 68; 18. 53. a hilly country. 3) Vā. 45. 136; M. 114. 56.

त्रिगर्त
Trigarta(ka) --a mountain kingdom of Trigartas visited by Balarāma. Bhā. X. 79. 19.

त्रिचक्ष
Tricakṣa --a son of Sutīrtha. Vā. 99. 274.

त्रिजटी
Trijaṭī --a Mind-born mother. M. 179. 17.

त्रिणाचिकेत
Triṇāciketas  (Triṇāciketa-Vā. P.) the Brahmanas of the Yajur Veda, fit for Śrāddha feeding. Vi. III. 15. 2; Vā 79. 58; 83. 53.

त्रितकूप
Tritakūpa --a Tīrtha visited by Balarāma. Bhā. X. 78. 19.

त्रिता
Tritā  (I)--a sage who called on the dying Bhīṣma; was invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira; came to Syamantapañcaka to see Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. I. 9. 7; X. 74. 7; 84. 5.

त्रिता
Tritā  (II)--a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu. A place sacred to him on the Sarasvatī; a Mantrakṛt. Bhā. IV. 13. 16; III. 1. 22; M. 145. 101. 

त्रिदण्डी
Tridaṇḍī --a class of ascetics. In that guise Arjuna spent four months in Dvāraka to marry Subhadrā; 1) Bhā. X. 86. 3; Br. III. 11. 5-12; 15. 64. wearing śikhā; specially fit for śrāddha; 2) Vā. 79. 90. with three daṇḍas (restraints) of Vāk, Karma and Manas. 3) Ib. 17. 6.

त्रिदशज्योति
Tridaśajyoti --a Tīrtham on the Narmadā. M. 194. 11.

त्रिदिवा
Tridivā  (I)--a R. from the Himālayas. Br. II. 16. 26.

त्रिदिवा
Tridivā  (II)--a R. from the Ṛkṣa. Br. II. 16. 31.

त्रिदिवा
Tridivā  (III)--a R. in the Plakṣadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 19; Vi. II. 4. 11.

त्रिदिवा
Tridivā  (IV)--(Śivetikā) a R. of the Bhāratavarṣa rising from the Mahendra mountain. Vā. 45. 101, 106.

त्रिदिवा
Tridivā  (V)--a R. of the Śākadvīpam. Vā. 49. 93.

त्रिदिवाचला
Tridivācalā --a R. from the Mahendra mountain. M. 114. 31.

त्रिदिवाबला
Tridivābalā --a R. from the Mahendra mountain. Br. II. 16. 37.

त्रिदेव
Trideva --a son of Sāmkṛti. Vā. 99. 160. 

त्रिधन्वा
Tridhanvā  (I)--a son of Sambhūti. M. 12. 36.

त्रिधन्वा
Tridhanvā  (II)--the son of Vasumata, a righteous king. Vā. 88. 77.

त्रिधन्वा
Tridhanvā  (III)--the son of Sumanā and father of Trayyāruṇi. Vi. IV. 3. 20.

त्रिधन्वा
Tridhanvā  (IV)--a son of Sumati. Br. III. 63. 76.

त्रिधामा
Tridhāmā --the name of Vyāsa in the tenth Dvāpara; Bhṛgu, the avatar of the Lord; 1) Br. II. 35. 119; Vā. 23. 147; Vi. III. 3. 13. heard the Br. and Vāyu Purāṇas from Sārasvata and narrated the former to Śaradvān. 2) Br. IV. 4. 61; Vā. 103. 61.

त्रिनाभ
Trinābha --a son of Khaśa, and a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 135.

त्रिनेत्र
Trinetra  (I)--see Śiva; 1) Br. II. 27. 69; III. 23. 31; 24. 79; 25. 2; 32. 18. constructed the Puṣpakam. 2) M. 129. 36; 130. 12.

त्रिनेत्र
Trinetra  (II)--the son of Nirvṛti; ruled for 28 years. M. 271. 27.

त्रिपथ
Tripatha --the name of a horse of the Moon's chariot. M. 126. 52. 

त्रिपथगा
Tripathagā(minī) --Gangā (s.v.) descended at the Gaura hill; 1) Br. II. 18. 27, 29, 30. fell on Śiva's head; 2) Ib. III. 13. 118; 25. 11. originating from the foot of Soma; 3) M. 102. 8; 106. 51; 121. 28-9; 183. 7. came to be divided into seven streams; flows in Antarikṣa, Divam and Bhūmi; Śiva prevented her course by yoga, when she grew angry and on account of which drops of water fell on the ground and collected themselves into a lake, Bindusaras; she resisted this and wanted to enter the Pātāla when Brahmā consoled her and let her flow in seven directions, three to the east, three to the west and the seventh to the south; the last one is Bhāgīrathī. 4) Vā. 47. 26-41. Stopped in the sky above Mānasa. 5) Ib. 77. 111.

त्रिपुण्ड्रम्
Tripuṇḍram --a mark on the forehead. Br. IV. 38. 22.

त्रिपुर
Tripura  (I)--a city built by Māyā, of gold, silver and iron fortifications for the sake of Asuras. 1) Bhā. IV. 17. 13; V. 24. 28; VII. 10. 54 and 68. VIII. 6. 31; XI. 16. 20; Br. III. 72. 82. Vā. 97. 82. Really three towns under Tāraka, Maya and Vidyunmāli; city described. Battle of Tripuram; march of Śiva's army. First battle at Tārakākhyapuram; non-combatants visiting it; fight between Nandi and Vidyunmāli; Tāraka's fight with the Gaṇas; actual battle on the shores of the western sea, described; battle in the air and under water; Tāraka slain by Nandi, as also Vidyunmāli; burning the city including women and children by Śiva. 2) M. Chh. 129-130; Chh. 135-140; 187. 8, 14-6; 188. 9-10.

त्रिपुर
Tripura  (II)--an Asura having his city in the third Talam. Br. II. 20. 27; III. 38. 4.

त्रिपुरभैरवी
Tripurabhairavī --the second charioteer of Lalitā. Br. IV. 20. 91. 

त्रिपुरम्
Tripuram --a Tīrtham sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 43.

त्रिपुरसुन्दरी
Tripurasundarī --is Lalitā. Br. IV. 18. 14; 39. 76, 96 ff; 40. 1, 43 ff.

त्रिपुरा
Tripurā --a name of Lalitā; worship of. Br. IV. 5. 31.

त्रिपुरान्तक
Tripurāntaka --(Tripuradhvamsa): see Śiva. Br. III. 23. 32; 25. 13.

त्रिपुराम्बिका
Tripurāmbikā --a mother Goddess, see Lalitā. Br. IV. 7. 72; 11. 1.

त्रिपुरारी
Tripurārī --an epithet of Rudra; Śiva with 16 hands danced in joy at the ruin of the city, Tripuram (s.v.). M. 179. 38; 259. 11.

त्रिपुरेशी
Tripureśī --a Guptayogini. Br. IV. 36. 72.

त्रिपुरोपाख्यान
Tripuropākhyāna --deals with the construction of Tripura by Maya; trouble to the world by the Asuras; Gods wait on Rudra; the war chariot of Śiva; Nārada's mediation; Maya gets ready for war; the war; the efforts of gaṇas, especially Nandi's part in the battle; death of Tāraka; the second day of the battle; Śiva's victory by burning the city. M. Chh. 129-141.

त्रिप्लक्ष
Triplakṣa  (I)--near the Dṛṣadvatī; 1) Br. III. 13. 69. like Śyāmaka and Ikṣu being created by Gods; 2) Ib. 14. 8. to be propitiated at the Parva and at the Tithis. 3) Ib. 17. 6. 

त्रिबन्धन
Tribandhana --the son of Aruṇa and father of Satyavrata. Bhā. IX. 7. 4-5.

त्रिभागा
Tribhāgā --a R. from the Mahendra hills. M. 114. 31.

त्रिभानु
Tribhānu --the son of Bhānumat, and father of Karamdhama. Bhā. IX. 23. 17.

त्रिमधु
Trimadhu --the Brahmanas of the Sāma Veda fit for feeding on the śrāddha occasions. Vi. III. 15. 2.

त्रिमना
Trimanā --a horse of the Moon's chariot. Vā. 52. 53.

त्रिमात्र
Trimātra --is Om; Praṇava constituted by Vaidyutī, Tāmasī and Nirguṇi Mātras. Vā. 20. 1.

त्रिमार्ष्टि
Trimārṣṭi --a Pravara. M. 196. 30.

त्रियामिका
Triyāmikā --(Niyāmikā) night, so called. Br. II. 8. 6, 23.

त्रिलोक
Triloka --progress of, depends on the sun without which there would be no reckoning of time and nothing would go on. Vā. 50. 60; 53. 34-41. 

त्रिलोचन
Trilocana  (I)--Śiva known in Trayambaka Kṣetra; meditation of. M. 22. 47; 131. 35; 266. 36; Vi. V. 33. 1.

त्रिलोचन
Trilocana  (II)--a name of Vighneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 67.

त्रिवक्रा
Trivakrā --a hunchback maid who supplied unguents to Kamsa. For the mere asking she gave them away to Kṛṣṇa and his brother. Pleased at this, Kṛṣṇa converted her into a beautiful maid. She requested him to go to her house and honour her with his company. He promised to do so after his other engagements were over. 1) Bhā. X. 42. 1-12. Visited by Kṛṣṇa with Uddhava. Her house was found filled with pictures drawn according to the Kāmaśāstra. After spending some time there, Kṛṣṇa left. 2) Ib. X. 48. 1-10. Her son was Viśoka. 3) Ib. X. 90. 34[1]. Came to see Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā returning from Indra's abode. 4) Ib. X. [67 (V) 50].

त्रिवन
Trivana --(Cyavana?) son of Antināra. M. 49. 8.

त्रिवर्ग
Trivarga --three ends of human endeavour, Dharma, Artha and Kāma; was taught to Prahlāda by his tutors. This did not appeal to him. It should be a means to realise Hari, according to Prahlāda. 1) Bhā. VII. 5. 52-53; 6. 26. Even the householder, it is said, should not exert himself too much for Trivarga. But it is generally observed by householders. 2) Ib. VII. 14. 10; VIII. 16. 11. Vi. III. 11. 6. A Bhikṣu is expected to discard it. 3) Bhā. VII. 15. 36; Br. III. 50. 52; 51. 15. To one devoid of Dharma, the other two, Kāma and Artha, are of one use. 4) M. 29. 3; 53. 4, 45; 212. 3-9. 

त्रिवर्षा
Trivarṣā --the eleventh Veda-Vyāsa. Br. II. 35. 119.

त्रिवाह
Trivāha --a group of mountains round Merumūla. Vā. 35. 7.

त्रिविक्रम
Trivikrama --an avatār of Viṣṇu who conquered the three worlds with three steps; the lustrous God with sword as weapon; 1) Br. III. 3. 118; IV. 34. 79; M. 176. 59; Vi. V. 5. 17. Mahātmyam of; in the Vāmana Purāṇa; icon of; 2) M. 53. 45; 260. 36. Brahma-Puruṣottama. 3) Vā. 108. 38.

त्रिविष्ट
Triviṣṭa --heard the Brahmāṇḍa and Vāyu Puraṇas from Śaradvān (Śaradvata) and narrated the former to Antarikṣa. Br. IV. 4. 61; Vā. 103. 61.

त्रिवृत्
Trivṛt --a Sāma; 1) Vā. 9. 48. created from Brahmā's face. 2) Br. II. 8. 50.

त्रिवृत्सोम
Trivṛtsoma --from the first face of Brahmā. Vi. I. 5. 53.

त्रिशंकु
Triśaṃku --Satyavrata (s.v): the son of Tribandhana and father of Hariścandra; became a Caṇḍāla by the curse of his Guru; three spikes meant for him by Vasiṣṭha. Result of his three sins--displeasing his father, killing the Guru's cow and eating unconsecrated flesh; banished from the kingdom; seeing this Viśvāmitra consoled him and agreed to be his Guru; the latter had him crowned after a purification bath in the river, Karmanāśā near the Vindhyas; this enabled him to go to heaven bodily and get a place among  the planets all in the presence of Vasiṣṭha; though thrust down headlong from heaven, he was stopped and given a place in the sky. Bhā. IX. 7. 5-7; Br. III. 63. 108; Vā. 88. 108-13. Vi. IV. 3. 21.

त्रिशङ्कुग्रह
Triśaṅkugraha --the planet Triśaṅku or Satyavrata in the moon's sphere, Cf. Rāmā. Yud., IV. 90. Vā. 88. 115-6.

त्रिशंकु
Triśaṃku(deśam) --the territory north of the Mahānadī and south of Vaikaṭa (Kaikaṭa-Vā. P.) unfit for Śrāddha. Br. III. 14. 31-2; M. 16. 16; Vā. 78. 21. 2.

त्रिशालम्
Triśālam --also known as Dhānyakam. M. 253. 51; 254. 4-7.

त्रिशिख
Triśikha  (I)--was Indra of the Tāmasa epoch. Bhā. VIII. 1. 28.

त्रिशिख
Triśikha  (II)--the Veda-Vyāsa of the eleventh Dvāpara, see Trivarṣa. Vi. III. 3. 14.

त्रिशिखरम्
Triśikharam --a Mt. sacred to Śiva. M. 183. 2.

त्रिशिखिर
Triśikhira --a hill. Vā. 42. 28.

त्रिशिर
Triśira  (I)--a son of Tvaṣṭa and Yaśodharā; 1) Br. III. 1. 86; Vā. 65. 85. his mother was a sister of Virocana; 2) Vā. 84. 19. a Rākṣasa killed by Rāma. 3) Bhā. IX. 10. 9; Vā. 69. 167. His city was in the third Talam. 4) Br. II. 20. 26; Vā. 50. 26. 

त्रिशिर
Triśira  (II)--a son of Khaśa and a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 135.

त्रिशिर
Triśira  (III)--a son of Viśravas and Vākā. Br. III. 8. 56; Vā. 70. 50.

त्रिशिर
Triśira  (IV)--a son of Prahrādi and Tvaṣṭā ?. Br. III. 59. 19-20.

त्रिशूलम्
Triśūlam --the trident of Śiva; 1) Br. III. 32. 14; IV. 19. 6, 85; 20. 81; Vā. 101. 271. made from the Vaiṣṇava tejas of the sun filed off by Tvaṣṭa. 2) M. 5. 31; 11. 29; 217. 31 Vi. III. 2. 11.

त्रिशृंग
Triśṛṃga --a Mt. on the north of Meru; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 27; M. 163. 86; Vi. II. 2. 44. west of the Śitoda. 2) Vā. 36. 29; 42. 72.

त्रिषवणस्नात
Triṣavaṇasnāta --one who performs the three ablutions, at dawn, noon and sunset; fit for performing Śrāddha. Vā. 74. 12.

त्रिष्टुभ्
Triṣṭubh --a poetic metre; 1) Bhā. III. 12. 45; XI. 21. 41; M. 125. 47. a Chandas serving as a horse in the Sun's chariot, 2) Br. II. 22. 72; Vā. 51. 64; Vi. II. 8. 5. with Gāyatri and Jagati forms the Trivarṇam or Praṇava. 3) Br. II. 13. 145; Vā. 31. 47.

त्रिसन्ध्या
