Daṇḍapāṇi  (II)--the son of Medhāvi. Vā. 99. 276.

दण्डप्रणयनम्
Daṇḍapraṇayanam --the code of punishments including fines, mutilation, penance, death, impalement, etc. M. Ch. 227 (whole). Daṇḍam--the stick of the ascetic to be placed in Viṣṇupāda instead of in the Piṇḍa. Vā. 105. 26.

दण्डश्री
Daṇḍaśrī --an Āndhra king; father of three sons. Vā. 99. 356.

दण्डश्रीशातकर्णि
Daṇḍaśrīśātakarṇi --an Āndhra king; son of Vijaya, ruled for 3 years. Br. III. 74. 169.

दण्डा
Daṇḍā --a R. of the Ketumāla country. Vā. 44. 22.

दण्डि
Daṇḍi  (I)--a Brahmana mendicant; the guise in which Budha approached Ilā. M. 11. 55. 

दण्डि
Daṇḍi  (II)--a door-keeper to the Sun god. M. 261. 5.

दण्डि
Daṇḍi  (III)--a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 17.

दण्डि
Daṇḍi  (IV)--performed tapas at Sitādri in Gayā. Vā. 108. 56.

दण्डिनी
Daṇḍinī --is Śrī Daṇḍanāthā. Br. IV. 20. 68-69.

दत्त
Datta (Atri)  (I)--the son of the sage Atri and Anasūyā and an avatār of Viṣṇu according to Paurāṇikas; brother of Durvāsa; by worshipping him, the Yadus, Haihayas, etc., got knowledge of yoga. 1) Bhā. II. 7. 4; IV. I. 15 and 33; XI. 4. 17; Br. III. 8. 82; IV. 28. 89; Vā. 70. 76-8. He knew Hari yoga, 2) Bhā. II. 7. 45. and followed Hari going to Pṛthu's sacrifice. 3) Ib. IV. 19. 6. A Siddha; 4) Ib. VI. 8. 16; 15. 14. worshipped by Arjuna (Haihaya), to whom he imparted yoga; 5) Ib. IX. 15. 17; 23. 24; Br. III. 30. 35; 34. 4; 38. 14; 40. 43, 57, 66; 69. 10; M. 43. 15. in the tenth Tretāyuga the 4th incarnation with Markaṇḍeya as Purohita; 6) Br. III. 73. 88; M. 47. 242; 99. 14; Vā. 98. 89. was worshipped by Arjuna who got four boons from him one of which was 1000 hands; 7) Vā. 94. 10-11; Vi. IV. 11. 12. Śyāmas, Mudgalas, Gaviṣṭhias and others belong to this Vamśa. 8) Ib. I. 10. 8.

दत्त
Datta  (II)--a sage of the Svārociṣa epoch. M. 9. 8.

दत्तक
Dattaka --a son of Umā. Br. III. 10. 18. 

दत्तालि
Dattāli: (Dattoli) --a son of Prītā and Pulastya; an Agastya in previous birth. Vā. 28. 22; Vi. I. 10. 9.

दत्तोत्रि
Dattotri  (I)--a Paulastya and one of the 7 sages of the Svārociṣa epoch. Br. II. 36. 18.

दत्तोत्रि
Dattotri  (II)--given by Manu to Ahi as son; see Uttānapāda. Br. II. 36. 85; III. 47. 65.

ददातिबादर
Dadātibādaras --Kauśikagotrakaras. Vā. 91. 101.

दधिक्राव
Dadhikrāva --a Marici God. Br. IV. 1. 58.

दधिपञ्चमुख
Dadhipañcamukha --a Ṛtvik at Brahmā's yajña. Vā. 106. 37.

दधिमण्डोद
Dadhimaṇḍoda --a sea that surrounds the Śākadvīpa. 1) Bhā. V. 1. 33; 20. 24. (Krauñcadvīpa Br. P.) also Dadhisindhu. 2) Br. II. 19. 77; IV. 31. 19; M. 122. 92. Vi. II. 4. 57.

दधिमुख
Dadhimukha --a Kādraveya Nāga. Br. III. 7. 35; Vā. 69. 72.

दधिवाहन
Dadhivāhana --the son of Bali and king of Anga, born without apāna, due to the blunder of Sudeṣṇa; hence Anapāna; father of Diviratha (see Sudeṣṇa). Br. III. 74. 102-3; M. 48-91; Vā. 99. 100. 

दधीच
Dadhīca  (I)--a Ṛṣika, who became a sage by satya; 1) Br. II. 32. 102. a Mantrakṛṭ 2) M. 145. 98. Heard the Viṣṇu Purāṇa from Stambhamitra and narrated it to Sārasvata. 3) Vi. VI. 8. 44.

दधीच
Dadhīca  (II)--urged Dakṣa to invite Paśupati to the sacrifice. Vā. 30. 103-7.

दधीचि
Dadhīci  (I)--(also Dadhyañja, Dadhyanga) the son of Atharvan and Citti. 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 42. A sage of much eminence. Taught Aśvāśiras mantra to Aśvins and Nārāyaṇa varma to Tvaṣṭri, who gave it to Viśvarūpa. The Lord advised Indra to meet the sage whose bones would serve as best weapons to cut Vṛtra's head. When the gods waited on him with this desire, he argued at first that no one would be willing to part with his life. But, he would agree for their sake to sacrifice his life. When he cast off his body, Viśvakarma made it a Vajra for the use of Indra. 2) Ib. VI. 9. 51-55; 10. 2-13; 11. 20. Dadhīci's is an example of one, who gave up life in service. 3) Ib. VIII. 20. 7.

दधीचि
Dadhīci  (II)--the son of Cyavana Bhārgava; married Sarasvatī and father of Sārasvata; 1) Br. III. 1. 93-4; Vā. 65. 90. Sage by garbha; 2) Ib. 54. 94. a Mantrakṛt. 3) Ib. 59. 96.

दधीचि
Dadhīci  (III)--the son of Vairāja Manu. Vā. 21. 41; 30. 102.

दध्यन्च
Dadhyanca (ga) --the son of Atharva Agni. Br. II. 12. 10; Vā. 29. 8.

दनायुषा
Danāyuṣā --had five sons; all powerful. Vā. 68. 30. 

दनु
Danu  (I)--a son of Kāśyapa and Diti; appointed Purohita. Br. IV. 9. 3.

दनु
Danu  (II)--61 days and nights. Vā. 50. 186.

दनु
Danu  (III)--a son of Angirasa. Vā. 65. 105.

दनु
Danu  (IV)--known for Māyā. Vā. 69. 93.

दनु
Danu  (V)--one of Kaśyapa's wives and a daughter of Dakṣa. Had Dvimūrdhā and sixty other sons; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 25; 29-31; Vā. 66. 55; Vi. I. 5. 124. Māyāśitā; 2) Br. III. 3. 56; 6. 1-2; 7. 466. also mother of 100 sons of whom Vipracitti was the chief; mother of the Dānavas; a mother-goddess. 3) M. 6. 1 and 16; 146. 18; 171. 29 and 58; 179. 19.

दनुपुत्र
Danuputras --the great Asuras, 100 in number, chief of them being Vipracitti; all resolute and bold; blessed after long and severe penance; truthful, powerful, cruel, magical; not performers of sacrifice; unbrahmanical; a list of the chief names; some of them took to human dharma. Vā. 68. 1-16.

दनोदकदुन्दुभि
Danodakadundubhi --see Andhaka. Br. III. 71. 118.

दन्तकाण्वोशन
Dantakāṇvośana --a son of Umā and Mahādeva. Vā. 72. 16.

दन्तपवनम्
Dantapavanam --cleaning the teeth with sticks of six trees like the Aśvattha and the banyan; part of Kṛṣṇāṣṭamī vrata. M. 56. 8. 

दन्तपुष्पवान्
Dantapuṣpavān --an elephant. Vā. 69. 221.

दन्तवक्त्र
Dantavaktra  (I)--a son of Yudhiṣṭhira's aunt and brother of Caidya, (s.v.). 1) Bhā. VII. 1. 32-46; 10. 38. Helped Jarāsandha in his siege of Mathurā and Gomanta by guarding the eastern gate of the former, and the western gate of the latter with his brother. 2) Ib. X. 50. 11 [2]; 52. 11 [11]. Vi. V. 26. 7. Attended the conference summoned by Śālva to defeat the Yadus, and got angry at Śālva's death. 3) Bhā. X. 76. 2 [10]; 77. 37. Arrival at Kuṇḍina; 4) Ib. X. 53. 17; 60. 18. was the king of Kalinga; when he heard that Kṛṣṇa was returning from the Yamunā to Dvārakā, he waylaid him to discharge the debt he owed to his friends. He struck Kṛṣṇa on the head but was himself hit on his chest; when he fell dead, a spark entered Kṛṣṇa's body and he became one with the Lord. 5) Ib. X. 78. 1-13; 37. 19; II. 7. 34; III. 3. 11; VII. 1. 17.

दन्तवक्त्र
Dantavaktra  (II)--(Dantavakra-Vā. P.)--a son of Diti, and cursed by a sage; was born of Śrutadevā; 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 37; Br. IV. 29. 122; Vā. 96. 155. and Vṛddhadharma, the Kārūṣa king. 2) Br. III. 71. 156; Vi. IV. 14. 40.

दन्तिवदन
Dantivadana --see Gaṇanātha. Br. IV. 27. 77.

दन्दशूक
Dandaśūka  (I)--one of the 28 hells; the cruel and merciless are tormented here by reptiles and others. Bhā. V. 26. 7 and 33.

दन्दशूक
Dandaśūka  (II)--the name of a serpant born of Krodhavaśā. Bhā. VI. 6. 28. 

दन्दशूक
Dandaśūka  (III)--a follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra. Bhā. VI. 10. [20].

दम
Dama  (I)--a son of Marutta, and father of Rājyavardhana. Bhā. IX. 2. 29.

दम
Dama  (II)--a son of Kriyā. Br. II. 9. 60.

दम
Dama  (III)--a Sudhāmāna God. Br. II. 36. 37.

दम
Dama  (IV)--a god of the Ābhūtaraya group. Br. II. 36. 55.

दम
Dama  (V)--a Vaikuṇṭha God. Br. II. 36. 57.

दम
Dama  (VI)--a son of Nariṣyanta, a daṇḍadhara and father of Vikrānta. (Rāṣtravardhana-Br. P.; RajavardhanaVi. P.). Br. III. 61. 8; Vā. 86. 12; Vi. IV. 1. 36.

दम
Dama  (VII)--an Ārṣeya pravara of Bhārgavas. M. 195. 36.

दम
Dama  (VIII)--a son of Maṇivara. Vā. 69. 160.

दम
Dama  (IX)--a Mukhya gaṇa. Vā. 100. 18.

दम
Dama  (X)--a son of Riṣyanta. Vā. 70. 30. 

दमघोष
Damaghoṣa --a king of the Cedis; queen Śrutaśravā; 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 39. Br. III. 71. 159. Vi. IV. 14. 44. (Paṭuśravā and Rujakanyā) father of Śiśupāla (Caidya: 2) Bhā. VII. 1. 17. Vā. 96. 158. s.v.), performed preliminaries to the marriage of his son with Rukmiṇī; when he went to Kuṇḍina, he was entertained by her father Bhīṣmaka. 3) Bhā. X. 53. 14-16. He was stationed on the south during the siege of Gomanta by Jarāsandha; 4) Ib. X. 52. 11 [8]. went to Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse. 5) Ib. X. 82. 26.

दमन
Damana  (I)--a son of Vasudeva and Rohiṇi. Br. III. 71. 165; M. 46. 12. Vā. 96. 163.

दमन
Damana  (II)--a commander to aid Viṣanga, killed by Kāmesvarī. Br. IV. 25. 30, 46, 94.

दमन
Damana  (III)--a son of Angirasa. M. 196. 2.

दमन
Damana  (IV)--the avatār of the Lord in the third Dvāpara; had four sons, Viśoka, Vikeśa, etc. Vā. 23. 123.

दमन
Damana  (V)--a Ṛtvik at Brahmā's sacrifice. Vā. 106. 36.

दमवाह्य
Damavāhya --a sage; exclusion of marriage with the Angirasas. M. 196. 29.

दमिन
Damina --the Brahmana caste of Kuśadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 38.

दम्भ
Dambha  (I)--a son of Adharma. Bhā. IV. 8. 2. 

दम्भ
Dambha  (II)--a son of Āyu. M. 24. 35.

दम्भा
Dambhā --a R. in Kuśadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 62.

दंष्ट्रा
Daṃṣṭrā --a daughter of Krodhavaśa and a wife of Pulaha; 1) Br. III. 7. 172; Vā. 69. 205. gave birth to lions, tigers, elephants, etc. 2) Br. III. 7. 412.

दंष्ट्राला
Daṃṣṭrālā --a Mind-born mother. M. 179. 23.

दंष्ट्री
Daṃṣṭrī --a monkey chief. Br. III. 7. 233.

दया
Dayā --a daughter of Dakṣa, and a wife of Dharma; mother of Abhaya; 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 49-50. a śakti. 2) Br. IV. 44. 89.

दरद
Darada  (I)--a Mahāratha; was stationed on the southern gate of Mathurā, and on the western gate of Gomanta by Jarāsandha when he besieged them. Bhā. X. 50. 11 [3]; 52. 11 [12].

दरद
Darada  (II)--a northern kingdom noted for horses; 1) Br. II. 16. 49; 18. 47; 31. 83; IV. 16. 17; M. 121. 46; 144. 57. a tribe. 2) Vā. 45. 118; 47. 44-5; 58. 83; 98. 108.

दरिद्योत
Daridyota --(Aridyota-Br. P.)--the son of Dundubhi and father of Punarvasu. Bhā. IX. 24. 20.

दरिद्रान्तक
Daridrāntaka  (I)--a son of Sāraṇa. Vā. 96. 165. 

दरिद्रान्तक
Daridrāntaka  (II)--a son of Balarāma. Br. III. 71. 167.

दरिमुख
Darimukha --born of Pulaha. Br. III. 7. 178.

दर्दुर
Dardura  (I)--vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. II. 7. 34.

दर्दुर
Dardura  (II)--a Mt. of the Bhāratavarṣa. Vā. 45. 90.

दर्प
Darpa  (I)--born of Dharma and Unnati. Bhā. IV. 1. 51.

दर्प
Darpa  (II)--a son of Lakṣmī. Br. II. 9. 8; Vā. 10. 34.

दर्पणम्
Darpaṇam --a looking-glass to be installed by the side of a deity. M. 57. 18; 265. 19; 289. 10.

दर्भ
Darbha --a son of Āngirasa. Vā. 65. 104.

दर्भक
Darbhaka  (I)--a son of Ajātaśatru and father of Ajaya. Bhā. XII, 1. 6.

दर्भक
Darbhaka  (II)--ruled for 35 years. Br. III. 74. 131.

दर्भावती
Darbhāvatī --a R. of the Ketumāla country. Vā. 44. 17. 

दर्व
Darvas --a hill tribe; 1) Br. II. 16. 67. a mountain kingdom. 2) M. 114. 56; Vā. 45. 136.

दर्वा
Darvā --one of the wives of Uśinara and mother of Suvrata. Br. III. 74. 18 and 20. Vā. 99. 19.

दर्श
Darśa  (I)--the son of Dhātā and Sinīvāli. Bhā. VI. 18. 3.

दर्श
Darśa  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Kālindi. Bhā. X. 61. 14.

दर्श
Darśa  (III)--a son of Brahmā and Mantrasarīra: a Jayadeva. Br. III. 3. 6; 4. 2; Vā. 66. 6; 67. 5.

दर्शक
Darśaka --a king of Magadha; ruled for 25 years. Vā. 99. 318.

दर्शनीय
Darśanīya --a Yakṣa; son of Puṇyajanī and Maṇibhadra. Br. III. 7. 125.

दर्शपूर्णमास
Darśapūrṇamāsa --a sacrifice performed by Bharata. Bhā. V. 7. 5.

दर्शम्
Darśam --a name for the 27th Kalpa; here Soma became Paurṇamāsi. Vā. 21. 67, 69.

दर्शा
Darśā --one of the five queens of Uśīnara; father of Suvrata. M. 48. 16, 18. 

दल
Dala  (I)--a son of Pratyuṣa and a Devaṛsi. Br. II. 35. 94.

दल
Dala  (II)--a son of Pariyātra (Pāripātra-Vā. P.) and father of Bala. Br. III. 63. 204: Vā. 88. 204.

दश
Daśa --one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 9.

दशकन्धर
Daśakandhara --Rāvana killed by Rāma. Bhā. II. 7. 23-25.

दशकृत्व
Daśakṛtva --the Yāma gaṇas who stand in ten parts in the Vairāja. Vā. 101. 64.

दशग्रीव
Daśagrīva  (I)--Rāvana (s.v.). 1) Bhā. VII. 10. 36; Br. III. 7. 262; 71 159. Śiśupāla in previous birth. 2) Vā. 96. 153.

दशग्रीव
Daśagrīva  (II)--an Asura in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. M. 161. 81.

दशताल
Daśatāla --the images of Rāma and Bali. M. 259. 1.

दशनामक
Daśanāmakas --a tribe. M. 114. 42. 

दशमानिक
Daśamānikas --a tribe. Vā. 45. 117.

दशमालिक
Daśamālika (c) --a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 48.

दशरथ
Daśaratha  (I)--a son of Mūlaka, and father of Aiḍaviḍa. (Ilīvila-Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 9. 41; V. IV. 4. 75.

दशरथ
Daśaratha  (II)--a son of Aja (Pāla) and of Indumatī; and father of Śrī Rāma (Dāśarathi Rāma-Vā. P.) and three other sons, being the amśas of Hari. 1) Bhā. IX. 10. 1-2; Br. III. 63. 184; IV. 40. 100; M. 12. 49-50; Vā. 88. 183-4; 111. 64; Vi. IV. 4. 86-7. A friend of Romapāda to whom he gave his daughter Śāntā in adoption. 2) Bhā. IX. 23. 7-8; Vi. IV. 18. 17-8. King of Ayodhyā. Having no sons worshipped Tripurasundarī at the capital and spent seven days at Kāñcī praying to Kāmākṣī who blessed him with four sons. 3) Br. III. 37. 31; 63. 184; IV. 40. 88.

दशरथ
Daśaratha  (III)--a son of Navaratha, and father of Śakuni (Ekādaśaratha-Br. P.). Bhā. IX. 24. 4-5; Br. III. 70. 43-4. Vā. 95. 42; Vi. IV. 12. 41.

दशरथ
Daśaratha  (IV)--a son of Satyaratha (Citraratha: Vā. P.). (Known also as Lomapāda). M. 48. 94; Vā. 9. 103.

दशरथ
Daśaratha  (V)--a Maurya king who ruled for eight years; son of Suyaśā and father of Samyuta. M. 272. 25; Vi. IV. 24. 30.

दशवर्णधनु
Daśavarṇadhanu --the bow of Śiva with ten colours. Vā. 101. 270. 

दशानन
Daśānana --see Rāvana. Vi. IV. 4. 97; 14. 48-9; 15. 7-8.

दशार्ण
Daśārṇas --a Vindhya tribe enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus. Bhā. X. [50. (v) 3]; Br. II. 16. 64; Vā. 45. 132.

दशार्णा
Daśārṇā --a R. in Bhāratavarṣa from the Rkṣa; sacred to Pitṛs. Br. II. 16. 30; III. 13. 100; M. 22. 34; Vā. 45. 99. M. 144. 25.

दशार्ह
Daśārha  (I)--the son of Nirvṛt(t)i, (Nidhṛti-V. P., Vīdūratha, M. P.), and father of Vyoma; 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 3; X. 36. 33; M. 44. 40. a man of much prowess. 2) Br. III. 70. 41; Vi. IV. 12. 41.

दशार्ह
Daśārha  (II)--a son of Gharmātmā. Vā. 95. 40.

दशार्ह
Daśārhas --(also Daśārhakās) a tribe related to the Pāṇḍavas. They defended Dvārakā when attacked. 1) Bhā. I. 11. 11; 14. 25; III. 1. 29. Praised Kṛṣṇa's heroism. 2) Ib. IX. 24. 63. Felt relieved at Kamsa's death as they heard of his plan to vanquish them. 3) Ib. X. 36. 33; 39. 25; 45. 15. Followed Balarāma to Dvārakā and fought their own kinsmen. 4) Ib. X. 61. 40; XI. 29. 39; 30. 18.

दशाश्वमेधजननम्
Daśāśvamedhajananam --a Tīrtha on the Narmadā; west of Gangeśvaram. 193. 20-2.

दाशाश्वमेधम्
Dāśāśvamedham --a Tirtham in Benares; 1) M. 185. 68. fit for śrāddha. 2) Vā. 77. 45. 

दशेरक
Daśeraka (c) --a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 50.

दस्यहन्तम
Dasyahantama --the name of Budha, son of Tārā and Soma who forcibly seized her from Bṛhaspati; 1) Br. III. 65. 41; Vā. 90. 37. called Budha after Tārā revealed his real father. 2) Vā. 90. 43.

दस्यु
Dasyu --The Ābhiras and Mlecchas; unfit for śrāddha; 1) Br. III. 14. 43; Vi. V. 38. 13; 25. 27. 497. checked by Yayāti; 2) Br. III. 68. 67. dharma of the; 3) Ib. III. 63. 194; Vā. 49. 55; 78. 34; 88. 105. seized 16000 ladies of Kṛṣṇa due to a curse by the Lord; 4) M. 70. 7. cudgels as chief weapons of; 5) Vi. V. 38. 51, 70, 82, 84. killing milch cows. 6) Vā. 93. 66.

दस्युमान्
Dasyumān --an Āngirasa and Mantrakṛt. Br. II. 32. 108.

दस्र
Dasra --a son of Mārtāṇḍa or the Sun; 1) Vā. 84. 24. Br. III. 59. 25; one of the Aśvins. 2) Vā. 84. 77.

दहन
Dahana --one of the eleven Rudras. M. 171. 39.

दह्राग्नि
Dahrāgni --born as Agastya to Pulastya. Bhā. IV. 1. 36.

दाकव्य
Dākavyas --Ekārṣeyas. M. 200. 3. 

दाकायन
Dākāyanas --sages. M. 200. 10.

दाकिनि
Dākinis --evil spirits injuring children. Bhā. X. 6. 27; 63. 10.

दाक्षपायन
Dākṣapāyana --a Kāśyapa gotrakāra. M. 199. 5.

दाक्षायणि
Dākṣāyaṇi  (I)--a son of Dāruka, an avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 196.

दाक्षायणि
Dākṣāyaṇi  (II)--the previous avatār of Umā; stars regarded as her daughters; 1) M. 13. 10; 128. 50; 199. 20. a daughter of Dakṣa; 2) Br. I. 1. 59. became Hiṃavān's daughter by worshipping Śiva. 3) Ib. III. 7. 472; IV. 11. 2-5.

दाक्षि
Dākṣi --a sage; a Trayārṣeya pravara. M. 196. 25; 197. 6.

दाक्षिणात्य
Dākṣiṇātyas --(Drāviḍas); southerners; 1) Br. II. 31. 82; Vā. 58. 82; 98. 107. to be conquered by Kalki. 2) Br. III. 73. 107.

दाता
Dātā --a Mukhya gaṇa of the Sāvarṇya epoch; 1) Vā. 94. 56; 100. 18; a Sukha God.  2) Br. IV. 1. 19.

दाता
Dātā --a Vaikuṇṭha God. Br. II. 36. 57.

दानम्
Dānam  (I)--a Sukha God. Br. IV. 1. 19. 

दानम्
Dānam  (II)--a Mukhya gaṇa. Vā. 100. 18.

दान
Dāna --a dharma; 1) Vā. 23. 101. a śiṣṭācāra; 2) Br. II. 32. 41. three kinds of; superior, middling and inferior; the first and last of which are called respectively jyeṣṭha and kaniṣṭha; the lower and the higher not fit for one's own welfare; the middling is the equal distribution among the deserving; the superior gift leads to Mokṣa and the inferior to one's own welfare; 3) Ib. II. 32. 54-56; Vā. 59. 49-50. he who performs sacrifice by ill-gotten wealth does not attain the fruits thereof; his gifts are not for dharma but only for show; but well-earned money given to right men without expecting fruits, merits Bhoga while Satya leads to heaven; 4) Ib. 67. 27; 91. 106-12; 104. 14. the making of, in a śrāddha and the fruits thereof; 5) Br. III. 4. 24; 16. 1. one of the upāyas of a king; even Gods are brought under control by gifts; sixteen kinds of; done by Kāma, Ambarīṣa, Pṛthu, Prahlāda and others; 6) M. 222. 2; 224. 1-4; 246. 25-7; 274 (whole). the vidhi of, enquired by Manu from the Matsya. 7) Ib. 2. 23. Incumbent on all castes 8) Vi. III. 8. 22. useless if given to a nonśrotriya; 9) Ib. V. 38. 30. conditions appropriate to. 10) Vā. 91. 107-13.

दानकाय
Dānakāyas --a group of sages. M. 200. 17.

दानव
Dānavas --a class of demons from Danu residing in Rasātala; Śvetaparvata their abode; 1) Bhā. II. 7. 13; V. 24. 30. Vā. 39. 29; 46. 35; 66. 1. were fascinated by Hari but they hated him; 2) Bhā. X. 40. 22; 85. 41; XI. 14. 5. Vipracitti was their overlord. 3) Br. III. 7. 255; 8. 7; 20. 3; IV. 4. 2.

दानव्रत
Dānavratas --a class of people in Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 27. 

दानाग्नि
Dānāgni --a son of Prīti and Pulastya; Agastya in previous birth; wife Sujanghi, had many sons known as Paulastyas. Br. II. 11. 26.

दानी
Dānī --a Sukha God. Br. IV. 1. 18.

दान्त
Dānta --a Sudhāmāna God. Br. II. 36. 27.

दाम
Dāma --a Sukha God. Br. IV. 1. 18.

दामोदर
Dāmodara --Kṛṣṇa; 1) Br. III. 36. 39; with the weapon pāśa; 2) Ib. IV. 34. 83. around his belly Yaśodā bound a rope and fastened him to a mortar. 3) Vi. V. 6. 20; 13. 34.

दारवत्या
Dāravatyā --an Apsaras. Vā. 69. 4.

दारिक
Dārika --(Dārakas-Vā. P.); a Pārāśara clan. Br. III. 8. 95. Vā. 70. 87.

दारुक
Dāruka  (I)--the charioteer of Kṛṣṇa; 1) Bhā. X. 50. 16. 20 [5]. [8]; 64. [6]; 71. 12. Vi. V. 37. 51. went with Kṛṣṇa to Śālva's station, and drove the chariot when Kṛṣṇa gained Lakṣmaṇā by svayamvara; 2) Bhā. X. 77. 9-11; 83. 33. took Kṛṣṇa to Mithilā and the Videha country. 3) Ib. 86. 17; 53. 4. His son was the charioteer of Pradyumna. 4) Ib. 76. 27. Stood before Kṛṣṇa on the eve of His returning from the earth. Kṛṣṇa asked him to inform the Dvārakā people of the position of the Yādavas at Prabhāsa and advise them to go to Indraprastha with Arjuna. Returning to the city, Dāruka informed Vasudeva and others accordingly. 5) Ib. XI. 30. 41-50; 31. 15-17; Vi. V. 37. 57-64. 

दारुक
Dāruka  (II)--the avatār of the Lord in the 21st Dvāpara with sons in the holy Dāruvana. Vā. 23. 95.

दारुण
Dāruṇa --a Gandharva. Br. III. 7. 11.

दारुवनम्
Dāruvanam --on the Himālayan crests; the abode of sages in Kṛtayuga engaged in severe austerities; Śiva appeared before them naked and sometimes wept and sometimes danced; the womenfolk were enchanted by him; the angry sages cursed him to become an ass and attempted to cut off his lingam; the Lord disappeared; finding the world beset with difficulties and dangers the sages appealed to Brahmā and learnt that it was due to Śiva; hence they made images of Linga and offered worship for a year; the Lord appeared before them, and was praised by all; 1) Br. II. 27. 2-90; the sages were treated by Śiva on Bhasmasnānavidhi. 2) Ib. II. 27. 105, 128.

दार्वा
Dārvā --a degraded Kṣatriya clan. Br. III. 63. 140.

दालकि
Dālaki --a disciple of Rathitara (s.v.). Vā. 60. 66.

दाल्भ्य
Dālbhya  (I)--a sage of the Auttama epoch. M. 9. 14.

दाल्भ्य
Dālbhya  (II)--the sage who initiated the fallen wives of Kṛṣṇa in the Anangadānavratam and thus rescued them. M. 70. 10, 13. 

दाविक
Dāvika (c) --the country of, (Dārvika--Wilson) under the mlecchas. Vi. IV. 24. 69.

दाशपुरम्
Dāśapuram --here were born as hunters the seven sons of Kauśika. But they remembered their previous births and refrained from cruel deeds. M. 20. 12-4; 21. 9 and 28.

दाशरथि
Dāśarathi --a name of Rāma, who destroyed Rāvana and his clan. Vā. 70. 48.

दाशार्ण
Dāśārṇas --Śatadhvaja (s.v.) was their king; when they heard of Kṛṣṇa going to Mithilā they met him with presents. Bhā. X. 52. 11 [12]; 86. 25.

दाशार्ह
Dāśārha --see Daśārhas. Bhā. XI. 30. 18.

दाशेयि
Dāśeyi --the fisher-woman, who took birth as Satyavatī and begot Vicitravīrya by Śantanu. M. 50. 45; Vā. 73. 21; 99. 240.

दास
Dāsa --servants entertained in a śrāddha; 1) M. 17. 57 and 62; Vā. 60. 37. appellation of the Śūdras. 2) Vi. III. 10. 9.

दासि
Dāsi  (I)--Slaves as present to learned men. Br. II. 34. 39. 

दासि
Dāsi  (II)--of four kinds, devadāsi, brahmadāsi, svatantra and Śūdradāsika; the first two occupy the status of a Kṣatriya lady; the third enjoys the status of a dancing girl (veśi), and the last that of a low caste (hīnajāti). 1) Br. IV. 8. 11-12. A synonym of Paricārika or a servant-maid. 2) M. 29. 17-23.

दासेर
Dāsera --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 85.

दाहकाल
Dāhakāla --the period at the end of a Kalpa. Vā. 7. 15.

दिक्
Dik --a son of Śatarūpā. M. 4. 25.

दिक्गज
Dikgajas --the four elephants at the four quarters with clouds; thrown about during Śiva's tāṇḍava. Br. II. 22. 47, 51; Vā. 51. 43-5. M. 1. 1; 125. 17-21.

दिक्पति
Dikpati --a Satya God. Br. II. 36. 34; Vā. 62. 31.

दिक्पाल
Dikpālas --the guardians of the quarters; Sudharman, Śankhapāda, Ketumān, and Hīraṇyaroman; destroy the enemies and protect the earth. Invoked in the grahabali; 1) M. 8. 9-11; 93. 52. worship of. 2) M. 67. 9-16; 69. 38.

दिक्वासस
Dikvāsasa --an attribute of Śiva. Br. II. 27. 98.

दिगङ्गन
Digaṅgana --These are Brāhmī, Āgneyī, Gādinī, Naiṛṛti, Vāruṇī, Patākinī, Śankhini and Māheśvari. M. 286. 5-11, 17. 

दिगीश्वरा
Digīśvarās --Lords of the quarters; present at Varuṇa's sacrifice. Br. III. 1. 28.

दिग्दन्ति
Digdanti --see Diggaja. Br. IV. 9. 79.

दिग्विजय
Digvijaya --conquest of the quarters; of Sagara; 1) Br. III. 49. 47; 52. 41. of Ila. 2) M. 11. 43.

दिण्डिपुण्यकरम्
Diṇḍipuṇyakaram --a Tīrtham sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 77.

दिण्डिम
Diṇḍima --a war-musical instrument. M. 138. 56; Mā. 40. 24.

दिति
Diti  (I)--a daughter of Dakṣa, and wife of Kaśyapa. 1) Bhā. III. 14. 7; Vā. 66. 54; Vi. I. 15. 124, 140. Her sons generally known as Daityas. Mother of Hiraṇyākṣa and Hiraṇyakaśipu. 2) Bhā. VI. 6. 25; 18. 11; VII. 1. 39; Br. III. 3. 56; M. 6. 1-8; Vā. 67. 49. Mother of Dantavaktra by the sage's curse. 3) Bhā. IX. 24. 37. Her sons Prahlāda and Hari were devotees of Hari. 4) Ib. VI. 18. 10. Always set her mind on truth; 5) Ib. VII. 2. 61. daughter Simhikā; 5a) Vā. 67. 60. (Ādity-Vā. P.). Finding her sons slain by Hari to help Indra, she became enraged, and asked her husband to bless her with a child to kill Indra. The unwilling husband offered it on condition of her observing certain vows for 100 years. So she observed them and Indra came to assist her. One day he found her sleeping in an unorthodox posture and entering her womb cut the embryo into seven and then into 49 pieces; but at her request he gave all of them the status of gods, known as Maruts. 6) Bhā. VI. 18. 23-77; Br. I. 1. 112; ch. 5 (whole); 7. 465; IV. 9. 3; M. 6. 47; ch. 7 (whole); Vā. 67. 86, 135; Vi. I. 21. 30-41. Impelled by passion and desire for children she approached her husband one evening for sexual intercourse. Kaśyapa said that it was the hour when Śivagaṇas moved about and for him, to offer the Śandhya-prayer. But she persisted and gained her object. She however requested to be redeemed of the sin. Kaśyapa  remarked that since she approached him at the wrong time, her sons would have paiśāca-character and would be killed by Hari. For her penitence she was blessed with a righteous child among her grandsons. 7) Bhā. III. 14 (whole). Held the tejas in embryo for a hundred years when darkness enveloped all directions. The two door-keepers of Vaikuṇṭha cursed by seers for preventing them from having darsan of Hari were born as her two sons, when there were evil omens. 8) Ib. VI. 15. 1-10; 16. 35; 17. 2-15. Prayed for another son. This was Vajrānga who on his birth according to her orders bound Indra. The latter was released on the mediation of Brahmā and Kaśyapa. 9) M. 146. 18-55; 171. 29. Mother of Daityas; a Mother Goddess to be worshipped in house and palace buildings 10) Ib. 171. 58; 179. 15; 251. 29; 253. 27; 268. 19. Yoganidrā addressed as; 11) Vi V. 2. 9. sons of, in the seventh talam or Pātālam. 12) Vā. 50. 43.

दिति
Diti  (II)--a Mauneya. Vā. 69. 2.

दिदेहक
Didehaka --a Śukra deva. Vā. 31. 9.

दिननाथ
Dinanātha --a name of the Sun God. Br. IV. 24. 61.

दिनमिश्रा
Dinamiśrā --a Sakti in the Ṣoḍaśapatrābja. Br. IV. 32. 11.

दिलीप
Dilīpa  (I)--a sage who knows the yoga power of Viṣṇu. Bhā. II. 7. 44. 

दिलीप
Dilīpa  (II)--a son of Amśuman and of Yaśodā; father of Bhagīratha; tried to bring down the Gangā but died without success. 1) Bhā. IX. 9. 2. M. 12. 44; 15. 19. Vā. 73. 42. 88. 167. Vi. IV. 4. 34-5. After a long rule, he retired to the forest. 2) Br. III. 10. 92; 56. 29, 32; 63. 166.

दिलीप
Dilīpa  (III)--a son of Ṛṣya and father of Pratīpa. Bhā. IX. 22. 11.

दिलीप
Dilīpa  (IV)--(Khaṭvāṅga) the son of Kṛśaśarma; comes down from heaven and resides here for a muhūrta; a master of the three worlds by intelligence and honesty. Br. III. 63. 182.

दिलीप
Dilīpa  (V)--a son of Raghu. M. 12. 48.

दिलीप
Dilīpa  (VI)--a son of Bhīmasena and father of Pratīpa. M. 50. 38; Vā. 99. 233; Vi. IV. 20 7-8.

दिलीप
Dilīpa  (VII)--a son of Viśvamahat. Vā. 88. 182.

दिवौकस
Divaukasas --Devas. Vā. 88. 78.

दिवम्
Divam --Heaven; see also Suvarlokam; presiding deity is Sūrya, who is therefore known as Divaspati; here live Gandharvas, Rākṣasas, Apsarasas, Yakṣas, Nāgas, and men; five-fold route to, from Pātālam; equal to earth in measurement of rotation or border. M. 2. 32; 124. 20. Vā. 47. 9; 101. 19.

दिवंजय
Divaṃjaya --a son of Udāradhi and Bhadra; husband of Varāngi and father of Ripu. Br. II. 36. 101; Vā. 62. 87. 

दिववष्टा
Divavaṣṭā --a Kaśyapa and a Trayārṣeya. M. 199. 13.

दिवस्पति
Divaspati  (I)--the Indra of the epoch of the 13th Manu (Ruci); a friend of Yogeśvara. Bhā. VIII. 13. 31-32; Br. IV. 1. 101; Vā. 100. 105. Vi. III. 2. 39.

दिवस्पति
Divaspati  (II)--Sūrya, Lord of Bhavya. Br. II. 23. 50; Vā. 101. 22.

दिवस्पति
Divaspati  (III)--a name of Dhruva. Vā. 62. 81.

दिवस्पर्शा
Divasparśā --a Tuṣita Deva. Br. II. 36. 10.

दिवाक
Divāka --(Divārka Br. P.)--son of Bhānu and father of Sahadeva; leader of an army. Bhā. IX. 12. 10-11.

दिवाकर
Divākara  (I)--the Sun god, king of the planets; 1) M. 150. 151; 265. 38 and 41. 266. 38. 281. 12. Vā. 28. 32. is Agni; 2) Ib. 53. 29, 30. different positions of, in the sky in different lands; 3) Br. II. 21. 37-43. struck by Svabhānu, fell on the earth; 4) Br. II. 22. 12; III. 3. 110; 8. 76. addressed by Kārttikeya to whom he went as a Brahmana; 5) Ib. III. 70. 4. at a distance of 1000×100 yojanas from the earth. 6) Vā. 101. 129.

दिवाकर
Divākara  (II)--a son of Prativyoma (Prativyūha Vā. P.); his capital Ayodhyā; (Vā. P.). 1) M. 271. 5; Vā. 99. 282. Father of Sahadeva. 2) Vi. IV. 22. 3.

दिवाकर
Divākara  (III)--divided the earth into ten political divisions and distributed them among Iksvāku and other  cognates. Sudyumna in woman's disguise did not get any share; Vasiṣṭha got him Pratiṣṭā and he in turn offered it to Pururavas. Vā. 85. 20-23.

दिवाकीर्त्य
Divākīrtyas --a class of Pitṛs propitiated on every NewMoon Day; 1) Br. II. 28. 23, 93; Vā. 56. 21; 73. 62. to them Kṛṣṇapakṣa is day and Śuklapakṣa is night. 2) Vā. 56. 87.

दिवाकृत्य
Divākṛtyas --a class of Gods performing Śrāddha. Br. III. 10. 110.

दिवावृत
Divāvṛta --Mt. a hill of Krauñcadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 67; Vā. 49. 62. Vi. II. 4. 51.

दिवि
Divi --a Satya God. Br. II. 36. 35.

दिविन्द
Divinda --Mt. a hill of Krauñcadvīpa. Vā. 49. 62.

दिविरथ
Diviratha  (I)--the son of Khanapāna (Anapāna Br. P. and Vi. P.) and father of Dharmaratha. Bhā. IX. 23. 6-7; Br. III. 74. 103; Vi. IV. 18. 15; Vā. 99. 101.

दिविरथ
Diviratha  (II)--the son of Dadhivāhana; his son was Vidvan Dharmaratha. M. 48. 92.

दिवोदास
Divodāsa  (I)--a son of Bhīmaratha and father of Dyumat. Bhā. IX. 17. 6.

दिवोदास
Divodāsa  (II)--son of Mudgala and father of Mitreyu. Bhā. IX. 21. 34; 22. 1. 

दिवोदास
Divodāsa  (III)--see Prajeśvara. Br. III. 67. 26.

दिवोदास
Divodāsa  (IV)--a son of Vindhyāśva; 1) M. 50. 7. a Mantrakṛt 2) Br. II. 32. 106; Vā. 59. 97. and a Rājaṛṣi; 3) M. 145. 100. excluded from marital alliances with Bhṛgus, etc. 4) Ib. 195. 42.

दिवोदास
Divodāsa  (V)--a name of Bhīmaratha, king of Kāśi; ruined by Rākṣasa Kṣemaka. Divodāsa established his headquarters at the city of Gomati on the outskirts of the state; a Rājaṛṣi, his wife Suyaśā prayed to Gaṇapati in the temple at the city of Nikumbha for a son and as the God was not pleased to grant her prayer even after a long time, Divodāsa had the temple demolished and hence cursed; defeated and slew the 100 sons of Bhadraśreni except the child Durdama; through queen Dṛṣadvati he got a son Pratardana. Vā. 92. 23-64; Vi. IV. 8. 11.

दिवोदास
Divodāsa  (VI)--the Rājaṛṣi, son of Badhyaśva and Menaka. Vā. 99. 201.

दिवोदास
Divodāsa  (VII)--the son of Haryaśva and father of Mitrāyu. Vi. IV. 19. 62, 69.

दिवौकस
Divaukasas --a class of deities of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. M. 9. 24.

दिव्य
Divya  (I)--a son of Sātvata. Bhā. IX. 24. 6; Br. III. 71. 1. Vi. IV. 13. 1.

दिव्य
Divya  (II)--a son of Uttama Manu. Br. II. 36. 39. 

दिव्य
Divya  (III)--a God of Sutāra group. Br. IV. 1. 89.

दिव्य
Divya  (VI)--a son of Kauśalyā. Vā. 96. 1.

दिव्यमहोरात्रम्
Divyamahorātram --360 days of human reckoning according to the sāvana calculation; ahas or day is udagāyanam and rātri or night is dakṣiṇāyanam; māsam, 30 years of human calculation; three months and ten days equal to 100 years of human counting; samvatsara = 360 years of human years; 1000 years = 360000 years. Vā. 57. 12, 19; 100. 224.

दिव्यमान
Divyamāna --a Pārāvata God of the Svarociṣa epoch. Br. II. 36. 14.

दिव्यमानुष
Divyamānuṣas --divine men, the ten sons of Vaivasvata Manu. M. 11. 41.

दिव्यविद्या
Divyavidyā --a Yoganāthā. Br. IV. 37. 30.

दिव्या
Divyā  (I)--a daughter of Hiraṇyakaśipu and wife of Bhṛgu, the first Prajāpati; son Śukra; had also a daughter. Br. III. 1. 74-6. 88; Vā. 65. 72.

दिव्या
Divyā  (II)--an Apsaras. Br. III. 7. 7.

दिव्यौषधि
Divyauṣadhi --a son of Uttama Manu. Br. II. 36. 39. 

दिशस्
Diśas  (I)--one of the Marutgaṇas. Vā. 67. 129.

दिशस्
Diśas  (II)--directions as the wives of Bhīma; Ākāśa tanu of the Lord; svarga as the sun. Br. II. 10. 82; Vā. 27. 54.

दिशानाम्
Diśānām devānām --deities of quarters sculptured in the pillars of the palace. Vā. 101. 290.

दिष्ट
Diṣṭa --a son of Vaivasvata Manu and father of Nābhāga. Bhā. VIII. 13. 2; IX. 1. 12; 2. 23; Br. II. 38. 31; III. 60. 3. Vi. IV. 1. 7.

दीक्षा
Dīkṣā  (I)--wife of Ugra, (Dīkṣita) son Santāna. Br. II. 10. 83; Vā. 27. 55.

दीक्षा
Dīkṣā  (II)--in connection with Lalitā's worship; Śāmbhavī Dīkṣā is the knowledge that comes at once by the Guru's look, speech or touch; Mānasi Dīkṣā where the disciple is initiated by the Guru in secret being pleased with his conduct; first was Kriyā Dīkṣā which consists of purificatory bath and recital of Devīsūkta and Puruṣasūkta with 16 upacāras; offering of the Puṣpāñjali with sahasrākṣara vidya; samādhi; the poor and disabled worship with bhāvanadravyas (i.e.) meditation in mind as if doing all of them; place of meditation or japasthāna; thinking of Bhaitrarī, then the ŚaṢa-Sa group of 42 letters, Pañcākṣara, Caturakṣara, etc.; contemplate on Varamūrtis and then Svaraśaktis and Varṇaśaktis; installation of Cakreśvarī and of Ananga Kusumadevī in the heart seeing the Mudrā; meditation of Manujapam pleases Devī. Br. IV. 43 (whole) and 44, 1 to 151. 

दीक्षा
Dīkṣā  (III)--as consort of a Brahmana Soma. Vi. I. 8. 8.

दीक्षित
Dīkṣita Brāhmaṇa --with Dikṣā a sthāna of Rudra; son Santāna. Vi. 1. 8. 7, 11.

दीधय
Dīdhaya --a Yāma Deva. Vā. 31. 6.

दीपप्रतिष्टाख्यव्रतम्
Dīpapratiṣṭākhyavratam --performed by Dharaṇī and got relieved of the distress caused by Paraśurāma. Br. III. 47. 61.

दीपिका
Dīpikā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 35. 98.

दीपेश्वरम्
Dīpeśvaram --a Tīrtham on the Narmadā (see Vyāsa Tīrtha). M. 191. 38.

दीप्त
Dīpta --a son of Uttama Manu. Vi. III. 1. 15.

दीप्तकेतु
Dīptaketu --a son of Dakṣa Sāvarṇi. Bhā. VIII. 13. 18; Vi. III. 2. 24.

दीप्ति
Dīpti  (I)--an Amitābha god; one of the twenty Amitābha gaṇas. Br. IV. 1. 17; Vā. 100. 16.

दीप्ति
Dīpti  (II)--the fruit of Prāṇāyāma; equal to the worship of planets of Sun, Moon, and able to know the past, present and future. Vā. 11. 4, 9. 

दीप्तिकेतु
Dīptiketu --a son of the first Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 64.

दीप्तिमान्
Dīptimān  (I)--one of the seven sages of the eighth Manvantara. Bhā. VIII. 13. 15. Vi. III. 2. 17.

दीप्तिमान्
Dīptimān  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Rohiṇi (Satyabhāmā M. P.). Bhā. X. 61. 18; 90. 33; M. 47. 17; Vi. V. 32. 2.

दीप्तिम्
Dīptim  (III)--(Ātreya)--a sage of the first epoch of Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 11.

दीप्तिमेधा
Dīptimedhā --a God of Sumedhasa group. Br. II. 36. 59.

दीप्तिव्रतम्
Dīptivratam --the gift of a light; leads to Rudraloka. M. 101. 41.

दीर्घकेशी
Dīrghakeśī --a Mother goddess. M. 179. 29.

दीर्घघोणा
Dīrghaghoṇā --a Svara Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 55, 74.

दीर्घजिह्व
Dīrghajihva --a commander of Bhaṇḍa to aid Viṣaṅga; killed by Bhagamālā. Br. IV. 21. 78; 25. 27. 94.

दीर्घजिह्विका
Dīrghajihvikā --a Svara Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 56. 

दीर्घतप
Dīrghatapa --(Saunahotra and Prakāśiraṭ)--the son of Kāśa (Rāṣṭra Vi. P.) and the king of Kāśi; see Kāśipa; 1) Br. III. 67. 7. Vi. IV. 8. 7-8. a Mantrakṛt and of the Angirasa branch. 2) Vā. 59. 102. Performed penance for sons on account of which Arjadeva Dhanvantri became his son; father of Dharma and Dhanvantri. 3) Ib. 92. 6, 18-19.

दीर्घतम
Dīrghatama  (I)--a son of Raṣṭra and father of Dhanvantari. Bhā. IX. 17. 4.

दीर्घतम
Dīrghatama  (II)--a son of Uśija; cursed even in the womb to lose consciousness by Bṛhaspati; learnt his Dharma from Saurabheya Vṛṣabha; it was Godharma to do as they pleased; once embraced in sexual love his brother's wife; for this he was floated down the Ganges; 1) M. 48. 41-57; Vā. 99. 34-76. met Vairocana Bali who engaged him for Kṣetraja sons, five through Bali's queen and one through her servant-maid. This was Kākṣīvat. 2) Bhā. IX. 23. 5; M. 48. 58-78; Vā. 99. 92. Surabhi warded him from the darkness clouding him; got the title Gotama; 3) M. 48. 79-84. with Kākṣīvat he went to Girivraja and after penance reached heaven; 4) Ib. 48. 85-86. a Ṛṣika and a Mantrakṛṭ. 5) Br. II. 32. 101, 111; M. 145. 95 and 105.

दीर्घतम
Dīrghatama  (III)--a sage by Garbha. Vā. 59. 93; 99. 37.

दीर्घतम
Dīrghatama  (IV)--a son of Utathya and Mamatā; father of Anga and others. Half-brother of Bharadvāja. Vi. IV. 18. 13; 19. 16.

दीर्घबाहु
Dīrghabāhu  (I)--a son of Khaṭvānga (Dilipa) and father of Raghu. Bhā. IX. 10. 1; Br. III. 63. 183; Vā. 88. 183; Vi. IV. 4. 83-4. 

दीर्घबाहु
Dīrghabāhu  (II)--a son of Aja. M. 12. 49.

दीर्घमुख
Dīrghamukha --alias Vigneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 66.

दीर्घा
Dīrghā --a Kalā of Viṣṇu. Br. IV. 35. 95.

दुन्दु
Dundu --the Asura who insulted the sage Udaka and met with death at the hands of Kuvalayāśva. Vi. IV. 2. 40.

दुन्दुभि
Dundubhi  (I)--the son of Andhaka and father of Daridyota (Aridyota-Br. P.). Bhā. IX. 24. 20.

दुन्दुभि
Dundubhi  (II)--a son of Dyutimān; a Janapada in Krauñcadvīpa called after him; Dundubhideśa. Br. II. 14. 23, 26; Vā. 33. 21, 23. Vi. II. 4. 48.

दुन्दुभि
Dundubhi(svana)  (III)--Mt. a hill of Krauñcadvīpa; also a region, a varṣa of the dvīpam. Br. II. 14. 26; 19. 69, 73; Vā. 49. 63, 68; Vi. II. 4. 51.

दुन्दुभि
Dundubhi  (IV)--Mt. one of the seven hills of Plakṣadvīpa where Dundubhi and the Asura Candramṛtyu were beaten by the Devas. Br. II. 18. 75; 19. 10; Vi. II. 4. 7; Vā. 47. 72; 49. 9; 96. 145; M. 122. 13.

दुन्दुभि
Dundubhi  (V)--one of the Danu's sons; a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 4; Vā. 68. 4.

दुन्दुभि
Dundubhi  (VI)--a son of Maya and Rambhā. Br. III. 6. 29; Vā. 68. 28. 

दुन्दुभि
Dundubhi  (VII)--a musical instrument whose sound causes death; used in the Tārakāmaya. M. 177. 26.

दुन्दुभि
Dundubhi  (VIII)--Mt. in Śākadvīpa; here the Devas once beat the drum, the sound of which caused death to Dundubhi and from thence took this name. M. 122. 13-14.

दुन्दुभि
Dundubhi  (IX)--a son of Sutāra, the Lord of the sacred Dvāpara. Vā. 23. 121.

दुन्दुभि
Dundubhi  (X)--(Sata Dundubhi?) a son of Jambha. Vā. 67. 78.

दुन्दुमार
Dundumāra --a name of Kuvalayāśva, (s.v.). Vi. IV. 2. 40.

दुरतिक्रम
Duratikrama --a son of Suhotri, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 127.

दुरितक्षय
Duritakṣaya --a son of Mahāvīrya and father of Trayyāruṇi and others; attained Brahmaṇagati; see Durukṣaya. Bhā. IX. 21. 19-20.

दुरुक्ति
Durukti --born of Krodha and Himsā; sister and also wife of Kali. Bhā. IV. 8. 3-4.

दुरुक्षय
Durukṣaya --see Duritakṣaya. According to Matsya Purāṇa the name is Urukṣaya. Vi. IV. 19. 24. 

दुर्गति
Durgati --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 86.

दुर्गमा
Durgamā --a R. from the Vindhyas. M. 114. 28.

दुर्ग
Durgas --fortified places unknown under Pṛthu; six kinds of: Giridurga is the best; described. 1) M. 10. 32; 217. 6-87; V. I. 6. 18. also four kinds of; three natural and one artificial; contain different outways; Kumāripuram, villages, towns surrounded by a moat, also mountains and rivers; 2) Vā. 8. 98, 108 ff. desert, mountain and water; man left the tree home for this; last was artificial; made by man with ramparts, moats and Kumāripuram; 3) Br. II. 7. 92, 101 ff. of the southern country. 4) Vā. 45. 128.

दुर्गा
Durgā  (I)--one of the names of Yogamāya propitiated by Devakī and others for Kṛṣṇa's safe return from the cave of Jāmbavān; 1) Bhā. X. 2. 11; 56. 35. worship of; 2) Ib. XI. 27. 29. a Śakti; 3) Br. III. 32. 24, 48 and 59; IV. 19. 81; 39. 57.; 44. 76. worshipped in the grahabali: Icon of. 4) M. 93. 16; 260. 55-66.

दुर्गा
Durgā  (II)--a R. originating from the Vindhya Mountains. Br. II. 16. 33; Vā. 45. 103.

दुर्गाख्य
Durgākhya --a commander of Bhaṇḍa; a son of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 83; 26. 49.

दुर्गाध्यक्ष
Durgādhyakṣa --the superintendent of fortresses; his qualifications. M. 215. 39. 

दुर्गाल
Durgāla (c) --a territory to the west of the Vindhya Mountains. Br. II. 16. 60.

दुर्जय
Durjaya --a son of Dana. Bhā. VI. 6. 31.

दुर्जय
Durja(e)ya --a son of Ananta (Ānarta-M. P.); a soldier of great fortune. Br. III. 69. 54; M. 43. 49; Vā. 94. 53.

दुर्दम
Durdama  (I)--(Durmada): a son of Vasudeva and Rohiṇi and father of Abhibhūta. Br. III. 71. 165, 171; M. 46. 12; Vā. 96. 163; Vi. IV. 15-22.

दुर्दम
Durdama  (II)--the son of Dhṛta and father of Pracetas. Br. III. 74. 11. Vā. 99. 11.

दुर्दम
Durdama  (III)--a king and a son of Rudraśreṇi. M. 43. 11.

दुर्दम
Durdama  (IV)--a son of Suhotrī, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 127.

दुर्दम
Durdama  (V)--the surviving son of Bhadraśreṇi out of his hundred sons, who were put to sword by Divodāsa. Vā. 92. 63.

दुर्दम
Durdama  (VI)--the son of Bhadraśreṇya and father of Dhanaka. Vi. IV. 11. 10.

दुर्दम
Durdama  (VII)--a son of Ghṛta and father of Pracetas. Vi. IV. 17. 4. 

दुर्दमन
Durdamana --the son of Śatānīka and father of Vahīnara. Bhā. IX. 22. 43.

दुर्दिह
Durdiha --a Deva. Br. II. 13. 95.

दुर्दुर
Durdura --a Mountain in Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 20.

दुर्भगा
Durbhagā  (I)--a name of the daughter of Kāla (time); enjoyed Pūru and blessed him with a boon; offered herself to Bṛhadratha and on his refusal cursed him to be ever wandering. She then approached Bhaya, the Yavana Lord who adopted her as his sister; helped the Yavanas in overcoming the city of Purañjana; 1) Bhā. IV. 27. 19-30; 28. 1, 3 and 10. allegorically “old age”; 2) Ib. 29. 22. a Śakti. 3) Br. IV. 44. 75.

दुर्भगा
Durbhagā  (II)--a Mind-born mother. M. 179. 14.

दुर्मद
Durmada  (I)--a companion of Purañjana, allegorically upastha. Bhā. IV. 25. 52; 29. 14.

दुर्मद
Durmada  (II)--a son of Bhadrasenaka (or Bhadrasena) and father of Dhanaka. (Kanaka-Br. P.). Bhā. IX. 23. 23; Br. III. 67. 66; 69. 7.

दुर्मद
Durmada  (III)--(see Durdama) a son of Rohiṇī and Vasudeva. Bhā. IX. 24. 46-47.

दुर्मद
Durmada  (IV)--a son of Vasudeva and Pauravī. Bhā. IX. 24. 47. 

दुर्मद
Durmada  (V)--an Asura commander of ten akṣauhiṇis was sent against Lalitā accompanied by noisy paṭaha; rode on the camel, succeeded in taking a jewel from the crown of Sampatkarī-Sarasvati, who being enraged struck him at the breast; he fell dead and his followers were massacred. The rest fled to the Sūnyaka city in fear. Br. IV. 22. 19, 28, 47.

दुर्मद
Durmada  (VI)--a name of Vighneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 68.

दुर्मद
Durmada  (VII)--a son of Bhadraśreṇi; (see Durdama). Vā. 94. 7.

दुर्मद
Durmada  (VIII)--of the Rohiṇi family; see also Durdama; a son of Rohiṇi and Ānakadundubhi. Vā. 96. 169; Vi. 15. 19.

दुर्मन
Durmana --the son of Dhṛta and father of Pracetas. Bhā. IX. 23. 15.

दुर्मर्ष
Durmarṣa --fought with Kāmadeva in the Devāsura war. Bhā. VIII. 10. 33.

दुर्मर्षण
Durmarṣaṇa --a son of Śṛñjaya and Rāṣṭrapāli. Bhā. IX. 24. 42.

दुर्मित्र
Durmitra --the son of Puṣpamiṣṭa. Bhā. XII. 1. 34.

दुर्मुख
Durmukha  (I)--a Rākṣasa killed in the Laṅkā war. Bhā. IX. 10. 18. 

दुर्मुख
Durmukha  (II)--a Kādraveya Nāga. Br. III. 7. 35; M. 6. 41; Vā. 69. 71.

दुर्मुख
Durmukha  (III)--a son of Khaśa and a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 136; Vā. 69. 167.

दुर्मुख
Durmukha  (IV)--a Vighnanāyaka. Br. IV. 27. 81.

दुर्मुख
Durmukha  (V)--a son of Suhotrī, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 127.

दुर्योधन
Duryodhana --the eldest of the hundred sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra and Gāndhāri; 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 26; X. 64. [4]; M. 50. 48; Vā. 99. 243; Vi. IV. 20. 39. Subhadrā was intended by Rāma to be given in marriage to him; 2) Bhā. X. 86. 3. was met by Kṛtavarman and taken leave of; 3) Ib. X. 52. (56. V. 12). went from Balabhadra and learnt gadā from Balarāma at Mithilā; 4) Ib. X. 57. 26; Br. III. 71. 84; Vā. 96. 83. mistook the colour of the flooring of the Pāṇḍava's sabhā (built by Maya) for a sheet of water and had a nasty fall at which Bhīma and the ladies laughed. This enraged Duryodhana who was conciliated by Yudhiṣṭhira who sent clothes to him through Kṛṣṇa. He did not accept them, but went home downcast; 5) Bhā. X. 58. 27; 75. 34-39. kept under influence Vinda and Anuvinda of Avanti; 6) Ib. X. 58. 30. banished the Pāṇḍavas and Draupadī to the forest for defeat in the game of dice; 7) Ib. X. 64. [4]. resented Sāmba's action in taking away his daughter Lakṣmaṇā in svayamvara and wanted to punish him; heard of Rāma's arrival and extended welcome to him; afraid of Rāma's prowess agreed to the marriage of his daughter to Sāmba and gave a rich dowry; 8) Ib. X. 68. (whole); Vi. V. 35. 4-5, 11. did not feel happy over the success of the Rājasūya, where he was in charge of the treasury; 9) Bhā. X. 74. 53; 75. 2 and 4. failed to hit the fish mark in Lakṣmaṇā's svayamvara; 10) Ib. X. 83. 23. Jealous of Kṛṣṇa and Draupadī, his mind set on the latter; 11) Ib. X. 75. 31-32. ordered Vidura's banishment for offering good counsel, and insulted him as the son of a dāsi; 12) Ib. I. 7. 14; III. 1. 14-15. met the Pāṇḍavas in war at Kurukṣetra; arranged in vyūha at Syamanta pañcaka; fought with Bhīmasena who killed him with his gada; lay in the battlefield with his thigh fractured, along with eleven Akṣauhiṇis. 13) Ib. X. 78 (16 (V) 15, 18-19), 39; 79. 23; 80 [1]; III. 3. 13; M. 103. 3-5. Built a house of lac to get the Pāṇḍavas consumed by flames. 14) Vi. IV. 13. 70.

दुर्वसु
Durvasu --a son of Devayāni; cursed by his father for refusing to part with his youth. 1) Vi. IV. 10. 6, 13. Viceroy of south-east kingdom; 2) Ib. IV. 10. 31. line of; father of Vanhi; got merged into Puru's line ultimately. 3) Ib. IV. 16. 2-6.

दुर्वार्क्षी
Durvārkṣī --(Dūrvākṣī-Br. P.) the queen of Vṛka. Bhā. IX. 24. 43.

दुर्वास
Durvāsa  (I)--a son of Atri and an younger brother of Dattātreya; 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 15; Br. III. 8. 82; Vā. 70. 76. an amśa of Śiva; 2) Bhā. IV. 1. 33. appeared before Ambarīṣa who was about to break his dvādasi fast; agreed to accept his hospitality, went to the river for bath and tarried there; finding the muhūrta for pāraṇa (break-fast) drawing to a close, the king broke his fast with some water. Coming to know of this on his return, the sage produced a flaming spirit to attack him. But Hari's cakra burnt it down and turned towards the sage, who ran for succour to Brahmā, Śiva and Viṣṇu. All of them were unable to help; but Hari advised him to meet Ambarīṣa and apologise to him. 3) Ib. IX. 4. 35-71. This he did and was set at liberty. After partaking the meals with him, he returned to Brahmaloka; 4) Ib. IX. 5. 1-22. blessed Pṛtha with secret mantras to summon gods. 5) Ib. IX. 24. 32; XI. 1. 12. Through him Duryodhana planned to destroy the Pāṇḍavas by inciting him to go to them and ask for a feast. But Kṛṣṇa protected them on the occasion. 6) Ib. I. 15. 11. In the course of his sojourn he met a Vidyā dhara maid with a garland given to her by the Devī; took it from her and presented it to Indra who put it on his elephant, who in turn threw it on the ground and trampled upon it. Enraged at this, the sage cursed him to be lost to all fortune. 7) Ib. VIII. 5. 16; Br. IV. 5. 16-20; 9. 31; 40. 120.

दुर्वास
Durvāsa  (II)--a Siddha. Bhā. VI. 15. 13.

दुर्वास
Durvāsa  (III)--one of the Sages who left for Piṇḍāraka. Bhā. XI. 1. 12.

दुर्विनीत
Durvinīta --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 87.

दुला
Dulā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 32. 29.

दुल्लोल
Dullola --a son of Saramā: had four sons. Br. III. 7. 441.

दुश्शठ
Duśśaṭha --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 87.

दुश्शला
Duśśalā --a daughter of Dhṛtarāṣṭra. Bhā. IX. 22. 26.

दुश्शासन
Duśśāsana --a son of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, gave evil advice to Duryodhana. Bhā. III. 3. 13; Vi. IV. 20. 39; V. 35. 27. 

दुष्कन्त
Duṣkanta --of the Paurava line, adopted as son by Marutta; father of Sarūpya. Br. III. 74. 3-5.

दुष्टशेखर
Duṣṭaśekhara --an Asura; created by Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 10. 81.

दुष्पूर
Duṣpūra  (Pūraṇa); one of the 16 classes of Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 377.

दुष्यन्त
Duṣyanta  (I)--a son of Raibhya and Upadānavī; a king; while out for hunting came to Kaṇva's hermitage, saw the beautiful Śakuntalā, married her by the gāndharvavidhi and left for his capital the next day. A son Bharata was born to Śakuntalā and he was brought up by Kaṇva. Śakuntalā came to his palace with the boy but Duṣyanta had forgotten her. A voice from the air asked him to accept them, his wife and son, which he did; 1) Bhā. I. 12. 20; IX. 20. 7-22 [1-2]; M. 49. 10-11; Br. III. 6. 25; Vā. 68. 24; 99. 133-6. removed from hell by the son. 2) Vi. IV. 19. 9-10.

दुष्यन्त
Duṣyanta  (II)--of Puru's line, was adopted by Marut(t)a as his son; returned to the line of Yadu, the eldest son of Yayāti; 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 17-18; Vā. 99. 3; Vī. IV. 16. 5-6. through Yayāti's curse the Turvasu and the Paurava dynasties became commingled. 2) M. 48. 2-3.

दुःक
Duḥka --sorrow: born of Vedanā. Br. II. 9. 35.

दुःशील
Duḥśīla --killed Candragupta, a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 25. 99.

दूत
Dūta --a messenger: to report as he has been told and to be skilled in languages of different countries; one who can adjust according to time and place; 1) M. 215. 12-4; 254. 24. of Indra to Tāraka  to get him ready for war after the birth of Kārttikeya; 2) M. 38. 19; 159. 24. of Pauṇḍraka. 3) Vi. V. 34. 6.

दूती
Dūtī  (I)--an Akṣara devī. Br. IV. 19. 58; 37. 34.

दूती
Dūtī  (II)--a Mind-born mother. M. 179. 10.

दूर्व
Dūrva  (I)--a plant sacred to Hari; 1) Bhā. V. 3. 6. from this Dūrvañjanam, being an auspicious thing to be looked at in the morning. 2) Br. III. 28. 10.

दूर्व
Dūrva  (II)--a son of Nṛpañjaya: his son Timi. Bhā. IX. 22. 42.

दूषण
Dūṣaṇa  (I)--an Asura; was killed by Rāma. Bhā. IX. 10. 9.

दूषण
Dūṣaṇa  (II)--a son of Viśravas and Vākā. Br. III. 8. 56. Vā. 70. 50.

दूषणा
Dūṣaṇā --the queen of Bhauvana and mother of Tvaṣṭā. Bhā. V. 15. 15.

दृढध्युम्न
Dṛḍhadhyumna --an Āgastya; a Brahmiṣṭha. M. 145. 114.

दृढनेमि
Dṛḍhanemi --a son of Satyadhṛti and father of Supārśva (Sudharma-M. P.). Bhā. IX. 21. 27. M. 49. 70. Vi. IV. 19. 49. 

दृढभक्ति
Dṛḍhabhakti --a monkey chief. Br. III. 7. 239.

दृढरथ
Dṛḍharatha  (I)--a son of Senajit. M. 49. 50.

दृढरथ
Dṛḍharatha  (II)--a son of Navaratha; father of Śakuni. M. 44. 43.

दृढरथ
Dṛḍharatha  (III)--a son of Jayadratha. Vā. 99. 111.

दृढरुचि
Dṛḍharuci --a son of Hiraṇyaretas of Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 14.

दृढव्रत
Dṛḍhavrata --a son of Śikhaṇḍi, the avatār of the 18th Dvāpara. Vā. 23. 183.

दृढव्रतम्
Dṛḍhavratam --leads to Varuṇa loka. M. 101. 44.

दृढसेन
Dṛḍhasena  (I)--(future Bṛhadratha line) ruled for 58 years. Br. III. 74. 118.

दृढसेन
Dṛḍhasena  (II)--the son of Suśravas and father of Subala. Vi. IV. 23. 7-8.

दृढहनु
Dṛḍhahanu --a son of Senajit. Bhā. IX. 21. 23. Vi. IV. 19. 36.

दृढायु
Dṛḍhāyu  (I)--a Brahmiṣṭha. Br. II. 32. 119. 

दृढायु
Dṛḍhāyu  (II)--a son of Purūravas and Urvaśi. M. 24. 33.

दृढाच्युत
Dṛḍhācyuta --a Sage; a son of Agastya and father of Idhmavāha. Bhā. IV. 28. 32.

दृढास्य
Dṛḍhāsya --a son of Agastya adopted by Pulaha; hence Pulahas are Āgastyas. M. 202. 11.

दृढाश्व
Dṛḍhāśva  (I)--a son of Kuvalāśva. Br. III. 63. 62.

दृढाश्व
Dṛḍhāśva  (II)--a son of Kuvalayāśva (Dhundumāra) and father of Haryaśva; swallowed the fire from Dhundhu's mouth. Bhā. IX. 6. 23-24. M. 12. 32: Vā. 88. 61-2. Vi. IV. 2. 42-3.

दृढेषुधि
Dṛḍheṣudhi --a son of Tāmasa Manu. Br. II. 36. 49.

दृश्यामेघा
Dṛśyāmeghās --a group of nāḍis pouring out dew from fire (sun). Br. II. 24. 28.

दृषदश्व
Dṛṣadaśva --a son of Pṛthu. Br. III. 63. 27.

दृषद्वती
Dṛṣadvatī  (I)--a R. from the Himālayas in Bhāratavarṣa, Kṛṣṇa crossed her on his way from Dvārakā to Hastināpura; 1) Bhā. V. 19. 18; X. 71. 22; Br. II. 16. 26; III. 13. 69; Vā. 59. 128; 99. 259. on her banks is the Naimiṣāraṇya, 2) Vā. 1. 14. Adhisīma Kṛṣṇa performed a sacrifice for two years on her banks. 3) M. 22. 20; 50. 67; 114. 22. 

दृषद्वती
Dṛṣadvatī  (II)--a queen of Samhatāśva. Br. III. 63. 65; Vā. 88. 64.

दृषद्वती
Dṛṣadvatī  (III)--the wife of Haryaśvā, son of Vasumata. Br. III. 63. 75. Vā. 88. 76.

दृषद्वती
Dṛṣadvatī  (IV)--the wife of Viśvāmitra and mother of Aṣṭaka. Br. III. 66. 75. Vā. 91. 103.

दृषद्वती
Dṛṣadvatī  (V)--the queen of Divodāsa and mother of Pratardana. Br. III. 67. 67; Vā. 92. 64.

दृषद्वती
Dṛṣadvatī  (VI)--one of the five queens of Uśīnara and mother of Śibi. Br. III. 74. 18, 20; M. 48. 16, 18; Vā. 99. 19, 21.

दृष्टकेतु
Dṛṣṭaketu  (I)--a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 86.

दृष्टकेतु
Dṛṣṭaketu  (II)--the son of Sukumāra and father of Vītihotra. Vi. IV. 8. 20.

दृष्टधर्म
Dṛṣṭadharma --a son of Upamadga. Vi. IV. 14. 9.

दृष्टहास
Dṛṣṭahāsa --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 86.

