Devaśarma  (II)--a disciple of Rathitara (s.v.). Vā. 60. 66.

देवश्रव
Devaśrava  (I)--a son of Devamīḍha and Mārīṣā; husband of Kamsavatī and father of two sons. Bhā. IX. 24. 28, 41. Vi. IV. 14. 30.

देवश्रव
Devaśrava  (II)--a Kauśika and a Sage. Br. II. 32. 118.

देवश्रव
Devaśrava  (III)--a son of Śūra and Bhojā. Br. III. 71. 149; M. 46. 2.

देवश्रव
Devaśrava  (IV)--the son of Devarāta according to the learned. Vā. 96. 185; Br. III. 71. 188.

देवश्रवस्
Devaśravas --see Devarātas. M. 145. 113. 198. 7, 9.

देवश्रेष्ठ
Devaśreṣṭha --a son of Manu Rudrasāvarṇi (Ṛthusāvarṇa, Vā. P.). Bhā. VIII. 13. 27; Br. IV. 1. 94; Vā. 100. 98; Vi. III. 2. 36.

देवसर्ग
Devasarga --is Vaikṛta: different species: Gods, Pitṛs, Asuras, Gandharvas, Apsarasas, Siddhas, Yakṣas, Rākṣasas,  Caraṇas, Bhūtas, Preta-piśācas, Vidhyādharas, Kinnaras, etc. 1) Bhā. III. 10. 16, 26-8. The sixth sarga. 2) Vā. 6. 63.

देवसावर्णि
Devasāvarṇi --the thirteenth Manu; father of Citrasena, and others; Divaspati is Indra. Nirmoka and others were sages; Yogeśvara is Hari's manifestation. Bhā. VIII. 13. 30-32.

देवसूनव
Devasūnavas --a class of Pitṛs among whom four divisions are distinguished; the past, the future, the elder and the younger. Vā. 71. 15-16.

देवसेना
Devasenā --a daughter of Indra, married to Kumāra. Br. IV. 30. 105; M. 159. 8.

देवसेनापति
Devasenāpati --is Skanda; 1) Br. III. 10. 50; 73. 110. anointed by all the Devas and their gaṇas; 2) Vā. 39. 33; 72. 49. as Viṣṇu. 3) Vi. I. 8. 28.

देवस्थानम्
Devasthānam  (I)--heaven, etc. for varṇāśramis; eight places beginning with Brahmā and ending with Piśāca; here are aṇimā and seven other aiśvaryas; there are three guṇas pervading here--Satva, etc.; realised not by eyes, but by experience. Vā. 102. 96-8.

देवस्थानम्
Devasthānam  (II)--Paiśāca, Rākṣasa, Gāndharva, Kaubera, Aindra, Saumya, Prājāpatya, and Brāhma; a yogi must give up all these sthānas to attain the Brahmanhood. Vā. 12. 39-42; 61. 170; 102. 96-8.

देवस्थानि
Devasthāni --a Pravara of Angiras. M. 196. 15. 

देवस्नपनम्
Devasnapanam --bathing a deity; described. M. 267. 1-35.

देवहूः
Devahūḥ --the entrance on the north side of the city of Purañjana, 1) Bhā. IV. 25. 51; 29. 12. allegorically the left ear.

देवहूती
Devahūtī  (I)--a daughter of Svāyambhuva Manu, and sister of Priyavrata and Uttānapāda; wife of Kardama and mother of Kapila; 1) Bhā. II. 7. 3; III. 12. 27, 55-6; 21. 3; 22. 9; VIII. 1. 5. heard of Kardama's greatness from Nārada and fixed her mind on him; accepted by Kardama; seeing her playing with balls in her mansion Viśvāvasu fell down in a fit of stupour; married Kardama with gifts from her parents; devoted herself to her husband's service like Pārvatī to Śiva; enjoyed his company in an aerial car well furnished with new cloths and ornaments after her bath in the Sarasvatisaras, where she was attended by many maids; roamed in all lovely parks throughout the earth. After a hundred years of enjoyment Devahūtī gave birth to nine daughters at a time, when Kardama told her of his departure for yoga; Devahūtī requested means for protection of herself and the new-born ones; was told that Viṣṇu would be born in her womb and he would bring comfort to her. Soon she gave birth to Lord Kapila when Brahmā and other seers called on Kardama. After they left, Kardama got his daughters married, and after praising Kapila, and with his permission he went away for penance. Heard all relating to the Sāṅkhya śāstra from Kapila and spoke in praise of him. Following the path prescribed by Kapila she attained nirvāṇa. The place where she attained siddhi became known as Śiddhapada. 2) Ib. VIII. Chh. 22 to 24 (whole); 33. 1-31; IV. I. 1 and 10. From her, Hari manifested Himself for imparting dharma and jñāna. 3) Ib. VIII. 1. 5.

देवहूती
Devahūtī  (II)--the wife of Purūravas. Vā. 2. 16. 

देवहोत्र
Devahotra --the father of Yogeśvara. Bhā. VIII. 13. 32.

देवह्रद
Devahrada --in the Sālagrāma; here Nāgarāṭ takes the piṇḍa of the deserving and rejects that of the undeserving. Br. III. 13. 90.

देवाक्रीडनक
Devākrīḍanakas --playing grounds of the Devas--four; Caitraratha,^8 Nandana, Vaibhrāja and Saviturvana (garden of the Sun). Vā. 36. 10.

देवागार
Devāgāras --abodes of the Devas; meddling with, was punished by death. M. 227. 174.

देवातिथि
Devātithi  (I)--a son of Krodhana and father of Ṛṣya. Bhā. IX. 22. 11. Vi. IV. 20. 5.

देवातिथि
Devātithi  (II)--a son of Akrodhana. M. 50. 37; Vā. 99. 232.

देवानीक
Devānīka  (I)--a Mt. in Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 15.

देवानीक
Devānīka  (II)--a son of Kṣemadhanva and father of Anīha (Ahīnagu-Br. P., Ahīnaka-Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 12. 2; Br. III. 63. 203; M. 12. 53; Vā. 88. 203; Vi. IV. 4. 106. 

देवानीक
Devānīka  (III)--a son of (Dharma) Sāvarṇa Manu. Vā. 100. 84. Vi. III. 2. 32.

देवानुज
Devānuja --a son of Auttama Manu. Vā. 62. 34.

देवान्तक
Devāntaka --a son of Kālanemi. Br. III. 5. 39; Vā. 67. 80.

देवापि
Devāpi  (I)--a son of Pratīpa and brother of Śantanu; renounced the home and turned muni; requested by Śantanu to take up the throne; he spoke impeaching the Vedas. He took to yoga living in Kalāpagrāma. He was to establish the Lunar race in the Kṛta Yuga; Purohita of the Devas; 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 12-18; XII. 2. 37; Vā. 99. 234. unacceptable to the people as he suffered from leprosy. 2) M. 50. 39-41; 273. 56. A Rājaṛṣi and a gotrapravartaka of the Treta yuga 3) Vā. 32. 39. and a Paurava.

देवापि
Devāpi  (II)--a Paurava king who continues to live in Kali in Kalāpagrāma; Kṣatrapraṇetāra in the 24th Caturyuga. Originator of Kṣatriyas in the Kṛta. 1) Vā. 99. 437-8; Vi. IV. 24-118. A son of Pratīpa. Even as a child retired to forest. The famine in his brother Santanu's (s.v) kingdom was said to be due to his elder brother Devāpi having been passed over for succession. Infected with heretical views through the minister of Śantanu by means of ascetics in the forest; thus disqualified for the throne. 2) Vi. IV. 20. 9-30.

देवाभ्र
Devābhra --a Mt. with a Janapada on it; afraid of Hiraṇyakaśipu's prowess. M. 163. 88. 

देवाम्बुज
Devāmbuja --a son of Uttama Manu. Br. II. 36. 39.

देवारण्यम्
Devāraṇyam Viśokam --a great forest on the banks of the Lauhityā lake. Vā. 47. 11.

देवार्ह
Devārha --one of the ten sons of Hṛdīka. Father of Kambalabarhiṣa. M. 44. 82-3; Vā. 96. 139; Vi. IV. 14. 24.

देवावृत्
Devāvṛt --a Mt. of Krauñcadvīpa. M. 122. 82.

देवावृध
Devāvṛdha  (I)--a son of Sātvata and father of Babhru; equal to Gods; 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 6-10; Vi. IV. 13. 1-3. sonless he performed penance on the banks of the Parṇāśā (s.v.) which became transformed into a maid, married him and became mother of Babhru. 2) Br. III. 71. 16-15; M. 44. 47-59; Vā. 96. 6-15. The Vāyu Purāṇa says that when he made austerities, he touched the waters of the Savaṛṇā when Sāvitrī appeared as a lady, received his tejas and brought forth a good son in the ninth month. This was Babhru. 2) Br. III. 71. 16-15; M. 44. 47-59; Vā. 96. 6-15. Belonged to the Anu line and was much praised by poets and scholars. 6608 disciples of his, obtained immortality. 3) Vi. IV. 13. 6.

देवावृध
Devāvṛdha  (II)--a son of Kauśalya. Vā. 1. 145; 96. 1. 

देवालय
Devālayas --the homes of the nine planets; 1) Br. II. 23. 95; Vā. 52. 85. temples visited by Paraśurāma; 2) Br. III. 24. 41; 27. 11; IV. 38. 57; M. 96. 25; 257. 6. see also Devagṛhas.

देवालयकल्पन
Devālayakalpana --building of temples, an act of charity. Br. IV. 7. 33.

देवासुर
De(ai)vāsura Yuddha --consequent on the Asuras not obtaining Amṛta for all their labours in the Amṛtamathana, war broke out. It was on the seashore and mainly a handto-hand fight; description of; at last Indra invoked Hari, who appeared on the scene and on him Kālanemi flung his śūla; with the same weapon Hari flung him down; so also Mālyavan, Māli and Sumāli were put to death. Fight continued till Nārada stopped it. 1) Bhā. VIII. 10. (whole); 11. 1-44; Vā. 92. 76. Twelve in number, after which the whole earth and yajña came over to the Devas. 2) Br. III. 72. 70, 106. Hearing the Asuras slain by Hari, Diti went to the earth and performed Madanadvādaśi vratam to get able bodied sons to kill Indra; 3) M. 7. 2-7. one, of three hundred years between Indra and Prahlāda. Indra with the help of Raji, a son of Āyu vanquished him. 4) M. 24. 37-8; 70. 26-32. Asuras under Hrāda vanquished the Gods after the battle which continued for a hundred divine years. The gods withdrew to the north of the milky ocean and prayed to Viṣṇu for succour. The latter deluded the Asuras in Māyāmoha form and the Asuras were defeated. 5) Vi. III. 17. 9-44; 18. 34-36.

देवाश्रव
Devāśrava --the brother of Vasudeva. Vā. 96. 147. 

देविका
Devikā  (I)--a R. from the Himālayas; 1) Br. II. 16. 25; M. 22. 20; 114. 21; Vā. 45. 96; 109. 17; 112. 30. in the chariot of Tripurāri. 2) M. 133. 24.

देविका
Devikā  (II)--a sacred Tīrtha, where there is a well by name Vṛṣa; 1) Br. III. 13. 41; Vā. 77. 41. on her banks was Vīranagara. 2) Vi. II. 15. 6.

देविकातट
Devikātaṭa --a Tīrtham sacred to Nandinī. M. 13. 38.

देविकोटम्
Devikoṭam --sacred to Lalitā-pīṭham. Br. IV. 44. 96.

देवी
Devī  (I)--the first charioteer; a Śakti. Br. IV. 6. 17; 20. 91.

देवी
Devī  (II)--the image of. M. 258. 75; 266, 42.

देवी
Devī  (III)--an Apsaras. Vā. 69. 6.

देवीव्रतम्
Devīvratam --the observance of this vow leads to the world of Lakṣmī. M. 101. 59.

देवीसूक्तम्
Devīsūktam --utterance of, in dīkṣā. Br. IV. 43. 11.

देवेन्द्र
Devendra --see Indra. Br. III. 7. 269; IV. 12. 35; M. 146. 20; Vi. I. 8. 26; 9. 16, 139. 

देवेन्द्र
Devendras --Gods of prime importance, of secondary importance; share in sacrifices; they are Gurus, Lords, Kings and Forefathers; protect the subjects. Vā. 64. 21-23.

देवेशी
Deveśī --Lalitā. Br. IV. 14. 1.

देवोद्यानानि
Devodyānāni --Vaibhrāja, Surabhi, Caitraratha, Viśoka, Sumana and Nandana gardens. Br. III. 7. 101-2.

देव्यालय
Devyālaya --in Siddhikṣetra; here Īśvara performed austerities standing on one leg. Vā. 77. 81.

देशा
Deśās --regions different from Rāṣṭras and Janapadas. Br. III. 50. 6.

देशरक्षित
Deśarakṣita --a provincial or District Governor; acquainted with the produce of the Deśa and expert in controlling officials and keeping accounts. M. 215. 17.

देशिका
Deśikās --ordinary teachers. Br. IV. 8. 5.

देशिकेश्वर
Deśikeśvara --Guru. Br. IV. 43. 7.

देह
Deha  (I)--human body; as a temple; philosophical interpretation of. Br. IV. 43. 53-54 ff. 

देह
Deha  (II)--one of the twenty Amitābha gaṇas. Vā. 100. 17.

देहसिद्धि
Dehasiddhi --a Yogasiddhi. Br. IV. 36. 53.

देही
Dehī --an Amitābha God. Br. IV. 1. 17.

दैत्यराक्षस
Daityarākṣasas --are Kāpileyas. Vā. 69. 177.

दैत्य
Daityas --the Asuras from Diti; 1) Vā. 66. 1. one of the Marut gaṇas. 2) Vā. 46. 35; 67. 129.

दैवज्ञ
Daivajñas --astrologers, residences of. M. 254. 26.

दोष
Doṣa --a Vasu; husband of Śarvarī and father of Śimśumāra; a kalā of Viṣṇu. Bhā. VI. 6. 11-14.

दोषा
Doṣā --a queen of Puṣpārṇa and mother of Pradoṣa, Niśitha and Vyuṣṭha. Bhā. IV. 13. 13-14.

दौर्गमन्त्रा
Daurgamantrā --in honour of Durgā. Br. IV. 38. 5.

दौवारिक
Dauvārika --to be worshipped in house-building. M. 253. 26. 

दौवारिक
Dauvārikas --palace officials. M. 215. 30.

दौष्यन्ति
Dauṣyanti --is Bharata (s.v.) noted for his sacrifices and love of people; Parīkṣit compared to him. Bhā. I. 12. 20.

द्युतय
Dyutaya --a Sudharmāṇa God. Br. IV. 1. 61.

द्युति
Dyuti  (I)--a Yāma deva. Br. II. 13. 92; Vā. 31. 6; 62. 61.

द्युति
Dyuti  (II)--(Vasiṣṭha): a Sage of the 4th Sāvarṇa epoch; 1) Br. IV. 1. 91. of the 12th epoch of Manu. 2) Vi. III. 2. 35.

द्युति
Dyuti  (III)--one of the 20 Sutapa gaṇas. Vā. 100. 14.

द्युतिमत्
Dyutimat  (I)--a Sage of the ninth Manvantara. Bhā. VIII. 13. 19; Vi. III. 2. 23.

द्युतिमत्
Dyutimat  (II)--a Yakṣa; a son of Puṇyajanī and Maṇibhadra. Br. III. 7. 125; Vā. 69. 156.

द्युतिमत्
Dyutimat  (III)--a Mt. in Kuśadvīpa; same as Balāhaka. M. 122. 55; Vi. II. 4. 41.

द्युतिमत्
Dyutimat  (IV)--a son of Prāṇa and father of Rājavan. Vi. I. 10. 5. 

द्युतिमत्
Dyutimat  (V)--a son of Priyavrata; became king of Krauñcadvīpa. Vi. II. 1. 7, 14.

द्युतिमन्त
Dyutimanta --a son of Dyutimān. Vā. 28. 7.

द्युतिमान्
Dyutimān  (I)--a son of Prāṇa (Pāṇḍu-Vā. P.) and Puṇḍarīkā; father of two sons. Br. II. 11. 40; Vā. 28. 7, 35.

द्युतिमान्
Dyutimān  (II)--one of the ten sons of Kardama and king of Krauñcadvīpa which he divided among his seven sons Kuśala, Manomaya, Uṣṇa, Pāvana, Andhakāra, Muni, and Dundubhi; ruled kingdoms after their names. Br. II. 14. 9, 13, 22-23; Vā. 33. 9.

द्युतिमान्
Dyutimān  (III)--Mt. a hill of Kuśadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 55; Vā. 49. 50.

द्युतिमान्
Dyutimān  (IV)--a God of the Ābhūtaraya group. Br. II. 36. 56.

द्युतिमान्
Dyutimān  (V)--(Angiras); a Sage of the Rohita epoch. Br. IV. 1. 63.

द्युतिमान्
Dyutimān  (VI)--a God of the Sutārā group (Supāra: Vā. P.). Br. IV. 1. 89; Vā. 100. 94.

द्युतिमान्
Dyutimān  (VII)--a son of Svāyambhuva Manu. M. 9. 5; Vā. 31. 18. Br. II. 13. 104.

द्युतिमान्
Dyutimān  (VIII)--Mt. a hill in Yamadvīpa. Vā. 48. 19. 

द्युती
Dyutī --left her consort Vibhāvasu and loved Soma with eight other Devis. M. 23. 24.

द्युमत्
Dyumat  (I)--one of the seven sons of Vasiṣṭha; 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 41. a friend who accompanied Purañjana when he went to Vibhrājita. 2) Ib. IV. 25. 47.

द्युमत्
Dyumat  (II)--a son of Svārociṣa Manu. Bhā. VIII. 1. 19.

द्युमत्
Dyumat  (III)--a son of Divodāsa and father of Alarka and others; (also known as Pratardana, Śatrujit, Vatsa, Ṛtadhvaja, and Kuvalayāśva). Bhā. IX. 17. 6.

द्युमत्
Dyumat  (IV)--the minister of Śālva, hit Pradyumna with his gada, but killed by the latter. Bhā. X. 76. 26. 27; 77. 1-3.

द्युमत्सेन
Dyumatsena  (I)--Dṛḍhasena-Br. P.) the son of Śama, and father of Sumati. Bhā. IX. 22. 48.

द्युमत्सेन
Dyumatsena  (II)--father of Satyavān; losing his eyesight and consequently his kingdom, took to forest life; got back his sight due to the grace of the God of death at the request of Sāvitrī. M. 208. 14-16; 214. 10.

द्युमत्सेन
Dyumatsena  (III)--a son of Trinetra; ruled for fortyeight years. M. 271. 27. 

द्युम्न
Dyumna  (I)--a son of Cākṣusa Manu. Bhā. IV. 13. 16.

द्युम्न
Dyumna  (II)--one of the ten branches of the Sukarmāna group of Devas. Br. IV. 1. 88; Vā. 100. 92.

द्युम्नि
Dyumni --son of Asanga. M. 45. 23.

द्यूतम्
Dyūtam --gambling; an adharma and of Kali; 1) Bhā. I. 17. 38; of Baladeva and Rukmin. 2) Vi. V. 28. 12.

द्योतन
Dyotana --one of the twenty Sutapa Gods. Br. IV. 1. 15; Vā. 100. 15.

द्यौ
Dyau --sky; presented flowers to Pṛthu on his accession. Bhā. IV. 15. 18.

द्रघण
Draghaṇa --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 85.

द्रवकेतु
Dravaketu --a Sudharmāṇa god. Br. IV. 1. 60.

द्रविड
Draviḍa  (I)--the kingdom of Malayadhvaja Pāṇḍya; the country in which there is Venkaṭa; 1) Bhā. IV. 28. 30; VIII. 4. 7; X. 79. 13. praise of Hari prevalent here in Kali; 2) Ib. XI. 5. 39. conquered by Kalki. 3) Br. III. 35. 10; 73. 107. 

द्रविड
Draviḍa  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Jāmbavatī. Bhā. X. 61. 12.

द्रविड
Draviḍas --people of Dravida; S. India; see Dakṣiṇātyās; 1) Br. II. 31. 82; Vā. 58. 82; 98. 107. ineligible for śrāddha; 2) M. 16. 16. country of. 3) Ib. 144. 56.

द्रविडा
Draviḍā --a daughter of Tṛṇabindu and mother of Viśravas. Vā. 86. 16.

द्रविडेश्वर
Draviḍeśvara --see Satyavrata. Bhā. VIII. 24. 13; IX. 1. 2.

द्रविण
Draviṇa  (I)--a son of Pṛthu and Arcis; was entrusted with the northern kingdom by his elder brother. Bhā. IV. 22. 54; 24. 2.

द्रविण
Draviṇa  (II)--Mt. a hill of Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 15.

द्रविण
Draviṇa  (III)--a Tuṣita God. Br. II. 36. 10.

द्रविण
Draviṇa  (IV)--a son of Dhara, a Vasava. Br. III. 3. 22; M. 5. 23; 203. 4; Vā. 66. 21.

द्रविण
Draviṇa  (V)--a son of Dharma. Vi. I. 15. 113. 

द्रविण
Draviṇas --a class of people in Krauñcadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 22.

द्रविणक
Draviṇaka --a son of Vasordhārā and Agni; a Vasu. Bhā. VI. 6. 13.

द्राविण
Drāviṇa --Mt. in the west that entered the sea for fear of Indra. M. 121. 75.

द्राविणी
Drāviṇī --a Varṇa Śakti; 1) Br. IV. 44. 58; on the third parva of the Geyacakraratha. 2) Ib. 19. 65.

द्राविणीका
Drāviṇīkā --a mudrā; here are Aṣṭa Śaktis commencing with Kusuma praying to Lalitā. Br. IV. 36. 73.

द्रुति
Druti --the wife of Nakta and mother of Gaya. Bhā. V. 15. 6.

द्रुपद
Drupada --a son of Pṛṣata and father of Draupadī, Dhṛṣṭadyumna and others; king of the Pāñcālas; 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 2; X. 52. 11 [8]. Vā. 99. 210; Vi. IV. 19. 73. stationed by Jarāsandha at the northern gate of Mathurā; 2) Bhā. X. 50. 11 [7]. stationed at the southern gate during the siege of Gomanta; 3) Ib. X. 52. 11 [8]. had been bound by the young Pāṇḍavas; 4) Ib. X. [56 (V) 2]. in the svayamvara he held, Arjuna hit the mark in the form of a fish and won Draupadī; 5) Ib. I. 15. 7. joined the Pāṇḍavas in the Kurukṣetra battle; 6) Ib. X. 78 [(95 V) 10]. went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse. 7) Ib. X. 82. 25. 

द्रुम
Druma --the king of the Kimpuruṣas and Kinnaras (s.v.) stationed on the west during the siege of Gomanta; 1) Bhā. X. 52. 11 [11]. Vā. 41. 30. stationed by Jarāsandha at the western gate of Mathurā; 2) Ib. X. 50 11 [5]. attended the conference at Kuṇḍīna summoned by Śālva. 3) Ib. X. 76. 2 [9-10].

द्रुमिल
Drumila --a Gandharva and a son of Ṛṣabha and a sage who was a Bhāgavata; in the guise of Ugrasena became the father of Kamsa; 1) Bhā. V. 4. 11; XI. 2. 21; X. 36. 24 [10-26]. discoursed to Nimi on the avatārs of Hari with different purposes. 2) Ib. XI. 4. (whole).

द्रुह्य
Druhyas --a tribe. M. 114. 41.

द्रुह्यु
Druhyu --a son of Yayāti and Sarmiṣṭhā and father of Babhru and Satu; 1) Bhā. IX. 18, 33 and 41; 23. 14; Br. I. 1. 133; Vā. 1. 156; 93. 17; 99. 7; Vi. IV. 17. 1. after being refused by Yadu and Turvasu approached by Yayāti; he also declined to part with his youth to his father and was therefore cursed to have no pleasures in life and to be wandering about the countries and oceans with no settled kingdom; 2) M. 24. 54; 32. 10; 23. 16-20; Vā. 45. 50; Vi. IV. 10. 6, 13. became over-lord of the south-eastern (west Br. P., Vā. P. and Vi. P.) part of the kingdom; 3) M. 34. 30; Vā. 45. 90; Vi. 10. 31. from him begins the Bhoja line. 4) M. 48. 6.

द्रोण
Droṇa  (I)--married Kṛpī, and was the father of Aśvatthāma. 1) Bhā. I. 7. 27; IX. 21. 36. Vi. IV. 19. 68; V. 35. 5, 27. Taught Dhanurveda to the Pāṇḍavas but served Duryodhana's army, succeeding Bhīṣma as commander, and after a five days' battle was killed by Dhṛṣṭadyumna; 2) Bhā. I. 15. 15-16; X. 78 [(95 (V) 16], 29-36. met by Kṛtavarman, Kṛṣṇa and Rāma. 3) Ib. X. 52. [56 (V) 4], 12; 57. 2. Informed by Uddhava of Rāma's visit to Hastināpura; invited for the  Rājasuya of Yudhiṣṭhira. 4) Ib. X. 68. 17 and 28; 74. 10. Went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse and met there Kṛṣṇa and the Vṛṣṇis. 5) Ib. X. 82. 24; 84. 57, 69 [1]. Ācārya of the Pāṇḍavas and the Kurus. 6) M. 103. 5. Baladeva's respect for. 7) Vi. V. 35. 36; 38. 16, 47, 64.

द्रोण
Droṇa  (II)--Mt. in Bhāratavarṣa, touching the sea; 1) Bhā. V. 19. 16; Br. II. 18. 76. entered the waters for fear of Indra. 2) M. 121. 73.

द्रोण
Droṇa  (III)--a Vasu born as Nanda; his wife was Abhimatī, and sons were Harṣa, Śoka, Bhaya and others. Bhā. VI. 6. 11; X. 8. 48-50.

द्रोण
Droṇa  (IV)--Mt. a hill of Śālmalidvīpa (KuśadvīpaM. P.) noted for great medicinal plants, viśalyakaraṇī and mṛtasanjīvini, capable of bringing back the dead to life. Br. II. 19. 38-39; Vā. 49. 35; Vi. II. 4. 26; M. 122. 56.

द्रोण
Droṇa  (V)--one of the seven Pralaya clouds. M. 2. 8.

द्रोण
Droṇa  (VI)--a measure of grain. M. 83. 12; 84. 2.

द्रोणि
Droṇi  (I)--(also Drauṇi) the future Veda Vyāsa in Dvāpara yuga. Br. II. 35. 125; Vi. III. 3. 21; Vā. 61. 104. 

द्रोणि
Droṇi  (II)--a Sage of the 8th epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 17.

द्रौणायन
Drauṇāyana --an Ārṣeya pravara of Bhārgavas. M. 195. 41.

द्रौणि
Drauṇi --see Droṇi. Br. IV. 1. 12.

द्रौपदी
Draupadī --the daughter of Yajñasena-Draupada, queen of the Pāṇḍavas and mother of five sons born to five brothers: Prativindhya to Yudhiṣṭhira, Śrutasena to Bhīma, Śrutakīrti to Arjuna, Śrutānīka to Nakula and Śrutakarma to Sahadeva; 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 2, 28; M. 50. 51; Vā. 99. 246; Vi. IV. 20. 41-2; paid respects to Kṛṣṇa; being newly married was bashful; 2) Bhā. X. 58. 5. consoled by Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā when banished to forest with her husbands; 3) Ib. X. 64. 10. joy at Kṛṣṇa's visit to Indraprastha; welcomed Rukmiṇī and the other wives of Kṛṣṇa; served food, etc., in the Rājasūya; performed Avabhṛta with Yudhiṣṭhira after the Rājasūya; Duryodhana's mind on; laughed at Duryodhana's fall in the Sabhā of Maya; 4) Ib. X. 71. 41-3; 75 (whole). asked Kṛṣṇa's wives about their marriage when all met at Syamantapañcaka and was lost in wonder. 5) Ib. X. 83. 6-7; 84. 1; Her sons were killed while asleep by Aśvatthāma; when the murderer was brought before her, she ordered his release as he was a Brahmana and the son of the preceptor; followed the funeral party to the Ganges for the cremation of her dead sons; 6) Ib. I. 7. 14 to the end; 8. 1 and 3, 17; 10. 9; was one among the party that welcomed Vidura; 7) Ib. I. 13. 4. out of devotion to Vāsudeva attained His lotus feet. 8) Ib. I. 15. 50. Felt sorry for the loss of Duryodhana and others. 9) M. 103. 12; 112. 1; 244. 4.

द्वयम्
Dvayam --name and form; a vain Arthavāda. Bhā. XI. 28. 37. 

द्वादशमूर्ति
Dvādaśamūrti --an epithet of the Sun god. Br. III. 59. 76; IV. 34. 75.

द्वादशाक्षर
Dvādaśākṣara --Those who medidate on the 12 letters are not re-born. Vi. I. 6. 40; 12. 97.

द्वादशि
Dvādaśi Vijaya --the day of the birth of Vāmana--Hari. Bhā. VIII. 18. 6.

द्वादशिव्रतम्
Dvādaśivratam --Ambarīṣa observed this vow for a year and ended it in the month of Kṛttika by bathing in the Yamunā. Bhā. IX. 4. 29-30.

द्वापर
Dvāpara(yuga) --Its nature; worship of Hari by service; 1) Bhā. XII. 2. 39; 3. 22-52. form of Hari as worshipped in; 2) Ib. XI. 5. 27-31. Parāśara taught Bhāgavata to his son in this yuga; 3) Ib. 1. 4. 14; II. 1. 8. a Vaiśya among the yugas; a period of wars. 4) Vā. 78. 36-7. Here Vyasa incarnates; duration of; 5) M. 53. 9; 142. 17, 23 and 26; 144. 1-5; Vā. 3. 21; 32. 61. Yajña the chief thing besides war; a combination of rajas and tamas; 6) Br. II. 7. 21; Vā. 8. 66. in the second Dvāpara Dhanvantari took birth as a man; 7) Ib. 92. 17. Dharma's state of anxiety; Śmṛti and Śruti quoted as authorities; but different opinions advanced. Rise of the Śākhas, and the Angas. 8) Ib. 58. 3-29.

द्वारका
Dvārakā --(also Dvāravatī and Kuśasthalī). Capital of Kṛṣṇa, built for him by Revata in the midst of sea 1(1/2) miles in circumference according to Vāstu rules and well furnished, for fear from Kālayavana; 1) Bhā. I. 8. 10-27; 11. 25; 12. 36; 13. 16; 14. 1-6; X. 50. 49-57; IX. 3. 28; Br. III. 71. 62-85; M. 4. 18; 246. 89; Vi. IV. 1. 91; 13. 19; V. 23. 13-15. sacred to Hari. 2) Bhā. VII. 14. 31. Kṛṣṇa released Nṛga in; 3) Ib. X. 37. 17-20. Kṛṣṇa carried the spoils of war with the Yavanas to that place; 4) Ib. X. 52. 5; return of Kṛṣṇa and Rāma to, after being besieged by Jarāsandha at Gomanta. 5) Ib. X. 52. 13-14 [1]; [56 (V) 7]. Left by Akrūra, when the city had no rains; hence Kṛṣṇa sent for him; 6) Ib. X. 57. 29-34. Kṛṣṇa and  Sātyakī returned from Hastināpura to; 7) Ib. X. 58. 28. here were sent 16000 maidens of Naraka's harem and 64 elephants of the Airāvata line; 8) Ib. X. 59. 36-7. reached by Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā after the fight for the pārijātā; 9) Ib. X. [67 (V) 38-40]. arrival of Aniruddha's marriage party from Bhojakaṭa; 10) Ib. X. 61. 40. visited by Citralekhā; 11) Ib. X. 62. 22. 64 [11]; Vi. V. 32. 28-30. besieged by Pauṇḍraka; 12) Bhā. X. 66. [1 and 13]. described when visited by Nārada, as containing 900,000 houses; 13) Ib. X. 69. 3-7; Śamba and others reached Dvārakā after Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya. 14) Ib. X. 75. 29. Blockaded by Śālva, and defended by Pradyumna and others; 15) Ib. X. 76. 8-14. reached by Kṛṣṇa after the Kurukṣetra war; city described; 16) Ib. X. 80. [8-12]; 82. 1. reached by Kṛṣṇa and his party after a long stay at Syamantapañcaka; 17) Ib. X. 84. 70. Kṛṣṇa performed the aśvamedha here; 18) Ib. X. 89. 22. [1]; 90. 1. visited by sages from Piṇḍāraka, Kurukṣetra and other places and filled with Brahmaghoṣa; 19) Ib. X. 28. 1-13. Nārada lived there for a time to worship Kṛṣṇa; 20) Ib. XI. 2. 1. visited by Brahmā and other gods to invite Kṛṣṇa to go back to Vaikuṇṭha; 21) Ib. XI. 6. 1-4. evil omens in the city; people, advised by Kṛṣṇa, left for Prabhāsā. 22) Ib. XI. 6. 33-35; 30. 1, 5, 10. Dāruka informs Vasudeva and others of Kṛṣṇa's condition and Rāma's entry to his Dhāma; 23) Ib. XI. 31. 15-17. swallowed up by the sea excepting Kṛṣṇa's mansion; 24) Ib. XI. 7. 3; 31. 23; XII. 12. 60; Vi. V. 37. 36; 30. 9-10. a Pitṛ Tīrtham; 25) M. 22. 38. represents the neck of the Vedas. 26) Vā. 96. 60; 104. 76. Pārijāta of heaven taken to. 27) Vi. V. 31. 10-11.

द्वारकानाथ
Dvārakānātha --Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 31.

द्वारपाल
Dvārapāla --a description of, on the gate-way to Śiva's abode; tiger's skin as clothing and holding triśūla and paṭṭiśa; 1) Br. III. 32. 12-16. eight of them invoked in tank rituals. 2) M. 58. 11-12. 

द्वारपाल
Dvārapālas --see Dauvārikas. M. 103. 15.

द्वारवती
Dvāravatī  (I)--(Dvārakā s.v.); a great city of Vāsudeva inhabited by Bhoja, Vṛṣṇi and the Andhakas; 1) Br. III. 61. 23; Vā. 86. 27; 96. 46. capital of Kṛṣṇa; 2) Br. III. 71. 48; M. 13. 38; 69. 9. Vi. V. 33. 10 ff. and abode of Rukmiṇī.

द्वारवती
Dvāravatī  (II)--the wife of Bhangakāra. Vā. 96. 54.

द्विकलम्
Dvikalam --the duration of the New Moon day when Pitṛs drink Sudhāmṛta. Vā. 52. 38; 56. 27.

द्विकलम्
Dvikalam Kālam --Amāvāsya. Vā. 52. 67.

द्विज
Dvija --a son of Surasena. Vā. 99. 112.

द्विजग्राम
Dvijagrāma --the birth place of Purūravas as a Brahmana in his previous birth. As a result of Dvādaśīvrata and prayer to Janārdana he attained a kingdom in the next birth. M. 115. 10-12.

द्विजबन्धु
Dvijabandhu --(Brahmabandhu); debarred from Trayī; exempt from capital punishment; subject to punishment of Vapana, confiscation of property and banishment, but not corporal punishment. Bhā. I. 4. 25; 7. 53-57.

द्विजमीढ
Dvijamīḍha --one of the three sons of Hastin and father of Yavīnara. V. IV. 19. 29, 48; Vā. 99. 166. 

द्विजवर्मा
Dvijavarmā --the name given to the wood-cutter by the Brahmanas for his great charities. Br. IV. 7. 35.

द्विजा
Dvijā(ti) --the first three castes socalled for following the common and special dharmas ordained. 1) Vā. 59. 21. Insult among themselves and to members of other castes punished; 2) M. 227. 72. also ruled as kings. 3) Vi. IV. 24. 68.

द्वित
Dvita --came to see Kṛṣṇa at Syamantapañcaka. Bhā. X. 84. 5.

द्विदन्त
Dvidanta(ka) --a name of Vighneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 66 and 69.

द्विपरार्ध
Dviparārdha --a period of Brahmā's life. Bhā. XII. 4. 5.

द्विपाद
Dvipāda --a name of Vighneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 68.

द्विमीढ
Dvimīḍha --a son of Hastin and father of Yavīnara. Bhā. IX. 21. 21, 27; M. 49. 43; Vā. 99. 166.

द्विमुखी
Dvimukhī --a Svaraśakti. Br. IV. 44. 56.

द्विमूर्ध
Dvimūrdha --an Asura, and a son of Danu; a follower of Vṛtra; his battle with Indra; took part in the Devāsura war between Bali and Indra; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 30; 10. 19; VII. 2. 4; VIII. 10. 20. Vā. 68. 4; Br. III. 6. 4; Vi. I. 21. 4. milkman of the Asuras to milk the cow-earth; assisted in the churning of the ocean. 2) M. 6. 17; 10. 21; 249. 67. 

द्वियज्ञ
Dviyajña --a son of Yajñaśrī and father of Candaśrī. Vi. IV. 24. 48.

द्विरम्या
Dviramyā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 74.

द्विराजम्
Dvirājam --Mt. a hill. Vā. 42. 70.

द्विलवम्
Dvilavam --the New Moon day; two lavas with Anumati in the evening and with Rāka in the afternoon; the moon touches the sun for two lavas in one full day and that period is fit for sacrificial rituals; the samudra of Kuhu and Sinivāli. Br. II. 28. 10, 38, 60. Vā. 56. 9, 35, 52, 55 and 57.

द्विविद
Dvivida  (I)--an Asura, and a friend of Kamsa; vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. III. 3. 11; X. 2. 1; 36. 35; Br. III. 73. 99; Vā. 98. 100.

द्विविद
Dvivida  (II)--a Vānara friend of Naraka; a minister of Sugrīva and brother of Mainda; wanted to avenge his friend's death; went about destroying Ānartas and cities belonging to Kṛṣṇa and met Rāma at the Raivata hill. There he offended him by grinning, breaking his wine pot and insulting his fair companions. This resulted in battle in which after a bold stand Dvivida fell dead. Bhā. X. 67. 2-26; Br. III. 7. 242. Vi. V. Ch. 36 (whole).

द्विविद
Dvivida  (III)--Mt. a hill in Krauñcadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 68.

द्विविध
Dvividha --same as Śibikā. M. 122. 32. 

द्वीप
Dvīpa --Island, as the cause of the Devāsura war; thousands in number, but seven are distinguished; 1) Br. III. 72. 71; M. 113. 4-5; 123. 35. ety. water on both sides. 2)M. 123. 35; Vā. 49. 132.

द्वीप
Dvīpas --seven in number; Plakṣa, Śālmalī, Kuśa, Krauñca, Śāka, Puṣkara and Jambu; description of. Bhā. IV. 21. 12; VIII. 19. 23; V. 20 (whole); Br. II. 19. 136.

द्वीपिन
Dvīpina --born of Hari and Pulaha; a Vānarajāti. Br. III. 7. 176, 319.

द्वैपायन
Dvaipāyana --Kṛṣṇa. Vā. 103. 51 and 65.

द्वैपायन
Dvaipāyana --(Kṛṣṇadvaipāyana) the name of Vyāsa in the 28th Dvāpara; also Kṛṣṇa by the sixth amśa; the avatār of the Lord. Yogātma; the son of Parāśara; 1) M. 164. 17; 171. 64; 201. 31; Vā. 60. 11. called his son Śuka when he renounced the world at an early age; 2) Bhā. I. 2. 2; 19. 10; II. 1. 8; VI. 8. 19; 14. 9. invited for the Rājasūya; 3) Bhā. X. 74. 7. came to Syamantapañcaka to see Kṛṣṇa and left the place; 4) Ib. X. 84. 3 and 57. heard the Br. Purāṇa from Jātukarṇi and narrated it to Sūta; 5) Br. I. 1. 11-14; II. 35. 124; 34. 11; IV. 4. 66. the Purohita of Buddha, the ninth incarnation of Hari. 6) M. 47. 247; 69. 8.

द्वयाख्येय
Dvayākhyeya --a Pravara of Angiras. M. 196. 19.

द्वयामुष्यायन
Dvayāmuṣyāyana --(Kaulīnas)--belonging to two castes like the Brahmanas and Kṣatriyas; a gotra. M. 49. 33; 196. 52.  Dh

धनक
Dhanaka  (I)--a son of Drumada and father of Kṛtavīrya and others. Bhā. IX. 23. 23.

धनक
Dhanaka  (II)--a Sage of the Tāmasa epoch. Vi. III. 1. 18.

धनक
Dhanaka  (III)--a son of Durdama, and father of four sons. Vi. IV. 11. 10.

धनंजय
Dhanaṃjaya  (I)--a name of Arjuna, son of Indra and Pṛthā, equal to Śakra in prowess. Bhā. I. 7. 50; Br. III. 71. 154; M. 46. 9; Vā. 96 153; 99. 245; Vi. V. 38. 27.

धनंजय
Dhanaṃjaya  (II)--a Kādraveya; an eminent Nāga of Pātāla, presiding over the month, Tapas; 1) Bhā. V. 24. 31; XII. 11. 39; Vā. 69. 70; Vi I. 21. 22. in Tatvalam; 2) Br. II. 20. 18; 23. 14; III. 7. 34. used for horses for Tripurāri's chariot; shaken by Hiraṇyakaśipu 3) M. 6. 39; 126. 15; 133. 33; 163. 56. in the Atalam 4) Vā. 50. 18. with the Sun in the Śarat. 5) Vā. 52. 14; Vi. II. 10. 11.

धनंजय
Dhanaṃjaya  (III)--a Kauśika and a Sage; the 16th Veda Vyāsa: 1) Br. II. 32. 118; M. 145. 113; Vi. III. 3. 15. Heard the Br. Purāṇa from Trayyāruṇi and narrated it to Kṛtamjaya; 2) Br. II. 35. 120; IV. 4. 52. heard the Vāyu Purāṇa from Trayyāruṇi. 3) Vā. 103. 63. 

धनंजय
Dhanaṃjaya  (IV)--a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 10.

धनंजय
Dhanaṃjaya  (V)--a son of Viśvāmitra. Vi. IV. 7. 38.

धनद
Dhanada  (I)--Kubera (s.v.) son of Viśravā. Bhā. IX. 2. 32. Vi. III. 2. 11.

धनद
Dhanada  (II)--an Āditya. M. 171. 56.

धनद
Dhanada  (III)--a Marut of the III Gaṇa. Br. III. 5. 94.

धनधर्म
Dhanadharma --the third king after Nakhavān of Vidiśa. Br. III. 74. 181; Vā. 99. 368.

धनम्
Dhanam --wealth, acquired by industry and labour stays long; a windfall should be spent righteously. Br. IV. 7. 21; M. 31. 22.

धनाधिप
Dhanādhipa --a name of Kubera. Br. III. 24. 4.

धनाध्यक्ष
Dhanādhyakṣa  (I)--see Kubera 1) M. 148. 85; 150. 12; 159. 9. (s.v.); the king of the Yakṣas; 2) Vā. 41. 4. gaḍā, his weapon; in charge of eight nidhis. 3) Ib. 41. 10-11.

धनाध्यक्ष
Dhanādhyakṣa  (II)--Treasury officer. M. 215. 32. 

धनायु
Dhanāyu --a son of Purūravas and Urvaśī. M. 24. 33.

धनिष्ठा
Dhaniṣṭhā --the constellation on the Simśumāra 1) Bhā. V. 23. 6; Vā. 66. 51; 82. 12. in the Dhruva maṇḍala; good for śrāddha offering; 2) Br. II. 24. 134; III. 18. 11; Vi. III. 14. 16. inauspicious for house-building. 3) M. 257. 1.

धनु
Dhanu  (I)--a son of Sṛnjaya, brother of Vasudeva. Br. III. 71. 193.

धनु
Dhanu  (II)--a son of Śamīka. M. 46. 27.

धनुक
Dhanuka --a son of Śambhu. Vā. 67. 81.

धनुदुर्ग
Dhanudurga --one of six kinds of fortresses; others are Mahīdurga, Naradurga, Vārkṣadurga, Ambudurga and Giridurga. M. 217. 6.

धनुर्दण्ड
Dhanurdaṇḍa --equal in measurement to yuga and nālika; four hastas. Vā. 8. 102, 106; 101. 125.

धनुर्धरी
Dhanurdharī --a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 74.

धनुर्मह
Dhanurmaha --Festival of arms--arranged by Kamsa to destroy Kṛṣṇa and Rāma. Vi. V. 15. 8 and 15. 

धनुर्याग
Dhanuryāga --(also Dhanurmakha) A sacrifice of the bow in honour of Śiva; conducted by Kamsa at Mathurā, visited by Kṛṣṇa and Rāma; Kamsa's. bow broken and the guards killed. Bhā. X. 36. 26-37; 42. 15-20.

धनुर्वेद
Dhanurveda --the science of war; taught by Droṇa to the Pāṇḍavas; 1) Vā. 61. 79. 91. 91. Vi. III. 6. 28; IV. 19. 60. Bhā. I. 7. 44; III. 12. 38. M. 4. 47; 50. 9. Satyadhṛti well versed in; 2) Bhā. IX. 21. 35; M. 215. 8. learnt by Kṛṣṇa and Rāma; 3) Bhā. X. 45. 34; Br. II. 35. 88; 37. 27. personified, 4) Ib. IV. 17. 38-41; M. 220. 2. knowledge of, essential to a king; Prācetasas was an expert in; 5) Vi. I. 14. 6. variety and detail of. 6) Ib. V. 21. 21.

धनुष
Dhanuṣa --a son of Satyadhṛti. M. 50. 30.

धनुष्कोटि
Dhanuṣkoṭi --the end of a bow; 1) Vā. 62. 169. used by Vaiṇyapṛthu to level the earth by removing mountains and make it habitable. 2) Br. II. 36. 195; M. 10. 31.

धनुस्
Dhanus --a pole from the term dhanurdaṇḍa, 96 angulas in measurement. Two of them measure one nāli, and 8000 one yojana. Br. I. 7. 96, 100; IV. 2. 124-6; Vā. 101. 124.

धनेश
Dhaneśa  (I)--a monkey chief. Br. III. 7. 244.

धनेश
Dhaneśa  (II)--an epithet of Kubera. Vi. V. 30. 61. 

धनेश्वरी
Dhaneśvarī --a Goddess of wealth. Bhā. VI. 19. 26.

धन्तपापा
Dhantapāpā --a R. rising on the Himālayas. M. 114. 22.

धन्या
Dhanyā  (I)--the Vaiśya caste of Krauñcadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 53.

धन्या
Dhanyā  (II)--a daughter of Manas; wife of Dhruva; gave birth to a son Śiṣṭa. M. 4. 38.

धन्व
Dhanva  (I)--a son of Dīrghatapas. Br. III. 67. 7.

धन्व
Dhanva  (II)--the place with water at all times, suitable for fortresses. Vā. 8. 98.

धन्व
Dhanva  (III)--a country, the people of which met Kṛṣṇa with presents on his way to Mithilā. Bhā. X. 86. 20.

धन्वकारा
Dhanvakārā --a Rudra on the ṣoḍaśa cakra. Br. IV. 34. 26.

धन्वतीरूपा
Dhanvatīrūpā --a R. rising on the Ṛṣyavat hill. M. 114. 24.

धन्वन्तरि
