Nandipurāṇam --an Upapurāṇa; contains the māhātmya of Nandi described by Kārttikeya. M. 53. 61.

नन्दियशस्
Nandiyaśas  (I)--the younger brother of Bhūtanandi (Madhunandi-Vā. P.); a king. Br. III. 74. 182.

नन्दियशस्
Nandiyaśas  (II)--a son of Nandana and brother of Sunandana. Vi. IV. 24. 56.

नन्दिवर्धन
Nandivardhana  (I)--a son of Udāvasu and father of Suketu. Bhā. IX. 13. 14; Br. III. 64. 7; Vā. 89. 7. Vi. IV. 5. 25.

नन्दिवर्धन
Nandivardhana  (II)--a son of Rājaka (Viśākhayūpa) and the last of the five Pradyotanas, who ruled for 138 years. Bhā. XII. 1. 4. 

नन्दिवर्धन
Nandivardhana  (III)--a son of Ajaya (Ajaka-Br. P.) and father of Mahānandi; ruled for 20 years (40)? Bhā. XII. 1. 7. Br. III. 74. 126 and 133.

नन्दिवर्धन
Nandivardhana  (IV)--a palace with seven storeys; the toraṇa is of 32 hastas. M. 269. 29, 48.

नन्दिवर्धन
Nandivardhana  (V)--a son of Sūryaka: was succeeded by Śiśunāka; ruled for thirty years. M. 272. 5.

नन्दिवर्धन
Nandivardhana  (VI)--the son of Udāsi, and a Śaisunāga ruled for 40 years. (42 years Br. P.). M. 272. 11; Vā. 99. 320.

नन्दिवर्धन
Nandivardhana  (VII)--a son of Manivara; a Yakṣa and a Guhyaka. Vā. 69. 158.

नन्दिवर्धन
Nandivardhana  (VIII)--a son of Janaka and father of Nandi of the Pradyota dynasty. Vi. IV. 24. 6-7.

नन्दिवर्धन
Nandivardhana  (IX)--a son of Udayana and father of Mahānandi of the Śaisanābha dynasty. Vi. IV. 24. 17-8.

नन्दीश
Nandīśa --one of the eighteen authors on architecture. M. 252. 3.

नन्दीश्वर
Nandīśvara --the god attendant on Śiva; 1) Vā. 77. 63. the vehicle of Rudra; 2) Bhā. X. 63. 6. Bhagavān with sūla; 3) Vā. 30. 91, 315. cursed Dakṣa for his hatred of Śiva; 4) Bhā. IV. 2. 20-26. caught hold of Bhaga on the occasion of the destruction of Daksa's sacrifice; 5) Ib. IV. 5. 17. his permission to see  Śiva; temple of, at Svargamārga Prasāda. 6) Br. III. 32. 23; 13. 63-4; IV. 30. 75; 34. 89; 41. 26 and 30; 43. 30. Observed the vow Saubhāgyaśayanam; lord of a gaṇa, versed in Maheśvara dharma; advised Nārada to take to Prayāga; the standard of Śiva. 7) M. 60. 49; 95. 3; 112. 21; 132. 18; 133. 60-5. Fought with Vidyunmāli in Tripuram; 8) Ib. 135. 48 and 53; 136. 68; 138. 44. 140. 20-1. related to Sanatkumāra about the sthānutvam of Śiva at Benares. 9) Ib. 181. 2; 183. 64; 245. 80. 266. 42. 278. 9.

नन्देन्दु
Nandendu --ruled for 100 years. Vā. 99. 330.

नभ
Nabha  (I)--a son of Niṣadha, and father of Puṇḍarīka. Bhā. IX. 12. 1.

नभ
Nabha  (II)--a month sacred to Indra. Bhā. XII. 11. 37.

नभ
Nabha  (III)--see Prathakvānya; 1) Br. II. 12. 23. fourfold agni in gratadvoca sthānam. 2) Vā. 29. 21.

नभ
Nabha  (IV)--a son of Nala and father of Puṇḍarīka of the dynasty of Kuśa, son of Rāma, (Nabhā-Br. P. and Vi. P.). Br. III. 63. 202; M. 12. 52. Vā. 88. 202. Vi. IV. 4. 106.

नभ
Nabha  (V)--a son of Svārociṣa Manu. M. 9. 7

नभ
Nabha  (VI)--a son of Auttama Manu. M. 9. 12. 

नभ
Nabha  (VII)--a Pravara Ṛṣi. M. 199. 15.

नभ
Nabha  (VIII)--a Mantrakṛt. Vā. 59. 97.

नभ
Nabha  (IX)--a son of Vipracitti. Vi. I. 21. 11.

नभग
Nabhaga --a son of Vaivasvata Manu and father of Nābhāga. Bhā. VIII. 13. 2; IX. 1. 12; 4. 1. Br. III. 63. 5; Vā. 88. 5.

नभश्री
Nabhaśrī --a queen of Vaṛṣaṛtu. Br. IV. 32. 28.

नभस
Nabhasa --a son of Ūrja; from him were born two pieces which were combined by old age (jarā) and hence Jarāsandha. Vā. 99. 225-26.

नभस्य
Nabhasya  (I)--the month sacred to Vivasvān. Bhā. XII. 11. 38; Br. II. 13. 9; Vā. 30. 8, 50, 201; 52. 11.

नभस्य
Nabhasya  (II)--one of the four sons of Svārociṣa Manu. M. 9. 7.

नभस्य
Nabhasya  (III)--a son of Auttama Manu. M. 9. 12.

नभस्य
Nabhasya  (IV)--(name of a month and tithi) (Trayodaśi)--a yugādi for śrāddha. Trayambaka to be worshipped in Kṛṣṇāṣtami vrata; 2) Ib. 56. 4. austerity to be observed in Saubhāgyasayana vrata in this month. 3) Ib. 60. 34. ^1 M. 17. 4. 

नभस्यश्री
Nabhasyaśrī --a queen of Vaṛṣaṛtu. Br. IV. 32. 28.

नभस्वन्
Nabhasvan --a son of Mura (s.v.), attacked Kṛṣṇa under direction from Naraka. Bhā. X. 59. 12-14.

नभस्वती
Nabhasvatī --a queen of Antardhāna and mother of Havirdhāna. Bhā. IV. 24. 5.

नमस्यु
Namasyu --a son of Pravīra and father of Cārupada. Bhā. IX. 20. 2.

नमुचि
Namuci --a son of Vipracitti. Lord of the Asuras, hostile to Indra; 1) Vi. I. 21. 11. a resident of the first talam or atala; 2) Vā. 50. 15; 98. 81. a nephew of Hiraṇyakaśipu; married Suprabhā, the daughter of Svarbhānu; 3) Bhā. VI. 6. 32; Br. III. 6. 19; M. 6. 27. followed Vṛtra against Indra; 4) Bhā. VI. 10. 19-31; Br. II. 20. 16. took part in the Devāsura war between Bali and Indra; fought with Aparājita; heard of Bali's and Jambha's fall and fought with Indra; resisted with success Vajra on account of the fact that he could not be killed either by a dry or wet thing; Indra who came to know of this by a voice in the air used phena (foam) and killed him to the satisfaction of all gods; 5) Bhā. VII. 2. 4; VIII. 10. 20 to the end; 11. 19, 23, 29-40; M. 22. 61. entertained desire for more territory; 6) Bhā. XII. 3. 11. taken to pātāla by Vāmana. 7) Br. III. 73. 81; M. 249. 67.

नय
Naya  (I)--is politics; according to Prahlāda, it must be a means to realise Hari; 1) Bhā. VII. 6. 26. persons versed in Naya praise bheda upāya. 2) M. 223. 4 and 16. 

नय
Naya  (II)--a son of Uttama Manu. Br. II. 36. 39.

नय
Naya  (III)--a son of Raucya Manu. Br. IV. 1. 104.

नय
Naya  (IV)--a son of Kriyā. Vā. 10. 35.

नय
Naya  (V)--a Sādhya god. Vā. 66. 16.

नय
Naya  (VI)--one of Viśvāmitra's sons. Vā. 91. 96.

नय
Naya  (VII)--one of the 20 Amitābha gaṇas. Vā. 100. 17.

नर
Nara  (I) (Nārāyaṇa)--an avatār of Viṣṇu, born of Dharma and Mūrtī, a daughter of Dakṣa; Ādiśeṣa form of Hari, distinguished for tapas; 1) Bhā. I. 2. 4; 3. 9; II. 7. 6-7; XII. 8. 32, 35. Br. II. 35-93; M. 1. 2. a friend and associate of Nārāyaṇa said to have performed tapas at Badarī; 2) Bhā. III. 4. 22; IV. 1. 52; VII. 6. 27. seeing the sage's penance Indra got afraid and sent the God of Love and the Apsarasas to disturb his contemplation. Nara invited him and was hospitable by creating a number of beautiful women who served them; Nara asked them to choose one among them as an ornament of Heaven. So they took Ūrvaśi and narrated to Indra the superior powers of the sage; 3) Ib. XI. 4. 6-16; 7. 18. was seen with Nārāyaṇa by Mārkaṇḍeya and was praised by him. 4) Ib. XII. 8. 32, 35, 40-49; 9. 1.

नर
Nara  (II)--a son of Tāmasa Manu. Bhā. VIII. I. 27; Br. II. 36. 49. Vi. III. 1. 19. 

नर
Nara  (III)--a son of Sudhṛti and father of Kevala (Candra Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 2. 29. 30; Br. III. 8. 35; 61. 9; Vi. IV. 1. 40-1; Vā. 86. 13-14.

नर
Nara  (IV)--a son of Manyu and father of Samkṛti. Bhā. IX. 21. 1.

नर
Nara  (V)--a son of Gaya and father of Virāt. Br. II. 14. 68; Vi. II. 1. 38; Vā. 33. 58.

नर
Nara  (VI)--one of the ten horses of the moon's chariot. Br. II. 23. 35; M. 126. 52.

नर
Nara  (VII)--a sādhya; is satya in the Svārociṣa epoch. Br. III. 3. 16-7; M. 203. 11; 251; 24-5; Vā. 66. 15; Br. II. 36. 50.

नर
Nara  (VIII)--a son of Bhuvamanyu. M. 49. 36; Vā. 99. 159.

नर
Nara  (IX)--the riding vehicle of Naiṛti and drawer of Kubera's chariot. M. 261. 15 and 22.

नर
Nara  (X)--a son of Tāmasa Manu. Vā. 62. 43.

नर
Nara  (XI)--a devaṛṣi. Vā. 61. 83.

नरक
Naraka --a son of Anṛta; another name of Raurava. Br. II. 9. 64; Vā. 10. 39.

नरक
Naraka --a nephew of Hiraṇyakaśipu and son of the Earth and Vipracitti; lived in Prāgjyotiṣa; 1) M. 6. 27; 161. 78; 163. 81-2; 245. 12. Vi. I. 21. 128; V. 1. 24; 12. 21. took away a  number of women belonging to sages and kings to his palace, robbed Mandara of its crest jewel, Aditi of her earrings and Varuṇa of his umbrella; demanded the Airāvata from Indra; at Indra's request was cut in twain by Kṛṣṇa in his own city Prāgjyotiṣa; 2) Ib. V. 29. 8-21. spoils distributed among his followers while all women were appropriated to Kṛṣṇa's harem. 3) Ib. V. 31. 14-15. Friend of Vānara Dvivida who was killed by Baladeva. 4) Ib. V. 36. 2-21.

नरक
Naraka --a Dānava with Manuṣya dharma; 1) Vā. 68. 15. a Saimhikeya; 2) Ib. 68. 19. killed by Kṛṣṇa. 3) Ib. 98. 102.

नरकम्
Narakam --is bhaumam (earth). M. 39. 4, 7-8; 41. 6.

नरक
Narakas --27 hells under Yama; to them go the unrighteous according to their respective sins; after a certain period they are born as low beings according to their karma. 1) Br. IV. 2. 146-150. Seven under the earth below the Śeṣaloka-Raurava, Śītastapa, Kālasūtu, Apratiṣṭha, Avīcī, Lohapṛṣṭha, and Avidhya. 2) Vā. 101. 144-92; Vi. II. 6. 1. (whole).

नरकान्तक
Narakāntaka --Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 34.

नरकासुर
Narakāsura --(Naraka, s.v. Bhauma); Born of Hari in his Boar manifestation when he touched and raised the Earth, 1) Bhā. X. 59. 30[1]; [65 (v) 1]. hence son of Earth, 2) Ib. X. 59. 59. [1]
and 2. an asura friend of Kamsa; 3) Ib. X. 2. 2; 36. 36. a friend of the Vānara Dvivida; 4) Ib. X. 67. 2; 69. [3]
1. ran away with the umbrella of Varuṇa, Kuṇḍala of Aditi and contested the position of Indra. 5) Ib. X. 59. [1]
and 2. Fought with Sanaiścara in the Devāsura war; 6) Ib. X. 73. 20; 83. 40; Br. III. 6. 15; 73. 102; IV. 29. 125. find ing Mura and his sons dead, came out with elephants, which were all killed by Garuḍa; fought with Kṛṣṇa till his head was cut off and the ladies of his harem married by Him (Kṛṣṇa); 7) Bhā. VIII. 10. 33. lost his kingdom through pride of power. 8) Ib. X. 59. 14-22; 37. 16; I. 10. 29.

नरदुर्ग
Naradurga --one of the 6 kinds of fortresses. M. 217. 6.

नरदेव
Naradeva (Rāma) --the eighteenth, out of the avatārs of Viṣṇu; did heroic deeds, subduing the sea and so on. Bhā. I. 3. 22.

नरदेव
Naradeva --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 243.

नरनारायण
Naranārāyaṇa --The two sages comprising the fourth avatār of Viṣṇu and born of Mūrtī; universal joy and good omens at their birth; Gandhamādana their abode; 1) Bhā. I. 2. 4, 26; 3. 9; IV. 1. 52-57; Vi. V. 24. 5; 37. 34 and 37. born later as Kṛṣṇa and Arjuṇa; 2) Ib. IV. 1. 59. worshipped by Nābhī; 3) Ib. V. 4. 4. worshipped in Bhāratavarṣa; 4) Ib. V. 19. 9. praised by Nārada. 5) Ib. V. 19. 12-15. To their āśrama the sages repaired for a visit; 6) Ib. IX. 1. 31. shrine of, at Badaryāśrama. 7) Ib. X. 52. 4.

नरनारायणौ
Naranārāyaṇau --one of the births of the Jayādevas; these are Vipaścit, Indra, Satya and Hari. Vā. 54. 75; 66. 14.

नरमेधम्
Naramedham --the belly of the personified Veda. Vā. 104. 84. 

नरवाहन
Naravāhana --an attribute of Kubera. M. 174. 18.

नरसिम्ह
Narasimha --The avatār of Hari to kill Hiraṇyakaśipu by the nails neither wet nor dry; 1) Br. III. 5. 26-27; 57. 57; 73. 74; Vā. 67. 66; 97. 73; 98. 73; 111. 72; Vi. I. 20. 32. on Brahmā granting the request of Hiraṇyakaśipu, Narasimha was approached by the gods; Narasimha promised to slay him and left for the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu; Prahlāda alone knew Him to be the Lord; all the Asuras attacked him from all sides; finally Narasimha killed him by tearing him with his teeth. 2) M. 53. 50. chh. 161, 162 and 163; 285. 6.

नरा
Narā --the daughter of Suyagña (Śvaphalka, Vā. P.) and wife of Bhangakāra; had two sons Śatrughna and Bandhumān, whom Akrūra killed. Br. III. 71. 87. Vā. 96. 86.

नराह्
Narāh --(ety.) waters. Vā. 7. 56-8; 100. 183.

नरान्तक
Narāntaka --a son of Kālanemi; 1) Br. III. 5. 39; Vā 67. 80. was killed in the Lankā war. 2) Bhā. IX. 10. 18.

नरिष्यन्त
Nariṣyanta  (I)--a son of Vaivasvata Manu and father of Citrasena and Suca; his line ends with Jātūkarṇya. Bhā. VIII. 13. 2; IX. 1. 12; 2. 19, 22; Br. III. 60. 3; M. 11. 41; 12. 20; Vā. 64. 29; 85. 4; Vi. III. 1. 33; IV. 1. 7.

नरिष्यन्त
Nariṣyanta  (II)--(Nābhāga) a son of Svāyambhuva Manu. Br. II. 38. 31. Vā. 85 4. 

नरिष्यन्त
Nariṣyanta  (III)--a son of Marutta and father of Dama. Br. III. 8. 35; 61. 7; Vā. 86. 12; Vi. IV. 1. 34-5.

नरेन्द्र
Narendra --is Candragupta Maurya. Br. III. 74. 143.

नर्मदा
Narmadā  (I)--a mahānadi of the Bhāratavarṣa; a R. from the Ṛkṣa or Ṛṣyavat hills: (Vindhyan ranges) on its northern bank was Bhṛgukaccha: a sacred river that survived the antarakṣaya, sacred to Pitṛs and for śrāddha; in the neighbourhood of the Haihaya kingdom. 1) Bhā. V. 19. 18; VIII. 18. 21; Br. II. 12. 14; 16. 29; III. 10. 97; M. 2. 13-15; 22. 25; 114. 23; Vā. 45. 99; 77. 32; 94. 28; 108. 82; V. II. 3. 11. The scene of battle between Vṛtra and Indra; here Rukmi challenged Kṛṣṇa when the latter was crossing the stream with Rukmiṇī; its current was stopped by Kārtavīrya. 2) Bhā. VI. 10. 16; X. 54. 23[1]; Br. III. 13. 8, 32; 26. 10 and 38; 38. 3 and 7; 41. 15; 45. 2; 69. 28; M. 43. 31; 44. 31; 44. 31; 163. 63; Vi. IV. 11. 19. The mahātmya of; just like Mārkaṇḍeya this river does not get lost in the time of the deluge; in Kalinga, near the Amarakaṇṭaka hill; has a number of tīrthas like Jaleśvara, Rudrakoṭi, Amrakaṇṭaka, Kapila and Viśalya Karaṇi. The devotee bathing in any tīrtha on the Narmadā gets the benefit of performing an Aśvamedha sacrifice. 3) M. ch. 186. The Lord enshrined here is Maheśvara who devised plans to vanquish Bāṇāsura of Tripura with the help of Nārada. The Lord was much concerned about virtuous ladies in Tripura and Nārada undertook to delude them by proclaiming ordinances to ladies to give gifts to poor and deserving Brahmanas. 4) Ib. ch. 187. Śiva got ready for war here and attacked Tripura with incendiary materials. Out of the three cities comprising Tripura, (s.v.) two fell down reduced to ashes. The first city became converted into the Śri Śaila hill, and the second Amarakaṇṭaka hill, both adorned by the Siddhas, Gandharvas and so on. The Lord enshrined at the latter is Jvāleśvara. The third city was left unconsumed. 5) Ib. ch. 188.  It is said that at the confluence of the Narmadā with Kāverī, Kubera practised tapas in honour of Śiva and became the Lord of the Yakṣas. A bath here is equal to that at the confluence of the Gangā and the Yamunā. 6) Ib. ch. 189. To the north of the Narmadā are a number of tīrthams like Mantreśvara, Garjanā, Amrātaka, Karanyā, Kuṇḍeśvara and others. A bath in each of them rids one of all sins. Then follows other tīrthas, all equally sacred, including Rāvaṇeśvara, the shrines of Kubera, Ahalyātīrtha, and the shrine of Janārdana. Here Agni, Dharmarāja and Vāyu practised asceticism and attained emancipation. A visit to Śuklatīrtham sacred to Rājaṛṣi Cāṇakya washes off all the sins of a life time. Any gift given here bears rich fruits. 7) Ib. chh. 190-192. Among the other sacred places can be mentioned the Bhṛgutīrtham, Kankhala, where Garuḍa once was in austereties, Kanyātīrtha, Pitāmahatīrtha, and Svargadvāratīrtham; He who reads or listens to the glory of the Namadā has his wishes fulfilled whatever be his caste. 8) Ib. chh. 193-194. On its banks Purukutsa heard the Viṣṇu Purāṇa from the sages. 9) Vi. I. 2. 9; IV. 3. 7-16. Penance here by Asuras, who became converted into Arhats. 10) Ib. III. 18. 1 and 13. Marubhūmīviṣaya on the N. ruled by Śūdras and other castes. 11) Ib. IV. 24. 68.

नर्मदा
Narmadā  (II)--the Mānasakanyā of Śukālā Pitṛs; given in marriage to Purukutsa by her brother Uraga; and mother of Trasadasyu; she took him to Rasātala where he killed some bad Gandharvas to the satisfaction of the Nāgas: 1) Bhā. IX. 7. 2-3; Br. III. 10. 97; Vā. 73. 48; 88. 74. Heard the Viṣṇu Purāṇa from him and narrated it to Dhṛtarāṣṭra the Nāga and Āpūraṇa. 2) Vi. VI. 8. 45. 

नर्मदा
Narmadā  (III)--the wife of Yuvanāśva, son of Ambarīṣa. Br. III. 63. 73.

नर्मदा
Narmadā  (IV)--a mind-born daughter of Somapa Pitṛs: one of the 16 wives of Havyavāhana: turned into a river of Dakṣiṇāpatha. M. 15. 25, 28; 51. 13; Vā. 77. 32.

नर्मदानिकत
Narmadānikata --sages of, visited Dvārakā. Bhā. X. 90. 28. [5].

नर्मदेश्वरम्
Narmadeśvaram --on the Narmadā. M. 194. 2.

नल
Nala  (I)--a son of Yadu. Bhā. IX. 23. 20; Vi. IV. 11. 5.

नल
Nala  (II)--a Vanara son of Agni born by the wife of Kanakabindu. Br. III. 7. 229.

नल
Nala  (III)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 234.

नल
Nala  (IV)--a nephew of Hiraṇyakaśipu. M. 6. 26.

नल
Nala  (V)--the son of Niṣadha, hence Naiṣadha; with the son of Vīrasena he made the two Nalas in the Kaśyapa line; 1) M. 12. 52, 56; Vā. 88. 202. taught the game of dice to King Ṛtuparṇa. 2) Bhā. IX. 9; 17; Br. III. 63. 173 and 202, 74. 190; Vā. 88. 174; Vi. IV. 4. 37. Learned in Aśvavidyā. 

नल
Nala  (VI)--a son of Vīrasena. M. 12. 56.

नल
Nala  (VII)--also known as Nandanodaradundubhi, son of Taittiri, performed aśvamedha, and in the middle of the atirātra rite Punarvasu appeared and became his son. M. 44. 63-5.

नलकालिक
Nalakālikas --a people of the southern country. Vā. 45. 127.

नलकूबर
Nalakūbara --a son of Kubera and Ṛddhi; as an attendant of Rudra became very proud and with his brother Maṇigrīva enjoyed maidens' embrace on the Ganges, all naked. Nārada saw this when the ladies put on their dress while Nalakūbara and his brother continued to remain naked owing to their drunkenness. The sage cursed them to become trees for a hundred divine years without losing the Pūrvavāsana. So they stood till Kṛṣṇa redeemed them by bringing down the trees; their prayer to Kṛṣṇa; set out to the north, permitted by Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 9. 22. 23; 10. (whole); Br. III. 8. 46. Vā. 70. 41.

नलिनी
Nalinī  (I)--one of the eastern entrances of the city of Purañjana 1) Bhā. IV. 25. 48. allegorically the nostrils. 2) Ib. 29. 11.

नलिनी
Nalinī  (II)--one of the wives of Ajamīḍha and mother of Nīla. Bhā. IX. 21. 30. Vi. IV. 19. 56.

नलिनी
Nalinī  (III)--a R. in Śākadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 96; Vi. II. 4. 65. 

नलिनी
Nalinī  (IV)--digging of lakes at the auspicious hour; the same prescription as for the excavation of tadāga; is also Puṣkaraṇi. M. 58. 1, 51.

नलिनी
Nalinī  (V)--a name for the Ganges; 1) M. 102. 6. a stream of the Gangā, flows east through the countries of Tomara, Hamsamārga, Haihaya, Karṇaprāvaraṇa, Aśvamukha, Śikatāparvatamaru, Vidyādhara, and Nāgamaṇḍala and reaches the salt ocean; 2) Br. II. 18. 40, 58-61; Vā. 47. 38 and 56. one of the seven streams, and one of the three going towards the western direction. 3) M. 121. 40.

नल्व
Nalva --a measurement in connection with the chariot of Maya; 1) M. 173. 2; Br. IV. 2. 125; 36. 49. the seat of Hiraṇyakaśipu in his sabhā was 10 nalvas in measurement; 2) M. 161. 71. a furlong in distance; 300 dhanus. 3) Vā. 83. 49; 101. 125.

नव
Nava  (I)--a son of Svārociṣa Maru. Br. II. 36. 19.

नव
Nava  (II)--a son of Navā and Uśīnara; chief of Navarāṣṭra. Br. III. 74. 19 and 21; M. 48. 18 and 21; Vā. 99. 20, 22. Vi. IV. 18. 9.

