निमि
Nimi  (I)--one of the elder sons of Ikṣvāku; solicited the service of Vasiṣṭha for performing a sacrifice; Vasiṣṭha asked Nimi to wait until he returned from Indra's sacrifice to which he had been invited earlier. But Nimi thinking of the mutability of things got it done with the help of other sages; finding that Nimi had finished his sacrifice the sage cursed ‘Let his body fall’. The king cursed the sage in his turn and cast off his body. After preserving the body in a balm for seven days the sages requested the gods to restore him to life; Nimi refused to enter again the bondage of the physical body; then the gods said, ‘let him live in the eyelids of all living beings’. But the sages were afraid of anarchy and churned the body of Nimi for a son and this was Janaka Vaideha; 1) Bhā. IX. 6. 4; 13. 1-13; X. 86. 36; Br. III. 63. 9; 64. 1; Vi. IV. 2. 12; 5. 1-23. performed a satra at which the nine sages, the sons of Ṛṣabha were present. These enlightened the king on Bhāgavata dharma. 2) Bhā. XI. 2. 14; 25-26; chh. 3 to 5: Br. III. 74. 244 and 248; Vā. 1. 142. For a slightly different version of the incident regarding the curse see Matsya. 3) M. 61. 32-5; 201. 1-20.

निमि
Nimi  (II)--a son of Daṇḍapāṇi and father of Kṣemaka. Bhā. IX. 22. 44. 

निमि
Nimi  (III)--a son of Bhajamāna. M. 44. 50. Vi. IV. 13. 2.

निमि
Nimi  (IV)--a commander of Tāraka's army; had a chariot of elephants; 1) M. 148. 42, 51. found out the trick of the Sun God in making Asuras appear like Devas and causing their slaughter; he reported this to Kālanemi; threw darts on Janārdana; 2) Ib. 150. 161; 224. sent cakra against Viṣṇu; 3) Ib. 151. 12, 31. fight of, with Janārdana; 4) Ib. 152. 33. fight with Dikpālakas and Kṛṣṇa and Indra; Indra wounded by Mudgara. 5) Ib. 153. 55, 62.

निमि
Nimi  (V)--the younger brother of Vikukṣi; established the city of Jayanta near Gautama's āśrama. Vā. 89. 1-2.

निमि
Nimi  (VI)--a son of Bāhyaka. Vā. 96. 4.

निमि
Nimi  (VII)--the father of six Ṛtus. Br. II. 13. 18.

निमित्त
Nimitta --the son of Daṇḍapāṇi and father of Kṣemaka. Vi. IV. 21. 15-6.

निमित्तम्
Nimittam --science of astrology; 1) M. 215. 9. throbbing of limbs on the right, auspicious, and on the left, inauspicious; the results of such movements; 2) Ib. 240. 15; 241. 1 ff. gifts of suvarṇam to the Brahmana; 3) Ib. 241. 4-12. a list of things that must not come against or cross the path when the king goes on a march; if seen, prayer to Keśava, mitigates effects; 4) Ib. 243. 2-3. in connection with the installation of images. 5) Ib. 264. 9. 

निमेष
Nimeṣa --a small unit of time measured by the wink of the eye; 1) Br. II. 21. 116, 126; 29. 6; 24. 143. from Nimi: 15 of them equal a Kāṣṭḥa 2) M. 61. 35; 142. 3; 201. 19; Vā. 50. 179; Vi. I. 3. 8; VI. 3. 6. the same mātra for laghvakṣara such as अ, ढ, उ some equal to a laghvakṣara. 3) Br. II. 13. 16 and 111; Vā. 31. 24; 30. 13; 53. 115; 57. 6; 100. 213; 104. 33.

निमेषम्
Nimeṣam  (Vaiṣṇava)--equal to 100 Śaiva years; when Viṣṇu wakes up, the world is active and when he sleeps the world is sleepy. M. 290. 21-2.

निम्न
Nimna --the son of Anamitra and father of two sons, Satrājita and Prasena. Bhā. IX. 24. 13.

निम्लोचनि
Nimlocani --the city of Varuṇa on the west of Meru. Bhā. V. 21. 7.

निम्लोचा
Nimlocā --the Apsaras with the sun in the months of Nabha and Nabhasya. Vā. 52. 11.

निम्लोचि
Nimloci  (I)--a son of Bhajamanā. Bhā. IX. 24. 7.

निम्लोचि
Nimloci  (II)--a son of Bhāhyaka. Br. III. 71. 4.

नियती
Niyatī --a daughter of Meru and Dhāraṇi; wife of Vidhāta (Dhāta-Vā. P.) and mother of Mṛkaṇḍu. Bhā. IV. 1. 43-44; Br. II. 11. 6; 13. 37; Vā. 28. 4; 30. 34. Vi. I. 10. 3. 

नियम
Niyama  (I)--a son of Dhṛti. Br. II. 9. 59. 10. 34.

नियम
Niyama  (II)--a god of Ābhūtaraya group. Br. II. 36. 55.

नियम
Niyama  (III)--a mukhya clan. Vā. 100. 19.

नियम
Niyama  (IV)--a Sukha God. Br. IV. 1. 19.

नियुत्
Niyut --a consort of Rudra. Bhā. III. 12. 13.

नियुतम्
Niyutam --a hundred thousand. Vā. 101. 94.

नियुत्स
Niyutsa --the wife of Prastāva and mother of Vibhu. Bhā. V. 15. 6.

निरञ्जन
Nirañjana --is Vighneśvara. M. 108. 29.

निरञ्जनम्
Nirañjanam  (I)--a tīrtham sacred to Āditya, on the north of the Yamunā. Br. IV. 44. 66.

निरञ्जनम्
Nirañjanam  (II)--the state of separation due to Kaivalyam; it makes one a Śuddha or Pure man, when there is nobody to guide him. Vā. 102. 79, 118. 

निरताल
Niratāla --a madhyamādhvaryu. Br. II. 33. 17.

निरमित्र
Niramitra  (I)--the son of Ayutāyu and father of Sunakṣtra (Sunetra-Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 22. 46-7; Vi. IV. 23. 4.

निरमित्र
Niramitra  (II)--a son of Daṇdapāṇi and father of Kṣemaka. M. 50. 87.

निरमित्र
Niramitra  (III)--a son of Apratipi, ruled for 40 years. M. 271. 21.

निरमित्र
Niramitra  (IV)--a son of Reṇumatī and Nakula. Vi. IV. 20. 48.

निरमित्र
Niramitra  (V)--a son of Nakula by Kareṇumatī. Bhā. IX. 22. 32.

निरय
Niraya  (I)--a son of Bhaya and Mṛtyu. Bhā. IV. 8. 4.

निरय
Niraya  (II)--one of the seven seers of the Svārociṣa epoch. Vi. III. 1. 11.

निरली
Niralī --a Śakti. Br. IV. 32. 29.

निरवद्यम्
Niravadyam --like sāvadyam is Yogaiśvara lying embedded in the five elements; it relates to Indriyas and Ahankāras. Vā. 13. 6. 

निरानन्द
Nirānanda --the son of Vyāghra, a destroyer of sacrifices. Br. III. 7. 96; Vā. 69. 131.

निरामय
Nirāmaya  (I)--a son of I Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 64.

निरामय
Nirāmaya  (II)--a son of Dakṣasāvarṇi. Vi. III. 2. 24.

निरामित्र
Nirāmitra  (I)--a son of Raivataka Manu. Br. II. 36. 64; Vā. 62. 55.

निरामित्र
Nirāmitra  (II)--of the Bṛhadratha line; 1) Br. III. 74. 112. ruled for one hundred years. 2) Vā. 99. 298.

निरामित्र
Nirāmitra  (III)--a son of the III Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 72.

निरामित्र
Nirāmitra  (IV)--a son of Bhṛgu, the avatār of the Lord Vā. 23. 149.

निरामित्र
Nirāmitra  (V)--a son of Daṇḍapāṇi. Vā. 99. 277.

निरालोक
Nirāloka --a dark territory, at the end of which is the world of Lord. Divyam, above the seven created worlds. 1) Br. II. 19. 151, 167-9; 21. 106; III. 7. 294; IV. 2. 188; Vā. 49. 145-159; 50. 160. The region above āloka. 2) M. 123. 47; 124. 83-84.

निराहार
Nirāhāra --a mountain kingdom. M. 114. 55. 

निरुक्त
Nirukta --the commentary of Jatukarṇya: Its author was Ratḥitara; 1) Bhā. XII. 6. 58; Br. II. 35. 3. rearranged by a pupil of Śākapūrṇa under his guidance; 2) Vi. III. 4. 23. part of Viṣṇu; 3) Ib. V. 1. 37. said to be the fourth Samhita; 4) Vā. 61. 2; 65. 28. authorship of, attributed to Rathitara. 5) Ib. 60. 65.

निरुत्सुक
Nirutsuka  (I): (Bhārgava)--a sage of the Raucya epoch (XII epoch-Vi. P.). Br. IV. 1. 102; Vi. III. 2. 40.

निरुत्सुक
Nirutsuka  (II)--a son of Raivata Manu. M. 9. 21.

निरृता
Nirṛtā --a daughter of Khaśā and a Rākṣasi. Br. III. 7. 138; Vā. 69. 170.

निरृति
Nirṛti  (I)--childless, adopted the twins of Adharma; 1) Bhā. IV. 8. 2; Vi. 3. 14. with his vehicle drawn by men went against Kṛṣṇa taking Pārijāta; but soon felt he could not fight Kṛṣṇa and went away quietly; 2) Ib. X. [65 (v) 42]; [66 (v) 36]. his town was visited by Arjuna in search of the dead child of the Dvārakā Brahmana. 3) Ib. X. 89. 44.

निरृति
Nirṛti  (II)--one of the western entrances to the city of Purañjana, leading to the country of Vaiśasa; allegorically guda. Bhā. IV. 25. 53; 29. 14.

निरृति
Nirṛti  (III)--a muhūrta of the day. Br. III. 3. 40, 70; Vā. 66. 41; 111. 40.

निरृति
Nirṛti  (IV)--one of the eleven Rudras with sword; 1) M. 171. 38; Vā. 66. 69. lord of a dik and a Rākṣasa who came and worshipped Lalītā, along with others. 2) Br. IV. 26. 53; 30. 9. 

निरृति
Nirṛti  (V)--found Kubera overwhelmed by Kujambha and took his sword for war; when he was about to be vanquished, Varuṇa tied down with noose the two hands of Kujambha; Mahiṣa defeated both Nirṛti and Varuṇa, released Kujambha; reported to Indra; 1) M. 150. 86, 126-8, 130-3. beaten by Tāraka. 2) Ib. 153. 180.

निरृति
Nirṛti  (VI)--a Vasu; a son of Dharma and Sudevī. M. 171. 47.

निरृति
Nirṛti  (VII)--as a lokapāla. M. 266. 22.

निरृति
Nirṛti  (VIII)--the God of the South-west. Vā. 108. 31.

निरृति
Nirṛtis --worshipped for the destruction of the foe; issued from the arms of Brahmā. Bhā. II. 3. 9; III. 12. 26.

निर्गुणा
Nirguṇā --a third mātra of Om. Vā. 20. 2.

निर्ग्रन्थ
Nirgranthas --a heretical sect of ascetics putting on monkish dress in Kali. Br. II. 31. 65; III. 14. 39; Vā. 58. 64; 78. 30.

निर्भय
Nirbhaya --a son of Raucya Manu. Br. IV. 1. 104; Vā. 100. 109.

निर्भया
Nirbhayā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 25.

निर्मम
Nirmama --a sense of detachment takes a man of Vairāgya; with ripe experience sees all life as sorrow. Vā. 102. 84-5. 

निर्मोक
Nirmoka: (Nirmoha) --a son of Manusāvarṇi; a sage of the epoch of the XIII Manu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 11, 31; Vā. 100. 21; Vi. III. 2. 19; Br. IV. 1. 22.

निर्मोह
Nirmoha  (I) (Kaśyapa)--a sage of the Raucya epoch. Br. IV. 1. 103.

निर्मोह
Nirmoha  (II)--a son of Raivata Manu. M. 9. 21.

निर्मोह
Nirmoha  (III)--a sage of the XII epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 40.

निर्यन्त्र
Niryantra --(Nirjatara Niryantara-Vā. P.) heard the Purāṇa from Gautama and told it to Vājaśravas; 1) Br. IV. 4. 63-4. heard the Vā. P. from Gautama. 2) Vā. 103. 63.

निर्वक्त्र
Nirvaktra --son of Adhisāmakṛṣṇa. Vā. 99. 271.

निर्वाक्
Nirvāk --a blind citizen of the Purañjana city aiding him in his work; allegorically the hands. Bhā. IV. 25. 54; 29. 15.

निर्वाण
Nirvāṇa --is mokṣa; 1) Bhā. III. 25. 28-29; VI. 4. 28; IX. 7. 27; Br. III. 56. 10. Vi. I. 20. 28 and 34; II. 8. 119; III. 18. 17; 8. 6. gained by doing the vibhūtīdvādaśivrata on the Ganges; 2) M. 100. 33. Prahlāda blessed with Nirvāṇa; 3) Vi. I. 19. 46. of Śatānīka; 4) Ib. IV. 21. 4. Mucukunda's request to Kṛṣṇa for Nirvāṇa. 5) Ib. V. 23. 47; VI. 7. 21. 2. 

निर्वाणरति
Nirvāṇaratis --the gods in the epoch of the III Śāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 73, 75.

निर्वाणरुचि
Nirvāṇarucis --Gods of the eleventh epoch of Manu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 25; Vi. III. 2. 30.

निर्विन्ध्या
Nirvindhyā --a R. from the Vindhyas; 1) M. 114. 27. Vā. 45. 102. in the Ṛkṣa Mt. in Bhāratavarṣa; 2) Bhā. IV. 1. 18; V. 19. 18; Br. II. 16. 32; Vi. II. 3. 11. visited by Balarāma. 3) Bhā. X. 79. 20.

निर्वृति
Nirvṛti  (I)--the son of Dhṛṣṭā(i) (Vṛṣṇi-Br. P.) the righteous, and father of Daśārha. Bhā. IX. 24. 3; Br. III. 70. 40.

निर्वृति
Nirvṛti  (II)--the son of Sunetra, ruled for 58 years. M. 271. 26.

निर्वृति
Nirvṛti --a son of Dhṛṣṭa and father of Vidūratha. M. 44. 39-40.

निर्हयु
Nirhayu --a deva. Vā. 31. 8.

निलायनक्रीडा
Nilāyanakrīḍā --a game of the Gopas in which the Gopas put on the guise of thieves, watchmen, and goats; Vyoma an Asura entered it in disguise and carried away almost all the Gopas to a cave near by; seeing only few left, Kṛṣṇa discovered the Asura and killed him at once. Bhā. X. 37. 26-32.

निवर्तनम्
Nivartanam --30 daṇḍas by a daṇḍa of 7 hastas. M. 283. 3, 14. 

निवात
Nivāta --a son of Śūra. Br. III. 71. 138; Vā. 96. 136.

निवातकवच
Nivātakavacas --the sons of Samhlāda; could not be slain by the Gods, Gandharvas, Nāgas and Rākṣasas; 1) M. 6. 28-9. Flourished in the age of Prahlāda; 2) Vi. I. 21. 14. A Dānava group of Rasātala, resident in Hiraṇyapura; 3) Bhā. V. 24. 30; X. 89. 34 (5) took part in the Devāsura war between Bali and Indra: fought with the Maruts; 4) Ib. VIII. 10. 22, 34. defeated by Arjuna. 5) Ib. X. 89. 34. (5); Br. III. 5. 37.

निवृत्ति
Nivṛtti  (I)--a R. in Śālmalidvīpa. Br. II. 19. 47; Vā. 49. 42; Vi. II. 4. 28.

निवृत्ति
Nivṛtti  (II)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 35. 98.

निवेशक
Niveśaka --a Yakṣagaṇa. Vā. 69. 39-40.

निशट
Niśaṭa --a son of Vasudeva and Rohiṇī. Vā. 96. 162.

निशठ
Niśaṭha(ta) --a son of Balarāma. Br. III. 71. 166; Vi. V. 25. 19.

निशा
Niśā  (I)--same as Sītā; a R. of the Kuśadvīpa. M. 122. 71.

निशा
Niśā  (II)--a daughter of Krodhā. Vā. 69. 205.

निशाकर
Niśākara --is Soma; 1) Br. II. 28. 43. full of ambrosia, the origin of Tithi, Parvasandhi, and Ṛg and Yajur metres; 2) Vā. 31. 40. 1000 Yojanas beyond the sun. 3) Ib. 101. 129. 

निसित
Nisita --a son of Balarāma. Vā. 96. 164.

निशिथ
Niśitha --a son of Doṣa and Puṣparṇā; 1) Bhā. IV. 13. 14. stationed to defend the E. gate of Mathurā; 2) Ib. X. 50. 20 [2];. fought with his kinsmen at Prabhāsa. 3) Ib. XI. 30. 17.

निशिथा
Niśithā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 32. 12.

निशुम्भ
Niśumbha --the son of Gaveṣṭhi; 1) Vā. 67. 77. took part in the Devāsura war between Bali and Indra; 2) Bhā. VIII. 10. 21, 31. fought with Bhadrakāli and was killed; 3) Br. IV. 29. 76. killed by Yoganidrā. 4) Vi. V. 1. 82.

निश्चर
Niścara (Paulastya) --a sage of the epoch of the III Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 79.

निश्चल
Niścala --a son of Atri, and one of the seven sages of the Svārociṣa epoch. Br. II. 36. 18.

निश्चीरा
Niścīrā --a R. of the Bhāratavarṣa. Vā. 45. 96.

निश्रव्यवन
Niśravyavana --a sage of the Svārociṣa epoch. M. 9. 8. 

निषदवान्
Niṣadavān --seventh note of the gamut; 1) Vā. 86. 37. origin in Niṣāda kalpa. 2) Ib. 21. 46.

निषध
Niṣadha  (I)--a son of Atithi and father of Nabha. (Anala-Vi. P.). The Br. P. makes him father of Nala. 2) Br. III. 63. 201-2. ^1 Bhā. IX. 12. 1; M. 12. 52; Vā. 88. 201; Vi. IV. 4. 105.

निषध
Niṣadha  (II)--a varṣaparvata; 1) Br. I. 1. 69; M. 113. 12, 22; 121. 66; 183. 1; Vā. 1. 85. Vi. II. 2. 28 and 39. a mountain range on the base of Meru and to the south of Ilāvṛta and a boundary of Harivarṣa; 2) Bhā. V. 16. 9, 26; Vā. 34. 14 and 25. migration of the Yadus to; 3) Bhā. 2. 3; Br. II. 15. 15 and 28. residence of the Vānaras and Nāgas; 4) Ib. II. 17. 34; III. 7. 194; IV. 31. 16. location of the Viṣṇu temple in. 5) Vā. 35. 8; 36. 19; 37. 28; 41. 48.

निषध
Niṣadhas  (I)--(also Naiṣadhas) contemporary rulers of the Āndhras, Kauśalas, and Vidūrapatis. Bhā. XII. 1. 35.

निषध
Niṣadhas  (II)--a Janapada of the Maṇidhānya. 1) Vā. 99. 384. On the other side of the Vindhyas. 2) Ib. 45. 133.

निषधन
Niṣadhana --a Marut gaṇa. M. 171. 53.

निषधा
Niṣadhā --a R. from the Vindhyas. Br. II. 16. 32; Vā. 45. 102.

निषधाधिपति
Niṣadhādhipati --an ally of Kārtavīrya, killed by Paraśurāma. Br. III. 39. 2, 8. 

निषधाश्व
Niṣadhāśva --a son of Kuru. Bhā. IX. 22. 4.

निषाद
Niṣāda  (I)--the black and dwarfish man who came out of the churning of the thigh of the dead Vena by the sages; the ancestor of the Naiṣadas, the Vindhyan tribe. Bhā. IV. 14. 45-46; Vi. I. 13. 35-6.

निषाद
Niṣāda  (II)--a son of Vasudeva; the first bowman; 1) Vā. 96. 184, 187. hunter. 2) Ib. 47. 51.

निषाद
Niṣāda  (III)--20th kalpa; Prajāpati Niṣāda performed austerities controlling the senses for a thousand divine years; seeing the son getting wearied by penance Brahmā said: “refrain from it,” hence the name, Niṣāda. Out of him came Niṣādavānsvara. Vā. 21. 43.

निषाधवंशकर्त
Niṣādhavaṃśakarta --the dwarfed black male arising out of the churning by the sages of the left hand of Vena; the residuals of the Vindhyas belonged to this; 1) Br. II. 36. 144-6. born of him were Dhīvara and others. 2) Vā. 62. 123.

निष्क
Niṣka --a gold coin for gifts; 1) M. 77. 11; Vā. 80. 16. sin, a fine for wounding or hurting; 2) M. 227. 86; Vā. 101. 160. necklace? 3) Bhā. III. 23. 31. Bala staked 1000 at the first game of gambling, another 1000 at the second and one crore at the succeeding one. 4) Vi. V. 28. 13-14, 18.

निष्कुट
Niṣkuṭa --groves as frequented by Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 404. 

निष्कुलाद
Niṣkulāda --an asura who has his city in Tatvalam. Br. II. 20. 17.

निष्कुलादपुरम्
Niṣkulādapuram --the city in the first tala; of an Asura chief. Vā. 50. 16.

निष्क्रिय
Niṣkriya --a class of ascetics. Bhā. III. 12. 43.

निष्टकर्मन्
Niṣṭakarman --a king who ruled for 25 years. Br. III. 74. 164.

निष्टीवी
Niṣṭīvī --a R. from the Himālayas. Br. II. 16. 26.

निष्ठा
Niṣṭhā --in the Pāṇigrahaṇa mantra in the seventh Pāda; known to Satyavrata. Vā. 88. 97.

निष्ठुर
Niṣṭhura --a mantrakāra and an Ātreya. Vā. 59. 104.

निष्पापा
Niṣpāpā --a R. of the Plakṣadvīpa. Vā. 49. 17.

निष्पाव
Niṣpāva --one of the eight saubhāgyams. M. 60. 8, 27.

निष्प्रकम्य
Niṣprakam(p)ya --(Ātreya) a sage of the Raucya epoch (XIII epoch Vi. P.). Br. IV. 1. 103; Vi. III. 2. 40. 

निसुन्द
Nisunda --a son of Hrāda; had two sons Sunda and Upasunda. Br. III. 5. 34; Vā. 67. 71.

निश्शेष
Niśśeṣa Kalpa --of Brahmā; the period twice the thousand of 1000 yugas and all antaras. Vā. 100. 212.

निस्वर
Nisvara --a sage of the XI epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 31.

नीति
Nīti --the policy taught by Śukra to the Asuras and sought by him from Maheśvara; 1) M. 47. 74, 75; Vā. 97. 105. according to Bṛhaspati, it commences with sāma for a conquering monarch; other angas are bheda, dāna, and daṇḍa; but the application depends on the place, time and resources of the enemy; in the case of Asuras only daṇḍa can be recommended. 2) M. 148. 65-71.

नीतिन
Nītina --a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 20.

नीतिशास्त्रम्
Nītiśāstram --of Śukra; 1) Br. III. 7. 191; 72. 107. Prahlāda trained in. 2) Vi. I. 19. 26-28, 34-49.

नीदाघ
Nīdāgha --son of Pulastya; initiated into jñāna by Ṛbhu. Engaged himself in austerities for a thousannd years in a grove in Vīranagara on the banks of the Devikā. After this period at the time of taking meals, Ṛbhu appeared before him, but was not recognised. Being requested for meals, Ṛbhu agreed on condition that he would be served with sweet viands. After meals, he found that he was his old master, and was overjoyed. He went away, and Nīdāgha continued his austerities for another 1000 years. At the end  of this period Ṛbhu appeared and saw him standing aloof from a crowd witnessing the king riding on his elephant. Ṛbhu asked him who was the king and who was the elephant. Nidāgha said that the man above was king and that below the elephant. Ṛbhu asked him what he meant by above and below. Little knowing that he was his master, Nīdāgha jumped on him and remarked he was above and Ṛbhu below. Finding that Nīdāgha had not attained full maturity in advaita, Ṛbhu once again initiated him and departed. From that day Nīdāgha looked upon anything without any distinction. Vi. II. chh. 15 and 16.

नीप
Nīpa  (I)--a son of Pāra (Paura-M. P.) wife Kṛtvī; father of 100 sons, Nīpās; Aṇuhasatyaka? was the eldest; among the others were Srīmān who was well known and was destroyed by Ugrasena (Ugrāyudha-Vā. P.) for the sake of Janamejaya; Brahmadatta was another son. Bhā. IX. 21. 24-25; M. 49. 52, 59; Vā. 99. 174-5.

नीप
Nīpa  (II)--the son of Kṛtin and father of Ugrāyudha. Bhā. IX. 21. 29.

नीप
Nīpas --100 sons of Nīpa, among whom Srīmān was the most celebrated; destroyed by Ugrāyudha for the sake of Janamejaya; 1) M. 49. 53, 59; Vi. IV. 19. 54. a tribe. 2) M. 273. 73.

नीपप्रिया
Nīpapriyā --is Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 34.

नीरमित्र
Nīramitra --a son of Nakuli by Kareṇumatī. M. 50. 55.

नीराजन
Nīrājana --(waving of lights) taken by the Apsarasas at the marriage of Kāmeśvara and Devī; one way of honouring deity. Br. IV. 15. 33; M. 267. 19. 

नील
Nīla  (I)--a mountain range in Bhāratavarṣa and to the north of Ilāvṛta; formed the boundary limit of Ramyaka; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 8; 19. 16; M. 113. 22; Vā. 34. 20, 25; 35. 8. one of the six varṣaparvatas in Jambūdvīpa; diamond like; 2) Br. I. 1. 69; II. 15. 22, 28; 17. 35; Vā. 1. 85; 42. 67; 46. 34. residence of the monkey tribes; 3) Br. III. 7. 194; IV. 31. 17. the residence of Brahmaṛṣis.

नील
Nīla  (II)--a monkey chief, a friend of Rāma; followed Rāma in the Lankā expedition. Bhā. IX. 10. 16, 19.

नील
Nīla  (III)--a Rākṣasa resident in Sutalam. Br. II. 20. 22; Vā. 50. 22.

नील
Nīla  (IV)--one of the five sons of Yadu. Br. III. 69. 2; M. 43. 7; Vā. 94. 2.

नील
Nīla  (V)--a king of Pāñcāla, slain by Ugrāyudha; 1) M. 49. 78; Vā. 99. 192. son of Ajamidha and Nīlinī; by great austerities Suśānti (ŚantiBhā. P.) was born. 2) Bhā. IX. 21. 30; M. 50. 1; Vā. 99. 194; Vi. IV. 19. 56-7.

नील
Nīla  (VI)--a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 19.

नीला
Nīlā  (VII)--one of the eight nidhis of Kubera. Vā. 41. 10.

नील
Nīla  (VIII)--a Kulaparvata of the Bhadrāśva; 1) Vā. 43. 14; 48. 8; Vi. I. 4. 26; II. 2. 39. bordering on Jambūdvīpa. 2) Ib. II. 1. 20; 2. 11. 

नील
Nīla  (IX)--a son of Pāra; father of a hundred sons. Vi. IV. 19. 38-39.

नील
Nīla  (X)--of Vānarajāti, born of Hari and Pulaha. Br. III. 7. 176, 319.

नील
Nīla  (XI)--a Parāśara clan. Br. III. 8. 95; Vā. 70. 87.

नीलक
Nīlaka --the name of the Rākṣasas in the Vajraka hill. Vā. 39. 31.

नीलकण्ठ
Nīlakaṇṭha --the God enshrined in Kālañjara hill; an epithet of Śiva; 1) M. 20. 15; 157. 23. narrated to Pārvatī that at the request of Brahmā and other gods he devoured the Kālakūṭa poison that came out of the churning of the ocean; 2) Br. II. 25. 90; Vā. 54. 3-94. praise of, by Rāma; 3) Br. II. 24. 25-31. by gods. 4) Vā. 54. 97-101.

नीलकुण्डम्
Nīlakuṇḍam --a tīrtham; sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 22.

नीलग्रीव
Nīlagrīva --is Rudra. Br. IV. 34. 27.

नीलपताका
Nīlapatākā --an Akṣarādevī; killed Jambukākṣa a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 19. 59; 25. 98, 37. 34.

नीलपर्वतम्
Nīlaparvatam --a tīrtham sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 70; 121. 68.

नीलम्
Nīlam  (I)--the kingdom of Ramya. Br. II. 14. 50; 15. 33; Vā. 33. 44. 

नीलम्
Nīlam  (II)--to be uttered in installing an image. M. 265. 28.

नीलमुखाह्
Nīlamukhāh (c) --a kingdom of the East watered by the Hlādinī; 1) Br. II. 18. 54; M. 121. 53. a tribe. 2) Vā. 47. 51.

नीललोहित
Nīlalohita  (I)--(Śiva, Mahādeva); 1) Br. III. 72. 109; 73. 1; Vā. 21. 4; 31. 32 and 59. praised by Śukra by as many as 300 names for His blessings on him. 2) M 47. 127-169.

नीललोहित
Nīlalohita  (II)--the second kalpa. M. 290. 3.

निलशैलेय
Nilaśaileya --(Nīlamauleya) a Janapada of the Bhadra continent. Vā. 43. 19.

नीलवत्
Nīlavat --a son of Anjanā, an elephant. Br. III. 7. 339.

नीला
Nīlā --a daughter of Keśinī, and a low type of Rākṣasī; gave birth to Kṣudra Rākṣasas called after her the Naila clan. Br. III. 7. 7. 147. Vā. 69. 178, 181.

नीलिनी
Nīlinī  (I)--one of the queens of Ajamīḍha. M. 49. 44; Vā. 99. 167.

नीलिनी
Nīlinī  (II)--mother of Nīla. Vā. 99. 194.

नीलोत्पला
Nīlotpalā --a R. of the Bhāratavarṣa. Vā. 45. 100. 

नीवार
Nīvāra --a kind of corn for śrāddha; 1) M. 15. 35. used as food by foresters and offered by Śakuntalā to Duṣyanta. 2) Bhā. IX. 20. 14.

नीहार
Nīhāra --the place where elephants of the four quarters throw out the waters in different ways. Br. II. 22. 52.

नीहिर
Nīhiras --a hill tribe. Br. II. 16. 67.

नूतन
Nūtana --the name of the varṣanāḍi or ray of the sun. Vā. 53. 20.

नूपा
Nūpā --a R. from the Pāriyātra. Br. II. 16. 28.

नृग
Nṛga  (I)--a son of Śrāddhadeva and Śraddhā and father of a son Sumati by name. Bhā. IX. 1. 12; 2. 17.

नृग
Nṛga  (II)--a son of Ikṣvāku; liberal in his gift of cows, silver, etc. Once a cow of a certain Brahmana got mixed up with his herd, and ignorant of this he made a gift of it to another Brahmana. The owner charged him, and when both went to the king, the owner was not prepared to take anything in its place and he who got the gift would not part with it for anything; when he went to Yama's abode he sent him as a lizard for this unrighteous act; in that form he lived in a well until Kṛṣṇa lifted it up when it became transformed into a celestial, and blessed by Kṛṣṇa rode in an aerial car to heaven; 1) Bhā. X. 64. 10-30, 43 and 44 [1]. release of, by Kṛṣṇa at Dvārakā; 2) Ib. X. 37. 17. his lust after more territory. 3) Ib. XII. 3. 10. 

नृग
Nṛga  (III)--a son of Vaivasvata Manu. Br. II. 38. 30; III. 60. 2; Vi. III. 1. 33; IV. 1. 7.

नृग
Nṛga  (IV)--a son of Uśīnara and Nṛgā (Bhṛśā, M. P.); his capital, Yaudheya; became lord of the Kekayas. Br. III. 74. 19, 21; M. 48. 18, 20, 20; Vi. IV. 18. 9.

नृगा
Nṛgā --one of the wives of Uśīnara and mother of Nṛga. Br. III. 74. 18-9.

नृचक्षुस्
Nṛcakṣus --a son of Sunītha and father of Sukhīnala. Bhā. IX. 22. 41; M. 50. 82.

नृत्य
Nṛtya --dancing; part of Viśokadvādaśivrata; 1) M. 82. 29. in connection with tree rituals; 2) Ib. 232. 15. in connection with Vāstu for palace building. 3) Ib. 268. 34.

नृदेव
Nṛdeva --the father of Pramati, God incarnate. M. 144. 59.

नृपचक्षु
Nṛpacakṣu --son of Sunitha and father of Sukhibala. Vi. IV. 21. 12.

नृपञ्जय
Nṛpañjaya  (I)--the son of Medhāvin and father of Dūrva. Bhā. IX. 22. 42.

नृपञ्जय
Nṛpañjaya  (II)--a son of Sunitha (Suvīra-Vā. P.). M. 49. 79; Vā. 99. 193.

नृमहिषा
Nṛmahiṣā --the daughter of Hamsakīla. Vā. 66. 73. 

नृम्णा
Nṛmṇā --a R. in Plakṣadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 4.

नृसिम्ह
Nṛsimha --(Nṛhari and Narahari Narasimham (s.v.) half man and half lion avatār of Viṣṇu, worshipped as such in Harivarṣa; 1) Bhā. II. 7. 14; V. 18. 7-14; VII. 8. 15-16; X. 2. 40; Vi. V. 5. 16. came out of a post which Hiraṇyakaśipu knocked with his fist; a description of his form and how he killed the demon; 2) Bhā. VII. 8. 15-31; XI. 4. 19. still his anger was not appeased; praised by Brahmā, Rudra, Indra, Sages, Pitṛs, Siddhas, Vidyādharas, Nāgas, progenitors, Gandharvas, Cāraṇas, Yakṣas, Kimpuruṣas, Vaitālikas, Kinnaras, and Viṣṇu's attendants; 3) Ib. VII. 8. 34 and 40-56. Śrī was afraid to go near him; 4) Ib. VII. 9. 2. at the request of the Gods Prahlāda praised the God for the welfare of the universe; offered boons to Prahlāda and advised him to rule his father's kingdom with his mind devoted to Hari until the time came for him to cast off his body; 5) Ib. V. 18. 7-14; VI. 8. 14; VII. 9 (whole); 10. 11-14. Brahmā's praise of the Lord's disappearance. 6) Ib. VII. 10. 26-31; Br. III. 33. 26. God incarnate of Viṣṇu remembered by Śiva for vanquishing mātṛgaṇa; 7) M. 179. 44-52, 76. created from out of his limbs a number of goddesses who overcame the Rudra, mātṛgaṇas and were blessed with divinity. 8) Ib. 245. 21.

नृसिम्हभैरवा
Nṛsimhabhairavā --a goddess following Bhavamālinī. M. 179. 71.

नेतिष्य
Netiṣya --one of the Bhārgava gotrakāras. M. 195. 27.

नेत्र
Netra --a son of Dharma and father of Kunti. Bhā. IX. 23. 22.

नेत्रवन्
Netravan --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 244. 

नेपाल
Nepāla (c) --sacred to Lalitā and hence to be included in the cakra. Br. IV. 44. 93.

नेपालपीथम्
Nepālapītham --one of the eyes of the Veda personified. Vā. 104. 79.

नेपालकम्बल
Nepālakambala --fit for śrāddham. M. 22. 86.

नेमि
Nemi  (I)--a Rākṣasa was asked by Bali to refrain from battle with Vāmana. Bhā. VIII. 21. 19.

नेमि
Nemi  (II)--a Sutapa God. Br. IV. 1. 14.

नेमि
Nemi  (III)--one of the sons of Ikṣvāku; a righteous king cursed by Vasiṣṭha to lose his body. Vā. 88. 9; 89. 3-4.

नेमिकृष्ण
Nemikṛṣṇa --a son of Āpādabaddha; ruled for 25 years. Vā. 99. 352.

नेमिचक्र
Nemicakra --the son of Āsīmakṛṣṇa and father of Ukta; Hastināpura being washed away he changed his capital to Kauśāmbī. Bhā. IX. 22. 39-40.

नेष्टा
Neṣṭā --one of the 16 Ṛtviks for yajña; created from the thighs of Nārāyaṇa. M. 167. 9. 

नैकजिह्व
Naikajihva --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 27.

नैकवक्त्र
Naikavaktra --the hump-backed Kubja in the employ of Kamsa for preparing perfumes. Kṛṣṇa got some for the mere asking. Pleased, Kṛṣṇa cured her deformity and made her a lovely damsel. She requested Kṛṣṇa to go to her residence, which he promised to do sometime later. Vi. V. 20. 4-13.

नैकशि
Naikaśi --a Bhārgava. M. 195. 33.

नैका
Naikās (Nailās) --born of Nila; belong to a branch of the Ālambeyas; invincible and bold. Vā. 69. 179.

नैगमेय
Naigameya --a son of Agni and brother of Kumāra; an amśa of Skanda. Br. III. 3. 25; M. 5. 26; Vā. 66. 24. 101. 280. Vi. I. 15. 115.

नैतुण्ड
Naituṇḍas --a Piśāca clan. Vā. 69. 264

नैदुन्द
Naidunda(ka)s --a Gaṇa of Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 383, 389.

नैध्रुव
Naidhruva --a Brahmavādin. Br. II. 32. 112; M. 145. 106.

नैमित्तिक
Naimittika --a form of Pralaya, which is dissolution of the universe after a kalpa; 1) Bhā. XII. 4. 4, 38; Vi. VI. 3. 1; 4. 7. one of the three kinds of samcāra (movements of creatures). 2) Vā. 1. 161; 100. 132. 

नैमित्तिककल्प
Naimittikakalpa --a division of the Brāhmakalpa. Vā. 100. 133, 196.

नैमित्तिकम्
Naimittikam --one of the three kinds of Śrāddha. M. 16. 5.

नैमिश
Naimiśa --a R.: a fit place for performing Śrāddha. Vi. III. 14. 18.

नैमिष
Naimiṣa --the southern sun; 1) Vā. 109. 21. a tīrtha for performing Śrāddha. 2) Ib. 106. 67

नैमिषक
Naimiṣakas--(c)  country of: under Maṇidhānyaka kings. Vi. IV. 24. 66.

नैमिषा
Naimiṣā --(also Naimiṣālaya s.v.) sacred to Viṣṇu; here Śaunaka and other sages performed a satra extending over a thousand years; 1) Bhā. I. 1. 4 and 21; III. 20. 7; VII. 14. 31; Br. IV. 4. 45. visited by Balarāma who was honoured by all except Śūta Romaharṣaṇa; Balarāma killed the Śūta in anger thus committing brahmicide; then at the instance of the sages and as an expiation for the offence he killed Asura Balvala here; 2) Bhā. X. 78. 20-32; 79. 5. revisited by Balarāma who took part in the sacrifices; 3) Ib. X. 79. 30-32. sages of, visited Dvārakā. 4) Ib. X. 90. 28. [6]. Br. I. 1. 37; III. 13. 100; IV. 2. 111 and 246; 4. 41.

नैमिषारण्यम्
Naimiṣāraṇyam --a Kṣetra and forest; a tīrtha where Goddess Lingadhāriṇī is enshrined; 1) M. 1. 4; 13. 26. best in Kṛtayuga; 2) Ib. 106. 57; 109. 3; 110. 1; 180. 55; 246. 93. sacred to the Piṭrs; here the spokes of Haricakra (DharmacakraVā. P.) fell to pieces; here is the image of Viṣṇu in Vārāha form; 3) Ib. 22. 12, 14; Vā. 1. 15. the sage Pipplāda living there was questioned by  Yudhiṣṭhira about Aṅgārakavrata; 4) M. 72, 2, Br. I. 2. 8; Vā. 2. 8; 21. 1; 23. 206; 77. 93; 108. 40 and 42. the forest where the seers performed sacrifices.^5

नैमिषालय
Naimiṣālaya --here Sūta expounded the Bhāgavata to the sages and seers at the request of Śaunaka and others. See Naimiṣā. Bhā. XII. 4. 43.

नैमिषेय
Naimiṣeyas --the sages and performers of penance in Naimiṣā forest. Vā. 67. 1; 101. 111, 292, 309; 103. 40, 42 and 46.

नैरृत
Nairṛta --a Rākṣasa Gaṇa from Nirṛti; the followers of Kubera; hence Devarākṣasas. Vā. 69. 173.

नैरृत
Nairṛtas --one of the four Rākṣasa clans after Nairṛta, moving about during nights: followers of Trayambaka: Devarākṣasas, heroic and valourous, with their leader Vīrūpākṣa: Alakādhipa was their king; 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 48; Br. III. 7. 141-4, 163; 8. 62. sons of Revatī and Pūtanā: overlord Skanda: gave trouble to babies. 2) Ib. III. 7. 439; Vā. 84. 14.

नैरृति
Nairṛti  (I)--a town of Nirṛti; 1) Bhā. X. 89. 44. bali to be given to Nirṛti in Śrāddha. 2) Vā. 111. 40.

नैरृति
Nairṛti  (II)--a Lokapāla: Image of. M. 261. 15-6; 266. 22; 286. 8.

नैरृती
Nairṛtī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 10. 

नैर्णिक
Nairṇika --a southern country. Vā. 45. 127.

नैल
Naila --a Śrutaṛṣi. Br. II. 33. 4.

नैल
Nailas --a Rākṣasa clan of low type, born of Nīla. Br. III. 7. 148.

नैश्रेयसम्
Naiśreyasam --the name of a garden in Vaikuṇṭha. Bhā. III. 15. 16.

नैषध
Naiṣadha --Nala of the Kaśyapa family entitled as N. Lust of, after more territory. M. 12. 56; Bhā. XII. 3. 10.

नैषधम्
Naiṣadham(c) --a kingdom of Harivarṣa; 1) Br. II. 14. 49; 15. 32; 18. 53. Vā. 33. 42. a division of Jambūdvīpa; 2) Vi. II. 1. 19. also Niṣadha. 3) Ib. II. 2. 11.

नैषध
Naiṣadhas  (I)--a tribe whose ancestor was Niṣāda and who made mountains and forests their home; 1) Bhā. IV. 14. 46; Br. III. 74. 189 and 196; M. 114. 53. a Vindhyan tribe; 2) Br. II. 16. 65. kingdom of. 3) M. 121. 52.

नैषध
Naiṣadhas  (II)--the kings of the family of Nala; 1) Vā. 99. 376-7. nine kings of, under Maṇidhānyaka line. 2) Vi. IV. 24. 60, 66.

नैष्ठीय
Naiṣṭhīya --the place of Kavi Agni (Uśīra). Vā. 29. 29. 

नौ
Nau --the boat in the Ocean; in the river; 1) Vā. 6. 27; 52. 86; 108. 37. illustrative of the earth floating on waters. 2) Vi. I. 4. 46.

नौ
Nau --(Mahīmayī) the divine boat given to Manu (Vaivasvata) by Viṣṇu in the shape of a fish to be tied to its horn; 1) M. 1. 30-32; Bhā. I. 3. 15. in the deluge it rescued the sun, moon, Brahmā, Narmadā, sage Mārkaṇḍeya, Śiva, the Vedas, Purāṇas and other Vidyas from ruin; 2) M. 2. 10-15. Druhyu to ply the ocean with. 3) Ib. 33. 20.

न्यग्रोध
Nyagrodha  (I)--a son of Ugrasena; 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 24; Br. III. 71. 133; M. 44. 74; Vā. 96. 132; Vi. IV. 14. 20. and brother of Kamsa killed by Balarāma. 2) Bhā. X. 44. 40-41.

न्यग्रोध
Nyagrodha  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 90. 34.

न्यग्रोध
Nyagrodha  (III)--the banyan tree of Ramaṇaka; of the shape of a lotus after which Puṣkaradvīpa is named; 1) Br. II. 15. 63-4; 19. 140; III. 11. 36, 109; IV. 43. 17; M. 123. 39; Vi. I. 12. 65; II. 4. 85; IV. 3. 23. during the deluge, Lord Nārāyaṇa in the form of a baby slept on a leaf of the tree. 2) M. 167. 31.

न्यग्रोधारोहिण
Nyagrodhā-rohiṇa --the city of the Yakṣas. Br. III. 7. 118; Vā. 69. 149.

न्यर्बुदम्
Nyarbudam --10 times the arbuda. Vā. 101. 101.

न्याय
Nyāya --a Śāstra; a servant of the Veda; 1) M. 3. 4; 53. 5; Vā. 2. 33; 61. 78; 104. 85; Vi. III. 6. 27; V. 1. 38. learnt by Kṛṣṇa and Balarāma; 2) Bhā. X. 45. 34. by Asuras. 3) Br. II. 35. 87; IV. 12. 17. 

न्यास
Nyāsa(mantra) --in connection with the installation of an image; eg. Ratnanyāsa for the eight directions: diamond, pearl, vaiḍūrya, conch, spaṭika, puṣparāga, indranīla and nīla; pastes of eight kinds: tālaka, śilāvajra, collyrium, śyāma, kañji, kāśi, mākṣikam, and gairikam; grains of eight kinds: wheat, barley, seasamum, mudga, nīvāra, śyāmaka, sarṣapa, and vrīhirice, scents like sandal, red sandal, agaru, añjanam, uśīram, vaiṣṇavī sahadevī, and Lakṣmaṇa; metals of eight kinds: gold, vidruma, copper, bronze, ārakūṭaka, silver, puṣpam and iron. Then the worship of the Lokhapālas with Nyāsamantras. M. 266. 9-29.

न्यास
Nyāsa --a Saimhikeya. Vā. 68. 18.

न्यासि
Nyāsi --see Yati and Bhikṣu. Br. II. 7. 181; Vā. 106. 18.  Pa and Pha

पक्ष
Pakṣa  (I)--a lunar period of 15 days; Śukla (white) and Kṛṣṇa (dark). Br. II. 21. 125; 24. 56; 28. 33; III. 1. 59; Vā. 30. 15; 49. 130; 50. 178; 56. 3 and 30.

पक्ष
Pakṣa  (II)--a Maṇivara Yakṣa and son of Devajanī. Br. III. 7. 129.

पक्ष
Pakṣa  (III)--of Bhārgava gotra. Vā. 65. 97.

पक्ष
Pakṣa  (IV)--a son of Anu. Vā. 99. 13

पक्षगन्त
Pakṣaganta --a Śrutaṛṣi. Br. II. 33. 4.

पक्षि
Pakṣi --a species of birds vanquished by Rāvaṇa; the name of a mūrchana after their name. Br. III. 7. 256, 307; 61. 52; IV. 4. 2.

पक्षिणी
Pakṣiṇī --a śakti on the ṣoḍaśa--patrābja. Br. IV. 32. 11.

पंकजवनम्
Paṃkajavanam --the name of a sacred forest; here is Pāṇḍuśilā fit for the performance of śrāddha; Yudhiṣṭhira performed śrāddha at the place; pleased at it Pāṇḍu blessed his son to rule the kingdom and go to heaven. Vā. 112. 43-49.

पंक्ति
Paṃkti --a metre: a Chandas. Bhā. XI. 21. 41; Br. II. 22. 72; M. 125. 47; Vā. 51. 65. Vi. II. 8. 5. 

पंक्तिपावन
Paṃktipāvana --Persons eminently fit to eat with; learned in six Angas, given to dhyāna and yoga; learned in tantras, and Yāyāvara: Also Sauparṇas, Pañcāgneyas, Sāmagas, Trināciketas, Trayīs, learned in Bārhaspatyaśāśtra; 1) Br. III. 15. 28-30. unfit: Anāśrami, Ayati, Mokṣavādi, Citravādi, heretics, atheists, Sānkhyas, Muṇḍa, Jaṭila, Kāpāḷikas, Kārukas, Songsters, sellers of Veda etc., persons not conforming to the rules of varṇa and āśrama. 2) Ib. III. 15. 39-55, 94; Vā. 79. 53-59; 83. 51-57.

पञ्चक
Pañcakas --a royal line established by Viśvasphāṇi. Vā. 99. 378.

पञ्चकाम
Pañcakāmas --Kāmarāja, Kandarpa, Manmatha, Makaradhvaja, and Manobhava; all decked with Kastūri tilaka and pearls. Br. IV. 19. 69.

पञ्चकूट
Pañcakūṭa --a Mt. inside Kailāsa; 1) Vā. 38. 33. the residence of the Dānavas. 2) Ib. 39. 53; 42. 32.

पञ्चगतय
Pañcagatayas --the Yajña leading to Devas; Tapas to Vairāgya; Karmasannyāsa to Brāhmaṇya; Vairāgya to Laya; Jñāna to Kaivalya. Vā. 57. 117-18.

पञ्चगव्यम्
Pañcagavyam --a mixture of 5 secretions of the cow for purifying the body; 1) M. 56. 6; 57, 5; 60. 17; 62. 8. milk, curd, ghee, urine and dung of the cow, constituents; 2) Ib. 266. 6; 267. 5-6; Vā. 110. 15. a panacea for stealing eatables, fruits and flowers, vehicles and beds; 3) M. 227. 44. ablution of image to be installed by. 4) Ib. 265. 8.

पञ्चगुणा
Pañcaguṇās --these are śabda, sparśa, rūpa, rasa and gandha. Vā. 4. 68. 

पञ्चचूडा
Pañcacūḍā --an Apsaras. Br. III. 7. 14.

पञ्चजन
Pañcajana  (I)--an asura in the form of a conch in the Prabhāsa. Son of Samhrāda and Kṛtī, and father of Asikni. He seized the son of Sāndipana (or Sāndīpanī) and devoured him. Kṛṣṇa plunged into the sea and killing him, removed the conch which covered his body. 1) Bhā. III. 3. 2; VI. 4. 51; 18. 14; X. 45. 40-42. Vi. V. 21. 27-8. Killed in Prāgjyotiṣa. 2) Ib. V. 29. 19.

पञ्चजन
Pañcajana  (II)--a son of Sagara. Br. III. 63. 147.

पञ्चजन
Pañcajana  (III)--the father of Amśumān and fatherin-law of Yaśodā. M. 15. 18.

पञ्चजनी
Pañcajanī --the daughter of Viśvarūpa and queen of Bharata. Bhā. V. 7. 1.

पञ्चजन्य
Pañcajanya --an Upadvīpa to Jambūdvīpa. Bhā. V. 19. 30.

पञ्चतीर्थम्
Pañcatīrtham --the name of a tīrtha in Kāñcī. Br. IV. 40. 60; 71, 115.

पञ्चतीर्थ
Pañcatīrtha --in Gayā. Vā. 111. 1, 21.

पञ्चदशम्
Pañcadaśam --a svara variety of a sāma. Br. II. 8. 51, 52; Vā. 9. 49.

पञ्चदशाक्षरी
Pañcadaśākṣarī --to be repeated 1008 times to get rid of sins; of the mantraśāstra, non-Vedic. Br. IV. 8. 36, 58. 

पञ्चदशी
Pañcadaśī  (I)--the fifteenth day of the Māgha month fit for performing sādhāraṇa śrāddha; 1) M 17. 2, 4. of the Āṣāda month for making gift of a cow. 2) Ib. 53. 24.

पञ्चदशी
Pañcadaśī  (II)--the day when the Pitṛs drink the rays of the moon. Vā. 52. 69; 56. 59.

पञ्चधाराशिक्ष
Pañcadhārāśikṣas --the five modes of training horses for war. Br. IV. 16. 20.

पञ्चनद
Pañcanada --the sacred place for the performance of śrāddha, at the confluence of the Sindhu and the ocean; 1) Br. III. 13. 57; Vā. 77. 56. Arjuna halted here on his way to Indraprastha from Dvārakā. 2) Vi. V. 38-12.

पञ्चनदेश्वर
Pañcanadeśvara --stationed by Jarāsandha at the southern gate of Mathurā. Bhā. X. 50. 11. [4].

पञ्चनिधनम्
Pañcanidhanam --a sūkta of the Sāma Samhita to be recited when a tank is dug. M. 58. 36.

पञ्चपञ्चात्म
Pañcapañcātma --a reference to 25 truths (tatvas) (in śloka 33) which arose out of the union of Devī with Puruṣa. Br. IV. 8. 29.

पञ्चपदी
Pañcapadī --a R. in Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 26.

पञ्चपापिन
Pañcapāpinas --the five great sinners. Vā. 108. 84; 111. 54. 

पञ्चबाण
Pañcabāṇa --a name of the God of love. M. 20. 29.

पञ्चब्रह्मस्वरूपिणी
Pañcabrahmasvarūpiṇī --is Lalitā. Br. IV. 15. 9.

पञ्चम
Pañcama  (I)--a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 51.

पञ्चम
Pañcama  (II)--outside the pale of the four āśramas: a mixed caste. Br. III. 15. 37.

पञ्चम
Pañcama  (III)--the twenty-first Kalpa; consisting of Prāṇa, apāna, samāna, udāna, and vyāna; mind-born sons of Brahmā. Vā. 21. 47.

पञ्चम
Pañcama  (IV)--the fifth note in music. Vā. 21. 49. 86. 37.

पञ्चम
Pañcama  (V)--a pupil of Hiraṇyanābha's son; a Sāmaga. Vā. 61. 44.

पञ्चमी
Pañcamī --a name of Lalitā; a śaktī. Br. IV. 17. 18; 36. 25.

पञ्चमुख
Pañcamukha --a name of Brahmā: for saying that, he saw the beginning of an effulgence of light in the form of a sthambha, which Mahesvara assumed; for not seeing it, Siva--Bhairava removed one of Brahmā's faces; hence Caturmukha from that day onwards. Br. IV. 40. 48, 56. 

पञ्चयाम
Pañcayāma --a son of Ātapa and grandson of the Vasu, Vibhāvasu; it is on account of him that all creatures perform their functions. Bhā. VI. 6. 16.

पञ्चरथ
Pañcaratha  (I)--a monkey chief. Br. III. 7. 239.

पञ्चरथ
Pañcaratha  (II)--a monkey chief. Br. III. 7. 235.

पञ्चरथ
Pañcaratha  (II)--a title conferred on able warriors as Surasena and others. Br. III. 46. 17.

पञ्चलक्षणम्
Pañcalakṣaṇam  (I)--of a Purāṇa: Sarga, Pratisarga, Manvantara, Vamśa and Vamśānucarita. M. 53. 65. 70; Vā. 4. 11.

पञ्चलक्षणम्
Pañcalakṣaṇam  (II)--śabda, rūpa, rasa, gandha, and sparśa; incidents relating to. Vā. 8. 45.

पञ्चलाङ्गलकम्
Pañcalāṅgalakam --a gift of five ploughs and cattle both in wood and gold as well as 100 nivartanas (or 50 or even a small area enough for a house to stand on) of land on an auspicious day leads one to heaven; rules relating to the performance of. M. 274. 9; ch. 283 (whole).

पञ्चवनम्
Pañcavanam --(Kauśiki tank): here is the tīrtha of Pāṇḍuviśala. Vā. 77. 99, 101.

पञ्चवन
Pañcavana --one of Sagara's sons who survived Kapila's tejas. Vā. 88. 149. 

पञ्चवर्णा
Pañcavarṇā --a R. of the Bhadra country Vā. 43. 27.

पञ्चविन्ध्य
Pañcavindhyas --Saptavindhyas excepting Hṝnkāra and Praṇava. Br. II. 33. 39.

पञ्चविंशक
Pañcaviṃśaka Puruṣa --the Lord made of 25 truths (tatvas). M. 274. 62.

पञ्चवीरा
Pañcavīrās --the sons of Sāmba and Kāśyā. M. 47. 24.

पञ्चशर
Pañcaśara --an epithet of the God of love; his dart is the twig of the mango, and his standard, the fish; his wife, Ratī and his friend, Madhu or the spring; also Pañcabāṇa and Madana. M. 154. 207-9, 212.

पञ्चशिख
Pañcaśikha  (I)--a Brahmaṛṣi 1) M. 102. 18. of the eighth dvāpara. 2) Vā. 23. 141.

पञ्चशिख
Pañcaśikha  (II)--a son of Brahmā. Vā. 101. 338.

पञ्चशिखर
Pañcaśikhara --a mountain peak in Sālmalidvīpa. Br. III. 7. 454.

पञ्चशिर
Pañcaśira --a Siddha. Bhā. VI. 15. 14.

पञ्चशैल
Pañcaśaila --a Mt. south of the Meru. Vā. 36. 24. 

पञ्चहस्त
Pañcahasta --a son of Dakṣasāvarṇī. Vi. III. 2. 24.

पञ्चाक्षरीमन्त्र
Pañcākṣarīmantra --sacred to Śivā. Br. IV. 36. 18.

पञ्चाग्नि
Pañcāgni --five fires eligible for Pārvaṇa śrāddha; 1) Vā. 83. 53; M. 16. 7. performance of penance by Yayāti for a year in the midst of five fires; 2) Ib. 35. 16. created by Agniśarman from his face. These are Dakṣināgni, Gārhapatya, Āhavanīya, Sabhya, and Āvasathya. 3) Vā. 106. 41. 2.

पञ्चाग्निपदम्
Pañcāgnipadam --in Gayā. Vā. 109. 19.

पञ्चाग्निमध्यस्थ
Pañcāgnimadhyastha --a kind of austerity performed by Parasurāma standing in the midst of five fires. Br. III. 22. 72.

पञ्चाग्नेय
Pañcāgneyas --fit for śrāddha. Br. III. 15. 30.

पञ्चाप्सरस्
Pañcāpsaras --sacred to Hari; visited by Balarāma Bhā. X. 79. 18.

पञ्चाब्दा
Pañcābdās --Pitṛs and sons of Brahmā 1) Br. II. 28. 17, 21; M. 141. 15, 19. limbs of the five year yuga; 2) Ib. 141. 57. known as Kāvyas. 3) Vā. 52. 68.

पञ्चायतनम्
Pañcāyatanam --a sacred place on the Narmadā. M. 191. 6. 

पञ्चाल
Pañcāla  (I)--(c) on the way from Dvārakā to Hastināpura; 1) Bhā. IV. 25. 50; 27. 8; X. 71. 22. migration of the Yadus to; 2) Ib. X. 2. 3. the territory divided among the five sons of Bheda. 3) Vā. 99. 192.

पञ्चाल
Pañcāla  (II)--a Yakṣa sent by Brahmā with the Goddess of Night to the Vindhyas to serve her as servant. M. 157. 18.

पञ्चाल
Pañcālas --the 25 kings who were contemporaries of the ten Śiśunāgas. Br. III. 74. 136.

पञ्चाशत्पीठम्
Pañcāśatpīṭham --see Bindupīṭha. Br. IV. 37. 47.

पाञ्चाश्वमेधिक
Pāñcāśvamedhika --a tīrtha fit for performing śrāddha. Vā. 77. 45.

पट
Paṭa --the painting canvas frame on which portraits were drawn. Citralekhā drew a good number of portraits for Uṣa's choice of a husband. Vi. V. 32. 22-5.

पट
Paṭa(ha) --a musical instrument. Vā. 40. 24; M. 261. 55.

पटच्चर
Paṭaccaras--(c)  a kingdom of Madhyadeśa; name of a tribe. Br. II. 16. 41; M. 114. 35.

पटह
Paṭaha --a war musical instrument. M. 137. 29; 138. 3. 

पटुम
Paṭuma --a king of the Śātakarni line; ruled for twenty-four years. Br. III. 74. 164.

पटुमन्
Paṭuman --the son of Meghasvāti and father of Ariṣṭakarman. Vi. IV. 24. 45-6.

पटुमित्र
Paṭumitras --an Andhra line of rulers. Vi. IV. 24. 58.

पटुश्रव
Paṭuśrava --a son of Damaghoṣa and Śrutaśravā. Vā. 96. 159.

पट्टम्
Paṭṭam --a plate or cloth or other substance to be presented with prescribed mantras as gift during an eclipse. M. 67. 21.

पट्टमित्रा
Paṭṭamitrās --a Māhiṣī line of 13 kings. Vā. 99. 374.

पट्टवर्धनम्
Paṭṭavardhanam --mode of wearing the tilaka on the forehead. Other modes are Ūrdhva puṇḍra, Tripuṇḍra and Agastyapatrākāra. Br. IV. 38. 22.

पट्टसेन
Paṭṭasena --a commander of Bhaṇḍa; 1) Br. IV. 21. 83. a son of Bhaṇḍa. 2) Ib. IV. 26. 49.

पट्टिश
Paṭṭiśa --one of the weapons of Śiva. Vā. 55. 45; 101. 270.

पण
Paṇa --a coin. M. 227. 14. 

पणव
Paṇava  (I)--a son of Bāhyaka. Vā. 96. 4.

पणव
Paṇava  (II)--a musical instrument. Vā. 45. 40; Bhā. V. 9. 15.

पणार्धार्ध
Paṇārdhārdha --the smallest coin. Vi. VI. 1. 22.

पणि
Paṇi  (I)--a priest in a Kāḷi temple; the reference is to the Paṇi of the Vṛṣala chief. Bhā. V. 9. 15-16.

पणि
Paṇi  (II)--a Dānava group of Rasātala. Bhā. V. 24. 30.

पणि
Paṇis --of Galava gotra. Br. III. 66. 71.

पण्डारकवनम्
Paṇḍārakavanam --in the Pāṇḍukula and near the sea; a place fit for śrāddha. Vā. 77. 37.

पतङ्ग
Pataṅga  (I)--a Mt. on the base of Meru; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 26. Vi. II. 2. 28. on the south of the Mānasa. 2) Vā. 36. 22; 38. 2.

पतन्ग
Patanga  (II)--a class of people in Plakṣadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 4.

पतङ्ग
Pataṅga  (III)--a son of Devakī killed by Kamsa; taken to Dvārakā from Sutala by Kṛṣṇa, and after having been seen by his parents, went to Heaven. Bhā. X. 85. 51-6. 

पतङ्ग
Pataṅga  (IV)--the helpmate of the Vālakhilyas; 1) Vā. 28. 32. the Sun God. 2) Br. II. 21. 67. Vā. 52. 48; 54. 8.

पतङ्गी
Pataṅgī --the wife of Tārkṣya and mother of birds. Bhā. VI. 6. 21.

पतञ्जलि
Patañjali  (I)--a Siddha. Bhā. VI. 15. 14; M. 196. 25.

पतंजलि
Pataṃjali  (II)--a pupil of Parāśarya Kauthuma. Br. II. 35. 46; Vā. 61. 41.

पताका
Patākā --a R. of the Bhadra continent. Vā. 43. 30.

पताकिनी
Patākinī --a Śaktī of the Vāyudik; her riding animal mṛga. M. 286. 9.

पतित
Patita --a fallen person from the path of righteousness, piṇḍa to be given in the evening and no pollution; whoever he be, even the guru, he must be abandoned; but the fallen mother must not be abandoned. M. 227. 59, 150.

पतिव्रता
Pativratā --conjugal fidelity; the greatness of, illustrated by the story of Sāvitrī and Satyavān; husband is the lord, God, partner and not others. M. 210. 16ff.

पत्तल्लक
Pattallaka --ruled after the Andhra king Hāla, for five years. Br. III. 74. 166. 

पत्रम्
Patram --(likhitam) written message sent by Rukmiṇī to Kṛṣṇa; text of the letter. Bhā. X. 52. 36 [1 and 2]; 37-43.

पत्रवान्
Patravān --a Mauneya Gandharva. Br. III. 7. 2.

पत्रिका
Patrikā --a medicinal plant. M. 218. 31.

पथ्य
Pathya  (I)--learnt the Atharva Samhitā from a pupil of Sumantu; Kumuda and others were his disciples. Bhā. XII. 7. 1 and 2.

पथ्य
Pathya  (II)--a disciple of Kabandha; he had three disciples; Jājali (Jābāli-Vi. P.), Kumulādi and Śaunaka. Br. II. 35. 56, 59; Vā. 61. 50; Vi. III. 6. 9-11.

पथ्य
Pathya  (III)--of Bhārgava gotra. Vā. 65. 96.

पथ्या
Pathyā --a daughter of Maru and wife of Atharva Angiras; father of 101 sons of whom were Ayāsya, Vāmadeva, Utathya, Uśiti, and Dhṛṣṇi. Br. III. 1. 103-5; Vā. 65. 98.

पद्गमा
Padgamās --a tribe of the Vindhya region. M. 114. 53.

पद्म
Padma  (I)--a Yakṣa; a son of Puṇyajanī and Maṇibhadra. Br. III. 7. 124; Vā. 69. 155. 

पद्म
Padma  (II)--the name of the 7th kalpa. Vā. 21. 12.

पद्म
Padma  (III)--a son of Bhadra; gave birth to eight kinds of elephants; 1) Vā. 69. 213, 217. vehicle of Ailavila. 2) Br. III. 7. 329. 331.

पद्म
Padma  (IV)--the forest of Padma between the Lauhitya and the Sindhu. Br. III. 7. 358.

पद्म
Padma  (V)--a Nāga (serpent) chief. Br. IV. 20. 53.

पद्मक
Padmaka --a palace with three bhūmikas and sixteen sides; 1) M. 269. 39, 43. also Śrivṛkṣaka; the toraṇa is of 20 hastas. 2) Ib. 269. 49.

पद्मकरा
Padmakarā --a goddess following Revatī. M. 179. 73.

पद्मगुल्म
Padmagulma --a son of Mṛga elephant. Br. III. 7. 332.

पद्मचित्र
Padmacitra --a Nāga. Vā. 69. 73.

पद्मदल
Padmadala --the vessel of the lotus leaf wherein the Gandharvas milked the cow-earth. M. 10. 24.

पद्मद्वयम्
Padmadvayam --a snake used as balabandham for Tripurāri's chariot. M. 133. 33. 

पद्मनाभ
Padmanābha  (I)--also Janārdana; the God who pervades all the worlds; lustrous as the sun and with bow as weapon. Br. II. 19. 177-80; III. 33. 17; IV. 34. 81.

पद्मनाभ
Padmanābha  (II)--a Yakṣa; a son of Devajanī and Maṇivara. Br. III. 7. 130; Vā. 69. 161.

पद्मपात्र
Padmapātras --the Gandharvas and the Apsarasas milked the earth making Citraratha the calf; milkman Śucī Viśvavasu. Vā. 62. 187.

पद्म
Padma(bhūḥ) --Brahmā; a thousand leafed lotus came out of the navel of the Lord on the eve of the creation of the universe; it resembled the earth in form; in it were found all the countries, mountains, peoples, etc. M. 4. 1; 168. 15; 169. 3 to 18.

पद्मम्
Padmam  (I)--1000 billions; ten times the śanku. M. 23. 39; Vā. 101. 101.

पद्मम्
Padmam  (II)--one of the eight nidhis of Kubera. Vā. 41. 10.

पद्मयोनि
Padmayoni --see Brahmā. Br. II. 25. 62. Vi. VI. 4-9.

पद्मवर्ण
Padmavarṇa --a Yakṣa; a son of Devajanī and Maṇivara. Br. III. 7. 129; Vā. 61. 190. 

पद्मविधि
Padmavidhi --in the yajñas after the world lotus of the Lord. M. 169. 16 and 18.

पद्मा
Padmā  (I)--a name of Śrī. Bhā. X. 47. 13; Vi. I. 8. 24.

पद्मा
Padmā  (II)--one of the ten pīṭhas for images; with sixteen corners, a little short at the bottom; gives one good luck (saubhāgya). M. 262. 7, 16, 18.

पद्मावती
Padmāvatī  (I)--the city of Purañjaya the capital of the Nāgas. Bhā. XII. 1. 37. Vi. IV. 24. 63.

पद्मावती
Padmāvatī  (II)--a daughter of Bhaṅgakāra, who was given in marriage to Kṛṣṇa. M. 45. 21.

पद्मासन
Padmāsana --a kind of āsana in yoga, once practised by Paraśurāma; of Kapila. Br. III. 24. 16; 53. 17.

पद्मोत्तम
Padmottama --a son of Mṛga elephant. Br. III. 7. 332.

पन
Pana --a Devagandharva. Vā. 68. 39.

पनस
Panasa --A Vānara, whose daughter was Rumā; 1) Br. III. 7. 221, 231. followed Rāma in his expedition to Lankā. 2) Bhā. IX. 10. 19. 

पन्नग
Pannaga --a Śrutaṛṣi. Br. II. 33. 4.

पन्नगा
Pannagās --semi-divine beings, see Sarpās. Br. II. 32. 1, 2.

पन्नागारि
Pannāgāri --a sage; one of the three disciples of Rathītara. M. 200. 12; Vā. 61. 3.

पप्लव
Paplavas --a tribe who were defeated by Sagara and deprived of their Kṣatriya right of Vedic study and sacrifice; became Mlecchas and were allowed to have long hair. Vi. IV. 3. 42, 47-8.

पम्पा
Pampā  (I)--a R. sacred to Hari; visited by Balarāma. Bhā. VII. 14. 31; X. 79. 12.

पम्पा
Pampā  (II)--a R. of the Bhadra country. Vā. 43. 27.

पम्पातीर्थम्
Pampātīrtham --sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 50.

पम्पावती
Pampāvatī --a R. of the Bhadra country. Vā. 43. 27.

पय
Paya --(Gavya) cow's milk for śrāddha; 1) M. 17. 34. not to be taken during nights. 2) M. 131. 43.

पयस्विनी
Payasvinī --a R. flowing in Draviḍa in the Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 18; XI. 5. 39. 

पयःकीर्ति
Payaḥkīrti --a monkey chief. Br. III. 7. 240.

पयोदजनपादप
Payodajanapādapa --a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 5.

पयोदम्
Payodam --a lake in the Nīla hill. Br. II. 18. 69.

पयोदा
Payodā  (I)--a R. from the lake Payodam. Br. II. 18. 70. Vā. 47. 66.

पयोदा
Payodā  (II)--a R. rising on the western side of the Meru mountain. Vā. 47. 67.

पयोराशि
Payorāśi --see Kṣīroda. Br. II. 25. 54.

पयोव्रत
Payovrata --(also called Sarvayajña, Sarvavrata) a votive offering of the essence of tapas, in honour of Hari to be observed for twelve days and in which Hari is represented in an image or in any other form; originally told about it by Brahmā, Kaśyapa suggested to his wife Aditi to observe it; Aditī observed it as instructed by Kaśyapa, when Hari manifested Himself and promised to be born of her womb; 1) Bhā. VIII. 16. 25-60; 17. 1-18. observed by Śraddhā. 2) IX. 1. 14.

