Pavanātmaja --Hanuman, Vāyuputra. Vā. 60. 69; 72.

पवमान
Pavamāna (Pāvamāna) --a son of Svāhā and a Laukikāgni; thought of as nirmanthya by poets; it is the gārhapatya. Bhā. IV. 1. 60. Br. II. 24. 15. Vā. 29. 2, 10. Vi. I. 10. 15.

पवमान
Pavamāna  (II)--a son of Vijitāśva and an Agni in  previous birth born thus because of Vasiṣṭha's curse. Bhā. IV. 24. 4.

पवमान
Pavamāna  (III)--a son of Medhātithi of Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 25. 

पवर्ग
Pavarga  (I)--Jayinī: a Śakti on Śarvarohaharacakra. Br. IV. 37. 6.

पवर्ग
Pavarga  (II)--the right feet of the Veda. Vā. 104. 72.

पवित्रवती
Pavitravatī --a R. in Krauñcadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 21.

पवित्र
Pavitras  (I)--Gods of the epoch of 14th Manu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 34; Vi. III. 2. 43.

पवित्र
Pavitras  (II) (Paritras)--one of the five devagaṇas of the 14th Bhauta Manu: are the seven worlds. Br. IV. 1. 106, 198. Vā. 100. 111-2.

पवित्रा
Pavitrā  (I)--a R. in Kuśadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 62. M. 122. 72.

पवित्रा
Pavitrā  (II)--a main stream of Kuśadvīpa. Vi. I. 4. 43.

पशु
Paśu --born of Savitā: grāmya and āraṇya; killing of except in Yajñas considered as himsā; sacrifice of, for preta, bhūta, and gaṇas irreligious and sinful; 1) Bhā. VI. 18. 1; VII. 15. 7-10; XI. 10. 28; 21. 29-30; Vi. I. 5. 51-2. the sages finding many heads of cattle for sacrificial purposes by Indra complained about the himsā and said that himsā must be removed from the sacrifices and that they could be performed only with seeds and corns; there was a difference of opinion and the sages referred the question to king Vasu; he called it himsā and was punished; final conclusion that in killing Paśu in a Yajña there was no himsā; 2) Vā. 57. 92-114. fourteen kinds distinguished. 3) Br. IV. 6. 54; II. 32. 11-2, 16. 

पशुगण
Paśugaṇas --attacked by Rudra. Vā. 88. 135.

पशुपति
Paśupati  (I)--fourth name of Śiva; the fifth tanu of Agni; has pacikaśakti; wife Svāhā and son Skanda; 1) Br. II. 10. 80; Vā. 27. 11, 53; 30. 89. hence fire to be kept clean. 2) Br. II. 10. 13 and 45.

पशुपति
Paśupati  (II)--see Rudra; 1) M. 154. 485. Vi. I. 8. 6; V. 18. 56. the presiding deity of fire. 2) M. 162. 9; 265. 40.

पशुपाल
Paśupāla --a name of Kārtavīrya. M. 43. 27; Vā. 94. 24.

पशुबन्धम्
Paśubandham --Vedic sacrifices; 1) M. 246. 64. in the chest of the personified Veda. 2) Vā. 104. 83.

पशुभर्ता
Paśubhartā --is Paśupati. Vā. 30. 104, 108.

पशुयज्ञ
Paśuyajña --sacrifice incumbent on house-holders. Br. IV. 6. 73.

पशुरूपि
Paśurūpi --Agni. Vā. 23. 94.

पशुसंस्था
Paśusaṃsthā --a Yāga. Bhā. X. 23. 8.

पशुसोम
Paśusoma --a sacrifice performed by Bharata. Bhā. V. 7. 5.

पशुहा
Paśuhā --a son of Vṛṣa (Viṣa Vā. P.). Br. III. 6. 34; 68. 33. 

पशुहिंसा
Paśuhiṃsā --in Yajña condemned by sages but justified by Indra. Br. II. 30. 17-18.

पश्यश्व
Paśyaśva --a mantrakṛt. Vā. 59. 97.

पश्वोषधि
Paśvoṣadhi --Prajāpati after creating the eight devayonis with four kinds of serpents and of spirits, proceeded to create birds and beasts; sheep from face, crows from breast, cows from belly, and sides; from feet, horses, elephants, śarabha, gavaya deer, camel, etc., from hairs, vegetables, fruits and roots. Vā. 9. 41-5.

पह्लवा
Pahlavās --defeated by Paraśurāma; 1) Br. II. 31. 83; III. 41. 39. attacked by Bāhu and defeated by Sagara; 2) Ib. III. 63. 120, 134. punished with wearing moustaches; 3) Ib. III. 73. 108. kingdom of 4) M. 121. 45; 144. 57; Vā. 45. 118; 58. 82.

पाक
Pāka --an Asura; resisted Indra and Mātali in Devāsura war and was slain. Bhā. VII. 2. 4; VIII. 11. 19, 22 and 28.

पाकयज्ञ
Pākayajña --Vidhāna of: to be observed by the husband in his fire offerings in the Pumsavana (s.v.) vratam, 1) Bhā. VI. 19. 22: Vā. 29. 38. prescribed for śūdras. 2) Vi. III. 8. 34; VI. 2. 23.

पाकशासन
Pākaśāsana --Indra, the lord of rains; 1) Br. III. 63. 99; 66. 35; M. 7. 51. Vā. 88. 85. fought with the Asuras and got the full share of Yajñas for devas and deprived them of their place. 2) Ib. 97. 93. 

पाखण्ड
Pākhaṇḍas (also Pākhaṇḍins) --deities of: kites, vultures, cranes, and banyan trees, not accepted by Ārya religion; 1) Bhā. V. 14. 29. Shine in Kali and oppose Vedic religion; 2) V. 20. 8 and 23. created by Indra; followers of Śiva according to the curse of Bḥṛgu. Two kinds, one naked and the other wearing red clothes; 3) IV. 2. 28 and 30; 19. 24-25, 35-36. Vṛddhaśrāvaka, Nirgrantha, Śākya, Ājivaka and Kārpaṭa are some sects: vanquished by Pramati in a Devāsura war. 4) Br. II. 31. 53, 66 and 80; III. 14. 39; 74. 207.

पाचि
Pāci --a son of Nahuṣa. M. 24. 50.

पाञ्चजनी
Pāñcajanī --one of the wives of Dakṣa who bore him 1000 sons, Haryaśvas (s.v.). M. 5. 4.

पाञ्चजन्य
Pāñcajanya --the conch of Kṛṣṇa, blown by him at the siege of Mathurā by Jarāsandha. Vi. V. 21. 30; Bhā. VIII. 4. 19; X. 50. 24[1-2]; 51 (v) 27; 59. 6; XI. 27. 27.

पाञ्चाल
Pāñcāla  (I)--(c) a kingdom of the north. Bhā. I. 10. 34. Br. II. 16. 46. M. 121. 50.

पाञ्चाल
Pāñcāla  (II)--a common name for the five sons of Bharmyāśva (Haryaśva Vi. P.) and who were capable of ruling five kingdoms. Bhā. IX. 21. 32-33; 22. 3; Vi. IV. 19. 59.

पाञ्चाल
Pāñcālas --their king was Drupada; 1) Bhā. X. 52. 11[8]. enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus; placed on the south by Jarāsandha in his siege of Gomanta, 2) Ib. X. [50 (v) 2]; 52. 11[8]. svayamvara of Draupadī at their capital; 3) Ib. X. 57. 10[1-2]. Kṛṣṇa met the Pāṇḍavas in disguise at their capital; 4) Ib. X. 58. 9. [1 and 2]. heard of Kṛṣṇa going to Mithilā and met him with presents. 5) Ib. X. 86. 20. 

पाञ्चालाधिपति
Pāñcālādhipati --married Kṛtvī daughter of Śuka; 1) M. 15. 9. Nīla subdued by Ugrāyudha. 2) Ib. 49. 79. 78.

पाञ्चालान्वयम्
Pāñcālānvayam --the Pāncāla line of kings, 27 in number. M. 20. 20; 272. 15; 273. 73.

पाटला
Pāṭalā  (I)--the goddess enshrined at Puṇḍravardhana. M. 13. 35.

पाटला
Pāṭalā  (II)--a tīrtha sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 33.

