Pāṇigraha --the chief function in a marriage; Devayānī claims that this happened to her by Yayāti when he rescued her from the well; 1) M. 30. 21. reference to the marriage between Śiva and Umā; 2) Ib. 60. 15. according to fire rite; 3) Ib. 154. 484. of Śiva at Kāñci. 4) Br. IV. 39. 61.

पाणिन
Pāṇina  (I)--a 1000 hooded snake. M. 6. 41.

पाणिन
Pāṇina  (II)--of the Kauśika gotra. Vā. 91. 99.

पाणिनि
Pāṇini --a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 10.

पाणिपात्र
Pāṇipātra(i) --a class of Piśācas eating bali with heads of the elephants, camels and raised napes. Br. III. 7. 379, 383, 394; Vā. 69. 264. 

पाण्ड
Pāṇḍa --of the Bhārgavagotra. Vā. 65. 96.

पाण्डर
Pāṇḍara --a hill west of the Śitoda. Vā. 36. 28; 38. 49.

पाण्डव
Pāṇḍavas (Pāṇḍus) --The five sons of Pāṇḍu (s.v.); rumour that they were burnt in the house of lac built by Duryodhana; their escape in the disguise of Brahmanas; met by Kṛṣṇa in a Potter's hall in Pāñcāla city; 1) Bhā. X. 57. 1, 10[2-4]; Br. III. 71. 65. married Draupadi; 2) Vā. 99. 240, 246. Kṛṣṇa sent Akrūra to Hastināpura to find out their position; seen by Akrūra; Akrūra pleaded their cause with Dhṛtarāṣṭra and reported his designs to Kṛṣṇa and Rāma; 3) Ib. X. 48. 32-25; 49. 2, 19 and 31. praised the heroic exploits of Kṛṣṇa; 4) Ib. IX. 24. 63; Vā. 77. 48. Kṛṣṇa who heard them burnt down, performed obsequies to. 5) Ib. 96. 63.

पाण्डवेशम्
Pāṇḍaveśam --a tīrtham on the Narmadā. M. 191. 61-2.

पाण्डु
Pāṇḍu  (I)--a Rājaṛṣi: one of the three sons of Vicitravīrya; (Kṛṣṇadvaipāyana--Vā. P.) born to Vyāsa; married two wives, Kunti alias Prthā, sister of Vasudeva and Mādri; father of the five Pāṇḍavas, who were born to Kunti by favour of Gods, himself being prevented by a curse from having sexual intercourse; on his death Pṛthā with the young children underwent a lot of difficulties. Bhā. I. 4. 7; IX. 22. 25, 27; 24. 36; I. 9. 13. M. 46. 8; 50. 47-9; Vā. 96. 150; 99. 242-3; 112. 45; Vi. IV. 14. 34; 20. 38-42.

पाण्डु
Pāṇḍu  (II)--an Ārṣeya Pravara (Āngīras). M. 196. 9.

पाण्डु
Pāṇḍu  (III)--a son of Vidhāta and Āyatī; married Puṇḍarīkā and had a son Dyutimān. Vā. 28. 5, 35. 

पाण्डुकूपम्
Pāṇḍukūpam --in the Piṇḍārakatata noted for śrāddha offerings. Br. III. 13. 37.

पाण्डुभूमि
Pāṇḍubhūmi --the earth in the second talam. Br. II. 20. 14, 25.

पाण्डुर
Pāṇḍura --a Mt. in the Bhāratavarṣa; 1) Br. II. 16. 21; Vā. 45. 91. residence of the Vīdyādharas. 2) Ib. 39. 60.

पाण्डुरक
Pāṇḍuraka --a Nāga having his city in the third talam. Br. II. 20. 29; Vā. 50. 28.

पाण्डुरोचि
Pāṇḍuroci --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 22.

पाण्डुविशाल
Pāṇḍuviśāla --a tīrtha in the Pañcavanam. Vā. 77. 99.

पाण्डुशिला
Pāṇḍuśilā --on the slope of the Himālayas; sporting ground of Skanda. Vā. 41. 42; 112. 44.

पाण्ड्य
Pāṇḍya  (I)--a son of Āndira and chief of the Pāṇḍyadeśa. Br. III. 74. 6; M. 48. 5.

पाण्ड्य
Pāṇḍya  (II)--one of the four sons of Janāpīḍa; his state, Pāṇḍyadeśa. Vā. 99. 6.

पाण्ड्य
Pāṇḍyas --a southern tribe; 1) Br. II. 16. 56. M. 114. 46; Vā. 45. 124. Kingdom of. 2) M. 163. 72. 

पाण्ड्यज
Pāṇḍyaja --a Rājaṛṣi who attained heaven by tapas. Br. II. 30. 40.

पातकम्
Pātakam --to kill one to advance one's own interest is sin; but not so, if done for the sake of many. Vā. 62. 161-2.

पातालस्थ
Pātālasthas --the Asuras whom Kārtavīrya defeated by crossing the ocean; seeing him the great Uragas stood dumb-founded like the plantain stem tossed about by the winds. Vā. 94. 30-4.

पाताल
Pātāla --(Sutalam): the nether-world where live the Lords of Nāgaloka with their hoods of jewels; at the bottom of this region lives Śeṣa; 1) Bhā. II. 1. 26; 5. 41; V. 24. 7 and 31; 25. 1; M. 154. 197; 163. 91; 249. 16; Vā. 49. 164; 97. 18; 98. 80 and 86; 100. 157; Vi. II. 5. 13; VI. 8. 48. of golden colour, residence of Bali having been given by Vāmana as also of Mucukunda, Daityas and Asuras; women of; 2) Br. II. 19. 172; 20. 13-15; 42. 5; III. 36. 4; 53. 11; 54. 12; 69. 30; IV. 1. 153; 38. 35. M. 43. 33; 246. 69; Vā. 50. 12; 41 ff. sacred to Parameśvarī; 3) M. 13. 39. when Śukra wanted to go to the camp of the Devas the Asuras threatened to leave for P.; 4) Ib. 47. 68. Vi. I. 9. 111. IV. 4. 19. of seven regions below the earth; 5) Vi. II. 5. 1-12; IV. 4. 19; V. 1. 72; destroyed by Rudra's flame in the dissolution. 6) Vi. VI. 3. 24-5.

पातालान्त
Pātālānta --abode of Śeṣa. Vā. 50. 45.

पातुन्धम
Pātundhama --a Mt. of the Bhāratavarṣa. Vā. 45. 91.

पाथिनम्
Pāthinam --a kind of fish used in the Śrāddhas. M. 15. 34. 

पादपोद्यापनम्
Pādapodyāpanam --(Vṛkṣotsava): dedication of trees and shrubs; same as taḍāgavidhi; further oblations to Lokapālas and Vanaspati, decoration of trees with golden fruits, etc., to be given away to Brahmanas at the end; a festival in honour of trees and plants; lasts four days; he who does it attains heaven and is rarely returned to earth. 1) M. 59. 1-18. If trees laugh or weep or flower in a wrong season they should be propitiated. 2) Ib. ch. 232 (whole)

पादिक
Pādikas --the time of the night, calculated from the moment of the moon. Vā. 66. 45.

पादुकम्
Pādukam --sandals to be given in vṛkṣotsavam; to be given as gift along with light, umbrella, seat, etc. M. 59. 14; 70. 48; 275. 25.

पाद्म
Pādma --a name of Brahmā. Bhā. I. 18. 19.

पाद्म
Pādma kalpa --succeeds Brāhma kalpa, then the lotus comes out of Hari's navel. Bhā. II. 10. 47; III. 11. 35; Vi. I. 3. 27-8.

पाद्मपुराण
Pādmapurāṇa --(Pādmam): one of the 18 Purāṇas and comprising 55000 ślokas; 1) Bhā. XII. 7. 23; 13. 4; Vā. 104. 9. Vi. III. 6. 21. he who copies and presents it with a golden lotus in the month of Jyeṣṭha (Āḍi) attains the fruit of an aśvamedha sacrifice; 2) M. 53. 14-15. contains a description of Narasimha in 18000 slokas; 3) Ib. 53. 60. to be read every parva. 4) Ib. 290. 17.

पाद्मम्
Pādmam --a mahākalpa. M. 164. 4. 

पानम्
Pānam --the region of adharma and of Kali; drinking liquor by a king is to be avoided. 2) M. 220. 8. ^1 Bhā. I. 17. 38.

पानम्
Pānam --the hamlet next in rank above kheta Br. II. 7. 110.

पानी
Pānī --a R. of the Śālmalidvīpa. Vā. 49. 42.

पान्नगारि
Pānnagāri --a pupil of Bāṣkali. Br. II. 35. 6.

पाप
Pāpa --a son of Brahmadhana. Vā. 69. 132.

पापा
Pāpās --kinds of sins; Niryāsam (drinking of the milk of trees) Kalamjam (taking opium), Kalingam, Gṛmyjanam (eating garlic), Chatrākam (eating of mushroom?), Mahākośātakī, Mallika (dealing in jasmine), use of the nut of the tree Katakam, and Umbaram (felling of fig trees), Kayakam? Vārtākam (eating brinjal), taking of pot-herbs, of bimbi fruits, of lambika, misappropriation of public funds (puragrāmanga), misuse of the special Vaiśya funds, residence in a kugrāma, profession of a physician, trafficing in women, living by arms, sale of oily foods, eating food from cowherds, 1) Br. IV. 8. 41-49. and eating without guest; 2) Ib. IV. 2. 161; Vi. II. 6. 6-29. brahmicide and teaching of Vedas for money; 3) Br. III. 14. 43; 15. 48. threefold, arising from speech, mind and body. 4) Vā. 18. 2.

पामराचार
Pāmarācāra --the customs of barbarians; Asura Viśukra spoke of Deva's ācāras. Br. IV. 21. 32. 

पांशव
Pāṃśava (Pāmśus) --a clan of Piśācas having hands above, as also hairs, and throwing out dust from their body. Br. III. 7. 379, 383, 39. Vā. 69. 272.

पांशुमती
Pāṃśumatī --a class of Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 379.

पार
Pāra  (I)--a son of Rucirāśva and father of Nīpa and Pṛthusena. Bhā. IX. 21. 24-25.

पार
Pāra  (II)--one of the three sons of Samara M. 49. 54; Vā. 99. 177; Vi. IV. 19. 41.

पार
Pāra  (III)--a son of Pṛthuṣeṇa, and father of Nīla Vā. 99. 174; Vi. IV. 19. 37-8.

पार
Pāras --Gods of the ninth Manvantara. Bhā. VIII. 19. 19. Vi. III. 2. 21.

पारण
Pāraṇas --Trayārṣeyaṣ: no marriage alliances with Paurṇamāsa and Agastya. M. 202. 4.

पारद
Pāradas  (I)--a tribe of a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 48. M. 114. 41. Vā. 47. 47, 58. 82; 88. 122; 98. 107.

पारद
Pāradas  (II)--a kingdom of the east watered by the Ganges; 1) Br. II. 18. 50; M. 121. 45; 144. 57. noted for horses; 2) Br. II. 31. 83; III. 48. 26, 29. defeated by Sagara; 3) Ib. III. 73. 108; IV. 16. 16; Vi. IV. 3. 42. attacked by Bāhu; 4) Br. III. 63. 120. punished with shaving of hairs 5) Ib. III. 63, 134. 139. and allowed to have their beards; deprived of their Kṣatriya rights of Vedic study and sacrifice; became Mlecchas. 6) Vi. IV. 3. 47-8. 

पारशर्य
Pāraśarya --Kauthuma: composed of six samhitas. Vā. 61. 41.

पारसव
Pārasavas --kings among the Mlecchas. M. 50. 75.

पारसीक
Pārasīka --the kingdom of. Vi. II. 3. 18.

पारा
Pārā --a R. from Ṛṣyavān. M. 114. 24.

पारावत
Pārāvata  (I)--also Parāvatās: a deva gaṇa of Manu Svārociṣa; 12 in number, Praceta, Viśvadeva, Samanja, Ajihma, Arimardana, Āyurdāna, Mahāmanā, Divyamāna, Ajeya, Yavīyam, Hotā and Yajva; these are all Vāsiṣṭhas and drinkers of the soma juice. Br. II. 36. 8, 14.

पारावत
Pārāvata  (II)--pigeons born of Gṛdhrī. M. 6. 32.

पारावारतट
Pārāvārataṭa --sacred to Matā. M. 13. 44.

पाराशर
Pārāśara(i) --a disciple of Bhāṣkali who gave him the third śākhā of the Ṛg Veda. Br. II. 34. 27. Vā. 60. 26.

पाराशर्य
Pārāśarya --a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 54.

पारिकाररि
Pārikārari --an Ārṣeya Pravara. M. 196. 10. 

पारिजात
Pārijāta  (I)--a heavenly plant; Satyabhāmā saw it in Indra's Nandana and asked Kṛṣṇa to take it home; Kṛṣṇa refused as it was once taken from the milk-ocean and by the consent of the gods given to Indra and to remove it was to face a war with him; still Satyabhāmā persisted and Kṛṣṇa yielding to her placed it on the Garuḍa; took it to the earth against Indra's will and placed it in Satybhāmā's garden; the watchmen objected and reported to Indra; war about the Pārijāta between the Gods and Kṛṣṇa; a compromise to be returned after Kṛṣṇa's decease; 1) Bhā. III. 15. 19; IV. 6. 14; 30. 32; VIII. 11. 10; X. 37. 16, 68. 35; 59. 39-40; [65 (v) 21-36], [37-51]; 66 (v); [67 (v) 1-16, 26], [34,]
[45,]; Ib. X. 68. 35. Vi. V. 30. 32, 80; 38. 7. rejoiced by Dvārakā ci{??}izens. 2) Ib. V. 31. 1-11; 35. 25: The tree in Śivaloka, that came out of the churning of the ocean. 3) Br. III. 32. 6; IV. 9. 70; Vā. 106. 74; Vi. I. 9. 95.

पारिजात
Pārijāta  (II)--a monkey chief and son of Śveta. Br. III. 7. 181 236.

पारिजात
Pārijāta  (III)--(Pariyatra) a Mt. west of the Śitoda. Vā. 36. 29; 42. 54.

पारिजातवनम्
Pārijātavanam --of Mahendra, in Śītānta Mt.; description of. Vā. 39. 10-26.

पारिजातापहारक
Pārijātāpahāraka --Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 30.

पारिपात्र
Pāripātra --a son of Ahīnaga. Vā. 88. 204.

पारिप्लव
Pāriplava --the son of Śukhībala and father of Sunaya. Vi. IV. 21. 12. 

पारिभद्र
Pāribhadra --a territorial division of Śālmalidvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 9.

पारियात्र
Pāriyātra  (I)--Mt. a hill in Bhāratavarṣa and on the west of the Meru; a Kulaparvata; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 27; 19. 16; Br. II. 16. 19. M. 114. 18; 148. 7-10; Vā. 45. 89; Vi. II. 2. 43; 3. 3. the place where Tāraka performed penance; 2) M. 162. 6; 163, 80. gives rise to many rivers. 3) Vā. 45. 98.

पारियात्र
Pāriyātra  (II)--son of Anīha and father of Balasthala (Bala Bhā. P.). Bhā. IX. 12. 2.

पारियात्र
Pāriyātra  (III)--a monkey chief. Br. III. 7. 233.

पारियात्र
Pāriyātra  (IV)--the son of Ahīnaga and father of Dala. Br. III. 63. 204.

पारियात्र
Pāriyātras --the kingdom of. Vi. II. 3. 17.

पारियात्रक
Pāriyātraka --the son of Rūru and father of Devala. Vi. IV. 4. 106.

पार्थ
Pārtha --Arjuna; 1) Br. III. 71. 178; M. 50. 56; 246. 93; Vi. V. 12. 19 etc. married Subhadrā and got by her Abhimanyu. 2) Vā. 96. 176; 99. 249.

पार्थसारथि
Pārthasārathi --is Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 38.

पार्थिव
Pārthiva  (I)--an Ārṣeya Pravara. M. 196. 9. 

पार्थिव
Pārthiva  (II)--one of the three fires; it was so called when (1/4) of the night of Brahmā was remaining. Vā. 53. 5-7.

पार्थिवच्छाया
Pārthivacchāyā --the shadow of the earth. Vā. 53. 63.

पार्थिवम्
Pārthivam --also Pavana; a kind of fire. Br. II. 24. 6.

पार्थिवम्
Pārthivam vratam --vow of kings to support all kinds of their people. M. 226. 8.

पार्थिव
Pārthivas --of Kauśika gotra. Vā. 91. 98.

पार्वणम्
Pārvaṇam (śrāddham) --done in Parvas without the invocation of deities; three fold; those eligible and those ineligible to be fed on the occasion; of the eligibles the family and gotra must have been known; they must be well behaved and going in the path of virtue; friends and preceptors, grandsons, sons-in-law, uncles and other relations, somayājins, vaiyākaraṇas, mīmāmsakas, sāmaga Brahmacāris are eligible; the ineligibles include the unrighteous, the diseased, bastards, aśvapālas, the mad, the self-conceited, the deceitful, the hypocritical, temple priests, etc., also Mlecchas, Lingins, Triśaṅkus, Barbaras, Drāviḍas, etc. They must be informed a day previous to the śrāddha; other details; 1) M. 16. 5-51. a dead person is entitled for share in the Pārvaṇa after sapiṇḍīkaraṇam. 2) Ib. 18. 16.

पार्वतिका
Pārvatikā --a R. sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 56. 

पार्वती
Pārvatī  (I)--Umā, wife of Śiva, attained half body of Śiva by virtue of the 108 names of the Devī; 1) M. 12. 9; 13. 51 and 60; 85. 6; 183. 14; 187. 44; Vā. 54. 20; 108. 51; 112. 35; Vi. V. 32. 11-15. (Ambā), the family deity of the Vidarbhas; present when Śiva gave his missile to Arjuna; 2) Bhā. I. 15. 12; X. 52. 42. conceived true love even as a girl; 3) Ib. X. 60. 47. went with Śiva to have a look at the Mohinī form of Viṣṇu; 4) Ib. VIII. 12. 2 and 25. once when she was sitting unclad on the lap of Śiva there came some sages to see the Lord; ashamed she got herself clothed; to please her Śiva said that any male who entered that place thereafter would become a female; 5) Ib. IX. 1. 29-32. presented Pṛthu with a sword Śatacandra; 6) Ib. IV. 15. 17; VI. 17. 11-12. prayed to by Rukminī to get Kṛṣṇa for her husband; to her shrine Rukminī went by foot and offered worship for the hand of Kṛṣṇa; 7) Ib. X. 53. 25, 39-40 and 44-49. Vṛka's aim to take her after killing Śiva; 8) Ib. X. 88. 23. prevented the enraged Śiva from killing Bhṛgu; 9) Ib. X. 89. 7. saw Mārkaṇḍeya engaged in tapas. 10) Ib. XII. 10. 3 and 35. A Śakti; 11) Br. II. 25. 23; III. 41. 38, 50; 42. 7, 17; 44. 28; IV. 6. 8, 30, 38; 10. 41, 42.felt for Vināyaka losing his teeth through Paraśurāma and appealed to Śiva who remembered Kṛṣṇa. The latter came with Rādhā and consoled her by addressing on Gaṇeśa's greatness.

पार्वती
Pārvatī  (II)--a name of the R. Nandā. Vā. 49. 92.

पार्वती
Pārvatī  (III)--(alias Vijayā); wife of Sahādeva and mother of Suhotra. Bhā. IX. 22. 31.

पार्वतीजानि
Pārvatījāni --is Śiva. Br. IV. 10. 29.

पार्वतीप्रिय
Pārvatīpriya --is Śiva; with Rudra gaṇas. Br. IV. 2. 258; Vā. 101. 321. 

पार्वतीमाय
Pārvatīmāya --applied by Maya who noticed the showers of snow and waters by moon and Varuṇa in the Tārakāmaya; warded off by Gadādhara; to the solace of all devas. M. 176. 25, 34.

पार्वतेय
Pārvateyas --a tribe; enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus. Bhā. X. [50 (v) 4]. Vā. 58. 81.

पार्श्वनन्दि
Pārśvanandi --a son of Sāraṇa. Vā. 96. 164.

पार्श्वमर्दि
Pārśvamardi --a son of Balarāma. Br. III. 71. 166.

पार्श्वि
Pārśvi  (I)--a son of Balarāma. Br. III. 71. 166.

पार्श्वि
Pārśvi  (II)--a son of Sāraṇa. Vā. 96. 164.

पार्षद
Pārṣadas --Śivagaṇas with awkward forms; fought with Tāraka and Māya in the battle of Tripuram. M. 135. 51, 73.

पार्ष्णिग्राह
Pārṣṇigrāha --the neighbour in the rear of the king's enemy; attacking him gives a good occasion to the king to start aggression; a king whose rear is not clear is not to engage in an aggressive expedition; 1) M. 240. 2, 4; Śiva was to Bṛhaspati during the Tārakā war; 2) Br. III. 65. 32. Viśanga in Bhaṇḍa's war; 3) Ib. IV. 25. 14. Uśana acted to Soma, as in the Tārakāmaya war. 4) Vi. IV. 6. 12. 

पालक
Pālaka  (I)--the son of Pṛadyota and father of Viśākhayupa. Bhā. XII. 1. 3.

पालक
Pālaka  (II)--a son of Bālaka, ruled for 28 years (24 Vā. P.). Br. III. 74. 125; M. 272. 3. Vā. 99. 312.

पालङ्कायन
Pālaṅkāyana --a sage. M. 200. 12.

पालपञ्जर
Pālapañjara --Mt. where there is a place of pilgrimage known as Kumāra Kośala. Vā. 77. 37.

पालमञ्जर
Pālamañjara --Mt. the hill with Sampāraka tīrtha. Br. III. 13. 37.

पालाशपात्रम्
Pālāśapātram --the vessel of palāśa wood used by the trees for milking the cow-earth. M. 10. 27.

पालिन्
Pālin --a son of Pṛthu. Vā. 63. 22.

पालिशय
Pāliśayas --Ekārṣeyas. M. 200. 4.

पावक
Pāvaka  (I)--(Agni) a son of Svāhā; 1) Bhā. IV. I. 60; Br. III. 8. 5; Vā. 53. 97, 30; Vi. I. 9, 63; 10. 15. as husband of Gangā; 2) Vā. 2. 17. Lord of Vasus; 3) Ib. 70. 5; Vi. I. 22. 3. also known as Vaidyuta. 4) Br. I. 2. 17; II. 12 2 and 33.

पावक
Pāvaka  (II)--a son of Vijitāśva and an Agni in previous birth born thus through Vasiṣṭha's curse. Bhā. IV. 24. 4. 

पावक
Pāvaka  (III)--an elephant. Br. III. 7. 332; Vā. 69. 216.

पावन
Pāvana  (I)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Mitravindā. Bhā. X. 61. 16.

पावन
Pāvana  (II)--a son of Dyutimān and king of Pāvana deśa. Br. II. 14. 22, 25.

पावनक
Pāvanaka --a Mt. of the Krauñcadvīpa. M. 122. 81. 85.

पावनी
Pāvanī --Nandā, one of the three branches of the Gangā going to the east; 1) Br. II. 12. 16; 18. 40, 56-7; M. 121. 40; 122. 31; Vā. 47. 38 and 53. wife of Havyavāhana. 2) Ib. 29. 14.

पावमान
Pāvamāna --a son of Svāhā. Br. II. 12. 2.

पावमानम्
Pāvamānam --the mantra of the Ṛg Vedins, to be recited in tank ritual relating to the digging of tanks. M. 58. 34.

पाविनी
Pāvinī --Lalitā. Br. IV. 13. 17.

पाश
Pāśa --noose peculiar to Varuṇa. M. 135. 77; 150. 128; 152. 2; 153. 211; 162. 31; 173. 12; 174. 13.

पाशा
Pāśā --a R. from the Pāriyātra. Br. II. 16. 28. 

पाशिनी
Pāśinī --a R. from Śuktimanta. M. 114. 32.

पाशुपतम्
Pāśupatam  (I)--the astram of Śiva. Br. III. 31. 39; 32. 57; 34. 34; 40. 65. IV. 29. 140.

पाशुपतम्
Pāśupatam  (II)--a tīrtha on the Pārvatīkā, sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 56.

पाशुपतयोग
Pāśupatayoga --the earliest form of yoga established; even Gods like Indra practised this and got wealth constituting aṇimā, mahimā, laghimā, prāpti, garimā, prākānujam, īśitvam, vāśitvam, and amaratvam; 1) Br. II. 27. 116, 128; Vā. 1. 195. one who practises it at Benares is rid of the cycle of births and deaths. 2) M. 182. 12.

पाशुपतव्रत
Pāśupatavrata (Paśupāśāvimocana) --ordained for all āśramas. Vā. 30. 295.

पाशुपता
Pāśupatās --followers of the Pāśupata yogam. Br. III. 32. 5.

पाशुपाल्यम्
Pāśupālyam --cattle raising and tending not in Puṣkadvīpa; 1) Br. II. 19. 121; Vā. 49. 117. duty of the Vaiśyas. 2) Br. II. 7. 162; Vi. III. 8. 30.

पाषण्ड
Pāṣaṇḍas --heretics in Kali; 1) Br. IV. 33. 60; M. 99. 14; 144. 40; Vi. III. 18. 22. came out of the Devāśura war--Nirgranthas, Kārpaṭas and Nagnas; 2) Vā. 78. 30. not fit for ritual purposes; 3) M. 57. 6; 69. 34; Vi. III. 18. 70-103; VI. 1. 37 etc. one connected with temple worship must not be a member of the Pāṣaṇḍa family; 4) M. 265. 3. their deities not to be honoured; 5) Ib. 267. 34. quelled by Pramati, God incarnate; 6) Ib. 144. 54. put down  by Kalki; 7) Ib. 47. 249; 273. 27. sell Vedas and tīrthas; 8) Vā. 58. 40, 52, 65. should be given up by a tīrthayātri. 9) Ib. 99. 396; 105. 42.

पिङ्ग
Piṅga  (I)--a madhyamādhvaryu. Br. II. 33. 16.

पिङ्ग
Piṅga  (II)--Tripravara. M. 196. 33.

पिङ्गल
Piṅgala  (I)--one of the eleven Rudras. M. 153. 19; 171. 39.

पिङ्गल
Piṅgala  (II)--a door-keeper of the Sun God. M. 261. 5.

पिङ्गल
Piṅgala  (III)--a Mt. west of the Śitoda. Vā. 36. 27.

पिङ्गला
Piṅgalā  (I)--an aged prostitute of the Videha city; her story as narrated by Avadhūta to Yadu is as follows; she spent her life as a public woman living by earning money every day from one paramour or other; one night she did not get a paramour though she waited to the middle of the night; she then grew disgusted with her life and turned her thought on Hari which resulted in her restful sleep; 1) Bhā. XI. 8. 22-44. her view of life cited by the Gopis to Uddhava. 2) Ib. X. 47. 47.

पिङ्गला
Piṅgalā  (II)--an elephant (nāga). Br. III. 7. 346. 

पिङ्गला
Piṅgalā  (III)--a śakti of Śri Mārutesvara. Br. IV. 33. 70.

पिङ्गला
Piṅgalā  (IV)--a mind-born mother. M. 179. 23.

पिङ्गला
Piṅgalā  (V)--gave birth to Mahāpadma and Ūrmimāli; husband, candra or moon; these families were fond of elephant fighting; some of them were used in the war between the Devas and Asuras. Vā. 69. 229 and 231.

पिङ्गलाक्ष
Piṅgalākṣa --a follower of Śiva. Br. III. 41. 27.

पिङ्गलेश्वरम्
Piṅgaleśvaram --a tīrtham of the Narmadā; good to give away a cow or to die there. M. 191. 32-36.

पिङ्गलेश्वरी
Piṅgaleśvarī --a Goddess enshrined at Payoṣṇī. M. 13. 44.

पिङ्गाक्ष
Piṅgākṣa  (I)--a Yakṣa; a son of Puṇyajanī and Maṇibhadra. Br. III. 7. 123.

पिङ्गाक्ष
Piṅgākṣa  (II)--a son of Lāngalī, an avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 200.

पिच्छला
Picchalā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 11.

पिञ्जर
Piñjara --a Kādraveya nāga. Br. III. 7. 33. 

पिण्डजिह्वा
Piṇḍajihvā --a mother Goddess. M. 179. 32.

पिण्डणिर्वपन
Piṇḍaṇirvapana (Piṇḍaḍāna) --a ceremonial of the śrāddha; the mode of offering three to Pitṛs, Pitāmahas and Prapitāmahas with the respective mantras to be uttered at that time; 1) Br. III. 11. 19. 58, 97; Vā. 74. 17; 75. 41; 76. 31-5; Vi. III. 15. 34. Piṇḍam may also be offered to fire, cows, crows, fowls, with their respective effects to the giver. 2) Vā. 120. 31-41.

पिण्डा
Piṇḍās --rice balls given on ceremonial occasions to Pitṛs: three to be given; like the calf in search of the cow lost in the stall, mantra takes them to the Pitṛs; to be given in the name of the gotra of the person; 1) Br. III. 20. 10-16. can be given to cows, Brahmanas, females, crows, hen or thrown into fire or water; the middle Piṇḍa can be eaten by the wife which leads to increase of santānam; 2) M. 16. 21, 35, 53-54; Vā. 71. 10; 75. 25, 36. Piṇḍadānam on the 12th day after death is supposed to be the Pātheyam or food for the way to heaven; 3) M. 17. 46. 55. seven Piṇḍas for seven generations; 4) Ib. 18. 5 and 29. giving of, in the tīrthas of the Narmadā; 5) Ib. 186. 15. 39; 239. 34. at Gayā with tila. 6) Vā. 105, 12, 33; 108. 15, 21; 110. 23-59.

पिण्डारक
Piṇḍāraka  (I)--a son of Vasudeva and Rohiṇī. Br. III. 71. 165; M. 46. 12; Vā. 96. 163.

पिण्डारक
Piṇḍāraka  (II)--a tīrtha sacred to Dhṛti; 1) M. 13. 48. sacred to Pitṛs; 2) Ib. 22. 69. Here the sages cursed the extinction of the Yadu family, when the Yādava youths played a joke on them by dressing up Sāmba as a woman and asking them to say what child he would bring forth. 3) Vi. V. 37. 6-10. 

पिण्डार्क
Piṇḍārka --city of: its sages visited Dvārakā; 1) Bhā. X. 90. 28[3]. the sages who knew of Kṛṣṇa's advent to Vaikuṇṭha left for this place; 2) Ib. XI. 1. 11. noted for Pāṇḍukūpatīrtha. 3) Br. III. 13. 37.

पिण्डिका
Piṇḍikā --of an image, to be purified with Pañcagavya. M. 266. 6.

पिण्याकम्
Piṇyākam --the fruit of ingudi tree offered with ghee as Piṇḍa (see Rāmā. Ayo. 102. 29: 105. 35). Vā. 16. 14.

पिता
Pitā --a son of Brahmadhāna. Vā. 69. 132.

पितामह
Pitāmaha --Brahmā for all the world. Br. IV. 6. 66; 7. 45; 9. 46; M. 1. 14; Vā. 21. 45-46; 22. 13 and 26; 23. 61, 97; 109. 24; 111. 43.

पितुरंश
Pituraṃśa --the portion of the body, a man gets from his father; this part of Vena's body yielded Pṛthu, a virtuous King armed with bow, arrow, mace, shield and armour. M. 10. 8-9.

पितृ
Pitṛs  (I)--a class of celestials belonging to the group of sacred fires; 1) Bhā. I. 2. 27; IV. 1. 63; Vā. 65. 49-52. worshipped for continuity of family line; 2) Bhā. II. 3. 8; Vā. 75. 7-35; 81. 8-20. married jointly a daughter of Dakṣa, 3) Bhā. IV. 1. 49. blessed Jyāmagha with a son; 4) Ib. IX. 23. 39. drink the svadhā of the moon and worship him on the new moon day: groups of--Saumya, Kāvya, Agniṣvātta and Bārhiṣada; 5) Br. II. 23. 39, 58, 71; 13. 6, 31; 8. 14-15. their role in the universe. 6) Vā. 71. 15-34, 45-67.

पितृ
Pitṛs  (II)--sons of Angiras and Svadhā. Bhā. VI. 6. 19; 10. 17. 

पितृ
Pitṛs  (III)--Pūrvadevatas; are of three categories; Pitṛs, Pitāmahas and Prapitāmahas of the forms of Vasus, Ṛudras and Ādityas according to sacred tradition; 1) M. 17. 36; 19. 3. milked the cow-earth in a silver vessel; Antaka acted as milk-man and Yama, the calf; the essence was svadhā; 1) Ib. 10. 18-19. Yama king of their loka. 3) Ib. 11. 20.

पितृ
Pitṛs  (IV)--general account of; 1) Vā. ch. 56. created out of the satva element and their active time was sandhyā: married svadhā: drink the last kalā of the moon: of three classes-Saumyas, Barhiṣadas and Agniṣvāttas; 2) Vā. 56. 8; Vi. I. 5. 35-6; 7. 27; II. 12. and 13. from Viṣṇu; 3) Ib. V. 1. 17. their relations with gods and sages. 4) Vā. 62. 21.

पितृकल्प
Pitṛkalpa --same as Kuhū; the 30th and last Kalpa. M. 290. 11.

पितृकार्यम्
Pitṛkāryam --more important than Devakāryam. Vā. 73. 55-73.

पितृकृत्
Pitṛkṛt --a son of Arkāgni. Vā. 29. 40.

पितृगण
Pitṛgaṇas (Pitṛs, Pūrvadevatas) --seven, in heaven, three without form and four with form; the formless are Vairājas; their mind-born daughter is the wife of Himavān whose sons are Krauñca and Maināka; 1) M. 13. 1-7; 15. 42; Vā. 72. 1-5. two classes of Devas and Laukikas; to them one full day is equal to our one month, our dark half being their day and bright half their night; our 100 years their 3 years; 2) M. 132. 3; 141. 57, 60; 142. 6-8. the places prescribed for srāddha offerings are said to be fire, the hand of a Brahmana, water, cattle-shed, and ears of goat or horse; always southern direction preferred; 3) Ib. 15. 32-33. to be worshipped in house building. 4) Ib. 253. 25. 

पितृगाथ
Pitṛgāthas --fit to be remembered on the days of ceremony. M. 204. 3-18.

पितृतर्पणम्
Pitṛtarpaṇam --ceremonial for Pitṛs whose overlord is Yama; list of offerings particularly pleasing to the Pitṛs. M. 1. 17; 8. 5; 15. 34-5.

पितृदत्ता
Pitṛdattā --one of the four forms of marriage; this is the wedded wife. Br. IV. 15. 4.

पितृमास
Pitṛmāsa --thirty months of human reckoning; samvatsara is 360 months of human reckoning; varṣāṇi=three or four months of Pitṛs equal to 100 years of human reckoning. Vā. 57. 9.

पित्र्य
Pitrya --an afternoon muhūrta. Br. III. 3. 39.

पितृयज्ञम्
Pitṛyajñam (Piṇḍa) --done chiefly in the dark half of the month (Indukṣaya). M. 16. 21; 17. 4.

पितृयान
Pitṛyāna --north of Agastya and south of Ajavīthi and outside Vaiśvānarapatha; 1) Br. II. 21. 159; 35. 111; M. 124. 97; Vā. 50. 208; 61. 100; Vi. II. 8. 85-7. residence of Agnihotrins, Vedic Karmins and Pitṛs; attained through Iḍa passage (on the left side of the body) 2) Bhā. II. 2. 24. in all four doors with a common doorway in candra or moon. 3) Vā. 8. 198.

पितृराज
Pitṛrāja --see Yama. M. 174. 19. 

पितृलोकम्
Pitṛlokam --reached by the southern part of Aryaman; 1) Bhā. III. 32. 20; V. 2. 1-2 and 22. Āgnīdhra wanted to attain this; 2) M. 194. 7.a bath in the Manoharam Tīrtham of the Narmadā leads one to.

पितृवर्ति
Pitṛvarti --one of the seven sons of Kauśika; suggested that the cow of their guru be offered in a srāddha and then shared by his brothers; accordingly two of the brothers were made Devas, three Pitṛs and one atithi in the srāddha; cakravāka in mānasa became desirous of being a king, seeing the Pāñcāla King in a pleasure garden; became son of Vibhrāja by name Brahmadatta and his wife Sanniti was the cow of Garga offered in śrāddha, born as a daughter of Devala. M. 20. 3-26.

पितृव्रतम्
Pitṛvratam --performed in honour of Pitṛs and includes gifts of milch cows; the performer becomes a Rājarāja. M. 101. 29-30.

पितृसर्ग
Pitṛsarga --once the whole world was covered with darkness; there were no air, no earth, no planets, no directions, no sun, no moon, no days or nights; the single Brahmā out of tapoyoga created worlds of Vedas and other devas; there were seven classes of which three had no form and four had forms: Devas and earth and rains; then śrāddhas. Vā. 71. 37, 57 and 65.

पितृस्थानम्
Pitṛsthānam --ākāśa and southern directions. Vā. 76. 34.

पितृहू
Pitṛhū --the southern entrance of the city of Purañjana who reached Dakṣiṇapāñcāla through it with Śrutadhara; allegorically the right ear. Bhā. IV. 25. 50; 29. 12. 

पित्तल
Pittalas --a Janapada of the Ketumālā continent. Vā. 44. 15.

पित्तवर्ग
Pittavarga --the category of bile; the place in the body round the region of the navel in the bowels; Pitta is agni and śoṇitam belongs to this category. Br. III. 72. 47f. Vā. 97. 48.

पिथर
Pithara --an asura in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. M. 161. 80.

पिनाक
Pināka --the bow of Śiva; hence Śiva is Pināki. Vā. 25. 2; 54. 108; 101. 317.

पिनाकधृक्
Pinākadhṛk --see Śiva: vanquished Pūṣan. ^1 Br. III. 23. 56; 24. 49; M. 180. 23; 281. 14. ^2 Vi. I. 9. 69. V. 16. 7:

पिनाकि
Pināki (Pinākapāṇi) --one of the eleven Rudras; an epithet of Maheśvara; 1) M. 5. 30; 6. 13; 12. 8; 23. 36, 41; 95. 38; 154. 118, 194, 395, 410. married Satī; has the bull for the riding animal and is the guardian deity for the N. E. 2) Ib. 60. 11; 67. 16.

पिपीलिका
Pipīlikā --the love quarrels between two ants, husband and wife, the husband having given pieces of modaka to some other she ant, the wife ant resented, the husband repented and promised to behave better in future; 1) M. 20. 39. marching north they forebode evil. 2) Ib. 238. 7.

पिप्पल
Pippala --a son of Mitra and Revatī. Bhā. VI. 18. 6. 

पिप्पला
Pippalā --a R. of the Bhāratavarṣa from the Ṛkṣa hill. Br. II. 16. 30. Vā. 45. 100.

पिप्पलाद
Pippalāda  (I)--a pupil of Devadarśa; the sage who communicated the Aṅgāravratam to Yudhiṣṭhira, narrating an old samvāda between Śukra and Virocana; 2) M. 72. 1, 5-6, 45. came to see Parīkṣit practising Prāyopaveśa; knew the Yoga power of Viṣṇu. 3) Bhā I. 19. 10; II. 7. 45: ^1 Br. II. 35. 57; Vi. III. 6. 10.

पिप्पलाद
Pippalāda  (II)--a disciple of Vedasparśa. Vā. 61. 51.

पिप्पलायन
Pippalāyana --a son of Rṣabha, a sage and a Bhāgavata; called the attention of Nimi to Nārāyaṇa as Brahman. Bhā. V. 4. 11; XI. 2. 21; 3. 35-40.

पिप्पलायनि
Pippalāyani --a pupil of Vedādarśa. Bhā. XII. 7. 2.

पिप्पल्य
Pippalya --a Pravara sage. M. 199. 15.

पिप्पलेशम्
Pippaleśam --a tirtham on the Narmadā. M. 190. 13-4.

पिलक
Pilaka --the son of Lambodara and father of Meghasvāti. Vi. IV. 24. 45.

पिलपिच्छिका
Pilapicchikā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 13. 

पिलि
Pili --an Ārṣeya Pravara (Bhārgavas). M. 195. 37.

पिशङ्ग
Piśaṅga  (I)--a Yakṣa; a son of Devajani. Br. III. 7. 128.

पिशन्ग
Piśanga  (II)--a Mt. to the south-west of the Kailāsa Mountain. Vā. 47. 9.

पिशन्ग
Piśanga Manu --from the Aikāra; of the ash colour. Vā. 26. 44.

पिशङ्गवर्ण
Piśaṅgavarṇa --the colour of the 11th Manu. Vā. 26. 43.

पिशंगाभ
Piśaṃgābha --the son of Maṇivara. Vā. 69. 159.

पिशाच
Piśāca --a son of Jāmbavān. Br. III. 7. 303.

पिशाचा
Piśācās --a kind of semi-divine beings governed by Śiva; 1) Br. II. 32. 1-2; 35, 191; M. 8. 5; Vā. 9. 55; 30. 90; 31. 12. three steps inferior to the Rākṣasas; 2) Br. III. 3. 97; 7. 168. born of Kapiśa; descendents of Krodhavaśā; sixteen kinds of, two distinguished among them; their forms and features, harassing children; seeing their awkward forms the creator blessed them with the powers of assuming any form and hiding themselves, moving about at both the sandhya times, frequenting deserted houses and waters, men devoid of ācāra and samskāra, royal roads, termini of roads, doors and doorways, trees on roads; deities for those professionalists who earn their livelihood by unrighteous means; bali offerings at the termini of the Parvas to them with liquor, flesh, sesamum, incense, black cloth,  etc.; 3) Ib. III. 7. 376-411: 8. 71; Bhā. I. 15. 43; II. 6. 43; 10. 38; VI. 8. 25; X. 6. 27; 45. 23; 63. 11; 85. 41. ruin the śrāddha, 4) Br. III. 11. 81. vanquished by Rāvaṇa; 5) Ib. III. 7. 256. people in Kali look like them; 6) Bhā. XII. 3. 40. create trouble to disputants in religion. 7) Vā. 66. 118.

पिशाचक
Piśācaka --a Mt. south of the Mānasa; 1) Vā. 36. 24. abode of Kubera. 2) Ib. 39. 57; 42. 31.

पिशाचानाम्
Piśācānām gaṇas --sixteen in number; Brahmā took pity on them and granted them a boon--to be invisible to men and to be able to take desirable forms; to wander at will at nightfall, to resort to deserted places and those frequented by few men, unclean residences, etc., royal roads, highways, doors, bolts, tīrthas, rivers, caitya trees, residences of Ajīvas, of mixed castes, artisans, the dishonest and ungrateful; money earned unworthily; here they live, to get rid of them bali is to be offered on the Parvas with honey, flesh, curds, tila, wine, black cloths, incense, etc. Vā. 69. 262-64, 286-88; 100. 159; 101. 28.

पिशाचिका
Piśācikā --a R. of the Bhāratavarṣa, from the Ṛkṣa hill. Br. II. 16. 30. Vā. 45. 100.

पिशाची
Piśācī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 16.

पिशिताद
Piśitādas --aerial beings with hands and feet on the back; live on the blood, shed in the field of battle. Vā. 69. 278.

पिशुन
Piśuna --one of the seven sons of Kauśika. M. 20. 3. 

पीठ
Pīṭha --the commander of Mura's forces; killed by Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 59. 12-14.

पीठिका
Pīṭhikā --a pedestal (base) on which the image is installed; here must be provided a Praṇālaka to let water flow; ten kinds of Pīṭhikas distinguished; Śthaṇḍita, Vāpī, Yakṣī, Vedī, Maṇḍalā, Pūrṇacandrā, Vajrā, Padmā, Ardhaśāsī, and Trikoṇa, 1) M. 262. 1-7. these may be made of stone, earth, or wood according to the Linga. 2) Ib. 262. 19-20; 269. 8.

पीडापर
Pīḍāpara --a son of Khaśa and a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 135.

पीतभौम
Pītabhauma --the earth of the fourth talam; atalam. Br. II. 20. 14.

पीतवासा
Pītavāsās --the 31st Kalpa; Brahmā attained pīta colour; a son of that colour came out of his contemplation; even the Yajñopavīta was of that colour; from his meditation of Maheśvarī, Brahmā saw Gāand Virūpa dropping out of the mouth of Maheśvara with four feet, four faces, four hands, four breasts, four eyes, etc. She was Rudrāṇi surrounded by sons who lived for 1000 years for the welfare of the Brahmanas and attained Rudrahood. Vā. 23. 1-21.

पीत
Pītas --the Vaiśya caste of Śālmalidvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 30.

पीताम्बरम्
Pītāmbaram --yellow cloth worn by Budha at birth. M. 24. 1; Vā. 104. 47.

पीतायुत
Pītāyuta --a son of Manasyu. M. 49. 2. 

पीप्पली
Pīppalī --a R. from Rṣyavān. M. 114. 25.

पीवर
Pīvara  (I)--A Vāsiṣṭha and one of the seven sages of Tāmasa Manu. Br. II. 36. 48; Vi. III. 1. 18.

पीवर
Pīvara  (II)--a son of Dyutimān; after his name a Janapada Pīvaram in the Krauñcadvīpa Vā. 33. 21, 22; Vi. II. 4. 48.

पीवरक
Pīvaraka --a region of Krauñcadvīpa (also Pāvana). Br. II. 19. 72.

पीवरी
Pīvarī  (I)--a daughter of Pulaha and Kṣamā. Br. II. 11. 31; Vā. 28. 26.

पीवरी
Pīvarī  (II)--the mind-born daughter of Agniṣvāttapitṛs; becomes the wife of Śuka in the 28th dvāpara. Br. III. 10. 77-78.

पीवरी
Pīvarī  (III)--a mind-born daughter of Barhiṣad manes who performed severe austerities and earned the title of Yogamātā. The Lord blessed her to be the wife of Śuka, the son of Vyāsa and after giving birth to four sons and a daughter she would attain salvation; 1) M. 15. 5-11. wife of Śuka. 2) Br. III. 8. 93.

पीवरी
Pīvarī  (IV)--the wife of Vedaśiras; 1) Vā. 28. 6. sons, Mārkaṇḍeyas. 2) Br. II. 11. 8.

पीवरी
Pīvarī  (V)--a R. of the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 22. 

पीवरी
Pīvarī  (VI)--the mind-born daughter of Pitṛ Dharmamūrtidharas; becomes the wife of Śuka and mother of Kīrtimatī. Vā. 73. 26.

पुञ्जि
Puñji(a) kasthali(ā) --a distinguished Apsaras engaged in playing with balls and presiding over the months of Madhu and Mādhava; was sent to disturb Mārkaṇḍeya's penance; but only in vain. Bhā. XII. 8. 26; 11. 34; Br. II. 23. 4; III. 7. 14; IV. 33. 19; Vā. 52. 4; 69. 49; Vi. II. 10. 5.

पुण्डरीक
Puṇḍarīka  (I)--the son of Nabha and father of Kṣemadhanvan. Bhā. IX. 12. 1; Br. III. 63. 202; Vā. 88. 202; Vi. IV. 4, 106. M. 12. 53.

पुण्डरीक
Puṇḍarīka  (II)--a Mt. in Krauñcadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 68; M. 122. 82; Vā. 49. 63.

पुण्डरीक
Puṇḍarīka  (III)--an elephant born of Rathanthara. Br. III. 7. 335; Vā. 69. 219.

पुण्डरीक
Puṇḍarīka  (IV)--a sacred tīrtha fit for śrāddha. Br. III. 13. 56; Vā. 77. 55.

पुण्डरीक
Puṇḍarīka  (V)--the name of a Yājña or sacrifice. M. 53. 27; Vā. 71. 77.

पुण्डरीक
Puṇḍarīka  (VI)--a Nāga. Vā. 69. 72.

पुण्डरीक
Puṇḍarīka  (VII)--(also Puṇḍarikākṣa) Viṣṇu. Vā. 106. 55; 108. 89; 109. 24 and 34. 

पुण्डरीकपुरम्
Puṇḍarīkapuram --a tīrtham, sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 77.

पुण्डरीकवान्
Puṇḍarīkavān --Mt. a chief hill of Krauñcadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 51.

पुण्डरीका
Puṇḍarīkā  (I)--the eldest daughter of Vasiṣṭha and Ūrjā; wife of Prāṇa (Pāṇḍu, son of Vidhāta and ĀyatīVā. P.) and mother of Dyutimān. Br. II. 11. 9, 40; Vā. 28. 7, 34-5.

पुण्डरीका
Puṇḍarīkā  (II)--a R. from the lake Payodā. Br. II. 18. 70.

पुण्डरीका
Puṇḍarīkā  (III)--a R. in Krauñcadvīpā. Br. II. 19. 75; M. 122. 88; Vā. 49. 69; Vi. II. 4. 55.

पुण्डरीका
Puṇḍarīkā  (IV)--an Apsaras. Br. III. 7. 8; Vā. 69. 7.

पुन्दरीका
Pundarīkā  (V)--a R. rising on the western side of the Meru Mountain. Vā. 47. 67.

पुण्डरीकाक्ष
Puṇḍarīkākṣa --the brother of Śrīdevī; 1) Br. IV. 39. 48. Lord of all sacrifices; 2) M 239. 38. an attribute of Viṣṇu. 3) Vi. I. 9. 68.

पुण्ड्र
Puṇḍra  (I)--a Kṣetraja son of Bali, born of Dīrghatamas and Bali's wife; a Bāleyakṣatra. Bhā. IX. 23. 5; M. 48. 25; Vā. 99. 28, 85.

पुण्ड्र
Puṇḍra  (II)--a pupil of Yājñavalkya. Br. II. 35. 29.

पुण्ड्र
Puṇḍra  (III)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 237. 

पुण्ड्र
Puṇḍra  (IV)--a son of Sugandhī and Vasudeva; became king. Br. II. 71. 186; Vā. 96. 182.

पुण्ड्र
Puṇḍra  (V)--a son of Vasudeva, became Jarā, a hunter; 1) M. 46. 21-22. became king. 2) Vā. 96. 182.

पुण्ड्रकेतु
Puṇḍraketu --a commander of Bhaṇḍa to aid Viṣanga, killed by Tvaritā. Br. IV. 21. 79; 25. 28, 97.

पुण्ड्रम्
Puṇḍram --a city between Hemakūṭa and Himālaya which is snowfed; 1) Br. II. 22. 53; Vā. 51. 48. under Devarakṣita. 2) Vi. IV. 24. 64.

पुण्ड्रवर्धन
Puṇḍravardhana --sacred to Pāṭalā. M. 13. 35.

पुण्ड्रा
Puṇḍrā --a R. of the Kuśadvīpa. M. 122. 73.

पुण्ड्रा
Puṇḍrās  (I)--a tribe; a Janapada of the East. M. 114. 45.

पुण्ड्रा
Puṇḍrās  (II) (c)--an eastern country named after Bali's son, Puṇḍra. Br. II. 16. 54; III. 73. 109; 74. 33, 87, 197; IV. 29. 131; Vi. II. 3. 16.

पुण्य
Puṇya --a king (see Puṇyavān). M. 50. 30. 

पुण्यजन
Puṇyajanas --(Yakṣas): sons and grandsons of Puṇyajaṇī who married Maṇibhadrā; 1) Vā. 69. 157; 88. 1. worshipped for protection. 2) Bhā. II. 3. 8; Br. III. 7. 162, Sacked Kuśaṣṭhalī during the absence of Kakudmi in Brahmaloka. 3) Ib. III. 68. 1; Vi. IV. 2. 1.

पुण्यजनी
Puṇyajanī --the wife of Maṇibhadra; gave birth to 24 sons, who in their turn gave birth to a number of sons and grandsons. Br. III. 7. 121, 126; Vā. 69. 153.

पुण्यवान्
Puṇyavān --a son of Vṛṣabha. M. 50. 29.

पुण्यश्लोक
Puṇyaśloka --a name of Yudhiṣṭhira. Bhā. I. 8. 32.

पुण्या
Puṇyā --a daughter of Kratu and Sannati and daughterin-law of Parvaśa. Br. II. 11. 38; Vā. 28. 33.

पुण्याहवाचनम्
Puṇyāhavācanam --preliminary to religious observances; (see Brāhmaṇavācanam). M. 275. 3.

पुण्येयु
Puṇyeyu --a son of Bhadrāśva. M. 49. 6.

पुण्योदा
Puṇyodā  (I)--a R. aerial river, springing from the moon; circumambulates Meru and flows in four directions; one goes round the Mandara and the Caitraratha hills and enters the Aruṇoda lake. Vā. 42. 3, 8, 15. 

पुण्योदा
Puṇyodā  (II)--a R. of the Ketumālā. Vā. 44. 19.

पुत्
Put --a hell. Br. II. 36. 151. Vi. I. 13. 42.

पुत्र
Putra  (I)--one of the seven sons of Vasiṣṭha Vā. 28. 36.

पुत्र
Putra  (II)--a son of Svāyambhuva Manu. Vā. 31. 18.

पुत्र
Putra  (III)--a son of Priyavrata given to yoga: had no inclination for ruling the kingdom. Vi. II. 1. 7-9.

पुत्रक
Putraka --a son of Kuru. Vā. 99. 218.

पुत्रधर्मा
Putradharmā --a son of Svarbhānu. Vā. 92. 2.

पुत्रव
Putrava --a Trayārṣeya. M. 196. 39.

पुत्रिकषेण
Putrikaṣeṇa --another reading (Purīkaṣeṇa): an Andhra king; ruled for 21 years. Vā. 99. 352.

पुत्रिका
Putrikā --an Apsaras. Vā. 69. 5.

पुत्रिका
Putrikā dharma --a son-less father generally gives his daughter in marriage and takes a promise from the sonin-law that the son of them would be counted as his own.  Though Svāyambhuva Manu had a son, he adopted Ākūti's son. Bhā. IV. 1. 2 and 5.

पुत्रिकापति
Putrikāpati --the son-in-law by Putrikā; 1) Vā. 79. 78. unfit for śrāddha. 2) Br. III. 15. 52.

पुत्रेष्टिः
Putreṣṭiḥ --a sacrifice performed by Diti when Āpastamba acted as priest; 1) M. 7. 33-34. performed by Vaivasvata Manu who got Ila. 2) Ib. 11. 40.

पुनर्वसु
Punarvasu  (I)--a Nakṣatra: Importance of Śrāddha on. Bhā. V. 23. 6; Vā. 66. 48; 82. 4. Br. III. 18. 4.

पुनर्वसु
Punarvasu  (II)--a son of Daridyota. Bhā. IX. 24. 20-1.

पुनर्वसु
Punarvasu  (III)--the son of Abhijit; performed Aśvamedha for the birth of a son; born in the middle of the Yajña, atirātra portion; he had twins Āhuka and Āhukī. Br. III. 71. 119, Vā. 96. 118. Vi. IV. 14. 14-5.

पुनर्वसु
Punarvasu  (IV)--a son of Nala. M. 44. 64-6.

पुमान्
Pumān --the 21st Kalpa. M. 290. 8.

पुंसवनम्
Puṃsavanam  (I)--a vrata of a year's duration imposed on Ditī by Kaśyapa for the birth of a son capable of  killing Indra; details of the vrata are given; generally begun by a woman with the permission of her husband on the bright fortnight of Mārgaśīrṣa; worship of Lakṣmīnārāyaṇa with the havis śeṣa; 12 Ahūtis made to Agni; this is to continue for twelve months; on the last day of Kārtikai she should keep fast; next day the husband offers twelve oblations according to the rule of pākayajña; Brahmanas to be fed and the remnant of the Caru to be offered to his wife; by this one is said to attain desired objects; it can be observed by an unmarried girl or married woman or mother for the sake of auspiciousness. Bhā. VI. 18. 47-54; 19. 5-28.

पुंसवनम्
Puṃsavanam  (II)--here Vāyu met Añjanā who gave birth to Hanumān. Br. III. 7. 224.

पुंसवनम्
Puṃsavanam  (III)--a samskāra. M. 275. 16.

पुंश्चली
Puṃścalī --a class of women who came from the mouth of Asura Bala when he yawned Bhā. V. 24. 16.

पुर
Pura --killed by Śiva. M. 55. 16.

पुरजित्
Purajit --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 83.

पुरञ्जन
Purañjana  (I)--a King of extensive learning, had a friend whose name and behaviour were not known; went in search of a suitable place for the realisation of various pleasures; this he found in a city of nine entrances resembling  Bhogavatī on the southern side of the Himālayas. By accident he met a charming lady protected by a serpent and followed by a number of ladies and men; moved by her charms he requested her to be his wife and she agreed; For a hundred years they continued to enjoy pleasures; Purañjana used to visit the kingdoms, Vibhrājita, Saurabha, Dakṣiṇa and Uttara Pāñcālas, Grāmaka, Vaiśasa and others through the different entrances of the city guarded by the Superintendent; influenced by her charms he came completely under her control; mad with desire for hunting, once he left his queen and went to the forest and after killing many a game, he returned home and desired to meet the queen whom he found lying on the bare ground in misery; he consoled her and once more yielded to her love and influence at the cost of his youth; he had 1100 sons and 110 daughters for whom he found worthy wives and suitable bridegrooms; he was then engaged in animal sacrifices, when the followers of Caṇḍavega, a Gandharva, attacked the city of Purañjana and the Superintendent defended it single-handed for 100 years. This placed the citizens and the kinsmen in misery. A daughter of Kāla, once in the company of Pūru went to Bhaya, the Lord of the Yavanas to marry him; he adopted her as his sister; with her and his brother Prajvāra he set out to wander in the world; in his tour the Yavanas attacked the city of Purañjana; Prajvāra burnt it down; Purañjana was seized and taken to the Yavana camp; the sacrificial animals tore him to pieces; was born as the daughter of Vidarbha Rājasimha; married by Malayadhvaja Pāṇḍya and gave birth to a daughter and seven sons, all kings of the Drāviḍa country. When the Pāṇḍya left for penance she went with him and served him; she wailed at his death; and when about to give up her own life, a Brahmana who called himself her friend consoled her by saying that he and she were once the two Hamsas of Mānasa and that she took to a household life and underwent all miseries; instructed thus she recollected her old status and remained calm; 1) Bhā. IV. chh. 25-28 (whole). an allegory  for Jīva and Paramātman; Pāñcālas are the five senses while the nine entrances to the city refer to the nine dvāras of the body; sometimes the Jīva is a male sometimes a female, and sometimes God, and sometimes man or beast in accordance with Karma. 2) Ib. IV. 29. 2-9, 29.

पुरञ्जन
Purañjana  (II)--an Asura having his city in the third talam. Br. II. 20. 27.

पुरञ्जनी
Purañjanī --the wife of Purañjana; a charming woman protected by a serpent with five hoods and followed by ten servants each in turn followed by a hundred; married Purañjana at his request and lived with him for years together; 1) Bhā. IV. 25. 20-24, 43-44. felt annoyed at his going for hunting and was consoled by him on his return after which he completely surrendered himself to her; 2) Ib. IV. 26. 4 and 13-26. mother of 1100 sons and 110 daughters; 3) Ib. IV. 27. 6-7. allegorically she is the buddhi or intellect. 4) Ib. IV. 29. 5. (See Purañjana).

पुरञ्जय
Purañjaya  (I)--alias Indravāha; also Kakustha: son of Vikukṣi father of Anenas; in a Devāsura war he became Pārṣṇigrāha to the Devas when Indra assumed the form of a bull over which he rode and discomfited the Asuras by his bhalla weapons; hence known as Kakustha; a Rājaṛṣi. Bhā. IX. 6. 12-20; Vi. IV. 2. 20-32.

पुरञ्जय
Purañjaya  (II)--a King of the Māgadhas including Pulindas Yadus and Madrakas among the castes; will establish anti-Brahmana subjects, will exterminate the Kṣatriyas and rule from Padmāvatī, the country along the Gangā as far as Prayāgā. Bhā. XII. 1. 36-37. 

पुरञ्जय
Purañjaya  (III)--the last of the Bārhadratha line; was killed by his minister Śunaka who placed his own son on the throne. Bhā. XII. 1. 2-3.

पुरञ्जय
Purañjaya  (IV)--the son of Sṛñjaya, (Sanjaya-M. P.) a hero equal to Indra, and whose glory was sung in heaven; 1) Br. III. 74. 14-15; M. 48. 12; Vā. 99. 14. father of Janamejaya. 2) Vi. IV. 18. 4-5.

पुरञ्जय
Purañjaya  (V)--a son of Medhāvi. M. 50. 84.

पुरञ्जय
Purañjaya  (VI)--the son of Suśānti and father of Ṛkṣa. Vi. IV. 19. 57.

पुरञ्जय
Purañjaya  (VII)--the son of Vindhyaśakti and father of Ramacandra. Vi. IV. 24. 56.

पुरन्दर
Purandara  (I)--Indra of the Vaivasvata epoch; 1000 eyed. Bhā. VIII. 13. 4; IX. 8. 8; X. 77. 36-7; XII. 8. 15. Br. II. 36. 205. Vā. 34. 75; 62. 178; 64. 7; 67. 102. Vi. III. 1. 31 and 43; V. 21. 16.

पुरन्दर
Purandara  (II)--Indra observed Ādityaśayanam; 1) M. 55. 32; 178. 65; 246. 69; 248. 14. one of the authors on architecture; 2) Ib. 252. 2. the abode of. 3) Ib. 274. 78.

पुरन्ध्राष्
Purandhrāṣ --a Northern tribe. M. 114. 40.

पुरम्
Puram --city; began with Pṛthu; 1) Br. II. 36. 197; III. 50. 9; 56. 24; 63. 165; 69. 40; IV. 38. 44; Vi. I. 6. 18-19; V. 36. 6; Vā. 34. 10; 48. 7. its evacuation by the people for the woods during periods of anarchy. 2) M. 6. 13, 10. 32; 47. 257; 143. 3. 

पुरवस
Puravasa --a son of Madhu and father of Purudvān. M. 44. 44.

पुरशतम्
Puraśatam --in Śataśṛṅga hill of the Yakṣas. Vā. 39. 54.

पुराकल्प
Purākalpa --(ety.) one of the ten lakṣanas of the Brāhmaṇa. Vā. 59. 137.

पुराजित्
Purājit --a son of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 26. 49.

पुराण
Purāṇa --on measurement of time. Br. II. 21. 137.

पुराणज्ञ
Purāṇajñas --Persons well-versed in the Purāṇas speak of eight-fold characteristics of Karmayoga; 1) Br. I. 2. 45. Vā. 1. 30; 2. 45; 70. 77; 88. 69; 96. 13; 99. 417; 101. 70. M. 44. 57; 52. 11. speak of the vow, Ādityaśayanam; 2) Ib. 55. 3. and the time between Parīkṣit and Mahāpadma is 1050 and that between Mahāpadma and Āndhrapulomā is 836. 3) Ib. 273. 38.

पुराणपुरुष
Purāṇapuruṣa --the Supreme Being or Viśvātmā, revealed the Purāṇas; 1) M. 53. 2; 61. is Nārāyaṇa; 2) Vā. 21. 81; 22. 13. is Kumāra. 3) Ib. 22. 13.

पुराण
Purāṇas --originally one: 100 crores of verses reduced to four lakhs by Vyāsa; 1) Br. I. 1. 39-40, 173; II. 21. 9, 37; 28, 96; 35. 63, 88; III. 19. 23; 42. 31; M. 3. 3; 53. 3-4, 9; Vā. 1. 11, 60; 9. 69. eighteen in number; Brāhma, Pādma, Vaiṣnava, Śaiva, Linga, Gāruda, Skānda, Nāradīya, Bhāgavata, Āgneya, Bhaviṣya, Brahmavaivartha, Mārkandeya, Vāmana, Vārāha, Mātsya, Kūrma and Brahmānḍa; total content of these 400,000 verses; 2) M. 53. 64-72; Vā. 95. 22; 104. 2, 11, 85, 108; Vi. III. 6. 20-25. Bhā. XII. 7. 22-4; 13. 9. known to Sūta; 3) Ib. I. 1. 6; III. 12. 39. speak of places where Hari worship is offered; 4) Ib. VII. 14. 29; X. 69. 28. the essence of the Purāṇas in the Śrutigīta; 5) Ib. X. 87. 43. Interpreters of the Purāṇas; 6) Vi. V. 20. 49. of four pādas; 7) Vā. 10. 70; 21. 3; 31. 30; 32. 67, 103. 44-5.  from Brahmā to Vyāsa and then to Sūta, 8) Br. IV. 2. 19; 4. 43-4, 58-67. Purāṇakathas, the first of all Śāstras remembered by Brahmā, and afterwards the Vedas issued from his faces 9) M. 1. 5; 2. 13; 17. 37; Vā. 56. 7; 61. 55, 78; 83. 53; 100. 33 ff. originally one and 100 crore slokas; treatise on Trivarga, during the disaster of the world by fire God Hayagrīva saved the Purāṇas among other sciences; again as Matsyajanārdana; in every dvāpara Vyāsa gives 18 versions of 4 lacs in verses, a summary account of the original now preserved in heaven; the names of 18 as given by Brahmā to Marīci in olden days; 10) M. 53. 3-12 and 13. five limbs: sarga, pratisarga, vamśa, manvantara and vamśyānucarita; description of deities and gods, of caturvarga; to be divided into sātvika where Viṣṇu is much extolled; rājasa where Brahmā is much extolled and tāmasa where Agni and Śiva are much extolled; in others Śarasvatī and Pitṛs are given (saṅkīrṇa); 11) Ib. 53. 65-69. hearing of; 12) Ib. 75. 6; 93. 3 and 7; 274. 38; 280. 12. Bhaviṣya the most ancient of the Purāṇas; 13) Ib. 58. 4, 50; 69. 18. the Purāṇa version of Varāha Avatāra attributed to Brahmā; 14) Ib. 247. 1, 5. the Purāṇa in general partakes the character of the epoch in which it is composed; 15) Ib. 290. 15. recital of, during srāddha. 16) Ib. 17. 37.

पुराणलक्षणम्
Purāṇalakṣaṇam --the ten characteristics of a Purāṇa; some speak of five characteristics only; the ten characteristics described. Bhā. XII. 7. 8-21; Br. I. 1. 38.

पुराणवेत्ता
Purāṇavettā --eligible for Pārvaṇa śrāddha; also Purāṇajña, Purāṇavid. M. 16. 9; 44. 22. 57. 2; 60. 1: 289. 9. 

पुराणसम्हिता
Purāṇasamhitā --a reference to the Matsyapurāṇa; superior to all the Śāstras; a road to Dharma, Artha and Kāma; 1) M. 290. 20, 25, 291. 1, 36. the last chapter is an appendix dealing with rules as to how the Purāṇa must be worshipped, read or heard. If they disregard the rules they would not only not get the fruits there of, but will be born as dogs, pigs, crows, etc. The vācaka must be honoured as Vyāsa and Aṅgiras; 2) Ib. Ch. 292 (whole). consists of ākhyāna, upākhyāna, gathas and kalpaja (Br. P.) (Kulakarmas-Vā. P.); 3) Br. II. 34. 21; Vā. 60. 21. Vi. III. 6. 16-17. Reference to Parāśara and Viṣṇu Purāṇa; 4) Ib. I. 1. 26; VI. 8. 2-3. follows Vedic tradition. 5) Ib. VI. 8. 12.

पुराणसम्हिता
Purāṇasamhitās --personified: came up to see Trivikrama Hari. Bhā. VIII. 21. 2.

पुराणाख्यान
Purāṇākhyāna --ety. of Purāṇa; ‘पुराहिअनतीदं’ this lived before. Br. I. 1. 7; Vā. 1. 8, 203.

पुरा
Purās --towns; triangular, round, short or long, condensed; but a square type is celebrated; the chief house, (Palace) measuring 800 Kiṣku. Br. I. 5. 99; 7. 93 and 105; Vā. 8. 99, 113ff.

पुरारित्वम्
Purāritvam --an incarnation of Śiva. M. 1. 8; 23. 37.

पुरीण
Purīṇas  (Purāṇas)--a Piśāca gaṇa; big faces, hanging brows, abnormal noses, residents of deserted places. Vā. 69. 263, 276.

पुरीन्द्रसेन
Purīndrasena --a son of Mandulaka (Āndhra). M. 273. 10. 

पुरीमान्
Purīmān --a King and son of Gomatiputra and father of Medaśiras. Bhā. XII. 1. 26. 7.

पुरीषभीरु
Purīṣabhīru --a king and son of Talaka and father of Sunandana: ruled for 21 years. Bhā. XII. 1. 25. Br. III. 74. 166.

पुरीषम्
Purīṣam --faeces; to be discharged at a distance from the house in the S.W. direction, without touching the head with the hand; other details connected with cleansing follow; he who discards these rules becomes a mleccha; śauca leads by itself to mokṣa. Vā. 78. 59-67 and 74-5.

पुरीषि
Purīṣi --produced by Brahmā. Bhā. III. 12. 40.

पुरीष्या
Purīṣyās --Agnis born of Krīyā and Samanantara. Bhā. VI. 18. 4.

पुरु
Puru  (I)--a son of Cāksuṣa Manu; his race was known as Pauravas; a son of Manu (also Maru) and Naḍvalā. Bhā. IV. 13. 16; III. 1. 2; 3. 17. Vi. I. 13. 5.

पुरु
Puru  (II)--a son of Vasudeva and Sahadevā. Bhā. IX. 24. 52-53.

पुरु
Puru  (III)--a son of Yayāti and Śarmiṣṭhā; his anointment by Yayāti on account of his faithfulness to his parents. Br. III. 6. 25; Vā. 68. 24; 93. 17, 55-88.

पुरु
Puru  (IV)--married Bṛhatī. Br. III. 71. 255. 

पुरुकुत्स
Purukutsa --a Rājaṛṣi and a son of Māndhāta and Bindumatī; An Angīrasa and Mantrakṛt; married Narmadā; father of Trasadasyu; went to Rasātala where he killed undesirable Mauneya Gandharvas on behalf of the Nagas; a Kṣetropetadvija; 2) Br. III. 63. 72; 66. 87. not to marry with the Angīras and Sādasyus; 3) M. 196. 37. Heard the Viṣṇu Purāṇa from Bhṛgu and the other sages on the banks of the Narmadā and narrated it to Sārasvata. 4) Vi. I. 2. 9; VI. 8. 45. ^1 Bhā. IX. 6. 38; 7. 2-3; Br. II. 32. 108; III. 10. 98; M. 12. 35; 145. 102; Vi. IV. 2. 67; 3. 6-16; Vā. 93. 49; 91. 116.

पुरुज
Puruja --the son of Suśānti and father of Arka. Bhā. IX. 21. 31.

पुरुजानु
Purujānu --a son of Suśānti. M. 50. 3; Vā. 99. 195.

पुरुजित्
Purujit  (I)--(Purajit Br. P.) the son of Aja and father of Ariṣṭanemi. Bhā. IX. 13. 22-23.

पुरुजित्
Purujit  (II)--a son of Rucaka. Bhā. IX. 23. 35.

पुरुजित्
Purujit  (III)--a son of Ānaka and Kankā. Bhā. IX. 24. 41.

पुरुजित्
Purujit  (IV)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Jāmbavatī. Bhā. X. 61. 11.

पुरुजित्
Purujit  (V)--a vassal of Yudhiṣṭhira who went to Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse. Bhā. X. 82. 25.

पुरुण्ड
Puruṇḍa --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 8. 

पुरुद्वान्
Purudvān --the son of Puruvasu (Puruvaśa-Vā. P.); the best among men; his wife was Bhadrāvatī and son Purūdvaha; 1) Br. III. 70. 47; Vā. 95. 46. (Father of Janhu by Bhadrasenī, the Vidarbha princess-M. P.). 2) M. 44. 44-5.

पुरुमित्र
Purumitra --the son of Anu and father of Amśu, a king. Vi. IV. 12. 42-3.

पुरुमीढ
Purumīḍha --a son of Hasti; childless. Bhā. IX. 21. 21, 30; M. 49. 43; Vi. IV. 19. 29.

पुरुवश
Puruvaśa --a son of Madhu. Vā. 95. 46.

पुरुवसु
Puruvasu --a son of Madhu and father of Purudvān. Br. III. 70. 46.

पुरुविश्रुत
Puruviśruta --a son of Vasudeva and Sahadevā. Bhā. IX. 24. 53.

पुरुष
Puruṣa  (I)--as Virāṭ; subject of meditation; ety. of; 1) Bhā. I. 3. 1; II. 1. 25-39; Vā. 59. 76. the invisible principle; 2) Bhā. XI. 16. 37; 22. 14; 24. 4-5. as dwelling in Hṛdākāśa; 3) Ib. II. 2. 8-13; Vā. 4. 44. as issuing from the primordial aṇḍa (egg); 4) Bhā. II. 5. 35-42. as yajña; 5) Ib. II. 6. 1-27. course of further cosmic evolution from Puruṣa; 6) Ib. II. 6. 28-31; Vi. I. 2. 14-15, 60-65; VI. 4. 46. first avatār of Para Iśvara and Prakṛti; 7) Bhā. II. 6. 41. Vā. 5. 20, 29, 32. avatārs of Puruṣa; 8) Bhā. II. 6. 41-5. as Varāha; 9) Ib. II. 7. 1; 10. 10; Ib. III. 26. 21-22; VI. 13. 18. His energy; 10) Ib. XII. 4. 22. identified with Suparṇa; 11) Ib. XII. 11. 19. invoked by cowherds; 12) Ib. X. 6. 23. personated as Kṛṣṇa and Rāma; 13) Ib. X. 38. 15 and 32. celebrated by Akrūra. 14) Ib. X. 40. (whole). Śiva according to the Sānkhyas; 15) Br. II. 9. 36, 39. primaeval male from whom the universe was evolved; supposed to be the 25th tatva according to one school and the 26th including Īśvara according to the other; 16) M. 3. 27-8. constitutes twenty-five truths; 17) Ib. 60. 3; 266. 52; 274. 62. description of. 18) Vā. 7. 62-7. 

पुरुष
Puruṣa  (II)--one of the names in the fifth Marut gaṇa. Br. III. 5. 97. Vā. 59. 76; 67. 128; 102. 117.

पुरुष
Puruṣa  (III)--a dānava, killed by Sampadīśa. Br. III. 6. 16; IV. 28. 38 and 101.

पुरुष
Puruṣa  (IV)--a son of Añjanāvatī an elephant. Br. III. 7. 343.

पुरुषपशु
Puruṣapaśu --sacrificed to Bhadrakāli for the sake of children. Bhā. V. 9. 12.

पुरुषमेध
Puruṣamedha --an offence leading to Rakṣogaṇabhojana hell; of Hariścandra with Śunaśśepa as paśu. Bhā. V. 26. 31; IX. 7. 21.

पुरुषसूक्त
Puruṣasūkta --Brahmā praised Hari by this; 1) Bhā. X. 1. 20; Br. IV. 43. 12. to be uttered while installing a new image. 2) M. 265. 26.

पुरुष
Puruṣas  (I)--a class of people in Krauñcadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 22.

पुरुष
Puruṣas  (II)--minor officials to be appointed in places according to qualifications. M. 215. 45.

पुरुषार्थ
Puruṣārthas --four in number; 1) Vi. I. 18. 21. realised by the study of Viṣṇu Purāṇa. 2) Ib. VI. 8. 3. 

पुरुषेण
Puruṣeṇa --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 84.

पुरुषोत्तम
Puruṣottama  (I)--a name of Bhāgavata; of Kṛṣṇa. 2) Ib. X. 58. 1; Vi. VI. 4. 42 and 45. ^1 Bhā. VII. 4. 2.

पुरुषोत्तम
Puruṣottama  (II)--a tīrtha sacred to Vimalā and the Pitṛs;^1 temple of; Kaṇḍu offered prayers and got rid of the sin of living with the Apsaras, Pramlocā by the Japa, Brahmapāra. M. 13. 35; 22. 38; Vi. I. 15. 52; V. 17. 6 and 33; 38. 45, 78-82.

पुरुहूत
Puruhūta --see Indra. Br. III. 72. 23; M. 55. 3. 3, 69. 60; 174. 3; Vā. 97. 24.

पुरुहूता
Puruhūtā --a Goddess enshrined at Puṣkara. M. 13. 30.

पुरुहोत्र
Puruhotra --a son of Anu and father of Āyu. Bhā. IX. 24. 6.

पुरू
Purū --a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu. Br. II. 36. 79. 106.

पुरूद्वह
Purūdvaha --a son of Purudvān and Bhadravatī; married Aikṣvākī (a daughter of Ikṣvāku) and had a son, Satva. Br. III. 70. 47; Vā. 95. 47.

पुरूमीध
Purūmīdha --one of the three sons of Hasti. Vā. 99. 166.

पुरूरवस्
Purūravas  (I)--(Aila) son of Budha and (Sudyumna in female form) Ilā; anointed king of Pratiṣṭhāna (Prayāgā) by Sudyumna when he retired to forest; 1) Bhā. IX. 1. 35, 42; Br. III. 65. 45-6; 66. 1-2, 19-22; M. 12. 15; Vā. 1. 106; Vi. IV. 1. 12 and 16. eager for territory; 2) Bhā. XII. 3. 9. having heard of his beauty from Nārada, Ūrvaśī  desired to marry him; she met the king and offered to be with him under two conditions, that he would undertake to protect the two sheep in her custody, and never to show himself naked except at their sexual intercourse; agreeing to the conditions he enjoyed her company, going round the earth, and frequenting Caitraratha and other gardens; missing Ūrvaśi, Indra asked his Gandharvas to fetch her back; at midnight they stole the sheep, and hearing their noise she induced Purūravas to recover them; the king who was then naked, went as he was and fetched them back; but Ūrvaśī seeing him naked left him; mad in love with her he followed her naked begging her to stay on; he found her playing in the Sarasvatī waters with five friends; on an appeal from him she agreed to sleep with him one day every year; but he was all anxious to have her for ever; on her advice he prayed to the Gandharvas who gave him accommodation and an Agnisṭhālī; he left it on the way in a forest and went home; meanwhile Tretāyuga had commenced; he went to see his sthālī but found an aśvattha instead; there in order to get at Ūrvaśī he cut off a couple of branches (araṇi) and churned them; fire, Jātavedas came with the three Vedas who all became his sons; by this one Veda became three; 3) Ib. IX. 14. 15-49; Vā. 91. 1-52; Vi. IV. 6. 34-93. had six sons Āyu and others by Ūrvaśī; 4) Bhā. IX. 15. 1; 17. 1; Vā. 91. 48; Br. I. 1. 89; 2. 14. finding she had gone once for all, he repented his action, got ashamed of his position as king and devoted himself to Hari; worshipped the Fire which was his son and reached the Gandharva world; the story given as an example of the evils of bad association; 5) Bhā. XI. 26. 3-35. meets Pitṛs every New Moon day; a Kṣatriya mantravādin; ācārya of Sāmagas; originator of three sacred fires 6) Br. II. 28. 1-9, 97; 32. 120; 33. 9; M. 145. 115; Vā. 56. 1, 22; 91. 48. of the Ikṣvāku line but originator of the lunar race and a Rājaṛṣi; the Ailas came into prominence in the Tretāyuga and declined in the Kali. 7) M. 12. 15; 13. 62; 273. 52-3, 65. By meditating on the 108 names of the Devī scored success over his enemies; 8) Ib. 13. 62. as a result of tapas at the Himālayas in honour of Janārdana, became the lord of the seven Dvīpas; slew Keśī and other Asuras; was offered ardhāsanam by Indra, going to see him every day; paid more attention to Dharma  and incurred the displeasure of Artha and Kāma; Initiated in Bharatanāṭya Śāstra 9) Ib. 24. 10-33. in Dvijagrāma, became the king of Madradeśa in the Cākṣuṣa Manvantara; 10) Ib. 115. 4, 7-8, 10-18. served Kūhu and Sinīvāli to obtain nectar from the moon for performing rituals to the Pitṛs; gained his wish by the blessings of Atri 11) Ib. 141, 1, 8-20. and by tapas in the Himālayas. 12) Ib. chh. 116-17, 119; 120. 48.

पुरूरवस्
Purūravas  (II)--a Viśvedeva. Br. III. 3. 31.

पुरूहूत
Purūhūta --a name of Indra; his city is said to have a 1000 gates. M. 38. 15.

पुरोजव
Purojava  (I)--a son of Medhātithi of Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 25.

पुरोजव
Purojava  (II)--a son of Prāṇa. Bhā. VI. 6. 12.

पुरोजव
Purojava  (III)--a son of Anila, a Vasava. M. 203. 7.

पुरोडाश
Puroḍāśa --the sacrificial offerings to Devas; 1) Br. III. 67. 97; Vā. 31. 48; 92. 92; Vi. IV. 9. 18. made of burnt flour; 2) M. 239. 32. symbol of Trayambaka Rudra. 3) Br. II. 9. 6; 13. 146. 

पुरोदा
Purodās --see Purohita. 1) Br. III. 10. 101; IV. 9. 11; Vā. 99. 37. 111. 81. Khāṇḍikya's Purodās followed the banished king to the forest. 2) Vi. VI. 6. 11.

पुरोध्यानम्
Purodhyānam --sacred to Lalitāpītham. Br. IV. 44. 100.

पुरोवह
Purovaha --a son of the third Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 80.

पुरोहित
Purohita --of the Asuras; 1) Bhā. VII. 5. 1. versed in the Atharvan rites; performed homa prior to Rukminī's marriage; 2) Ib. X. 53; 12. of the king; 3) Br. II. 29. 76; III. 26. 22; 27, 30; Vā. 57. 70; 90, 72; 101. 81; Vi. V. 34. 29; VI. 6. 26. does expiatory ceremonies to ward off evils to the state. 4) M. 229. 12; 230. 9-11; 231. 9.

पुलक
Pulaka --killed the king Bṛhadratha and installed his son, Bālaka on the throne. M. 271. 30; 272. 1.

पुलस्त्य
Pulastya --a mind-born son of Brahmā born of his ears in Vāruṇī yajna; married Kardama's daughter Havirbhū; father of Agastya (Dhrāgni in another birth) and Viśravas; 1) Bhā. III. 12. 22 and 24; 24. 22; IV. 1. 36; Br. II. 32. 96; III. 1. 21 and 45; M. 3. 6; Vā. 25. 82; 61. 82; 65. 42; 94. 36; 101. 35, 49. a Mahaṛṣi; sage presiding over the month of Madhu; 2) Bhā. XII. 11. 33; M. 145. 90; Vā. 52. 2; Vi. II. 10. 3. āśrama of; near Pulaha's; 3) Bhā. V. 8. 30. requested Parāśara to impart Bhāgavata to Maitreya; 4) Ib. III. 8. 9. not seen the Supreme Being; 5) Ib. IV. 29. 43. came to Syamantapañcaka to see Kṛṣṇa; 6) Ib. X. 84. 4. a Devaṛṣi of Dāruvana; 7) Br. II. 35. 92; 27. 104; III. 1. 21, 45. married the twelve daughters of Krodha, whose sons were Uragas and Nagas; 8) Ib. III. 7. 171; 8. 70; II. 35. 92. father of Kubera and Rāvaṇa and appealed to Kārtavīrya Arjuna to release Rāvaṇa; 9) Ib. III. 69. 36; M. 43. 38. his sons are the groups of Yakṣas, Rākṣasas, etc., who worship the Barhiṣad manes; 10) Ib. 15. 1-4. praised Śiva, out to destroy Tripuram; 11) Ib. 102. 19; 126. 3; 133. 67. from the Keśa of fire to which Brahmā's śukram was offered; 12) Ib. 171. 27; 195. 10. gave Vāmana white cloths. 13) Ib. 245. 87. 

पुलस्त्य
Pulastya  (II)--created from Udāna; 1) Br. I. 1. 117; 5. 70; Vā. I. 138; 3. 3. a son of Brahmā and the elder brother of Pulaha; 2) Ib. 25. 82; 36. 48; Vi. I. 1. 22-3. of the Svāyambhuva epoch; 3) Vā. 9. 102; 28. 22. married Prītī, daughter of Dakṣa; 4) Br. II. 9. 18, 24, 55. father of three sons, of whom Dattāli was one; 5) Ib. II. 11. 26; 13. 53; Vā. 31. 16. married to Bhūti; 6) Vi. I. 7. 5 and 7. by his gift Parāśara remembered the Viṣṇu Purāṇa. 7) Ib. VI. 8. 50.

पुलह
Pulaha  (I)--one of the ten mind-born sons of Brahmā, born of his navel; married Kardama's daughter, Gatī and had three sons; born from the Keśa of fire to which Brahmā's śukram was offered; presiding over the month of Mādhava; 1) Bhā. III. 12. 22, 24; 24. 23; IV. 1. 38; XII. 11. 34; M. 3. 7; 171. 27; 195. 10; 202. 7 and 9. a Mahaṛṣi; his hermitage, sacred to Hari; visited by Balarāma; Bharata spent his last days in it; 2) Bhā. VII. 14. 30; X. 79. 10; V. 7. 8; 8. 30; M. 145. 90; Vā. 52. 2; Vi. II. 10. 5. had not realised the Supreme Being; 3) Bhā. IV. 29. 43. his descendants became Ājyapa manes; 4) M. 15. 21. praised Śiva out to destroy Tripura; 5) Ib. 102. 19; 126. 3; 133. 67. gave akṣasūtra to Vāmana; 6) Ib. 245. 87. younger brother of Pulastya, married Sambhūti; 7) Vi. I. 1. 23; 7. 5 and 7. King Ṛṣabha spent his last days in his hermitage. 8) Ib. II. 1. 29.

पुलह
Pulaha  (II)--created from vyāna of Brahmā; out of the Vāruṇi yajña with hairs hanging from his body; 1) Br. I. 5. 70; II. 9. 18 and 24; Vā. 3. 3; 9. 102; 61. 82 and 84. son of Brahmā; 2) Br. II. 9. 55; 13. 53; Vā. 25. 82. Prajāpati of the Svāyambhuva period; 3) Ib. 28. 25; 101. 35 and 49. son-in-law of Dakṣa; 4) Ib. 30. 48. wife Kṣamā; 5) Ib. 31. 16. father of four sons and a daughter, Pīvarī. 6) Br. II. 11. 30. 

पुलिक
Pulika --a kingdom on the Himālayas. M. 121. 44.

पुलिन्द
Pulinda --the son of Bhadraka and father of Ghoṣa of the Śunga dynasty. Bhā. XII. 1. 17.

पुलिन्द
Pulindas --a tribe of Dakṣiṇapatha formed into a caste by Purañjaya; purified of sin by the worship of Hari; 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 36; II. 4. 18; Vā. 45. 126; 47. 48; 98. 108; 99. 268 and 378. kings of the; 2) M. 50. 76. kingdom of the, established by Visvaphāṇi; 3) Br. II. 16. 58; III. 73. 108; 74. 191; M. 114. 48; 121. 49. elevated to royalty by Viśvasphaṭika. 4) Vi. IV. 24. 62.

पुलिन्दक
Pulindaka  (I)--a son of Antaka, ruled for three years. Br. III. 74. 153. M. 272. 29.

पुलिन्दक
Pulindaka  (II)--son of Udanka and father of Ghoṣavasu. Vi. IV. 24. 35.

पुलिन्दसेन
Pulindasena --the son of Palelaka and father of Sundara. Vi. IV. 24. 47.

पुलिन्द्य
Pulindyas --women of Pulindas. Bhā. X. 21. 17; 83. 43.

पुलेय
Puleyas --a tribe of the southern country. Vā. 45. 129.

पुलोमकन्या
Pulomakanyā --at first a Vaiśya by caste, became the queen of Puruhūta by observing the Kalyāṇivratam. M. 69. 60. 

पुलोम
Puloma  (I)--An Asura; a son of Danu; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 31; VII. 2. 5; Vā. 68. 7; Vi. I. 21. 5. followed Vṛtra in his battle with Indra; fought with Anila or Agni in the Devāsura war; 2) Bhā. VI. 10. 20 and 31; VIII. 10. 31. residing in Rasātalam; 3) Br. II. 20. 49; III. 6. 7 and 24; Vā. 50. 37. father of Śacī. 4) M. 6. 20-1.

पुलोम
Puloma  (II)--a son of Prahati; the Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 91; Vā. 69. 129.

पुलोम
Puloma  (III)--a son of Gautamīputra, ruled for 28 years. M. 273. 13.

पुलोम
Puloma  (IV)--an Andhra King, who ruled for seven years; The period from Mahāpadma to Puloma is 836 years. M. 273. 15, 37.

पुलोम
Puloma  (V)--name of the lord of the Vidyādharas. Vā. 38. 16.

पुलोम
Puloma  (VI)--a Mauneya. Vā. 69. 2.

पुलोमा
Pulomā --a daughter of Vaiśvānara and a wife of Kaśyapa (Mārīca); after her, were called Paulomas. Bhā. VI. 6. 33-4; Br. III. 6. 25; M. 6. 22; Vā. 68. 23; Vi. I. 21. 8-9.

पुलोमापिहि
Pulomāpihi --the son of Candraśri; the last of the Andhras, who ruled for 486 years (456 years: Br. P.). Vi. IV. 24. 49-50. 

पुलोमारि
Pulomāri --an Andhra King, who ruled for 7 years. Br. III. 74. 169.

पुलोमिन्
Pulomin --the father of Pulomi and father-in-law of Bhṛgu, the sage. Br. III. 1. 75.

पुलोव
Pulova --ruled for 7 years; with him are 30 Kings of the Andhra line who ruled for 411 years in all; twelve branches are distinguished among them. Vā. 99. 357-9.

पुल्कस
Pulkasa --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 79.

पुल्कस
Pulkasas --are purified of sin by the worship of Hari: got released from bondage by hearing the name of Hari once; 1) Bhā. II. 4. 18; VI. 16. 44. Rantideva gave the drink which he had for himself, to a certain Pulkasa. 2) Ib. IX. 21. 10 and 14; XI. 29. 14.

पुष्कर
Puṣkara  (I)--see Puṣkaradvīpa. Bhā. V. 1. 32.

पुष्कर
Puṣkara  (II)--the son of Sunakṣatra and father of Antarikṣa. Bhā. IX. 12. 12

पुष्कर
Puṣkara  (III)--a son of Durvārkṣī and Vṛka. Bhā. IX. 24. 43.

पुष्कर
Puṣkara  (IV)--a son of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 90. 34. 

पुष्कर
Puṣkara  (V)--a son of Bharata founded Puṣkarāvatī as his capital in Gāndhāra. Br. III. 63. 190; Vā. 29. 8; 88. 189.

पुष्कर
Puṣkara  (VI)--Kṛṣṇa (black) Parāśara. M. 201. 35.

पुष्कर
Puṣkara  (VII)--a Kingdom watered by the Sītā; fit for śrāddha. 2) Br. III. 13. 40. ^1 Br. II. 18. 45; Vā. 33. 14; 42. 69; 50. 119.

पुष्कर
Puṣkaras  (I)--clouds of the Pakṣaja variety. Br. II. 22. 40.

पुष्कर
Puṣkaras  (II)--the Brahmana caste of the Krauñcadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 53.

पुष्करचूड
Puṣkaracūḍa --an elephant at one of the four cardinal points to maintain the balance of the worlds. Bhā. V. 20. 39.

पुष्करणि
Puṣkaraṇi --a son of Viśālā. Vā. 99. 163.

पुष्करद्वीप
Puṣkaradvīpa --the island twice the Dadhimaṇḍoda in size, and surrounded by sea of fresh water: named after a huge lotus with golden petal intended to be Brahmā's throne: called after the King Puṣpavāhana of Rathantarakalpa; here is the hill Citrasānu. There is only one mountain Mānasottara in the middle of this dvīpa, dividing it into portions East and West. On it in the four directions are the cities of gods like Indra. On its top rotates the wheel of the Sun's chariot which makes the year of men and the day of gods. Vītihotra, a son of Priyavrata was the ruler who divided it among his two sons. Brahmā is worshipped  here; 1) Bhā. V. 1. 32; 20. 29-33; M. 100. 4; 123. 13; 248. 13; Vā. 49. 101-141. here people live for 10000 years. No caste or Vedas: worship banyan tree: Kaśyapa performed his Aśvamedha and Vāli defeated Rāvaṇa; 2) Br. II. 14. 14; 19. 108-26, 140-1; III. 5. 7; 7. 267. visited by Paraśurāma; 3) Ib. III. 32. 60; 44. 22; Vi. II. 4. 72-86, 92. one of the seven continents of which Savana was the first King. His sons Mahāvīra and Dhātuki divided it between them. 4) Ib. II. 1. 15; 2. 5.

पुष्करपर्वत
Puṣkaraparvata --a hill in Bhāratavarṣa: felt the influence of Hiraṇyakaśipu. M. 163. 88.

पुष्करम्
Puṣkaram --a place sacred to Hari. Sages of Puṣkara visited Dvārakā; 1) Bhā. VII. 14. 30; X. 90. 28[3]; XII. 12. 60. sacred to Indra and Pitṛs in the Tretāyuga; 2) M. 13. 30; 22. 62; 106. 57; 109. 3; 110. 1; 180. 55; 184. 16; 192. 11. a tīrtha; here was Adhisāmakṛṣṇa's sacrifice for three years; 3) Ib. 50. 67. here Kaśyapa performed the Aśvamedha; 4) Vā. 67. 53; Vi. VI. 8. 29. fit for śrāddha. 5) Vā. 77. 40; 106. 69.

पुष्करमन्दिरम्
Puṣkaramandiram --abode of Puṣkara, a wonderful lotus moving at will, gained by Puspavāhana's self denial in his previous birth. M. 100. 30.

पुष्करस्वन
Puṣkarasvana --a son of Viśvaśā. M. 171. 49.

पुष्कराक्ष
Puṣkarākṣa --the son of Sṛcandra; an able charioteer; used vāyavyāstram against Paraśurāma who attacked him with brahmāstram and cut him into two with the Paraśu. Br. III. 40. 1.

पुष्करारुणि
Puṣkarāruṇi --a son of Duritakṣaya. Bhā. IX. 21. 20. 

पुष्करावती
Puṣkarāvatī  (I)--the capital of Puṣkara, son of Bharata. Br. III. 63. 191; Vā. 88. 190.

पुष्करावती
Puṣkarāvatī  (II)--a Goddess enshrined at Prabhāsa. M. 13. 43.

पुष्करावर्तक
Puṣkarāvartakas --a group of rain-bearing clouds, born of the wings of the mountains shorn by Indra; description of; rain at the commencement of Pralaya and are instrumental in putting an end to them also. M. 125. 11-15; Vā. 51. 37-40.

पुष्करि
Puṣkari --the son of Urukṣava and Viśālā, became a Brahmana, and one of the three best mahaṛṣis among the Kāvyas. M. 49. 39.

पुष्करिण
Puṣkariṇa --a son of Durukṣaya. Vi. IV. 19. 25.

पुष्करिणी
Puṣkariṇī  (I)--the queen of Vyuṣṭa, and mother of Cakṣuṣ. Bhā. IV. 13. 14.

पुष्करिणी
Puṣkariṇī  (II)--the queen of Ulmuka. Bhā. IV. 13. 17.

पुष्करिणी
Puṣkariṇī  (III)--see Vāruṇī--daughter of progenitor Vīraṇa; wife of Cākṣuṣa. Br. II. 36. 102. Vi. I. 13. 3.

पुष्करिणी
Puṣkariṇī  (IV)--a tīrtha: on the Narmadā. M. 190. 16. 

पुष्कल
Puṣkala --a son of Bharata. Bhā. IX. 11. 12; Vi. IV. 4. 104.

पुष्कला
Puṣkalās  (I)--a group of clouds. Br. IV. 28. 63.

पुष्कल
Puṣkalas  (II)--the Kṣatriya caste of Krauñcadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 53.

पुष्कला
Puṣkalā --R. of the Ketumālā continent. Vā. 44. 20.

पुष्टि
Puṣṭi  (I)--a daughter of Dakṣa, and a wife of Dharma: gave birth to Smaya (Lābha-Vā. P.). Bhā. IV. 1. 49 and 51; Vā. 9. 49, 59; 10. 25, 35; Vi. I. 7. 23 and 28.

पुष्टि
Puṣṭi  (II)--one of the nine devīs attending on Soma. Br. II. 26. 45; III. 65. 26; Vā. 90. 25.

पुष्टि
Puṣṭi  (III)--a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 52.

पुष्टि
Puṣṭi  (IV)--a son of Vasudeva and Madirā. Br. III. 71. 172; Vā. 96. 170.

पुष्टि
Puṣṭi  (V) Angiras--a sage of the epoch of the third Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 79.

पुष्टि
Puṣṭi  (VI)--a God of the Rohita gaṇa. Br. IV. 1. 86.

पुष्टि
Puṣṭi  (VII)--a Brahmana kalā. Br. IV. 35. 94. 

पुष्टि
Puṣṭi  (VIII)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 71.

पुष्टि
Puṣṭi  (IX)--a Goddess enshrined at Devadāru forest. M. 13. 47.

पुष्टि
Puṣṭi  (X)--a son of Dhruva. Vā. 62. 82.

पुष्प
Puṣpa --the son of Hiraṇyanābha and father of Dhruvasandhi. Br. III. 63. 209.

पुष्पक
Puṣpaka  (I)--the aerial car in which Rāma flew to Ayodhyā; 1) Bhā. IX. 10. 45. of Kubera; 2) M. 174. 1-7; 191. 88; 193. 10; Vā. 41. 6-7. constructed by Śiva. 3) M. 130. 12.

पुष्पक
Puṣpaka  (II)--the maṇṭapa with 64 pillars. M. 270. 3, 7.

पुष्पक
Puṣpaka  (III)--a Mt. north of the Mahābhadra; 1) Vā. 36. 32; 38. 71. the residence of sages. 2) Ib. 39. 62.

पुष्पगिरि
Puṣpagiri --a Mt. in Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 22; Vā. 45. 92.

पुष्पजा
Puṣpajā --a R. from the Malaya hill. M. 114. 30.

पुष्पजाति
Puṣpajāti --a R. originating from the Malaya hills. Br. II. 16. 36; Vā. 45. 105.

पुष्पदन्त
Puṣpadanta  (I)--attacked the Asura followers of Bali. Bhā. VIII. 21. 17. 

पुष्पदन्त
Puṣpadanta  (II)--a Yakṣa; a son of Devajanī. Br. III. 7. 128.

पुष्पदन्त
Puṣpadanta  (III)--the elephant of the sāma fold (Bṛhatsāma) with six tusks; his sons are Tāmraparṇa and others roaming in groups. Br. III. 7. 337; Vā. 69. 221.

पुष्पदन्त
Puṣpadanta  (IV)--a Kādraveya nāga; a serpent. Vā. 69. 71.

पुष्पदन्त
Puṣpadanta  (V)--to be worshipped before the commencement of house and palace building operations. M. 253. 26; 255. 9; 268. 15.

पुष्पदन्तक
Puṣpadantaka --Gayā-śilā known as. Vā. 108. 48.

पुष्पदंष्ट्र
Puṣpadaṃṣṭra  (I)--a Kādraveya Nāga. Br. III. 7. 35.

पुष्पदंष्ट्र
Puṣpadaṃṣṭra  (II)--a thousand-hooded snake. M. 6. 40.

पुष्पध्वंस
Puṣpadhvaṃsa --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 243.

पुष्पबाण
Puṣpabāṇa --the God of love; see Madana. M. 154. 245.

पुष्पभद्र
Puṣpabhadra --a maṇṭapa with 62 pillars. M. 270. 3, 7. 

पुष्पभद्रक
Puṣpabhadraka --a pleasure garden to which went Kardama and Devahūtī. Bhā. III. 23. 40.

पुष्पभद्रा
Puṣpabhadrā --R. (also Puṣpavahā)--on its banks in the Himālayas, Mārkaṇḍeya performed tapas. Bhā. XII. 8. 17; 9. 10 and 30.

पुष्पमित्र
Puṣpamitra  (I)--the commander-in-chief of the Mauryan King Bṛhadratha; did away with his master and became King; ruled for six (sixty Vā. P.) years; had eight sons, of whom the first ruled for seven years. Br. III. 74. 150; Vā. 99. 337-8.

पुष्पमित्र
Puṣpamitra  (II)--a King of the Mahiṣas, ruled for six years. Br. III. 74. 187; Vā. 99. 374.

पुष्पमित्र
Puṣpamitras --a royal dynasty after the Bāhlikas in the Kingdom of Magadha. Vi. IV. 24. 58.

पुष्पमिष्ट
Puṣpamiṣṭa --(Puṣpamitra-Br. P.) a Kṣatriya King after the Bāhlikas. Bhā. XII. 1. 34.

पुष्पवन्त
Puṣpavanta --a son of Maṇivara. Vā. 69. 159.

पुष्पवर्ष
Puṣpavarṣa --Mt. in Śālmalidvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 10. 

पुष्पवहा
Puṣpavahā --a R. see Puṣpabhadrā. Bhā. XII. 9. 30.

पुष्पवान्
Puṣpavān  (I)--the son of Satyahita, and father of Jahu. Bhā. IX. 22. 7.

पुष्पवान्
Puṣpavān  (II)--a Mt. in Kuśadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 55; Vā. 49. 50. Vi. II. 4. 41.

पुष्पवान्
Puṣpavān  (III)--same as Droṇa. M. 122. 57.

पुष्पवान्
Puṣpavān  (IV)--the righteous son of Ṛṣabha (VṛṣabhaVi. P.) Father of Satyahita. Vā. 99. 224; Vi. IV. 19. 82.

पुष्पवाहन
Puṣpavāhana --a King of Rathantara Kalpa; Brahmā was pleased at his tapas and gave him a golden lotus; after him came the 7th dvīpa, Puṣkaradvīpa (s.v); he got a vehicle of Puṣpavāhana which took him to any place; his wife was Lāvaṇyavatī; once he met the sage Prācetas and asked him the reason for his wealth etc. He said that in the previous birth he was a hunter and owing to a distressing famine, he could not get anything to eat; so he plucked some lotus flowers and went to the Vaidiśa city for selling them; none offered to buy; soon he heard a musical sound near by; going in that direction he saw a courtesan engaged in vibhūtidvādaśi vratam; there, he gave all flowers needed for the performance of the vow and did not take gold or food offered in return; he felt no thirst or hunger; and became changed at that sight; for that service he became King and the courtesan Prītī, wife of the Lord of love. M. 100. 1-32. 

पुष्पवाहिनी
Puṣpavāhinī --a R. in Bhāratavarṣa: felt the prowess of Hiraṇyakaśīpu. M. 163. 64.

पुष्पान्वेषि
Puṣpānveṣi --a Pravara (Āngiras). M. 196. 14.

पुष्पायुध
Puṣpāyudha --Viṣṇu's wedding present to Kāmeśvara. Br. IV. 15. 19.

पुष्पार्ण
Puṣpārṇa --a son of Vatsara; had two queens, Prabhā and Doṣā. Each of them had three sons. Bhā. IV. 13. 12-13.

पुष्पोत्कटा
Puṣpotkaṭā --a daughter of Mālyavān and one of the four wives of Viśravas; her sons, Mahodara, Mahāpārśva, (Mahāpāmśu-Vā. P.) Prahasta, and Khara; daughter Kumbhīnasī. Br. III. 8. 39 and 55; Vā. 70. 34, 49.

पुष्य
Puṣya  (I)--a nakṣatra in Airāvati vīthi. Bhā. V. 23. 6; Vā. 66. 48.

पुष्य
Puṣya  (II)--a son of Hiraṇyanābha and father of Dhruvasandhi. Bhā. IX. 12. 5; Vā. 88. 209; Vi. IV. 4. 108.

पुष्य
Puṣya  (III)--the month sacred to Bhaga, etc. Bhā. XII. 11. 42. 

पुष्यम्
Puṣyam --a term for Kali-yuga, evils of. M. 144. 30-48.

पुष्यमित्र
Puṣyamitra --Commander-in-chief of Bṛhadratha, the Mauryan King; killed his own master and usurped the throne. He was a Śunga and his line was therefore called the Śungas. Father of Agnimitra; 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 15[1], 16. Vi. IV. 24. 34. ruled for 36 years. 2) M. 272. 27.

पूतना
Pūtanā  (I)--a demoness and a friend of Kamsa; was deputed by him to kill all infants. Once she came to Vraja and changing her form to that of a fascinating lady, entered Nanda's house and began to suckle the baby Kṛṣṇa. He understood the purpose and sucked her life out to the wonderment of the Gopīs and Gopas. Her body was cremated and she reached heaven; 1) Bhā. X. 2. 1; 6. 2-17, 28 and 34-38; 14. 35; 26. 4; 43. 25; Br. IV. 29. 124; III. 73. 100; Vā. 9. 97; 98. 100; Vi. V. 4. 1; 5. 7-11, 23; 6. 23; 15. 2; 29. 5. to be propitiated at the commencement of building operations of palaces. 2) M. 268. 29.

पूतना
Pūtanā  (II)--a daughter of Bali; 1) Br. III. 5. 43; Vā. 67. 84. mother of the bhūtas and a graha. 2) Br. III. 7. 158 and 161.

पूतना
Pūtanā  (III)--a Varṇa śakti. Br. IV. 44. 59.

पूतना
Pūtanā  (IV)--a Rākṣasī and wife of Bhadra: Her sons are called Naiṛrtas. Br. III. 59. 12-4. 

पूतन
Pūtanas --a class of fearful Rākṣasas. Vā. 69. 190.

पूतनाजीवितहर
Pūtanājīvitahara --is Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 24.

पूतनानुग
Pūtanānuga --a Marut gaṇa. M. 171. 54.

पूतिचक्षु
