Pṛthūdakam --a tīrtha sacred to the Pitṛṣ; 1) M. 22. 52. visited by Balarāma. 2) Bhā. X. 78. 19.

पृथ्वी
Pṛthvī  (I)--first milked by Brahmā; Calf Vāyu; In Svāyambhuvamanvantara by Agnidhara--Calf Svāyambhuva. In Svārociṣa by Caitra--Calf Svārociṣa Manu. In Uttama by Devabhuja--Calf Uttama Manu. In Tāmasa by Bālabandhu--Calf Tāmasa Manu. In Cāriṣṇava by Purāṇa--Calf Cariṣṇava Manu. In Cākṣuṣa by Purāṇa-Calf Cākṣuṣa Manu. In Vaivasvata by Vainya--Calf Soma. Vā. 63. 12-19. 

पृथ्वी
Pṛthvī  (II)--the first seven Vātaskandas; also known as Āhava. Vā. 67. 114.

पृथ्वीतलसम्भूत
Pṛthvītalasambhūta --born of Arundhatī and Dharma. M. 5. 19.

पृथ्वीधर
Pṛthvīdhara --to be worshipped in house-building. M. 253. 30, 39; 268. 23.

पृश्नि
Pṛśni --the son of Mādhri's son, Yudhājit; had two sons Śvaphalka and Citraka. Vā. 96. 101.

पृश्निगर्भ
Pṛśnigarbha --a manifestation of Hari born of Pṛśni and Sutapas during the Śvāyambhuva epoch. Bhā. X. 3. 41.

पृश्निज
Pṛśnijas --a class of gods doing śrāddha. Br. III. 10. 109; Vā. 73. 61.

पृश्निमेधा
Pṛśnimedhās --a god of Sumedhasa group. Br. II. 36. 59.

पृश्नी
Pṛśnī  (I)--the wife of Savitā, and mother of Śāvitrī, Vyāhṛtī and others. Bhā. VI. 18. 1.

पृश्नी
Pṛśnī  (II)--Devakī in the epoch of Svāyambhuva Manu: Married Sutapas the progenitor: was engaged in tapas with her husband for 12000 divine years. To them was born Hari by name Pṛśnigarbha. Bhā. X. 3. 32-41; 6. 25.

पृष
Pṛṣa --Indra of the XI epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 30. 

पृषत
Pṛṣata --the last son of Somaka Ajamīḍha and father of Drupada. Bhā. IX. 22. 2; Vā. 99. 192; Vi. IV. 19. 73.

पृषदर्भ
Pṛṣadarbha --a son of Śibi. Vi. IV. 18. 10.

पृषदश्व
Pṛṣadaśva  (I)--A son of Virūpa, and father of Rathitara; 1) Bhā. IX. 6. 1; Br. III. 63. 6; Vā. 88. 6; Vi. IV. 2. 8-9. a Mantrakṛt. 2) M. 145. 103.

पृषदश्व
Pṛṣadaśva  (II)--the son of Pṛthu and father of Āndhra; 1) Vā. 88. 26. a Mantrakṛt and of the Angirasa branch. 2) Ib. 69. 100.

पृषदश्व
Pṛṣadaśva  (III)--the son of Anaraṇya and father of Haryaśva. Vi. IV. 3. 18.

पृषदाज्य
Pṛṣadājya --a mixture of ghee and curds as a sacrificial offering. Br. IV. 1. 98; Vā. 100. 103.

पृषध्र
Pṛṣadhra  (I)--a son of Vaivasvata Manu. Being appointed by his teacher to be in charge of cattle he attended to it zealously. During nights he kept awake in vīrāsana posture. On a dark rainy night a tiger entered the stall and caught hold of a cow, when the other cows ran pell-mell. At this the prince drew the sword, and in the darkness he cut off the head of a cow and the ear of the tiger. Next morning he reported the sad news to the preceptor, who cursed him to become a śūdra. He however continued to live a life of celibacy, and detachment to things mundane, ever contemplating on Hari. He reached Brahmā by entering the forest-fire in the course of his wanderings. Bhā. VIII. 13. 3; IX. 1. 12; 2. 3-14; Br. III. 60. 3; M. 11. 41; 12. 25; Vā. 64. 30; 86. 1; Vi. III. 1. 34; IV. 1. 7, 17. 

पृषध्र
Pṛṣadhra  (II)--a son of Svāyambhuva Manu; 1) Br. II. 38. 31; Vā. 85. 4; 86. 1. killed his preceptor Cyavana's cow and was cursed to become a Śūdra. 2) Br. III. 61. 1.

पृषभ
Pṛṣabha --one of the seven seers of the Svārociṣa epoch. Vi. III. 1. 11.

पृष्ट
Pṛṣṭa --one of the ten branches of the Sukarmāṇa clan of Devas. Br. IV. 1. 88; Vā. 100. 92.

पृष्टी
Pṛṣṭī --a daughter of Marīci and Sambhūti. Vā. 28. 9.

पेशस्कृत
Peśaskṛta --one of the two blind citizens of the city of Purañjana, aiding the Puruṣa in his work; allegorically feet. Bhā. IV. 25. 54; 29. 15.

पेषणम्
Peṣaṇam --Piṇḍas or rice balls to be offered thrice for Pitṛs and once for gods. Vā. 75. 20.

पैंगलायनि
Paiṃgalāyani --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 25.

पैज
Paija --a pupil of Jātūkarṇya. Bhā. XII. 6. 58.

पैतामहतीर्थ
Paitāmahatīrtha --in the Narmadā. M. 194, 4-5.

पैतामहम्
Paitāmaham cakram --a weapon of war. M. 162. 20. 

पैत्रितनु
Paitritanu --of Prajāpati; gave rise to sages and men, the latter with rajas. Vā. 9. 16.

पैप्पल
Paippala --a Pravara Ṛṣi. M. 199. 18; 200. 15.

पैल
Paila  (I)--a pupil of Vyāsa, Parāśarya and in charge of the Ṛg Veda; 1) Bhā. I. 4. 21; Vā. 60. 13; Vi. III. 4. 8. was taught Bahvṛca (Ṛg Veda). He taught it to Indrapramati and to Bāṣkala; 2) Bhā. XII. 6. 36, 52 and 54. Vi. III. 4. 16. was invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira. 3) Bhā. X. 74. 8. A Śrutaṛṣi. 4) Br. II. 33. 2; 34. 13. He took the flating Ṛks and classified them into two parts each of which was given to two disciples, Indrapramati and Bāṣkala. 5) Vā. 60. 19, 24-25.

पैल
Paila  (II)--a disciple of Parāśara. Bhā. IX. 22. 22.

पैल
Paila  (III)--a pupil of Rathītara. Br. II. 35. 4.

पैल
Paila  (IV)--a Bhārgava gotrakṛt. M. 195. 18; 196. 18.

पैलमौलि
Pailamaulis --Kaśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 6.

पैलव
Pailava --one of the five pupils of Vyāsa. Vā. 108. 42.

पैशाचविवाह
Paiśāca-vivāha --one of the eight forms of marriage. Vi. III. 10. 24. 

पोता
Potā --one of the 16 Ṛtviks for a yajña; created from the belly of Nārāyaṇa. M. 167. 9.

पोत्रिणी
Potriṇī  (I)--a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 14 and 19.

पोत्रिणी
Potriṇī  (II)--(Daṇḍanāyikā): on the first parva of the Kiri cakraratha; 1) Br. IV. 20. 5. just in front of her lay the lion--Caṇḍoścaṇḍa with four hands and three eyes, wearing śūla, khaḍga and pāśa. 2) Ib. IV. 24, 31 ff; 28. 48.

पोत्रिमुखीदेवी
Potrimukhīdevī --a name of Lalitā; also Potriṇī. Br. IV. 17. 6. 14.

पोत्रियम्
Potriyam --Agni, or Havyavāhana; known as. Vā. 29. 27.

पोष्ट
Poṣṭa --an Amitābha god. Br. IV. 1. 17.

पौडव
Pauḍava --an Ekārṣeya. M. 200. 6.

पौड्र
Pauḍras --a Janapada. Vā. 99. 385.

पौण्डरीक
Pauṇḍarīka --a sacrifice whose fruits are attained by going round Amarakaṇṭaka. M. 188. 93.

पौण्ड्र
Pauṇḍra  (I)--the kingdom named after the people. M. 163. 73. 

पौण्ड्र
Pauṇḍra  (II)--a son of Bali, after whom came the name of the kingdom. Vi. IV. 18. 13-14.

पौण्ड्रक
Pauṇḍraka  (I)--(also Pauṇḍra): King of Kāśi; son of Vasudeva, and Sutanu, daughter of Kāśirāja. When he became king, he asserted that he was the real Vāsudeva, and married Devakī the youngest sister of Kamsa. Besieged Dvārakā during Kṛṣṇa's absence at night, and being put to defeat by Balarāma and Sātyaki, went back to his capital. Sent a messenger to Kṛṣṇa saying that he was the real Vāsudeva and that Kṛṣṇa was either to give up the title or offer battle. Kṛṣṇa invaded Kāśi and killed him and his allies; 1) Bhā. X. 66. [1-12], 1-23. 27. Vi. V. 26. 7; 34, 4-28. was stationed by Jarāsandha during the siege of Mathurā on its southern gate, and also during the siege of Gomanta on the southern gate. Arrived at Kuṇḍina. 2) Ib. X. 50. 11 [4]
and [9]; 53. 17. Father of Sudakṣiṇā. 3) Ib. X. 78. 5. Attained mokṣa by hatred of Hari. 4) Ib. II. 7. 34; X. 37. 19; XI. 5. 48; Br. IV. 29. 122.

पौण्ड्रक
Pauṇḍraka  (II)--a son of third Sāvarna Manu. Br. IV. 1. 81. Vā. 100. 84.

पौण्ड्रवर्धन
Pauṇḍravardhana --a kṣetra sacred to Lalitā. Br. IV. 44. 93. Vā. 104. 79.

पौत्रि
Pautri --a Putrikāputri of Atri. M. 197. 10.

पौनिक
Paunikas --a Dakṣinātya deśa. Vā. 45. 127.

पौर
Paura  (I)--a son of Pṛthusena. M. 49. 52. 

पौर
Paura  (II)--a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 20.

पौर
Paura  (III)--a kingdom after Pṛthudarbha, son of Śibi. M. 48. 20.

पौरकुत्स
Paurakutsa --an Āngirasa and Mantrakṛṭ. Br. II. 32. 102.

पौरजानपद
Paura-Jānapadas --citizens and people of country parts; agreed to Puru's coronation by Yayāti in preference to his elders on account of his discipline; 1) M. 34. 28. of Ayodhyā; 2) Br. III. 49. 16. in the royal sabhā of Sagara; 3) Ib. III. 55. 23. abandoned Lohagandhi Janamejaya for bad conduct. 4) Ib. III. 68. 23; Vā. 93. 23.

पौर
Pauras  (I)--treated with respect by Pṛthu; 1) Bhā. IV. 17. 2; 21. 6. were provided with seats in Mallaranga; 2) Ib. X. 36. 24. also Paurajanas. 3) Br. III. 51. 34 and 36.

पौर
Pauras  (II)--a Parāśara clan. Br. III. 8. 95.

पौरव
Paurava --a Rājaṛṣi. Vā. 32. 39.

पौरववंश
Pauravavaṃśa --the line beginning with Puru, son of Yayāti. M. 24. 70; 34. 31; ch. 49. (whole).

पौरवी
Pauravī --a queen of Yudhiṣṭhira, and mother of Devaka. Bhā. IX. 22. 30. 

पौरवी
Pauravī  (II)--one of Vasudeva's wives, and mother of Subhadrā and eleven sons. 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 45 and 47. A daughter of Vālmīki and sister of Bāhlika. 2) Br. III. 71. 161, 163; M. 46. 11; Vā. 96. 160-61; Vi. IV. 15. 18.

पौराणिक
Paurāṇika (Purāṇajña) --is Sūta; ancient Purāṇateller; 1) Br. III. 8. 83; M. 114. 3; Vā. 45. 71; 70. 76; 88. 67, 114, 168; 101. 72. on Māndhāta and Hariścandra; 2) Br. III. 63. 69, 113. alias Vamśavittama. 3) Ib. III. 63. 168.

पौरिक
Paurikas --a southern country. Br. II. 16. 58.

पौरुकुत्स
Paurukutsa --a Mantrakṛt and of the Āngirasa branch. Vā. 59. 99.

पौरुकुत्सा
Paurukutsā(ī) --wife of Gādhi; 1) Vā. 91. 66-7. gave birth to Viśvāmitra taking the caru of Ṛcika intended for her daughter Satyavatī. 2) Br. III. 66. 36.

पौरुषम्
Pauruṣam --see Utthānam. M. 221. 2.

पौरुषंज्ञणम्
Pauruṣaṃjñaṇam --the fourth Puruṣārtha, the other three being Dharma, Artha and Kāma. Vā. 67. 12.

पौरुषम्
Pauruṣam sūktam --Puruṣa sūkta of the Ṛg Veda to be recited before digging a tank. (See Puruṣa Sūkta, s.v.) M. 58. 34. 36.

पौरुषी
Pauruṣī --Sātvikī. Vā. 66. 104. 

पौरुषेय
Pauruṣeya  (I)--the Rākṣasa presiding over the month of Śukra and Śuci 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 35; Br. II. 23. 6. with the sun in the summer. 2) Vā. 52. 8; Vi. II. 10. 7.

पौरुषेय
Pauruṣeya  (II)--one of the sons of Yātudhāna, had five sons, all man-eating ones, Krūra, Vikṛta, etc. Br. III. 7. 89, 93-4.

पौरुषेय
Pauruṣeya  (III)--a Piśāca. Vā. 69. 127.

पौरोधसम्
Paurodhasam --‘not a profession to be coveted’, was the remark of Viśvarūpa to the gods, who requested him to be their ācārya, (see Purohita). Bhā. VI. 7. 35-36.

पौरोहित्यम्
Paurohityam --the office of Purohita; Bṛhaspati for the Devas and Śukra for the Asuras; the low status of, as viewed by Sarmiṣṭhā, the daughter of Vṛṣaparvana. M. 25. 9; 27. 9-11.

पौर्णमास
Paurṇamāsa  (I)--son of Śrīśāntakarṇa, and father of Lambodara. Bhā. XII. 1. 23-24.

पौर्णमास
Paurṇamāsa  (II)--the Full Moon day. (See also Paurṇamāsī.) ^1 Br. II. 23. 63; Vi. I. 20. 38.

पौर्णमास
Paurṇamāsa  (III)--a Jayadeva; a Mantraśarīra and a son of Brahmā; 1) Br. II. 23. 66; Vā. 66. 6; 67. 5. his amṛta was drunk by 33 crores of gods. 2) Br. III. 3. 6. 

पौर्णमास
Paurṇamāsa  (IV)--the son of Marīci and Sambhūti. Father of Viraja and Parvata. Vi. I. 10. 6.

पौर्णमासा
Paurṇamāsās --Trayārṣeyas; no marriage alliance with Pāraṇa an Agastya. M. 202. 4.

पौर्णमासि
Paurṇamāsi  (I)--the Devī of the 27th Kalpa became a twin. Vā. 21. 62, 68.

पौर्णमासि
Paurṇamāsi  (II)--the Full Moon day; the Moon has a full white maṇḍala by the apyāyita of the sun; 1) Vā. 50. 200; 52. 59; Vi. II. 8. 80. at the end of the Kṛṣṇa and Śukla pakṣas. 2) Vā. 56. 30, 36.

पौलस्त्य
Paulastya  (I)--a name of Rāvaṇa. Br. III. 63. 196; Vā. 88. 195.

पौलस्त्य
Paulastya  (II)--a Ṛṣi. Vā. 61. 84; 62. 42, 53.

पौलस्त्य
Paulastya  (III)--a Deva in the 11th antam. Vā. 62. 17.

पौलस्त्य
Paulastya  (IV)--one of the seven sages. Vā. 100. 83; 97, 106, 116.

पौलस्त्य
Paulastyas  (I)--a Devagaṇa; one of the Niśācara Rākṣasa clans; 1) Br. III. 1. 50; 7. 162; 8. 57 and 62. of Agastya family. 2) M. 202. 2. 

पौलस्त्य
Paulastyas  (II)--a Rākṣasa clan; 1) Vā. 69. 195. sons of Dānāgni and Sujamghī. 2) Br. II. 11. 29.

पौलह
Paulaha --a Prajāpati; 1) Vā. 62. 17. and 42. father of the Pitṛs, Agniṣvāttas. 2) Ib. 70. 64; 73. 25.

पौलहअग्नितेज
Paulaha-Agnitejas --one of the seven sages of the 11th antam; 1) Vā. 100. 83. a Tapośayāna; 2) Ib. 100. 97. a Tatvadarśi. 3) Ib. 100. 107.

पौल
Paulas --a hundred in number. Br. III. 74. 268; Vā. 99, 455.

पौलि
Pauli --an Ekārṣeya. M. 200. 6.

पौलिकायनि
Paulikāyani --an Ārṣeya Pravara (Aṅgiras). M. 196. 22.

पौलेय
Pauleyas --a western country. Br. II. 16. 60.

पौलोम
Pauloma --an Asura, who got exhausted in Amṛtamathana. Bhā. VIII. 7. 14.

पौलोम
Paulomas --a class of Asuras, who took part in the Devāsura war between Bali and Indra, and fought with Viśvedevās; 1) Bhā. VIII. 10. 22, and 34. sons of Mārica, a Dānava, 2) M. 6. 23; Vi. I. 21. 9. and of Pulomā. 

पौलोमा
Paulomā (ī) --a daughter of Puloma and wife of Bhṛgu the sage; 1) Br. III. 1. 75; Vā. 65. 73. mother of twelve sons, Bhṛgus, Gods; their younger brothers Viprās; 2) M. 195. 14. son Pṛcetāscyavana or Cyavana having aborted in the eighth month attacked by a Rākṣasa. 3) Br. III. 1. 91.

पौलोमी
Paulomī --a name of Indrāṇī. Bhā. VI. 18. 6; Vi. V. 30. 49.

पौष
Pauṣa --a month. On the Ekādaśi day is to be performed Manvantarādi śrāddha; on the aṣṭami Śambhu is to be worshipped. M. 17. 7; 56. 2; 60. 35.

पौषाजिति
Pauṣājiti --an Arṣeya Pravara (Aṅgiras). M. 196. 7.

पौष्कर
Pauṣkara --the blue colour; of Viṣṇu (Prādurbhāva). M. 171. 64 and 70.

पौष्टिकम्
Pauṣṭikam --the Mantras of the Atharvavedins recited in tank ritual. M. 24. 46; 58. 37.

पौष्ण्यायन
Pauṣṇyāyanas --Ārṣeya Pravaras (Bhārgavas). M. 195. 38.

पौष्यञ्जि
Pauṣyañji  (I)--one of the two best Sāmagas. Vā. 61. 48.

पौष्यञ्जि
Pauṣyañji  (II)--(Pauṣpinji-Vi. P.) a disciple of Sukarma among the disciples of the North given by Indra; taught the five hundred Samhitas; Langākṣi and Mangali were some of his disciples; 1) Bhā. XII. 6. 77 and 79; Vā. 61. 33. a Srutaṛṣi and the chief among the Sāmagas; 2) Br. II. 33. 7; III. 63. 207. his disciples; 3) Vā. 61. 36; Vi. IV. 6. 4. Udicya Samagas. 

प्रकटशक्ति
Prakaṭaśaktis --(see Mudrā devīs): a group of Śaktis. Br. IV. 19. 15.

प्रकाशक
Prakāśaka --a son of Raivata Manu. M. 9. 21.

प्रकुन्दक
Prakundakas --a Piśāca gaṇa. Vā. 69. 263.

प्रकृति
Prakṛti  (I)--Matter as opposed to Puruṣa; could be conquered by one's yogabala; 1) Bhā. I. 8. 18; III. 5. 46; Br. II. 19. 173, 195-7; III. 42. 47; 43. 3. has the three guṇas--satva, rajas and tamas. 2) Bhā. VII. 1. 7. Eight kinds of; 3) Ib. VII. 7. 22; XI. 22. 18-24. the seven principles leading to pralaya; 4) Ib. XII. 4. 5; Br. IV. 2. 231; 6. 6; 15. 7; 43. 76. also known as pradhāna and avyakta; makes and unmakes the universe; created by the unborn Iśvara; 5) M. 3. 14; 154. 356; Vi. I. 2. 19. is yoganidrā. 6) Ib. V. 2. 7; VI. 4. 34-5.

प्रकृति
Prakṛti  (II)--the subjects of a king; Pṛthu treated them with respect; 1) Bhā. IV. 17. 2; Br. III. 49. 17; M. 34. 26; 226. 6; 240. 11. acquiesed in selecting Pūru and also Dyumatsena. 2) Ib. 36. 5; 214. 16.

प्रकृति
Prakṛtis  (I)--seven kinds, which support the monarch. Bhā. VI. 14. 17-18.

प्रकृति
Prakṛtis  (II)--usually eight, the eight places of gods, from Brahmā to Piśāca, eight-fold aiśvarya, the eight rūpas, etc. 1) Br. IV. 3. 27 to 73. regarded as truth and their opposite as false. 2) Ib. IV. 3. 85. 

प्रकृति
Prakṛtis  (III)--seven avyakta, waters, tejas, vāyu, ākāśa, bhūtādi and mahat enter gradually and bring about Pratyāhara; 1) Vā. 102. 26; 49. 185. also eight kinds. 2) Ib. 102. 95.

प्रकृतिप्रसूति
Prakṛtiprasūti --Brahmam, the first Pravṛtti of Īśvara. Vā. 3. 9; 61. III.

प्रक्रियार्थपाद
Prakriyārthapāda --(also Prakriyāpāda) the first part of the Purāṇa; 1) Br. I. 1. 38; IV. 4. 43; Va. 7. 1. contains the contents of the Purāṇa; 2) Ib. 4. 13; 103. 44. is of 4000 ślokas and represents the Kṛtayugam. 3) Ib. 32. 59.

प्रघस
Praghasa --an Asura follower of Bali. M. 245. 32.

प्रघास
Praghāsa --a god of the Lekha group. Br. II. 36. 75.

प्रघोष
Praghoṣa --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Mādrī (Lakṣmaṇā). Bhā. X. 61. 15.

प्रचण्डा
Pracaṇḍā --a goddess enshrined at Chāgalāṇḍa. M. 13. 43.

प्रचिन्वान्
Pracinvān --the son of Janamejaya and father of Pravīra. Vi. IV. 19. 1.

प्रचेतस्
Pracetas  (I)--the son of Durdama; had a hundred sons who went to the North as lords of the Mlecchas. 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 15-16; Br. III. 74. 11-12; Vā. 99. 11. Father of Śatadharma. 2) Vi. IV. 17. 4-5. 

प्रचेतस्
Pracetas  (II) (Praśānti): a name of Śanti Agni. Br. II. 12. 29; Vā. 29. 27.

प्रचेतस्
Pracetas  (III)--a Mantrakṛt; see Cyavana. Br. II. 32. 104; III. 1. 92; Vā. 65. 54, 88.

प्रचेतस्
Pracetas  (IV)--a Pārāvata god. Br. II. 36. 13. Vā. 62. 12.

प्रचेतस्
Pracetas  (V)--a god of Prasūta group. Br. II. 36. 70.

प्रचेतस्
Pracetas  (VI)--a god of the Lekha group. Br. II. 36. 75.

प्रचेतस्
Pracetas  (VII)--one of the Mind-born sons of Brahmā; a Mantrakṛt. M. 3. 7; 102. 19; 145. 98; Vā. 59. 96.

प्रचेतस्
Pracetas  (VIII)--the son of Viduṣa; had 100 sons, all chieftains of the Mleccha countries of the northern regions. M. 48. 8-9.

प्रचेतस्
Pracetas  (IX)--the father of the Yakṣas. Vā. 69. 11.

प्रचेतस
Pracetasa --a Prajeśvara. Br. III. 1. 54.

प्रचेतस
Pracetasas(also Pracetas) --the collective name of the ten sons of Prācīnabarhiṣa and Sāmudrī; commanded by their father they engaged themselves in penance in the  midst of the ocean and meditated on the teachings of Śiva given to them; leaving their home they proceeded to the west and in a park near a great lake heard the divine music; when listening to it, there appeared Śiva who on request initiated them in the meditation on Viṣṇu (Rudragītā); when Śiva left they meditated under the waters for 1000 years. Viṣṇu appeared before them and promised them a son by asking them to marry the daughter of Kaṇḍu and Pramlocā; pleased with seeing the God they praised Him; after his disappearance they came out of the waters and seeing the earth filled with wild growth they began to burn the trees by breathing spiritual fire and wind from their mouth. Brahmā (Soma) interceded then and prevented them from further destroying the trees by offering Vārkṣi (Māriṣā) the daughter of the trees in marriage to them; they married her and she gave birth to Dakṣa on the eve of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. 1) Bhā. IV. 24 (whole); 25. 1-2; 30 (whole) VI. 4. 4-17; Br. II. 13. 40; 37. 27; M. 4. 47-9; Vā. 63. 27-9. After a long period of enjoyment of life they placed their wife under their son Dakṣa and went away to the western sea where Jajali attained siddhi; seeing them steadfast in devotion Nārada came there, and was welcomed by them; requested by them to be instructed to get rid of samsāra, Nārada advised them to worship and contemplate on Viṣṇu directly, and than departed; they did so and attained the world of Viṣṇu; 2) Bhā. IV. 31. 1-25. sacrifice of, when Nārada sang praises of Dhruva; 3) Ib. IV. 12. 40; 13. 2. worshipped for treasure. 4) Ib. II. 3. 7.

प्रज
Praja --a son of Havirdhāna. Br. II. 37. 24.

प्रजन
Prajana  (I)--a son of Kuru. M. 50. 23.

प्रजन
Prajana  (II)--an Asura in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. M. 161. 81. 

प्रजाति
Prajāti --a Yāmadeva. Vā. 31. 6.

प्रजादर्प
Prajādarpa --a Madhyamādhvaryu. Br. II. 33. 16.

प्रजानि
Prajāni --the father of Khanitra. Vā. 86. 4.

प्रजापति
Prajāpati  (I)--a title of honour earned by Manu and the mind-born and other sons of Brahmā; 1) M. 1. 33. describes the creator; 2) Ib. 4. 8. anointment of the Dikpālas by; 3) Ib. 8. 9. Dakṣa a Prajāpati; 4) Bhā. II. 6. 7; IV. 5. 17; VII. 12. 26; V. 23. 5; X. 54. 49. Nine in number, worshipped for the sake of progeny. 5) Ib. I. 3. 27; II. 3. 2; VII. 8. 38.

प्रजापति
Prajāpati  (II)--the lord of Vairājaka Kalpa; wife Gāyatrī; son Snigdhasvara. Vā. 21. 41-2.

प्रजापति
Prajāpati  (III)--the Veda-Vyāsa of the second Dvāpara. Vi. III. 3. 11.

प्रजापति
Prajāpati  (IV)--the son of Prāmśu and father of Khanitra. Vi. IV. 1. 23.

प्रजापति
Prajāpatis --Prajeśvaras; they are Kardama, Kaśyapa, Śeṣa, Vikrānta, Suśrāva, Bahuputra, Kumāra, Vivasvān, Śuciśravas, Pracetas, Ariṣṭanemi and Bahula. Vā. 65. 53-54.

प्रजापतिक्षेत्रम्
Prajāpatikṣetram --a tīrtha between Prayāgā, Pratiṣṭhāna and the Vāsukihṛadā. M. 104. 5. 

प्रजापतिगिरि
Prajāpatigiri --a Mt. felt the prowess of Hiraṇyakaśipu's arms. M. 163. 88.

प्रजासम्भवन
Prajāsambhavana --Svāyambhuva came out of him. Vā. 21. 60.

प्रजाहेतव
Prajāhetava --the Saptaṛṣis as Dārāgṇihotrins. Vā. 61. 100.

प्रजेश्वर
Prajeśvara --the son of Bhīmaratha: was a Divodāsa, lord of Vāraṇāsi; Kṣemaka ruined the city and Nikumbha cursed it to be desolate when the king established himself at Gomati; killed the 100 sons of Bhadrasena and took his kingdom leaving Durmada a son of Bhadrasena to escape as a baby; 1) Br. III. 67. 26. father of Pratardhana by Dṛṣadvatī; his wife Suyaśā had no son in spite of her worship at Nikumbha's temple. 2) Ib. III. 67. 47-67.

प्रज्योति
Prajyoti --an Amitābha god of the Svārocisa epoch. Br. II. 36. 53.

प्रज्वार
Prajvāra --the brother of Bhaya, Lord of the Yavanas; consumed the city of Purañjana to flames; allegorically the two forms of fever. Bhā. IV. 27. 30; 28. 11; 29. 23.

प्रज्ञ
Prajña  (I)--an Amitābha god. Br. II. 36. 53.

प्रज्ञ
Prajña  (II)--(ety): all the senses came out of Īśvara. Vā. 4. 37.

प्रणव
Praṇava --the top mantra; glorifies Īśvara; Yajña glorifies Praṇava; manas Yajña in the form of Rudra; hence  Paramampadam; Omkāram, Akṣaram, Brahmā and three varṇas; 2) Ib. 32. 1. Praṇavātmaka is Brahmā; 3) Ib. 24. 51. is Rudra. 4) Br. II. 13. 137. ^1 M. 85. 6; Vā. 20. 38.

प्रणवावस्तिथ
Praṇavāvastithas --Bhūha, Bhuva, and Sva. Vā. 61. 108.

प्रणाल
Praṇāla  (also Praṇālaka)--the water-vent on the Pīṭha of an image; facing the North. M. 262, 5 and 16.

प्रणीत
Praṇīta --a Marīci god. Br. IV. 1. 58.

प्रतक्वान्य
Pratakvānya --an Agni named Nabha. Br. II. 12. 23.

प्रतपन
Pratapana --a hell. Br. IV. 33. 61.

प्रतर्दन
Pratardana  (I)--see Dyumat. Bhā. IX. 17. 6.

प्रतर्दन
Pratardana  (II)--a son of Divodāsa; father of Vatsa and Garga; 1) Br. III. 67. 67-9; Vā. 92. 64, 65. earned the title, Śatrujit by destroying the line of Bhadraśreṇīya; known as Vatsa, so called by his father out of love, and as Ṛtadhvaja by being truthful. For possessing a horse by name Kuvalāyaśva, he came to be known by that name. Alarka was the son of Vatsa. 2) Vi. IV. 8. 11-16.

प्रतर्दन
Pratardana  (III)--a grandson of Yayāti by his daughter who with Aṣṭaka, Śibi and Pratardana was engaged in a sacrifice; 1) M. 35. 5. discoursed with Yayāti on different worlds and  promised to give those worlds to which he was entitled to; went to heaven with the above. 2) Ib. 38. 22; 41. 13-14; 42. 14, 26 and 28.

प्रतर्दन
Pratardanas --a group of gods, twelve in number, of the epoch of Uttama Manu. Br. II. 36. 27, 31. Vā. 62. 24; Vi. III. 1. 14.

प्रताप
Pratāpa --a follower of Bali. M. 245. 32.

प्रतावि
Pratāvi --a son of Udgītha. Vā. 33. 56.

प्रति
Prati --the son of Kuśa and father of Sañjaya. Bhā. IX. 17. 16; Br. III. 3. 35.

प्रतिक
Pratika --the son of Manu and father of Kṛtaratha. Vi. IV. 5. 27.

प्रतिकाश्व
Pratikāśva --the son of Bhānumat and father of Supratīka. Bhā. IX. 12. 11.

प्रतिकृत्
Pratikṛt --one of the names of the fourth Marut gaṇa. Vā. 67. 127.

प्रतिक्षत्र
Pratikṣatra  (I)--the son of Śami and father of Svayambhoja. Br. III. 71. 139; M. 44. 80; Vi. IV. 14. 23.

प्रतिक्षत्र
Pratikṣatra  (II)--a son of Kṣatravrddha and father of Samjaya. Vi. IV. 9. 25-26. 

प्रतिक्षिप्त
Pratikṣipta --a son of Śami. Vā. 96. 137.

प्रतिक्षेत्र
Pratikṣetra --a son of Pratikṣatra and father of Bhoja. M. 44. 80.

प्रतित्वक
Pratitvaka --a son of Maru and father of Kīrtiratha. Vā. 89. 11.

प्रतिदृक्ष
Pratidṛkṣa --one of the names of the Marut gaṇa. Vā. 67. 178.

प्रतिप
Pratipa --a son of Dilīpa, and father of three sons: Devāpi, Śantanu and Bāhlika. Vā. 99. 234.

प्रतिपक्ष
Pratipakṣa --a son of Kṣatradharma and father of Śṛñjaya (Sañjaya Vā. P.). Br. III. 68. 7; Vā. 93. 7.

प्रतिपत्
Pratipat --the first among the tithis; 1) Br. II. 24. 142. the first day after the two parvas in the month fit for Anvādhānakriya. 2) Ib. II. 28. 37.

प्रतिप्रस्तर
Pratiprastara --one of the sixteen Ṛtviks for Yajña; issued from the back of Nārāyaṇa. M. 167. 8.

प्रतिबाहु
Pratibāhu  (I)--a son of Śvaphalka. Bhā. IX. 24. 17.

प्रतिबाहु
Pratibāhu  (II)--the son of Vajra and father of Subāhu (Sucāru Vi. P. and Vā. P.). Bhā. X. 90. 38; Vā. 96. 251; Vi. IV. 15. 41-2. 

प्रतिभा
Pratibhā (Prabhāva) --characteristics of; Vidyā, Kāvyam, Śilpam, etc. Vā. 12. 6-8.

प्रतिभानु
Pratibhānu --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā. Bhā. X. 61. 11.

प्रतिम
Pratima (Paulastya) --a sage of the second Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 70.

प्रतिमालक्षण
Pratimālakṣaṇa --rules relating to the carving of different sizes of images and of gods to be worshipped in houses: relative proportions of a Navatāla image; 1) M. 258. 4-25, 26-57. Specialities of feminine forms; 2) Ib. 25.8; 58-74. Images of other sizes including Rāma, Varāha, Narasimha, of Śiva with ten arms, four or eight arms: defective forms to be condemned; 3) Ib. ch. 25.9. Specialities of Ardhanārīśvara or Umāmaheśvara; 4) Ib. 260. 1-20. of Śivanārāyaṇa; 5) Ib. 260. 21-27. of Brahmā and Kārttikeya; 6) Ib. 260. 40-55. of Kātyāyanī; 7) Ib. 260. 56-65. of Indra; 8) Ib. 260. 66-69. images of Mother goddesses. 9) Ib. 261. 24-49. Pedestals of different images--A pedestal is divided into 16 parts; ten kinds of pedestals described: made of stone, earth, wood or a mixture according as the devata is made of; 10) Ib. ch. 262. The symbol of Śiva in the shape of a phallus, the size depending on the size of the temple: made of ruby, diamond, earth, wood, gold and stone according to one's choice and means. 11) Ib. ch. 263.

प्रतिमेधा
Pratimedhā --a god of Sumedhasa group. Br. II. 36. 60.

प्रतिम्बक
Pratimbaka --a son of Maru; father of Kīrtiratha, Br. III. 64. 11. 

प्रतिरूप
Pratirūpa --a daughter of Maru and wife of Kimpuruṣa. Bhā. V. 2. 23.

प्रतिवाह
Prativāha  (I)--a son of Gāndhinī. Vā. 96. 111. Br. III. 71. 112.

प्रतीवाह
Pratīvāha  (II)--a son of Upamadgu. Vi. IV. 14. 9.

प्रतिविन्ध्य
Prativindhya --a son of Yudhiṣṭhira and Draupadī. Bhā. IX. 22. 29; M. 50. 51; Vā. 99. 246. Vi. IV. 20. 42.

प्रतिविन्ध्य
Prativindhyas --a 100 kings; ruled after the Bhojas. Br. III. 74. 267; M. 273. 71. Vā. 32. 50; 99. 453.

प्रतिव्यूह
Prativyūha --the son of Vatsavyūha and father of Divākara. Vā. 99. 282.

प्रतिव्योम
Prativyoma  (I)--a son of Vatsavṛddha and father of Bhānu. Bhā. IX. 12. 10.

प्रतिव्योम
Prativyoma  (II)--a son of Vatsadroha. M. 271. 5.

प्रतिव्योम
Prativyoma  (III)--the son of Vatsavyūha and father of Divākara. Vi. IV. 22. 3.

प्रतिश्रव
Pratiśrava --a Rudra on the 12th cover of the Ṣoḍaśa Cakra. Br. IV. 34. 33.

प्रतिश्रुत
Pratiśruta --a son of Śāntidevā and Vasudeva. Bhā. IX. 24. 50. 

प्रतिष्ठा
Pratiṣṭhā  (I)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 35. 98.

प्रतिष्ठा
Pratiṣṭhā  (II)--a description of the consecration of the Linga in temples; 1) M. ch. 263. Māgha, Phālguṇa, Caitra, Vaiśākha, and Jyeṣṭha are auspicious months. The auspicious asterisms, planets and lagnas are also mentioned; 2) Ib. 264. 3-12. the maṇṭapa should lie on the east or north of the temple, of different measurements. An altar to be located in its centre. It is a temporary structure for performing the consecration ceremony, mantras and music form part of the ritual. The image to be then installed. The qualifications of the Sthāpaka: the details of the ceremony of worshiping the idol, offerings to the Bhūtas in all the three parts of the day: worship in the night time; should have dancing and singing as part of the ritual. 4) Ib. ch. 263. The image of Śiva to face North only; 5) Ib. 266. 4. then Lokapālas to be consecrated, and appeased with śānti. 6) Ib. 266. 19-65. The constituents of Arghya and how it is to be offered; 7) Ib. 267. 2-22. offering of 40 lights. 8) Ib. 267. 24-28. ^3 Ib. 264. 13-35.

प्रतिष्ठान
Pratiṣṭhāna  (I)--the capital of Aila Purūravas; 1) Vā. 91. 18. originally given to Sudyumna by Manu. 2) Vi. IV. 1. 16.

प्रतिष्ठान
Pratiṣṭhāna  (II) (Pratiṣṭhā)--capital of Sudyumna and Purūravas on the northern bank of the Yamunā, and near Prayāgā; 1) Bhā. IX. 1. 42; Br. III. 60. 21; 66. 21; M. 12. 18; 104. 5; 106. 30. offered to Sudyumna and by him to the Purūravas. 2) Vā. 85. 22.

प्रतिसन्धि
Pratisandhi --intermediate creation, description of; interval between two cosmic ages; 1) Br. II. 31. 113; M. 144. 101; Vā. 7. 2-3; 58. 112; 61, 145 and 148. no Pratisandhi between  one Kalpa and the other; but there is one between the different Manvantaras. 2) Br. II. 6. 2, 3 and 10.

प्रतिसंचर
Pratisaṃcara--pralaya  or deluge of all creatures, three kinds: naimittika, Prākṛtika and Ātyantika; 1) Vā. 100. 132; Vi. I. 2. 25; 3. 22-5. the Viṣṇu Purāṇa adds a fourth kind--nitya also called dainandini. 2) Ib. I. 7. 41-4; VI. 3. 1-3; 4. 7; 8. 1.

प्रतिसर्ग
Pratisarga  (I)--secondary creation, three-fold; 1) Br. IV. 3. 31, 110, 113; Vā. 102. 46, 53; Vi. VI. 8, 2 and 15. done by the ten sons, seven sages and Yāmadevas of the epoch of Svāyambhuva Manu; 2) M. 8. 1. one of the five characteristics of the Purāṇa. 3) Ib. 52. 2; 53. 65; Br. I. 1. 37; 3. 26.

प्रतिसर्ग
Pratisarga  (II)--a topic of the Purāṇa: at the evening of the day of Brahmā, Pralaya sets in, when the whole universe appears like an oven with blazing fire. Then come different clouds pouring in torrents everywhere (Ekārṇava) 1) Vā. 4. 10; 100. 133-79. Lord's sleep in the waters. 2) Ib. 100. 185-9.

प्रतिहर्ता
Pratihartā  (I)--a Marut of the sixth gaṇa. Br. III. 5. 97.

प्रतिहर्ता
Pratihartā  (II)--the son of Pratihāra. Vā. 33. 55; Vi. II. 1. 37.

प्रतिहर्ता
Pratihartā  (III)--a son of Pratīha, versed in sacrificial lore and father of Aja and Bhūman, by Stutī. Bhā. V. 15. 5; Br. II. 14. 66.

प्रतिहर्ता
Pratihartā  (IV)--one of the sixteen Ṛtviks for yajña; from the belly of Nārāyaṇa. M. 167. 9. 

प्रतीक
Pratīka --the son of Vasu and father of Oghavan and Oghavatī; 1) Bhā. IX. 2. 18. the Godāvari split herself, out of fear of him. 2) M. 22. 58.

प्रतीचि
Pratīci --a Ṛ. in the Draviḍa country. Bhā. XI. 5. 40.

प्रतीच्य
Pratīcyas --a tribe of the western regions. Vā. 58. 81.

प्रतीताश्व
Pratītāśva --the son of Bhānuratha; 1) Vā. 99. 284. father of Supratīka. 2) Vi. IV. 22. 4.

प्रतीप
Pratīpa  (I)--a son of Dilīpa and father of three sons, Devāpi and others. Bhā. IX. 22. 11-12; M. 50. 38. Vā. 99. 418; Vi. IV. 20. 8-9.

प्रतीप
Pratīpa  (II)--the first day of the Pakṣa; in the bright half, the moon leaves the Sūryamaṇḍala and takes the middle place between that maṇḍala and that of the moon; the time for sacrifices and oblations; 1) Vā. 56. 36, 47. first of tithis. 2) Ib. 53. 114.

प्रतीपक
Pratīpaka --a son of Maru and father of Kṛtiratha. Bhā. IX. 13. 16.

प्रतीपाश्व
Pratīpāśva --a son of Dhruvāśva. M. 271. 7.

प्रतीह
Pratīha --a son of Parameṣṭhi and Suvarcalā (VarcalāBr. P.) had three sons through his wife Suvarcalā; an adept in Ātmavidyā. Bhā. V. 15. 3-5. 

प्रतीहार
Pratīhāra --a door-keeper of the king's palace; Kālanemi's arrival is announced to Tāraka by the door-keeper kneeling and with mouth shut by his hand; 1) M. 154. 1, 4. Vīraka for Śiva; 2) Ib. 154. 383, 386. characteristics of; skilled, of good personality, speaking agreeably, and not overbearing. 3) Ib. 215. 11.

प्रतीहार
Pratīhāra --of the family of Parameṣṭhi. Br. II. 14. 65; Vi. II. 1. 36.

प्रकुंदकस्
Prakuṃdakas --a gaṇa of the Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 382.

प्रतुंदस्
Pratuṃdas --a class of Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 378.

प्रतोष
Pratoṣa --a son of Dakṣinī; a Tuṣita god. Bhā. IV. 1. 7-8.

प्रत्यक्षलवणम्
Pratyakṣalavaṇam --adding salt to food in the presence is forbidden to the Yatis. Vā. 18. 20.

प्रत्यग्र
Pratyagra --(Pratyagraha-Vā. P.) a son of Uparicara Vasu and a Cedipa. Bhā. IX. 22. 6. Vā. 99. 222; Vi. IV. 19. 81.

प्रत्यङ्गिरसयोगा
Pratyaṅgirasayogā --of the Brahma veda. Br. III. 1. 26.

प्रत्यश्रव
Pratyaśrava --a son of Caidyoparicara. M. 50. 27.

प्रत्यह
Pratyaha --an Ārṣeyapravara (Bhārgavas). M. 195. 43. 

प्रत्याहार
Pratyāhāra  (I)--the stage of the dissolution or withdrawal of creation on the commencement of Pralaya at the end of Kali; then the primordial spirit (avyakta) swallows that which is manifest (vyakta): waters swallow the gandha quality of the earth thus plunging the earth in waters; then the rasa quality of the waters gets merged in fire which spreads in all directions; the rūpa quality of fire is in turn eaten away by wind; this permeates all the ten directions, both above and below; the sparśa quality of wind is swallowed by ākāśā; the śabda (sound) quality of which is overwhelmed by bhūta and other gross elements; the great souls absorb these (mahā); seven Prakṛtis one covering the other. Br. II. 6. 14; IV. 3. 1-21; Vā. 102. 1-2, 5.

प्रत्याहार
Pratyāhāra  (II)--a dharma of the yoga, ruins all viṣayas or sense pleasures. 1) M. 183. 54. Vā. 10. 76 and 93. Vi. VI. 7. 45. The yogin sees God in himself. 2) Vā. 11. 18-9, 30; 101. 211; 104. 24.

प्रत्यूष
Pratyūṣa  (I)--a Devaṛṣi. Br. II. 35. 92.

प्रत्यूष
Pratyūṣa  (II)--one of the eight Vasus; (a Vasava); father of Devala the sage. Br. III. 3. 21, 27; M. 5. 21, 27; 203. 4; Vā. 61. 84; 66. 20. Vi. I. 15. 110, 117.

प्रत्यूष
Pratyūṣa  (III)--a Śakti of Kāla in the Pañcakoṇa. Br. IV. 32. 10.

प्रथम
Prathama --an Asura residing in Sutalam. Br. II. 20. 21; Vā. 50. 20. 

प्रथम
Prathama sāhasam --see Pūrva sāhasam; for being a pseudo-physician one deserves punishment. M. 227. 65, 177.

प्रथित
Prathita --a Vānara born of Pulaha. Br. III. 7. 179.

प्रदेश
Pradeśa --a measurement; ten angulas in length. Vā. 8. 102.

प्रदेशिनि
Pradeśini --the index finger used for measuring angulas. Vā. 8. 103.

प्रदोष
Pradoṣa --a son of Doṣa and Puṣpārṇa. Bhā. IV. 13. 14.

प्रदोषा
Pradoṣā --a Śakti on the Soḍaśapatrābjā. Br. IV. 32. 12.

प्रद्युम्न
Pradyumna  (I)--the eldest son of Kṛṣṇa by Rukminī; in his previous birth the God of Love (Kāma, Smara); 1) Vi. IV. 15. 37; V. 26. 12 to the end; ch. 27 (whole); 28. 6-7; 32. 1 and 6; Bhā. I. 10. 29; 11. 17; 14. 30; X. 40. 21; 61. 7 and 9; 90. 35; Br. III. 71. 245; 72. 1; IV. 29. 128; Vā. 96. 237. within ten days of his birth Śambara stole him and threw the babe into the sea; was swallowed by a fish; fishermen who caught the fish presented it to Śambara who asked the cooks to cook it; when cut open there was the child inside and Nārada asked Māyāvatī in charge of the kitchen to take care of the child after telling her the truth about it; that it was the re-incarnation of her husband Kāma; she brought up the child more as a lover; asked by Pradyumna why she was not behaving as a mother but as a wife she explained that she was Ratī and himself Kāma, and also as to how he came there by Śambara's act; taught Māyāvatī the vidyā of  Mahāmāyā: he invited Śambara to battle and cut off his head; then Māyāvatī took him by air to Dvārakā the residence of Rukmiṇī and Kṛṣṇa; in Kṛṣṇa's palace, women found the likeness of Kṛṣṇa in him and Rukminī thought of her lost son; to their wonder and joy Nārada related the life story of Pradyumna; the couple were embraced by all of them and the whole Dvārakā was filled with satisfaction. 2) Bhā. X. ch. 55 (whole); M. 47. 15, 23; 93. 51; 101; 10; 248. 48. Won his wife Rukmāvatī (Vaidarbhī) in a Svayamvara after vanquishing his rivals; father of Aniruddha; 3) Bhā. X. 61. 18, 22, 23 [8]; 90. 36. Vi. IV. 15. 39. attended his son's marriage at Bhojakaṭa; 4) Bhā. X. 61. 26. Picture drawn by Citralekha; 5) Ib. X. 62. 20; Vi. V. 32. 24. one among the Vṛṣṇis who went to attack Bāṇa's city; 6) Bhā. X. 63. 3. fought with Guha; 7) Ib. X. 63. 7. went along with his brothers to play and seeing a huge lizard in a well reported the same to Kṛṣṇa; 8) Ib. X. 64. 1-4. defended Dvārakā with other Yadus when Śālva besieged it; defeated Śālva's commander-in-chief and did other feats of valour; had a hit in the chest by Śālva's minister Dyumat and was taken out by his charioteer, whom he chided for his action; the charioteer defended his action under the ethics of war; attacked and vanquished Dyumat; 9) Ib. X. 76. 13-33. 77. 1-3. went to Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse; 10) Ib. X. 82. 6. went with Kṛṣṇa's sacrificial horse; 11) Ib. X. 89. 22. [2]. unable to recover the dead son of the Dvārakā Brahmana; 12) Ib. X. 89. 31 and 41; 90. 33. fought with Sāmba at Prabhāsa deluded by Kṛṣṇa; 13) Ib. XI. 30. 16. at his death his wives burnt themselves in fire. ^14 Ib. X. 31. 20; Vi. V. 33. 12; 37. 46.

प्रद्युम्न
Pradyumna  (II)--a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu. Bhā. IV. 13. 16

प्रद्युम्न
Pradyumna  (III)--a son of Bhānumān. Br. III. 64. 19; Vā. 89. 19. 

प्रद्युम्न
Pradyumna  (IV)--an epithet of Viṣṇu; 1) M. 276. 8; Vi. V. 18. 58; Vā. 111. 21. worship of. 2) Bhā. I. 5. 37; IV. 24. 35; VI. 16. 18.

प्रद्युम्न
Pradyumna  (V)--a Vamśavīra. Vā. 97. 1.

प्रद्योत
Pradyota  (I)--a son of Śunaka, the minister of Purañjaya; when Purañjaya was killed by Śunaka, Pradyota became king; father of Pālaka; founder of the line of Pradyotanas, five in number and who ruled for 138 years. Bhā. XII. 1. 3-4.

प्रद्योत
Pradyota  (II)--a Yakṣa; a son of Puṇyajani and Maṇibhadra. Br. III. 7. 124; Vā. 69. 156.

प्रद्योत
Pradyota  (III)--the son of Munika, killed his master Ripumjaya and ruled for 23 years; a Praṇatasāmanta, his four successors ruled for 138 years; Śiśunāka slew him and became king. Father of Balāka. Vā. 99. 310-4; Vi. IV. 24. 2-3.

प्रद्योतन
Pradyotanas --five beginning with Pradyota and ending-with Nandivardhana: they ruled the earth for 138 years. Bhā. XII. 1. 4.

प्रद्योति
Pradyoti --ruled for 23 years with the Sāmantas subdued. Br. III. 74. 123.

प्रधान
Pradhāna --an Ananta and Avyayātma; covers the mahat. Br. II. 21. 28; III. 43. 4; IV. 4. 12 and 20. 

प्रधानपुरुषौ
Pradhānapuruṣau--tamas  and satva; Pradhāna appears at the time of creation from Sadasadātmakam. Br. I. 4. 1; Vā. 5. 7-8, 22.

प्रधानम्
Pradhānam --(Māyā-Vā. P.) a term for Prakṛti; with vikāra results in mahat-tatvam. Br. I. 1. 88 and 93; 3. 9; 5. 103; Vā. 103. 12, 21, 36. M. 3. 15, 17; 60. 3; Vā. 4. 19; 23. 56; 24. 66. Vi. I. 2. 15-16.

प्रधानेशी
Pradhāneśī --a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 33.

प्रपितामह
Prapitāmaha --Kālātma, and the origin of the Ṛg, Sāma and Yajur Samhitas. Vā. 31. 33; 111. 84.

प्रपोहय
Prapohayas --Nīla (blue) Parāśaras. M. 201. 34.

प्रबल
Prabala  (I)--an attendent of Hari; attacked the Asura followers of Bali. Bhā. II. 9. 14; VIII. 21. 16.

प्रबल
Prabala  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Mādrī. Bhā. X. 61. 15.

प्रबाही
Prabāhī --brought forth 10 Deva-gandharvas, all best songsters. Vā. 68. 37.

प्रबुद्ध
Prabuddha --a son of Ṛṣabha; a Bhāgavata; advised Nimi how to get rid of the Māyā by means of going to a Guru and following the path of devotion to Hari. Bhā. V. 4. 11; XI. 2. 21; 3. 18-33. 

प्रभञ्जन
Prabhañjana  (I)--God of the wind; 1) Bhā. II. 25. 7. narrator of the Vāyu Purāṇa. 2) Vā. 2. 2.

प्रभञ्जन
Prabhañjana  (II)--a monkey chief. Br. III. 7. 233.

प्रभञ्जना
Prabhañjanā --a R. in the Ketumālā continent. Vā. 44. 18.

प्रभव
Prabhava  (I)--a son of Bhṛgu and a deva. ^1 Br. III. 1. 90. ^2 M. 195. 13.

प्रभव
Prabhava  (II)--a Sādhya. M. 171. 43; Vā. 66. 16.

प्रभवन्
Prabhavan --a Viśvedeva. Vā. 66. 32.

प्रभविष्णु
Prabhaviṣṇu --is Lord Śiva. Vā. 101. 294.

प्रभा
Prabhā  (I)--a queen of Puṣpārṇa, and mother of Prāta, Mādhyandina, and Sāyam. Bhā. IV. 13. 13.

प्रभा
Prabhā  (II)--a daughter of Svarbhānu; wife of Āyu and mother of Nahuṣa and four others; 1) Br. III. 6. 23-4; 67. 1; M. 6. 21; Vā. 68. 22, 24; Vi. I. 21. 7. one of the nine Devis serving Soma; 2) Vā. 90. 25. wife of Svarbhānu. 3) Ib. 92. 1.

प्रभा
Prabhā  (III)--one of the three wives of Vivasvat; 1) M. 11. 2. mother of Prabhātā; the goddess enshrined in Sūryabimba; 2) Ib. 13. 52. abandoned her consort for Soma with eight other Devis. 3) Ib. 23. 25. 

प्रभा
Prabhā  (IV)--the wife of Sagara; Yādavī and mother of 60,000 Sagaras. M. 12. 39, 42.

प्रभाकर
Prabhākara  (I)--a son of Jyotiṣmat after whom the varṣa was named. Br. II. 14. 28-29; Vā. 33. 24. Vi. II. 4. 36.

प्रभाकर
Prabhākara  (II)--the father of Soma through Madrā. Br. III. 8. 76.

प्रभाकर
Prabhākara  (III)--one of the 20 Sutapa gaṇas. Br. IV. 1. 14; Vā. 100. 14.

प्रभाकर
Prabhākara  (IV)--the Sun and consort of Prabhā who left him for Soma; image of; one wheel and seven horses; Daṇḍi and Pingala are the door-keepers; Dhātā with the pen in his hand; the charioteer, Aruṇa. M. 23. 25; 261. 1-8.

प्रभाकर
Prabhākara  (V)--an Ātreya; when Sūrya was beaten by Svarbhānu and was falling down to the earth, the whole world became dark when the sage by his words was able to prevent his falling down and thus giving light in the place of darkness. Vā. 70. 70-4; 99. 127.

प्रभाकरम्
Prabhākaram(c) --a kingdom of Kuśadvīpam. Br. II. 14. 29; 19. 58; Vā. 33. 26; 49. 54.

प्रभात
Prabhāta (Prabhāsa?) --the eighth Vasu who had for his wife Yogasiddhi (Varastrī) the sister of Bṛhaspati; their son was Viśvakarman; [see Rāmā; Bāl. Khān. 27-35 where he is named Sāvitra]. Br. III. 3. 21; 59. 16; M. 5. 21, 27; 203. 4; Vā. 61. 82; 66. 20, 27-8; 83. 20; 84. 16. 

प्रभानु
Prabhānu --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā. Bhā. X. 61. 10.

प्रभास
Prabhāsa  (I)--a tīrtha sacred to Hari and famous for the west flowing Saravatī. 1) Bhā. VII. 14. 31; XI. 30. 6; Br. III. 13. 40; Vā. 23. 215; 77. 40. Sages of this place visited Dvārakā. 2) Bhā. X. 90. 28 [5]. During his pilgrimage tour Arjuna went to this; 3) Ib. X. 86. 2. was visited by Balarāma and revisited by him; 4) Ib. X. 78. 18; 79. 21. here the Moon God who was struck with consumption (yakṣma) by the curse of Dakṣa got rid of his disease. 5) Ib. XI. 6. 35-8. Here Sāndipāni's son was drowned, and Vidura cast off his body. 6) Ib. X. 45. 37-8; III. 1. 20; I. 15. 49; Vi. V. 21. 25. To this came once the Vṛṣṇis, Bhojas, and Andhakas for sacred ablution when they had been cursed by some munis, and gave gifts of gold, silver and bed to Brahmanas. 7) Bhā. III 3. 25-8. On Kṛṣṇa's suggestion the Yadus left Dvārakā for good and went to this place, where they drank heavily induced by Kṛṣṇa, and fighting with one another, all of them died. 8) Ib. XI. 30. 10-19. Vi. V. 37. 30, 38-9. Sacred to Puṣkarāvati 9) M 13. 43. the intervening space between the cheek and neck of the personified Veda. 10) Vā. 104. 78.

प्रभास
Prabhāsa  (II)--one of the twenty Sutapa gaṇas. Br. IV. 1. 14; Vā. 100. 15.

प्रभास
Prabhāsa  (III)--Mt. covering the foot of the śilā of Gayāsura; ety. that which shines bright; from the little finger of the śilā came out Īśa; in Gayā. Vā. 108. 13-4; 109. 14.

प्रभास
Prabhāsa  (IV)--a Vasu; married the sister of Bṛhaspati. Father of Viśvakarman. Vi. I. 15. 110, 118-19. 

प्रभासेश
Prabhāseśa --is Śiva, the God who came out as a little finger of the śilā at Gayā; by cutting through the Prabhāsa hill. Vā. 108. 14, 23.

प्रभाव्रतम्
Prabhāvratam --the performer of it becomes a Rājarāja. M. 101. 54.

प्रभासौरी
Prabhāsaurī --at sunset the rays of the sun enter fire and hence the latter is seen in the night; when the sun rises in the morning, fire enters the sun's rays and hence the light of fire is not seen in the day; when the sun is in the middle of the earth night enters the waters and hence they are of the copper colour. In the night day enters the waters and hence waters take the white colour. Thus ahorātras enter waters. Vā. 50. 112-17.

प्रभु
Prabhu  (I)--a son of Bhaga and Siddhi. Bhā. VI. 18. 2.

प्रभु
Prabhu  (II)--a son of Śuka and Pīvarī; a Sādhya. Br, III. 3. 17; 8. 93; M. 15. 10; 203. 12; Vā. 70. 85; 73. 30.

प्रभु
Prabhu  (III)--see Maru. Br. III. 63. 211.

प्रभु
Prabhu  (IV)--one of the Amitābha gaṇa. Br. IV. 1. 16; Vā. 100. 16.

प्रभुशक्ति
Prabhuśakti --of the king. Br. II. 29. 82; M. 142. 68; Vā. 57. 75.

प्रभूति
Prabhūti --a Marīci God. Br. IV. 1. 58. 

प्रमति
Pramati  (I)--the son of Prāmśu, and father of Khanītra. Bhā. IX. 2. 24.

प्रमति
Pramati  (II)--the son of Nṛdeva, of the gotra of the Moon; vanquished the Mlecchas and adharmic kings; took the form of an aśva. Br. II. 31. 76; 89; M. 144. 51, 63.

प्रमति
Pramati  (III)--a son of Janamejaya; 1) Br. III. 61. 17. heard the Viṣṇu Purāna from Vedaśiras and narrated it to Jātukarṇa. 2) Vi. VI. 8. 48-9.

प्रमति
Pramati  (IV)--an incarnation of Viṣṇu. Br. III. 73. 111; M. 144. 60.

प्रमति
Pramati  (V)--an Amitābha god. Br. IV. 1. 17; Vā. 100. 16.

प्रमति
Pramati  (VI)--an Asura in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. M. 161. 79.

प्रमथ
Pramathas --a class of Bhūtas who constituted the gaṇa of Śiva; 1) Bhā. IV. 2. 15; V. 5. 21; Vā. 39. 43; 72. 50. evil-eyed spirits; 2) Br. III. 16 51; 42. 33; Bhā. VI. 8. 25. followers of Rudra and of Dakṣiṇa Agni; 3) Ib. X. 63. 6; 66. 30. of animal and other cruel faces; 4) M. 135. 33. fight of, under the leadership of Nandi, against the Asuras; 5) Ib. 136. 19, 34, 67; 137. 1; 138. 10, 55. defended the chariot of Tripurāri; 6) Ib. 133. 66 and 69. put down by Kṛṣṇa; 7) Bhā. X. 37. 13; 85. 41; Vi. V. 33. 13, 24 and 27, 34. 40. at Bāṇa's capital.

प्रमथनाथमख
Pramathanāthamakha --a sacrifice in honour of Pramathanātha (Mahābhairava) conducted by Jarāsandha with kings who were taken captives. Bhā. I. 15. 9. 

प्रमथि
Pramathi --a son of Añjanāvati; an elephant. Br. III. 7. 343.

प्रमद
Pramada  (I)--a son of Vasiṣṭha, and one of the seven sages of the epoch of Uttama Manu. Bhā. VIII. 1. 24.

प्रमद
Pramada  (II)--a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 10.

प्रमन्थु
Pramanthu --a son of Vīravrata and Bhoja. Bhā. V. 15. 15.

प्रमर्दन
Pramardana  (I)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 239.

प्रमर्दन
Pramardana  (II)--an elephant born of Sāma. Br. III. 7. 335; Vā. 69. 219.

प्रमाणाष्टकम्
Pramāṇāṣṭakam --the eight Pramāṇas. M. 3. 4.

प्रमाथिनी
Pramāthinī --a Śakti. Br. IV. 19. 74.

प्रमानज्ञ
Pramānajñas --the experts in the measurement of time. Vā. 100. 219.

प्रमालिका
Pramālikā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 27. 38.

प्रमिति
Pramiti  (I)--(Pramati-Br. P.) (Atreya): of Candramasa gotra; killed the Mlecchas and the Pāṣaṇḍas; the  avatār of the Lord in the Kali age; has an amśa of Mādhava; went about the earth for 20 years surrounded by armed Brahmanas; having killed many a tribe attained samādhi in the midst of the Ganges and the Yamunā. Br. I. 1. 99; Vā. 58. 76-88.

प्रमिति
Pramiti  (II)--the previous birth of Kalki. Vā. 98. 110.

प्रमोद
Pramoda(ka)  (I)--a Vināyaka. Br. IV. 27. 81; 44. 68.

प्रमोद
Pramoda  (II)--born out of the neck of Brahmā. M. 3. 11.

प्रमोद
Pramoda  (III)--a son of Dṛḍhāśva. M. 12. 33.

प्रमोदा
Pramodā --a mother-goddess. M. 179. 27.

प्रमोदाह
Pramodāha --a Dānava. Vā. 68. 10.

प्रम्लोचा
Pramlocā --the Apsaras, who bore a daughter Māriṣā to Kaṇḍu, and left the child among the trees and went away. Presides over the months of Nabho-Nābha; with the sun in the Nabhasya; 1) Bhā. IV. 30. 13; XII. 11. 37; Br. II. 23. 10; III. 7. 15. M. 126. 11; Vā. 52. 11; 69. 50; Vi. II. 10. 9. in the months Āvaṇi and Puraṭṭāśi (Aug.Sept.-Oct.); in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. 2) M. 161. 74.

प्रयागा
Prayāgā  (I)--a tīrtha sacred to Hari. Sages of this place visited Dvārakā; was visited by Balarāma; 1) Bhā. VII. 14. 30; X. 90. 28 [3]; XII. 1. 37; X. 79. 10; M. 22. 8. capital of  the Aila Purūravas on the north bank of the Yamunā. 2) Br. III. 13. 100; 66. 21; IV. 44. 98; Vā. 91. 50. Lalitā enshrined at; 3) M. 13. 26. fit for śrāddha; 4) Vā. 77. 92. occupied by the Kurus, 5) Ib. 99. 215. represents the nose of the personified Veda; 6) Ib. 104. 76; 106. 69. a Janapada of the Gupta emperors. 7) Ib. 99. 383; Vi. IV. 24. 63; VI. 8. 29.

प्रयागा
Prayāgā  (II)--(Māhātmyam): Markaṇḍeya to Yudhiṣṭhira on; here is Prajāpatikṣetra; people who bathe here go to heaven and who die here are liberated from samsāra; guarded by Indra; there are five deep channels in Prayāgā with the Ganges flowing in their midst. Sins are washed off by entering its boundary. The goddess Yamunā, the daughter of the Sun God is ever present: It is a place haunted by the Gods, Asuras, Ṛṣis and Siddhas; 1) M. ch. 104. one who remembers Prayāgā from his own native home or from a foreign place on the eve of his death goes to the world of Brahmā. Leaving the heaven, he is reborn as a King of Jambūdvīpa; gifts of cows, jewels and gold here attain great merit: The giver is born in Uttara Kuru regions and enjoys long life. 2) Ib. ch. 105. One should not drive to the place in a conveyance drawn by bullocks lest the virtue of bathing should be lost. Giving daughters in marriage, and death near the Akṣayavaṭa helps one in going to the world of Śiva. One should go and do charities with utmost faith. Here are 60 crores and 10000 holy spots; wellknown for a Śiva shrine: Pratiṣṭhāna lies to the east of the Ganges, and to its north lies the Hamsaprapatana Tīrtha. There are again Ūrvaśīramaṇa, Sandhya Vaṭa, Koṭī Tīrtha, and others, all holy; 3) Ib. ch. 106. by merely listening to the greatness of Prayāgā a man gets liberated. To the south of Prayāgā there is a Ṛṇamocana Tīrtha where by residing for a night and by bathing, one never runs into debts. A pilgrimage to P. gives the benefit of an Aśvamedha sacrifice: relieves his manes for ten generations: its circumference is five yojanas  and every step is sacred: the greatness of the Yamunā described; 4) Ib. chh. 107-8. a man dying at P. gets the benefits of a Yogin: the king of all tīrthas: P. is again the place where both Kambala and Aśvatara reside. It is the altar of Prajāpati. It is more sacred, being situated on the banks of the Ganges. It is the giver of heaven, the personification of bliss and truth: Reading the Mahātmya takes one to heaven; 5) Ib. chh. 109-110. Here Brahmā, Viṣṇu and Śiva are all present. Brahmā stands on the Northern part of the Tīrtha to protect it: Viṣṇu is represented as Veṇī Mādhava, while Śiva is present in the shape of a banyan tree. In addition to them, the gods, oceans and mountains also live there. It is known as Prajāpati Indrakṣetra. One who remembers this every day attains heaven. After hearing this, Yudhiṣṭhira is said to have bathed in Prayāgā. 6) Ib. chh. 111-112; 180. 56; 192. 11; 193. 19.

प्रयाति
Prayāti --a Yāmadeva. Br. II. 13. 92.

प्रयुत
Prayuta --a Mauneya Gandharva. Br. III. 7. 2.

प्रलम्ब
Pralamba --An Asura friend of Kamsa; 1) Bhā. II. 7. 34; X. 2. 1; Br. III. 6. 15; IV. 29. 123; Vi. V. 1. 24; 4. 1-2; 15. 1. in the guise of a gopa, was admitted to the games by Kṛṣṇa's playmates, as Kṛṣṇa had decided on his death. In a game Rāma was to carry on his back the Assura. While doing so, the Asura grew to a huge size to defeat Rāma. By the fist of his hand, Rāma broke his head and killed him. 2) Bhā. X. 18. 17-30; 20. 1; 43. 30; 46. 26; 51. 42; Vi. V. 9. 13 to the end; Vā. 68. 15.

प्रलम्बायन
Pralambāyanas --the sages. M. 200. 11. 

प्रलय
Pralaya --the deluge: destruction; after Manvantaras; 1) M. 2. 22; 142. 36. two kinds--one at the end of a Kalpa or the day of Brahmā and the other at the end of the life of Brahmā. 2) Vi. VI. 1. 3.

प्रवर्षण
Pravarṣaṇa --the top hill of Gomanta. Pursued by Jarāsandha, Rāma and Kṛṣṇa fled to this. Besieged by Jarāsandha. Bhā. X. [53 (v) 5]; 52. 10-11 [3], [16].

प्रवह
Pravaha --one of the seven Maruts; 1) Br. II. 22. 39; M. 163. 32. the kind of wind that helps Brahmaja clouds to rain: the chief of the second vātaskandha; 2) Br. II. 23. 98; III. 5. 83; Vā. 67. 115. the clouds controlling Jīmūta clouds. 3) Ib. 51. 36.

प्रवहन
Pravahana --a sage of the Auttama epoch. M. 9. 14.

प्रवाहन
Pravāhana --Agni (Dhiṣṇi). Br. II. 12. 20.

प्रवाहुक
Pravāhuka --a son of the Muṇḍīśa avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 211.

प्रविजय
Pravijayas --a tribe; 1) M. 114. 45. an eastern Janapada. 2) Vā. 45. 123.

प्रवीण
Pravīṇa --one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 7.

प्रवीर
Pravīra  (I)--a son of Prācīnavat, and father of Namasyu (Manasyu Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 20. 2; Vi. IV. 19. 1. 

प्रवीर
Pravīra  (II)--a son of Vindhyaśakti and a great hero: capital at Kāncanaka: performed the Vājapeya and other Yajñas, father of four sons: ruled for 6 years. Br. III. 74. 184-6; Vā. 99. 371-2.

प्रवीर
Pravīra  (III)--a son of Upadānavī. M. 49. 10.

प्रवीर
Pravīra  (IV)--a son of Trasyu. Vā. 99. 133.

प्रवीर
Pravīra  (V)--a king of the dynasty of Vindhyaśakti. Vi. IV. 24. 56.

प्रवीरक
Pravīraka --a ruler of Kilikilā. Bhā. XII. 1. 33.

प्रवृत्तिकालस्
Pravṛttikālas --at the time of creation men full of rajas attain the bhūtas and indriyas through the favour of gods; by the meditation of the Lord the three guṇas get their respective guṇas defined; all of common dharmas attain vikāra for creation; happiness and misery, dharma and adharma, truth and untruth reach each according to his inclination; separation of Guṇas. Vā. 103. 25-33.

प्रशान्त
Praśānta --Agni Pracetas. Br. II. 12. 29.

प्रशुस्रुक
Praśusruka --(Prasuśruta-Bhā. P.) a son of Maru and father of Susandhi. Vi. IV. 4. 111. Bhā. IX. 12. 7. 

प्रश्रय
Praśraya --born of Dharma and Hṝ. Bhā. IV. 1. 52.

प्रसव
Prasava --a son of Bhṛgu. Vā. 65. 87.

प्रसाद
Prasāda  (I)--born of Maitrī. Bhā. IV. 1. 50.

प्रसाद
Prasāda  (II)--a fruit of Prāṇāyāma; control of the five winds by the senses. Vā. 11. 4, 10.

प्रसुश्रुत
Prasuśruta --a son of Manu and father of Susandhi. Vā. 88. 211.

प्रसूत
Prasūtas --a group of eight gods of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Śyenabhadra, Paśya, Pathyanetra, Sumana, Suveta, Revata, and Dhyuti, and Supracetas so-called. Br. II. 36. 66, 71; Vi. III. 1. 27. Vā. 62. 60.

प्रसूति
Prasūti  (I)--a daughter of Svāyambhuva Manu, married to Dakṣa: gave birth to sixteen (Twenty four Br. P.) daughters; was afraid of Vīrabhadra and his party in the sacrificial hall of her husband. Bhā. III. 12. 55-56; IV. 1. 1 and 11, 47-48; 5. 9. Br. I. 1. 59; II. 9. 42-7; Vā. 1. 66 and 68; Vi. I. 7. 18-19, 22-27.

प्रसूति
Prasūti  (II)--an elephant daughter of the Dignāgas. Br. III. 7. 354.

प्रसूति
Prasūti  (III)--a daughter of Vairāja; was given in marriage to Dakṣa; Dakṣa to be conceived as Prāṇa and  Maru as Saṅkalpa; to them were born 24 daughters, all Viśvamātaras. Vā. 10. 17, 22-3; 67. 27-8.

प्रसूति
Prasūti  (IV)--a wife of Vasiṣṭha. Vi. I. 7. 8.

प्रसेन
Prasena --a son of Nighna (Nimna-Bha. P.) and brother of Satrājit (Sakrājit-Vā. P.): went out ahunting with the Syamantaka jewel and was killed by a lion and the jewel was taken by it: his death wrongly ascribed to Govinda: was stationed by Kṛṣṇa (s.v.) to defend the western gate of Mathurā. Bhā. IX. 24. 13; X. 50. 20 [4]; 56. 13-14; Br. III. 71. 21-52; M. 45. 3-18; Vā. 96. 20, 30, 31, 33 and 35; Vi. IV. 13. 10, 29-39, 77.

प्रसेनजित्
Prasenajit  (I)--a son of Viśvasāhvan, and father of Takṣaka. Bhā. IX. 12. 7-8.

प्रसेनजित्
Prasenajit  (II)--a son of Lāngala and father of Kṣudraka. Bhā. IX. 12. 14.

प्रसेनजित्
Prasenajit  (III)--a son of Siddhārtha. M. 271. 13.

प्रसेनजित्
Prasenajit  (IV)--a son of Haimavatī (Kṛśāśva-Vi. P.) and father of Yuvanāśva. Vā. 88. 64; Vi. IV. 2. 47-8; Br. III. 63. 66.

प्रसेनजित्
Prasenajit  (V)--a son of Rāhula. Father of Kṣudraka. Vā. 99. 289; Vi. IV. 22. 8-9.

प्रसृति
Prasṛti --one of the four sons of Svārociṣa Manu. M. 9. 7. 

प्रस्कण्व
Praskaṇva --a Brahmana line from Medhātithi. Bhā. IX. 20. 7.

प्रस्कन्द
Praskanda --a class of Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 380.

प्रस्ताव
Prastāva --a son of Udgītha, married Niyutsā, and father of Vibhu. Bhā. V. 15. 6.

प्रस्तोता
Prastotā --one of the 16 Ṛtviks for Yajña; issued forth from Nārāyaṇa. M. 167. 8.

प्रस्थ
Prastha --a measure of capacity. Bhā. III. 11. 9; Br. IV. 1. 212; Vā. 100. 215.

प्रस्थल
Prasthala --a son of Tāmasa Manu. Br. II. 36. 49.

प्रस्थल
Prasthalas --a tribe: a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 50; Vā. 45. 119; M. 144. 43.

प्रस्थावि
Prasthāvi --a son of Udgītha. Br. II. 14. 67.

प्रहर
Prahara --a measure of time. Bhā. III. 11. 8.

प्रहरण
Praharaṇa --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Bhadrā. Bhā. X. 61. 17.

प्रहस्त
Prahasta  (I)--a Rākṣasa who was killed in the Lankā war. Bhā. IX. 10. 18. 

प्रहस्त
Prahasta  (II)--a son of Puṣpotkaṭa and Viśravas. Br. III. 8. 55; Vā. 70. 49.

प्रहारि
Prahāri --a son of Supratīka the elephant. Br. III. 7. 341.

प्रहासक
Prahāsaka --a son of Khaśa and a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 134; Vā. 69. 166.

प्रहेति
Praheti --a partisan of Vṛtra: took part in the Devāsura war between Bali and Indra and fought with Mitra; 1) Bhā. VI. 10. 20; VIII. 10. 20 and 28. the Rākṣasa presiding over the month of Mādhava; 2) Ib XII. 11. 34. a son of Yātudhāna and father of Mālyavan and others: a Rākṣasa in the Vaidyuta hill; 3) Br. II. 18. 16; 23. 4; III. 7. 89 and 91. with the sun in the spring; 4) Vā. 52. 5; Vi. II. 10. 5. father of Puloma. 5) Ib. II. 10. 5; Vā. 69. 127.

प्रह्रादि
Prahrādi --a wife of Viśvakarman. Vā. 84. 19.

प्रह्लाद
Prahlāda  (I)--(also Prahrāda): son of Hiraṇyakaśipu and Kayādhu, a dānavī; 1) Bhā. VI. 18. 12, 13. VII. 1. 41; Br. III. 5. 33; 8. 6; M. 6. 9; Vā. 67. 70; Vi. I. 15. 142. a devotee and attendant of Hari; of Narasimha and Kṛṣṇa in Harivarṣa, 2) Bhā. I. 3. 11; 12. 25; IV. 21. 29; V. 18. 7; VI. 18. 10, 16; VII. 1. 41-43; X. 39. 54; 63. 47-9; Vi. I. 15. 143-52. Lord of the Daityas and Dānavas; 2a) M. 8. 5; Vā. 70. 6. most righteous of Hiraṇyakaśipu's sons, a Mahābhāgavata and a Mahātma, 3) Bhā. VII. 4. 30-43. Dattātreya was a tutor: Saṇḍa and Marka, sons of Śukra, were his tutors to teach him kingly policy and Trivarga; 4) Ib. VII. 5. 1-3. served as calf for the Asuras to milk liquor from the earth; 5) Ib. IV. 18. 16. one of the twelve, who knew the dharma ordained by Hari; 6) Ib. VI. 3. 20. at the repeated tests of his father he spoke of the nine ways of devotion to Hari; was ordered to be killed, by being trodden by elephants, or to be done to death by poison, fire or water; all these were of no avail; he was then bound by noose; Prahlāda once lectured to his playmates and classmates on the importance of devo tion to Hari even from childhood as it is rare to be born a man, and even as a man one half of the life is wasted in sleep and one quarter in old age; once one got into the groove of samsāra it was not possible to get out of it; so he asked them to aim at knowledge following the pure Bhāgavata Dharma; asked by the Daitya boys how and when he got that knowledge, he narrated how when his father went out to Mandara for penance, his mother was taken captive by Indra who set her at liberty on the advice of Nārada, who kept her in custody until his father's return. As she was pregnant she prayed to the sage for the welfare of the child in the womb; thus he earned the grace of Nārada. He therefore looked upon ātman as the only thing eternal and all other things unreal; to attain Hari there were several ways, such as listening to his stories, or singing his praise; samsāra and other objects of desire were to be discarded and anybody of any caste or creed could attain salvation by worshipping Hari; when this was reported to his father by the tutor, Prahlāda was sent for and threatened with death if he persisted in his devotion to Hari. Prahlāda was defiant in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu; found in Narasimha the Lord Vāsudeva and spoke to those in the sabhā, but in vain; taking up his sword Hiraṇyakaśipu asked him to show Hari at the post near by which he knocked with his fist; out came Narasimha and destroyed Hiraṇyakaśipu in the midst of portents; universal rejoicing and praise of Hari; the Gods found Narasimha still raging in anger and requested Prahlāda to praise Him; his praise; pleased, the Lord prompted him to ask for boons; Prahlāda said that desires were the seeds of samsāra and therefore he did not want them; he only wanted to be ever devoted to him; Narasimha asked him to be king and at the same time be devoted to him; and when the time came for him he could cast off his body and get himself merged into Hari; then Prahlāda requested for the pardon and purification of his father which were granted; after the funeral ceremonies of his father, Prahlāda  became king; then he worshipped Brahmā, Śiva and other Gods who all blessed him; obliged to Viṣṇu; 7) Ib. VII. 5. 5-50; chh. 6 to 9 (whole) 10 1-24, 32-4; IV. 21. 29 and 47; M. 161. 79; 162. 2. father of Āyuṣmān, Śibi, Bāṣkala and Virocana; 8) Bhā. VI. 18. 15, 16; M. 6. 9. Indra afraid of; 9) Bhā. IX. 17. 14. a boon to Prahlāda not to kill any of his race; 10) Ib. X. 63. 47. praise of by Bali who belonged to his family; arrived when Bali bound by ropes was addressing Hari; and was bowed to by him; addressed Hari; Kṛṣṇa who had promised Prahlāda not to slay princes of his line allowed Bāṇa to escape; blessings to Bali; 11) Ib. VIII. 22. 8, 12-14, 16-17, X. 63, 47-9; VIII. 15. 6-7. his request to Hari before leaving for Sutala; left Sutala or the great cave; attained final release by satsanga. 12) Ib. VIII. 23. 6-8, 11-12; Br. II. 20. 25. Parīkṣit compared to for his pure devotion; 13) Bhā. I. 12. 25; Br. III. 34. 39. Prahlāda compared to the moon shining in the sky. 14) Bhā. VIII. 19. 4. One of the three Indras of the Dānavas and Asuras; 15) Br. III. 67. 88; 72. 79; 73. 41-2; M. 8. 5; 47. 77. fought for 300 years with Indra, but was finally defeated by Raji son of Āyu; defeated by Indra in the churning of the ocean for nector (an avatār of Viṣṇu); 16) Ib. 24. 38-42; 47. 48. duration of rule, as long as that of Bali; 17) Ib. 47. 58. deceived by Bṛhaspati begged excuse of Śukra; 18) Ib. 47. 207, 210. Brahmā was purohita to God incarnate, 19) Ib. 47. 236. made the 16 gifts, 20) Ib. 274. 12. asked by Bali why the Asuras lost their effulgence Prahlāda found out by Yoga the Lord in the womb of Aditi and predicted evil to the Asuras; Bali poohpoohed and spoke of his prowess. Prahlāda predicetd that he would be ruined with his kingdom for having insulted the Lord. 21) Ib. 245. 1-50. Indra of the Asuras 22) Va. 92. 83; of the Vitalam; 23) Ib. 50. 25. Maitreya's question on the career of; 24) Vi. I. ch. 16; tormented by his father for thinking of God Viṣṇu in different ways; 25) Ib. I. ch. 17; was administered poison and other means to kill him; Śambara's hand in; 26) Ib. I. chh. 18-19. his father killed by Narasimha 27) Ib. I. ch. 20. becomes the lord (Indra) of the Daityas, and Dānavas. 28) Ib. I. 21. 14; 22. 4; IV. 9. 8. 

प्रह्लाद
Prahl(r)āda  (II)--a Kādraveya Nāga. Br. III. 7. 36; Vā. 69. 73.

प्रह्रादि
Prahrādi --a wife of Tvaṣṭa and sister of Virocana; mother of Triśiras. Br. III. 59. 19.

प्राकाम्यम्
Prākāmyam --an Uttama siddhi; 1) Br. IV. 19. 5; 36. 51: 44. 108. a yogaiśvarya. 2) Vā. 13. 3, 14.

प्राकृतसर्ग
Prākṛtasarga --the creation of mahat, bhūta and aindriyaka; 1) Vā. 6. 62; Vi. VI. 2. 40. eight prakṛtis covering this aṇḍa at the time of creation. 2) Vā. 4. 90; Vi. VI. 3. 1; 4. 11, 30.

प्राकृतिक
Prākṛtika --the name of Pralaya. Bhā. XII. 4. 5-6. Vā. 104. 110.

प्राक्सती
Prāksatī --is Bhavānī. Br. III. 9. 1.

प्रागायण
Prāgāyaṇas --Kaśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 6.

प्राग्ज्योतिष
Prāgjyotiṣas --an eastern tribe. M. 114. 45. Br. II. 16. 54. 

प्रागियोतिषपुर
Prāgiyotiṣapura (c) --an eastern kingdom; the city of of Naraka surrounded by nooses (Paśās); entered by Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā; its fortress pulled down; invited by its citizens, Kṛṣṇa entered the city and found Maṇiparvata and the umbrella of Varuṇa there; then entered the palace; was left by Kṛṣṇa. M. 163. 81; Bhā. X. 59. 2-5; 22 [1-3], 32; [65(v)1]; Vi. V. 29. 8, 14, 16-7.

प्राग्देश
Prāgdeśa --a country noted for horses. Br. IV. 16. 18.

प्राङ्मुख
Prāṅmukha --a R. sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 65.

प्राचीत्वत
Prācītvata --son of Janamejaya made the Prācī (east) direction. M. 49. 1.

प्राचीनगर्भ
Prācīnagarbha --a son of Sṛṣti (Puṣṭi-Vā. P.) and Chāyā; wife Suvarcā and son Udāradhi (dhīya-Vā. P.). Br. II. 36. 98-100; Vā. 62. 83, 85.

प्राचीनबर्हिस्
Prācīnabarhis --(Barhiṣad); a son of Havirdhāna and Dhiṣaṇā; a Prajāpati and Ekarāṭ, etc.; married Sāmudrī (Savarṇā), daughter of the ocean (Samudra) of the same caste; had ten sons named Prācetasas, all versed in the Dhanurveda; performed tapas for 10,000 years when even the wind could not blow; out of their anger came fire and burnt down trees, etc.; taking soma; Drumakṣaya represented their case to these Pracetasas and offered their daughter Mārīṣā in marriage to them; their son was Dakṣa; 1) Bhā. VI. 4. 4; Br. II. 13. 39, 69; 30. 40; 37. 24-41; M. 4. 46-7; Vā. 63. 23-25; Vi. I. 14. 4-7. knew the power of Viṣṇu's yoga; 2) Bhā. II. 7. 43; IV. 24. 13. a Rājaṛsi; 3) Vā. 57. 122. it was he, who made the kuśa  grass rest eastward and earned the name, Prācīnabarhis; always devoted to yajña. 4) Bhā. II. 7. 43; IV. 24. 13; Vi. I. 14. 2-4.

प्राचीनबर्हिष
Prācīnabarhiṣas --the ten sons of Sāmudri, also known as Pracetasas versed in Dhanurveda. Vā. 30. 36.

प्राचीनयोग
Prācīnayoga --a disciple of Śringiputra; author of a Samhita. His son was a pupil of Kauthuma. Vā. 61. 40; Br. II. 35. 45-6.

प्राचीनयोगपुत्र
Prācīnayogaputra --a Kauthuma Śākhā. Vā. 61. 42.

प्राचीन्वन्
Prācīnvan --a son of Janamejaya and father of Pravīra. Bhā. IX. 20. 2.

प्राचीसरस्वती
Prācīsarasvatī --the east Sarasvatī, the place where the Gandharva, Citraratha got his redemption after his bath. Bhā. VI. 8. 40.

प्राचीसरस्वती
Prācīsarasvatī tīrtha --in Gayā; bath and offer of evening prayers lead one to Viṣṇuloka. Vā. 112. 23.

प्राचेतस
Prācetasa --the sage who revealed the previous birth of king Puṣpavāhana to him. M. 100. 7; Vā. 62. 72.

प्राचेतस
Prācetasas --(see Pracetasas); the surname of the ten sons of Prācīnabarhis and Śatadrutī; their history; performed tapas as directed by Rudra for 10,000 years. Hari revealed himself before them; entrusting their house to their  son, Dakṣa and following Nārada's precepts attained mokṣa; when they rose from the sea they saw the earth covered with trees; 1) Bhā. IV. 24. 13-18; 25. 2; chh. 30 and 31; IX. 23. 15-16. Vi. I. 14. 6. wife Mārīṣā, the daughter of plants given in marriage by Soma, king of plants, became the mother of Dakṣa. 2) Bhā. VI. 4. 4-5; Vi. I. 15. 1-10, 71-4. Father ordered them to worship Govinda and increase the world's population. The prayer was granted by Govinda. Burnt down trees and uprooted them as they were hindrances to the growth of population. 3) Vi. I. 14. 10-48.

प्राचेय
Prāceyas --Kaśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 8.

प्राच्य
Prācya --a Sāmaga. Vā. 99. 191.

प्राच्यसाम
Prācyasāmas --of six Samhitas, attributed to Kṛta. Bhā. IX. 21. 28-9; Br. III. 63. 207. M. 49. 76.

प्राच्यसामग
Prācyasāmagas --disciples of Hiraṇyanābha. Vi. III. 6. 5-24; IV. 19. 52.

प्राच्य
Prācyas --a tribe. Vā. 58. 81.

प्राजक
Prājaka --the driver of vehicles; if he is unskilled, for injury caused by him, his master will be punished; if skilled, he himself will be punished. M. 227. 95-6.

प्राजापत्य
Prājāpatya  (I)--a sacrifice which Yudhiṣṭhira performed as a preparation to cast off his mortal body. Bhā. I. 15. 39; III. 12. 42; Vā. 81. 3. 

प्राजापत्य
Prājāpatya  (II)--a muhūrta of the day and the night; 1) Br. III. 3. 40, 42; Vā. 61. 75; 66. 41. in the month of Puṣya, the eighth day in the dark half of the month; 2) Ib. 66. 43. the tenth gāndhara grāmika. 3) Ib. 86. 43.

प्राजापत्य
Prājāpatya  (III)--a form of marriage; others are Brahmā, Daivata, Ārṣa, Āsura, Gāndharva, Rākṣasa and Paiśāca. Vi. III. 10. 24.

प्राजापत्यम्
Prājāpatyam (vratam) --the performance of the vow leads to the world of Śaṅkara. M. 101. 66.

प्रागियोतिष
Prāgiyotiṣas --a Janapada of the east. Vā. 45. 123.

प्राड्विवाक
Prāḍvivāka --a judge, to be banished for miscarriage of justice. M. 227. 160-1.

प्राण
Prāṇa  (I)--a son of Vidhātri and Niyatī (Āyati-Br. P.). His wife was Puṇḍarīkā and Dyutimān was his son. Bhā. IV. 1. 44-45; Br. II. 11. 6-9, 40.

प्राण
Prāṇa  (II)--a Vasu and a son of Dharma; married Ūrjasvatī. Father of Saha and two other sons. Bhā. VI. 6. 11-12; Vi. I. 15. 113.

प्राण
Prāṇa  (III)--a Bhārgava and a sage of the Svārociṣa epoch. Br. II. 36. 17; M. 9. 8. 

प्राण
Prāṇa  (IV)--a son of Dhara; 1) M. 5. 24. a Sādhya. 2) Ib. 203. 11; Br. III. 3. 16.

प्राण
Prāṇa  (V)--a son of Angiras; 1) M. 196. 2; Vā. 65. 105. a Sādhya; 2) Ib. 66. 15. a Tuṣita; 3) Br. III. 3. 19; Vā. 66. 18. an Ajitadeva. 4) Ib. 67. 34.

प्राण
Prāṇa  (VI)--the antarātma; it is annam or food; annam is Brahmā, etc.; from this grows creatures. (cf. Upaniṣad; also Yajur Veda); 1) Vā. 15. 14. one of the Vāyus which determine the karma of people; 2) Ib. 21. 47; 31. 41. is jīva. 3) Ib. 102. 101.

प्राण
Prāṇa  (VII)--a son of Dhātṛ and father of Dyutimat. V. I. 10. 4-5.

प्राण
Prāṇa  (VIII)--one of the seven seers of the Svārociṣa epoch. Vi. III. 1. 11.

प्राणरोध
Prāṇarodha  (I)--One of the 28 hells where those who indulge in the hunting and killing of animals are punished. Bhā. V. 26. 7 and 24.

प्राणरोध
Prāṇarodha  (II)--control of the breath, one of the aids to deep meditation. Vā. 104. 24.

प्राणाचार्य
Prāṇācārya --the purohita to be consulted by the king. M. 215. 35.

प्राणायाम
Prāṇāyāma  (I)--a sādhana for yoga. Vi. I. 22. 45; V. 10. 15; VI. 7. 40. 

प्राणायाम
Prāṇāyāma  (II)--three-fold: its utility; a mode of penance. 1) Bhā. IV. 8. 44; 23. 8; Br. III. 22. 74; M. 227. 37. one of the constituents of Maheśvara yoga; ety., the control of Prāṇa or wind; three ways are distinguished; mandha, madhya and uttama; the Pramāṇa of Prāṇāyāma is 12 mātras; manda is of 12 mātras as also udghātā; madhyama is twice udghātā or 24 mātras; uttama is three udghātās or 36 mātras; uttama produces sveda, kampa and viṣāda; Prāṇa is like the cruel wild animal which if tamed becomes soft; if approached direct by yoga, prāṇa becomes disciplined in course of time; having controlled the vāyu one can live as he pleases; there is no sin in his body; Prāṇāyāma is equal to all penances and fruits of yajña; all doṣas become burnt as it were by this practice. 2) Vā. 10. 78-92. fruits of; śānti, praśānti, dīpti, and Prasāda; 3) Ib. 11. 4; 18. 17-19. practice of:--draw in aum, pray to sun and moon, and sit in svastika or padma posture; halfshut eyes; look at the tip of the nose a little raising the head, neck and the body; hence tamas and rajas look on satva; attaining this yoga, pratyāhāra to be begun, mātra--nimiṣonmeṣa--12 mātras. 4) Ib. 11. 12-29; 22. 19; 110. 13.

प्राणिन
Prāṇinas --the Saptāngas of kings; wife, purohita, senāni, charioteer, minister, horse and elephant. Br. II. 29. 76; Vā. 57. 70.

प्रात
Prāta  (I)--a son of Puṣpārṇa and Prabhā. Bhā. IV. 13. 13.

प्रात
Prāta  (II)--morning; born of Dhātri and Rākā. Bhā. VI. 18. 3.

प्रात
Prāta  (III)--a Rākṣasa with the sun in Āvaṇi and Puraṭṭaśi (Sep-Oct.). Vā. 52. 10. 

प्रातस्तन
Prātastana --when the sun passes three muhūrtas commencing with the Lekha, that time is the fifth part of the day; 1) Vā. 50. 170. the first six nālikas. 2) Ib. 56. 46.

प्रातिमेधी
Prātimedhī --a Brahmavādini. Br. II. 33. 19.

प्रादेश
Prādeśa --eight angulas by the index finger, tāla by the middle finger and gokarṇa by the third finger and vidasti by the little finger; 1) Vā. 8. 103. ten angula parvas. 2) Br. II. 7. 96.

प्राद्योत
Prādyotas --five kings from Pradyota to Nandivardhana; ruled for 138 years. Br. III. 74. 127.

प्राधानिकी
Prādhānikī --creation from Pradhāna or māyā (Sānkhya). Vā. 102. 133.

प्रान्तदेश
Prāntadeśa --noted for horses. Br. IV. 16. 18.

प्रापण
Prāpaṇa --an Asura. Br. III. 6. 7.

प्राप्ति
Prāpti  (I)--a daughter of Jarāsandha and queen of Kamsa. After Kamsa's death she went to her father's house and reported the circumstance under which he was killed. Bhā. X. 50. 1-2; Vi. V. 22. 1.

प्राप्ति
Prāpti  (II)--a siddhi devi. Br. IV. 19. 4; 44. 108. 

प्राप्ति
Prāpti  (III)--one of the eight yogaiśvaryas Vā. 13. 3, 13.

प्राप्ति
Prāpti  (IV)--one of the ten branches of the Supāra group of Devas. Vā. 100. 94.

प्रांशु
Prāṃśu  (I)--a son of Vatsaprīti and father of Pramati (Prajāpati-Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 2. 24; Vi. IV. 1. 21-2.

प्रांशु
Prāṃśu  (II)--one of the nine sons of Vaivasvata Manu. Br. II. 38. 31; III. 60. 3; Vā. 85. 4. Vi. IV. 1. 7.

प्रांशु
Prāṃśu  (III)--a son of Bhalandana; had a son Prajāni who was taken to Heaven by Samvarta. Br. III. 61. 4; Vā. 86. 3-4.

प्रायश्चित्त
Prāyaścitta --expiation: of no use to one not devoted to Nārāyaṇa. Bhā. VI. 1. 11, 18.

प्रायोपवेश
Prāyopaveśa --vow of fasting unto death pratcised by Parīkṣit contemplating on Viṣṇu; 1) Bhā I. 19. 7. undertaken by Sukarmā when Indra killed his pupils. 2) Vā. 61. 29. Br. II. 35. 34.

प्रालेयशैलम्
Prāleyaśailam (Prāleyādri) --the Himālayas, Lord of the hills. M. 86. 25, 57, 59.

प्रावरक
Prāvaraka --a varṣa of Krauñcadvīpa. Vā. 49. 67. 

प्रावहि
Prāvahi --Pravara Angiras. M. 196. 13.

प्रावेपि
Prāvepi --Pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 16.

प्रावृषेया
Prāvṛṣeyās --an eastern country. Br. II. 16. 54.

प्राश्निक
Prāśnika --Brahmā as, in the fights of Madhu and Kaitabha and Viṣṇu and Jiṣṇu. Vā. 25. 41.

प्रासाद
Prāsāda--ety.  that which pleases the mind; generally a palace. Vā. 8. 127; 35. 4; 39. 36; 40. 9.

प्रासाद
Prāsādas --of Viṣṇu; offering of bali to deities as a preliminary to building; varieties of buildings descrbied--Meru, Mandara, Kailāśa, Kumbha, Simha, Mṛga, Vimāna, Chandaka, Catusra, Aṣṭāsra, Ṣoḍaśāsra, Vartula, Sarvabhadraka, Simhāsya, Nandana, Nandivardhanaka, Hamsa, Vṛṣa, Suvarṇeśa, Padmaka and Samudraka; with toraṇas and archways of wood, stone or brick. Br. IV. 7. 28; M. chh. 268-9.

प्रासेव्य
Prāsevya --a Kaśyapa gotrakara. M. 199. 8.

प्रास्तावि
Prāstāvi --a son of Udgītha. Vi. II. 1. 37.

प्राह्लाद
Prāhlāda --(also Prahlāda) defeated by Indra in war; 1) Vā. 97. 79. was regarded as the Indra of the Asuras; 2) Ib. 97. 90. came after Hiraṇyakaśipu and Bali. 3) Ib. 98. 41, 81. 

प्रियकप्रिया
Priyakapriyā --a name of Lalitā; Mantrinī. Br. IV. 17. 34, 43; 31. 105.

प्रियनिश्चय
Priyaniścaya --a Bhavya god. Br. II. 36. 72.

प्रियभृत्य
Priyabhṛtya --a son of Tāmasa Manu. Br. II. 36. 49; Vā. 62. 43.

प्रियमुख्य
Priyamukhya --an Apsaras. Vā. 69. 4.

प्रियमेध
Priyamedha --a Brahmana belonging to the Ajamīḍha family. Bhā. IX. 21. 21.

प्रियव्रत
Priyavrata  (I)--one of the two sons of Svāyambhuva Manu and an amśa of Vasudeva; 1) Bhā. III. 12. 55; 21. 2; IV. 1. 9; XI. 2. 15; IV. 8. 7; M. 4. 34; Vā. 33. 6; 57. 57; Vi. I. 7. 18. married two wives Barhiṣmatī daughter of Viśvakarman and another; had ten sons and a daughter through his first wife; among whom were two sons Āgnidhra and Manu Uttama; through the second wife he had three sons, all rulers of Manvantaras; though a Bhāgavata and devoted to Nārada, in obedience to his father's wishes remained a house-holder and administered his kingdom; three of the ten sons by the first wife Mahāvīra, Kavi and Savana remained bachelors all through life; ruled for eleven arbuda years; possessed superhuman powers; he followed the sun by making seven circuits, determined to make night also day; these seven circuits resulted in the formation of seven seas and seven continents of which his sons became rulers; gave his daughter to Uśanas; following the footsteps of Nārada he classified the land fixing rivers, mountains and forests as boundaries; 2) Bhā. V. 1. (whole); 16. 2; VIII. 1. 23; XI. 2. 15; founder of a glorious line; his descendents; 3) Ib. V. 6. 14; ch. 15 (whole). obliged to Viṣṇu; 4) Ib. IV. 21. 28; 31. 26; Br. II. 14. 6; 29. 63; 30. 39; 36. 65; Vi. III. 1. 24-5. went to heaven by tapas. 5) M. 143. 38; Vi. I. 11. 1. Married the daughter of Kardama and had two  daughters, Samrāt and Kukṣī besides ten sons; to this line belong the Manus, Svārociṣa, Uttama, Tāmasa and Raivata. 6) Ib. II. 1. 3-6.

प्रियव्रत
Priyavrata  (II)--a son of Śatarūpā. Br. I. 1. 57; Vā. 62. 59.

प्रियव्रत
Priyavrata  (III)--a son of Vairāja Manu; 1) Br. II. 9. 41; Vā. 1. 66; 10. 16. married Kāmyā; 2) Ib. 28. 28. had ten sons and two daughters. 3) Br. II. 11. 33.

प्रियव्रत
Priyavrata  (IV)--a god of the Ādyā group. Br. II. 36. 69

प्रियव्रत
Priyavrata  (V)--heard the Viṣṇu Purāṇa from Ṛbhu and narrated it to Bhāguri. Vi. VI. 8. 43.

प्रियव्रतान्वय
Priyavratānvayas, --the dynasties of Priyavrata; Svārociṣa, Uttama, Tāmasa, and Raivata Manus. Vā. 62. 56.

प्रिया
Priyā --a daughter of Dakṣa. Vā. 1. 122.

प्रियाकारिणिसर्वाद्या
Priyākāriṇisarvādyā --a Mudrādevī. Br. IV. 44. 114.

प्रीत
Prīta --a Carakādhvaryu. Br. II. 33. 13. 

प्रीति
Prīti  (I)--a Kalā of the moon. Br. IV. 35. 92.

प्रीति
Prīti  (II)--a Kalā of Viṣṇu. Br. IV. 35. 95.

प्रीतिव्रतम्
Prītivratam --a vow in honour of Hari. M. 101. 6.

प्रीती
Prītī  (I)--a wife of the God of Love, the other being Rati; was in her previous birth a courtesan, Anangavati who observed vibhūtidvādaśīvratam. M. 100. 32.

प्रीती
Prītī  (II)--a daughter of Dakṣa and wife of Pulastya; 1) Vā. 10. 27, 31; 28. 22; Vi. I. 7. 25. mother of three sons, Dānāgni, Devabāhu and Atri; 2) Br. II. 9. 52, 55; 11. 26. also son Dattoli (Vi. P.). 3) Vi. I. 10. 9.

प्रीती
Prītī  (III)--a wife of Angirasa. Vi. I. 7. 7.

प्रेतआशौचम्
Preta-āśaucam --death pollution for ten days for Brahmanas, 12 for Kṣatriyas, 15 for Vaiśyas and one month for Śūdras. Vi. III. 13. 18-19.

प्रेतकर्म
Pretakarma --funeral rites described. Vi. III. 13. 7-16.

प्रेतकूट
Pretakūṭa --in Gayā. Vā. 109. 15.

प्रेतपक्ष
Pretapakṣa --mahālaya lasting for fifteen days. Vā. 83. 41.

प्रेतपर्वतम्
Pretaparvatam --in Gayā. Vā. 83. 20; 110. 8 and 9. 

प्रेतयाना
Pretayānā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 19.

प्रेतराज
Pretarāja --is Yama: once he asked a certain merchant to take all his wealth and spend (5/6) of it at Gayā for śrāddha in his name; and (1/6) for himself for doing the Karma; so he did and the Preta got released from the bondage of samsāra. Vā. 112. 15-20; Vi. V. 23. 44.

प्रेतलोकम्
Pretalokam --the world of the dead. Vā. 110. 44.

प्रेतशिला
Pretaśilā --a part of the śilā at Gayā where Piṇḍa is offered to the dead; here is Pretakuṇḍa; 1) Vā. 108. 15, 67. here Pretas receive offering; on the head of Gayā. 2) Ib. 110. 66.

प्रेत
Pretas --spirits harassing children. Bhā. II. 6. 43; 10. 38; VI. 8. 25; X. 6. 27; 63. 11; XI. 10. 28.

प्रेतावासकृतालय
Pretāvāsakṛtālaya --is Śiva: he who finds his abode among the graves. Vā. 30. 141.

प्रौष्ठपद्यष्टका
Prauṣṭhapadyaṣṭakā --the form taken by Acchodāmatsya Gandhī; on the earth she is known as Satyavatī and in the Pitṛloka Aṣṭakā; 1) M. 14. 18-9. the month of Prauṣṭhapada. 2) Ib. 53. 52.

प्लक्ष
Plakṣa  (I)--the lord of forest trees; acted calf for trees to milk the cow-earth; sticks of this tree to be used in ceremonies connected with the Kṛṣṇāṣṭamivratam and the digging of tanks. 2) Ib. 56. 7; 58. 10. ^1 M. 8. 8; 10. 28; 

प्लक्ष
Plakṣa  (II)--a son of Dāruka; an avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 196.

प्लक्ष
Plakṣa  (III)--a continent; a part of Kimpuruṣa equal to Nandana; there is a plakṣa tree here. Vā. 33. 11; 46. 4.

प्लक्षतीर्थम्
Plakṣatīrtham --a sacred tank in Kurukṣetra where played the Apsarasas; and Ūrvaśī was found by Purūravas among them. Vā. 91. 32-3.

प्लक्ष
Plakṣa(dvīpa) --twice as broad as the Jambūdvīpa and thrice its width and in circumference; Agni, the God of fire shines there; its first ruler Idhmajihva divided it among his seven sons after whose names the countries became known; there are several rivers and (seven Vā P.) mountains; people are engaged in sun worship; surrounded by the sea of sugar-cane juice (salt ocean Vā. P.); people here live to an age of 5000 (0) years and enjoy always the felicities of the tretāyuga wealth, health, etc; in its midst is the Plakṣa tree sacred to Śiva. 1) Bhā. V. 1. 32; 20. 1-7; Br. II. 14. 11-15; 19. 1-31, 138; Vā. 49. 1-28. Another version--one of the nine continents, Medhātithi being the first king. Divided it among his seven sons, named as Śantahaya, Śiśira, Sukhadeya, Ānanda, Śiva, Kṣemaka, and Dhruva. Gomeda was one of its seven mountains. The four castes are named Aryaka, Kurarā, Vidiśya and Bhāvina. Viṣṇu resides here as Soma. 2) Vi. II. 1. 12; 2. 5; 4. 2-20.

प्लक्षप्रश्रवण
Plakṣapraśravaṇa --a sacred spot for śrāddha; on the Sarasvatī. Br. III. 13. 69.

प्लवङ्गमातन्गस्
Plavaṅgamātangas --a tribe. M. 114. 44. 

प्लवङ्गव
Plavaṅgava --an eastern country. Br. II. 16. 53.

प्लव
Plavas --ducks born of Śuci. M. 6. 32.

फट्करिणी
Phaṭkariṇī --a Śaktī. Br. IV. 44. 88.

फणिकन्यक
Phaṇikanyakas --Nāgakanyas. Br. IV. 38. 35.

फणिनायक
Phaṇināyaka --Śeṣa. Br. III. 36. 7.

फलमुख
Phalamukha --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 78.

फलव्रतम्
Phalavratam --the observance of the vow leads one to the world of Viṣṇu M. 101. 62.

फलसप्तमी
Phalasaptamī --in the saptamī of the Mārgaśīrṣa month in honour of the Sun God; he who does this goes to the world of Sūrya. M. 76. 1.

फलाहार
Phalāhāra --a Pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 16.

फल्गुतन्त्र
Phalgutantra --a king of Ayodhyā, defeated by Tālajangha: settled in the forest near Aurva's hermitage followed by his pregnant wife. After his death was born the future Sagara in the hermitage. Br. III. 47. 76. 

फल्गुतीर्थम्
Phalgutīrtham --in Gayā: Here resides Gadādhara. Vā. 105. 6, 36; 109. 16, 43; 111. 13-20.

फल्गुनि
Phalguni --the name of an asterism. Vā. 82. 6.

फालमुख
Phālamukha --a brother of Balāhaka and a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 24. 9 and 48.

फाल्गुण
Phālguṇa  (I)--the amāvāsya in the month of, (MarchApril); a Manvantarādi for śrāddha. M. 17. 7.

फाल्गुण
Phālguṇa  (II)--(also Phalguṇa) sacred to Hari; visited by Balarāma. Bhā. VII. 14. 31; X. 79. 18.

फाल्गुण
Phālguṇa  (III)--another name of Arjuna. Vi. V. 37. 2; 38. 35.

फाल्गुनि
Phālguni  (I)--sacred to the planet Guru: śrāddha performed that day, gives one beauty of form. Br. II. 24. 132; III. 18. 6; Vā. 23. 107; 53. 107.

फाल्गुनि
Phālguni  (II)--the month of, good for the gift of the Liṅga Purāṇa; 1) M. 53. 38. Mahādeva to be worshipped in the month of, by the person who observes Kṛṣṇāṣṭamīvrata; 2) Ib. 56. 2. Pancagavya to be taken in this month while observing Saubhāgyaśayanavrata. 3) Ib. 60. 36.

फेनप
Phenapas --a class of seers; 1) Bhā. III. 12. 43. Bhārgava-gotrakāras. 2) M. 195. 21.  Ba and Bha

बक
Baka  (I)--an Asura; a son of Andhaka and brother of Āḍi; 1) M. 156. 12. friend of Kamsa; seized Kṛṣṇa in the guise of a crane; was torn to death. 2) Bhā. X. 2. 1; 11. 48-52; 12. 14; 26. 8; 43. 30; 46. 26.

बक
Baka  (II)--a son of Maṇivara. Vā. 69. 160.

बक
Bakas --sons of Vṛtra and who became followers of Mahendra. Br. III. 6. 36.

बकमुख
Bakamukhas --a Piśāca gaṇa. Vā. 69. 263.

बकव्रतिन्
Bakavratin --one who practises a deceitful vow. M. 95. 30.

बकी
Bakī --sister of Baka, the asura. Bhā. X. 12. 14.

बजुला
Bajulā --a R. from the Sahya hills. Br. II. 16. 34. 

बञ्जुला
Bañjulā  (I)--a R. from the Ṛkṣa hill. Br. II. 16. 31.

बञ्जुला
Bañjulā  (II)--a R. from the Mahendra hill. Br. II. 16. 37.

बटु
Baṭu --a tribe that attained kingship by the efforts of Viśvasphatika. Vi. IV. 24. 62.

बडवा
Baḍavā --a wife of the Sun god; mother of the Aśvins. Bhā. VIII. 13. 9, 10.

बदरि
Badari --āśrama at, sacred to Nara-Nārāyaṇa in Gandhamādana; the place where Hari is said to perform tapas for the welfare of the world; visited by Kṛṣṇa; as directed by Kṛṣṇa on the eve of his departure to Heaven, Uddhava made it his abode; 1) Bhā. III. 4. 4, 22, 32; VII. 11. 6; X. 66[13]; XI. 4. 7; 29. 41, 47; XII. 9. 7; Br. III. 25. 67; Vi. V. 37. 34. Kakudmi spent the evening of his life at that place. 2) Bhā. IX. 3. 36 See Badrikā. Here Mucukunda performed tapas meditating on Hari. 3) Ib. X. 52. 4. See Badariyāśrama. A tīrtha sacred to Ūrvaśī; 4) M. 13. 49. sacred to the Pitṛs; 5) Ib. 22. 73. āśrama where Mitra and Varuṇa performed penance. 6) Ib. 201. 24.

बदरिका
Badarikā --the sages of, visited Dvārakā. Bhā. X. 90. 28[5].

बदरीयाश्रम
Badarīyāśrama --see Badari; 1) Bhā. X. 52. 4. in the the brahmarandhra of the personified Veda. 2) Vā. 104. 78. 

बदरी
Badarī --the name of the dvīpa where Bādarāyaṇa was born. M. 14. 16.

बद्ध
Baddha--samsāra is bandhana;  hence called so. Vā. 102. 76.

बधिरक
Badhiraka --a Mt. which entered the sea for fear of Indra. M. 121. 74.

बध्र्यश्व
Badhryaśva --(also Bandhyaśva) the first son of Mudgala and a Brahmiṣṭha through Indrasenā; his wife Menakā, gave birth to a mithuna, Divodāsa and Ahalyā. Vā. 99. 200-1.

बन्धम्
Bandham --the place of Budha in the maṇḍalam. Vā. 53. 74.

बन्ध
Bandhas --three, Prākṛta, Vaikārika and dakṣiṇa, which have their origin in ignorance. Vā. 102. 59, 60.

बन्धनम्
Bandhanam --jail; escaping from and letting one to do so will be punished; 1) M. 227. 208-10. also bandhasthānam. 2) Ib. 256. 35.

बन्दनरक्षित
Bandanarakṣita --the guardian of prisons. Vā. 101. 154.

बन्धु
Bandhu  (I)--the son of Vegavat and father of Tṛṇabindu. Bhā. IX. 2. 30. 

बन्धु
Bandhu  (II)--a God of one of the ten branches of the Rohītā gaṇa. Br. IV. 1. 85. Vā. 100. 90.

बन्धुपालित
Bandhupālita --son of Kuśāla (Kunāla-Vā. P.) (Maurya)--ruled for 8 years. Br. III. 74. 146. Vā. 99. 333.

बन्धुमन्
Bandhuman  (I)--a son of Kevala and father of Vegavat. Bhā. IX. 2. 30; Br. III. 8. 36; 61. 9; Vā. 86. 14; Vi. IV. 1. 43-4.

बन्धुमन्
Bandhuman  (II)--a son of Bhangakāra and Narā; 1) Br. III. 71. 86-88. killed by Akrūra. ^2 Vā. 96. 85.

बभ्रव
Babhrava --a disciple of Śaunaka; 1) Vā. 61. 53. of Kauśikagotra. 2) Ib. 91. 99.

बभ्रव
Babhravas --Kāśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 7.

बभ्रु
Babhru  (I)--one of the two sons of Druhyu and father of Setu (Ripu-Br. P.) Bhā. IX. 23. 14; Br. III. 74. 7; Vā. 99. 7; Vi. IV. 17. 1-2.

बभ्रु
Babhru  (II)--a son of Romapāda; (Lomapāda-Br. P.) and father of Kṛti. Bhā. IX. 24. 2; Br. III. 70. 38; Vi. IV. 12. 39.

बभ्रु
Babhru  (III)--a disciple of Śunaka (Śaunaka-Br. P., Vi. P.) who taught him a Samhitā. Bhā. XII. 7. 3; Br. II. 35. 60; Vi. III, 6. 12. 

बभ्रु
Babhru  (IV)--a son of Devavṛdha and Gāndhinī; the best among men; righteous and truthful; a Mahāratha of the Sātvatas; through his precept and that of his father, several thousands attained immortality; 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 9-11; Vā. 96. 15; Vi. IV. 13. 3-6, 107; M. 44. 56-60. performed sacrifices and lavished gifts; got the jewel Syamantaka and gave it to Kṛṣṇa, to be returned by the latter. 2) Br. III. 71. 13, 81-2, 96 and 98.

बभ्रु
Babhru  (V)--a son of Sampāti. M. 6. 35.

बभ्रु
Babhru  (VI)--is Akrūra. Vā. 96. 56.

बभ्रु
Babhrus --of Kauśika gotra. Br. III. 66. 71.

बब्रुवाहन
Bab(h)ruvāhana  (I)--a son of Arjuna and Ulūpi, the daughter of the king of Maṇipura; became a putrikāputra. Bhā. IX. 22. 32; Vi. IV. 20. 50.

बभ्रुवाहन
Babhruvāhana  (II)--a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 85.

बरद
Baradas --a tribe to be conquered by Kalki. Br. III. 73. 108.

बर्बर
Barbaras (Barbas) --people of the northern kingdom; a forest tribe; defeated by the Sagaras; 1) Bhā. IX. 8. 5; Br. II. 16. 49, 65; 18. 44; 31. 83; M. 121. 47; 144. 57; Vā. 45. 118; 47. 42; 58. 83; 98. 108. ineligible for śrāddha. 2) M. 16. 16; 121. 43, 45. 

बर्बरि
Barbari --a son of Aṭṭahāsa, an avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 193.

बर्ब
Barbas --(Barbaras) the kingdom of. M. 121. 47; 144. 57.

बर्हनाश्व
Barhanāśva --(Varhanāśva-Br. P.); son of Nikumbha and father of Kṛśāśva. Bhā. IX. 6. 25.

बर्हि
Barhi --the son of Bṛhadrāja and father of Kṛtamjaya. Bhā. IX. 12. 13.

बर्हिकेतु
Barhiketu --a son of Sagara. Br. III. 63. 147; Vā. 88. 149.

बर्हिणद्वीप
Barhiṇadvīpas --a group of islands in the south of Bhāratavarṣa. Vā. 48. 12.

बर्हिपीच्छधर
Barhipīcchadhara --a bunch of peacock's feathers as paraphernalia of a naked ascetic; Viṣṇu-Māyāmoha appeared in this form before the Asuras. Vi. III. 18. 2.

बर्हियोगगदायन
Barhiyogagadāyanas --Kāśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 4.

बर्हिषद्
Barhiṣad  (also Prācīnabarhiṣa)--a son of Havirdhāna; married Śatadrutī, a well accomplished daughter of Samudra under directions from Brahmā; Agni conceived a passion for her as he conceived for Śukī; by Śatadrutī, Barhiṣad had ten sons who were collectively known as Prācetasas; being versed in the Vedic lore he continued to per form Vedic sacrifices always; 1) Bhā. IV. 24. 8-13. Nārada called on him and in imparting Ātmatatva by saying there was no use of killing animals in sacrifices, narrated to him the legend of Purañjana; the interpretation of the legend of Purañjana by Nārada himself and the relation between jīva and paramātma which it conveyed; Nārada's return to Siddhaloka; the sage-king appointed his sons to be in charge of the administration and withdrew for tapas to Kapila's hermitage where he attained mokṣa. 2) Ib. IV. 25. 3-62; chh. 26-29.

बर्हिषद
