बृहस्पति
Bṛhaspati-(Vedhas)  (I)--a son of Angiras by Sunīpā; (also Prajāpati-Vā. P.); a Brahmiṣṭha famous in Svārociṣāntara; a sage of the Svārociṣa epoch, 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 35; 17. 9. 8. M. 192. 10; 196. 5. 19, 24. Vā. 52. 77; 53. 33; 59. 90, 131; 85. 100; 98. 24 and 27. born of Phalguni in Cakṣuṣāntara; a Mantra-Brāhmaṇa; identified with Bhagavān, 2) Bhā. XI. 16. 22; M. 245. 86; 249. 11. lord of Viśravas and Angiras; sister, Yogasiddha, wife of Prabhāsa; wife Tārā who was taken away by Soma; she came back after Śiva's war with him and Brahmā's intervention; father of Kaca and Bharadvāja; 3) Bhā. IX. 14. 4; M. 23. 30, 47; 26. 3; Vā. 65. 103; 70. 4; 76. 1 and 25; Vi. IV. 6. 10. had sexual  intercourse with Mamata (brother's wife), when she was pregnant; cursed the baby in the womb for obstructing the entry of his semen. Bharadvāja was born who was brought up by the Maruts; 4) Bhā. IX. 20. 36-9; M. 48. 33-41; 49. 15. Vi. IV. 19. 16; Vā. 99. 37; 103. 59; 106. 50. appointed Purohita of the Gods and got back to life the Gods killed by the Asuras; 5) Ib. IX. 24. 45; 25. 9. 12; Vā. 2. 19; 3. 4; 38. 44. had faith in Kriyāyoga; 6) Bhā. XI. 27. 2. served as calf for the sages (milked the cowearth-Vā. P.) to milk the Vedic lore from the earth and got the essence of tapas; saciva of Indra; caused illusion for ^7 Ib. IV. 18. 14; M. 10. 17; Vā. 62. 138 and 177. Rajo's sons and got back the place for Indra; 8) Bhā. V. 24. 24; M. 29. 11; Vā. 53. 67; Vi. IV. 9. 17-22. wielded overlordship over Indra and was the cause of his Yogakṣema; 9) Vā. 84. 15; 92. 91. master of Mantras; 10) M. 47. 81. finding Śukra engaged for ten years with Jayanti, Br. took the guise of Śukra and acted as Śukra to the Asuras; when Śukra spoke of the deceit, they would not listen to him and hence were cursed; Bṛhaspati threw off his guise and went to his place; 11) Ib. 47. 181-205. appeared before the Asuras in the guise of Kāvya; 12) Vā. 97. 106, 121. fought with Uśanas or Śukra in the Devāsura war; 13) Bhā VIII. 10. 33. advised Indra besieged by Bali, to abandon the city and await better times 14) Ib. VIII. 15. 28-31. was not accorded due welcome by Indra in his pride and hence Bṛhaspati abandoned the Devas when the Asuras rose up in arms against them; after consulting him on Tāraka's advance, Indra resolved on war; 15) Ib. VI. 7. 79 and 16-19; M. 148. 62-76. blessed Umā with a son; blessed the Deva host in the Tārakāmaya. 16) Ib. 154. 507; 174. 52.

