Brahmakalpa --the period when Brahmā was born. Bhā. II. 8. 28; 10. 46; III. 11. 34.

ब्रह्मकुण्ड
Brahmakuṇḍa --in Brahmakṣetra. Vā. 59. 122; 83. 20; 110. 8.

ब्रह्मक्षेत्र
Brahmakṣetra --a mahātīrtha founded by Brahmā in olden days in Kurukṣetra; famous as the place of origin for the Vāyu Purāṇa: the home of the seven sages. Vā. 59. 106-7; 97. 5.

ब्रह्मगार्ग्य
Brahmagārgya --the Purohita of Vāsudeva. Vā. 98. 94.

ब्रह्मघोष
Brahmaghoṣa --Vedic chanting; 1) M. 256. 8. in connection with the founding of temples. 2) Ib. 264. 34.

ब्रह्मचर्यम्
Brahmacaryam --the disciplined life of celibacy; followed by Kara; 1) M. 25. 23. greatness of; 2) Ib. 175. 33, 36-41; Vā. 49. 138; 56. 69; 67. 27; 104. 23. observers of it at Benares attain salvation. 3) M. 182. 8-11.

ब्रह्मचारि
Brahmacāri --a son of Krodhā and a Devagandharva. Br. III. 6. 39; Vā. 68. 38.

ब्रह्मचारिन्
Brahmacārin --duties of: with a daṇḍa and tuft, bed on the earth over skin, service to Guru, learning and living on alms; 1) Bhā. VII. 12 (whole), XI. 18. 42-3; Br. II. 7. 175; 32. 24; III. 9. 70; M. 40. 2; Vā. 59. 23; Vi. III. 9. 1-7. may remain so throughout life by taking to Vaikhānasa or Parivratāśrama. 2) Ib. III. 10. 14-15. 

ब्रह्मज
Brahmajas --clouds out of the breath of Brahmā; they cause thunder and lightning; by them the earth attains youthhood; chief among them are the Jīmūta which rain from a distance of a Yojana and a half. Vā. 51. 28, 34-7.

ब्रह्मजित्
Brahmajit --a son of Kālanemi. Vā. 67. 80.

ब्रह्मज्योति
Brahmajyoti --(see Vasurdhāma): Vasu, located at Brahmasthānam. Br. II. 12. 25. Vā. 29. 21.

ब्रह्मज्ञानम्
Brahmajñānam --one of the four means of attaining mukti. Vā. 105. 16.

ब्रह्मण
Brahmaṇa --a Kādraveya Nāga. Br. III. 7. 36.

ब्रह्मणपुत्र
Brahmaṇaputras --the sages who were born of Brahmā's heart, ears, eyes, breath etc. Vā. 9. 100-3.

ब्रह्मणस्पति
Brahmaṇaspati --to be worshipped for increase of Brahmavarcas. Bhā. II. 3. 2.

ब्रह्मण्य
Brahmaṇya --eligibility for Pārvaṇaśrāddha. M. 16. 10.

ब्रह्मतन्वि
Brahmatanvi --Pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 15. 

ब्रह्मतीर्थम्
Brahmatīrtham --also Amohakam; 1) M. 191. 104-5. visited by Balarāma; 2) Bhā. X. 78. 19; Br. III. 13. 56. fit for śrāddha. 3) Vā. 77. 55; 111. 26 and 30.

ब्रह्मतुण्डह्रद
Brahmatuṇḍahrada --(Brahmatuṅgahṛda Vā. P.) a sacred tīrtha near Yamunā: Here Vasiṣṭha performed tapas standing like a pillar; 1) Br. III. 13. 73. fit for śrāddha; bathing once here makes a man a Brahmā; there is a tulā (balance) at the place to measure one's righteousness or sins. 2) Vā. 77. 71-3.

ब्रह्मदण्ड
Brahmadaṇḍa --the rod of punishment of the creator; 1) M. 245. 2; 249. 65. the punishment to the Sagaras; they live in hell. 2) Br. III. 53. 45; 54. 8, 25; 56. 35.

ब्रह्मदत्त
Brahmadatta  (I)--the son of Nīpa and Kṛtvī daughter of Śuka; a Yogi; wife Go and son Viṣvaksena; 1) Bhā. IX. 21. 25; M. 15. 10. king of Sālva (s.v.); 2) Bhā. X. 52. 11[8]. killed by Kṛṣṇa. 3) Ib. X. 52 [56(v)8].

ब्रह्मदत्त
Brahmadatta  (II)--the son of Aṇuha and Kīrtimatī. Br. III. 8. 94; 10. 82; 74. 268; M. 49. 57; Vā. 70. 86; 73. 31; 99. 180; Vi. IV. 19. 45-6.

ब्रह्मदत्त
Brahmadatta  (III)--the son of Vibhrāja, the Pāñcāla king; in previous birth Pitṛvarti (s.v.), a son of Kauśika; his queen Sannati, daughter of Devala, being in one of her previous births the cow of Garga, was killed by Kauśika's sons during a famine; was anointed the Pāñcāla king, and his two brothers in his previous birth, became his ministers;  both king and queen once visited the pleasure garden and were taken by surprise at the sight of the love quarrels between two ants who were husband and wife; the wife accused the husband of taking pieces of modaka (sweetmeat) to a neighbouring lady-love, an ant; the husband confessed that it was offered so thinking that she was herself, his own wife and that he would behave more carefully in future; B. understood this as he could follow the language of all insects by divine grace; when Sannati thought that the king laughed at her and took it seriously, he took a vow for seven days and at the sight of Sudaridra, the Brahmana, remembered his past and became a Siddha himself having anointed his son Viśvakṣena on the throne. M. 20. 23-38; 21. 16, 24-35.

ब्रह्मदत्त
Brahmadattas --a royal line of 100 warriors cf. Jātakas: Vāyu P. 376 (Car. Lec. 1918. p. 56). M. 273. 72; Vā. 99. 454.

ब्रह्मदा
Brahmadā --a R; a Mahānadī in Bhāratavarṣa. Vā. 108. 81.

ब्रह्मदानम्
Brahmadānam --the ninth Gandharva Grāmikā. Vā. 86. 43.

ब्रह्मदिनम्
Brahmadinam --the day of Brahmā the creator, at the end of which the Vairājas are born as Brahmavādins. M. 13. 5.

ब्रह्मदुर्ग
Brahmadurga --sages of, visited Dvārakā. Bhā. X. 90. 28[6].

ब्रह्मदेयसुत
Brahmadeyasuta --the son of a family of hereditary Vedic teachers. Vā. 83. 54. 

ब्रह्मधन
Brahmadhana --a son of Brahmadhana. Vā. 69. 125.

ब्रह्मधना
Brahmadhanā  (I)--a daughter of Brahmadāna, married by Śaṇḍa. Br. III. 7. 84-7.

ब्रह्मधना
Brahmadhanā  (II)--married a Yakṣa, one of the two sons of Khaśa; the hair-less. Vā. 69. 123.

ब्रह्मधाता
Brahmadhātā --a Rākṣasa on the Vaidyuta mountain. M. 121. 18.

ब्रह्मधान
Brahmadhāna --one of the three Rākṣasa clans moving about in the day as against the Niśācaras. Br. III. 8. 61.

ब्रह्मन्
Brahman --the nature of, explained; 1) Vā. 61. 107-12. Praṇava form; three-fold nature of Ṛk, Sāma and Yajus; 2) Vi. III. 3. 23-30. with or without form and also para and apara; three-fold bhāvana of Brahman--Brahmā, Karmasamjña and of both; 3) Ib. VI. 7. 47-8. worshipped by Sakarmaka-karman in Puṣkaradvīpa. 4) Bhā. V. 20. 32-3.

ब्रह्मौदनाग्नि
Brahmaudanāgni --Bharata, son of Laukikāgni. Vā. 29. 7.

ब्रह्मपद
Brahmapada --the oneness with the Brahmā; 1) Vā. 101. 91. in Gayā. 2) Ib. 109. 18; 111. 48 and 56. 

ब्रह्मपात
Brahmapāta --the son of Prahetu and a Rākṣasa, living in the Vaibhrājavana on the Sarayu; a follower of Kubera. Vā. 47. 16.

ब्रह्मपार्श्वम्
Brahmapārśvam --the sthāna of Brahmā in the northern portion of the Niṣadha hill; here is the temple of Agni. Vā. 41. 59-61.

ब्रह्मपुरम्
Brahmapuram --Brahmaloka. Vā. 108. 39, 45; 109. 39.

ब्रह्मपुराणम्
Brahmapurāṇam --the Purāṇa containing 10, 000 stanzas. Vā. 104. 6.

ब्रह्मबल
Brahmabala  (I)--a Śrutaṛṣi: a pupil of Devadarśa; 1) Br. II. 33. 10; 35. 57. an Ekārṣeya. 2) M. 200. 6.

ब्रह्मबल
Brahmabala  (II)--a disciple of Vedasparśa. Vā. 61. 51.

ब्रह्मबलि
Brahmabali --a pupil of Vedadarśa. Bhā. XII. 7. 2; Vi. III. 6. 10.

ब्रह्मभागा
Brahmabhāgā --a R. of the Bhadra continent. Vā. 43. 28.

ब्रह्ममालिन
Brahmamālina --a sage. M. 200. 12.

ब्रह्मयज्ञ
Brahmayajña --the sacrifice leading to mokṣa or salvation. Vā. 14. 5. 

ब्रह्मराक्षस
Brahmarākṣasas --a class of demons: Agastyas and Visvāmitras come under this group; 1) Bhā. X. 63. 11; Br. I. 2. 33; III. 7. 100; 8. 59; 41. 29; Vā. 2. 33. live in the Surabhi forest; 2) M. 121. 62. born in the family of Brahmarākṣasis; generally reside in śleṣmātaka trees. 3) Vā. 69. 134-5.

ब्रह्मरात
Brahmarāta --Śuka (s.v.). Bhā. I. 9. 8.

ब्रह्मरात्र
Brahmarātra --the period before dawn when after rāsakrīḍa (s.v.) the Gopis went back to their Vraja. Bhā. X. 33. 39.

ब्रह्मलोक
Brahmaloka --the abode of Brahmā; the eternal world; 1) M. 86. 6; 178. 76; Bhā. IV. 31. 23; XI. 23. 30; Vā. 101. 27. thirteen crores and fifteen niyuktas of yojanas from the Bhūloka and one crore and 500 niyuktas above the Satyaloka; 2) Ib. 61. 87; 101. 112, 220; 65, 141; 106. 20; 108. 12; 111. 33, 49. baths in Agastyesvaram and Devatīrtham lead one to; 3) M. 191. 16, 24. Viraja became Ekārṣṭaka here; 4) Ib. 15. 24. hearing of the legend of Brahmadatta takes one to; 5) Ib. 21. 41. Yayāti went from Devaloka to; 6) Ib. 36. 2. the giver of Hiraṇyagarbha enjoys the world of; 7) Ib. 194. 28; 205. 8; 275. 26. the giver of the Brahmavaivarta Purāṇa on the Full Moon day of Māgha reaches this; 8) Ib. 53. 34-6. residence of the Brahmaṛṣis; 9) Br. II. 35. 97; Vā. 61. 87. fire reduced to ashes would not become fire again; so also the person reaching this loka would not have rebirth: advaita mokṣa; 10) Ib. 7. 32; 21. 70; 22. 20. Brahmā, Purohita at; 11) Ib. 65. 68 and 77. the last place where Vaitātrika Devas went and became one with God during the Pralaya. 12) Br. I. 5. 110; II. 6. 31.

ब्रह्मलौकिक
Brahmalaukikas --Residents of Brahmaloka. Vā. 102. 43; Br. IV. 2. 82. 

ब्रह्मवनम्
Brahmavanam --here is a Brahmavṛkṣa (tree). Vā. 9. 116.

ब्रह्मवन्
Brahmavan --a Mantrakṛt. M. 145. 100.

ब्रह्मवराहम्
Brahmavarāham --an account of, in the Brahmavaivarta. M. 53. 35.

ब्रह्मवादिन्
Brahmavādin --He who realises the one God in the Trinity. Vā. 66. 114; 101. 112.

ब्रह्मवादिन्
Brahmavādins --born of five gotras, Kaśyapa, Vasiṣṭha, Bṛgu, Angiras and Atri. Vā. 61. 81.

ब्रह्मवाह
Brahmavāha --the father of Yājñavalkya. Vā. 60. 41.

ब्रह्मविष्णुशिवात्मिका
Brahmaviṣṇuśivātmikā --is Lalitā. Br. IV. 12. 71.

ब्रह्मवृक्ष
Brahmavṛkṣa --in Brahmaloka; only one tree; the śarira or body is tree and the Jīva is Īśvara. Vā. 9. 116, 118-19.

ब्रह्मवेद
Brahmaveda --(Atharva) personified in the Vārunī Yajña; 1) Br. III. 1. 26-30. with cruel Kṛtyavidhi; with Pratyangarasayoga and with a head with two bodies. 2) Vā. 65. 27.

ब्रह्मवैवर्तपुराण
Brahmavaivartapurāṇa --Brahmavaivartam, one among the Mahāpurāṇas and comprising 18,000 ślokas; deals with  the Rathantarakalpa, Kṛṣṇamāhātmya, and Brahmavarāha; narrated to Nārada by Sāvarṇi; he who gives it on the Full Moon day of the Māgha month reaches Brahmaloka. Bhā. XII. 7. 24; 13. 6; M. 53. 34-6; Vā. 104 4. Vi. III. 6. 22.

ब्रह्मव्रतम्
Brahmavratam --the observance of this vow leads to nirvāṇam. M. 101. 48.

ब्रह्मशिरस्
Brahmaśiras --an astra applied by Aśvatthāma against Arjuna; 1) Bhā. I. 7. 19 and 27; 8. 15; 12. 1. used in the Tāraka war. 2) Br. III. 65. 33.

ब्रह्मशिला
Brahmaśilā --the stone between the Kūrmaśilā and the Piṇḍika of an image. M. 266. 5.

ब्रह्मशीर्षम्
Brahmaśīrṣam --a deadly weapon discharged by Rudra against Soma. M. 23. 43.

ब्रह्मसत्र
Brahmasatra --Brahmā honoured in this Yajña; 1) Vā. 30. 119. in Janaloka. 2) Bhā. X. 87. 9.

ब्रह्मसत्रम्
Brahmasatram --White, eternal, never failing, all pervading (Vedānta); 1) Vā. 101. 86. enjoyed by Devaṛṣis. 2) Br. IV. 2. 84.

ब्रह्मसदन
Brahmasadana --Here Gangā divides into four branches: the abode of Brahmā. Bhā. V. 17. 4-5; Br. IV. 9. 20.

ब्रह्मसरस्
Brahmasaras --a tīrtha sacred to the Piṭrs, and fit for śrāddha. M. 22. 12; Vā. 77. 51. 

ब्रह्मसावर्णि
Brahmasāvarṇi --the tenth Manu; son of Upaśloka; Bhūriṣeṇa and others were the ten sons; Haviṣmat and others were the sages: Śrīmūrti was the name of the manifestation of Hari in this epoch; Śambhu [Śānti (Vi. P.)]
was Indra. Bhā. VII. 13. 21-3. Vi. III. 2. 25-28.

ब्रह्मसुत
Brahmasuta --is Sūta. M. 180. 3.

ब्रह्मसूत्रम्
Brahmasūtram --a part of the place where Linga or image is installed to the left of it. M. 263. 3 and 6.

ब्रह्मस्थानम्
Brahmasthānam --a place in the Vedi where Brahmajyoti agni is located; 1) Vā. 29. 21. here is Viśvavyaca agni. 2) Br. II. 12. 24.

ब्रह्मस्वम्
Brahmasvam --the property of a Brahmana which should not be confiscated by a king; Haihaya paid a penalty for taking Jamadagni's cow. Br. III. 28. 38-50, 68; 29. 1; 30. 2.

ब्रह्महत्ति
Brahmahatti --killing of a Brahmana; will burn even Indra; 1) M. 25. 48; Vā. 50. 221; 61. 22; 101. 153; 105. 13; 108. 55. incurred by Balarāma when he killed Romahaṛṣaṇa and expiated by his destruction of Balvala at the request of the sages; 2) Bhā. X. 78. 23-40. by Vaiśampāyana and by Śiva; 3) Br. II. 35. 16; III. 23. 62. drinking of spirituous liquor equal to; 4) M. 25. 62. released from, by observing Nakṣatrapuruṣam; 5) Ib. 54. 30. released from, by vow of Śubhasaptami; 6) Ib. 80. 12. by offering gṛhabali; 7) Ib. 90. 11; 93. 139. got rid of at Benares; Sīva cut off the fifth head of Brahmā, but expiated the sin by his stay at Benares; 8) Ib. 182. 15; 183. 101. to be got rid of by a bath in the Narmadā; 9) Ib. 186. 56; 192. 16; 227. 215. expiation for; Vaiśampāyana guilty of. 10) Vi. III. 5. 14. 

ब्रह्मह
Brahmaha  (I)--a son of Vṛṣa. Br. III. 6. 34.

ब्रह्मह
Brahmaha  (II)--a son of Viṣa. Vā. 68. 33.

ब्रह्मह
Brahmaha  (III)--a killer of Brahmanas. Vā. 101. 152; 112. 10.

ब्रह्महा
Brahmahā --one who fails to satisfy a woman's love when requested to do so in secret, incurs the sin of; was urged by Yayāti in defence of his marrying Śarmiṣṭhā. M. 32. 33.

ब्रह्मह्रद
Brahmahrada --near Vyāsasaras once visited by Akrūra; Kṛṣṇa took Nārada and the Gopas to this place where they saw the Vedas chanting the praise of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 28. 16-17; Br. III. 13. 52.

ब्रह्मा
Brahmā  (I)--Pitāmaha, (Lokapitāmaha)--appeared on the lotus from the navel of Hari at the end of the Kalpa; the Lord with four faces: origin of five faces connected with his daughter and wife Śatarūpā; 1) Bhā. I. 3. 2; III. 8. 13-16; IX. 1. 8-10; XI. 4. 5; XII. 5. 1; M. 1. 14; 2. 36; 3. 1, 37, 40. Born of Hari's grace: expression of rajas: By Yoga saw the one Puruṣa lying on Śeṣa: Praised Him, who instructed him in the art of creation: nine-fold creation from Prakṛti; created the Vedas and human society: created also a mind-born son to Śambhu who attained Brahmalokam: a second son of his, was Bhuva, who was sent to the mother--earth: the third son Bhūrbhuva and his son became Gopati. From his body was created Gāyatrī, who became his wife: then came Prajāpatis, oceans. etc. 2) Bhā. I. 18. 14. III. 8. 22-32; 9. 1-24, 29-44; 10. 3-6, 8, 13-26; 12. 37-56.  Known for impartiality, Parīkṣit compared to him; 3) M. 171. 8-14, 17, 21; 183. 84. obliged to Viṣṇu; 4) Bhā. III. 12. 23. knew the dharma of Hari; a Parameṣṭhin; 5) Ib. IV. 21. 29; 29. 42. resident at Gayā and guards Benares; 6) Ib. VI. 3. 20. his golden city being in Meru; 7) Ib. IV. 8. 20. his curses and blessings moderate. 8) M. 22. 4; 184. 28. A day of, is a thousand cycles of the 4 yugas; Pralaya, the night of Brahmā; period of his life is dvīparārdha. All the fourteen Manus flourish during his day. 9) Bhā. V. 16. 28. Author of the Atharva mantras; learnt the Veda from Hari and taught it to Manu; 10) Ib. X. 88. 12. his sons were Marīci and Atri whose son was Soma. The last was made the lord of Brahmanas, stars, etc. Influenced Soma to restore Tārā to Bṛhaspati. Found out that Budha was Soma's son. Punished Soma as a sinful planet for enjoying Tārā. 11) Ib. XII. 4. 2-5; Vi. I. 3. 15-24; IV. 1. 5; VI. 3. 11-12. Made Dakṣa the overlord of the Prajāpatis; 12) Bhā. XI. 14. 3-4; Vi. III. 4. 12. called on Kailāsa. 13) Bhā. IX. 1. 8-10; 14. 2-3, 8, 12 [1]
and 13. XII. 8. 12; M. 23. 10, 44-6. Presented Pṛthu with armour and prevented him from slaying Indra. 14) M. 201. 17; 225. 12; 249. 13, 58. Visited Manu and Priyavrata and addressed her on home life. 15) Bhā. IV. 3. 2. gifts to Māya. 16) Ib. IV. 6. 2. Did not help Durvāsa pursued by the cakra of Viṣṇu; 17) Ib. XI. 13. 16-41. was unable to answer the question of his son, Sanaka and others on the subtlity of yoga; remembered Hari who explained it in the form of a Hamsa. 18) M. 178. 56, 64, 79. Praised Viṣṇu for killing Kālanemi. 19) Bhā. VIII. 5. 18-50; 6. 1-15. Met Hari-Ajita to restore the fortune of Indra; cursed by Durvāsa and his prayer. 20) Ib. X. 87. 9. Performed yajña in Janaloka; 21) Ib. X. 89. 3-4. was displeased at Bhṛgu's behaviour; 22) Ib. VII. 3. 14-38; 4. 2-3; 8. 40; 10. 26-29, 33; M. 161. 17. went with Bhṛgu and Dakṣa to Hiraṇyakaśipu engaged in austerities; granted boons to him and disappeared. Was present at Prahlāda's coronation; 23) Ib. 161. 18-23. when petitioned by the gods to show a way to get rid of Hiraṇyakaśipu, suggested Hari for it. Took the form of a calf, 24) Bhā. VII. 10. 62, 70. when Hari in the guise of a cow went to drink the immortalising fluid in Śrīpura; praised Śiva who burnt the Tripura; 25) M. 133. 52. charioteer of Tripurāri. 26) Bhā. VIII. 21. 1, 3 and 5; 22. 21-3; 23. 24, 26-7. Came to see Vāmana measuring the world with his two steps; washed his feet with waters; and with other Gods worshipped Him with tributes; addressed Vāmana-Hari; with his approval Vāmana was taken to Indra's capital; praised Vāmana's deeds and also Aditi. 27) Ib. X. 1. 17-35; 2. 25-42; 13. 40-64; 14. 1-40.  On an appeal from Mother-Earth that she had to bear a heavy burden of the Asuras, Brahmā went with Śiva to the shore of the milk ocean and eulogised Hari by Puruṣasūkta; they were told of the incarnation of Kṛṣṇa at Vasudeva's residence; encouraged Devakī on the eve of Kṛṣṇa's birth; came to see Hari at Bṛndāvan; was staggered at the potency of his māyā and praised the Lord. 28) Ib. IX. 3. 33-4; X. 52. 15 [3-11]. Suggested to Raivata that Balarāma was a suitable husband for Revatī and asked him to give his daughter in marriage to him; 29) Ib. X. 74. 13. attended the sacrifices of Varuṇa and Yudhiṣṭhira. 30) Ib. XI. 6. 1, 21-27; 7. 1-2. Went with all the Devas to Dvārakā first to remind Kṛṣṇa to go back to his eternal abode; addressed the Lord on the purpose and fulfilment of the avatār. 31) Ib. XII. 8. 12. Wondered at Mārkaṇḍeya's vrata; 32) Ib. XII. 13. 10 and 19. heard the Bhāgavata Purāṇa from Hari. 33) Ib. II. 5. 9 to the end. narrated to Nārada the legend of the creation of the universe; 34) Ib. I. 7. 18. allusion to his fear of Rudra; 35) Br. III. 7. 270; 24. 4. worshipped by Vāli with fire rite.

ब्रह्मा
Brahmā  (II)--a division of the night. Vā. 66. 44.

ब्रह्मा
Brahmā  (III)--son of Brahmadana. Vā. 69. 132. 

ब्रह्मा
Brahmā  (IV)--one of the 16 Ṛtviks for a yajña; issued from the mouth of Nārāyaṇa. M. 167. 7.

ब्रह्मा
Brahmā  (V)--one of the authors on architecture. M. 252. 3.

ब्रह्मा
Brahmā  (VI)--image of; four faces and sitting on a lotus; on the swan; on either side Sāvitrī and Sarasvatī. M. 260. 40; 266. 42; 285. 6.

ब्रह्माख्या
Brahmākhyā --the manifestation of the energy in the Puruṣa. Vā. 66. 93.

ब्रह्माणी
Brahmāṇī --the image of; four faces and four hands with the swan for riding. M. 261. 24.

ब्रह्माण्ड
Brahmāṇḍa --(Purāṇam) one among the Mahāpurāṇas; comprises 12,000 (12, 200 M. P. and 12,100 Vā. P.) ślokas dealing with the future kalpas; narrated by Brahmā; contains a description of Brahmāṇḍa; he who gives it with two yellow woollen garments and a golden cow in the Vyatīpāta attains the merit of performing a thousand Rājasūyas. Bhā. XII. 7. 24; 13. 8. M. 53. 56; Vā. 104. 5; Vi. III. 6. 23.

ब्रह्माण्डम्
Brahmāṇḍam  (I)--the whole universe; above this are mānasa worlds of Somapā-manes. 1) M. 15. 25; 249. 29; 266. 28; 289. 13. Īśvara entered into; 2) Vā. 103. 20-1; 104. was split by Bhaṇḍa. 3) Br. IV. 10. 82.

ब्रह्माण्डम्
Brahmāṇḍam  (II)--a dānam of the image of the universe in gold weighing not less than 20 palas and up-to 1000 according to capacity with 8 guardian elephants, Vedas and Angas, and all the deities beginning from Brahmā; then  worship of the different manifestations of Viṣṇu--Anantaśayana, Pradyumna, Samkarṣaṇa, Aniruddha, Vāsudeva; the giver enjoys in heaven with the heavenly damsels. M. 274. 7.

ब्रह्मापेत
Brahmāpeta --the Rākṣasa presiding over the month of Īṣa; a son of Brahmadāna. Bhā. XII. 11. 43; Br. II. 23. 22; III. 7. 98.

ब्रह्मावर्त
Brahmāvarta  (I)--(c) a kingdom; 1) Bhā. I. 10. 34. the land of Parīkṣit where dharma and satya were practised and yajñas performed; 2) Ib. I. 17. 33. residence of Svāyambhuva Manu, to which he returned after the marriage of his daughter; 3) Ib. III. 21. 25; 22. 26. the land of Manus as also of Pṛthu; the place where the R. Sarasvati flows eastward; 4) Ib. IV. 19. 1. visited by Ṛṣabha. 5) Ib. V. 4. 19; 5. 28.

ब्रह्मावर्त
Brahmāvarta  (II)--a son of Ṛṣabha and Jayantī. Bhā. V. 4. 10.

ब्रह्मावर्त
Brahmāvarta  (III)--a tīrtha sacred to the Pitṛs; near the Dhārātīrtha on the Narmadā; here Brahmā resides always. M. 22. 69; 190. 7-8; 191. 70.

ब्रह्मासनम्
Brahmāsanam --Paraśurāma was sitting in this posture while performing penance. Br. III. 57. 6.

ब्रह्मास्त्रम्
Brahmāstram --in Janaloka; given to Paraśurāma by Śiva; 1) Br. III. 32. 57. employed by Aśvatthāma against Parīkṣit in his mother's womb. 2) Vi. IV. 20. 52.

ब्रह्मिष्ठ
Brahmiṣṭha  (I)--a son of Mudgala. Br. 50. 6.

ब्रह्मिष्ठ
Brahmiṣṭha  (II)--a son of Asita. Vā. 70. 27. 

ब्रह्मेषु
Brahmeṣu(Rukmeṣu) --a king; his dependant, Pṛthurukma. Vā. 95. 29.

ब्रह्मोत्तर
Brahmottaras --a kingdom of the East. M. 121. 50; Vā. 45. 123; 47. 49.

ब्रह्मोदनाग्नि
Brahmodanāgni --the son of Laukika Agni, also known as Bharata; father of Vaiśvānara. Br. II. 12. 8; Vā. 29. 7.

ब्रह्मोपदेशम्
Brahmopadeśam --the initiation ceremony in Upanayana. Br. IV. 8. 4.

ब्रह्मोपेत
Brahmopeta --the Rākṣasa who resides in the sun's chariot during the month of Māgha. Vi. II. 10. 16.

ब्राह्म
Brāhma --a muhūrta, early in the morning of the day. Vā. 66. 40; Br. III. 3. 39; Vi. III. 11. 5.

ब्राह्मकल्प
Brāhmakalpa --when Brahmā was known as Śabdabrahman. Bhā. III. 11. 34.

ब्राह्मण
Brāhmaṇas  (I)--came out from the face of the Puruṣa; Brahmavādins; a portion of Hari's body; 1) Bhā. II. 1. 37; VIII. 5. 41; X. 4. 39; Vi. I. 6. 6, 34. considered to be equal to Gods, spoken so by Viṣṇu; views of Kṛṣṇa on; none equal to their greatness; 2) Bhā. III. 16. 4-11; VII. 14. 42; X. 81. 39, 41; V. 5. 23. an embodiment of the Vedas and deserving of veneration and worship; the mouth of Hari as embodying all the Vedas; disregard to them would result in the defacement of the Vedic teachings and Vedic Gods; 3) Ib. III. 16. 23-4; VIII. 16. 9; X. 64. 32-43; 86. 53-57. characteristics of; by birth a Brāhmaṇa is a guru; to live by studying the Vedas; some devoted  to karma, some to tapas, some to Vedic studies, some to teaching and others to jñāna and yoga; 4) Ib. VII. 11. 21; 15. 1; X. 8. 6; 24. 20; XI. 17. 16. Kṛṣṇa on the need for keeping them contented; 5) Ib. X. 52. 30-34. Kṛṣṇa on their property; however small it should not be touched, but should be considered poison since its enjoyment leads to shortness of life and hell; 6) Ib. X. 64. 32-43. their words always become true; 7) Ib. V. 3. 17. showed to Nābhi Yajñeśa himseslf; 8) Ib. V. 4. 7. helped Ṛṣabha in his administration; 9) Ib. V. 4. 16. Kamsa decided to kill all of them and ordered his men to that effect. 10) Ib. X. 4. 39-45. Prohibited from agriculture, trade, tending of cattle and from selling the Vedas; from taking liquor but may take meat in times of danger. 11) Br. II. 29. 55; III. 15. 45. in Kali, in the service of Śūdras and Mlecchas and become Śivasūlas; 12) Ib. II. 31. 40-50. adopt Śūdra practices. 13) Vā. 58. 41.

ब्राह्मण
Brāhmaṇas  (II)--superior to all castes; anger of, more troublesome than even a venomous serpent and all burning fire and more dreadful than a firearm; for, it results in wholesale destruction; 2) M. 30. 23-25. 30. to honour Brāhmaṇas is useful; to dishonour them is dangerous; 3) Ib. 93. 80. warriors with Pramati god incarnate of Kali; 4) Ib. 114. 12; 144. 53. observe ten day's pollution for father's death; 5) Ib. 18. 2. created from face; 6) Br. I. 5. 108. those who spoke the truth became Brāhmaṇas; teaching, sacrifice, receiving and making of gifts, their chief duties; go to the abode of Brahmā; 7) Ib. II. 7. 155, 161 and 165. can take to Vaiśya and Kṣatriya duties; 8) Vi. III. 8. 22-5, 39. established in the kingdom of Māghada. 9) Ib. IV. 24. 62. ^1 Vā. 27. 19; 30. 232; 45. 83; 54. 111; 59. 141; 100. 246; 101. 5, 352; 104. 13.

ब्राह्मणम्
Brāhmaṇam --a branch of the Vedic literature with ten vidhis; 1) Br. II. 31. 14; 33. 1, 12; 35. 73; Vā. 59. 132-9; 68. 12-14. starts in dvāpara. 2) M. 144. 13. 

ब्राह्मणवाचनम्
Brāhmaṇavācanam --the purificatory ceremonial popularly known as Puṇyāhavācanam done in any auspicious karma; 1) M. 54. 8; 58. 5; 66. 5; 67. 3. preliminary to gṛhabali; 2) Ib. 93. 4. in the course of palace building; 3) Ib. 268. 34. to be uttered in making all the 16 gifts. 4) Ib. 274. 25.

ब्राह्मणाच्छम्सि
Brāhmaṇācchamsi --Vaisvadeva Agni; 1) Br. II. 12. 29. one of the 16 Ṛtviks of yajña. 2) M. 167. 8.

ब्राह्म
Brāhma Purāṇa --also Brāhmam; one of the eighteen Mahāpurāṇas; comprises 10,000 ślokas; 1) Bhā. XII. 7. 23; 13. 4. with 30,000 ślokas; he who writes this and makes a gift of it in the Vaiśāka, Full Moon day, attains Brahmaloka; 2) M. 53. 13; 290. 17. the First Purāṇa. 3) Vi. III. 6. 20.

ब्राह्मपुरेयक
Brāhmapureyakas --Ekārṣeyas. M. 200. 4.

ब्राह्मम्
Brāhmam  (I)--the Kṛtayuga. Vā. 78. 36.

ब्राह्मम्
Brāhmam  (II)--one of the six Darśanas. Vā. 104. 16.

ब्राह्मम्
Brāhmam  (III)--a form of marriage. Vi. III. 10. 24.

ब्राह्मिनीश
Brāhminīśa --a deluge during the reign of Satyavrata of Draviḍadeśa; this was the epoch of the Matsyāvatāra of the Lord. Bhā. VIII. 24. 37. 

ब्राह्मिसिद्धि
Brāhmisiddhi --oneness with the Supreme Being. Vā. 77. 123.

ब्राह्मी
Brāhmī  (I) (Sankhyā)--creatures and worms (1/1000) of sthāvara; (1/1000) of the above result in watery animals. (1/1000) of the above become birds; (1/1000) of birds become four-footed animals; (1/1000) of these become two-footed animals including men; (1/1000) part of these go to heaven; (1/1000) of these attain salvation; others fall into hells. Br. IV. 2. 199-210.

ब्राह्मी
Brāhmī  (II)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 20. 13; 36. 58.

ब्राह्मी
Brāhmī  (III)--a mind-born mother; in the kalpalata gift. M. 179. 9; 286. 6.

ब्राह्मी
Brāhmī  (IV)--a R. of the Ketumālā continent. Vā. 44. 21.

ब्राह्मोविधि
Brāhmovidhi --the Vedic injunction. M. 215. 58.

ब्राह्म्यम्
Brāhmyam --in the Brahmarandhra of the personified Veda. Vā. 104. 81.

भक्ति
Bhakti --selfless devotion; leads one to self-realisation; methods and results of; destroys rajas and tamas qualities; roots out sorrow, illusion and fear; redeems the sinners; 1) Bhā. I. 2. 12-21; 5. 28; 7. 7; VI. 1. 15. superior to karma; 2) Ib. X. 23. 39-50 one of the five means of concentrating the mind on Hari, (i.e.) (1) kāma as in the case of the Gopis; (2) fear and hatred as in the case of Kamsa and Śiśupāla; (3) relationship as in the case of the Vṛṣṇis;  (4) friendship as in the case of Yudhiṣṭhira and (5) devotion as in the case of Nārada; Vena does not come under any of these heads; 3) Ib. VII. 1. 29-31. but nine-fold according to Prahlāda: hearing of Hari, praising of, remembering, serving His holy feet, arcana, prostrating, service, friendship and surrender of self; 4) Ib. VII. 5. 23. women more devout than men. 5) Ib. X. 23. 38, 41-43. Three-fold--uttama as that of Nārada and Śuka: middling as that of Vasiṣṭha, and inferior; 6) Br. III. 34. 37-8; 36. 3. another classification: three-fold, Śāṅkhya, Yoga, and Jñānam; a pure man can meditate on the Supreme Being by means of Pratyāhāra finally leading to the supreme knowledge; 7) M. 183. 49-55. mārga to. 8) Vā. 104. 15.

भक्तियोग
Bhaktiyoga --disinterested devotion: 1) Bhā. XI. 14. 2. of different kinds--tāmasa, rājasa, sātvika, nirguṇa, ātyantika; 2) Ib. III. 29. 7-14. greater than the Veda, tapas, and gifts; purifies even śvapākas; 3) Ib. XI. 14. 20-21; 20. 6, 8, 29 and 33. its relation to Sānkhya Śāstra; 4) Ib. III. 29. 2. recapitulation of. 5) Ib. XI. 29. 8-34.

भक्ष्यक
Bhakṣyakas --a Janapada. Vā. 99. 387.

भग
Bhaga  (I)--a son of Aditi; an Āditya; married Siddhi; father of Mahiman and others; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 39; 18. 2; M. 6. 4; 155. 7; Vā. 66. 66; Vi. I. 15. 131. seized by Nandi; his eyes were pulled out by Vīrabhadra (Rudra) as he made a sign with his eyes to Dakṣa when he insulted Śiva; Śiva ordered him to see with the eye of Mitra; 2) Bhā. IV. 5. 17, 20; 6. 51; 7. 3; Br. II. 24. 33; III. 3. 67. to be worshipped before building a palace. 3) M. 171. 56; 268. 19.

भग
Bhaga  (II)--the name of the sun in the month of Puṣya (Tiṣya) (Hemanta-Vā. P.). Bhā. XII. 11. 42; Br. II. 23. 16; Vā. 52. 16; Vi. II. 10. 4. 

भग
Bhaga  (III)--a muhūrta of the day. Br. III. 3. 40.

भगदत्त
Bhagadatta  (I)--was presented with an elephant (of the Airāvata breed) Supratīka by Kṛṣṇa; 1) Bhā. X. 59. 37. in the army of Duryodhana. 2) Ib. X. 78. [95 (v) 16].

भगदत्त
Bhagadatta  (II)--a King of the Kinṇaras. Vā. 41. 30.

भगनेत्रह
Bhaganetraha --also Bhaganetrahara and Bhaganetrāntaka, an attribute of Śiva. Br. II. 27. 31; Vā. 25. 14; 30. 179, 253.

भगपाद
Bhagapāda --an Ātreya gotrakāra. M. 197. 4.

भगमाला
Bhagamālā --one of the 15 Akṣaradevis, killed Dīrghajihva, a commander of Bhaṇḍa; 1) Br. IV. 19. 57; 25. 94. city of. 2) Ib. IV. 31. 24.

भगमालिनी
Bhagamālinī --a Śakti; a mother. Br. IV. 19. 52; 37. 33; M. 179. 11.

भगवती
Bhagavatī --also Māyā. Br. IV. 6. 53; 12. 42.

भगवत्पदी
Bhagavatpadī --a celestial stream (Gangā) which entered Brahmāṇḍa from outside by its being pierced by the tip of the toe of Trivikrama's left foot; in course of time she reached the celestial region known as Viṣṇupada; held sacred by Dhruva and the seven sages; crossing the region of the  moon she reaches the city of Brahmā; there she divides into four branches and falls into the western and eastern seas. Bhā. V. 17. 1-9.

भगवान्
Bhagavān  (I)--The principal and eternal god;^1 the sum and substance of the three Vedas; Bha.-cherisher and supporter of the universe; Ga,--the leader or creator; Bhaga indicates six properties, dominion, might, glory, splendour, wisdom and detachment; Va, elemental spirit in which all beings exist and which exists in all beings; thus it is the name of Vāsudeva. Vi. VI. 5. 69-79.

भगवान्
Bhagavān  (II)--a Tuṣita God. Br. II. 36. 10.

भगवान्
Bhagavān  (III)--the quality of Bhaga and Sadbhāva. Vā. 5. 36.

भगवान्
Bhagavān  (IV)--one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 5.

भगानन्दा
Bhagānandā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 11.

भगीरथ
Bhagīratha --the son of Dilīpa and father of Śruta (Suhotra Vi. P.); by penance on the banks of the Bindusaras he succeeded in bringing the Ganges; was asked how she was to dispose of the sins of men discharged into her waters; Bhagīratha said that Sādhus and others among whom was Hari would take off the sins from her: was asked to pray to Śiva to check her course; so he prayed to Śiva and it was heard; by this he was able to shake off the sins of his ancestors; 1) Bhā. IX. 9. 2-13 and 16; Br. II. 18. 25; M. 12. 44; 15. 19; 121. 26; Vā. 88. 167; Vi. IV. 4. 35-6. a Rājaṛṣi; went to the forest of the Gaura hills in search of Gangā; 2) Vā. 47. 24. his lust after more territory; 3) Bhā. XII. 3. 10. after him  Gangā became the Bhāgīrathī; so-called after the seventh branch of the Ganges. 4) Br. III. 54. 48-51; 63. 166-8; Vā. 47. 40.

भगीवसु
Bhagīvasu --not to marry with the members of the Vasiṣṭha and Indra Pramati groups. M. 200. 13.

भङ्गकार
Bhaṅgakāra  (I)--An Āndhra chief: wife Narā, daughter of Suyagñā. Father of two sons. Bhangakāra and his sons were killed in battle by Akrūra. Br. III. 71. 87-8.

भङ्गकार
Bhaṅgakāra  (II)--the eldest of the 101 sons of Satrājit (Śakrajit-Vā. P.); his wife was Vratavatī (Dvāravatī-Vā. P.); she gave birth to three daughters, Satyabhāmā, Vratinī and Padmāvatī; these were given in marriage to Kṛṣṇa, killed by Śatadhanvā for the jewel Syamantaka taken from him and handed over it to Akrūra. M. 45. 19-21; Vā. 96. 52-5, and 58. Br. III. 71. 55.

भङ्गकारि
Bhaṅgakāri --an Asura of Bali. M. 245. 31.

भङ्गतीर्थम्
Bhaṅgatīrtham --near the Narmadā. M. 191. 52-3.

भजन
Bhajana --a son of Sātvata. Vi. IV. 13. 1. 

भजमान
Bhajamāna  (I)--(Bhajina) a son of Sātvata: had two sons by one wife and three others by another wife (six sons by two wives Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 24. 6-8; Br. III. 71. 1-3. M. 44. 47; Vi. IV. 13. 1-2.

भजमान
Bhajamāna  (II)--the son of Śūra and father of Śini. Bhā. IX. 24. 26.

भजमान
Bhajamāna  (III)--a son of Satyaka and the daughter of the King of Kāśī; father of a son Viduratha. Br. III. 71. 116; Vā. 96. 115, 135. Bhā. IX. 24. 19.

भजमान
Bhajamāna  (IV)--a son of Andhaka and father of Vidūratha, a great charioteer. M. 44. 61, 77; Vi. IV. 14. 12, 22.

भजमान
Bhajamāna  (V)--a son of Kauśalyā; through his wife Śṛñjayyā, he got two sons, Bāhya and Bāhyaka. Vā. 96. 1, 3.

भजि
Bhaji --a son of Sātvata. Bhā. IX. 24. 6; Br. III. 71. 1.

भजिन
Bhajina --(Bhajamāna): a son of Sātvata and Kauśalyā. M. 44. 47; Vā. 96. 1.

भज्य
Bhajya --a pupil of Bāṣkali. Bhā. XII. 6. 59.

भद्र
Bhadra  (I)--a son of Dakṣiṇā and a Tuṣita God. Bhā. IV. 1. 7-8.

भद्र
Bhadra  (II)--a son of Pauravī and Vasudeva. Bhā. IX. 24. 47. 

भद्र
Bhadra  (III)--a son of Vasudeva and Devakī. Bhā. IX. 24. 54.

भद्र
Bhadra  (IV)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Kālindī; and full of prowess; went with the Vṛṣṇis to Bāṇa's city, Śoṇitapura. Bhā. X. 61. 14; 63. 3.

भद्र
Bhadra  (V)--a kingdom in Madhyadeśa. Br. II. 16. 42.

भद्र
Bhadra  (VI)--a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 48; 18. 46.

भद्र
Bhadra  (VII)--a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 6.

भद्र
Bhadra  (VIII)--an elephant; the vehicle of Bali. Br. III. 7. 328.

भद्र
Bhadra  (IX)--(also Supratīka) a Nāga and a vehicle of Varuṇa (Viṣṇu-Vā. P.). Br. III. 7. 330; Vā. 69. 212, 214.

भद्र
Bhadra  (X)--a son of Jāmbavatī and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 249; Vā. 96. 241.

भद्र
Bhadra  (XI)--a son of Rukmiṇī and Kṛṣṇa. M. 47. 16.

भद्र
Bhadras --the Gods of Uttama epoch. Bhā. VIII. 1. 24.

भद्र
Bhadra(ka)  (I)--a son of Vasumitra and father of Pulinda: ruled for two years. Bhā. XII. 1. 17; Br. III. 74. 152. 

भद्रक
Bhadraka  (II)--a son of Śibi. M. 48. 19.

भद्रक
Bhadrakas --a kingdom after Bhadraka, son of Śibi. M. 48. 20.

भद्रकर
Bhadrakara --(c) a kingdom in the Madhyadeśa. Br. II. 16. 41.

भद्रकर्णिका
Bhadrakarṇikā --a Goddess enshrined at Gokarṇa. M. 13. 30.

भद्रकल्प
Bhadrakalpa --a son of Śaṭha, of the Rohiṇī family. Br. III. 71. 170; Vā. 96. 168.

भद्रकार
Bhadrakāras --a tribe; 1) M. 14. 35. a Janapada. 2) Vā. 45. 110, 116.

भद्रकाली
Bhadrakālī --a name of Yogamāyā; 1) Bhā. X. 2. 11. bestows good on children when propitiated with human sacrifice; when the Goddess found the man sacrificed was a virtuous Brahmana like Bharata she became fiery and cut off the heads of the Vṛṣala chief and his attendants who offered him to her; 2) Ib. V. 9. 12-18. fought with Niśumbha and Śumbha in the Devāsura war; 3) Ib. VIII. 10. 31. worshipped by the Gopīs at the end of their vrata. 4) Ib. X. 22. 5. Lion as her riding animal; having three eyes and a trident: praised by Paraśurāma; 5) Br. III. 39. 33, 44 to 53. came out of the wrath of Umā for the destruction of the Dakṣa's yajña. 6) Vā. 30. 140, 165.

भद्रकालेश्वरम्
Bhadrakāleśvaram --a tīrtha sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 74.

भद्रगुप्त
Bhadragupta --a son of Jāmbavatī and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 249; Vā. 96. 241. 

भद्रगुप्ति
Bhadragupti --a son of Śaṭha, of the Rohiṇī family. Br. III. 71. 169; Vā. 96. 167.

भद्रचारु
Bhadracāru --a son of Rukmiṇī and Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 61. 8; Br. III. 71. 246; M. 47. 16; Vā. 96. 237; Vi. V. 281.

भद्रचीत्र
Bhadracītra --a son of Jāmbavatī and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 249.

भद्रज
Bhadraja --of the Rohiṇī family. Vā. 96. 168.

भद्रतीर्थम्
Bhadratīrtham --a tīrtha sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 50.

भद्रदेव
Bhadradeva --a son of Devakī and Vasudeva, killed by Kamsa. Br. III. 71. 175; Vi. IV. 15. 26-7.

भद्रबाहु
Bhadrabāhu  (I)--a son of Śaṭha, of the Rohiṇī family, Br. III. 71. 170; Vā. 96. 168; Vi. IV. 15. 22.

भद्रबाहु
Bhadrabāhu  (II)--a son of Jāmbavatī and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 250.

भद्रम्
Bhadram --a sacred lake in Meru. M. 113. 46.

भद्रम
Bhadrama --a son of Kali and a cannibal: wife Tāmasīpūtanā. Br. III. 59. 10.

भद्ररथ
Bhadraratha  (I)--a son of Haryaṅga, and father of Bṛhadratha. M. 48. 99; Vā. 99. 109; Vi. IV. 18. 22. 

भद्ररथ
Bhadraratha  (II)--a son of Śaṭha, and of the Rohinī family. Br. III. 71. 170; Vā. 96. 168.

भद्रवती
Bhadravatī  (I)--R. a branch of the Ganges. Br. III. 56. 52.

भद्रवती
Bhadravatī  (II)--wife of Purūdvata (Purudvān-Vā. P.). Br. III. 70. 47; Vā. 95. 47.

भद्रवती
Bhadravatī  (III)--a daughter of Jāmbavatī and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 250.

भद्रवाह
Bhadravāha --(Bhadrabāhu): a son of Vasudeva and Pauravī. Bhā. IX. 24. 47.

भद्रविदेह
Bhadravideha(ka) --a son of Devakī and Vasudeva; killed by Kamsa. M. 46. 13; Vā. 96. 173.

भद्रविद्य
Bhadravidya --of the Rohiṇī family. Vā. 96. 167.

भद्रविन्द
Bhadravinda --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Nāgnajitī. Vi. V. 32. 3.

भद्रविन्द्र
Bhadravindra --a son of Jāmbavatī. Vā. 96. 241.

भद्रविष्ठ
Bhadraviṣṭha --a son of Śaṭha and of the Rohiṇī family. Br. III. 71. 169. 

भद्रवेय
Bhadraveya --He brought down trees and plants to Govardhana to please Rāma. Vā. 45. 114.

भद्रवैशाखी
Bhadravaiśākhī --one of Vasudeva's wives: mother of four sons. Br. III. 71. 161 and 173.

भद्रश्रव
Bhadraśrava --a son of Dharma after whom came the continent of Bhadrāśva; a devout worshipper of Hayagrīva. Bhā. V. 18. 1.

भद्रश्रेण्य
Bhadraśreṇya --the son of Mahismān, a man of great prowess; king of Vārāṇasi, father of Durdama and 99 other sons, all able archers, whom Dīvodāsa slew except Durdama; 1) Vā. 92. 61; 94. 6; Vi. IV. 11. 10. the family was destroyed by Pratardana. 2) Ib. IV. 8. 12.

भद्रसार
Bhadrasāra --a Maurya who ruled for 25 years. Br. III. 74. 145; Vā. 99. 332.

भद्रसीमा
Bhadrasīmā --a R. of the Uttarakuru country. Vā. 45. 25.

भद्रसुन्दरी
Bhadrasundarī --a Goddess enshrined at Vikūṭa. M. 13. 36.

भद्रसेन
Bhadrasena  (I)--a son of Ṛṣabha. Bhā. V. 4. 10.

भद्रसेन
Bhadrasena  (II)--a son of Devakī and Vasudeva killed by Kamsa. Bhā. IX. 24. 54; Br. III. 71. 175; M. 46. 13; Vā. 96. 173; Vi. IV. 15. 26-7. 

भद्रसेन
Bhadrasena  (III)--a playmate of Kṛṣṇa; he carried Vṛṣabha on his back being defeated in a certain game. Bhā. X. 18. 24.

भद्रसेन
Bhadrasena(ka)  (IV)--a king of Kāśī and son of Mahiṣmān: Had a hundred sons whom Divodāsa killed and took the kingdom, leaving a baby son, unhurt (see Bhadraśreṇya). Bhā. IX. 23. 22-3; Br. III. 67. 65-66; 69. 6-7.

भद्रसेनी
Bhadrasenī --the Vaidarbhī queen of Purudvān. M. 44. 45.

भद्रसोमा
Bhadrasomā --R. rises from the Meru, passes through Savitā's forest, Śankhakūṭa, Vṛṣaparvatam, Vatsagiri, Nāgaśaila, Nīlam, Kapiñjalam, Indranīlam, Mahānīlam, Hemaśṛṅgam, Śveta, Sunaga, Śataśṛṅga, Puṣkaram, Dvirājam, Varāhaparvatam Mayūram, Jātudhi, Triśṛṅgam, Maryādaparvatam, Vīrudham and falls into the western ocean. Vā. 42. 61-74.

भद्रा
Bhadrā  (I)--a daughter of Meru (Ghṛtācī) and queen of Bhadrāśva; gave birth to Soma. Bhā. V. 2. 23; Vā. 70. 68. 70.

भद्रा
Bhadrā  (II)--a branch of the Gangā issuing out of the city of Brahmā and descending the Śṛngavan hills, traverses the continent of the Uttarakurus and falls into the north sea. Bhā. V. 17. 5 and 8: Vi. II. 2. 34; 8. 113.

भद्रा
Bhadrā  (III)--alias Kauśalyā: one of Vasudeva's wives; mother of Keśin and three other sons. Bhā. IX. 24. 45, 48; Vā. 96. 160. 171; Vi. IV. 15. 18, 24. 

भद्रा
Bhadrā  (IV)--a daughter of Śrutakīrti of Kekeya; married by Kṛṣṇa with the approval of her brothers Santardana and others; 1) Bhā. X. 58. 56; 61. 17. welcomed to Hastināpura by Draupadī; narrated to Draupadī how she was married to Kṛṣṇa. 2) Ib. X. 71. 42; 83. 12.

भद्रा
Bhadrā  (V)--a wife of Udāradhī. Br. II. 36. 101.

भद्रा
Bhadrā  (VI)--a daughter of Rohiṇī: gave birth to goats and sheep; 1) Br. III. 3. 74-5. brought forth the Gandharvas and Vājins known as Uccaiśrvas. 2) Vā. 66. 72-3.

भद्रा
Bhadrā  (VII)--one of the ten wives of Atri. Br. III. 8. 75.

भद्रा
Bhadrā  (VIII)--a Varṇa Śakti. Br. IV. 32. 13; 44. 59 and 90.

भद्रा
Bhadrā  (IX)--a Goddess enshrined at Bhadreśvara. M. 13. 31.

भद्रा
Bhadrā  (X)--the daughter of Anuhrāda, the daitya; married Rajatanābha, the Yakṣa. Vā. 69. 151.

भद्रा
Bhadrā  (XI)--a wife of Garuḍa. Vā. 69. 328.

भद्र
Bhadras --a continent. Vā. 41. 85. 

भद्राकर
Bhadrākara --the island of Vāyu; to the west of Candradvīpam; people here live to an age of 500 years, and are righteous. Vā. 45. 62-6.

भद्रानदी
Bhadrānadī --R. of the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 18.

भद्रावती
Bhadrāvatī --a daughter of Jāmbavatī. Vā. 96. 241.

भद्राश्व
Bhadrāśva  (I)--a son of Āgnīdhra and lord of Mālyavanta: had ten daughters (apsaras) through Ghṛtācī; 1) Bhā. V. 2. 19; Br. II. 14. 47, 51; III. 8. 74; Vā. 33. 41, 44. 70. 68. placed in charge of the kingdom east of Meru. 2) Vi. II. 1. 17 and 22.

भद्राश्व
Bhadrāśva(m)  (II)--a continent of Mandara hill east of Meru; bounded on one side by Gandhamādana; traversed by the stream Sītā; the capital of Bhadrāśvas, son of Dharma, engaged in the worship of Hayagrīva with due praises; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 10; 17. 6; 18. 1-6; M. 83. 31; 113. 44, 52; Vā. 34. 57; 35. 23; Vi. III. 2. 24. country conquered by Parīkṣit; 2) Bhā. I. 16. 13. people residing here are white in colour and women excell in beauty living for thousands (10,000-Vā. P.) of years; non-injury and truth prevalent here; people here worship Śaṅkara and Gaurī; 3) Br. II. 15. 50, 57-60; Vā. 42. 24; 43. 5-9, 11-38. Viṣṇu in the form of Hayaśiras. 4) Vi. II. 2. 50.

भद्राश्व
Bhadrāśva  (III)--a son of Kuvalayāśva who survived the fire from Dhundhu's mouth. Bhā. IX. 6. 23-24; Br. III. 63. 63. 

भद्राश्व
Bhadrāśva  (IV)--a son of Śaṭha, of the Rohiṇī family. Br. III. 71. 169; Vā. 96. 167; Vi. IV. 15. 22.

भद्राश्व
Bhadrāśva  (V)--a son of Rahmavarca and father of 10 sons through an Apsaras, Ghṛtā (Dhṛtā). M. 49. 4.

भद्राश्व
Bhadrāśva  (VI)--a son of Pṛthu and father of five sons, who were residents of the Pañcāladeśa. M. 50. 2-4.

भद्राश्व
Bhadrāśva  (VII)--one of the three sons of Dhundhumāra. Vā. 88. 61.

भद्रेश्वरम्
Bhadreśvaram --a tīrtha sacred to Bhadrā and the Pitṛs. M. 13. 31; 22. 25, 32.

भय
Bhaya  (I)--a son of Kali and Duruktī. Bhā. IV. 8. 4.

भय
Bhaya  (II)--Lord of the Yavanas: adopted the daughter of Kāla as his sister; his brother was Prajvāra; 1) Bhā. IV. 27. 23 and 30. when attacking the city of Purañjana he captured Purañjana himself; 2) Ib. IV. 28. 22-23. allegorically death; the Yavanas represent mental worries. 3) Ib. IV. 29. 22, 23.

भय
Bhaya  (III)--a son of Droṇa, a Vasu. Bhā. VI. 6. 11.

भय
Bhaya  (IV)--a son of Nikṛti. Br. II. 9. 64; Vā. 10. 39. 

भय
Bhaya  (V)--a son of Tāmasa Manu. Vā. 62. 43.

भया
Bhayā --a Kalā of Rudra. Br. IV. 35. 96.

भयासख
Bhayāsakha --a son of Vasudeva and Sahadevā. Vā. 96. 177.

भरणि
Bharaṇi --a nakṣatra: fit for performing śrāddha. Br. III. 18. 14; Vā. 82. 14.

भरत
Bharata  (I)--(Jaḍa): the eldest of the hundred sons of Ṛṣabha (Nābhi) and Jayantī; was devoted to Nārāyaṇa; 1) Bhā. V. 4. 9; 7. 3; XI. 2. 17. a Mahābhāgavata; married Pāñcajanī, daughter of Viśvarūpa and she gave birth to five sons; was installed on the throne; protected his subjects righteously and performed yajñas by the method of Cāturhotra; having spent a million years thus he divided his property among his sons and placed Sumati on his throne; he left for the hermitage of Pulastya as a hermit and became constant in the worship of Hari; gave up his kingdom and sought refuge in Hari; 2) Ib. V. 5. 28; 7. (whole); X. 60. 41; Vā. 33. 51-3. a sage; 3) Ib. 41. 44. one day when sitting on the bank of the river Cakranadī he saw a deer coming to the river and quenching her thirst; hearing a lion roar near by the deer took a leap when the young one slipped from her womb into the water and the deer herself fell dead; seeing this helpless one of a deer, Bharata loved it and brought it up as his own son; out of strong attachment to it he was born as a deer when he remembered his past life and was full of remorse; gave up his body by falling into the waters; 4) Bhā. V. 8. (whole); Vi. II. chh. 14-16, 20. next he was born as the son of a Brahmana of the Angirasa line and with upanayana the father taught him Vedic literature; on his parents' death his brothers found him mad and unpractical and appointed him to work in the fields; once a certain Vṛṣala chieftain wanted to offer human sacrifice to Bhadrakālī and finding that the victim had escap ed, his attendants took this Jaḍabharata by force for sacrifice; at the point of his being sacrificed, Kālī who knew the Brahmana's spiritual virtue appeared in a ferocious form and cutting off the heads of all, rescued Bharata; 5) Bhā. V. 9. (whole). once on his way to sage Kapila, King Rahūgaṇa felt the need for a palanquin-bearer and seeing Bharata the dull-witted at a distance on the banks of the Ikṣumatī, asked him to bear his palanquin; finding it carried irregularly causing inconvenience to him the haughty king chastised the Brahmana and threatened him with punishment; to this Bharata made a learned reply that all his remarks were true and nothing would harm one who had realised himself; on this the king free from haughtiness, thought that he was a yogin, and perhaps Kapila incognito; so he asked him who he was; Bharata spoke on mind and its eleven courses modified by māyā as obstacles to the dawn of knowledge; he continued to say that what was important was jñāna or knowledge which could be acquired by association with great and detached men; in his own case he got defeated in his purpose by attachment to a deer. 6) Ib. V. chh. 10 and 11. (whole); and 12. 5-16. Bharata described in metaphysical language samsāra as a forest, and the jivas as a company of travelling merchants now meeting a Gandharva and now devils, now gathering wealth and now robbed of it; he then explained the implications of samsāra in plain language and said that the quest after desires and pleasures led one to acquire more karma and sow the seeds for a further cycle of births and deaths; 7) Ib. V. 13. 1-20; 14. 1-41. was succeeded as king by his son Sumati, 8) Ib. V. 15. 1. Manu so-called for sustaining the people; after him the Varṣa came to be known as Bhārata; 9) Ib. V. 4. 9; 7. 3; XI. 2. 17; Br. II. 14. 60-63; Vā. 45. 76; Vi. II. 1, 28, 32-4. desirous of the territory on earth. 10) Bhā. XII. 3. 9. 

भरत
Bharata  (II)--a son of Daśaratha; 1) Bhā. IX. 10. 3; Vā. 88. 184, 189; Vi. IV. 4. 87. had two sons Takṣa and Puṣkala who had Gāndhāra for their kingdom; 2) Bhā. IX. 11. 12; Br. III. 63. 185; Vi. IV. 4. 104. wore bark of wood and ate food dressed with gomūtra, took bed on the bare earth during Rāma's exile, when he was at Nandigrāma meditating on the Pādukā of Rāma he took his place on the śilā; his āśrama, where holy men congregated; returned to Ayodhyā with all royal paraphernalia on hearing of Rāma's arrival; embraced by Rāma; 3) Bhā. IX. 10. 34-40, 43; Vā. 108. 24, 33-5. was present at Rāma's coronation; 4) Vi. IV. 4. 100. killed a number of Gandharvas. 5) Bhā. IX. 11. 13.

भरत
Bharata  (III)--a son of Duṣyanta and Śakuntalā; announced to Duṣyanta as such by a voice from the air; an amśa of Hari; brought up in his early age by the sage Kaṇva; became cakravarti after his father; anointed Adhirāṭ; performed 55 horse sacrifices on the banks of the Ganges and the Yamunā with the aid of Purodha Māmatiya; he tied to the sacrificial post 3300 horses and distributed liberally cows and elephants to priests; he brought under his subjection the Kirātas, Hūṇas, Yavanas, Āndhras, and all the Mlecchas; he recovered the celestial women from Rasātala; he ruled righteously for 27000 years; he had three wives of Vidarbha origin; as they did not resemble their father the nine sons born to these were killed by their mothers who feared that they might be set aside; to perpetuate his line, Bharata performed Marutsoma when the Maruts presented him Bharadvāja, son of Bṛhaspati whom he adopted as his son; 1) Bhā. IX. 20. 17-35; M. 49. 11-5, 28-31; Vā. 99. 134; Vi. IV. 19. 10-16. made the 16 gifts; 2) M. 274. 12. again performed Marutsoma for getting a son; Bharadvāja was born as Vitatha to Bharata when Bharata died. ^3 Vā. 99. 152-8.

भरत
Bharata  (IV)--a name of Brahmandanāgni Br. II. 12. 8; Vā. 29. 7. 

भरत
Bharata  (V)--also Bhāratavarṣa--a country adjacent to Meru: north of the sea and south of the Himālayas: nine divisions of; S. to N. 1000 Yojanas, from Kumarī to the Ganges' source: E. to W. 9000 Yojanas: the Kirātas were on the East and the Yavanas on the West: slowly the four castes grew; seven Kulaparvatas; was peopled by the Aryas and the Mlecchas and fed by a number of rivers of ever flowing waters like the Ganges, Sindhu: contains a number of kingdoms and tribes: four Yugas in. Br. II. 15. 50; 16. 4-69; 29. 23; Vā. 34. 57; 41. 85.

भरत
Bharata  (VI)--a kingdom in the east, watered by the Ganges. Br. II. 18. 50.

भरत
Bharata  (VII)--born from the middle of the hand of Brahmā. M. 3. 11.

भरत
Bharata  (VIII)--the famous author of the Nāṭyaśāstra; got Menakā, Ūrvaśī and Rambhā to enact Lakṣmīsvayamvara before Indra and Purūravas when Ūrvaśī fell in love with the latter and forgot her abhinaya, for which Bharata cursed her. M. 24. 27-33.

भरत
Bharata  (IX)--a son of Karandhama. M. 48. 2.

भरत
Bharata  (X)--a son of Tālajangha and father of Vṛṣa. Vi. IV. 11. 24-5.

भरतवंश
Bharatavaṃśa --the family of Bharata, who was the first of the line. M. 4. 19, 23. 

भरत
Bharatas --a tribe. Vā. 47. 48.

भरता
Bharatā --an Apsarasa and a daughter of Suyaśā. Vā. 69. 14.

भरताग्नि
Bharatāgni --a son of Angiras; wife Sadvatī, and son, Parjanya. Vā. 28. 15; Br. II. 11. 18.

भरताश्रम
Bharatāśrama  (I)--in the Himālayan forests; fit for śrāddha offering; here is the foot print of Matanga; 1) Br. III. 13. 105; Vā. 77. 98. a tīrtha sacred to Lakṣmīranganā. 2) M. 13. 46.

भरताश्रम
Bharatāśrama  (II)--the hermitage of Bharata in Gayā. Vā. 112. 24.

भरद्वसु
Bharadvasu  (I)--a Vāsiṣṭha Brahmavādin. Br. II. 32. 115; M. 145. 110.

भरद्वसु
Bharadvasu  (II)--a resident of Brahmakṣetra. Vā. 59. 105.

भरद्वाज
Bharadvāja  (I)--also called Vitatha: a Siddha; 1) Bhā. VI. 15 [14]. became a son of Bharata; when Mamatā, the wife of the brother of Bṛhaspati was pregnant, Bṛhaspati had sexual intercourse with her; the foetus obstructing him, he cursed the child in embryo; fearing divorce by her husband, Mamatā abandoned the child when Gods said “Bhara dvājam” i.e. ‘rear the child born of two’, and hence he became Bharadvāja; still she abandoned him; nourished by the Maruts he was given over to Bharata; 2) Ib. IX. 20. 35-39. father of Manyu; 3) Ib. X. 21. 1. a sage of the Vaivasvata epoch; 4) Ib. VIII. 13. 5. invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira; 5) Ib. X. 74. 7. called on the dying Bhīṣma; 6) Ib. I. 9. 6. came to Syamantapañcaka to  see Kṛṣṇa; 7) Ib. X. 84. 3. came to see Parīkṣit practising Prāyopaveśa; 8) Ib. I. 19. 10. officiated in Paraśurāma's sacrifice. Heard the Purāṇa from Sṛñjaya and narrated it to Gautama. 9) Br. III. 47. 46; IV. 4. 63.

भरद्वाज
Bharadvāja  (II)--a sage of the Vaivasvata epoch; a yogi; son of Bṛhaspati arisen out of the sexual fluid at the refusal of Mamatā to receive it; abandoned by his parents, was brought up by the Maruts who gave him to Bharata who wanted him; hence two castes Brahmanas and Vaiśyas sprang from him; became a Kṣatriya; 1) M. 9. 27; 49. 15-33; Br. II. 38. 27; Vā. 99. 137, 148, 150, 169. residence at Govardhana where he planted flowers and trees; lives with the sun for part of the year; 2) M. 114. 39; 126. 13; Br. II. 16. 45. a Ṛṣika; a Mantrakṛt; 3) M. 145. 95, 101; Br. II. 32. 101 and 107. a Pañcārṣeya; dvayāmuṣyāyana gotra; 4) M. 196. 50, 52. no marital relations among the Bṛhaspati, Gārga and Bharadvāja lines. 5) Ib. 196. 20, 24. Praised Śiva for burning Tripuram; 6) Ib. 133. 67. the 19th Veda-Vyāsa; Jaṭāmāli, the avatār of the Lord. 7) Br. II. 33. 7; 35. 121; Vā. 23. 185; Vi. III. 3. 16.

भरद्वाज
Bharadvāja  (III)--a son of Bṛhaspati and Maruttā; born when Dīrghatamas was already in the womb; brought by the Maruts to Bharata and became his son Vitatha; 1) Vā. 99. 140-156; Vi. IV. 19. 16-19. father of Manyu. 2) Ib. IV. 19. 20.

भरद्वाज
Bharadvāja  (IV)--son of Bṛhaspati; a branch of Angiras; 1) Vā. 65. 103, 107. a Mantrakṛt of the Angirasa branch; 2) Ib. 59. 101. the father of Āyurveda which he compiled in eight parts and imparted them to his pupils; 3) Ib. 92. 22. one of the seven sages. 4) Ib. 100. 12; 103. 63. 

भरद्वाज
Bharadvāja  (V)--a sage presiding over the month of Tapasya; 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 40. Vā. 52. 12. in the sun's chariot in the month of Kārttika. 2) Vi. II. 10. 12.

भरद्वाज
Bharadvāja  (VI)--a northern kingdom; a tribe. Br. II. 16. 50; M. 114. 43.

भरद्वाज
Bharadvāja  (VII)--a son of Amitrajit and father of Dharmi. Vā. 99. 286.

भरद्वाज
Bharadvāja  (VIII)--the Veda-Vyāsa of the 12th dvāpara. Vi. III. 3. 14.

भरद्वाजि
Bharadvāji --a sage. M. 196. 28.

भरुक
Bharuka --a son of Vijaya and father of Vṛka. Bhā. IX. 8. 2.

भर्ग
Bharga  (I)--a son of Vītihotra and father of Bhārgabhūmi. Bhā. IX. 17. 9.

भर्ग
Bharga  (II)--a son of Vanhi and father of Bhānuman. Bhā. IX. 23. 16.

भर्ग
Bharga  (III)--enabled Arjuna to conquer the Nivātakavacas; 1) M. 6. 29. a Devata. 2) Vā. 108. 32.

भर्त्स्य
Bhartsya --a Pravara sage. M. 199. 17. 

भर्म्याश्व
Bharmyāśva --a son of Arka and father of five sons, Mudgala and others; as the five sons were fit to rule five countries Bharmyāśva called them by the common name, the Pāñcālas. Bhā. IX. 21. 31-33.

भलन्दक
Bhalandaka --a Vaiśya Mantrakṛt. M. 145. 116.

भलन्दन
Bhalandana  (I)--a son of Nābhāga Ariṣṭa and father of Vatsaprīti (Prāmśu-Br. P. and Vā. P.) Bhā. IX. 2. 23. Br. III. 61. 3. Vā. 86. 3-4.

भलन्दन
Bhalandana  (II)--a Vaiśya Mantrakṛt. Br. II. 32. 121.

भलन्दन
Bhalandana  (III)--an Ātreya gotrakāra. M. 197. 7.

भल्लाट
Bhallāṭa --to be worshipped in house and palace building. M. 253. 27; 255. 9; 268. 18.

भल्लाद
Bhallāda --(Bhallāṭa-M. P.) son of Udaksvana (Udaksena-Br. P., M. P., and Vā. P.); with him ends the line of Bārhadīṣavas. Bhā. IX. 21. 26; M. 49. 59; Vā. 99. 182.

भल्लाभ
Bhallābha --a son of Udaksena. Vi. IV. 19. 47.

भव
Bhava --(Girīśa, Śankara, Maheśvara); one who first appeared himself; an epithet of Śiva; other names of; presiding deity of the waters; a resident of the Aruna hill; wife  Oṣā; son Uśana; made the Rudrakunṭasaras in the Kuru country; 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 49; M. 11. 16; 129. 3; 132. 18, 21; 156. 10; 184. 4, 7, 12; 185. 12; 250. 51; 265. 41; Br. II. 18. 19, 21, 32 ff and 72; Vā. 4. 43; 21. 7; 27. 8; 100. 43; 111. 29. the Tāmasi aspect of Svayambhu; destroyer; 2) Br. III. 1. 15; 3. 85. ordered Indra and Hari to take up the first lead in Tripuram; his part in the war; burnt the God of Love; 3) M. 137. 36; 138. 39-41; 154. 251. worshipped by the Bhūtas; 4) Br. III. 7. 372-3. favoured Jambha with the boon of immunity from being hurt by weapons; 5) Ib. III. 42. 17; 65. 31; 72. 80; IV. 2. 247; 1. 40. ety. hence waters to be kept pure; 6) Ib. II. 10. 8, 30 ff; 13. 42 and 136. married Satī, Dakṣa's daughter; was disobedient to his father-in-law; 7) Ib. II. 9. 54; Vā. 30. 38. cursed the seven ṛṣis, who spoke on behalf of Satī, daughter of Dakṣa. 8) Ib. 65. 20.

भव
Bhava  (II)--a Rudra; the son of Bhūta and Sarūpā; wife Satī. Bhā. VI. 6. 17; Br. IV. 34. 26; Vi. I. 7. 26; 8. 6-7.

भव
Bhava  (III)--a son of Raucya Manu. Br. IV. 1. 104; Vā. 100. 108.

भव
Bhava  (IV)--a son of Vasudeva. M. 46. 22.

भव
Bhava  (V)--a Sādhya. M. 171. 43.

भव
Bhava  (VI)--the first kalpa where Bhagavān is known as Ānanda. Vā. 21. 28.

भव
Bhava  (VII)--the fourth kalpa. Vā. 21. 30. 

भव
Bhava  (VIII)--the son of Pratihartā. Vi. II. 1. 37.

भव
Bhava  (IX)--a son of Dhruva, a Vasu. Vā. 66. 20.

भवनन्दि
Bhavanandi --a Kaśyapa gotrakāra. M. 199. 5.

भवनम्
Bhavanam --house; the time for the building of houses; Vaiśākha, Āṣāḍha, Śrāvaṇa, Kārttika, Mārgaśīrṣa, Phālguṇa are recommended; Citra, Jyeṣṭha, Bhādrapada, Āśvayuja, Pauṣa, and Māgha are not recommended; the nakṣatras Aśvini, Rohiṇi, Mūlam, the three Uttaras, Svāti, Hasta and Anūrādha are commended; excepting Sundays and Wednesdays all days are good; the respective position of Sūrya and Candra must be considered; this also applies to the making of wells and tanks; the examination of the ground is differently mentioned for different castes; Sāmāhika vāstu is to be installed; details as regards the kind of wood, the position and other technique are also given in the chapter; the following chapter (254) gives a description of catusśāla, triśāla, dviśāla and ekaśāla. That of the king (palace): consists of five prākāras; of Yuvarāja, etc., of the four castes and then of performers of penance. M. Chh. 252-4.

भवमालिनी
Bhavamālinī --a Śakti created from Nṛsimha's guhya. M. 179. 64.

भवलोक
Bhavaloka --see Rudraloka. Vā. 101. 208. 

भवस्
Bhavas --an Apsarasa clan from the earth. Vā. 69. 57.

भवानी
Bhavānī --Umā; 1) Bhā. III. 23. 1; IV. 5. 1; Br. III. 9. 1; 41. 42; 43. 1 and 23 Parāśakti; enshrined at Sthāneśvara. 2) M. 13. 31; 101. 16; Vā. 71. 2.

भवानीव्रतम्
Bhavānīvratam --the vow in honour of Śivā. M. 101. 77.

भविष्यपुराण
Bhaviṣya-Purāṇa (Bhaviṣyam) --one among the Mahāpurāṇas; comprises 14,500 ślokas; narrated by Brahmā to Manu containing the māhātmyam of the sun, and the account of Aghora kalpa with the characteristics of Bhūtagrāma; he who makes a gift of it with a kumbha on the Full Moon day of the Puṣya month gets the fruits of the Agniṣṭoma; Lomaharṣaṇa revealed it to the sages. Bhā. XII. 7. 24; 13. 6. M. 50. 68, 73-77; 53. 31-33. Vā. 104. 3; Vi. III. 6. 22.

भव्य
Bhavya  (I)--a son of Dhruva and father of Śambu. Vi. I. 13. 1.

भव्य
Bhavya  (II)--a son of Priyavrata; 1) Vi. II. 1. 7. became king of Śākadvīpa. 2) Ib. II. 1. 14.

भव्य
Bhavya  (III)--a sage of the IX epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 23.

भव्य
Bhavyas --a group of gods of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Vi. III. 1. 27. 

भस्म
Bhasma --sacred ash supposed to be the vīrya of Śiva who is Bhasmasamcchannadeha; 1) Br. II. 27. 10 and 92, 105-28; III. 28. 12. snānam of, makes one pure: amulet for places of confinement. 2) Ib. II. 27. 105-115.

भस्मकूट
Bhasmakūṭa --Mt. on the right side of the śilā, where Yama, and Agastya with his wife are residing; 1) Vā. 108. 53, 85. here for self and others Piṇḍa is offered, 2) Ib. 109. 15; 112. 53. after worshipping Bhasmanātha enshrined here.

भस्मनाथ
Bhasmanātha --the deity at Bhasmakūṭa in Gayā. Vā. 112. 53.

भाक्ष
Bhākṣas --a branch of Angiras. Vā. 65. 107.

भागन्य
Bhāganya --a Rājaṛṣi, becoming a Brahmana. Vā. 91. 116.

भागवत
Bhāgavata --a son of Vajramitra and father of Devabhūti: ruled for 32 years. Bhā. XII. 1. 18; Br. III. 74. 154; Vi. IV. 24. 35-6.

भागवत
Bhāgavata dharmas --Detachment (Virakti) and devotion (Bhakti) are the main planks. Bhā. XI. 2. 7, 11, 31, 42; 3. 33.

भागवत
Bhāgavata Purāṇa --(also Bhāgavatam) a Mahāpurāṇa recited by Kṛṣṇa to Brahmā at the beginning of the creation; 1) Bhā. III. 4. 13; XII. 7. 23; Vi. III. 6. 21. as sacred as and equal to the Veda; the sun to the darkness of Kali; 2) Bhā. II. 1. 8; XII. 4. 42; I. 1. 3; 3. 40, 45. a compendium of the Lord's glories; the essense of all Vedāṅgas, the first among the Purāṇas and just like Kāśi in importance; 3) Ib. II. 7. 51; XII. 4. 15-17. contains 18000 verses; abstract of the contents:--an exposition of the Gāyatrī and  the incident of the killing of Vṛtrāsura; a composition of the Śārasvata Kalpa, the heyday of it; 4) Ib. II. 10. 1-17; XII. 12. 1-45; 13. 5, 9; M. 53. 20-22. fruit of studying it; 5) Bhā. XII. 12. 46-68. the Purāṇa Samhitā was taught originally to Nārada by the sage Nārāyaṇa; Nārada told it to Vyāsa who told it to Śuka in the beginning of the Dvāpara Yuga; 6) Ib. XII. 4. 41-3; I. 7. 8; II. 1. 8. Sankarṣaṇa taught it to Sanatkumāra who instructed Sānkhyāyana; he in turn imparted it to Parāśara and Bṛhaspati; requested by Pulastya, Parāśara taught it to Maitreya; 7) Ib. III. 8. 2-9. narrated to Parīkṣit by Śuka; 8) Ib. II. 8. 28. expounded by Sūta at Naimiṣālaya to the sages and seers. 9) Ib. XII. 4. 41-43. Purāṇadaśalakṣaṇam; 10) Ib. II. 9. 43. one who makes a gift of it with a golden lion on the Full Moon day of Prauṣtapada would reach the heaven of bliss; 11) M. 53. 20-22. contains 18000 stanzas. 12) Vā. 104. 5.

भागवत
Bhāgavatas --those who had dedicated themselves to the service of God by singing in His praise. Vā. 104. 14.

भागवताण्डम्
Bhāgavatāṇḍam --above Brahmaloka and at a distance of a crore of yojanas and 50 niyuktas; here are prakṛtis, sūkṣma, prolific depending on each other. Vā. 101. 221-6.

भागवतोत्तम
Bhāgavatottama --one devoted to Hari; attributes of. Bhā. XI. 2. 45-55.

भागवित्तायन
Bhāgavittāyanas --Sages. M. 200. 8.

भागवित्ति
Bhāgavitti  (I)--an Āṛseya Pravara (Bhārgava). M. 195. 37. 

भागवित्ति
Bhāgavitti  (II)--a son of Kuthumi. Vā. 61. 38.

भागिल
Bhāgila --an Ārṣeya Pravara of the Bhārgavas. M. 195. 37.

भागीरथी
Bhāgīrathī --(Gaṅgā): so-called on account of Bhagīratha having brought her; a sacred river; 1) Br. II. 18. 42; III. 13. 100; 54. 51; 63. 168-9; M. 12. 44; 163. 60; Vā. 88. 169; Vi. III. 18. 57; IV. 4. 35; V. 35. 30. Indra worshipped Lalitā on the banks of the; 2) Br. IV. 12. 44. to its east lay Hamsaprapatanam. a sacred spot; 3) M. 106. 32. the seventh stream of the Gaṅgā flowing towards the south in Himāhvavarṣa; 4) Ib. 121. 41; Vā. 47. 40. fit for srāddha. 5) Ib. 77. 92.

भागुरि
Bhāguri --a seer; 1) Vā. 34. 62. heard the Viṣṇu Purāṇa from Priyavrata and narrated it to Stambhamitra. 2) Vi. VI. 8. 44.

भाजर
Bhājaras  (Bhājiras)--one of the five Deva gaṇas of the 14th Bhauta Manu; are seven rivers. Vā. 100. 111, 112.

भाण्डीरक
Bhāṇḍīraka --a banyan tree whose shade is fit for playing games; near Bṛndāvana. Bhā. X. 18. 22; 19. 13.

भाण्डीरवटम्
Bhāṇḍīravaṭam --in the vicinity of Bṛndāvana where lived Pralamba, the demon; 1) Vi. V. 9. 2. the sporting ground of the cowherds. 2) Ib. V. 9, 3-15.

भाद्रपद
Bhādrapada (Tṛtīya) --a Manvantarādi for śrāddha; 1) M. 17. 6. a nakṣatra. 2) Ib. 54. 11; 55, 10; Vā. 66. 52. 

भानव
Bhānavas --son of Bhānu and Dharma. Br. III. 3. 32; M. 5. 18; 203. 8; Vā. 66. 33. Vi. I. 15. 106.

भानु
Bhānu  (I)--a daughter of Dakṣa and one of the ten wives of Dharma; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 4-5; M. 5. 15; Vā. 66. 2; Vi. I. 15. 105. her sons were Bhānavas of whom Devaṛṣabha was one. 2) Br. III. 3. 2, 32; M. 5. 18; Vi. I. 15. 106.

भानु
Bhānu  (II)--a son of Prativyoman and father of Divā(r)ka. Bhā. IX. 12. 10.

भानु
Bhānu  (III)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā; 1) Bhā. X. 61. 10; 90. 33; Br. III. 71. 247-48; M. 47. 17; Vā. 96. 238; Vi. V. 32. 1. went out with his brothers for sport and seeing a huge lizard on a wall reported it to Kṛṣṇa; 2) Bhā. X. 64. 1-4. got himself killed in Prabhāsā. 3) Ib. XI. 30. 17.

भानु
Bhānu  (IV)--a son of Krodhā and a Devagandharva. Br. III. 6. 39.

भानु
Bhānu  (V)--one of the 20 Sutapa gods. Br. IV. 1. 15; Vā. 100. 15.

भानु
Bhānu  (VI)--one of the four sons of Svārociṣa Manu. M. 9. 7.

भानु
Bhānu  (VII)--the father of Bhānavas. M. 203. 8; Vā. 66. 33.

भानु
Bhānu  (VIII)--a daughter of Satyabhāmā. Vā. 96. 240.

भानु
Bhānu  (IX)--a son of Bhārga and father of Trayīsānu. Vi. IV. 16. 3. 

भानुकच्छस्
Bhānukacchas --the people of the south. Vā. 45. 130.

भानुमन्
Bhānuman  (I)--the son of Bṛhadaśva and father of Pratīkāśva. Bhā. IX. 12. 11.

भानुमन्
Bhānuman  (II)--the son of Keśidhvaja and father of Śatadyumna; 1) Bhā. IX. 13. 21. brother of Śīradhvaja. 2) Br. III. 64. 18.

भानुमन्
Bhānuman  (III)--a son of Bharga and father of Tribhānu. Bhā. IX. 23. 16-17.

भानुमन्
Bhānuman  (IV)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā. Bhā. X. 61. 10.

भानुमन्
Bhānuman  (V)--a son of Sīradhvaja Maithila; his brother Kuśadhvaja, lord of Kāśi. Vā. 89. 18. Vi. IV. 5. 30.

भानुमती
Bhānumatī  (I)--the wife of Sagara and mother of Asamanjasa. M. 12. 39, 42.

भानुमती
Bhānumatī  (II)--the chief among the 10,000 queens of Dharmamūrti, the king of Bṛhatkalpa; wife of the goldsmith, Śauṇḍa in previous birth; was born again as queen for her services in connection with a gift of Lavaṇācala by Līlāvatī (s.v.). M. 92. 19-24. 

भानुरथ
Bhānuratha --the son of Bṛhadaśva and father of Pratītāśva. Vā. 99. 284; Vi. IV. 22. 4.

भानुलोक
Bhānuloka --the world of the sun. M. 280. 10.

भानुविन्द
Bhānuvinda --took part in the defence of Dvārakā from Śālva. Bhā. X. 76. 14.

भानुव्रतम्
Bhānuvratam --the observance of the vow leads to the world of the sun. M. 101. 60.

भानुश्चन्द्र
Bhānuścandra --a son of Candragiri. M. 12. 55.

भामिनी
Bhāminī --brought forth tigers, lions, elephants, etc. Vā. 69. 289.

भारत
Bhārata --an ākhyāna by Vyāsa; the essentials of the Vedas are introduced for the use of women, Śūdras and others. Bhā. I. 4. 25, 29; 5. 3.

भारत
Bhāratas --belonging to the line of Pūru; after the name of Bharata son of Duṣyanta; 1) M. 24. 71; 49. 11. kingdom of the. 2) Ib. 121. 49.

भारत
Bhārata Yuddha --Bṛhadbala killed by Abhimanyu in. Br. III. 74. 109; M. 12. 55; 103. 2; 271. 19; Vā. 99. 296; Vi. IV. 4. 112. 

भारतम्
Bhāratam varṣam --after king Bharata, son of Ṛṣabha; Viṣṇu in the form of Kūrma; south of the Himālayas and north of the sea; 1) Bhā. V. 4. 9; 6. 13; 16. 9; M. 113, 28, 44; 114. 11; Vi. II. 3. 1-22. a Karmabhūmi; 2) Bhā. V. 17. 11. 9000 yojanas in extent; 3) Br. III. 53. 14; 56. 2; II. 14. 62, 72; 17. 1; 21. 6. the seven chief mountains in it are the Mahendra, Malaya, Sahya, Śuktimat, Ṛkṣa, Vindhya and Pāriyātra; divided into nine divisions. Indradvīpa, Kaśeru, Tāmraparṇa, Gabhastimat, Nāgadvīpa, Saumya, Gandharva, and Vāruṇa (c. Aruna ?), besides the present land; a 1000 yojanas from north to south; on the east are the Kirātas and on the west the Yavanas; in the middle, men of the four castes; then rivers are mentioned; 4) Bhā. V. 17. 9; 19. 9-28; Vā. 24. 1; 33. 52, 61; 34. 28; 41. 32; 45. 75, 89, 94-5; 57. 20. here time reckoned as four yugas; the best of all territories in Jambūdvīpa; original name was Ajanābha; 5) Bhā. V. 7. 3. conquered by Parīkṣit; 6) Ib. I. 16. 13. described. 7) Vā. 45. 72-137.

भारती
Bhāratī  (I)--is Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 14. 72.

भारती
Bhāratī  (II)--(Vāṇī and Sarasvatī); wife of Prajāpati; served Lalitā with cāmara; gave the flywhisk to Gangā and entered the face of Brahmā. Br. IV. 39. 70-71; M. 4. 8.

भारती
Bhāratī  (III)--a R. in the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 21.

भारद्वाज
Bhāradvāja  (I)--with the sun in the Śarat season. Br. II. 23. 12; 35. 64.

भारद्वाज
Bhāradvāja  (II)--a son of Bṛhaspati; 1) Vā. 66. 1 and 2, 55; 64. 26. a branch of Angirasa; 2) Ib. 65. 97 and 106. a sage by Garbha; 3) Ib. 59. 92. a Mantrakṛt; a Mantra Brāhmāṇa kāraka. 4) Ib. 59. 98, 131. 

भारद्वाज
Bhāradvāja  (III)--performed śrāddha at Kaśyapapada and found two hands black and white protruding, and feeling a doubt asked his mother who said the black hand was his father; but the white hand contested that he was the Procreator; the black said, that he was the owner of kṣetra; Bhāradvāja found her of bad character. Vā. 111. 58-63.

भारभूति
Bhārabhūti --a tīrtha on the Narmadā, where Lord Virūpākṣa is enshrined; its merits detailed. M. 194. 18-30.

भारम्
Bhāram --a measure of weight. M. 82. 5; 85. 2.

भारताख्यानम्
Bhāratākhyānam --the Mahābhārata containing the cssence of the Vedas in a lakh of verses. M. 53. 70.

भारुकच्छस्
Bhārukacchas --(of Broach); a tribe. M. 114. 50.

भारुण्डानि
Bhāruṇḍāni(Sāmāni) --to be uttered in founding a new temple. M. 265. 28.

भार्ग
Bhārga  (I)--a son of Vītihotra, and father of Bhārgabhūmi. Vi. N. 8. 20.

भार्ग
Bhārga  (II)--a son of Vanhi and father of Bhānu. Vi. IV. 16. 3.

भार्गभूमि
Bhārgabhūmi --a son of Bhārga. The line of Kaśya ends with him; 1) Bhā. IX. 17. 9-10. did propaganda for the spread of varṇa dharma. 2) Vi. IV. 8. 20. 

भार्गव
Bhārgava  (I)--an eastern country. Br. II. 16. 54; Vā. 45. 123.

भार्गव
Bhārgava  (II)--a Śrutaṛṣi; 1) Br. II. 24. 89, 104; 33. 2. got wealth by meditating on the 108 names of the Devī; 2) M. 13. 62. made the 16 gifts; 3) Ib. 274. 11. got siddhi at Benares. 4) Ib. 184. 15.

भार्गव
Bhārgava  (III)--(Jamadagni, Unnata, Vedaśrī): a sage of the first epoch of Sāvarṇa Manu; drank Soma; killed by the Sāmhikeyas and their groups of Asuras; 1) Br. III. 6. 22; IV. 1. 10. Vā. 62. 16 and 41, 54, 65; 64. 25; 86. 49. of the family of Bhṛgu; 2) Ib. 64. 2; 100. 82, 97, 107 and 116; 106. 35. Bhārgavam Vapuṣmān; one of the seven sages; Tapomati, Niruṭsāka, Agnibāhu.

भार्गव
Bhārgava  (IV)--(planet: Śukra); in size (1/16) of the moon; 1) M. 128. 47 and 63; Vā. 53. 66; 111. 5. chariot of, drawn by eight steeds (M. P.); drawn by ten horses (Br. P. and Vā. P.) of different colours--śveta, piśanga, sāranga, nīla, pīta, vilohita, kṛṣṇa, harita, pṛṣata and pṛśni; 2) M. 127. 7; Br. II. 23. 81; Vā. 52. 74. stood near the wheel of the chariot of Tripurāri in defence; 3) M. 138. 20, 61. has sixteen rays; 4) Vā. 53. 86. born of Tiṣya in the Cākṣuṣa epoch; the first of Tārāgrahas. 5) Ib. 53. 111.

भार्गव
Bhārgava  (V)--the name of Vyāsa in the third dvāpara. The Lord takes the avatār of Damana with four sons. Vā. 23. 123.

भार्गव
Bhārgava  (VI)--a son of Ṛṣabha, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 144. 

भार्गव
Bhārgava  (VII)--(Śukrācārya); priest of the Asuras; 1) Vā. 53. 80. conversation of, with Virocana on the origin of Angāravrata. 2) M. 24. 52; 72. 6.

भार्गव
Bhārgava  (VIII)--Rāma--is Paraśurāma created by Lalitā in her war with Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 29. 110.

भार्गव
Bhārgavas --a Devagaṇa. Br. III. 1. 50.

भार्गवगोत्र
Bhārgavagotras --Vatsa, Viśva, Aśviṣeṇa, Pāṇḍa, Pathya, Śaunaka, Pakṣas are collectively called as. Vā. 65. 96.

भार्गवत
Bhārgavata --an Ārṣeyapravara (Angiras). M. 196. 7.

भार्गवा
Bhārgavā Devas --seven Devas who live in the midst of three worlds for 71 yugas; leave for Maharloka at the end of the Manvantara and the three worlds become unsupported; stars, planets, etc., become lost to their places; here these Devas become 14 gaṇas commencing with Jita and leave for Janaloka at the time of Saṅkalana; all creatures are destroyed when a new creation sets in. Vā. 100. 119-32.

भार्गवेशम्
Bhārgaveśam --a kṣetram sacred to Viṣṇu who defeated a number of Asuras. M. 192. 1-2.

भार्गव्योम
Bhārgavyoma --a Kṣatriya who became a dvija. Br. III. 66. 87. 

भालचन्द्र
Bhālacandra --a name of Vināyaka. Br. III. 42. 36.

भालुकि
Bhāluki --a Lāngala. Vā. 61. 42.

भाव
Bhāva (Darśa) --the 27th kalpa; Agni became Maṇḍali and shone over bhuva and deva; after the end of 1000 years came the Sūrya maṇḍala. Vā. 21. 61-7.

भावदोष
Bhāvadoṣa --impure mind, spoils the effects of good deeds (dharma). Vā. 8. 190-2.

भावन
Bhāvana --a son of Bhṛgu, and a Deva. Br. III. 1. 89; Vā. 65. 87.

भावन
Bhāvanas --the Devas of the Auttama epoch. M. 9. 13.

भावपुष्प
Bhāvapuṣpas --are said to be eight flowers; such as clemency, self-restraint, tenderness, patience, resignation, devotion, meditation and truth (Cf. Wilson). Vi. V. 7. 69.

भावभावन
Bhāvabhāvanas --three-fold, Brahma bhāvana, Karma bhāvana and Ubhaya bhāvana, according to the commentator. Vi. VI. 8. 7.

भावास्यायनि
Bhāvāsyāyani --a sage. M. 196. 27. 

भाविन
Bhāvina --a caste equal to Śūdra in Plakṣadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 17.

भावीमन्द्र
Bhāvīmandras --a Janapada of the Bhadra country. Vā. 43. 22.

भाव्य
Bhāvyas --a group of Gods in the Cākṣuṣa epoch; they are Vijaya, Sujaya, Mana, Udyāna, Sumati, Supari and Arthapati. Br. II. 36. 66, 72; Vā. 62. 60-1.

भाषी
Bhāṣī --the wife of Śūra; mother of Devamīdhuṣa and ten other sons. Vā. 96. 143.

भाष्यविद्
Bhāṣyavid --one who knows the Bhāṣya; perhaps Mahābhāṣya of Patañjali. Vā. 83. 52.

भाष्यविद्या
Bhāṣyavidyā --the knowledge of, starting in Dvāpara. Br. 11. 31. 24; M. 144. 13. 23.

भास
Bhāsa --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 242.

भास
Bhāsas --sons of Bhāsī and Garuḍa; 1) Br. III. 7. 455. kites of Tāmrā line. 2) Vi. I. 21. 16.

भासकृत्
Bhāsakṛt --one of the 20 Sutapa gods. Vā. 100. 15.

भासी
Bhāsī  (I)--a daughter of Ṛṣita. Br. III. 7. 13. 

भासी
Bhāsī  (II)--a daughter of Tāmrā and Kaśyapa; married Garutmān; mother of Bhāsas, Ulūkas, Crows, Hens, Cuckoos, Kalavinkas, Doves, Lāvatittiras, Sparrows, Partridges, Owls, Vultures, Kākakukkuṭas, etc. Br. III. 7. 446-448, 455; M. 6. 30-31; Vā. 69, 325, 328, 335-36; Vi. I. 21. 15-16.

भासी
Bhāsī  (III)--an Apsaras. Vā. 69. 48.

भासुर
Bhāsura --a Tuṣita god. Br. II. 36. 10.

भास्कर
Bhāskara --(Āditya, Sūrya): an epithet of the Sun; 1) M. 11. 10; 93. 13; Vā. 31. 35, 37; Vi. II. 8. 2; VI. 7. 3 and 20. creator of days and therefore of time; is Samvatsara; 2) Br. II. 13. 124, 126; 21. 6. vanquished by Rāvaṇa; 3) Ib. III. 5. 79; 7. 254; IV. 9. 35. devotees of, reach Śivālayam by dying at Benares; 4) M. 183. 104. the maṇḍalam of, 9000 yojanas in extent, twice that of the Moon; 5) Vā. 50. 61, 63. Dvādaśātma. 6) Ib. 53. 42.

भास्व
Bhāsva --see Sūrya. Vi. IV. 14. 36.

भिक्षु
Bhikṣu  (I)--(mārga) taught by Nārada to the children of Dakṣa; 1) Bhā. VI. 5. 36. duties of. 2) M. 40. 1, 5.

भिक्षु
Bhikṣu  (II)--(see also Yati) main vratas five; and supplementary, five; main:--dhyānam, samādhi of the senses, begging at seven houses, silence and release from sangha. Supplementary:--Purity in conduct, discipline (vinaya) śaucam, non-retaliation and samyakdarśanam, besides non theft, Brahmacarya, non-covetousness, ahimsa, non-anger, service to the Guru, medicated food, daily study, alms, resig  nation, generosity, etc., becomes one with Brahmā for observing such dharma. Br. II. 7. 179; Vā. 8. 186-7; 16. 18-9; 59. 25; 105. 25; Vi. III. 9. 24-42.

भिन्नदर्शन
Bhinnadarśanas --those who could not find the one in the three but think of them as separate and even as superior to one's own. Some call the one God Brahmā, Prajāpati, Śiva and Viṣṇu; these will be troubled by Yātudhānas and Piśācas. Vā. 66. 111-8.

भिन्नदर्शि
Bhinnadarśi --as against Tatvadarśi--sectarians in religion. Br. III. 3. 89-90. 97.

भिरु
Bhiru --a son of Maṇibhadra. Vā. 69. 155.

भिल्ल
Bhillas --a tribe. Br. IV. 7. 19.

भिषक्
Bhiṣak --a son of Hṛdika. Br. III. 71. 141.

भिषग्द्वैतरत
Bhiṣagdvaitarata --a son of Hṛdika. Vā. 96. 139.

भीम
Bhīma --the son of Vijaya and father of Kāñcana. Bhā. IX. 15. 3.

भीम
Bhīma  (II)--Śiva with ākāśasthānam; wife, Diks and son Svarga; 1) Br. II. 10. 81; Vā. 27. 14, 45, and 54. the sixth name of Mahādeva, with the ākāśa element predominating; hence nuisance should not be committed nor conjugal union in the open. 2) Br. II. 10. 14, 50. 

भीम
Bhīma  (III)--a Vaikuṇṭha God; 1) Br. II. 36. 57. with the sun in the months, Madhu and Mādhava. 2) Ib. II. 23. 3.

भीम
Bhīma  (IV)--a Marut of the third gaṇa. Br. III. 5. 94; Vā. 67. 126.

भीम
Bhīma  (V)--a Mauneya Gandharva. Br. III. 7. 3.

भीम
Bhīma  (VI)--a son of Khaśā and a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 133; Vā. 69. 165.

भीम
Bhīma  (VII)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 235.

भीम
Bhīma  (VIII)--a king; the son of Amāvasu, and father of Kāñcanaprabha; 1) Br. III. 66. 23; Vi. IV. 7. 2-3. a Viśvajit. 2) Vā. 91. 52.

भीम
Bhīma  (IX)--(Bhīmasena) the Pāṇḍava, who killed Jarāsandha and gave his chariot to Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 68. 28; Vi. V. 35. 28.

भीम
Bhīma  (X)--one of the eleven Rudras; a son of Bhūta and Sarūpā; 1) M. 153. 19; Bhā. VI. 6. 17; Br. IV. 34. 41. Vi. I. 8. 6. the presiding deity of ākāśa. 2) M. 265. 42.

भीम
Bhīma  (XI)--an Asura of the Atala region. Vā. 50. 17.

भीम
Bhīma  (XII)--a Rākṣasa gaṇa. Vā. 69. 165. 

भीम
Bhīma  (XIII)--a son of Mahāvīrya. Vā. 99. 162.

भीमकर्म
Bhīmakarma --a minister of Bhaṇḍa who advised him to fight Indra. Br. IV. 12. 56.

भीमद्वादशी
Bhīmadvādaśī --once called Kalyāṇinī; preached to Bhīma by Lord Kṛṣṇa; once observed by Ūrvaśī, Satyabhāmā and others to attain status; worship of Garuḍa, Govinda, Śiva, Vināyaka, Dikpālas. M. 69. 19-57.

भीमनाद
Bhīmanāda --one of the seven pralaya clouds. M. 2. 8.

भीमरथ
Bhīmaratha  (I)--son of Ketuman and father of Divodāsa (Prajeśvara-Br. P.); himself known as Divodāsa in Vā. P.; king of Vārāṇasi. Bhā. IX. 17. 5-6; Br. III. 67. 26; Vā. 92. 23; Vi. IV. 8. 11.

भीमरथ
Bhīmaratha  (II)--a son of Vikṛti, and father of Navaratha (Rathavara-Br. P.) Bhā. IX. 24. 4; Br. III. 70. 42; Vā. 95. 41; Vi. IV. 12. 41.

भीमरथ
Bhīmaratha  (III)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 238.

भीमरथ
Bhīmaratha  (IV)--a son of Vimala and father of Navaratha. M. 44. 41. 

भीमरथी
Bhīmarathī --a R. in the Sahya hill in Dakṣiṇāpatha; 1) Vā. 45. 104; Vi. II. 3. 12. in Bhāratavarṣa; visited by Balarāma from the Sahya hill; 2) Bhā. V. 19. 18; X. 79. 12; Br. II. 16. 34. sacred to the Pitṛs. 3) M. 22. 45; 114. 29.

भीमरोमक
Bhīmaromakas(c) --a kingdom through which the Gangā flows. M. 121. 47.

भीमवेग
Bhīmavega --a Tripravara. M. 196. 34.

भीमव्रतम्
Bhīmavratam --the observance of the vow leads to the world of Viṣṇu. M. 101. 51.

भीमसेन
Bhīmasena  (I)--(also Bhīma); a Pāṇḍava son of Kuntī; father of Śrutasena; had another son Ghaṭotkaca by Hidimbā, and a third Sarvagata by Kālī; 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 29-31; Vi. IV. 14. 35; 20. 40. failed to hit the fish in Lakṣmaṇā's svayamvara; 2) Ib. X. 71. 27; 58. 4; 64. 9. joy at Kṛṣṇa's visit to Indraprastha and Kṛṣṇa's respects to him; was consoled by Kṛṣṇa when banished to forest; 3) Bhā. X. 83. 23. sent to the western territories with the Matsyas, Kekayas and Madrakas. 4) Ib. X. 72. 13. Advised by Uddhava to go in Brahmana's disguise to Jarāsandha and vanquish him; went with Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna to Girivraja. After killing Jarāsandha, Bhīmasena returned to Hastināpura. 5) Ib. X. 71. 7; 72. 32-46; 73. 31. Declined to follow Balarāma's advice not to fight; fought with Duryodhana at Kurukṣetra and felled him with his gadā; 6) Ib. X. 78 [95(v)39]; 79. 23 and 28; I. 7. 13. was in charge of cooking in the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira; 7) Ib. X. 75. 4. fed Dhṛtarāṣṭra; advocated killing of Aśvatthāma and felt sorry at Kṛṣṇa's separation; 8) Ib. I. 13. 22; II. 7. 35; I. 7. 51 and 54; 9. 15; 10. 10. put an end to the Rākṣasas born of Krodhavaśā: propagator of Bhīmadvādaśīvrata; 9) M. 6. 43; 69. 12-3. gave Piṇḍa sitting on his left leg to Janārdhana,  and attained Brahmaloka with his brothers; 10) Vā. 86. 48; 108. 91. strength of; depended on the good will of Kṛṣṇa. 11) Vi. V. 38. 33.

भीमसेन
Bhīmasena  (II)--a son of Parīkṣit. Bhā. IX. 22. 35; Vi. IV. 20. 1; 21. 2.

भीमसेन
Bhīmasena  (III)--a Mauneya Gandharva. Br. III. 7. 1.

भीमसेन
Bhīmasena  (IV)--an author of a treatise on Music. Br. III. 61. 42.

भीमसेन
Bhīmasena  (V)--a son of Dakṣa. M. 50. 38.

भीमसेन
Bhīmasena  (VI)--a son of Suratha. Vā. 99. 229.

भीमसेन
Bhīmasena  (VII)--a son of Ṛkṣa, and father of Dilīpa. Vā. 99. 233; Vi. IV. 20. 7.

भीमा
Bhīmā  (I)--a mother-goddess; 1) M. 179. 22. enshrined in Himādri. 2) Ib. 13. 47.

भीमा
Bhīmā  (II)--a R of the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 18.

भीमेश्वरम्
Bhīmeśvaram --a tīrtha on the Narmadā; sacred to the Piṭrs. M. 22. 46, 75; 191. 5. 

भीरव
Bhīravas --one of the 14 gaṇas of Apsarasas, born of Mṛtyu. Br. III. 7. 20.

भीरु
Bhīru --a Yakṣa, son of Puṇyajanī and Maṇibhadra. Br. III. 7. 123.

भीषण
Bhīṣaṇa  (I)--a Vānara born of Pulaha. Br. III. 7. 179.

भीषण
Bhīṣaṇa  (II)--a son of Hṛdīka. M. 44. 82.

भीषणिका
Bhīṣaṇikā --a Goddess following Revatī. M. 179. 73.

भीष्म
Bhīṣma --son of Śantanu; Grandsire of the Pāṇḍavas and Gangā. The best of Bharatas, the foremost of the Vasus, and versed in dharma: Learned, self-controlled, and devoted to Hari. His prowess was praised even by Paraśurāma. Leader of a thousand legions, called Sahasrāṇī; 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 19-20; I. 9. 4-6, 30; M. 103. 5. Vā. 99. 240. Vi. IV. 20. 33; V. 35. 5 and 27. Informed by Uddhava of Balarāma's visit to Hastināpura: was invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira; 2) Bhā. X. 68. 17 and 28; 74. 10. went to Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse and there met Kṛṣṇa and the Vṛṣṇis. Left it for his home. 3) Ib. X. 82. 24; 84. 57, 69 [1]. Joined Duryodhana's army and was commander for ten days when he was mortally wounded; while on his deathbed he welcomed the sages and the royal guests, who visited him; 4) Ib. X. 78. [95(v)16], [28]; I. 9. 8-10; 15. 10. told the Pāṇḍavas that they were safe under the guidance of Kṛṣṇa; 5) Ib. I. 9. 11-14. Yudhiṣṭhira addressed B. lying on a bed of arrows on the various aspects of dharma and especially mokṣa dharma. The discourse was over when it was uttarāyana, B. cast off his mortal coil with his mind fixed on Kṛṣṇa Vāsudeva. His praise of Kṛṣṇa; 6) Ib. I. 9. 25-42; XI. 19. 11-12. was  seen among others by Akrūra, Kṛtavarman, Kṛṣṇa and Balarāma; 7) Ib. X. 49. 1; 52. [56(v)4, and 11]; 57. 2. one of the twelve, who knew the dharma ordained by Hari; 8) Ib. VI. 3. 20.  gave piṇḍa in Viṣṇupada; 9) Vā. 111. 69. Baladeva's respect for; 10) Vi. V. 35. 36; 38. 16, 47, 49 and 64. narrated to Nakula what he heard from his Brahmana friend Kālingaka, on the mystery of birth and death; 11) Ib. III. 7. 8. the best of the Kurus; 12) Ib. III. 7. 35. heard a legend from Vasiṣṭha as to who was a Nagna. 13) Ib. III. 17. 7.

भीष्मक
Bhīṣmaka --the invincible king of Vidarbha, capital of Kuṇḍina (Berar); 1) Bhā. III. 3. 3; Vi. V. 26. 1. had five sons (Rukmi one of them) and a daughter, known as Vaidarbhī and Rukmiṇī. Agreed to his son, Rukmi's wish to give Rukmiṇī in marriage to Śiśupāla: on the eve of the day of marriage, the city was decorated; prayers were offered to Piṭrs and Devas; preseṅts were given to Brahmanas to exalt mangalam. Damaghoṣa and other friends of the Cedi King were welcomed. Housed Rāma and Kṛṣṇa in comfortable lodgings. But Kṛṣṇa won her in the svayamvara; 2) Bhā. X. 52. 16, 21-22; 53. 7-35; Vi. V. 26. 3-6. was stationed by Jarāsandha on the northern side during the siege of Gomanta; 3) Bhā. X. 52. 11[15]. went to the Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse. 4) Ib. X. 82. 15.

भीष्ंअचण्डिक
Bhīṣṃacaṇḍika --a place near Benares. M. 183. 62.

भुजङ्ग
Bhujaṅga --served as a rope for Manu to tie the divine boat to the horn of the fish; 1) M. 2. 18; 4. 6. Indra took the guise of, to disturb the tapas of Vajrāngī; 2) Ib. 146. 65. born to ward off poison. 3) Ib. 219. 6. 

भुजङ्गमस्
Bhujaṅgamas --see Nāgas; vanquished by Rāvaṇa. Br. III. 7. 255.

भुजातपूर
Bhujātapūra --a Pravara Ṛṣi. M. 199. 16.

भुतावाप्ति
Bhutāvāpti --of five elements: pṛthvi, vāyu, ākāśa, āpa, and jyoti; each has its own function; the body is of the earth, prāṇa of māruta or wind, the ākāśa of water, and tejas of jyotsna; by their virility, sangrāmas and visayas do their respective work. Vā. 97. 55.

भुद्रक
Bhudrakas --the Rākṣasas, being the destroyers of yajñas as also nikaras. Vā. 69. 189.

भुरण्य
Bhuraṇya --a Sudhāmāna god. Br. IV. 1. 60.

भुर्भर
Bhurbhara --a weapon. Vā. 30. 236.

भुव
Bhuva  (I)--also antarikṣa--the second of the seven created worlds: Vāyu is its presiding deity: burnt down by pralaya fire; 1) Br. II. 19. 155; 21. 21; IV. 1. 156; 2. 14-17, 27-30. residents: Marut, Mātariśva, Rudras, Aśvins, Ādityas, Sādhyas, Pitrs, Angirasa sages etc., intervening between the earth and the sun; the residents here drink soma and ghee. 2) Vā. 101. 19, 29, 40, 43.

भुव
Bhuva  (II)--the second kalpa. Vā. 21. 29. 

भुव
Bhuva  (III)--the eleventh kalpa. Vā. 21. 31.

भुव
Bhuva  (IV)--a son of Unnetā. Vā. 33. 56.

भुव
Bhuva  (V)--the seventh son of Devakī. Vā. 96. 181.

भुवत
Bhuvata --a son of Kṣema, a Bṛhadratha: ruled in Magadha for 64 years. Vā. 99. 303.

भुवन
Bhuvana  (I)--a son of Bhṛgu and a Deva. Br. III. 1. 89; M. 195. 12; Vā. 65. 87.

भुवन
Bhuvana  (II)--(Bhuvaneśvara) a Rudra. Br. III. 3. 71; Vā. 66. 70.

भुवना
Bhuvanā --the sister of Bṛhaspati and wife of Prabhāta, the 8th Vasava. Br. III. 3. 28.

भुवनाण्डगर्भ
Bhuvanāṇḍagarbha --Lord of the Universe; Brahmā. M. 8. 10.

भुवमन्यु
Bhuvamanyu --a son of Vitatha, and father of four powerful sons, Bṛhadkṣatra and three others. M. 49. 35; Vā. 99. 158-59. 

भुवर्लोक
Bhuvarloka --from Bhuvana according to Niruktañja; 1) Br. II. 38. 16; Vā. 23. 84; 49. 148; 64. 14; 100. 160. that world between the earth and the sun; burnt by the flame of Rudra in the dissolution. 2) Vi. II. 7. 17; VI. 3. 26 and 39.

भुवस्थानम्
Bhuvasthānam --the place of Acchāvaka agni. Vā. 29. 28.

भुवस्पति
Bhuvaspati --is Vāyu, lord of Bhuva. Br. IV. 2. 20; Vā. 101. 22.

भुशुण्डि
Bhuśuṇḍi  (I)--a weapon of war used in the Kubera Jambha war; 1) M. 150. 73. used by Kujambha; 2) Ib. 150. 106. Tāraka defeated Yama with. 3) Ib. 152. 28; 153. 195; 177. 9.

भुशुण्डि
Bhuśuṇḍi  (II)--a mind-born mother. M. 179. 16.

भू
Bhū  (I)--Earth: (Bhūmi, s.v.) one of the seven worlds; released from Rasātala by Hari in Varāha form, this, Devī worships Hari in that form in Uttara-Kuru; 1) Bhā. IV. 17. 34; M. 60. 2. when Pṛthu wanted to punish her for scarce supply of food, she trembled and appealed to him to make the ground level plain and milk her with a calf and a pail; was milked by the King, sages, Gods, asuras and others; hilly tracts got levelled, and cities and villages were founded. 2) Bhā. IV. 17. 13-36; 18. 2-32. Bhū is said to have given yogic pādukas to Pṛthu. 3) Ib. IV. 15. 18. presiding deity is Agni;  burnt by pralaya fire; 4) Br. II. 19. 155; 21. 21; IV. 1. 156; 2. 9-19, 41, 223. the measurement of the earth (Pramāṇam) attempted by Haryaśvas (s.v.). 5) M. 5. 6.

भू
Bhū  (II)--(Samiti) a Kṛtaloka, the first world; first was said Bhū and then came this world; 1) Vā. 23. 107; 24. 18. 101. 11, 35-36. is Pārthiva loka; 2) Ib. 101. 18. these lokas are burnt by the flames of the seven suns; 3) Ib. 101. 20.  Marīci, Kaśyapa, Dakṣa and other Prajāpatis live here; 4) Ib. 101. 34. people here live on rice and juice. 5) Ib. 101. 40, 42.

भूत
Bhūta  (I)--a sage who married two daughters of Dakṣa --Bhūtā and Sarūpā. Had sons; eleven Rudras, besides crores of their attendants. Bhā. VI. 6. 2, 17-18.

भूत
Bhūta  (II)--a son of Pauravī and Vasudeva. Bhā. IX. 24. 47.

भूत
Bhūta  (III)--a name for Prajāpati. Vā. 100. 239.

भूत
Bhūta  (IV)--a member of the Rohiṇī family. Vi. IV. 15. 22.

भूतकेतु
Bhūtaketu --a son of Dakṣa sāvarṇi. Bhā. VIII. 13. 18.

भूतगण
Bhūtagaṇas --a deva gaṇa. Vā. 72. 50. 

भूतग्राम
Bhūtagrāma --the group of five bhūtas; 1) Br. II. 37. 6; III. 1. 32; M. 1. 15; 165. 23-24. beings are of four kinds; viviparous, aṇḍaja (egg-born), udbhijja (sprouting as plant) and svedaja (sweat produced); 2) Vā. 23. 82; 30. 101 and 227; 63. 5; 65. 122. worshipped in ceremonies prior to the construction of tanks, etc. 3) M. 53. 31; 58. 26; 166. 5-8. Born of the sacrifice of Varuṇa clothed with tamas, rajas and satva. 4) Vā. 65. 33.

भूतज्योतिस्
Bhūtajyotis --son of Sumati, and father of Vasu. Bhā. IX. 2. 17.

भूतडामरी
Bhūtaḍāmarī --a mother-goddess. M. 179. 31.

भूततन्मार्ग
Bhūtatanmārga(mātra-Vi. P.) sarga --Bhūta and others. 1) Vā. 4. 49. elementary creation proceeding from tāmasic ahamkāra; see Puruṣa. 2) Vi. I. 2. 46.

भूतनन्द
Bhūtananda --a prince who ruled from Kilikilā after the Maunas ceased to reign. Bhā. XII. 1. 32.

भूतपति
Bhūtapati --is Agni; 1) Br. IV. 2. 19; Vā. 101. 21. also Śiva. 2) Br. II. 25. 39.

भूतपति
Bhūtapatis --see Bhūtas. Bhā. I. 2. 26.

भूत
Bhūta(bali) --see Andhaka. M. 252. 5-19. 

भूतमता
Bhūtamatā --a varṇa śakti. Br. IV. 44. 58.

भूतरय
Bhūtarayas --a group of 13 gods of the Raivata epoch. Bhā. VIII. 5. 3; Br. II. 36. 51 and 56; Vi. III. 1. 21.

भूतलम्
Bhūtalam --is Pṛthvī. Br. III. 2. 21.

भूतवटम्
Bhūtavaṭam --the residence of different Bhūtas and gaṇas of Trayambaka; description of. Vā. 40. 20-6; 101. 208.

भूतवादी
Bhūtavādī --as different from Bhūtānuvādi; is also Pravātī. Br. III. 3. 125-6.

भूतविनायक
Bhūtavināyakas --leaders of Bhūtas and attendants on Rudra. Bhā. VI. 6. 18.

भूतसंताप
Bhūtasaṃtāpa --an Asura who took part in the Devāsura war between Bali and Indra. Bhā. VIII. 10. 20.

भूतसंतापन
Bhūtasaṃtāpana --a son of Hiraṇyākṣa. A follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra. Bhā. VII. 2. 18; VI. 10. [20]; Br. III. 5. 31; M. 6. 14; Vā. 67. 68; Vi. I. 21. 3.

भूतसम्प्लव
Bhūtasamplava --the period when the planets, seers, Manus and other gods cease their work and seek their abode in Maharloka. Br. II. 21. 156-64; 24. 85; 25. 106; 32. 63; 35. 168, 198 and 203. 

भूत
Bhūtas  (I)--(also Bhūtapatis)--fierce, and abandoned by those who seek mokṣa; spirits harassing children; 1) Bhā. I. 2. 26; II. 6. 13; IV. 2. 15; VI. 8. 24; IX. 14. 6; X. 6. 27; 66. 34; XI. 10. 28. followers of Rudra (Śiva) some born of sexual union; and some mind-born; belong to the line of Krodhavaśā; vanquished by Rāvaṇa; 2) Br. II. 25. 39; III. 7. 256, 359-74; 440; 8. 71; M. 8. 5. sons of Bhūti and followers of Rudra and Niśācaras; described. 3) Vā. 54. 37-43; 69. 242-56.

भूत
Bhūtas  (II)--five elements--Pṛthvī, Vāyu, Āpa, Ākāśa and Jyoti. Br. III. 72. 54; IV. 2. 116.

भूता
Bhūtā  (I)--a wife of Bhūta and a daughter of Dakṣa. Her sons were the Ekādaśa Rudras. Bhā. VI. 6. 17.

भूता
Bhūtā  (II)--a daughter of Krodhavaśā (KrodhāVā. P.), and a wife of Pulaha. Br. III. 7. 172; Vā. 69. 205.

भूतादिक
Bhūtādika sarga --creation; first is mahat sarga, second bhūta sarga, third aiṅdriyaka sarga; this is prākṛta sarga. Vā. 4. 50; 6. 58-62.

भूतादित
Bhūtādit(k)a --(Ahamkāra); of the 6th sarga; the five bhūtas: earth, waters, fire, wind and ether; each is ten times greater than the preceding one. Br. I. 5. 53-8; II. 32. 76. M. 123. 52; Vā. 101. 116.

भूतानि
Bhūtāni --three-fold movements; naimittika, prākṛtika, and ātyantika; naimittika is Brahmā; in the dissolution of creatures lies the natural destruction of all beings; ātyantika is due to knowledge, not as a result of action; from these Brahmā again begins the work of creation after he wakes  up from his sleep; during his sleep there is no continuous rain; rivers are with little or no waters; the sun's seven rays scorch the earth and draw away even the little water; everything is burnt down; no trees or plants; the heat penetrates the Pātāla and the Vāyu lokas; all the worlds are burnt down; everywhere is to be seen one flame of fire; then set in clouds in different hues and in different shapes, pour down rains and appease the fire which enters into waters, resulting in the condition of ekārṇava out of which emerges Brahmā, the first progenitor and Puruṣa; the seven sages see him; then, are gradually born all the kings one by one; similarly sages, men, gods and other things. Br. IV. 1. 128 to 207.

भूति
Bhūti  (I)--a son of Yuyudhāna and father of Yugandhara. Br. III. 71. 101; Vā. 96. 100.

भूति
Bhūti  (II)--the mother of Bhautya. Br. IV. 1. 51.

भूति
Bhūti  (III)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 74.

भूति
Bhūti  (IV)--a son of Bhautya; the future Manu. M. 9. 35; Vā. 100. 55.

भूति
Bhūti  (V)--a Sādhya; destroyer of all Asuras. M. 171. 44.

भूति
Bhūti  (VI)--gave birth to Bhūtas, followers of Rudra. Vā. 69. 242.

भूति
Bhūti  (VII)--the wife of Pulastya. Vi. I. 7. 7. 

भूतिनन्द
Bhūtinanda --the king after Dhanadharma. His brother was Nandiyaśa; the fifth ruler of Vidiśa. Br. III. 74. 182; Vā. 99. 368.

भूतिमित्र
Bhūtimitra --the son of Navakaṇṭhāyana, a Śunga ruled in Maghada for 24 years. Vā. 99. 345.

भूतेश
Bhūteśa --as calf for the Yakṣas and the Rākṣasas, bhūtas and others, to milk āsava in a skull from the earth as cow. Bhā. IV. 18. 21.

भूमन्
Bhūman  (I)--a son of Pratihartu and Stutī; wife Ṛṣikulyā, and son Udgītha. Bhā. V. 15. 5-6.

भूमन्
Bhūman  (II)--a son of Unnetā. Br. II. 14. 66.

भूमि
Bhūmi --(also Bhū) Earth personified; 1) Bhā. III. 3. 6. a Śakti; 2) Br. IV. 44. 74; M. 2. 32. equal to divam in measurement; 150 crores of yojanas; extends in all directions from Meru; wife of Dhruva and mother of Sṛṣṭi; milked as cow by Pṛthu with Cākṣuṣa Manu as calf, by Bṛhaspati for the sages, by the sun for the gods, by Antaka for Pitṛs, by Diti's son for the Asuras, by Vāsuki for the Nāgas, by Rajatanābha for the Yakṣas, by the Rākṣasas and Piśācas; 500 crores in extent. 3) Br. II. 21. 3, 12-17; 36. 96; 202. 27; IV. 37. 90. Felt the heavy weight of the Asuras and reported to Brahmā in the assemblage of Gods at Meru with special reference to Kamsa,. Viṣṇu performed an avatār as Kṛṣṇa to do away with him. 4) Vi. V. 1. 12-66. On the death of Naraka, she appealed to Kṛṣṇa to forgive his inequities and liberate him. 5) Ib. V. 29. 23-30. 

भूमिगोजरक
Bhūmigojaraka --the name of a Yakṣagaṇa. Vā. 69. 40.

भूमित्र
Bhū(mi)mitra  (I)--the son of Vasudeva Kaṇva, and father of Nārāyaṇa; ruled for 24 years (14 years M. P.). Bhā. XII. 1. 20; Br. III. 74. 158; M. 272. 34; Vi. IV. 24. 40.

भूमिमित्र
Bhūmimitra  (II)--a son of Vindhyasena, ruled for 14 years. M. 272. 9.

भूमिराक्षस
Bhūmirākṣasas --sons of Vikacā and Virūpaka; inferior in status to the Rākṣasa clan, 1) Br. III. 7. 153-5: move about in different guises unobserved both in air and on earth. 2) Vā. 69. 184-7.

भूयसि
Bhūyasi --a sage. M. 196. 26.

भूयोमेध
Bhūyomedhas --a God of Sumedhasa group. Br. II. 36. 59.

भूरि
Bhūri  (I)--a son of Somadatta of the Bāhlikas; resented Sāmba's action in seizing Lakṣmaṇā; took active part in the Rājasūya of Yudhisthira. Bhā. IX. 22. 18; X. 68. 5; 75. 6; Vā. 99. 235; Vi. IV. 20. 32; V. 35. 27.

भूरि
Bhūri  (II)--a son of Gaveṣaṇa (Gaveṣa-Vā. P.). Br. III. 71. 259; M. 47. 22; Vā. 96. 250.

भूरि
Bhūri  (III)--the eldest son of Vivakṣu. M. 50. 80. 

भूरिद्युम्न
Bhūridyumna --a son of the first Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 65 and 72.

भूरिन्द्रसेन
Bhūrindrasena --a son of Gaveṣaṇa (Gaveṣa). Br. III. 71. 259; M. 47. 22; Vā. 96. 250.

भूरिश्रवस्
Bhūriśravas  (I)--a son of Somadatta; was stationed on the west of Gomanta during its siege by Jarāsandha, and also of Mathurā. Bhā. IX. 22. 18; X. 52. 11 [11]; 50. 11 [5]; Vā. 99. 235; Vi. IV. 20. 32; V. 35. 27.

भूरिश्रवस्
Bhūriśravas  (II)--a Madhyamādhvaryu. Br. II. 33. 14.

भूरिश्रवस्
Bhūriśravas  (III)--a son of Śuka. Br. III. 8. 93; Vā. 70. 85.

भूरिश्रुत
Bhūriśruta --a son of Śuka. Br. III. 10. 81; Vā. 73. 30.

भूरिषेण
Bhūriṣeṇa  (I)--a sage who knew the yoga power of Hari; son of Brahmasāvarṇi. Bhā. II. 7. 45; VIII. 13. 21.

भूरिषेण
Bhūriṣeṇa  (II)--a son of Śaryāti. Bhā. IX. 3. 27.

भूरिसेन
Bhūrisena  (I)--a son of Sāvarṇa Manu II and one of the ten Mānavas. Br. IV. 1. 71.

भूरिसेन
Bhūrisena  (II)--a son of Brahmasāvarṇi. Vi. III. 2. 28. 

भूर्लोक
Bhūrloka --(Bhūloka) earth; 1) Br. II. 38. 12, 14; M. 7. 2; Vā. 23. 84; 30. 101, and 227; 49. 148. the first of the worlds. 2) Ib. 64. 10 11; 100. 160; 30. 65.

भूषिक
Bhūṣika --a northern country. Br. II. 16. 50.

भृगव
Bhṛgavas --Trayārṣeyas. M. 199. 10.

भृगु
Bhṛgu  (I)--born from fire; one of the ten mind-born sons of Brahmā; born of his skin; married Kardama's daughter Khyātī and had two sons and a daughter; married the daughter of Puloma and brought forth twelve sons besides Cyavana and Ānuvan; married two daughters of Dakṣa; a sage of the Cākṣuṣa epoch; 1) Bhā. III. 12. 22-23; 24. 23; IV. 1. 43; M. 3. 8; 5. 14; 9. 22; 195. 8; Vi. I. 7. 5, 7, 26, 37; 8. 15. a Mahaṛṣi; a Mantrakṛt; a Pravara; accompanied Brahmā going to Hiraṇyakaśipu; was present at the anointing of Vāmana Hari and praised the Lord and Aditi; learnt the kriyayoga from Brahmā; 2) M. 145. 90, 98; 171. 27; 195. 29. and the Vedas from Manu. 3) Bhā. VII. 3. 14; VIII. 23. 20-27; XI. 27. 3; 14. 4. Deputed by the sages to find out the greatest of the Gods, went to his father's court without invoking him in praise; Brahmā grew angry but restrained his anger. Then he went to Śiva, who embraced him. Bhṛgu told him that he did not like his behaviour when Śiva grew angry and started to attack him with his trident. He was stopped by Pārvatī's intervention. Next he called on Hari and kicked him while sleeping, on His chest. Hari coolly bore it, bowed to him and said that only then he became purified and united with Lakṣmī. Bhṛgu wondered at his patience and concluded that he was the greatest of all the gods. 4) Ib. X. 89. 2-19. Wondered at Mārkaṇḍeya's vrata; took part in crowning Vena to avoid the evils of anarchy; did not find fault with Hara violating dharma. 5) Ib. XII. 8. 12; IV. 14. 1; 29. 43; VI. 17. 12. Officiated at Viśvasṛja yajña when he cursed the followers of Śiva to become Pākhaṇḍis; created  Ṛbhus to put down the Pramathas and others who disturbed Dakṣa's sacrifice; was bound by Maṇiman and the beard cut off. It was Śiva's wish that the beard of a sheep be substituted for his original one. 6) Ib. IV. 2. 27-8; 4. 32; 5. 17 and 19; 7. 5. Was born again of Carṣaṇi and Varuṇa 7) Ib. VI. 18. 4. acted as adhvaryu in Soma's Rājasūya; 8) M. 23. 20. cursed Viṣṇu to take the form of a human being seven times for slaying his wife to protect Indra. 9) Ib. 47. 39, 105. Praised Śiva out to burn Tripura. 10) Ib. 102. 19; 126, 10; 133. 67. Performed penance on the Narmadā but was not free from anger; cursed Śiva's riding animal when it was sent to examine his mind; but still he prayed to the Lord who blessed a tīrtha at that place in his honour.

भृगु
Bhṛgu  (II)--a sage and a contemporary of Kṛṣṇa; came to see Kṛṣṇa at Syamantapañcaka; one of the sages who left for Piṇḍāraka; came to see Parīkṣit practising prāyopaveśa. Bhā. X. 84. 4; XI. 1. 12; I. 19. 9.

भृगु
Bhṛgu  (III)--a Ṛṣi presiding over the month of Nabhasya; 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 38. in the Sun's chariot in the month of Bhādrapada. 2) Vi. II. 10. 10; Vā. 29. 9; 52. 9.

भृगु
Bhṛgu  (IV)--the father of Atharvaṇa Agni. Br. II. 12. 10.

भृगु
Bhṛgu  (V)--one of the eighteen authors on architecture. M. 252. 2. 

भृगु
Bhṛgu  (VI)--in the Viśvacakra. M. 285. 6.

भृगु
Bhṛgu  (VII)--the teacher of Vyāsa. Vā. 1. 42; 3. 2; 10. 29.

भृगु
Bhṛgu  (VIII)--the author of 10380 Ṛks and 1000 mantras. Vā. 61. 71.

भृगु
Bhṛgu  (IX)--heard the Viṣṇu Purāṇa from Sārasvata and narrated it to Purukutsa. Vi. VI. 8. 45.

भृगु
Bhṛgus --Divine seers and teachers. Helped Bali in his aśvamedha. Śukra, a Bhṛgu. Bhā. VI. 7. 24; VIII. 18. 20-21; IX. 18. 14. Vā. 10. 71.

भृगुकच्छ
Bhṛgukaccha --a place on the northern bank of the Narmadā. Here Bali performed his aśvamedha. Bhā. VIII. 18. 21.

भृगुक्षेत्र
Bhṛgukṣetra --sages of, visited Dvārakā. Bhā. X. 90. 28. [4].

भृगुतीर्थम्
Bhṛgutīrtham --the place where the sage Bhṛgu performed austerities until he was covered by an ant-hill; Umā asked Śiva to bless him; the Lord replied that he was not free from anger; and tested it by sending Dharma as a bull to ruin the ant-hill; seeing it, the sage cursed the animal. But later finding that it was the Lord's act uttered the prayer, 

करुणाभ्युदयम्
Karuṇābhyudayam  and was blessed with a tīrtha on the Narmadā; 1) M. 193. 23-49. merits of the place. 2) Ib. 193. 50-60.

भृगुतुंग
Bhṛgutuṃga --a place fit for śrāddha; sacred to the Piṭrs; 1) Br. III. 13. 88; M. 22. 31; Vā. 23. 148; 77. 82. Yayāti spent the evening of his life there. 2) Br. III. 14. 83; 68. 104; Vā. 93. 102.

भृगुदास
Bhṛgudāsa --a Bhārgava. M. 195. 33.

भृगुनगर
Bhṛgunagara --sacred to Lalitāpīṭha. Br. IV. 44. 95.

भृगुपीठम्
Bhṛgupīṭham --in the ears of the personified Veda. Vā. 104. 81.

भृङ्गराज
Bhṛṅgarāja --a bird; 1) Vā. 36. 2. a god to be worshipped before building houses and palaces. 2) M. 219. 19; 253. 25; 268. 14.

भृङ्गि
Bhṛṅgi  (I)--the head of a Śiva gaṇa. Br. III. 41. 28; IV. 30. 75; 34. 89.

भृङ्गि
Bhṛṅgi  (II)--an image of, in attendance on Śiva. M. 259. 24; 266. 42.

भृतकील
Bhṛtakīla --a Kauśika Brahmiṣṭha. M. 145. 112. 

भृती
Bhṛtī --one of the ten branches of the Rohita group of devas. Vā. 100. 90.

भृत्य
Bhṛtyas --servants engaged for service, those who do not do properly or neglect, are liable to be punished with a fine of 8 Kṛṣṇalas besides being deprived of their wages; 1) M. 227. 9. conduct of, reported by cāras; 2) Ib. 215. 89; Vā. 110. 54. not loyal in the kaliyuga. 3) Ib. 58. 42.

भृश
Bhṛśa --to be worshipped in house-building, with fish. M. 253. 24; 268. 12.

भृशा
Bhṛśā --a queen of Uśīnara and mother of Nṛga. M. 48. 16-17.

भृशी
Bhṛśī --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 5.

भेत्त
Bhetta --a Vaikuṇṭha God. Br. II. 36. 57.

भेद
Bheda  (I)--one of the upāyas; to be used against the wicked, the insolent and the proud; makes the enemy afraid of himself and brings him under his control; this upāya is praised by statesmen; the king must endeavour to practise this against the enemy through his cognates. M. 222. 2; 223, 1, 4, 15. 

भेद
Bheda  (II)--a son of Ṛkṣa; had five sons, Mudgala and others among whom were distributed the kingdom later known as Pāñcāla. Vā. 99. 195.

भेरि
Bheri --drums beaten in rituals for tank digging; 1) M. 58. 22. a warmusical instrument; 2) Ib. 135. 83; Vā. 37. 12; 40. 24. sounded by the Asuras and Devas in the battle of Tripuram; 3) M. 136. 27, 53. a call to arms; 4) Ib. 148. 39. in the Tārakāmaya. 5) Ib. 149. 2; 177. 24. in Rāma's abhiṣecana. 6) Vi. IV. 4. 99.

भेरुण्ड
Bheruṇḍa --a bird, born of Jaṭāyu. M. 6. 36.

भेरुण्डा
Bheruṇḍā --an Akṣaradevī. Br. IV. 19. 58; 25. 95; 37. 33.

भैरव
Bhairava  (I)--a Śiva gaṇa. Br. III. 41. 27; IV. 14. 7; 17. 4; 19. 78-9; 33. 17.

भैरव
Bhairava  (II)--An epithet of Rudra; the form assumed by Śiva when Gaurī returned from penance; She became Bhairavī; 1) M. 158. 24; 179. 1. Image of, to be placed in each temple but not in mūlāyantana. 2) Ib. 252. 10; 259. 14.

भैरवम्
Bhairavam  (I)--a tīrtha on the banks of Carmanvatī sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 31.

भैरवम्
Bhairavam  (II)--tapas performed by Brahmā. Vā. 26. 10. 

भैरवत्वम्
Bhairavatvam --an incarnation of Śiva (Bhairava s.v.). M. 1. 8.

भैरव
Bhairavas --an Apsarasa clan from Mṛtyu. Vā. 69. 57.

भैरवी
Bhairavī --an epithet of Umā; when Śiva is Bhairava, Umā is Bhairavī; 1) M. 158. 25. a mother-goddess. 2) Br. IV. 7. 72; 44. 22.

भोगवती
Bhogavatī  (I)--the capital of the Nāgas, compared to the city of Puramjana; 1) Bhā. I. 11. 11; IV. 25. 15. north of Vāsukihrada, a sacred spot of Prayāgā. 2) M. 163. 80.

भोगवती
Bhogavatī  (II)--the name of Gangā in Pātāla. Bhā. X. 70. 44.

भोगवर्धन
Bhogavardhanas --the people of the southern country. Br. II. 16. 58; Vā. 45. 127.

भोगि
Bhogi --son of Śeṣa, the Nāga king. Br. III. 74. 180; Vā. 99. 367.

भोगिनी
Bhoginī --a Rahasya Yoginī Devī. Br. IV. 19. 48.

भोज
Bhoja  (I)--a Yadu prince. He once dreamt that he ate the remnants of the food of his enemy, and that his enemies deprived him of his wives, and kingdom. This caused deep misery in his mind. He left his home and bestowed all his thoughts on Paramātman from that day: entered Brahmanirvāṇa. Fought with Akrūra at Prabhāsā. Bhā. X. 36. 33; VI. 15. 26 [1-4]; XI. 30. 16. Br. III. 61. 23. 

भोज
Bhoja  (II)--a king noted for his large elephant forces. Br. II. 71. 126-7.

भोज
Bhoja  (III)--a son of Bali. Br. III. 5. 43.

भोज
Bhoja  (IV)--a son of Jāmbavatī. Br. III. 7. 303.

भोज
Bhoja  (V)--a son of Pratikṣetra and father of Hṛdīka. M. 44. 80.

भोज
Bhojas  (I)--a Vindhya clan; 1) Br. II. 16. 64; Vā. 45. 132; 86. 28. in Dvāravatī: one of the five clans (gaṇas) of the Haihayas beginning with Druhyu, son of Yayāti; 2) Br. III. 69. 52; 74. 265; M. 34. 30; 43. 48; 44. 69; 163. 72; Vā. 94. 52. had two hundred branches; 3) Ib. 99. 452. all of them Kṣatriyas; 4) Ib. 32. 48. Kaśyapa gotrakāras. 5) M. 199. 2.

भोज
Bhojas  (II)--a Yādava tribe to which Kamsa belonged: were related to the Pāṇḍavas; 1) Bhā. X. 1. 35, 37 and 69; IX. 24. 11 and 63; I. 14. 25; M. 114. 52; 273. 70. defended Dvārakā against the enemies and praised the heroic deeds of Kṛṣṇa; 2) Bhā. I. 11. 11; IX. 24. 63. Kamsa planned in vain to vanquish them. Fought with their kith and kin and ended their lives; 3) Ib. X. 36. 33; 39. 25; XI. 30. 18. line of the, traced from Mahābhoja; kings of Mṛttikāvara Pura; hence Mārttikāvaras: killed Sātvata Śatrughna and left Dvārakā with Akrūra. 4) Vi. IV. 13. 7, 11.

भोजकट
Bhojakaṭa --the capital of Rukmin: the city founded by him for his residence, as he wanted to keep his word not to enter Kuṇḍina without killing Kṛṣṇa. Here was celebrated the marriage of Aniruddha and which Balarāma and others attended and then left for Dvārakā; 1) Bhā. X. 54. 52; 61. 19 and 23 [5]; 61. 26 and 40. the svayamvara of Pradymna's daughter took place at. 2) Vi. V. 28. 9. 

भोज
Bhoja(tvam) --usually a title of a monarch; 1) Br. III. 71. 194, 223; Vā. 96. 190. Śamīka, abandoned this title being a Rājaṛṣi. 2) M. 46. 28.

भोजन
Bhojana --Mt. of Krauñcadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 21.

भोजा
Bhojā  (I)--the queen of Viravrata: mother of Manthu and Pramanthu. Bhā. V. 15. 15.

भोजा
Bhojā  (II)--the wife of Śūra; mother of ten sons and five daughters. M. 46. 1.

भौतपायन
Bhautapāyanas --Kaśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 3.

भौतिकम्
Bhautikam --see Vaidyuta--one of the three fires originating in waters. Br. II. 24. 6; Vā. 53. 5.

भौत्य
Bhautya --the 10th Manu (14th. Vā. P.) of the future; son of Bhūti and Kavī; 1) Br. IV. 1. 51; M. 9. 35; Vā. 62. 4; 100. 55, 110. the 14th Paryāya: under him the Kalpa comes to an end. 2) Br. II. 36. 4; IV. 1. 105-7, 116.

भौम
Bhauma  (I)--a name of the Asura, Naraka (s.v.) a Saiṃhikeya Asura. Bhā. I. 10. 29; XII. 3. 11; Br. III. 6. 20.

भौम
Bhauma  (II)--Mars: one of the nine planets; also called Angāraka and Kumāra; of red colour; 1) Br. II. 23. 84; M. 93. 10; Vi. II. 12. 18. his chariot drawn by eight horses. 2) M. 127. 4. 

भौम
Bhauma  (III)--a son of Rucira. M. 50. 36.

भौम
Bhauma  (IV)--the XIV Manu; Śuci is Indra; five groups of gods; Agnibāhu and others are sages; Ūru, Gambhīra and others, his sons. Vi. III. 2. 42-5.

भौमज्ञ
Bhaumajña --a name of Budha. Vā. 111. 5.

भौमतापन
Bhaumatāpana --of the Parāśara family; (white). M. 201. 33.

भौमरि
Bhaumari --a son of Satyabhāmā. Vā. 96. 239.

भौमरिका
Bhauma(e)rikā --a daughter of Satyabhāmā. Vā. 96. 240; Vi. V. 32. 1.

भौमवार
Bhaumavāra --Tuesday; unfit for commencing house building. M. 253. 7.

भौवन
Bhauvana  (I)--a son of Manthu and Satyā. His queen was Dūṣaṇā and son Tvaṣṭa. Bhā. V. 15. 15.

भौवन
Bhauvana  (II)--a son of Mahān, married Irāvatī: father of Airāvaṇa, the vehicle of Indra; sang the Rathantara. Br. II. 14. 69; III. 7. 324-6; Vā. 33. 59.

भौवन
Bhauvana  (III)--a son of Bhṛgu. M. 195. 12. 

भौवन
Bhauvana  (IV)--see Airāvata. Vā. 69. 209.

भ्रमावर्त
Bhramāvarta --of Siddhi: to go about as if aimlessly and with an absent mind induced by the inner soul. Vā. 12. 7, 11 and 12.

भ्रमिशिर
Bhramiśiras --a Mauneya. Vā. 69. 3.

भ्रमी
Bhramī --a daughter of Śiśumāra and wife of Dhruva; mother of Vatsara. Bhā. IV. 10. 1; 13. 11.

भ्राजित
Bhrājit(k)as --a gaṇa of the epoch of Bhautya Manu: these are the seven rivers; 1) Br. IV. 1. 106-8. a group of gods of the XIV epoch of Manu. 2) Vi. III. 2. 43.

भ्राजिष्ठ
Bhrājiṣṭha --a son of Ghṛtapṛṣṭha of the Plakṣadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 21.

भ्राजिष्णु
Bhrājiṣṇu --resides in the Vaibhrāja hill of Plakṣa. Br. II. 19. 13.

भ्राष्ट्रकायणि
Bhrāṣṭrakāyaṇi --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 24.

भ्राष्ट्रकृत्
Bhrāṣṭrakṛt --an Ārṣeyapravara; (Angiras). M. 196. 21.

भ्रुकुटी
Bhrukuṭī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 19.

भ्रूणहत्त्या
Bhrūṇahattyā --(abortion): a person guilty of, gets released by performing śubhasaptami; 1) M. 80. 12; Vā. 101. 152. relieved by gṛahabali; 2) M. 93. 139. common in Kali. 3) Ib. 144. 55; 192. 16. 

मकर
Makara  (I)--a Mt. to the north of Meru. Bhā. V. 16. 27.

मकर
Makara  (II)--a sea monster; gift of a golden one in the ceremony of digging tanks, etc. M. 58. 19.

मकर
Makara  (III)--one of the eight nidhis of Kubera. Vā. 41. 10.

मकर
Makara  (IV)--the Tamil month, Tai; with Sūrya, 1) Vā. 105. 48. in the Capricornus; the sun entering which, Uttarāyaṇa commences. 2) Vi. II. 8. 28, 68.

मकर
Makaras --the sons born to the daughters of Ṛkṣa. Br. III. 7. 415.

मकरध्वज
Makaradhvaja --is Madana, God of Love with the fish standard. Br. IV. 11. 28; 19. 67; 30. 56; M. 154. 244; 261. 53.

मकरध्वजा
Makaradhvajā --a śakti. Br. IV. 44. 74.

मकरन्दक
Makarandaka --sacred to Caṇḍikā M. 13. 43.

मकरव्यूह
Makaravyūha --Jarāsandha arranged his army in this vyūha and attacked the Yadus; but it was broken by Kṛṣṇa with trees as missiles. Bhā. X. 52. 6[1-4]. 

मकार
Makāra --is Pluta, consonant and svarloka; the third mātrā is plutavatī, protracted as a vowel. Vā. 20. 9, 10, 14.

मक्रुणा
Makruṇā --a R. of the Bhāratavarṣa. Vā. 45. 101.

मक्षिक
Makṣikas --do not sit on poisoned food. M. 219. 17.

मख
Makha --same as yajña; 1) M. 7. 62; Vā. 97. 26. a share of it was rescued to the Maruts. 2) M. 7. 65.

मखरतीर्थम्
Makharatīrtham --got by churning the araṇi of the śamī wood. Vā. 112. 51.

मखशत्रु
Makhaśatru --a commander and son of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 81; 26. 48.

मखापेत
Makhāpeta --the Rākṣasa presiding over the month of Ūrja. Bhā. XII. 11. 44.

मखास्कन्दि
Makhāskandi --a son and commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 81; 26. 48.

मगध
Magadha  (I)--the kingdom of Jarāsandha (s.v.), see also Māgadha. Bhā. III. 3. 10; Br. III. 39. 2, 8. 

मगध
Magadha  (II) (c)--a Janapada; an eastern kingdom; 1) Br. II. 16. 55; 18. 51; Vā. 45. 111. 47. 48; 62. 147; 99. 294; Vi. II. 3. 16. got from Pṛthu by Māgadha; kingdom of the Māgadhas; 2) Br. II. 36. 172; M. 50. 27. kings of; 3) Bhā. IX. 22. 44-5. sometimes ruled by the Nāgas; 4) Br. III. 74. 195. kingdom of Mahāratha Bṛhadratha; 5) Vā. 99. 221. under the Guptas. 6) Ib. 99. 383; Vi. IV. 24. 63.

मगध
Magadha  (III)--king Viśvasphāṭika pulled down Kṣatriyas and established new varṇas; people of, like Kaivartas, Baṭu, Pulinda and Brahmanas. Vi. IV. 24. 61.

मगधगोविन्द
Magadhagovindas --a Janapada of the East. Vā. 45. 123.

मघवान्
Maghavān  (I)--another name of Indra; 1) Bhā. I. 16. 21. Br. II. 13. 79; Vā. 64. 7. served as calf when the Gods milked the earth; 2) Br. II. 36. 206. as Vāyu he mixed up the garments of girls playing in a pleasure garden especially those of Śarmiṣṭhā and Devayānī; 3) M. 27. 3-4; 138. 1. wife Śaci. 4) Vā. 30. 72.

मघवान्
Maghavān  (II)--a dānava. Br. III. 6. 5.

मघा
Maghā  or Maghas--a constellation attached to Śiśumāra; 1) Bhā. V. 23. 6; VII. 14. 22; XII. 2. 28-9. Vā. 66. 49; 80. 44; 81. 25; 82. 6; 99. 423. śrāddha in, marks the rise in social status. 2) Br. III. 17. 21; 18. 5; M. 17. 3; 54. 18; 55. 14; 204. 5.

मंकनम्
Maṃkanam --Nikumbha appeared in the disguise of a barber of this name in a dream to Divodāsa before the ruin of the city and asked him to find his abode in the outskirts of the kingdom. Vā. 92. 38. 

मङ्गल
Maṅgala  (I)--the Matsya king, slain by Paraśurāma. Br. III. 38. 49, 51.

मन्गल
Mangala  (II)--a commander of Bhaṇḍa, vanquished by Svapneśī. Br. IV. 21. 85; 28. 41.

मन्गल
Mangala  (III)--a Yāmadeva. Vā. 31. 7.

मङ्गलप्रस्थ
Maṅgalaprastha --a Mt. in Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 16.

मङ्गला
Maṅgalā  (I)--a servant maid of Pārvatī. Br. IV. 40. 25.

मन्गला
Mangalā  (II)--a goddess enshrined at Gangā; a mother goddess. M. 13. 35; 179. 21.

मन्गला
Mangalā  (III)--Gaurī; 1) Vā. 106. 58. prayer to. 2) Ib. 112. 58.

मन्गला
Mangalā  (IV)--Lakṣmī. Vā. 109. 24.

मङ्गलारार्ति
Maṅgalārārti --done by women to Bhaṇḍa's sons marching against Lalitā's host. Br. IV. 26. 62.

मंगु
Maṃgu --a son of Gāndinī. Br. III. 71. 111; Vā. 96. 110. 

मज्जा
Majjā --a śakti. Br. IV. 44. 90.

मञ्जरी
Mañjarī --a Varṇa śakti. Br. IV. 44. 59.

मञ्जुघोषा
Mañjughoṣā --an Apsarasa. Br. IV. 33. 19.

मठ
Maṭhas --public halls in the city of Tripura; 1) M. 139. 20. institutions of. 2) Br. IV. 38. 57.

मणि
Maṇi  (I)--a jewel of the king. Br. II. 29. 75; IV. 21. 12; Vā. 57. 68; 78. 53.

मणि
Maṇi  (II)--a Kādraveya Nāga. Br. III. 7. 37; Vā. 69. 74.

मणि
Maṇi  (III)--gems as ornaments of Nāgas. Vi. II. 5. 6.

मणिक
Maṇika --a big water vessel into which Manu threw the growing fish. M. 1. 20.

मणिकर्णिका
Maṇikarṇikā --one of the five principal tīrthas at Benares; a person dying here will have his desires fulfilled. M. 182. 24; 185. 69.

मणिकूट
Maṇikūṭa --a boundary hill in Plakṣa. Bhā. V. 20. 4. 

मणिग्रीव
Maṇigrīva --a son of Kubera (see Nalakūbara). Bhā. X. 9. 22-23; 10 (whole).

मणिचक
Maṇicaka --a son of Havya. Vā. 33. 16.

मणिचकम्
Maṇicakam --a varṣa round the Syāma hill of Śākadvīpam. Vā. 33. 18; 49. 86.

मणितटा
Maṇitaṭā --a R. of the Bhadrā country. Vā. 43. 29.

मणिदत्त
Maṇidatta --a son of Maṇibhadra. Vā. 69. 154.

मणिधर
Maṇidhara --a Yakṣa living in the (Hemaśṛnga M. P.) Lohita hill; son of Rajatanābha. Br. II. 18. 12; 36. 216; M. 121. 13.

मणिधान्यकवंश
Maṇidhānyakavaṃśa --enjoyed the Naiṣadha, Naimiṣaka, Kālakośa and Kañjanapadas. Vi. IV. 24. 66.

मणिधान्यज
Maṇidhānyajas --members of the Maṇidhānya royal family who ruled over the Niṣadhas, Yadukas, Śaiśitas and Kālatoyakas. Vā. 99. 384; Br. III. 74. 196.

मणिनाग
Maṇināga --the Nāga residing in the third Talam. Br. II. 20. 30.

मणिपर्वतम्
Maṇiparvatam --the crest jewel of Mandara stolen by Naraka; Kṛṣṇa removed it from Prāgjyotiṣa, after killing him. Vi. V. 29. 10. 34; 30. 1. 

मणिपुर
Maṇipura --a city; Arjuna married the daughter of the king of Maṇipura. Bhā. IX. 22. 32; Vi. IV. 20. 50.

मणिभद्र
Maṇibhadra --a son of Rajatanābha, (Bhadrā-Vā. P.) married Puṇyajanī who was the mother of a number of Yakṣas; 1) Br. III. 7. 120; Vā. 69. 152, 157. the commander of the army of the Yakṣas living in Candraprabhā; lived on the hill adjoining Caitraratha; 2) Br. II. 18. 7-8; M. 121. 8-9. devoted to Lalitā; 3) Br. IV. 33. 78. Yakṣa senāpati. 4) Vā. 47. 7.

मणिमत्
Maṇimat  (also Maṇiman)--a Yaksa devoted to Lalitā; followed Satī going to her father's sacrifice; 1) Bhā. IV. 4. 4; Br. IV. 33. 78. seized Bhṛgu at Dakṣa's sacrifice. 2) Bhā. IV. 5. 17.

मणिमती
Maṇimatī --a R. sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 39.

मणिमन्
Maṇiman --a son of Maṇivara. Vā. 69. 158.

मणिमन्त
Maṇimanta  (I)--a Yakṣa; a son of Puṇyajanī and Maṇibhadra. Br. III. 7. 123.

मणिमन्त
Maṇimanta  (II)--a Mt. in Śālmalidvīpa. Br. III. 7. 453.

मणिमन्त्र
Maṇimantra --a Nāga of the Vitalam. Vā. 50. 29. 

मणिवक
Maṇivaka --a son of Havya, after whom was called the Maṇivakavarṣa. Br. II. 14. 17-9.

मणिवकम्
Maṇivakam --(c) of Śākadvīpa. Br. II. 14. 19; 19. 92.

मणिवक्त्र
Maṇivaktra --a son of Āpa. M. 5. 22.

मनिवप्रा
Manivaprā --a R. of the Bhadrā country. Vā. 43. 28.

मणिवर
Maṇivara  (I)--a son of Rajatanābha, his wife, Devajanī 1) Br. III. 7. 120; 72. 2. a Yakṣa king in Kailāsa; 2) Vā. 41. 25. resides in the Lohita hill. 3) Ib. 47. 12.

मणिवर
Maṇivara  (II)--a son of Bhadrā; his wife, Devajanī or Devajananī; gave birth to a number of sons, known as Guhyakas. Vā. 62. 183; 69. 151; 97. 2.

मणीवर्तन
Maṇīvartana --the place where three crores of its inhabitants were slain by Arjuna. Vā. 67. 73-4.

मणिवाहन
Maṇivāhana --one of the sons of Vidyoparicara. Vā. 99. 222.

मणिशील
Maṇiśīla --a Mt. to the east of Aruṇoda. Vā. 36. 18; 37. 16.

मणिस्थक
Maṇisthaka --a Kādraveya. Nāga. Br. III. 7. 36. 

मण्ड
Maṇḍa --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 21.

मण्डप
Maṇḍapas --three kinds of, superior, middling and inferior; the different varieties are Puṣpaka, Puṣpabhadra, Suvrata, Amṛtananda, Kauśalya, Buddhisamkīrṇa, Gajabhadrā, Jayāvaha, Śrīvatsa, Vijaya, Vāstukīrti, Śrutinjaya, Yajñabhadra, Viśāla, Suśliṣṭa, Śatrumardana, Bhāgapañca, Nandana, Mānava, Mānabhadraka, Sugrīva. Harita, Karnikāra, Śatardhika, Simha, Śyāmabhadra, Subhadra, all totalling 27; these may be triangular, circular, semi-circular, eight cornered, sixteen cornered, etc.; generally ten kinds of doorways are furnished avoiding Vedha; fruit and flower trees are to be grown all round; a pool of water must be maintained; on the south a tapovanam, on the north a devī temple, on the north-east a kitchen and on the south-east a Vināyaka shrine and then Yajñaśālā; these constitute a temple; the bell near the gateway. M. 270. 1-36.

मण्डल
Maṇḍala  (I)--a mountain kingdom. M. 114. 56.

मण्डल
Maṇḍala  (II)--(Vartula): a palace in the form of a circle; the toraṇa is twenty hastas. M. 269. 36, 49.

मण्डल
Maṇḍala  (III)--of the sun; the place of all planets, stars and the moon. Vā. 53. 28.

मण्डलम्
Maṇḍalam  (I)--(Brāhmaṇam) to be selected for recitation at śrāddha. M. 17. 39. 

मण्डलम्
Maṇḍalam  (II)--a place near Prayāgā protected by Hari; 1) M. 104. 9. five yojanas in extent; 2) Ib. 108. 9. every step there, is equal to an aśvamedha. 3) Ib. 111. 8.

मण्डला
Maṇḍalā --one of the ten pīṭhas for images; round in shape with a number of mekhalas. M. 262. 6, 9, 17.

मण्डलाध्यायम्
Maṇḍalādhyāyam --to be uttered in installing an image. M. 265. 26.

मण्डलेश्वर
Maṇḍaleśvaras --provincial heads. Br. III. 38. 20.

मण्डवाय
Maṇḍavāya --the hill for performing śrāddha. Vā. 77. 56.

मण्डूक
Maṇḍūka --a Yakṣa; son of Punyajanī and Maṇibhadra. Br. III. 7. 123.

मण्डूकम्
Maṇḍūkam --gift of a copper one in ceremonials connected with the digging of tanks. M. 58. 19.

मण्डोदरी
Maṇḍodarī  (I)--the queen of Rāvaṇa; heard of Rāvaṇa's death, and went to the battlefield and bewailed the fate of all Rākṣasas. Bhā. IX. 10. 24-28.

मण्डोदरी
Maṇḍodarī  (II)--a daughter of Maya and Rambhā. Br. III. 6. 29. 

मतङ्ग
Mataṅga --a sage of great repute; father of Mātanga; 1) Br. IV. 31. 90. footprint of, seen in the Bharatāśrama. 2) Vā. 77. 98.

मतङ्गपदम्
Mataṅgapadam --the āśrama of Matanga, the sage, at Gayā where the performance of Pitṛ śrāddha is an act of merit. Vā. 108. 25.

मतङ्गवनम्
Mataṅgavanam --fit for performing śrāddha offerings. Br. III. 13. 106.

मतङ्गवापी
Mataṅgavāpī --a sacred place for performing śrāddha in the Kosala country; 1) Vā. 77. 36. in Gayā sacred to Matanga. 2) Ib. 111. 24.

मता
Matā --a goddess enshrined at Pārāvārataṭa. M. 13. 44.

मति
Mati  (I)--a Yāma deva; 1) Br. II. 13. 92; Vā. 31. 6. addressed as, by Brahmā. 2) Ib. 23. 8.

मति
Mati  (II)--an Ābhūtaraya god. Br. II. 36. 55; Vā. 62. 48.

मति
Mati  (III)--a Bhavya god. Br. II. 36. 72.

मति
Mati  (IV)--Bhagavān so-called because the Kṣetrajña has a knowledge of kṣetra. Vā. 59. 77.

मत्त
Matta --an attribute of Vighneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 69. 

मत्तकासिक
Mattakāsikas --a Janapada of the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 15.

मत्स्य
Matsya  (I) (c)--in the Madhyadeśa, on the way from Dvārakā to Hastināpura; 1) Bhā. I. 10. 34; X. 71. 22; Br. II. 16. 41; 18. 51; M. 121. 50. visited by Vidura; 2) Bhā. III. 1. 24. king of, vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. 3) Ib. II. 7. 35.

मत्स्य
Matsya  (II)--an avatār of Viṣṇu; 1) Bhā. I. 15. 35; X. 2. 40; XI. 4. 18; Br. III. 7. 433; 22. 66; 57. 61; IV. 4. 22; 29. 136; M. 260. 39; 285. 6; 290. 23; Vi. I. 4. 8. once during a Pralaya an Asura, Hayagrīva, carried off the Vedas when Hari took the form of a fish with one horn and fell into the palm of the Draviḍa king Satyavrata, performing ablutions; finding that it outgrew the size of his palm he took it to a pond; it outgrew the size of the pond when it was taken to a lake; it was also too small to hold it; hence after many trials it was taken to the sea; addressed by the king the fish revealed to him his true form and warned him of the Pralaya coming in a week and prepared him to get into a boat to be sent by him and have it tied to its horn; the deluge came and Satyavrata did as was directed; when they were all floating on the sea, Matsya Hari narrated to him the Matsya Purāṇa; after the deluge Matsya killed the demon, Hayagrīva and recovered the Vedas; through his blessings Satyavrata became Vaivasvata Manu; 2) Bhā. VIII. ch. 24 (whole). appeared to Vaivasvata Manu during deluge; protected Manu and others; 3) Ib. II. 7. 12; XI. 4. 18; M. 22. 92. the form of Viṣṇu worshipped in Ramyaka. 4) Bhā. V. 18. 24.

मत्स्य
Matsya  (III)--a Vasu; a son of Uparicara and a Cedipa. Bhā. IX. 22. 6; M. 50. 28.

मत्स्य
Matsya  (IV)--gift of a silver one during the ceremonial relating to the digging of tanks. M. 58. 19. 

मत्स्य
Matsya  (V)--the image of. M. 259. 2.

मत्स्य
Matsya  (VI)--the disciple of Śākalya. Vā. 60. 64.

मत्स्य
Matsya  (VII)--also Matsya Purāṇa; a Mahā Purāṇa consisting of 14000 ślokas, 1) Vi. III. 6. 23; Bhā. XII. 7. 24; 13. 8. styled as Purāṇa Samhita with details of Sānkhya, Yoga and Karma narrated by Matsya Hari to king Satyavrata during the deluge. 2) Ib. VIII. 24. 54-5.

मत्स्य
Matsyas --a trible; country of the; 1) M. 114. 35. placed on the East of the Gomanta hill by Jarāsandha; 2) Bhā. X. 52. 11[7]. enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus; 3) Ib. X. 52. 50 (V) 2. followed Bhīma in his conquests; 4) Ib. X. 72. 13. rose against Śiśupāla; 5) Ib. X. 74. 41. heard of Kṛṣṇa going to Mithilā and met him with presents; 6) Ib. X. 86. 20. their king was Virāṭa; 7) Ib. X. 52. 11[7]. he went to Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse. 8) Ib. X. 82. 13.

मत्स्यकाल
Matsyakāla --a son of Vidyoparicara. Vā. 99. 222.

मत्स्यगन्ध
Matsyagandha --an Ārṣeya Pravara (Bhārgava). M. 195. 43.

मत्स्यदग्ध
Matsyadagdha --not to marry with Angiras or Mudgalas. M. 196. 42.

मत्स्यनदी
Matsyanadī --a R. sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 49.

मत्स्यमांस
Matsyamāṃsa --for manes. Vi. III. 16. 1. 

मत्स्ययोनिजा
Matsyayonijā --the birth of Pitṛkanyā Acchodā in the 28th dvāpara; wife of Parāśara and mother of Vyāsa. M. 14. 13; Vā. 73. 16.

मत्स्यराज
Matsyarāja --was Mangala, (s.v). Br. III. 38. 42; 39. 1.

मत्स्याच्छाद्य
Matsyācchādya --a Pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 16.

मथन
Mathana --a commander of Tāraka's army; the special arm was the noose; 1) M. 148. 43, 54. threw darts on Viṣṇu; 2) Ib. 150. 224. on horse back; 3) Ib. 151. 5. Garuḍa was ordered to break his chariot; overpowered by the gadā of Mādhava, Mathana fell dead when Mahiṣa appeared on the scene. 4) Ib. 152. 7-14.

मथनम्
Mathanam --the divine union of Śakta and Śakti resulting in 25 truths. Br. IV. 8. 29, 33.

मथित
Mathita  (I)--born of Pulaha. Br. III. 7. 179.

मथित
Mathita  (II)--an Ārṣeya Pravara. (Bhārgava). M. 195. 36.

मथित
Mathita  (III)--a son of Bharatāgni. Vā. 29. 8.

मथुरा
Mathurā  (I)--founded by Śatrughna after killing Lavaṇa; 1) Bhā. IX. 11. 14; Br. III. 63. 186; IV. 40. 19; Vā. 88. 185-6; Vi. IV. 4. 101. capital of Subāhu and Śūrasena; here was celebrated the marriage of Vasudeva and Devakī when the couple  were the recipients of rich presents of elephants, horses, dāsis and others; Kamsa joined in the festivities when a voice in the sky said that her eighth son was to kill him; 2) Bhā. X. 1. 27-34; 2. 4. visited by Nanda to pay his annual tribute; left by Nanda; 3) Ib. X. 5. 19, 32; 6. 31. capital of the Yadus, besieged by Jarāsandha and his followers; defended by the Yādavas on all the four sides; entered by Kṛṣṇa after defeating Jarāsandha; second attempt of Jarāsandha on the city with Bāṇa's army; entered by Kṛṣṇa after a third success over Jarāsandha; 4) Ib. X. 50. 4. 11 [1-9], 20 [1-5], 36-40. 50 (V) 6, [51 (V) 21-3], [52 (V) 9]. Rājamārga and sabhā of; 5) Ib. X. 50. 10-13. with a huge army Kṛṣṇa and Rāma returned to; besieged by Yavana; abandoned by Kṛṣṇa in fear, for Dvārakā; 6) Ib. X. 53 (V) 21-2, 50, 45, 53; 72. 31. reached by Rāma, Kṛṣṇa, Akrūra and others; Gopa's camp outside the city; entered by the brothers and Gopas; the city described; joy of the women at the sight of the brothers; 7) Ib. X. ch. 41 (whole); 42. 23. left by Akrūra for Vraja by chariot, as also by Uddhava; Gopis' enquiry about Kṛṣṇa. Uddhava's return to Mathurā from Vraja. 8) Ib. X. 38. 1; 47. 21, 68. reached by Nanda, Gopas and Gopis after Vasudeva's sacrifice at Syamantapañcaka; 9) Ib. X. 84. 69. Vajra anointed king of, by Yudhiṣṭhira; 10) Ib. I. 15. 39. sometime ruled by seven Nāga kings; 11) Br. III. 74. 194. sacred to Devakī. 12) M. 13. 39. Vasudeva's residence in; 13) Vi. V. 3. 16. left by Akrūra in a chariot as directed by Kamsa to fetch Kṛṣṇa from Vraja; Kṛṣṇa's visit to, which travelling by chariot took one day; 14) Ib. V. 15. 24; 18. 9ff. ruled by Kamsa and then Ugrasena; 15) Ib. V. 19. 8 ff. evacuated for fear of Kālayavana and migrated to Dvārakā, 16) Ib. V. 21. 32; 23. 15. temple of Hari at. 17) Ib. VI. 8. 31.

मथुरा
Mathurā  (II)--(Dakṣiṇa) visited by Balarāma. Bhā. X. 79. 15. 

मथुरा
Mathurā  (III)--the capital of the Nāgas of whom seven are distinguished. Vā. 99. 383.

मथुरानाथ
Mathurānātha --is Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 31.

मथुरापीठम्
Mathurāpīṭham --in the neck of the personified Veda. Vā. 104. 80.

मद
Mada  (I)--followed Satī going to Dakṣa's sacrifice. Bhā. IV. 4. 4.

मद
Mada  (II)--a son of Kali and Surā. Br. III. 59. 9; Vā. 84. 9.

मद
Mada  (III)--born out of the ahankāra of Brahmā. M. 3. 11.

मद
Mada  (IV)--an Ābhūtaraya god. Vā. 62. 48.

मदम्
Madam --a lake of Kailāsa. Br. II. 18. 3.

मदगल
Madagala --a Śrutaṛṣi. Br. II. 33. 11.

मदजिह्व
Madajihva --a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 73. 

मदन
Madana  (I)--a name of Kāma, God of Love: also Makaradhvaja (s.v.); 1) Bhā. XI. 4. 8. created by Brahmā when he looked at Mahālakṣmī after praying to Janārdana; was given the flower dart and the sugarcane bow; Hari blessed him with all conquest and no defeat; 2) Br. IV. 8. 24-9; 11. 7. performed Saubhāgya--Śayanam; 3) M. 60. 49. at the request of the Devas and persecuted by Tāraka, Madana took courage and secretly entered Śiva's abode; the latter grew angry and burnt him with his third eye; 4) Br. IV. 11. 28. remembered by Indra, went to him and was ordered to create sexual desire in Śiva; he got frightened at Śiva's third eye, but pressed by Indra he agreed to meet the Lord and sent his arrow of Mohana when Siva's third eye burnt him down; Rati wept with Madhu or Spring and both went to Śiva; Rati praised him for grace; Śiva replied that Madana would attain fame as Ananga in the world sometime hence. 5) M. 154. 212-51, 260-70.

मदन
Madana  (II)--the seventh son of Devakī. M. 46. 19.

मदन
Madana(ka) --a commander of Bhaṇḍa sent to aid Viṣanga. Br. IV. 21. 78; 25. 27.

मदनद्वादशीव्रतम्
