Manu  (VII)--a son of Śighraka; established himself in Kalāpagrāma by yoga. Vā. 88. 210.

मनु
Manu  (VIII)--one of the sons of Madhu. Vā. 95. 45.

मनु
Manu  (IX) (Raivata)--the fifth Manu; son of Priyavrata and brother of Tāmasa; Bali and others were his sons. Vibhu was Indra; Bhūtarayas were the gods of the epoch; Vaikuṇṭha was the manifestation of Hari in this manvantara. 1) Bhā. V. 1. 28; VIII. 5. 2-5. Devabāhu and others were the seven sages; served as calf to milk the earth. 2) Br. II. 36. 3, 51. 64; 37. 17. 8. 

मनु
Manu  (X)--(Cākṣuṣa)--a son of Viśvakarman (Viśveśa-M. P.) and Kṛtī. Father of Viśvas and Sādhyas. Bhā. VI. 6. 15; M. 171. 48.

मनु
Manu  (XI) (Sāvarṇi)--the eighth Manu. A son of Chāyā and Vivasvān. Father of Nirmoka and other sons. In this epoch Sutapas, Virajas Amitābhas, Mukhyas were the gods. Bali was Indra. Gālava, Kṛpa, Rāma and others were the sages. Hari manifested himself as Sārvabhauma. 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 41; VIII. 13. 11-7; 22. 31; Vi. III. 2. 4; 13-19. Initiated in the mystery of Lord's glories by Nārada, worshipping Naranārāyaṇa; 2) Bhā. V. 19. 10. originally Śrutaśravas; performs austerities on the slopes of Meru even to-day. 3) Br. IV. 1. 28; III. 59. 49 and 80.

मनु
Manu  (XII) (Svāyambhuva)--the first son of Brahmā and the first king (Samrāṭ) also Virāṭ. Ruled the earth, girt by seven seas, occupying Brahmāvarta with Barhiṣmatī as capital. A Viprarājaṛṣi. Learnt the Veda from his father, who asked him to rule according to Dharma. Wife Śatarūpā; sons Priyavrata and Uttānapāda besides eight more through Anantā and a daughter, Devahūtī. Other daughters were Ākūti and Prasūti 1) Bhā. VIII. 1. 1, 5 and 7, XI. 14. 4; III. 20. 1 and 10; 21. 1-3, 25-26; 22. 26-9; VI. 1. 1; 8. 6; Br. II. 13. 105; M. 3. 44-5; 4. 34; 145, 90; Vā. 3. 2, 36; 23. 47; 59. 56-7; Vi. I. 7. 14-19; III. 1. 6. who married Dakṣa and Ruci respectively. Met Kardama on the Sarasvatī, spoke of interdependence of the Kṣatriya and the Brahmana, and offered his daughter Devahūtī in marriage to that sage. 2) Bhā. III. 21. 45; 22. 3-14. Another daughter Dhanyā became the wife of Dhruva. Seeing Dhruva fighting with the Yakṣas in utter wrath, Manu asked him to cease slaughtering the innocents and to ask pardon of Kubera, their chief. 3) Ib. IV. 11. 6-34; M. 4. 38. Appointed Priyavrata in charge of the kingdom and retired to tapas. Spent 71 yugas meditating on Viṣṇu, and gave Him the name, Hari. Did not take objection to Hara's violation of dharma, though he was one of the twelve who knew the dharma ordained by Hari. 4) Bhā. V. 1. 21-2; XI. 2. 15; III. 22. 31-6; II. 7. 2; VI. 17. 12; 3. 20; IV. 21. 28. Served as calf for Pṛthu to milk the earth. 5) Ib. IV. 18. 12; 29. 42. Formed one half of the Creator  and the other was Śatarūpā. Asked Brahmā for the earth being lifted out of the waters to form an abode for him and his subjects, when a Varāha issued from Brahmā's nostrils to do the work. 6) Ib. III. 12. 53-4; 13. 3-18. Renouncing the world, Manu stood on one leg meditating on the glory of Hari on the bank of the Sunandā for a hundred years; when the Asuras tried to attack and devour him, Hari in the form of yajña slew them. 7) Bhā. VIII. 1. 7-10. The first to give out Smārta dharma, Varṇāśrama dharma and the first to practice śiṣṭācāra; requested by Brahma to protect the Vedas and consequently the yajñas. Divided the Vedas into four sections. 8) Br. II. 29. 46, 61-4; 30. 34; 32. 35-8, 96; 34. 2-8; 35. 175; 36. 3; 37. 14; IV. 1. 32 and 109; M. 142. 42. An Ādipuruṣa. From him were born Vairājas. 9) Ib. 3. 45-6; 171. 27; 192. 10; 227. 32.

मनु
Manu  (XIII)--(Svārociṣa)--the second Manu, and son of Agni. Father of Dyumat and others. In this epoch Rocana was Indra, Tuṣita and others were gods, Ūrjjastamba and six others were the seven sages. Bhā. VIII. 1. 19-20; Br. II. 36. 3, 23; 37. 15.

मनु
Manu  (XIV)--(Vaivasvata)--the seventh Manu, also known as ‘Śrāddhadeva’. 1) Bhā. VIII. 13. 1-9; Br. II. 36. 4, 81; III. 59. 22 and 38; 63. 215; IV. 1. 6-28; Vā. 84. 22; Vi. IV. 1. 6-7. Son of Samjñā and Vivasvat (Sureṇu and Vivasvān Vā. P.): wife Śraddhā: father of ten sons of whom Ikṣvāku was the eldest; 2) Br. II. 38. 1. in this epoch Purandara was Indra: Kaśyapa, Atri and others were sages: Ādityas and Vasus were gods: Vāmana was the manifestation of Hari; 3) Bhā. VIII. 13. 1-9. a Kṣatriya mantravādin: His sacrifice was disturbed by sons of Varūtri who were burnt by Indra in the vedi:  a Prajāpati: king and daṇḍadhara. 4) Br. II. 32. 120; 38. 26 and 32; III. 1. 3 and 6; 8. 21; 10. 98; 60. 7; M. 145. 115; 248. 15. Saved by the Matsya Hari during the deluge. After anointing his son on the throne, M. performed penance on the Malaya Mt. for a lac of years when Brahmā blessed him as protector of the universe after the pralaya. Once in making a water oblation to his manes, a fish fell into his hand which he put into his water vessel. Finding its rapid growth he placed it in a well, tank, Ganges and the sea respectively. From its abnormal growth he suspected it to be an asura or Vāsudeva; on questioning it he found it to be the Lord and was asked to use it (the fish) as the life boat when the whole world went down in the deluge, saving at the same time some lives; 5) Ib. 1. 11 to the end; 2. 16; 9. 1; 16. 1; 52. 3. performed tapas on the Yamunā for one hundred years with a view to get progeny; 6) Bhā. I. 3. 15; VIII. 24. 50; IX. 1. 3-12; 2. 1; 6. 4. see Satyavrata; celebrated an Aśvamedha in honour of Mitra and Varuṇa; out came Ilā who went to them; 7) Br. III. 60. 1-10. the Lord of men, and seven worlds with towns; 8) Vā. 70. 18. divided the Vedas into four for the progress of the world; 9) Ib. 60. 8. in order to get sons he performed the Mitrāvaruṇa ritual; owing to the hota's carelessness a daughter Ilā came out; she became again a male Sudyumna by name; by an imprecation of Śiva he again became a woman near Budha's hermitage. Budha got by her a son by name Purūravas; 10) Vi. IV. 1. 8-12. interpretation of Śabdabrahma by. 11) Ib. VI. 5. 64.

मनु
Manu  (XV) (Dakṣa Sāvarṇī)--the ninth Manu. Born of Varuṇa; father of Bhūtaketu and other sons. Pāras and others were gods of his epoch, and Adbhuta was Indra; Dyutimat and others were sages. During this period Hari manifested himself as Ṛṣabha. Bhā. VIII. 13. 18-20. 

मनु
Manu  (XVI) (Rudrasāvarṇi)--the twelfth Manu; father of Devavān and other sons. Ṛtadhāman was Indra. Hārita and others were gods. Tapomūrti and others were sages. Svadhāma was Hari manifesting in this epoch; 1) Bhā. VIII. 13. 27-29. the fourth Sāvarṇa Manu in the 12th paryāya. 2) Br. IV. 1. 82-93.

मनु
Manu  (XVII) Sāvarṇa(i)--the second Manu in the epoch of the Vaivasvata Manvantara; son of Sāvarṇa; 1) Br. IV. 1. 51-5, 73-81. in his age Bali was to reign over the whole world. 2) Ib. II. 36. 4; III. 73. 52.

मनु
Manu  (XVIII) (Raucya)--a Sāvarṇa Manu of the XIII paryāya; three groups of gods, all addicted to Soma and ghee through yajñas. Br. IV. 1. 95-116.

मनु
Manu  (XIX)--(Cākṣuṣāntaram)--Bhṛgu and other sages lived in this epoch. 1) M. 2. 14; 6. 3; 8. 12. There were five classes of devas, Lekha, Ṛbhava, Ṛbhādya, Vārimūla, and Divaukasa; Cākṣuṣa had ten sons commencing with Ruru; 2) Ib. 9. 22, 25. King Purūravas flourished in the same line in this epoch. 3) Ib. 115. 7-8.

मनु
Manu  (XX) (Auttama)--the third Manu; 1) M. 3. 47. father of ten sons; the devas of the epoch are Bhāvanas and there were also seven sages, Kaukuruṇḍi, etc., all engaged in yoga. 2) Ib. 9. 11.

मनु
Manu  (XXI) (Cākṣuṣa) (VI)--the son of Cakṣu and Vīriṇī; married a royal princess Naḍvalā and had ten sons. M. 4. 40; Vi. I. 13. 4.

मनु
Manu  (XXII)--the son of Haryaśva and father of Pratika. Vi. IV. 5. 27. 

मनु
Manus --worshipped with Devas for kingdom; their duties in different epochs described. 1) Bhā. II. 3. 9; VIII. 14. 2-10 Fourteen in number; went to Maharloka when their duties were over; 2) Br. IV. 2. 2 nad 5. in order: Svāyambhuva, Svārociṣa, Auttama, Tāmasa, Raivata, Cākṣuṣa; these six are past ones; the future are eight; Sāvarṇa, Pañcaraucyas, Bhautya and Vaivasvata. 3) Vā. 62. 3-4.

मनुकाल
Manukāla --the whole period of the fourteen Manus covering a kalpa of one thousand yugas--the fourteen manvantaras. Bhā. VIII. 13. 36; 14. 11.

मनुग
Manuga --a son of Dyutimān after whose name is a Janapada. Vā. 33. 21.

मनुज
Manuja --a Viśvedeva. M. 203. 13.

मनुतीर्थ
Manutīrtha --a tīrtha visited by Balarāma. Bhā. X. 79. 21.

मनुत्तम
Manuttama  (Manutta or Marutta)--a king equal to a cakravartin, went to heaven with Samvarta, a sage; father of Nariṣyanta. Vā. 86. 9.

मनुवन्ती
Manuvantī --a daughter of Tumburu. Br. III. 7. 13.

मनुवंशधर
Manuvaṃśadhara --an avatār of Hari. Bhā. II. 7. 20. 

मनुवश
Manuvaśa --a son of Madhu. Vā. 95. 45.

मनुष्य
Manuṣyas --created out of the rajas element; 1) Vi. I. 5. 23, 37-8; 6. 1. four varṇas of. 2) Ib. I. 6. 5.

मनुष्यपितृ
Manuṣyapitṛs --are Laukikas (s.v.). Br. II. 28. 71, 78, 95.

मनोजव
Manojava  (I)--a son of Medhātithi of Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 25.

मनोजव
Manojava  (II)--a son of Īśāna and Śivā. Br. II. 10. 79; Vā. 27. 52.

मनोजव
Manojava  (III)--a Lekha god. Br. II. 36. 75.

मनोजव
Manojava  (IV)--the Indra of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Br. II. 36. 76; Vi. III. 1. 26.

मनोजव
Manojava  (V)--a son of Anila (Anala-M. P.) a Vasava. Br. III. 3. 26; M. 5. 25; Vā. 66. 25; Vi. I. 15. 114.

मनोजव
Manojava  (VI)--a god of one of the ten branches of the Harīta gaṇa. Br. IV. 1. 84; Vā. 100. 89.

मनोजवा
Manojavā --a R. in Krauñcadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 75; M. 122. 88; Vā. 49. 69; Vi. II. 4. 55. 

मनोदण्ड
Manodaṇḍa --restraint of mind. Vā. 17. 6.

मनोनुग
Manonuga  (I)--a son of Dyutimān after whom the kingdom, Mānonuga took its name. Br. II. 14. 22, 24.

मनोनुग
Manonuga  (II) (c)--a region of the Krauñcadvīpa adjoining the Vāmana hill. Br. II. 14. 24; 19. 71; M. 122. 84.

मनोनुग
Manonuga  (III)--a varṣa of the hill, Vāmanaka. Vā. 49. 66.

मनोभवा
Manobhavā --an Apsarasa. Br. III. 7. 7.

मनोरमा
Manoramā  (I)--a mind-born mother. M. 179. 26.

मनोरमा
Manoramā  (II)--an Apsarasa. Vā. 69. 6.

मनोवती
Manovatī  (I)--the sabhā of Brahmā on the first innerslope of Meru in which reside Īśāna and Indra besides sages and seers. Vā. 34. 72-7.

मनोवती
Manovatī  (II)--a daughter of Tumburu. Vā. 69. 49.

मनोहरम्
Manoharam --a tīrtha on the Narmadā sacred to Pitṛs. M. 194. 7. 

मनोहरा
Manoharā  (I)--a wife of Dhara. M. 5. 24.

मनोहरा
Manoharā  (II)--the wife of Dharma, the Vasu. Vi. I. 15. 113.

मंकनम्
Maṃkanam --the form of a Brahmana assumed by Gaṇeśa Nikumbha when he appeared in a dream to Divodāsa. Br. III. 67. 42.

मंकुति
Maṃkuti --a R. from the Ṛkṣa hill. Br. II. 16. 31.

मन्त्रद्रुम
Mantradruma --Indra of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Bhā. VIII. 5. 8.

मन्त्रनाथा
Mantra(i)nāthā --also Mantriṇī, 1) Br. IV. 17. 22, 27; 27, 58; 19. 61. and Mantriṇīśyāmā; war master of Lalitā; residence at Kadambavanavāṭikā; 2) Ib. IV. 31. 82, 89. helped Kumārī in vanquishing Bhaṇḍa's sons; rode on Kiricakra; consulted Daṇḍanāthā; 3) Ib. IV. 26. 2, 83, 113; 27. 58. invoked Madīrāsindhu (s.v.). 4) Ib. IV. 28. 14, 48, 92, 103.

मन्त्रनायिका
Mantra(i)nāyikā --see Mantranāthā. Br. IV. 17. 31, 33, 40.

मन्त्रप्रवचन
Mantrapravacanas --a branch of the Vedic literature. Vā. 58. 14.

मन्त्रब्राह्मणम्
Mantrabrāhmaṇam --a branch of Vedic literature; 1) Br. II. 31. 12; 33. 54; Vā. 59. 138. ety. of. 2) Ib. 50. 141; 61. 102. 

मन्त्रम्
Mantram  (I)--(also Mantrasthānam, Council Chamber) consultation to be held with many and individually and with people in whom the king has confidence; at least one expert must be consulted; generally with people learned in the three Vedas, elders who have the ability to correct the erring king; 1) M. 215. 48-52. kingdom rests on mantra; 2) Ib. 220. 33. king not to decide alone nor to consult too many; 3) Ib. 220. 37. Bhaṇḍa's War Council. 4) Br. IV. 21. 21; 25. 3

मन्त्रम्
Mantram  (II)--a portion of the Pūrva samhitā. Vā. 61. 65.

मन्त्र
Mantras --take the food offered in sacrifices to the Pitṛs as the calf finds out its mother among the lost cows; 1) Br. II. 28. 91; Vā. 59. 61. came out of discontent, fear, difficulties, happiness and misery of ṛṣis; later put into form and order by sages; differences in mantras as many as twenty-four; 2) Br. II. 32. 68; 33. 42; Vā. 59. 35-61; M. 145. 62-3. the two major divisions 
--grāmyam and āraṇyakam; 3) Br. II. 35. 73, 85; IV. 8. 51-3, 57. Veda mantras, Viṣṇu mantra, Durgā mantra, Gāṇapata mantra, etc.; 4) Ib. IV. 38. 4. ety of. 5) Vā. 59. 141.

मन्त्रमाला
Mantramālā --a R. in Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 15.

मन्त्रय
Mantraya --a son of Satyabhāmā. Vā. 96. 238.

मन्त्रवित्
Mantravit --a son of Satyabhāmā and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 247.

मन्त्रशरीर
Mantraśarīras --the 12 sons who came out of Brahmā's face. Vā. 67. 4. 

मन्त्रात्म
Mantrātma śaktikā --a Varṇa śakti. Br. IV. 44. 58.

मन्त्रि
Mantri  (I)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 238.

मन्त्रि
Mantri  (II)--the chief counsellor of the king; 1) Vā. 57. 70. looks after the kingdom in the absence of the king; 2) M. 115. 17; 217. 18. to be consulted before undertaking an expedition; 3) Ib. 223. 9; 240. 27. residence of. 4) Ib. 254. 20.

मन्त्रिणि
Mantriṇi --is Mantranāthā. Br. IV. 17. 33; 19. 87; 31. 82-9.

मन्त्रिप्रवरम्
Mantripravaram --the ministry which ruled the kingdom in the absence of king, Sagara. Br. III. 50. 32.

मन्त्रोपनिषद्
Mantropaniṣad --a secret mantra in honour of Sankarṣaṇa, taught to king Citraketu by Nārada; its text. Bhā. VI. 15. 27; 16. 18-25.

मन्थु
Manthu --a son of Vīravrata and Bhojā; his wife was Satyā, and son Bhauvana. Bhā. V. 15. 15.

मन्द
Manda --a son of Abhramu elephant; 1) Br. III. 7. 330. also Padma; the vehicle of Kubera. 2) Vā. 69. 214, 216.

मन्दक
Mandaka --a son of Śrīdevā and Vasudeva. Br. III. 71. 181. 

मन्दग
Mandagas --the Śūdra caste of Śākadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 69.

मन्दगा
Mandagā --a R. from the Śuktimat. Br. II. 16. 38; M. 114. 32; Vā. 45. 107.

मन्दगामिनी
Mandagāminī --a R. from the Suktimat hill. Br. II. 16. 38.

मन्दनी
Mandanī --a mūrchana; the presiding deity of the Viśvedevas. Vā. 86. 63.

मन्दपन्नग
Mandapannaga --a Marut gaṇa. M. 171. 54.

मन्दबाह्य
Mandabāhya --a son of Balarāma. Br. III. 71. 167.

मन्दर
Mandara  (I)--(Mt.) on one side of Meru; one of Viṣkambhagiris round the Meru; sacred to Śiva; in its valleys Hiraṇyakaśipu performed austerities; used in churning the milk ocean; lest it should sink in the sea Hari in the form of Kūrma supported the mountain; was lifted up with great difficulty by the Gods and Asuras, who could not carry it to the ocean, when Hari asked Garuḍa to bear it on his back to the sea and which he did. 1) Br. IV. 9. 51, 56, 60; Bhā. I. 3. 16; III. 28. 27; V. 16. 11; VII. 3. 2; 7. 2; VIII. 5. 10; 6. 33-9; X. 40. 18; XII. 13. 2; M. 69. 1; 249. 15; 250. 26; 251. 35; Vi. I. 9. 77, 84. Recipient of mango fruits as large as hill-tops falling from a divine mango tree, 1100 yojanas high (see Aruṇodā). 2) Bhā. V. 16. 16. Here Pṛthu died and was cremated. 3) Ib. IV. 23. 24. (Also known, Mandaragiri and Mandarācalam). Bhadrāśva varṣa and Caitraratha park in; 4) M. 83. 20, 31. Śiva spent his honeymoon here with Umā after marrying her; Umā's delights in the woods. 5) Ib. 113. 45; 154. 496, 573; 163. 87; 183. 1. 

मन्दर
Mandara  (II)--a Mt. of Kuśadvīpa, from waters called mandas; 1) Br. II. 13. 36; 19. 56; Vā. 36. 19; 42. 14; 45. 90; 49. 51; 101. 288. a son of Meru; 2) Ib. 30. 33. on the other side of Gandhamādhana; its mahāvṛkṣa is Keturāṭ. 3) Ib. 35. 16.

मन्दर
Mandara  (III)--a Mt. in Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 20; III. 27. 28.

मन्दर
Mandara  (IV)--a tīrtha sacred to Kāmacāriṇī. M. 13. 28; 184. 18.

मन्दर
Mandara  (V)--same as Kakudmān. M. 122. 61.

मन्दर
Mandara  (VI)--a palace of 12 floors; three-fourths of Meru; the toraṇa is 45 hastas. M. 269. 28, 32, 47.

मन्दर
Mandara  (VII)--a Mt. in Malayadvīpa. Vā. 48. 23.

मन्दर
Mandara  (VIII)--a hill on the east of Ilāvṛta. Vi. II. 2. 18.

मन्दरशोभि
Mandaraśobhi --a son of Maṇibhadra. Vā. 69. 155.

मन्दरहरिण
Mandarahariṇa --an upadvīpa to Jambūdvīpa. Bhā. V. 19. 30.

मन्दराचल
Mandarācala --a chief hill of Kuśadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 41. 

मन्दवाहिनी
Mandavāhinī --R. from Śuktimanta (Śuktimat). M. 114. 32; Vā. 45. 107.

मन्दवाह्य
Mandavāhya --a son of Sāraṇa. Vā. 96. 165.

मन्दाकि
Mandāki --a son of Bhavya of Śākadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 60.

मन्दाकिनी
Mandākinī  (I)--a R. in Bhāratavarṣa; Gangā in Devaloka; 1) Bhā. V. 19. 18; X. 70. 44; Vā. 45. 99. R. of the Kailāsa hill. Here Aila and Urvaśī lived for sometime. 2) Br. II. 18. 3; III. 66. 6; M. 121. 4; Vā. 41. 14-17; 91. 6. Other rivers in Kailāsa are Alakanandā and Nandā. 3) Ib. 41. 18; 47. 3.

मन्दाकिनी
Mandākinī  (II)--a R. sacred to the Pitṛs; 1) M. 22. 23. rises from Ṛṣyavān; 2) Ib. 105. 10; 114. 25. water for bathing a deity. 3) Ib. 267. 20.

मन्दाकिन्य
Mandākinyas --Kaśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 3.

मन्दकूरी
Mandakūrī --a R. from the Ṛkṣa hill. Br. II. 16. 30.

मन्दार
Mandāra --a Śiva gaṇa. Br. III. 41. 27.

मन्दारवती
Mandāravatī --a division of Śrīpuram. Br. IV. 32. 33.

मन्दारसप्तमी
Mandārasaptamī --the performance of, on the fifth day of the bright half of the month of Māgha in honour of the Sun God, gets one the desired objects. M. 74. 3; 79. 1. 

मन्दुलक
Mandulaka --an Andhra king who ruled for five years. M. 273. 10.

मन्देह
Mandehas  (I)--three crores of Rākṣasas who attack the rising sun and who are disarmed by the sandhya worship of gods and by the chanting of the Gāyatrī by the Brahmanas. 1) Br. II. 21. 110; Vā. 50. 163.

मन्देह
Mandehas  (II)--the Śūdra caste of Kuśadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 38.

मन्दोदक
Mandodaka --the lake in the Kailāsa; the water in it is like curd; the Nandana is on its bank, and the Mandākinī rises from it. M. 121. 4-5.

मन्दोदरी
Mandodarī  (I)--a daughter of Maya. M. 6. 21; Vā. 68. 29.

मन्दोदरी
Mandodarī  (II)--a tīrtha sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 41.

मन्मथ
Manmatha --(Kāma); God of Love; 1) M. 118. 13. on the third Parva of the Geyacakra; 2) Br. IV. 19. 67. recreated by Lalitā, who said he was her son; went to Śiva's abode accompanied by his friend Vasanta. 3) Ib. IV. 30. 46. Got burnt by Śiva and in effecting his revival Māyavatī (Ratī) deluded Śambara by her charms; she brought up Pradyumna who was a part of the Love God. 4) VI. V. 27. 28-30. 

मन्मथा
Manmathā --a goddess enshrined at Hemakūṭa. M. 13. 50.

मन्यु
Manyu  (I)--a name of a Rudra. Bhā. III. 12. 12.

मन्यु
Manyu  (II)--the son of Vitatha (Bharadvāja); father of Bṛhadkṣatra and four other sons. Bhā. IX. 21. 1; Vi. IV. 19. 20, 21.

मन्युमान्
Manyumān --the son of Jāṭharāgni; see Vidvānagni. Br. II. 12. 34; Vā. 29. 32.

मन्वन्तर
Manvantaras --periods of Manus; seven in number and seven to come, of Svāyambhuva, Svārociṣa, Auttama, Tāmasa, Raivata, Cākṣuṣa, Sāvarṇi (after Vaivasvata in M. P.), Raucya (Br. P.); Vaivasvata present according to the M. P.) Ruci, Bhautya, Merusāvarṇi, Rta, Ṛtadhāmān and Viṣvaksena; the last seven are future Manus; 1) Br. II. 6. 6, 20; 36. 1-4; M. 2. 22; 9. 2-36; Vā. 21. 11, 14, 19, 38, 44; 57. 33-6; Vi. I. 3. 18. one of the five characteristics of the Purāṇa; 2) M. 53. 65; Br. I. 1. 37; Vā. 4. 10. calculation of the duration of the epochs of Manus; 3) M. 142. 30. constitutes 71 yugas at the end of which comes Kṣaya 4) Vā. 10. 12; 32. 41. according to Mānuṣa and Divyavatsara. 5) Ib. 61. 138-144; 150. 176.

मन्वन्तर
Manvantara of Svāyambhuva Manu --the Gods of three worlds, sages, pitṛs, and people help him; but finding the diminished powers, go to Maharloka. Vā. 61. 149-51. 

ममता
Mamatā --the wife of the sage Uśija (Asija-Vā. P.), (Utathya Vi. P.) whose younger brother Bṛhaspati wanted sexual union with her when she was pregnant eight months; he raped her, and cursed the baby in the womb which obstructed the completion of the act, to be ever in darkness, and hence the child was born blind, Dīrghatamas; the result of the union was Bharadvāja; Mamatā, abandoned Bharadvāja fearing divorce by her husband on account of the indiscret act of Bṛhaspati (s.v.) see also Dīrghatamas. Bhā. IX. 20. 37-39; Br. III. 74. 36-7; M. 48. 32-41; 49. 17, 26; Vā. 99. 36-8; Vi. IV. 19 16.

मय
Maya  (I)--The architect of the Asuras of the other world, and a past master in the practice of māyā. Served as calf for the Māyins to derive māyā from Earth. Built aerial cities, three in number, of gold, silver and iron for the protection of the Asuras, and constructed the divine sabhā. The cities were well equipped and furnished, with paintings and drawings of couples of Nāgas and Asuras, pigeons, parrots and śārikas, interspersed by charming gardens of flowers and fruits with lakes of crystal waters. Being the Lord of Tripura which he built, he took part with Bali in the Devāsura war, and also fought with Viśvakarman; 1) Bhā. I. 15. 8; II. 7. 37; IV. 18. 20; V. 24. 9-10; VII. 10. 22 and 29, 51-60. son of Viśvakarman; Sureṇu was his sister; 2) Br. III. 59. 21; IV. 12. 3; 20. 46; 31. 7; Vā. 84. 20-1. had an evil dream that a naked lady and a man of three eye burning the city: reported it to the Sabhā: was explained by Nārada: precautions for defence: army stationed at respective places of vantage; Vidyunmāli was over-powered; Maya constructed a tank of medicinal waters to make the dead live and restored Vidyunmāli. Knowing this immortalising fluid, Brahmā and Hari drank the whole of it; fierce war; Śiva directed his arrows against the three cities and killed the Asuras by destroying their cities. Maya's address to the Asuras for a bold stand. Vidyunmāli and Tāraka were killed. Maya was let off and asked to live in a special house  after burning the city. In the Tārakāmaya it is said he rode on a golden chariot with arms and weapons. 3) M. ch. 129; 131. 25-30; 134. 9-30; chh. 135-140. 173. 2-13; 177. 3-6.

मय
Maya  (II)--the Asura architect and a contemporary of Kṛṣṇa. His son enslaved the gopas and hid them in a cave. Kṛṣṇa recovered them; 1) Bhā. II. 7. 31. freed from the forest fire of Kāṇḍava by Arjuna, he erected a sabhā for the use of the Pāṇḍavas. Once Duryodhana (s.v.) mistook a floor of this for a sheet of water and had a nasty fall; 2) Ib. X. 55. 21; 71. 45; 58. 27; 75. 34 and 37. Supplied a magic car to Śālva under orders of Śiva. 3) Ib. X. 76. 7; 77. 28.

मय
Maya  (III)--an Asura; Lord of Talātala region, won the grace of Śiva and attained mokṣa by satsanga. A follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra; 1) Bhā. V. 24. 28; XI. 12. 5; VI. 10. 31. wife Rambhā and father of six sons; 2) Br. III. 6. 5 and 28; Vā. 68. 28-9. had daughters like Upadānavī. 3) M. 6. 21.

मय
Maya  (IV)--father of Māyā. Br. II. 9. 64.

मय
Maya  (V)--an author on architecture. M. 252. 2.

मया
Mayā --a Śakti created from the heart of Nṛsimha. M. 179. 64.

मयूर
Mayūra  (I)--the riding animal of Kārttikeya; several on the Himālayas; 1) Br. II. 25. 16, 27; III. 10. 47. M. 160. 21. Vā. 36. 2; 54. 19. a banner of Skanda presented to Vāyu. 2) Ib. 72. 46. 

मयूर
Mayūra  (II)--a peak on the Varāha hill. Vā. 42. 70.

मयूरध्वज
Mayūradhvaja --Bāṇa with the peacock standard; the breaking of the flag was a sign of impending war. Vi. V. 33. 3.

मयोभुव
Mayobhuva --of the Agastya family. M. 202. 2.

मरीचक
Marīcaka --a son of Bhavya of Śakadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 60.

मरीच
Marīca (i) Kaśyapa --a Prajāpati; husband of Aditī and father of the Ādityas. Vā. 30. 72; 50. 168; 52. 95; 67. 43; 100. 20; 101. 35 and 49.

मरीचि
Marīci  (I)--a mind-born son of Brahmā born with Nārada at the beginning of creation; 1) Bhā. I. 6. 31; III. 12. 22; IX. 1. 10; Br. II. 32. 96; III. 1. 21, 43-4; M. 3. 6; 4. 26; 195. 9. married Kalā a daughter of Kardama; 2) Bhā. III. 24. 22; IV. 1. 13. father of Kaśyapa; 3) Ib. III. 14. 7; 20. 10. came with Brahmā to see Kapila born to Kardama; 4) Ib. III. 24. 9. was present in Dakṣa's yajña; 5) Ib. IV. 7. 43; 29. 43. directed the Aśvamedha of Indra; 6) Ib. VI. 13. 21. came to see the Trivikrama avatār of the Lord; 7) Ib. VIII. 21. 1. did not comprehend Hari's māya. 8) Ib. IX. 4. 58. The chief sage of Vena's reign responsible for punishing him. A sage in Dāruvana; 9) Br. II. 21. 115; 27. 104; 36. 133; III. 10. 52; M. 145. 90; 154. 352; 171. 27. one of the seven sages of Svāyambhuva epoch: instructed by Brahmā on the eighteen Purāṇas; praised Śiva, out to destroy Tripuram; 10) Ib. 9. 4; 53. 12; 102. 19; 127. 24; 133. 67. had a daughter Surūpā, whom Angiras got married. 11) Ib. 196. 1; 245. 86; 250. 4. 

मरीचि
Marīci  (II)--a son of Samrāṭ and Utkalā. Father of Bindumatī. Bhā. V. 15. 15.

मरीचि
Marīci  (III)--His wife was Ūrṇā; had six sons in the first antara; then Gods laughed at Brahmā seeking connection with his daughter; these were born of Hiraṇyakaśipu as Asuras, but were taken away by Yogamāyā; then they were born of Devakī and killed by Kamsa. Bhā. X. 85. 47-49.

मरीचि
Marīci  (IV)--created from the eyes; one of the Nine Brāhmaṇas alluded to in the Purāṇas. Br. I. 5; II. 9. 18 and 22; 11. 10; 13. 54.

मरीचि
Marīci  (V)--a sage of the Svāyambhuva epoch; 1) Vā. 3. 2; 31. 16; 62. 113; 65. 44. son-inlaw of Dakṣa; 2) Ib. 30. 48. married Sambhūtī; 3) Br. II. 9. 55; Vā. 28. 8; Vi. I. 10. 6; 11. 43. advised Dhruva to pray to Viṣṇu. 4) Ib. I. 12. 6.

मरीचि
Marīci  (VI)--a son of Brahmā married Dharmavratā, the daughter of Dharma whom he cursed for dereliction of duty, to become a stone; got one hundred sons through her; in turn cursed by her for the unjust curse. Vā. 107. 7, 26; 112. 36.

मरीचि
Marīci  (VII)--a mind-born son of Brahmā; married Sannatī. Vi. I. 7. 5, 7, 37.

मरीचिगर्भ
Marīcigarbhas  (I)--the gods of the ninth Manvantara; a gaṇa of 12 gods. Bhā. VIII. 13. 19; Br. IV. 1. 55, 58-9; Vi. III. 2. 21. 

मरीचिगर्भ
Marīcigarbhas  (II)--the world of Haviṣmanta Pitṛs in the Mārtāṇḍamaṇḍalam. M. 15. 16.

मरीचिगर्भ
Marīcigarbhas  (III)--the world of Upahūta Pitṛs; belonging to Kṣatriyagaṇa. Vā. 73. 38-9.

मरीचिगर्भ
Marīcigarbhas  (IV)--sons of Meru Sāvarṇi. Vā. 100. 59.

मरीचिप
Marīcipas --do severe austerities at Benares. M. 183. 31.

मरीचिमन्
Marīciman --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 244.

मरीचिरक्षक
Marīcirakṣaka --one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 5.

मरीषा
Marīṣā --a daughter of trees given by Soma as wife of Pracetasa for the generation of Dakṣa. Vā. 63. 33-7.

मरु
Maru  (I)--the name of a desert; 1) Bhā. I. 10. 35. water in, due to ignorance. 2) Vā. 104. 39.

मरु
Maru  (II)--the son of Śighrarāja and father of Praśruta (Prasuśraka-Vi. P.); having attained perfection in yoga: he  resides in Kalāpagrāma (still rooted in Yoga-Vi. P.): would revive the solar race at the end of Kali. Bhā. IX. 12. 5-7; Br. III. 63. 210-11. Vi. IV. 4. 108-11.

मरु
Maru  (III)--a son of Haryaśva and father of Pratīpaka (Pratyambaka Br. P.; Pratitvaka-Vā. P.). Bhā. IX. 13. 15-6; Br. III. 64. 11. Vā. 89. 11.

मरु
Maru(c)  (IV)--on the way from Dvārakā to Hāstinapura. Bhā. X. 71. 21.

मरु
Maru  (V)--of the Ikṣvāku line, living in Kalāpagrāma and endowed with Yoga. Bhā. XII. 2. 37.

मरु
Maru  (VI)--a son of the III Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 81.

मरु
Maru  (VII)--the place sacred to Lalitā. Br. IV. 44. 98.

मरुण्ड
Maruṇḍas --13 Kings of this line ruled for 200 years with Vṛṣalas. Vā. 99. 360, 363.

मरुत
Maruta  (I)--a son of Karandhama; he had no son and regarded Duṣyanta of Puru's family as his son. Bhā. IX. 23. 17.

मरुत
Maruta  (II)--born of Marutvatī. Br. I. 1. 112; 2. 41; Vā. 10. 71; 66. 33.

मरुत
Maruta  (III)--Mitrajyoti was his daughter. Br. III. 68. 1, 4. 

मरुत्
Maruts  (I)--fortynine in number, born of Diti and Kaśyapa; seven in each of the seven vātaskandhas; brothers of Indra and participators in sacrifices; 1) Bhā. VI. 18. 19, 23-77: VIII. 13. 4: Br. III. 5. 79, 90, 99, 104: M. 6. 47; 163. 22-3. when Diti conceived a son to be the slayer of Indra, the latter began to serve her throughout her pregnancy. Once finding that she did not keep to her vows he entered her womb and cut the foetus into 49 pieces, when they cried. He said to them mā ruda and hence māruta: being divine, were born as 49 sons: at the request of their mother Indra made them a devagaṇa, called Marutgaṇa. 2) M. Ch. 7. Gods of the Vaivasvata epoch, Indra being their overlord: requested Soma to give up Tārā to Bṛhaspati. 3) Ib. 8. 4: 9. 29: 23. 35: 36. 1. Fought with Nivātakavacas in the Devāsura war: mounted guards in Marutta's Yajñas: nourished Bharadvāja abandoned by Mamatā and gave him to Bharata as his son; 4) Bhā. VI. 10. 17: IX. 2. 28; 20. 35-9: M. 49. 15, 25-30: 58. 33. helped Indra in the heavy downpour on Nandavraja: went with the gods to Dvārakā to request Kṛṣṇa to go back to Vaikuṇṭha; 5) Bhā. X. 25. 7: XI. 6. 2. Fathers of Śobhavatya group of Apsarasas; presiding deity of Kālopanata mūrchana; line in Bhuvarloka and Lokāloka: perform śrāddha; 6) Br. III. 7. 20: 61. 46: IV. 2. 27, 197: III. 10. 110. are worshipped for lasting strength (ojas). 7) Bhā. II. 3. 8. Their service in the battle of Tripuram: Shaken by Hiraṇyakaśipu; glad at Hari's attack on the Asuras; 8) M. 58. 33: 132. 3; 137. 18; 172. 14-44; 174. 32. attained siddhi at Siddeśvaram; 9) Ib. 191. 117; 246. 60. companions of those who are devoted to their brothers; 10) Bhā. VI. 5. 31. brought up Bharadvāja, son of Bṛhaspati. 11) Vā. 99. 139-51.

मरुत्
Maruts  (II)--one of the Marut gaṇas. Vā. 67. 128. 

मरुत्गण
Marutgaṇas  (I)--the seven pieces of Diti's garbha became seven gaṇas in the Vāyu mārga; each originated seven 1) Vā. 30. 99: 64. 2: Vi. I. 9. 64 and 70: 21. 40. gaṇas in turn and thus 49 Marut gaṇas are distinguished; they partake in yajñas especially garuḍa śayana yajña; 2) Vā. 67. 110, 123-29. residents of Bhuvarloka; 3) Ib. 101. 29. part of Viṣṇu; 4) Vi. V. 1. 17. see Śakra.

मरुत्त
Marutta  (I)--the son of Avikṣit, a cakravarti and father of Dama; helped by Samvarta, he performed sacrifices; his yajñas were of a high order; Indra was much pleased with soma, and the Brahmanas with dakṣiṇā; Maruts were the guards and Viśvedevas were members of the sabhā; 1) Bhā. IX. 2. 26-9. still is sung the glory of his sacrifice in which everything was of gold; father of Nariṣyanta. 2) Vi. IV. 1. 31-4. Br. III. 61. 7; 8. 35.

मरुत्त
Marutta  (II)--a son of Karamdhama (KaramdanaVi. P.): issueless, adopted Duṣkanta of the Paurava line and thus Purvasu family got merged in the Paurava line. It was a result of Yayāti's curse. Br. III. 74. 2-4; Vā. 99. 2-4: Vi. IV. 16. 3-6.

मरुत्त
Marutta  (III)--a son of Uśanas, a great warrior and Rājaṛṣi; father of Kambalabarhis. Br. III. 70. 25: M. 44. 24: Vā. 95. 24.

मरुत्वती
Marutvatī --a mind-born daughter of Brahmā (a daughter of Dakṣa, Bhā. P. and Vi. P.) and one of the ten wives of Dharma; mother of the Maruts among whom were Marutvān and Jayanta; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 4 and 8: Br. III. 3. 2 and 32: M. 5. 15. 17: 171. 32, 51, 55; 203. 9. Vā. 66. 2: Vi. I. 15. 105. other names of the Maruts. 2) M. 171. 52-5.

मरुत्वन्त
Marutvantas --sons of Marutvatī and Dharma; 1) M. 5. 17; 36. 1; 132. 3; 171. 51; Br. III. 3. 32; Bhā. VI. 6. 8; Vi. I. 15. 105. for names of the gaṇas of the Maruts. 2) M. 171. 52; 203. 9. 

मरुत्सोम
Maruts(t)oma --a sacrifice performed by Bharata anxious to have a son; 1) Bhā. IX. 20. 35: Br. III. 68. 2: M. 49. 28. Vā. 99. 153; Vi. IV. 19. 6. performed by Marutta for 60 years to please the Maruts and get inexhaustible annam from them. 2) Vā. 93. 2-3.

मरुदेव
Marudeva --a son of Supratīka (Supratīpa-M.P.) and father of Sunakṣatra. Bhā. IX. 12. 12: M. 271. 8; Vi. IV. 22. 4.

मरु
Maru(deśa) --also Marudhanva; arid tract 1) Vā. 86. 51. where Samjñā roamed in the guise of a mare; 2) Bhā. I. 10. 35. M. 11. 26. Vā. 8. 97; 88. 35. heaven became like a desert by the havoc of Tāraka. 3) M. 154. 34. (See Maru).

मरुद्वृधा
Marudvṛdhā (Marudvriddha-Br. P.) --a R in Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 18.

मर्क
Marka --(Śaṇḍa) an Asura; one of the four sons of Śukra and a tutor of Prahlāda; 1) Bhā. VII. 5. 1-2, 48-50; Br. III. 1. 78; 72. 72, 87; 73. 63-4; M. 47. 41; Vā. 65. 77. seen by the Gods at the sacrifice; 2) M. 47. 54. one of the two disciples the other being Śaṇḍa of Śukra sent to help the Asuras; but he joined the camp of the Devas, the latter offering him a place in sacrifices. 3) Ib. 47. 224-31; Vā. 97. 72 and 86; 98. 63; 108. 60.

मर्कोट
Markoṭa --sacred to Mukuṭeśvarī. M. 13. 33.

मर्दल
Mardalas --war musical instruments. M. 140. 43; Vā. 54. 37. 

मर्याद
Maryādas  (I)--thousands of mountains on all directions of Merumūla, full of lofty buildings; boundary limits; 1) Vā. 35. 3; 40. 1; 42. 72. Vā. 101. 157. transgression of, punished. 2) M. 227. 184.

मर्याद
Maryādas  (II)--conventions of society for the welfare of the world introduced after those of vārtā; establishment of, by kings; for breaking them, a king goes to hell. Br. II. 7. 153; 29. 89; 36. 133; IV. 2. 159; M. 225. 10; Vi. I. 6. 32.

मर्ष
Marṣa --another name for Sahasvān. Vā. 88. 211.

मर्षन
Marṣanas --belonging to the Kauśika gotra. Br. III. 66. 70; Vā. 91. 98.

मलक
Malaka  (I)--was the Asura who entered heaven, snatched away the nectar vessel from Dhanvantari: Mohinī helped the gods in the scuffle that ensued and Malaka fled to Pātālam. Br. IV. 9. 38. 10. 2, 23.

मलक
Malaka  (II)--a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 85.

मलद
Malada --was attacked by Unmattabhairavī. Br. IV. 28. 40.

मलद
Maladas --a Vindhyan tribe; an eastern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 53 and 63.

मलदा
Maladā  (I)--one of the ten wives of Atri. Br. III. 8. 75. 

मलदा
Maladā  (II)--a daughter of Bhadrāśva and Ghṛtācī. Vā. 70. 68.

मलन्दरा
Malandarā --a R. sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 63.

मलय
Malaya  (I)--a son of Ṛṣabha and Jayanti. Bhā. V. 4. 10.

मलय
Malaya  (II)--a Mt. (Kulaparvata Vā. P.) in Bhāratavarṣa; 1) Bhā. V. 19. 16; Br. II. 16. 18; Vā. 45. 89, 105; Vi. II. 3. 3. noted for sandal; 2) Bhā. I. 8. 32. sacred to Hari; 3) Ib. VII. 14. 32. the residence of Agastya; 4) Ib. VI. 3. 35; X. 79. 17; XII. 8. 16; M. 61. 37. visited by Balarāma; 5) Bhā. X. 79. 16. Manu performed tapas at. 6) M. 1. 12.

मलयद्वीपम्
Malayadvīpam --a pradeśa of Jambudvīpa of the Mlecchas; here is Mahāmalaya hill called second Mandaram as also Agastya's āśrama and Lankā. Vā. 48. 14, 20-30.

मलयध्वज
Malayadhvaja --the Pāṇḍya who married the daughter of the Vidarbha King Rājasimha and became the father of a daughter and seven sons; a Rājaṛṣi; divided his kingdom among his sons and with his mind set on Kṛṣṇa retired to Kulācala followed by his queen; after a period of strenuous tapas he died and the queen wailed. Bhā. IV. 28. 29-30, 33-34, 36-50.

मलयपर्वत
Malayaparvata --sacred to Goddess Rambhā; 1) M. 13. 29. rich with tamāla trees. 2) Ib. 114. 17, 30; 163. 71. 

मलयाचल
Malayācala --sacred to Kalyāṇī. M. 13. 36.

मलवर्तिक
Malavartikas --an eastern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 53.

मलिन
Malina --a son of Trasu, a Brahmavādin. Vā. 99. 132.

मल्ल
Malla  (I)--Candraketu, a son of Lakṣmaṇa styled thus or his country? Vā. 88. 188.

मल्ल
Malla  (II)--the Lord of Rājagṛha, vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 73. 100.

मल्ल
Mallas --a tribe and an eastern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 55; M. 163. 67.

मल्लक्रीड
Mallakrīḍa --wrestling matches in ancient Mathurā in which all the people from the peasant to the king took part; described. Bhā. X. 36. 24; 42. 32-38; 44. 2-5.

मल्लग
Mallaga --a son of Dyutiman after whom came the kingdom of Mallagam. Vi. II. 4. 48.

मल्लराज
Mallarāja --killed by Kṛṣṇa. Vā. 98. 101.

मल्लवर्णक
Mallavarṇakas --a tribe. M. 114. 44. 

मषीपात्रणि
Maṣīpātraṇi --Ink bottles. Br. IV. 37. 89.

मसमूलिक
Masamūlika(c) --watered by R. Cakṣu. Br. II. 18. 46.

मसूर
Masūras --lentils unfit for śrāddha. Vi. I. 6. 21; III. 16. 7.

मसृण
Masṛṇa --a Pravara sage. M. 199. 17.

मह
Maha  (I)--a son of Bharatāgni. Vā. 29. 8.

मह
Maha  (II)--one of the twenty Amitābha gods. Br. IV. 1. 17; Vā. 100. 16.

मह
Maha  (III)--(Maharloka) the fourth of the seven worlds; 1) Br. II. 19. 155; M. 60. 2; 61. 1; 184. 23; Vā. 101. 17. Manus went to it after tapas at Meru; Manus retire to this place when the periods of their duties are over; Gods like Ajitas, Yāma gaṇas and Āyuṣmantas besides Śukra, Cākṣuṣa and others live in Maharloka; 2) Br. II. 21. 22; 35. 179, 197; IV. 1. 25, 33, 122. Vā. 101. 41, 52, 208; 109. 48. the space between Dhruva and Jana; the residents of this loka possess mental powers to create any desired thing; even gods sacrifice to each other; 3) Br. IV. 2. 2, 21, 40, 42-3; Vā. 101. 44. created from Vyāhṛti. 4) Br. IV. 2. 2, 21; Vā. 101. 23.

महत्
Mahat  (I)--a tatva or principle; 1) Bhā. I. 3. 1; II. 1. 35; M. 3. 17. identified with Brahmā; 2) Bhā. III. 6. 26; XI. 14. 14; 16. 37-8; 24. 25-26; 28. 16. a name of Rudra; 3) Ib. III. 12. 12. absorbs the ahankāra 4) Ib. XII. 4. 17. covered by Pradhāna. 5) Br. II. 21. 27; 32. 76; IV. 3. 6 and 21. Ten times greater than bhūtādi; the order  of evolution of the universe according to Sānkhya; 6) M. 123. 52-61. evolution of Prakṛti in its vikāras. 7) Ib. 3. 17-26; Vā. 100. 243.

महत्
Mahat  (II)--(a Rudra), son of Bhūta and Sarūpā. Bhā. VI. 6. 18.

महती
Mahatī  (I)--a R. from Ṛṣyavān in Bhāratavarṣa. M. 114. 23; Vā. 45. 97.

महती
Mahatī  (II)--a R. of the Kuśadvīpa. M. 122. 74.

महत्पौरव
Mahatpaurava Nandana --of the family of Sārvabhauma. Vā. 99. 187.

महर्लोक
Maharloka --the neck of the Puruṣa; 1) Bhā. II. 1. 28. due to fire of Sankarṣaṇa sages leave this to Janaloka; 2) Ib. VIII. 20. 34. the goal of yogins 3) Ib. XI. 24. 14. (see Mahat) above the Pole Star; the residence of Kalpa people; at a distance of two crores of yojanas is Janaloka; becomes devoid of all beings at the end of the kalpa but not extinguished; 4) Vi. II. 7. 13. burnt in the Pralaya. 5) Ib. VI. 3. 28-9.

महऋषि
Mahaṛṣis --mind-born sons of Brahmā, seven in number, like Bhṛgu, Marīci, and Angiras; 1) Br. II. 32. 89, 97; M. 145. 85; 247. 10. ety. from root ṛṣi gatau--meaning knowledge; great jñānins; 2) Br. II. 6. 71; Vā. 7. 74; 59. 82 and 89. their role in creation. 3) Ib. 7. 75-6.

महवीर्य
Mahavīrya --a son of Virāṭ. Vā. 33. 58. 

महस्वत्
Mahasvat --a son of Amarṣaṇa and father of Viśvasāhvan. Bhā. IX. 12. 7.

महाकर्ण
Mahākarṇa  (I)--a Kādraveya Nāga. Br. III. 7. 34; Vā. 69. 71.

महाकर्ण
Mahākarṇa  (II)--a sage. M. 200. 7.

महाकापि
Mahākāpi --a Pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 14.

महाकाय
Mahākāya --a son of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 26. 47.

महाकाल
Mahākāla  (I)--a son of Guhāvasa, the avatār of the 17th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 177.

महाकाल
Mahākāla  (II)--a Gaṇeśvara; an attendant of Śiva; with Mahākāli engaged in the service of Lalitā as one of her guardsmen; he is served by servants like Kālamṛtyu; in charge of the first entrance to Śrīpuram; other Śaktis attached to him are Mahāsandhya and Mahāniśā in the Trikoṇa and five Śaktis on the Pañcakoṇa as also those on the ṣoḍaśa patra and nāga patra; his seat is Kālacakra. Br. III. 41. 26; M. 183. 64; 192. 6; 266. 42; Br. III. 32. 23; IV. 30. 75; 32. 2, 40; 34. 89.

महाकाल
Mahākāla  (III)--sacred to Maheśvarī. M. 13. 41.

महाकालम्
Mahākālam --a place sacred to Śiva. M. 181. 26. 

महाकालत्वम्
Mahākālatvam --attained by Bāṇa. M. 6. 13.

महाकालवनम्
Mahākālavanam --a garden in the country of Avantī. M. 179. 5.

महाकाली
Mahākālī  (I)--a Varṇa śakti. Br. IV. 44. 57; 32. 4.

महाकाली
Mahākālī  (II)--a mind-born mother. M. 179. 14; Vi. II. 13. 49.

महाकाली
Mahākālī  (III)--came out from the wrath of Śiva. Vā. 101. 298.

महाकूट
Mahākūṭa --a sacred hill 1) Br. III. 13. 58. fit for śrāddha. 2) Vā. 77. 57.

महाकेश
Mahākeśas --a Janapada of the Bhadrā country. Vā. 43. 20.

महागणपति
Mahāgaṇapati --(also) Mahāgaṇeśvara. Br. IV. 14. 8; 27. 83, 102; 36. 18.

महागार्ग्य
Mahāgārgya --one of the sons of Danu. Vā. 68. 5.

महागिरि
Mahāgiri --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 9; Vā. 68. 9.

महागिरिनगर
Mahāgirinagara --a city in the Himālayas. M. 154. 469.

महागुरु
Mahāguru --he, who imparts Brahmopadeśa. Br. IV. 8. 4. 

महागोष
Mahāgoṣa --a kinnara gaṇa; horse-faced. Vā. 69. 32.

महागौरी
Mahāgaurī --a R. from the Vindhyas. Br. II. 16. 33; M. 114. 28; Vā. 45. 103.

महाग्रीवा
Mahāgrīvā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 24.

महाघोर
Mahāghora --a hell. Vā. 101. 148.

महाचक्रा
Mahācakrā --a R. of Bhadrā country. Vā. 43. 25.

महाचक्रि
Mahācakri --a Kaśyapa gotrakāra. M. 199. 5.

महाचित्रा
Mahācitrā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 26.

महाजम्भ
Mahājambha --a Rākṣasa in Sutalam. Br. II. 20. 21; Vā. 50. 20.

महाजय
Mahājaya --a son of Maṇivara. Vā. 69. 159.

महाजिह्वा
Mahājihvā --a Brahmarākṣasī. Br. III. 7. 99; Vā. 69. 134.

महाज्वाल
Mahājvāla --a hell for several offences detailed; such as sexual intercourse with daughters and daughters-in-law, selling or censuring the Vedas, insulting or assaulting the ācāryas. Br. IV. 2. 147, 151, 156-7; Vā. 101. 146, 155; Vi. II. 6. 2 and 12. 

महांगस्
Mahāṃgas --a Janapada of the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 14.

महाण्ड
Mahāṇḍa --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 89.

महातल
Mahātala --the ankle of the creator; 1) Bhā. II. 1. 26; 5. 41. an underworld, where a gaṇa of Nāgas by name Krodhavaśa live; 2) Ib. V. 24. 7, 29. of gravel colour where are the cities of Virocana, the Asura chief and eight others. 3) Vā. 50. 12, 34-7.

महात्रिपुरसुन्दरी
Mahātripurasundarī --a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 18. 14.

महादन्त
Mahādanta --a Nāga in Vaidūrya śālā of Lalitā. Br. IV. 33. 36.

महादंष्ट्र
Mahādaṃṣṭra --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 86.

महादीप्त
Mahādīpta --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 236.

महाद्रुम
Mahādruma --a son of Havya after whom the Mahādruma varṣa. Br. II. 14. 17. 21.

महादेव
