Mahāhaya --a son of Śatajit. Bhā. IX. 23. 21

महाहविविधि
Mahāhavividhi --the other name for the Kālasūtra hell. Vā. 101. 178.

महिनस
Mahinasa --a Rudra. Bhā. III. 12. 12. 

महिमा
Mahimā  (I)--a siddhi devī. Br. IV. 19. 4; 36. 51; 44. 108.

महिमा
Mahimā  (II)--one of the eight Yogaiśvaryas; the third Yoga. Vā. 13. 3, 13.

महिमान्
Mahimān  (I)--a son of Bhaga and Siddhī. Bhā. VI. 18. 2.

महिमान्
Mahimān  (II)--a son of Āyu Agni; also Śāvan. Vā. 29. 37.

महिष
Mahiṣa  (I)--a son of Anuhrāda and Sūrmyā: fought with Vibhāvasu in the Devāsura war. Bhā. VI. 18. 16; VIII. 10. 32.

महिष
Mahiṣa  (II)--the son of Āyu and father of Sahasa. Br. II. 12. 40.

महिष
Mahiṣa  (III)--a Mt. of Kuśadvīpa (Śālmalidvīpam Br., Vā., and Vi. P.); here lives a fire called Mahiṣa, and born of waters. Br. II. 19. 40-41. M. 122. 59-60; Vā. 49. 37. Vi. II. 4. 27.

महिष
Mahiṣa  (IV)--the name of a water-born fire in the Mahiṣa hill of the Śālmalidvīpa. Br. II. 19. 41; Vā. 49. 37.

महिष
Mahiṣa  (V)--an Asura residing in Rasātalam; 1) Br. II. 20. 39. was present at Tāraka's coronation; a commander of Tāraka's force and had a chariot drawn by camels; 2) M. 147. 28; 148. 42, 50. threw Sāvitram astram against Kubera; defeated both Nṛṛti and Varuṇa and released Kujambha from the noose; somāstram and vāyavyāstram throwing out snow and wind, were sent to disable the Asuras,  when Kālanemi created a glowing fire by māyā and removed the snow and wind etc; 3) Ib. 150. 113, 135; 151. 13. found Mathana vanquished by Janārdana and sent his Śūla against Janārdana and Śakti against Garuḍa when Janārdana repelled him and said: “You are to be killed by a woman; get away; 4) Ib. 152. 17-24. killed by Durgā. 5) Br. IV. 29. 75 and 88.

महिष
Mahiṣa  (VI)--a son of Maya. Br. III. 6. 29; Vā. 68. 28.

महिष
Mahiṣa  (VII)--the kingdom of, to be ruled over by Guha. Br. III. 74. 198.

महिष
Mahiṣa  (VIII)--born of Surabhī; Buffalo as the riding animal of Yama; as also of Vārāhī; 1) M. 6. 44; 261. 13, 30. its flesh for śrāddha. 2) Ib. 17. 33.

महिष
Mahiṣa  (IX)--an Asura of Śrītalam. Vā. 50. 38.

महिष
Mahiṣas  (I)--a Vindhyan tribe: Puṣpamitra was a king; 1) Br. III. 74. 187. born of Hamsa Kāli; 2) Ib. III. 3. 75. the kingdom of. 3) Vā. 99. 386.

महिष
Mahiṣas  (II)--a Janapada of the Ketumālā continent. Vā. 44. 12.

महिषिक
Mahiṣikas --a tribe of the south; 1) M. 114. 47. a kingdom of. 2) Br. II. 16. 57.

महिषी
Mahiṣī --a R. of the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 22. 

महिष्मत्
Mahiṣmat  (I)--the son of Sohañji and father of Bhadrasenaka. Bhā. IX. 23. 22.

महिष्मत्
Mahiṣmat  (II)--a son of Samjaya and father of the powerful Bhadrasena. Br. III. 69. 5; Vā. 94. 5.

महिष्मत्
Mahiṣmat  (III)--a son of Samhata. M. 43. 10.

महिष्मति
Mahiṣmati --the capital of Kārtavīryārjuna. Vā. 94. 26.

मही
Mahī  (I)--a R. in Kuśadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 62; M. 163. 64; Vi. II. 4. 43.

मही
Mahī  (II)--Mādhavī, (Vasundharā); 1) Vi. I. 4. 7, 25-28. rescued by the Lord in Vārāha disguise from Pātāla; earth addressed the Lord in words of praise of his greatness; 2) Ib. I. 4. 12-24. addressed by Sananda and other sages; the earth was rescued with mountains; and was divided into seven islands and created the four; bhū and other worlds; 3) Ib. I. 4. 27-44. see Bhūmī. 4) Ib. V. 1. 57.

मही
Mahī  (III)--with Vikeśī: a sthāna of Rudra; 1) Vi. I. 8. 7. his son was Lohitānga. 2) Ib. I. 8. 11.

महीदुर्ग
Mahīdurga --one of six kinds of fortresses. M. 217. 6.

महीधर
Mahīdhara --an epithet of Viṣṇu. Vi. V. 5. 21. 

महीनेत्र
Mahīnetra --a son of Dyumatsena, ruled for 33 years. M. 271. 28.

महेन्द्र
Mahendra  (I)--a name of Indra (s.v.); 1) Bhā. I. 15. 12; Vā. 39. 10; 53. 33; Vi. I, 9. 18; V. 10. 36; 11. 14. in the Simsumāra. 2) Vā. 52. 95; M. 127. 24.

महेन्द्र
Mahendra  (II)--a Mt. a Kulaparvata of the Bhāratavarṣa; 1) Bhā. V. 19. 16; VII. 14. 32; Br. II. 16. 18; M. 114. 17, 31; 124. 21; Vā. 45. 89; Vi. II. 3. 3. sacred to Indra and Hari and fit for śrāddha; 2) Br. III. 13. 17. Paraśurāma's penance here for 12 years, twice; 3) Ib. III. 44. 36; 46. 29; Bhā. X. 79. 12; IX. 16. 26. aśvamedha at; 4) Br. III. 47. 39, 45; 56. 23; 57. 1; 58. 3; IV. 21. 2; 31. 17; 44. 99. during the war with Bhaṇḍa, the Devī enclosed M. all round by a wall of fire; 5) Ib. IV. 26. 17-32. rivers taking their origin from. 6) Vā. 45. 106.

महेन्द्रनिलय
Mahendranilayas --the people of a Janapada. Vā. 99. 386; Br. III. 74. 198.

महेन्द्रपर्वत
Mahendraparvata --a sacred place for śrāddha; resorted to by Indra; noted for a bilvatree, the making of offerings under which gives good eye-sight. Vā. 77. 17-18.

महेन्द्रभौम
Mahendrabhaumas --hill regions of Mahendra under the Guhas. Vi. IV. 24. 65.

महेन्द्रम्
Mahendram --a tīrtha sacred to the Piṭrs. M. 22. 44.

महेन्द्रवनालयम्
Mahendravanālayam --the place where Vaivasvata Manu performed austerities after retirement from rulership of the world. M. 11. 42. 

महेश्वर
Maheśvara  (I)--(Śiva): cursed the seven sages to be born in every epoch; 1) Br. II. 27. 47; III. 1. 9. got vṛṣa (bull) from Surabhī for his standard; 2) Ib. III. 3. 78-79. lived long in his father-in-law's house after marriage; Meru insulted him as poor and useless when Umā insisted on her husband to go to his house; he went to Benares after which it became Avimukta; 3) Ib. III. 31. 35. 67. 32, 60. also Brahmā; 4) Ib. IV. 1. 203; 2. 221, 257; 4. 35, 73; 7. 49; 14. 18. Stambha; Kāpāli on earth for having removed one face of Brahmā; to get rid of this brahmicide Śiva's service to Kāmākṣī at Kāñcī; blessed for his samādhi; bathed in Pañcasaras and found himself at Kāśi, from there to Kāñcī; Jyotirmayibhikṣa given; the Kapāla dropped out and he was relieved; 5) Ib. IV. 40. 52-59. blessed Kubera to be the lord of the Yakṣas for his penance at the confluence of the Narmadā and the Kāverī. 6) M. 181. 3-5; 185. 12; 189. 10. Praise of, by Kāvya. 7) Vā. 97, 162-202.

महेश्वर
Maheśvara  (II)--as cosmos; hence acintyātma but the source of all beings; Brahmanas from face, Kṣatriyas, from breast, Vaiśyas from the thighs and Śūdras from the feet; 1) Vā. 9. 122. created the world, men, devas, asuras, constellation, night, day, Vedas, etc.; 2) Br. I. 5. 95. the smallest atom among the prakṛtis, never failing, absolute; formless, and of form; the darkness becomes illumination by the contact of tejas; 3) Vā. 101. 226. the six angas of; all wise, all satiating, ever arousing, all free, eternally powerful, and of undiminished strength; 4) Ib. 12. 31-3. a Mahāyogi; 5) Ib. 21. 36. Lokeśa, worshipped in different ways. 6) Ib. 49. 171.

महेश्वरी
Maheśvarī --the Goddess enshrined at Mahākāla; 1) M. 13. 41. a name of Lalitā; 2) Br. IV. 10. 7; 14. 3; 28. 89; 29. 102; 40. 2. Gā and Virūpā dropped out of the face of  Maheśvara; also Rudrāṇī and Mahādevī; was Mati, Smṛti, and Buddhi; asked by Mahādeva to bring the world under control by Yoga. 3) Vā. 23. 5.

महोग्र
Mahogra --a son of Praheti, the Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 91.

महोत्पला
Mahotpalā --a Goddess enshrined at Kamalākṣa. M. 13. 34.

महोत्साह
Mahotsāha --a son of Auttama Manu. Br. II. 36. 39; Vā. 62. 34.

महोदक
Mahodaka --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 10.

महोदया
Mahodayā --the sabhā of the Lord of the Nakṣatras, the seats and altars of pure beryl. Vā. 34. 90.

महोदर
Mahodara  (I)--a son of Puṣpotkaṭā and Viśravas; 1) Br. III. 8. 55; Vā. 70. 49. a Dānava. 2) Ib. 68. 10.

महोदर
Mahodara  (II)--a leader of Śiva Gaṇa ordered by Śiva to fetch Paraśurāma to help the Devas in their war against the Asuras; 1) Br. III. 24. 50, 57; 25. 46. especially to fight Śūra. 2) Ib. III. 46. 11.

महोदरी
Mahodarī --a mother goddess. M. 179. 31.

महोरग
Mahoraga --a son of Viśveśā. M. 171. 49. 

महोष्णीष
Mahoṣṇīṣa --a Rākṣasa residing in Sutalam. Br. II. 20. 23; Vā. 50. 22.

महौजस्
Mahaujas  (I)--a Tuṣita god. Br. II. 36. 11.

महौजस्
Mahaujas  (II)--a son of Bhadrā and Vasudeva. Vā. 96. 171; Br. III. 71. 173.

माक्षतय
Mākṣataya --a Trayārṣeya. M. 200. 15.

मागध
Māgadha  (I)--Jarāsandha who was vanquished by Kṛṣṇa, see Magadha (s.v.). Bhā. III. 3. 10; X. 2. 2; 83. 23.

मागध
Māgadha  (II)--born of Pṛthu's sacrifice with Sūta; panegyrised Pṛthu and got Māgadha country as gift; 1) Bhā. IV. 15. 20; X. 5. 5; 50. 37; 53. 43; 70. 20; 71. 29; 84. 46; Br. II. 36. 113, 159-160, 172; Vā. 62. 95, 137; Vi. I. 13. 52. 64. at Kṛṣṇa's Jātakarma; 2) Br. III. 28. 1 and 4; 27. 13; 49. 21; 55. 9 and 14; IV. 26. 62 in the royal household. 3) M. 212. 14; Vā. 62. 147-148.

मागध
Māgadha  (III)--(Paulastya)--a sage of the 14th epoch of Bhautya Manu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 34; Br. IV. 1. 112; Vā. 100. 116; Vi. III. 2. 44.

मागध
Māgadha  (IV)--a Gandharva. Vā. 69. 26.

मागध
Māgadha  (V)--for Śrutaśravas, son of Somādhi. Vā. 99. 228. 

मागध
Māgadhas  (I)--the people of the Magadha country (eastern country M. P.); a Kingdom of Madhyadeśa; 1) Bhā. X. 2. 2; Br. II. 16. 42; M. 114. 45; 121. 50; 163. 66. Kṣatriya caste of Śākadvīpa. 2) Vi. 11. 4. 69.

मागध
Māgadhas  (II)--the royal line from Bṛahadratha to Śrutaśravas. M. 50. 27-34.

मागधमान
Māgadhamāna --a kind of measure. Vi. VI. 3. 8.

माघ
Māgha  (I)--considered as the first of months; 1) Br. II. 24. 141. gift of Brahmavaivarta Purāṇa in this month leads one to Brahmaloka; 2) M. 53. 36. Mahesvara to be worshipped in this month. 3) Ib. 56. 2; 60. 36; Vā. 50. 122; 53. 113.

माघ
Māgha  (II)--(Pañcadaśi): a yugādi for śrāddha; (saptami) a manvantarādi for śrāddha. M. 17. 4, 7.

माङ्कायन
Māṅkāyana --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 22.

माङ्गलि
Māṅgali --(also Mangali) a pupil of Pauṣyañji, and who learnt a hundred Sāma Samhitas. Bhā. XII. 6. 79.

मंगल्यसूत्रम्
Maṃgalyasūtram --the sacred cord or tāli worn by a married woman. Br. IV. 39. 87.

माठर
Māṭhara  (I)--a Śrutaṛṣi. Br. II. 33. 3. 

माठर
Māṭhara  (II)--the sacred forest in the Vindhyas fit for śrāddha. Br. III. 13. 33; Vā. 77. 33.

माठर
Māṭharas --Kaśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 2.

माणिकन्धर
Māṇikandhara --a Yakṣa, devoted to Lalitā. Br. IV. 33. 78.

माणिचर
Māṇicara --a Yakṣa. M. 47. 30.

माण्डवी
Māṇḍavī --a Goddess enshrined at Māṇḍavya. M. 13. 42.

माण्डव्य
Māṇḍavya  (I)--a tīrtha sacred to Māṇḍavī. M. 13. 42.

माण्डव्य
Māṇḍavya  (II)--a Bhārgava gotrakāra. 1) M. 195. 21. The sage who cursed Yama to be born as Vidura. 2) Bhā. III. 5. 20; Br. II. 27. 25.

माण्डुक
Māṇḍuka --a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 51.

माण्डुकि
Māṇḍuki --a Śrutaṛṣi; a pupil of Indrapramati in charge of a part of the Ṛg Veda. Br. II. 33. 3; 34. 28.

माण्डुकेय
Māṇḍukeya --the sage-poet who was instructed in the Ṛg Samhitā by Indrapramati; his pupil was Devamitra. Bhā. XII. 6. 56; Vi. III. 4. 19. 

माण्डूक
Māṇḍūka --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 21.

माण्ड्व्य
Māṇḍvya --a Ṛtvik at the yajña of Brahmā. Vā. 106. 35.

मातङ्ग
Mātaṅga  (I)--a son of Khaśa and a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 134; Vā. 69. 165; 111. 53.

मातन्ग
Mātanga  (II)--a son of Matanga, and a sage; his wife Siddhimatī gave birth to Laghuśyāmā or Mātangī. Br. IV. 31. 89, 91-106.

मातंगिन्स्
Mātaṃgins --Kaśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 10.

मातंगी
Mātaṃgī --a mind-born mother; is Laghuśyāmā. Br. IV. 19. 80; 31. 104; M. 179. 27.

मातर
Mātaras --Mother Goddesses present in Varuṇa's sacrifice; nine in number; Lakṣmī, Sarasvatī, Gaurī, Caṇḍikā, Tripurāmbikā, Bhairavā, Kālī, Mahāśāstri; use of liquor in the worship of the deities; 1) Br. III. 1. 28; IV. 7. 72; 14. 6; 20. 46; 44. 111-12. consorts of; 2) Ib. II. 25. 69. Mātras: also Kīrti (fame), Lakṣmī (riches), Dhṛtī (courage), Medhā (wisdom), Puṣṭi (strength), Śraddha (faith), Kriyā (action), Mati (Knowledge), Buddhi (intelligence), Lajjā (modesty), Vapu (body), Śānti (peace), Tuṣṭi (contentment) and Kānti (beauty) invoked in Gṛahabali. 3) M. 93. 53. A list of Mātaras created by Rudra to vanquish the Andhaka Asuras; the mother-goddess felt hungry and thirsty and asked Śiva for food; the pangs of hunger were so keen that they ate of the worldly beings; Śiva then thought of Nṛsimha and praised Him; he created a number of mother-goddesses to overpower them; then all of them  were blessed to be divine beings and help people to tide over difficulties when they would remember and pray to them; seven mothers. 4) Ib. 179. 9-32, 41-89.

मातरिश्व
Mātariśva --is Vāyu; heard the Bṛahmāṇḍa Purāṇa from the Creator and narrated it to Uśanas; 1)Br. IV. 2. 112, 114, 259; 4. 58. related the story in sweet words as seen and in logical order. 2) Vā. 1. 47; 59. 111; 101. 7 and 112, 114, 323; 103. 58.

मातरिश्वान
Mātariśvānas --resident Gods of Bhuvarloka. Vā. 101. 29.

मातलि
Mātali --the charioteer of Indra; 1) M. 148. 81. attacked by Jambha in the Devāsura war; attacked by Pāka; in chariot, surrounded by all the Devas against Tāraka on the other side; wounded by three darts of Tāraka; his mudgara thrown on the chariot, went to pieces. Mātali did not die; 2) Bhā. VIII. 11. 16-18, 22; M. 153. 161, 181, 193; 174. 10. acted as the charioteer of Rāma in his war with Rāvaṇa. 3) Bhā. IX. 10. 21.

माता
Mātā  (I)--is Lalitā; the goddess enshrined at Siddhapura, and at Kāyārohaṇa. Br. IV. 29. 44, 142; M. 13. 46, 48.

माता
Mātā  (II)--the daughter of Ṛṣā; gave birth to Grahas, Anujyeṣṭakas, Niṣkas, and Śiśumāras; 1) Vā. 69. 291. different fishes; (the word reads mīnā by mistake.) 2) Ib. 69. 293.

मातुरंश
Māturaṃśa --the portion of a man's body, which he derives from his mother; this part of Vena's body gave rise to the Mlecchas. M. 10. 8. 

मातुलङ्गस्थली
Mātulaṅgasthalī --the āśrama of Bṛhaspati. Vā. 38. 42-4.

मातुलसम्बन्दम्
Mātulasambandam --marrying in maternal uncle's family. Yayāti cursed his son Yadu to bring forth refractory sons by such relationship. M. 33. 8.

मातेय
Māteyas --sages. M. 200. 12.

मातृ
Mātṛs --a Deva gaṇa; 1) Vā. 72. 50. fought with Utkala in the Devāsura war, but were put to flight by Kṛṣṇa. 2) Bhā. II. 10. 38; VI. 8. 25; VIII. 10. 33; X. 63. 11.

मातृकम्
Mātṛkam --a mantranyāsa in Dīkṣa. Br. IV. 43. 11.

मातृका
Mātṛkā --the wife of Aryama and mother of Carṣaṇis. Bhā. VI. 6. 42.

मातृक
Mātṛkas --evil spirits (see Mātṛs). Bhā. X. 6. 28.

मातृगण
Mātṛgaṇas --see Mātaras. M. 184. 11.

मातृगृहम्
Mātṛgṛham --a tīrtha sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 76.

मातृनन्दा
Mātṛnandā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 12.

मातृसामान्य
Mātṛsāmānyas --the Rākṣasas who cause fear to children. Vā. 69. 190. 

मात्रा
Mātrā --the shortest period of time. Vi. VI. 3. 6.

मात्स्य
Mātsya --a son of Vasu. Vi. IV. 19. 81.

मात्स्य
Mātsyas --a tribe. Vā. 47. 48.

मात्स्यन्याय
Mātsyanyāya --the small fish being eaten by big fish; the rule of might. M. 225. 9.

मात्स्यम्
Mātsyam (Purāṇam) --originally told by Gadādhara; 1) M. 1. 10. told by Janārdana in the guise of a fish to Manu consisting of a description of Narasimha and an account of the seven kalpas and consisting of 14,000 verses; he who gives it along with a golden fish and a cow on the first day of the Caitra month gets the benefit of the gift of the whole world. 2) Ib. 53. 50-2; Vā. 104. 3.

मात्स्य
Mātsya Rūpa --(Matsya avatār) of Viṣṇu, being the tenth avatār during the deluge in the epoch of Cākṣuṣa manvantara for the protection of Vaivasvata Manu. Bhā. I. 3. 15.

माथुर
Māthuras --a tribe; ended their lives by killing their own men. Bhā. X. 1. 27; XI. 30. 18.

माथैल्य
Māthailya --one of the seven sons of Vidyoparicara. a Vasu and Girika. Vā. 99. 222. 

मादि
Mādi --a sage. M. 196. 26.

माद्रवती
Mādravatī --(Mādrī) one of the two wives of Pāṇḍu, gave birth to two twins, Nakula and Sahadeva by the grace of Aśvins. Bhā. IX. 22. 28; Br. III. 71. 155; M. 46. 10; 50. 48; Vā. 96. 154; 99. 243; Vā. 99. 243; Vi. IV. 14. 37-8; 20-40.

माद्रवस
Mādravasa --a Viśvedeva. Br. III. 3. 31.

माद्राराम
Mādrārāmas --the country of. Vi. II. 3. 18.

माद्रि
Mādri --a Tripravara. M. 196. 33.

माद्री
Mādrī  (I)--see Mādravatī. Bhā. IX. 22. 28; M. 50. 48; Vā. 99. 243.

माद्री
Mādrī  (II)--one of the wives of Dṛṣṭi; her sons were Yudhājit, Midharāmsa, Animitra and Śinī. Br. III. 71. 18-19.

माद्री
Mādrī  (III)--the second wife of Vṛṣṇi; gave birth to five sons, Yudhājit (Devamiḍhuṣa), Anamitra, etc. M. 45. 1-2; Vā. 96. 17-9.

माद्री
Mādrī  (IV)--a queen of Kṛṣṇa; mother of Vṛka and other sons. M. 47. 14; Vā. 96. 234; Vi. V. 32. 4.

माद्री
Mādrī  (V)--the mother of Suhotra by Sahadeva, the Pāṇḍava. M. 50. 55. 

माद्रेय
Mādreya --a kingdom of Madhyadeśa. Br. II. 16. 40.

माधव
Mādhava  (I)--a name of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. I. 15. 18; Br. II. 31. 77; III. 33. 18; 72. 140; IV. 9. 61; 34. 72 and 77; Vi. V. 20. 35.

माधव
Mādhava  (II)--the month sacred to Aryaman; 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 34. (Tamil Vaikāśi); with the month of Madhu forms a ṛtu. 2) Br. II. 13. 9; Vā. 52. 5.

मधव
Madhava  (III)--a son of Auttama Manu. M. 9. 12.

माधव
Mādhava  (IV)--with Vaṭeśvara in Prayāgā; 1) M. 22. 9; forming a part of the figure, Śivanārāyaṇa; 2) Ib. 249. 48; 260. 22. in the middle of the Viśvacakra. 3) Ib. 285. 16.

माधव
Mādhava  (V)--an Asura killed by Śatrughna. Vā. 88. 185; 112. 40.

माधव
Mādhavas --a tribe deriving its name from Madhu. Bhā. IX. 23. 30.

माधववन
Mādhavavana --sacred to Sugandhā. M. 13. 37.

माधवश्री
Mādhavaśrī --a queen of Vasanta ṛtu. Br. IV. 32. 23, 46. 

माधवा
Mādhavā --an Apsarasa sent by Indra to destroy Viṣṇu's tapas. M. 61. 22.

माधवी
Mādhavī  (I)--a name of Yogamāyā. Bhā. X. 2. 12.

माधवी
Mādhavī  (II)--name of Subhadrā. Bhā. X. 84. 1.

माधवी
Mādhavī  (III)--a R. in the Kuru country. Br. II. 18. 73.

माधवी
Mādhavī  (IV)--a Varṇa śakti. Br. IV. 44. 61.

माधवी
Mādhavī  (V)--a Goddess enshrined at Śrīśaila. M. 13. 31.

माधवी
Mādhavī  (VI)--a R. from the Jayā lake. Vā. 47. 71.

माधवी
Mādhavī  (VII)--see Mahī. Vi. I. 4. 20.

माधवीयम्
Mādhavīyam --a stotra in praise of Kṛṣṇa. M. 248. 58.

माध्यम्दिन
Mādhyamdina --a Trayārṣeya. M. 200. 15.

माध्यन्दिन
Mādhyandinas --learnt the Vājaseni yajus. Bhā. XII. 6. 74. 

माध्रि
Mādhri --a son of Yudhājit. Vā. 96. 101.

मान
Māna --a Sādhya. M. 203. 11.

मानद
Mānada --Pṛthu was this, to those who were pitiful. Bhā. IV. 16. 16.

मानदा
Mānadā  (I)--a kalā of the moon. Br. IV. 35. 92.

मानम्
Mānam --four kinds of; Saura, Saumya, Nakṣatra and Sāvana; a measurement. Vā. 50. 188. Br. II. 21. 137.

मानरसा
Mānarasā --a daughter of Bhadrāśva and Ghṛtācī. Vā. 70. 69.

मानव
Mānava  (I)--a Pañcārṣeya. M. 196. 50.

मानव
Mānava  (II)--the 20th kalpa. M. 290. 8.

मानस
Mānasa  (I)--a Mt. of Puṣkaradvīpa; the limit of Pṛthu's dominion; west of the city of Vasavī. Br. II. 19. 112-14, 117; M. 123. 16; Vā. 49. 108; Vi. II. 8. 7-8.

मानस
Mānasa  (II)--a son of Vapuṣmān and the founder of the Mānasa kingdom. Br. II. 14. 32, 34; Vā. 33. 28, 30; Vi. II. 4, 23, 29. 

मानस
Mānasa  (III)--a Vamśavartin god. Br. II. 36. 29.

मानस
Mānasa  (IV)--a Yakṣa; a son of Devajanī and Maṇivara. Br. III. 7. 130.

मानस
Mānasa  (V)--one of the four lakes in Meru; surrounds all the sides of the Meru over which is established the capital of the Lokapālas; at the foot of the Vaidyūta hill from which the R. Sarayu rises; 1) M. 113. 46; 121. 16; 163. 86; 183. 2; 194. 8; Br. II. 18. 15; 21. 29-33; Vā. 47. 14; 50. 87-90; 111. 4. north of the Ganges; 2) Br. I. 1. 76; M. 70. 20; 107. 2; Vā. 36. 16; 42. 27; 77. 110-11. a tīrtha sacred to Kumuda and the Pitṛs; 3) M. 13. 27; 22. 23. fit for śrāddha; contains a shrine on its banks; 4) Br. III. 13, 58, 115-6; IV. 2. 25-6. in Ilāvṛta. 5) Vi. II. 2. 26. Kardama went there with his wife; 6) Bhā. I. 5. 10; III. 23. 40. a reference to two Hamsas of the lake; one of them who took to household life was Purañjana; hearing from the other Hamsa he remembered his old place and became calm; 7) Ib. V. 28. 54 and 63. Indra spent 1,000 years in the lotus stalks of the lake; 8) Ib. VI. 13. 14-5. here was the third rebirth of Kauśika's seven sons as Cakravāka birds and their final salvation after becoming Siddhas. 9) M. 20. 17; 21. 35. Ūrvaśī sported with Purūravas in. 10) Vi. IV. 6. 48.

मानस
Mānasa  (VI)--Father of Riṣyanta, belonging to the commencement of the Dvāpara in the 11th Manvantara. Vā. 70. 30.

मानस
Mānasas  (I)--the Pitṛs as sons of Vasiṣṭha, with forms, live in jyoti worlds; their mind-born daughter is Gau, wife of Śukra. M. 15. 12-15. 

मानस
Mānasas  (II)--the Vaiśya caste of Śākadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 69.

मानसम्
Mānasam --the region of Śālmalidvīpa adjoining the Mahiṣa hill. Br. II. 19. 45; Vā. 49. 40.

मानसा
Mānasā --the world above Brahmāṇḍa where live the Somapa Pitṛs; 1) M. 15. 25. the country of Pitṛs--Sukālas. 2) Br. III. 10. 97; Vā. 73. 47.

मानसी
Mānasī --a Dīkṣā. Br. IV. 43. 7.

मानसी
Mānasī siddhi --five characteristics of; Devas resident in Maharloka possessed of this power, perform sacrifices. Vā. 101. 44-5.

मानसोत्तर
Mānasottara --a hill of Puṣkaradvīpa to the east of Meru; Devadhāni, the city of Indra and other cities are there; like the wheel of an oil mill the wheel of Sūrya's chariot is said to rotate on the hill as its axis; resorted to by the Devas and Daityas. ^1 Bhā. V. 20. 30; 21. 7 & 13; Vi. II. 4. 74. ^2 Vi. II. 4. 80.

मानस्तोक
Mānastoka --a mantra for grahahoma. M. 239. 9.

मानुष
Mānuṣa sarga --the seventh sarga with hitherward current (arvāk srota). Vā. 6. 64. 

मानुषी
Mānuṣī --a R. of the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 22.

मानुषीविश
Mānuṣīviśa --one of the Marut gaṇas. Vā. 67. 129.

मान्धात
Māndhāta (Māndhātri) --a son of Yuvanāśva, was born of him by splitting open the right side of his stomach; to the crying child Indra gave his first finger to suckle and called him Trasadasyu (s.v.) as he was a terror to the Dasyus; celebrated as a great emperor by the Paurāṇikas, having lust for more territory; married (Bindumatī-Bhā and Vi. P.) Caitrarathī, daughter of Śaśabindu, (Satabindu-Vi. P.); had three sons, Purukusta, Ambarīṣa, and Mucukunda besides fifty daughters, all of whom were married to Saubhari; 1) Bhā. IX. 6. 30-38; 7. 1; X. 51. 14; XII. 3. 9; Vā. 99. 130; Vi. IV. 2. 61-112; Br. III. 63. 68-72; M. 12. 34; 49. 8. he built for them crystal palaces; gave them all comforts and himself lived constantly with each of them by his yogic powers; they gave birth to 150 sons and Māndhāta visited them after a long time and found them happy; was blessed by the sage and returned home; a Kṣatropetadvija; 2) Br. III. 66. 86. an incarnation of Viṣṇu as human being with Uthathya, in the 15th Treta (with Uttankapurohita in the 15th Tretāyuga-M. P.); 3) Ib. III. 73. 90; M. 47. 243; Vā. 98. 90. an Angirasa and mantrakṛt; 4) Br. II. 32. 108; M. 145. 102; Vā. 59. 99. worshipped Hari as yajña, knew the yoga power of Hari and got over his māyā; 5) Bhā. II. 7. 44. a great conquering monarch; a popular king, a yajva, of good character; 6) Vā. 88. 66-70. became a Brahmana; 7) Ib. 91. 115. Tattya was his purohita. 8) Ib. 99. 130. 

मामतेय
Māmateya --the Purohita of Bharata. Bhā. IX. 20. 25.

मांस
Māṃsa --flesh offered to Goddess Kālī. Vi. V. 1. 86.

माय
Māyas--Mohanavidyas  taught to Pradyumna by Māyāvatī. Vi. V. 27. 14.

मायव
Māyava --a Vānara jāti. Br. III. 7. 319.

माया
Māyā  (I)--created by the Lord with a view to creating the world; 1) Bhā. I. 2. 30; III. 5. 25. Role of: source of bondage; 2) Bhā. XI. 11. 1-3; Vā. 94. 15. four characteristics of: its influence on jñāna: means to get rid of. 3) Bhā. XI. 3. 1-33.

माया
Māyā  (II)--a daughter of Adharma. Bhā. IV. 8. 2.

माया
Māyā  (III)--is Yogamāyā; a mind-born mother; 1) Bhā. X. 2. 12; M. 179. 21. from the heart of Narasimha; 2) Ib. 179. 64. a śakti. 3) Br. II. 26. 9, 29; IV. 6. 53; 12. 21 & 49; 44. 62; Vā. 24. 86.

माया
Māyā  (IV)--a daughter of Maya; 1) Br. II. 9. 64. wife of Bhayam and mother of Mṛtyu; 2) Vā. 10. 40. helpmate of Vārāhaviṣṇu. 3) Br. I. 5. 19. 

माया
Māyā  (V)--the essence milked by the Asuras from the cow-earth. M. 10. 21.

माया
Māyā  (VI)--one of the kingly upāyas. M. 222. 2.

माया
Māyā  (VII)--(Vaiṣṇavī): Atimohini and Triguṇātmaka. Vi. V. 21. 1; 30. 14-9.

माया
Māyā  (VIII)--represents the lips of the Vedas, 1) Vā. 104. 75. makes different varieties of and varied guṇas with śīlas. 2) Ib. 104. 41.

मायाकिरात
Māyākirāta --reference to Śiva as a divine Hunter. Bhā. III. 1. 38.

मायादेवी
Māyādevī --worshipped by a seeker of fortune. Bhā. II. 3. 3.

माया
Māyā(purī) --also Māyā, one of the seven great cities; 1) Br. IV. 40. 91. sacred to Kumārī and to Pitṛs. 2) M. 13. 34; 22. 10.

मायामयम्
Māyāmayam sthānam --the atom of Īśvara; Śānkhyas style Prakṛti for māyā. Vā. 101. 218.

मायामोह
Māyāmoha --the form which Viṣṇu took to vanquish the Asuras under Hrāda who defeated the Gods; he approached the Asuras as a naked mendicant, clean shaven and with a bunch of peacock feathers, performing austeri ties in the Narmadā and led them from the path of the Vedas by calling them Arhats; they left the trodden path and abandoned vedic practices and rites, and decried vedic sacrifices. Vi. III. 17. 14-45; 18. 1-32.

मायावती
Māyāvatī --Rati in her former birth: when her husband was burnt by Śiva, she was reborn as the superintendent of Śambara's kitchen. Hearing from Nārada that Pradyumna was Kāma and that he was thrown into sea by Śambara and swallowed by a fish and was brought to her kitchen, she nursed him lovingly and when he came of age, she spoke the truth and taught him mahāmāyā vidyā with which he killed Śambara: She took him by air to Kṛṣṇa and was rejoiced to become the daughter-in-law of Kṛṣṇa and Rukmiṇī. Bhā. X. 55. 6-38; Vi. V. 27. 7-16, 27-30.

मायाविनोद
Māyāvinodas --are the Daityas, Dānavas and Kādraveyas; enjoy life to the utmost; only afraid of Hari's cakra. Bhā. V. 24. 8. 11-15.

मायावी
Māyāvī --a son of Maya and Rambhā. Br. III. 6. 29; Vā. 68. 28.

मायु
Māyu --belonging to the line of Krodhavaśa. Br. III. 8. 70.

मारकतशाला
Mārakataśālā --next to muktāśālā of Lalitā--Palmyra juice is used here: nearby in a grove lives the creator: Fourteen Vidyas, Upavidyas 64 Kalas all reside here: a little away is Viṣṇuloka with a 1000 pillars: beyond that is Śivaloka. Br. IV. 34. 54. 

मारिष
Māriṣa --a southern country. Br. II. 16. 59.

मारिषा
Māriṣā --a daughter of a Bhoja king; wife of Devamīḍha and mother of Vasudeva and others. Bhā. IX. 24. 27; Br. III. 71. 145.

मारी
Mārī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 15.

मारीच
Mārīca  (I)--a son of Sunda and Tāḍaka; set up by Rāvaṇa to take the form of a golden deer in order to secure Sītā: killed by Rāma. Bhā. IX. 10. 5, 10; Br. III. 5. 35-6; Vā. 62. 72; Vi. IV. 4. 89.

मारीच
Mārīca  (II)--the author of a Purāṇa: married Pulomā and Kālakā, daughters of Vaiśvānara: These had 1000 sons besides the fourteen who lived in Hiraṇyapura. Br. II. 38. 5; III. 6. 26; 7. 464; 47. 60.

मारीच
Mārīca  (III)--(Mārīcakaśyapa): a son of Antardhāna and grandson of Pṛthu; 1) M. 4. 45. his wife Vasu abandoned him for Soma; 2) Ib. 23. 25. his sons are said to reside in the Somapatha worlds of the Pitṛs. 3) Ib. 14. 1.

मारीच
Mārīcas  (I)--a devagaṇa. Br. III. 1. 50.

मारीच
Mārīcas  (II)--Kaśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 9. 

मारीचवंश
Mārīcavaṃśa --the world created with moveables and immoveables in the epoch of; he stood in waters and performed penance for 7000 years and got Surucirditi who in turn got Ariṣṭanemi; then Kaśyapa to whom Dakṣa, gave his daughter in marriage. Vā. 65. 109, 118.

मारीचि
Mārīci --a son of Danu; father of many sons numbering 6000, Paulomas and Kālakeyas, all residents of Hiraṇyapura and could not be killed even by the Devas, because of a special boon from Brahmā; Arjuna slew them; 1) Br. III. 6. 5; M. 6. 18, 23-35. his wives, Pulomā and Kālakā, the daughters of Vaiśvānara. 2) Vi. I. 21. 8-9.

मारीची
Mārīcī  (I)--the wife of Parjanya. Br. II. 11. 19; Vā. 28. 16.

मारीची
Mārīcī  (II)--an Apsarasa. Br. III. 7. 6; Vā. 69. 5.

मारीषा
Mārīṣā  (I)--a daughter of Kaṇḍu and Pramloca (of Soma M. P.) (of plants and trees, Śākhin Br. P.) brought up by trees and married to Pracetasas who were the ten sons of Prācīnabarhisa; mother of Dakṣa: gave birth to trees, plants, and (R. Candravatī (M. P.) In the previous birth, she was the queen of a king who died young. She became a widow with no son; prayed to the Lord who blessed her with ten righteous husbands. These were the Pracetasas and had a number of sons; she herself had a miraculous birth. Bhā. IV. 30. 13 and 47-9; Br. I. 1. 107; II. 13. 70; 37. 32-8; M. 4. 49-50. Vi. I. 15. 8-9, 46-50, 61-71.

मारीषा
Mārīṣā  (II)--the wife of Śūra and mother of Vasudeva and others. Vi. IV. 14. 26-7. 

मारुत
Māruta  (I)--the Wind God, a) Br. II. 10. 43; Vā. 101. 194; 106. 59. appointed father of Bhīma; 1) Br. III. 71. 154; M. 50. 49; Vā. 96. 153. with Agni appointed to destroy the Asuras; Soma escaped to the ocean; Indra ordered them to dry up the ocean and they refused to incure this sin; hence were cursed to be born on the earth; did so in one body as Agastya; 2) M. 61. 3-19. the lord of gandhas or scents. 3) Vā. 70. 11.

मारुत
Māruta  (II)--a Pravara of the Bhārgavas. M. 195. 31; 196. 19.

मारुतम्
Mārutam Purāṇam --the Vāyu Purāṇa equal to the Vedas. Vā. 4. 12.

मारुतंव्रतम्
Mārutaṃvratam --of Kings whose spies enter everywhere as the wind enters everything unnoticed. M. 226. 12.

मारुतालयम्
Mārutālayam --a tīrtha on the Narmadā; bath in it takes one to the Vāyuloka in a heavenly chariot. M. 191. 86-8.

मारुति
Māruti --is Hanumān, of superior bhakti. Br. III. 34. 39.

मारुतेश्वर
Māruteśvara --is Vāyu; consorts are Iḍā, Piṅgalā and Suṣumṇā; 1) Br. IV. 33. 69-70. a pītha sacred to Lalitā. 2) Ib. IV. 44. 96.

मार्कण्ड
Mārkaṇḍa --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 20; 196. 45.

मार्कण्डेय
Mārkaṇḍeya  (I)--a Siddha not lost in deluge; 1) Bhā. VI. 15. 12; M. 2. 13; 186-3. son of Mṛkaṇḍa; 2) Bhā. IV. 1. 45. his firm and non-parallelled tapas and vow of  celibacy; saw the Puruṣa sleeping on a leaf of the vaṭavṛksa; his āśrama near the Himālayas on a Śila-citra; Indra sent the God of Love, Apsaras and others to disturb him, but in vain; the mahātmā, seeing Hari in Nara-Nārāyaṇa form praised him; pleased with him as one who would be ever meditating on his feet Hari showed him what a Pralaya was; Pārvatī and Śiva. saw him, and were praised; when Śiva offered to grant him anything he wanted, he expressed his wish to be ever devoted to him and Hari; pleased with him Śiva went away with Pārvatī; this worthy son of the Bhṛgu race having earned Yogic vision and absolutely devoted to Hari even now goes about the world; 3) Ib. XII. Chh. 8, 9 and 10. an authority on Rāma's story. 4) Ib. VII. 1. 44.

मार्कण्डेय
Mārkaṇḍeya  (II)--a contemporary of Dattātreya; Purohita, the fourth incarnation of Dāttātreya, born to help him; 1) Br. II. 33. 11; III. 73. 89; M. 47. 242; 53. 26; Vā. 98. 89; 109. 24; 112. 34. narrated the Mārkaṇḍeya Purāṇa; 2) M. 47. 242; 53. 26. acted as Brahmā in Paraśurāma's sacrifice. 3) Br. III. 47. 46; IV. 39. 55.

मार्कण्डेय
Mārkaṇḍeya  (III)--speaks of the greatness of the Narmadā to Yudhiṣṭhira; 1) M. 190. 1; 191. 81; 192. 6; 193. 66; 194. 48. came to Syamantapāncaka to see Kṛṣṇa. 2) Bhā. X. 84. 4.

मार्कण्डेय
Mārkaṇḍeya  (IV)--a son of Manasvinī and Mṛkaṇḍu; 1) Vā. 28. 5; Vi. I. 10. 4. wife Dhūmrapatnī and son Vedaśiras; 2) Br. II. 11. 7. present at Rāma's abhiṣeka. 3) Vi. IV. 4. 99.

मार्कण्डेय
Mārkaṇḍeya  (V)--a disciple of Indra Pramati entrusted with a Samhitā; his son and grandson were respectively Satyaśravas and Satyahita who traditionally handed it down. Vā. 60. 27-28. 

मार्कण्डेय
Mārkaṇḍeyas --the sages, descendants and sons of Pīvarī and Vedaśiras. Vā. 28. 6.

मार्कण्डेयम्
Mārkaṇḍeyam --a Mahā Purāṇa told by Mārkaṇḍeya; containing 9000 ślokas; he who copies it and makes a gift of it in the month of Kārttika attains the fruits of Puṇḍarīka yajña. Bhā. XII. 7. 24; 13. 5; Vā. 104. 4; Vi. III. 6. 21; M. 53. 26-7.

मार्कण्डेयी
Mārkaṇḍeyī --the wife of Rakṣa (Rajas Vā. P.) her son was Ketumān. Br. II. 11. 42; Vā. 28. 37.

मार्कति
Mārkati --an Ārṣeyapravara. (Angiras). M. 196. 22.

मार्ग
Mārgas --highways and byways; diśāmārga, grāmamārga, rājapatha, sākharathyas, gṛharathyas, uparathyas, ghaṇṭāpatha, grahāntaram, vṛttimārga and prāgvamśa with their respective measurements. Avaskaram and Parīvāham are other dispositions of open spaces. 1) Vā. 7. 118-22. 1. dik--20 dhanus in breadth. 2. Grāma 20 dhanus in breadth. 3. Sīma 10 dhanus in breadth. 4. Rājapatha 10 dhanus in breadth. 5. Śākhāratyas or streets 4 dhanus. 6. Rathyoparathyas 3 dhanus. 7. Upārathya rathas 2 dhanus.  8. Janghāpatha 4 feet 9. Gṛhāntaram (lanes) 3 feet. 10. Dhṛtimārga 6 feet and more. 11. Avaskāraparīvāra 1 ft. all round. 2) Br. II. 7. 112-16.

मार्गदायिनी
Mārgadāyinī --a Goddess enshrined at Kedāra. M. 13. 30.

मार्गपथ
Mārgapatha --a Bhārgava. M. 195. 33.

मार्गशीर्षि
Mārgaśīrṣi --month of, good for the gift of the Agni Purāṇa; 1) M. 53. 29. best for military expedition. 2) Ib. 56. 2; 60. 35; 240. 5.

मार्गा
Mārgā --a Brahmavādin. Br. II. 33. 19.

मार्गेय
Mārgeya --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 20.

मार्जार
Mārjāra  (I)--a Vānara jāti; born of Hari and Pulaha. Br. III. 7. 177. 305, 319; 51. 11.

मार्जार
Mārjāra  (II)--a son of Jāmbavān. Br. III. 7. 303.

मार्जारि
Mārjāri --a son of Sahadeva and father of Śrutaśravas. Bhā. IX. 22. 46.

मार्ताण्ड
Mārtāṇḍa  (I)--the Sun God; Brahmā placed the tejas of the Aṇḍam in the garbha of Aditī and when everything became stunted, the God removed it from the garbha mak ing it into two pieces; finding the weakness of the garbha Brahmā caused it to be placed in the lap of the Sun God; hence the name; 1) Br. III. 7. 275-288; M. 2. 35. another ety.:--when Kaśyapa found the universe divided into two, he was in distress and said you be Martāṇḍa or Vivasvān, son of Kaśyapa and Dākṣāyanī; had seven sons; Sāvarṇi and Śanaiścara are the last; 2) Vā. 84. 25. R. Yamunā, the daughter of; 3) Br. III. 13. 72. Nāsatya and Dasra, sons of; 4) Ib. III. 59. 25; IV. 38. 23. golden image of, for gift; 5) M. 9. 3; 280. 6. maṇḍalam of. 6) Br. I. 1. 115.

मार्ताण्ड
Mārtāṇḍa  (II)--handing over the Yajus to Yajñavalkya, Brahmarateya. Vā. 61. 21.

मार्ताण्डकुलम्
Mārtāṇḍakulam --the solar line. M. 290. 24.

मार्ताण्डमण्डलम्
Mārtāṇḍamaṇḍalam --here is located the world of Marīcigarbha where live the Haviṣmanta Pitṛs. M. 15. 16.

मार्त्तिकावरस्
Mārttikāvaras --Bhojas called as after the city, Mṛttikāvara. Vi. IV. 13. 7.

मार्षा
Mārṣā --the mother of Dakṣa in the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Vā. 30. 61. 74.

मार्ष्टपिंगलि
Mārṣṭapiṃgali --a Pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 18.

मार्ष्ठि
Mārṣṭhi --a son of Sāraṇa. Vi. IV. 15. 21. 

माल
Mālas --a Janapada of the East. Vā. 45. 123.

मालती
Mālatī --(also Mālavī) the queen of Aśvapati and mother of Sāvitrī, the pativrata; 1) M. 208. 10. her sons are called the Mālavas of pure Kṣatriya stock. 2) Ib. 213. 16.

मालयनि
Mālayani --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 26.

मालव
Mālava  (I) (Mālva)--sacred to Lalitā. Br. IV. 44. 95.

मालव
Mālava  (II)--(c) dvijas of; became Vrātyas after the days of Purañjaya. Bhā. XII. 1. 38; Vi. II. 3. 17.

मालव
Mālavas --a Kṣatriya tribe of the Vindhyas; sons of Aśvapati and Mālavī; 1) M. 114. 44. 52; 163. 67; 213. 16; Vā. 45. 132. enlisted by Jarāsandha against the Yadus. 2) Bhā. X. [50 (V) 2].

मालवी
Mālavī --same as Mālatī. M. 213. 16.

माला
Mālā (Cintāmaṇi) --Kubera's wedding present to Kāmeśvara. Br. IV. 15. 22.

मालाकार
Mālākāra --the flower seller who offered Kṛṣṇa and Rāma flowers liked by them and was blessed with wealth and long life to him, to his generations of his successors. Vi. V. 19. 17-28. 

मालि
Māli(n) --the father of Kaikasī and father-in-law of Visravas; a follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra; a Rākṣasa in the fifth talam; slain by Hari in the Devāsura war. Bhā. VI. 10. 21; VIII. 10. 57; Br. II. 20. 37; III. 8. 40. Vā. 70. 34.

मालिनी
Mālinī  (I)--a śakti; a mind-born mother. Br. IV. 36. 76, 96; M. 179. 9.

मालिनी
Mālinī  (II)--the ancient name of the city of Campā; also known as Campāvatī. M. 48. 97; Vā. 99. 105.

माल्यवन्
Mālyavan  (I)--Mt. a mountain range to the east of Meru, south of Nīla, north of Niṣādha and west of Ilāvrata and a boundary limit of Ketumālā, a thousand yojanas in extent; the stream Cakṣus descends from its summits; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 10; 17. 7; M. 113. 35; Vā. 34. 33-4; 42. 19 and 42; Vi. II. 2. 27, 39. at its top is Amarakaṇṭaka in Kalinga. 2) Br. II. 15. 38; 17. 18; III. 13. 7 and 13.

माल्यवन्
Mālyavan  (II)--a son of Rākṣasa, Prahati; slain by Hari in the Devāsura war; his daughters were Puṣpotkaṭā and Vākā; father-in-law of Viśravas. Bhā. VIII. 10. 57; Br. III. 7. 90; 8. 39. Vā. 70. 34.

माल्यवन्
Mālyavan  (III)--(varṣam) a kingdom of Bhadrāśva. Br. II. 14. 51; Vā. 33. 44; 43. 5.

माल्यवन्
Mālyavan  (IV)--a son of Lanku. Vā. 69. 129. 

माष
Māṣas --a tribe; 1) M. 114. 52. a kind of grain. 2) Ib. 217. 38.

माषकम्
Māṣakam --weight in gold; fine for failure to feed Brahmanas when there is occasion for it and for mentioning one man to a prostitute and taking her to another; in silver for causing injury to animals and insects and for other offences. M. 227. 7, 89, 108, 146.

माषम्
Māṣam --a small coin; fine of, for removing the rope, pot, etc., from a well; 1) M. 227. 98. a weight. 2) Vi. VI. 3. 8.

माषशरावय
Māṣaśarāvayas --sages. M. 200. 9.

मास
Māsa --30 days and nights; two pakṣas; two months equal to a ṛtu; six months constitute an ayaṇa and two ayaṇas make one year; the twelve names of months Tapa, Tapasya, etc. are mentioned. Br. II. 7. 20; 13. 14 and 114; Vā. 3. 14; 30. 16 and 178; 31. 26; Vā. 65. 58; Vi. I. 3. 9-10; II. 8. 81; VI. 3. 10.

मासकृत्
Māsakṛt --a Sutapa god. Br. IV. 1. 14.

मासश्राद्ध
Māsaśrāddha --the feeding of Manuṣya Pitṛs or Laukikas. Br. II. 28. 67, 78. M. 141. 65. Vā. 83. 3-10.

माहिष
Māhiṣa --the region under the Guhas. Vi. IV. 24. 65.

माहिष
Māhiṣas --a royal dynasty. Vā. 99. 374. 

माहिषक
Māhiṣakas --the people of the Dakṣiṇāpatha. Vā. 45. 125.

माहिषिक
Māhiṣikas --a degraded Kṣatriya clan. Br. III. 63. 140.

माहिष्मती
Māhiṣmatī --the capital of the Haihayas, on the Revā (Narmadā). Entered by Paraśurāma who put to sword all the Kṣatriyas to avenge his father's death; visited by Balarāma; 1) Bhā. IX. 15. 22; 16. 17; X. 79. 21. originally a Nāga capital with Karkoṭaka sabhā; 2) Br. III. 38. 2; 46. 11; 69. 26. the place where Kārtavīrya defeated Karkoṭaka's son; 3) M. 43. 29. the place where Rāvaṇa was imprisoned by Kārtavīryārjuna; 4) Ib. 43. 38. founded by Māhiṣmān and capital of Kārtavīryārjuna. 5) Vi. IV. 11. 9, 19.

माहिष्मान्
Māhiṣmān --a son of Sahajit, founded the city of Māhiṣmatī; father of Bhadraśreṇiya. Vi. IV. 11. 9-10.

माहेन्द्र
Māhendra --a Rākṣasa of the Atalam. Vā. 50. 18.

माहेन्द्री
Māhendrī  (I)--see Amarāvatī. Br. II. 21. 30.

माहेन्द्री
Māhendrī  (II)--a śakti. Br. IV. 19. 7; 36. 58.

माहेश्वर
Māheśvara  (I)--the 29th Kalpa in which Tripuram was burnt. M. 290. 10.

महेश्वर
Maheśvara  (II)--born of Pradhāna and Puruṣa; father of world creation; 1) Vā. 103. 36. the universe as limbs of. 2) Ib. 103. 71-3. 

माहेश्वरज्वर
Māheśvarajvara --created by Śiva to attack Kṛṣṇa; unable to stand the Vaiṣṇava jvara, it bowed and vanished. Bhā. X. 63. 22-30.

माहेश्वरधर्म
Māheśvaradharmas --in the Skānda Purāṇa; 1) M. 53. 42. Nandi gave out to Nārada the Māheśvara dharmas and vratam. 2) Ib. 95. 3, 4.

माहेश्वरपुरम्
Māheśvarapuram --sacred to Svāhā. M. 13. 42.

माहेश्वरम्
Māheśvaram balam --the Mahāyogam of Śiva; the origin of Linga. Br. II. 26. 65.

माहेश्वरंव्रतम्
Māheśvaraṃvratam --(Śivacaturdaśi): revealed by Nandi to Nārada; to be begun on the 13th day of the bright half of Mārgaśīrṣa in honour of Śaṅkara; details of the worship on the next day; a gold cow and calf to be offered as present to a sāmaga or other śrotriya; ladies who perform this with permission from husband go to the world of Pinākini. M. 95. 5-38.

माहेश्वरी
Māheśvarī  (I)--a śakti and a mother goddess; 1) Br. IV. 19. 7; 36. 58; 44. 111. Images after the manner of Māheśvara. 2) M. 179. 9; 261. 25; 286. 10.

माहेश्वरी
Māheśvarī  (II)--created out of Dakṣiṇāgni for the use of the Kāśi King's son to avenge his father's death at the hands of Kṛṣṇa; unable to bear the Sudarśana of Kṛṣṇa she fled to Kāśī. Vi. V. 34. 39. 

माहेश्वरीविद्या
Māheśvarīvidyā --is Mṛtasamjīvanīvidyā (S. V.) that came out of the face of Maheśvara. M. 249. 6.

माहेश्वर्यम्
Māheśvaryam --a Yoga; the five dharmas originally given by Rudra; other dharmas promulgated by Ādityas, Vasus, Sādhyas, Aśvins, Maruts, Bhṛgus, Yama, Śukra and other agents and Pitṛkālāntakas; the five dharmas are Prāṇāyāma, dhyānam, Pratyāhāra, dhāraṇa and smaraṇa of the Māheśvara Yoga. Vā. 10. 70-74; 23. 153, 224.

मित
Mita  (I)--a Marut of the 5th gaṇa. Br. III. 5. 96.

मित
Mita  (II)--a Sudharmāṇa god. Br. IV. 1. 60.

मितध्वज
Mitadhvaja --a son of Dharmadhvaja and father of Khāṇḍikya. Bhā. IX. 13. 19-20.

मितवान्
Mitavān --a deva of the Svāyambhuva epoch. Br. II. 13. 95.

मिताहार
Mitāhāra --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 239.

मित्र
Mitra  (I)--a Brahmaṛṣi, and one of the seven sons of Vasiṣṭha. Bhā. IV. 1. 41.

मित्र
Mitra  (II)--a son of Aditī; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 39. an Āditya; a name used for the sun; 2) Ib. I. 13. 30; M. 6. 4; Br. II. 23. 5, 104; 24. 33, 39; III. 3. 67; IV. 20. 48; Vā. 66. 66; Vi. I. 15. 131. Bhaga to see through the eye of; 3) Bhā. IV. 7. 3. acted as milkman of the Devas to milk the cow-earth when Indra was calf; the  milk was of vigorous strength and the vessel was of gold; 4) M. 10. 17. loved Ūrvaśī and finding her thinking of Varuṇa, cursed her to be born on the earth; performed austerities at Badarī, saw Ūrvaśī and let flow his retas, which was collected by Ūrvaśī in a pot and from which came Agastya and Vasiṣṭha; 5) Ib. 61. 27, 31; 126. 6; 171. 56; 201. 23-9. fought with Praheti in the Devāsura war; 6) Bhā. VIII. 10. 28. was offered sacrifice by Vasiṣṭha on behalf of Śrāddhadeva; 7) Ib. IX. 1. 13. worshipped by Yudhiṣṭhira and Akrūra; 8) Ib. X. 39. 32. to be worshipped in house-building; also in palace building; 9) M. 253. 43; 268. 22. in the sun's chariot in the months of Śuci and Jyeṣṭha. 10) Vi. II. 10. 7.

मित्र
Mitra  (III)--His wife was Revatī. Utsarga and others were her sons. Bhā. VI. 18. 6.

मित्र
Mitra  (IV)--the name of the sun in the month of Śukra (Jyeṣṭha). Bhā. XII. 11. 35; Vā. 52. 6.

मित्र
Mitra  (V)--a son of Vasudeva and Madīrā. Br. III. 71. 171; Vā. 96. 169.

मित्र
Mitra  (VI)--a Marut gaṇa. M. 171. 52.

मित्र
Mitra  (VII)--of three kinds to a King; the hereditaryally, the enemy of the enemies and the Kṛtrima (acquired) ally. M. 220. 17-18.

मित्र
Mitra  (VIII)--a son of Maṇibhadra. Vā. 69. 156. 

मित्र
Mitra  (IX)--a Vāsiṣṭha branch. Vā. 70. 90.

मित्रक
Mitraka --a tapasvi and a son of the avatār of the 28th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 223.

मित्रज्योति
Mitrajyoti --a daughter of Maruta (MaruttaVā. P.). Br. III. 68. 5; Vā. 93. 5.

मित्रदेवी
Mitradevī --a daughter of Devaka and one of the seven wives of Vasudeva. M. 44. 73.

मित्रपदम्
Mitrapadam --a tīrtha in Kedāra; sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 11.

मित्रबाहु
Mitrabāhu  (I)--a son of Nāgnjiti and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 252; M. 47. 19; Vā. 96. 243.

मित्रबाहु
Mitrabāhu  (II)--a son of the 4th (Ṛtu-Sāvarṇa-Vā. P.). Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 95; Vā. 100. 99.

मित्रवान्
Mitravān  (I)--a son of the IV (Ṛtu-Sāvarṇa-Vā. P.) Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 94; Vā. 100. 99.

मित्रवान्
Mitravān  (II)--a son of Mitravindā and Kṛṣṇa. M. 47. 19.

मित्रविन्द
Mitravinda --a son of Mitravindā and Kṛṣṇa. M. 47. 19. 

मित्रविन्दा
Mitravindā  (I)--a R. in Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 15.

मित्रविन्दा
Mitravindā  (II)--daughter of Kṛṣṇa's aunt in Avantī. Discomfiting Vinda and Anuvinda, Kṛṣṇa married her; her sons; 1) Bhā. X. 58. 31; 61. 16; M. 47. 14; Vā. 96, 234; Vi. V. 28. 3. welcomed by Draupadī to Hāstinapura, she explained how she was married to Kṛṣṇa. 2) Bhā. X. 71. 43; 83. 15-6.

मित्रविन्दु
Mitravindu --a son of Ṛtu Sāvarṇa Manu. Vā. 100. 99.

मित्रसह
Mitrasaha --see Saudāsa--also Kalmāṣapāda. Bhā. IX. 9. 18; Br. III. 63. 176; Vā. 88. 176.

मित्रसेन
Mitrasena --a son of the IV (Ṛtu Vā. P.) Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 94; Vi. 100. 99.

मित्रा
Mitrā --mother of Maitreya and (Maitreyī--Bhā. P.). Her son was seen by Vidura on the banks of the Ganges. Bhā. III. 4. 36.

मित्रायु
Mitrāyu  (I)--a Vāsiṣṭha. Br. II. 35. 64.

मित्रायु
Mitrāyu  (II)--a son of Divodāsa and a Brahmiṣṭha; after him Maitreyas belonging to the side of Bhārgavas. Father of Cyavana. M. 50. 13; Vā. 99. 206; Vi. IV. 19. 69-70.

मित्रायु
Mitrāyu  (III)--a pupil of Romaharṣaṇa. Vi. III. 6. 17. 

मित्रावरुण
Mitrāvaruṇa  (I)--the scrotum of the Supreme Being; 1) Bhā. II. 1. 32. father of Agastya and Vasiṣṭha by dropping semon in a jar at the sight of Ūrvaśī 2) Ib. VI. 18. 5-6; IX. 13. 6. cursed Ūrvaśī to be born a human being; 3) Ib. IX. 14. 17. in the course of a ritual in their honour done by Manu was born Ilā. 4) Br. III. 8. 99; 60. 5 & 8.

मित्रावरुण
Mitrāvaruṇa  (II)--a Vāsiṣṭha Brahmavādin. M. 145. 110.

मित्रावरुण
Mitrāvaruṇa  (III)--one of the 16 Ṛtviks for yajña; issued from the back of Nārāyaṇa. M. 167. 8.

मित्रावरुण
Mitrāvaruṇa  (IV)--the two Vedic deities in whose honour Prajāpati made a sacrifice out of which came Iḍā; 1) Vā. 85. 6-7. into their tejas the soul of Vasiṣṭha entered, cursed by Nimi; they met Ūrvaśī and Vasiṣṭha took another body from her. 2) Vi. IV. 5. 11-12.

मित्रावरुण
Mitrāvaruṇa Iṣṭi --a yajña performed by Manu for the birth of a son. Vi. IV. 1. 8.

मित्री
Mitrī --a Yoganāthā. Br. IV. 37. 29.

मित्रेयु
Mitreyu  (I)--(Mitrāyu)--a son of Divodāsa and father of Cyavana. Bhā. IX. 22. 1.

मित्रेयु
Mitreyu  (II)--a branch of the Bhārgavas. Br. III. 1. 100. 

मिथि
Mithi --a son of Ni (e) mi, born out of the churning of Araṇi; see Janaka: founded the city of Mithilā. Br. III. 64. 4; Vā. 89. 4-6; Vi. IV. 5. 23.

मिथिला
Mithilā --founded by Janaka-Vaideha: capital of the Videhas whose king was Janaka: here Śatadhanvan lost his horse and ran on foot afraid of Kṛṣṇa: Balarāma visited it and lived there for some time. Bhā. IX. 13. 13; X. 57. 20-26; Br. III. 64. 6; 71. 80; Vā. 96. 74; 99. 324.

मिथिलावनम्
Mithilāvanam --Śatadhanu was killed by Kṛṣṇa in. Vi. IV. 13. 93.

मिथिलेश्वर
Mithileśvara --also Maithila--King of Mithilā. Br. III. 39. 2, 8.

मिथिलोपवनम्
Mithilopavanam --Here Kṛṣṇa vanquished Bhoja. Br. III. 71. 76.

मिरिकावनम्
Mirikāvanam --on the Narmadā. Br. III. 70. 32.

मिश्रकेशी
Miśrakeśī --an Apsaras and wife of Vatsaka; in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. Bhā. IX. 24. 43; Br. III. 7. 6; M. 161. 75; Vā. 69. 5.

मीड्वांस
Mīḍvāṃsa --a son of Mādrī. Br. III. 71. 19.

मीढुस्
Mīḍhus --a son of Indra. Bhā. VI. 18. 7. 

मीढुष्टम
Mīḍhuṣṭama --a name of Śiva. Bhā. IV. 7. 6.

मीढ्वन्
Mīḍhvan  (I)--a son of Dakṣa, and father of Kūrca (Pūrva Br. P.). Bhā. IX. 2. 19.

मीढ्वन्
Mīḍhvan  (II)--a name of Śiva. Bhā. III. 14. 34; Br. III. 24. 27.

मीन
Mīna --the Tamil month of Panguni: Sūrya in the month of. Vā. 105. 46.

मीना
Mīnā --a daughter of Ṛṣā; gave birth to fishes--makara, pāṭhina, and timirohita. Br. III. 7. 414-5; Vā. 69. 291-2.

मीमांसा
Mīmāṃsā --a philosophical system issuing from Brahmā's mouth; 1) M. 3. 4; 53. 6; Vi. III. 6. 27; V. 1. 38. read by the Asuras; 2) Br. II. 35. 87; IV. 12. 17. an anga of the Vedas. 3) Vā. 61. 78.

मुकुट
Mukuṭa  (I)--a tīrtha sacred to Satyavādinī. M. 13. 50.

मुकुट
Mukuṭa  (II)--a hill, west of the Śitoda; 1) Vā. 36. 28. residence of the Pannagas. 2) Ib. 39. 62; 42. 52.

मुकुटा
Mukuṭā --a R. from Ṛṣyavān. M. 114. 26. 

मुकुटेश्वरी
Mukuṭeśvarī --a Goddess enshrined at Markoṭa. M. 13. 33.

मुकुन्द
Mukunda  (I)--a name of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. I. 5. 19; Br. III. 33. 14. IV. 9. 45. 40. 7.

मुकुन्द
Mukunda  (II)--Mt. in Śālmalidvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 10.

मुक्त
Mukta  (I)--(Paulaha)--a sage of the epoch of Bhautya Manu. Br. IV. 1. 113.

मुक्त
Mukta  (II)--one released from samsāra knows his own self and assumes the shape foreign to the everyday world. Vā. 16. 21-2; 102. 76-7, 105.

मुक्ता
Muktā --a main stream of Śālmalidvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 28.

मुक्ताशाला
Muktāśālā --of Lalitā. Br. IV. 34. 53.

मुक्ताफलोदका
Muktāphalodakā --a R. in Śrīnagar in Muktāphalaśālā. Br. IV. 33. 52.

मुक्ति
Mukti  (I)--an Uttama siddhi. Br. IV. 5. 23; 36. 51.

मुक्ति
Mukti  (II)--one of the two Gods forming a boat to cross the ocean of samsāra; 1) Vā. 108. 37. four-fold of which Gayā is best. 2) Ib. 105. 16. 

मुक्तिका
Muktikā --a mother goddess. M. 179. 30.

मुक्तिमन्
Muktiman --Mt. near Ṛksavanta. Br. III. 70. 32.

मुक्तिसिद्धि
Muktisiddhi --a devī. Br. IV. 19. 5.

मुख
Mukha --the head of the Śiva Gaṇas. Br. III. 41. 28.

मुख
Mukhas (Sukhas) --one of the three gaṇas; 1) Vā. 100. 13. 20 branches of them mentioned. 2) Ib. 100. 18-19.

मुखमण्डिका
Mukhamaṇḍikā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 12.

मुखेविला
Mukhevilā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 21.

मुख्य
Mukhyas --the gods of Sāvarṇi epoch. Vi. III. 2. 15.

मुख्यतीर्थम्
Mukhyatīrtham --in the left foot of the Śilā at Gayā. Vā. 108. 40.

मुख्या
Mukhyā --the fifth entrance on the east of the city of Puramjana. Through this Puramjana went to the kingdoms of Āpaṇa and Bahūdana with his companions Rasajña and Vipaṇa; allegorically the mouth. Bhā. IV. 25. 49; 29. 11. 

मुचुकुन्द
Mucukunda  (I)--a son of Māndhāta of the Ikṣvāku line, and a yogin; knew the yoga power of Hari. 1) Bhā. IX. 6. 38; II. 7. 44; M. 12. 35; Vā. 88. 72. Devoted to Brahman and truth. After his encounter with the Asuras on behalf of Indra, he wanted rest and the celestials allowed him to sleep undisturbed, adding that whoever disturbed him, would be burnt to death. So he slept in a cave where Kṛṣṇa led his Yavana foe (Kālayavana) who disturbing Mucukunda's sleep was burnt to death. Soon Kṛṣṇa appeared before him and informed him of his avatār and its purpose. Mucukunda's praise of Kṛṣṇa and request of union with Him. Kṛṣṇa replied that he had to undergo still one more birth as a dharmic Brahmana and then reach Him. Taking leave of the Lord, he saw the advent of Kali and entered Gandhamādana. He worshipped Hari in the Badarī āśrama by tapas. 2) Bhā. X. 51 (whole); 52. 1-4; Br. III. 36. 26; Vi. V. 23. 18-47; 24. 1-5.

मुचुकुन्द
Mucukunda  (II)--a Daitya in the Pātāla or 7th tala. Br. II. 20. 44; Vā. 50. 42.

मुञ्ज
Muñja --a Rākṣasa in the fourth tala or Gabhastalam. Br. II. 20. 33; Vā. 50. 32.

मुञ्जकेश
Muñjakeśa --a disciple of Saindhava. Vā. 61. 54.

मुञ्जकेश्य
Muñjakeśya --a sage. Br. II. 35. 61.

मुञ्जवत्
Muñjavat --the peak in the Aruṇa hill. Br. II. 18. 20. 

मुञ्जिकेश
Muñjikeśa --a pupil of Saindhava, rearranged the Atharva Veda again into three parts and included nakṣatra kalpa. Vi. III. 6. 13.

मुण्ड
Muṇḍa --an Asura killed by the Devī. Br. IV. 29. 75.

मुण्ड
Muṇḍas  (I)--a tribe. M. 163. 66.

मुण्ड
Muṇḍas  (II)--a Janapada of the East. Vā. 45. 123.

मुण्ड
Muṇḍas  (III)--Shavelings in the guise of Sanyasins in Kaliyuga. Vā. 58. 59.

मुण्ड
Muṇḍas  (IV)--a dynasty of kings; thirteen in number. Vi. IV. 24. 53.

मुण्डक
Muṇḍaka --one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 8.

मुण्डपृष्टम्
Muṇḍapṛṣṭam --the place where Mahādeva performed penance; protected by poisonous reptiles; fit for śrāddha; to the east of it is the tīrtha of Kanakanandi; a mere plunge into the waters relieves one of his three debts; 1) Br. III. 13. 110; Vā. 77. 102-7. in Gayā. 2) Ib. 109. 45 and 52; 111. 45 and 74. 

मुण्डपृष्ठाद्रि
Muṇḍapṛṣṭhādri --the śilā on the back of the Gayāśma, leading the Pitṛs to Brahmaloka.

वा
Vā.  108. 12.

मुण्डि
Muṇḍi  (I)--a heretic; not fit for śrāddha. Br. III. 14. 40; 15. 42, 62.

मुण्डि
Muṇḍi  (II)--a name of Vighneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 70.

मुण्डि
Muṇḍi  (III)--one of the four sons of the 33rd kalpa. Vā. 23. 59.

