Medaśiras --a son of Purīman, and father of Śivaskandha. Bhā. XII. 1. 27.

मेदाश
Medāśa --a son of Pauruṣeya, a Rāksasa. Br. III. 7. 94.

मेदिनी
Medinī --the earth; deluge foretold by the fish; 1) M. 1. 24-9. of seven dvīpas; 2) Vā. 1. 89. surrounded by seas; filled with medas of Madhu and Kaiṭabha. 3) Ib. 63. 1 and 2.

मेधस्
Medhas  (I)--one of the ten sons of Svāyambhuva Manu. Br. II. 13. 104; M. 9. 5; Vā. 31. 17; 33. 9.

मेधस्
Medhas  (II)--one of the ten sons of Kardama. Br. II. 14. 9.

मेधस्
Medhas  (III)--a god of the Sumedhasa group. Br. II. 36. 58.

मेधस्
Medhas  (IV)--a son of Priyavrata: given to Yoga as he had no inclination for kingship. Vi. II. 1. 7 and 9. 

मेधस्
Medhas  (V)--a pupil of Devadarśa. Vi. III. 6. 10.

मेधज
Medhaja --a god of the Sumedhasa group. Br. II. 36. 60.

मेधहन्ता
Medhahantā --a god of the Sumedhasa group. Br. II. 36. 60.

मेधा
Medhā  (I)--a daughter of Dakṣa and a wife of Dharma: Mother of Smṛti [Śruta Vā. and Vi. P.]. Bhā. IV. 1. 50-52; Br. II. 9. 49, 59; Vā. 10. 25. 34; 55. 43; Vi. I. 7. 23. 29.

मेधा
Medhā  (II)--a kalā of Brahmā. Br. II. 26. 45; IV. 35. 94.

मेधा
Medhā  (III)--a Śakti; 1) Br. IV. 44. 72. the goddess enshrined at Kāśmīramaṇḍala. 2) M. 13. 47; 246. 62.

मेधातिथि
Medhātithi  (I)--a sage who came to see Parikṣit practising prāyopaveśa. Bhā. I. 19. 10.

मेधातिथि
Medhātithi  (II)--a son of Priyavrata, and appointed lord of the Śākadvīpa (Plakṣadvīpa-Vi. P.). He divided it among his seven sons and retired to a hermitage. Bhā. V. 1. 25 and 33; 20. 25; Vi. II. 1. 7, 12.

मेधातिथि
Medhātithi  (III)--a son of Kaṇva. From him came Praskaṇva and other Brahmanas; ancestor of the Kāṇvāyana dvijas. Bhā. IX. 20. 7; M. 49. 47; Vi. IV. 19. 6-7, 31-2. 

मेधातिथि
Medhātithi  (IV)--one of the ten sons of Svāyambhuva Manu; attained heaven by tapas; 1) Br. II. 13. 104; M. 9. 5; 143. 38; Vā. 31. 17. consecrated for Plakṣadvīpa; 2) Ib. 33. 9. a Rājaṛṣi. 3) Ib. 57. 122.

मेधातिथि
Medhātithi  (V)--one of the ten sons of Kardama and king of Plakṣadvīpa. 1) Br. II. 14. 9, 11, 35-7, 40-41. His sons, Śāntabhaya, Śiśira, Sukhodaya, Nanda, Śiva, Kṣemaka and Dhruva. These ruled the varṣas of the same names in the epoch of Svāyambhuva Manu; attained heaven by tapas. ^2 Ib. II. 30. 39.

मेधातिथि
Medhātithi  (VI)--a god of Sumedhasa group. Br. II. 36. 58.

मेधातिथि
Medhātithi  (VII)--(Paulastya) a sage of the Rohita group. Br. IV. 1. 62.

मेधातिथि
Medhātithi  (VIII)--a son of Kaṇṭha; from him Kāṇṭhāyana Brahmanas; married the daughter of Anupama and had a number of sons. Vā. 99. 131.

मेधातिथि
Medhātithi  (IX)--a son of Ajamīḍha and Keśinī. Vā. 99. 169.

मेधातिथि
Medhātithi  (X)--a sage of the IX epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 23.

मेधाविन्
Medhāvin  (I)--a son of Sunaya, and father of Nṛpamjaya (Ripumjaya-Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 22. 42; Vā. 99. 276; Vi. IV. 21. 12-13. 

मेधाविन्
Medhāvin  (II)--a son of Sutapā. M. 50. 84.

मेध्य
Medhyas --the snow-making rays of the sun. Vā. 53. 21.

मेन
Mena --the father of Menakā. Br. III. 7. 17; Vā. 69. 52.

मेनका
Menakā  (I)--the mother of Śakuntalā; she abandoned the child in the forest and went away. Bhā. IX. 20. 13.

मेनका
Menakā  (II)--the Apsaras presiding over the month of Śukra and Śuci; coupled with Sahajanyā; 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 35; Br. II. 23. 6; III. 7. 14; IV. 33. 18; Vā. 69. 49; Vi. II. 10. 7. with the sun in the summer. 2) Vā. 52. 7.

मेनका
Menakā  (III)--one, who was asked to dance along with Ūrvaśī and Rambhā; 1) M. 24. 28. in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. 2) Ib. 126. 7; 161. 75.

मेनका
Menakā  (IV)--the Apsaras wife of Vindhyāśva (Badhyaśva Vā. P.): gave birth to twins, Divodāsa and Ahalyā. M. 50. 7; Vā. 99. 200.

मेनका
Menakā  (V)--a mind-born mother. M. 179. 20.

मेना
Menā  (I)--a Pitṛkanyā; mind-born daughter of Agniṣvātta Pitṛs; queen of Himavān; had two sons Maināka and Krauñca (son of Maināka-Vā. P.) and three daughters, Umā,  (Ekapāṭalā-Vā. P.) Ekaparṇā and Aparṇā who married respectively Rudra, Asita and Jaigīṣavya (Devara-Vā. P.); the second took to the nyagrodha and pāṭala trees; the first performed tapas for thousands of years, whom the mother said “So-mā”, and hence Umā; on the eve of her giving birth to Umā, the goddess of Night entered her eyes; persuaded by the seven sages Menā and Himavān gave Umā in marriage to Śiva; and their son was the warrior God; 1) Bhā. IV. 7. 58; Br. III. 9. 2; 10. 6-20; M. 13. 7; 154. 86-93, 413; Vā. 30. 28-9, 31-2; 71. 3; 92. 31; Vi. I. 8. 14; Br. II. 13. 30 ff. 77. spoke to Umā of her poverty-stricken husband, Maheśvara living in their house after marriage. 2) Ib. III. 67. 34.

मेना
Menā  (II)--a daughter of Svadhā and Pitṛs. A Brahmavādinī. Vi. I. 10. 19.

मेरु
Meru  (I)--(Mt.) the hill that stands in the middle of Ilāvṛta, equal in height to the length of Jambūdvīpa, surrounded on four sides by Mandara, Merumandara, Supārśva and Kumuda. In these four ranges are four great trees-Mango, Jambu, Kaḍamba and Banyan; four pools of milk, honey, sugarcane and fresh water; four celestial gardens-Nandana, Caitraratha, Vaibhrājaka, and Sarvatobhadra. Encircling the base of Meru, stand two hills. On the east are Jaṭhara and Devakūṭa; on the west Pavana and Pāriyātra; on the south Kailāsa and Karavīra, and on the north Triśṛnga and Makara. In the central part of its summit is Brahmā's square city of gold. Surrounding the outskirts of that city, are the eight cities of the eight guardians. 1) Bhā. V. 16 (whole); 20. 2; VIII. 5. 18; Br. I. 1. 69; 4. 28. There is a forest at its foot where Rudra sports with Pārvatī; Bhāgavan identified with; 2) Bhā. IX. 1. 25. one of the six Varṣaparvatas of Jambūdvīpa occupying the middle portion. The dwelling place of Deva gaṇas; on its four sides are four countries, Bhādrāśva, Bharata, Ketumālā, and Uttarakuru. 4) Ib. II. 15. 16, 42-51; 17. 19, 34, 84; 21, 14, 28-34; III. 7. 194, 258; 61. 24; 63. 36; 66. 7; IV. 1. 24; 9. 17; Vi. II. 1. 20-22; 2. 39-41; 8. 19; V. 1. 12, 66; 38. 72. The relation of Dhruva to. 5) Br. II. 23. 108. Here the sages met to consider a certain question and it was announced that he, who did not arrive in time would have to submit himself to the prāyascitta of brahmicide. Vaiśampāyana unable to go, undertook to do so. 6) Ib. II. 25. 96; 35, 15-18. Acted as milkman of hills in milking the cow-earth. 7) M. 2. 33; 10. 26; Br. II. 36. 223. Sāvarṇi Manu's penance at. 8) M. 11. 38. North of it were ruling 15 sons of Vikukṣi and south of it 114 sons of Ikṣvāku of whom Kakuśtha was the eldest. 9) Ib. 12. 26-8; 113. 12ff; 124. 13; 163. 83; 182. 21; 183. 1; 184. 18; 249. 12. ^3 Ib. XI. 16. 21; Br. II. 13. 32 and 36.

मेरु
Meru  (II)--a temple with 100 beautiful towers, four gates, sixteen storeys and many fine turrets; the toraṇa of Meru is 50 hastas. M. 269. 28, 31, 47.

मेरु
Meru  (III)--a Dānava with manuṣya dharma. Vā. 68. 15.

मेरु
Meru  (IV)--the mother of Niyati and Āyati. Vi. I. 10. 3.

मेरुगुहा
Meruguhā --entered by Yogātmā avatār of Śiva along with Brahmā and Viṣṇu to become Nakulī. Vā. 23. 221.

मेरुदानम्
Merudānam --ten-fold, corns, salt, jaggery, gold, seasamum, cotton, ghee, precious stones, silver and sugar. M. 83. 2-6. 

मेरुदेवी
Merudevī --wife of Nābhi of Himāhva kingdom and a daughter of Meru; son Ṛṣabha; 1) Bhā. I. 3. 13; V. 2. 23; Vā. 33. 50; Vi. II. 1. 27. took part in the yajña conducted by her husband desirous of a son and the Lord was pleased to be born to her. Followed her husband to Viśālā (Badarī) and attained mukti there with him. 2) Bhā. V. 3. 1 and 19 and 20; 4. 5; Br. II. 14. 59.

मेरुमन्दर
Merumandara --(Mt.) on one side of Meru. Bhā. V. 16. 11.

मेरुमूलम्
Merumūlam --(Karṇikāmūlam); 70,000 yojanas in height and 48,000 yojanas in circumference. Vā. 35. 1-2.

मेरुसावर्णि
Merusāvarṇi  (I)--the first of the four sons of Brahmā, grandson of Dakṣa and son of his daughter Kriyā; engaged in austerities on the slopes of the Meru; went to Maharloka and was reborn in the epoch of Cākṣuṣa; the other three names are Parā, Marīcigarbha, and Sudharmāṇa; all of them sons of Rohita Prajāpati; 1) Br. IV. 1. 23, 53. the eleventh Manu of the future. 2) M. 9. 36.

मेरुसावर्णि
Merusāvarṇi  (II)--Manu, son of Dakṣa; had three sons, Marīcigarbhas, Suśarman and Sambhūta--in the Vaivasvata epoch. Vā. 100. 59.

मेष
Meṣa  (I)--sheep born of Sugrīvī; 1) M. 6. 33. Indra took the guise of, to disturb the tapas of Vajrānga's wife. 2) Ib. 146. 64.

मेष
Meṣa  (II)--Sūrya in, the month of Citra. Vā. 105. 46. 

मेषकीरिटकायन
Meṣakīriṭakāyanas --Kaśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 2.

मेषप
Meṣapas --Kaśyapa-gotrakāras. M. 199. 7.

मेषान्त
Meṣānta --equinox, end of. Vā. 50. 195.

मैत्र
Maitra --one of the 8 muhūrtas of the afternoon. Br. III. 3. 39; Vā. 66. 40.

मैत्रवर
Maitravara  (also Mitravara)--a Pañcārṣeya. M. 196. 50.

मैत्रायणावर
Maitrāyaṇāvara (Maitreya) --a son of Divodāsa; his descendents became Bhārgava Brahmanas. M. 50. 13.

मैत्रावरुण
Maitrāvaruṇa (c) --a resident of Brahmakṣetra; a Vāsiṣṭha and a sage; 1) Vā. 59. 106; Br. II. 32. 116. Purohita of Ikṣvāku. 2) M. 12. 4-5.

मैत्री
Maitrī --a daughter of Dakṣa and a wife of Dharma; mother of Prasāda. Bhā. IV. 1. 49-50.

मैत्रेय
Maitreya  (I)--(also Kauṣārava); a son of Mitrā; a siddha; himself a Purāṇa of information; 1) Bhā. III. 4. 36; VI. 15. [14]; III. 7. 42. went with Kṛṣṇa to Mithilā; met Kṛṣṇa on the eve of his departure to Heaven, and was ordered to be the preceptor to Vidura; the latter met him on the Ganges and after describing the creation of the world, answered Vidura's questions. 2) Ib. X. 86. 18; III. 4. 9 and 26; 5. 1 and 22-36; 8. 1ff. Taught him Ātma  vidyā and told him that the goal was Hari; 3) Ib. I. 13. 1; 19. 10; II. 10. 49. was invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira. 4) Ib. X. 74. 7; XII. 12. 8.

मैत्रेय
Maitreya  (II)--a name of Maitrāyaṇavara. M. 50. 13.

मैत्रेय
Maitreya  (III)--a pupil of Parāśara; enquired of him as to the origin of the world. Vi. I. 1. 10.

मैत्रेय
Maitreyas --Ārṣeyapravaras; (Bhārgavas). M. 195. 40.

मैथिल
Maithila  (I)--is Janaka; went to Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse. Bhā. X. 82. 26.

मैथिल
Maithila  (II)--the son of the Mithila king, Śatadhanva. Vā. 96. 78.

मैथिल
Maithilas --a dynasty of 28 kings, contemporaneous with the 10 Śaiśunāgas. Br. III. 64. 24; 74. 137; M. 272. 16.

मैन
Maina --(gaṇa) springs from Mīnā, a daughter of Ṛṣā. Br. III. 7. 415.

मैनाक
Maināka --(Mt.) in Bhāratavarṣa; son of Himavān and Menā; father of Krauñca hill; sacred for śrāddha and to Pitṛs; of Indra; famous for medicinal herbs. Bhā. V. 19. 16; Br. II. 13. 34-5; 16. 21; III. 9. 3; 10. 7; 13. 70; M. 13. 7; 121. 72; 162. 30; Vā. 30. 32; 45. 90; 47. 75; 71. 4; 72. 5; 77. 68. 

मैनाकम्
Mainākam --the continent about the Āmbikeya hill. M. 122. 25.

मैन्द
Mainda --a brother of Vānara Dvivida (s.v.); fatherin-law of Angada. Bhā. X. 67. 2; Br. III. 7. 220 and 238.

मैरेयम्
Maireyam --a kind of wine; 1) M. 120. 26. flows in some rivers of the Uttarakuru region. 2) Vā. 45. 27.

मोक्ष
Mokṣa --no bondage; three-fold mokṣa; renunciation by knowledge, diminution of rāga and loss of Tṛṣṇā; 1) Br. IV. 3. 55; Vā. 23. 81; 102. 76, 78, 80, 93. dharma of; 2) Br. III. 10. 116. is yogasiddhi; 3) Ib. IV. 36. 52; 44. 108. salvation, attained at the sacred Benares; 4) M. 180. 52; 183. 36-37; 185. 15; 193. 40. oneness with Brahmam. 5) Vā. 104. 94.

मोक्षवादि
Mokṣavādi --unfit for śrāddha. Vā. 79. 67.

मोचिका
Mocikā --a śakti. Br. IV. 35. 98.

मोद
Moda  (I)--a pupil of Devadarśa. Br. II. 35. 57.

मोद
Moda  (II)--a disciple of Vedasparśa. Vā. 61. 51.

मोदक
Modakas --a Janapada of the Ketumālā continent. Vā. 44. 15. 

मोदाक
Modāka --a son of Havya after whom came Modākavarṣa. Br. II. 14. 17. 20.

मोदाकम्
Modākam --a kingdom of Śākadvīpa adjoining the Āmbikeya hill named after Modāka. Br. II. 14. 20; 19. 93; Vā. 33. 19; 49. 87.

मोदिनी
Modinī --a devi. Br. IV. 37. 4.

मोदोष
Modoṣa --a pupil of Vedadarśa. Bhā. XII. 7. 2.

मोह
Moha --born from the buddhi of Brahmā. M. 3. 11.

मोहन
Mohana --in the Gayāśilā. Vā. 108. 48.

मोहनम्
Mohanam --an arrow of the God of Love, sent against Śiva. M. 154. 244; 162. 21, 24.

मोहना
Mohanā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 25.

मोहिनी
Mohinī --the thirteenth avatār of Viṣṇu (Nārāyaṇa) to delude the Asuras from having any share of the Amṛta and distribute it to the Devas; reappeared in that form before Śiva at his request and Śiva who got enamoured of her, ran after her letting his seed fall down; 1) Bhā. I. 3. 17; VIII. 8. 41-46; Chh. 9 and 12 (whole) M. 251. 7; Vā. 25. 48. a Śakti. 2) Br. IV. 10. 27. 34; 19. 65 and 74; 20. 6, 38 and 57; 44. 72 and 141. 

मौञ्ज
Mauñja --Ārṣeya Pravara (Bhārgavas). M. 195. 37.

मौञ्जकेश
Mauñjakeśa --an Ātreya-gotrakāra. M. 197. 7.

मौञ्जयनि
Mauñjayani --a sage. M. 198. 20.

मौञ्ज
Mauñja vṛṣṭi --a Pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 18.

मौद्गलायन
Maudgalāyana --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 22.

मौद्गल्य
Maudgalyas (Kāṇva Mudgalas) --Kanṭha MudgalasVā. P.) from Mudgala, son of Bhadrāśva; Brahmanas with Kṣatriya profession; belonging to the Angirasa line; 1) Bhā. IX. 21. 33; M. 50. 5; Vā. 99. 198; Vi. IV. 19. 60. no marriage alliance with Tāṇḍi or Angiras. 2) M. 196. 43.

मौन
Maunas --eleven of them ruled as kings, (18 kingsVā. P.); for three centuries, while the total reign of Ābhīras, Gardabhins, Kankas, Yavanas, Turuṣkas and Guruṇḍas amounted to 1099 (1009 Vi. P.) years. Thereafter came the Maunas. Bhā. XII. 1. 30-32; Br. III. 74. 173-7; Vā. 99. 360; Vi. IV. 24. 53-54.

मौनिक
Maunikas(c) --a Dākṣiṇāthya deśa. Vā. 45. 127. 

मौनिदेश
Maunideśa (c) --a kingdom after Muni. Br. II. 14. 26.

मौनेय
Mauneyas --Devagandharvas; 16 in number; (24 Vā. P.) Apsarasas were their younger sisters; had six daughters. Br. III. 7. 1-2; Vā. 69. 1, 4, 10.

मौर्य
Mauryas --(Maurvyas-Vi. P.) succeeded the Nandas. The Purāṇa speaks of ten kings ruling for 137 (173 Vi. P.) years. Only nine kings are mentioned from Candragupta to Bṛhadratha; were succeeded by the Śungas. 1) Bhā. XII. 1. 12 and 15; Br. III. 74. 149; Vā. 99. 336; Vi. IV. 24. 27, 32-3. M.P. mentions Śatadhanva, Bṛhadratha, Śaka and his grandson Daśaratha and his son; the first four are missing. 2) M. 272. 22, 26.

मौलि
Mauli  (I)--a Tripravara. M. 196. 33.

मौलि
Mauli  (II)--a son of Maṇibhadra. Vā. 69. 156.

मौलिक
Maulikas --a southern country. Br. II. 16. 58.

मौसल
Mausala --the battle with clubs after the Mahābhārata war. M. 70. 11.

मौहूर्तिकी
Mauhūrtikī --the gati of the sun; when the sun is in Māgha it moves past southward; returning from the south  it goes to Viṣu rising in the north of the milky ocean; when the sun is in Śravaṇa nakṣatra it goes to the north and rises in the north end of Śākadvīpam. Vā. 50. 121-7.

मौहूर्तिक
Mauhūrtikas --a gaṇa born of Muhūrtā and Dharma. These regulate the timely results of the actions of Beings. Bhā. VI. 6. 9.

म्लेच्छस्
Mlecchas  (I)--born out of the left side of Vena's body when the latter's body was churned; 1) M. 10. 7; begin with Anu, son of Yayāti; ruled by Dakṣa; ruled by Turvasu; ruled by the hundred sons of Pracetas of Druhyu family in the east; the rule of the kings; 2) Ib. 34. 30; 4. 54; 33. 14; 48. 9; 50. 76; Bhā. IX. 23. 16. not to be seen in Kuśadvīpa; Śakas (Parādas-Vi. P.), Pallavas (Paplava-Vi. P.) and Kāmbojas, all Mlecchas; (Ābhiras-Vi. P.) Guruṇdas and Vṛṣalas, also belonged to this group; 3) Br. II. 16. 12; 19. 60; 31. 79, 84 and 90; III. 20. 5; 48. 48-9; 68. 44; 73. 109; 74. 11-12, 203-6, 215; M. 273. 22; Vi. IV. 3. 48; 17. 5; 24. 69; V. 38. 28. kingdoms of, found in the lotus coming out of the naval of the Lord; 4) M. 169. 11; their kingdoms side by side with those of the Āryas; 5) Ib. 273. 25. people who live in their countries are ineligible for Pārvana śrāddha; 6) Ib. 16. 16. attain salvation at Benares; 7) Ib. 181. 19. do not molest the women of their enemies; 8) Ib. 188. 51. to be conquered by Kalki; 9) Br. II. 18. 43. put down by Pramati god. 10) M. 114. 11-12; 121. 43; 144. 53.

म्लेच्छस्
Mlecchas  (II)--these were the elder Madhucchandasas, who were cursed by Viśvāmitra to become Mlecchas; defeated by Bharata; these were the Mlecchas of the north; 2) Bhā. IX. 16. 33; 20. 30; 23. 16; XII. 1. 40-43.  worship progenitors; 3) Vā. 93. 44. eleven kings ruled for 300 years. 4) Ib. 99. 364. Then Kolikilas followed; 5) Vā. 99. 364. their dharma described. 6) Ib. 99. 392-400. ^1 Vā. 45. 82; 47. 41; 48. 15, 21, 36; 58. 78; 83. 112; 99. 12, 268; 98. 109.

म्लेच्छगणस्
Mlecchagaṇas --foreign tribes on the Himālayan slopes. Vā. 41. 46. 

यक्ष
Yakṣa  (I)--a Rākṣasa and a son of Khaśā. As he wanted to eat his own mother, he got the name of Yakṣa; of four hands and four feet, a fearful figure wandering in the night in search of prey; took the form of Vasuruci and lived with the apsaras Krathusthalā in Nandana; she bore him a son Rajatanābha; went home in the Himālayas with the son, when Krathusthalā came to know of his birth as a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 60, 100-17; 22. 14; 41. 30; 71. 111; Vā. 69. 160, 167.

यक्ष
Yakṣa  (II)--a son of Gāndinī. Vā. 96. 110.

यक्ष
Yakṣas --a semi-celestial group, usually of the class of demons; born of Viśvā and Kaśyapa; 1) Bhā. II. 6. 13; VI. 8. 24; X. 6. 27; 62. 19; 85. 41; Br. II. 32. 1-2; 35. 191; 36. 118; M. 6. 46. followers of Rudra (Śiva), their overlord; their lord, Kubera; 2) Bhā. IV. 10. 5; XI. 16. 16; 23. 24; M. 8. 5. milked the cowearth, with Vaiśravaṇa as the calf and āma as the vessel; 3) Ib. 10. 22. worship the Barhiṣad manes; 4) Ib. 15. 4. helped Vṛtra against Indra and went with Satī to Dakṣa's sacrifice; 5) Bhā. VI. 10. 20; IV. 4. 4, 34. sport of; 6) Ib. X. 90. 9. got mokṣa meditating on Hari; 7) Ib. VII. 7. 50. usurped the Ānarta kingdom of Kakudmi when he was absent at Brahmā's court; 8) Ib. IX. 3. 36. came with the gods to see Kṛṣṇa and saw Kṛṣṇa retiring to his own region; 9) Ib. VII. 8. 38; XI. 31. 2. (see Puṇyajanas); vanquished by Rāvaṇa; 10) Br. III. 7. 255. worship the Pitṛs and ruin the śrāddha; 11) Ib. III. 10. 38, 111; 11. 81; IV. 2. 26; 14. 4; 20. 50; 30. 9; 33. 75. their kingdom; 12) M. 23. 39; 121. 48. their loka; 13) Br. IV. 39. 56. the nails of Vāmana when he grew. 14) M. 246. 54. 

यक्षगण
Yakṣagaṇas --chiefly four, Loheyas, Bharateyas, Kṛśāṅgeyas, and Viśāleyas after the four daughters of Suyaśā (s.v.). Vā. 69. 15-6.

यक्षराक्षस
Yakṣarākṣasas --the tribe born to Kapila, the Yakṣa and Keśinī--inferior to Gandharvas by three steps. Br. III. 7. 146-167; IV. 4. 2; Vā. 69. 178.

यक्षास्य
Yakṣāsya --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 235.

यक्षि
Yakṣis --women of the Yakṣas. Bhā. X. 90. 9.

यक्षिणी
Yakṣiṇī --a Śakti; 1) Br. IV. 20. 15. an image of; surrounded by the Devas, Dānavas and the Nāgas; hoods and two tongues to be carved above the head; also the spirits of the air and the evil spirits encircle her. 2)  M. 261. 47-50.

यक्षी
Yakṣī --one of the ten pīṭhas for images with three mekhalas; this gives one plenty of cows. M. 262. 6, 8, 17.

यक्षेश्वर
Yakṣeśvara --is Kubera (s.v.); 1) Br. IV. 20. 50. a follower of Śiva in battle; helped Vāmadeva Śiva in his war with Soma. 2) M. 23. 38.

यक्ष्म
Yakṣma --Phthisis which afflicted Soma as a result of Dakṣa's curse. Bhā. VI. 6. 23. 

यजनी
Yajanī --the wife of Śukra; mother of Devayānī. Vā. 65. 84.

यजमान
Yajamāna --the man who installs a new image, becomes part of the deity; the presiding deity is Ugra. M. 265. 38, 41.

यजुस्
Yajus  (I)--imparted to Vaiśampāyana 1) Bhā. I. 4. 21; IV. 4. 32; X. 7. 14; 53. 12. its history; 2) Ib. XII. 6. 64-65. Sūrya celebrated in; 3) Ib. XII. 11. 47. fruits of its repetition; 4) Ib. XII. 12. 62. arranged by Vyāsa; learnt by the Asuras; 5) Br. II. 33. 37; 35. 73; IV. 12. 17. rearranged by Vaiśampāyana into four. It is Yajus by the action of yajanam. It is caturhotram, divided into four parts, hence yajña; three versions --northern with Syāmāyani, middle country with Āsuri, and eastern with 86 Samhitas Alambī; 6) Ib. II. 34. 14-22; 35. 11; Vā. 60. 14, 17, 22; 61. 5-8. personified as present in Varuṇa's sacrifice; 7) Br. III. 1. 24; Vā. 65. 25. with Vṛttādhya, face in the shape of Aum and with sūkta, Brāhmaṇa and mantra; served as horse of Tripurāri's chariot; 8) M. 93. 129; 133. 31. length of, including Śukriyas and Yājñavalkya portions; 9) Vā. 31. 33; 32. 2; 101. 346. two mātras, Īkārākṣara. 10) Ib. 26. 20.

यजुस्
Yajus  (II)--one of the ten horses of the moon's chariot. Br. II. 23. 56.

यजुस्
Yajus  (III)--the fifth son of Caidyoparicara, the Vasu and Girikā. M. 50. 28.

यजुस्
Yajus  (IV)--one of the Marutgaṇas. Vā. 67. 129.

यजुदाय
Yajudāya --a son of Devakī. Vā. 96. 173. 

यजुर्धामन्
Yajurdhāman --a son of Parvaśa. Br. II. 11. 16.

यजुर्वाक्यार्थपण्डित
Yajurvākyārthapaṇḍitas --interpreters of the Yajur Veda. They are Lomaharṣaṇikas, Kāśyapikas and Sāvarṇikas. Vā. 61. 60.

यजुर्
Yajur Veda --see Yajus; 1) Br. II. 34. 14-18: M. 93. 129; 133. 31. Vā. 26. 20. 60. 14, 17, 22; 61. 5-8; 65. 25. divided into four parts from which originated yajña, performed by four orders of priests --adhvaryu to recite Yajus, hota, the Rks, and Udgāta, the Sāman, and Brahmā, the Atharvamantras, 2) Vi. III. 4. 8-12. its śākhas are 27; arranged by Vaiśampāyana, pupil of Vyāsa, and taught to his disciples including Yājñavalkya; the latter was made to vomit for his behaviour, all the texts, which the other disciples digested, in the form of partridges and hence this portion came to be known as Taittirīya; but Yājñavalkya prayed to the Sun-god who initiated him into the other portions of the Yajus in the form of a horse and hence called Vājaseneya; 3) Ib. III. ch. 5 (whole). part of Viṣṇu. 4) Ib. V. 1. 37.

यजूंषि
Yajūṃṣi --from the right (south Vi. P.) face of Brahmā; 1) Br. II. 8. 51 and 55; Vi. I. 5. 54. one learned in, becomes an expert in yajñas. 2) Vā. 79. 95.

यज्ञ
Yajña  (I)--the seventh avatār of Viṣṇu; born with Dakṣiṇā as twins to Akūtī and Ruci. Adopted as his son by his grandfather Svāyambhuva Manu. 1) Bhā. I. 3. 12; III. 19. 13; IV. 1. 4-5; VI. 8. 15; VIII. 1. 6. Followed by the Yāma gods, slew the Asuras and Yātudhānas who attacked and sought to devour Svāyambhuva Manu engaged in contemplation of Hari, and ruled the celestial kingdom; 2) Ib. VIII. 1. 17-18; X. 6. 22. worshipped for attaining celebrity; 3) Ib. II. 3. 7; Br. II. 34. 7. to Yajña and Dakṣiṇā were born twelve sons who were known as Yāmas in the period of Svāyambhuva; Yajña also Yāma; 4) Vā. 10. 19-20; Br. II. 9. 44ff. constitutes Dharma and  mantra; the Yajva goes to heaven; 5) Vā. 32. 16. a soma yajus of paśu, dravya, havis, Ṛtviks, Dakṣiṇa. 6) Ib. 57. 107; 59. 42.

यज्ञ
Yajña  (II)--a Jayādeva. Br. III. 3. 7; 4. 3; Vā. 66. 7.

यज्ञ
Yajña  (III)--origin of, in Treta and dispute on its nature, whether himsā or not; 1) Vā. 57. 86-125. trees fit for; samāna, plakṣa, nyagrodha, aśvattha, udumbara, vikarika, bilva, candaṇa, sarala, devadāru, śāla, khadira; unfit are: śleṣmātaka, naktamāla, kapittha, śālmali, nīpa, vibhītaka and those which are enveloped by creepers and are the residence of birds; 2) Ib. 75. 71-76. of Śūdras by Brahmanas for livelihood (vṛtti); 3) Ib. 99. 426; 101. 296; 112. 1 and 14. performance of, pleases the gods who give rain; 4) Vi. I. 6. 8. personified as God with wife Dakṣiṇā and twelve sons, generally known as Yāmas; 5) Ib. I. 7. 21. born of Viṣṇu and Ākūtī in the Svāyambhuva epoch; of Tuṣitā in Svārociṣa, of Satyā in Uttama, of Havya in Tāmasa and Sambhūti in Raivata; 6) Ib. III. 1. 36-40. duty of all. 7) Ib. III. 8. 22

यज्ञ
Yajña  (IV)--(Japa) for Brahmanas; 1) Br. II. 29. 55. introduced by Indra in Tretāyuga; questioned by the sages as to himsā of animals. Vasu, son of Uttānapāda who was appointed arbitrator said that yajña pleases the gods and tapas, Vairāja leading to Kaivalya. Not favoured in Kaliyuga; 2) Ib. II. 30. 4-42; 31. 64; 32. 47; 34. 6; M. Ch. 143 (whole). prohibited by Vena, but reintroduced by Vainya in the Vaivasvata epoch; 3) Br. II. 36. 130; III. 72. 2; 73. 72; IV. 6. 55, 73. Sruca clan of apsaras born of; 4) Br. III. 4. 24; 7. 22. the five to be done by householders daily, chanting of the Vedas, homas, śrāddha for pitṛs, gifts of rice, etc. to bhūtas and balikarma; 5) M. 10. 34; 52. 14-15. performed by the Asuras. 6) Ib. 83. 3, 8; 130. 19. 

यज्ञ
Yajña  (V)--the son of Brahmadhana. Vā. 67. 28; 69. 132.

यज्ञकेतु
Yajñaketu --resented Śāmba's action in seizing Lakṣmaṇā. (s.v.). Bhā. X. 68. 5.

यज्ञत्रयम्
Yajñatrayam --are Graha yajñam, Lakṣahoma and Koṭi homa. M. 239. 40.

यज्ञद्रव्य
Yajñadravyas --yūpa, samit, sruk, sruva, pavitram and paridhi. Vā. 97. 28.

यज्ञपति
Yajñapati  (I)--an Ārṣeya pravara; (Bhārgava). M. 195. 43.

यज्ञपति
Yajñapati  (II)--Viṣṇu; 1) M. 246. 10; Vi. I. 11. 47. method of meditating on, prescribed by the sages to Dhruva. 2) Ib. I. 11. 52-5.

यज्ञपत्नि
Yajñapatnis --(wives of sacrificers) attain salvation by satsanga. Bhā. XI. 12. 6.

यज्ञपिण्डायन
Yajñapiṇḍāyana --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 23.

यज्ञपुरुष
Yajñapuruṣa --is Viṣṇu. Vi. V. 17. 6; VI. 4. 42. 

यज्ञबाहु
Yajñabāhu --a son of Priyavrata, appointed lord of Śālmalidvīpa. He divided it among his seven sons after whose names the countries came to be known. Bhā. V. 1. 25 and 33; 20. 9.

यज्ञभद्र
Yajñabhadra --a maṇḍapa with forty pillars. M. 270. 4, 11.

यज्ञरक्षाधिकारिण
Yajñarakṣādhikāriṇas --the four sons of Āpa, one of the eight Vasus. M. 5. 22.

यज्ञरूपा
Yajñarūpā --a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 13. 7.

यज्ञवराह
Yajñavarāha --an avatār in Gomatī tīrtha; 1) M. 22. 13; 248. 77. vārāham rūpam; the boar described; the Vedas are the feet, upa, teeth; yajña, breast; citi, mouth; fire, tongue; kuśa grass, hair; Brahmā, head; day and night, eyes; Vedangas and śrutis, jewels; ghee, nose; sruva, face; sāmaghoṣa, the speech, embodiment of satya and dharma, ūrdhvagātra, nerves; homa, linga; the residence, ocean; Vedi, the inner body; mantras, the hinder part, soma, blood; Veda, skandha; havi, the smell and pride; havya-kavya fast running; prāgvamśa prāyaścitta, the terrible chariot; the body, Dakshiṇa heart; upākarmeṣṭhi, the pleasant form, pravargya materials, ornaments; different metres footpath, upaniṣad the seat; Chāyā wife and tall as Maṇisṛṅga. 2) Vā. 6. 11-23.

यज्ञवाटम्
Yajñavāṭam --the hall of sacrifice in Naimiṣa; all built of gold. Vā. 2. 18.

यज्ञवाम
Yajñavāma --a son of Parvasa. Vā. 28. 13. 

यज्ञ
Yajña vidyā --symbolical of Devī. Vi. I. 9. 120.

यज्ञश्री
Yajñaśrī --(Sānti karnika) son of Śivaskandha, and father of Vijaya; (Dviyajña-Vi. P.) ruled for 19 years (29?M.P.). Bhā. XII. 1. 27; Br. III. 74. 168; M. 273. 14. Vā. 99. 355; Vi. IV. 24. 48.

यज्ञसूनव
Yajñasūnava --the former birth of the twelve Yāma devas. Vā. 31. 3, 6-7.

यज्ञसेन
Yajñasena --the Pāñcāla, who invited Kṛṣṇa to Draupadi's svayamvara. Bhā. X. 57. 10. [1].

यज्ञसेनि
Yajñaseni --a name of Draupadī. Bhā. X. 84. 1.

यज्ञह
Yajñaha(hā)  (I)--a son of Vṛṣa (Viṣa). Br. III. 6. 34; Vā. 68. 33.

यज्ञह
Yajñaha(hā)  (II)--a son of Brahmadhāna (Brahmadanu, Vā. P.). Br. III. 7. 98; Vā. 69. 132.

यज्ञहोत्र
Yajñahotra --a son of Uttama Manu. Bhā. VIII. 1. 23.

यज्ञापेत
Yajñāpeta --a son of Brahmadhāna. Br. III. 7. 98. 

याज्ञेयि
Yājñeyi --a Bhārgava gotrakara. M. 195. 24.

यज्ञोपवीतम्
Yajñopavītam --the sacred thread; 1) Vā. 23. 3, 26. of Śiva, skin of Vyāla. 2)  Ib. 55. 55.

यज्ञोपेत
Yajñopeta --a Rākṣasa with the śisira sun; resides in the sun's chariot in the month of Phālguna (Vi. P.) Br. II. 23. 22; Vi. II. 10. 18.

यज्वन्
Yajvan --a Pārāvata god. Br. II. 36. 15.

यति
Yati  (I)--a son of Brahmā, who remained a celibate. Bhā. IV. 8. 1.

यति
Yati  (II)--the eldest son of Nahuṣa who did not like to be king and who devoted himself to the realisation of Ātman; became a Vaikhānasa yogi even as a boy; 1) Bhā. IX. 18. 1-2; M. 24. 50; Vi. IV. 10. 1-2. married Gā, daughter of Kākustha. 2) Br. III. 68. 12; Vā. 93. 13-14.

यति
Yati  (III)--feeding of, in a śrāddha pleases Brahmā; duties of; 1) Br. II. 7. 169; 32. 25; III. 15. 16-30; 68. 6; Vā. 59. 24. Prāyaścittas, for commissions and omissions; 2) Ib. 18. 1-22. Śūdra Yatis with bald heads and red robes at the end of Kali. 3) Ib. 58. 50 and 59; 93. 6; 104. 23.

यति
Yati  (IV)--a Śiva god. Br. II. 36. 33. 

यथार्थक
Yathārthaka --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 236.

यदु
Yadu  (I)--originator of the Yādava race; the eldest son of Yayāti and Devayānī. Father of Sahasrajit and other sons. 1) Bhā. IX. 18. 33; 23. 20-1; M. 4. 22; 24. 53; Vā. 1. 155; Vi. IV. 11. 1-5. His line glorified by the birth of Kṛṣṇa, as the Malaya hill by the sandal tree; became overlord of the southern part of the kingdom. Refused to part with his youth to his father and hence was cursed to become the father of refractory sons and was also refused a share in the kingdom; father of five sons; debarred by his father to succeed him; was placed in charge of the southern territory; 2) Bhā. I. 8. 32; IX. 19. 22; 18. 34-40; chh. 23 and 24 (whole); M. 33. 1-8; 34. 16-20, 30; 43. 6; Vā. 93. 16, 30-40; Vi. IV. 10. 12. his descendants; 3) Br. I. 1. 166; III. 68. (whole); 69. 1-5; 73. 125; Vā. 93. 89; Vi. IV. 10. 31. had a discourse on detachment and realisation of Ātman from an Avadhūta sannyasin, when the ascetic spoke of his twenty-four gurus; earth, air, sky, waters, fire, moon, sun, kapota (pigeon), boaconstrictor, sea, moth, bee, elephant, honey-gatherer, deer, fish, Piṅgala, Kurara, child, girl, blacksmith, serpent, spider and wasp. From the exemplary ways of each of them, the ascetic learnt his lessons which are elaborated. Hearing this Yadu became free from all attachments and looked on all things as equal; 4) Bhā. XI. 7. 9; X. 1. 2. equal to Indra. 5) M. 32. 9.

यदु
Yadu  (II)--a Yāma deva. Br. II. 13. 92; Vā. 31. 6.

यदु
Yadus --(also Yadu kula and Yadu vamśa); members and descendants innumerable; one hundred and one families recognised. 1) Bhā. X. 90. 40-4. Their king was Ugrasena. Ill-treated by Kamsa, they migrated to different countries like Kuru and Pāñcāla, and became delighted at Kamsa's death. Their Purohita was Garga. 2) Ib. X. 1. 69; 2. 2-3; 45. 15; 8. 1. Krsna born among them; 3) M. 246, 90. cursed by  Yayāti, his successors could not be kings; unacceptable to good men according to Śiśupāla; 4) Bhā. X. 45. 13; 74. 36. took part in the marriage festivities of Kṛṣṇa and Rukminī, and attended the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira; turned into a caste by Puramjaya; 5) Ib. X. 54. 58; 75. 12; XII. 1. 36. destroyed by Kṛṣṇa before he left the earth, under the pretext of the Brahmanas' curse; the rest lost their reason after Kṛṣṇa's departure to Heaven, drank wine and killed one another. Four or five alone left alive. Attained yoga through the grace of Datta; became defunct after the Mahābhārata war. 6) Ib. XI. 1. 4-5; 31. 16; I. 15. 22-6; II. 7. 4; M. 70. 12.

यदुक
Yadukas --a Janapada of Maṇidhānya; 1) Vā. 99. 384. the kingdom of. 2) Br. III. 74. 196.

यदुलोक
Yaduloka --the Yadu public. Vi. IV. 13. 35.

यदूद्वह
Yadūdvaha --a name of Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 29.

यन्त्र
Yantra --a mechanical contrivance used by Tvaṣṭā to diminish the tejas of the sun; the surplus tejas became Viṣṇu's cakra, Rudra's trident and Indra's thunder bolt. M. 11. 27-9.

यन्त्रिणी
Yantriṇī --an attendant on Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 46.

यन्त्रेश्वर
Yantreśvara --a tīrtha on the north bank of the Narmadā; a bath there secures the company of Gods for 5000 years. M. 190. 1-2. 

यम
Yama  (I)--(Vaivasvata) the Lord of Pitṛs; punishes men after death according to their actions, sinful or otherwise. 1) Bhā. V. 26. 6; M. 8. 5; Vā. 62. 186; 65. 52; 70. 8; Vi. I. 22. 5. A son of Vivasvat (Sūrya)  and Samjñā; explains the nature of dharma and the glory of Hari to his messengers (Yamadūtas, s.v.). Appeared in the form of a child before the queen and the subjects of Suyajña weeping over his dead body and showed the truth that no amount of wailing would bring the dead back to life; 2) Bhā. VI. 6. 40; VIII. 13. 9; VI. 3. 12-34; VII. 2. 36-58; welcomed Rāma and Kṛṣṇa and fulfilled their desire by restoring Sāndipāni's son; presented Pṛṭhu with a rod of justice. Punished Nṛga to be a lizard for having given a cow of a Brahmaṇa as a gift to another, and as the owner refused to accept the apologies and compensation offered by Nṛga; 3) Ib. X. 45. 42-6; IV. 15. 15; III. 30. 23; X. 64. 16-24. fought with Kālanābha in the Devāsura war; rode on buffalo to help Indra against Kṛṣṇa taking away pārijāta, but discomfited, ran away in fear; 4) Ib. VIII. 10. 29; X. [65 (v) 41]; [66 (v) 33-5]; Vi. V. 30. 60; VI. 5. 44. his authority set aside in the case of Ajāmila. Dhruva is said to have set his foot on his head; was a Śudra for a hundred years owing to a curse; 5) Bhā. VI. 3. 2; IV. 12. 30; I. 13. 15. His penance at Gokarṇa and Śiva made him lokapāla; his city being Samyamana; represents the planet Śanaiścara; served as calf for Pitṛs milking the earth; Dharmarāja; Lord of three deva gaṇas-Amarttas, Aprakāśas, and Jyotiṣmantas; 6) Br. II. 21. 31; 24. 49; 29. 65; 36. 208; III. 1. 52; 7. 253 and 330; 13. 72; M. 93. 14; 266. 21 and 63; Vā. 50. 88; 69. 215; Vi. II. 8. 9; III. 7. 19, 35. narrated to Śaśabindu varieties of śrāddha; protested against the ill-treatment by his stepmother Chāyā and was cursed by her to lose his legs. [Cursed his legs to be sores and worms. His father gave him a cock to eat them. M.P.]. The father assured their restoration after a temporary loss; overlord of Pitṛs. 7) Br. III. 18. 1; 24. 4; 59. 23, 52-80; M. 11. 4-20. in charge of hells; 8) Br. IV. 2. 151; 7. 54. buffalo, his riding animal; 9) M. 67. 11. his active part in Tripuram, defeated by Kālanemi; 10) Ib. 133. 63; 137. 32; 138. 25; 177. 50. burnt with Kāma and attained godhood again by pleasing Śankara by tapas; 11) Ib. 191. 112-4. dialogue of, with his servant about those who could not be taken to his region. 12) Vi. II. 6. 6; III. 7. 5, 13-20. acted as calf when Antaka milked the cow-earth; other names of; world of; 13) M. 10. 19; 31. 12; 93. 14; 102. 22-3; 124. 22; 146. 77. in the war against Tāraka: war with Grasana and the latter's success. 14) Ib. 148. 79-81; 150. 1-49; Vi. III. 2. 2. Samvāda with Sāvitrī; the latter's praise of; 15) M. 211. 14-28 and ch. 213 (whole). Kāla and Mṛtyu are assistants; god to be worshipped in house building. 16) Ib. 250. 46; 253. 25.  Image of, with Citragupta by the side; gift of  buffalo pleasing to; 17) Ib. 261. 12; 268. 13. (Dharmarāja): a golden image of him standing on a copper plate to be given to guru in Saptamīsvapana; 18) Ib. 68. 20. weapon of daṇḍa, used by, in the battle of Tripuram; 19) Ib. 135. 77. seen by Sāvitrī while taking the life of her husband; blessed her with three requests of hers and finally the life of her husband; 20) Ib. 210. 5, chh. 211-14. meting out justice impartially; 21) Ib. 213. 3. father of two daughters Upadānavī and Himā. 22) Vā. 68. 23; 69. 61; 75. 56; 82. 1; 101. 150, 286; 106, 46; 108. 4 and 31; 110 10 and 38.

यम
Yama  (II)--a Yājñiya god. Br. II. 36. 33.

यम
Yama  (III)--a muhūrta of the night. Br. III. 3. 42.

यम
Yama  (IV)--a Sukha god. Br. IV. 1. 18.

यम
Yama  (V)--a son of Havirdhāna. M. 4. 45.

यम
Yama  (VI)--an Āditya. M. 6. 4.

यम
Yama  (VII)--the father of Ilinā, (s.v.). M. 49. 9. 

यम
Yama  (VIII)--a Vasu; a son of Dharma and Sudevī. M. 171. 47.

यम
Yama  (IX)--the agent of a class of devas. Vā. 10. 72.

यम
Yama  (X)--the son of Sureṇu and Vivasvan; ill-treated by stepmother Chāyā, was about to kick her when she cursed him that he would lose his leg; he became Dharmarāja, lord of Pitṛs and Protector of the world. Vā. 84. 22, 56-61.

यम
Yama  (XI)--a mukhya gaṇa. Vā. 100. 18.

यम
Yamas --prescriptions. Vā. 104. 14.

यमक
Yamakas --an eastern tribe. M. 114. 44.

यमकिंकर
Yamakiṃkara --servants of Yama. Vā. 110. 45.

यमजिह्व
Yamajihva --a Bhairava god. Br. IV. 20. 82.

यमदण्ड
Yamadaṇḍa --an adhikāra. M. 225. 16; Vā. 108. 4.

यमदूत
Yamadūtas --met Viṣṇu dūtas at the death of Ajāmila, and argued that punishment depended on the character of one's action, and that Ajāmila a Brahmana deserved punishment for having forsaken his svadharma and led an evil life with a dāsi. Overpowered by Hari's dūtas, they reported  to Yama (s.v.) and wanted to know the truth of the matter. Instructed by Yama as knower of Dharma and ordained by Hari, his messengers cherished Hari's glory, and did not go near his devotees. Bhā. VI. 1. 20, 40. 68; 3. 10-34.

यमद्वीपम्
Yamadvīpam --a region of the Jambudvīpa; here is Dutimat, a Mt. Vā. 48. 14, 19.

यमपुरि
Yamapuri --the kingdom of Dharma. Vā. 106. 20; 108. 3; Vi. V. 21. 30.

यमपुरुष
Yamapuruṣa --(Kiṇkara): a servant of Yama with a noose. Vi. III. 7. 13, 19.

यमबलि
Yamabali --the offering to Śiva at the Prabhāsa hill. Vā. 108. 23; 110. 38.

यममुञ्चत
Yamamuñcatas --of Kauśika gotra. Vā. 91. 98.

यमल
Yamala --a Dānava king. Br. IV. 29. 124.

यमलार्जुनभंजन
Yamalārjunabhaṃjana --a name of Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 28.

यमवनम्
Yamavanam --also known as Anuparvatam, west of the Lauhitī and the Sindhu. Vā. 69. 241.

यमव्रतम्
Yamavratam --of kings; to punish impartially. M. 226. 4. 

यमसादनम्
Yamasādanam--Yātanādeha  taken to the abode of Yama in two or three muhūrtas covering about 99000 yojanas; tortures in. Bhā. III. 30. 20-28.

यमान्तक
Yamāntaka --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 82.

यमिन
Yamina --a Śukradeva. Vā. 31. 8.

यमी
Yamī --a daughter of Vivasvan (Sūrya-Vi. P.) and Samjñā; also Yamunā. Bhā. VI. 6. 40: VIII. 13. 9: Br. III. 59. 38; Vi. III. 2. 2.

यमुना
Yamunā  (I)--(Kālindī) (R.) in Bhāratavarṣa from the Himālayas; a divine stream. 1) Bhā. V. 19. 18; Vā. 45. 95. A mahānadī. 2) Ib. 104. 50. Here Vidura met Uddhava; 3) Bhā. III. 1. 24; 2. 27; IV. 2. 35. the co-wives who administered poison to Citraketu's son, had a purificatory bath in; Citraketu, who was initiated into the Vidyā by Nārada had his preliminary bath in this river. 4) Ib. VI. 16. 14 and 16. On its banks Vaivasvata Manu performed tapas for progeny, and Bharata celebrated his horse sacrifice. On its banks stands Madhuvana near Bṛṇdāvana. Kṛṣṇa, his brother, and others played there and once defeated the Asura Vatsa. Gopi girls bathed there as part of the Kātyayanī vratam. Nanda used to bathe here. 5) Ib. IX, 2. 1; 4. 30; 20. 25; X. 11. 36-43; 22. 2, 6, 36; 28. 1. Immersed in its waters Saubhari performed penance. Poisoned by the Kālīya; Kṛṣṇa sent away the reptile to the sea and made its waters drinkable; unapproachable to Garuḍa by a curse of Saubhari. 6) Ib. IX. 6. 39; X. 15. 47-8; 16. 4, 60-7; 17. 8-11. Akrūra who took Kṛṣṇa and Rāma to Mathurā, had his bath on the way in this river. Inside the waters he saw both Kṛṣṇa and Rāma; also saw Hari on the Śeṣa. Here Kṛṣṇa killed Hamsa. 7) Ib. X. 39. 38-46; 76. 2 [8]; 78. [1). On its bank Jarāsandha encamped to besiege Mathurā. Here Kṛṣṇa had his avabhṛta after the horse sacrifice. Here again Kṛṣṇa and Arjuṇa met Kālindī. 8) Ib. X. [50 (v) 6 and 14]; 89. 63 [4]; 58. 16-7. During his pilgrimage  Balarāma visited this. 9) Ib. X. 78. 20. Was in floods when Vasudeva crossed it for Gokula with the new born babe, Kṛṣṇa. 10) Ib. X. 3. 50. Sacred for śrāddha; sometimes too hot and sometimes too cold; daughter of Mārtāṇḍa and Samjñā and sister of Yama; got changed into a sacred river. On its northern bank is Prayāgā (Pratiṣṭhāna). 11) Br. II. 16. 25; III. 13. 71-2; 59. 23 and 83; 66. 21; 73. 117; IV. 15. 23; M. 11. 4, 39; 104. 19; 108. 22; Vā. 77. 69-70. Sacred to Mṛgāvatī; sacred to the Pitṛs; 12) M. 13. 40. a boundary of the kingdom of Pitṛs; 13) Ib. 22. 20. in the chariot of Tripurāri; 14) Ib. 110. 5; 114. 21; 133. 23; 163. 61; 239. 18. one of the 16 wives of Havyavāhana (fire) 15) Ib. 51. 13; Vā. 29. 13. forms the left side of the Veda; 16) Ib. 104. 77; 108. 79. daughter of Sureṇu and Sūrya; 17) Ib. 58. 88; 84. 22. a sacred river. 18) Br. II. 12. 14; Vā. 98. 117; Vi. III. 14. 18; V. 3. 18; 7. 7ff; 18. 33.

यमुना
Yamunā  (II)--(personified) sister of Yama. Once Balarāma invited her for watersports, and got enraged at her delay. Hence he dragged her by means of his plough through Bṛṇdāvan. This changed her course; then she prayed for mercy which was granted. She presented Rāma with clothes and jewels. Even now the change in the course is noticeable. Bhā. X. 3. 50; Ib. ch. 65 (whole); Vi. V. 25. 8-11, VI. 8. 31.

यमौ
Yamau --twins--Nakula and Sahadeva. Bhā. I. 10. 9; Vi. V. 35. 28; 38. 91.

ययाति
Yayāti --the middle son of Nahuṣa and Virajā, the mindborn daughter of Ajyapas: married Śarmiṣṭhā, daughter of Vṛṣaparvan, 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 32; Br. III. 10. 95; 68. 12-4; M. 15. 23; Vā. 1. 143; 73. 46. and had three sons by her; pleased with him Indra gave him a golden chariot yoked with swift horses and which became the ratha of the Paurava kings. 2) Ib. 93. 16-20. Became king after his father: desire for more territory; placed his  younger brothers in charge of the four quarters of the kingdom; nature of his good rule described; in the course of a hunting expedition, he heard the cry of a girl coming out of a well and going near it found a girl inside standing helpless and naked; he gave her his upper cloth to wear and lifted her up. She was Devayānī, the daughter of Śukra and she became his wife and bore him two sons, Yadu and Turvasu. Śukra in offering his daughter to the king asked him not to share his bed with Śarmiṣṭhā. In a weak moment, forgetting his promise, he yielded to the entreaties of Śarmiṣṭhā and on this Devayānī departed to Śukra's place. Yayāti followed her and was cursed by Śukra to become old; but Śukra said that he could take the youth of somebody by exchanging it for his old age. He enquired of all his sons and all except Pūru refused to comply with his request. With Pūru's youth he enjoyed for long the company of Devayānī; narrated to her an old story of an ewe found in a well, loving a ram, who was not faithful at first but who spent ultimately a long time of enjoyment with her. He compared himself to that ram and said that he should thereafter bestow his thought on Hari. So he returned his youth to Pūru and led a life of penance at Bhṛgutunga after anointing Pūru on the throne and appointing his other sons in different parts of the kingdom; discourses of, to Pūru on gentleness and friendliness to all; was devoted to Hari. Parīkṣit compared to Yayāti for his dharma. 3) Bhā. IX. ch. 18 (whole); 19. 1-25; XII. 3. 10; X. 60. 41; I. 12. 24; Br. III. 68. 14-105; M. 24. 50, 66; 27. 14-22; chh. 30-35; 34. 4-7; 36. 6-13; Vā. 93. 13-16 and 20-76. Cursed that Yadu and his line be debarred from succeeding to the throne, though five dynasties of his sons are distinguished like the sun's rays. 4) Bhā. X. 45. 13; 74. 36; Br. III. 71. 202; 74. 275; Vā. 93. 76-102. Tenth in generation from Prajāpati. 5) M. 25. 4. Went to heaven but Indra sent him back; one version is that he stands in the antarikṣa and the other is that he went back to heaven; met Indra and narrated Pūru's coronation: Indra told him of the completion of his righteousness and hence birth on the earth. 6) Ib. 35. 4-5; chh. 36-37. Falling down, met Aṣṭaka and the other grandsons, who cleared him of his doubts regarding the course of fate and man's helplessress, the fruits of karma, the worlds enjoyed by him, the  bhauma naraka, the means to get samjñā, and the duties of four āśramas and munis. 7) Ib. chh. 38-40. These with Pratardana, Vasuman and Śibi offered a part of their punyam to make Yayāti enjoy heaven. Śibi leading Yayāti to heaven in a golden chariot as a result of their good deeds and truthfulness. 8) Ib. 42. 13-28; 273. 80.

ययाति
Yayāti  (II)--a Yāma deva. Br. II. 13. 92.

ययातिचरित
Yayāticarita --Śaunaka's narration to Śatānīka. M. Chh. 25-43.

ययु
Yayu --a horse of the moon's chariot. Vā. 52. 53.

यरलव
Yaralava --the hairs of the Veda. Vā. 104. 73.

यव
Yava  (I)--the food of Naimiṣeyas; havis of, in a śrāddha. Br. I. 1. 159; II. 7. 144; 32. 13; III. 14. 11; 19. 3; Vi. I. 6. 21, 24; II. 15. 30. Vi. III. 16. 6; IV. 10. 24.

यव
Yava  (II)--a measurement, eight times the yūkā (s.v.) M. 258. 18.

यवतीर्थम्
Yavatīrtham --on the Narmadā, no rebirth after a bath there. M. 191. 88-89.

यवन
Yavana --an asura who, induced by Nārada besieged Mathurā with three crores of mlecchas; saw Kṛṣṇa and ran  towards him when he fled to a cave. Yavana followed him and in the cave saw somebody sleeping; thought it was Kṛṣṇa and kicked him, when he woke up and burnt the asura to ashes by his energy. The sleeping person was Mucukunda (s.v.). 1) Bhā. X. 50. 44; 51. 1-23, 42. Thus he was vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. 2) Ib. II. 7. 34; X. 37. 16; Br. III. 73. 102; Vā. 98. 102.

यवन
Yavanas --a tribe on the west of India; a northern kingdom west of Bhāratavarṣa noted for horses; 1) Br. II. 16. 12 and 47; 18. 44; 31. 83; IV. 16. 17; 29. 131. M. 114. 11. 41; 121. 43; 144. 57; Vā. 88. 122; 45. 82, 116; 47. 42; 58. 82; 98. 107; Vi. II. 3. 8. attacked Bāhu and was defeated by Sagara; escaped with their moustaches (heads Vi. P.) shaved and lived in hills and caves; vanquished by Bharata; unsympathetic false and unrighteous; no right for abhiṣeka; eight kings ruled for eighty years (Vā. P.) (eighty seven M. P.); 2) Bhā. IX. 8. 5; 20. 30; Br. III. 48. 23-6, 44-9; 63. 120-134. after the Śakas; 3) Bhā. XII. 1. 30; Br. III. 74. 172-5, 200; M. 273. 19-20, 25; Vā. 99. 268, 360, 362, 388; Vi. IV. 3. 42, 47-8. purified of sin by devotion to Hari; 4) Bhā. II. 4. 18; IV. 27. 27; 28. 4-5; Vi. IV. 24. 53. originated from Turvasu a son of Yayāti. 5) M. 34. 30; 50. 76.

यवनेश
Yavaneśa --had no son, and hence appointed Gārgya to bless him with one; this son was Kālayavana. Vi. V. 23. 4-5.

यवस
Yavasa  (I)--(Yaśasya) one of the seven divisions of Plakṣadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 3.

यवस
Yavasa  (II)--a son of Sāvarṇi Manu. M. 9. 33.

यविक
Yavika --a son of Maṇibhadra. Vā. 69. 154. 

यविष्ट
Yaviṣṭa --a Śukra deva. Vā. 31. 8.

यवीनर
Yavīnara  (I)--the son of Dvimīḍha, and father of Kṛtimān. Bhā. IX. 21. 27; Vā. 99. 184.

यवीनर
Yavīnara  (II)--a son of Bharmyāśva (Haryaśva-Vi. P.) Bhā. IX. 21. 32; Vi. IV. 19. 59.

यवीनर
Yavīnara  (III)--a son of Ajamīḍha and Dhūminī M. 49. 70.

यवीनर
Yavīnara  (IV)--the son of Dvijāmīḍha and father of Dhṛtimān. Vi. IV. 19. 48-9.

यवीयस
Yavīyasa --a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 53; Vā. 61. 46.

यवीयान्
Yavīyān --a Pārāvata god. Br. II. 36. 14.

यश
Yaśa  (I)--a son of Kīrti. Br. II. 9. 62; Vā. 10. 37.

यश
Yaśa  (II)--a Vaikuṇṭha god. Br. II. 36. 57; Vā. 62. 9.

यश
Yaśa  (III)--one of the twenty Sutapa gaṇas. Vā. 100. 15; Br. IV. 1. 15.

यशस्करी
Yaśaskarī --the goddess enshrined at Kārtikeya. M. 13. 45. 

यशस्विज
Yaśasvija --a Pratardana god. Br. II. 36. 31.

यशस्विनी
Yaśasvinī --a Durgā and Viśvarūpinī who got śūla from Śiva, cakra from Viṣṇu, śankha from Varuṇa, śakti from Agni, bow and arrow from Marut, Vajra from Indra, caṣaka from Kubera, daṇḍa and pāśa from Yama, kuṇṭika from Brahmā, khaḍga and keṭa from Mṛtyu, jewels from Viśvakarman. Br. IV. 29. 80-8; 44. 90.

यशोदा
Yaśodā  (I)--the wife of Nanda (gopa); 1) Bhā. I. 8. 31; X. 2. 9; M. 47. 7; Vi. IV. 15. 31. gave birth to a female child who was Yogamāyā incarnate. Without her knowledge, Vasudeva placed Kṛṣṇa born on the same day in her bed and removed the girl to his residence. This was known to Nārada. 2) Bha. X. 3. 47-53; 36. 17; Vā. 96. 206-9. Regarded Kṛṣṇa as her own child; performed rakṣā to Kṛṣṇa after his killing Pūtanā; her concern at Kṛṣṇa's kicking the cart (Śakaṭāsura) upside down, and śānti arranged; distressed at Kṛṣṇa being carried away by the whirlwind (Tṛṇāvarta); glad to see him alive; her concern at Kṛṣṇa's eating mud, and wonder when he revealed his true form and the whole universe in his mouth; binding of Kṛṣṇa with a rope for breaking the pot and stealing butter; took home Kṛṣṇa playing on the river-bank; intense love to Kṛṣṇa; joy at his escape from Kālīya; surprise at Kṛṣṇa holding Govardhana; recalled his exploits at Uddhava's visit, and gave him a hearty welcome. 3) Bhā. X. 6. 19-29; Chh. 7-9 (whole); 11. 14-20; 15. 44; 17. 15; 25. 30; 46. 28-9. Went to Syamantapañcaka and was embraced with affection by Rohiṇī and Devakī; 4) Ib. X. 82. 36-9. represents the Mother Earth; 5) Br. III. 71. 212-3, 236 and 239. remedy of, against bāladoṣa; 6) Vi. V. 1. 77; 2, 3; 3. 20. prayer of, to Śakaṭa; 7) Ib. V. 5. 12. rope round the belly of Kṛṣṇa for mischief. 8) Ib. V. 6. 7, 14; 7. 20. 

यशोदा
Yaśodā  (II)--the mind-born daughter of Upahūta Pitṛs; wife of Viśvamahat; mother of Khaṭvānga. Br. III. 10. 90; Vā. 73. 40-41.

यशोदा
Yaśodā  (III)--a mind-born daughter of the Haviṣmantapitṛs, wife of Amśumān, daughter-in-law of Pañcajana, mother of Dilīpa, and grandmother of Bhagīratha. M. 15. 18-19.

यशोदानन्दन
Yaśodānandana --is Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 33. 20.

यशोदावत्सल
Yaśodāvatsala --is Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 22.

यशोदेवी
Yaśodevī --a queen of Brhanmanas and mother of Jayadratha. M. 48. 105; Vā. 99. 115.

यशोधरा
Yaśodharā(ī)  (I)--the wife Kanakapīṭha. Br. II. 11. 35.

यशोधरा
Yaśodharā  (II)--a daughter of Virocana and wife of Tvaṣṭā. Br. III. 187.

यशोधरा
Yaśodharā  (III)--a daughter of Devaka and one of the seven wives of Vasudeva. M. 44. 73.

यशोधारी
Yaśodhārī --mother of Kāmadeva. Vā. 28. 30. 

यशोनन्दि
Yaśonandi --a brother of Śiśunandi; ruled from Kilikilā. Bhā. XII. 1. 32-3.

यशोमेधा
Yaśomedhā --a god of the Sumedhasa group. Br. II. 36. 59.

यशोवति
Yaśovati --the sabhā of Iśāna in the eighth slope of Meru; bright with lustrous gold. Vā. 34. 91.

यष्टि
Yaṣṭi --staves and cudgels, used by the barbarians against the enemies; 1) Vi. V. 38. 17. used by the Ābhiras against Arjuna. 2) Ib. V. 38. 52.

यष्टिकृट्
Yaṣṭikṛṭ --a son of Arkāgni. Br. II. 12. 43.

यस्क
Yaska --an Ārṣeya pravara (Bhārgava). M. 195. 36.

यस्क
Yaskas --a Bhārgava branch. Br. III. 1. 100.

याक्षिका
Yākṣikā --the name of a mūrchana. Vā. 86. 59.

याज्ञवैक्य
Yājñavaikya  (I)--a pupil of Bāṣkala(i); taught the Trayī, to Śatānīka; 1) Bhā. XII. 6. 55; IX. 22. 38; Vi. III. 4. 18; IV. 21. 4. was given the fourth śākha of the Ṛg Veda by his master. 2) Vā. 60. 26. 

याज्ञवल्क्य
Yājñavalkya  (II)--a pupil of Vaiśampāyana and son of Devarāta (Brahmarāta Vi. P.) quarrelled with his guru and vomited the Yajus (s.v.) he learnt; propitiated the Sun god to get Chandas unknown to his guru. Pleased with him the Sun god instructed him in Vājasenyastas (Yajus ayātayāma, Vi. P.); in the form of a horse; 1) Bhā. XII. 6. 62-74; Br. II. 35. 9-30; Vi. III. Ch. 5 whole; Vā. 61. 17-19, 21. a Śrutaṛṣi; one of the madhyamādhvaryus; in charge of a śākhā in the Ṛg Veda; recipient of Janaka's present in a contest for great learning; 2) Br. II. 32. 3 and 16, 34. 27, 45-68. an Ekārṣeya. 3) M. 198. 4; 200. 6.

याज्ञवल्क्य
Yājñavalkya  (III)--(Kauśalya) learnt yoga from Hiraṇyanābha; siddha; disciple of Pauṣyañji. Bhā. IX. 12. 4; VI. 15. 13; Br. III. 63. 208; Vi. IV. 4. 107.

याज्ञवल्क्य
Yājñavalkya  (IV)--a sage who came to see Kṛṣṇa at Syamantapañcaka. Bhā. X. 84. 5.

याज्ञवल्क्य
Yājñavalkya  (V)--as a contemporary of Kalki; 1) Br. III. 73. 105. will precede Kalki. 2) M. 47. 249; 192. 10.

याज्ञवल्क्य
Yājñavalkya  (VI)--a son of Brahmavāha, who won the prize for learning in Janaka's (s.v). hall of sacrifice. Vā. 60. 41.

याज्ञवल्क्य
Yājñavalkya  (VII)--disqualified; 1) Vā. 61. 1, 6. learnt the yoga of Vasiṣṭha; 2) Ib. 88. 208. purohita of Kalki. 3) Ib. 98. 104. 

याज्ञवल्क्यम्
Yājñavalkyam --the portion of the Samhita composed by Yājñavalkya. Br. II. 35. 77; Vā. 61. 68.

याज्ञवल्क्य
Yājñavalkyas --belong to Kauśika gotra. Br. III. 66. 70; Vā. 91. 98.

यातना
Yātanā --a daughter of Bhaya and Mṛtyu. Bhā. IV. 8. 4.

यातुधान
Yātudhāna --the father of Jantudhāna; had ten sons, all Rākṣasas, and followers of the Śun god. Br. III. 7. 86-90; 8. 61; Vā. 69. 128; 75. 45.

यातुधान
Yātudhānas --evil spirits hurting children; 1) Bhā. II. 10. 39; VI. 8. 25; X. 6. 27; Vā. 47. 16; 52. 5; 66. 118. rushed to devour Manu engaged in meditation; 2) Bhā. VIII. 1. 17. put to flight by Kṛṣṇa; 3) Ib. X. 63. 10. freedom by association with the wise; 4) Ib. XI. 12. 3. one of the three Rākṣasa clans moving about in the day time and ruining the śrāddha. 5) Br. III. 3. 97; 8. 61; 11. 81.

यात्राकालविधानम्
Yātrākālavidhānam --If a king finds his enemy troubled by his neighbour or in other ways, if he feels strong in his hereditary army, if his neighbour is an ally, he can undertake the march in the month of Citra, Mārgaśīrṣa and when the planets are in his favour; he must engage after consulting the place and time; if rainy season there must be much of infantry and elephants; if spring or winter, chariots and horse; if summer camels or mules, and in other seasons, the fourfold army; the way must be such that yavasa (food) and fuel are available all along; after consultation with ministers and at an auspicious hour he must start; much importance is attached to the śakunam (good omens) and  dreams; 1) M. Ch. 240. methods of counteracting them; 2) Ib. Ch. 241. details of the auspicious things to look at and hear. 3) Ib. Ch. 243.

यादव
Yādava --a name of Kṛṣṇa. Vā. 96. 40; Br. III. 71. 41.

यादव
Yādavas  (I)--descendants of Yadu also called Mādhavas and Vṛṣṇis; a tribe who had Kṛṣṇa and Balarāma as their lords; 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 30; X. 67. 25; XI. 30. 11; Br. III. 71. 216; M. 271. 2. the maternal uncle line of Sagara with capital at Mathurā; Kakudmin was their king for some time; 2) Br. III. 49. 6; 61. 22. inhabitants of Dvāravatī; three crores strong; formerly Asuras who were killed in the Devāsura wars, and were born as men; of them 600,000 were warriors; eleven kulas or clans distinguished among them; all Vaiṣṇavas. 3) Vā. 86. 27; 96. 215 and 252-5.

यादव
Yādavas  (II)--the family of Yadu; 1) Vi. IV. 11. 30. unlimited in numbers; had 38 millions of teachers of army; 2) Ib. IV. 15. 45-6. consisted of 101 families over whom Viṣṇu was ruler and teacher; 3) Ib. IV. 15. 48-9. consisted of Kukuras, Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas; 4) Ib. V. 35. 16; 37. 39. to deprive them of all their possessions was the plan of Kamsa; 5) Ib. V. 15. 20. on Kṛṣṇa's advice and in fulfilment of the curse of sages to die of the iron club born to Sāmba, left Dvārakā for Prabhāsa; having drunk they attacked one another and finally took hold of rushes grown out of the iron pieces of musala and killed themselves. 6) Ib. V. 37. 38-47.

यादवनन्दन
Yādavanandana --is Kṛṣṇa, also Yādavendra. Br. III. 71. 200; 36. 48; Vā. 96. 196. 

यादवान्वय
Yādavānvaya --of the family of the Yādava tribe; Yādavas from Yadu, son of Yayāti; 1) M. 4. 17. begged excuse from Vāsudeva for suspecting him from killing Prasena; 2) Ib. 34. 30; 45. 18. 101 families are distinguished of whom Viṣṇu is the Lord; originally Asuras killed in the Devāsura war, became incarnate as Yādavas. 3) Ib. 47. 6; 25. 9.

यादव
Yādava samāja --(Yadukula samājam); the popular assembly of the Yādavas to whom Kṛṣṇa explained his adventure and recovery of the jewel Syamantaka. Vi. IV. 13. 61-2, 137, 146.

यादवी
Yādavī --the wife of Bāhu and mother of Sagara (s.v.) Br. III. 63. 130; Vā. 88. 131.

यादिवर्णा
Yādivarṇā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 37. 6.

यादृक्
Yādṛk --one of the names in the fourth Marut gaṇa. Vā. 67. 127.

यान
Yāna --a Sādhya god. Vā. 66. 15.

याम
Yāmas --the twelve devas born of Yajña and Dakṣiṇā and waited on Hariyajña; 1) Bhā. I. 3. 12; VIII. 1. 18. they are Yadu, Yayāti, Vivadha, Srāsata, Mati, Vibhāsa, Kratu, Prayāti, Viśruta, Dyuti, Vāyavya and Samyama, 2) Br. II. 9. 45; 13. 89-90; Vā. 10. 20; 31. 3, 6-7. born in the epoch of Svāyambhuva Manu. 3) M. 9. 3; 51. 40; Vi. I. 7. 21; 12. 12. 

यामदूत
Yāmadūtas --belong to Kauśika gotra. Br. III. 66. 72; Vā. 91. 100.

यामदेव
Yāmadevas --residents of Maharloka; by turns go to Janaloka; born of Prajāpati. Br. IV. 2. 51-55.

यामिनी
Yāminī --one of the wives of Tārkṣya and mother of locusts (śalabhas); 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 21. a Śakti. 2) Br. IV. 44. 75.

यामी
Yāmī --one of the ten wives of Dharma and mother of Nāgavīthi. M. 5. 15; Vā. 66. 2.

यामुन
Yāmunas --a tribe. Bhā. I. 10. 34.

यामुना
Yāmunā --on its north bank was situated Pratiṣṭhāna Vā. 91. 50.

यामुनि
Yāmuni --a Kaśyapa and a Trayārṣeya. M. 199. 13.

याम्यम्
Yāmyam(yā) --is Bharaṇi. Br. II. 21. 77; Vā. 66. 48.

याम्य
Yāmyas --a group of nāḍis emitting dew from the sun. Br. II. 24. 28.

याय
Yāyas --a class of deities. Br. IV. 39. 57. 

युक्त
Yukta  (I)--a deva. Br. II. 13. 94; Vā. 31. 8.

युक्त
Yukta  (II)--a son of Raivata Manu. M. 9. 21.

युक्त
Yukta  (III)--a sage of the XIV epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 44.

युग
Yuga --the intervening time between one yuga-sandhyapūrva and sandhyāmśa; four in number; Kṛta, Treta, Dvāpara and Kali. The extent is of 12,000 years of celestial measure; the duration of the yugas includes sandhya, 12,000 divine years, 1,000 caturyugas make a day of Brahmā. 1) Bhā. II. 8. 17; III. 11. 18; XII. Ch. 4 (whole) ; Vā. 7. 22; 23. 83; 24. 1; 31. 21; Vi. I. 3. 11-15. A yugam of five years, commencing with Śravaṇa and ending with Dhaniṣṭhā nakṣatra--the five years are respectively Agni, Sūrya, Soma, Vāyu and Rudra; consists of Samvatsara, Parivatsara, Idvatsara, Anuvatsara and Vatsara; revolves like the wheel owing to the movement of the Sun. 2) Br. II. 13. 115, 147; 21. 131; 24. 57 and 144; 28. 22; Vā. 31. 28, 49; 32. 57-65; 50. 182; 53. 116; 56. 21; Vi. II. 8. 72. Social conditions in; 3) M. Ch. 165. of Śaptaṛṣis. 4) Vā. 99. 419.

युगदत्त
Yugadatta --a son of Brahmadatta. M. 49. 58.

युगन्धर
Yugandhara  (I)--a son of Kuṇi; with him the Śaineya line. Bhā. IX. 24. 14; Vi. IV. 14. 3-4.

युगन्धर
Yugandhara  (II)--son of Bhūti--also Bhautya. Br. III. 71. 101; Vā. 96. 100.

युगन्धर
Yugandhara  (III)--a son of Dyumni and Śainya. M. 45. 24. 

युगपत्
Yugapat --a Mauneya. Vā. 69. 2.

युगम्
Yugam --a measurement equal to four hastas or dhanus; equal to a dhanurdaṇḍa. Br. II. 7. 100; Vā. 8. 106; 101. 125.

युगान्त
Yugānta --description of terrible state of, towards the end of a yuga. M. 144. 65-87.

युजाजित्
Yujājit --(Yudhājit Br. P. and M. P.) son of Mādrī and Vṛṣṇi and father of Śini. Bhā. IX. 24. 12; Br. III. 71. 19; M. 45. 2.

युद्धतुष्टि
Yuddhatuṣṭi --(Yuddhamuṣṭi, M. P.) a son of Ugrasena. Vā. 96. 132; Br. III. 71. 133; Vi. IV. 14. 20; M. 44. 75.

युधाजित्
Yudhājit  (I)--a Mantrakṛt. Br. II. 32. 105; Vā. 1. 146.

युधाजित्
Yudhājit  (II)--a son of Mādri and Vṛṣṇi. Br. III. 71. 19; M. 45. 2; Vā. 96. 18; Vi. IV. 13. 8.

युधाजित
Yudhājita --a son of Anamitra. M. 45. 25.

युधामन्यु
Yudhāmanyu --a partisan of Jarāsandha stationed by him at the western gate of Mathurā during its siege, and on the southern gate of Gomanta during its siege; went to Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse. Bhā. X. 50. 11[5]; 52. 11[9]; 82. 26. 

युधिष्ठिर
Yudhiṣṭhira --a son of Kuntī and Pāṇḍu born of Dharma, and father of Prativindhya and Sudhanu. Devaka was another son by Pauravī; descendants of Ajamīḍha; 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 27-30; I. 15. 13; Br. III. 71. 154 and 259; M. 46. 9; 50. 49; 103. 2; 189. 1; Vā. 96. 153; 99. 244; 112. 44; Vi. IV. 14. 35. was defeated in a game of dice and was banished to the forest with his brothers and their wife. Was met and consoled by Kṛṣṇa and Satyabhāmā. Kṛṣṇa's respects to: heard from Nārada that Kṛṣṇa was the Supreme Hari and was much pleased. Enquired of Him when he met him at the city of the Pāñcālas. He and his four brothers were met by Kṛtavarman. 2) Bhā. X. 64. 4-10; 58. 4 and 11; VII. 15. 79; X. 52. [56 (v) 5-8]; 57. 10[4]. His desire to perform the Rājasūya; joy at Kṛṣṇa's visit: provided suitable lodgings for Kṛṣṇa and his family. Addressing of the assembly on his desire to perform the Rājasūya, Kṛṣṇa asked him to get ready by defeating all the kings and bringing thus all the earth under his control: sent out his brothers in the four directions who defeated kings and brought much wealth. Was glad of Jarāsandha's death at the hands of his brothers: Sent for Purohitas for the sacrifice and invited all his kith and kin. The yajña comparable to that of Varuṇa; attended by all gods. For doing honour to the Sadasyas there was some doubt about the first place, and Sahadeva's suggestion of Kṛṣṇa's name was accepted by all except Śiśupāla who insulted him in the public assembly. Kṛṣṇa's silence. The Pāṇḍavas with the Matsyas and others unsheathed their swords, and Kṛṣṇa sent his cakra which cut off his head. After avabhṛta, Yudhiṣṭhira shone like Indra. All took leave of him in joy except Duryodhana, who became jealous of the success of the Rājasūya and of Draupadī, and of Kṛṣṇa. Heard of Duryodhana's fall in the sabhā and sent Kṛṣṇa with dress and ornaments to him, which he rejected. 3) Ib. X. 70. 41; 71. 23-6 and 44; 72. 1-14; 73. 35; Chh. 74 and 75 (whole); 76. 2[3]; 77. 7. On the occasion of the Rājasūya, asked Nārada how Caidya, Śiśupāla and Dantavaktra, haters of Hari became merged with him after their death, as also about Sanātana dharma; 4) Ib. VII. 1. 12-20 and 30; 11. 1. was met by Upaplāvya, by Kṛṣṇa and the other Yadus; 5) Ib. X. 78[95 (v) 2-5]; Ch. 78 whole; 79. 24; 80 [5-6], [16]. went to Kurukṣetra for war. On his side were Virāṭa, Drupada, Śīkhaṇḍi, Dhṛṣṭadyumna, Sātyaki, Kekayas, Saibya and others. Killed Śālva in the field. Welcomed Balarāma after  the war, and left for Hāstinapura and was anointed king: rule of righteousness. 5) Ib. X. 78[95 (v) 2-5]; Ch. 78 whole; 79. 24; 80 [5-6], [16]. Felt aggrieved over the slaughter of his kith and kin: agreed with Draupadī regarding the release of Aśvatthāma, went with his brothers to see Bhīṣma in his death-bed, like Kubera with the Yakṣas. Requested Bhīṣma to give him the truth of mokṣa dharma. Did the funeral rites to him, and after returning to the capital, ruled righteously with the approval of Dhṛtarāṣṭra and Kṛṣṇa: three aśvamedhas were performed by him at the suggestion of Kṛṣṇa: Missed seeing Dhṛtarāṣṭra and Gāndhārī, and learnt of their life in the Himālayas. The rule was characterised by plenty of rains and crops and by absence of diseases and difficulties; 6) Ib. I. 7. 49; 8. 47; Ch. 9. whole; 12. 4-6, 34; 13. 30-57; XI. 19. 11-12; III. 3. 18; M. 112. 3. learnt the Angāravrata from the sage, Pippalāda; 7) Ib. 72. 1. went to Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse and there met Kṛṣṇa and other friends; was taken leave of by the sages: left it for his capital. 8) Bhā. X. 82. 27; 83. 1-4; 84. 27, 69[3]. Felt the advent of Kali everywhere: Installed his grandson Parīkṣit on the throne and Vajra at Mathurā: Prepared to go to svarga: Clad in bark, fasting, and silent, he went towards north with a view to attaining heaven: was followed by his brothers: Attained Hari through friendship. 9) Ib. I. 15. 32-48; VII. 1. 30; Vi. IV. 20. 40; 24. 110-1; V. 12. 24; 35. 28.

युयुत्सु
Yuyutsu --survived the Kurukṣetra war: grieved at Kṛṣṇa's departure from Hāstinapura: received Vidura in joy. Bhā. I. 10. 9; 13. 3; X. 80.[4].

युयुध
Yuyudha --a son of Vasvananta, and father of Subhāṣaṇa. Bhā. IX. 13. 25. 

युयुधान
Yuyudhāna --(see Sātyaki) the grandson of Śini, and son of Satyaka, and father of Jaya. 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 14; Br. II. 71. 101; M. 45. 23; Vā. 96. 100; Vi. IV. 14. 2. Learnt the dhanurveda from Arjuna. Approved of Draupadī's suggestion to release Aśvatthaman: accompanied Kṛṣṇa to Hāstinapura; 2) Bhā. I. 7. 50; III. 1. 31; X. 58. 1; 63. 3. took active part in the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira: was sent to Dvārakā for defence; 3) Ib. X. 75. 6; 76. 7[5]. went with the sacrificial horse of Kṛṣṇa. 4) Ib. X. 89. 22[2].

युवत्य
Yuvatyas --one of the 14 gaṇas of apsaras born of the sun's rays. Br. III. 7. 19.

युवन
Yuvana --a god of the Lekha group. Br. II. 36. 76.

युवनाश्व
Yuvanāśva  (I)--a son of Candra, (Indu) and father of Śrāva. Bhā. IX. 6. 20-21; M. 12. 29.

युवनाश्व
Yuvanāśva  (II)--a righteous king and a son of (Pra) Senājit: Issueless though he had a hundred wives of whom Gaurī was one; went to the forest, where he got up the Aindra Iṣṭi, a sacrifice in honour of Indra. One night he felt thirsty and drank the consecrated water from the sacrificial pot. In due time a son was born splitting open the right side of his stomach. He lived for some time and went to Heaven. This son was the great Māndhāta (s.v.). Bhā. IX. 6. 25-32; 7. 1; Br. III. 63. 66; Vā. 88. 65; Vi. IV. 2. 48-63.

युवनाश्व
Yuvanāśva  (III)--An Angirasa and Mantrakṛt. By his curse half the Ganges came out. Br. II. 32. 108; III. 66. 29; Vā. 59. 99. 

युवनाश्व
Yuvanāśva  (IV)--a son of Andhra. Br. III. 63. 27; Vā. 88. 26.

युवनाश्व
Yuvanāśva  (V)--the son of Ambarīṣa, wife Narmadā, and son Sambhūta (Harita-Vā. P. and Vi. P.). Br. III. 63. 73; Vā. 88. 73; Vi. IV. 3. 2-3.

युवनाश्व
Yuvanāśva  (VI)--during his yajña, there were differences as to the division of Paśu. Brahmā interfered and appeased while Śakti got angry. Br. IV. 6. 59.

युवनाश्व
Yuvanāśva  (VII)--a son of Raṇāśva and father of Mandhāta; a Mantrakṛt. M. 12. 34; 145. 102.

युवनाश्व
Yuvanāśva  (VIII)--a son of Śūli of the 24th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 207.

युवराज
Yuvarāja --the Crown Prince; 1) Vā. 96. 219. his initiation against a King, an instance of antahkopa; 2) M. 223. 8. the residence of, to consist of five wings as that of the Kings. 3) Ib. 254. 17.

युषिताश्व
Yuṣitāśva --the son of Śankhaṇa and father of Viśvasaha. Vi. IV. 4. 106.

यूका
Yūkā --a measurement; eight times the likhyā (s.v.), (likṣā). Br. IV. 2. 121; M. 258. 18; Vā. 101. 121.

यूथपा
Yūthapās --Dhūmra Parāśaras. M. 201. 38. 

यूप
Yūpa --a sacrificial post; 1) Vā. 30. 148; 94. 17; 97. 28; 106. 43. circumambulation of the, leads to the fruit of Vājapeya; 2) Ib. 111. 31-2. in the Gaura hill on the banks of the Ganges where Indra made many sacrifices; 3) Br. II. 18. 28. near Brahmatīrtha where Brahmā performed sacrifice and planted a Yūpa. 4) Vā. 111. 31.

योग
Yoga  (I)--practices of: 1) Bhā. I. 2. 28; II. 1. 6; 2. 23; M. 1. 12. eight-fold: its characteristics. 2) Bhā. III. Ch. 28. Bhaktiyoga: 3) Ib. III. Ch. 29. born of Kriya, Kriyāyoga: 4) Ib. IV. 1. 51; Vā. 71. 64. the course of: followed by Nārada and others in their worship of Nārāyaṇa: 5) Bhā. V. 14. 45; 19. 10; VII. 3. 9; 11. 3. System of. 6) Ib. IX. 12. 4; X. 8. 45; Ch. 29 (whole) ; XI. 14. 20. Also three-fold jñāna, bhakti and karma: of this bhakti is important. 7) Ib. XI. 20. 6-8. Spoiled by bad association, especially association of women; 8) Ib. XI. 26. 3 and 24. is an aiśvarya, and possible through kriya and gurupriya: of 24 truths: Trayī is its limb; 9) Br. II. 34. 65; III. 3. 89; 9. 62 and 66; 10. 4 and 115; 19. 29 and 62; IV. 3. 55. other limbs, yama, niyama, 10) M. 13. 5; 183. 44 and 50; 193. 38; 247. 9; 248. 17. yajña, dāna, vedābhyāsa, and Dhāraṇa; philosophy of; 11) Ib. 2. 16; Vā. 66. 110. the strength of the Pitṛs, out of which soma grows; from jñāna; 12) Ib. 71. 66; 101. 75, 211, 350. methods of: control of the senses and the mind by fasting; a means to fructify austerities, then knowledge sprouts; 13) Ib. 77, 124-35. praise of; 14) Br. I. 6. 40; Vā. 18. 5-6. of Nakṣatra and Ṛṣi; 15) Ib. 99. 422. as a result of svādhyāya or study and vice-versa; 16) Vi. VI. 6. 2. explanation of the nature of yoga by Keśidhvaja to Khāṇḍikya. 17) Ib. VI. 7. 26-92.

योग
Yoga  (II)--a name of Śiva. Vā. 97. 175.

योगतन्त्र
Yogatantra --authorship attributed to Viṣvaksena. Bhā. IX. 21. 26. 

योगधर्म
Yogadharma --the first of all dharmas; 1) Vā. 83. 60. hidden by Kaśyapa in a cave and discovered and published by Sanatkumāra for the benefit of humanity; 2) Ib. 83. 83-4. not to be discussed with Yogins; but implicit obedience to it leads to heaven, and nonconformity would lead to hell. 3) Ib. 83. 91-94; 104. 14.

योगनिद्रा
Yoganidrā --of Viṣṇu on the waters: His primordial form; 1) Bhā. I. 3. 2-5. his sleep at Prayāgā; 2) M. 22. 9. left it for churning the ocean. 3) Ib. 150. 212; 249. 45.

योगप्रवृत्ति
Yogapravṛtti --the signs in the body of; when the Yogi feels himself and the earth full of tejas, then siddhi is attained; 1) Vā. 11. 62-63. Kriyāyoga. 2) Ib. 71. 64.

योगमाया
Yogamāyā --Ordered by Hari to transfer the dhāma of His in the womb of Devakī to that of Rohiṇī; she was to take birth as the daughter of Yaśodā and Nanda, at the same time he became Kṛṣṇa. She would be worshipped by all as Durgā, Bhadrakālī, Ambikā. She did as was commanded. Born of Yaśodā: taken to prison by Vasudeva leaving Devakī's babe at Yaśodā's bed. Dashed against a rock by Kamsa, she predicted that soon a baby born already would kill him (See Viṣṇumāyā). Bhā. X. 2. 6-15; 3. 45[1]-53; 4. 7-13, 29.

योगशास्त्र
Yogaśāstras --works on Yoga. Br. IV. 37. 27.

योगसिद्धा
Yogasiddhā --the sister of Bṛhaspati and wife of Prabhāsa, the eighth of the Vasus; son, Viśvakarma, author of the Sīlpaśāstra. Vā. 84. 15-16. 

योगसूनु
Yogasūnu --a son of Brahmadatta. Vā. 99. 180.

योगा
Yogā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 32. 17.

योगाग्नि
Yogāgni --by his quality of lordship, God assumes this shape in the world. Vā. 101. 217.

योगाचार्य
Yogācārya --Lord Nārāyaṇa. M. 171. 3.

योगात्म
Yogātma --the avatār of the Lord in the 28th dvāpara with a bachelor's body; entered the Meru cave with Brahmā and Viṣṇu and took the name of Nakuli. Vā. 23. 219-21.

योगि
Yogi --(Siddha) he who has practised brahmacarya, ahimsa, satya, non-stealing, and a parigraha and cultivated a sense of detachment; 1) Vā. 76. 28; Vi. VI. 7. 36. is superior to all for he performs tapas for a hundred years standing on one foot and living on air; 2) Vā. 71. 73. dharmaśāsanam of: ahimsaka; walking on good roads, drinking clean and filtered water and speaking truthful words; after serving his guru for a year goes about begging alms; 3) Ib. 16. 8-17. gets the dhāraṇa and tries to avoid the upasargas; must understand the seven sūkṣmas; mahisūkṣma, āpa, tejas, vāyu, vyoma, manas and buddhi sūkṣma, and the condition of these before these elements attain the sthūlabhāva; all of them inter-dependent; 4) Ib. 12. 9, 17. always intent on Prāṇāyāma becomes one with the great being; 5) Ib. 10. 94. the best to be fed on the occasion of the Śrāddha; superior to the feeding of a thousand householders, a hundred vānaprasthas and a thousand Brahmacārins. 6) M. 13. 5; 16. 10; Vā. 71. 67; Vi. III. 15. 2 and 24. 

योगिनी
Yoginī  (I)--a Varṇa śakti: an attendant on Śiva. Br. IV. 44. 59 and 105; III. 41. 30.

योगिनी
Yoginī  (II)--the goddess who stands in Kanakhalatīrtha and dances with Śiva. M. 193. 70.

योगेश्वर
Yogeśvara --a manifestation of Hari in the epoch of XIII Manu: a friend of Indra Divaspati. Bhā. VIII. 13. 32.

योगेश्वरी
Yogeśvarī --image of, with hanging tongue, knotted hair on the top of the head and a garland of skulls and bones, etc. M. 261. 33-6.

योगोत्पत्ति
Yogotpatti --the mind-born daughter of Kāvya Pitṛs. Br. III. 10. 86.

योजन
Yojana --8000 Dhanus make one yojana. Br. II. 7. 101; IV. 2. 126; Vā. 8. 107; 51. 37; 101. 113 and 126.

योधनिपुरम्
Yodhanipuram --a place sacred to Vāsudeva; bath in the tīrtha here rids one of his Brahmahatti doṣa. M. 191. 100.

योधयान
Yodhayānas --Kaśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 5.

योनि
Yoni  (I)--same as Dhūtapāpā: a river in Kuśadvīpa. M. 122. 71.

योनि
Yoni  (II)--the sacrificial fire-place, a vitasti in measurement and in appearance like the lips of an elephant. M. 265. 34. 

योनि
Yoni  (III)--from Prakṛti. Vā. 101. 228.

योनितोया
Yonitoyā --a sacred river of Śalmalidvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 28.

योनिमुद्रा
Yonimudrā --the symbol pertaining to Devī; description of. Br. IV. 42. 18; 44. 11.

योषित्सङ्ग
Yoṣitsaṅga --contact with women, condemned. Bhā. III. 31. 34-42.

यौधेय
Yaudheya --a son of Yudhiṣṭhira by Devakī. M. 50. 56.

यौधेया
Yaudheyā --the capital of Nṛga (Mṛga-Vā. P.). Br. III. 74. 21; Vā. 99. 21.

यौधेयी
Yaudheyī --a queen of Yudhiṣṭhira and mother of Devaka. Vi. IV. 20. 44.

यौवनाश्व
Yauvanāśva  (I)--a son of Ambarīṣa, and father of Hārita; 1) Bhā. IX. 7. 1. killed in a battle lasting for 14 months and more Aruddha and Ripu. 2) Br. III. 74. 8; Vā. 99. 8.

यौवनाश्व
Yauvanāśva  (II)--a grandson of Kāverī. Vā. 91. 58.  Ra

रक्त
Rakta --the thirtieth Kalpa; Brahmā got a son red in colour, dress and eyes; finding him to be Mahādeva, Brahmā bowed to him and contemplated upon Vāmadeva; Śarva appeared to him and made aṭṭahāsa when were born four sons beginning with Viraja. Vā. 22. 21-30.

रक्तकम्पना
Raktakampanā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 26.

रक्तकर्णा
Raktakarṇā(ī) --a Brahmarākṣasī. Vā. 69. 134. Br. III. 7. 99.

रक्तबीज
Raktabīja --an Asura killed by Durgā. Br. IV. 29. 76.

रक्तयोगिनीवल्लभ
Raktayoginīvallabha --one of the six charioteers of Lalitā. Br. IV. 20. 92.

रक्ता
Raktā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 12.

रक्ताक्ष
Raktākṣa --an attendant on Śiva. Br. III. 41. 26.

रक्ष
Rakṣa  (I)--a son of Vasiṣṭha and Ūrjā. Br. II. 11. 41. 

रक्ष
Rakṣa  (II)--the son of Khaśa: A fearful figure of three heads, three hands and three feet: roamed in the night in search of prey of men and animals. Br. III. 7. 61-77.

रक्ष
Rakṣa  (III)--meaning Pālana or protection from Rākṣasas. Vā. 69. 101.

रक्ष
Rakṣa  (IV)--resides in the sun's chariot during the month of Śucī; 1) Vi. II. 10. 7. Phālguna. 2) Ib. II. 10. 18.

रक्ष
Rakṣas --(also Rākṣasas) evil spirits. Bhā. X. 6. 27.

रक्षस
Rakṣasas --born of Viśvā and Kaśyapa; 1) M. 5. 1; 6. 29, 46. worship Barhiṣad manes. 2) Ib. 15. 4.

रक्षा
Rakṣā  (I)--the sister of Ṛkṣa; wife of Prajāpati and mother of Jāmbavan. Br. III. 7. 299-300.

रक्षा
Rakṣā  (II)--the use of amulets to protect children and others from evils. Vi. V. 5. 13.

रक्षात्मिका
Rakṣātmikā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 86.

रक्षावधारिणी
Rakṣāvadhāriṇī --a Varṇaśakti. Br. IV. 44. 61. 

रक्षोगणभोजन
Rakṣogaṇabhojana --one of 28 hells for the sin of Puruṣamedha. Bhā. V. 26. 7 and 31.

रक्षोघ्नमन्त्रपठनम्
Rakṣoghnamantrapaṭhanam --cited on the śrāddha day to keep off the Rākṣasas. Vi. III. 15. 31.

रक्षोघ्नम्
Rakṣoghnam sūktam --to be uttered in founding a new temple; 1) M. 265. 25. to be uttered in palace building; 2) Ib. 268. 34. of the Sāmavedins, recited in tank ritual. 3) Ib. 58. 37.

रक्षोहा
Rakṣohā --a son of Arkāgni. Br. II. 12. 43; Vā. 29. 40.

रघु
Raghu  (I)--a son of Dīrghabāhu, and a man of everlasting glory. His son was Aja. Lust after more territory: knew the power of Viṣṇu's yogamāyā. Bhā. IX. 10. 1; XII. 3. 9; II. 7. 44; Br. III. 63. 183; Vā. 88. 183; Vi. IV. 4. 84-5.

रघु
Raghu  (II)--a son of Nighna. M. 12. 47.

रघुनन्दन
Raghunandana --an epithet of Viṣṇu. M. 54. 18.

रङ्गम्
Raṅgam --the wrestling place where separate seats were arranged for judges, nobles, women, cowherds, etc. Women of the palace and the city attended such matches; these women recalled Kṛṣṇa's former exploits. Vi. V. 20. 23-29, 43, 45-7. 

रंगोपजीवक
Raṃgopajīvaka --professional actors. Vā. 101. 164.

रचना
Racanā --a Daitya lady and queen of Tvaṣṭa. Bhā. VI. 6. 44.

रज
Raja  (I)--son of Viraja and father of Ketuman (Śatajit, Vi. P.). Br. II. 14. 70; III. 8. 19; Vi. II. 1. 40.

रज
Raja  (II)--son of Dhara. Br. III. 3. 22.

रज
Raja  (III)--is Rājasīvṛtti: Leads to duhkha and Tṛṣa. Br. IV. 3. 32-41.

रज
Raja  (IV)--one of the seven sons of Vasiṣṭha and Ūrjā; wife Mārkaṇḍeyī and son Ketuman. Vā. 28. 36-37; Vi. I. 10. 13.

रज
Raja  (V)--the quality present both in tamas and satva as oil in the oil-seed and ghee in milk; it is the result of agitation in the pradhāna. Vā. 3. 2; 5. 10, 12.

रज
Raja  (VI)--son of Arija; a Rājaṛṣi and tapassiddha. Vā. 33. 60; 57. 122.

रज
Raja  (VII)--one of the ten branches of the Rohita clan of devas. Vā. 100. 90. 

रजक
Rajaka --a washerman; 1) M. 192. 20. Śuklatīrtham, compared to, in washing sins; to be fined a māṣa of gold by the king for not properly washing. 2) Ib. 227. 155. the washerman of Kamsa was killed on his refusing cloths to Kṛṣṇa and Rāma. 3) Vi. V. 19. 14-17.

रजत
Rajata --son of Varatri. Br. III. 1. 79.

रजतनाभ
Rajatanābha  (I)--the milkman of the Yakṣas on the earth and father of Maṇidhara. Born of Yakṣa and apsaras Kratusthalā. Br. II. 36. 216; III. 7. 111.

रजतनाभ
Rajatanābha  (II)--the grandfather of the Yakṣas, married Bhadrā, the daughter of Anuhrāda, the Daitya; father of Maṇibhadra and Maṇivara; wives of these two become the aunts of Samsiddhakaraṇa. Vā. 69. 151-2.

रजतम्
Rajatam --silver, came out of Śiva's eyes; hence dear to Pitṛs; but inauspicious and to be avoided in devakāryas. M. 17. 22-3.

रजनी
Rajanī --a R. in Śālmalidvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 10.

रजि
Raji --son of Āyu and father of five hundred (hundred M.P.) sons known as Rajeyas; a devotee of Nārāyaṇa; was invested with conquering powers; fearing Prahlāda and other enemies, Indra gave his kingdom to Raji; once when the Devāsura (Kolāhala) war broke out between Prahlāda and Indra extending for 300 years both parties invoked his assistance; he joined the Devas who unlike the Asuras  accepted him as their Lord and he vanquished the Asuras; Indra became thus his adopted son to whom he gave back his kingdom and returned to forest for penance. Indra, however, returned the kingdom to Raji; after Raji's death his sons appropriated the kingdom and refused to give it to Indra; the latter therefore killed all of them with the help of Bṛhaspati. 1) Bhā. IX. 17. 1-16; Br. III. 67. 2, 79-105; 72. 86; M. 24. 35-42; Vā. 97. 86; Vi. IV. 8. 3, 21; 9. 1-23. It is said where Raji is, there Lakṣmī finds her abode; where Lakṣmī is there Dhṛti lives; where Dhṛti resides, Dhāma lives; where Dhāma lives, there is Jaya. 2) Vā. 92. 74-99.

रजेयु
Rajeyu --one of the ten sons of Raudrāśva. Vā. 99. 124.

रञ्जन
Rañjana --son of Varūtri. Vā. 65. 78.

रणक
Raṇaka --son of Kṣudraka, and father of Suratha. Bhā. IX. 12. 15.

रणचन्द्र
Raṇacandra --born of Pulaha. Br. III. 7. 178.

रणञ्जय
Raṇañ(m)jaya  (I)--a son of Kṛtañ(m)jaya, and father of Samjāya; of the Bṛhadbala (Bārhadbalāyana-Bhā. P.) dynasty. Bhā. IX. 12. 13; Vi. IV. 22. 7-8.

रणञ्जय
Raṇañjaya  (II)--a son of Vrāta. Vā. 99. 287.

रणधृष्ट
Raṇadhṛṣṭa --a son of Dhṛṣṭa. M. 12. 21. 

रणाश्व
Raṇāśva --a son of Samhatāśva. M. 12. 34.

रणेजय
Raṇejaya --a son of Kṛtamjaya, the Ikṣvāku king. M. 271. 11.

रति
Rati  (I)--a name of Śatarūpā; wife of Svāyambhuva Manu. Br. II. 9. 38; Vā. 10. 13.

रति
Rati  (II)--the consort of Kāma. Hearing that he was burnt by Śiva, she clad herself in sorrowful clothes. Śyāmalā restored him back to life, and in her presence both were married again; 1) Br. IV. 30. 37-51; M. 7. 13; 100. 32; 154. 219, 272-3; a śakti; 2) Br. IV. 19. 64-71; 44; 72. mother of Harṣa; 3) Vā. 10. 38. Prīti became her co-wife; after the burning of Kāma, was Māyāvatī in Śambara's house and brought up Pradyumna (an incarnation of Kāma); 4) Vi. I. 7. 31; V. 27. 30. Image of, with swan. 5) M. 261. 55.

रति
Rati  (III)--a kalā of the moon. Br. IV. 35. 92.

रति
Rati  (IV)--a son of Śatarūpā. M. 4. 25.

रतिप्रिया
Ratipriyā --the goddess enshrined at Gangādvāra. M. 13. 37.

रती
Ratī  (I)--the wife of Vibhu and mother of Pṛthusena. Bhā. V. 15. 6.

रती
Ratī  (II)--see Māyāvatī. Bhā. X. 55. 7. 

रत्नकूटा
Ratnakūṭā  (I)--one of Atri's wives. Br. III. 8. 76.

रत्नकूटा
Ratnakūṭā  (II)--a daughter of Bhadrāśva and Ghṛtācī. Vā. 70. 69.

रत्नकूटि
Ratnakūṭi --the tenth daughter of Raudrāśva. Vā. 99. 126.

रत्नधर
Ratnadhara --a Mt. south of Mānasa; 1) Vā. 36. 23. residence of the seven sages. 2) Ib. 38. 27; 39. 45.

रत्नधेनु
Ratnadhenu --the gift of a cow with precious gems set in every part of its body takes one to the world of Viṣṇu and makes him attain the place of Śambhu; 1) M. 274. 10; 288. 1-17. Gudadhenu, fit for gift on the Viśokadvādaśi day. 2) Ib. 82. 2.

रत्नमय
Ratnamaya śālā --of Lalitā described. Br. IV. ch. 33 (whole).

रत्नशैल
Ratnaśaila  (I)--(Ratnācalam): of thousand pearls is the best; then of 500 and 300; with 250 pearls Viṣkambhaparvatas to be made around the principal one; the giver is relieved from Brahmahatti and other sins. M. 83. 6; 90. 1.

रत्नशैल
Ratnaśaila  (II)--a chief hill of Krauñcadvīpa like Vaḍavāmukha. Vi. II. 4. 50.

रत्ना
Ratnā --a daughter of Śaibya, queen of Akrūra and mother of eleven heroic sons. M. 45. 28. 

रत्नाकर
Ratnākara --ocean personified. Br. IV. 15. 21.

रत्नानि
Ratnāni  (I)--of kings; are seven in number; cakra, ratha, maṇi, queen, nidhi, horses and elephants. Br. II. 29. 74-5; M. 217. 37; Vā. 57. 68.

रत्नानि
Ratnāni  (II)--the essence got by mountains by milking the cow-earth; 1) M. 10. 25. seven gems in the epoch of Svāyambhuva; generally gems. 2) Vi. III. 12. 2.

रत्नि
Ratni --a measurement of 21 angula parvas. Br. II. 7. 98; IV. 2. 122. M. 16. 25; 58. 7. Vā. 101. 122.

रथ
Ratha --of the moon, description of; sprang out of waters with ten horses, charioteer, etc., has three wheels. Vā. 52. 50-4.

रथकृच्छ्र
Rathakṛcchra --a grāmaṇi with the sun in spring. Vā. 52. 4.

रथकृत्
Rathakṛt  (I)--the yakṣa presiding over the month of Madhu. Bhā. XII. 11. 33; Br. II. 23. 3.

रथकृत्
Rathakṛt  (II)--one of the seven Prānins of the king. Vā. 57. 70, Br. II. 29. 76.

रथचित्र
Rathacitra  (I)--with the sun in the months of Śuci and Śukra (in the month of Āṣāḍha Vi. P.). Br. II. 23. 7; Vi. II. 10. 8.

रथचित्र
Rathacitra  (II)--a grāmaṇi with the sun in summer. Vā. 52. 7. 

रथञ्ज
Rathañja --a Yakṣa, who resides in the sun's chariot during the month of Mādhava. Vi. II. 10. 5.

रथन्तर
Rathantara --a Jayādeva and son of Brahmā; a mantraśarīra. Br. III. 3. 6; Vā. 66. 6; 67. 5.

रथन्तरकल्प
Rathantarakalpa --an account of, in the Brahmavaivarta Purāṇa; 1) M. 53. 34; 69. 1, 5. king Puṣpavāhana belonged to this aeon. 2) Ib. 100. 1.

रथन्तरम्
Rathantaram  (I)--the Sāma sung by Bhauvana; elephants, Kapila and Puṇḍarīka born of; 1) Br. III. 7. 324 and 335; Vā. 9. 48; 22. 8; 30. 119; 69. 209. to be heard on the śrāddha day; 2) M 17. 38. to be uttered while installing a new image; 3) Ib. 58. 37; 265. 27. from the first face of Brahmā. 4) Br. II. 8. 50; III. 4. 2. Vi. I. 5. 53.

रथन्तरम्
Rathantaram  (II)--(Sūryamaṇḍalam) 88,000 yojanas in measurement. Vā. 21. 75 and 79.

रथभृत्
Rathabhṛt --a yakṣa who resides in the sun's chariot in the months of Caitra and Madhu. Vi. II. 10. 3.

रथराजी
Ratharājī --a wife of Vasudeva. M. 46. 21.

रथरेणु
Rathareṇu --a measurement; 8 trasareṇu. Br. IV. 2. 120; Vā. 101. 120. 

रथवर
Rathavara --a son of Bhīmaratha, and father of Navaratha; 1) Br. III. 70. 42. adhered to dharma and satya. 2) Vā. 95. 41-2.

रथसप्तमि
Rathasaptami --the Saptami of the month of Māgha when the sun turns his chariot; fit for making gifts and performing śrāddha to please Pitṛs. M. 17. 9-10.

रथस्वन
Rathasvana  (I)--the Yakṣa presiding over the month of śukra (in the sun's chariot during the month of ŚuciVi. P.). Bhā. XII. 11. 35; Br. II. 23. 7; Vi. II. 10. 7.

रथस्वन
Rathasvana  (II)--a grāmaṇi with the sun in the summer. Vā. 52. 7.

रथाकार
Rathākāra --a kingdom of Kuśadvīpa. Br. II. 14. 29; 19. 58.

रथान्तर
Rathāntara  (I)--a Kṣatropeta dvija. Br. III. 66. 88.

रथान्तर
Rathāntara  (II)--a disciple of Satyaśriya; a śākha pravartaka, śākhapūrṇarathītara (?). Vā. 60. 29, 65.

रथान्तर
Rathāntara  (III)--an elephant. Vā. 69. 219.

रथिमुख्य
Rathimukhya --a son of Bhajamāna. Va. 96. 135. 

रथी
Rathī --a military title below mahāratha 1) Vā. 99. 249. earned by Yayāti and Kārtavīryārjuna. 2) Br. III. 68. 20; 69. 21.

रथीतर
Rathītara  (I)--a son of Pṛṣadaśva; had no issue and at his desire, Angiras blessed him with sons. Their descendants became Angirasas and Kṣatropeta dvijas. Bhā. IX. 6. 1-3; Br. III. 63. 6-7; Vā. 88 6-7. Vi. IV. 2. 9-10.

रथीतर
Rathītara  (II)--a pupil of Satyaśṛṇga--also Śākhavaiṇa; author of three Samhitas given to four pupils Paila and others; also author of Nirukta--a Trayārṣeya, with Angiras and Virūpa; 1)  Br. II. 34. 32. 35. 3; M. 196. 38; Vā. 61. 2. had four disciples, Ketava, Dalaki, Dhamaśarma and Devaśarma; all of them became murderers of Brahmanas on the death of their master; they approached the creator for light who advised them to make a visit to Vālukesvaram to get redeemed of their sins by bath and prayer; on the completion of the pilgrimage they reached Sūryamaṇḍalam. 2) Ib. 60. 65-72.

रथीतर
Rathītara  (III)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 234.

रथीतर
Rathītara  (IV)--a rājaṛṣi who became a Brahmana and attained siddhi. Vā. 91. 117.

रथीतर
Rathītaras --a branch of the Angirasas. Vā. 65. 106.

रथोर्मि
Rathormi --a Pratardana god. Br. II. 36. 31. 

रथौजस्
Rathaujas --a Yakṣa with the sun in the months of Madhu and Mādhava. Br. II. 23. 3.

रन्ति
Ranti  (I)--a son of Nandana. Br. III. 71. 192.

रन्ति
Ranti  (II)--a son of Riveyu, his wife was Sarasvatī. Vā. 99. 128, 129.

रन्तिदेव
Rantideva  (I)--a son of Samkṛti: attained permanent fame. He performed a sacrifice when he gave up all he had and suffered with his family having nothing to eat for fortyeight days. When he had something to eat, there came a Brahmana guest and a Vṛṣala, and another guest with dogs around him; they all shared it. When he had something to drink, there came a Pulkasa and asked for the drink and got it. To such a high soul, the gods showed darśan. All his followers became Yogins, himself having realised the Yogamāyā of Viṣṇu. 1) Bhā. IX. 21. 2-18; X. 72. 21; II. 7. 44; Vi. IV. 19. 22. Parīkṣit compared to him for his generosity. 2) Bhā. I. 12. 24; Br. III. 34. 38.

रन्तिदेव
Rantideva  (II)--a son of Mahāyaśas. M. 49. 37.

रन्तिपाल
Rantipāla --a son of Nandana. Br. III. 71. 192. 

रन्तिभास
Rantibhāsa --a son of Ṛteyu, and father of Sumati and two other sons. Bhā. IX. 20. 6.

रन्ध्रकरक
Randhrakarakas --a kingdom of the West watered by the Sindhu. Br. II. 18. 48.

रभस
Rabhasa --a son of Rambha, and father of Gambhīra. Bhā. IX. 17. 10.

रभसा
Rabhasā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 26.

रमण
Ramaṇa --a son of Dhara. M. 5. 24.

रमणक
Ramaṇaka  (I)--An upadvīpa to Jambūdvīpa: a territorial division of Śālmalidvīpa: 1) Bhā. V. 19. 30; 20. 9. The island where Kālīya originally lived. Here the serpents agreed to give bali every fortnight to Garuḍa, except Kālīya. 2) Ib. X. 16. 63; 17. 1-4. South of Śveta and north of Nīla. People live here for thousands of years (10150 years Vā. P.) by drinking the juice of the fruit of the banyan tree, Rohaṇa in the island; people living there, pleasant to look at, devoid of disease and difficulties. 3) Br. II. 15 62-5; M. 113. 61; Vā. 45. 2-5.

रमणक
Ramaṇaka  (II)--son of Vītihotra of Puṣkaradvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 31.

रमणा
Ramaṇā --the Goddess enshrined at Rāmatīrtha. M. 13. 40. 

रमा
Ramā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 90.

रमोद
Ramoda --Ārṣeyapravaras (Bhārgavas). M. 195. 39.

रम्बला
Rambalā --a daughter of the Vāleyas; originator of the Kambaleyagaṇa. Vā. 69. 21.

रम्भ
Rambha  (I)--a son of Vivimśati, and father of Khaninetra. Bhā. IX. 2. 25.

रम्भ
Rambha  (II)--a son of Āyu, and father of Rabhasa: known for his valour; 1) Bhā. IX. 17. 1 and 10; Br. III. 67. 2. had no son. 2) Vi. IV. 8. 3; 9. 24.

रम्भ
Rambha  (III)--the fifth Kalpa. Vā. 21. 30.

रम्भक
Rambhaka --with the sun in the months of Śuci and Śukra. Br. II. 23. 8.

रम्भा
Rambhā  (I)--the Apsaras presiding over the month of Śuci; 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 36. wife of Maya; 2) Br. III. 6. 28; 7. 7. presiding over the month of Ūrja. 3) Ib. II. 23. 22; IV. 33. 18; Bhā. XII. 11. 44.

रम्भा
Rambhā  (II)--the goddess enshrined at Malaya hills: a mother goddess. M. 13. 29; 179. 20. 

रम्भा
Rambhā  (III)--An Apsaras versed in dancing; 1) M. 24. 28; Vā. 69. 6. created by Brahmā; 2) M. 136. 11. going with the sun sometime; 3) Ib. 126. 23. seized by the Asuras; 4) Ib. 126. 7; 133. 9. in the Sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. 5) Ib. 161. 75.

रम्भा
Rambhā  (IV)--a snake with the sun in summer. Vā. 52. 6.

रम्भा
Rambhā  (V)--with the sun during Phālguna month; Śukra or Āṣāḍha; 1) Vi. II. 10. 18. along with other Apsaras cursed by Aṣtāvakra. 2) Ib. V. 38. 73. 77.

रम्य
Ramya  (I)--son of Āgnīdhra, and Lord of Nīlam (Nīlavarṣa-Vā. P.); 1) Br. II. 14. 46-50; Vā. 33. 39, 42. placed in charge of the kingdom bordering on Nīlācala. 2) Vi. II. 1. 17 and 20.

रम्य
Ramya  (II)--(Keśari s.v.) Mt. in Śākadvīpam. Vā. 49. 84.

रम्यक
Ramyaka  (I)--son of Āgnīdhra. Bhā. V. 2. 19.

रम्यक
Ramyaka  (II)--(Nīlavarṣa) a continent bounded by Nīla on one side: Here Viṣṇu in the form of Matsya is worshipped by Manu. Bhā. V. 16. 8; 18. 24-28. M. 113. 30; Vā. 34. 30. Vi. II. 2. 14.

रम्या
Ramyā --a daughter of Meru, and wife of Ramyaka. Bhā. V. 2. 23.

रय
Raya --son of Purūravas and Ūrvaśī. Father of Eka. Bhā. IX. 15. 1-2. 

रव
Rava --disciple of Lokākṣi, an avatār of the lord. Vā. 23. 134.

रवन
Ravana --son of Dharma (Vasu). Vi. I. 15. 113.

रवय
Ravayas --their lord is Viṣṇu. M. 8. 4.

रवि
Ravi  (I)--from av to protect--see Sūrya; 1) Br. II. 21. 4; 23. 26; 24. 35; III. 59. 37; IV. 1. 138; Vā. 50. 60; Vi. II. 8. 11-12. got a place among śrāddhadevas; 2) M. 13. 1. the śrāddhadeva; 3) Ib. 15. 43. an Āditya; 4) Ib. 171. 56. in three forms, Gayāditya, Uttarārka, and Dakṣiṇārka; 5) Vā. 106. 57. movements of the sun, detailed; maṇḍala measurement of; rise at Samyamana, mid-day at Amarāvatī, mid-night at Suṣā, setting at Vibhāvarī; other similar calculations; the movement in a muhūrta; movement for a day and a night; movement in Dakṣiṇāyanam; chariot of, limbs of the year; the seven horses are Cchandas, Gāyatrī, Triṣṭub, Jagatī, Anuṣṭub, Paṅktī, Bṛhatī and Uṣṇik; gives a list of sages, Gandharvas, Apsaras, Nāgas, Grāmaṇi and Rākṣasas with the sun in the six seasons; these go with the sun in his own wheel; 6) M. chh. 124-6; Vā. 100. 222. a marutgaṇa; 7) M. 171. 52. standard of Nāga in the Tārakāmaya. 8) Ib. 173. 9.

रवि
Ravi  (II)--son of Svārociṣa Manu. Br. II. 36. 19; Vā. 62. 19.

रविद्वारम्
Ravidvāram --the path of devas. Vā. 8. 198.

रविनन्दन
Ravinandana --a name of Manu. M. 1. 11 and 22. 

रविपदम्
Ravipadam --in Gayā. Vā. 109. 19.

रविमूर्ति
Ravimūrtis --four, representing the four Yugas. Vā. 108. 36.

रशदु
Raśadu --a son of Svāhā and father of Citraratha; the best among givers; performed many sacrifices. Vā. 95. 16-17.

रश्मि
Raśmi --one of the 20 Sutapa gaṇas. Vā. 100. 15.

रस
Rasa  (I)--a Tuṣita god. Br. III. 3. 19.

रस
Rasa  (II)--the guṇa of waters becomes absorbed in jyotis or tejas and consequently waters reach the verge of destruction. Vā. 101. 42. 102. 9.

रसकर्षनिका
Rasakarṣanikā --a devī. Br. IV. 19. 18; 36. 69; 44. 118.

रसकल्याणिनी
Rasakalyāṇinī --a vrata to be performed on the third day of the Māgha month; sacred to Lalitā; this is continued every month preceded by fasting and followed by gifts to Brahmanas; the person who does this enjoys in the world of Gaurī. It is equal to performing 1000 Yajñas. M. ch. 63 (whole)

रसकुल्या
Rasakulyā --a R. in Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 15. 

रसज्ञ
Rasajña --a companion of Puramjana, allegorically the organ of taste. See mukhyā. Bhā. IV. 25. 49; 29. 11.

रसधेनु
Rasadhenu --fit for gift during the Viśokadvādaśi vrata. M. 82. 19.

रसन
Rasana --a son of the Rākṣasa Vidyuta. Br. III. 7. 95.

रसपासर
Rasapāsara --son of Kuthumi. Vā. 61. 38.

रसराज
Rasarāja --one of the eight saubhāgyams. M. 60. 8, 28.

रससिद्धि
Rasasiddhi --is a yoga siddhi. Br. IV. 36. 52; 44. 108.

रसातल
Rasātala --(also Pātālam) the underworld of rocky soil. Here live Paṇis, Nāgas, Nivātakavacas and Kāleyas; all dānavas of great strength and enterprising spirit and afraid of Hari and Sarama, the messenger of Indra. 1) Bhā. V. 24. 7 and 30; Br. II. 19. 171; 20. 10 and 12, 39-40; 30. 31; M. 47. 63; Vā. 49. 163; 97. 95; 100. 157; Vi. IV. 3. 4 and 8; V. 1. 28. Visited by Arjuna in search of the dead child of the Dvārakā Brahmana; 2) Bhā. X. 89. 44. burnt by Pralaya; 3) Br. III. 53. 1; 72. 96. 73. 46 and 48; IV. 1. 153. the Asuras entered it helpless; 4) M. 47. 212-13, 233. Vasu, cursed by the sages to live there, for his decision against the killing of Paśu in sacrifices; 5) Ib. 143. 24-25; 166. 3; 248, 4, 11, 53, 67ff; Vā. 57. 110. of 10,000 Yojanas in extent; other talams are Atala, Sutala, Vitala, Gabhastala, Mahātala, Sritala, and Patāla with the characteristics of black, white, pītam, chunam, rocky and gold they are in groups of earth, water and space. 6) Ib. 6. 25; 50. 9-14. 

रसौ
Rasau --the months of Madhu and Mādhava. Br. II. 13. 9; Vā. 30. 8.

रहम्वर्च
Rahamvarcas --a son of Sampāti. M. 49. 4.

रहस्ययोगिनी
Rahasyayoginī --a group of deities. Br. IV. 19. 46.

रहूगण
Rahūgaṇa --the king of Sindhu--sauvīra kingdom: employed Jaḍa-Bharata as his palanquin bearer, and found fault with him for not bearing it properly: He understood that he was a Brahmana, felt remorse and enquired who he was. Heard precepts on Ātmavidyā from Bharata and became devoted to Hari in a spirit of detachment. Bhā. V. 10. 1-25; 13. 25.

राका
Rākā  (I)--a daughter of Angiras and Smrtī; wife of Dhātri, and mother of Prātas; 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 34; VI. 18. 3; Vā. 28. 15; Vi. I. 10. 7. a Śakti. 2) Br. IV. 32. 12.

राका
Rākā  (II)--a R. in Śālmalidvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 10.

राका
Rākā (Ekā?)  (III)--the full moon shining resplendent and much pleasing to the eye; 1) Br. II. 11. 18; 28. 38, 46 and 60; Vā. 50. 201; 56. 35, 41 and 55. a day fit for giving gifts; 2) Vi. II. 8. 80. ety. of. 3) Vā. 56. 41.

राका
Rākā  (IV)--Two lavas of the afternoon of Pratipada. M. 133. 36; 141. 33, 41, 51. 

राक्षस
Rākṣasa --a form of marriage by which Kṛṣṇa married Rukmiṇī. But Rukmi objected to this form of marriage. Bhā. X. 52. 18 and 41; 54. 18; Vi. III. 10. 24.

राक्षस
Rākṣasas  (I)--see Rakṣas: semi-divine beings; 1) Bhā. VI. 8. 24; Br. II. 32. 1 and 2; 35. 191. different clans--Devarākṣasas like Nairṛtas, Bhūmirākṣasas, Guhyarākṣasas Daityarākṣasas like Kāpileyas; Another classification is dīvācaras (Yajñamukhas) (Yātudhāna, Brahmadhāna, and Vārtta) and Niśācaras (Paulastya, Nairṛta, Āgastya, and Viśvāmītra) who ruin the Śrāddha, but worship Pitṛs; 2) Ib. III. 7. 132167; 8. 60-65; 10. 111; 11. 81; IV. 1. 155; 2. 26; 20. 47; Vā. 70. 54-7. of sharp teeth, reside in Bhaumanarakam; 3) M. 39. 8-9. sons of Yātudhāna; 4) Vā. 69. 128. description of their forms and features; 5) Ib. 70. 54-63. mother, Svasā; 6) Vi. I. 21. 25. both Dānavas and Daityas live in Pātāla. 7) Ib. II. 5-4.

राक्षस
Rākṣasas  (II)--ety: (see also Yakṣa, Niśācara). When out of hunger the first created beings began to swallow water, the Rākṣasas tried to protect the waters; then the hairs of Prajāpati stood on end with anger; out of this came snakes of all sorts; 1) Br. II. 8. 32; Vā. 9. 30-5; Vi. I. 5. 43. occupy Vajraka hill. 2) Vā. 30. 90; 31. 12; 34. 55; 39. 36; 100. 159; 101. 3, 28.

राक्षसजित्
Rākṣasajit --a son of Jāmbavan. Br. III. 7. 303.

राक्षसमातृ
Rākṣasamātṛs --eight in number: perhaps the seven daughters of Khaśa and Nīlā; create fear and disease among children (human beingsVā. P.). Br. III. 7. 156-61; Vā. 69. 188.

राक्षसी
Rākṣasī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 16. 

राक्षसीवेला
Rākṣasīvelā --when no ceremonies are to be performed; the first three muhūrtas or nālikas of the morning, saṅghava (8-30 to 11 A.M.) of noon, afternoon and evening. M. 22. 82-83.

राक्षी
Rākṣī --a chief doorkeeper in Geyacakraratha. Br. IV. 19. 88.

राग
Rāga --carries away bhūta; leads to samsāra and its ills; Viṣayarāga, reason for re-birth. Vā. 102. 67, 69.

राघव
Rāghava --see Rāma (s.v.); 1) Br. III. 5. 36. killed Tāḍakā; 2) Vā. 67. 73. his consort was Sītā; 3) Vi. I. 9. 144. an avatār of Viṣṇu to kill Rāvaṇa. 4) Ib. IV. 14. 49.

राघवेश्वरम्
Rāghaveśvaram --a tīrtha sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 66.

राज
Rāja  (I)--one of the ten branches of the Rohita clan of devas. Br. IV. 1. 86; Vā. 100. 90.

राज
Rāja  (II)--(see also Rājan) qualifications of: should not retreat from the battle-field; should protect Brahmanas, the poor and the helpless; insist on svadharma of his subjects, aid tapasvins, befriend the truthful and avoid the vakras; 1) M. 215. 56-99; 238. 12. precautions to be observed; befriend enemy's subjects and provide them with jobs; use spies in administration; 2) Ib. 220. 8-47. prescriptions for personal conduct and successful rule of a king; some vratams like the Āgneya, Pārthiva, etc. 3) Ib. 223. 7f. Avoid the two kinds of discontent,--antahkopa and bahihkopa; the former brings more ruin it being towards the mem bers of the royal household; the latter towards Sāmantas. 4) Ib. 226. 3-12. Collect taxes through faithful servants annually. 5) Ib. 215. 57. Earn the title of Rājaṛṣi like Yayāti; 6) Ib. 13. 62; 43. 23; 46. 28. ety. of. 7) Vā 62. 134; 109. 54.

राजऋषि
Rājaṛṣi --a title of Purūravas, Yayāti and Kārtavīrya; 1) M. 13. 62; 43. 23; Vā. 96. 190. attained by Śamika. 2) M. 46. 28. For some more names see Vā. P. 3) Vā. 32, 38, 54; 61. 80, 86-88; 99. 15, 127.

राजक
Rājaka --son of Viśākhayūpa, and father of Nandivardhana, the Magadha king. Bhā. XII. 1. 3-4.

राजकृत्यम्
Rājakṛtyam --to punish evil doers and to protect the law abiding. M. 211. 9.

राजकेशि
Rājakeśi --a sage. M. 196. 26.

राजगृह
Rājagṛha --the capital of Malla whom Kṛṣṇa vanquished; the palace of. Br. III. 73. 100; IV. 14. 11.

राजगृहम्
Rājagṛham --a sacred place in Kīkaṭa. Vā. 108. 73.

राजत
Rājata --a dāna; also Raupyācalam; the best gift is of 10,000 palams of silver; the giver goes to the world of the moon; then of 5,000 and then 2,500 palams; anything above 20 palams. M. 83. 6; 91. 1ff. 

राजतम्
Rājatam --the silver vessel used by Pitṛs in milking the cow-earth; 1) M. 10. 18. out of Śiva's eye; 2) Ib. 15. 31; 17. 20. 23. best for use in śrāddha. 3) Vā. 73. 51; 74. 1.

राजधर्म
Rājadharma --also Kṣatradharma; no sin to kill one in war. M. 103. 22.

राजन्
Rājan --ety. daṇḍadhārin; crimes escaping his notice are dealt with by Yama. In Kali the king is mostly of the fourth caste and takes the profession of robbery rather than protection. Earth loses its fertility. The wealth and wives of others are coveted; Mlecchas are patronised. Duties-salutation to cows and Brahmanas, sandhya worship and gifts to the deserving; not to deprive forcibly a Brahmana of his property; 1) Br. II. 29. 63-64; 31. 41-156; 36. 156; III. 28. 10-74. renowned kings get the title of Rājaṛṣi, generally of the family of Manu, Aila, Ikṣvāku. 2) Ib. II. 35. 90, 96-102; III. 71. 194.

राजनीति
Rājanīti --six-fold; learnt by Rāma and Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 45. 34.

राजपथ
Rājapatha --10 dhanus broad; permits of easy movement for men, horses, chariots and elephants. Vā. 8. 119.

राजपुत्र
Rājaputra  (I)--a name of Budha, the son of Rājasoma and the originator of the science of elephantology. M. 24. 3.

राजपुत्र
Rājaputra  (II)--prince; special teachers are to be appointed to teach him Dharma, Artha and Kāma śāstras, to train him in elephant riding, chariot riding, and in arts and crafts; he must have his bodyguard so that he may not mix with the undesirables and may control his senses; he  must live in a private residence, for an ill-disciplined prince will root out the family. 1) M. 220. 1-6 A possible internal enemy of the king. 2) Ib. 223. 9.

राजपुत्रीयम्
Rājaputrīyam --a work on elephantology by the sage Rājaputra, identified with Budha. M. 24. 3.

राजभट
Rājabhaṭas --police officials; 1) Vā. 101. 154. go to hell. 2) Br. IV. 2. 155.

राजमार्ग
Rājamārgas  (also Rājapathas)--royal roads as frequented by Piśācas; 1) Br. III. 7. 404; 27. 11. in the city of Śrīpuram; 2) M. 130. 3. in the city of Mathurā; 3) Vi. V. 19. 12. lighted by lamps during nights; 4) M. 139. 19. persons committing nuisance in public roads were visited by fines and required to clean them. 5) Ib. 227. 175.

राजमाष
Rājamāṣa --unfit for śrāddha. Vi. III. 16. 7.

राजयक्ष्म
Rājayakṣma --smitten by this, Soma was relieved by his father, Atri. Br. III. 65. 46-8.

राजयक्ष्मा
Rājayakṣmā --to be worshipped in house-building. M. 253. 30, 42; 268. 23.

राजरक्षारहस्य
Rājarakṣārahasyas --devices for the protection of the king's person; different kinds of mixtures of medicines used for 15 days, one month, etc.; remedies to avert houses being consumed by fire; against snakes by burning their coating; examination of cooked food by giving it to birds or throwing it into the fire and then examining the change in colour;  flies would not sit on the poisoned food; its effect on birds and beasts; the same is applicable to drinking water; such protection needed since he is the root of the tree of the people. M. 219. 1-34.

राजराज्यम्
Rājarājyam --the abode of Kubera. M. 83. 45.

राजराज
Rājarāja --the giver of gift; kalpa tree becomes so in the next birth; 1) M. 101. 30, 54, 71; 277. 21. for the gift of gosahasra. 2) Ib. 278. 25.

राजराट्
Rājarāṭ --the special title awarded by Brahmā to Soma. Br. III. 65. 20; Vā. 90. 20.

राजवर्तप
Rājavartapa --a Kaśyapa and a Trayārṣeya. M. 199. 12.

राजवर्धन
Rājavardhana --son of Dama, and father of Suvrddhi. Vi. IV. 1. 36-7.

राजवान्
Rājavān --son of Dyutimat. Vi. I. 10. 5.

राजवृत्ति
Rājavṛtti --followed by robbers as the kings themselves begin to rob in the Kali age. Vā. 58. 42.

राजवेश्म
Rājaveśma --sacred to Lalitāpīṭha. Br. IV. 44. 96.

राजशासनम्
Rājaśāsanam --for wrong entry in, punished with uttama daṇḍa. M. 227. 202. 

राजस
Rājasa --otherwise known as Ketumān, a Lokapāla; 1) Br. II. 21. 157; M. 124. 95. attained heaven by tapas. 2) Ib. 143. 38.

राजसिम्ह
Rājasimha --a king of Vidarbha. His daughter was married to Malayadhvaja Pāṇḍya. Bhā. IV. 28. 28-29.

राजसी
Rājasī --also Prajākarī; this quality possessed by Marīci Kaśyapa. Vā. 66. 87, 104, 105.

राजसीवृत्ति
Rājasīvṛtti --intervening both satva and tama; leads to karma and rebirth and hence duhkha or misery due to ear, eye, tongue, body and smell. Vā. 102. 54, 62.

राजसूय
Rājasūya  (I)--the conqueror of cardinal points was fit to perform this: Yudhiṣṭhīra on this, to Kṛṣṇa: Done by Soma who conquered the three worlds; 1) Bhā. X. 71. 2[1]; 72-3; IX. 14. 4; Vā. 90. 22. Yudhiṣṭhira's desire to be a Pārameṣṭhī. So Ṛtviks were sent for, including Bhīṣma, Vidura. Even Śūdras were invited. After the sacrifice, on the suggestion of Sahadeva, the first honour was given to Kṛṣṇa. Śiśupāla's protest and vilification of Kṛṣṇa who had his head cut off. In the sacrifice each brother was assigned specific functions--Duryodhana in charge of treasury, Bhīma cooking, Nakula the supply of provisions, etc. The avabhṛta bath at Gangā accompanied by divine music. Every visitor duly honoured, returned back. Jealousy of Duryodhana at the success of the sacrifice. 2) Bhā. VII. 1. 13;; X. 70. 41; Chh. 74-75. The consecration ceremony of a king done by Pṛthu, Vāli and others. 3) Br. II. 36. 113; III. 7. 268; 8. 25; 63. 116; 72. 28; Vā. 62. 95; 70. 21. 

राजसूय
Rājasūya  (II)--the head of the Veda. Vā. 71. 77; 88. 118. Ib. 104. 84; 112. 63.

राजसूय
Rājasūya  (III)--the fifth gāndhāra grāmika. Vā. 86. 42.

राजसूयम्
Rājasūyam --the gift of Brahmāṇḍa Purāṇa equal to the performance of 1000 sacrifices. 1) M. 53. 57. The fruits of this yajña are equal to fasting and praying to Viṣṇu on the akṣayatṛtīya day; 2) Ib. 65. 7. a plunge in the Prayāgā is equal to this yajña. 3) Ib. 106. 21. Sacrifice performed by Soma when Viṣṇu was Brahmā, Śiva, the protector, Atri, the hota, Bhṛgu, the adhvaryu, Brahmā, the udgāta, Sanaka and others were the Sadasyas, ten Viśvedevas Camasādhvaryavas, and the three worlds dakṣiṇa; after this sacrifice the nine Devīs, Lakṣmī, Sinivālī, Kīrtī, Vasu, Dhṛtī and others left their husbands and sported with Soma who acted as their consort; 4) Ib. 23. 19-27; 58. 54; 239. 37; Vi. IV. 6. 8. the title of Soma after the Rājasūya. 5) Vā. 90. 26.

राजाज
Rājāja --a son of Śambhu. Br. III. 5. 40.

राजाधिदेव
Rājādhideva --a son of Vidūratha and a hero; had two sons Śoṇāśva and Śvetavāhana equal to gods. M. 44. 77-8.

राजाधिदेवी
Rājādhidevī --a Vīramātā; a sister of Vasudeva; a daughter of Śūra and Bhoja and queen of Jayasena, king of Avantī; 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 31 and 39; Br. III. 71. 151; M. 46. 4; Vi. IV. 14. 31. paternal aunt of Kṛṣṇa and queen of Avantī. Her daughter Mitravindā loved by Kṛṣṇa who took her away by force and married her, as her brothers wanted to bestow  her on Duryodhana; 2) Bhā. X. 58. 31. according to the Bhāgavata had two sons Vinda and Anuvinda; 3) Vā. 96. 149. mother of two sons. 4) Vi. IV. 14. 43.

राजान
Rājāna --the first kings of the earth were Priyavrata and Uttānapāda, sons of Manu; wielders of daṇḍa; ety. of. Vā. 57. 58.

राजिक
Rājika --a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 51; Vi. 61. 44.

राजीवकोकिल
Rājīvakokilas --a Janapada of the Ketumālā continent. Vā. 44. 14.

राजीवल
Rājīvala --a horse of the moon's chariot. Vā. 52. 53.

राजेय
Rājeyas --the collective name for the hundred sons of Raji; the latter won over the Asuras and finally established Indra on the throne and retired for penance; his sons deprived Indra of his power when the latter appealed to Bṛhaspati; he increased Indra's strength by rituals and made the Rājeyas adopt the Jīnadharma and hence got outside the pale of the Veda, when Indra easily overcame them and got back his kingdom; beginning of Jīna dharma and hetuvāda. M. 24. 35-49.

राज्यम्
Rājyam --a kingdom; if a king has no legitimate successor, it changes hands; ruled by ministry in the king's absence; is concerned with two main things (bāhya) or foreign affairs and (abhyantara) or home policy; 1) Br. III. 50. 29-51; Vā. 88. 94; 112. 14. 46. of Pṛthu, described. 2) M. 1. 11; 10. 10-35. 

राज्यवर्धन
Rājyavardhana(ka) --son of Dama, and father of Sudhṛti. Bhā. IX. 2. 29; Br. III. 8. 35.

राज्याधिदेव
Rājyādhideva --son of Bhajamāna. Vā. 96. 135.

राज्ञी
Rājñī --one of the three wives of Vivasvān; she was the daughter of Raivata and had a son Revata. M. 11. 2-3.

राडवीय
Rāḍavīya --a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 51.

राडि
Rāḍi --a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 51.

राणायनीय
Rāṇāyanīya --a composer of Sāma Veda; 1) Br. II. 35. 44. a Kauthuka and a disciple of Lokākṣi. 2) Vā. 61. 37-39.

रात्रि
Rātri  (I)--a R. in Krauñcadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 75; M. 122. 88; Vā. 49. 69; Vi. II. 4. 55.

रात्रि
Rātri  (II)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 75.

रात्रि
Rātri  (III)--Pārameśvara; pralaya or destruction at the end of which recurs the creation of the universe. Vā. 5. 2 and 6.

रात्रि
Rātri  (IV)--when the Asuras were born to Prajāpati night came into being; ety.; three yāmas of the night are full of darkness--Triyāmikā; then Prajāpati took another guise and created the devas; āsuri of tamas quality; 1) Vā. 9. 6-15; Br. II. 13. 14. no  night for the region to the north of Meru and south of Lokāloka as the sun is far removed and the earth is surrounded by the lekha; 2) Vā. 50. 108.  for the Pitṛs is Suklapakṣa; 3) Ib. 51. 11; 57. 9. enters water in the morning. 4) Ib. 53. 14.

रात्रिसूक्तम्
Rātrisūktam --a mantra of the Ṛg Vedins to be recited in tank ritual. M. 58. 34; 93. 131.

राथंतर
Rāthaṃtara --the 4th kalpa. M. 290. 3.

राधा
Rādhā  (I)--came with Kṛṣṇa to mediate between Paraśurāma and Vināyaka; spoke on the non-differentiation of Śiva and Viṣṇu; Gaṇeśa was a Vaiṣṇava and Paraśurāma Śaiva. Br. III. 42. 21, 47-8; 43. 21 and 29; 44. 29; Vā. 104. 52.

राधा
Rādhā  (II)--the goddess enshrined at Vṛndāvana. M. 13. 38.

राधाकान्त
Rādhākānta --is Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 56.

राधिक
Rādhika --son of Jayasena, and father of Ayuta. Bhā. IX. 22. 10.

राम
Rāma  (I)--Balabhadra of the Yādava race and lord of Dvārakā. (Balarāma): brother of Kṛṣṇa and Subhadrā; See Baladeva; eldest son of Vasudeva by Rohinī; father of two sons; welcomed Kṛṣṇa to Dvārakā; asked by Kṛṣṇa to take one of the two heavenly chariots and get ready to fight Jarāsandha. Rāma blew his conch and began fighting  under his palmyra ensign; defeated the enemies on all sides. Fastened Jarāsandha with ropes but Kṛṣṇa set him free; when Jarāsandha encamped on the Yamunā, was consulted by Kṛṣṇa; fought successfully Jarāsandha a third time and defeated Bāṇa's army; when about to give a death-blow to Jarāsandha, a voice from the welkin said “do not kill Jarāsandha; go back.” Thus Jarāsandha was allowed to go back to his city. 1) Bhā. I. 11. 16; X. 50. 12-32; [50 (v)  8]; [51 (v)  38-58]; [52 (v) 1-6]; Br. III. 61. 25; 71. 164-8; M. 46. 11; Vā. 86. 30; 96. 162; Vi. V. 6. 9; 13. 16. Honoured by the Yādhava sabha, went with Kṛṣṇa to the Gomanta hill; on the way met and bowed to Paraśurāma; helped Kṛṣṇa in killing Śṛgāla Vaśudeva and was welcomed by the citizens of Karavīrapura. Stayed in this city for four months and returned to Mathurā with his brother. Attacked by Jarāsandha's army, fled with Kṛṣṇa to Gomanta, pursued by Jarāsandha; reached Dvārakā safe. 2) Bhā. X. [52 (v)  13-41]; [53(v) 1-22]; 52. 5-6 [5-7]; 7. 14 [1 and 2]. Married Revatī before the advent of Kali and hence very tall in appearance; with his plough he brought down her height to his level. 3) Ib. X. 52. 15 [11-12]. Heard of Kṛṣṇa going alone to Kuṇḍina and of the preparations of Caidya to fight him; went with his army to Kuṇḍina and was welcomed by its king: Attacked Caidya's party pursuing Kṛṣṇa and Rukmiṇī on that account. 4) Ib. X. 53. 20-21 and 32; Ch. 54 (whole). Went to Hāstinapura with Kṛṣṇa after the reported burning of the Pāṇḍavas and Kuntī: Pursued Śatadhanvan with Kṛṣṇa and finding he had not the Syamanta in his person, sent Kṛṣṇa back to Dvārakā and himself to Mithilā as Janaka's guest; taught the use of the gadā (mace) to Duryodhana. Did not agree with Kṛṣṇa in returning the jewel to Akrūra. Left for Videha after Satadhanvan's death. 5) Ib. X. 57 (whole) ; 58. 9 [4 and 5]; 67 (v) 42. Attended Aniruddha's marriage at Bhojakaṭa where induced by Kalinga and other friends, Rukmin invited Rāma for a game of dice: in it, Rāma sometimes lost and sometimes gained. At his loss Kalinga laughed showing his teeth. When Rukmin played false it was referred to  a mediator who was unfortunately Kalinga and who therefore maintained that Rukmi was in the right. A voice from the air said: “Rukmi tells an untruth”. Without heeding to this Rukmi insulted Rāma as a forester and herdsman and new to the art of dice. Rāma got enraged, took the mace and vanquished Rukmi: next he pulled out the teeth of Kalinga making fun of him all the time: others fled in fear; returned to Dvārakā. 6) Ib. X. 61. 26-40. His picture was among those drawn by Citrālekhā: Invaded Bāṇa's city, fought with Kumbhāṇḍa and Kūpakarṇa. Once drove to Vraja and spent two months there. During nights he sported and sang with Gopis on the Yamunā drinking Vāruṇī and playing in the waters: changed the course of the river by his plough: 7) Ib. X. 62. 20; 63. 3-8. Yamunā (s.v.) presented him with clothes, and ornaments with which he shone brighter than ever. 8) Ib. X. Ch. 65 (whole). Desire for more territory. 9) Ib. XII. 3. 9. Wanted to give Subhadrā in marriage to Duryodhana but Kṛṣṇa was for her marriage with Arjuna. The latter went to Dvārakā as an ascetic when Rāma one day invited him for bhikṣa. It was an opportunity for Arjuna and Subhadrā to see each other. Arjuna carried her away on a festive occasion with Kṛṣṇa's consent. Rāma's wrath was pacified by Kṛṣṇa. Then he approved of the marriage and sent him presents. 10) Ib. X. 86. 1-12, 18. Unable to recover the dead son of the Dvārakā Brāhmaṇa. 11) Ib. X. 89, 31 and 41. Founded the city of Govardhana on the upper regions of the Godāvarī in the northern part of the Sahya mountain. 12) Br. II. 16. 44. The God of Love cursed to be born as the brother of Kṛṣṇa at Dvārakā. 13) M. 4. 17-21. 

राम
Rāma  (II)--a son of Daśaratha known for his righteousness and truth: Parikṣit compared to him: An avatār of Hari born in the Ikṣvāku line; killed Rāvaṇa; His fame equalled that of Pṛthu. 1) Bhā. I. 12. 19; II. 7. 23-25; IV. 22. 63; IX. 10. 3; M. 12. 50-51. King of the Kośala country and brother of Lakṣmaṇa, Bharata, and Śatrughna: Disfigured Sūrpaṇakā; killed Mārīca (Subāhu?) and other Rākṣasas in the yajña of Viśvāmitra, bent and broke the bow of Śiva and married Sītā, put down the pride of Paraśurāma, spent a forest life with his wife in obedience to his father's command, killed Khara, Triśiras and 14,000 Rākṣasas; performed the funeral rites to Jaṭāyu, and Kabandha, killed Vāli for the sake of Sugrīva, put up a bridge across the sea, welcomed by the Lord of the seas; killed Rāvaṇa and Kumbhakarṇa in their capital, ordered Vibhīṣaṇa to perform funeral rites to his dead kith and kin; recovered Sītā; enthroned Vibhīṣaṇa; left in an aerial chariot to Ayodhyā, embraced Bharata, paid respects to Brahmanas, Gurus, elders and was crowned by Vasiṣṭha just like Indra. In his period which was the Tretāyuga, it looked like Kṛtayuga; sons, Kuśa and Lava; ruled for 1010 years; 2) Bhā. V. 19. 1; VII. 1. 44; 10. 36; IX. 10. 3-52; X. 40. 20; XI. 4. 21; Br. III. 7. 203; 8. 54; 37. 30; 63. 185-193; 64. 16; 73. 91; Vā. 88. 192-4; Vi. IV. 4. 87-102, 104. led an exemplary household life, by his loyalty to his wedded wife; performed sacrifices by giving all his kingdom as dakṣiṇa, retaining only the ornaments and dress, and for Sītā, her saumāngalya. The Brahmanas returned the kingdom as they had no use for it and praised him. 3) Bhā. IX. 10. 53-6; 11. 1-7; Vā. 70. 48; 88, 184, 191-7. One night he went about to know what people talked of his rule. He heard a person saying that Rāma was mad after Sītā, taking her back though she was at another's house for long. Next day he abandoned her and left her at Vālmīki's abode. Here were born his two sons--Kuśa and Lava. When Sītā entered the bowels of the earth, Rāma led a life of celibacy for 13,000 years giving joy and happiness to the people of Kośala. Sent his brothers on digvijaya and himself resided at the capital. 4) Bhā. IX. 11. 8-35. Hearing of the Rāmacarita of Vālmīki, rids one of karmabandhas; 5) Ib. IX. 11. 23; M. 12. 50-51. resided on the banks of the Kadalī river; 6) Ib. 22. 53. the 24th in the Tretāyuga; 7th incarnation  with Vasiṣṭha as Purohita; 7) Ib. 47. 245; 114. 38; Vā. 98. 92; 108. 16, 24-5. image of, generally ten talas in measurement; 8) M. 259. 1. an earthly paradise created by Rāma in the upper regions of Godāvarī in Govardhana; 9) Vā. 45. 113. performed śrāddha at Rudrapada and Daśaratha took the piṇḍa and went to Rudraloka blessing his son to go to Viṣṇuloka; 10) Ib. 111, 64. an incarnation of Nārāyaṇa. 11) Vi. IV. 13. 53.

राम
Rāma  (III) (Paraśurāma)--a son of Jamadagni and Reṇukā; an amśa of Hari. Heard from his father that Arjuna-Haihaya had taken Kāmadhenu against his wish, and getting angry went to Haihaya's capital, cut off the king's head and took back the cow. In order to get rid of the sin of killing a king, he went on tīrthayātra for a year. 1) Bhā. IX. 15. 13 to the end. Br. III. 1. 98; 66. 63; 69. 48; M. 43. 40; 285. 7. In obedience to his father's command he killed his mother and brothers. This pleased the father and by his boon to his son, they all came back to life. During his absence, the sons of Haihaya killed his father, and on his return, found his mother crying over the death of Jamadagni. He took his axe, ran to Māhiṣmatī, rooted out all the Kṣatriyas by defeating them twenty-one times; with their blood he made nine pools at Syamantapañcaka, where he worshipped his father's dead body and distributed the various regions to the priests; ended it with avabhṛta in the Sarasvatī. 2) Bhā. IX. 16. 1-23; M. 273. 66. He would be a great sage in the forthcoming manvantara. A sage of the 8th manvantara. Even today resides in Mahendra contemplating on Hari; 3) Bhā. VIII. 13. 15; IX. 16. 25-7. was invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira and came to see Kṛṣṇa at Syamantapañcaka. 4) Ib. X. 74. 9; 84. 4. In his early years, with the leave of his parents, he visited his grand parents Ṛcīka and Satyavatī; and after some stay there, called on his great grandfather Bhṛgu, who advised  him to do tapas in the Himālayas in honour of Śiva. Engaged in tapas by standing in water in the winter and on the fire in summer, by means of Padmāsana; Śiva in hunter's guise visited him and asked him to quit his place. Suspecting him to be god, Rāma, appealed to him when Śiva showed his true form. Instructed by Śiva, he went round the earth on a pilgrimage tour. Helped the Devas in routing the Asuras; continued his tapas by worshipping Śiva as mṛgavyādha. Pleased, the Lord instructed him in the astragrāma in its four aspects; went to Brahmā for advice before he started on his crusade against the Kṣatriyas. Advised to meet Śiva and to get initiated into Kṛṣṇamantra kavacam; Śiva instructed him with Trailokya vijayam mantram. On his way back he stayed at Puṣkara and heard a male deer narrating the story of Paraśurāma and Akṛtavraṇa to the female deer, adding that his was not the uttama bhakti but the madhyama. He took the hint from that conversation that he would achieve his end by Agastya's grace. Rāma repaired to the hermitage of Agastya, followed by the deer. 5) Br. III. Chh. 21-35. Mūlaka afraid of; 6) Ib. III. 63. 179; 74. 262. a Brāhmaṇa; 7) Vā. 94. 46; 99. 449. a slayer of the Kṣatriyas; versed in Dhanurveda; 8) Ib. 91. 91. equal in prowess to Indra resplendent and a mixture of Brahma and Kṣatra; 9) Ib. 65. 94. consort Dharanī. 10) Vi. I. 9. 143.

राम
Rāma  (IV)--a son of Śivadatta. Br. III. 35. 12.

राम
Rāma  (V)--a sage of the Sāvarṇi epoch. (eighth epoch Vi. P.). M. 9. 32; Vi. III. 2. 17. 

राम
Rāma  (VI)--son of Senājit. Vā. 99. 173.

रामचन्द्र
Rāmacandra --son of Puramjaya; and father of Dharmavarmā. Vi. IV. 24. 56.

रामण
Rāmaṇa --a son of Sāraṇa. Vā. 96. 165.

रामकृष्णौ
Rāmakṛṣṇau --the nineteenth avatār of Hari born among the Vṛṣṇis. Bhā. I. 3. 23.

रामठ
Rāmaṭhas --a northern tribe. M. 114. 42.

रामतीर्थ
Rāmatīrtha --a R.; the mahānadī touching the hill of Prabhāsa where Rāma bathed with his wife; all sins committed in a hundred generations vanish as a result of a bath in this tīrtha; 1) Vā. 108. 16-18. the mantra for bathing in; 2) Ib. 108. 20. sacred to Ramanā and the Pitṛs 3) M. 13. 40; 22. 70. in Ayodhyā. 4) Ib. 191. 93.

रामेश्वर
Rāmeśvara --is Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 33. 12.

रामेश्वरम्
Rāmeśvaram --a tīrtha sacred to Pitṛs; one visiting it after bath at Gayā has no rebirth. Vā. 108. 27.

रामोपाख्यानम्
Rāmopākhyānam --narrated by Vālmīki; originally narrated by Brahmā in a hundred crore of verses to Nārada who gave it to Vālmīki. M. 53. 71-2. 

रावण
Rāvaṇa --a son of Viśravas and Keśinī; 1) Bhā. VII. 1. 43; IV. 1. 37; Br. III. 8. 47; Vā. 70. 41-8. pleased Śiva by his praises; 2) Bhā. X. 88. 16. afraid of Māndhāta; 3) Ib. IX. 6. 33. heard of Śītā's beauty and set up Mārīca to display himself as a golden deer and entice Rāma away; 4) Ib. IX. 10. 10 resented Arjuna-Haihaya's action in ruining his camp by blocking a river and was overpowered by him in the presence of women and imprisoned in his capital Māhiṣmatī; 5) Ib. IX. 15. 21-2; Br. III. 32. 50; 69. 35-7. pursued by the king of kites, compared to Indra being pursued by Vīra; 6) Bhā. IV. 19. 16-17. killed by Rāma; 7) Ib. VII. 1. 44; 10. 36; X. 40. 20; Br. III. 8. 54; M. 12. 50; 47. 245; Vā. 88. 197; 94. 35; 98. 92. lost his kingdom through pride of power; desire for more territory. 8) Bhā. X. 73. 20; XII. 3. 11. Vanquished by Vāli at Puṣkara, agreed to be his ally. 9) Br. III. 7. 248-67. A description of: 10) Ib. III. 8. 48-50. Killed Anaraṇya; 11) Ib. III. 63. 74; Vā. 88. 75; Vi. IV. 3. 17; 15. 1. also Daśagrīva; defeated by Kārtavīrya and released at the request of Pulastya. 12) M. 43. 37-9.

रावणेश्वरम्
Rāvaṇeśvaram --a tīrtha on the Narmadā. M. 191. 26.

राशि
Rāśi --three-fold, as Brahmā, Rudra and Viṣṇu; (fourfold, according to another reading; see Wilson's translation). Vi. VI. 8. 7.

राष्ट्र
Rāṣṭra --son of Kāśi (Kāśeya Vi. P.) and father of Dīrghatamas (tapas Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 17. 4; Vi. IV. 8. 7.

राष्ट्रपाल
Rāṣṭrapāla --one of the nine sons of Ugrasena. Bhā. IX. 24. 24; Br. III. 71. 133; M. 44. 75; Vā. 96. 132; Vi. IV. 14. 20. 

राष्ट्रपालिका
Rāṣṭrapālikā --a daughter of Ugrasena, and wife of Sṛñjaya. Bhā. IX. 24. 25 and 42; Br. III. 71. 134; M. 44. 76; Vā. 96. 133; Vi. IV. 14. 21.

राष्ट्रपिण्डी
Rāṣṭrapiṇḍī --an Ārṣeyapravara (Aṅgiras). M. 196. 21.

राष्ट्रभृत्
Rāṣṭrabhṛt --a son of Bharata. Bhā. V. 7. 3.

राष्ट्रवर्धन
Rāṣṭravardhana --son of Dama. Br. III. 61. 8.

रासक्रीडा
Rāsakrīḍā  (also Rāsagoṣṭhi)--in this was seen the same Kṛṣṇa between every two gopīs, his hands over the shoulder of each gopī engaged in dancing and singing, until all of them were tired. Bhā. X. Ch. 29 (whole); 33. 2-22; 39. 29; 47. 43 and 60, 62.

रासभ
Rāsabhas --created by Brahmā from his feet. Vi. I. 5. 49.

रासारम्भप्रिय
Rāsārambhapriya --is Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 33. 21.

राह
Rāha --a clan belonging to Rohita Prajāpati. Vā. 100. 61.

राहु
Rāhu  (I)--(also Svarbhānu); an Asura and the eldest of the 14 sons of Vipracitti and Simhikā; a servant of Hiraṇyakaśipu; attained the status of a planet and immortality by drinking amṛta in the disguise of a deva, and when detected and reported by the sun and the moon, the Lord threw his cakra which cut off his head; hence he became the enemy of the sun and  the moon. 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 37; 18. 13-14; VIII. 9. 24-26; Br. III. 5. 13; 6. 20; M. 251. 12; Vā. 52. 81; 67. 60; 68. 20; 111. 5; Vi. I. 19. 52; II. 12. 22. Asked by Bali to refrain from battle; position on the Śiśumāra about the neck; with Soma in the devāsura war; 2) Bhā. V. 23. 7; VIII. 10. 31; 21. 19. his daughter, was the wife of Āyu. 3) Vi. IV. 8. 1. one of the nine planets; black in colour; it is said that the sun and the moon interrupt him and therefore both are attacked on new moon or full moon days; it is Sudarśana that makes Rāhu withdraw himself; such occurrences are said to be eclipses; below the region of Rāhu is the abode of the Siddhas, Cāraṇas and Vidyādharas; 4) Bhā. V. 24. 1-4; Br. II. 23. 89; 24. 136; III. 14. 3; M. 93. 10. Rāhu leaving the moon is compared to getting rid of all sins by a bath in Prayāgā; 5) Ib. 106. 26. attains Soma in Parvas and then Ādityas; 6) Ib. 107. 12; 127. 10. swallowing of the moon is a bad omen; 7) Ib. 163. 42. with sun or moon fit for gifts in Amarakaṇṭaka; 8) Ib. 188. 87. rise of, must lead to the performance of śrāddha. 9) Vā. 78. 3.

राहु
Rāhu  (II)--a Parā god. Br. IV. 1. 57.

राहुकर्णि
Rāhukarṇi --an Ārṣeya pravara (Aṅgiras). M. 196. 7.

राहुल
Rāhula --son of Śuddhodana, and father of Prasenajit. Vā. 99. 289; Vi. IV. 22. 8.

रिक्तवर्ण
Riktavarṇa --son of Svātivarṇa (Āndhra) ruled for 25 years. M. 273. 9.

रिक्ष
Rikṣa --son of Purujānu. Vā. 99. 195. 

रिटि
Riṭi --a head of a Śiva gaṇa. Br. III. 41. 28.

रित
Rita --one of the 20 Sutapa gaṇas. Vā. 100. 14.

रितु
Ritu --one of the 20 Amitābha gaṇas. Vā. 100. 16.

रिपु
Ripu  (I)--a son of Yadu. Bhā. IX. 23. 20.

रिपु
Ripu  (II)--son of Varāngī and Divamjaya; married Bṛhatī; father of Cākṣuṣa. Br. II. 36. 101; Vā. 62. 87.

रिपु
Ripu  (III)--a son of Babhru; 1) Br. III. 74. 7. killed by Yauvanāśva in a battle which lasted for 14 months. 2) Vā. 99. 7-8.

रिपु
Ripu  (IV)--(also Vairī). Even though insignificant, not to be neglected. It was Bhūta that slew Hiraṇyakaśipu, and a woman Caṇḍikā that killed Niśumbha, Śumbha and Mahiṣa. Br. IV. 21. 43 and 55.

रिपु
Ripu  (V)--a son of Śiṣṭi(ī) and Succhāyā, wife Bṛhatī; his son Cākṣuṣa. M. 4. 39; Vi. I. 13. 2.

रिपुञ्जय
Ripuñjaya  (I)--the son of Suvīra (Sudhīra Vi. P.) and father of Bahuratha. Bhā. IX. 21. 29-30; Vi. IV. 19. 55. 

रिपुञ्जय
Ripuñjaya  (II)--a son of Viśvajit--last link of the line; 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 49. with him ends the Bṛhadratha line after ruling for 1000 years; 2) Vi. IV. 23. 12. his minister Munika murdered him and enthroned his own son Pradyota. 3) Ib. IV. 24. 1-2. Ruled for thirty-five years. 4) Br. III. 74. 114.

रिपुञ्जय
Ripuñjaya  (III)--a son of Acala, ruled for 50 years. M. 271. 29.

रिपुञ्जय
Ripuñjaya  (IV)--a son of Varāṅgī and Divamjaya. Vā. 62. 87.

रिपुञ्जय
Ripuñjaya  (V)--a son of Medhāvi and father of Urva. Vi. IV. 21. 13.

रिपुञ्जय
Ripuñjaya  (VI)--a son of Śiṣṭi and Succhāyā. Vi. I. 13. 2.

रिवेयु
Riveyu --a son of Anādṛṣṭa; a Rājaṛṣi; Jvalanā, daughter of Dakṣa was his consort. Vā. 99. 127-8.

रिष्टा
Riṣṭā --an apsaras; mother of the Vegavatī group. Br. III. 7. 12 and 21.

रिष्यन्त
Riṣyanta --son of Mānasa. Vā. 70. 30. 

रीतिक
Rītika --(bell metal) a gift of, pleases Vāyu. M. 266. 64.

रुक्म
Rukma --a son of Rucaka. Bhā. IX. 23. 35.

रुक्मकवच
Rukmakavaca  (I)--a son of Kambalabarhis; father of Rukmeṣu and four other sons. Learned and wealthy; conquered the whole earth by killing of Kavacinas (soldiers in armour) with sharp arms and performed aśvamedha; Rukmeṣu became king and another Pṛthurukma helped him; two other sons, Parigha and Hari were appointed over Videha; banished by them the other son Jyāmagha performed penance. 2) M. 44. 25-30; Va. 95. 25-26. ^1 Br. III. 70. 26-9.

रुक्मकवच
Rukmakavaca  (II)--the father of Paravṛt. Vi. IV. 12. 10.

रुक्मकुण्डम्
Rukmakuṇḍam --in Gayā. Vā. 112. 32.

रुक्मकेश
Rukmakeśa --a son of Bhīṣmaka. Bhā. X. 52. 22.

रुक्मगर्भ
Rukmagarbha --the lord of stars, trees, plants, etc. M. 8. 3.

रुक्मपारिजातवन
Rukmapārijātavana --in Gayā where Śankara sported with Pārvatī and to which Marīci went to gather fruits and flowers; interrupted in his enjoyment Śiva cursed him, but the latter praised him in prayer; Śiva promised him release from the curse if he would visit Gayā; the blackman became changed into white colour. Vā. 112. 35-39. 

रुक्मबाहु
Rukmabāhu --a son of Bhīṣmaka. Bhā. X. 52. 22.

रुक्ममालिन्
Rukmamālin --a son of Bhīṣmaka. Bhā. X. 52. 22.

रुक्मरथ
Rukmaratha  (I)--a son of Bhīṣmaka. Bhā. X. 52. 32.

रुक्मरथ
Rukmaratha  (II)--a son of Mahāpaurava (nandana). M. 49. 73; Vā. 99. 187.

रुक्मराट्
Rukmarāṭ(n) --see Praviṣṭa Agni; son of Arkāgni. Br. II. 12. 43; Vā. 29. 40.

रुक्मवती
Rukmavatī --a daughter of Rukmi, and wife of Pradyumna; mother of Aniruddha. Bhā. X. 61. 18 and 23 [9]; Vi. IV. 15. 38-9.

रुक्मि
Rukmi --first son of the Vidarbha king, Bhīṣmaka; brother of Rukmiṇī, and enemy of Kṛṣṇa; capital Bhojakaṭa; wanted to give his sister Rukmiṇī to Caidya, though his brothers were for Kṛṣṇa. 1) Bhā. X. 52. 22; 60. 18; Vi. V. 28. 9; Br. IV. 29. 122. Followed Kṛṣṇa running with his sister and near the Narmadā fought with him. On an appeal from Rukmiṇī to spare his life, Rukmi was put to shame by the removal of his locks of hair and moustache and tied to his chariot; could not reconcile himself with Kṛṣṇa's action and resolved to kill Kṛṣṇa and then enter Kuṇḍina. Released by Balarāma, he built and lived in Bhojakaṭa without going back to Kuṇḍina. 2) Bhā. X. 52. 25; 53. 2; 54. 18-36, 52; Vi. V. 26 (whole). Was met by Śālva at Kuṇḍina; was stationed by Jarāsandha at the western gate of Mathurā and on the eastern side during the siege of Gomanta. 3) Bhā. X. 76. 2 [9]; 78 [5]; 50. 11 [5]; 52. 11 [6]. Gave his daughter to Pradyumna in marriage to please his sister, but continued to hate Kṛṣṇa; prayed to Śiva who gave him a bow saying that it would not harm Hari; went back to  Bhojakaṭa, afraid of meeting Kṛṣṇa. 4) Ib. X. 61. 19-23 [1-7]; Vi. V. 28. 6. Gave his granddaughter to Aniruddha in marriage. When he invited Rāma for a game of dice on the occasion, he played falsely and insulted Balarāma (s.v.) as a cowherd and forester at which he was struck dead. Kṛṣṇa passed no comments on his death out of consideration for his brother and Rukmiṇī. 5) Bhā. X. 61. 25-39; II. 7. 34; Vi. V. 28. 11-26.

रुक्मिणी
Rukmiṇī  (I)--a daughter of Bhīṣmaka and known as Vaidarbhī. Married to Kṛṣṇa according to Gāndharva? (Rākṣasa) form; 1) Bhā. III. 3. 3; X. 52. 16-18; Br. III. 71. 242-6; Vi. I. 9. 144; V. 26 (whole). when she came to know of the proposal of her eldest brother Rukmi (s.v.) to give her in marriage to Caidya, she sent a letter through a Brāhmaṇa to Kṛṣṇa showing her unflinching devotion to him and requesting that she might be carried off when she would be on her way to the Devī temple on the day prior to the wedding as was the custom. That day she had her bath and decked herself with two clothes and many jewels. Her anxiety at not having heard from Kṛṣṇa, when the Brāhmaṇa came to tell her that Kṛṣṇa would do the needful. Citizens were also for her marriage with Kṛṣṇa. Well guarded and accompanied by singing and dancing, Rukmiṇī entered the temple and prayed for Kṛṣṇa's hand. After worshipping Indrāṇī nearby she returned when Kṛṣṇa carried her away in his chariot. Seeing the party of Caidya pursuing him, Rukmiṇī became nervous when Kṛṣṇa consoled her. When Caidya was about to be killed by Kṛṣṇa she appealed to the Lord to spare him; Rāma consoled her. The regular marriage and festivities followed. 2) Bhā. X. Chh. 52-54. Mother of 11 sons and a daughter; gave birth to Pradyumna who was stolen by Śambara and thrown into the sea. Recovered and taken back by Māyāvatī alias Ratī; Rukmiṇī remembered her lost son and wondered at his exact resemblance. At that time came Kṛṣṇa and Nārada who explained the history of Pradyumna to  her great joy; 3) Ib. III. 1. 28; X. 55 (whole) ; M. 47. 13, 15-16; Vā. 96. 233; Vi. V. 27. 3, 27; 28. 1-2; 30. 35; 32. 1. was the chief queen of Kṛṣṇa and more attached; would not like to be away from Kṛṣṇa; when she was once fanning him gently Kṛṣṇa cut a joke that his status was poor and that she could even then get married to a rich prince and enjoy luxuries. Rukmiṇī wept in deep distress and spoke words reiterating her full devotion to him. Kṛṣṇa consoled her assuring her of his loyalty. 4) Bhā. X. 60 (whole) ; 70. 3; 90. 30. Grave concern at Kṛṣṇa not returning from the cave of Jāmbavan for a long time. Her daughter Cārumatī was married to the son of Kṛtavarman. 5) Ib. X. 56. 34; 61. 24. Attended the marriage of Aniruddha and Rocanā at Bhojakaṭa; out of regard for her and Balarāma, Kṛṣṇa said nothing on Rukmi's death. 6) Ib. X. 61. 26-39. Explained to Draupadī how she became married to Kṛṣṇa; welcomed to Hāstinapura by Kuntī and Draupadī; served Kucela, a friend and classmate of Kṛṣṇa. 7) Ib. X. 71. 42; 76. 2; 80. 23; 83. 8. Entered fire on Kṛṣṇa's decease; 8) Ib. XI. 31. 20. Vi. V. 38. 1-2. is Lakṣmī. 9) Ib. IV. 15. 35.

