रुद्र
Rudra  (I)--born of anger of Brahmā; name explained; ‘the weapon’: places assigned to him; his women; asked to procreate and be a Prajāpati; created beings which would burn the universe; persuaded by Brahmā to stop this, and proceed to tapas; expression of the tamas. 1) Bhā. III. 12, 7-20; XI. 4. 5, 30. 38. Claimed the remaining wealth of the Angirasa sacrificers as his own, which Nābhāga thought was his. When Nābhāga gave it to Rudra, the worshipful god presented him that wealth and disappeared; presented Pṛthu with a sword daśacandra. 2) Ib. IX. 4. 6-11; IV. 15. 17. Taught Kriyā yoga to Umā; Brahmā fled in fear from; 3) Ib. XI. 27, 3; I. 7. 18. came with the gods to Dvārakā to ask Kṛṣṇa to go back to Vaikuṇṭha, and glorified Hari. 4) Ib. IV. ch. 24 (whole) ; XI. 6. 1; 7. 1. VI. 17. 26-39. No offerings by Dakṣa in his sacrifice, and Satī's voluntary death. Rudra created Vīrabhadra to cause Dakṣa's death. Brahmā pacified Rudra and revived Dakṣa and others. 5) Ib. IV. chh. 4-7. Rudra to bear the Gangā; 6) Ib. IX. 9. 7-9; X. 7. 29; 39. 53. addressed Kṛṣṇa as Hari; 7) Ib. X. 63. 34-45. worship of, leads to wealth and pleasure. Conferred a boon on Vṛkāsura and came to grief. 8) Ib. X. ch. 88 (whole).  The presiding deity of the planet Śanaiścara. KāloRudra is Śiva; at the end of a Kalpa he assumes the form of a Samvarttaka sun and burns down all the worlds. His own messengers of death; worshipped by Kāma with Śatarudrīya. 9) Br. II. 24. 49; III. 3. 102 and 109; 23. 64; 65. 32; IV. 6. 70; 7. 38; 10. 87; 11. 33; 15. 24; 30. 8; 36. 16; 40. 13 and 27. Enshrined in Gokarṇa. 10) Ib. III. 13. 20. Destroyed the god of Love and married Umā on the advice of the seven sages; marriage rites described. 11) M. 4. 12, 22; 11. 29; 13. 9. and 14; 138. 26; 154. 194-245, 439-83. Umā's transfer as Gaurī. 12) Ib. ch. 155. Āḍi, son of Andhaka, who attacked him was killed. 13) Ib. ch. 156. Agni's entrance into the harem when Śiva made him drink his Vīra. This was God Subrahmaṇya nursed by Kṛttikas; 14) Ib. ch. 158. blessed Bāṇāsura. 15) Ib. ch. 188; 225. 13; 253. 42. Icon of; in the form of a 16 year old boy; worshipped before buildings; different postures detailed. 16) Ib. 259. 3-26; 265. 41; 266. 43; 268. 22.

रुद्र
Rudra  (II)--born of Ananta from between the agitated brows: Exhibited in eleven forms with Śūla and three eyes. His name is Sankarṣaṇa. Bhā. V. 25. 3; XII. 5. 1-3.

रुद्र
Rudra  (III)--a Mt. west of the Śitoda. Vā. 36. 27.

रुद्र
Rudras  (I)--(hundred?) Eleven in number, heads of Gaṇas: born of Bhūta and Bhūtā: gods of the Vaivasvata epoch: 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 17; VIII. 13. 4; M. 5. 30-2; Vi. III. 1. 31. Fought with Krodhavaśas in a Devāsura battle; 2) Bhā. VIII. 10. 34. came with the other gods to Dvārakā to invite Kṛṣṇa back to Vaikuṇṭha; 3) Ib. XI. 6. 2. worshipped for prowess. 4) Ib. II. 3. 3. Wait upon Indra. Nīlalohita, a chief Rudra. 5) Ib. VI. 7. 2; 10. 17; XI. 16. 13. According to the Br. P. sons of Surabhī and Kaśyapa. These are Angāraka, Sarpa, Niṛṛti, Sadasaspati, Ajaikapāt, Ahirbudhnya, Ūrdhvaketu, Jvara,  Bhuvana, Īśvara, Mṛtyu, and Kapāli. Their sisters were Rohiṇī and Gāndharvī: Their overlord was Vṛṣadhvaja. Live in Śivapuram: 6) Br. III. 1. 61; 3. 72; 8. 6; 32. 22; IV. 2. 27 and 257; 20 47; 30. 8. Vanquished by Rāvaṇa; 7) Ib. III. 7. 254; Vā. 66. 68-70. part of Viṣṇu; 8) Vi. V. 1. 17 and 58. Rudras as different from Mahārudra, and as his attendants. For different names of Rudras see the text; 9) Br. IV. 33. 84-96; 34. 4-52. one of the seven Devagaṇas of the Vaivasvata epoch: Pitāmahas considered as; 10) M. 6. 44; 9. 29; 19. 3. their part in Devāsura wars. 11) Ib. 153. 16-21; 154. 24; 171. 38-40; 247. 10; 248. 22; 285. 8.

रुद्र
Rudras  (II)--a tribe. Vā. 98. 108.

