रेवती
Revatī  (VIII)--a constellation 1) Vā. 49. 81; 53. 109; 66. 52; 82. 14. that stops always in Raivataka (s.v.); sacred to Śanaiścara. 2) Br. II. 19. 87; 24. 134.

रेवन्त
Revanta --born of Samjña as a mare of the Sun god. Vi. III. 2. 7.

रेवा
Revā --a R. near the Māhiṣmatī in the Bhārata varṣa. Bhā. X. 79. 21; V. 19. 18.

रैभ्य
Raibhya  (I)--a son of Sumati, and father of Duṣyanta. Bhā. IX. 20. 7.

रैभ्य
Raibhya  (II)--a son of Vatsāra; his children, Raibhyas. Vā. 70. 25-6.

रैभ्य
Raibhya  (III)--a son of Rebhya and a Brahmavādin. Br. II. 32. 112; III. 8. 30; Vā. 59. 103.

रैभ्य
Raibhyas --one of the three belonging to Kaśyapa group. Br. III. 8. 33.

रैवत
Raivata  (I)--a Rudra and a son of Bhūta and Sarūpā. Bhā. VI. 6. 17; M. 5. 29; VI. I. 15. 122. 

रैवत
Raivata  (II)--a son of Reva (known also as Kakudmin); king of Ānarttas; had a daughter Revatī (s.v.) whom he took to Brahmā to consult him as to a suitable bridegroom. The music of Hāha and Hūhu was going on, and when it was finished, there was a different kalpa in the earth; was advised to give her to Balarāma, and so he did. Bhā. X. 52. 15 [1-11]; Br. III. 61. 20; M. 12. 23; Vā. 86. 25.

रैवत
Raivata  (III)--the fifth Manu; during his epoch were Devabāhu and six other sages, Gods named Ābhūtarajasas. 1) M. 9. 19-22; Vā. 62. 3. Vibhu was Indra; Amitābha and other three gaṇas of gods each 14 in number; Hiraṇyaroma and other six formed the saptaṛṣis; Balabandhu and others were his sons; of the Priyavrata line. 2) Vi. III. 1. 6, 20-4.

रैवत
Raivata  (IV)--a class of reptiles, as arrows of Tripurāri. M. 133. 25.

रैवत
Raivata  (V)--a king and father-in-law of Baladeva. Vi. V. 25. 19.

रैवत
Raivata  (VI)--a Prasūta god. Vā. 62. 60.

रैवतक
Raivataka  (I)--Mt. in Śākadvīpa. Here Revatī nakṣatra stops always, and hence sacred to it. Br. II. 19. 87; Vā. 49. 81; Vi. II. 4. 62.

रैवतक
Raivataka  (II)--(Mt.) in Bhāratavarṣa; 1) Vā. 45. 92; Bhā. V. 19. 16; Br. II. 16. 22. here Dvivida met Rāma and provoked him to a battle and in it was killed. 2) Bhā. X. 67. 8-25. 

रैवतकम्
Raivatakam --a tīrtha sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 74.

रैवस
Raivasa --a Pravara of the Bhārgavas. M. 195. 39.

रोकल
Rokalas --a tribe of the Vindhyas. Vā. 45. 132.

रोग
Roga --to be worshipped in housebuilding and palace building. M. 253. 26; 268. 17.

रोचन
Rocana  (I)--a son of Dakṣiṇā and a Tuṣita god. Bhā. IV. 1. 7-8.

रोचन
Rocana  (II)--the name of Indra of the Svārociṣa epoch. Bhā. VIII. 1. 20.

रोचन
Rocana  (III)--a son of Vasudeva. Br. III. 71. 182.

रोचन
Rocana  (IV)--a son of Upadevā. Vā. 96. 179.

रोचना
Rocanā  (I)--one of Vasudeva's wives, and mother of Hasta and other sons. Bhā. IX. 24. 45 and 49.

रोचना
Rocanā  (II)--grand daughter of Rukmi, married to Aniruddha. Bhā. X. 61. 25.

रोचना
Rocanā  (III)--a Mind-born mother. M. 179. 23. 

रोचमान
Rocamāna  (I)--a Viśvedeva. Br. III. 3. 31; M. 203. 13; Vā. 66. 32.

रोचमान
Rocamāna  (II)--a son of Ānartta and father of Reva. M. 12. 22-23.

रोचमान
Rocamāna  (III)--a son of Upadevī and Vasudeva. M. 46. 17.

रोचिष
Rociṣa --a son of Uṣā and Vibhāvasu. Bhā. VI. 6. 16.

रोचिष्मत्
Rociṣmat --a son of Svārociṣa Manu. Bhā. VIII. 1. 19.

रोदसी
Rodasī --the two mothers of the world (Heaven and Earth) worshipped for security of place. Bhā. II. 3. 5.

रोध
Rodha --a kind of hell; here fall slayers of cows, of phoetus murderers and those who set fire to cities. Vā. 101. 146, 152; Vi. II. 6. 2 and 8.

रोधस्वती
Rodhasvatī --a R. in Bhārata varṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 18.

रोमपाद
Romapāda  (I)--see Citraratha. Bhā. IX. 23. 7; Vi. IV. 18. 16.

रोमपाद
Romapāda  (II)--the famous son of Vidarbha and father of Babhru; attained wisdom from Nārada. Bhā. IX. 24. 1-2; Vi. IV. 12. 38-9.

रोमवन्त
Romavantas --fourteen gaṇas of gods; live in maha, tapa and jana lokas. Vā. 24. 2. 

रोमश
Romaśa  (I)--a siddha. Bhā. VI. 15. 14.

रोमश
Romaśa  (II)--a Vidyādhara chief in Veṇumanta hill. Vā. 39. 38.

रोमहर्षण
Romaharṣaṇa --a pupil of Vyāsa in charge of ItihāsaPurāṇa, and father of Sūta. Himself a sage and Sūta. Adopted as Brahmā by the sages in their yajña at Naimiṣa; also Lomaharṣaṇa (s.v.); killed by Balarāma for his failure to honour him by rising from his seat. 1) Bhā. I. 4. 22; X. 78. 22-30, 36; Br. I. 1. 18. II. 16. 3; 22. 2; 24. 1; Vā. 67. 2-3; Vi. III. 4. 10. His was the mūlasamhitā; adept in ākhyāna narrated royal genealogies. 2) Br. I. 1. 14; II. 34. 13-16; 35. 68; III. 59. 3; IV. 4. 8. Had six disciples. 3) Vi. III. 6. 16.

रोमहर्षणिका
Romaharṣaṇikā --the Purāṇa (mūla) samhitā compiled by Romaharṣaṇa. Vi. III. 6. 18.

रोहक
Rohaka --a kingdom of the West watered by Sindhu. Br. II. 18. 48; Vā. 47. 46.

रोहिण
Rohiṇa  (I)--same as Rohita. M. 122. 97.

रोहिण
Rohiṇa  (II)--the banyan tree in the Ramaṇaka varṣa. Vā. 45. 4.

रोहिणी
Rohiṇī  (I)--a daughter of Vālmīki; one of Vasudeva's wives, and mother of Gada, Balarāma and five other sons besides a daughter, Citrā. 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 45-6; X. 1. 8; Br. III. 71. 161-5; Vā. 96. 160-3; Vi. V. 1. 74-6; 2. 2; 5. 5; 6. 11; IV. 15. 18-9. Had her residence at Nandagokula. Hari ordered Yogamāyā to transfer his Dhāma in the womb of Devakī to that of Rohiṇī. This was the future Balarāma Sankarṣana. Nārada spoke about this to Kamsa. 2) Bhā. X. 2. 7-8, 15.  Her joy at the birth of Kṛṣṇa, and helped Yaśodā in her rakṣa ritual to Kṛṣṇa; joy at his escape from Kālīya; intensely attached to Rāma; surprised at Kṛṣṇa holding the Govardhana; came to see him taking Pārijāta from Indra's abode. Kṛṣṇa's respects to; 3) Ib. X 5. 17; 6. 19; 11. 12; 15. 44; 17. 15; 25. 30; 36. 17; [67 (v) 47-8]. went to Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse, met Yaśodā there and embraced her. Lamented the decease of Kṛṣṇa and Rāma. 4) Ib. X. 82. 37; XI. 31. 18. Entered fire after their deceuse; 5) Vi. V. 38. 4. also known as Pauravī. 6) M. 46. 11.

रोहिणी
Rohiṇī  (II)--one of Kṛṣṇa's wives; a Devī; mother of Dīptimat, Tāmrapakṣa and other sons. Bhā. X, 61. 18; Br. III. 71. 242; Vā. 96. 233. Vi. V. 28. 4; 32. 2.

रोहिणी
Rohiṇī  (III)--a wife of Mahādeva-Candramatanu of Śiva; mother of Budha. Br. I. 2. 9; II. 10. 84; M. 55. 12; 139. 25; Vā. 27. 56; 66. 22. Vi. I. 8. 8.

रोहिणी
Rohiṇī  (IV)--a daughter of Surabhī and Kaśyapa; a sister of the Rudras; mother of four daughters--Surūpā, Hamsakālī (kīlā), Bhadrā and Kāmadu(a)ghā. Br. III. 3. 73-5; Vā. 66. 71-72.

रोहिणी
Rohiṇī  (V)--a constellation important for śrāddha performance; 1) Br. III. 18. 3; M. 17. 3; 54. 9; Vā. 82. 3. the worship of, in go sahasra dānam. 2) M. 163. 41; 171. 32; 278. 14.

रोहिणी
Rohiṇī  (VI)--had Saumya as her son. Vā. 2. 9.

रोहिणीचन्द्र
Rohiṇīcandra śayanam --with which Nārāyaṇa is worshipped with the names of the moon; to be observed on the full moon day when Rohiṇī is the nakṣatra or Monday being  a Śuklapañcami; even Śūdras can observe it; a list of flowers given for worship; it lasts for a year; at the end a furnished bed with looking glass, etc., to be given to a learned Śrotriya; the giver attains the world of Candra; even women may observe it. M. 57. 3-27.

रोहित
Rohita  (I)--a son of Hariścandra; knowing that he would be sacrificed, went out of his kingdom. Having heard of the decease of his father, he wanted to return but was prevented by Indra. At the end of the sixth year, he purchased Sunaśśepa and returned home. Father of Harita. Bhā. IX. 7. 9-21; 8. 1; Br. III. 63. 117; M. 12. 38; Vā. 88. 119.

रोहित
Rohita  (II)--a son of Vapuṣmatī, after whom came the kingdom of Rohita. Br. II. 14. 32-3; Vā. 33. 28-29; Vi. II. 4. 23, 29.

रोहित
Rohita  (III)--a son of Satyabhāmā and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 247; M. 47. 17; Vā. 96. 238.

रोहित
Rohita  (IV)--a progenitor and a son of Dakṣa; Parā, Marīci, and Sudharmāna gaṇas, all of 12 gods each are from him. Br. IV. 1. 56-61; Vā. 100. 60.

रोहित
Rohita  (V)--a Mt. a hill of Śālmalidvīpa. M. 122. 96.

रोहित
Rohitas --one of the five deva gaṇas of the 4th Ṛtu Sāvarṇa Manu; of ten gods; mind-born sons of Budha with ten branches; 1) Br. IV. 1. 83-6; Vā. 100. 87. of the XII epoch of Manu. 2) Vi. III. 2. 34. 

रोहिताश्व
Rohitāśva  (I)--a son of Śaṭha. Br. III. 71. 170.

रोहिताश्व
Rohitāśva  (II)--of the Rohiṇi family. Vā. 96. 168.

रोहिताश्व
Rohitāśva  (III)--son of Hariścandra and father of Harita. Vi. IV. 3. 25.

रौक्मायणि
Raukmāyaṇi --an Ārṣeya pravara (Bhārgava). M. 195. 41.

रौच्य
Raucya  (I)--see Manu (s.v.). Br. II. 36. 4; IV. 1. 95.

रौच्य
Raucya  (II)--a son of Ruci, a Prajāpati of the Vaivasvata epoch; 1) Br. IV. 1. 50. the ninth Manu. 2) M. 9. 35; Vā. 100. 54.

रौद्र
Raudra  (I)--a muhūrta of the afternoon. Br. III. 3. 39; Vā. 66. 40.

रौद्र
Raudra  (II)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 233.

रौद्रम्
Raudram --a mantra of the Ṛg Vedins, to be recited in tank ritual; 1) M. 58. 34. a Sūkta of the Yajur Vedins to be recited in tank ritual. 2) M. 58. 35; 93. 102 and 131.

रौद्र
Raudras --the Gaṇeśvaras who sprang from the hair roots of the angry Vīrabhadra. Vā. 30. 142. 

रौद्राश्व
Raudrāśva --a son of Ahamyāti (Samjāti-Vā. P.) and father of Ṛkyu(ṣu). Nine other sons through the Apsaras, Ghṛṭācī. Bhā. IX. 20. 3-5; Vā. 99. 123. Vi. IV. 19. 1-2.

रौद्री
Raudrī --a kalā of Rudra and a Śakti. Br. IV. 19. 73; 35. 96.

रौध्र
Raudhras --the kingdom of the; the Ganges flows through this. M. 121. 43.

रौपसेवकि
Raupasevaki --a Kaśyapa and a Trayārṣeya. M. 199. 12.

रौप्यनाभ
Raupyanābha --was the milkman of the Pretas and Rākṣasas for milking the cow-earth; the essence was blood; Sumāli acted as the calf. M. 10. 23.

रौमहर्षणि
Raumaharṣaṇi --son of Romaharṣaṇa; name of SūtaPaurāṇika. Bhā. I. 2. 1.

रौरव
Raurava  (I)--one of the 28 hells ever burning and under the earth; he who is self-centred and accumulates wealth at the cost of others suffers here; especially from animals, called Rurus (s.v) more cruel than serpents. 1) Bhā. III. 30. 28; V. 26. 7-11. False witnesses, men who are partial and speak untruth, people guilty of infanticide and of incendiarism go to this; also mahāraurava; 2) Br. I. 1. 141; IV. 2. 146, 151-3, 180; 7. 76; 33. 60; Vi. I. 6. 41; II. 6. 2, 7. those who perform rituals with joy and wrath also go here; below this is the tapa. 3) Br. II. 9. 65; Vā. 101. 146, 151-2, 177, 180, 205; 110. 42. 

रौरव
Raurava  (II)--the flesh of the Ruru antelope for śrāddha. M. 17. 34.

रौरव
Raurava  (III)--the fifth kalpa. M. 290. 4.

रौरवम्
Rauravam --a sūkta of the Sāma samhitā recited in tank ritual. M. 58. 37.

रौरस
Raurasa --a kingdom of the West, watered by the Sindhu. Br. II. 18. 47.

रौहिण
Rauhiṇa --a muhūrta fit for dānas. M. 17. 3.

रौहिणम्
Rauhiṇam --a branch of Sāman for recitation at śrāddha. M. 17. 38.

रौहिणेय
Rauhiṇeya --(Balarāma); reminded Kṛṣṇa of his divinity and mission on earth when he had been overpowered by Kālīya. Vi. V. 7. 33-42.

रौहिण्यायनि
Rauhiṇyāyani --an Ārṣeya pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 9.

रौहित्यायनि
Rauhityāyani --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 19.  La

लकुच
Lakuca --a tree of six rasas in the Hairaṇvata (Hiraṇvata) country. Br. II. 15. 68; IV. 31. 58; M. 113. 67; Vā. 45. 9.

लक्षण
Lakṣaṇa --an elephant, son of Añjanā. Br. III. 7. 339.

लक्षणञ्ज
Lakṣaṇañja --a son of Jāmbavān. Br. III. 7. 303.

लक्षणा
Lakṣaṇā --an Apsaras. Vā. 69. 6.

लक्षहोम
Lakṣahoma --one of the three forms of gṛahabali; in addition to the procedure in the Ayutahoma, garuḍa worship is added; fulfils all desires; if no specific benefits are wanted, it grants Brahmapada. M. 93. 5, 84-118; 239. 1-16.

लक्ष्मण
Lakṣmaṇa  (I)--a son of Daśaratha and younger brother of Rāma; 1) Bhā. IX. 10. 3; V. 19. 1 and 6. took part in the Lankā expedition; respected the Brahmaṇas and elders; present at Rāma's coronation; father of Angada and Citraketu, 2) Ib. IX. 10. 19, 41-7; 11. 12; Br. III. 37. 31; 63. 185; Vā. 88. 184, 187; 108. 25; Vi. IV. 4. 87, 104. whose cities were Korayaṇa and Candracakra, near the Himālayas; created with Rāma by Lalitā, he killed Meghanāda in Bhaṇḍāsura war. 3) Br. IV. 29. 114.

लक्ष्मण
Lakṣmaṇa  (II)--a mantrakṛt. M. 145. 101.

लक्ष्मणा
Lakṣmaṇā  (I)--a daughter of the king of the Madras; heard of Kṛṣṇa's glory from Nārada and set her mind on  him. It was arranged that in a svayamvara he, who hit a target (fish) correctly by looking at its reflection in the water below was to wed her. All tried in vain but Kṛṣṇa succeeded and married her; when she was taken in a chariot, other kings attacked Kṛṣṇa; he vanquished all of them, and reached Dvārakā. Addressed Draupadī at length on her marriage; 1) Bhā. X. 58. 57; 83. 6, 17-39; M. 47. 13; Vā. 96. 234; Vi. V. 28. 5. sons, Gātravat and others. 2) Ib. V. 32. 4.

लक्ष्मणा
Lakṣmaṇā  (II)--a daughter of Duryodhana married by Sāmba in a svayamvara. For this the Kurus like Karṇa and Duryodhana took him captive after a severe fight and threw him into prison. Afraid of Balarāma's prowess, Duryodhana agreed to her marriage with Sāmba and sent a rich dowry. Bhā. X. 68. 1-12, 43-51.

लक्ष्मणा
Lakṣmaṇā  (III)--an Apsaras. Br. III. 7. 7.

लक्ष्मी
Lakṣmī  (I)--also Ramā and Śrī--born out of the churning of the ocean; seeing her unequalled beauty, the sages anointed her amidst divine music and dancing. Every god presented her with something or other. She desired to be a partner of Hari, and the latter assigned her a place in his chest. Presented Prthu with inexhaustible wealth; 1) Bhā. VIII. 8. 8-29; IV. 15. 16. a kalā of Brahmā; a devī attending on Soma; a Varṇa śakti; 2) Br. III. 65. 26; IV. 19. 74; 35. 94; 44. 62. a mind-born daughter of Brahmā; 3) M. 171. 32. consort of Viṣṇu; 4) Ib. 187. 45. brought forth Kāma by Dharma; 5) Ib. 171. 42. left Nārāyaṇa and loved Soma along with eight other devīs; 6) Ib. 23. 24. wealth; 7) Ib. 221. 12; 246. 62; 247. 30; 285. 20. residing in the lotus in śrī sara; 8) Vā. 37. 8. with the appellation of Sitā in Gayā. 9) Ib. 106. 58; 112. 64. 

लक्ष्मी
Lakṣmī  (II)--a daughter of Dakṣa 1) Vā. 10. 25, 34; 55. 43; Br. II. 9. 49, 58; 26. 45. and a wife of Dharma, and mother of Sūnṛtā; 2) Br. II. 36. 88; Vā. 62. 76; Vi. I. 7. 23, 28; 8-21. a mother goddess as mūlaprakṛti or māyā; 3) Br. IV. 7. 72. abode of, in the Meru. 4) Vi. II. 2. 47.

लक्ष्मी
Lakṣmī  (III)--a daughter of Bhṛgu and Khyātī and sister of Dhātā and Vidhātā; 1) Vi. I. 10. 2. gave Baladeva an ear-ring and a lotus garland at Vṛndāvana. 2) Ib. V. 25. 16.

लक्ष्मीकल्प
Lakṣmīkalpa --in the Kūrma Purāṇa; 1) M. 53. 48. the 23rd kalpa. 2) Ib. 290. 8.

लक्ष्मीकान्त
Lakṣmīkānta --is Viṣṇu. Vā. 108. 90.

लक्ष्मीपति
Lakṣmīpati --is Viṣṇu. Br. IV. 15. 23; 43. 75 and 86.

लक्ष्मीमन्त्र
Lakṣmīmantras --mantras sacred to the goddess. Br. IV. 38. 6.

लक्ष्मीरङ्गना
Lakṣmīraṅganā --a goddess enshrined at Bharatāśrama. M. 13. 46.

लक्ष्मीस्वयम्वरम्
Lakṣmīsvayamvaram --apparently a dramatic composition of Bharata (s.v.) enacted in the presence of Purūravas at Indra's command. M. 24. 28-9.

लगुद
Lagudas --see Yaṣṭi, the weapons of the Ābhīras. Vi. V. 38. 50-51. 

लघिमा
Laghimā  (I)--a devī. Br. IV. 19. 4; 36. 51.

लघिमा
Laghimā  (II)--one of the eight yogaiśvaryas; this second step of the yoga consists of lambanam, plavanam, and śighragam. Vā. 13. 3, 12.

लघु
Laghu --one of the five sons of Yadu. Br. III. 69. 2; M. 43. 7; Vā. 94. 2.

लघुवक्षर
Laghuvakṣara --hṛsva letters such as A, I, U. Vā. 100. 213.

लघुश्यामा
Laghuśyāmā --a daughter of Mātanga and hence Mātangī. Br. IV. 28. 40; 31. 103-4.

लघ्वि
Laghvi --a sage. M. 196. 28.

लङ्का
Laṅkā --an upadvīpa to Jambūdvīpa; a great city in Trikūṭa; was besieged by Rāma and his Vānara hosts and made desolate by Rāvaṇa's indiscretion; Vibhīṣaṇa as king of; Jāmbavatī alluded to this incident in praising Kṛṣṇa; 1) Bhā. V. 19. 30; IX. 10. 16-33; X. 56. 28; Vā. 48. 28. capital of Rāvaṇa; 2) Br. III. 7. 266; 69. 35; M. 43. 37. conquered by Arjuna; one of the places for residence of Agastya. 3) Ib. 61. 51.

लङ्काक्षि
Laṅkākṣi --a Ṛtvik at Brahmā's yajña. Vā. 106. 36.

लंकु
Laṃku --a son of Hetru and father of two sons. Vā. 69. 128. 

लंगाक्षी
Laṃgākṣī --a pupil of Pauṣyañji: learnt a hundred Sāma samhitas. 1) Bhā. XII. 6. 79. an Ārṣeya Pravara; (Angiras) . 2) M. 196. 6.

लंघा
Laṃghā --a daughter of Dakṣa, wife of Dharma and mother of Ghoṣa. Vi. I. 15. 105, 107.

लज्जा
Lajjā  (I)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 74.

लज्जा
Lajjā  (II)--R. from Ṛṣyavān. M. 114. 26.

लज्जा
Lajjā  (III)--a daughter of Dakṣa; 1) Vā. 10. 25; Vi. I. 7. 23. married Dharma; 2) Br. II. 9. 50, 61. mother of Vinaya. 3) Vā. 10. 36; 55. 43; Vi. I. 7. 30.

लडुन
Laḍuna --a son and commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 83; 26. 48.

लता
Latā  (I)--a daughter of Meru and wife of Ilāvṛta. Bhā. V. 2. 23.

लता
Latā  (II)--a daughter of Irā and mother of Vanaspati. Br. III. 7. 460.

लद्विला
Ladvilā --a daughter of Vairāja Prajāpati; wife of Cākṣuṣa Manu and mother of ten children. Vā. 62. 89-90.

लमक
Lamaka --a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 50. 

लम्पाक
Lampākas --a tribe; kingdom of the. M. 114. 43; 144. 58; Vā. 45. 119; 58. 83; 98. 108.

लम्पाकार
Lampākāra --a kingdom to be conquered by Kalki. Br. II. 31. 84; III. 73. 109.

लम्ब
Lamba  (I)--a Dānava in the army ranks of Tāraka. M. 173. 22; 177. 7.

लम्ब
Lamba  (II)--a son of Ugra, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 153.

लम्बकेशक
Lambakeśaka --a son of Ugra, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 153.

लम्बन
Lambana --a son of Jyotiṣmat; kingdom of, named after him. Vi. II. 4. 36.

लम्बमेखला
Lambamekhalā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 27.

लम्बसटा
Lambasaṭā --a mother Goddess. M. 179. 28.

लम्बस्तनी
Lambastanī --a mother Goddess. M. 179. 28.

लम्बा
Lambā  (I)--a daughter of Dakṣa and one of the 10 wives of Dharma. Mother of Vidyota and Ghoṣa. Bhā. VI. 6. 4. 5; Br. III. 3. 2 and 32; M. 5. 15, 18; 203. 8; Vā. 66. 2, 33.

लम्बा
Lambā  (II)--a mind-born mother. M. 179. 23. 

लम्बाक्ष
Lambākṣa --a son of Ugra, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 153.

लम्बायन
Lambāyanas --a tribe. M. 200. 10.

लम्बोदर
Lambodara  (I)--a son of Paurṇamāsa, and father of Cibilaka. Bhā. XII. 1. 24.

लम्बोदर
Lambodara  (II)--a name of Vighneśvara. Br. III. 42. 34; IV. 44. 67.

लम्बोदर
Lambodara  (III)--a son of Śāntikarṇi (ŚatakarṇiVi. P.), ruled for 18 years; father of Pilaka. M. 273. 4; Vi. IV. 24. 45.

लम्बोदर
Lambodara  (IV)--a son of Ugra, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 153.

लम्बोदरी
Lambodarī --a Varṇa śakti. Br. IV. 44. 58.

लय
Laya --the dissolution pertaining to Prakṛti; a state in which there is no rain for a century, famine rages and the fire of deluge consumes all spaces, accompanied by violent winds and so on. It is of four kinds; nitya, naimittika, prākṛtika, and ātyantika; deluge, when the universe merges when the guṇas are in a balanced state. Bhā. XII. 4. (whole); M. 1. 33; Vā. 5. 9. 

लयवारिद
Layavāridas --the seven clouds (named) which cause Pralaya. They take their origin from the steam caused by fire and cause the several oceans to become one. M. 2. 8-9.

ललिता
Lalitā  (I)--Upākhyāna of; narrated to Agastya by Hayagrīva-Viṣṇu; different names like Śakti, Parāśakti, Bhagavatī are given. 1) Br. IV. 5. (whole) ; Chh. 17-18. Originally mind-born daughter of Brahmā, named Prakṛti. then as Mohini in the churning of the milk ocean; originator of all gods and creatures. The third was the form of Lalitā when she killed Bhaṇḍa, in consequence of the penance done in her honour by Indra, and out of his offerings. All gods call on Her and praise Her. Finding her reigning alone, Brahmā remembered a form of Śankara, as Kāmeśvara, who was married to the Devī, the sister of Hari; rejoicing and presents on the occasion. Lalitā came to be known as Kāmeśvarī. War with Bhaṇḍa assuming the office of Śrīdaṇḍanāthā; sovereignty of; 2) Ib. IV. Chh. 6, 8, 10, 12-16. description of the nine parvas of Cakrarājaratha and seven parvas of Geyacakraratha sacred to Lalitā. She rode on the Cakraratha with the sāmrājya umbrella amidst war-music. Bhaṇḍa treated it as a woman's march and with contempt. Night attacks and deceitful attacks by Bhaṇḍa's soldiers; assisted by Mantriṇī and Daṇḍanāthā, Lalitā's march. Gaṇanātha's aid in encouraging the fallen Śaktis and vanquishing the asuras. For this the honour of first worship was awarded. Burning of the city Śūnyakam along with non-combatants. Bhaṇḍa's death and Lalitā's victory; created Kāma and consoled Rati. Glad at the birth of Kumāra and his marriage with Devasenā. Went back to her city, Śrīpuram. 3) Ib. IV. Chh. 19, 20, and 21; 26, 27, 29, 30; 37. 84. Pañcadaśākṣarī and other mantras sacred to Lalitā; meditation of. 4) Ib. IV. 38. 8-31. 

ललिता
Lalitā  (II)--the Goddess at Prayāgā. M. 13. 26.

ललिता
Lalitā  (III)--a Goddess enshrined at Santāna. M. 13. 34.

ललिता
Lalitā  (IV)--a name of Satī, wife of Śiva. M. 60. 11.

ललित्थ
Lalittha --one of the seven sons of Vidyoparicara. Vā. 99. 222.

लव
Lava  (I)--a son of Rāma, born and brought up in Vālmīki's āśrama; 1) Bhā. IX. 11. 11; M. 12. 51; Vā. 88. 198. ruled over Uttara Kośala with Śrāvasti as capital. 2) Br. III. 63. 198; Vā. 88. 200.

लव
Lava  (II)--a measurement of five kṣaṇas. Br. II. 7. 19; Vā. 100. 214.

लवण
Lavaṇa  (I)--a son of Rākṣasa Madhu, killed by Śatrughna in Madhuvana. Bhā. IX. 11. 14; Br. III. 63. 186; Vā. 88. 185; Vi. I. 12. 4; IV. 4. 101.

लवण
Lavaṇa  (II)--a son of Jyotiṣmat, after whom Lavaṇavarṣa took the name. Br. II. 14. 27-9; Vā. 33. 24.

लवण
Lavaṇa  (III)--a son of Mahogra, prayed to Śiva. Br. III. 7. 91.

लवण
Lavaṇa  (IV)--a hell; disrespect to guru, reviling and selling of the Vedas and laxity in sex relations lead to it. Vi. II. 6. 2 and 13. 

लवणम्
Lavaṇam  (I)--one of the eight saubhāgyas. M. 60. 9.

लवणम्
Lavaṇam  (II)--a kingdom of Kuśadvīpa after Lavaṇa. Br. II. 14. 29; 19. 58; Vā. 33. 25; 49. 53.

लवणम्
Lavaṇam  (III)--also Lavaṇa sindhu, Lavaṇāmbudhi-an ocean of salt; 1) Br. III. 52. 42; IV. 31. 18; Vā. 34. 12. origin from waters of the aṇḍam; 2) M. 2. 34. jalam. 3) Ib. 251. 34.

लवणम्
Lavaṇam  (IV)--unfit for śrāddha. Vi. III. 16. 8.

लवणाचल
Lavaṇācala --a gift of a hill of 16 droṇas of salt, is the best; he who makes a gift of it goes to the world of Umā; 1) M. 83. 4; 84. 1. complimentary to Vibhūti dvādaśi vratam. 2) Ib. 92. 31; 99. 15; 100. 18.

लवणार्णव
Lavaṇārṇava --the sea of salt. Vi. V. 21. 25; 27. 4.

लवणोगण
Lavaṇogaṇa --salt from sea, from bilva, bālakeya, yavāhvaka, aurva, kṣāram and kālabhasma. M. 217. 60-61.

लाकिनी
Lākinī --a śakti. Br. IV. 20. 15.

लांगल
Lāṃgala  (I)--a son of Śuddhoda, and father of Prasenajit; 1) Bhā. IX. 12. 14. in charge of a Samhitā. 2) Br. II. 35. 47.

लांगल
Lāṃgala  (II)--as a weapon of Śeṣa. Vi. II. 5. 18; V. 33. 30. 

लाङ्गलावती
Lāṅgalāvatī --a Mother Goddess. M. 179. 27.

लांगलि
Lāṃgali --a Vānara chief born of Svetā. Br. III. 7. 179.

लांगली
Lāṃgalī  (I)--one of the four pupils of Pauṣyañji; a Śrutaṛṣi; 1) Br. II. 33. 8; 35. 40; Vā. 61. 36; Vi. III. 6. 6. composed six Samhitas. 2) Vā. 61. 42.

लांगली
Lāṃgalī  (II)--is Balarāma; entered Mithilā and was received with presents by Maithila; after having chastised Kṛṣṇa for having killed Śatadhanva when he did not have the Syamantaka saying that he could have nothing to do with Dvārakā or Kṛṣṇa; but entreated by the Vṛṣṇis and Andhakas, was brought back to Dvārakā; see Hala (Baladeva). Br. III. 71. 77; Vi. V. 25. 6, 9; Vā. 96, 75-8, 84.

लांगली
Lāṃgalī  (III)--an avatār of the Lord in the 22nd dvāpara in Vārāṇasī with halā for weapon and with four righteous sons. Vā. 23. 199.

लांगली
Lāṃgalī  (IV)--a mind-born mother. M. 179. 16.

लांगूलिनी
Lāṃgūlinī --a R. from the Mahendra hill. Br. II. 16. 37; Vā. 45. 106.

लाज
Lāja --also Lājavarṣam--thrown over on festive occasions; 1) Br. III. 27. 26; 49. 14; 55. 17. scattered over the couple Kāmeśvara and Devī. 2) Ib. IV. 15. 32; 18. 9; 26. 61.

लाभ
Lābha --a son of Puṣṭi. Br. II. 9. 59; Vā. 10. 35. 

लामिनी
Lāminī --a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 90.

लाम्यक
Lāmyaka --a kingdom watered by the R. Cakṣuṣ. Br. II. 18. 46.

लालाक्षेप
Lālākṣepa --a hell. Br. IV. 33. 61.

लालाटि
Lālāṭi --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 25.

लालात्य
Lālātyas --belong to Kauśika gotra. Br. III. 66. 73.

लालाभक्ष
Lālābhakṣa --one of the 28 hells for making one's own wife taste one's semen; 1) Bhā. V. 26. 7 and 26. for eating without guests or before offering food to gods and manes; a naraka of offensive smell to which goes one who holds intercourse with a daughter of his friend and a Brāhmaṇa lady. 2) Br. IV. 2. 147 and 161; Vā. 101. 147, 159; Vi. II. 6. 3 and 16.

लालावि
Lālāvi  (I)--a son of Khaśā and a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 133.

लालावि
Lālāvi  (II)--a Rākṣasa gaṇa. Vā. 69. 165.

लावकी
Lāvakī --a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 20.

लावकृत्
Lāvakṛt --an Ārṣeya Pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 22. 

लावण्यवति
Lāvaṇyavati --the wife of king Puṣpavāhana and mother of 10,000 (ayatam) heroic soldiers. M. 100. 6.

लिखित
Likhita --a son of Jaigīṣavya and Ekapāṭalā. Br. III. 10. 21; Vā. 72. 19.

लिख्या
Likhyā --eight times the Vālāgram (s.v.). M. 258. 18.

लिंग
Liṃga  (I)--a term for mahat. Vā. 102. 21.

लिंग
Liṃga  (II)--a term for Jīva. Vā. 102. 101.

लिंगधारिणी
Liṃgadhāriṇī --the Goddess at Naimiṣa. M. 13. 26.

लिंग
Liṃga Purāṇa (Lingam) --one among the Mahā-Purāṇas; comprises 11,000 ślokas. Bhā. XII. 7. 23; 13. 6; Vi. III. 6. 22.

लिंगम्
Liṃgam --Origin of; came out of a ball of ever-burning fire and grew and grew; Viṣṇu and Brahmā undertook to find out its beginning and the end. It was all effulgence. They found it impossible and prayed to Śiva who initiated them into māheśvaram Balam. 1) Br. II. 26. 21 to the end; 27. 30-101; Vā. 55. 21-61. Establishment of the cult in the presence of Śiva and the sages; is Jīva, mahat; leads to kaivalya; 2) Br. IV. 3. 22, 56-9, 79. found in Godāvarī; 3) M. 22. 57. worship of at Benares relieves one of rebirth; 4) Ib. 154. 350; 185. 57. its size for installation in the palace depends on the measurement of the palace; nine varieties are distinguished. The technique of the making of a  Linga is furnished in detail. It may be of gems, spaṭika, of stone, earth, or wood. 5) Ib. 263. 1, 11, 25.

लिंगरूप
Liṃgarūpa --Gadādhara became turned to Linga in Kaliyuga; a Prapitāmaha. Vā. 111. 84.

लिंगसारम्
Liṃgasāram --a sacred place on the Narmadā. M. 191. 51-2.

लिंगिन्स्
Liṃgins --ineligible for śrāddha. M. 16. 17.

लिंगोद्भव
Liṃgodbhava --story and praise of. Vā. Ch. 55.

लीला
Līlā --a Svara śakti. Br. IV. 44. 57.

लीलावती
Līlāvatī --the courtesan who had faith in Śiva and who did the dāna of Lavaṇācala and gained heaven. M. 92. 23.

लीलाव्रतम्
Līlāvratam --the observer of this vrata attains the Viṣṇuloka. M. 101. 5.

लुब्ध
Lubdha --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 19. 

लुब्धक
Lubdhaka --a companion of Puramjana; allegorically pāyu. Bhā. IV. 25. 53; 29. 15.

लेख
Lekhas  (I)--eight groups of Gods of the Cākṣuṣa epoch; 1) Br. II. 36. 67, 76; M. 9. 23; Vi. III. 1. 27. Manojava, Praghāsa, Pracetas, Vāta, Dhruvakṣiti, Adbhuta, Avana and Bṛhaspati. 2) Vā. 62. 63-4.

लेख
Lekhas  (II)--a class of Pitṛs propitiated on every New Moon day. Vā. 56. 21.

लेखक
Lekhaka --a scribe who is an expert in all languages and who is versed in all Śāstras; characteristics of writing; a scribe must be able to reproduce in a few sentences much that is spoken. M. 215. 26-8.

लेखा
Lekhā  (I)--the sun standing above this, results in the end of the five year Yuga. M. 124. 64; 141. 35.

लेखा
Lekhā  (II)--of the earth; on account of this the sun is seen above though at a height of 1000 Yojanas. Vā. 50. 110.

लेखिनी
Lekhinī --the Goddess from the back part of Nṛsimha; follower of Vāgīśi. M. 179. 68.

लेलिहाना
Lelihānā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 18.

लेलिहानतीर्थम्
Lelihānatīrtham --in Gayā near Bharatāśrama. Vā. 112. 24. 

लैंगम्
Laiṃgam --the Purāṇa of 11,000 verses; narrated by Maheśvara in the midst of Agniliṅga, a treatise on the four means (Trivarga and mokṣa) at the end of the Āgneyakalpa; he who makes a gift of it with cow and sesame in phālguṇi attains oneness with Śiva. M. 53. 37-38.

लैन्द्रानि
Laindrāni --an Ātreya gotrakāra. M. 197. 3.

लैन्द्रानि
Laindrāni --an Ārṣeya pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 21.

लोक
Lokas --seven in number, one above the other like several umbrellas spread over. To the usual seven are added Vaikuṇṭha and Golokam; 1) Br. II. 19. 155-6; 21. 19. 21; III. 41. 54-5. the fourteen sthalas or places of which seven are Kṛta and seven are Akṛta; Bhūḥ and other six are Kṛtas; the Akṛtas are Prākṛtas; Pṛthvī, Antarikṣa, divya and maharlokas are known as Arṇavakas or which stand until ābhūtasamplava; Jana, tapa and sabya are jñānalokas; Vyaktalokas are Bhūḥ, Bhuvaḥ, Svaḥ, Maha, Jana, Tapa and Satya (Brahma); their residents are given, those attaining Brahmaloka (satya) do not have rebirth. 2) Vā. 101. 10-39; Vi. I. 22. 80; V. 2. 16.

लोकगुरु
Lokaguru --is Brahmā. Vā. 65. 71.

लोकपरम्परा
Lokaparamparā --the world of Sāntānikas and Ādidevas of seven guṇas; above and below them are another seven guṇas; after which come the devas and earth; from them are rains which invigorate the world. Vā. 71. 57. 

लोकपाला
Lokapālās --eight in number, each with a city of his own situated in the eight cardinal points, surrounding the outskirts of Brahmā's city; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 29. stand in the midst of Lokāloka, on the four sides of Meru in their respective towns: EastIndia in Vasvaukasāra: South-Yama in Samyamana: WestVaruṇa in Sukha and North-Candra in Vibhāvari. These are stationed round the Mānasa lake for the protection of Dharma and progress of the world; 2) Br. II. 21. 28-34, 156; III. 3. 102; M. 124. 94; Vā. 50. 86, 91; 111. 25. an amśa of the Supreme Lord; 3) M. 52. 21. served Tāraka as servants; beaten by Tāraka; 4) Ib. 148. 27; 153. 183. served in the battle of Tripura; 5) Ib. 24. 5; 138. 1. requested Soma to restore Tārā back to Bṛhaspati; 6) Ib. 23. 35. oblations to, in rituals of digging tanks and planting gardens; 7) Ib. 58. 33; 59. 10. invoked in making the 16 gifts; 8) Ib. 274. 41f; 285. 9; 291. 3. function until the Pralaya. 9) Vā. 50. 155 and 205.

लोकपालत्वम्
Lokapālatvam --the lordship of a quarter of the world; Yama became a Lokapāla by pleasing Śiva. M. 11. 20.

लोकपितामह
Lokapitāmaha  (I)--a hymn to Vāmana. M. 245. 66, 67-80.

लोकपितामह
Lokapitāmaha  (II)--is Brahmā. Vā. 25. 84.

लोकप्रकालन
Lokaprakālana --a son of Dhruva. Vā. 66. 21.

लोकमात
Lokamātas --the mother goddesses being the 14 daughters of Dakṣa, married to Kaśyapa. Br. III. 3. 55-6; 7. 469. 

लोकसन्तानक
Lokasantānaka --south of Nāgavīthi and north of Lokāloka. Br. II. 21. 103.

लोकसिद्धि
Lokasiddhi --a Yoga siddhi. Br. IV. 36. 52.

लोकाक्षि
Lokākṣi  (I)--the avatār of the Lord in the sixth dvāpara with four learned disciples, all yogins. Vā. 23. 133.

लोकाक्षि
Lokākṣi  (II)--one of the four disciples of Pauṣyañji Vā. 61. 36-7; Vi. III. 6. 6.

लोकाधानम्
Lokādhānam --Soma takes away the water drunk by the sun through nāḍis and thus sets in motion the Jyotiṣa cakram. The clouds drink from Soma and pour in as rain for six months by the heaviness of the wind; thus the waters are not wasted; once taken they are returned; from the sun comes heat, and from the moon śītalam. Vā. 51. 14-16.

लोकान्तकान्तक
Lokāntakāntaka --Īśvara, the bridge among bridges, the holy among the holies, the Vedya among the Vedic scholars, the Prabhu among Lords, somabhūta for beings, agnibhūta for promoting the effulgence of Agni, manobhūte for men, tapobhūta for tapasvins, vinaya for police men, tejas among tejasvins, vigraha among idols, and the place for journey men. Va. 97. 40-43.

लोकालोक
Lokāloka  (I)--the Mt. forming the boundary of the earth. Br. I. 1. 78; 3. 31; Vā. 49. 144; 50. 155, 160, 205; 101. 191-2. 

लोकालोक
Lokāloka  (II)--(Mt.) a chain of hills beyond the Svādūdaka, between the Loka where the sun shines and Aloka where he does not. The regions lighted by the sun are said to cover 50 crores of yojanas. The chain of the Lokāloka is said to occupy a fourth of the area of the globe. In the Aloka Yogeśvara-Kṛṣṇa travels. 1) Bhā. V. 20. 34-42; M. 123. 47; 124. 38, 81. Crossed by Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa on their way to Vaikuṇṭha in search of the dead child of the Brāhmaṇa of Dvārakā. A. mythical mountainous belt in the south separating the visible world from the world of darkness. 3) Br. II. 15. 3; 19. 150; 21. 51, 101 and 106, 155; III. 7. 294; IV. 2. 194. 10,000 yojanas in height and breadth; protected by four guardians, Sudhāman and others on the four directions. 4) Vi. II. 4. 94; 8. 82-3. ^2 Bhā. X. 89. 48.

लोपामुद्रा
Lopāmudrā  (I)--consort of Agastya; a Brahmavādinī. Br. II. 33. 19; IV. 10. 78; Vā. 108. 55.

लोपामुद्रा
Lopāmudrā  (II)--is Hrādi. Br. IV. 38. 9-10.

लोपामुद्रापति
Lopāmudrāpati --is Agastya. Br. IV. 31. 27; M. 61. 52.

लोभ
Lobha  (I)--born of Brahmā's lower lip. Bhā. III. 12. 26; M. 3. 10.

लोभ
Lobha  (II)--born of Lambha and Māyā. Bhā. IV. 8. 3.

लोभालोभ
Lobhālobha --a Śrutaṛṣi. Br. II. 33. 10. 

लोमगायनि
Lomagāya(i)ni --a pupil of Lāngala. Br. II. 35. 48; Vā. 61. 42.

लोमपाद
Lomapāda  (I)--a son of Vidarbha, and father of Babhru (Vastu-Vā. P.) the righteous; got war elephants from the devas. Br. III. 70. 38; M. 44. 36; Vā. 95. 37.

लोमपाद
Lomapāda  (II)--alias Daśaratha, son of Satyaratha; (Citraratha-Vā. P.); had a daughter Śāntā, and son, Caturanga. M. 48. 95; Vā. 99. 103.

लोमपाद
Lomapāda  (III)--an elephant. Br. III. 7. 349.

लोमयान
Lomayānas --Ekārṣeyas. M. 200. 5.

लोमश
Lomaśa --the Sūta; performed tapas with success in the Muṇḍapṛṣṭa hill of Gayā; called to that place all the mahānadīs of India--Śarāvadī to Carmavatī. Vā. 26. 5; 108. 77-81.

लोमहर्षण
Lomaharṣaṇa  (I)--see Romaharṣaṇa: asked by Munis to reveal the Bhaviṣya agreed to do so. M. 50. 68, 73-74.

लोमहर्षण
Lomaharṣaṇa  (II)--a sage; 1) Vā. 45. 70. one who would make the hairs of his hearers stand with joy; (ety.); the disciple of Vyāsa and well known for his supreme knowledge in all the three worlds; 2) Ib. 1. 16-17, 29. spoke logically; 3) Ib. 103. 8. Sūta; 4) Ib. 53. 1. was entrusted with the Itihāsa, Purāṇa and known as Purāṇārtha viśārada. 5) Ib. 46. 1; 60. 13, 21. 

लोमहर्षण
Lomaharṣaṇa  (III)--performed tapas in the Muṇḍapṛṣṭa hill of Gayā; called the many rivers named there. Vā. 108. 77-82.

लोला
Lolā --the Goddess enshrined at Utpalāvastaka. M. 13. 45.

लोलाक्षि
Lolākṣi --one of the Bhārgava gotrakāras. M. 195. 27.

लोलाक्षी
Lolākṣī --a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 55 and 75.

लोलार्क
Lolārka --a tīrtha at Benares. M. 185. 68.

लोह
Loha --the sixth hell under the earth. Br. IV. 2. 150, 182-5; Vā. 101. 149.

लोहगन्धी
Lohagandhī(dha-Vā. P.)  the wicked king troubled by Janamejaya; a Rājaṛṣi abandoned by Paurās and Jānapadas; deep in distress fell at the feet of sage Indrota; performed Aśvamedha; spent the rest of his life with the sage. Br. III. 68. 23-6; Vā. 93. 22.

लोहदण्डम्
Lohadaṇḍa(ka)m --a tīrtha sacred to the Pitṛs; 1) M. 22. 65. in Gayā. 2) Vā. 108. 74; 109. 16.

लोहपृष्ठ
Lohapṛṣṭha --also Loha (s.v.) the sixth hell, known also as tama; below the earth, up the hill and with people. Vā. 101. 149 and 179, 182. 

लोहम्
Loham --the loadstone attracting iron, illustrative of the supreme spirit attracting one who meditates on it. Vi. VI. 7. 30.

लोहामिषम्
Lohāmiṣam --flesh of red goat for śrāddha. M. 15. 35.

लोहास
Lohāsa --a Vānara tribe. Br. III. 7. 319.

लोहिणि
Lohiṇi --a wife of Bāna. Br. III. 5. 45.

लोहिणि
