Vāṅgas --a Janapada of the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 15.

वाङ्गायनि
Vāṅgāyani --one of the Bhārgava gotrakāras. M. 195. 28.

वाच
Vāca  (I)--a Marut gaṇa. M. 171. 53.

वाच
Vāca  (II)--the name of Vyāsa of the 20th dvāpara; the avatār of the Lord Aṭṭahāsa. Vā. 23. 189.

वाच
Vāca  (III)--one of the nine sons of Sāvarṇi. Vā. 100. 22.

वाच
Vāca  (IV)--The Vedas go to Īśvara with mind and unable to attain Him return back (Upaniṣad); it is avyakta and parokṣa. Vā. 103. 10. 

वाचवृद्ध
Vācavṛddhas --one of the five groups of devas of the 14th Manu Bhauta--the seers of Svāyambhuva Manu. Vā. 100. 111, 113.

वाचश्रवस्
Vācaśravas --a son of Śikhaṇḍi, an avatār of the 18th dvāpara; 1) Vā. 23. 183. Vedavyāsa of 22nd dvāpara. 2) Vi. III. 3. 17.

वाचस्पति
Vācaspati  (I)--Bṛhaspati (s.v.) who by means of propitiatory ceremonies to planets, etc., disillusioned Raji's sons and won back the kingdom for Indra; 1) M. 24. 44-9. worship of. 2) Ib. 73. 7.

वाचस्पति
Vācaspati  (II)--the name of Vyāsa of the 21st dvāpara; Dāruka avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 194.

वाचा
Vācā --one of the ten branches of the Rohita group of devas. Vā. 100. 90.

वाचाङ्ग
Vācāṅgas --a Janapada of the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 14.

वाचावृद्ध
Vācāvṛddhas --a gaṇa of the epoch of Bhautya Manu; they were the seven sages of the Svāyambhuva epoch. Br. IV. 1. 107-9; Vi. III. 2. 43.

वाजपेय
Vājapeya --a sacrifice; 1) Vā. 99. 372. represents the waist of the personified Veda; 2) Ib. 30. 292; 104. 83; 111. 33. produced by Brahmā and performed by Dakṣa. 3) Bhā. III. 12. 40; IV. 3. 3; Br. III. 74. 185. 

वाजश्रवस्
Vājaśravas --a Ṛṣika who became sage by practice of satya; 1) Br. II. 32. 102 and 110; Vā. 59. 94, 101. an Angīrasa and mantrakṛt; the 24th Vedavyāsa; heard the Vāyu Purāṇa from Nīryantara and narrated it to Somaśuṣman. 2) Br. II. 35. 122; IV. 4. 64; Vā. 103. 64.

वाजसनेयकम्
Vājasaneyakam --of 1900 Samhitas. Br. II. 35. 76; Vā. 99. 254.

वजसनेयिक
Vajasaneyikas --the Brāhmaṇas established by Janamejaya. Vā. 99. 250.

वाजसनेयिक
Vājasaneyika Brāhmaṇa --to be divided into four. Vā. 61. 67.

वाजसन्यस्त
Vājasanyastas --the Yajus śākhas imparted by the Sun god to Yājñavalkya. These were fifteen branches each comprising hundreds of Yajus (sentences). These were learnt by Kaṇva, Mādhyandina and others. Bhā. XII. 6. 74.

वाजसृक्
Vājasṛk --a son of Arka Agni. Br. II. 12. 43.

वाजि
Vāji --one of the ten horses yoked to the chariot of the Moon. Br. II. 23. 56.

वाजिजित्
Vājijit --a Marīci god. Br. IV. 1. 58. 

वाजिन्
Vājin(a)s --the common name to the fifteen pupils of Yājñavalkya; 1) Br. II. 35. 26, 30; Vā. 61. 24-6; Vi. III. 5. 29-30. sons of Gāndharvī; 2) Br. III. 3. 76. the Yajus granted to Yājñavalkya as horse by Sūrya. 3) Vā. 61. 22.

वाजिन
Vājinas --the sons of Bhadrā; of different colours and able to fly in the air; white, pink, red, black, green and grey for use by the devas. Vā. 66. 73-4.

वाजिप
Vājipa --a Marīci god. Br. IV. 1. 58.

वाजिमेध
Vājimedha --see Aśvamedha. Br. III. 52. 36; 63. 142 and 48; Vā. 88. 144; Vi. III. 18. 85; VI. 8. 55.

वाजिरूप
Vājirūpa --the incarnation of Hayagrīva who restored the Angas, Vedas, Purāṇas, Dharmaśāstras, Nyāya and Mīmāmsa when all the universe was burnt. M. 53. 5.

वाजिवक्त्र
Vājivaktra --see Hayagrīva. Br. IV. 18. 13.

वाजिवासिका
Vājivāsikās --a southern tribe. M. 114. 47.

वाजिश्रव
Vājiśravas --a Ṛṣika; a mantrakṛt. M. 145. 96, 104.

वाजी
Vājī --a horse of the Moon's chariot. M. 126. 52. 

वाटधान
Vāṭadhāna(c) --a northern kingdom, a tribe. Br. II. 16. 46; M. 114. 40; Vā. 45. 115.

वाडव
Vāḍava --a Marut gaṇa. M. 171. 54.

वाडव
Vāḍavas --the Brahmans of Vāyupura. Vā. 60. 71.

वाडववन्हि
Vāḍavavanhi --fire devouring the waters of the ocean. Vi. V. 9. 30.

वाडादित्य
Vāḍāditya --the Sun God in Vāyupura. Vā. 60. 75.

वाणी
Vāṇī --a whisk bearer of Lalitā, became consort of Brahmā--also Sarasvatī and Bhāratī. Br. IV. 39. 67, 74; 43. 75 and 86.

वाणिज्यम्
Vāṇijyam --trade as the profession of the Vaiśyas. Br. II. 7. 162; Vā. 79. 71; Vi. III. 8. 30; V. 10. 26 and 29.

वात
Vāta  (I)--the Rākṣasa presiding over the month of Tapas; with the śarat Sun. Bhā. XII. 11. 39; Br. II. 23. 15; Vā. 52. 15; Vi. II. 10. 11.

वात
Vāta  (II)--a son of Yātudhāna, and father of Virodha who was death to the people. Br. III. 7. 89 and 96.

वात
Vāta  (III)--a son of Śūra. Br. III. 71. 138; Vā. 96. 136.

वात
Vāta  (IV)--a piśāca. Vā. 69. 127. 

वात
Vāta  (V)--one of the seven seers of the Svārociṣa epoch. Vi. III. 1. 11.

वातगज
Vātagaja --a son of Mṛga elephant. Br. III. 7. 332.

वातड्य
Vātaḍyas --of Kauśika gotra. Br. III. 66. 70.

वातपति
Vātapati --a son of Satajit. Br. III. 71. 55.

वातंधम
Vātaṃdhama --(Mt.) a hill in India. Br. II. 16. 21.

वातरम्ह
Vātaramhas --a Janapada of the Bhadrā country. Vā. 43. 20.

वातरशन
Vātaraśanas --a class of gods performing śrāddha. Br. III. 10. 110; Vā. 73. 62.

वातस्कन्ध
Vātaskandha --There are seven Vātaskandhas each with a Marut gaṇa of seven. In the first the seven are Śakrajyoti, Satya, Satyajyoti, Citrajyoti, Jyotiṣmān, Sutapas and Caitya; Ṛtajit, Satyajit, Suṣeṇa, Senajit, Sutamitra, Amitra and Suramitra are in the second; in the third Dhātu, Dhanada, Ugra, Bhīma, Varuṇa, Abhiyuktākṣika and Sāhvaya; in the fourth, the names of the gaṇa are omitted in the text; in the fifth Īdṛk, Anyādṛk, Sasariddrumavṛkṣakas, Mita and Samita; in the sixth, Īdṛk Puruṣa, Nānyādṛk, Samacetana, Sammita, Samavṛtti, and Pratiharta; in the seventh, the names not clear. Br. III. 5. 78-80, 90-96. 

वातस्कन्ध
Vātaskandhas --Paths of Vāyu through which the Marut gaṇas travel. Seven of them are said to have their stations in Pṛthvī (earth), Bhāskara (sun), Soma (moon) Constellation group, Planets, Saptaṛṣimaṇḍala and Dhruva, with their respective chiefs: Āvaha, Pravaha, Udvaha, Samvaha, Vivaha, Anuvaha and Parivaha. Br. III. 5. 78-80; Vā. 67. 110-12.

वातापि
Vātāpi  (I)--a son of Hrāda, and Dhamanī: fought with the sons of Brahmā in the Devāsura war; 1) Bhā. VI. 18. 15; VIII. 10. 32. a Saimhikeya Asura. 2) Br. III. 6. 19; Vā. 68. 19.

वातापि
Vātāpi  (II)--a nephew of Hiraṇyakaśipu, eaten up by Agastya; 1) M. 6. 26; 61. 51. a son of Vipracitti. 2) Vi. I. 21. 11.

वातापितापन
Vātāpitāpana --a name of Agastya. Br. IV. 37. 9 and 19: 41. 83; 42. 9.

वातारणि
Vātāraṇi --the Taijasa Prakṛti as a result of the sabda guṇa of Ākāśa commingling with the sparśa guna of Vāyu. Vā. 2. 44.

वातिक
Vātika --Śyāma Parāśara. M. 201. 37.

वात्स्य
Vātsya  (I)--a pupil of (Vedamitra) Śākalya. Bhā. XII. 6. 57; Vi. III. 4. 22.

वात्स्य
Vātsya  (II)--a gotrakāra (Bhārgava). M. 195. 17.

वात्स्य
Vātsya  (III)--a Vājin; son of Vatsa. Vā. 61. 25; 92. 73. 

वात्स्य
Vātsya  (IV)--a son of Gārgya. Vā. 92. 73.

वात्स्यतरायण
Vātsyatarāyaṇas --Ārṣeya pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 21.

वात्स्यायन
Vātsyāyana mukhas --sages offered prayers to Nāgarāja for obtaining jñāna. Br. III. 36. 6.

वात्स्यायन
Vātsyāyanas --Kāśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 6.

वात्स्यायनि
Vātsyāyani --a Tripravara. M. 196. 33.

वाद
Vāda --an Amitābha god. Br. II. 36. 54.

वादि
Vādi --a son of Pṛthu. Vi. I. 14. 1.

वादित्रोक
Vāditroka --a mountain to the left of Śila, where Vidyādharas dance and sing with the Gandharvas and Apsarasas. Vā. 108. 45.

वाद्य
Vādyas --names of musical instruments mentioned. Br. IV. 16. 3-6; M. 7. 14; 105. 6.

वाध्नीणस
Vādhnīṇasas --sons of Krauñca. Br. III. 7. 456.

वानदृष्ट
Vānadṛṣṭa --a Pṛthuka god. Br. II. 36. 73. 

वानप्रस्थ
Vānaprastha  (I)--a sādhu: fit for Śrāddha feeding; 1) Br. II. 32. 26; III. 7. 317; 9. 70; 15. 16 and 35. duties of: living on fruits and roots; clothing with skins and barks of trees; bathing morning and evening; performance of homa; life in forest; 2) Vā. 8. 176; Vi. III. 9. 18-23. M. 225. 3. the third order of life. 3) Vi. II. 1. 30.

वानप्रस्थ
Vānaprastha  (II)--the third āśrama; 1) Vā. 59. 25; 104. 23. adopted by Yayāti after Pūru's coronation; living on fruits and roots and always in peace, having conquered his mind and anger, was engaged for 1,000 years in offering oblations to Pitṛs and Devas and in fire rites and entertaining guests; performed penance feeding on water alone for 3 years, on air for a year, in the midst of fire for another year and standing on one leg for six months; reached heaven. 2) M. 35. 1-2, 13-17; 40. 1, 4 and 7.

वानर
Vānaras --(also Haris)--born of Harī and Pulaha: eleven groups distinguished: Dvīpins, Śarabhas, Simhas Vyāghras, Nīlas, Salyakas, Ṛkṣas, Mārjāras, Lohāsas, Vānaras, and Māyavas. Vāli was their Lord: Belong to the line of Krodhavaśa; 1) Br. III. 7. 176 and 320: 8. 71. should not see the Śrāddha food. 2) Vi. III. 16. 12.

वान्नशिला
Vānnaśilā --a R. from the Vindhyas. Br. II. 16. 33.

वापी
Vāpī  (I)--the construction of small ponds at the auspicious time; the same prescription for excavating taḍāgas (tanks). M. 58. 1, 51.

वापी
Vāpī  (II)--one of the ten pīṭhas for images with two mekhalas. M. 262. 6, 8. 

वाम
Vāma  (I)--a name of Śiva. Bhā. IV. 3. 8.

वाम
Vāma  (II)--a son of Bhūta and Sarūpā: a Rudra. Bhā. VI. 6. 17.

वाम
Vāma  (III)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Bhadrā. Bhā. X. 61. 17.

वामचूड
Vāmacūḍas --a southern tribe. M. 163. 73.

वामदेव
Vāmadeva  (I)--a name of Śiva; immortal; 1) Bhā. II. 6. 36; III. 12. 12; Br. II. 26. 33; III. 72. 182. with the trident created Brahmans from his face; Kṣatriyas from his arms, Vaiśyas from his thigh and Śūdras from his feet; 2) M. 4. 27-30. was not allowed to proceed with the creation of beings and hence got the name Sthāṇu; 3) Ib. 4. 31. five faced Śiva grew angry at Soma's refusal to send back Tārā to Bṛhaspati and waged war with him. 4) Ib. 23. 36.

वामदेव
Vāmadeva  (II)--a mountain of Śālmalidvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 10.

वामदेव
Vāmadeva  (III)--a son of Hīraṇyaretas of Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 14.

वामदेव
Vāmadeva  (IV)--a sage who was invited for Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya. Went with Kṛṣṇa to Mithilā, and came to Syamantapañcaka to see him. One of the sages who left for Piṇḍāraka; 1) Bhā. X. 74. 8; 84. 5; 86. 18; XI. 1-12. a sage by tapas: an Angirasa and mantrakṛt; 2) Br. II. 32. 99 and 110; M. 145. 93, 104; Vā. 59. 90, 101. a son of Surūpā and a gotrakāra; 3) M. 196. 4. a Tripravara, not to marry with Angiras and Bṛhaduktas. 4) Ib. 196. 35-36. 

वामदेव
Vāmadeva  (V)--a son of Atharvan Angiras: visited Paraśurāma in penance; 1) Br. III. 1. 105; 23. 4; IV. 39. 56. a Ṛṣi by tapas; 2) M. 145. 93. father of Asija and Bṛhaduttha. 3) Vā. 65. 100-2.

वामदेव
Vāmadeva  (VI)--the third Kalpa. M. 290. 3.

वामदेव
Vāmadeva  (VII)--the contemplated being in the 30th Kalpa; also Śarva; Vāma Īśvara leads to Rudralokam. Vā. 22. 25, 32 and 34.

वामदेव
Vāmadeva  (VIII)--the name of the Lord of the Lohita Kalpa. Vā. 23. 70-3.

वामदेव
Vāmadeva  (IX)--a son of Guhāvāsa of the 17th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 177.

वामदेव
Vāmadevas --a branch of Angiras. Vā. 65. 106.

वामदेव्यम्
Vāmadevyam --a Sūkta of the Sāma samhita recited in tank ritual; 1) M. 58. 37. to be uttered in installing a new image. 2) Ib. 265. 27.

वामन
Vāmana  (I)--(also Vāmanaka): the fifteenth incarnation of Hari to do good to Indra. Second of the avatārs (M.P.). 1) Bhā. I. 3. 19; II. 7. 17-18; V. 24. 18 and 23; X. 40. 19; XI. 4. 20. M. 47. 42-46; Vi. III. 1. 42-3; V. 5. 17. Son of Aditi and Kaśyapa: wife was Kīrtī and son Bṛhatśloka: Born on the Vijaya dvādaśi of Bhādrapada (bright) fortnight under the star Śravaṇa at the abhijit hour. After manifesting his true form to Brahmā and Aditi, he changed it to a Brāhmaṇa Brahmacārin. At his initiation ceremony all the gods were present and gave him presents; 2) Bhā. VIII. 13. 6; X. 3. 42; VI. 18. 8-9; VIII. 18. 5-17. went to the sacrificial hall of Bali; after welcoming him,  Bali wanted to know what his desire was. He asked for three feet of ground, and commended him as a worthy descendant of Prahlāda. Notwithstanding Śukra dissuading him, Bali made the desired gift when Vāmana assumed the Viśvarūpa form, and measured the earth with one foot and the svarga with the other. The Gods washed the uplifted foot of Hari and celebrated a great festivity. This brought joy to Jāmbavān. The Asuras began to attack but were roughly handled by Hari's attendants. Finding Bali unable to keep his word, Vāmana said that he should go to hell; 3) Ib. VIII. 18. 20-32; chh. 19-21 (whole) ; X. 62. 2; M. 47. 72. Praised by Bali, by Prahlāda, Vindyāvali, and Brahmā: blessed Bali and assured Prahlāda of future bliss: asked Śuka to complete the sacrifice started by Bali and bestowed the kingdom on his brother Indra: anointed Lord of all the worlds and became known as Upendra. Taken to Heaven in a celestial car when the universe was given to Indra; 4) Ib. VIII. chh. 22 and 23. (whole); Vā. 66. 137. 97. 73, 103; 98. 74-87. According to Br. P. this is the second avatār; 5) Br. III. 37. 5; 72. 73, 77 and 105; 73. 77; IV. 34. 79. Details of the avatār; 6) M. chh. 244-6; 259. 2. Icon of: temple of, in Kurukṣetra. 7) Ib. 244. 2-3; 285. 6.

वामन
Vāmana  (II)--an elephant at one of the four cardinal points to maintain the balance of the worlds; 1) Bhā. V. 20. 39; Vā. 69. 69. son of Irāvatī. 2) Br. III. 7. 292, 328 and 39.

वामन
Vāmana  (III)--a Dānava; 1) Br. III. 6. 5. a son of Danu. 2) M. 6. 17.

वामन
Vāmana  (IV)--a 1000 hooded snake. M. 6. 41.

वामन
Vāmana  (V)--a son of Bhadra, the elephant. Vā. 69. 213. 

वामन
Vāmana  (VI)--a son of Vāmadeva; his wife was Angadā; two sons; Añjanaśyāma and Sāmna who were good looking animals fit for riding by men. Vā. 69. 223-4; Br. III. 7. 339.

वामनक
Vāmanaka --a mountain in Krauñcadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 67; Vā. 49. 61; Vi. II. 4. 50.

वामनगिरि
Vāmanagiri --a mountain sacred to Lalitāpīṭha. Br. IV. 44. 99.

वामनगुहा
Vāmanaguhā --sacred for Śrāddha. Br. III. 13. 92; Vā. 77. 82.

वामनपुराण
Vāmanapurāṇa --a Mahāpurāṇa comprising ten thousand ślokas (a lac of ślokas Vā. P.) (see Vāmanam). Bhā. XII. 7. 24; 13. 7; Vā. 104. 6; Vi. III. 6. 23.

वामनम्
Vāmanam --the Purāṇa of 10000 verses, with the Māhātmya of Trivikrama and dealing with Trivarga in the Kūrma Kalpa; he who gives it in the viṣu of Śarad attains Vaiṣṇavahood (see Vāmanapurāṇa). M. 53. 45-6.

वामनवनम्
Vāmanavanam --on the west is the Utkala and on the east the country of the Āvedins; belongs to the son of Ekabhū. Vā. 69. 240.

वामनस
Vāmanasa --one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 5.

वामरथ्य
Vāmarathyas --Ātreya gotrakāras; Putrikāputras of Atri. M. 197. 3 and 9. 

वाम
Vāma --a horse of the moon's chariot; 1) Vā. 52. 53. sons of Kratu. 2) Ib. 62. 9.

वामा
Vāmā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 19. 73; 44. 140.

वामाक्षी
Vāmākṣī --a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 13. 2.

वामोदा
Vāmodā --a R. of the Bhadrā continent. Vā. 43. 30.

वायव
Vāyava --a branch of Angiras. Vā. 65. 107.

वायवी
Vāyavī --a Varṇa Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 61.

वायवीयम्
Vāyavīyam --a Purāṇa narrated by Vāyu including the māhātmyam of Rudra dealing with Śvetakalpa; of 24000 ślokas; he who copies this and makes a gift of it on the Śrāvaṇa day of the Śrāvaṇa month attains the kingdom of Śiva: is Vāyu Purāṇa. M. 53. 18.

वायव्य
Vāyavya  (I)--(Vāyasa; Vā. P.) a Yāmadeva. Br. II. 13. 93; Vā. 31. 7.

वायव्य
Vāyavya  (II)--a muhūrta of the night. Br. III. 3. 43; Vā. 66. 44.

वायव्या
Vāyavyā  (I)--the region of Vāyu. Bhā. X. 89. 44. 

वायव्या
Vāyavyā  (II)--a mind-born mother. M. 179. 10.

वायस
Vāyasa  (I)--to be fed with srāddha piṇḍa for long life; 1) Br. III. 12. 33; IV. 2. 174. the crow as belonging to Indra, Varuṇa, Yama and Nirṛti; 2) Vā. 101. 171; 108. 31; 111. 40. one of copper, as gift for the ceremonial connected with tank construction. 3) M. 58. 19.

वायस
Vāyasa  (II)--(see Vāyavya): a Yāmadeva. Vā. 31. 7.

वायु
Vāyu  (I)--a God and father of Ilā; 1) Bhā. IV. 10. 2; 14. 26. and Mudā clan of Apsarasas: presented Pṛthu with cāmaras: worshipped through Prāṇāyama in Śākadvīpa; 2) Ib. V. 15. 15; 20. 27. A Lokapāla and father of Bhīma. Took part in the Devāsura wars and killed the Asuras. Deprived of his force by the Asuras; 3) Ib. VIII. 5. 19; 10. 26; 11. 1 and 42; IX. 22. 27. M. 31. 12; 46. 9. 266. 24; Vā. 99. 244. set out on a black antelope against Kṛṣṇa taking pārijāta, but returned afraid of him; 4) Bhā. X. [65 (v)  44]: [66 (v)  27-32]; M. 148. 60-61. his city was visited by Arjuna in search of the dead child of a Dvārakā Brāhmaṇa; 5) Ib. X. 89. 44; Br. IV. 33. 67. Born of Ākāśa: the wind-god loved Añjanā and gave birth to Hanumān: overlord of the winds, formless creatures and of time. Presiding deity of Bhuvarloka and hence Bhuvaspati (also Mātariśva). Addressed by the sages engaged in sacrifice to speak on lokāloka; 6) Ib. II. 20. 1 and 7; 25. 5-14; III. 7. 23, 224-5, 296; 8. 12; IV. 2. 20; 195-7, 212, 245-6. narrates the fourth pāda of the Brahmāṇḍa Purāṇa, 7) Ib. IV. 1. 227; 4. 44. reported to Umā in penance of a lady in her chamber little knowing her to be Ādi in disguise; 8) M. 156. 39. worship of; 9) Ib. 236, 5; 253. 24; 265. 39 and 41. 268. 12. Icon of, mounted on a black deer, 10) Ib. 261. 19; 289. 6. a sthāna of Rudra; 11) Vi. I. 8. 7. father of Manojava and Bhīma; 12) Ib. I. 8. 11; IV. 20. 40. Kṛṣṇa's messenger to Indra. 13) Ib. V. 21. 14-17; 37. 16-28. 

वायु
Vāyu  (II)--is a transformation of ākāśa with the two qualities of śabda and sparśa. Its subtle element is sparśa from which came tejas; 1) M. 3. 24. it is Prāṇa, Apāna and Samāna; 2) Ib. 166. 5. role of, in sustaining life. 3) Vā. 31. 41-5.

वायु
Vāyu  (III)--a Vasu: a son of Dharma and Sudevī. M. 171. 47.

वायु
Vāyu  (IV)--a son of Anuhrāda; 1) Vā. 63. 12; 67. 75. the lord of sabda, ākāśa and bala, 2) Ib. 70. 12. the appointed father of Vṛkodara; 3) Ib. 99. 244. presented Skanda with the banners of the cuckoo and hen. 4) Ib. 72. 45.

वायु
Vāyu  (V)--a tirtha sacred to, in the Sarasvatī. Bhā. III. 1. 22.

वायु
Vāyu Purāṇa --contents of; originally narrated by Brahmā; or Pāśupata Yoga, origin of Linga, glorification of Nīlakaṇṭha; one who does not know this Purāṇa, though learned in all the Vedas and other branches, will not be a man of culture; the whole Purāṇa is full of the greatness of Maheśvara; 1) Vā. 1. 48-205. narrator Vāyu; 2) Ib. 26. 5. (see Vāyavīyam) .

वायुलोक
Vāyuloka --burnt by the Pralaya fire. Br. IV. 1. 153.

वायुस्कन्ध
Vāyuskandha --the residence of Marut Gaṇas. Vā. 1. 134.

वारण
Vāraṇa --the heavenly animal which came down for Haryanga's help. M. 48. 98. 

वारणशैलेन्द्र
Vāraṇaśailendra --Śiva in Kāñcī. Br. IV. 5. 7.

वारणावतम्
Vāraṇāvatam --the city of Hastināpura; Satyabhāmā goes there to complain to Kṛṣṇa often about the death of her father by Śatadhanvā; 1) Vā. 96. 61. here Kṛṣṇa went to perform the last obsequies to the Pāṇḍavas who were reported to have been burnt down. 2) Br. III. 71. 63; Vi. IV. 13. 70.

वारा
Vārā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 32. 17.

वाराणसी
Vārāṇasī --Kāśī: sacred to Hari; 1) Bhā. VII. 14. 31; X. 66. 40. fit for Śrāddha offering, and sacred to Lalitā; 2) Br. III. 13. 101; IV. 44. 93. the capital of Divodāsa devastated by the Rākṣasa Kṣemaka, resulting in the change of capital to Gomatī. The abode of Śiva and Umā after their marriage, and hence the name Avimuktam Kṣetram; 3) Ib. III. 67. 26-62. the goddess enshrined here is Viśālākṣī: a place of pilgrimage; 4) M. 13. 26; 22. 7. capital of Rudraśṛeṇya of the Yadu race: city where Mārkaṇḍeya lived. 5) Ib. 43. 11; 103. 13. Lord became Kṣetrapāla: the Yakṣa Harikeśa performed penance here; 6) Ib. 180. 1-5, 15 and 54. the place of Yogis and Siddhas: death here is release from rebirth; 7) Ib. 180. 72-79. a siddha kṣetra where Śiva and His consort live all the three yugas and make Avimuktam gṛham in Kaliyuga; 8) Vā. 77. 93; 92. 27, 58-59; 99. 315. avatār of Lāngali at, in the 22nd dvāpara; 9) Ib. 23. 198. cursed by Nikumbha to become deserted for 1,000 years; 10) 92. 23-28. burnt down by Kṛṣṇa. 11) Vi. V. 34. 3, 39-41.

वाराणसी
Vārāṇasī Māhātmyam --Śiva addresses Pārvatī on, in taking her out and showing the grandeur and majesty of the forest and garden round about Kāśī; the place of Vidyā dharas, Siddhas and Cāraṇas. Here Bhagavān Piṅgala became Gaṇeśvara and Kṣetrapāla and distributor of food to the residents in the city. He was originally a Yakṣa, son of Pūrṇabhadra. He devoted himself to severe austerities and was blessed by Śiva to be a Gaṇapati. 1) M. ch. 180. It is Avimukta tīrtha for here Śiva is omnipresent and is never absent from there. All sinners who die here become Rudras in time. Śiva stands here like a pillar, motionless till the deluge. Every part of the city is holy. 2) Ib. ch. 181. He who remains here for a month gets the benefit of observing the Pāśupata vow. By living permanently one gets true emancipation. By giving up life at the Maṇikarṇikā ghat one secures the desired goal. Perpetual life in Kāśī leads one to union with Śiva. 3) Ib. ch. 182. Kāśī's importance on account of its sacred stream, the Ganges; survives all deluge; Śiva addresses Pārvatī on the great glory of the kṣetram in terms of Paramayoga, Paramagati and Paramamokṣa. It is a place where people of all varṇas attain immortality. Gifts of cow and other things in this city are always beneficial. 4) Ib. ch. 183. It is the place where Śiva got rid of the curse of Brahmā to roam about with a skull for having cut off the fifth head of the creator. Through the grace of Hari, the skull fell down in Kāśī and broke into a thousand pieces. 5) Ib. ch. 184. It is the burial ground of all the gods, the ground being the Avimukta temple. It is the seat of Brahmā. But it deludes nondevotees. Here Vedavyāsa resided for 12 years observing the vow of silence. At the end of the vow he felt hungry and asked for alms. None was able to feed him. When he was about to curse the city, Śiva and Pārvatī took the human form and entertained him to his satisfaction. Then Vyāsa knew of his guests who remarked that a man of choleric temper like himself should not live in that city. But he was permitted to visit it twice a fortnight on Aṣṭami and Caturdaśī days. 6) Ib. ch. 185. 

वाराह
Vārāha  (I)--(Viṣṇu). An avatār of Hari who raised the earth from the waters, see Varāha, the form which Viṣṇu takes in the Śvetakalpa with four feet, four hands, etc., becomes Samvatsara and assumes the form of Yajña; the four yugas are four feet, the kratus are aṅgas or limbs, the four Vedas are the hands ṛtu, sandhimukhas, two ayanas are the faces and eyes, three parvas are the heads, etc., 1) Bhā. XI. 4. 18; Vā. 23. 103-7; 48. 40; 49. 11; Vi. I. 4. 8, 26. appropriate to water sports; description of; 2) Br. I. 5. 11, ff. helped by Māyā, wife (Chāyā-Vā. P.) out of the recovered earth came mountains and seven worlds; creation of human beings; 3) Ib. I. 5. 19. where Brahmā is said to assume this form. 4) Ib. II. 7. 7-9.

वाराह
Vārāha  (II)--a Mt. afraid of Hiraṇyakaśipu's arms. M. 163. 81.

वाराह
Vārāha  (III)--the 26th kalpa. M. 290. 9.

वाराह
Vārāha  (IV)--the present kalpa; fourteen Manus beginning with Svāyambhuva; name and features explained. Vā. 21. 12, 23, 26 f. Vi. I. 3. 28; II. 1. 43.

वाराह
Vārāhas --a Janapada of the Bhadrā continent. Vā. 43. 22.

वाराह
Vārāha kalpa --in this aeon, Hari took the incarnation of a boar; see Varāha. Bhā. III. 11. 36.

वाराहम्
Vārāham --a Mahāpurāṇa, comprising 24,000 ślokas; 1) Bhā. XII. 7. 24; 13. 7; Vi. III. 6. 23. narrated by Viṣṇu to Kṣoṇi containing the māhātmya of  Mahāvārāha; he who gives it with a golden eagle on the Full Moon day of Madhu reaches oneness with Viṣṇu. 2) M. 53. 39-41.

वाराहमुखी
Vārāhamukhī --a Śakti. Br. IV. 20. 37.

वाराहि
Vārāhi --a Pravara (Angiras). M. 196. 12, 13.

वाराही
Vārāhī  (I)--a surname of Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 19.

वाराही
Vārāhī  (II)--a Śakti; a mind-born mother. 1) Br. IV. 19. 7; 20. 37; M. 179. 11. Icon of, with buffalo mount. 2) Ib. 261. 30.

वाराही
Vārāhī  (III)--a R. of the Varāhadvīpam. Vā. 48. 39.

वारि
Vāri --a transformation of tejas or fire; has four qualities, sound, touch, form and taste (rasa). M. 3. 25.

वारिधार
Vāridhāra --a Mt. in Bhārata varṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 16.

वारिधारा
Vāridhārā --a queen of Varṣa Ṛtu. Br. IV. 32. 29.

वारिमूल
Vārimūlas --a class of deities of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. M. 9. 24.

वारिमेजय
Vārimejaya --a son of Akrūra. M. 45. 29.  Vāriṣeṇa--a Kinnara with human face. Vā. 69. 35.

वारिसार
Vārisāra --a son of Candragupta Maurya and father of Aśokavardhana. Bhā. XII. 1. 13.

वारुण
Vāruṇa  (I)--one of the nine divisions of Bhārata varṣa. Br. II. 16. 9; M. 114. 8; Vā. 45. 79. Vi. II. 3. 7.

वारुण
Vāruṇa  (II)--a muhūrta of the day; 1) Br. III. 3. 40; Vā. 66. 41. offer of piṇḍa in the śrāddha. 2) Ib. 111. 40.

वारुणक्रतु
Vāruṇakratu --Brahmā took the Vāruṇi body and offered his śukra (semon) to Agni to beget sons; hence eight sons who are ṛṣis; Bhṛgu, Angiras, Marīci, Pulastya, Pulaha, Kratu, Atri, and Vasiṣṭha; all devas and yajñaṅgas in the shape of human forms were present; also Vedas as well as lakṣaṇa, svara, sthopa, nirukta, devakanyas, deva-patnis, devamātaras, all in human form. Vā. 65. 18-30.

वारुण
Vāruṇa nakṣatram --fit for śrāddha offering. Vā. 82. 13. Br. III. 18. 12.

वारुण
Vāruṇa Bhṛgus --descendants of Bhṛgu adopted by Varuṇa from Yajña. Vā. 65. 39.

वारुण
Vāruṇa mantras --used for ceremonials of digging tanks; 1) M. 58. 25. for planting trees and shrubs; 2) Ib. 59. 12. to ward off the evils of the state. 3) Ib. 234. 6. 

वारुणम्
Vāruṇam padam --the region of God Varuṇa, attained by one who gives the Viṣṇu Purāṇa in Āṣāḍha; 1) M. 53. 17. attained by one who performs the Dṛḍhavrata. 2) Ib. 101. 44.

वारुणम्
Vāruṇam vratam --of kings; to punish sinners. M. 226. 5.

वारुणहोमम्
Vāruṇahomam --in the course of the gift of Sapta sāgara. M. 287. 10.

वारुणि
Vāruṇi  (I)--a siddha. Bhā. VI. 15. [14].

वारुणि
Vāruṇi  (II)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 234.

वारुणी
Vāruṇī (devī)  (I)--came out of the churning of the Kṣīroda and was appropriated by the Asuras; 1) Bhā. VIII. 8. 30; Vi. I. 9. 94. Devas cherished her and became suras; 2) Br. IV. 9. 67-8. the goddess attending on Śeṣa. 3) Vi. II. 5. 18. presented liquor to Baladeva in the Brindāvana. 4) Ib. V. 25. 2.

वारुणी
Vāruṇī (madirā)  (II)--drunk by Balarāma and gopīs, being sent by Varuṇa; 1) Bhā. X. 65. 19. drunk by the Yadus who became intoxicated and killed one another. Stupefied by it, all the Yādava tribes fought with one another and killed themselves; 2) Ib. I. 15. 23; III. 4. 1-2. came out of the churning of the ocean. 3) M. 249. 61. 

वारुणी
Vāruṇī  (III)--the region sacred to Varuṇa. Bhā. X. 89. 44.

वारुणी
Vāruṇī  (IV)--(also known as Puṣkariṇī) a daughter of Araṇya Prajāpati; a wife of Cakṣuṣa, and mother of Cākṣuṣa Manu; sister of Udaka who attained Varuṇahood. Br. II. 36. 102-4; Vā. 62. 89.

वारुणी
Vāruṇī  (V)--a Varṇa Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 61.

वारुणी
Vāruṇī  (VI)--a mind-born mother; on the fish with the serpent with pāśa or noose. M. 179. 10; 286. 9.

वारुणीम्
Vāruṇīm tanum --composed mostly of water; Brahmā took it in Vāruṇi kratu; 1) Vā. 65. 26. celebrated at the first Tretāyuga. 2) Br. II. 13. 84.

वार्क्षम्
Vārkṣam --one of the six kinds of forts. M. 217. 7.

वार्क्षी
Vārkṣī --the daughter of trees, given in marriage to the ten Pracetas as. Dakṣa was their son. Bhā. VI. 4. 15-17.

वार्ता
Vārtā --produced by Brahmā; according to Prahlāda, should be a means to realise Hari; profession of Vaiśyas. Fourfold--kṛṣi, vāṇijyam, go-rakṣa, and kusīda (usury). 1) Bhā. III. 12. 44; VII. 6. 26; 11. 16; X. 24. 21. Br. I. 1. 92; Vā. 49. 117; 57. 89; 58. 25; 59. 36; 61. 160 and 166. Began in the Tretāyuga and disappears towards the close of the Kali; not known in Puṣkaradvīpa. 2) Br. II. 19. 121. 30. 3 and 8; 32. 40; 35. 187 and 195; III. 74. 210-2. Vi. II. 4. 83. Origin of commerce; came into being after the beginning of the Tretāyuga  when the grāmāraṇya corns were not enough and when people wanted something more to live on; with vārtā came maryādā and conventions of society; 3) Vā. 8. 159, 202; Br. II. 7. 151. Vi. I. 6. 20 and 22. symbolical of Devī; 4) Ib. I. 9. 121. a vidyā. 5) Ib. V. 10. 27-28.

वार्ताकम्
Vārtākam --brinjal, not fit for śrāddha. Vā. 78. 48.

वार्तालि
Vārtāli --a name of Lalitā; a Śakti. Br. IV. 17. 19; 20. 34 and 37.

वार्त्तस्
Vārttas --one of the three Rākṣasa clans, moving about in day time as opposed to Niśācaras. Br. III. 8. 61.

वार्त्र
Vārtra --the name of the tenth battle between the Devas and Asuras (Vārta-Vā. P.). Br. III. 72. 75; Vā. 97. 76.

वार्धुषि
Vārdhuṣi --a money-lender, unfit for pankti feeding and for śrāddha. Br. III. 15. 53; 19. 30.

वार्षपर्वणी
Vārṣaparvaṇī  (I)--Śarmiṣṭhā (s.v.). Vā. 68. 23.

वार्षपर्वणी
Vārṣaparvaṇī  (II)--a daughter of Svarbhānu. Vi. I. 21. 7.

वार्षव्रतम्
Vārṣavratam --leads to the world of Śiva; consists of dedication of a bull in the month of Kārtika. M. 101. 65. 

वार्षायणि
Vārṣāyaṇi --a seer. Vā. 34. 63.

वार्ष्टक
Vārṣṭaka --(Dhārṣṭaka) the line of Dhṛṣṭa. Vi. IV. 2. 4.

वार्ष्णायना
Vārṣṇāyanās --Dhūmra Parāśaras. M. 201. 38.

वालखिल्य
Vālakhilya --the name of a Samhitā imparted by Bāṣkali to Bālāyani and others. Bhā. XII. 6. 59.

वालखिल्य
Vālakhilyas --a class of seers, 60,000 in number, born of Kratu: 1) Bhā. III. 12. 43; IV. 1. 39; V. 21. 17; Br. I. 2. 27; Vi. I. 10. 11; II. 10. 22. advised Citraratha, who fell to the ground to gather Kauśika's bones to throw them into the Sarasvatī and get redemption; 2) Bhā. VI. 8. 40. They go in front of the Sun from his rise to his setting, singing his glory; 3) Ib. XII. 11. 49; Br. II. 11. 37; 21. 115; 23. 28 and 49, M. 126. 28; Vā. 2. 27; 23. 159; 28. 31; 50. 168; 52. 26 and 49; 54. 8; 55. 41; 59. 91. live on air; sages by tapas; authors of certain Samhitas; live in Brahmaloka; 4) Br. II. 25. 4; 26. 43; 32. 99; 35. 71 and 94; III. 1. 55; 15. 16; IV. 2. 216. Ṛṣis by tapas. 5) M. 126. 45; 145. 93; 200. 8. Of the category of Sāvarna; 6) Vā. 61. 62, 84. were born out of kuśa grass and endowed with all powers in Vāruṇi yajña; 7) Ib. 65. 55; 101-213. Puṇyā and Sumatī are younger sisters of. 8) Ib. 28. 33.

वाला
Vālā --a R. from the Vindhyas. Br. II. 16. 33.

वालाग्रम्
Vālāgram --eight times the measurement of Trasareṇu (s.v.). M. 258. 17. 

वालि
Vāli  (I)--a son of Virajā (the daughter of Ṛkṣa) and Mahendra. Crowned king of Kiṣkinda and ruled with Sugrīva; wife Tārā and son Angada: crossed the seas, vanquished Rāvaṇa at Puṣkara, and agreed to be his ally on his request; performed Vedic yajñas, learned in the Vedic lore; applauded by Nārada; 1) Br. III. 7. 214-48. killed by Rāma. 2) Bhā. IX. 10. 12; Vi. IV. 4. 96.

वालि
Vāli  (II)--an Asura in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. M. 161. 81.

वालि
Vāli  (III)--an avatār of the Lord in the 13th dvāpara in the Vālakhilyāśrama of the Gandhamādana with tapasvin sons. Vā. 23. 159.

वालुकेश्वर
Vālukeśvara --a name of Śiva. Vā. 60. 69.

वालुवाहिनी
Vāluvāhinī --a R. of the Bhārata varṣa. Vā. 45. 100.

वाल्मीक
Vālmīka(c) --noted for horses. Br. IV. 16. 17.

वाल्मीकि
Vālmīki  (I)--originally born out of an ant-hill, born again of Carṣaṇī and Varuṇa. In his āśrama, Śītā was left when pregnant. There she gave birth to two sons whom the sage brought up; 1) Bhā. VI. 18. 5; IX. 11. 10-11, 15; Br. III. 36. 6. author of Rāma's story; of the family of Bhārgava; 2) M. 12. 51. heard it from Nārada who got it from Brahmā. 3) Ib. 53. 71-2. Vedavyāsa of the 26th dvāpara; 4) Vi. III. 3. 18. present at Rāma's abhiṣeka. 5) Ib. IV. 4. 100. 

वाल्मीकि
Vālmīki  (II)--the father of Rohiṇi and Panavī. Vā. 96. 161.

वाशिष्ठी
Vāśiṣṭhī --R. a mahānadī sacred to Pitṛs. Vā. 108. 79.

वासचूर्णिनी
Vāsacūrṇinī --a Mother Goddess. M. 179. 28.

वासना
Vāsanā --a wife of Arka, a Vasu. Bhā. VI. 6. 13.

वासव
Vāsava  (I)--is Indra (s.v.) protects gems in the Kakudmān hill in Śālmalidvīpa: draws water for rain from Jaladhāra mountain in Śākadvīpa; 1) Br. II. 18. 44; 19. 42 and 86; M. 37. 2. and 7; Vi. I. 22. 6; V. 30. 46. overlord of the Maruts: killed the pupils of Sukarman for learning the samhitā on forbidden days: set up Vāyu to lead off Sagara's horse to Rasātala; 2) Br. II. 35. 36; III. 8. 5; 28. 72; 53. 1; IV. 9. 5 and 19; 13. 30; 20. 49; Vā. 70. 5. son of Aditi, protects Prayāgā; 3) M. 104. 9; 134. 6; 244. 38. gave by a vara two good disciples to Sukarma (s.v.) to pacify his anger at the loss of his pupils. 4) Vā. 61. 32.

वासव
Vāsava  (II)--a muhūrta of the after-noon; 1) Br. III. 3. 39. a deva of the Auttama Manu. 2) Vā. 62. 32; 66. 40.

वासवी
Vāsavī --(Satyavatī): the mind-born daughter of Pitṛs; became Matsyayoni; wife of Parāśara; from her was born Vyāsa as fire from Araṇi. Bhā. I. 4. 14; 6. 38; Vā. 1. 40. 

वासवी
Vāsavī Purī --the city of Vāsava on the east of the Mānasottara hill, south of Yama, west of Varuṇa and north of Soma--also Vasvaukasārā. Vi. II. 8. 8-9.

