Vinayalakṣaṇas --Kaśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 2.

विनशन
Vinaśana  (I)--another name of Kurukṣetra. Bhā. I. 9. 1. 

विनशन
Vinaśana  (II)--the place where the Sarasvatī disappears: on the way from Dvārakā to Hāstinapura. Bhā. X. 71. 21; 79. 23.

विनायक
Vināyaka  (I)--a name of Vighneśvara or Vighneśa (s.v.) 1) Bhā. XI. 27. 29. in charge of Kailāsa hill 2) Br. II. 25. 30. a graha. 3) Ib. III. 7. 161. Asked Paraśurāma not to enter Śiva's abode as he was with Umā. When he forced entry, Vināyaka made him wander all the seven worlds. Paraśurāma knocked his teeth with his axe to the enragement of Pārvatī. Śiva thought of Kṛṣṇa who appeared on the scene with Rādhā. Kṛṣṇa said that Vināyaka should be remembered on all auspicious and other occasions to bring out the desired results. The Śaiva Gaṇeśa became Vaiṣṇava: 4) Ib. III. 41. 17-32, ch. 42, 44. 23. worshipped in all ceremonials as preliminary, in the Bhīṣma dvādaśi, in grahabali; 5) M. 58. 26. 69. 27; 93. 16. when Umā made out of earth an elephantfaced doll and threw it in the Ganges, it became a huge figure, adopted as son both by Umā and Gangā; came to be known as Gāngeya and Gajānana; invested with overlordship of all Vināyakas. 6) Ib. 154. 505; 230. 8. Icon of, with mūṣika mount Ṛddhi and Buddhi on either side; worship of; 7) Ib. 260. 19, 52-5: 261. 38: 266, 42; 269. 56; 274; 15; 289. 7. elephant shaped. 8) Vā. 30. 311; 54. 35; 106. 57; 109. 23.

विनायक
Vināyaka  (II)--a tīrtha sacred to Umā. M. 13. 41.

विनायका
Vināyakās  (I)--a variety of evil spirits; 1) Bhā. II. 10. 38; VI. 8. 24; X. 2. 33; 6. 27. a group of Bhūtas, followers of Śiva 2) Br. II. 25. 114; III. 10. 52.

विनायका
Vināyakās  (II)--different gaṇas like Kūṣmāṇḍa, Gajatuṇḍa and Jayanta; described as having faces of lion and tiger, short and crooked, etc. 1) M. 183. 63-4. a devagaṇa. 2) Vā. 72. 50. 

विनीत
Vinīta  (I)--a son of Uttama Manu. Br. II. 36. 40.

विनीत
Vinīta  (II)--the third son of Prītī and Pulastya. Vā. 28. 22.

विनेयु
Vineyu --a son of Bhadrāśva. M. 49. 5.

विन्द
Vinda --a prince of Avanti, a son of Rājādhidevī and brother of Anuvinda; 1) Vā. 96. 157; Vi. IV. 14. 43. under the influence of Duryodhana (as also Anuvinda) the brothers wanted to give their sister in marriage to Duryodhana, and not to Kṛṣṇa whom she loved: stationed by Jarāsandha at the southern gate of Mathurā and Gomanta during their respective sieges. 2) Bhā. X. 58. 30; 50. 11[3]; 52. 11[9]; Br. III. 71. 158.

विन्दावन
Vindāvana --sacred to Rādhā. M. 13. 38.

विन्ध्य
Vindhya  (I)--a Mt. (Kulaparvata-Vā. P.) in Bhārata varṣa. Here Dakṣa performed tapas; 1) Bhā. V. 19. 16; VI. 4. 20; Vi. II. 3. 3. a Kulaparvata sacred for Śrāddha offerings. 2) Br. II, 16. 19; III. 7. 356; 13. 34; M. 114. 18; Vā. 45. 89; 58. 81; 69. 239; 77. 34; 88. 199; 96. 38. Here Haihaya came for hunting: Kṛṣṇa went there in search of Prasena; 3) Br. III. 26. 25; 71. 39. sacred to Vindyādhivāsinī and the Pitṛs; 4) M. 13. 39; 22. 66. caused by Agastya to bow down and not to rise in height; 5) Ib. 61. 51. joining with the Ganges is more sacred than Kurukṣetra; 6) Ib. 106. 49. rivers originating from; 7) Ib. 114. 27-8; Vā. 45. 103. obstructed by it the Gaṅgā enters the sea; 8) M. 121. 51; Vā. 47. 50. Goddess of night was asked to seek shelter in the Vindhyas after she left Umā's body. 9) M. 157, 17, 19.

विन्ध्य
Vindhya  (II)--a son of Raivata Manu. Bhā. VIII. 5. 2. 

विन्ध्यक
Vindhyakas --the tribes of the Vindhya region. Br. III. 74. 186; M. 114. 51 and 54.

विन्ध्यचूलिक
Vindhyacūlikas --(c) a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 48.

विन्ध्यमथन
Vindhyamathana (niṣūdana)  and (mardana)--is Agastya. Br. IV. 10. 76; 32. 28 and 48.

विन्ध्यमूलिक
Vindhyamūlikas --of the Dakṣiṇāpatha. Vā. 45. 126.

विन्ध्यमौळीय
Vindhyamauḷīyas --(c) a southern country. Br. II. 16. 58.

विन्ध्यशक्ति
Vindhyaśakti --a son of Kilakila (Kaiṅkila YavanaVi. P.) succeeded by Vaidiśaka kings; 1) Br. III. 74. 178. ruled for 96 years; 2) Vā. 99. 365. father of Purañjaya. 3) Vi. IV. 24. 56.

विन्ध्यसेन
Vindhyasena --a son of Kṣemajit, ruled for 28 years. M. 272. 8.

विन्ध्याधिवासिनी
Vindhyādhivāsinī --the Goddess enshrined in the Vindhyas. M. 13. 39.

विन्ध्यानिलय
Vindhyānilayas --a tribe on the border of the Vindhyas. Vā. 62. 124.

विन्ध्यापरान्ति
Vindhyāparānti (ta) kas --(c) people bordering the Vindhyas on the western side. Br. III. 73. 107; Vā. 98. 106. 

विन्ध्यारे
Vindhyāre --one of the sixteen śaktis of Lalitā. Br. IV. 35. 99.

विन्ध्यावलि
Vindhyāvali --the queen of Bali, who participated in his gift to Vāmana. Seeing Bali bound with cords, she appealed to Hari; 1) Bhā. VIII. 20. 17; 22. 19-20. mother-in-law of Anaupamyā wife of Bāṇa; had a daughter called Kumbhīnasī; both of them ill-treated Bāṇa's wife. 2) M. 187. 40.

विन्ध्याश्व
Vindhyāśva --a son of Indrasena and father of twins by Menakā. M. 50. 6-7.

विपक्व
Vipakva --a Marīci god. Br. IV. 1. 58.

विपण
Vipaṇa --a companion of Puramjana, allegorically the organ of speech (see Mukhyā). Bhā. IV. 25. 49; 29. 11.

विपश्चि
Vipaści --Devendra of Svārociṣa epoch. Vi. III. 1. 10.

विपश्चित
Vipaścita --a god of the ten branches of the Sukarmāṇa group of devas. Br. IV. 1. 88; Vā. 100. 92.

विपाद
Vipāda --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 4.

विपाद
Vipāda(ka)s --a class of Piśācas: nude and drinkers of blood in the field of battle. Br. III. 7. 377 and 399. 

विपादांगारिकस्
Vipādāṃgārikas --a Piśāca gaṇa, drink the blood shed in wars. Br. III. 7. 382 and 399; Vā. 69. 263.

विपादी
Vipādī --a group of Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 377.

विपाप्मा
Vipāpmā --a son of Āyu. M. 24. 35.

विपाशा
Vipāśā  (I)--visited by Balarāma; 1) Bhā. X. 79. 11. R. of the Plakṣadvīpa, 2) Br. II. 19. 19; Vi. II. 4. 11; III. 14. 18. from the Himālayas, 3) Br. II. 16. 25. in Bhāratavarṣa; 4) Ib. II. 12. 15; Vā. 45. 96, 99. sacred to Amoghākṣī and the pitṛs. 5) M. 13. 35; 22. 23.

विपाशा
Vipāśā  (II)--one of the 16 wives of Havyavāhana; 1) M. 51. 14; Vā. 29. 14. in the chariot of Tripurāri. 2) M. 133. 23.

विपुरम्
Vipuram --ety. one who is void of dvandva, happiness and misery, cold and heat, etc. Vā. 4. 28.

विपुल
Vipula  (I)--a son of Vasudeva and Rohiṇī. Bhā. IX. 24. 46.

विपुल
Vipula  (II)--a Mt. sacred to Vipulā; a Viṣkambhaparvata, 1) M. 13. 36; Vā. 35. 16. to the west of Ilāvṛta. 2) Vi. II. 2. 18.

विपुल
Vipula  (III)--a son of Maṇivara. Vā. 69. 159. 

विपुला
Vipulā  (I)--the Goddess enshrined at Vipula. M. 13. 36.

विपुला
Vipulā  (II)--the sabhā of Kubera; description of; here is Puṣpaka, the Vimāna; around are the ten cities of the Gandharvas in the east, thirty cities of the Yakṣas in the west, and a hundred cities of the Kinnaras in the south. Vā. 41. 5-11, 20, 24, 27-8.

विपृथु
Vipṛthu  (I)--a son of Citraka; 1) Br. III. 71. 114; Vā. 96. 113; Vi. IV. 14. 11. stationed by Kṛṣṇa at the northern gate of Mathurā for defence against Jarāsandha; was on the right detachment of Kṛṣṇa's army; 2) Bhā. X. 50. 20 [3]; [50 (v) 12]. killed in the Yādava contest at Prabhāsā. 3) Vi. V. 37. 46.

विपृथु
Vipṛthu  (II)--a son of Aśvinī and Akrūra. M. 45. 32.

विपृष्ठ
Vipṛṣṭha --a son of Vasudeva and Dhṛtadevā. Bhā. IX. 24. 50.

विप्र
Vipra  (I)--a son of Sṛtaṃjaya, and father of Śuci. Bhā. IX. 22. 47; Vi. IV. 23. 5.

विप्र
Vipra  (II)--a son of Śiṣṭi and Succhāyā. Vi. I. 13. 2.

विप्रचित्
Vipracit (Vipracitti) --chief among the 100 sons of Danu, married Simhikā who bore one hundred and one sons collectively called Simhikeyas. Father of Rāhu; a follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra. Took part in the Devāsura  war between Bali and Indra, but was asked by Bali to refrain from battle; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 31 and 37; 18. 13; 10. 19 and 31; VII. 2. 5; VIII. 10. 19; 21. 19; M. 6. 16, 25; Vi. I. 9. 107; 15. 141; 21. 6, 10-12. in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu; 2) M. 161. 79. in the churning of the ocean; 3) Ib. 245. 31; 249. 67. in the guise of a standard killed by Mahendra in Kolāhalā war: 4) Ib. 47. 52. the overlord of the Dānavas; the brother of Dhvaja who was killed by Indra; had his aim in the dhvaja or standard. 5) Br. III. 5. 13; 6. 1 and 18; 8. 7: 72. 85; Vā. 67. 60; 70. 7; 97. 85.

विप्रचित्ति
Vipracitti  (I)--an Apsaras with the sun in Hemanta. Vā. 52. 18.

विप्रचित्ति
Vipracitti  (II)--a servant of Hiraṇyakaśipu. Vi. I. 19. 52.

विबुध
Vibudha --a son of Devamīḍha (ṭha, Vā. P.); father of Mahādhṛti. Br. III. 64. 12; Vā. 89. 12; Vi. IV. 5. 27.

विभव
Vibhava --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 232.

विभाव
Vibhāva --a deva. Br. II. 13. 95; Vā. 31. 9.

विभा
Vibhā (varī)  (I)--the city of Varuṇa, entered by Hiraṇyakaśipu; 1) Bhā. III. 17. 26. sun sets here when it is mid-day in Amarāvatī, and rises when it is mid-day in Saumyakam. 2) Br. II. 21. 33-9. 

विभावरी
Vibhāvarī  (II)--the city of Soma in the Mānasa on the north of Meru. Bhā. V. 21. 7; Br. II. 21. 33; Vā. 50. 90; Vi. II. 8. 9; M. 124. 24.

विभावरी
Vibhāvarī  (III)--same as Puṇḍra; a R. of Kuśadvīpa. M. 122. 73.

विभावरी
Vibhāvarī  (IV)--the Goddess of Night: invoked by Brahmā to enter into Umā's body until she should be able to beget Guha. By so doing, the Night could get an amśa of the Devī and will be praised as Devī. She went to Menā, entered her eyes when the latter gave birth to Umā early in the morning; then entered Umā after her penance; hence dark in colour; Brahmā asked the goddess to go with the lion to the Vindhyas and reside there. M. 154. 57-96; 426-588: chh. 155-6.

विभावसु
Vibhāvasu  (I)--a Vasu worshipped for tejas; 1) Bhā. II. 3. 3; XI. 26. 3. wife Uṣā who bore three sons, Vyuṣṭha, Rociṣa and Ātapa; 2) Ib. VI. 6. 11 and 16. fought with Mahiṣa in the Devāsura war. 3) Ib. VIII. 10. 32.

विभावसु
Vibhāvasu  (II)--a son of Danu; a follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra. Bhā. VI. 6. 30; 10 [20].

विभावसु
Vibhāvasu  (III)--a son of Mura (s.v.). Bhā. X. 59. 12.

विभावसु
Vibhāvasu  (IV)--a name of Sūrya. Br. II. 21. 83.

विभावसु
Vibhāvasu  (V)--a Pratardana god. Br. II. 36. 30. 

विभावसु
Vibhāvasu  (VI)--was abandoned by his wife Dyutī for Soma; 1) M. 23. 24. Yayāti of Kuruvamśa compared to. 2) Ib. 35. 8.

विभावसु
Vibhāvasu  (VII)--the king of elephants. Vā. 69. 237.

विभास
Vibhāsa  (I)--a Yāmadeva. Br. II. 13. 92; Vā. 31. 6.

विभास
Vibhāsa  (II)--a Vamśavartin god. Br. II. 36. 30.

विभास
Vibhāsa  (III)--one of the twenty Amitābha gaṇas. Br. IV. 1. 16; Vā. 100. 16.

विभीषण
Vibhīṣaṇa  (I)--one of Bhaṇḍa's eight councillors. Br. IV. 12. 12.

विभीषण
Vibhīṣaṇa  (II)--a son of Viśravas and Kaikaśī, and a friend of Rāma. On the advice of Rāma, performed funeral rites to his kith and kin, according to established conventions. Was made king of Lankā by Rāma. Held the cāmara when Bharata carried pādukā of Rāma; 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 37; IX. 10. 16, 29 and 43. knew the yoga power of Hari and attained salvation by satsanga; of superior bhakti; 2) Ib. II. 7. 45; XI. 12. 5; Br. III. 34. 39. a brother of Rāvaṇa; 3) Ib. III. 8. 47. was present at Rāma's abhiṣeka. 4) Vi. IV. 4. 99.

विभु
Vibhu  (I)--a name of Hari. Bhā. III. 9. 16.

विभु
Vibhu  (II)--a son of Dakṣiṇā and a Tuṣita god. Bhā. IV. 1. 7-8. 

विभु
Vibhu  (III)--a name of Śiva. Bhā. IV. 4. 9.

विभु
Vibhu  (IV)--a son of Prastāva (i); wife Ratī, and son Pṛthusena. Bhā. V. 15. 6; Br. II. 14. 67.

विभु
Vibhu  (V)--a son of Bhaga and Siddhi. Bhā. VI. 18. 2.

विभु
Vibhu  (VI)--a son of Vedaśiras and Tuṣitā. From him 88,000 sages learnt celibate life. Bhā. VIII. 1. 21-22.

विभु
Vibhu  (VII)--the Indra of the Raivata epoch. Bhā. VIII. 5. 3; Br. II. 36. 61; Vi. III. 1. 20.

विभु
Vibhu  (VIII)--a name of Brahmā. Bhā. IX. 3. 29; X. 1. 18.

विभु
Vibhu  (IX)--agni (Dhiṣṇi). Br. II. 12. 20.

विभु
Vibhu  (X)--a deva. Br. II. 13. 95; Vā. 31. 8.

विभु
Vibhu  (XI)--a sādhya god. Br. III. 3. 17; Vā. 66. 16.

विभु
Vibhu  (XII)--the son of Satyaketu; father of Suvibhu. Br. III. 67. 75; Vā. 92. 71. Vi. IV. 8. 20.

विभु
Vibhu  (XIII)--one of the twenty Amitābha gods. Br. IV. 1. 16; Vā. 100. 16. 

विभु
Vibhu  (XIV)--a son of Pratyūṣa, a Vasava; 1) M. 5. 27. a Sādhya. 2) Ib. 203. 12.

विभु
Vibhu  (XV)--a son of Śrutamjaya, ruled for 28 years. M. 271. 24.

विभु
Vibhu  (XVI)--(Vasu) a grandson of Svāyambhuva. Vā. 31. 17; 33. 9.

विभु
Vibhu  (XVII)--a son of Pratāvī (Prāstāvī-Vi. P.). Vā. 33. 57; Vi. II. 1. 37.

विभूति
Vibhūti --a name of Śrī (Lakṣmī). Her abode in the chest of the Lord; wife of Hari. Bhā. I. 18. 20; III. 16. 20; 28. 26; V. 20. 40; VI. 16. 25; 19. 8.

विभूतिधारि
Vibhūtidhāri --is Śiva with the sacred ash smeared all over his body. Br. III. 32. 13; Vā. 55. 45.

विभूतिद्वादशी
Vibhūtidvādaśī --in honour of Viṣṇu; in the months of Kārtika, Caitra, Vaiśākha, Mārgaśīrṣa, Phālguṇa and Āṣāḍha; gift of a gold fish recommended; the end of the year must close with Lavana parvata dāna; the ten avatārs of Hari with Dattātreya and Vyāsa to be worshipped; 1) M. 99. 1-21. was observed by the courtesan Anangavatī who became the queen of God of Love; 2) Ib. 100. 18-32. doing it on the banks of the Ganges gives one nirvāṇa. 3) Ib. 100. 33.

विभूति
Vibhūtis --of Hari; Indra among gods, Viṣṇu among Ādityas, Bhṛgu among Brahmaṛṣis and so on. Bhā. XI. 16. 9-40; Vā. 101. 329. 

विभृत
Vibhṛta  (I)--a son of Svārociṣa Manu. Br. II. 36. 19.

विभृत
Vibhṛta  (II)--a god of Sukarmāṇa group. Br. IV. 1. 88.

विभ्रम
Vibhrama --a Brahmavādin. Vā. 59. 103.

विभ्राज
Vibhrāja  (I)--the father of Brahmadatta, the king of Pāñcāla; his name was Anagha; he had no son and so he performed austerities; and was blessed by Nārāyaṇa with Brahmadatta. M. 20. 23; 21. 11-16.

विभ्राज
Vibhrāja  (II)--the son of Sukṛta (ti-Vā. P.), and father of Aṇuha. M. 49. 56; Vā. 99. 178; Vi. IV. 19. 42-3.

विभ्राज
Vibhrāja  (III)--the hill of Sākadvīpa; here there is resplendent fire. M. 122. 17-8.

विभ्राजा
Vibhrājās --the pitṛs in the Barhiṣada worlds. M. 15. 1.

विभ्राजित
Vibhrājita --the kingdom to which Puramjana went through the gates, Khadyota and Āvirmukhi, with his friend Dyumat; allegorically bright colour. Bhā. IV. 25. 47; 29. 10.

विभ्रान्त
Vibhrānta --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 238. 

विमनुष्या
Vimanuṣyā --an Apsaras. Br. III. 7. 5.

विमल
Vimala  (I)--a son of Sudyumna and a Lord of Dakṣiṇāpatha. Bhā. IX. 1. 41.

विमल
Vimala  (II)--a son of Devayānī and a Yakṣa. Br. III. 7. 128.

विमल
Vimala  (III)--the son of Jīmūta and father of Bhīmaratha. M. 44. 41.

विमला
Vimalā  (I)--a Rahasyayoginī Devī. Br. IV. 19. 48.

विमला
Vimalā  (II)--the goddess enshrined at Puruṣottama M. 13. 35.

विमला
Vimalā  (III)--a R. from Ṛṣyavān. M. 114. 26.

विमलानन
Vimalānana --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 243.

विमलेश्वरम्
Vimaleśvaram --a tīrtha on the Narmadā sacred to the Pitṛs; 1) M. 22. 8. Lord Vimaleśvara is enshrined here; 2) Ib. 190. 14. here a devaśilā was established by Rudra and death on it takes one to Rudraloka. 3) Ib. 194. 39.

विमान
Vimāna --a temple with eight floors and a number of towers; the toraṇa is of 34 hastas. M. 269. 28, 32, 47. 

विमानम्
Vimānam --Indra took Ditī and the Maruts in it to  heaven; 1) M. 7. 64. Vivasvān took Samjñā with him. 2) Ib. 11. 37.

विमान
Vimānas --vehicles of gods; 1) Vā. 30. 96. built by Viśvakarma. 2) Br. III. 10. 119; 16. 14 and 51; 59. 18; IV. 17. 16; Vā. 66. 30.

विमोचना
Vimocanā (nī) --R. a main stream of Sālmalidvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 28; Vā. 49. 42; Br. II. 19. 46.

विमोह
Vimoha(na) --(Vimocana-Vā. P.) the name of a hell. He who transgresses boundary limits goes to this as also thieves. Br. IV. 2. 147 and 159; Vā. 101. 146, 157.

विंश
Viṃśa  (I) (Vivimśa)--the father of a son Kalyāṇa by name. Vā. 86. 6.

विंश
Viṃśa  (II)--a son of Cakṣuṣa and father of Vivimśaka. Vi. IV. 1. 26.

विंशज
Viṃśaja --the fourth king of Vidiśa. Vā. 99. 368.

विय
Viya (yā) ti --a son of Nahuṣa. Bhā. IX. 18. 1; Br. III. 68. 12; Vi. IV. 10. 1.

विरक्ष
Virakṣa --a son of Danāyuṣa and father of two sons Kālaka and Vara. Vā. 68. 30, 33.

विरज
Viraja  (I)--a son of Pūrṇiman. Bhā. IV. 1. 14. 

विरज
Viraja  (II)--one of the seven sons of Vasiṣṭha--sage of the Cākṣuṣa epoch; 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 41; Br. II. 36. 77; M. 9. 22. attained heaven by tapas. 2) Ib. 143. 38.

विरज
Viraja  (III)--a son of Tvaṣṭri, wife Viṣūci: father of a hundred sons--Śatajit and others, besides a daughter; raised the status of Priyavrata line as Hari did for the greatness of gods. Bhā. V. 15. 15-16; Br. II. 14. 70; Vi. II. 1. 40.

विरज
Viraja  (IV)--a pupil of Jātūkarṇya. Bhā. XII. 6. 58.

विरज
Viraja  (V)--a Prajāpati who offered his daughter Virajā to Ṛkṣa; father of Sudhanvan and Vairājas--pitṛs living by yoga; 1) Br. III. 7. 212; 8. 17; 10. 4. father of Naḍvalā, the queen of Cākṣuṣa Manu; a Rājaṛṣi and a tapassiddha. 2) Ib. II. 30. 40; 36. 105; Vā. 57. 122.

विरज
Viraja  (VI)--a son of Sṛñjaya, brother of Vasudeva. Br. III. 71. 193.

विरज
Viraja  (VII)--one of the four sons in the 30th kalpa of Śarva--red in colour, attire, etc. Vā. 22. 30.

विरज
Viraja  (VIII)--a disciple of Lokākṣi, an avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 135.

विरज
Viraja  (IX)--a son of Vāli, the avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 160.

विरज
Viraja  (X)--a son of Pūrṇamāsa and Sarasvatī; his wife was Gaurī; son Sudhāmā. Br. II. 11. 13; Vā. 28. 10-12; Vi. I. 10. 6. 

विरज
Viraja  (XI)--the name of a Lekha. Vā. 62. 66.

विरज
Viraja  (XII)--the adopted son of Vastāvana. Vā. 96. 190.

विरज
Viraja  (XIII)--a son of Sāvarṇi Manu. Vi. III. 2. 19.

विरजस्क
Virajaska --a son of Manu Sāvarṇi. Bhā. VIII. 13. 11.

विरजा
Virajā  (I)--a daughter of progenitor, Viraja; wife of Ṛkṣa; loved by Mahendra, became mother of Vāli; loved by Sūrya, became mother of Sugrīva. Br. III. 7. 212-15.

विरजा
Virajā  (II)--the mind-born daughter of Ājyapa pitṛs; queen of Nahuṣa and mother of Yayāti; belonging to the Vaiśya gaṇa. Br. III. 10. 95; Vā. 73. 45; 93. 12.

विरजा
Virajā  (III)--a svara śakti. Br. IV. 44. 55 and 96.

विरजा
Virajā  (IV)--a sacred place near Nābhikūpa in Gayā; 1) Vā. 106. 85. no fasting or shaving here. 2) Ib. 105. 25.

विरजा
Virajās --the gods of the Sāvarṇi epoch; 1) Bhā. VIII. 13. 12. Agniṣvātta-pitṛs. 2) Br. III. 10. 75-6; IV. 1. 22.

विरञ्चि
Virañci --introduced paśu himsa in sacrifices. Br. II. 30. 21. 

विरथ
Viratha --a son of Nṛpamjaya. M. 49. 79.

विराग
Virāga --a son of Vāta. Vā. 69. 130.

विराज्
Virāj (Virāṭ-Puruṣa) --the form of the Lord during the period of creation, just emerged from Aṇḍa. 1) Bhā. II. 1. 25; III. 6. 6-34; 7. 22-25; 26. 51. To rouse him to activity gods were created; but he was not roused until the Kṣetrajña along with citta entered the heart and roused the Puruṣa from waters; 2) Ib. III. 36. 54-70; X. 3. 15; XI. 3. 11-12; 17. 13. is Hari who is described as MahāPuruṣa; 3) Ib. XII. 11. 5-26. son of Nara; 4) Br. II. 14. 68. Antarikṣa so called. 5) Ib. II. 16. 17; III. 43. 9.

विराज
Virāja  (I)--a son of Śamīka. M. 46. 27.

विराज
Virāja  (II)--a Marut gaṇa. M. 171. 53.

विराज
Virāja  (III)--(Virāṭpuruṣa; also Samrāt and Manu) 1) Vā. 10. 15. married Śatarūpā; sons Priyavrata and Uttānapāda and two daughters, Ākūtī and Prasūtī; the latter was given to Dakṣa and the former to Ruci to whom twins, Yajña and Dakṣiṇa were born. 2) Br. II. 9. 39.

विराज
Virāja  (IV)--a Mt. north of the Mahābhadra lake. Vā. 36. 33.

विराजस
Virājasa --a Vamśavartin god. Br. II. 36. 29. 

विराट्
Virāṭ  (I)--a Sutapa god. Br. IV. 1. 14.

विराट्
Virāṭ  (II)--is a name of Svāyambhuva Manu. M. 3. 45.

विराट्
Virāṭ  (III)--the son of Nara; 1) Vā. 30. 260; 33. 58; Vi. II. 1. 38. a Pratardana god. 2) Vā. 62. 26.

विराट्
Virāṭ  (IV)--one of the twenty Sutapa gaṇas. Vā. 100. 15.

विराट
Virāṭa --the father of Uttarā: the Matsya king; as a friend of Jarāsandha, besieged the southern gate of Mathurā, and the eastern gate of Gomanta. 1) Bhā. I. 8. 14; 10. 9; X. 50. 11 [3]; 52. 11 [7]. But he joined the Pāṇḍavas against the Kurus, and went to Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse; 2) Ib. X. 78 [95 (v) 9]; 82. 25. in charge of Dakṣiṇāpatha. 3) Br. III. 63. 11.

विराट्पुरुष
Virāṭpuruṣa --Virāja created by Brahmā; Vairāja Manu, his son by Śatarūpā. Vā. 10. 15; Br. II. 9. 39.

विरादप
Virādapa --a Trayārṣeya. M. 196. 43.

विराध
Virādha --a Rākṣasa of the Vitalam. Vā. 50. 28.

विराव
Virāva --an Amitābha god. Br. II. 36. 53. 

विरिञ्च
Viriñca --(Virañcya-Bhā. P.); also Viriñci, a name of Brahmā. Bhā. X. 9. 20; M. 154. 17-54.

विरिञ्चिभवनम्
Viriñcibhavanam --the abode of Brahmā. Br. III. 52. 9; 58. 9; IV. 39. 66.

विरुद्ध
Viruddhas --the gods of the epoch of the Tenth Manu; 1) Bhā. VIII. 13. 22. a gaṇa of the Second Sāvarṇa Manu. 2) Br. IV. 1. 67.

विरूप
Virūpa  (I)--a son of Ambarīṣa, and father of Pṛṣadaśva. Bhā. IX. 6. 1; Br. III. 63. 6; Vā. 88. 6. Vi. IV. 2. 7-8.

विरूप
Virūpa  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 90. 34.

विरूप
Virūpa  (III)--a mantrakṛt of the Angirasa branch. M. 145. 103; Vā. 59. 100.

विरूप
Virūpa  (IV)--not to have matrimonial connections with Angiras and Rathītaras. M. 196. 38.

विरूप
Virūpa  (V)--the formless form attained by a mukta. Vā. 102. 77.

विरूपक
Virūpaka --the leader of the Rākṣasa clan--Nairṛtas, followers of Trayambaka: married Vikacā, daughter of Nīla: their issues were the awkward, disfigured and short figures known as Bhūmirākṣasas. Br. III. 7. 143; Vā. 69. 174. 

विरूपा
Virūpā --came out of the face of Mahādeva. Vā. 23. 5.

विरूपाक्ष
Virūpākṣa  (I)--a son of Danu, and a follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra. Bhā. VI. 10. [20]; Br. III. 6. 11; Vā. 68. 11.

विरूपाक्ष
Virūpākṣa  (II)--another name for Śiva having the sun, moon and fire for eyes. Br. II. 25. 64.

विरूपाक्ष
Virūpākṣa  (III)--a Śiva gaṇa. Br. III. 41. 27.

विरूपाक्ष
Virūpākṣa  (IV)--one of the 11 Rudras; as a lokapāla. M. 5. 29; 153. 19; 194. 19; 266. 27.

विरूपाक्ष
Virūpākṣa  (V)--a Bhārgava gotrakartā. M. 195. 19.

विरूपाक्ष
Virūpākṣa  (VI)--the lord of the south-west direction. Vā. 34. 87.

विरूपाश्व
Virūpāśva --an Angirasa and mantrakṛt. Br. II. 32. 109.

विरोचन
Virocana  (I)--a son of Prahlāda, and father of Bali. Took part in the Devāsura war between Bali and Indra, and fought with Savitā; 1) Bhā. V. 24. 18; VI. 18. 16; VIII. 10. 20 and 29; M. 6. 10; Vi. I. 21. 1. the Daitya king residing in the fifth talam: served as calf for the Asuras to milk the earth: killed by Indra in the Tārakāmaya war. 2) Br. II. 20. 35; 36. 210; III. 5. 41; 72. 79 and 105; M. 10. 21; 47. 48 and 72; 172. 14; 178. 67: 245. 12 and 45. Laughed at by Śukra: in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. 3) Ib. 61. 4-5; 72. 6-10; 161. 78. 

विरोचन
Virocana  (II)--an Asura of the Mahātalam. Vā. 50. 34.

विरोचनकुल
Virocanakula --the family of Bali sent to Pātāla by Vāmana. Vā. 98. 86.

विरोचना
Virocanā --the queen of Tvaṣṭri, and mother of Viraja. Bhā. V. 15. 15; Vā. 84. 19.

विरोध
Virodha  (I)--a son of Vāta, the Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 96.

विरोध
Virodha  (II)--a son of Bāṣkala. Vā. 67. 79.

विलोमन्
Viloman --a son of Vanhi, and father of Kapotaroman. (Br. and Vi. P. make him a son of Kapotaroman). Bhā. IX. 24. 19-20; Br. III. 71. 117; Vi. IV. 14. 13.

विलोहित
Vilohita  (I)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 243.

विलोहित
Vilohita  (II)--one of the 11 Rudras. M. 153. 19.

विलोहित
Vilohita  (III)--the second son of Khaśā (s.v.) with three heads, three feet, three hands, black eyes, etc. Vā. 69. 76, 80-3.

विलोहित
Vilohita (Viloha)  (IV)--a hell, to which go the thieves and those who transgress established rules. Vi. II. 6. 2 and 14. 

विवक्षु
Vivakṣu --a son of Adhisomakṛṣṇa; when Nāgasāhvaya was washed away by floods, he made Kauśāmbī his capital; father of eight powerful sons. M. 50. 78-9.

विवर्ण
Vivarṇa --a kingdom of the east watered by Hlādinī. Br. II. 18. 55; Vā. 47. 52.

विवस्वत्
Vivasvat  (I)--see Sūrya. Bhā. VIII. 13. 8; Vā. 63. 55.

विवस्वत्
Vivasvat  (II)--the name of the sun in the month of Nabhasya (Bhādrapada). Bhā. XII. 11. 38; Br. II. 23. 9; Vi. II. 10. 10. M. 126. 10.

विवस्वत्
Vivasvat  (III)--a son of Aditi: Āditya of the month Śrāvaṇa: a Prajāpati: born of Kaśyapa and Dākṣāyaṇī--see Sūrya; 1) Br. II. 24. 34, 88, 129; III. 1. 6 and 54; 3. 68; 71. 23; M. 6. 4; 11. 2-8; Vā. 52. 91. 65. 53. worship in buildings; 2) M. 253. 43; 268. 21. father of Manu. 3) Vi. IV. 1. 6.

विवस्वत्
Vivasvat  (IV)--a sage of the Cākṣuṣa Manu. M. 9. 23.

विवस्वत्
Vivasvat  (V)--an Āditya. Vā. 3. 3; 66. 66; Vi. I. 15. 131.

विवह
Vivaha --the chief of the fifth Vātaskandha, situated between the Nakṣatras (Ṛkṣa-Vā. P.) and the planets; 1) Br. III. 5. 86; Vā. 67. 118. one of the seven Maruts. 2) M. 163. 32.

विवाह
Vivāha --one of the four sons in the 30th Kalpa of Śarva, red in colour, attire, etc. Vā. 22. 30. 

विवाह
Vivāhas --eight-fold: Brāhma, Daiva, Ārṣa, Prājāpatya, Āsura, Saindhava, Rākṣasa, and Paiśāca; 1) Vi. III. 10. 24; Kṛṣṇa married Rukmiṇī by the Rākṣasa form; 2) Ib. V. 26. 11. the marriage day fit for merudāna: gṛhabali recommended in. 3) M. 83. 8; 93. 83.

विविक्त
Vivikta --(Viviktanāman-Bhā. P.)--a son of Hiraṇyaretas of Kuśadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 14.

विविचि
Vivici --(Vividha-Br. P.): a son of Adbhuta Agni. Vā. 29. 39.

विवित्ति
Vivitti --a Jayādeva. Br. III. 3. 6.

विविद
Vivida --a dānava. Br. III. 6. 6.

विविध
Vividha --(Vivici-Vā. P.): son of Adbhuta Agni, tutelary deity of expiatory penances (prāyaścitta): Father of Arka. Br. II. 12. 41; Vā. 29. 39.

विविंश
Viviṃśa (ka) --a son of Vimśaputra (Vimśa-Vi. P.) and father of Khaninetra. Vā. 86. 6; Vi. IV. 1. 27.

विविंशति
Viviṃśati --a son of Cākṣuṣa, and father of Rambha. Bhā. IX. 2. 24-25.

विविसार
Vivisāra --ruled for 28 years. Vā. 99. 318. 

विवृत्त
Vivṛtta --by the passage of time Kṣetrajña becomes vivṛtta by a single reason; it is likened to a light of Khadyota in extreme darkness; he returns from Avyakta; he is a śarīri and a mahān. Vā. 59. 70-2.

विश्
Viś(ḍ) --see Vaiśya. Bhā. VIII. 5. 41.

विश
Viśa --a Ṛṣi. Vā. 62. 22.

विशठ
Viśaṭha --a son of Revatī and Baladeva. Vi. IV. 15. 20.

विशत
Viśata --a Yāmadeva. Vā. 31. 6.

विशद
Viśada --a son of Jayadratha, and father of Senajit. Bhā. IX. 21. 23.

विशंसन
Viśaṃsana --a hell, intended for makers of kāṇḍa, carpenters, potters, and robbers of gold, physicians, those that burn gardens. Br. IV. 2. 147 and 162; Vā. 101. 147 and 160.

विशल्यकरणि
Viśalyakaraṇi --a medicinal herb in Droṇa hill of Śālmalidvīpa; has the power to bring the dead back to life. Br. II. 19. 39; M. 122. 56; Vā. 49. 35.

विशल्यकरणी
Viśalyakaraṇī --R. in Kalingadeśa near the Amarakaṇṭaka hills also Viśalya, 1) Br. III. 13. 12; Vā. 77. 12. a great and holy river serving the Narmadā. 2) M. 186. 43. 

विशल्यातीर्थम्
Viśalyātīrtham --in the Daṇḍaka forest. Br. III. 13. 107.

विशस
Viśasa (na) --one of the twenty-eight hells--a slaughter house for hypocritical sacrificers of animals; makers of lances, swords and other implements. Bhā. V. 26. 7 and 25; Vi. II. 6. 2 and 17.

विशाख
Viśākha  (I)--a son (brother Vā. P., Vi. P.) of Skanda: an amśa of Skanda-Vā. P. [a son of Agni (Br. and M. P.)]; 1) Br. III. 3. 25; M. 5. 26. Vā. 53. 104; 66. 24; 101. 280. Vi. I. 15. 115. from him originated the planet Sūrya; 2) Br. II. 24. 129. an epithet of Kumāra; 3) M. 159. 3. commander. 4) Ib. 230. 7.

विशाख
Viśākha  (II)--a Mt. on the south of the Mānasa; 1) Vā. 36. 23; temple of Guha at. 2) Ib. 39. 55.

विशाख
Viśākha  (III)--when the sun is in Viśākha, fourth amśa, the moon is then at the head of Kṛttikā. Vā. 50. 196; Br. II. 21. 145; Vi. II. 8. 76-7.

विशाख
Viśākha  (IV)--is Skanda. Bhā. VI. 6. 14.

विशाखयूप
Viśākhayūpa  (I)--a son of Pālaka and father of Rājaka: ruled for 50 years (53 years M. P.). Bhā. XII. 1. 3; Br. III. 74. 125; M. 272. 4; Vā. 99. 312.

विशाखयूप
Viśākhayūpa  (II)--a son of Balāka and father of Janaka. Vi. IV. 24. 4-5. 

विशाखा
Viśākhā --a constellation: Śrāddha performance on that day leads to birth of sons. Br. III. 18. 8; Vā. 66. 50; 82. 9.

विशाप
Viśāpa --a son of Damana, an avatār of the lord in the third dvāpara. Vā. 23. 124.

विशाल
Viśāla  (I)--a son of Tṛṇabiṅdu and father of Hemacandra. Founder of Vaiśāli. Bhā. IX. 2. 33-34; Br. III. 61. 12.

विशाल
Viśāla  (II)--a playmate of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 22. 31.

विशाल
Viśāla  (III)--a tīrtha visited by Balarāma. Bhā. X. 78. 19.

विशाल
Viśāla  (IV)--A Kulaparvata of Ketumālā. Vā. 44. 4.

विशाल
Viśāla  (V)--a nāga of the Vitalam. Vā. 50. 29.

विशाल
Viśāla  (VI)--a very righteous king, a son of Viśravas (Tṛṇabiṅdu-Vi. P.) and Ālambuṣa, the Apsaras; father of Hemacandra; built the city of Viśālā; 1) Vā. 86. 16-7; Vi. IV. 1. 49-50. having no sons, consulted the Brahmans who advised him to give Piṇḍa in Gayā; he did so and got a son; once he saw three men white, red and black in colour in the clouds and asked them who they were; the white man said that he was his father coming from Indraloka, the red was his father who had slain Brahmans and the black was his grand-father who had slain a number of sages; the latter two were in Avīcinaraka and now got  released by the Gayāpiṇḍa of Viśāla; then blessed him with a long life of prosperous reign, sacrifices and attainment of Viṣṇuloka 2) Vā. 112. 7-14. in the end.

विशालक
Viśālaka --a maṇṭapa with 38 pillars. M. 270. 4, 11.

विशालदंष्ट्रिणी
Viśāladaṃṣṭriṇī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 17.

विशाला
Viśālā  (I)--(Badarikāśrama). To this Dhruva went for meditation in the evening of his life. Similarly Nābhi and Merudevī spent their last years here. Bhā. IV. 12. 16; V. 4. 5; XI. 29. 47.

विशाला
Viśālā  (II)--a R. from the Ṛkṣa hill. Br. II. 16. 31.

विशाला
Viśālā  (III)--(Viśālayā) city founded by Viśāla, son of Tṛṇabindu; 1) Br. III. 61. 12; Vā. 86. 17; 112. 7; Vi. IV. 1. 49. no shaving or Upavāsa, at. 2) Vā. 105. 25.

विशाला
Viśālā  (IV)--the wife of Urukṣava (ya): had three sons. M. 49. 39; Vā. 99. 162.

विशाला
Viśālā  (V)--a R. issuing from the Himālayas. M. 114. 21.

विशाला
Viśālā  (VI)--a R. of the Ketumālā country. Vā. 44. 21.

विशाला
Viśālā  (VII)--a daughter of Suyaśā: the most beautiful. Vā. 69. 14. 

विशालाक्ष
Viśālākṣa  (I)--the king of Mithilā: went to Syamantapañcaka for the solar eclipse. Bhā. X. 82. 26.

विशालाक्ष
Viśālākṣa  (II)--a Nāga in the third Talam. Br. II. 20. 30.

विशालाक्ष
Viśālākṣa  (III)--the name of a Śiva gaṇa. Br. III. 41. 27.

विशालाक्ष
Viśālākṣa  (IV)--a Mt. the abode of the Nāgas. M. 163. 79.

विशालाक्ष
Viśālākṣa  (V)--one of the 18 authors on architecture. M. 252. 2.

विशालाक्षी
Viśālākṣī --the Goddess at Benares. M. 13. 26; 185. 38.

विशिख
Viśikha --a son of Śukī and Garuḍa. Br. III. 7. 450.

विशिखा
Viśikhā --a gem. M. 218. 35.

विशुक्र
Viśukra --a younger brother of Bhaṇḍa spoke of Devas as Pāmaras (uncivilised) and of the invasion of a woman. 1) Br. IV. 10. 80; 21. 25. His battle with the Śaktis. 2) Ib. IV. 27. 10-56; 28. 3-106. 

विशुद्धगान्धारी
Viśuddhagāndhārī --a special rāga; presiding deity, Gandharva. Vā. 86. 65-6.

विशुद्धा
Viśuddhās --a group of gods of the X epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 25.

विशेष
Viśeṣas --Mahat and others; from them came the aṇḍa or universe; all water; from this came the fish (Puruṣa) with body. Hiraṇyagarbha with four faces. Vā. 4. 75-8.

विशोक
Viśoka  (I)--a son of Trivakrā by Kṛṣṇa, and devoted to him; the author of Sātvata Tantra for the good women, Śūdras and slaves. A disciple of Nārada. Bhā. X. 90. 34 [1-2].

विशोक
Viśoka  (II)--one of the four sons in the 30th kalpa of Śarva, red in colour, attire, etc. Vā. 22. 30.

विशोक
Viśoka  (III)--a son of Damana, an avatār of the Lord in the 3rd dvāpara. Vā. 23. 124.

विशोकद्वादशीव्रतम्
Viśokadvādaśīvratam --removes one's difficulties and prepares the way for the final bliss; performed in honour of Keśava or Lakṣmī in the month of Āśvayuja: gift of bed with guḍadhenu after the pūja and other observances in the prescribed manner; the gift of guḍa-dhenu on the beginning day of the ayana or days of Viṣu or eclipse, attended by music and dancing; the gift of a sugar cow. M. chh. 81 and 82. 

विशोकम्
Viśokam --a divine forest in the Lohita hill; a garden of the gods. Br. II. 18. 12; III. 7, 102.

विशोकसप्तमी
Viśokasaptamī --to be observed on the sixth day of the white half of Māgha month. M. 74. 2; 75. 1-2.

विशोका
Viśokā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 25.

विश्रवस्
Viśravas  (I)--a son of Pulastya and Iḍivilā and of great tapas. Father of Kubera through Iḍaviḍā (Iḍivilā) one of his four wives. By another wife he had sons--Rāvaṇa, Kumbhakarṇa and Vibhīṣaṇa. Ceḍaviḍā was the name of one of his wives. 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 36-37; VII. 1. 43; IX. 2. 32; 10. 15. Son of Ilavilā (Iḍaviḍā, Iḍivilā) and a sage by tapas. Married Bṛhaspati's daughter. 2) Br. II. 32. 99; III. 8. 38; 61. 11; M. 145. 93. Wives of: Devavarṇanī, Puṣpotkaṭā, Vākā and Kaikasī; the first brought Vaiśravaṇa whom the father named Kubera; Kaikasī gave birth to Rāvaṇa, Kumbhakarṇa, Śūrpanakhā and Vibhīṣaṇa; Puṣpotkaṭa's sons--Mahodara, Prahasta, Mahāpāmśu, Khara; daughter, Kumbhīṇasī; Vākā's sons Triśiras, Dūṣaṇa, Vidhyutjihva; daughter Asalikā. 3) Vā. 70. 32-35, 41, 49, 50.

विश्रवस्
Viśravas  (II)--a Ṛṣi by tapas. M. 145. 93. Vā. 59. 91.

विश्रवस्
Viśravas  (III)--a son of Draviḍā; had a son Viśāla. Vā. 86. 16.

विश्रवस्
Viśravas  (IV)--the father of two gaṇas, Śiva and Sumanas. Vā. 69. 28. 

विश्रान्तकवपु
Viśrāntakavapu --a son of Viśveśā. M. 171. 50.

विश्रुत
Viśruta  (I)--(Viśruti-Br. P.): a Yāmadeva. Br. II. 13. 92. Vā. 62. 12.

विश्रुत
Viśruta  (II)--one of the twenty Amitābha gaṇas. Vā. 100. 17.

विश्रुतवत्
Viśrutavat --a son of Sahasvat, and father of Bṛhadbala; a king. Br. III. 63. 212; Vā. 88. 212.

विश्व
Viśva  (I)--a name of Hari. Bhā. XII. 11. 22.

विश्व
Viśva  (II)--the Gandharva presiding over the month, Tapasya. Bhā. XII. 11. 40.

विश्व
Viśva  (III)--a branch of the Bhārgava gotra. Vā. 65. 96.

विश्व
Viśva  (IV)--a son of Upamadgu. Vi. IV. 14. 9.

विश्व
Viśva  (V)--a Satya god. Br. II. 36. 34.

विश्वकर्मा
Viśvakarmā  (I)--a Prajāpati. His daughter Barhiṣmatī was the wife of Priyavrata. 1) Bhā. V. 1. 24. A son of Vāstu and Āngirasī; wife was Kṛti (Akṛti-Bhā. P.). Father of Manu Cākṣuṣa. 2) Ib. VI. 6. 15. The divine architect skilled in making weapons.  Made vajra of Dadhīci's body and built Indra's abode and erected Sutalam. 3) Ib. VI. 9. 54: 10. 13. VII. 4. 8; VIII. 15. 15; 22. 32. M. 5. 27-8; 58. 33. Fought with Maya in Devāsura war. Two more daughters of his were Samjñā and Chāyā who were married to the Sun god. 4) Bhā. VIII. 10. 29; 13. 8. Vi. III. 2. 2, 8, 10-12. Was ordered by Kṛṣṇa to build a city for the Pāṇḍavas; 5) Bhā. X. 58. 24. built Garuḍa's abode; 6) M. 163. 68: 203. 7. an author on architecture; 7) Ib. 252. 2; Br. IV. 31. 6-7. father of four sons; originator of all śilpas, arts and crafts; 8) Vi. I. 15. 119-20; III. 2. 11. presented Śrī with jewels. 9) Ib. I. 9. 104; Br. IV. 9. 81; 14. 4; 15. 20; 20. 46; 29. 84.

विश्वकर्मा
Viśvakarmā  (II)--a son of Tvaṣṭā and Yaśodharā; father of Maya, and his daughter was Sureṇu; originator of arts and crafts. Br. I. 2. 19; 5. 27. III. 1. 87. 7. 195; 32. 7: 59. 17-21: Vā. 65. 85.

विश्वकर्मा
Viśvakarmā  (III)--divided the earth into seven islands, oceans and hills, Bhūḥ and other worlds; created the people as in the previous kalpas; but the whole was clouded in smoke, in five forms like a light enveloped by a pot; finding no light and all in their place (Nyāsa) was pondering over when a cross current passed that way and resulted in a second universe. Vā. 6. 33-45. 109. 4.

विश्वकर्मा
Viśvakarmā  (IV)--one of the seven important rays of the sun on the south; helps the growth of the Budha planet. Br. II. 24. 66-69.

विश्वकर्मा
Viśvakarmā  (V)--a Vamśavartin god; a son of Prabhāta and Bhuvanā; Lord of Prajāpatis. Br. II. 36. 29; III. 3. 29. 

विश्वकाया
Viśvakāyā --the goddess enshrined at Ambarā. M. 13. 27.

विश्वक्ज्योति
Viśvakjyoti --the first of the 100 sons of Śatajit. Vi. II. 1. 41.

विश्वग
Viśvaga  (I)--a son of Pūrṇiman. Bhā. IV. 1. 14.

विश्वग
Viśvaga  (II)--a son of Pṛthu and grandson of Suyodana. M. 12. 29.

विश्वचक्रम्
Viśvacakram --a gift; a wheel of the world in gold (20 palas to 1000) with Jalaśāyi Viṣṇu and His avatārs, the sages, the four Vedas, the Pañca Bhutās, the Rudras and the Lokapālās placed thereon; to be given as a gift on an auspicious day; daily worship of the cakra yields one plenty of wealth and long life. M. 274. 9: 285. 1-23.

विश्वजित्
Viśvajit  (I)--a sacrifice performed by Bali with the aid of Bhṛgu Brāhmaṇas. Bhā. VIII. 15. 4.

विश्वजित्
Viśvajit  (II)--a son of Satyajit, and father of Ripumjaya; a link in the line. 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 49; Vi. IV. 23. 11-12. A Bṛhadratha king who ruled for 25 years. 2) Br. III. 74. 120.

विश्वजित्
Viśvajit  (III)--one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 6.

विश्वजित्
Viśvajit  (IV)--Janamejaya: a son of Dṛḍharatha. Vā. 99. 111. 

विश्वजित्
Viśvajit  (V)--a son of Bṛhadratha. Vā. 99. 172.

विश्वजित्
Viśvajit  (VI)--a son of Jayadratha; father of Senajit. Vi. IV. 19. 34-5.

विश्वदेव
Viśvadeva  (I)--a Pārāvatā god. Br. II. 13. 95; 36. 13.

विश्वदेव
Viśvadeva  (II)--the Agni at Brahmasthānam. Vā. 29. 28.

विश्वदेवद्यम्
Viśvadevadyam --a Śukradeva. Vā. 31. 8.

विश्वदेव
Viśvadevas --see Viśvedevas. Vā. 62. 12.

विश्वध
Viśvadha --a Vamśavartin god. Br. II. 36. 29; Vā. 62. 26.

विस्वधार
Visvadhāra --a son of Medhātithi of Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 25.

विश्वनन्द
Viśvananda --a disciple of Brahmā. Vā. 22. 16.

विश्वपदम्
Viśvapadam --sacred to the pitṛs. M. 22. 35.

विश्वभव
Viśvabhava --a son of Sahasvān and father of Bṛhadbala. Vi. IV. 4. 111-12. 

विश्वभावन
Viśvabhāvana --one of the four sons in the 30th kalpa of Śarva, red in colour, attire, etc. Vā. 22. 30.

विश्वभुक्
Viśvabhuk --Indra of Śukra devas whose cognates are Asuras. Vā. 31. 11; 57. 91 and 102.

विश्वभृत
Viśvabhṛta --a group of nāḍis of the sun pouring out heat. Br. II. 24. 29; Vā. 53. 22.

विश्वम्
Viśvam --false; like a serpent in rope, and water in the desert, etc. Vā. 104. 39.

विश्वमह
Viśvamaha --a son of Kṛtaśarma. Vā. 88. 181.

विश्वमहत्
Viśvamahat --a son of Viśvaśarma; his wife, Yasodā, the mānasī kanyā of the Pitṛs. Vā. 73. 40.

विश्वमाला
Viśvamālā --a R. from the Vindhyas. M. 114. 27.

विश्वमुखी
Viśvamukhī --the Goddess enshrined at Jālandhara. M. 13. 46.

विश्वमोहिनी
Viśvamohinī --the form which Viṣṇu assumed, and embraced by Śiva, resulting in the birth of Mahāśāsta. Br. IV. 10. 77. 

विश्वम्भरा
Viśvambharā --the earth which covers the whole universe, etc. Its manifestations are Dhṛti, Sthiti, Kṣamā, Kṣoṇī, Pṛthvī, Vasumatī and Rasā. M. 284. 16.

विश्वयोषा
Viśvayoṣā --an Apsaras. Br. II. 33. 18.

विश्वरथ
Viśvaratha --another name for Viśvāmitra. Br. III. 66. 65; Vā. 91. 93.

विश्वरन्धि
Viśvarandhi --(Viṣvagandhi)--son of Pṛthu and father of Candra. Bhā. IX. 6. 20.

विश्वरूप
Viśvarūpa  (I)--a son of Tvaṣṭri and Rocanā (Yaśodharā-Br. P.) adopted by Suragaṇas when their guru Angiras left them. At first he did not agree as Paurodhasa was not a coveted profession. Finally he accepted and initiated Indra into a mantra known as Varma Nārāyaṇātmakam; with this Indra enjoyed once more the Trailokyalakṣmī: Father of Pañcajanī. 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 44-5; ch. 7-8 (whole); V. 7. 1; Br. III. 1. 86. Viśvarūpa had three heads Somapīṭḥa, Surāpīṭḥa, and Annāda. Finding the ācārya giving a part of his sacrificial offerings to Asuras, Indra cut off his heads which became Kapiñjala, Kalavinka and Tittiri birds. His vadha, 2) Bhā. VI. 9. 1-5; 13. 5. in the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu. 3) M. 161. 80.

विश्वरूप
Viśvarūpa  (II)--a Śukradeva (ajita). Br. II. 13. 94; Vā. 31. 7.

विश्वरूप
Viśvarūpa  (III)--a son of Rūpavatī, and devoted to Nārāyaṇa: elected Purohita in the absence of Bṛhaspati who went to the earth due to a curse by sages: Indra quarrelled with him, and the latter repaired to spend his life in penance. Sages cursed Indra for this. Br. IV. 9. 4-8. 

विश्वरूप
Viśvarūpa  (IV)--a name of Triśiras, a son of Tvaṣṭa. Vā. 65. 85.

विश्वरूपा
Viśvarūpā  (I)--in the 33rd Kalpa Sarasvatī became Viśvarūpā with four hands, four feet, four teeth, four eyes, etc. Brahmā prayed to Viśveśa who explained the nature of Sarasvatī as Prakṛti and made aṭṭahāsa when Jati, Muṇḍi and other sons came; after performing austerities for 1000 years they attained Rudrahood. Vā. 23. 36-61.

विश्वरूपा
Viśvarūpā  (II)--wife of Dharma and mother of Dharmavratā. Vā. 107. 2.

विश्वव्यच
Viśvavyaca --the agni in Brahmasthāna. Br. II. 12. 24.

विश्वव्रतम्
Viśvavratam --performer of, becomes Brahmāṇḍādhipati. M. 101. 83.

विश्वशर्म
Viśvaśarma --the father of Viśvamahat. Vā. 73. 40.

विश्वश्रव
Viśvaśravas --one of the seven important rays of the Sun; helps the growth of the planet, Śukra. Br. II. 24. 66; Vā. 53. 45, 48.

विश्वसह
Viśvasaha  (I)--a son of Aiḍaviḍa (Ilivila-Vi. P.) and father of Khaṭvānga. Bhā. IX. 9. 41; Vi. IV. 4. 75-6. 

विश्वसह
Viśvasaha  (II)--a son of Vyuṣitāśva, (Yuṣitāśva-Vi. P.), (Dhyuṣitāśva-Vā. P.), and father of Hiraṇyanābha Kauśalya: a king. Br. III. 63. 206-7; Vā. 88. 206; Vi. IV. 4. 106-7.

विश्वसहस्र
Viśvasahasra --His daughter married Iḍaviḍa. Br. III. 63. 181.

विश्वसाह्वन्
Viśvasāhvan --a son of Mahasvat and father of Prasenajit. Bhā. IX. 12. 7-8.

विश्वसृज
Viśvasṛja --another name for Viśvakarmā. Bhā. X. 75. 32.

विश्वसृजस्
Viśvasṛjas --the sacrifice of creation; continued for thousands of years in the Naimiṣa region (see for a description Yajurveda Brāhmaṇa). Vā. 2. 5-7.

विश्वसृजाम्
Viśvasṛjām satra --the sacrifice of the Prajāpatis. Here Dakṣa insulted Śiva. The sacrifice lasted for a thousand years. The avabhṛta was at the confluence of the Gangā and the Yamunā. Bhā. IV. ch. 2 (whole); 3. 24.

विश्वस्फाटिक
Viśvasphāṭika --the king of Magadha who introduced new varṇas for Kṣatriyas and also kingship. Vi. IV. 24. 61. 

विश्वस्फानि
Viśvasphāni --a Māgadha king equal to Hari in battle: cut at the root of the Kṣatriya order and established his own castes: viz. Kaivartas, Madrakas, Pulindas, Brāhmaṇas, and Pañcakas; said to be an enuch; offerings of, to devas, pitṛs, and Brahmans; died on the banks of the Ganges as an ascetic and went to Indraloka. Br. III. 74. 190-3. Vā. 99. 377-82.

विश्वस्फूर्जि
Viśvasphūrji --a king of Magadha. Bhā. XII. 1. 36.

विश्वस्य
Viśvasya --the place of Samudra agni. Vā. 29. 22.

विश्वा
Viśvā  (I)--a R. in Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 18.

विश्वा
Viśvā  (II)--a daughter of Dakṣa and one of the ten wives of Dharma married by Brāhma form; her sons were Viśvedevas. Bhā. VI. 6. 4. and 7; Br. III. 3. 3 and 30. M. 5. 16-17; 203. 12; Vā. 66. 3, 31; 76. 3; Vi. I. 15. 105.

विश्वा
Viśvā  (III)--one of the 13 wives of Kaśyapa; mother of Yakṣas and Rākṣasas. M. 6. 2; 146. 18.

विश्वा
Viśvā  (IV)--the Goddess enshrined at Viśveśvara. M. 13. 29.

विश्वाचि
Viśvāci --an Apsaras, coupled with Pūrvaciti: with her Yayāti enjoyed in Vaibhrāja nandana: Danced at the appearance of Śrī from the milk-ocean; went with Māyā to counteract Bhaṇḍa's imperialism; 1) Br. III. 7. 15; 68. 70; IV. 9. 78; 12. 25; 33. 19; Vā. 69. 49. 93. 69. Vi. IV. 10. 20. with the Śarat sun; 2) Br. II. 23. 13. in  the sabhā of Hiraṇyakaśipu; 3) M. 161. 74. resides in the sun's chariot in Kārtika. 4) Vi. II. 10. 12.

विश्वामित्र
Viśvāmitra  (I)--A sage of the Vaivasvata epoch; 1) Bhā. VIII. 13. 5. M. 9. 27. was invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira; 2) Bhā. X. 74. 8. came to see Kṛṣṇa at Syamantapañcaka 3) Ib. X. 84. 3; and Parikṣit practising prāyopaveśa. 4) Ib. I. 19. 9. Acted as Purohita at Kṛṣṇa's sacrifice in Kurukṣetra, left Dvārakā for Piṇḍāraka; 5) Ib. XI. 1. 12; X. 90. 46 [2]. Purohita of Jamadagni; the 6th incarnation of Viṣṇu to do away with the Kṣatriyas; became a Brāhmaṇa by tapas. 6) M. 47. 244; 198. 2 and 3.

विश्वामित्र
Viśvāmitra  (II)--(Viśvaratha-Vā. P.): a son of Gādhi and Kuśika (Kucika gotra-Vā. P.). Though born a Kṣatriya, by his tapas he obtained brahmanhood. He had 101 sons. The middle one was known Madhucchandas and hence all sons bore that common name. He asked his sons to regard Sunaśśepa as their eldest brother. The first fifty refused and were cursed to become mlecchas. Madhucchandas and the younger fifty agreed to adopt Śunaśśepa. Visvāmitra blessed them. He had eight other sons like Aṣṭaka. Owing to divisions among his sons, the Kauśika family became different from the Viśvāmitras. There was a change of pravara since adoption was introduced. Father of Śakuntalā through Ūrvaśī. 1) Bhā. IX. 16. 28-37; Br. I. 2. 11; II. 32. 117; 38. 26. III. 66. 58; Vā. 1. 177; 64. 25; 91. 87, 93, 95-6. Helped Triśanku to go to heaven with the mortal body and secured for him a place in the sky. Fought Vasiṣṭha in the guise of a bird concerning Hariścandra, son of Triśanku. Acted as hotri to Hariścandra and was pleased with the fervour of the king and his queen; 2) Bhā. IX. 7. 5-26. when he performed a Yajña, Rāma, son of Daśaratha killed Rākṣasas who disturbed it; 3) Ib. IX. 10. 5. officiated as hota in Paraśurāma's aśvamedha; 4) Br. III. 47. 46; 73. 91. a Kṣatriyadvija--sons and family of. 5) Ib. III. 66. 86; 63. 85-90. Performed tapas near the sea; his wife had her son bound  to her neck and sold him for a hundred cows; Satyavrata released the son to earn the goodwill of Viśvāmitra: Helped by Satyavrata--Triśanku during the 12 years famine, he took him bodily to heaven for it; 6) Vā. 88. 86-8; Br. III. 63. 112. in Dāruvana; 7) Ib. I. 1. 149; II. 27. 103. a Brahmiṣṭa. 8) M. 145. 111.

विश्वामित्र
Viśvāmitra  (III)--the sage presiding over the month of Ūrja; 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 44. with the Śiśira Sun; 2) Br. II. 23-20. with the sun in Phālguna. 3) Vi. II. 10. 18.

विश्वामित्र
Viśvāmitras --(also Kauśikas): Brahmarākṣasas; one of the four clans moving about in the night; 1) Br. III. 8. 59-61; Vā. 69. 195. against Vedas and Yajñas. 2) Ib. 70. 53.

विश्वान्देव
Viśvāndevas --see Viśvedevas. Bhā. II. 3. 4.

विश्वायु
Viśvāyu  (I)--a Vamśavartin god. Br. II. 36. 29.

विश्वायु
Viśvāyu  (II)--one of the six sons of Purūravas. Vā. 91. 52.

विश्वावसु
Viśvāvasu  (I)--a Gandharva got infatuated at the sight of Devahūti playing on the terrace of her house: served as calf for Gandharvas and Apsarasas to milk GandharvaMadhu from earth; 1) Bhā. III. 20. 39; 22. 17; IV. 18. 17. Br. III. 7. 12. IV. 14. 4. praised Hīraṇyakaśipu, the over lord of all worlds: sang the glory of Indra defeating Namuci. 2) Bhā. VII. 4. 14; VIII. 11. 41; XI. 16. 33. 

विश्वावसु
Viśvāvasu  (II)--the Gandharva presiding over the month of Nabha; in the sun's chariot, with the sun in Āvaṇi and Puraṭṭāśi, (śarat season); 2) Vā. 52. 10, 13; 62. 188. in the sun's chariot during the month of Kārtika. 3) Vi. II. 10. 12. ^1 Bhā. XII. 11. 37; Br. II. 23. 10; Vi. II. 10. 9.

विश्वावसु
Viśvāvasu  (III)--a son of Krodhā and a Devagandharva. Br. III. 6. 39.

विश्वावसु
Viśvāvasu  (IV)--a son of Purūravas and Ūrvaśī; 1) Br. III. 66. 23; IV. 20. 48 and 101; Vi. IV. 7. 1. the Gandharva who brought back Ūrvaśī to heaven from earth. 2) Br. III. 66. 16.

विश्वावसु
Viśvāvasu  (V)--a Sādhya. M. 171. 43.

विश्वावसु
Viśvāvasu  (VI)--a Vasu, a son of Dharma and Sudevī. M. 171. 46.

विश्वावसु
Viśvāvasu  (VII)--a Gandharva and the best of speakers; deprived Ūrvaśī and Purūravas of the two sheep. Vā. 91. 16-22; Vi. I. 9. 102; IV. 6. 51.

विश्वावसु
Viśvāvasu  (VIII)--a Gandharva; 1) Vā. 30. 86. an expert in divine music. 2) Ib. 69. 47.

विश्वावसु
Viśvāvasus --a class of musicians who sang the Sāma Veda. Br. III. 1. 25.

विश्वावसुमति
Viśvāvasumati --a Marut gaṇa. M. 171. 53. 

विश्वा
Viśvās  (I)--the sons of Cākṣuṣa Manu. Bhā. VI. 6. 15.

विश्वा
Viśvās  (II)--the ten sons of Dharma and Viśvā. As a result of their penance in the Himālayas, they were blessed to enjoy a part of the Śrāddha offerings: Their duty was to protect the Śrāddha and be its guests. (see Viśvā). Br. III. 3. 80; 12. 3-14.

विश्वा
Viśvās  (III)--residents of Bhuvarloka. Vā. 64. 2; 73. 61; 101. 30.

विश्वेदेव
Viśvedevas --Dharmaputras: (see Viśvāndevas). Ten sons of Viśvā and Dharma: these are childless gods: wait on Indra; worshipped for gain of a kingdom. 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 7; 7. 3; 10. 17; II. 3. 4; M. 171. 48; 217. 48; 246. 54; 247. 10; 5. 17; Vā. 21. 23; 66. 31, 32; Vi. I. 15. 105; Br. II. 38. 2-3; III. 3. 30; 8. 4; 10. 109; 15. 35. Fought with Paulomas in Devāsura war: gods of Vaivasvata epoch. 2) Bhā. VIII. 10. 34; 13. 4; M. 9. 29. Formed the Sadas of Marutta's yajñas: blessed Jyāmagha with a son: sūktas sacred to; 3) Bhā. IX. 2. 28; 23. 39. 4. 4. came with other gods to Dvārakā to ask Kṛṣṇa to go back to Vaikuṇṭha; 4) Ib. XI. 6. 2. Kratu, Dakṣa, Śrava, Satya, Kāla, Kāma, Muni, Purūravas, Ārdravasa, and Rocamāna are their names, live in Bhuvarloka; 5) Br. IV. 2. 28; 20. 46. see Viśvas, ten in number, were Camasādhvaryavas for Soma's rājasūya; 6) M. 17. 14 and 52; 23. 22; 203. 12. performed austerities in the Himālayas, and Pitṛs pleased with them blessed them; Brahmā gave them the first place of honour in the Śrāddha and the second to devas. 7) Vā. 76. 3, 12-14; 106. 59.

विश्वेश
Viśveśa --description of: nirindriya, alingi, nirguṇa, cetana, etc. Cf. Gītā. Vā. 14. 6-11, 13.

विश्वेशा
Viśveśā  (I)--a mind-born daughter of Brahmā. M. 171. 32. 

विश्वेशा
Viśveśā  (II)--her sons by Dharma. M. 171. 48 and 51.

विश्वेशानन्दकाननम्
Viśveśānandakānanam --Benares. M. 185. 68.

विश्वेश्वर
Viśveśvara  (I)--sacred to Goddess Viśvā. M. 13. 29.

विश्वेश्वर
Viśveśvara  (II)--the God enshrined at Benares. M. 184. 69.

विश्वेश्वर
Viśveśvara  (III)--a name of Hari. Bhā. II. 2. 14; Br. III. 41. 42.

विश्वेश्वरी
Viśveśvarī --is Lalitā. Br. IV. 13. 28.

विश्वे
Viśve sādhyas --the sons of Cākṣuṣa Manu (s.v.). Bhā. VI. 6. 15.

विष
Viṣa  (I)--a Śiva god. Br. II. 36. 32.

विष
Viṣa  (II)--an Asura, attacked by Nakuli Devī. Br. IV. 28. 39.

विष
Viṣa  (III)--a son of Danāyuṣa; father of four sons all bent on doing cruelty. Vā. 68. 30, 33.

विषघ्नानि
Viṣaghnāni --details of preparations of antedotes to poisons to ward off evils in the palace. M. 218. 1-38. 

विषङ्ग
Viṣaṅga --a younger brother of Bhaṇḍa well read in nīti treatises, advised that even a woman should not be neglected and war to be embarked upon after proper consultation. 1) Br. IV. 20. 30; 21. 25; 27. 10; 28. 3 and 37. His fight; took to kūṭayuddha and fled for life. 2) Ib. IV. 28. 106 and 114; 25. 14 and 33, 104.

विषधार
Viṣadhāra --a Mt. south of the Mānasa. Vā. 36. 23.

विषम्
Viṣam --produced by the churning of the ocean by the Devas and Asuras. Vā. 54. 49; 62. 180.

विषय
Viṣaya --a kingdom in general; qualities of a good one; 1) M. 217. 1-5. gift of. 2) Ib. 275. 25.

विषयाविषयत्वम्
Viṣayāviṣayatvam --Viṣaya is Brahmā and aviṣaya is kṣetra. Vā. 102. 36.

विषुवत्त
Viṣuvatta--Brahmam  attained through Suṣumnā situated between Iḍa and Piṅgala. Bhā. II. 2. 24[2]

विषु
Viṣu (vam) --see Vaivasvatagati; equinox, distance of; fit time for making gifts; 1) Br. II. 21. 68, 72-3; M. 124. 93; 187. 37; 274. 19; Vā. 50. 125; Vi. II. 8. 74 and 78. occurs between the spring and winter. 2) M. 17. 2; 82. 25; 83. 7; 98. 2. 124. 47.

विषूचि
Viṣūci --queen of Viraja, and mother of a hundred sons and one daughter. 1) Bhā. V. 15. 15. Mother of Viṣvaksena. 2) Ib. VIII. 13. 23. 

विषेण
Viṣeṇa --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 84.

विष्कम्भ
Viṣkambha --a son of Viśveśā. M. 171. 50.

विष्कम्भपर्वत
Viṣkambhaparvatas --hills round about Meru; these are Mandara, Gandhamādhana, Tilācala, (Vipula) and Supārśva. M. 83. 11, 19, 36; 113. 45.

विष्टराश्व
Viṣṭarāśva --a son of Pṛthu; and father of Cāndra-yuvanāśva. Vi. IV. 2. 35-6.

विष्टाकीर्ण
Viṣṭākīrṇa --also Viḍbhuk--a hell. Br. IV. 2. 148 and 170.

विष्टि
Viṣṭi  (I)--a daughter of Vivasvān and Chāyā; became Kāla of cruel deeds. M. 11. 9, 39.

विष्टि
Viṣṭi  (II)--a yugādi for śrāddha. M. 17. 3.

विष्णु
Viṣṇu  (I)--the name of the sun in the month of Ūrja (Kārtika); 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 44; Br. II. 23. 20; Vā. 66. 61, 66. an Āditya and Lord of Ādityas; 2) Br. II. 24. 34; III. 3. 68; M. 6. 4; 171. 56. Vi. I. 15. 130. in the sun's chariot in Phālguna. 3) Ib. I. 22. 3; II. 10. 18.

विष्णु
Viṣṇu  (II)--a god of Ābhūtaraya group. Br. II. 36. 56.

विष्णु
Viṣṇu  (III)--(Uttamaśloka) worshipped for dharma. His abode above the position of seven sages, where is found the great Dhruva with others; 1) Bhā. II. 3. 22; III. ch. 13 (whole); V. 22. 17; 23. 1. different forms of; as Trivikrama broke aṇḍakaṭāha and let the Ganges in; as Sankar ṣaṇa, worshipped by Śiva in Ilāvṛta; as Hayagrīva in Bhadrāśva country; as Nṛsimha in Harivarṣa; as Kāmadeva in Ketumālā; as Matsya in Ramyaka; as Kūrma in Hiraṇmaya; also Sānkhyanidarśana; as Varāha in Uttara Kuru country; also in the form of both Yajña and Kratu; as Sītārāma in Kimpuruṣa; as Naranārāyaṇa in Bhāratavarṣa; as Sūrya in Plakṣadvīpa; as Soma in Śālmali; as Agni in Kuśadvīpa; as a form of water in Krauñcadvīpa; as Vāyu in Śākadvīpa; as Brahmā in Puṣkaradvīpa. 2) Ib. V. 17. 1 and 16; chh. 18-20 (whole); Propitiated by Dakṣa after his reconciliation with Śiva, Viṣṇu came to receive offerings in person in the form of yajña and was praised by all present including Brahmā and Śiva. He told Dakṣa that he was not different from Śiva or Brahmā. 3) Ib. IV. 7. 18-54; 14. 26. presented Pṛthu with Sudarśana and addressed him to befriend Indra, to be devoted to Him and to conduct himself righteously. 4) Ib. IV. 15. 16; 20. 2-16, 31 [1-2]. His residence near Kṣīroda where he sleeps in yoga: vanquisher of Bali; saw a linga of effulgence and with Brahmā went down and up to know its origin and end, but could not get at that. Śiva's remark that his right and left arms were Brahmā and Viṣṇu. This is Mahāyāgam and Māheśvaram balam; 5) Br. II. 26. 2; 27. 22. cursed by Bhṛgu to take 10 (7 M. P.) incarnations on the earth; called Puruṣa and Yajña. 6) Ib. III. 3. 85-106; 72. 3-17; M. 47. 99-103. In Svāyambhuva epoch was born of Ākūtī, in Svārociṣa, born of Tuṣitā as Ajita, in Uttama epoch, born of Satyā as Satya, in Tāmasa born of Hariṇī as Hari, in Vaivasvata, born of Kaśyapa and Aditī with the name Vaikuṇṭha. 7) Br. III. 107-122. Overlord of Ādityas; gave peacock and fowl to Kumāra. 8) Ib. III. 10. 46; 24. 6; 33. 15; 42. 48; 71. 176 and 262. M. 6. 4; 171. 56. Killed Daityas in Tārakāmaya and especially Kālanemi. Aided Indra against Asuras. Introduced yajña and other rites, divisions of time, three castes, three Vedas, three guṇas and so on. 9) Br. III. 72. 18-64, 133. 142; M. ch. 172. Got Indra redeemed of the sin of hitting his Purohita Viśvarūpa, by distributing it among the women, trees and earth. When Durvāsa cursed Indra for refusing to accept Devī's garland, the Asuras destroyed the Devas and entered heaven. Then Hari suggested churning of the ocean and distributed as Mohinī nectar to Devas making them invincible. 10) Br. IV. 9. 23-81; 10. 4-5; 14. 2. Gave his sister Devī in marriage to Śiva with wedding presents. 11) Ib. IV. 15. 15-23; 28. 89; 30. 8; 31. 6; 34. 71-2;  Fond of soma drink. Got Viṣṇutvam by meditating upon Lalitāmantra. 12) Ib. IV. 38. 39. Reflections of Kālanemi on his eternal enmity to Asuras. Killed Kālanemi after a fierce fight, described; re-establishes order and goes back to his abode. 13) M. 178. 5-80; 87. 1. Lord of Ravis; as Kapila destroyed the Sagaras. 14) Ib. 8. 4; 12. 41-3; 17. 1. Born in the family of Kroṣṭhu, helped the Vṛṣṇis; 15) Ib. 44. 15; 47. 29, 33. helped Indra by killing Kāvya's mother; 16) Ib. 47. 99. worship of, in the Vibhūti dvādaśivratam; 17) Ib. 174. 51; 225. 14; 246. 41, 69. 248. 40. Icon of, with different postures described; 18) Ib. 258. 4-15; 266. 42. Viṣṇu (Janārdana); 19) Ib. 7. 20; 154. 351. blessed Vaibhrāja of Pāñcāla with a son, Brahmadatta; 20) Ib. 9. 1; 21. 11-6. in Nārasimha form; 21) Ib. 22. 17. in Meghakara tīrtham; 22) Ib. 22. 40. blessed Soma with fulfilment of all his desires; 23) Ib. 23. 17-19. regained the jewel Syamantaka from the bear and gave it to Satrājit; 24) Ib. 45. 16-17. spoke of Ādisarga and Pratisarga; 25) Ib. 52. 2. worshipped by Purūravas when he was a Brahman in previous birth; 26) Ib. 65. 7; 115. 12. came out of the arrow of Tripurāri and drank of the medicinal tank of Tripuram; 27) Ib. 136. 58. overwhelmed by Asuras on all sides broke the chariot of Kālanemi who escaped; 28) Ib. 136. 65; 150. 222. cut off Grasana's neck by the cakra; 29) Ib. 150. 243; 151. 34. disabled in fight with other Rākṣasas especially Jambha and Nimi, fled with Garuḍa; 30) Ib. ch. 152. Indra met him and praised his past exploits and promised to help himself with 11 Rudras; with Indra's army Janārdana went to war once more; 31) Ib. 153. 1-4. vanquished the Asuras at Bhārgaveśa; 32) Ib. 192. 1-2. residence of, in the Mandara hill; 33) Ib. 206. 18; 245. 9; 246. 24, 30f; 249. 32. meditation of; 34) Ib. 266. 35. spoke of the 16 gifts to Manu; 35) Ib. 274. 16. fish form of. 36) Ib. 290. 23. 

विष्णु
Viṣṇu  (IV)--a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 20.

विष्णु
Viṣṇu  (V)--one of the nine sons of Sāvarṇi. Vā. 100. 22.

विष्णुतीर्थम्
Viṣṇutīrtham --of Yodhanīpuram; where the Asuras were slain by Vāsudeva in large numbers; 1) M. 191. 99-101. more efficacious than the Ganges. 2) Vā. 111. 41. 2.

विष्णुदूत
Viṣṇudūtas --met Yamadūtas at the death of Ajāmila and argued that the uttering of Hari's name before his death was an expiation for all sins committed. Yama's tribute to them as objects of worship for they go about protecting the votaries of Hari. 1) Bhā. VI. 1. 20; 2. 2-39; 3. 17-18. Residents of Viṣṇuloka. 2) Br. IV. 7. 38.

विष्णुपदम्
Viṣṇupadam  (I)--a lake in the Niṣadha hill; 1) Br. II. 18. 67; III. 43. 14; M. 121. 66; Vā. 47. 64. sacred to Pitṛs; 2) M. 22. 25. the place where Dhruva is located. 3) Vā. 50. 222.

विष्णुपदम्
Viṣṇupadam  (II)--the path where Dharma, Dhruva and others take their stand above the seven sages; the region between the seven ṛṣis and Dhruva where live ascetics and yogis of a high order; the source of rain and the stay of the three worlds; from this proceeds the Gangā; issuing from the nail of the great toe of Viṣnu's left foot; 1) Br. II. 21. 176; Vi. II. 8. 98-109; the third division of the celestial region. 2) Ib. II. 8. 122.

विष्णुपदम्
Viṣṇupadam  (III)--a Mt. in Gayā; a hill where Dharmaratha performed a sacrifice. M. 48. 93; Vā. 99. 102; 105. 26; 109. 18; 111. 46-7 and 56. 

विष्णुपदी
Viṣṇupadī --a R. of the Bhadrā country. Vā. 43. 29.

विष्णुपाद
Viṣṇupāda --the celestial regions where Dhruva holds the Bhagavatpadī on his head with intense devotion; 1) Bhā. V. 17. 1-2. sacred for Gangā. 2) Br. III. 13. 118.

विष्णुपुरम्
Viṣṇupuram --sacred to Viṣṇu; attained by Heti after having been killed by Viṣnu. Vā. 109. 25; 274. 76.

विष्णुपुराण
Viṣṇupurāṇa --one among the eighteen Purāṇas; comprises 23,000 ślokas. Bhā. XII. 7. 23. 13. 4.

विष्णु
Viṣṇu Māyā --incarnation of, at the time of Kṛṣṇa's birth. See Yogamāyā. Bhā. X. 1. 25.

विष्णुयशस्
Viṣṇuyaśas --another name of Kalki to be born to a Brahman of Śambhalagrāma. Bhā. I. 3. 25; XII. 2. 18; Vi. IV. 24. 98. Br. III. 73. 104; Vā. 98. 104.

विष्णुरात
Viṣṇurāta --a name of Parikṣit. Bhā. I. 12. 17.

विष्णुलोकम्
Viṣṇulokam --the abode of Viṣṇu 1) Vā. 108. 19; 111. 67; Vi. V. 38. 94. in Pāṇḍaveśam; attained by one who bathes in cakratīrtham; 2) M. 191. 21, 62. he who does tulāpuruṣa goes to Viṣṇulokam. 3) Ib. 193. 74.

विष्णुवृद्ध
Viṣṇuvṛddhas  (I)--Kṣatriyas who became dvijas. Br. III. 66. 88; Vā. 91. 117. 

विष्णुवृद्ध
Viṣṇuvṛddhas  (II)--the descendants of Viṣṇuvṛddha, cognates of Angiras; Brahmans with Kṣatriya dharma. Vā. 65. 107; 88. 79.

विष्णुव्रतम्
Viṣṇuvratam --in honour of Viṣṇu, leads to Paramapada. M. 101. 37, 64.

विष्णु
Viṣṇu Śakti --three-fold; ability to perceive the absolute truth, ability to perceive the nature of the embodied soul and thirdly inability to know one's nature; the technical terms used are parā, kṣetrajñā or aparā and avidyā karmasamjñā. Vi. VI. 7. 60-1.

विष्णु
Viṣṇu siddhi --a Trayārṣeya. M. 196. 39.

विष्णुस्थानम्
Viṣṇusthānam --here Gangā was born and here are the footprints of Vāmana. Br. III. 37. 4.

विष्णोराराधनम्
Viṣṇorārādhanam --once asked of it by Sagara the sage Aurva narrated it to him; was repeated by Parāśara to Maitreya. Vi. III. 8. 3-5.

विष्वक्सेन
Viṣvaksena  (I)--is Viṣṇu; 1) Bhā. I. 2. 8; III. 13. 3. a son of Brahmadatta and Go; author of yogatantra under the guidance of Jaigīṣavya; the concrete form of the Pāñcarātra and other Tantras. Father of Udaksvana; 2) Ib. IX. 21. 25-26; worship of; 3) Ib. XI. 27. 29; XII. 11. 20. M. 21. 35; Vi. IV. 19. 46. Brahmadatta anointed him king and left for yoga practice. 

विष्वक्सेन
Viṣvaksena  (II)--forms one of the retinue of the Lord on the Lokāloka mountain. Bhā. V. 20. 40.

विष्वक्सेन
Viṣvaksena  (III)--born of Viṣūcī; to be friendly to Śambhu, the Indra of the Tenth Manu; attacked Asura followers of Bali. Bhā. VIII. 13. 23; 21. 16.

विष्वक्सेन
Viṣvaksena  (IV)--an attribute of Hari, Vāsudeva, Madhusūdana and Janārdana. Br. III. 71. 50 and 245; Vā. 96. 48, 236; 106. 50; Bhā. VI. 8. 29.

विष्वक्सेन
Viṣvaksena  (V)--the future Manu, and the last (14th) in number. M. 9. 36.

विष्वक्सेन
Viṣvaksena  (VI)--a son of Yugadatta; was born again as Vibhrāja on account of his good deeds. M. 49. 58.

विष्वक्सेन
Viṣvaksena  (VII)--a son of Gaveṣṭhi. Vā. 67. 77.

विष्वक्सेन
Viṣvaksena  (VIII)--a son of Yogasūnu. Vā. 99. 180.

विष्वक्सेन
Viṣvaksena  (IX)--a name of Kṛṣṇa. Vi. V. 38. 20.

विष्वग्रूपा
Viṣvagrūpā --is Lalitā. Br. IV. 13. 17. 

विसटा
Visaṭā --a mother goddess. M. 179. 28.

विसर्जन
Visarjanas --a Yadu tribe; ended their lives by killing their kinsmen. Bhā. XI. 30. 18.

विसर्जम
Visarjama --a kingdom of the west watered by the Sindhu. Br. II. 18. 48.

विस्तृत
Vistṛta (Viśruta) --a son of Devamīḍha and father of Mahādhṛti. Bhā. IX. 13. 16.

विस्फूर्जन
Visphūrjana --a son of Khaśā and Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 134.

विस्फूर्जि
Visphūrji --a piśāca. Vā. 69. 127.

विस्फूर्जित
Visphūrjita --a Rākṣasa. Vā. 69. 165.

विस्वची
Visvacī --an Apsaras with the sun in the śarat. Vā. 52. 13.

विहम्गमा
Vihamgamās  (I)--the gods of the epoch of the eleventh Manu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 25; Vi. III. 2. 30.

विहम्गमा
Vihamgamās  (II)--(Laukika) (1/1000) of the watery creatures. Vā. 101. 200. 

विहरणीय
Viharaṇīyas --eight kinds of Agni. Vā. 29. 25.

विहस्
Vihas --a Janapada of the Ketumālā. Vā. 44. 11.

विहीनर
Vihīnara --a son of Udayana and father of Daṇḍapāṇi. Vi. IV. 21. 15.

वीचि
Vīci --the name of a hell. Br. IV. 2. 150.

वीच्य
Vīcya --a name of a hell. Vā. 101. 149.

वीजा
Vījā --a Viśvedeva. M. 203. 13.

वीणा
Vīṇā --Lute; 1) Vā. 54. 35. presented by Sarasvatī to Skanda; 2) Ib. 72. 46. in the garland of Umeśa, figures of apsaras with vīṇās 3) M. 260. 20. in Pātālam 4) Vi. II. 5. 11. in Rāma's abhiṣeka. 5) Ib. IV. 4. 100.

वीणावती
Vīṇāvatī --a name of Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 34.

वीतहव्य
Vītahavya  (I)--a son of Śunaka (Sunaya-Br. & Vā. P.) and father of Dhṛti. Bhā. IX. 13. 26; Br. III. 64. 23; Vā. 89. 22; Vi. IV. 5. 31.

वीतहव्य
Vītahavya  (II)--a mantrakṛt. Br. II. 32. 105; M. 145. 99; Vā. 59. 97. 

वीतहोत्र
Vītahotra --the family of. Vā. 99. 309.

वीति
Vīti --a sādhya. Br. III. 3. 17.

वीतिहव्य
Vītihavya --a Bhārgava gotrakṛt; an ārṣeya pravara. M. 195. 18, 36.

वीतिहोत्र
Vītihotra  (I)--a son of Priyavrata: appointed Lord of Puṣkaradvīpa. Father of Ramaṇaka and Dhātakī. After dividing the kingdom among his sons he became religiously devoted. Bhā. V. 1. 25 and 33; 20. 31.

वीतिहोत्र
Vītihotra  (II)--a son of Indrasena and father of Satyaśravas. Bhā. IX. 2. 20.

वीतिहोत्र
Vītihotra  (III)--a son of Sukumāra and father of Bharga. Bhā. IX. 17. 9.

वीतिहोत्र
Vītihotra  (IV)--the eldest son of Tālajangha; father of Ananta; escaped to Himālayas from Paraśurāma's attack. Bhā. IX. 23. 29; Br. III. 46. 26; 47. 67; 69. 53; M. 43. 49; Vi. IV. 11. 24.

वीतिहोत्र
Vītihotra  (V)--invited for Yudhiṣṭhira's Rājasūya. Bhā. X. 74. 9.

वीतिहोत्र
Vītihotra  (VI)--a son of Dṛṣṭaketu and father of Bhārga. Vi. IV. 8. 20. 

वीतिहोत्र
Vītihotras --a Vindhya tribe: one of the five gaṇas of the Haihayas; 1) Br. II. 16. 65; III. 69. 52; 74. 138; M. 43. 48; 114. 54; Vā. 45. 134. twenty kings of these, contemporaneous with ten of Śiśunāgas, ruled from Avanti. 2) M. 272. 1, 17.

विदूरथ
Vidūratha  (I)--a son of Bhajamāna and father of Rājādhideva. M. 44. 77.

विदूरथ
Vidūratha  (II)--a son of Suratha. M. 50. 35.

विदूरथ
Vidūratha  (III)--the king and ally of Bhīṣmaka and Jarāsandha. Vi. V. 26. 7.

वीद्युत्वन्त
Vīdyutvanta --Mt. a kulaparvata in the south of Bhārata varṣa. Vā. 48. 3.

वीर
Vīra  (I)--a son of Pṛthu; pursued Indra at the instance of Atri when Indra walked away with Pṛthu's sacrificial horse. Bhā. IV. 19. 17; 20. 21.

वीर
Vīra  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyā. Bhā. X. 61. 13-14.

वीर
Vīra  (III)--a son of Satrajit. Br. III. 71. 55.

वीर
Vīra  (IV)--a name. of Vighneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 68. 

वीर
Vīras  (I)--the gods of Tāmasa epoch. Bhā. VIII. 1. 28.

वीर
Vīras  (II)--a class of Piśācas. Br. III. 7. 378.

वीरक
Vīraka  (I)--(Virāka-Bhā. P.) a sage of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Bhā. VIII. 5. 8.

वीरक
Vīraka  (II)--the head of a Śiva gaṇa. Br. III. 41. 28.

वीरक
Vīraka  (III)--the door-keeper of Śiva, with the cane in hand; directed the Devas to their proper seats in the marriage of Umā and Śiva; adopted as son by Umā who brought him up tenderly, played with Vidyādharas; appointed to guard the harem by Umā when she went for penance; when he allowed Āḍi in the guise of a woman to enter, he was cursed to be born as man and join the gaṇa afterwards. M. 154. 230, 383, 445-54, 465-577; chh. 155-158.

वीरकम्बलबर्हि
Vīrakambalabarhis --(also Kambalabarhis)--son of Marutta and father of Rukmakavaca. Br. III. 70. 25.

वीरजा
Vīrajā --a mind-born daughter of Ājyapa pitṛs; married Nahuṣa and became the mother of Yayāti. M. 15. 23.

वीरजा
Vīrajās --a sage of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Vi. III. 1. 28. 

वीरण
Vīraṇa --a progenitor; father of Asiknī and father-inlaw of Dakṣa (Cākṣuṣa-Vi. P.); 1) Br. III. 2. 5; Vā. 65. 128; Vi. I. 13. 3. his daughter Vīriṇī married Cakṣus. 2) M. 4. 40.

वीरणि
Vīraṇi --a Vāgin. Vā. 61. 25.

वीरदत्त
Vīradatta --the name of the wood-cutter who became Dvijavarma. Br. IV. 7. 32.

वीरनगरम्
Vīranagaram --the city in whose grove Nidāgha engaged himself in austerities for a 1000 divine years. Vi. II. 15. 6-7.

वीरबाहु
Vīrabāhu --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 241.

वीरभद्र
Vīrabhadra  (I)--created out of anger of Śiva on his hearing of Satī's self-sacrifice to destroy Dakṣa's yajña; seized Dakṣa, cut off his head and offered it to Dakṣiṇāgni, and then set out for Kailāsa. After reconciliation with Śiva, Viṣṇu was propitiated with Puroḍāśa to get rid of pollution due to Vīrabhadra's interference in the Yajña; 1) Bhā. IV. ch. 5 (whole); 7. 17; Vā. 30. 130-160; 101. 299. after destroying the sacrifice was about to destroy the world; Śiva stopped him and blessed him to be the first of all grahas by name Aṅgāraka; 2) M. 72. 13-6; 192. 6. hearing that he came out of the wrath of Paśupati Dakṣa appeased him by prayers. Śiva rose from the fire altar and granted him his request that his sacrifice be fruitful when Dakṣa praised him with 1008 names. 3) Vā. 30. 161-180. 

वीरभद्र
Vīrabhadra  (II)--one of the Śiva's attendants; the head of a Śiva gaṇa. Br. III. 32. 23; 41. 28; IV. 14. 8.

वीरमरू
Vīramarū --the kingdom of. M. 121. 45.

वीररथ
Vīraratha --a son of Nṛpamjaya. Vā. 99. 193.

वीरवती
Vīravatī --the wife of Satrājit; mother of Bhangakāra, Satyabhāmā and others. Br. III. 71. 56.

वीरवान्
Vīravān --one of the nine mind-born sons of Sāvarṇi. Vā. 100. 21.

वीरव्रत
Vīravrata --a son of Madhu and Sumanas; wife Bhojā; Father of Manthu and Pramanthu. Bhā. V. 15. 15.

वीरव्रतम्
Vīravratam --in honour of Śiva; here a golden lion is offered as present. M. 101. 28.

वीरसेन
Vīrasena  (I)--a Brahman sage who was invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira. Bhā. X. 74. 9.

वीरसेन
Vīrasena  (II)--a son of Ṛtuparṇa, and father of Sudāsa. Br. III. 63. 174.

वीरसेन
Vīrasena  (III)--his son Nala, to be distinguished from the friend of the Ikṣvākus. Vā. 88. 175. 

वीरहत्ति
Vīrahatti --the sin of killing Kṣatriyas. Br. III. 47. 26.

वीरहन्त्र
Vīrahantras --succeeded the Bṛhadratha kings. Śunaka killed the reigning king and anointed his son, Pradyota. Br. III. 74. 122.

वीरहोत्र
Vīrahotras --a Haihaya clan beginning with Vīrahotra. Vā. 94. 52.

वीरासन
Vīrāsana --the posture in which Pṛṣadhra sat and protected the cattle of his preceptor during nights. Bhā. IX. 2. 3.

वीरिण
Vīriṇas --a tribe. Br. III. 74. 268.

वीरिणी
Vīriṇī  (I)--a Varṇa Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 59.

वीरिणी
Vīriṇī  (II)--a wife of Dakṣa, and mother of Suvrata. Br. IV. 1. 39.

वीरिणी
Vīriṇī  (III)--from her the dharmasarga of Kaśyapa originated. Vā. 1. 131.

वीरिणी
Vīriṇī  (IV)--a daughter of Vīrasena; grand-daughter of Brahmā and wife of Cakṣus. M. 4. 39.

वीरुधा
Vīrudhā --a daughter of Irā and mother of creepers and bushes. Br. III. 7. 460-2. 

वीरेश्वर
Vīreśvara --Icon of; seated on the bull, with plaited tuft, and trident and Vīṇā in his hands; generally in the presence of mātṛgaṇa images. M. 261. 39.

वीर्य
Vīrya --a son of Akrūra. M. 45. 29.

वीर्यधर
Vīryadharas --a class of people in Śālmalidvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 11.

वीर्यवत्
Vīryavat --a sādhya. Br. III. 3. 16; M. 203. 11.

वीर्यवान्
Vīryavān --a Deva gandharva. Vā. 68. 38.

वीर्यवाङ्कृतञ्जय
Vīryavāṅ-Kṛtañjaya --a son of Bṛhadrāja. M. 271. 10.

वीर्यशुल्क
Vīryaśulka --prize of Valour in svayamvara. Bhā. I. 10. 29.

वीर्या
Vīryās --the Kṣatriya Brahmans of Angirasa line. Vā. 99. 164.

वीवध
Vīvadha --a Yāma deva. Br. II. 13. 92.

वृक
Vṛka  (I)--a son of Pṛthu and Arcis: was entrusted with the western part of the kingdom by his elder brother. Bhā. IV. 22. 54; 24. 2.

वृक
Vṛka  (II)--an Asura who followed Vṛtra against Indra; a son of Hiraṇyākṣa. Bhā. VI. 10. [20]; VII. 2. 18. 

वृक
Vṛka  (III)--a son of Bharuka and father of Bāhuka. Bhā. IX. 8. 2.

वृक
Vṛka  (IV)--a son of Devamīḍha and Māriṣā; married Durvārkṣī and had Takṣa and other sons. Bhā. IX. 24. 29 and 43.

वृक
Vṛka  (V)--a son of Vatsaka and Miśrakeśī. Bhā. IX. 24. 43.

वृक
Vṛka  (VI)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Mitravindā. Bhā. X. 61. 16.

वृक
Vṛka  (VII)--a son of Śakuni and an Asura; met Nārada who advised him to perform tapas in honour of Śiva. He did so by cutting his own flesh for six days and on the seventh was about to cut off his head when Śiva appeared and blessed that whosesoever head he touched that person should die. He attempted it on Śiva who ran to Vaikuṇṭha. Hari in the form of a Brahmacārin asked him to try the boon on himself. The wicked Asura did so and met with his death. Bhā. X. 88. 13-36.

वृक
Vṛka  (VIII)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyā (Mādrī-Vi. P.). Bhā. X. 90. 33; Br. III. 71. 252; Vi. V. 32. 4.

वृक
Vṛka  (IX)--sonless, adopted Saumi and Kauśika. Br. II. 71. 192.

वृक
Vṛka  (X)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 242; 51. 11.

वृक
Vṛka  (XI)--a son of Ruruka and father of Bāhu. Br. III. 63. 119; Vi. IV. 3. 25-6. 

वृक
Vṛka  (XII)--a son of Śūra. Br. III. 71. 149.

वृक
Vṛka  (XIII)--a son of Śiṣṭa. M. 4. 39.

वृक
Vṛka  (XIV)--a son of Rohita. M. 12. 38.

वृक
Vṛka  (XV)--a son of Chāyā and Puṣṭi (Sṛṣti-Br. P.). Vā. 62. 83; Br. II. 36. 98.

वृक
Vṛka (jit)  (XVI)--one of the sons of Nāganajit. Vā. 96. 243.

वृकजित्
Vṛkajit --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyā. Br. III. 71. 252.

वृकतेजस
Vṛkatejasa --a son of Śiṣṭa (i) and Succhāyā. M. 4. 39; Vi. I. 13. 2.

वृकदेवा
Vṛkadevā --one of the seven daughters of Devaka; married Vasudeva. Vā. 96. 130; Vi. IV. 14. 18.

वृकदेवी
Vṛkadevī --one of the wives of Vasudeva and mother of Agāvaha (Avagāha, M. P.) and Nandaka. Br. III. 71. 180; M. 46. 18; Vā. 96. 180.

वृकल
Vṛkala  (I)--a son of Sṛṣṭi (Puṣṭi-Vā. P.) and Chāyā (Succhāyā-Vi. P.). Br. II. 36. 98; Vā. 62. 83; Vi. I. 13. 2.

वृकल
Vṛkala  (II)--a son of Akrūra. M. 45. 29. 

वृकवक्त्र
Vṛkavaktra  (I)--a Rākṣasa living in Atalam. Br. II. 20. 33.

वृकवक्त्र
Vṛkavaktra  (II)--an Asura of the fourth tala or gabhastala. Vā. 50. 32.

वृकाश्व
Vṛkāśva --a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyā. Br. III. 71. 252; Vā. 96, 243.

वृका
Vṛkās --a Janapada. Vā. 45. 111.

वृकोदर
Vṛkodara --a name of Bhīmasena; 1) Bhā. I. 7. 13; Br. III. 71. 154. son of Vāyu and Pṛthā; 2) M. 46. 9; Vā. 96. 153; 99. 244. Bhīma, son of Vāyu through the God Marut; 3) M. 50. 49. fire called Vṛka, in his stomach. 4) Ib. 69. 14.

वृक्षवीरुत्
Vṛkṣavīrut --milked the earth in Palāśapātra. Vā. 62. 191.

वृक्षा
Vṛkṣās --sacred as houses for the primitive man and supplied him with honey, fruits and clothing; Gandharvas live in them; these kalpavṛkṣās deteriorated and man who took to caves began to build houses on the model furnished by the trees with the upward, downward and crosswise trees; 1) Br. II. 7. 75-91, 117-20. milked the cow-earth; the essence was tender leaves; the vessel was of pālāśa wood and the plakṣa tree acted as the calf. 2) M. 10. 27.

वृक्षायु
Vṛkṣāyu --a son of Bāṣkala. Vā. 67. 79. 

वृक्षोत्सवम्
Vṛkṣotsavam --(Pādapodyāpana): festivities connected with the planting of trees and the laying out of gardens. M. 59. 17.

वृज
Vṛja --a son of Havirdhāna. Vi. I. 14. 2.

वृजिनी
Vṛjinī  (I)--a daughter of Kṛṣṇa and Satyā. Br. III. 71. 252.

वृजिनी
Vṛjinī  (II)--a daughter of Nāgnajit. Vā. 96. 243.

वृजिनीवत्
Vṛjinīvat --a son of Kroṣṭu, and father of Svāhi. Bhā. IX. 23. 31; Br. III. 70. 15-16; M. 44. 15; Vā. 95. 15.

वृत्त
Vṛtta --a son of Śiṣṭa. M. 4. 39.

वृत्ता
Vṛttā --a daughter of Ṛṣā; mother of Tortoise, śankha, etc. Br. III. 7. 414-17; Vā. 69. 291-92.

वृत्ति
Vṛtti  (I)--means of living by Ṛta, Amṛta, Mṛta Pramṛta and Satyāmṛta or Satyānṛta; never by śvavṛtti. Bhā. VII. 11. 18-20.

वृत्ति
Vṛtti  (II)--transformation of Jayādevas in the seven epochs of Manu. Br. III. 4. 12, 37.

वृत्तिराशी
Vṛttirāśī --an Amitābha god. Br. II. 36. 54. 

वृत्तिरूपवती
Vṛttirūpavatī --a R. of Krauñcadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 21.

वृत्र
Vṛtra  (I)--a son of Tvaṣṭri, created out of a sacrificial offering with an ugly appearance to avenge Indra, the murderer of Viśvarūpa. Hari advised Indra on the means to end Vṛtra. In the battle Vṛtra encouraged his soldiers and uttered words of heroism. Ran towards Indra as Kaiṭabha against Hari and had one hand cut off. But in the contest the Vajra of Indra slipped and Vṛka asked him to take up the weapon and fight. He had his other arm cut off. But Vṛka swallowed Indra into his stomach from which Indra escaped and cut off his head. Vṛtra attained Aloka due to his faith in Hari having been born as Citraketu (s.v.) in his previous birth. 1) Bhā. VI. chh. 9-12 (whole); ch. 14 (whole); 17. 38-39; X. 77. 36; Br. III. 72. 83. Attained release by satsanga. His greed for more territory. 2) Bhā. XI. 12. 5; XII. 3. 11. Killed by Hālāphala avatār. An account of the death in the Bhāgavata; an Asura of Kṛtayuga. 3) M. 47. 51; 53. 20; 249. 67. Brought forth sons from his terrible breathing during his fight with Indra in thousands. All followers of Mahendra, those who have realised Brahmā, are happy, dharmic and live in small bodies. 4) Vā. 68. 34-6.

वृत्र
Vṛtra  (II)--a son of Anāyuṣa. Father of Bakas in hundreds who followed Mahendra. Br. III. 6. 31.

वृत्रघातक
Vṛtraghātaka --the ninth of the twelve incarnations of Viṣṇu. M. 47. 44.

वृत्रघ्नी
Vṛtraghnī --a R. from the Pāriyātra hill; from Ṛṣyavān; in Bhāratavarṣa. Br. II. 16. 27; M. 114. 23; Vā. 45. 97 

वृत्ररिपु
Vṛtraripu --an epithet of Indra. Vi. V. 1. 58.

वृत्रहा
Vṛtrahā --is Indra; 1) Br. III. 10. 23. got frightened at the prolonged love of Umā and Śankara and asked Agni to disturb their sport. 2) Vā. 72. 21.

वृद्धगर्ग
Vṛddhagarga --taught Atri the consequences of disastrous signs in a state. M. 229. 2.

वृद्धगार्ग्य
Vṛddhagārgya --a contemporary of Mucukunda; told the latter that towards the end of Dvāpara he would have the darśan of Kṛṣṇa Viṣṇu. Vi. V. 23. 258.

वृद्धश
Vṛddhaśa (dha) man --of Kārūṣa line, married Śrutadevā, sister of Vasudeva. She gave birth to Dantavaktra; 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 37; Br. III. 71. 156; Vā. 96. 155; Vi. IV. 14. 39. son of Āyu. 2) M. 24. 34.

वृद्धसेन
Vṛddhasena --a queen of Sumatī and mother of Devatājit. Bhā. V. 15. 2.

वृद्धावेशा
Vṛddhāveśā --the goddess following Bhavamālinī. M. 179. 71.

वृद्धिश्राद्धम्
Vṛddhiśrāddham --done prior to maṅgala occasions such as festivals, sacrifices, marriages, etc.; here prayers offered first to mātṛs, then to pitṛs, maternal grandfather, and Viśvedevas; in it yava is used for tila and prefaced by Nāndi śabda; 1) M. 17. 65 9; Vā. 110. 17. a house-holder is eligible to perform it after the sapiṇḍi karaṇam of the deceased. 2) M. 18. 16. 

वृन्दावनम्
Vṛndāvanam --sacred to Rādhā. Br. III. 33. 24; 36. 32. M. 13. 38; Vi. V. 25. 4.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (I)--a son of Śṛnjaya and Rāṣṭrapāli. Bhā. IX. 24. 42.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyā. Bhā. X. 61. 13.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (III)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Kālindī. Bhā. X. 61. 14.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (IV)--one of the ten horses of the moon's chariot. Br. II. 23. 56; M. 126. 52; Vā. 52. 53.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (V)--a Vaikuṇṭha god. Br. II. 36. 57.

वृष
Vṛṣa (bha)  (VI)--the milk-white humped bull born of Surabhī and the standard of Śiva; 1) Br. III. 3. 78-79; 74. 48-51; IV. 14. 2. taught Godharma to Dīrghatamas; 2) Ib. III. 74. 47; gift of, in a Śrāddha. 3) Ib. III. 19. 15.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (VII)--a son of Anāyuṣā: Father of Śrāddhāda, Yajnahā, Brahmahā and Paśuhā, all cruel minded. Br. III. 6. 31.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (VIII)--the sacred well in Devikā. Here is the Jātavedaśilā. Br. III. 13. 41; Vā. 77. 41-4.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (IX)--the Vedic lore rooted in Brahmacarya. Br. III. 14. 36-7. 

वृष
Vṛṣa  (X)--a son of Kārtavīrya who escaped Paraśurāma: a mahāratha. Br. III. 41. 13; 69. 50; Vā. 94. 49.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (XI)--the Indra of the epoch of the III Sāvarṇa. Br. IV. 1. 77; 18. 8.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (XII)--a Maheśvara Gaṇa. M. 266. 42.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (XIII)--a palace in the form of a bull M. 269. 36, 45.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (XIV)--Dharma; 1) Vā. 78. 27; Br. III. 14. 36. a son of Maya. 2) Vā. 68. 28.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (XV)--a son of Pāra. Vā. 99. 177.

वृष
Vṛṣa  (XVI)--a son of Bharata and father of Madhu. Vi. IV. 11. 25-6.

वृषक
Vṛṣaka --a son of Chāyā and Puṣṭi. Vā. 62. 83.

वृषकण्ड
Vṛṣakaṇḍa --a Pravara sage. M. 199. 17.

वृषकेतन
Vṛṣaketana --a name of Vighneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 70. 

वृषदक्ष
Vṛṣadakṣa --a son of Surabhī and Kaśyapa with a jewelled necklace given by mother for the use of Maheśvara as dhvaja. Vā. 66. 75-6.

वृषदर्भ
Vṛṣadarbha --a son of Śibi, after whom came the Janapada Vṛṣadarbha. Br. III. 74. 23; Vā. 99. 23.

वृषध्वज
Vṛṣadhvaja  (I)--a follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra. Bhā. VI. 10. [20].

वृषध्वज
Vṛṣadhvaja  (II)--Śiva as overlord of the Rudras; 1) Br. III. 8. 6; M. 180. 89-90; 189. 14. prayer to. 2) Ib. 266. 47.

वृषध्वज
Vṛṣadhvaja  (III)--is Vighneśvara. Br. IV. 44. 66.

वृषपर्वन्
Vṛṣaparvan --a son of Danu. Father of Śarmiṣṭhā whom Yayātī married. Sudarī and Candrā were his other daughters. Helped Vṛtra against Indra, and fought with Aśvins in the Devāsura war. 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 31-2; 10. 20; VIII. 10. 30; Vi. I. 21. 5; Vā. 68. 8; 93. 16; Br. III. 6. 8, 23; 68. 15; M. 6. 20-22; 24. 52; 25. 6. Heard of Śukra's anger on account of the offence given by his daughter to Devayānī and requested Śukra to stay on, promising to make his daughter a servant of Devayānī. 2) Bhā. IX. 18. 4 and 6, 26-28; XI. 12. 5; M. chh. 27 and 29. Attained salvation by satsanga.

वृषपर्वन्
Vṛṣaparvans --not to marry with Aṅgiras and Virūpas. M. 196. 40. 

वृषभ
Vṛṣabha  (I)--a son of Kārtavīryārjuna. Bhā. IX. 23. 27.

वृषभ
Vṛṣabha  (II)--a playmate of Kṛṣṇa. Being a victor in a game was carried on his back by Bhadrasena. Bhā. X. 18. 23-24.

वृषभ
Vṛṣabha  (III)--a son of Sṛṣṭi and Chāyā. Br. II. 36. 98.

वृषभ
Vṛṣabha  (IV)--the Asura vanquished by Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 37; 73. 100; Vā. 98. 100.

वृषभ
Vṛṣabha  (V)--a god of the Sukarmāṇa group. Br. IV. 1. 88; Vā. 100. 92.

वृषभ
Vṛṣabha  (VI)--a son of Anamitra, married Jayanti the daughter of the Kāśirāja. M. 45. 25-6.

वृषभ
Vṛṣabha  (VII)--a son of Kuśāgra and father of Punyavān (Puspavān-Vi. P.). M. 50. 29; Vi. IV. 19. 82.

वृषभ
Vṛṣabha  (VIII)--the Lord of cattle: dedication of a dark Vṛṣa is equal to going to Gayā for Śrāddha. M. 8. 8; 22. 6.

वृषभ
Vṛṣabha  (IX)--the Mt. Sumana in Plakṣa; to the east of Aruṇoda; 1) Vā. 36. 18. north of the Mahābhadra lake. 2) Ib. 36. 20. 

वृषभध्वज
Vṛṣabhadhvaja --Śiva with the standard of the bull; also Vṛṣavāhana; 1) M. 1. 8; 133. 13; Vā. 30. 180, 261; Vi. V. 33. 50; 34. 35. prayed to by Kāma and others; 2) M. 140. 85; 191. 115; 192. 27; 206. 27 and 28. see Vṛṣadhvaja the Lord of Rudras. 3) Vā. 70. 6.

वृषल
Vṛṣala --see Śūdra; 1) Br. II. 31. 89; III. 14. 38. unfit for Pankti feeding. 2) Ib. III. 19. 31; IV. 8. 19; Vā. 78. 29.

वृषल
Vṛṣalas --rule with Guruṇḍas (Maruṇḍas-Vā. P.); both Mlecchas; 1) Br. III. 74. 177; Vā. 58. 88; 99. 363. joined with the Mlecchas; 2) M. 273. 22. to be put down by future Kalki. 3) Ib. 47. 252; Vā. 98. 114.

वृषलपति
Vṛṣalapati --the chieftain of the Vṛṣalas: offered human sacrifice to Kālī for getting a son. Bhā. V. 9. 12.

वृषलापुरी
Vṛṣalāpurī --the capital of Kṛśa. M. 48. 21.

वृषसेन
Vṛṣasena  (I)--a son of Karṇa; with him comes to an end the Anga line. Bhā. IX. 23. 14; M. 48. 102.

वृषसेन
Vṛṣasena  (II)--a son of the II Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 72.

वृषसेन
Vṛṣasena  (III)--a son of Kārtavīryārjuna. Vi. IV. 11. 21.

वृषाकपि
Vṛṣākapi  (I)--a Rudra, and a son of Bhūta and Sarūpā: Fought with Jambha in the Devāsura war. Bhā. VI. 6. 17; VIII. 10. 32; Vi. I. 15. 122. 

वृषाकपि
Vṛṣākapi  (II)--a name of Indra. Bhā. VI. 13. 10.

वृषाकपि
Vṛṣākapi  (III)--a name of Hari. Bhā. X. 1. 20.

वृषाकृति
Vṛṣākṛti --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 242.

वृषाङ्क
Vṛṣāṅka --a name of Śiva. Bhā. VIII. 8. 1; M. 154. 196.

वृषादर्भ
Vṛṣādarbha --a son of Śibi; 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 3. an Angirasa and mantrakṛṭ. 2) Br. II. 32. 109.

वृषा
Vṛṣās --a line of kings in Vidiśa. Vā. 99. 366.

वृषास्य
Vṛṣāsya --a son of Kārtavīrya who escaped Paraśurāma: a Mahāratha. Br. III. 41. 13; 69. 50.

वृषोत्सर्ग
Vṛṣotsarga --rules for the dedication of a bull; the characteristics and adornments of the bull intended for gift and of the cow, its mother; intended for all castes; different coloured bulls and their significance; gift of nīla bull best for pitṛs; 1) M. 18. 14; 207. 1-41; Vā. 83. 12, 45-6. at Gayā. 2) Ib. 112. 58.

वृष्ट
Vṛṣṭa --(Dhṛṣṭa): his line was Vārṣṭaka. Vi. IV. 2. 4.

वृष्टि
Vṛṣṭi  (I)--a son of Sāvarṇi Manu. M. 9. 33. 

वृष्टि
Vṛṣṭi  (II)--a son of Kakuda. Vā. 96. 116.

वृष्टिनेमि
Vṛṣṭinemi --a son of Aśvinī and Akrūra. M. 45. 33.

वृष्टिमत्
Vṛṣṭimat --a son of Kaviratha, and father of Suṣeṇa. Bhā. IX. 22. 41.

वृष्टी
Vṛṣṭī --a daughter of Marīci. Br. II. 11. 12.

वृष्ट्याद्य
Vṛṣṭyādya --one of the sons of Kārtavīrya and a Mahāratha. Vā. 94. 49.

वृष्णि
Vṛṣṇi  (I)--the eldest of Madhu's hundred sons. After him the line became famous, a gotra name. Bhā. IX. 23. 29; Vi. IV. 11. 27-8.

वृष्णि
Vṛṣṇi  (II)--a son of Sātvata and father of Sumitra and Yujājit; 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 6 and 12. darling of the Yadus; had two wives, Gāndhārī and Mādrī; the former bore Sumitra and the latter, five children; 2) M. 44. 48; 45. 1-2. suspected Kṛṣṇa of having appropriated the syamantaka gem from which he honourably redeemed himself; 3) Br. III. 71. 1, 36, 102. belonged to the Kṛoṣṭhu line; 4) Ib. III. 70. 15; 73. 91. originator of the Vṛṣṇi kula. 5) Vā. 95. 14.

वृष्णि
Vṛṣṇi  (III)--a son of Anamitra (a member of that family, Vi. P.) and father of Śvaphalka and Cītraratha. Bhā. IX. 24. 15. Vi. IV. 14. 5.

वृष्णि
Vṛṣṇi  (IV)--a son of Bhajamāna. M. 44. 50; Vi. IV. 13. 1-2. 

वृष्णि
Vṛṣṇi  (V)--a son of Kukura and father of Kapotaroman and Dhṛti. Br. III. 71. 117; M. 44. 62.

वृष्णि
Vṛṣṇi  (VI)--the best of the Yadus and a son of Kausalyā. Vā. 96. 2.

वृष्णि
Vṛṣṇi  (VII)--a son of Bāhyaka--two queens Gāndhārī and Mādrī. Vā. 96. 4, 17.

वृष्णि
Vṛṣṇi  (VIII)--a son of Satvata; had two sons Sumītra and Yudhājit. Vi. IV. 13. 1, 8.

वृष्णि
Vṛṣṇis --the community of Dvāravatī in which Balarāma and Kṛṣṇa were born; 1) Bhā. I. 3. 23; 11. 11; 14. 25; Br. III. 61. 23; 71. 85; Vā. 1. 145; 96. 84, 175; 86. 28. Kuntī was attached to these people while Kamsa devised means to vanquish them. Were relieved at Kamsa's death. 2) Bhā. I. 8. 41; X. 36. 33; 39. 25; 45. 15; Its name derived from Vṛṣṇi. 3) Ib. IX. 23. 30. They praised the heroic deeds of Kṛṣṇa who was their Lord and who lived with them. But they did not recognise in Him the Almighty Lord; 4) Ib. I. 9. 18; II. 4. 20; IX. 24. 63; X. 1. 11 and 62; 90. 46. ended their lives by fighting their kinsmen at Prabhāsā. Attained Hari through relationship. 5) Ib. XI. 30. 18; VII. 1. 30.

वृष्णिकुलम्
Vṛṣṇikulam --its old fame was raised by the birth of Lord Viṣṇu. M. 44. 15; 47. 12 and 33; 69. 10.

वृष्णिमान्
Vṛṣṇimān --a son of Śucidrava (Śuciratha-Vi. P.) and father of Suṣeṇa. M. 50. 80; Vi. IV. 21. 12. 

वृह
Vṛha --a Śukradeva. Vā. 31. 9.

वेगवत्
Vegavat  (I)--a son of Bandhumat and father of Bandhu. (Budha-Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 2. 30; Br. III. 8. 36; 61. 10; Vi. IV. 1. 44-5.

वेगवत्
Vegavat  (II)--a son of Nāgnajit. Bhā. X. 61. 13.

वेगवत्
Vegavat  (III)--the father of a son Budha. Vā. 86. 14-5.

वेगवत्य
Vegavatyas --one of the 14 gaṇas of Apsaras, born of Ṛṣtā. Br. III. 7. 18.

वेगवन्त
Vegavanta --an Apsara gaṇa from Variṣṭa or Ariṣṭa. Vā. 69. 54.

वेगिनी
Veginī --a Śakti on the Drāviṇikā Mudrā. Br. IV. 36. 76.

वेंक
Veṃka --(c) a kingdom through which Ṛṣabha passed. Its king was Arhat. Bhā. V. 6. 7 and 9.

वेंकट
Veṃkaṭa --a Mt. in Bhāratavarṣa: visited by Balarāma. Its sages visited Dvārakā. Bhā. V. 19. 16; X. 79. 13; 90. 28[3].

वेणा
Veṇā  (I)--a tīrtha sacred to Amṛta; 1) M. 13. 49. sacred to the Pitṛs. 2) Ib. 22. 34. 

वेणा
Veṇā  (II)--a R. from the Vindhyas; visited by Balarāma. M. 114. 27. Bhā. X. 79. 12.

वेणी
Veṇī --a R. in Bhāratavarṣa, from the Vindhyas. Bhā. V. 19. 18; Br. II. 16. 33.

वेणीमाधव
Veṇīmādhava --Viṣṇu at Prayāgā. M. 111. 9.

वेणु
Veṇu --flute; 1) Vā. 45. 40; 56. 32; 104. 48; Vi. II. 14. 32. in Rāma's abhiṣeka; 2) Ib. IV. 4. 99. in Pātālam. 3) Ib. II. 5. 11.

वेणुदारि
Veṇudāri --an ally of Jarāsandha: attacked the eastern gate of Mathurā and the northern gate of Gomanta during their siege by Jarāsandha. Bhā. X. 50. 11[2]; 52. 11[14].

वेणुमण्डलम्
Veṇumaṇḍalam --(c) a kingdom of Kuśadvīpa after Veṇumat. Br. II. 14. 28; 19. 57; Vā. 33. 25; 49. 52.

वेणुमत्
Veṇumat  (I)--a son of Jyotiṣmat after whom Veṇumaṇḍalam took its name. Br. II. 14. 27-8; Vā. 33. 24; Vi. II. 4. 36.

वेणुमत्
Veṇumat  (II)--a Mt. to the east of Aruṇoda; 1) Vā. 36. 19. the cities of Vidyādharas in. 2) Ib. 37. 3, 26.

वेणुमती
Veṇumatī --a R. rising from the Pāriyātra hills. M. 22. 20. 

वेणुहय
Veṇuhaya --one of the three sons of Śatajit. Bhā. IX. 23. 21; Br. III. 69. 4; M. 43. 8; Vā. 94. 4; Vi. IV. 11. 7.

वेणुहोत्र
Veṇuhotra --a son of Dhṛṣṭaketu. Br. III. 67. 77; Vā. 92. 72.

वेण्वा
Veṇvā --a R. originating from the Vindhyas. Vā. 45. 102.

वेताल
Vetālas --(also Betālas) a class of spirits, a gaṇa, largely followers of Śiva; 1) Bhā. II. 10. 39; VII. 8. 38; X. 63. 10; Br. III. 41. 29; IV. 14. 10; 24. 55; M. 8. 5; 23. 39. Vampires: dance and feast on flesh and blood on the field of battle; 2) Ib. 149. 16. images of, attending on Śiva. 3) Ib. 259. 24.

वेताली
Vetālī --a R. of the Bhadrā. Vā. 43. 30.

वेत्रवती
Vetravatī  (I)--a R. from the Pāriyātra hill. Br. II. 16. 28; Vā. 45. 98.

वेत्रवती
Vetravatī  (II)--a R. from the mountain Ṛṣyavān; 1) M. 114. 23. sacred to the Pitṛs. 2) Ib. 22. 20. 163. 63.

वेत्रवती
Vetravatī  (III)--a R., a mahānadī summoned to Gayā by Lomeśa. Vā. 108. 78.

वेत्रसंखुपथस्
Vetrasaṃkhupathas --the kingdom of the; the R. Pāvanī flows through. M. 121. 56; Br. II. 18. 57. 

वेद
Veda  (I)--the science of Dharma together with the ācāra of those who know it. M. 52. 7; 164. 16.

वेद
Vedas --First came nāda from the Supreme Brahman, then Omkāra and then mantropaniṣad. Brahmā created Akṣaras, and out of his four mouths appeared the four Vedas, which were taught to his sons. This was handed down by tradition through the ages. 1) Bhā. XII. 6. 36-46; III. 12. 36-37; IV. 24. 62; M. 2. 13; 3. 2; 4. 7; 285. 8. Originally one, rearranged by Vyāsa into four Samhitās--Ṛg, Yajus, Sāman and Atharvan: distribution among his pupils done by Kṛṣṇadvaipāyana with the help of Paila, Jaimini, Sumantu, and Vaiśampāyana: growth of Śākhās. Lost in a deluge. Then Hari. taught them to Brahmā who taught in his turn to his sons. A three fold division of the Vedas conveys the truth of Brahman and Ātman. In these Hari manifests himself: its metres are Gāyatrī, Uṣṇik and so on. 2) Bhā. I. 4. 19-23; XI. 14. 3-6; 21. 35-43; XII. 6. 49-50; Vi. III. 3. 20; 4. 7-9. Symbolised by Garuḍa: do not shine in Kali. 3) Bhā. XII. 11. 19; X. 20. 8. Personified: These with Upavedas came to see the Trivikrama form of Hari. 4) Ib. VIII. 21. 2; IX. 22. 37. Learnt by Balarāma and Kṛṣṇa. 5) Ib. X. 45. 33. Twenty-eight Vedavyāsas rearranged them in the 28 periods: compiled into four by Parāśara's son, originally one; 6) Br. II. 34. 2, 12-30; 35. 116-26; III. 10. 69; IV. 1. 30; 6. 64; M. 14. 16. served as vessel for Bṛhaspati to milk the cow-earth; 7) Ib. 10. 17. restored by Matsya after deluge. 8) Ib. 53. 5; 83. 3; 172. 50.

वेदकौण्डिल्य
Vedakauṇḍilya --a Ṛtvik at Brahmā's yajña. Vā. 106. 34.

वेदचिन्तक
Vedacintakas --those that have not understood the Vedas as Vedavits do. Vā. 83. 100. 

वेददर्श
Vedadarśa --learnt the Atharva Samhitā from a pupil of Sumantu. Śauklāyani and others were his disciples. Bhā. XII. 7. 1-2.

वेदना
Vedanā --married Raurava Naraka; son born of Vedanā and Māyā was Duhkham. Vā. 10. 40-1; Br. II. 9. 64.

वेदबाहु
Vedabāhu  (I)--a son of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 90. 34.

वेदबाहु
Vedabāhu  (II)--a sage of the Raivata epoch. Vi. III. 1. 22; Vā. 62. 53.

वेदमित्र
Vedamitra --Śākalya learnt the Samhitā entrusted by Indrapramati to his son and re-arranged it into five with his pupils. Vi. III. 4. 21.

वेदरूपिणी
Vedarūpiṇī --is Lalitā. Br. IV. 13. 28.

वेदवती
Vedavatī  (I)--a R. from the Pāriyātra hill. Br. II. 16. 27; Vā. 45. 97.

वेदवती
Vedavatī  (II)--an Apsaras (Suranārī); from the veditala of Brahmā. Vā. 69. 60.

वेदवदनम्
Vedavadanam --a tīrtha sacred to Gāyatri. M. 13. 51. 

वेदवित्
Vedavit --one who knows the Veda and understands it for yoga; understands it in the right direction as prescribed; distinct from Vedacintaka; 1) Vā. 83. 99, 100. eligible for Pārvaṇa śrāddha. 2) M. 16. 8.

वेदवेदांगपारग
Vedavedāṃgapāraga --one fully versed in the Vedas and Vedāngas. Vā. 34. 94; 109. 54.

वेदव्यास
Vedavyāsa  (I)--(Vyāsa) a sage; twenty-eight Vedavyāsas for twenty-eight dvāparas of the Vaivasvata epoch; Svayambhuva, Vedavyāsa, Uśanā, Bṛhaspati, Savitā, Mṛtyu, Indra, Vasiṣṭha, Sārasvata, Antarikṣa, Dharma, Traiyāruṇi, Dhanañjaya, Kṛtamjaya, Ṛjīṣa, Bharadvāja, Gautama, Uttama, Haryavana, Vena, Vājaśrava, Arvāk, Somamukhyāyana, Tṛṇabindu, Tataja, Śakti, Parāśara, Jātūkarṇa, and Dvaipāyana; in the future Dvāparadroṇi (more names are given); 1) Br. II. 33. 33; 35. 117-125. son of Parāśara born in the 28th dvāpara; eighth human incarnation of Viṣṇu with Jātūkarṇi (ja) as purodha (purohita). 2) Ib. III. 73. 93; M. 47. 246; Vā. 98. 93.

वेदव्यास
Vedavyāsa  (II)--Kṛṣṇadvaipāyana; he who split the one Veda into four parts; 1) Vā. 1. 17, 179. different Vedavyāsas are said to be compilers of the Veda in different Yugas. 2) Ib. 58. 11; 61. 104.

वेदशब्द
Vedaśabda --with the aid of which Maheśvara created the universe. Vā. 9. 63.

वेदशाखा
Vedaśākhās --10 Purāṇa variations; 4000 verses each except Śāmśapāyikas; each in four parts and all conveying the one meaning. Vā. 61. 58, 59; 110. 7. 

वेदशिर
Vedaśira --a tīrtha sacred to the pitṛs. M. 22. 71.

वेदशिरस्
Vedaśiras  (I)--a son of Prāṇa. Bhā. IV. 1. 45.

वेदशिरस्
Vedaśiras  (II)--a son of Kṛśāśva and Dhiṣaṇā. Bhā. VI. 6. 20.

वेदाशिर
Vedāśiras  (III)--a sage and a siddha. His wife was Tuṣitā. Father of Vibhu, a manifestation of Hari. Bhā. VI. 15. 14; VIII. 1. 21.

वेदशिरस्
Vedaśiras  (IV)--a sage of the Raivata epoch. Bhā. VIII. 5. 3.

वेदशिरस्
Vedaśiras  (V)--the avatār of the lord in the 15th dvāpara; the name of a weapon sacred to Parameśvara in the hill of Vedaśīrṣa on the slopes of the Himālayas. Vā. 23. 166-68.

वेदशिरस्
Vedaśiras  (VI)--a son of Mārkaṇḍeya and Mūrdhani (Dhūmrapatni-Br. P.); married Pīvarī; his sons Mārkaṇḍeyas. Vā. 28. 6; Br. II. 11. 7.

वेदशिरस्
Vedaśiras  (VII)--heard from the Nāgas at Pātālam the Viṣṇu Purāṇa; he communicated it to Pramati. Vi. VI. 8. 48.

वेदशीर्ष
Vedaśīrṣa --a Mt. on the slope of the Himālayas near the Sarasvati hills. Vā. 23. 168.

वेदशेरका
Vedaśerakās --sages. M. 200. 11. 

वेदश्री
Vedaśrī --a Bhārgava and a sage of the Raivata epoch. Br. II. 36. 62; Vi. III. 1. 22.

वेदश्रुत
Vedaśrutas --the gods of the Uttama epoch. Bhā. VIII. 1. 24.

वेदस्पर्श
Vedasparśa --a disciple of Kabandha divided the portion received of Atharva into four parts. Vā. 61. 50.

वेदस्मृती
Vedasmṛtī --a R. in Bhāratavarṣa from the Pāriyātra hill (from the mountain Ṛsyavān-M. P.). Bhā. V. 19. 18; Br. II. 16. 27; M. 114. 23; Vā. 45. 97; Vi. II. 3. 10.

वेदानग
Vedānaga --from Viṣṇu. Vā. 54. 82; Vi. I. 22. 83-84; Vi. 17. 5.

वेदान्तशास्त्रम्
Vedāntaśāstram --the Vedānta to be loved by the Gṛhasthas: Vedāntadarśanam being the end of a student's life. Br. IV. 2. 85; 8. 4; M. 52. 26; Vā. 101. 87-91; 104. 42.

वेदि
Vedi  (I)--a R. served by the Siddhas. Br. III. 13. 81.

वेदि
Vedi  (II)--one of the ten pīṭhas for images, oblong; unfit for installing lingas; this gives abundant riches. M. 262. 6, 17.

वेदि
Vedi  (III)--(also Veditalam) the place of the fire altar in the sacrifice. Vā. 69. 60; 97. 25.

वेद्यर्ध
Vedyardha --in Jambūdvīpa, south of Meru; 1) Br. II. 15. 36; Vā. 34. 23. three varṣas to the south of it, and three to its north. 2) Ib. 34. 32. 

वेधस्
Vedhas  (I)--a name of Hari. Bhā. I. 5. 31.

वेधस्
Vedhas  (II)--a measure of time. Bhā. III. 11. 6.

वेधस्
Vedhas  (III)--a name of Brahmā 1) Bhā. VIII. 5. 24; Br. III. 21. 59. (s.v.). He created a daughter Śatarūpā (Sāvitrī); she was so charming that he himself fell in love with her; her brothers like Vasiṣṭha and she herself deplored the absurdity of a father marrying his daughter; the creator turned a deaf ear and all his attention became centred on her; to see her wherever she was he created more eyes on all his five faces; after ordering his sons to take up the work of creation, he lived with Śatarūpā for years in the midst of the lotus flower unseen by others, like an ordinary human being. To him was born Manu Svāyambhuva also known as Virāṭ and Ādipuruṣa; from him were born the Vairāja devas and others; 2) M. 3. 29 to the end. grandfather of all the worlds. 3) Vā. 106. 40; 108. 42; 109. 26.

वेधस्
Vedhas  (IV)--a name of Bṛhaspati. Vā. 98. 23.

वेधक
Vedhaka --a hell for the maker of arrows. Vi. II. 6. 16.

वेधस
Vedhasa --a mantrakṛt and of Angira branch. M. 145. 99; Vā. 59. 98.

वेन
Vena --a son of Anga, of cruel and wrong behaviour; fell dead due to the curse of sages who churned his right arm out of which came Pṛthu; born after aśvamedha  of his father. The twenty-third Vedavyāsa. 1) Bhā. IV. 13. 18-20; 35. 38; Br. II. 35. 122; M. 4. 44. Brought up in the house of his grandfather who was an amśa of Mṛtyu (adharma) Vena acquired bad conduct, killed his playmates like animals and became a source of vexation to his father who left the kingdom in disgust and distress. Vena was crowned. Blinded by pride he proclaimed that there should be no more yajñas or gifts in his kingdom. Lost it through pride of power. He did not listen to the words of sages and asserted he was the highest of all gods. Seeing him perverse and vile, the sages slew him; Sunīthā protected his body by mantra. To avoid anarchy and to preserve the line of Anga, the sages churned the thigh of the dead prince and there came a black dwarfish man, the ancestor of the Niṣādha race. 2) Bhā. IV. 13. 39, 42 and 47; ch. 14 (whole). They continued to churn the two arms out of which came a male and female child, being the amśa of Viṣṇu and Lakṣmī. 3) Ib. IV. 15. 1-3; 16. 11; X. 73. 20. Thrown into hell by Brāhmaṇas, was saved from hell by Pṛthu. 4) Ib. II. 7. 9; VII. 1. 16; Br. II. 36. 108-12, 121-27, 150. Pṛthu was the father's part of Vena's body; from the mother's part of his body came the Mlecchas. 5) M. 10. 4-10. Another version: A son of the daughter of Kāla; took to kāma and covetousness; founded an adharma sthāpana, gave up Veda śāstras; subjects of, did not learn Vedas or performed ceremonials or yajñas; made himself the object of sacrifice and worship; enraged by the ṛṣis led by Marīci who advised him to take up the right path; ridiculed them and said he was a mahātmā and could burn the whole world or flood it; hence the sages held him down and had his left hand churned by force; there came out a short black figure who stood trembling; the sages said niṣīda, the forerunner of the niṣādavamśa; then they churned his right hand and Pṛthu was born; Vena died; Pṛthu crowned by all; a good king; his rule and achievements, including the milking of the earth by all beings. 6) Vā. 62. 108-193. 

वेनुका
Venukā --a R. of the Śākadvīpa. M. 122. 33. Br. II. 19. 96; Vi. II. 4. 65.

वेला
Velā  (I)--a daughter of Meru and Dhāraṇi; married Sāgara and brought forth a daughter. Savarṇā; 1) Vā. 30. 35. she was married to Prācīnabarhis to whom were born ten sons collectively known as Pracetas versed in Dhanur Veda. 2) Br. II. 13, 37, 39-40.

वेला
Velā  (II)--a daughter of Bhadrāśva and Ghṛtāci. Vā. 70. 69.

वेश
Veśa --married Nadhi; father of Marīca-Kaśyapa. Vā. 65. 112.

वेश्याधर्मम्
Veśyādharmam --the life and duties of a dancing girl; Ūrvaśī suffered for adopting it; 1) M. 6. 1. 31. to serve as courtesans in the palace, temples and also those who are prepared to spend money on them. They in turn were to give gifts in days of festivals; 2) Ib. 70. 19, 28-33. residence of, plan for. 3) Ib. 254. 23.

वेषपरायण
Veṣaparāyaṇa --a sage by garbha. Vā. 59. 94.

वैकंक
Vaikaṃka --a Mt. on the base (east) of Meru; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 26; Vi. II. 2. 27. residence of Sugrīva, son of Garuḍa. 2) Vā. 37. 16; 39. 39-41; 42. 19.

वैकर्णिनि
Vaikarṇini --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 24.

वैकर्णेय
Vaikarṇeyas --Kāśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 9. 

वैकारिक
Vaikārika --the Sun and the son of Brahmā with rajoguṇa. Vā. 31. 36.

वैकारिक
Vaikārikas --a group of ten devas, born of Vaikārika, called generally digdevatas. Bhā. II. 5. 30; Vā. 4. 61.

वैकारिकसर्ग
Vaikārikasarga --explains the five buddhi and the five karma senses and manas the eleventh. Vā. 4. 60.

वैकुण्ठ
Vaikuṇṭha  (I)--a name of Hari. Bhā. I. 15. 46.

वैकुण्ठ
Vaikuṇṭha  (II)--the abode of Viṣṇu, established by Him at the request of Śrī in his manifestation as Vaikuṇṭha: Famous for Naiśreyasa vana, filled with different trees and birds. It had seven enclosures into which sin had no free entrance. On the seventh were stationed two guardian deities. These once prevented Lakṣmī from entering in during the yoganidrā of Hari; 1) Bhā. III. 15. 13-27; 16. 27-30; VIII. 5. 5. happiness (saubhāgya) of beings retired to, during the burning of the worlds. 2) M. 60. 2; 245. 34; 285. 19.

वैकुण्ठ
Vaikuṇṭha  (III)--a manifestation of Hari born of Vaikuṇṭhā and Śubhra in Cākṣuṣa epoch. At the request of his spouse Śrī, Vaikuṇṭha (Heaven) came into existence in the Vaivasvata epoch, to the right of Śivaloka. Bhā. VIII. 5. 4-6; Br. III. 3. 117; 32. 3; IV. 29. 136; 40. 9; Vi. III. 1. 41; V. 5. 21.

वैकुण्ठ
Vaikuṇṭha  (IV)--the 22nd kalpa. M. 290. 8. 

वैकुण्ठ
Vaikuṇṭha  (V)--in the Cyavana āśrama of Gayā; 1) Vā. 108. 74. the abode of Viṣṇu. 2) Ib. 24. 20; 109. 16.

वैकुण्ठ
Vaikuṇṭhas --a class of gods, 1) Bhā. VIII. 5. 4; Vi. III. 1. 21. Jayādevas, fourteen in number in the epochs of Raivata Manu and Svāyambhuva. 2) Br. II. 36. 51 and 58; III. 3. 9, 58 and 67; 4. 31; Vā. 66. 9; 67. 40-41.

वैकुण्ठ
Vaikuṇṭha tīrtham --sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 75.

वैकुण्ठा
Vaikuṇṭhā --the mother of Vaikuṇṭha devas. Vā. 67. 40.

वैकृत
Vaikṛta --a Mt. noted for śrāddha offerings. Br. III. 13. 28; Vā. 77. 28.

वैकृत
Vaikṛta sargas --five: Mukhya sarga, Tiryak yoni sarga, Deva Sarga, Mānuṣa sarga, and Anugraha sarga; three Prākṛta sargas; these are the conscious creations of the spirit (Brahmā). Vā. 6. 65. 6.

वैकृतिगालव
Vaikṛtigālava --a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 3.

वैक्लवा
Vaiklavās --of the Vāsiṣṭha gotra. M. 200. 2.

वैखरीवाक्
Vaikharīvāk --one of the four tongues of the Veda. Vā. 104. 74. 

वैखानस
Vaikhānasa  (I)--a Vaiṣṇava of the ardent type. Br. IV. 8. 44

वैखानस
Vaikhānasa  (II)--practices for a Brahmacārin before becoming a full fledged mendicant. Vi. III. 10. 15; IV. 2. 130.

वैखानस
Vaikhānasas --a class of seers, born on vyapohini rite on ashes. Pṛthu became a Vaikhānasa in the evening of his life; a son of Nahuṣa; 2) M. 24. 51. Agastya followed the system; 3) Ib. 61. 37. tapas in the forests. 4) Ib. 145. 24; Vā. 2. 27; 59. 24. ^1 Bhā. III. 12. 43; IV. 23. 4; Br. I. 2. 27; II: 32. 25; III. 1. 57; Vā. 65: 56.

वैगायन
Vaigāyana --a Bhārgava gotrakṛt. M. 195. 18.

वैजयन्ति
Vaijayanti --the garland worn by Arjuna (Haihaya) and by Ananta; 1) Bhā. IX. 15. 20; V. 25. 7. presented by sages to Balarāma after he killed Balavala. 2) Ib. X. 79. 8. The garland of Harī. 3) Vi. I. 22. 72.

वैडूर्य
Vaiḍūrya --a hill range on the west of Meru. Vi. II. 2. 29.

वैणि
Vaiṇi --of the Sahya hills in the Dakṣināpatha. Vā. 45. 104.

वैणिकी
Vaiṇikī --is Lalitā. Br. IV. 17. 34.

वैणोय
Vaiṇoya --a pupil of Yājñavalkya. Br. II. 35. 29. 

वैतण्ड
Vaitaṇḍa --a son of Āpa. Vi. I. 15. 111.

वैतण्ड्य
Vaitaṇḍya --a son of Āyu (Āpa-Vā. P.). Br. III. 3. 24; Vā. 66. 23.

वैतरणी
Vaitaraṇī  (I)--(Vaitaraṇam) one of twenty-eight hells. Intended for the mad, and for those fallen from character and conduct, those that spoil makha or devastate villages. Bhā. V. 26. 7; Br. II. 28. 83; IV. 2. 149-171; M. 141. 69; Vā. 56. 78; 101. 148, 169; Vi. II. 6. 3 and 24.

वैतरणी
Vaitaraṇī  (II)--a R. in hell. For transgressing law and convention one gets drowned in this river of refuse and urine, etc. Bhā. II. 2. 7; V. 26. 22; VII. 9. 43.

वैतरणी
Vaitaraṇī  (III)--a R. from the Vindhyas; fit for Śrāddha offerings; 1) Br. II. 16. 33; III. 13. 103; M. 114. 27; Vā. 45. 102; 77. 95. a deva nadī; gift of a cow here secures release for twenty-one generations. 2) Vā. 105. 44; 108. 80; 109. 17; 112. 26.

वैतसेन
Vaitasena --a name of Purūravas. Bhā. XI. 26. 35.

वैतान
Vaitāna --a portion of Atharva Samhitā. Br. II. 35. 61; Vā. 61. 53.

वैतानिक
Vaitānikas --the name of planets in the Vaivasvata epoch. Br. II. 24. 87, 111.

वैताल
Vaitāla  (I)--a pupil of Jātūkarṇya. Bhā. XII. 6. 58. 

वैताल
Vaitāla  (II)--evil spirits. M. 218. 36.

वैतालिक
Vaitālika --a pupil of Śākapūrṇa. Vi. III. 4. 24.

वैताली
Vaitālī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 18.

वैदर्भ
Vaidarbha --a southern country; a tribe; 1) Br. II. 16. 58; M. 114. 47; Vā. 45. 126. on the other side of the Vindhyas. 2) Ib. 45. 133.

वैदर्भा
Vaidarbhā --a R. sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 64.

वैदर्भी
Vaidarbhī --a name of Rukmiṇī. Bhā. X. 52. 16-17.

वैदिक
Vaidikas --on the other side of the Vindhyas. Vā. 45. 133.

वैदिकीश्रुति
Vaidikīśruti --the sacred tradition. M. 19. 3.

वैदिश
Vaidiśa --the capital of Bhūtinanda ? Br. III. 74. 182.

वैदिशक
Vaidiśakas --the kings after Vindhyaśakti. Br. III. 74. 179; Vā. 99. 366.

वैदिश
Vaidiśas --a Vindhyan tribe. Br. II. 16. 64; M. 114. 53. 

वैदिशपुरम्
Vaidiśapuram --the city of Vidiśā where Puṣpavāhana met Anangavatī in his previous birth. M. 100. 14.

वैदुरिकम्
Vaidurikam --the nīti discourse of Vidura to Dhṛtarāṣṭra. Bhā. III. 1. 10-13.

वैदूर्य
Vaidūrya  (I)--a Mt. on the base of Meru, and west of Śitoda. Bhā. V. 16. 26; Vā. 36. 27; 42. 50.

वैदूर्य
Vaidūrya  (II)--an Asura of the Mahātalam. Vā. 50. 35.

वैदेह
Vaideha --see Janaka. Vi. IV. 5. 23.

वैदेहराता
Vaideharātās --Trayārṣeyas. M. 198. 8.

वैदेह्यम्
Vaidehyam --Subāhu and Śūrasena, son of Śatrughna. Vā. 88. 186.

वैद्य
Vaidya  (I)--a son of Varuṇa and Sunādevī; father of Ghṛṇi and Muni, both of whom ate each other and died. Br. III. 59. 6; Vā. 84. 6-8.

वैद्य
Vaidya  (II)--a Sukha god. Br. IV. 1. 18.

वैद्य
Vaidya  (III)--the king's physician skilled in aṣṭāṅga; 1) M. 215. 34. residence of. 2) Ib. 254. 26. 

वैद्य
Vaidya  (IV)--a mukhya gaṇa. Vā. 100. 18.

वैद्यग
Vaidyaga --an Angirasa and mantrakṛt. Br. II. 32. 107.

वैद्यनाथम्
Vaidyanātham --a tīrtha sacred to Aroga and the Pitṛs. M. 13. 41; 22. 24.

वैद्युत
Vaidyuta  (I)--a king of fire originating in waters, and hence cannot be quenched by waters. (Pāvaka Agni); a son of Brahmā. Br. II. 12. 2; 24; 11; Vā. 29. 7; 51. 26; 53. 8.

वैद्युत
Vaidyuta  (II)--a son of Vapuṣmat after whom came the kingdom Vaidyuta. Br. II. 14. 32-4; 33. 29-30; Vi. II. 4. 23, 129.

वैद्युत
Vaidyuta  (III)--a Mt. in India. Br. II. 16. 21; Vā. 45. 90; 47. 14.

वैद्युत
Vaidyuta  (IV)--Mt. near Kailāsa, noted for lake Mānasa. It has the stream Sarayū and forest Vaibhrāja. Here lives Prahati's son, being a follower of Kubera. Br. II. 18. 14-16.

वैद्युत
Vaidyuta  (V)--a Daitya in the fifth talam. Br. II. 20. 36.

वैद्युत
Vaidyuta  (VI)--a son of Sahiṣṇu, an avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 213.

वैद्युत
Vaidyuta  (VII)--a hill near Kakudman. M. 121. 16; Vā. 47. 14. 

वैद्युतम्
Vaidyutam --a region of Śālmalidvīpa adjoining the hill Kanka. Br. II. 19. 45; Vā. 49. 40.

वैद्युती
Vaidyutī --one of the three mātras of Om. Vā. 20. 2.

वैधृत
Vaidhṛta --Indra of the eleventh epoch of Manu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 25.

वैधृता
Vaidhṛtā --the wife of Āryaka, and mother of Dharmasetu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 26.

वैधृति
Vaidhṛtis --sons of Vidhṛti. These were gods who treasured up the Vedas in their minds. Bhā. VIII. 1. 29.

वैधृतिवासर
Vaidhṛtivāsara --a yugādi for śrāddha; fit for sixteen kinds of gifts. M. 17. 3; 274. 20.

वैधेय
Vaidheya --a pupil of Yājñavalkya. Vā. 61. 24; Br. II. 35. 28.

वैन
Vaina --a pupil of Langākṣī. Br. II. 35. 41, 45.

वैनतेय
Vainateya --the Garuḍa; 1) M. 150. 214; Br. I. 1. 116; Vā. 1. 137. abode of, as tall as the Kailāsa hills; 2) M. 163. 67-8. city of, in the fourth talam or gabhastalam. 3) Br. II. 20. 34; III. 7. 229; Vā. 50. 33. 

वैनतेयम्
Vainateyam--(the Garuḍam)  the Purāṇa of 19,000 stanzas. Vā. 104. 8.

वैनायकम्
Vaināyakam  (I)--a tīrtha sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 32.

वैनायकम्
Vaināyakam  (II)--the vrata in honour of Vināyaka; gift of a golden elephant on Caturthi. M. 101. 61.

वैनायकी
Vaināyakī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 18.

वैन्य
Vainya  (I)--see Pṛthu; a mantrakṛt; 1) M. 145. 100; Vā. 1. 33; 59. 97. introduced yajña in Vaivasvata epoch when Brahmā was Purohita. 2) Br. III. 73. 72-73.

वैन्य
Vainya  (II)--a son of Vena (s.v.), got by ṛṣis from his arms; 1) Vā. 62. 94. story of, narrated in detail; 2) Ib. 62. 103-193. milking of the earth by. 3) Br. I. 1. 105.

वैन्य
Vainyas --a branch of the Bhārgavas. Br. III. 1. 100.

वैभ्राज
Vaibhrāja (ka)  (I)--a pleasure garden of gods; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 14; Br. II. 18. 16; Vā. 36. 11. here Yayāti enjoyed with Viśvācī. 2) Br. III. 7. 101; Vā. 47. 16.

वैभ्राज
Vaibhrāja  (II)--a Mt. of Plakṣadvīpa, the residence of Bhrājiṣṇu; 1) Br. II. 19. 13; Vi. II. 4. 7. shining like quartzite (sphātika). 2) Vā. 49. 12. 

वैभ्राज
Vaibhrāja  (III)--a forest in the Ketumālā continent (on the west of Ilāvṛta). M. 83. 33; 131. 48; Vi. II. 2. 25.

वैभ्राज
Vaibhrāja  (IV)--a forest on the shore of the Sarayū river. M. 121. 17; Vā. 47. 15.

वैमानिक
Vaimānikas --gods like Ādityas, Visvedevas, Sādhyas, Pitṛs, sages like Angiras and so on at the beginning of dāhakala; 1) Br. IV. 2. 29; Vā. 7. 15. residents of tāra and gṛhas; 2) Vā. 101. 31. at the commencement of Pralaya spring forth these gods, with planets and stars, with no social restrictions of caste or orders; went to Maharloka, Janaloka and lastly to Brahmaloka never to come back; appointed by the creator in different stations. 3) Br. II. 6. 16, 21.

वैमृग
Vaimṛga --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 11.

वैरथ
Vairatha --a son of Jyotiṣmat after whom came the Rathākāra kingdom (a part of the Kuśadvīpa). Br. II. 14. 27; Vi. II. 4. 36.

वैरपरायण
Vairaparāyaṇa --a Trayārṣeya. M. 196. 39.

वैरा
Vairā --a R. sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 64.

वैराग्यम्
Vairāgyam --detachment and devotion to jñānam; leads to purification of body and mind. One such person becomes a nirmama. Br. III. 4. 10; IV. 3. 45, 60; Vā. 57. 117; 102. 66, 82; 104. 15. 

वैराज
Vairāja  (I)--father of Ajita Hari; 1) Bhā. VIII. 5. 9. a Lokapāla. 2) Br. II. 21. 157; Vā. 50. 206.

वैराज
Vairāja  (II)--a Prajāpati, whose Pitṛs are formless. M. 13. 3.

वैराज
Vairāja  (III)--same as Sudhāman; 1) M. 124. 95; Br. II. 11. 14. a son of Viraja, the lord of Prācidik; a Lokapāla; 2) Vā. 28. 11. married Śatarūpā whose sons were Priyavrata and Uttānapāda and whose daughters were Ākūtī and Prasūtī; 3) Br. II. 9. 39. grandfather of Cākṣuṣa Manu. 4) Vā. 62. 90.

वैराज
Vairāja  (IV)--the 27th kalpa;^1 (19th kalpa-Vā. P.); the period of Vairāja Manu, son of the Creator. M. 290. 10; Vā. 21. 40-2; Br. IV. 2. 65.

वैराज
Vairāja  (V)--is Brahmā. Vā. 100. 43.

वैराज
Vairāja  (VI)--father of Nadvalā; a progenitor and father-in-law of sixth Manu. Vi. I. 13. 4.

वैराज
Vairāja  (VII)--also a vīrapuruṣa from whom was born Śatarūpā and two sons Priyavrata and Uttānapāda as also two daughters Ākūtī and Prasūtī. Vā. 10. 15-7.

वैराजम्
Vairājam  (I)--got by tapas; 1) M. 93. 133; 143. 33; Br. II. 30. 44; IV. 2. 60. a loka. 2) Ib. IV. 2. 141.

वैराजम्
Vairājam  (II)--the abode of Brahmā. M. 161. 17. 

वैराजम्
Vairājam  (III)--a metre, creation of. Vā. 9. 52.

वैराजस्थ
Vairājastha --is Brahmā. Br. IV. 1. 40.

वैराजा
Vairājās  (I)--the first gods created by Brahmā to occupy the first worlds by name Samtānakas; among them seven groups are distinguished, three formless and four with form; then earth, rains, food, worship of moon for rice; the formless attain absolution through yoga power; 1) Br. III. 9. 52-62; Vā. 71. 52. the three formless groups are Pitṛs engaged in yoga; 2) Br. III. 10. 4. Ṛbhu and Sanatkumāra come under this class; they attained Brahmaloka or siddhi. 3) Ib. IV. 2. 35, 70 ff.

वैराजा
Vairājās  (II)--a class of formless Pitṛs: Fallen from Yoga, they attain eternal worlds (lokān sanātanān) and are reborn as Brahmavādins at the end of a day of Brahmā: they then gain their old memory and by sānkhya and yoga they attain final release. Their mind-born daughter Menā is the wife of Himavān. M. 13. 3-6.

वैराजा
Vairājās  (III)--the Brahmans living in the Virajasa world; this is said to be the first Kalpa of the Vairājās. Vā. 72. 4; 101. 61-4.

वैराज्य
Vairājyas --(see Vairājās): performers of austerities; stand ten times until ābhūtasamplava, after Pralaya, entering Praṇava aimed at Brahmaloka through Yogadharma and attained the ānanda of Brahmā; six characteristics of; deprived of three bhāvas (body, mind and speech) do not regard dvandva (sukha duhkha, etc.); reach buddhāvasthā. Vā. 101. 37, 71, 80, 81, 140. 

वैराज्यम्
Vairājyam --a Sūktam of the Sāma Samhitā to be recited in the ritual associated with the digging of a tank. M. 58. 36.

वैरिणा
Vairiṇā --the daughter of Dakṣa so-called. Br. I. 1. 112.

वैरिणी
Vairiṇī --one of the wives of Dakṣa, mother of 1000 sons and 60 daughters. M. 5. 8; 146. 15.

वैरूपम्
Vairūpam --created from the west face of Brahmā. Vi. I. 5. 55.

वैरूप्य
Vairūpya --a Sāma; 1) Vā. 9. 51. from the face of Brahmā, 2) Br. II. 8. 52. helped Supratīka elephant to get sārūpyam. 3) Ib. III. 7. 341.

वैरोचनि
Vairocani --a wife of Tvaṣṭa. Vā. 65. 85.

वैलाटसि
Vailāṭasi --a crest on the Mahendra hill. Br. III. 13. 18.

वैवर्तज्ञानम्
Vaivartajñānam --said to be the cause of nivṛtti. Vā. 24. 83.

वैवशपा
Vaivaśapās --Kāśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 8.

वैवस
Vaivasa --a Pravara of the Bhārgavas. M. 195. 39. 

वैवस्वत
Vaivasvata  (I)--Seventh Manu, see under Manu; epoch of; 1) Bhā. I. 1. 109; 3. 15; Br. II. 13. 67; Vā. 21. 15; 62. 4; 64. 1-2; 98. 71. a son of Brahmā from the seventh face; 2) Vā. 1. 127; 23. 114. from Ṛkāra Svara--the 7th face of the 14 faced god; 3) Ib. 21. 39; 26. 39; 31. 15. eight devagaṇas born of Mārīca and Kaśyapa; 4) Br. I. 1. 109; Vā. 64. 1-2. sons of, nine. 5) Ib. 64. 29-30. The great Śrāddhadeva. 6) Vi. III. 1. 30-33.

वैवस्वत
Vaivasvata (antaram)  (II)--the epoch of Vaivasvata Manu in the Vārāha Kalpa; the seventh Manu; Atri and six others are sages who re-establish dharma and reach the final beatitude; here are seven devagaṇas, Sādhyas, Viśvas, Rudrās, Maruts, Vasus, Aśvins and Ādityas. Ikṣvāku and 9 others are the sons of Vaivasvata Manu; the reference is to the present manvantara by the term sāmpratam; 1) M. 4. 17; 6. 3; 8. 12; 9. 26-30; 69. 6; 124. 22. having appointed Ilā, his eldest son, he went to Mahendravana for penance; 2) Ib. 11. 40-42. heard from the Matsya the end of kalpa and ruled his territory; he belonged to the solar race; this is the current epoch. 3) Ib. 246. 72; 290. 24; Vi. III. 1. 7. 8.

वैवस्वत
Vaivasvata  (III)--Yama, the God of death; overlord of the Pitṛs; 1) M. 174. 49; 213. 7; Vā. 70. 8; Vi. V. 21. 30. offering of piṇḍas in śrāddha to; 2) Br. III. 8. 8; 11. 94; 12. 39; Vi. III. 15. 28. resident of Samyamana. 3) Vā. 50. 88; 108. 30; 111. 39.

वैवस्वत
Vaivasvata  (IV)--temple of, in Supakṣa hill. Vā. 39. 63.

वैवस्वत
Vaivasvata  (V)--the planet Śanaiścara with Prakṛti of Rudra. Vā. 53. 32.

वैवस्वत
Vaivasvata  (VI)--a son of Samjña; learned and great; antara of, constituting 28 yugas when rājaṛṣis rule at the end  of which a period of 40 yugas set in; 1) Vā. 100. 56; 99. 435, 457-60; Vi. III. 2. 2. offered the kingdom of earth after the epoch of Cākṣuṣa Manu; the first Manu had nine sons; finding at first that he could not create beings he caused a sacrifice in honour of Mitra and Varuṇa out of which came Iḍā or Ilā. 2) Vā. 85. 1-7.

वैश
Vaiśa --also Vidarbha; the son of Saivyā and Jyāmagha after the former's severe austerities; married Snuṣā; got two sons and a third Lomapāda. Vā. 95. 36.

वैशम्पायन
Vaiśampāyana  (I)--a pupil of Vyāsa in charge of the Yajus; was taught Nigada (Yajurveda). His pupils were Carakādhvaryus. Yājñavalkya was one of the pupils; was also a Paurāṇika. 1) Bhā. I. 4. 21; XII. 6. 52 and 61; XII. 7. 5. Vā. 60. 13; 61. 5. A Śrutaṛṣi, divided the Yajur Veda into 86 parts and distributed them among his 86 pupils; 2) Br. II. 1. 13; 33. 5; 34. 13; 35. 8-9, 20-22. did not attend the Meru conference and ordered his pupils to take to Brahma vidyā. 3) Vā. 61. 14-16.

वैशम्पायन
Vaiśampāyana  (II)--a sage who was invited for the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhīra. Bhā. X. 74. 8.

वैशम्पायन
Vaiśampāyana  (III)--the sage who cursed king Janamejaya; questioned by Śaunaka for light on rituals conducive to realisation of one's desires. M. 50. 58; 93. 1; Vā. 99. 251.

वैशम्पायन
Vaiśampāyana  (IV)--of Bhārgava gotra. M. 195. 24. 

वैशस
Vaiśasa --the kingdom to which Puramjana went with his companion Lubdhaka; allegorically Naraka. Bhā. IV. 25. 53; 29. 15; V. 26. 25.

वैशाकपूर्णिमा
Vaiśākapūrṇimā --the full moon day of the Vaiśākha month; good for gift of the Brāhma Purāṇa. M. 53. 13.

वैशाख
Vaiśākha --(Tṛtīya) a Yugādi for śrāddha. M. 17. 4; 56. 3.

वैशाख
Vaiśākha śukla dvādaśi --the 12th day of the bright half of Vaiśākha, the day on which Uṣā dreamt of her future husband. Vi. V. 32. 14.

वैशाखी
Vaiśākhī --one of the 13 wives of Vasudeva, the son of Kauśika. Vā. 96. 160, 172.

वैशाख्य
Vaiśākhya --a pupil of Parāśara Kauthuma. Br. II. 35. 46.

वैशाली
Vaiśālī  (I)--founded by king Viśāla. Bhā. IX. 2. 33; Vā. 61. 46.

वैशाली
Vaiśālī  (II)--one of Vasudeva's queens and mother of Kauśika. Br. III. 71. 174; Vi. IV. 15. 25.

वैशाली
Vaiśālī  (III)--an Ārṣeya pravara. M. 196. 8.

वैश्यम्
Vaiśyam --represents Dvāparayuga. Vā. 78. 36. 

वैश्य
Vaiśyas --created from the thighs of Brahmā; the less powerful, but are engaged in agriculture and commerce; 1) Vā. 30. 232; 34. 17; 45. 83 and 117; 54. 111; 57. 52; 78. 29; 93. 66; 100. 246; 101. 5 and 352; 104. 13; Vi. I. 6. 6, 35. for doing their svadharma they go to the abode of Vāyu. 2) Br. I. 5. 108; 7. 157, 166; Vi. III. 8. 30-31, 39. propitiate Ājyapa Pitṛs; 3) Br. III. 10. 94; M. 15. 21. selling and buying, their duties; 4) Br. III. 15. 51. protected by Yayāti; 5) Ib. III. 68. 67. for the sake of 100 Vaiśyas one Brahman may be killed; 6) Ib. IV. 6. 43. profession originated in the time of Pṛthu; 7) Ib. II. 37. 10. meditate on Devī's 108 names; 8) M. 13. 63. observe 15 days' pollution for father's death; 9) Ib. 18. 2. to be much in numbers in a State. 10) Ib. 114. 12; 217. 2.

वैश्या
Vaiśyā --a wife of Vasudeva. M. 46. 20.

वैश्रम्भक
Vaiśrambhaka --a pleasure garden to which Kardama and Devahūti went. Bhā. III. 23. 40.

वैश्रवण
Vaiśravaṇa  (I)--a Ṛṣika and a king who became sage by satya. Br. II. 32. 102; M. 145. 96; Vā. 59. 94.

वैश्रवण
Vaiśravaṇa  (II)--served as calf when the Yakṣas milked the earth; 1) Br. II. 36. 216; M. 10. 22. overlord of the Yakṣas and the Rākṣasas; the first son of Viśravas and Davavarṇinī; seeing the Rākṣasa form and asura prowess he got the name Kubera; 2) Br. III. 8. 7, 40-46; M. 8. 3; 154. 338. defeated by Kālanemi. 3) Ib. 174. 49; 177. 49.

वैश्रवण
Vaiśravaṇa  (III)--is Rāvaṇa. Br. III. 71. 160. 

वैश्रवण
Vaiśravaṇa  (IV)--(Kubera: Kuśarīram beram); the first son of Viśravas and Devavarṇinī; in form a Rākṣasa and in strength an Asura; description of; three feet, big head, eight teeth, yellow moustache, ears like śanku, short hands; full of the knowledge of Vaivarta; and in the guise of Viśvarūpa or various forms; 1) Vā. 70. 35-40; Vi. I. 22. 3. the king of Yakṣas. 2) Vā. 30. 84-5; 41. 26; 62. 182; 70. 7.

वैश्रवणालय
Vaiśravaṇālaya --a tīrtha sacred to Nidhi. M. 13. 51.

वैश्वदेव
Vaiśvadeva (ka)  (I)--Agni also known as Brāhmaṇa chamsi. Br. II. 12. 29; Vā. 62. 137.

वैश्वदेव
Vaiśvadeva  (II)--a muhūrta of the afternoon. Br. III. 3. 39; Vā. 66. 40.

वैश्वदेव
Vaiśvadeva  (III)--is a homa, generally before the principal meals of the day; 1) Br. III. 14. 5; M. 16. 55; 17. 61; Vi. II. 15. 9; III. 11. 47-57. food to Vāstu follows this; 2) M. 252. 17; done in evenings also. 3) Vi. III. 11. 105; 15. 16 and 50.

वैश्वदैविकि
Vaiśvadaiviki --the eighth day in the dark half of Māgha. Vā. 81. 3.

वैश्वानर
Vaiśvānara  (I)--a name of Agni; 1) Bhā. II. 2. 24. to be propitiated by eight oblations or Vaiśvadeva and five others. Prāṇa, apāna, samāna, udāna and vyāna. 2) Vā. 15. 3-8. 

वैश्वानर
Vaiśvānara  (II)--a son of Danu, and father of four daughters, Upadānavī and others. Bhā. VI. 6. 33; Br. III. 6. 7; Vā. 68. 7.

वैश्वानर
Vaiśvānara  (III)--father of two daughters, Pulomā and Kāla (li) kā who were married to Mārica; from them 74,000 Dānavas; lived in Hiraṇyapura; slain by Arjuna. M. 6. 22; Vā. 68. 23-27.

वैश्वानर
Vaiśvānara  (IV)--resides in Somapānam tīrtham. M. 22. 62.

वैश्वानर
Vaiśvānara  (V)--a son of Bharatāgni. Vā. 29. 8; Br. II. 12. 8.

वैश्वानरपथ
Vaiśvānarapatha --outside it was Pitṛyāna. Vi. II. 8. 85; Br. II. 21. 103, 159; M. 124. 80.

वैश्वानरम्
Vaiśvānaram --the Dakṣiṇasthānam, which has three roads or vīthis. Br. I. 2. 28; Vā. 45. 91; 50. 156; 66. 47, 52.

वैश्वानरव्रतम्
Vaiśvānaravratam --leads to the world of Brahmā. M. 101. 57.

वैश्वानरि
Vaiśvānari  (I)--of Bhārgava gotra. M. 195. 19.

वैश्वानरि
Vaiśvānari  (II)--a nakṣatra. Vā. 66. 51.

वैश्वानरि
Vaiśvānari (vīthi)  (III)--in Dakṣiṇa mārga; Mūlam and Pūrvottarāṣāḍhas are the nakṣatras. M. 124. 59; Vā. 66. 52. 

वैषुवतीगति
Vaiṣuvatīgati  --vernal equinox; 1) Vi. II. 8. 29. day and night equal; this viṣuvam takes place during the spring and autumn when the sun enters the signs of Aries (Tulām) and Libra (Meṣa). 2) Ib. II. 8. 65-7.

वैष्ठिय
Vaiṣṭhiya --the place of Angāri Agni. Br. II. 12. 30.

वैष्णव
Vaiṣṇava --a muhūrta of the night. Br. III. 3. 43; Vā. 66. 44.

वैष्णव
Vaiṣṇavas --eligible for Pārvaṇa śrāddha. M. 16. 9.

वैष्णवम्
Vaiṣṇavam  (I)--the Purāṇa of 23,000 ślokas compiled by Parāśara; he who copies this and makes a gift of it on the āṣāḍha full moon day reaches the world of Varuṇa; gives an account of Varāha kalpa. M. 53. 16-17.

वैष्णवम्
Vaiṣṇavam  (II)--one of the six darśanas; 1) Vā. 104. 16. the heart of the personified Veda. 2) Ib. 104. 82.

वैष्णवम्
Vaiṣṇavam lokam --is Vaikuṇṭha. Br. III. 36. 61.

वैष्णवज्वर
Vaiṣṇavajvara --vanquished Māheśvara jvara. Bhā. X. 63. 23-4.

वैष्णवी
Vaiṣṇavī  (I)--a name of Yogamāyā; 1) Bhā. X. 2. 11. Sātvikī śakti; 2) Br. IV. 19. 7; 36. 58; 44. 111; Vi. II. 11. 14. a mind-born mother; 3) M. 179. 11. makes the sun shine radiant. 4) Vi. II. 11. 20. 

वैष्णवी
Vaiṣṇavī  (II)--a goddess among the mātṛs; Icon of, after the manner of Viṣṇu; Garuḍa is the riding animal; four hands in the varada pose. M. 13. 52; 261. 28.

वैहायस
Vaihāyasa --an aerial car constructed by Maya. Bhā. VIII. 10. 16.

वैहायसी
Vaihāyasī --a R. in Bhārata varṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 18.

वैहार
Vaihāra --a Mt. in Bhārata varṣa. Br. II. 16. 20; Vā. 45. 90.

वैहीनरि
Vaihīnari --of Bhārgava gotra. M. 195. 19.

वोढु
Voḍhu  (I)--a Brahmaṛṣi. M. 102. 18.

वोढु
Voḍhu  (II)--a son of Brahmā. Vā. 101. 338.

वौलि
Vauli --an Ekārṣeya. M. 206. 6.

वौषडि
Vauṣaḍi --a sage. M. 196. 26.

व्यक्त
Vyakta --the second form of Parabrahmam. Vi. I. 2. 15, 18.

व्यक्तम्
Vyaktam --the absolute, developed out of avyakta; 1) Vā. 101. 211. swallowed by avyakta in the stage of Pratyāhara; 2) Ib. 102. 2. of five characteristics; 3) Ib. 34. 37. seen by tarka and yoga as also by pratyāhara, dhyāna and tapas. 4) Br. IV. 2. 115, 213; 3. 107-8; 4. 71. 

व्यजय
Vyajaya --a son of Bhṛgu. Vā. 65. 87.

व्यतीपात
Vyatīpāta --(of full moon) when the sun and moon look at each other; when they stand equally at one point it is Vyatīpāta day; it is reckoned to be Vaṣaṭkriyākāla; 1) Br. II. 28. 40-44; Vā. 56. 37-8. a yugādi fit for śrāddha; 2) M. 17. 3; 82. 25. inauspicious for building houses. 3) Ib. 83. 7; 141. 35; 253. 7.

व्यपोहिनि
Vyapohini --a special rite in the sacrifice. Vā. 65. 56.

व्यंश
Vyaṃśa --a nephew of Hiraṇyakaśipu. M. 6. 26.

व्यवधारण
Vyavadhāraṇa kalpana --(ety.) one of the ten lakṣaṇas of the Brāhmaṇas. Vā. 59. 138.

व्यवसाय
Vyavasāya --a son of Vapu. Vā. 10. 36; Br. II. 9. 61.

व्यश्रुष
Vyaśruṣa --a son of Bhṛgu. Vā. 65. 87.

व्यष्टि
Vyaṣṭi --individuality as opposed to samaṣṭi or Brahmam. Vā. 3. 10.

व्यसनानि
Vyasanāni --the difficulties and dangers of a kingdom; the king must avert them. M. 220. 25.

व्याकरण
Vyākaraṇa --Pāṇini's grammar. Br. III. 19. 22; Vā. 83. 52; Vi. V. 1. 38. 

व्याख्यान
Vyākhyāna vedikā --the place where sages expound the Vedic lore. Br. III. 21. 52.

व्याघ्र
Vyāghra  (I)--a son of Yātudhāna and father of Nirānanda. Br. III. 7. 89 and 96.

व्याघ्र
Vyāghra  (II)--one of the five sons of Ūrddhvadṛṣṭi and father of Śarabha. Br. III. 7. 205.

व्याघ्र
Vyāghra  (III)--the tiger, said to have eaten Garga's cow; 1) M. 20. 10. its skin, the dress of Śiva. 2) Ib. 217. 5; 259. 6.

व्याघ्र
Vyāghra  (IV)--a snake with the sun in Āvaṇi and Puraṭṭāśi. Vā. 52. 11.

व्याघ्र
Vyāghra  (V)--a piśāca. Vā. 69. 127.

व्याघ्र
Vyāghra  (VI)--the Rākṣasa residing in the sun's chariot in the Bhādrapada month. Vi. II. 10. 10.

व्याघ्र
Vyāghra  (VII)--the Rākṣasa presiding over the month of Nabhasya. Bhā. XII. 11. 38; Br. II. 23. 11.

व्याघ्र
Vyāghras --born of Hari and Pulaha; a vānarajāti and son of Jāmbavān; 1) Br. III. 7. 176, 304, 319; 51. 9. could be killed as wild animals. 2) Ib. IV. 6. 50; 29. 41. 

व्याघ्रपादा
Vyāghrapādā --a Vāsiṣṭha. M. 200. 2.

व्याघ्री
Vyāghrī --wife of Jāmbavat; mother of Jāmbavatī. Br. III. 7. 301.

व्याज
Vyāja --a son of Bhṛgu; a deva. Br. III. 1. 89.

व्याध
Vyādha --a hunter who attained permanent fame. Bhā. X. 72. 21.

व्याधाज्य
Vyādhājya --of Bhārgavagotra. M. 195. 27.

व्याधि
Vyādhi --a son of Mṛtyu. Vā. 10. 41.

व्याधिनी
Vyādhinī --a śakti. Br. IV. 35. 99.

व्यान
Vyāna  (I)--a Tuṣita. Br. III. 3. 19; Vā. 66. 18.

व्यान
Vyāna  (II)--a mind-born son of Brahmā in the 21st Kalpa. Vā. 21. 47; 31. 41.

व्यापक
Vyāpaka --all pervadingness from apavarga; from that comes Puruṣa. Vā. 13. 23.

व्यापिनी
Vyāpinī --a śakti. Br. IV. 35. 99; 44. 62. 

व्यापृत
Vyāpṛta --a god of Sutāra group. Br. IV. 1. 90.

व्यापृथ
Vyāpṛtha --one of the ten branches of the Supāra group of devas. Vā. 100. 94.

व्याल
Vyāla --from the hairs of the head of Prajāpati. ety. ahi, the vilest of creatures; Pannaga. ety. creeping on the ground; sarpa, from escaping or fleeting nature; all have their abode in the earth under the sun and moon; out of anger came viṣa or poison; then airy beings were created; cūṭas, piśācas from eating flesh, Gandharvas sucking cows. Vā. 9. 34-40.

व्यालयज्ञोपवीतिन्
Vyālayajñopavītin --is Śiva. Br. II. 27. 99.

व्यास
Vyāsa  (I)--an amśāvatāra of Viṣṇu; also known as Dvaipāyana and Kṛṣṇa; son of Parāśara and Vāsavī (Satyavatī) in Dvāpara yuga. Father of Śuka; appointed by his mother, he begot three sons on his brother's wife being childlessDhṛtarāṣṭra, Pāṇḍu and Vidura. 1) Bhā. I. 2. 4; 4. 14-15; IX. 22. 22-25; XII. 6. 36; III. 5. 19-20; M. 15. 8; 180. 64; Br. III. 10. 79-80; 13. 77. Rearranged the Vedas into four parts, and taught each of them to four respective pupils--Paila, Vaiśampāyana, Jaimini and Sumantu. Rearranged Itihāsa-Purāṇas also; composed the Bhārata for Strīśūdra-dvijabandhus; composed also the Bhāgavata and taught it to his son Śuka, having heard it from Nārada. 2) Bhā. XII. 6. 49-53; I. 4. 16-25; 7. 1-8; II. 9. 44; III. 5. 10 and 12; XII. 4. 42; 13. 19; Br. I. 1. 25; II. 31. 28; 33. 32-3; 34. 11-12; III. 17. 295.  When he felt a mental dissatisfaction, Nārada met him and was praised. Asked as to the reason for his uneasiness, Nārada emphasised devotion to Hari as the means of release and proceeded to narrate the story of his previous birth. When the sage left Vyāsa retired to his hermitage Śamyāprāsa on the Sarasvatī and meditated on the Lord who appeared before him with māyā depending on him. Learnt  devotion as the means of ending samsāra. 3) Bhā. I. 4. 30-33; chh. 5 and 6 (whole); 7. 1-4; One of Yudhiṣṭhira's party on a visit to Bhīṣma; was a Purohita at Kṛṣṇa's sacrifice at Kurukṣetra; told the history of Citraketu to Śuka who bowed to him. 4) Ib. I. 8. 46; 9. 2; X. 90. 46[2]; VI. 14. 9; VII. 1. 5. Heard Śrutigītā from Nārāyaṇa. Faith in Kriyāyoga; a siddha. 5) Ib. X. 87. 47-8; XI. 27. 2; VI. 15. 12. Taught Lomaharṣaṇa about the future of the world and its history. 6) M. 50. 72. An incarnation of the Lord in every dvāpara; 7) Ib. 53. 9. took a vow of silence and fasting for 12 years after which he wandered for food but could not get any in Benares; when he was about to curse the city, Śiva and Umā took the guise of householders and offered him rich food. So he blessed it. 8) Ib. 185. 17-38. A tīrtha in his honour. 9) Ib. 191. 41; 203. 14.

व्यास
Vyāsa  (II)--a sage of the eighth manvantara. Bhā. VIII. 13. 15; Vi. III. 2. 17.

व्यास
Vyāsa tīrtham --near Dṛṣadvati; 1) Br. III. 13. 69, 80. in Dīpeśvara, a tīrtham of the Narmadā sacred to Vyāsa. 2) M. 191. 38-42.

व्यास
Vyāsa saras --the sacred lake near Śiva lake. Br. III. 13. 52; Vā. 77. 51.

व्याहृति
Vyāhṛtis --daughters of Savitā; 1) Bhā. VI. 18. 1; III. 12. 44. three in number. 2) Vā. 64. 19.

व्युच्छिन्न
Vyucchinna Pratisandhi --complete extermination between one kalpa and the next one, while the sandhis or connections between the manvantaras or yugas is not broken (avyucchinna sandhi). Vā. 7. 8-9. 

व्युषिताश्व
Vyuṣitāśva --a son of Śankhaṇa and father of Viśvasaha. Br. III. 63. 206.

व्युष्ट
Vyuṣṭa  (I)--a son of Doṣā and Puṣpārṇa; wife Puṣkariṇī and son Sarvatejas. Bhā. IV. 13. 14.

व्युष्ट
Vyuṣṭa  (II)--a son of Vibhāvasu, and a Vasu. Bhā. VI. 6. 16.

व्युष्टि
Vyuṣṭi --one of the ten branches of the Rohita clan of devas. Vā. 100. 91.

व्यूहतत्वविधानम्
Vyūhatatvavidhānam --the knowledge of Vyūha. M. 215. 10.

व्योम
Vyoma  (I)--a son of Daśārha, and father of Jīmūta. Bhā. IX. 24. 3-4; Br. III. 70. 41; M. 44. 40; Vā. 95. 40; Vi. IV. 12. 41.

व्योम
Vyoma  (II)--a son of Maya and follower of Kamsa, came to Vraja in the guise of a Gopa, and mixed in a game with Gopas. Removed a good number of them to a cave nearby. Finding the numbers reduced, Kṛṣṇa spotted out the mischievous foe and killed him on the spot. Bhā. X. 37. 28-32.

व्योम
Vyoma  (III)--one of the ten horses of the moon's chariot. Br. II. 23. 57.

व्योम
Vyoma  (IV)--the intervening space between heaven and earth. M. 2. 32. 

व्योमचारिणी
Vyomacāriṇī --the goddess from the back portion of Nṛsimha; follower of Vāgiśī. M. 179. 68.

व्योममृग
Vyomamṛga --a horse of the moon's chariot. M. 126. 52.

व्योमरूपिका
Vyomarūpikā --a śakti. Br. IV. 35. 99.

व्योमी
Vyomī --a horse of the moon's chariot. Vā. 52. 53.

व्रज
Vraja  (I)--a son of Havirdhāna. Vā. 63. 23.

व्रज
Vraja  (II)--(Gokulam) the residence of cowherds. 1) Vi. V. 5. 11. Here lived Rohiṇī, Nanda and others. Keśin was killed in this place. Visit of Akrūra to. Nanda's return to Vraja after Kamsa's death. Visited by Uddhava at Kṛṣṇa's request. Visited by Balarāma. 2) Bhā. IX. 24. 66; X. 1. 9; 2. 7; 5. 6 and 18; 37. 1 [1]; 38. 1 and 24, 28; 45. 25; 46. 3 and 7; 47. 9 and 55; 65. 1. Deserted by the cowherds after their supposed ill omens, the boy sports of Kṛṣṇa. 3) Vi. V. 6. 27; 7. 8.

व्रजक
Vrajakas --a Janapada of the Bhadrā continent. Vā. 43. 19.

व्रजन
Vrajana --a Sudharmāna god. Br. IV. 1. 60.

व्रजपति
Vrajapati --is Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 37. 11.

व्रजाजिनौ
Vrajājinau --sons of Ūru and Āgneyī. Br. II. 36. 108.

व्रत
Vrata  (I)--a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu. Bhā. IV. 13. 16. 

व्रत
Vrata  (II)--a god of the Ābhūtaraya group. Br. II. 36. 56.

व्रत
Vratas --vows enumerated. M. Ch. 101 (whole).

व्रतवती
Vratavatī --a wife of Bhangakāra (s.v.). M. 45. 20.

व्रतिनी
Vratinī --a daughter of Bhangakāra and queen of Kṛṣṇa. M. 45. 21.

व्रती
Vratī --a sham heretic. Br. III. 14. 41.

व्रतेयु
Vrateyu --a son of Raudrāśva. Bhā. IX. 20. 4.

व्रात
Vrāta --a son of Kṛtamjaya. Vā. 99. 287.

व्रातपति
Vrātapati --a son of Śakrajit and a great warrior. Vā. 96. 53.

व्रातिनी
Vrātinī --a second daughter of Bhangakāra given to Kṛṣṇa in marriage. Vā. 96. 55.

व्रात्य
Vrātyas --a stage devoid of varṇa and āśrama conduct; 1) Br. III. 48. 47. the rule of, in the south and north. 2) Vi. IV. 24. 68-69.

व्
V (B) rindāvanam --the Gopas immigrated to this forest region from Vraja to avoid omens that threatened that place. Vi. V. 6. 24 ff; 16. 1.

व्रीहि
Vrīhi --a kind of paddy. Br. II. 7. 144; M. 34. 11; 239. 22; Vā. 93. 96.  S

शक
Śaka  (I)--a northern kingdom. Br. II. 16. 48.

शक
Śaka  (II)--the tree after which the Śākadvīpa takes its name. Br. II. 19. 94, 140.

शक
Śaka  (III)--a son of Bṛhadratha Maurya, ruled for 36 years; his grandson ruled for 17 years. (?) M. 272. 24.

शक
Śakas  (I)--a hill tribe; 1) Br. II. 16. 67; III. 48. 23, 44 and 49; Vā. 88. 122; 98. 107. were defeated by Paraśurāma, Sagara and Bharata; punished with half shaving; 2) Bhā. IX. 8. 5; 20. 30; III. 41. 39; Vi. IV. 3. 42; were denied the Vedic study and sacrifice and hence reduced to Mlecchahood. 3) Ib. IV. 3. 48.

शक
Śakas  (II)--the 18 kings (ten-Vā. P.) of, ruled for 380 years; 1) M. 50. 76; 273. 18; Vā. 99. 268, 324, 359, 361. kingdom of; 2) M. 114. 41; 121. 45; 144. 57. contemporaries of the Śiśunāgas, and after Gardabins; to be conquered by Kalki. 3) Br. III. 63. 120, 134; 73. 108; 74. 137. 172 and 175; Vi. IV. 3. 47.

शकट
Śakaṭa --(cart) upturned by Kṛṣṇa as a baby. (Taken generally to be an Asura) 1) Bhā. X. 7. 7-10; Br. IV. 29. 124. of Nanda, apparently his waggon or cart, which was then a means of transport. 2) Vi. V. 5. 1 and 6: 5. 22; 6. 1 and 23 ff; 15. 2. 

शकटा
Śakaṭās --of the Agastya family. M. 202. 1.

शकटासुरभञ्जन
Śakaṭāsurabhañjana --is Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 36. 24.

शकवर्ण
Śakavarṇa --a son of Śiśunāka; ruled for 36 years; conquered Girivraja. Vā. 99. 315, 316.

शकुन
Śakuna (i)  (I)--an Asura follower of Hiraṇyakaśipu, and a son of Hiraṇyākṣa. Bhā. VII. 2. 5 and 18; Br. III. 5. 30; M. 6. 14; Vā. 67. 67; Vi. I. 21. 3.

शकुन
Śakuna  (II)--a Pṛthuka god. Br. II. 36. 73.

शकुनज्ञानम्
Śakunajñānam --the science of birds, etc; 1) M. 215. 9; in connection with founding temples. 2) Ib. 240. 15; 264. 9.

शकुनि
Śakuni  (I)--(saubala) a prince of Gāndhāra and an evil adviser to Duryodhana; joined him in insulting Vidura; attacked the northern gate of Mathurā, and the eastern gate of Gomanta when they were besieged by Jarāsandha. Bhā. III. 1. 14; 3. 13; VII. 2. 18; X. 50. 11 [7]; 52. 11. [6].

शकुनि
Śakuni  (II)--father of Asura Vṛka; took part in the Devāsura war between Bali and Indra. Bhā. VIII. 10. 20; X. 88. 14. 

शकुनि
Śakuni  (III)--a son of (Ekā) Daśaratha and father of Karambhi (aka). Bhā. IX. 24. 4-5; Br. III. 70. 44; Vā. 95. 43; Vi. IV. 12. 41.

शकुनि
Śakuni  (IV)--a son of Vikukṣi. Br. III. 63. 9.

शकुनि
Śakuni  (V)--a son of Sanadvāja; father of Svāgata. Br. III. 64. 20.

शकुनि
Śakuni  (VI)--a son of Danu M. 6. 17.

शकुनि
Śakuni  (VII)--a son of Dṛḍharatha and father of Karambha. M. 44. 42.

शकुनि
Śakuni  (VIII)--had 500 brothers who were rulers of Uttarāpathadeśa; of these 48 had sovereignty over the south; all sons of Ikṣvāku. Vā. 88. 9.

शकुनि
Śakuni  (IX)--a son of Sutadvāja. Vā. 89. 20.

शकुनी
Śakunī  (I)--a daughter of Bali. Br. III. 5. 43; Vā. 67. 84.

शकुनी
Śakunī  (II)--the wife of Nāka. Br. III. 59. 13; Vā. 84. 13. 

शकुनी
Śakunī  (III)--a mind-born mother. M. 179. 12.

शकुन्तला
Śakuntalā --the daughter of Viśvāmitra and Menakā; was brought up in Kaṇva's āśrama with nīvāra food; Duṣyanta who came there was entertained and was accepted as her Lord by Gāndharva vidhi. Gave birth to the future Bharata and came to the king's palace with the child; was refused admission by the king who had forgotten her. A voice in the air urged the king to accept her and he did so; 1) Bhā. IX. 20. 8-22 [1-2]; M. 49. 11; Cā. 99. 134. a queen of Duṣyanta and mother of Bharata. 2) Vi. IV. 19. 12-13.

शक्त
Śaktas --a devagaṇa, mind-born sons of Brahmā, in the Svāyambhuva epoch. Br. II. 13. 90.

शक्ति
Śakti  (I)--(Śaktri-Br. P.) the eldest of the 100 sons of Vasiṣṭha and Arundhatī. Father of Parāśara through Adṛśyanti; 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 41; Br. I. 1. 9; III. 8. 91; 36. 6; M. 201. 30; Vā. 1. 174; 70. 83. a sage by tapas; a Vedavyāsa. Heard the Vāyu Purāṇa from Dakṣa and narrated it to Parāśara in embryo; 2) Br. II. 32; 99 and 115; 35. 124; IV. 4. 65; M. 196. 26; Vā. 103. 65. a resident of Brahmakṣetra; 3) Vā. 59. 91, 105. cursed king Kalmāṣapāda in Naimiṣa. 4) Ib. 2. 10-11.

शक्ति
Śakti  (II)--the principle identified with Śiva; 1) Bhā. IV. 6. 43. urges creation by Brahmā. 2) Vi. I. 5. 47.

शक्ति
Śakti  (III)--as a daughter of Vasiṣṭha and Arundhatī. Br. I. 2. 10. 

शक्ति
Śakti  (IV)--(Parāśakti): the Goddess as potency in all creatures; by worshipping her in any manner one gets salvation; 1) M. 13. 53. by worshipping her Śiva became Ardhanārīśvara; as also other Gods like Brahmā; known as Tripurā; 2) Br. IV. 5. 29. mind-born daughter of Brahmā by name Prakṛti; was born during the course of the churning of the ocean; known also as Bhagavatī and Māyā; angry at not getting a share in the yajña of Yuvanāśva but appeased by Brahmā that she may be propitiated with paśu offerings. 3) Ib. IV. 6. 6, 53, 67. A number of Śaktis mounted on cuckoos, swans, mungooses followed Lalitā's army. 4) Ib. IV. 17. 23.

शक्ति
Śakti  (V)--the tula or balance of scale, addressed as. M. 274. 59.

शक्ति
Śakti  (VI)--the name of Vyāsa in the 25th (27th-Vi. P.) Dvāpara; Muṇḍīśvara avatār of the lord. Vā. 23. 208; Vi. III. 3. 18.

शक्ति
Śakti  (VII)--a resident of Brahmakṣetra. Vā. 59. 105.

शक्ति
Śakti  (VIII)--an Ajitadeva. Vā. 67. 34.

शक्ति
Śakti  (IX)--the wife of Gods generally. Vā. 106. 59.

शक्ति
Śakti  (X)--of Viṣṇu; is Pradhāna puruṣātmaka; this energy separates at the deluge and unites at the time of creation; 1) Vi. II. 7. 31-2. something like fire in wood or oil in sesamum; from Pradhāna germinate intellect and rudiments of things and from them Asuras; 2) Ib. II. 7. 33-9. Pradhāna compared to a tree; Viṣṇu is mūla-prakṛti or the primary nature in whom all beings  exist and all finally immerse; 3) Ib. II. 7. 42-3. is three-fold made up of the three energies of Hari. 4) Ib. VI. 8. 7.

शक्ति
Śakti  (XI)--of Guha, created by Viśvakarma from the Vaiṣṇava effulgence of Sūrya. Vi. III. 2-12.

शक्तिमार्ग
Śaktimārga --leads all to prosperity and heaven irrespective of caste or sex. Br. IV. 43. 79-81.

शक्तिराज
Śaktirāja --a Śrutaṛṣi. Br. II. 33. 8.

शक्तिवर्धन
Śaktivardhana --(Śakti); a sage by tapas; a Brahmavādin. M. 145. 93, 109.

शक्तिसेन
Śaktisena --a son of Nighna. M. 45. 3.

शक्यम
Śakyama --a king of Māhiṣas. Vā. 99. 374.

शक्र
Śakra  (I)--(Śatakratu) a son of Aditi, and surname of Indra (s.v.); his brother Upendra; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 39; 10. 18; Br. II. 6. 11; Vā. 30. 95, 109; 61. 30; 96. 196; 97. 23. deceived Rāji accepting him to be his son in the first instance and finally contrived to oust him from Indrahood. 2) Vā. 92. 88. 

शक्र
Śakra  (II)--a son of Śoṇāśva. M. 44. 79.

शक्र
Śakra  (III)--a son of Śūra. Vā. 96. 137.

शक्र
Śakra  (IV)--an Āditya. Vi. I. 15. 130.

शक्र
Śakra  (V)--Indra; 1) Vi. V. 11. 1; 29. 1; 30. 4 and 26; 34. 1. attended on Diti and cut the embryo in seven parts and later into forty-nine pieces; these are the Maruts; 2) Ib. I. 21. 33, 40. city of Vaśankasāra; 3) Ib. II. 8. 9. joined Bṛhaspati in the Tārakāmaya; 4) Ib. IV. 6. 16. father of Arjuna. 5) Ib. IV. 20. 40.

शक्रक
Śakraka --a Sudharmāṇa god. Br. IV. 1. 60.

शक्रक्
Śakrak (m) ośāntaram --a distance equal to 1000 yojanas. Br. IV. 2. 127; Vā. 101. 127.

शक्रजित्
Śakrajit  (I)--a son of Nighna; to him the sun was a great companion; once he visited him and wanted to see his form; for this the sun handed over Syamantaka the best of gems wearing which he saw his form distinctly; it was so beautiful that he desired to keep the gem himself to which the sun agreed; then he returned to his city with the jewel; he shone like the sun himself and entered the harem to the wonderment of his people. 1) Vā. 96. 20-9. Śakrajit received back the maṇi from Vāsudeva; he had 100 sons by his ten wives; of these three were famous, Bhangakāra, Vratapati and Apasvān. 2) Vā. 96. 50, 53. 

शक्रजित्
Śakrajit  (II)--a son of Śūra. Vā. 96. 137.

शक्रतीर्थम्
Śakratīrtham --on the southern bank of the Narmadā; sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 191. 20; 22. 73.

शक्रपदम्
Śakrapadam --in Gayā. Vā. 111. 52.

शक्रप्रस्थ
Śakraprastha --is Indraprastha. Bhā. X. 71. 22.

शक्रमह
Śakramaha --(Śakrapūja) a festival in honour of Indra; 1) Vi. V. 10. 18 and 25. being the Lord of rains he was expected to shower seasonal rains. 2) Ib. V. 10. 23.

शक्रयणा
Śakrayaṇās --of Kaśyapagotra. M. 199. 4.

शंकमान
Śaṃkamāna --a son of Pravīra, the King of the Mahiṣas. Br. III. 74. 187.

शंकर
Śaṃkara  (I)--a name of Śiva; four kalās of; 1) Bhā. II. 4. 19; Br. II. 9. 90; 13. 62; IV. 35. 97; Vā. 21. 10; 24. 62. 43. 38; 54. 48; 112. 35; Vi. I. 9. 2; V. 34. 29. also Śambhu, Umāpati, Sūlapāṇi, Vṛṣabhadhvaja and Hara; fight of, with Kṛṣṇa for Bāṇa; bound by Jṛmbāstra he became disabled; asked Kṛṣṇa to spare the life of Bāṇa. 2) Ib. V. 32. 8; 33. 21. Also (Śaṃkara)--an epithet of Mahādeva; 3) M. 154. 235. the āśrama of; 4) Ib. 154. 381. approached  Vāsudeva to aid him to put down the Asura Andhakas; 5) Ib. 154. 437, 514; 179. 35. remembered Nṛsimha to vanquish the mātṛgaṇa. 6) Ib. 179. 54; 180. 20.

शंकर
Śaṃkara  (II)--a son of Danu. Vi. I. 21. 4.

शंकरपुरम्
Śaṃkarapuram --same as Śivapuram. M. 283. 17.

शंकरायतनम्
Śaṃkarāyatanam --a Śiva temple. Br. IV. 7. 29.

शंकरी
Śaṃkarī --the devī; became twins in the 26th kalpa. Vā. 21. 59.

शंकु
Śaṃku  (I)--a son of Ugrasena; 1) Bhā. IX. 24. 24; Br. III. 71. 33; M. 44. 74; Vi. IV. 14. 20. a follower of Bali. 2) M. 245. 31.

शंकु
Śaṃku  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Satyā. Bhā. X. 61. 13.

शंकु
Śaṃku  (III)--a son of Ūrjā and Vasiṣṭha. Br. II. 11. 42.

शंकु
Śaṃku  (IV)--one hundred thousand crores. Vā. 101. 97. 

शंकुकर्ण
Śaṃkukarṇa  (I)--the Asura in Tatvalam (AtalamVā. P.); 1) Br. II. 20. 16; III. 6. 4; Vā. 50. 16. one of Danu's sons. 2) Ib. 68. 4.

शंकुकर्ण
Śaṃkukarṇa  (II)--(Vighneśvara); informed Maheśvara of the medicinal tank of waters created by Maya. Br. IV. 44. 66; M. 136. 48, 51.

शंकुकर्णस्
Śaṃkukarṇas --created by Dakṣa. M. 4. 52.

शंकुकर्णम्
Śaṃkukarṇam --a place sacred to Śiva. M. 181. 27.

शंकुकर्णी
Śaṃkukarṇī --a mother goddess. M. 179. 31.

शंकुकूट
Śaṃkukūṭa --(Śankhakūṭa) a Mt. north of the Mahābhadra lake. Vā. 36. 31; 42. 65.

शंकुनिरास
Śaṃkunirāsa (ma)ya:  one of Danu's sons. Vā. 68. 4.

शंकुरथ
Śaṃkuratha --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 4.

शंकुरोमन्
Śaṃkuroman --a thousand-hooded snake. M. 6. 41.

शंकुशिरस्
Śaṃkuśiras --a son of Danu; a follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra; joined Bali in the Devāsura battle. Bhā. VI. 6. 30; 10. 19; VIII. 10. 21; Vi. I. 21. 4. 

शंकुशिरोधर
Śaṃkuśirodhara --a son of Danu. M. 6. 17.

शङ्कोद्धार
Śaṅkoddhāra --a tīrtha sacred to Dhvani and the Pitṛs. M. 13. 48; 22. 69.

शंख
Śaṃkha  (I)--a mountain on the base of Meru. Bhā. V. 16. 26.

शंख
Śaṃkha  (II)--an eminent Nāga of Pātāla; 1) Bhā. V. 24. 31; Vā. 69. 70. a Kādraveya nāga; 2) Br. III. 7. 34. a thousand-hooded snake. 3) M. 6. 39.

शंख
Śaṃkha  (III)--to be killed by Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. X. 37. 16.

शंख
Śaṃkha  (IV)--a mind-born son of Jaigīṣavya and Ekapāṭalā; attained heaven by tapas. Br. II. 30. 40; Vā. 72. 19.

शंख
Śaṃkha  (V)--a Yakṣa; a son of Puṇyajanī and Maṇibhadra. Br. III. 7. 123.

शंख
Śaṃkha  (VI)--one of the eight nidhis of Kubera. Vā. 41. 10.

शंख
Śaṃkha  (VII)--the conch of Viṣṇu; 1) Vi. IV. 15. 3. in Rāma's abhiṣeka; 2) Ib. IV. 4. 100. sounded by Kṛṣṇa on the eve of his battle with Indra. 3) Ib. V. 30. 56. Was invoked to protect the baby Kṛṣṇa. 4) Bhā. X. 6. 23. Blowing of it indi cated Kṛṣṇa's arrival in Ānarta; was a sign of auspiciousness; 5) Ib. I. 11. 1 and 18. one of the gifts to please the planet moon; 6) M. 57. 21; 93. 60. war music in the Tārakāmaya war; 7) Ib. 135. 83; 136. 53; 138. 3; 149. 2; 174. 16; 177. 24; 192. 28. discovered at the confluence of the Tāmraparṇī and the ocean with pearls. 8) Vā. 77. 25.

शंखकूट
Śaṃkhakūṭa --Mt. a hill range on the north of Meru. Vi. II. 2. 30.

शंखगिरि
Śaṃkhagiri --in Śankhadvīpam. Vā. 48. 32.

शंखचूड
Śaṃkhacūḍa  (I)--a chief Nāga of pātāla. Bhā. V. 24. 31; Br. IV. 33. 36.

शंखचूड
Śaṃkhacūḍa  (II)--a follower of Kubera. He seized certain gopis whom Kṛṣṇa recovered. He was pursued and his head cut off. His cūḍāmaṇi was presented to Balarāma. Bhā. X. 34. 25-32.

शंखण
Śaṃkhaṇa --a son of Vajranābha and father of Vyuṣitāśva. Br. III. 63. 205-6; Vā. 88. 205.

शंखद्वीपम्
Śaṃkhadvīpam --a region of Jambudvīpa; here is Ekarājyam or rule by one, of Mlecchas; here is the hill Śankhagiri from which flows the Śankhanāgā river; the residence of Śankhamukha, the king of Nāgas. Vā. 48. 14, 31-3.

शंखनागा
Śaṃkhanāgā --a R. in the Śankhadvīpam. Vā. 48. 33. 

शंखपद
Śaṃkhapada --a son of Kardama Prajāpati and Śruti anointed king of the south; 1) Br. III. 8. 19; Vā. 28. 19; Vi. I. 22. 12. lord of the south direction; 2) M. 8. 10; Vā. 28. 27-29; Br. II. 11. 22 and 33. attained heaven by tapas; 3) M. 143. 38. a Ṛṣika who became ṛṣi by satya. 4) Ib. 145. 96.

शंखपद्म
Śaṃkhapadma --Royal symbols in the arms of a cakravartin. Br. II. 29. 86; Vā. 57. 79.

शंखपात्
Śaṃkhapāt  (I)--a disciple of Lokākṣi, an avatār of the Lord; 1) Vā. 23. 135. a Rājaṛṣi. 2) Ib. 57. 122.

शंखपात्
Śaṃkhapāt  (II)--a son of Kardama, and Lokapāla of the Lokāloka hill. Vi. II. 8. 83.

शंखपाल
Śaṃkhapāla --the Nāga presiding over the month of Nabhasya; 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 38; Br. II. 23. 9; IV. 20. 54. a 1000 hooded snake; lives with the sun for a part of a year; 2) M. 6. 40; 126. 10. with the sun in Āvaṇi and Puraṭṭāśi; 3) Vā. 52. 10. with the sun in the Bhādrapada month. 4) Vi. II. 10. 10.

शंखमान्
Śaṃkhamān --a sage by garbha. Vā. 59. 94.

शंखमुख
Śaṃkhamukha --the king of the Nāgas in Śankhadvīpa. Vā. 48. 33.

शंखश्वेत
Śaṃkhaśveta --a reptile; (Kādraveya). Vi. I. 21. 21.

शंखा
Śaṃkhā --the city of the second talam. Vā. 50. 21. 

शंखाख्य
Śaṃkhākhya --a daitya in Sutalam. Br. II. 20. 22.

शंखाख्यस्
Śaṃkhākhyas --a Janapada of the Bhadrā continent. Vā. 43. 22.

शंखिनि
Śaṃkhini --a śakti on the fourth parvan of the Kiricakra. Br. IV. 20. 15; 44. 60; M. 286. 10.

शंखिनी
Śaṃkhinī --the Goddess from the back portion of Nṛsimha; follower of Vāgīśī. M. 179. 23. 68.

शङ्ग
Śaṅga --a sage of the epoch of Auttama Manu M. 9. 14.

शची
Śacī --a daughter of Puloma, consort of Indra and mother of Jayanta. Br. II. 13. 79; III 6. 23; M. 6. 21; Vā. 68. 22, 24.

शचीन्द्रौ
Śacīndrau --represent Brahmam. Br. IV. 43. 75.

शचीपति
Śacīpati --Indra; 1) Vi. I. 9. 7; V. 21. 16; 34. 24. adhidevata for Śukragraham; 2) Br. III. 67. 95; M. 93. 14; 251. 4. see Indra.

शट
Śaṭa --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 9.

शठ
Śaṭha --went with Kṛṣṇa to Upaplāvya to see the Pāṇḍavas; 1) Bhā. X. 78. [95 (V) 3]. a son of Vasudeva and Rohiṇī; father of several sons. 2) Br. III. 71. 164, 169-70; Vi. IV. 15 19. 

शठा
Śaṭhās --Ekārṣeyas. M. 200. 3.

शण्ड
Śaṇḍa  (I)--a son of Śukra and a tutor of Prahlāda; reported with Marka to Hiraṇyakaśipu of their inability to bring the boy to his way of thinking and advised him to keep him in custody until Śukra's arrival. Bhā. VII. 5. 1-2, 48-50; Br. III. 1. 78; Vā. 65. 77.

शण्ड
Śaṇḍa  (II)--a Kūṣmāṇḍa Piśāca, one of the two sons of Kapi; father of Brahmadhāmā. Br. III. 7. 74-84.

शण्ड
Śaṇḍa  (III)--an Asura; seen in the bathing ceremony of the sacrifice of the gods; 1) M. 47. 41, 54. one of the disciples of Śukra given to the Asuras to guide them; but he was bought off by the gods by giving him a place in sacrifices. 2) Ib. 47. 224-36.

शण्डिलि
Śaṇḍili  --an Ekārṣeya. M. 200. 5.

शत
Śata --a son of Jambha. Vā. 67. 78.

शतकेसर
Śatakesara --a boundary hill of Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 26.

शतक्रतु
Śatakratu  (I)--a name of Indra; 1) Bhā. IV. 19. 2; Br. II. 24. 38; Vā. 91. 63; Vi. I. 9. 134; V. 10. 19. killed the pupils of Sukarma for adhyaya during anadhyaya. 2) Vā. 61. 29. 

शतक्रतु
Śatakratu  (II)--the name of Vyāsa in the 7th dvāpara; his original name, Vibhu; the avatār of the lord Jaigiṣavya. Vā. 23. 135.

शतक्रतु
Śatakratu  (III)--Nara, a brother of Ādityas. Vā. 66. 61.

शतगामी
Śatagāmī --a son of Jaṭāyu. M. 6. 36.

शतगाल
Śatagāla --a saimhikeya. Vā. 68. 18.

शतगुण
Śataguṇa --a son of Krodhā and a devagandharva. Br. III. 6. 39.

शतग्रीव
Śatagrīva --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 11.

शतघ्न
Śataghna --a son of Upamadgu. Vi. IV. 14. 9.

शतजित्
Śatajit  (I)--one of the hundred sons of Viraja. Bhā. V. 15. 15.

शतजित्
Śatajit  (II)--a son of Sahasrajit (Sahasraji-M. P., Saharajit-Vā. P.) and father of Mahāhaya and two other sons, (three famous sons, Haihaya, Haya and Veṇuhaya, Vi. P. and M. P.); 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 21; M. 43. 7-8; Vā. 94. 3-4; Vi. IV. 11. 6-7. a king. 2) Br. III. 69. 3.

शतजित्
Śatajit  (III)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Jāmbavatī (Sudevī ?); 1) Bhā. X. 61. 11; Br. III. 71. 25. got killed in Prabhāsā. 2) Bhā. XI. 30. 17. 

शतजित्
Śatajit  (IV)--the Yakṣa presiding over the month of Iṣa. Bhā. XII. 11. 43.

शतजित्
Śatajit  (V)--a son of Rajas; had a hundred sons, all kings and responsible for world's progress; 1) Br. II. 14. 70-72; Vā. 33. 60; Vi. II. 1. 40. Viṣvagjyoti, the chief among them, held the whole of Bhāratavarṣa with credit and success; his descendants continued to the Vārāha kalpa. 2) Ib. II. 1. 41-3.

शतजित्
Śatajit  (VI)--a son of Upavātyaka. Br. III. 71. 5.

शतजित्
Śatajit  (VII)--one of the two sons of Sudevī and Viṣvaksena. Vā. 96. 242.

शतजित्
Śatajit  (VIII)--a son of Bhajamāna. Vi. IV. 13. 2.

शततेजस्
Śatatejas --the name of Vyāsa in the 12th dvāpara; avatār of the Lord as Atri. Vā. 23. 154.

शतदंष्ट्र
Śatadaṃṣṭra --a son of Khaśā and a Rākṣasa. Br. III. 7. 135; Vā. 69. 167.

शतदुन्दुभि
Śatadundubhi  (I)--a son of Bāṣkala. Br. III. 5. 38-9.

शतदुन्दुभि
Śatadundubhi  (II)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 232. 

शतदृक्शक्र
Śatadṛkśakra --Indra of 1000 eyes; adopts Yoganidrā as his sister. Vi. V. 1. 81.

शतद्युम्न
Śatadyumna  (I)--a son of Bhānumat and father of Śucī. Bhā. IX. 13. 21-22; Vi. IV. 5. 30.

शतद्युम्न
Śatadyumna  (II)--a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu and Nāḍvalā. Br. II. 36. 79, 106; M. 4. 41; Vā. 62. 91; Vi. I. 13. 5; III. 1. 29.

शतद्री
Śatadrī --a R. in Bhāratavarṣa, flows from the Himālayas. Bhā. V. 19. 18; Br. II. 12. 15; 16. 25; Vā. 45. 95; Vi. II. 3. 10; III. 14. 18.

शतद्रु
Śatadru --in the chariot of Tripurāri. M. 114. 21; 133. 23.

शतद्रुती
Śatadrutī --a queen of Barhiṣat; Agni fell in love with her. Bhā. IV. 24. 11.

शतद्रुसलिलम्
Śatadrusalilam --(Śatadru): a tīrtha sacred to Pitṛs; one of the sixteen rivers married to Havyavāhana. M. 22. 12; 51. 14.

सतद्रू
Satadrū --a wife of Havyavāhana. Vā. 29. 14.

शतधनुस्
Śatadhanus  (I)--a son of Hṛdīka. Bhā. IX. 24. 27; Vi. IV. 14. 24.

शतधनुस्
Śatadhanus  (II)--a son of Devavarman Maurya. Br. III. 74. 148. 

शतधनुस्
Śatadhanus  (III)--a king of yore; his wife Śaivyā, a woman of piety; both worshipped Janārdhana; after fasting on the Kārttika full moon day and bath in the Bhāgīrathī, they met a heretic, a friend of the king's military preceptor; he talked to him but she looked at the sun; soon the king died and she ascended the funeral pyre; for the sin of talking to a heretic he was born as a dog in Vidiśa and his wife as a daughter of the king of Kāśī; she had a knowledge of her former birth and accepted the dog for her husband; when the dog remembered his former condition, he fell dead in a forest and was born as a jackal in the Kolāhala hill; the daughter of the king of Kāśī repaired to the mountain when he remembered his previous birth and was born as a wolf; again the daughter of the king of Kāśī met him; remembering his former state he was born as a vulture, crow and a peacock; when she bathed him during the sacrificial bath of Janaka he was born as the son of Janaka. Then a svayamvara was held, she married him, lived as his queen and attained heaven. See Śaivyā. Vi. III. 18. 53-95.

शतधन्वन्
Śatadhanvan  (I)--the wicked; of the race of Bhojas, and king of Mithilā; set up Akrūra and Kṛtavarman who were displeased with Satrājita for not giving his daughter in marriage to them; Śatadhanvan killed Satrājita while asleep, and walked away with the jewel; when Kṛṣṇa heard of this from Satyabhāmā, he came back to Dvārakā from Hāstinapura to kill Śatadhanvan. Knowing this, the latter requested Kṛtavarman and Akrūra for help and they refused; placing the jewel under Akrūra's custody he rode one hundred yojanas and on reaching Mithilā, his horse fell tired. Then he ran on foot pursued by Kṛṣṇa. Kṛṣṇa got his head cut off but found no jewel. His death was known in Dvārakā; knew the yoga power of Hari. Bhā. X. ch. 57 (whole); 58. 9 [4]; II. 7. 44; Vā. 96. 56-74; Vi. IV. 13. 67-100. 

शतधन्वन्
Śatadhanvan  (II)--the son of Somaśarman and father of Bṛhadratha. Bhā. XII. 1. 15; Vi. IV. 24. 30-1.

शतधन्वन्
Śatadhanvan  (III)--the fifth son of Hṛdīka; 1) Br. III. 71. 140; Vā. 96. 139. the middle (second ?) among the ten sons of Hṛdīka; 2) M. 44. 81. performed saubhāgyaśayanam. 3) Ib. 60. 49.

शतधन्वन्
Śatadhanvan  (IV)--a Maurya king, ruled for six years. M. 272. 23.

शतधन्वन्
Śatadhanvan  (V)--a son of Pracetas; overlord of numerous Mlecchas of the north. Vi. IV. 17. 5.

शतधर
Śatadhara --a son of Devavarma, ruled for eight years. Vā. 99. 335.

शतधृति
Śatadhṛti  (I)--a name of Indra. Bhā. IX. 10. 34.

शतधृति
Śatadhṛti  (II)--a name of Brahmā. Bhā. XI. 4. 5.

शतध्वज
Śatadhvaja  (I)--of Dāśārṇas; was stationed by Jarāsandha on the west of Gomanta fort during its siege. Bhā. X. 52. 11[12].

शतध्वज
Śatadhvaja  (II)--a son of Ūrja and father of Kṛti. Vi. IV. 5. 31.

शतपथ
Śatapathas --a Janapada. Vā. 45. 110. 

शतपर्वन्
Śataparvan --is Indra. Br. III. 5. 69; Vā. 67. 103.

शतबला
Śatabalā --a daughter of Śāraṇa. Br. III. 71. 169; Vā. 96. 167.

शतबलाक
Śatabalāka --a pupil of Rathītara. Br. II. 35. 4.

शतबलि
Śatabali --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 235.

शतबाहु
Śatabāhu --an Asura. Bhā. VII. 2. 4.

शतभिषक्
Śatabhiṣak --a constellation. Vā. 66. 51.

शतभिषा
Śatabhiṣā --a constellation. Bhā. V. 23. 6.

शतमन्यु
Śatamanyu --a name of Indra. Bhā. I. 8. 6.

शतमायु
Śatamāyu --a Dānava. Vā. 68. 11.

शतरथ
Śataratha --a son of Mūlaka. Br. III. 63. 180; Vā. 88. 180. 

शतरुद्र
Śatarudras --a class of Rudras fit to receive oblations at sacrifices. Vā. 10. 59; 30. 244.

शतरुद्रीयम्
Śatarudrīyam --a portion of the Vedic (Yajus) literature except which the Trayī exists until the pralaya; 1) Vā. 59. 57. here the Rudras partake of the offerings; 2) Br. II. 9. 84. sacred to pitṛs; 3) M. 22. 35. Citrakarma, the Gaṇeśvara taught this to Madana; 4) Br. II. 32. 63; IV. 7. 49; 11. 30-33; 34. 52. japa at Benares leads one to eternal beatitude; 5) M. 184. 56. identified with Śiva. 6) Vā. 30. 244.

शतरूप
Śatarūpa --a son of Sutāra, the lord of the II dvāpara. Vā. 23. 121.

शतरूपा
Śatarūpā  (I)--the female half of Brahmā's body--spread over all the worlds; performed austerities for a lakh of years and became queen of Svāyambhuva Manu as Rati; gave marriage presents to her daughter Devahūtī; mother of three daughters, 1) Bhā. III. 12. 54; 21. 26; 22. 23; IV. 1. 1; 8. 7; VIII. 1. 7; XI. 16. 25; Vā. 10. 8-13; 57. 57; Br. II. 9. 15 and 33. and of sons Priyavrata and Uttānapāda; 2) Ib. II. 1. 57; II. 29. 62-3. a tapasvinī. 3) Vi I. 7. 17.

शतरूपा
Śatarūpā  (II)--daughter of Brahmā whom the father married and brought forth Svāyambhuva Manu; other sons, seven in number. M. 3. 31, 43; 4. 24-5.

शतवल्श
Śatavalśa --the mythical banyan tree on the mount Kumuda. From its joints flow rivers capable of fulfilling all desires in Ilāvṛta. Bhā. V. 16. 24-25. 

शतशलाक
Śataśa(i)lāka --the father of Jaigīṣavya who married Ekapāṭala. Br. III. 10. 20; Vā. 72. 18.

शतशृंग
Śataśṛṃga --a Mt. in Śālmalidvīpa; 1) Bhā. V. 20. 10; Br. III. 7. 453. north of the Mahābhadra, has 100 cities. 2) Vā. 36. 32; 39. 54; 42. 69.

शतसंख्या
Śatasaṃkhyā --a group of gods of the X epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 25.

शतसेन
Śatasena --a son of Śāntasena. Bhā. X. 90. 38.

शतह्रद
Śatahrada --a son of Danu. M. 6. 18.

शतह्रदा
Śatahradā --a R. of the Bhadrā continent. Vā. 43. 26.

शताजित्
Śatājit --a son of Bhajamāna. Bhā. IX. 24. 8.

शतानन्द
Śatānanda  (I)--a son of Ahalyā and Gautama, (Śaradvān-M. P.). Father of Satyadhṛti. Bhā. IX. 21. 34-35; M. 50. 8; Vi. IV. 19. 63.

शतानन्द
Śatānanda  (II)--came to see Kṛṣṇa at Syamantapañcaka. Bhā. X. 84. 3.

शतानन्द
Śatānanda  (III)--a sage of the period of Sāvarṇi. M. 9. 32. 

शतानन्द
Śatānanda  (IV)--a son of Śāradvata, a great seer. Vā. 99. 202.

शतानन्दा
Śatānandā --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 11.

शतानीक
Śatānīka  (I)--a son of Nakula and Draupadī. Bhā. IX. 22. 29; M. 50. 53.

शतानीक
Śatānīka  (II)--a son of Janamejaya, versed in Trayī, and a pupil of Yājñavalkya, and also of Śaunaka; learnt the science of arms from Kṛpa; father of Sahasrānīka (Aśvamedhadatta-Vi. P.); 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 38-39. performed Aśvamedha; 2) M. 50. 65-6. asked Śaunaka about Yayāti and his reply; 3) Ib. 25. 3. anointed by Brahmans; 4) Vā. 99. 256. realised ātmajñāna from Śaunaka and attained nirvāṇa. 5) Vi. IV. 21. 3-5.

शतानीक
Śatānīka  (III)--a son of Sudāsa and father of Durdamana. Bhā. IX. 22. 43.

शतानीक
Śatānīka  (IV)--a son of the second Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 72.

शतानीक
Śatānīka  (V)--a son of Vasudāma. M. 50. 86.

शतानीक
Śatānīka  (VI)--a son of Bṛhadratha. Vi. IV. 21. 14.

शतांकू
Śatāṃkū --a daughter of Ugrasena. Vā. 96. 133. 

शतायु
Śatāyu  (I)--a Rākṣasa with the Hemanta sun. Br. II. 23. 19.

शतायु
Śatāyu  (II)--one of the six sons of Purūravas and Ūrvaśī. M. 24. 34; Vā. 91. 52; Vi. IV. 7. 1

शताह्वा
Śatāhvā --a tīrtha sacred to the pitṛs. M. 22. 35.

शताह्व्य
Śatāhvya --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 6.

शत्रुघ्न
Śatrughna  (I)--a son of Daśaratha; bore the bow and quivers when Bharata carried the Pādukā. Father of Subāhu and Śrutasena (Sūrasena-Vi. P.); killed the Rākṣasas Mādhava and Lavaṇa; seized Madhuvana and founded the city, Mathurā. Bhā. IX. 10. 3 and 44; 11. 13-14; Br. III. 63. 185; 71. 111; Vā. 88. 184-5; Vi. I. 12. 4; IV. 4. 87. 101, 104.

शत्रुघ्न
Śatrughna  (II)--a son of Śvaphalka. Bhā. IX. 24. 17.

शत्रुघ्न
Śatrughna  (III)--a son of Bhangakāra and Narā; killed by Akrūra. Br. III. 71. 86-8; Vā. 96. 85.

शत्रुघ्न
Śatrughna  (IV)--a son of Akrūra. M. 45. 29.

शत्रुघ्न
Śatrughna  (V)--a son of Aikṣvākī and Anādhṛṣṭi. M. 46. 24. 

शत्रुघ्न
Śatrughna  (VI)--a son of Gāndinī. Vā. 96. 110.

शत्रुघ्न
Śatrughna  (VII)--the great-grandson of Sātvata, killed by the Bhojas. Vi. IV. 13. 111.

शत्रुजित्
Śatrujit  (I)--see Dyumat. Bhā. IX. 17. 6.

शत्रुजित्
Śatrujit  (II)--a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 237.

शत्रुजित्
Śatrujit  (III)--a son of Śūra. Br. III, 71. 138.

शत्रुजित्
Śatrujit  (IV)--a son of Māndhātā. M. 12. 35.

शत्रुजित्
Śatrujit  (V)--a son of Śoṇāśva. M. 44. 79.

शत्रुजित्
Śatrujit  (VI)--a name of Pratardana. Vi. IV. 8. 12.

शधीय
Śadhīya --a pupil of Kṛta. Br. II. 35. 53.

शनत्कुमार
Śanatkumāra --a son of Anala; 1) Vā. 66. 24; 101. 26, 37, 75, 212; 105. 2; 112. 68. sacred to Kurukṣetra; 2) Ib. 77. 64. discovered yoga; 3) Ib. 83. 84. attended Soma's rājasūya. 4) Ib. 90. 23. 

शनि
Śani --a son of Vivasvat and Chāyā; attained the status of a planet by penance; see Śanaiścara. M. 11. 9 and 38.

सनैश्चर
Sanaiścara  (I)--(Saturn) Śrutakarma, traverses each sign of the zodiac in thirty months--generally an evil planet. 1) Bhā. V. 22. 16. A son of Chāyā and Vivasvat (Mārtāṇḍa-Vi. P.); 2) Ib. VI. 6. 41; VIII. 13. 10; Br. II. 24. 50, 71, 83, etc; III. 59. 32, 49, 82; Vā. 84. 31; Vi. I. 8. 11; III. 2. 4. fought with Naraka in the Devāsura war; 3) Bhā. VIII. 10. 33. fed by the svarāṭ ray of the sun; above the Bṛhaspati planet; goes on in an iron chariot. 4) Br. III. 23. 87; IV. 2. 133. One of the nine grahas; 5) M. 93. 44; Vā. 84. 83. found on the side of Soma; 6) M. 23. 40. rise of, reddish in colour, a bad omen; 7) Ib. 133. 21. stands above Bṛhaspati; 8) Vā. 101. 133. in the chariot of Tripurārī; 9) M. 127. 8; 128. 49; 133. 21. chariot of, drawn by horses. 10) Vā. 52. 79; 53. 32; Vi. II. 12. 20.

शनैश्चर
Śanaiścara  (II)--a son of Rudra and Suvarcalā. Vā. 27. 49; Br. II. 10. 76; 11. 23.

शनैश्चर
Śanaiścara  (III)--an Ātreya. Vā. 28. 20.

शंतनु
Śaṃtanu --a son of Pratīpa and a brother of Devāpī; was a great king learned and a specialist in medicine (mahābhiṣak); it is said that a touch of his hand cured people of any disease and made them youthful again; hence his name Śamtanu; married Jāhnavī; father of Devavrata (Bhīṣma); from the dark fisherwoman he got Vicitravīrya. Another son was Citrāngada; a Paurava with an amśa of  Samudra. 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 12-21; XII. 2. 37; Br. III. 10. 69, 70; M. 14, 17; 50. 11, 39. 45; Vā. 73. 18; 99. 234, 237-41; 111. 70; Vi. IV. 20. 9. 34. Came upon the twins of Satyadhṛti, in the course of a hunting, Kṛpa and Kṛpi and took them by grace; greed for more territory. 2) Bhā. IX. 21. 36; XII. 3. 10; Vā. 1. 158; 99. 204; Vi. IV. 19. 67-8.

शफरी
Śapharī --the form taken by Harī. Bhā. VIII. 24. 9.

शबर
Śabara --an Amitābha god. Br. II. 36. 54.

शबर
Śabaras --an inferior class of people; 1) Bhā. II. 7. 46; M. 114. 47; Vā. 78. 69; 99. 268. on the Himālayas; their country unfit for śrāddha performance; to be conquered by Kalki; 2) Br. III. 14. 80; 22. 22; 73. 108; IV. 29. 131. kings of. 3) M. 50. 76.

शबल
Śabala  (I)--a son of Sarama. Br. III. 7. 312.

शबल
Śabala  (II)--a hell, reached by those who indulge in unrighteous sexual unions Br. IV. 2. 147, 158; Vā. 101. 146, 157.

शबल
Śabala  (III)--one of the two dogs of the family of Vaivasvata to whom Bali is to be offered at Gayā. Vā. 108. 30; 111. 39.

शबल
Śabalas  (I)--sons of Kallolaha. Br. III. 7. 442. 

शबल
Śabalas  (II)--the 1000 sons of Dakṣa through Vairiṇī who died in the attempt to get at the measurement of the earth by following their elder brothers. M. 5. 9.

शबलाश्व
Śabalāśvas --the second one thousand sons of Asiknī and Dakṣa. Advised by Nārada they took to the path of ‘Not returning’, taken by their elder brothers; went to different parts of the world in search of their brothers, Haryaśvas and were lost. Bhā. VI. 5. 24; Br. III. 2. 24-5; Vā. 65. 152-4; Vi. I. 15. 97-100.

शब्दकर्षनिककला
Śabdakarṣanikakalā --a gupta śakti. Br. IV. 19. 17; 44. 117.

शब्दब्रह्मा
Śabdabrahmā --the name of the Creator during Brāhma kalpa; possesses both vyakta and avyakta forms; two forms of spirit; the word and the supreme God; this is the interpretation of Manu, and also the Atharva Veda; the word is the Vedas as distinguished from and leading to Parabrahman (Supreme). Bhā. III. 11. 34; 12. 48; Vā. 104. 94, 110; Vi. VI. 5. 64-5.

शब्दम्
Śabdam --the guṇa of ākāśa; swallowed by Bhūta and others. Vā. 102. 17.

शब्दलक्षणम्
Śabdalakṣaṇam --from śabda came sparśa. Vā. 4. 50-1.

शब्दार्थौ
Śabdārthau --represent Brahman. Br. IV. 43. 76. 

शम
Śama  (I)--a son of Dharmasūtra and father of Dyumatsena. Bhā. IX. 22. 48.

शम
Śama  (II)--a son of Kriyā. Br. II. 9. 60.

शम
Śama  (III)--a son of Āyu. Br. III. 3. 24.

शम
Śama  (IV)--a Sukha god. Br. IV. 1. 19.

शम
Śama  (V)--the regulation of senses on one's own account and on account of others. Vā. 59. 47.

शम
Śama  (VI)--a son of Āpa. Vā. 66. 23.

शम
Śama  (VII)--a mukhya gaṇa. Vā. 100. 18.

शमृथ
Śamṛtha --a kingdom of the west watered by the Sindhu. Br. II. 18. 48.

शमन
Śamana --a son of Vadha. Vā. 69. 130.

शमि
Śami  (I)--a son of Uśīnara. Bhā. IX. 23. 3. 

शमि
Śami  (II)--a son of Śoṇāśva (Śūra-Br. P.) and father of Pratikṣatra. M. 44. 79-80; Br. III. 71. 138.

शमि
Śami  (III)--a son of the daughter of the Kāśi king and Satyaka. Vā. 96. 115.

शमि
Śami  (IV)--a name of Vāsudeva. Vā. 96. 172.

शमित
Śamita --a Sādhya. M. 171. 44.

शमी
Śamī  (I)--a son of Śūra, and father of Pratikṣatra. Vā. 96. 137; Vi. IV. 14. 23.

समी
Samī  (II)--the principal tree of the Kali age. Vi. VI. 1. 53.

शमीक
Śamīka  (I)--a son of Devamīḍha and Māriṣā; queen Sudāminī; father of Sumitra and other sons. Bhā. IX. 24. 29 and 44.

शमीक
Śamīka  (II)--a son of Śūra and Bhoja, and father of four sons; became a Rājaṛṣi. Br. III. 71. 150, 194; M. 46. 3, 27, 28.

शमीक
Śamīka  (III)--a brother of Vāsudeva. Vā. 96. 148.

शम्ब
Śamba --a Dānava with manuṣya dharma. Vā. 68. 15. 

शम्बर
Śambara  (I)--a son of Danu, and a follower of Vṛtra in his battle with Indra. Bhā. VI. 6. 30; 10. 19 [3]; M. 6. 17; 249. 67; Vā. 68. 11; 98. 81; Vi. I. 19. 14; 21. 4.

शम्बर
Śambara  (II)--a son of Hiraṇyākṣa; 1) Bhā. VII. 2. 4 and 18; Br. III. 5. 30. a Dānava king; taken to Pātāla with Bali by Vāmana; 2) Ib. III. 6. 4 and 11; IV. 29. 123; 73. 81. guiles of, towards Prahlāda at the instance of Hiraṇyakaśipu. 3) Vi. I. 15. 153; 16. 9.

शम्बर
Śambara  (III)--a resident of Tripura; participated in the Devāsura war between Bali and Indra; fought with Tvaṣṭri. Bhā. VIII. 6. 31; 10. 19 and 29.

शम्बर
Śambara  (IV)--a companion of Kamsa; walked away with child Pradyumna within ten days [six days (Vi. P.)]
of its birth. He knew that the bady was his enemy but he threw it into the sea and went away. Māyāvatī, the superintendent of his kitchen discovered a child in a fish brought to the kitchen, and hearing from Nārada that it was Kāma reborn, and that she herself was Ratī, she brought up the child and when he came of age, she told him the truth and asked him to fight Śambara with the aid of mahāmāyā vidyā. His head was cut off by Pradyumna. Bhā. X. 36. 36; 55. 3. 24; II. 7. 34; III. 3. 11; Vi. V. 26. 12; Ch. 27 (whole).

शम्बर
Śambara  (V)--(Śabara-Bhā. P.); his greed for more territory. Bhā. XII. 3. 11.

शम्भलग्राम
Śambhalagrāma --(Śambala-Bhā. P.); the birth place of Kalki-Viṣṇu. Bhā. XII. 2. 18; Vi. IV. 24. 98. 

शम्भु
Śambhu  (I)--the Indra of the epoch of the Tenth Manu, and a friend of Viṣvaksena. Bhā. VIII. 13. 22-23.

शम्भु
Śambhu  (II)--a son of Ambarīṣa. Bhā. IX. 6. 1.

शम्भु
Śambhu  (III)--a name of Śiva. Bhā. X. 4. 36; Br. III. 10. 48; M. 154. 438; 171. 38.

शम्भु
Śambhu  (IV)--father of Rājāja and Goma. Br. III. 5. 40.

शम्भु
Śambhu  (V)--a son of Pīvarī and Śuka. Br. III. 8. 93; 10. 81; M. 15. 10; Vā. 73. 30.

शम्भु
Śambhu  (VI)--one of the eleven Rudras; 1) M. 153. 19; 171. 38; Vi. I. 15. 122. had the Ganga in his plaited hair for more than 100 years. 2) Ib. II. 8. 115; V. 32. 11; 33. 4.

शम्भु
Śambhu  (VII)--a son of Virocana; had six sons. Vā. 67. 76, 81.

शम्भु
Śambhu  (VIII)--a son of Bhavya. Vi. I. 13. 1.

शम्याप्रास
Śamyāprāsa --the hermitage of Vyāsa on the bank of the Sarasvatī. Bhā. I. 7. 2-3.

शम्यु
Śamyu --a son of Bṛhaspati; asked his father as to the pros and cons of the śrāddha. Br. III. 9. 38-44; Vā. 71. 37. 

शंसप
Śaṃsapa --a Ṛṣika who became a sage by satya. Br. II. 32. 102.

शंसपि
Śaṃsapi --a sage. M. 196. 26.

शंस्य
Śaṃsya --one of the two sons of Gārhapatya; also Āhavanīya and Havyavāhana; father of two sons, Savya and Apasavya; married the 16 rivers for his wives; their sons were Dhiṣṇis. Br. II. 12. 12; Vā. 29. 11-12.

शय्या
Śayyā --bed; characteristics of a good one; 1) Vi. III. 11. 111-12. to sleep on, with head to the east or south to avoid disease. 2) Ib. III. 11. 113.

शरणागति
Śaraṇāgati --the act of falling at the feet of the Devī for protection, sixfold. Br. IV. 41. 74-81.

सरत्
Sarat --a mind-born son of Brahmā in the 16th kalpa. Vā. 21. 35.

शरदृतु
Śaradṛtu --the guardian of Mandāravāṭikā; Iṣaśrī and Ūrjaśrī his queens. Br. IV. 32. 33; Vā. 52. 12; 53. 25.

शरद्वत्
Śaradvat  (I)--a sage who came to see Parīkṣit practising prāyopaveśa. Bhā. I. 19. 9. 

शरद्वत्
Śaradvat  (II)--a son of Satyadhṛti, born at the sight of Ūrvaśī. Bhā. IX. 21. 35.

शरद्वत्
Śaradvat (a)  (III)--a Ṛṣika who became a sage by satya. Br. II. 32. 101.

शरद्वत्
Śaradvat  (IV)--a son of Setu. M. 48. 6.

शरद्वत्
Śaradvat  (V)--(also Śuradvat) a sage by garbha; 1) Vā. 59. 93. heard the Vāyu Purāṇa from Tridhāmā and narrated it to Triviṣṭha; 2) Br. II. 38. 28; III. 74. 60; IV. 4. 61; Vā. 103. 61. see Gautama.

शरद्वसु
Śaradvasu --a son of Śūli of the 24th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 207.

शरद्वान्
Śaradvān  (I)--a sage by garbha of the Sāvarṇi epoch; 1) M. 9. 32; Vā. 1. 186; 59. 93. husband of Ahalyā and father of Śatānanda; 2) M. 50. 8; Vi. IV. 19. 63. a Ṛṣika and a mantrakṛt. 3) M. 145. 95, 104.

शरद्वान्
Śaradvān  (II)--a son of Udathya and of Gautamagotra. Vā. 64. 26; 65. 101.

शरभ
Śarabha  (I)--a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 12; Vā. 68. 12.

शरभ
Śarabha  (II)--a Vānarajāti born of Hari and Pulaha; hunted by Haihaya in the Vindhyas. Br. III. 7. 174, 319; 26. 30; 35. 21; 51. 11; IV. 29. 41. 

शरभ
Śarabha  (III)--a son of Vyāghra and father of Śuka. Br. III. 7. 207, 233.

शरभ
Śarabha  (IV)--a son of Jāmbavat; after him came the Śarabhas, a Vānara jāti. Br. III. 7. 304, 319.

शरभ
Śarabha  (V)--a son of Rukmiṇī and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 245; Vā. 96. 237.

शरवणम्
Śaravaṇam --the pleasure garden of Umā and Śiva in the Himālayas; 1) M. 11. 44; Vā. 41. 37. here Ila was converted into a female; 2) M. 12. 1. Kumāra born in. 3) Vā. 72. 32.

शरवा
Śaravā --a R. from the Mahendra hill. M. 114. 31.

शरवृष्टि
Śaravṛṣṭi --a Marutgaṇa. M. 171. 52.

शरावती
Śarāvatī --R. a mahānadī. Vā. 108. 78.

शरीर
Śarīra --a pupil of Vedamitra Śākalya. Vi. III. 4. 22.

शरीरा
Śarīrā karṣaṇikalā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 19. 20; 36. 70; 44. 120.

शरूथ
Śarūtha --a son of Duṣyanta (Duṣkṛta). Vā. 99. 5. 

शर्करभौम
Śarkarabhauma --the earth of the fifth talam; arvāk talam. Br. II. 20. 14, 35.

शर्करा
Śarkarā --sugar; 1) M. 7. 13. an article for śrāddha. 2) Ib. 17. 30; 92. 2; 266. 51; 279. 9.

शर्कराचल
Śarkarācala --the best gift is 8 bhārams of sugar; then 4 and 2; even 1 or (1/2) allowed; the giver goes to heaven. M. 83. 6; 92. 1-13.

शर्कराधेनु
Śarkarādhenu --fit for gift during the Viśokadvādaśi. M. 82. 19.

शर्करावर्ता
Śarkarāvartā --a R. in Bhāratavarṣa. Bhā. V. 19. 18.

शर्करासप्तमी
Śarkarāsaptamī --on the seventh day of the white half of Mādhava (Viśākha) month for meditating on Saurasūktam and purāṇam; next gifts are made and Brahmans are fed; this is to continue every month for a year; equal to the fruits of the performance of aśvamedha. M. 74. 3; 77. 1-9.

शर्म
Śarma --a common designation for a Brahman. Vi. III. 10. 8-9.

शर्मिष्ठा
Śarmiṣṭhā  (I)--a daughter of Vṛṣaparvan (hence Vārṣaparvaṇi-Vi. P.) and wife of Yayāti. She once went with her attendants and Devayānī, and became engaged in water sports. Śiva and Pārvatī passed them when they put on their dress. In doing so Śarmiṣṭhā put on Devayānī's dress by mistake and was taken to task by Devayānī who called  her a slave, arrogating superiority as a Brahmana girl. Śarmiṣṭhā grew angry and stripping her of her clothes threw her into a well and returned home; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 32; Br. III. 6. 23; 68. 15; M. 6. 22; 24. 52; Chh. 27-30; Vi. IV. 10, 4. Śukra resented the action of the princess and left the palace though the king begged his pardon. Śukra agreed to stay on condition that Śarmiṣṭhā would follow Devayānī wherever she went. It was agreed. She was given to Yayāti when Devayānī was married to him. Yayāti advised not to share his bed with Śarmiṣṭhā. One day after her monthly period Śarmiṣṭhā requested him to embrace her, which he did. She became mother of three sons--Druhya, Anu and Pūru. 2) Bhā. IX. 18. 6-33; M. Chh. 31-32; Vā. 68. 23; 93. 16.

शर्मिष्ठा
Śarmiṣṭhā  (II)--a daughter of Svarbhānu. Vi. I. 21. 7.

शर्याता
Śaryātās --a Haihaya clan. M. 43. 48.

शर्याति
Śaryāti  (I)--a son of Vaivasvata Manu. A saintly king who gave a discourse on the second day of Angiraś Yajña. Father of twins Ānarta and Śukanyā: with the latter he went once to the āśrama of Cyavana. In an ant-hill the girl saw two luminous objects and little knowing that they were the eyes of the sage, she pricked them by a thorn. There was an overflow of blood and this disabled all the attendants of the king from answering calls of nature. On enquiry the king found out the mistake committed by his daughter and persuaded the sage to excuse her, by offering her in marriage to him. Taking leave of them he returned to the city. 1) Bhā. VIII. 13. 2; IX. 1. 12; 3. 1-9; M. 11. 41; 12. 21; Br. III. 60. 2; 61. 18; Vā. 64. 29; 85. 4; 86. 23; Vi. III. 1. 33; IV. 1. 7. Desirous of performing a sacrifice, Śaryāti called on the āśrama of his son-in-law after some time and found a young man seated on his daughter's side little knowing that the  sage had changed his form due to the blessings of Aśvins: the king admonished his daughter for her misbehaviour. But when he heard how Cyavana got back his youth, he was pleased and hugged his daughter. 2) Bhā. IX. 3. 18. 27; XII. 3. 10. Father of three sons: his greed for more territory.

शर्याति
Śaryāti  (II)--a son of Nahuṣa. M. 24. 50.

शर्याति
Śaryāti  (III)--a son of Aśvinī and Akrūra. M. 45. 33.

शर्व
Śarva --a name of Śiva Rudra; 1) Bhā. VI. 15. 28; Br. II. 25. 23; M. 180. 19; Vi. I. 8. 6; 15. 122; III. 2. 11; V. 34. 1. the presiding deity of the earth; 2) M. 265. 40. represents the earth and hence the earth should not be made impure or unclean; 3) Br. II. 10. 10. the lord created by Brahmā in the 30th Kalpa who made aṭṭahāsa; 4) Vā. 22. 28. the third son of Kṛṣṇalohita; 5) Ib. 27. 28. his wife, Vikeśi and son Angāraka. 6) Br. II. 10. 78; 13. 54.

शर्वक
Śarvaka --a son of the Sahiṣṇu avatār of the Lord. Vā. 23. 213.

शर्वरी
Śarvarī --the wife of Doṣa, a Vasu: their son is Simsumāra. Bhā. VI. 6. 14.

शर्वा
Śarvā --a name of Umā. Bhā. XII. 10. 35. 

शर्वाणी
Śarvāṇī --an epithet of Umā. M. 180. 22.

शल
Śala  (I)--an athlete of Kamsa: could not vanquish Arjuna as he was supported by Kṛṣṇa: Resented Śāmba's action in seizing Lakṣmaṇā: had his allotted seat in the arena but was killed by Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. I. 15. 16; X. 36. 21; 68. 5; 42. 37; 44. 27.

शल
Śala  (II)--a son of Somadatta. Bhā. IX. 22. 19; X. 68. 5; Vā. 99. 235.

शल
Śala  (III)--a son of Durvākṣī and Vṛka. Bhā. IX. 24. 43.

शल
Śala  (IV)--a Saimhikeya asura. Br. III. 6. 19.

शल
Śala  (V)--a Kṣatriya who became a dvija. Br. III. 66. 87.

शल
Śala  (VI)--a son of Sutahotra. Vā. 92. 3.

शलङ्क
Śalaṅka --a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 3.

शलदा
Śaladā --a daughter of Bhadrāśva and Ghṛtācī. Vā. 70. 68.

शलभ
Śalabha  (I)--a Saimhikeya asura. Br. III. 6. 19; Vā. 68. 12. 

शलभ
Śalabha  (II)--a son of Jāmbhavān. Br. III. 7. 304.

शलभ
Śalabhas  (I)--children of Yāminī. Bhā. VI. 6. 21.

शलभ
Śalabhas  (II)--too much of them, forebodes famine. M. 237. 9.

शलभा
Śalabhā --one of the ten wives of Ahi. Br. III. 8. 75.

शलामुखीयक
Śalāmukhīyaka --a place where Ajaikapāt Agni is located. Br. II. 12. 25.

शल्य
Śalya  (I)--Appointed commander of the Kuru army after Karṇa's death, for half a day when Yudhiṣṭhira killed him. His army was defeated by Arjuna and Kṛṣṇa. Went to Syamantapañcaka for solar eclipse. Bhā. I. 15. 15; X. 78. [95 (V) 38]: 82. 25.

शल्य
Śalya  (II)--a son of Vipracitti. Vi. I. 21. 11.

शल्य
Śalya  (III)--a son of Somadatta. Vi. IV. 20. 32.

शल्यक
Śalyaka --a Vānara. Br. III. 7. 319.

शल्व
Śalvas --a tribe. M. 114. 45. 

शश
Śaśa --the flesh of the hare, good for śrāddha. M. 17. 33.

शशक
Śaśaka --the animal fit for śrāddha purposes. Vā. 88. 13.

शशबिन्दव
Śaśabindavas --the line of Śaśabindu; performed aśvamedhas. Br. III. 74. 269; M. 273. 73.

शशबिन्दु
Śaśabindu  (I) (Citraratha)--a son of Citraratha; highly learned and a yogin; an emperor of glory; had ten thousand wives and thousands of sons of whom six were distinguished. Possessed fourteen excellent jewels. His daughter Bindumatī (Caitrarathī) had 100 famous sons with names beginning with Pṛthu; 1) Bhā. IX. 23. 31-33; 6. 38; Br. III. 70. 19-22; M. 44. 18-19; Vā. 88. 70; 95. 18-21. father-in-law of Māndhātā; heard of the significance of Śrāddha from Yama. 2) Br. III. 18. 1 and 15; 63. 70.

शशबिन्दु
Śaśabindu  (II)--the moon. Vā. 82. 1.

शशांक
Śaśāṃka --the Moon God; see Soma. M. 150. 53.

शशाद
Śaśāda --see Vikukṣi. Bhā. IX. 6. 11; Br. III. 63. 21; Vā. 88. 24; Vi. IV. 2. 18.

शशि
Śaśi  (I)--a son of Andhaka. M. 44. 61. 

शशि
Śaśi  (II)--moon; 1) M. 93. 13. chariot of, described; relation of, to the sun cosmology; his nectar and its use to gods, ṛṣis and pitṛs; 2) Ib. 126. 48-73. his maṇḍala twice that of the sun; 3) Ib. 124. 8. vanquished by Rāvaṇa. 4) Br. II. 21. 8; 24. 67; III. 7. 254.

शशिनी
Śaśinī --a kalā of the moon. Br. IV. 35. 92.

शशिप्रभा
Śaśiprabhā --a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 75.

शशिबिन्दु
Śaśibindu --a son of Citraratha; lord of 14 mahāratnas and cakravarti; had 100,000 wives and ten lakhs of sons, among whom the chief were Pṛthuśrava, Pṛthukarma and four others; (see Śaśabindu). Vi. IV. 12. 3-6.

शशिमण्डलम्
Śaśimaṇḍalam --the region of the moon, 100,000 yojanas from that of the sun; above it is the nakṣatra maṇḍalam. Vi. II. 7. 5-6.

शश्वती
Śaśvatī --a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 91.

शाक
Śāka --is Śākadvīpa; the hill after which the dvīpa is named. 2) M. 123. 36. ^1 Bhā. V. I. 32.

शाक
Śāka  (II)--the tree in the midst of Śākadvīpam. Vā. 49. 88; Vi. II. 4. 63. 

शाकटाक्ष
Śākaṭākṣa --an ārṣeyapravara of (Bhārgava gotra). M. 195. 40.

शाकटायन
Śākaṭāyana --a pravara of the Bhārgavas. M. 195. 31; 196. 45.

शाकद्वीप
Śākadvīpa --thirty-two lakhs of yojanas in extent and encircled by sea of curds (Dadhimaṇḍoda) (Kṣīroda-Vi. P.) of equal dimension; takes its name from a great śāka tree; ruled by a son of Priyavrata, Medhātithi who divided it among his seven sons and retired to forest; here Vāyu is worshipped by Prāṇāyāma; 1) Bhā. V. 20. 24-28. divided into seven kingdoms bearing the respective names of the seven sons of the first king Havya (Bhavya-Vi. P.), a grandson of Svāyambhuva; contains seven streams, several towns and villages; people here follow svadharma and varṇāśrama dharma; 2) Br. II. 14. 13; 19. 27, 80-107; 21. 73; Vā. 33. 13; 49. 74; 50. 127. seven mountains; 3) M. 122. 1. one of the seven continents, double the size of the Krauñcadvīpa; the four castes in it; Vangas, Magadhas, Mānasas and Mandagas; Viṣṇu stands in the form of Sūrya. 4) Vi. II. 1. 14; 2. 5; IV. 58. 71.

शाकधिय
Śākadhiya --sage. M. 200. 9.

शाकपूर्ण
Śākapūrṇa --made a classification of the Ṛk Samhitā into three parts together with Nirukta as the fourth; had four disciples to assist him. Vi. III. 4. 23-24.

शाकमुण्ड
Śākamuṇḍas --a Janapada of the Bhadrā continent. Vā. 43. 21. 

शाकल
Śākala --the king of the Madras; see under Aśvapati. M. 208. 5.

शाकल्य
Śākalya (Devamitra) --a son of Māṇḍukeya; divided the Samhitā into five parts and transmitted them to five disciples --Vātsya, Mudgala, Śālīya, Gokhalya and Sīsira (Mudgala, Golka, Khāliya, Matsya and Śośareya-Vā. P.). 1) Bhā. XII. 6. 57; Br. II. 35. 1; Vā. 60. 32, 64. A pupil of Satyaśriya and a Śākapravartaka. During the sacrifice of Janaka, there was a dispute as to who was the learned among those present. The prize was won by Yājñavalkya but Śākalya insulted him and was cursed. 2) Br. II. 34. 32-67; Vā. 60. 31, 63.

शाकवती
Śākavatī --a R. of the Ketumālā continent. Vā. 44. 19.

शाकवैण
Śākavaiṇa --see Rathītara Br. II. 35. 3.

शाकलि
Śākali --a Śrutaṛṣi. Br. II. 35. 3.

शाक
Śākas --a tribe. Vā. 45. 116; 47. 44.

शाकायन
Śākāyanas --a tribe ? M. 200. 9.

शाकाहार्या
Śākāhāryā --a sage. M. 200. 9.

शाकुनम्
Śākunam --the flesh of the parrot for śrāddha. M. 17. 31. 

शाकिनी
Śākinī --a śakti in Kiricakra. Br. IV. 20. 16.

शाक्तम्
Śāktam  (I)--one of the six darśanas. Vā. 104. 16.

शाक्तम्
Śāktam  (II)--the tip of the tongue of the personified Veda. Vā. 104. 82.

शाक्य
Śākya --a son of Sanjaya, and father of Śuddhoda (na). Bhā. IX. 12. 14; M. 271. 12; Vā. 99. 288; Vi. IV. 22. 8.

शाक्रम्
Śākram --of the Yajurvedins, to be recited in rituals connected with the digging of tanks. M. 58. 35; 93. 132.

शाकू
Śākū --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 10.

शाख
Śākha --a son of Agni and brother of Kumāra, 1) Br. III. 3. 25; M. 5. 26; Vā. 66. 24; Vi. I. 15. 115. an amśa of Skanda. 2) Vā. 101. 280.

शाखावती
Śākhāvatī --a R. of the Bhadrā continent. Vā. 43. 26.

शाखि
Śākhis --parents of Māriṣā, mother of Dakṣa in Cākṣuṣaantara. Br. II. 13. 70; Vā. 30. 61. 

शाख्य
Śākhya --a heretical sect. Br. III. 14. 39.

शाख्य
Śākhya --a gotrakara. M. 197. 1.

शांकरम्
Śāṃkaram tīrtham --sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 43.

शांकरम्पदम्
Śāṃkarampadam --the lotus feet of Śaṅkara. M. 13. 57.

शाङ्करी
Śāṅkarī --a mind-born mother. M. 179. 16.

शांकृतिकस्
Śāṃkṛtikas --a branch of Angirasa. Vā. 65. 106.

शाठ्यायनि
Śāṭhyāyani --a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 20.

शाण्डित
Śāṇḍitas --one of the three Kaśyapa groups. Br. III. 8. 33.

शाण्डिलि
Śāṇḍili --sacred for śrāddha. Br. III. 19. 92.

शाण्डिल्य
Śāṇḍilya  (I)--Agni, as son of Śāṇḍili. Br. III. 10. 91.

शाण्डिल्य
Śāṇḍilya  (II)--a Dānava. M. 199. 18. 

शाण्डिल्य
Śāṇḍilyas --the sons of Devala. Vā. 70. 28.

शातकर्णि
Śātakarṇi  (I)--ruled for a year (1(1/2) years-Vā. P.) Br. III. 74. 166; Vā. 99. 353.

शातकर्णि
Śātakarṇi  (II)--a son of Bhāta, ruled for 56 years. Vā. 99. 350.

शातकर्णि
Śātakarṇi  (III)--a son of Sundara and father of Śivasvāti. Vi. IV. 24. 47.

शातकर्णि
Śātakarṇi  (IV)--the son of Pūrṇotsanga and father of Lambodara. Vi. IV. 24. 45.

शाद्वल
Śādvala --the forest in the country of Uttarakurus where Samjana roamed as a mare. Vā. 84. 68.

शाद्वलायन
Śādvalāyanas --Ekārṣeyas. M. 200. 2.

शानैश्चरम्
Śānaiścaram --the place of Śanaiścara above that of Bṛhaspati. Vā. 53. 60, 97.

शान्त
Śānta  (I)--one of the seven divisions of Plakṣadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 3.

शान्त
Śānta  (II)--a son of Āyu. Br. III. 3. 24. 

शान्त
Śānta  (III)--a sage: His son went on a pilgrimage on his way to Sāligrāma, he wished to see Gandhamādana, Badarikāśrama and others: got frightened by a Gandharva in the form of a tiger which was killed by Paraśurāma. Him followed the sage. Br. III. 25. 66-77

शान्त
Śānta  (IV)--a son of Āpa. M. 5. 22; Vā. 23. 84; 66. 23; Vi. I. 15. 111.

शान्तकर्णि
Śāntakarṇi  (I)--a son of Pūrṇotsaṅga, ruled for 56 years. M. 273. 4.

शान्तकर्णि
Śāntakarṇi  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and father of Pūrṇotsaṅga. Vi. IV. 24. 45.

शान्तकर्णि
Śāntakarṇi  (III)--a son of Ahimān and father of Śivaśrita. Vi. IV. 24. 48.

शान्तभय
Śāntabha(ha)ya --a son of Medhātithi and founder of the Śāntabha(ha)ya kingdom in Plakṣadvīpa. Br. II. 14. 36. 8; Vā. 33. 32; Vi. II. 4. 3 and 5.

शान्तभयम्
Śāntabhayam --the Gomedavarṣa of Plakṣadvīpa. Vā. 49. 13.

शान्तरय
Śāntaraya --a son of Trikakut (Dhamasārathi). He realised the Ātman. Bhā. IX. 17. 12. 

शान्तसेन
Śāntasena --a son of Subāhu, and father of Śatasena. Bhā. X. 90. 38.

शान्ता
Śāntā  (I)--a daughter of Daśaratha, and adopted by Citraratha-Romapāda: married by Rṣyaśṛṇga, (a daughter of Daśaratha-Lomapāda, M. P.). Bhā. IX. 23. 8; M. 48. 95; Vi. IV. 18. 18.

शान्ता
Śāntā  (II)--a R. in the Kuru country. Br. II. 18. 73.

शान्ता
Śāntā  (III)--a daughter of Lomapāda. Vā. 99. 103.

शान्ता
Śāntā  (IV)--the mother of the sage Bharadvāja. Vā. 111. 60.

शान्ति
Śānti  (I)--a daughter of Kardama, married to Atharvaṇa: Dadhyañca was her son. Yajña was popularised in the world by her. Bhā. III. 24. 24; IV. 1. 42.

शान्ति
Śānti  (II)--a son of Dakṣiṇā, and a Tuṣita god. Bhā. IV. 1. 7-8.

शान्ति
Śānti  (III)--a daughter of Dakṣa, and a wife of Dharma, gave birth to Sukha (Kṣema-Vā. P.). Bhā. IV. 1. 49 and 51; Br. II. 9. 50, 61; Vā. 10. 25. 37; Vi. I. 7. 23, 30.

शान्ति
Śānti  (IV)--a son of Nīla, and father of Suśānti. Bhā. IX. 21. 30-31; Vi. IV. 19. 57. 

शान्ति
Śānti  (V)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Kālindī. Bhā. X. 61. 14.

शान्ति
Śānti  (VI)--(Kalpa) author of: a master of Atharva Samhitā. Bhā. XII. 7. 4; Br. II. 35. 62.

शान्ति
Śānti  (VII)--a R. in Śālmalidvīpa. Br. II. 19. 46.

शान्ति
Śānti  (VIII)--a son of Tāmasa Manu. Br. II. 36. 49.

शान्ति
Śānti  (IX)--the Indra of the gods--Sudhāmāna and Viruddhas; 1) Br. IV. 1. 69. Indra of the tenth epoch of Manu. 2) Vi. III. 2. 26.

शान्ति
Śānti  (X)--a kalā of Hari. Br. IV. 35. 95.

शान्ति
Śānti  (XI)--a Śakti. Br. IV. 44. 71.

शान्ति
Śānti  (XII)--to avert impending evils; abhayā to get rid of fear, saumyā to get rid of disease, vaiṣṇavī against famine and fear from insects and robbers, raudrī if beasts get sick and die, brāhmī when hetrodoxy prevails, raudrī for fear of other king's troubles, vāyavī for diseases of wind, etc., vāruṇī for famines and absence of rains, bhārgavī for fear of curse, etc., prājāpatyā for miscarriages in delivery, tvāṣṭrī for bad growth of vegetables, kaumārī for well being of children, āgneyī for fear of fire and disobedience, troubles from servants, etc., gāndharvi for horses, āngirasi for elephants,  naiṛṛtī for fear of ghosts and spirits, yāmyā for bad dreams, kauberi for loss of wealth, pārthivī for loss of trees and lands. These are to be done at particular times of the day when certain nakṣatras like Hasta, Svāti are in the ascendant. M. 228. 5-27.

शान्ति
Śānti  (XIII)--one of the four fruits of Prāṇāyāma, the ruin of all sins of the Pitrs and cognates. Vā. 11. 6.

शान्ति
Śānti  (XIV)--(Pracetas): Agni. Vā. 29. 27.

शान्तिकम्
Śāntikam --the mantras of the Atharvavedins recited in a ritual connected with digging of tanks. M. 58. 37.

शान्तिकल्प
Śāntikalpa --the fifth part of the Atharva Samhitā. Vā. 61. 54. Vi. III. 6. 14.

शान्तिका
Śāntikā --a mother goddess. M. 179. 28.

शान्तिकाध्यानम्
Śāntikādhyānam --the chapter dealing with propitiatory rites to be recited in śrāddha; 1) M. 17. 39. to be repeated in founding a temple; 2) Ib. 265. 25. preliminary to the giving of 16 great gifts. 3) Ib. 274. 56.

शान्तिदेवा
Śāntidevā --a daughter of Devaka, and a queen of Vasudeva. Bhā. IX. 24. 23 and 50; Br. III. 71. 131 and 62; Vā. 96. 130; Vi. IV. 14. 18. 

शान्ति
Śānti --a R. from the lake Jayā. M. 121. 71; Vā. 47. 71.

शाप
Śāpa --a son of the first Sāvarṇa Manu. Br. IV. 1. 64.

शापनासन
Śāpanāsana --a son of Damana, an avatār of the Lord in the third dvāpara. Vā. 23. 124.

शापेयि
Śāpeyi --a Vājin. Vā. 61. 25.

शामित्र
Śāmitra --the place of Havya agni. Br. II. 12. 23; Vā. 29. 22.

शामित्रम्
Śāmitram --the act of killing the sacrificial victim and making it ready for offering; 1) Vā. 2. 6. performed by Mṛtyu in the Viśvaśṛj sacrifice. 2) Br. I. 2. 6.

शांकृतस्
Śāṃkṛtas --of Kauśika gotra. Br. III. 66. 72.

शाम्ब
Śāmba --a Saimhikeya. Vā. 68. 18.

शाम्ब
Śāmba --a son of Āpa. M. 5. 22.

शाम्बवी
Śāmbavī --Lalitā; see Dīkṣā. Br. IV. 13. 26; 43. 5. 

शांशपायन
Śāṃśapāyana --a sage of the Naimiṣā forest; 1) Vā. 30. 38; 49. 97; 56. 2; 57. 88. versed in the Purāṇas; 2) Br. II. 35. 64-6, 69. was addressed by Sūta; 3) Br. II. 13. 41-3; 15. 1; 19. 99; 28. 2; 30. 5. a pupil of Romaharṣaṇa. 4) Vā. 61. 56; 65. 1; 89. 16; Vi. III. 6. 17.

शांशपायिनक
Śāṃśapāyinakas --have to their credit 8608 Ṛks. Vā. 61. 61, 62.

शारदा
Śāradā --a name of Yogamāyā. Bhā. X. 2. 12.

शारदातीर्थम्
