Sahadeva  (V)--a son of Mādrī (Mādravatī-Br. P.), born through the grace of the Aśvins. Father of Śrutakarman. His other son was Suhotra by Vijayā; 1) Bhā. IX. 22. 28-31; Br. III. 71. 155; M. 46. 10; 50. 50; Vā. 96. 154; 99. 245. Vi. IV. 14. 38; 20. 40. joy at Kṛṣṇa's visit to Indraprastha; paid his respects to him; was consoled by  Kṛṣṇa when banished to the forest; 2) Bhā. X. 71. 27. 58. 4; 64. 9. was sent to southern countries with Sṛñjayas. 3) Ib. X. 72. 13; 74. 18-25; 75. 4. His suggestion that Kṛṣṇa should be accorded the first honour among the Sadasyas in the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira was accepted. Entertained guests in that sacrifice. Approved of Draupadī's desire to release Aśvatthāman. 4) X. I. 7. 50; 10. 9.

सहदेव
Sahadeva  (VI)--a son of Sṛñjaya and father of Kṛśāśva. Br. III. 61. 15; Vā. 86. 20; Vi. IV. 1. 54-5.

सहदेव
Sahadeva  (VII)--a son of Havyaśva; father of Ahīna. Br. III. 68. 9.

सहदेव
Sahadeva  (VIII)--a son of Tāmarā and Sahadeva. M. 46. 16.

सहदेव
Sahadeva  (IX)--a son of Haryadvata, a great soldier. Vā. 93. 9.

सहदेव
Sahadeva  (X)--a son of Supratīta. Vā. 99. 284.

सहदेव
Sahadeva  (XI)--a son of Haryadhana and father of Adīna. Vi. IV. 9. 27.

सहदेव
Sahadeva  (XII)--a son of Devaka. Vi. IV. 14. 17. 

सहदेवा
Sahadevā --a daughter of Devaka, and a queen of Vasudeva; mother of eight sons, of whom Bhayāsakha was one. Bhā. IX. 24. 23 and 52; Br. III. 71. 131, 162 and 179; Vā. 96. 177; Vi. IV. 14. 18.

सहश्री
Sahaśrī --a queen of Hemanta ṛtu. Br. IV. 32. 37.

सहस
Sahasa --the tutelary deity of Pākayajnas; father of Adbhuta. Br. II. 12. 40.

सहस
Sahasas --of the south. Vā. 45. 130.

सहसात्यपुत्र
Sahasātyaputra --belonging to Lokākṣi. Vā. 61. 37.

सहस्यश्री
Sahasyaśrī --a queen of Hemanta ṛtu. Br. IV. 32. 37.

सहस्रजित्
Sahasrajit  (I)--(Sahasrajiḥ-M. P.); the eldest of the five sons of Yadu and father of Śatajit. Bhā. IX. 23. 20. 21; Br. III. 69. 2. M. 43. 7; Vā. 94. 2; Vi. IV. 11. 5-6.

सहस्रजित्
Sahasrajit  (II)--a son of Jāmbavatī; got killed in Prabhāsa. Bhā. X. 61. 11; XI. 30. 17.

सहस्रजित्
Sahasrajit  (III)--a son of Sudevī and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 251. 

सहस्रजित्
Sahasrajit  (IV)--one of the sons of Sudevī and Viṣvaksena. Vā. 96. 242.

सहस्रजित्
Sahasrajit  (V)--a son of Bhajamāna. Vi. IV. 13. 2.

सहस्रधार
Sahasradhāra --a Vamśavartin god. Br. II. 36. 29; Vā. 62. 26.

सहस्रपात्
Sahasrapāt --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 240.

सहस्रलिंगम्
Sahasraliṃgam --a tīrtha sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 60.

सहस्रशिखर
Sahasraśikhara --a Mt. for garuḍa birds; 1) Br. III. 7. 453. west of the Śitoda; 2) Vā. 36. 28. of Daityas. 3) Ib. 39. 61; 42. 53.

सहस्रश्रुति
Sahasraśruti --a Mt. in Śālmalīdvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 10.

सहस्रस्तम्बकम्
Sahasrastambakam --a thousand pillared maṇṭapa with sculptured images of Hari. Br. IV. 34. 85.

सहस्रस्रुति
Sahasrasruti --(Sahasrastuti-Bhā. P.) a R. in Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 26.

सहस्रस्रोतस्
Sahasrasrotas --a boundary hill of Śākadvīpa. Bhā. V. 20. 26. 

सहस्राक्ष
Sahasrākṣa  (|)--an attribute of Indra; 1) Br. III. 5. 75, 101 etc.; Vā. 39. 19; 64. 7; Vi. I. 9. 19: V. 14. 14. served his mother Diti (s.v.) during her penance to get a son to slay him; later he cut her phoetus into seven parts; they became Maruts. 2) Vā. 67. 95-6.

सहस्राक्ष
Sahasrākṣa  (II)--the agni of the Asuras; 1) Vā. 29. 41, 5 and 34. the son of Pāvaka (Vaḍavāmukha-Br. P.) 2) Br. 12. 5, and 36.

सहस्राक्ष
Sahasrākṣa  (III)--tīrtha sacred to Utpalākṣī; 1) M. 13. 34. sacred to Pitṛs. 2) Ib. 22. 52.

सहस्राजित्
Sahasrājit  (I)--a son of Bhajamāna. Bhā. IX. 24. 8.

सहस्राजित्
Sahasrājit  (II)--a son of Upavāhyakā. Br. III. 71. 5.

सहस्राम्शु
Sahasrāmśu --is sun. Br. II. 21. 111.

सहस्रानीक
Sahasrānīka --a son of Śatānīka, and father of Aśvamedhaja. Bhā. IX. 22. 39.

सहस्राश्व
Sahasrāśva --a son of Ahīnaga. M. 12. 54.

सहस्वान्
Sahasvān --a (Marṣa) son of Susandhi and father of Visrutavān. Also called Marṣa. 1) Br. III. 63. 212; Vā. 88. 211. He is called the son of Marṣa and father of Viśvabhava. 2) Vi. IV. 4. 111. 

सहस्वास
Sahasvāsa --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 243.

सहानन्दि
Sahānandi --(Mahānandī?) ruled for 43 years; father of Mahāpadma born of a Śūdra woman. Br. III. 74. 134.

सहाय
Sahāyas --king's advisers and servants; a cammanderin-chief either a Brahman or a Kṣatriya; Pratīhāra, dūta, rakṣiṇs or bodyguards; a nārī or nurse; a sāṅdhivigrahika; desarakṣita; a revenue minister; swordsmen and other soldiers; a charioteer; sūdādyakṣa; judges; members of assembly; Lekhaka; dauvārika; dhanādhyakṣa; vaidya; ācārya; gajādhyakṣa; aśvādhyakṣa; durgādhyakṣa; sthapati; astrācārya; Purādhyakṣa; āyūdhāgārādhyakṣa; mantrins; upadhās; cārās. M. ch. 215.

सहिष्णु
Sahiṣṇu --(Paulaha) a son of Pulaha and Gatī (Kṣamā-Vā. P.); a sage of the Cakṣuṣa epoch. Bhā. IV. 1. 38; Br. II. 11. 31; 36. 78; Vā. 28. 26. 62. 66; Vi. I. 10. 10; III. 1. 28. M. 9. 22.

सहिष्णु
Sahiṣṇu  (II)--the avatār of the Lord of the 26th dvāpara in the holy Rudravaṭa with four sons. Vā. 23. 212.

सहूदक
Sahūdakas --a hilly country. Vā. 45. 136.

सहैषिक
Sahaiṣikas --a southern country; 1) Br. II. 16. 57. a tribe. 2) M. 114. 47.

सहोत्कच
Sahotkaca --a Janapada of the Ketumālā. Vā. 44. 12. 

सह्य
Sahya --(also Sahyādri): a Kulaparvata; Mt. in Bhārtavarṣa; from this the Kāverī rises. Sages of this place visited Dvārakā. 1) Bhā. V. 19. 16; VII. 13. 12; X. 90. 28 [4]; Vā. 45. 89. 104; Vi. II. 3. 3. A Kulaparvata where sages performed penance; recovered from the sea with cities and villages. 2) Br. II. 16. 8; III. 56. 22 and 57; 57. 27; 58. 24; M. 114. 17, 29.

सह्यधृति
Sahyadhṛti --son of Śatānanda, expert in arms; he once saw an Apsaras and dropped semen in a lake; it took the shape of a mithuna who were rescued by Śantanu and became Gautamas. M. 50. 9-11.

सह्याद्रि
Sahyādri --sacred to Ekavīra; see Sahya. M. 13. 40.

साकलायनि
Sākalāyani --an ātreyagotrakāra. M. 197. 3.

साकेत
Sāketa --is Ayodhyā; sometime ruled by the Nāgas. Br. III. 54. 54; 74. 195.

साकेत
Sāketa --a Janapada over which the Guptas ruled. Vā. 99. 383.

साक्षि
Sākṣi --witness; the Devas as witnesses to piṇḍadāna. Vā. 110. 59 and 60.

साक्षिप
Sākṣipa --one of the names in the third Marutgaṇa. Vā. 67. 126.

सागर
Sāgara  (I)--(Sindhu): one of the principal kṣetrams. M. 110. 1. 

सागर
Sāgara  (II)--the lord of rivers; 1) Vā. 70. 9. married Velā, the daughter of Meru; 2) Ib. 30. 35. had a daughter Savarṇā married to Prācinabarhis. 3) Br. II. 13. 38.

सागर
Sāgara  (III)--a son of Śakti. Vā. 70. 83.

सागर
Sāgaras --(also Sagaras s.v.) were purified by the waters of the Ganges flowing from the foot of Viṣṇu. 60,000 sons of Sumatī who were unrighteous; sent by Sagara to seize the sacrificial horse; finding it near Kapila they treated him as thief but perished by the fire of his wrath; as they dug up the earth, the sea got enlarged and came to be known as Sāgara; ruled Campā. ^1 Bhā. X. 41. 15; Br. III. chh. 52-3; 54. 11; 56. 3. ^2 Ib. III. 74. 197.

सांकाश्या
Sāṃkāśyā --the capital of Kuśadhvaja; 1) Br. III. 64. 19. also the name of the kingdom. 2) Vi. IV. 5. 29.

सांकृतस्
Sāṃkṛtas --of Kauśika gotra. Vā. 91. 100.

सांकृतय
Sāṃkṛtaya --the Kṣeropeta Brahmans; of Angirasa line. Vā. 99. 164.

सांकृति
Sāṃkṛti --a son of Nara. Vā. 99. 160.

सांकृत्य
Sāṃkṛtya --a Bhārgava gotrakāra; a śruta ṛṣi. Br. II. 33. 2; M. 195. 23. 

सांख्य
Sāṃkhya (Sāṃkhyamukhya) --Śiva. Vā. 30. 220. 97. 175.

सांख्य
Sāṃkhya (Yoga) --Revealed by Viṣṇu: taught by Kapila to Āsuri. 1) Bhā. I. 3. 10; II. 1. 6; V. 18. 33; M. 3. 29; Vā. 30. 293. Here tattvas or first principles are taught. Puruṣa the eternal, acts as agent to get things done by the guṇas of Prakṛti. Its relation to Bhaktiyoga. 2) Bhā. III. 24. 17; 25. 31; ch. 26 (whole); 29 2; Vā. 61. 111. Its principles are differently enumerated as eleven, five, three and so on; according to one's yuktī or reason. Creation of universe according to Sānkhya, and the place of Prakṛti and Puruṣa therein. 3) Bhā. XI. 22. 1-25; Bhā 24 (whole). Followed by Kṛṣṇa while ruling from Dvārakā and by Nārada in his worship of Naranārāyaṇa. 4) ch. III. 3. 19; V. 19. 10; IX. 8. 14; X. 8. 45; XI. 14. 20. Practised by Vairājasas; 5) M. 13. 5. is itself a kind of yoga; 6) Ib. 52. 3; 110; 19; 182. 18; 183. 44; Vā. 66. 110. born out of the creator. 7) M. 183. 50; 184. 24; 245. 87; 247. 9; 248. 17; 291. 2.

सांख्यायनस्
Sāṃkhyāyanas --sages of rigid vows: learnt the Bhāgavata from Kumāra and imparted it to Parāśara and Bṛhaspati. Bhā. III. 8. 7-8; M. 200. 11.

सात्यकि
Sātyaki (also Śaineya and Yuyudhāna)  a son of Satyaka; 1) Bhā. I. 10. 18; IX. 24. 13-14; M. 45. 22; Vā. 96. 63; Vi. IV. 14. 2. followed Kṛṣṇa to Hāstinapura and was welcomed. Returned back to Dvārakā with him. Followed the Vṛṣṇi host to the city of Bāṇa and fought with Kumbhāṇḍa, his minister; 2) Bhā. I. 13. 16 [1]; X. 58. 1 and 6, 28; 63. 3 and 8; [51 (v) 3031; 59. 63]. learnt the secrets of archery from Arjuna; 3) Ib. III. 1. 31 and 35. defended the western gate of Mathurā, being on the right detachment of Kṛṣṇa's army: pursued the retreating enemy to five yojanas and came out successful; 4) Ib. X. 50. 20 [4]; [50 (V) 12], [30]; [51 (V) 25]. entered Yādava sabhā with Kṛṣṇa and Rāma and was honoured. Defended Dvārakā and expelled Sālva's army; 5) IbX. [42 (V) 13-14]; 52 [56 (V) 1]; 76. 14; 77. 4. went to see the Pāṇḍavas at Upaplāvya; was consulted by Kṛṣṇa on the eve of his war with Jarāsandha. Joined Yadus in defeating Pauṇḍraka; 6) IbX. 78 [95 (V) 2]; [50 (V) 8 and 28]. went with the sacrificial horse of Kṛṣṇa; fought with Aniruddha  at Prabhāsa; 7) Ib. X. 89. 22 [2]; XI. 30. 16. survived Kurukṣetra war; 8) Ib. X. 80. [3]. was killed in Yādava battle at Prabhāsa. 9) Vi. V. 37. 46.

सात्यमुग्रि
Sātyamugri --a sage and a Trayārṣeya with Hiraṇyastambi and Mudgala. M. 196. 41.

सात्यायनि
Sātyāyani --a Bhārgava gotrakāra. M. 195. 26.

सात्राजिती
Sātrājitī --a devī and wife of Kṛṣṇa. Vā. 96. 233.

सात्वकीवृत्ति
Sātvakīvṛtti --that which is above and divine; 1) Vā. 102. 54. the mind becomes clean and the truth is open to him and leads to jñānam or knowledge; 2) Ib. 74. 76. of Viṣṇu. 3) Ib. 66. 87, 104-6.

सात्वत
Sātvata  (I)--a son of Āyu, and father of Bhajamāna and six other sons. Attacked the Asura followers of Bali. Bhā. VIII. 21. 17; IX. 24. 6-7.

सात्वत
Sātvata  (II)--the son of Satva (Janhu M. P.); wife, Kausalyā; father of four sons, Bhajamāna, Bhaji etc., who founded four different dynasties. Br. III. 70. 48; 71. 1, 2; M. 44. 46-8; Vā. 95. 47.

सात्वत्
Sātvats (sātvatas) --a Yādava tribe related to the Pāṇḍavas. Their overlord was Kṛṣṇa; 1) Bhā. 1. 4. 7; 14. 25; II. 4. 20. knew how to read  others' minds and possessed high understanding and culture; 2) Ib. III. 2. 9. ended their lives by fighting their own relations; 3) Ib. XI. 30. 18. are Bhāgavatas; 4) Ib. XII. 8. 46. a line of Kings from Sātvata. 5) Vi. IV. 12. 44.

सात्वतम्
Sātvatam Tantram --(sātvata śāstra) is Pāñcarātra? Propounded by Viśoka, a means of obtaining mukti for women, śūdras and slaves by the sāmpradāya given here; 1) Bhā. X. 90. 34 [2]; VI. 16. 33. taught by Nārada. 2) Ib. I. 3. 8.

सात्वत
Sātvata--samhitā  the Bhāgavatam a means to bhakti (see Sātvati śruti). Bhā. I. 7. 6-7.

सात्वतीय
Sātvatīyas --the followers of sātvatatantra. Bhā. V. 25. 1.

सात्वती
Sātvatī Śruti --is Bhāgavata: a discourse between Śuka and Parīkṣit at Hāstinapura. Bhā. I. 4. 7.

सात्वनुह
Sātvanuha --married Kīrtimatī. Vā. 70. 86; 73. 31.

साद्यसुग्रीवि
Sādyasugrīvi --a Pravara of Angiras. M. 196. 16.

साधक
Sādhakas --Dakṣa and other sons of Brahmā live in a place two crores of Yojanas above Maharloka. Vā. 101. 139. 

साधर्म्यवैधर्म्यकृत
Sādharmyavaidharmyakṛta --Sadasadātmaka in other worlds: the eternal being. Vā. 102. 34, 131.

साधिता
Sādhitā --a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 5.

साधु
Sādhu --(Brahmacāri): He who has the means of vidyā; a Brahmacārin well disposed to a guru; (sādhugrahasta)--the means of doing the Karmas ordained (sādhu vaikhānasa)--by performing penance in the forest (sādhu yati) by endeavouring to apply himself to yoga. Vā. 59. 23-4.

साध्य
Sādhya  (I) (Gaṇa)--born of Sādhyā and Dharma: their son was Arthasiddhi; 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 7; Br. II. 24. 27; 38. 3. created by Vāmadeva; of the Tāmasa epoch; 2) M. 4. 30; 5. 17; 9. 16. one of the 7 gaṇas of the Vaivasvata epoch. 3) Ib. 9. 29; Vā. 10. 71; 21. 22; 30. 99.

साध्य
Sādhya  (II)--Viṣṇu, Nārāyaṇa, lying in sleep in the vast mass of water. Vā. 23. 108.

साध्य
Sādhya  (III)--a son of Atri, the avatār of the 12th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 157.

साध्य
Sādhyas  (I)--the sons of Manu (Cākṣuṣa); 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 15; 7. 3; 13. 17. worshipped for control of subjects; 2) Ib. II. 3. 5; III. 20. 42; V. 1. 8. came with other gods to Dvārakā to ask Kṛṣṇa to go back to Vaikuṇṭha. 3) Ib. XI. 6. 2. 

साध्य
Sādhyas  (II)--the twelve sons of Dharma and Sādhyā; superior to Gods; first created as Jayādevas from the face of Brahmā, again born in Svāyambhuva epoch as Jitas, in Tāmasa epoch as Harayas, in Raivata epoch as Vaikuṇṭhas, Svārociṣa epoch as Tuṣitas, in Uttama epoch as Satyas, in Cākṣuṣa epoch as Chāndajas, and in the Vaivasvata epoch as Sādhyas; Vasus are their brothers; Gods of Cākṣuṣa and Vaivasvata epochs; their names are Mana, Anumanta, Prāṇa, Nara, Apāna, Vīryavān, Vīti, Naya, Haya, Hamsa, Nārāyaṇa, Vibhu, and Prabhu; live in Bhuvarloka; Nārāyaṇa, their overlord; 1) Br. III. 3. 4-20, 58, 67; 4. 33. 8 6; 10. 88; IV. 2. 28; 15. 24, 20. 46; 30. 8.; M. 36. 1; 132. 3; 171. 42; 203. 10-12; 246. 54; 247. 10; Vā. 66. 4-12; 101. 30; Vi. I. 9. 64 and 70. worship gau, the mind-born daughter of the Mānasa manes; 2) M. 15. 15. requested Soma to give up Jārā to Bṛhaspati; 3) Ib. 23. 35. with Angirasa's sons spread themselves in the world of Marici Garbha. 4) Vā. 73. 38. 5) Ib. V. 1. 17.

साध्या
Sādhyā  (I)--a daughter of Dakṣa and one of the 10 wives of Dharma: mother of Sādhya gaṇa. 1) Bhā. VI. 6. 4 and 7; Br. III. 3. 3 and 8. M. 5. 16-17; 171. 42; 203. 10; Vā. 66. 2; Vi. I. 15. 105.

साध्या
Sādhyā  (II)--one of the mind-born daughters of Brahmā. M. 171. 32.

साध्या
Sādhyā  (III)--the mother of Vaikuṇṭhas. Vā. 67. 41.

सानन्दम्
Sānandam (Saunanda-Wilson) --the musala or club of Hari. Vi. V. 22. 7. 

सानु
Sānu --a son of Satyabhāmā and Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 247; Vā. 96. 238.

सान्तानिकलोक
Sāntānikalokas --the devas known as Vairājas live in. Vā. 71. 52.

सान्तपनम्
Sāntapanam --an expiation ceremony for ascetics guilty of sexual act. Vā. 18. 8.

सान्दीपनि
Sāndīpani --(also Sāndīpana); of Kāśī, and a resident of Avanti; was the preceptor of Kṛṣṇa and Balarāma. Taught them all branches of learning in 64 days; got back his dead son recovered from the world of Yama (from the sea Vi. P.) by his pupils as gurudakṣiṇa; acted as purohita in the yajñas performed by Kṛṣṇa at Kurukṣetra; 1) Bhā III. 3. 2; X. 45. 31-49; 90. 46. Vi. V. 21, 19-31. [2]
Vā. 98. 99. his concern when Kṛṣṇa and Kucela were caught once in storm and rain. 2) Bhā X. 80. 39-40; Br. III. 73-79.

सान्धिविग्रहिक
Sāndhivigrahika --one who has a knowledge of ṣāḍguṇya, knows the language of countries and is skilled in policy. M. 215. 16.

सापिण्ड्यम्
Sāpiṇḍyam --extends to several generations. M. 18. 29.

सापत्य
Sāpatya --a pupil of Yāñavalkya. Br. II. 35. 28.

साम
Sāma --one of the political expedients used by Ṛṣabha; 1) Bhā. V. 4. 16. two fold, the real and the unreal; the first to be applied to the sādhus (good men); by this the righteous are brought  under control; 2) M. 222. 1-10. there is no use applying it to the unrighteous. One of the four limbs of nīti, the others being bheda, dāna (uppradāna-Vi. P.) and daṇḍa (daṇḍa pātaVi. P.). 3) Ib. 148. 65-77; Vi. V. 22. 17; 33. 40.

सामग
Sāmaga --eligible for Pārvaṇa śrāddha; 1) Br. III. 15. 30; M. 16. 12. best for a gift; 2) Ib 54. 21. to be sung in connection with the rituals in digging tanks, wells, etc. 3) Ib 58. 37, 43.

सामग
Sāmagas --Prācya and Kārtā; 1) Vā. 30. 230; 32. 17-21; 99. 191. 8014 sāmas, āraṇyaka and homa. 2) Ib. 61. 47-8; 62. 137.

सामघोष
Sāmaghoṣa --chanting of Sāma Veda identified with the voice of the Varāha (avatār); 1) M. 248. 69. also Sāmaghoṣa. 2) Vā. 62. 137.

सामज
Sāmaja --see Nāgas. Br. III. 7. 351.

साम
Sāma (samhitā) --a Veda imparted to Jaimini, 1) Bhā. I. 4. 21; IX. 11. 2; 21. 28; X. 7. 14; 53. 12; XI. 27. 31; XII. 6. 76; 11. 47; 12. 62. Vā. 31. 33; 65. 26. Vi. III. 4. 9 and 13. who arranged it under Vyāsa's guidance; present in Vāruṇi yajña with Viśvāvasus and Gandharvas; 2) Br. II. 34. 15; III. 1. 25. gave birth to a number of elephants; 3) Ib III. 7. 334, 339. learnt by the Asuras; 4) Ib IV. 12. 17. taught by Jaimini to his son Sumantu and his grandson Sutavāna; the latter's son Sukarma composed Sahasra samhitā and taught to his pupils Hiraṇyanābha, Kausalya and Pauṣpiñji; 500 pupils of the latter were the northern chanters of the Sāma; Hiraṇyanābha's disciples the eastern chanters of the Sāma; one of his pupils, Kṛta, taught to his disciples 24 branches  of the Samhitā; 5) M. 49. 76; Vā. 99. 130. Vi. III. 6. 1-7. part of Viṣṇu; 6) Ib V. 1. 37. served with other Vedas as a horse of the chariot of Tripurāri. 7) M. 85. 5; 133. 31;

सामन्त
