Hari  (I)--praise of: by Arjuna; 1) Bhā. I. 7. 22-26. by Kuntī; 2) Ib. 8. 18-43. by Bhīṣma; 3) Ib. 9. 32-42. by women of Hāstinapura; 4) Ib. 10. 21-30. by Śuka; 5) Ib. II. 4. 12-24; 9. 5-16. by Brahmā; 6) Ib. 9. 24-29. by Jīva in embryo; 7) Ib. III. 12-21. by Devahūtī; 8) Ib. 33. 2-8. by Dakṣa and others; 9) Ib. IV. 7. 26-47. by Sunīti; 10) Ib. 8. 19-3. by Dhruva; 11) Ib. 9. 6-17. by Pṛthu; 12) Ib. 20. 23-31. by Pracetasas; 13) Ib. 30. 22-42. by Nārada; 14) Ib. 31. 9-22[4]. Rudragītā in praise of: taught by Śiva to Pracetasas; 15) Ib. 24. 33-79. praise of Hari leads to attain divine knowledge and also to mokṣa; 16) Ib. VII. 1. 4-5 [1-2]; 7. 31. praise of, by Manu (Svāyambhuva), 17) Ib. VIII. 1. 9-16. by Gajendra; 18) Ib. 3. 2-29. by Brahmā; 19) Ib. 5. 26-50; 6. 8-15; 17. 25-28. by Śiva; 20) Ib. 12. 4-13. by Aditi; 21) 17. 8-10. by Bali in bondage, by Prahlāda; 23) Ib. 23. 6-8. and by Satyavrata; 24) Ib. 24. 29-30, 46-53. by Trayī and Upaniṣadic and Yoga literature; 25) Ib. X. 8. 45. praise of: by Garuḍa; 26) Ib. X. [53v 14-16]. by Mucukunda; 27) Ib. 51. 46-58. by Jāmbavat; 28) Ib. 56. 26-8. by Kṛtavarman, and Akrūra; 29) Ib. 40. 1-30; 57. 12-17. by Bhūmi, mother of Naraka; 30) Ib. 59. 25-31. by Rukmiṇī; 31) Ib. 60. 34-48. by Indra; 32) [67 (v) 24-30]. by Nṛga; 33) Ib. 60. 44; 64. 10-29. and by Rudra; 34) Ib. 63. 34-45. his deeds recalled by the citizens of Mathurā; 35) Ib. X. 43. 22-31. praise of; nature of; much in evidence in Draviḍa; 36) Ib. XI. 5. 32-40. by Nārada; 37) Ib. X. 37. 9-23; 69. 17-18; 70. 37-44. by kings in Jarāsandha's prison, and after their  release; 38) Ib. 70. 25-30; 73. 8-16. by Yudhiṣṭira; 39) Ib. 74. 2-5. by Ṛṣis; 40) Ib. 84. 16-26. by Vasudeva, Devakī and Bali; 41) Ib. 85. (whole). by Bahulāśva; 42) Ib. 86. 31-6. by Śrutadeva; 43) Ib. 86. 44-9. by Śrutis (Śrutigīti); 44) Ib. 87. 14-41. by gods; 45) Ib. XI. 6. 7-19. by Brahmā; 46) Ib. 6. 21-7; X. 14. 1-40. by Uddhava; 47) Ib. 42. 49; 7. 14-18; 11. 13, 34, 36; 29. 37-40. by Nalakūbara and Maṇigrīva; 48) Ib. X. 10. 29-38. by Kāliya and his wives; 49) Ib. 16. 33-59. by Gopis (Gopigītā); 50) Ib. 21. 7-19; 31. 1-19; 35. 2-25. by Indra. 51) Ib. 27. 4-13. ^22 Ib. 22. 2-11, 21-23.

हरि
Hari  (II)--a name given to Viṣṇu by Svāyambhuva Manu for saving three worlds from affliction; 1) Bhā. II. 7. 2. acted as Brahmā in Soma's Rājasūya; 2) M. 23. 21. adhidevata for the planet Budha; 3) Ib. 93. 13; 246. 4, 34: 247. 19; 248. 36. does praṇāma every day to Śaṅkara. 4) Vā. 21. 7; 35. 13.

हरि
Hari  (III)--a son of Ṛṣabha and a Bhāgavata: expounded to Nimi the nature of a Bhāgavatottama. Bhā. V. 4. 11; XI. 2. 21, 45-55.

हरि
Hari  (IV)--an avatār: born as son of Hariṇī and Harimedhas: awarded mokṣa to Gajendra. Bhā. VIII. 1. 30.

हरि
Hari  (V)--son of Vasudeva and Devakī to put down adharma. Bhā. IX. 24. 55-67. 

हरि
Hari  (VI)--(Matsya). Bhā. X. 40. 17.

हरि
Hari  (VII)--(as horse) killed Madhu and Kaiṭabha. Bhā. X. 40. 17.

हरि
Hari  (VIII)--(Kūrma) bore Mandara. Bhā. X. 40. 18.

हरि
Hari  (IX)--(Varāha) raised the Earth. Bhā. X. 40. 18; Br. 5. 15.

हरि
Hari  (X)--Narasimha. Bhā. X. 40. 19.

हरि
Hari  (XI)--Nirguṇa and apart from Prakṛti: makes his devotees the poorest so as to create in them a spirit of detachment: Blesses and curses: In the garb of a Brahmacārin persuaded Vṛka to test Śiva's boon on himself: Bhṛgu kicked the sleeping Hari in his chest and helped him to get united with Lakṣmī: Bhṛgu's wonder at it; 1) Bhā. X. Chh. 88-89. Has root in religious performances of Brahmanas and is himself Yajña and source of all Dharma: the 25th principle: Helped Śiva in regaining his lost glory through Maya: took the form of a cow and with Brahmā as calf drank the immortalising fluid of the well in Tripura; 2) Ib. VII. 2. 11; 8. 52; 10. 51 and 62; 11. 7. Vibhūtis of; 3) Ib. 16. 9-40. Brahmā born of his grace and Rudra of his wrath. 4) Ib. XII 5. 1.

हरि
Hari  (XII)--avatārs of: Puruṣa as Brahmā, Viṣṇu and Rudra, Naranārāyaṇa, Hamsa, Datta, Kumāra, Ṛṣabha, Hayagrīva, Matsya, Varāha, Kūrma, Nṛsimha, Vāmana, Paraśurāma and Rāma. Bhā. XI. 4 (whole). 

हरि
Hari  (XIII)--in a group--form of Vāsudeva, Sankarṣaṇa, Pradyumna and Aniruddha: as the indwellers of sūrya: spoken of in nine forms such as time, place and so on. In the form of time, for every month seven attendants lead him; 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 21 and 28, 31-44. other attendants of. 2) Ib. XI. 27. 27-9.

हरि
Hari  (XIV)--a Tuṣita god in the Svārociṣa and a Sādhya in the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Br. III. 3. 15.

हरि
Hari  (XV)--a son of Rukmakavaca appointed over Videha with his brother Parigha. Br. III. 70. 29; M. 44. 28-9; Vā. 95. 28.

हरि
Hari  (XVI)--same as Mahiṣa. M. 122. 59.

हरि
Hari  (XVII)--an attribute of Viṣṇu; everywhere in his universal form (Viśvarūpa). Vi. II. 2. 51; III. 8. 10; V. 1. 32; 4. 4; 13. 48, 50; 17. 8, 17; 18. 31; 20. 59; 21. 8, 11; 24. 1; 31. 20; 32. 8; 33. 11 ff; 34. 13, 17; VI. 4. 4; 8. 18, 31 ff.

हरि
Hari  (XVIII)--Mt. a chief hill of Kuśadvīpa. Vi. II. 44. 41.

हरि
Hari  (XIX) a son of Viśvāmitra. Vi. IV. 7. 38.

हरि
Haris --the gods of the Tāmasa epoch, see Haraya. Bhā. VIII. 1. 28.

हरिकथा
Harikathā --(also Nārāyaṇa Kathā) sung in the sabhās of Brahmā and Śiva: sacred, never dull and always new; 1) Bhā. X. 60. 44; 52. 20. one way of getting divine knowledge: leads to virtue, nectar itself: purifies men and women; 2) Ib. VII. 1. 5 [3]; 7. 31. X. 1. 13 and 16. XI. 3. 2. fit to listen to, and fit to  be told and listened to: would never give satiety: by listening to it one gets proper vision and crosses the road of samsāra. For instance hearing of the avatār of Vāmana leads one to bliss and that of Matsya to world's welfare; 3) Ib. I. 15. 36; 18. 9-10 and 14; V. 12. 16. VIII. 23. 30; 24. 1-3; X. 90. 21 [1], 24 and 50. XI. 14. 26; 19. 20. XI. 14. 26; 19. 20. purifies the worlds and destroys the sins of Kali; 4) Ib. XI. 11. 23 and 35; XII. 8. 6. faith in the Kathā important; 5) Ib. XI. 20. 8-9, 27; 26. 28-29; 27. 44. importance of, stated by Nṛsimha to Prahlāda, and by Nārada to Yudhiṣṭira; 6) Ib. VII. 10. 12; 14. 3. praise of; 7) Ib. II. 1. 5, 2. 36-37; 3. 14. 25; 4. 8. 2-6, 17; III. 19. 33-8; 20. 6; 32. 18-19; X. 1. 4-16; 7. 1-3; 12. 41-3; 13. 1. 2; 16. 2-3; 78. [96 (v) 2-4]; 80. 1-4; XI. 5. 4. Parīkṣit's deep interest in, and Nārada singing of; 8) Ib. X. 1. 15; I. 5. 26 and 28; 6. 33. Ariṣtasena hears it and narrates it to Kimpuruṣa; 9) Ib. V. 19. 2; VI. 2. 26; 3. 31. narrated by Śuka; 10) Ib. VII. 1. 5. by Gopis on the eve of Kṛṣṇa's departure to Mathurā, and on hearing Kṛṣṇa's message through Uddhava. 11) Ib. X. 39. 19. 30; 47. 37-52.

हरिकुण्डम्
Harikuṇḍam --in Brahmakṣetram. Vā. 59. 122.

हरिकूट
Harikūṭa --a Mt. and residence of Hari Mahānābha. Vā. 39. 58.

हरिकेश
Harikeśa  (I)--a son of Śyāmaka and Śūrabhū. Bhā. IX. 24. 42.

हरिकेश
Harikeśa  (II)--one of the seven important rays of the sun, said to be the root of planets, and the first originator of stars. Br. II. 24. 66; Vā. 53. 47.

हरिकेश
Harikeśa  (III)--a son of Pūrṇabhadra, the Yakṣa; he became a devotee of Śiva and gave up the svadharma of the Yakṣas. Hence the angry father banished him. He perform ed austerities so severely at Benares for thousands of years that he was covered over with mud and eaten by ants till he was reduced to bones. Śiva came to the spot with Pārvatī and made him Dhanada, the Ganeśvara and Kṣetrapāla; he was also made Annada. Two Gaṇas Udbhrama and Sambhrama were given for his service. Then Śiva and Pārvatī disappeared. M. 180. 5-9, 82. 99; Vā. 69. 12.

हरिकेश
Harikeśa  (IV)--a Gandharva king in Kailās. Vā. 41. 21.

हरिगिरि
Harigiri --a Mt. of Kuśadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 56; Vā. 49. 51.

हरिचक्र
Haricakra --the wheel of Viṣṇu, fell to pieces at Naimiṣa. M. 22. 14.

हरिचन्दनम्
Haricandanam --offered to Śeṣa by Nāga maids. Vi. II. 5. 25.

हरिचन्दनवाटी
Haricandanavāṭī --a division of Śripuram. Br. IV. 32. 25.

हरिण
Hariṇa --see Haraya. Br. III. 7. 179; 22. 45.

हरिणाकूडनम्
Hariṇākūḍanam --Boyish sport, in which boys are coupled with one another and go leaping away; the vanguard brings back the victor to the starting ground; Govinda was matched with Śrīdāman and Rāma with Pralamba in the disguise of a Gopa. Vi. V. 9. 12-14. 

हरिणास्या
Hariṇāsyā --(music) coming out from Harideśa; Indra is the presiding deity. Vā. 86. 38, 57.

हरिणी
Hariṇī --mother of Hari, in the Tāmasa epoch. Bhā. VIII. 1. 30; Br. III. 3. 116.

हरिण्मान्
Hariṇmān --a son of Agnidhra; Kingdom Uttaraśveta. Vā. 33. 39, 42.

हरित
Harita  (I)--a grandson of Hariścandra, and the son of Rohita, (Rohitāśva-Vi. P.) and father of Campa (CancuVi. P.). Bhā. X. 8. 1; Br. III. 63. 117; Vā. 88. 119; Vi. IV. 3. 25.

हरित
Harita  (II)--a son of Vapuṣmat, after whom came the Hārita varṣa. Br. II. 1. 32-3; Vā. 33. 28, 29. Vi. II. 4. 23, 29.

हरित
Harita  (III)--born of Pulaha. Br. III. 7. 179.

हरित
Harita  (IV)--a son of Paravṛt. Vi. IV. 12. 11.

हरित
Haritas  (I)--a group of ten gods of the epoch of the 12th Manu, 1) Bhā. VIII. 13. 28; Vi. III. 2. 34. of the IV Sāvarṇa Manu. 2) Br. IV. 1. 83-4.

हरित
Haritas  (II)--a branch of Angiras. Vā. 65. 107. 

हरित
Haritas  (III)--family of, famous warriors. Vā. 88. 73.

हरित
Haritas  (IV)--one of the five devagaṇas of the 12th period of Manu (Ṛthusāvarṇa); mind-born son of Brahmā with ten branches.

हरितक
Haritaka --belonging to Tripravara. M. 196. 33.

हरितम्
Haritam --a varṣa round Droṇa. Vā. 49. 40.

हरितम्
Haritam vanam --the garden where Yayāti's family and children used to take rest and engage in recreation; 1) M. 32. 11. a region of Śālmalidvīpa. 2) Br. II. 19. 44.

हरिताश्व
Haritāśva --a son of Ilasudyumna; the lord of the east including the Kurus. M. 12. 17-18.

हरितोया
Haritoyā --a R. of the Bhadrā country. Vā. 43. 26.

हरिदास
Haridāsa  (I)--see Uddhava. Bhā. X. 47. 53.

हरिदास
Haridāsa  (II)--a Vānara chieftain and son of Śveta. Br. III. 7. 181.

हरिदाश
Haridāśa (Haridehe?) --the birthplace of Hariṇāśva mūrchana. Br. III. 61. 44. Vā. 86. 51. 

हरिनाम
Hari-nāma --uttering the four lettered name of Hari, Ajāmila expiated his sins. By hearing his name once even a Pulkaśa got released from samsāra; 1) Bhā. VI. 2. 7. 9, 14, 18, 46 and 50; 16. 44. Durvāsa on. 2) Ib. IX. 4. 61-2.

हरिनेत्र
Harinetra --a Vānara chief. Br. III. 7. 240.

हरिपर्वत
Hariparvata --a Kulaparvata of the Ketumālā. Vā. 44. 4.

हरिपुरम्
Haripuram --the world of Viṣṇu. Vā. 106. 19; 108. 3.

हरिभद्रा
Haribhadrā --a daughter of Krodhavaśā and Hari and a wife of Pulaha; sons, monkeys of different kinds; Kinnaras, Kimpuruṣas, etc. Br. III. 7. 172; Vā. 69. 205, 208.

हरिमित्र
Harimitra --one of the names in the second Marutgaṇa. Vā. 67. 125.

हरिमेधस्
Harimedhas --the father of Hari. Bhā. VIII. 1. 30.

हरिवर्मन्
Harivarman --born of Pulaha. Br. III. 7. 179.

हरिवर्ष
Harivarṣa  (I)--a son of Agnīdhra, and Lord of Niṣadha. Bhā. V. 2. 19; Br. II. 14. 46-9; Vā. 33. 39, 43; Vi. II. 1. 16, 19.

हरिवर्ष
Harivarṣa  (II)--(Naiṣadha) a continent in Jambudvīpa. Here Viṣṇu revealed himself as Nṛsimha and is worshipped by Prahlāda; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 9; 18. 7-14; Vi. II. 2. 13. country, gold in colour; people of, white  in colour; drink sugar-cane juice and live for 11000 years; 2) Br. II. 17. 1, 6-9; Vā. 34. 29; 46. 8-10. belongs to Niṣadha. 3) M. 113. 29; 114. 59, 66 ff.

हरिवाहन
Harivāhana --a son of Caidyoparicara. M. 50. 27.

हरिश्चन्द्र
Hariścandra --son of Triśanku and Satyaratā. Concerning him there was a battle between Vasiṣṭha and Viśvāmitra in the disguise of birds for many years. Issueless, and advised by Nārada, he prayed to Varuṇa for a son, promising to offer him in sacrifice to the deity. The son was Rohita. Varuṇa reminded him often about the promised sacrifice, and the king evaded saying that he was not yet fit for it. Knowing this Rohita left for forests and the king had a disease mahodara: when the boy returned to relieve his father, Indra prevented him from going home. Six years passed and Rohita purchased Sunaśśepa, the second son of Ajiganta and returned home. Hariścandra proceeded to offer Sunaśśepa in sacrifice and was relieved of his disease. Sunaśśepa was sold as a sacrificial animal to Rohita. 1) Bhā. IX. 7. 7-27; 16. 31; M. 12. 38; Vā. 88. 117-9; Vi. IV. 3. 25. Attained permanent fame; 2) Bhā. X. 72. 21. a samrāṭ by performing Rājasūya 3) Br. III. 63. 115; 66. 66; Vā. 91. 94.

हरिश्चन्द्रम्
Hariścandram --sacred to Candrikā; sacred to Pitṛs; 1) M. 13. 40; 22. 52. sacred to Śiva. 2) Ib. 181. 28.

हरिश्मश्रु
Hariśmaśru --a son of Hiraṇyākṣa. Bhā. VII. 2. 18.

हरिषेण
Hariṣeṇa --a Kinnara with a man's face. Vā. 69. 35. 

हर्यक्ष
Haryakṣa --a son of Pṛthu and Arcis; was entrusted with eastern kingdom by his elder brother. Bhā. IV. 22. 54; 24. 2.

हर्यङ्ग
Haryaṅga --a son of Campa in his sacrifice, the Vāruṇa able to conquer enemies came from heaven; father of Bhadraratha. M. 48. 98-99; Vā. 99. 107; Vi. IV. 18. 21-22.

हर्यद्वत
Haryadvata --a son of Jaya. Vā. 93. 9.

हर्यधन
Haryadhana --a son of Kṛta and father of Sahadeva. Vi. IV. 9. 27.

हर्यवन
Haryavana  (I)--a son of Kṛta, and father of Sahadeva. Bhā. IX. 17. 17.

हर्यवन
Haryavana  (II)--Vedavyāsa XXII. Br. II. 35. 122.

हर्यश्व
Haryaśva  (I)--a son of Dhṛḍhāśva, and father of Nikumbha. Bhā. IX. 6. 24; Br. III. 63. 63; Vā. 88. 62; Vi. IV. 2. 43.

हर्यश्व
Haryaśva  (II)--a son of Anaraṇya, and father of Aruṇa; wife Dṛṣadvatī. Bhā. IX. 7. 4; Br. III. 63. 75.

हर्यश्व
Haryaśva  (III)--a son of Dhṛṣṭaketu and father of Manu. Bhā. IX. 13. 15; Br. III. 64. 10; Vā. 89. 10; Vi. IV. 5. 27.

हर्यश्व
Haryaśva  (IV)--a son of Pramoda. M. 12. 33. 

हर्यश्व
Haryaśva  (V)--a son of Trasadaśva; wife Dṛṣadvatī; father of Vasumata. Vā. 88. 76.

हर्यश्व
Haryaśva  (VI)--a son of Pṛṣadaśva and father of Hasta. Vi. IV. 3. 18-19.

हर्यश्व
Haryaśva  (VII)--a son of Ṛkṣa; father of five sons, the well-known Pāñcālas. Vi. IV. 19. 589.

हर्यश्व
Haryaśva  (VIII)--a son of Mudgala; had twins, Divodāsa and Ahalyā. Vi. IV. 19. 61-2.

हर्यश्व
Haryaśvas --the thousand (five thousand-Vi. P.) sons of Dakṣa and Asi(a)knī; on the advice of Nārada they took to the path of ‘Not returning’. Perished in the attempt to get a knowledge of the entire earth according to Nārada's directions, 1) Bhā. VI. 5. 1-21; Br. III. 2. 15, 22-3; Vi. I. 15. 90-96. were put to shame and went to Vāyu, and became one with him and still wander there aimlessly. 2) M. 5. 5. Vā; 65. 139, 146-50.

हर्यश्वक
Haryaśvaka --a son of Jaya and father of Sahadeva. Br. III. 68. 9.

हर्यश्वि
Haryaśvi --belonging to nīla (blue) Parāśara group. M. 201. 34.

हर्या
Haryā --the mother of Hari in the Tāmasa epoch. Vi. III. 1. 39.

हर्य्यात्मा
Haryyātmā --Vedavyāsa of the 21st dvāpara. Vi. III. 3. 16. 

हर्ष
Harṣa  (I)--a son of Droṇa and a Vasu. Bhā. VI. 6. 11.

हर्ष
Harṣa  (II)--a son of Kṛṣṇa and Mitravindā. Bhā. X. 61. 16.

हर्ष
Harṣas --gods in Tāmasa manvantara. Vā. 67. 39.

हल
Hala --a weapon peculiar to Balarāma; reached him during the siege of Mathurā. Bhā. X. 50. 11 [15]; Vā. 23. 199; Vi. V. 22. 7.

हल
Hala --a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 11.

हलमुल्लुञ्च
Halamulluñca --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 79.

हलयम
Halayamas --a Trayārṣeya. M. 198. 5.

हल
Halas --a Trayārṣeya. M. 200. 14.

हला
Halā --one of Atri's ten wives. Br. III. 8. 75.

हलि
Hali  (also Lāṅgali and Baladeva)--Balarāma, brother of Kṛṣṇa; took Kṛṣṇa to task for not getting syamantaka after killing Bhoja and went to Mithilā where he was honoured by its king; Duryodhana learnt gadā from him here; taken back to Dvārakā by Kṛṣṇa. Br. III. 71. 66. 80. 85; Vi. V. 28. 11. 

हलिक
Halikas --the kingdom of the. M. 144. 57.

हवि
Havi  (I)--a god of Sutārā group. Br. IV. 1. 90.

हवि
Havi  (II)--a son of Cākṣuṣa Manu. M. 4. 41.

हवि
Havi  (III)--an oblation; often comes with kavyam; a compound word, havyakavyam. M. 7. 25; 22. 59.

हवि
Havi  (IV)--a deva of the Harita group. Vā. 100. 88.

हवि
Havi  (V)--one of the ten branches of Supārā group of devas. Vā. 100. 94.

हविर्धान
Havirdhāna  (II)--a son of Vijitāśva and Nabhasvatī. His queen was Havirdhānī who was the mother of Barhiṣad and five other sons; 1) Bhā. IV. 24. 5 and 8. attained heaven by tapas; 2) Br. II. 30. 40. a Rājaṛṣi and a tapassiddha. 3) Vā. 57. 122.

हविर्धान
Havirdhāna  (II)--a son of Antardhāna and Śikhaṇḍini; wife, Āgneyī-Dhiṣaṇā; had six sons. Br. II 37. 23-4; Vā. 63. 22, 23; Vi. I. 14. 1-2.

हविर्धान
Havirdhāna  (III)--a son of Pṛthu married Dhiṣaṇā and got a number of sons; attained heaven by tapas. M. 4. 45; 143. 39. 

हविर्धानी
Havirdhānī --the queen of Havirdhāna. Bhā. IV. 24. 8.

हविर्भुक्
Havirbhuk --is Agni. Br. IV. 35. 82.

हविर्भू
Havirbhū --a daughter of Kardama married to Pulastya. Father of Agastya and Viśravas. Bhā. III. 24. 22; IV. 1. 36.

हविर्यज्ञ
Haviryajñas --for Vaiśyas. Br. II. 29. 55; Vā. 57. 50.

हविष्कृत
Haviṣkṛta --one of the ten branches of the Supāra group of devas. Vā. 100. 94.

हविष्णु
Haviṣṇu --a son of Angirasa. Vā. 65. 105.

हविष्मत्
Haviṣmat  (I)--a son of Angiras; a sage of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Bhā. VIII. 5. 8; Br. II. 36. 77; Vā. 65. 105.

हविष्मत्
Haviṣmat  (II)--a sage of the tenth epoch of Manu. Bhā. VIII. 13. 21-22; Vi. III. 2. 27.

हविष्मत्
Haviṣmat  (III)--a sage of the Cākṣuṣa epoch. Vi. III. 1. 28.

हविष्मत्
Haviṣmat  (IV)--a sage of the XI epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. 4. 

हविष्मन्त
Haviṣmanta --Pitṛs, sons of Angiras who live in the world of Marīcigarbha; lords of those who perform tīrtha śrāddhas and of Kṣatriyas; their mind-born daughter, Yaśodā, wife of Amśumān. M. 15. 16; 102. 20.

हविष्मान्
Haviṣmān (Paulaha) --a sage of the second Sāvarṇa epoch. Br. IV. 1. 69.

हविष्मान्
Haviṣmān  (II)--(Kāśyapa) a sage of the epoch of III Sāvarṇa. Br. IV. 1. 78.

हविष्मान्
Haviṣmān  (III)--wife Kuhū, abandoned him for Soma. M. 23. 25.

हविष्मान्
Haviṣmān  (IV)--a son of Angirasa. M. 196. 2; Vā. 62. 65.

हविष्य
Haviṣya --a Sādhya. M. 171. 44.

हव्य
Havya  (I)--one of the ten sons of Kardamā and Svayambhu and king of Śākadvīpa and had seven sons, Jalada, Kumāra, Sukumāra, Manivaha, Kurumottara, Modālla and Mahādrumga, the founders respectively of seven kingdoms bearing their names; these are demons of the Śākadvīpa. Br. II. 11. 23; 13. 104; 14. 9-21; Vā. 31. 18; 33. 9, 16, 20; M. 9. 5.

हव्य
Havya  (II)--a god of Ādya group. Br. II. 36. 69.

हव्य
Havya  (III)--an Ātreya. Vā. 28. 20. 

हव्यम्
Havyam  (I)--a Sukhā god. Br. IV. 1. 19.

हव्यम्
Havyam  (II)--a mukhya gaṇa. Vā. 100. 18.

हव्यप
Havyapa --a son of Raivata Manu. M. 9. 21.

हव्यभाग
Havyabhāga --Saharakṣa mantras in the Yajña to keep out Asuras; Havyas for devas. Vā. 97. 26.

हव्यवाह
Havyavāha  (I)--a son of Suci Agni; the agni of devas. Br. II. 12. 5. Vā. 29. 4, 5.

हव्यवाह
Havyavāha  (II)--one of the ten kalas energising Agni. Br. IV. 35. 83.

हव्यवाह
Havyavāhas --those charged with different directions. Vā. 69. 67.

हव्यवाहन
Havyavāhana  (I)--is Agni (Hohīya) sent by Indra to disturb the love of Umā and Śankara; 1) Br. II. 12. 28. III. 10. 24; 11. 37. cursed by Umā to bear the burdens of maternity; 2) Vā. 72. 21-8. he in his turn requested Gangā to share it.

हव्यवाहन
Havyavāhana  (II)--(Ātreya) a sage of the Rohita epoch. Br. IV. 1. 63.

हव्यवाहन
Havyavāhana  (III)--a son of Dhara, a Vasava. M. 5. 23. 

हव्यवाहन
Havyavāhana  (IV)--the name of the ninth kalpa. Vā. 21. 31; 24. 162.

हव्यसूद
Havyasūda --another name for Asamsṛṣṭa located at what is known as Śāmitra. Vā. 29. 22.

हसौतिका
Hasautikā --the charioteer of Geyacakra. Br. IV. 20. 93.

हस्त
Hasta  (I)--a son of Rocana and Vasudeva. Bhā. IX. 24. 49.

हस्त
Hasta  (II)--a son of Sāvarṇa Manu I. Br. IV. 1. 64.

हस्त
Hasta  (III)--a measurement of 24 angulas. Vā. 8. 102, 105; 101. 123.

हस्त
Hasta  (IV)--a son of Haryaśva and father of Sumanas. Vi. IV. 3. 19-20.

हस्तम्
Hastam --a constellation; 1) Vā. 66. 49; 82. 7. śrāddham that day makes one important in an assembly. 2) Br. III. 18. 7.

हस्ति
Hasti --is Nāga; a line of Krodhāvaśa. Br. III. 7. 349; 8. 70.

हस्तिकर्ण
Hastikarṇa --a Kādraveya nāga. Br. III. 7. 33.

हस्तिदान
Hastidānas --Kāśyapa gotrakāras. M. 199. 5. 

हस्तिन्
Hastin  (I)--a son of Bṛhadkṣatra, (Suhotra-Vā. P.). After him came Hastināpura. 1) Bhā. IX. 21. 20-21; Vā. 99. 165; Vi. IV. 19. 28; M. 49. 42. Father of Ajāmīḍha and two other sons. 2) Vi. IV. 19. 29.

हस्तिन्
Hastin  (II)--a son of Vasiṣṭha and a Prajāpati of the Svārociṣa epoch. M. 9. 9.

हस्तिन
Hastina Chāyā --is Kuñjara chāyā. Br. III. 16. 44.

हस्तिनापुर
Hastināpura (Kurukṣetra) --named after Hastin, son of Suhotra; see Hāstinapura; 1) Bhā. IX. 21. 20; Vā. 99. 165; Vi. IV. 19. 28. sacred to Lalīṭā pīṭha; 2) Br. IV. 4. 97. sacred to Jayanti; 3) M. 103. 14. washed away by the Ganges floods. 4) Vi. IV. 21. 8.

हस्तिनापुरि
Hastināpuri --washed away by the Gaṅgā. M. 50. 78.

हस्तिनि
Hastini --a son of Bhadra. Vā. 69. 213.

हस्तिशास्त्रम्
Hastiśāstram --Budha caused the science of elephant to be made known. Hence Gajavaidyaka. M. 24. 2.

हस्तिशिक्षा
Hastiśikṣā --science of elephants. M. 215. 8, 36.

हहा
Hahā --the Gandharva presiding over the month of Śukra; 1) Bhā. XII. 11. 36; Br. III. 7. 8. with the sun in summer; 2) Vā. 52. 7. expert in divine music. 3) Ib. 69. 46. 

हहू
Hahū --a Gandharva with the sun in summer. Vā. 52. 7.

हाकिनी
Hākinī --a Śakti in the Kiricakra. Br. IV. 20. 15; 44. 91.

हाटक
Hāṭaka  (I)--a liquid by administering which a person feels rejuvenated; used in Atala. Bhā. V. 24. 16.

हाटक
Hāṭaka  (II)--the gold found in Vitala. Bhā. V. 24. 17.

हाटकी
Hāṭakī --R. in Vitala; the vīrya of Śiva (Hāṭakeśvara and Bhavānī). Bhā. V. 24. 17.

हाटकेश्वर
Hāṭakeśvara --the name as the Lord enshrined in Vitala. Bhā. V. 24. 17.

हारमूर्तिक
Hāramūrtikas --a tribe. M. 114. 41.

हारवामक
Hāravāmakas --a Janapada of the Bhadrā country. Vā. 43. 22.

हारिकर्णि
Hārikarṇi --a Pravara of Angiras. M. 196. 15.

हारिण
Hāriṇa --the flesh of the deer used for śrāddha. M. 17. 31. 

हारित
Hārita  (I)--a son of Yuvanāśva: after him came the well-known Angirasa Hāritas. Bhā. IX. 7. 1.

हारित
Hārita  (II)--a son of Viśvāmitra. Bhā. IX. 16. 36.

हारित
Hārita  (III)--a Paurāṇika. Bhā. XII. 7. 5.

हारित
Hārita  (IV)--a Ṛtvik at Brahmā's yāga. Vā. 106. 34.

हरित
Haritas --the descendants of Harita, son of Yuvanāśva, all able warriors; sons of Angiras and Brahmans with Kṣatriya dharma. Vā. 88. 73; Vi. IV. 3. 3.

हारिद्रवीय
Hāridravīyas --the khila and upakhila portions of Vedas. Br. II. 35. 75; Vā. 61. 65.

हारीतम्
Hārītam --a tīrtha sacred to the Pitṛs. M. 22. 68.

हार्दिक्य
Hārdikya --was sent with Kṛṣṇa's sacrificial horse; took active part in the Rājasūya of Yudhiṣṭhira, and being on the left detachment of Kṛṣṇa's army to attack Jarāsandha; defended Dvārakā against Śālva; in Duryodhana's army. Bhā. X. 89. 22 [2]; [50 (V) 11]; 75. 6; 76. 14; 78 [95 (V) 16].

हाल
Hāla  (I)--a Trayārṣeya. M. 200. 14. 

हाल
Hāla  (II)--an Āndhra king; ruled for five years (one year-Br. P. and Vā. P.); with him are twelve (pañcasaptaka) kings. M. 273. 9; Br. III. 74. 165; Vā. 99. 352.

हालाहल
Hālāhala(m)  (I)--the poison that first issued from the Amṛtamathana. Śiva consumed it with Pārvati's permission. That which was split became poisonous scorpions, serpents, cobras and other plants; 1) Bhā. VIII. 7. 18. 46. administered to Prahlāda. 2) Vi. I. 15. 154; 16. 10; 18. 3.

हालाहल
Hālāhala  (II)--the XI battle between the Gods and the Asuras. Br. III. 72. 75, 86.

हालाहल
Hālāhala  (III)--the eleventh of the twelve incarnations in Vārāha kalpa; 1) M. 47. 45; Vā. 97. 76. Vṛtra killed by Mahendra. 2) M. 47. 51.

हालाहल
Hālāhala  (IV)--a son of Ariṣṭakarman, and father of Palalaka. Vi. IV. 24. 46-7.

हालाहलगण
Hālāhalagaṇa --the community of Anuhrāda's sons. Vā. 67. 75.

हालिनि
Hālini --a pupil of Lāngala. Br. II. 35. 48.

हालेय
Hāleya --a son of Ariṣṭakarman, and father of Talaka. Bhā. XII. 1. 25.

हासिनी
Hāsinī --a Mother Goddess. M. 179. 30. 

हास्तिनापुर
Hāstināpura --(also Hastināpura and Gajāhva); 1) Bhā. I. 4. 6; 8. 45. 10. 7; 13. 1; visited by Kṛṣṇa often. Here Kṛṣṇa spent some months after Bhīṣma's death and Yudhiṣṭhira's coronation. A Brahmana of this city informed Kṛṣṇa of the banishment of the Pāṇḍavas to forest; 2) Ib. I. 9. 48; X. 58. 1; 64; 2-4; 71. 22; 75. 38 [2]; 80 [2]; 80 [5]; 84. 69 [3]. visited by Akrūra, 3) Ib. X. 48. 32; 49. 1. and by Balarāma. The latter got offended at the remark of the Kurus about his king and threatened to lift up the city and throw it into the Ganges. 4) Ib. X. 68. (whole). Return of the Pāṇḍavas and others after visit to Syamanta pañcaka; visited by Kṛtavarman 5) Ib. X. 52 [56 (v) 3]
[13]. and by Satyabhāmā after her father's death; 6) Ib. X. 57. 8. left by Vidura; 7) Ib. III. 1. 17; IV. 31. 30. when this city was washed away Kauśāmbī became capital; 8) Ib. IX. 32. 40. capital of the Kurus and Parīkṣit. 9) Ib. I. 17. 44; Vi. V. 35. 32.

हाहा
Hāhā --a Gandharva singer who entertains Brahmā with music; 1) Bhā. X. 52. 15[4]; Vi. IV. 1. 68. with the sun in the months of śuci and śukra; 2) Br. II. 23. 7; Vi. II. 107: see Hāhā.

हाहाहूहू
Hāhāhūhūs --Divine musicians. Vā. 108. 48.

हिडिम्बा
Hiḍimbā --a wife of Bhīma and mother of Ghaṭotkaca. Bhā. IX. 22. 30-31; Vā. 99. 247; Vi. IV. 20. 45.

हिनान
Hinānas --a Janapada of the Ketumālā continent. Vā. 44. 12.

हिमवान्
Himavān  (I)--(personified) as Mena's husband;^a acted as calf when the mountains milked the cow earth; 1) Bhā. IV. 7. 58; M. 10. 26. wife was the mind-born daughter of the Pitṛs; 2) Ib. 13. 7. Krauñja and Maināka were sons; 3) Ib. 113. 11. 114. 20-22; rivers from; 4) Ib. 117. 1-21. beauty of. 5) Ib. 154. 52; 162. 6; 183. 

हिमवान्
Himavān  (II)--(also Himagiri): one of the six traversed by Alakanandā; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 9; 17. 9; Br. II. 15. 15, 28; IV. 31. 16, 97; Vi. V. 9. 30. Varṣaparvata of Himācala. King of mountains; overlord of all hills; 2) Br. III. 8. 9; 22. 8; Vi. I. 22. 8; II. 2. 11. noted for the sacred pool of Suṣumṇa; 3) Br. III. 10. 7; 12. 5; 13. 122-3. a description of the forests, trees and the races inhabiting the mountain; waterfalls and caves in; cool with snow; 4) Ib. III. 22. 7-44. served as calf when the mountains milked the earth for medicinal plants and gems; 5) Ib. II. 36. 223. where Paraśurāma performed penance; 6) Ib. III. 21. 74; 22. 4. people towards the end of Kaliyuga leave their homes and retire to forests and caves in the Himālayan slopes; 7) Ib. III. 74. 214. residence of Rākṣasas, Piśācas and Yakṣas; 8) Ib. II. 17. 33. Parīkṣit compared to, in worthiness: Dhṛtarāṣṭra spent here his last days. 9) Bhā. I. 12. 33; 13. 29.

हिमशैलराट्
Himaśailarāṭ --see Himavān: also Himādri. M. 156. 19. Br. II. 25. 49.

हिमसर्जन
Himasarjanas --snow making rays of the sun. Vā. 53. 21.

हिमाख्यम्
Himākhyam --the Dakṣiṇa varṣa of Jambūdvīpa with Nābhī as first King. Br. II. 14. 48.

हिमाह्वम्
Himāhvam(varṣam) --is Himākhyam; 1) Br. II. 18. 42; III. 7. 194. the continent of Jambūdvīpa. 2) Vi. II. 1. 18, 27.

हिंसा
Hiṃsā  (I)--born of Lobha and Nikṛti; 1) Bhā. IV. 8. 3. wife of Kali, of bad mind. 2) Br. III. 59. 9; Vā. 84. 9. 

हिंसा
Hiṃsā  (II)--one of the five heinous sins--narrated to Indra by Bṛhaspati; it is a sin against men, women, animals, and creatures of all sorts. Exceptions are given. Any man of any caste or any animal attacking may be attacked and killed in self-defence; this applies to family members also; wild animals like lions and tigers may be killed by the King for the benefit of Gods and Brahmans, and not for self-enjoyment; Bhagavatī Māyā created men and Gods and 14 kinds of animals as also sacrifices and ordered the worship of Gods by sacrificing Paśu to get oneself blessed with health and wealth; Paśus may be killed for Gods, Pitṛs, and for feeding great and respectable persons; in times of danger no sin in the eating of flesh by Brahmans; animals could be sacrificed in honour of Śakti. Br. IV. 6. 37-67.

हिंसा
Hiṃsā  (III)--gave birth to Nikṛti (daughter) and Anṛta (son) by Adharma. Vā. 10. 39; Vi. I. 7. 32.

हिंसाधर्म
Hiṃsādharma --Yajña, as adharma. Vā. 57. 98.

हिंस्र
Hiṃsra --one of the seven sons of Kauśika. M. 20. 3.

हिरण्मय
Hiraṇmaya  (I)--a son of Āgnīdhra. Bhā. V. 2. 19.

हिरण्मय
Hiraṇmaya  (II)--a continent bounded by Śveta hills on one side. Here Aryaman and other Pitṛs worship Viṣṇu in  the form of Kūrma, as the embodiment of the Sānkhya system. Bhā. V. 16. 8; 18. 29-33.

हिरण्मय
Hiraṇmaya  (III)--a Dānava. Br. III. 6. 11; Vā. 68. 11.

हिरण्मयवर्षम्
Hiraṇmaya(m)varṣam --(Śvetavarṣa); next to Ramya; 1) Vā. 34. 30. of Jambūdvīpa. 2) Vi. II. 2. 14.

हिरण्यकम्वर्षम्
Hiraṇyakamvarṣam --belonging to Śveta. M. 113. 31.

हिरण्यकशिपु
Hiraṇyakaśipu  (I)--a son of Ditī and Kaśyapa: reduced to subjection the three worlds with the Lokapālas: secured heaven through his son Prahlāda. His queen was Kayādhu; 1) Bhā. III. 17. 18-19; IV. 21. 47; VI. 18. 11-12; M. 6. 8, 9; Vi. I. 15. 140. wanted to avenge his brother Hiraṇyākṣa's death; 2) Bhā. VIII. 19. 7-9. the six sons born of his Asura Yoni were carried off by Yogamāyā's effort. They were again born of Devakī and killed by Kamsa; 3) Ib. X. 85. 46-49; Vi. V. 1. 70. lust after more territory; 4) Bhā. XII. 3. 11. in his previous birth an attendant of Hari. He was next born as Rāvaṇa and afterwards Caidya. Destroyed the whole world by fire and by sword all friends of Hari for the killing of his brother, consoled his wife and sons pointing to the old saying that to die at the hands of an enemy leads one to heaven and cited the story of Suyajña that it was no use to weep over the dead body. Then Ditī set her mind on the truth; 5) Ib. VII. 1. 39-45; Ch. 2 (whole). Hiraṇyakaśipu began austere penance in the Mandara hill and the fire of his penance spread far and wide and created fear in the Devas. Brahmā paid a visit and saw Hiraṇyakaśipu covered by an ant hill. Sprinkling divine waters, he woke him up to see the Lord on the Swan, and he praised His glory. He asked that (1) he might not meet with death at the hands of any being  created by Brahmā; (2) might not meet with death inside or outside, by day or night, by any weapon not on earth or in sky, by men or beasts, gods or asuras; (3) he was to be without an equal; (4) he should possess undiminishing power (5) and be the one ruler of all creatures. 6) Ib. I. Ch. 3 (whole): M. Chh. 161-3. These were granted and Hiraṇyakaśipu spread his sway on all the worlds and took up the seat of Indra. All gods except the Triad bowed to him; 7) Bhā. VII. 4. 2, 28; M. 47. 35-59. father of four sons, chief of whom was Prahlāda whom he hated as he was a devotee of Hari. Śukra's sons Śaṇḍa and Marka were appointed to be his tutors to get a knowledge of Trivarga. This only increased Prahlāda's devotion. Hiraṇyakaśipu put it to some inborn defect of the boy. Means to kill the child by wild beasts, poison, fire and water were of no avail. He was bound by noose and imprisoned; 8) Bhā. VII. 4. 29-43; Ch. 5. (whole); M. 146. 21; 153. 6; Vi. I. 15. 142; 17. 2-29. when he was absent in Mandara hill Indra harassed his followers and captured his queen with Prahlāda. Nārada asked him to release her, which he did. She was under the custody of the sage, praying to him for the birth of a good son; 9) Bhā. VII. 7. 2-16. in the course of his father's (Kaśyapa's) aśvamedha sacrifice, the child Hiraṇyakaśipu sat on one of the golden seats reserved for Hotṛ, and hence the name. Ruled for nearly (1/4) of the manvantara, got aurvimāyā from Aurva to dispel; 10) Br. III. 5. 4-29, 34. Tāmaśimāyā; 11) M. 175. 25, 64-71; 178. 10 and 19. rivers, mountains, worlds, etc. shaken by him; 12) Ib. 163. 56-92. first of Daityas, killed by Narasimha whom he never considered as Viṣṇu; 13) Vi. IV. 14. 46-7; 15. 1, 5. taken out by action of Yoganidrā under orders from Viṣṇu. 14) Ib. V. 1. 72-3.

हिरण्यकशिपु
Hiraṇyakaśipu  (II)--father of Divyā, wife of sage Bhṛgu. Br. III. 1. 74. 

हिरण्यकामधेनु
Hiraṇyakāmadhenu --gift of a cow and a calf in gold (3 to 100 palas in weight) on an auspicious day with preliminary prayers to deities; the giver enjoys heaven. M. 274. 8.

हिरण्यगर्भ
Hiraṇyagarbha  (I)--is Brahmā. Br. III. 1. 35; 65. 23.

हिरण्यगर्भ
Hiraṇyagarbha  (II)--is Vāsudeva; 1) Vi. VI. 7. 56. as the author of Yogaśāstra. 2) Ib. II. 13. 44.

हिरण्यगर्भदानम्
Hiraṇyagarbhadānam --the gift of an image in gold of the creator of the form of a golden egg like a lotus on an auspicious day and with special prayers to deities. The donor entered the egg and sat like a child in womb when the ceremonies of conception and birth were gone through by priests. The gift was accompanied by sandals, umbrella, seats, villages or districts. The giver would enjoy Brahmaloka. M. 274. 7; 275. 1-29.

हिरण्यद्वीपम्
Hiraṇyadvīpam --sacred to Viṣṇu--a tīrtham of the Narmadā. M. 193. 68-9.

हिरण्यनाभ
Hiraṇyanābha  (I)--of Kośala was a pupil of Sukarman and his pupil was Kṛta: a siddha; 1) Bhā. XII. 6. 76 and 80; VI. 15. 15. son of Vidhṛti and pupil of Jaimini. From him Yājñavalkya learnt the Ātmavidyā. Father of Puṣya (son of Viśvasaha; got instructed in Yoga from Yājñavalkya disciple of Jaimini-Vi. P.); 2) Ib. IX. 12. 3-5; 21. 28; Vi. IV. 4. 107. 108. a Śrutaṛṣi: considered as the disciple of Pauṣyañji in the Prācyasāma. His disciples were Samagas of the East; 3) Br. II. 33. 8; III. 63. 207-8. teacher of Kṛta who composed the Sāmasamhitā in 24 parts known as Prācya sāmas sung by him and the Kārtasāmagas; 4) M. 49. 75-6; Vi. III: 6: 5. IV. 19. 51. composed 24 samhitās which he taught to as many pupils (named). 5) Vā. 61. 44-7.

हिरण्यनाभ
Hiraṇyanābha  (II)--Kauśalya: Vasiṣṭha: son of Viśvasaha; a pupil of Jaimini's pautra and guru of Yājñavalkya in yoga. Vā. 88. 207-8.

हिरण्यनाभ
Hiraṇyanābha  (III)--Kauśilya: a King and one of the two disciples of Sukarma given by Indra; taught 500 samhitās to śiṣyas known as Eastern Sāmagas. Vā. 61. 33-35.

हिरण्यनाभ
Hiraṇyanābha  (IV)--Kauthuma: composed Sāmasamhitās in 24 parts. Vā. 99. 189.

हिरण्यनामा
Hiraṇyanāmā --a son of Jatāmāli of the 19th dvāpara. Vā. 23. 187.

हिरण्यपुर
Hiraṇyapura --a city of Rasātala, the residence of Nīvātakavacas; 1) Bhā. V. 24. 30; X. 89. 34 [5]. residence of fourteen sons of Mārīca (Dānavas); 2) Br. III. 6. 27; 44. 99. the residence of the Paulomas and the Kālakeyas; 3) M. 6. 24. residence of the sons and grandsons, etc. of the two daughters of Vaiśvanara. 4) Vā. 68. 26.

हिरण्यबाहु
Hiraṇyabāhu --a Pravara sage. M. 199. 16.

हिरण्यम्
Hiraṇyam --cash in gold; the best gift. M. 34. 11; 55. 19; Vi. IV. 10. 24. 

हिरण्यरेतस्
Hiraṇyaretas --a son of Priyavrata, and king of Kuśadvīpa. Divided it among his seven sons. Bhā. V. 1. 25, 33; 20. 14.

हिरण्यरोमा
Hiraṇyaromā  (I)--an Angirasa: a sage of the Raivata epoch. Bhā. VIII. 5. 3; Br. II. 36. 62; M. 9. 20; Vi. III. 1. 22.

हिरण्यरोमा
Hiraṇyaromā  (II)--also Parjanya, a Lokapāla; son of Parjanyaprajāpati and Mārīci; lord of the northern direction (guardian of the Eastern quarter-Vi. P.). Br. II. 11. 19; 21. 157; III. 8. 20; M. 8. 11; 124. 95; Vā. 28. 16.

हिरण्यरोमा
Hiraṇyaromā  (III)--a Gandharva. Vā. 62. 54; 69. 26.

हिरण्यरोमा
Hiraṇyaromā  (IV)--a Lokapāla of Lokāloka. Vi. II. 8. 83.

हिरण्यलोमा
Hiraṇyalomā --a Lokapāla. Vā. 50. 206.

हिरण्यवान्
Hiraṇyavān --a son of Āgnīdhra; placed in charge of the Kingdom north of Śveta. Vi. II. 1. 17 and 21.

हिरण्यवाहिनीला
Hiraṇyavāhinīlā --a R. of the Bhadrā country. Vā. 43. 30.

हिरण्यसृङ्ग
Hiraṇyasṛṅga --a powerful follower of Kubera, lives in Surabhi; forbidden to take part in sacrifices. M. 121. 61-62. 

हिरण्यष्ठीव
Hiraṇyaṣṭhīva --a Mt. (boundary hill) in Plakṣa. Bhā. V. 20. 4.

हिरण्याक्ष
Hiraṇyākṣa  (I)--a son of Kaśyapa and Ditī and an Ādīdaitya who died in fight with Viṣṇu; a brother of Hiraṇyakaśipu. Sought fight in heaven, entered the ocean and called upon Varuṇa to fight. Entered Rasātala in search of Hari and seeing Varāha--Hari remarked that it was a forest beast. A mad fight ensued when he put an end to him. It was sandhya with abhijit yoga, unfavourable to the enemy; 1) Bhā. III. 17. 18-31; Chh. 18 and 19 (whole); III. 14. 2-3; VI. 18. 11; M. 6. 8; Vi. I. 15. 140; Vā. 67. 59, 67. lust of, for more territory; 2) Bhā. XII. 3. 11. married Upadānavī; 3) Ib. VI. 6. 34. in the next birth he was Kumbhakarṇa, and in the succeeding one Dantavaktra. A person of much valour and heroism, defeated by Hari with difficulty; 4) Ib. VII. 1. 39-45; 19. 5-6. father of Śambara, Śakuni, Kālanābha, Mahānābha, Ulūka and Bhūtasantāpana; 5) Br. II. 19. 13; 20. 36; III. 5. 4-5, 12-32; 72. 77; M. 6. 14. killed by Varāhaviṣṇu at the Sumana hill of the Śakadvīpa. 6) Ib. 47. 47; 122. 16; 153. 6; 250. 57.

हिरण्याक्ष
Hiraṇyākṣa  (II)--a son of Śūrabhūmī and Syāmaka. Bhā. IX. 24. 42.

हिरण्याक्ष
Hiraṇyākṣa  (III)--a son of Devajānī an yakṣa. Br. III. 7. 130.

हिरण्याक्ष
Hiraṇyākṣa  (IV)--a son of Maṇivara, killed by the boar. Vā. 49. 11; 69. 161; 97. 78.

हिरण्याक्ष
Hiraṇyākṣa  (V)--an Asura of the V tala or Mahātala. Vā. 50. 35.

हिरण्याक्ष
Hiraṇyākṣas --of Kauśīka gotra. Br. III. 66. 72; Vā. 91. 100. 

हिरण्याक्षम्
Hiraṇyākṣam --a tīrtha sacred to Pitṛs. M. 22. 52.

हिरण्याश्व
Hiraṇyāśva --the gift of a golden horse in an auspicious hour leads one to the world of the sun. M. 274. 8; 280. 1-15.

हिरण्याश्वरथ
Hiraṇyāśvaratha --a gift of a chariot with 7 or 8 horses in gold on an auspicious day keeps one away from hell and takes him to the abode of Śiva. M. 274. 8; 281. 1-16.

हिरण्यास्तम्बि
Hiraṇyāstambi --a Trayārṣeya. M. 196. 41.

हिरण्वतम्वर्षम्
Hiraṇvatamvarṣam --north of Śveta and south of Śṛngasāhva; here is Hairanvatīnadī; age of the people 11,000 years; there is a tree Lakuca whose juice endows the people with long life; three peaks of jewels, gold and precious stones; full of splendid houses. M. 113. 64; Vā. 45. 6-10.

हीरण्वान्
Hīraṇvān --a son of Āgnīdhra and lord of Śveta. Br. II. 14. 46, 50.

हीन
Hīna --(Ahīna)--a son of Sahadeva and father of Jayasena. Bhā. IX. 17. 17.

हुत
Huta --of Dvayāmuṣyāyana gotra. M. 196. 52.

हुतम्
Hutam  (I)--a Sukha god. Br. IV. 1. 19. 

हुतम्
Hutam  (II)--a mukhya gaṇa. Vā. 100. 18.

हुतहव्य
Hutahavya(vaha) --a son of Dhara (Dharma-Vi. P.) Br. III. 3. 22; Vā. 66. 21; Vi. I. 15. 113.

हुताशन
Hutāśana(Vanhi)  (I)--as Viṣṇu and Svāhā as Śrī. Vi. I. 8. 22; 9. 34.

हुताशन
Hutāśana  (II)--Agni with Māruta (wind) ordered by Indra to destroy the Asuras; when some of them escaped to the ocean and Hutāśana and Māruta refused to dry up the oceans as per his orders Indra caused them to be born on the earth with one body; 1) M. 61. 3-16; Br. II. 11. 100, 112. riding animal of, sheep; his arm was Śakti; appointed a commander of Indra's host to attack Tāraka; 2) M. 148. 83; 289. 6. father of all the Apsarasa ladies; 3) Ib. 70. 21. entered the harem of Śiva and Umā in the form of a parrot and drank of His vīrya; 4) Ib. 158. 32. burnt with Kāma and reattained godhood. 5) Ib. 191. 112.

हुबक
Hubaka --(also Humbeka) a commander to aid Vīṣanga; killed by Bheruṇḍa. Br. IV. 25. 28, 95.

हुम्बक
Humbaka --a commander of Bhaṇḍa. Br. IV. 21. 79.

हुलुमुलु
Hulumulu --Hulumallaka--a commander to aid Vīṣanga; killed by Bheruṇḍa. Br. IV. 25. 28, 95.

हुहुरथ
Huhuratha --resides in the sun's chariot during the month of Āṣāḍha. Vi. II. 10. 8. 

हूण
Hūṇas --a tribe defeated by Bharata; purified of their sin by the worship of Hari; 1) Bhā. IX. 20. 30; II. 4. 18. specially created in the war of Lalitā with Bhaṇḍa; 2) Br. IV. 29. 131. nineteen in number; 3) M. 273. 19. the country of the. 4) Vā. 45. 136; Vi. II. 3. 17.

हूनदर्व
Hūnadarva --an eastern country. Br. II. 16. 52.

हूंकारि
Hūṃkāri --a Mother goddess. M. 179. 31.

हूयन्त
Hūyanta --a Marut gaṇa. M. 171. 54.

हूहुक
Hūhukas --a hill tribe. Br. II. 16. 67; Vā. 47. 56.

हूहू
Hūhū --a Gandharva in Brahmaloka who entertains Brahmā with music; 1) Vi. IV. 1. 68. cursed by sage Devala to become a crocodile; caught hold of Gajendra and was released from his curse; 2) Bhā. X. 52. 15[4]; VIII. 4. 3-5. with the sun in the months of Śuci and Śukra. 3) Ib. XII. 11. 36; Br. II. 23. 7; III. 7. 8; Vā. 69. 46.

हृच्छय
Hṛcchaya --a son of Avabhṛta; agni or Pāvaka; located at the Jaṭhara of men or Jaṭharāgni; son Mṛtyumān. Br. 12. 34; Vā. 29. 31.

हृदय
Hṛdaya --the horse of Bhoja which would go at a stretch 100 yojanas. Br. III. 71. 71-2.

हृदाकर्षणरूपिणी
Hṛdākarṣaṇarūpiṇī --a kala. Br. IV. 44. 119. 

हृदिक
Hṛdika --a son of Svayambhoja and the father of Kṛtavarman and nine other sons, and a votary of Kṛṣṇa. Bhā. I. 14. 28; IX. 24. 26-7; X. 52 [56 (v) 5]
[10]; III. 1. 35; Br. III. 71. 139-42; M. 44. 80-1; Vā. 96. 138; Vi. IV. 14. 23-4.

हृद्देवि
Hṛddevi --a deity in the Angadevyantaram. Br. IV. 37. 42.

हृषीकेश
Hṛṣīkeśa --an epithet of Viṣṇu; 1) Vi. I. 15. 67; 22. 75; V. 5. 21; 30. 1. God Viṣṇu who appeared in the dream of Brahmadatta and got him released from worldly life to one of Siddhas; 2) Br. IV. 34. 80; M. 21. 25; 100. 19; 167. 42. in the Tārakāmaya; 3) M. 174. 35; 245. 81, 85; 246. 35; 247. 27. ety. from Hṛṣīka (Indriya) and Īśa; 4) M. 248. 44-45. in Bhadrāśva. 5) Vā. 35. 23.

हृषेयु
Hṛṣeyu --a son of Bhadrāśva. M. 49. 5.

हृष्ट
Hṛṣṭas (Vidas) --those censuring the eternal principle. Vā. 100. 115.

हेति
Heti  (I)--a Rākṣasa and a son of Yātudhāna; follower of Vṛtra against Indra; took part in a Devāsura war between Bali and Indra. 1) Bhā. VI. 10. 20; VIII. 10. 20 and 28.

हेति
Heti  (II)--the Rākṣasa presiding over the month of Madhu. Bhā. XII. 11. 33; Br. II. 23. 4; III. 7. 89.

हेति
Heti  (III)--a Rākṣasa, and a son of Brahmā; performed severe austerities for a hundred thousand divine years by living on air and dried leaf with face and hands turned upwards and the little finger of foot planted on earth; got a  boon that he must not be killed by implements, or gods or men; Heti defeated the gods and became Indra himself; the gods gave the gadā to Viṣṇu to kill Heti and hence ādigadādhara; Heti was killed and taken to heaven; 1) Vā. 109. 5-12, 25; 111. 75. with the sun in spring; 2) Ib. 52. 5. in the sun's chariot in the months of Caitra and Madhu. 3) Vi. II. 10. 3.

हेतु
Hetu --a Piśāca; had a son Lanku. Vā. 69. 127, 129.

हेतुक
Hetuka --a Bhairava in the Kiricakra. Br. IV. 20. 81; 34. 62.

हेतुक
Hetukas --the śaktis in the last parva of the Kiricakra; best of Bhairavas. Br. IV. 20. 78.

हेतुवादम्
Hetuvādam --special to the Jains; 1) M. 24. 48. a śāstra of dvāpara. 2) Ib. 144. 22; Vā. 58. 23.

हेम
Hema --a son of Ruśadratha (Uśadratha-Vā. P.) and father of Sutapas. Bhā. IX. 23. 4; Br. III. 74. 25; Vā. 99. 25; Vi. IV. 18. 12.

हेमक
Hemaka --a Nāga in the third Talam or Vitalam (Vā. P.) Br. II. 20. 29; Vā. 50. 28.

हेमकक्ष
Hemakakṣa --a Mt. and residence of the Gandharvas and others. Vā. 36. 36; 39. 51.

हेमकूट
Hemakūṭa  (I)--Mt. to the south of Ilāvrata, and a boundary hill of Kimpuruṣa. From it falls Alakanandā; 1) Bhā. V. 16. 9; 17. 9; M. 113. 23; 114. 82; Vā. 47. 63. a  varṣaparvata; residence of Gandharvas and Apsaras; 2) Br. II. 15. 15 and 28. 17. 33; IV. 31. 16; Vi. II. 2. 41; Vā. 1. 85; 34. 14 and 25; 42. 31; Vi. II. 1. 19. a hill of the south where is the Puṇḍra city; 3) Vā. 51. 47; Br. I. 1. 68. a division of Jambūdvīpa. 4) Vi. II. 2. 11.

हेमकूट
Hemakūṭa  (II)--a tīrtha sacred to Manmatha. M. 13. 50.

हेमगर्भ
Hemagarbha --a Mt. M. 163. 84.

हेमचन्द्र
Hemacandra --a son of Viśāla and father of Sucandra (Candra-Vi. P.). Bhā. IX. 2. 34; Br. III. 61. 13; Vā. 86. 17-8; Vi. IV. 1. 50. 51.

हेमचित्रम्
Hemacitram --a city in the Triśṛṅga hill; temples of Nārāyaṇa (East), Brahmā (middle) and Śaṅkara (West). Vā. 41. 62. 3.

हेमन्त
Hemanta  (I)--a mind-born son of Brahmā in the 16th kalpa. Vā. 21. 35.

हेमन्त
Hemanta  (II)--cold season; 1) Vā. 53. 26; 88. 116. constitutes the months of Satra and Sahasya; 2) Ib. 52. 19. Parjanya and diggajas snow freely during the period. 3) Ib. 51. 45.

हेमन्तऋतु
Hemantaṛtu --queens were Sahaśrī and Sahasyaśrī. Br. IV. 32. 35. 

हेमतालवनम्
Hematālavanam --the residence of Āpava sage, burnt down by Kārtavīryārjuna for which he was cursed. M. 43. 41.

हेमपर्वत
Hemaparvata  (I)--a Mt. of Kuśadvīpa. Br. II. 19. 54; Vā. 49. 49.

हेमपर्वत
Hemaparvata  (II)--same as Unnata. M. 122. 54; 125. 22.

हेमपर्वतदानम्
Hemaparvatadānam (Svarṇācala) --the best is to give 1000 palams in weight in gold; if not 500 or 250; even one palam of gold is commended. The giver goes to Brahmalokam. M. 83. 5; 86. 1.

हेममाष
Hemamāṣa --a measurement of 16 inches equal to one nālikoccaya. Br. IV. 1. 219.

हेमरथ
Hemaratha --a son of Maṇivara. Vā. 69. 158.

हेमवान्
Hemavān --a Varṣaparvata in Jambūdvīpa. M. 113. 11.

हेमशृङ्ग
Hemaśṛṅga --Mt. lustrous as the sun, on the south of the Kailāsa; 1) M. 121. 11. residence of Brahmā. 2) Vā. 39. 46; 42. 31, 68; 47. 10.

हेमशैल
Hemaśaila --Mt. a chief hill of Kuśadvīpa. Vi. II. 4. 41. 

हेमसख
Hemasakha --a Mt. M. 163. 84.

हेमहस्तिरथ
Hemahastiratha --the gift of a chariot with elephants in gold on an auspicious day with prayers to all deities takes one to the abode of Śiva. M. 274. 8; 282. 1-16.

हेमा
Hemā --an Apsaras; daughter of Yama, of golden mien and excellent eyes. Vā. 69. 7, 61.

हेमांगद
Hemāṃgada --a son of Rocanā and Vasudeva. Bhā. IX. 24. 49.

हेमालयम्
Hemālayam --(Himālayas). Vi. IV. 1. 96.

हेरम्ब
Heramba --a name of Vināyaka. Br. III. 42. 8.

हेरम्ब
Herambas --a group of seven crores of divinities with Mahāgaṇapati as their lord. Br. IV. 27. 82.

हेहय
Hehaya --a son of Śatajit. Vi. IV. 11. 7.

हैडम्बि
Haiḍambi (Haiḍimbi) --mother of Ghaṭotkaca by Bhīmasena. M. 50. 54.

हैमकम्
Haimakam --the forest of Atri. Vā. 23. 155. 

हैमभौमक
Haimabhaumakas --a Janapada of the Bhadra country. Vā. 43. 22.

हैमवतम्
Haimavatam Varṣam --is Bhāratavarṣa; 1) Br. II. 15. 31. Bhāratam in Jambūdvīpa. 2) Vā. 34. 28.

हैमवती
Haimavatī --a wife of Akṣayāśra. Vā. 88. 64.

हैरण्वत
Hairaṇvata --a kingdom to the south of the Śṛṅgavān and north of the Śveta hills, people rolling in wealth and living for thousands of years; noted for the tree Lakuca. Br. II. 15. 66-9.

हैरण्वती
Hairaṇvatī --a R. in the kingdom of Hairaṇvata. Br. II. 15. 66; M. 113. 64; Vā. 45. 6.

हैहय
Haihaya  (I)--one of the three sons of Śatajit (SatajiM. P.) and father of Dharma. (Dharmanetra-M. P.). (Dharmatantra-Vā. P.). Bhā. IX. 23. 21, 22; Br. III. 69. 4. M. 43. 8-9; Vā. 94. 4; Vi. IV. 11. 7-8.

हैहय
Haihaya  (II)--(Arjuna s.v.); lost his kingdom through pride of power. Bhā. X. 73. 20.

हैहय
Haihayas  (I)--attained yoga through the grace of Datta; were defeated by Sagara and destroyed by Paraśurāma; 1) Bhā. II. 7. 4; IX. 8. 5; 15. 14. their king was Kārtavīrya and then his grandson Tālajangha. Five groups among them are distinguished; Vītihotras, Bhojas, Avantis, Tuṇḍikaras and Tālajanghas; 2) Br. III. 48. 13 and 22; 63. 120; 69. 52. 24 kings contemporaneous with ten Śiśunāgas; 3) Ib. III. 74. 136. 28 in number; 4) M. 272. 15. Tālajanghas of  whom five clans are distinguished; these are Vītihotras, Śaryātas, Bhojas, Avantis and Kuṇḍikeras; 5) Ib. 43. 48. country of, watered by Nalinī. 6) Br. II. 18. 59.

हैहय
Haihayas  (II)--100 kings after the Prativindhyas: Dhārtarāṣṭra, 51-100. Janamejayas, 51-80. Brahmadattas, -100. Vīryiṇas, -100. Paulas, 52-100. Kāśikuśa,-100. Śasabindavas, -1000 all Aśvamedhins. Br. III. 74. 261-71; Vā. 32. 50.

हैहय
Haihayas  (III)--a tribe; 1) Vā. 88. 122; 99. 323. defeated Bāhu. 2) Vi. IV. 3. 26, 40-1.

होता
Hotā --a Ṛtvik for yajña; 1) M. 167. 7; 246. 12; Br. III. 5. 10. Atri, for Soma's Rājasūya; 2) M. 23. 20. eight in connection with the ceremonials for constructing ponds. 3) Ib. 58. 11.

होतृ
Hotṛ --a Pārāvata god. Br. II. 39. 15.

होत्रक
Hotraka --a son of Kāñcana and father of Janhu. Bhā. IX. 15. 3.

होत्रम्
Hotram --from the Ṛk; 1) Vā. 60. 18. the Ṛk formulae uttered by the Hotā in an yajña. 2) Vi. III. 4. 12. 

होत्रिय
Hotriya --is Agni. Br. II. 12. 28.

होम
Homa  (I)--a Sukha god. Br. IV. 1. 19.

होम
Homa  (II)--a mukhya gaṇa. Vā. 100. 18.

होरा
Horā --a śakti. Br. IV. 32. 14.

ह्रद
Hrada --a son of Hiraṇyakaśipu; sons Hrāda and Nisunda. Vā. 67. 70, 71.

ह्रद
Hradas --the Jayādevas became converted into. Vā. 67. 32.

ह्रदिन्य
Hradinya --a group of nāḍis giving out dew from the sun (fire). Br. II. 24. 28.

ह्रस्वरोमन्
Hrasvaroman --a son of Svarṇaroman and father of Sīradhvaja (Sariddhaja). Bhā. IX. 13. 17-18; Br. III. 64. 14; Vā. 89. 14; Vi. IV. 5. 27.

ह्राद
Hrāda  (I)--a son of Hiraṇyakaśipu; wife Dhamani, and sons Vātāpi and Ilvala; other sons were Sunda, Nisunda and Mūka. Bhā. VI. 18. 13 and 15; Br. III. 5. 34-5.

ह्राद
Hrāda  (II)--a son of Hrada. Vā. 67. 71. 

ह्राद
Hrāda  (III)--the leader of Asuras in Devāsura war. Vi. III. 17. 9.

ह्रादिका
Hrādikā --R. from Ṛṣyavān; 1) M. 114. 26. (Āplādinī) a branch of the Ganges, flows through countries of the hunters and others. 2) Vā. 47. 38, 51-53.

ह्रादिनी
Hrādinī --a wife of Havyavāhana. Vā. 29. 14.

ह्री
Hrī --a daughter of Dakṣa and a wife of Dharma; mother of Praśraya; 1) Bhā. IV. 1. 50 and 52. a śakti. 2) Br. IV. 44. 71.

ह्लाद
Hlāda --a son of Hiraṇyakaśipu. Vi. I. 15. 142.

ह्लादिनी
Hlādinī  (I)--a R.; wife of Havyavāhana. Br. II. 12. 16.

ह्लादिनी
Hlādinī  (II)--one of the three streams of the Gaṅgā flowing through the countries of Niṣadha, Trigartas, Dhīvara, Ṛṣikam, Nīlamukha, Kakara, Oṣṭakarṇa, Kirāta, Kalodara, Vivarṇa, Kumāra and Svarṇabhūmika; goes to the east through the countries of Upaka, Niṣāda and enters the sea. Br. II. 18. 40, 53-5; M. 121. 40, 52-4.

ह्लादिनी
Hlādinī  (III)--a R. of Kuśadvīpa. M. 122. 72.

ह्लादिनी
Hlādinī  (IV)--a kalā of Hari. Br. IV. 35. 95. 

